प्राकारकर्ण
Prākārakarṇa m.: An owl, living on
the mountain Himavant 3. 191. 4.
Sage Mārkaṇḍeya and king (राजर्षि)
Indradyumna approached the owl Prākāra-
karṇa since he was guessed by Mārkaṇḍeya to
be older than both of them; king Indradyumna
asked Prākārakarṇa if he recognized the king;
Prākārakarṇa thought for a while and said
he did not; when asked by Indradyumna if
Prākārakarṇa knew any one older than he, the
owl directed the king to the crane Nāḍījaṅgha
living in the lake Indradyumna; then the king
Indradyumna took both Mārkaṇḍeya and
Prākārakarṇa to Nāḍījaṅgha 3. 191. 5-10.

बधिर
Badhira m.: A mythical serpent, living
in Bhogavatī Purī 5. 101. 16, 1.
Son of Surasā and Kaśyapa 5. 101. 4, 17;
description 5. 101. 5-7.

बलहेड
Balaheḍa m.: A mythical serpent.
Born in the कुल of Takṣaka, listed by
Sūta among those who were offered in the
snake sacrifice of Janamejaya 1. 52. 8, 7, 9.

बलाह
Balāha m.: Name of Kṛṣṇa's horse.
[See Balāhaka2]

बलाहक
Balāhaka1 m.: A mythical serpent.
One of the serpents who, without feeling
fatigue (विगतक्लम), wait upon Varuṇa in
his सभा; described as marked with banner
(पताकिन्), round spots (मण्डलिन्), and
hooded (फणवन्त्) 2. 9. 9, 10, 11.

बलाहक
Balāhaka2, Balāha m.: Name of one of
the four horses yoked to Kṛṣṇa's chariot.
They all were of excellent Kamboja-breed
(परमकाम्बोज) 10. 13. 1; decorated with
gold strings (हेममालिन् 10. 13. 1) and gold-
harness (हेमभाण्डविभूषित 7. 122. 45);
endowed with all excellences (सर्वसंपद्-)
5. 81. 19; very swift (महावेग) and could
go where they desired (कामग) 7. 122. 45;
10. 13. 9; when they sped along they appeared
to swallow the sky (ते ग्रसन्त इवाकाशं
वेगवन्तो महाबलाः) 12. 53. 22-23; all
the four horses specially marked for their
speed, hence Uttara compared his right side-
horse with Balāhaka and thought him to be
speedier than Balāhaka 4. 40. 21; Balāhaka
was one of the two side-horses (पार्ष्णिवाह),
he being on the right side 4. 40. 21; 10. 13. 2;
Balāhaka mentioned among the four horses
yoked to Kṛṣṇa's chariot when it was got
ready for various occasions—for Kṛṣṇa
when he proceeded to Hāstinapura on his
peace mission 5. 81. 19; for Kṛṣṇa's likely
intervention in war to kill Karṇa, Droṇa and
the rest and to enable Arjuna kill Jayadratha
within the stipulated time 7. 56. 35, 25-37; for
the use by Sātyaki when he lost his chariot
while fighting with Karṇa 7. 122. 45; for
Kṛṣṇa when he followed Bhīma who had left
in pursuit of Aśvatthāman 10. 13. 1-2; for
Kṛṣṇa when he started to visit Bhīṣma lying
on his bed of arrows at Kurukṣetra 12. 53. 21
(here short form Balāha).

बाहुक
Bāhuka m.: A mythical serpent.
Born in the कुल of Kauravya, listed by
Sūta among those offered in the snake sacrifice
of Janamejaya 1. 52. 12, 1, 3.

बाह्यकर्ण
Bāhyakarṇa m.: A mythical serpent.
Son of Kadrū, listed among her sons by
Sūta at the request of Śaunaka 1. 31. 9, 2.

बाह्यकुण्ड
Bāhyakuṇḍa m.: A mythical serpent,
living in Bhogavatī Purī 5. 101. 10, 1.
Son of Surasā and Kaśyapa 5. 101. 4, 17;
description 5. 101. 5-7.

बिल्वपत्र
Bilvapatra m.: A mythical serpent,
living in Bhogavatī Purī 5. 101. 14, 1.
Son of Surasā and Kaśyapa 5. 101. 4, 17;
description 5. 101. 5-7.

बिल्वपाण्डुक
Bilvapāṇḍuka m.: A mythical serpent.
Son of Kadrū, listed among her sons by
Sūta at the request of Śaunaka 1. 31. 12, 2.

भद्रमना
Bhadramanā f.: A mythical female
elephant (?).
One of the nine self-born (आत्मसं-
भवा) daughters of Krodhavaśā (or of
Tāmrā (?) 1. 60. 54; in that case क्रोधवशा
‘irascible’); the divine lordly elephant Airā-
vata her son 1. 60. 58, 61.

भासी
Bhāsī f.: A mythical being.
One of the five daughters of divine (देवी)
Tāmrā, she gave birth to vultures (गृध्रस्)
and other birds of prey (भासस्) 1. 60. 54, 55;
also mentioned as one of the seven (eight ?)
daughters of divine (देवी) Prāvā 1. 59.
44, 47.

भूलिङ्गशकुनि
Bhūliṅgaśakuni f.: Name of a female
bird.
Lives on the other side of Himavant; re-
puted to utter cries which sound like मा-
साहसम् ‘do not commit a rash act’, but
herself acts rashly; she, a dull-witted bird,
tries to pick out pieces of flesh stuck between
the teeth of a lion when he is eating flesh;
obviously she lives at the pleasure of the lion;
hence cited as an example for those who,
while living at the pleasure of others, act
rashly but tell others not to do so; according
to Śiśupāla Bhīṣma acted like this Bhūliṅga-
śakuni when he praised Kṛṣṇa 2. 41. 18-23.

भैरव
Bhairava m.: A mythical serpent.
Born in the family of Dhṛtarāṣṭra, listed
by Sūta among those offered in the snake
sacrifice of Janamejaya; described as ‘fast as
wind’ (वातवेग), ‘having excess of poison’
(विषोल्बण) 1. 52. 15, 13.

मणि
Maṇi, Maṇināga m.: A mythical ser-
pent, living in Bhogavatī Purī 5. 101. 10, 1.
Son of Surasā and Kaśyapa 5. 101. 4, 17;
description 5. 101. 5-7; also listed by Sūta
among the sons of Kadrū 1. 31. 6; according
to Kṛṣṇa, Maṇināga had his residence
(आलय) near Girivraja in the Magadha
country; due to his presence the land of
Magadha could never be avoided by the
clouds (अपरिहार्या मेघानां मागधेयं
मणेः कृते) 2. 19. 9-10.

मणिमत्|मणिमन्त्
Maṇimant m.: A mythical serpent.
One of the serpents who, without feeling
fatigue, wait on Varuṇa in his सभा;
marked with banner (पताकिन्) and round
spots (मण्डलिन्), hooded (फणवन्त्) 2.
9. 9, 10, 11; according to Kṛṣṇa, he and
the नाग Kauśika continue to favour the
Magadha country 2. 19. 10.

मणिस्कन्ध
Maṇiskandha m.: A mythical serpent.
Born in the कुल of Dhṛtarāṣṭra, listed
