his माया; Rākṣasas mounted them and follow-
ed Ghaṭotkaca on his Airāvata (also created
by माया) when he attacked Bhagadatta on
his elephant; they all were of huge shape,
with rut flowing from temples, very strong and
endowed with lustre; they had four tusks 6.
60. 51, 50, 52, 54; excellent elephants born
in the कुल of Mahāpadma were killed by
Sātyaki in the war 7. 97. 24, 26.

महाहनु
Mahāhanu m.: A mythical serpent.
Born in the कुल of Dhṛtarāṣṭra, listed
by Sūta among those offered in the snake
sacrifice of Janamejaya; described as ‘fast
as wind’ (वातवेग), ‘having excess of
poison (विषोल्बण) 1. 52. 16, 13.

महोदर
Mahodara m.: A mythical serpent.
Son of Kadrū, listed among her
sons by Sūta at the request of Śaunaka 1.
31. 15, 2.

मातङ्गी
Mātaṅgī f.: A mythical female ele-
phant.
One of the nine self-born (आत्मसं-
भवा) daughters of Krodhavaśā (or of
Tāmrā (?) 1. 60. 54; in that case क्रोधवशा
‘irascible’); she gave birth to elephants 1.
60. 58, 59, 64.

मातरिश्वन्
Mātariśvan m.: A mythical bird, living
in the world of Suparṇas to 5. 99. 14, 1.
Born in the कुल of Vainateya (Garuḍa),
in the वंश of Kaśyapa; feeding on serpents;
marked with श्रीवत्स, his deity is Viṣṇu;
by action a Kṣatriya, not obtaining Brahmin-
hood because engaged in destroying kinsmen
5. 99. 2-8.

मानव
Mānava m.: A mythical serpent.
Born in the कुल of Dhṛtarāṣṭra, listed
by Sūta among those offered in the snake
sacrifice of Janamejaya; described as ‘fast
as wind’ (वातवेग), ‘having excess of
poison’ (विषोल्बण) 1. 52. 15, 13.

मानस
Mānasa m.: A mythical serpent.
Born in the कुल of Vāsuki, listed by
Sūta among those offered in the snake sacrifice
of Janamejaya; some of the serpents in this
family were dark-red others white; all of them
