to Yudhiṣṭhira 8. 49. 107-109 (प्रतिज्ञा);
Yudhiṣṭhira, in a fit of anger, asked Arjuna
to give away Gāṇḍīva to Kṛṣṇa and act as
his charioteer, and hence Yudhiṣṭhira's life
was in danger 8. 48. 14; 8. 49. 1.
I. Com-
parisons: 1 (i) Arjuna with the stretched
Gāṇḍīva forming a full circle appeared like the
sun with a halo around it (यथैव सूर्यः
परिवेषगस् तथा) 8. 57. 57; (ii) when
Arjuna released arrows using both hands,
Gāṇḍīva looked like a swinging wheel of
fire (अग्निचक्रम् इवाबद्धम्) 4. 59. 12;
(iii) in the sacrifice to be performed with
weapons (शस्त्रयज्ञ), Gānḍīva would serve
as a sacrificial ladle (स्रुच्) 5. 139. 30;
2. Standard of comparison: (i) The
lustre of Rukmin's bow (Vijaya), obtained
from Mahendra, compared with that of
Gāṇḍīva 5. 155. 4; (ii) the sound (घोष)
of Abhimanyu's bow compared with that of
Gāṇḍīva 6. 45. 16
J. Defeat: 1. Occa-
sional: (i) When Arjuna's arrows had no
effect on the armour of Duryodhana, Kṛṣṇa
asked Arjuna whether his Gāṇḍīva had lost
its former force (प्राणाः) 7. 78. 7; (ii)
Jayadratha on one occasion succeeded in
piercing the Gāṇḍīva with three arrows
7. 121. 12; (iii) as long as Karṇa had his
armour, ear-rings, and the शक्ति, Arjuna, even
with his Gāṇḍīva, could not defeat Karṇa
7. 155. 17; 7. 155. 13-15; (iv) when
Aśvatthaman excelled Arjuna, Krṣṇa in
surprise asked him whether he still held the
Gāṇḍīva in his hand 8. 40. 124; (v) Gāṇ-
ḍīva dropped down from the hand of Arjuna
when Dhṛtavarman of the Trigartas hit
Arjuna on his hand with a sharp arrow
14. 73. 22-24 (picked up by Arjuna 14. 75.
24); (vi) when the Sindhu kings attacked
Arjuna and he swooned, Gāṇḍīva slipped
from his hand 14. 76. 21, (which he picked
up again 14. 76. 26); (vii) According to
Ulūka, Gāṇḍīva of no help to Arjuna at
the game of dice 5. 158. 28-29; 2. Final:
When Arjuna was taking with him the
Vṛṣṇi women to Hāstinapura, he was attacked
on way by the Dasyus; at that time Arjuna
could string the Gāṇḍīva with great effort
(यत्नाद् इव कथंचन; कृच्छ्रेण) 16.
8. 52-53; his arrows were exhausted so
that Arjuna had to strike the Dasyus with
the tip of the bow (धनुष्कोट्या) 16. 8.
58-60, 63 (धनुषश् चाविधेयत्वात्); 16.
9. 17-18; this was the defeat of Gāṇḍīva
(गाण्डीवस्य पराभवम्) 1. 2. 226.
K.
Returned to Varuṇa: When the Pāṇḍavas
started for the forest, Arjuna would not
leave his bow and quivers behind; Agni, who
had burnt the Khāṇḍava, asked Arjuna
to abandon the bow as it had no further
purpose to serve; Agni got it from Varuṇa
for Arjuna, hence Arjuna should return it
to Varuṇa; at the instance of his brothers,
Arjuna dropped the bow and the quivers into
the water 17. 1. 32, 36-37, 39-40.

गान्धर्व
Gāndharva1 adj.: Of a kind of missile
known to the Gandharvas.
Arjuna obtained the Gāndharva missile
from Tumburu and the other Gandharvas
by practising austerities; (Abhimanyu had
apparently received it from Arjuna); Abhi-
manyu used it against his adversaries; the
missile produced मायास् with which Abhi-
manyu deluded his opponents (तेनामोह-
यताहितान्) 7. 44. 21-24.

गान्धर्व
Gāndharva2 adj.: Of a kind of a व्यूह
(arrangement of the army) known to the
Gandharvas.
Bhīṣma knew different kinds of व्यूहस्,
one of them being the Gāndharva 5. 162. 10;
6. 19. 2; he arranged the Kaurava army
everyday in a different way, one of the ways
being the Gāndharva 6. 20. 18; Dhṛṣṭadyumna
also knew how to arrange the army in the
Gāndharva and the other ways 5. 56. 11.

गान्धर्व
Gāndharva3 adj.: Of the way the
Gandharvas fought.
The fight between Karṇa and Sātyaki
(7. 122. 49) and the one between Droṇa and
Arjuna (7. 163. 37) excelled the fights of the
Gandharvas.

गारुड
Gāruḍa adj.: Of a व्यूह।
Described as महाव्यूह; used by
Bhīṣma on the third day of the war. [See
Garuḍa]

गुह्यकास्त्र
Guhyakāstra nt.: Name of a missile.
It was used by Rāma (Jāmadagnya) to
combat the Vāyavya astra employed by
Bhīṣma against him 5. 181. 11.

घोर
Ghora nt.: Name of a missile.
One of the eight missiles known to
Arjuna 5. 94. 38-40; for the effects produced
by it see Akṣisaṃtarjana.

चक्रव्यूह
Cakravyūha m.: Name of a व्यूह (a
particular arrangement of the army). Droṇa
arranged the Kaurava army according to this
व्यूह on the thirteenth day of the war.
A. Description: impenetrable (दुर्-
भिद) 7. 32. 18; impenetrable even for the
gods (अभेद्यस् त्रिदशैर् अपि) 7. 32. 13;
unassailable (अनाधृष्य) 7. 34. 1; difficult
to look at, when it moved it shone like
the mid-day sun (चरन् मध्यंदिने
सूर्यः प्रपतन्न् इव दुर्दृशः) 7. 32.
17.
B. Arrangement: A special force
of ten thousand kings (राजानः 7. 33.
12; संघातो राजपुत्राणां 7. 33. 13)
fighting with strong bows under the leader-
ship of Lakṣmaṇa (son of Duryodhana) was
employed in it; they were comparable with
Indra, had golden banners with red flags,
dressed in red robes, and wearing red decora-
tions and gold strings; they had formed a cove-
nant (कृताभिसमयाः 7. 33. 13); they shared
their grief with each other, they were of equal
daring and they vied with each other (in
this regard), and were intent on each other's
well-being (अन्योन्यसमदुःखास् ते अन्यो-
न्यसमसाहसाः।अन्योन्यं स्पर्धमानाश्
च अन्योन्यस्य हिते रताः 7. 33. 16); Dur-
yodhana, surrounded by Karṇa, Duḥśāsana
and Kṛpa was also involved in it; Droṇa
and Jayadratha stood at the head of the
army (प्रमुखे 7. 33. 18); thirty sons of
Dhṛtarāṣṭra, with Aśvatthāman to lead them,
stood on one side of Jayadratha and on the
other stood Śakuni, Śalya and Bhūriśravas
7. 33. 12-20.
C. Abhimanyu agreed to
penetrate the Cakravyūha: Penetrating
the व्यूह was a task difficult to be ac-
complished 7. 32. 19 (दुष्करं कर्म), a
burden difficult to bear (अविषह्यं गुरुं
भारम्) 7. 34. 12; its penetration (भेद)
not known to any one except Kṛṣṇa, Arjuna,
Pradyumna and Abhimanyu; even Abhi-
manyu was taught by Arjuna the way to
enter it, but not the way to get out of it
in case of emergency (नोत्सहे तु विनिर्-
गन्तुम् अहं कस्यांचिद् आपदि) 7. 34.
14-15, 19; 7. 50. 20-21; Abhimanyu commis-
sioned by Yudhiṣṭhira to penetrate the व्यूह
and the Pāṇḍavas assured him of support
from the rear 7. 34. 16-17; 20-23, 7. 32. 18;
(subsequently when Abhimanyu entered it
and was isolated from the other Pāṇḍavas
by Jayadratha, he was killed while fighting).

चक्रशकट
Cakraśakaṭa, Śakaṭa m.: Name of a
व्यूह (a particular arrangement of the
army; also called for short Śakaṭa) 7. 63.
26, 28; 7. 65. 2; 7. 53. 27.
A. Description: Constituetd of a con-
centration of many chariots, foot-soldiers,
horses, and elephants; the व्यूह looked like
an agitated sea; it appeared as if it could
swallow the entire earth with mountains,
oceans and forests, and different peoples
(जनपद); it was capable of striking terror
in the hearts of the enemies 7. 63. 31-33;
called महाव्यूह (7. 63. 24); it was
twelve गव्यूतिस् long and five गव्यूतिस्
wide in the rear half (7. 63. 21).
B.
Arrangement: In the interior of the rear
half, a section of the army was arranged to
form Padmavyūha which was difficult to
penetrate (पश्चार्धे तस्य पद्मस् तु गर्-
भव्यूहः सुदुर्भिदः 7. 63. 23; 7. 53.
27; concealed (गूढः) within the Padma-
vyūha there was yet another व्यूह known
as Sūcī 7. 63. 23; at the entrance (मुख)
of the main Cakraśakaṭavyūha stood Droṇa
himself with the king of the Bhojas to offer
protection to him 7. 63. 28-29; in the front
of all the army divisions (अग्रटः सर्वसैन्-
यानाम् 7. 63. 19) stood Durmarṣaṇa, the
son of Dhṛtarāṣṭra, with a thousand and five
hundred fierce elephants mounted by skilled
fighters; Durmarṣaṇa was accompanied by
his brothers Duḥśāsana and Vikarṇa (they
were अग्रानीके व्यवस्थितौ) to guard the
interests of Jayadratha 7. 63. 19-20; at the
entrance (मुख) of the Sūcīvyūha stood
ready Kṛtavarman, followed by the Kām-
bhoja king and king Jalasandha; they were
supported by Duryodhana and his ministers
(सहामात्यः 7. 63. 25); behind them all
were stationed, to protect the Sūcivyūha,
hundreds and thousands of warriors who
would never turn back while fighting
(योधानाम् अनिवर्तिनाम् 7. 63. 26); behind
them, at the position of the ‘eye of the
needle’ (सूचिपाशे) of the Sūcīvyūha stood
Jayadratha surrounded by a large force 7.
63. 27; 7. 53. 27; he was guarded by six
principal warriors, Saumadatti (Bhūriśravas),
Karṇa, Aśvatthāman, Śalya, Vṛṣasena, Kṛpa,
with a force consisting of a hundred thou-
sand horsemen, six अयुतस् of chariot-
fighters, fourteen thousand elephant-riders,
and twentyone thousand foot-soldiers; the
place where Jayadratha was stationed was at
a distance of three गव्यूतिस् from the main
battle front where Droṇa stood guard 7. 63.
11-14; 7. 53. 26, 28.
C. Purpose: The
व्यूह was designed by Droṇa on the
14th day of the war to save Jayadratha
from being killed by Arjuna 7. 63. 21, 22,
24, 15.

चन्द्रार्ध
Candrārdha m.: Name of a व्यूह (a
particular arrangement of the army).
The Saṃśaptakas arranged their army
according to the व्यूह known as Candrārdha
in which only the chariot-fighters were
stationed in the front (व्यूह्यानीकं रथैर्
एव); the army was stationed on level
ground (समे देशे व्यवस्थिताः) 7. 17. 1.
[See Ardhacandra]

जैत्र
Jaitra m.: Name (?) of Indra's
chariot.
The excellent chariot of Indra (स्यन्द-
नोत्तम, रथोदार) Jaitra (? or ‘victori-
ous’), drawn by bay horses (हर्यश्वयुज्),
riding which Indra killed hundreds of Daityas
and Dānavas; it was sent by Indra to Rāma
while the latter was engaged in a battle with
Rāvaṇa 3. 274. 13-14. [See Sudarśana2]

ज्योतिष
Jyotiṣa nt.: Name of a missile.
Employed by Arjuna to dispel the dark-
ness created by the माया of Śakuni 7. 29.
24, 15.

तामसास्त्र
Tāmasāstra nt.: Name of a missile.
Arjuna struck down with fortitude the
Tāmasāstra employed against him apparently
by the Rākṣasas 8. 65. 18.

त्रैय्यम्बक
Traiyyambaka (for Traiyambaka ?)
adj.: of the missile belonging to Tryambaka,
i. e. Śiva.
Droṇa knew the use of many missiles,
one of these was Traiyyambaka 7. 5. 34.
[See Pāśupata]

त्वाष्ट्र
Tvāṣṭra adj.: of the missile belonging
to Tvaṣṭṛ.
A. Description: great missile (पर-
मास्त्र) and ‘killer of the host of enemies’
(अरिसंघघ्न) 7. 18. 14, 11.
B. Uses:
(1) According to Bhīṣma, only Arjuna and
Kṛṣṇa, and no one else, knew the missile of
Tvaṣṭṛ and other heavenly missiles 6. 116.
38-39; when employed by Arjuna against the
Saṃśaptakas it created thousands of forms
so that some of the warriors on the enemy's
side looked like Arjuna and Kṛṣṇa; deceived
by this delusion, the enemies killed warriors of
their own side mistaking them to be Arjuna
and Kṛṣṇa; it also destroyed thousands of
arrows released by the enemies and killed
them 7. 18. 11-15; (2) However, Bhīma
himself, like Tvaṣṭṛ, employed this weapon
against the demon Alambusa to release thou-
sands of arrows to rout the Kaurava army;
it destroyed Alambusa's powerful माया
(महामाया) and tormented him 7. 83.
34-36; (3) Also employed by Droṇa against
Yudhiṣṭhira, but was repelled by the latter
7. 132. 29-30; employed by Droṇa against
Arjuna, but was made ineffective by him
7. 163. 28.

दण्ड
Daṇḍa m.: A missile associated with
Yama, Antaka, Mṛtyu, Kāla, Brahman and
Rudra.
A. Creation: Indra got heavy Daṇḍas
made (कारयाम् आस … गुरुदंडांश् च
पुष्कतान्), and other heavenly missiles (like
वज्राणि and चक्राणि) out of the bones of
the sage Dadhīca 9. 50. 30; Śiva is called
the creator of the Brahmadaṇḍa (ब्रह्म-
दण्डविनिर्माता) 13. 17. 130.
B. Asso-
ciations: (1) It was looked upon as a weapon
specially of Yama (cf. the expression Yama-
daṇḍa in section C below); hence Yama called
‘holding दण्ड in hand’ (दण्डपाणि) 3.
12. 46; 3. 42. 10; (दण्डहस्त) 8. 29. 28
(Vaivasvata); (दण्डधार) 3. 40. 38; or
‘equipped with Daṇḍa’ (दण्डिन्) 1. 180.
16; it was Yama who gave his irresistible
(अप्रतिवारण) Daṇḍa to Arjuna with proper
rites (विधिवत्), together with the मन्त्रस्
(समन्त्रम्), and instruction regarding its
full operation (सोपचारम् = सेतिकर्तव्यता-
कम् according to Nī. on Bom. Ed. 3. 41.
26), its release (समोक्षम्), and withdrawal
(सनिवर्तनम्); Arjuna was supposed to
perform great deeds with it 3. 42. 23-24; 3.
89. 12; 4. 56. 14; 7. 53. 43; 12. 5. 13; Yama
held it (कालदण्ड) when he wished to fight
with Kṛṣṇa and Arjuna at the time of the
Khāṇḍava fire 1. 218. 31, 37; some people
afraid to commit sins due to their fear of
Yama's Daṇḍa 12. 15. 5; (a king punish-
ing the unrighteous with दण्ड (punish-
ment) acts like Yama 12. 68. 45); (2)
of Antaka (cf. the expression Antaka-
daṇḍa in section C below); hence Antaka
called दण्डपाणि 4. 22. 19; 5. 50. 7;
6. 50. 2; 6. 58. 51; 6. 59. 11; 6. 78. 57; 6.
103. 68; 8. 43. 70; 9. 18. 46; 9. 24. 28;
दण्डहस्त 2. 72. 31; 6. 98. 35; 7. 14. 5;
7. 131. 30; 9. 25. 2; 9. 31. 39; (3) of
Mṛtyu (cf. the expression Mṛtyudaṇḍa in
section C below) who is equipped with fierce
Daṇḍa 1. 167. 19; (4) of Kāla (cf. the
expression Kāladaṇḍa in section C below);
Kāla called ‘equipped with दण्ड’ (दण्डिन्)
9. 60. 60; Yama held कालदण्ड 1. 218. 31;
Antaka held कालदण्ड 7. 107. 87; (5) of
Brahman (cf. the expression Brahmadaṇḍa in
section C below); angry Sudhanvan compar-
ed with the burning Brahmadaṇḍa 2. 61. 62;
Vāsuki, afraid of his mother's curse, confused
the directions as though he was tormented
by Brahmadaṇḍa 1. 49. 22; Āstīka would
destroy the Brahmadaṇḍa (महाघोर) of
which Vāsuki was so much afraid 1. 49. 24;
serpents, struck by Brahmadaṇḍa, fell into
the snake sacrifice of Janamejaya 1. 52. 22;
Brahmadaṇḍa mentioned among the missiles
which should be known to a king 2. 5. 111;
Brahmadaṇḍa and other missiles moved
around the chariot of Śiva (परिस्कन्दाः)
to guard it in all directions 8. 24. 79; (6)
of Rudra: Rudradaṇḍa among those missiles
which moved round the chariot of Śiva
(परिस्कन्दाः) to guard it in all directions
8. 24. 29.
C. Comparisons: Missiles
like arrows, गदा, शक्ति, or even a tree or
a stick used as a powerful weapon, compar-
ed with the दण्ड (Yamadaṇḍa, Antakadaṇḍa,
Mṛtyudaṇḍa, Kāladaṇḍa or Brahmadaṇḍa):
(a) arrows: (1) of Droṇa compared with
Yamadaṇḍa 6. 102. 5 (शित); with Kāla-
daṇḍa 6. 43. 30 (महाघोर); with Mṛtyu-
daṇḍa 6. 49. 9; with Brahmadaṇḍa 7.
164. 122; (2) of Arjuna compared with
Yamadaṇḍa 6. 106. 39 (घोर); 9. 26. 42
(शित); with Antakadaṇḍa 8. 66. 31; with
Brahmadaṇḍa 6. 114. 57; (3) of Bhīma
compared with Mṛtyudaṇḍa 6. 76. 5 (घोर);
with Yamadaṇḍa 9. 25. 22 (शुभ ‘shin-
ing’ ?); 7. 108. 25; (4) of Karṇa
compared with Mṛtyudaṇḍa 8. 42. 12; (5)
of Aśvatthāman compared with Yamadaṇḍa
7. 141. 34 (घोर); 9. 13. 38 (तीक्ष्ण);
with Antakadaṇḍa 8. 15. 39; (6) of
Sātyaki compared with Yamadaṇḍa 6. 70.
20 (घोर); 7. 92. 38; (7) of Jaya-
dratha compared with Yamadaṇḍa 6. 81.
30; (8) of Abhimanyu compared with
Yamadaṇḍa 6. 96. 4 (घोर); (9) of
Alaṃbusa compared with Yamadaṇḍa 6. 97.
18 (शित); (10) of Nakula compared with
Yamadaṇḍa 8. 17. 15; (11) of Sahadeva
compared with Yamadaṇḍa 8. 17. 38 (त्विष्);
(12) of Śrutarvan compared with Yama-
daṇḍa 9. 25. 22 (शुभ ‘shining’ ?); (13)
of Rāma compared with Brahmadaṇḍa 3. 274.
27; (b) गदा: (1) of Bhīma compared
with Yamadaṇḍa 3. 152. 15 (गुर्वी); 6. 58.
57 (गुर्वी); 6. 59. 16 (उग्रा); 6. 81. 33; 6.
90. 21 (गुर्वी); 9. 10. 43; 9. 56. 12 (गुर्वी,
रौद्री, विशसनी); 9. 56. 24-25 (गुर्वी,
घोरा); compared with the Daṇḍa of Antaka
2. 72. 31; 5. 50. 7 (घोरा); 6. 50. 2; 6.
58. 51; 6. 59. 11 (गुर्वी, महती); 6. 78. 57;
9. 18. 46 (महती); 9. 24. 28 (महती); 9.
25. 2 (गदा not mentioned); compared with
the Daṇḍa of Kāla 7. 102. 87; 7. 104. 3;
7. 170. 46; with the Daṇḍa of Brahman
5. 50. 8; (2) of Dhṛṣṭadyumna compared
with Yamadaṇḍa 6. 112. 47; (3) of
Duryodhana: Duryodhana with his गदा
compared with Antaka holding दण्ड 9.
31. 39; Duryodhana with his गदा in hand
cannot be killed even by Kāla armed with
his Daṇḍa (कालेनापीह दण्डिना) 9. 60. 60;
(4) Śalya with his गदा compared with
Antaka holding दण्ड 7. 14. 5; (c) शक्ति:
(1) of Rāma Jāmadagnya compared with
Yamadaṇḍa 5. 185. 5 (प्रभा); (2) of
Bhagadatta compared with Yamadaṇḍa 6.
107. 11 (दृढा, घोरा); (3) of Yudhi-
ṣṭhira compared with Brahmadaṇḍa 9. 16. 42
(उग्ररूपा); (d) शूल: of Rāvaṇa hurled
against Rāma compared with Brahmadaṇḍa
3. 274. 19; cut off by Rāma 3. 274. 20;
(e) तोमर: Naiṣādi (not identified) armed
with तोमर compared with Antaka holding
the दण्ड 8. 43. 70; (f) Bow: (1)
Ghaṭotkaca with bow in his hand compared
with Antaka holding दण्ड in his hand 7.
131. 30; with Antaka holding Kāladaṇḍa in
hand 7. 150. 33 (उग्र); (2) Aśvatthāman
(bow not mentioned) compared with Kāla
holding Daṇḍa 5. 164. 10; (g) a tusk of
an elephant: Bhīma holding a tusk compared
with Antaka holding his Daṇḍa 6. 98. 35;
(h) a tree or a stick: (1) the tree held by
Bhīma compared with the Daṇḍa of Yama
(Pitṛrāja) 1. 180. 16 (उग्र); the tree of
Bhīma to fight with Kirmīra compared with
Yamadaṇḍa 3. 12. 43; Bhīma with tree in
hand compared with Antaka holding his Daṇḍa
4. 22. 19; (2) the tree of Kirmīra compared
with the Daṇḍa of Yama (not named) 3.
12. 46; (3) King Kalmāṣapāda with stick
(काष्ठ) in hand compared with Mṛtyu
holding Daṇḍa 1. 167. 19 (उग्र); (4) the
stick (दण्ड) held by Ruru compared with
Kāladaṇḍa 1. 9. 21; (5) the त्रिदण्ड held
by Śunaḥsakha compared with Brahmadaṇḍa
13. 95. 48; (6) Garuḍa: compared with a
raised Brahmadaṇḍa 1. 26. 7. [See Kiṃkara]

देवदत्त
Devadatta m.: Name of Arjuna's
conch.
A. Origin: Produced in water जलो-
द्भव 3. 165. 22; वारिज 3. 172. 5.
B.
Description: Heavenly (दिव्य) 5. 47. 58;
6. 1. 17; 6. 23. 14; excellent conch, excellent
among all conches, unsurpassed (शङ्ख-
प्रवर) 3. 165. 21; (शङ्खवर) 6. 47. 25;
(सर्वशङ्खवर) 7. 79. 11; (अनुत्तम)
2. 3. 18; of large size (महाशङ्ख) 2.
3. 7; 7. 18. 10; frightful (भीम) 8. 54.
27; shining white like snow (हिमावदात)
8. 68. 56, or shining like a white cloud
(पाण्डुराभ्रप्रकाश) 8. 54. 27; producing
loud sound (महास्वन) 3. 166. 11; 8. 68.
56; (महारव) 3. 171. 5, or good sound
(सुघोष) 8. 54. 27; 8. 68. 55; (सुघोषवन्त्)
2. 3. 7; decorated with gold (हेमपरिष्कृत)
7. 17. 8, with golden net (सुवर्णजालावतत)
8. 68. 56, or with gold and jewels (हेम-
रत्नपरिष्कृत) 6. 47. 24.
C. History:
It belonged to Varuṇa (वारुण); Maya
brought it from Bindusaras for Arjuna
2. 3. 7, 16, 18; but according to another
tradition it was in the possession of Indra and
he conquered the worlds with it; it was given
by the gods to Arjuna when he was to leave
for his battle with the Nivātakavacas 3.
165. 21, 22; God (Indra) gifted it to
Arjuna when he returned victorious from his
fight with the Nivātakavacas and the Kāla-
keyas 3. 171. 5; 8. 57. 43.
D. Effect of
its sound: When blown by Arjuna its sound
filled the space and reached up to the heaven
3. 166. 12; 7. 17. 8; 7. 79. 12; 8. 68. 57; it
terrified the minds of the enemies (but caused
delight to the friends) 6. 23. 19; 4. 61. 28;
8. 68. 57; hearing it the enemies and the
horses yoked to their chariots ejected urine and
excreta 6. 1. 18; or, hearing it the army of
the opponents became stupefied and the horses
ejected urine and blood 7. 17. 9-10, the
elephants became distracted (विचेतसः) and
slower in movement (मन्दवेगतराः) 7.
65. 15; even big creatures were frightened to
hear the sound and they lay low (वित्रेसुश् च
निलिल्युश् च भूतानि सुमहान्त्य् अपि) 3. 166.
12.
E. Use: Having received Devadatta,
Arjuna kept it on his chariot (along with his
bow and the quivers) 5. 47. 58; 8. 54. 27;
he must have blown it on all important
occasions; specific mention of the blowing is
found: (1) when Arjuna attacked the city
of the Nivātakavacas 3. 166. 11; when he
got ready to demonstrate his acquisition of the
divine weapons to his brothers 3. 172. 5;
when Arjuna defeated the Kaurava heroes at
the time of the cattle-raid 4. 61. 28; when the
two armies of the Kauravas and the Pāṇḍavas
were arrayed against each other 6. 1. 17-18;
6. 23. 15; 6. 47. 25; while fighting with the
Saṃśaptakas 7. 17. 8; 7. 18. 10; 8. 37. 19;
when Arjuna took the vow to kill Jayadratha
7. 51. 41; while fighting with the elephants
of Duḥśāsana 7. 65. 14; while fighting with
the warriors who protected Jayadratha 7. 79.
11; when he succeeded in killing Karṇa 8.
68. 57.

दैतेयास्त्र
Daiteyāstra nt.: Name (?) of a missile.
The terrible माया of the Asuras (आसुरीं
दारुणीं मायाम्), employed by Śālva against
Pradyumna, so called; with its employment
Śālva was able to shoot at once a number
of arrows; the missile was successfully cut
down half way by Pradyumna by using
Brahmāstra 3. 20. 16-18.

धातुर्
Dhātur astra nt.: Missile (not named)
of God Dhātṛ.
It was known to Arjuna (and possibly to
Kṛṣṇa) 6. 116. 38-39.

नन्द
Nanda m.: Name of a drum (मृदङ्ग).
One of the two drums (the other being
Upananda), of suitable size, producing sweet
sound at the crest of the flag of Yudhiṣṭhira
(यस्य ध्वजाग्रे नदतो मृदङ्गौ नन्दो-
पन्दौ मधुरौ युक्तरूपौ) 3. 254. 6.

नन्दक
Nandaka m.: Name of the sword of
Kṛṣṇa (Viṣṇu).
It appeared from Kṛṣṇa's body (together
with his conch, disk, mace etc.) when he
laughed to show his terrible form to Duryo-
dhana and others in the Sabhā of the
Kauravas 5. 129. 9; (hence Nandakin one of
the thousand names of Viṣṇu 13. 135. 120).

नर्तन
Nartana nt.: Name of a missile (अस्त्र).
One of the eight missiles known to
Arjuna; enumerated by Rāma Jāmadagnya
for the information of Duryodhana 5. 94. 3
[for the effects produced by it on the enemy
see Akṣisaṃtarjana].

नाक
Nāka nt.: Name of a missile (अस्त्र).
One of the eight missiles known to
Arjuna, enumerated by Rāma Jāmadagnya
for the information of Duryodhana 5. 94. 38
[For the effects produced by it on the enemy
see Akṣisaṃtarjana].

नाग
Nāga astra nt.: Name of a missile.
It was employed repeatedly by Arjuna
to tie the feet of the army of the Saṃśap-
takas and render them motionless (पद-
बन्धं ततश् चक्रे … नागं अस्त्रं
महाराज संप्रोदीर्य मुहुर् मुहुः॥
यान् उद्दिश्य रणे पार्थः पदबन्धं
चकार ह।ते बद्धाः पदबन्धेन
पाण्डवेन महात्मना।निश्चेष्टा अभवन्)
8. 37. 21, 22; it was rendered useless by
Suśarman by employing Sauparṇa astra 8.
37. 25-27 (बभौ बलं तद् विमुक्तं
पदबन्धात्).

नारायणास्त्र
Nārāyaṇāstra nt.: Name of the missile
employed unsuccessfully by Aśvatthāman,
after the death of his father Droṇa, to kill
the Pāṇḍavas 1. 1. 145; 1. 2. 165; 7. 166. 55;
a sub-पर्वन् related to the employment of
the Nārāyaṇāstra occurs after the sub-पर्वन्
related to द्रोणवध 1. 2. 58.
A. History: Droṇa received the Nārā-
yaṇāstra as a boon from Nārāyaṇa himself
who appeared before him in the form of
a Brāhmaṇa 7. 166. 43-44, 51; with its
acquisition Droṇa became unrivalled in
battle 7. 166. 45; given by Nārāyaṇa
also to Aśvatthāman 7. 166. 50; Aśva-
tthāman knew how to release it (सकल्यम्
for सकल्पम् ? See Cr. Notes 7, p. 1157
on 166. 42; Nī. कल्यः प्रयोगः on Bom.
Ed. 7. 195. 30), and how to withdraw it
(सनिवर्तनम्) 7. 166. 42 (but See Section
C. 3 below); Nārāyaṇāstra known only to
Droṇa and Aśvatthāman; it was not known
even to Arjuna and the other Pāṇḍavas, nor
to Kṛṣṇa, Sātyaki, Dhṛṣṭadyumna and
Śikhaṇḍin 7. 166. 2. 41-42.
B. Descrip-
tion: heavenly (दिव्य) 1. 1. 145; 7. 166.
60; great missile (महास्त्र) 7. 166. 49;
(परम) 7. 166. 44; fierce, frightful (उग्र)
1. 2. 165; (घोररूपं भयावहम्) 7. 167.
6.
C. Use: (1) To be used with great
circumspection: The missile was not to be
employed in haste (न त्व् इदं सहसा
ब्रह्मन् प्रयोक्तव्यं कथंचन); since
it did not return without killing the enemy,
it might kill, if used without circumspection,
even one who did not deserve to be killed
7. 166. 46-47; (2) Mode of release: To use
it, Aśvatthāman touched water and produced
the divine missile (तथोक्त्वा द्रोणपुत्रो ऽपि
तदोपस्पृश्य भारत।प्रादुश्चकार तद्
दिव्यम् अस्त्रं नारायणं तदा) 7. 166. 60;
(3) Restrictions: It could be used only
once, and it could not be withdrawn; hence
Aśvatthāman unable to employ it again when
requested by Duryodhana to do so; if with-
drawn the अस्त्र would kill the user 7. 171.
24, 27, 28, 30.
D. Effects: When em-
ployed, the missile released powerful arrows
(? कृशाश्वतनयाः), as also sharp arrows
which would fill the directions 7. 166. 38;
it let loose many heavenly weapons (दिव्यानि
शस्त्रवर्षाणि) and the employer (Aśvat-
thāman) shone with lustre 7. 166. 50; the
arrows released from it would hit the enemies
as desired by the employer (Aśvatthāman);
it would release rocks at will and iron-tipped
arrows which would put the enemy to flight
7. 166. 53-54; when Aśvatthāman produced
the missile, thunderous winds carrying water-
drops blew in cloud-less sky, the earth shook,
and the ocean was agitated; rivers started
flowing in the opposite direction; peaks of
mountains were shattered; sun became turbid
(कलुष), and the gods, the demons, and
the Gandharvas were frightened 7. 167. 1-5;
arrows with shining tips appeared in thou-
sands to cover the army of the enemy and
fill the directions; (hot) iron balls (कार्ष्णाय-
समया गुडाः) shining like celestial bodies,
शतघ्नीस् (‘hundred-killers’), fire-arms
(? हुताशदाः), and disks with sharp ends
(चक्राणि क्षुरान्तानि), all these were produc-
ed by the Nārāyaṇāstra (7. 170. 16-19); as the
Pāṇḍava warriors tried to resist the missile,
it grew in strength 7. 170. 21; as a result,
the Pāṇḍava army was burnt and destroyed
7. 170. 22-23; to combat it successfully
Kṛṣṇa advised the warriors to lay down arms
and get down from their chariots and mounts
7. 170. 38-42; when all followed his in-
struction, Bhīma wanted to resist the missile
with arrows, mace, and the strength of his
arms; as a consequence, the Nārāyaṇāstra
grew in strength; since other warriors
had laid down their arms the missile des-
cended on Bhīma with all its strength 7.
170. 45-46, 50-51, 57-60; seeing Bhīma
surrounded by the Nārāyaṇāstra, Arjuna tried
to protect him from the missile by using
Vāruṇāstra; since this was of no avail,
Arjuna and Vāsudeva left from their chariot,
ran to Bhīma, and entered through the cover
of lustre produced by the अस्त्र; since they
had no weapons, the अस्त्र did not affect them
(and also because of the effect of the Vāru-
ṇāstra and the prowess of Kṛṣṇa and Arjuna);
Bhīma was forced down by Nara (Arjuna)
and Nārāyaṇa (Kṛṣṇa) from his chariot and
forced to give up weapons; the Nārāyaṇāstra
was then pacified; the quarters became clear
and gentle winds blew; the birds and the
animals felt assured 7. 171. 1, 3, 6, 10-14,
20-22; if Vāsudeva had not shown the way
to combat the Nārāyaṇāstra it would have
meant death for the enemy (of the Kauravas)
7. 171. 28; but the missile was rendered in-
effective and the Pāṇḍavas freed from it 7.
171. 33; 8. 1. 42.
E. The means to pacify
the Nārāyaṇāstra: When released, the missile
must kill the enemy and only then it would
subside; the other ways of pacifying it were to
run away from it, to lay down the arms, to
beg for life, and ask refuge (वधः संख्ये
द्रवश् चैव शस्त्राणां च विसर्जनम्।
प्रयाचनं च शत्रूणां गमनं शर-
णस्य च॥एते प्रशमने योगा महास्त्रस्य
परन्तप) 7. 166. 48-49.
F. Status:
The Pāśupatāstra of Śiva rated superior to
the Nārāyaṇāstra 13. 14. 127.

निवृत्त
Nivṛtta nt.: One of the twenty-one
movements (सो ऽचरद् विविधान् मार्गान्) used
while fighting with a sword and a shield.
Dhṛṣṭadyumna used it when he, with a
sword and a shield in hand, wanted to attack
Droṇa who was shooting arrows at him 7.
164. 145-148.

पद्म
Padma m.: Name of a particular
arrangement of the army (व्यूह).
It was arranged by Droṇa in the in-
terior of, and in the rear portion of, the
principal व्यूह called Cakraśakaṭa; Padma
was considered extremely impenetrable (पश्च्-
आर्धे तस्य पद्मस् तु गर्भव्यूहः
सुदुर्भिदः) 7. 63. 23; in addition, inside
the Padma was arranged a concealed
(गूढ) व्यूह called Sūcī. [See Cakra-
śakaṭa].

परशु
Paraśu m.: An axe (not named) used
as a weapon by Rāma Jāmadagnya.
Described as having a sharp and shining
edge (तीक्ष्णधार 13. 14. 137, दीप्तधार
13. 14. 139), of extremely fearful front
(सुरौद्रास्य 13. 14. 139), it shines like
a burning flame of fire (दीप्तवह्निशिखो-
पम 13. 14. 139); since it belongs to
Śiva, it is circled by the neck of the ser-
pent (सर्पकण्ठाग्रवेष्टित) 13. 14. 139;
it was given by Śiva to Rāma Jāmadagnya
when he was satisfied with Rāma 13. 14.
137; Rāma used it to cut off the head of
his mother Reṇukā at the instance of his
father Jamadagni 3. 116. 14; Rāma used it
also to kill in battle the universal ruler
Kārtavīrya 13. 14. 137; he used this weapon
(शस्त्र) to kill the sons of Kārtavīrya and
the Kṣatriyas who were his followers 3. 117.
7-8; Rāma exterminated the Kṣatriyas from
this earth twenty-one times using this axe
13. 14. 138; (3. 117. 9).

परानीकभिद्
Parānīkabhid m.: Name (?) of a
particular arrangement of the army (व्यूह).
The Pāṇḍava army was arranged this
way on the seventeenth day of the battle; it
is described as ‘having no parallel’ (अप्र-
तिम) 8. 31. 1; it was arranged by Arjuna
8. 32. 3; apparently Dhṛṣṭadyumna, guarded
on two sides by the sons of Draupadī, stood
at its head 8. 32. 4, 6; but at the start of
the war Arjuna rushed to the front 8. 31.
36; 8. 32. 7; it was used against the
Kaurava army which was arranged accord-
ing to the Bārhaspatya vyūha 8. 31. 26.

परिघ
Parigha m.: A club (not named)
mentioned as a weapon of Aryaman.
He roamed around with it when he got
ready to help Indra in his fight with Kṛṣṇa
and Arjuna at the time of the burning of the
Khāṇḍava forest 1. 218. 34.

परिवृत्त
Parivṛtta nt.: One of the twenty-one
movements (सो ऽचरद् विविधान् मार्गान्
प्रकारान् एकविंशतिम्) used while fighting
with a sword and a shield.
Dhṛṣṭadyumna used it when he, with a
sword and a shield in hand, wanted to attack
Droṇa who was shooting arrows at him 7.
164. 145-148.

पर्जन्यास्त्र
Parjanyāstra, Pārjaynāstra nt.: Name
of a missile used to produce clouds or water.
Arjuna created clouds by releasing it
(पार्जन्येनासृजद् घनान्) when he display-
ed his skill in the use of missiles to all those
assembled in the arena 1. 125. 19; Arjuna
employed it by reciting मन्त्रस् on the
shining arrow with which he pierced the
earth to produce jets of water for Bhīṣma
(संधाय च शरं दीप्तम् अभिमन्त्र्य
महायशाः।पर्जन्यास्त्रेण संयोज्य …
अविध्यत् पृथिवीं पार्थः) 6. 116. 22-23.
[Parjanyāstra apparently different from
Vāruṇāstra for which see below].

पर्वत
Parvata m.: Mountain (not named),
used as a weapon by Tvaṣṭṛ.
Tvaṣṭṛ held it when he got ready to help
Indra in his fight with Kṛṣṇa and Arjuna at
the time of burning the Khāṇḍava forest 1.
218. 33; a heavenly weapon (not named)
of Tvaṣṭṛ, known to Arjuna and Kṛṣṇa,
is referred to by Bhīṣma 6. 116. 38-39.
[Identical with Pārvata ?]

पाञ्चजन्य
Pāñcajanya m.: Name of the conch of
Kṛṣṇa.
A. Origin: Ocean (समुद्र 1. 19. 3)
said to be the origin of Pāñcajanya (पाञ्च-
जन्यस्य जननम्) 1. 19. 10.
B. History:
It belonged to the demon (?) Pañcajana
residing in Pātāla; after conquering Varuṇa
in the waters of the ocean, Kṛṣṇa killed
Pañcajana and obtained the conch from him
7. 10. 19-20.
C. Description: water-born
(जलज) 3. 15. 20; 3. 21. 30; (अम्बुज) 7. 78.
35; (सलिलज) 7. 102. 59; heavenly (दिव्य)
5. 47. 58; 6. 1. 17; 6. 23. 14; 7. 10. 20; king
of conches or excellent among conches
(शङ्खराज्) 7. 85. 36, 38; 7. 102. 59;
(शङ्खवर) 6. 47. 24; 8. 68. 56; (शङ्ख-
प्रवर) 3. 21. 12; 7. 64. 20; (सर्व-
शङ्खवर) 7. 79. 11; white in colour
(हिमावदात) 8. 68. 56; (गोक्षीर-
कुन्देन्दुमृणालरजतप्रभ) 3. 21. 30;
adorned with gold and jewels (हेमरत्न-
परिष्कृत) 6. 47. 24, and covered with golden
net (सुवर्णजालावतत) 8. 68. 56; produc-
ing loud sound (सुघोष) 8. 68. 55; (महा-
स्वन) 8. 68. 56.
D. Sound: Its sound
(नाद, निर्घोष, रव, निनद) was frightful
(भैरव) 7. 56. 36; (घोर) 7. 102. 57,
58; the sound (निर्घोष) was produced only
on the ऋषभ note (आर्षभेणैव पूरि-
तम्) 7. 56. 36 [Nī. आर्षभेण ऋष्भस्वर-
प्रकारेण on 7. 79. 39 Bom. Ed.]; Kṛṣṇa
filled it fully with breath while blowing it (3.
21. 30) and the sound caused the whole world,
including the पाताल, the heaven, and the guar-
dians of the quarters, to tremble 7. 51. 42;
Kṛṣṇa blew it forcefully to produce a shrill
note (पाञ्चजन्यं च बलवद् दध्मौ
तारेण केशवः) 7. 78. 37; the sound excelled
all other sounds and filled the heaven and
the earth 7. 79. 13; 7. 102. 59; 8. 37. 19; 8.
68. 57; it reverberated in forests, mountains,
rivers and directions 8. 68. 57; 6. 55. 102; it
produced sound like the one heard at the flash
of a lightning 5. 149. 65.
E. Effect of the
sound: The sound caused delight to warriors
on Kṛṣṇa's side 5. 149. 65; 6. 1. 17; but the
enemies felt dejected (5. 47. 59; 8. 37. 20),
and trembled; they lost courage, and the
draught-animals passed urine and dung 7.
64. 21-24; 6. 1. 18; 6. 67. 2; 7. 3. 19; 8.
68. 55; 9. 3. 19; hearing it enemies, strong
and weak, fell on the ground 7. 78. 38.
F. Uses: (1) In the epic war: (i) when
the Pāṇḍava warriors reached Kurukṣetra
they blew their respective conches and so did
Kṛṣṇa and Arjuna 5. 149. 64-65; (ii) when
the two armies were arrayed against each
other, ready to fight, Kṛṣṇa and Arjuna blew
their conches 6. 1. 17; 6. 23. 15; (iii) Kṛṣṇa
blew his Pāñcajanya at the start of the
second day's war 6. 47. 25 (and presumably
at the start of the war on all subsequent
days); (iv) when Arjuna vowed to fight
more seriously with Bhīṣma 6. 55. 102;
(v) when Arjuna rushed at Bhīṣma who was
fighting with other Pāṇḍavas 6. 67. 2;
(vi) Kṛṣṇa blew his conch when Arjuna
took the vow to kill Jayadratha 7. 51. 41;
(vii) at the start of the day on which Jaya-
dratha was killed 7. 64. 20; when Arjuna was
heading forward looking for Jayadratha in
the Kaurava army 7. 75. 31; as Arjuna was
nearing Jayadratha 7. 78. 37; 7. 79. 11; at
the end of the day when Jayadratha was killed
7. 123. 41; [It is significant that the sounding
of Pāñcajanya is mentioned on many occa-
sions on the day on which Arjuna had to
fulfil his difficult vow to kill Jayadratha];
(viii) Kṛṣṇa blew it when Arjuna got rid
of the Saṃśaptakas who had overwhelmed
both of them 8. 37. 19, 15-17; (ix) at the
death of Karṇa and the subsequent rout of
the Kaurava army 8. 68. 57; (x) at the fall
of Duryodhana 9. 60. 65; (2) Outside the
epic war: Kṛṣṇa blew it to challenge Śālva
when he reached Śālva's Saubhapura 3. 15.
20; when Kṛṣṇa started fighting with Śālva
3. 21. 12; when, during his fight with Śālva,
Kṛṣṇa killed many Dānavas 3. 21. 29-30;
G. Its use as a signal: (1) Kṛṣṇa had told
Dāruka, his charioteer, that when he heard
the sound of Pāñcajanya he was to rush to
the battle-field driving Kṛṣṇa's chariot for its
eventual use by Kṛṣṇa to enable Arjuna to
fulfil his vow to kill Jayadratha 7. 56. 36;
(2) The sound was once interpreted by
Droṇa to mean that Arjuna wanted to set
aside other heroes and attack Bhīṣma 6. 108.
14; (3) It was once interpreted by
Yudhiṣṭhira to mean that Arjuna was in
danger 7. 85. 35; on another occasion, the
sound meant for Yudhiṣṭhira the death of
Arjuna, and hence Kṛṣṇa's starting to fight
7. 102. 32-33.
H. End: When the time
of the destruction of the Vṛṣṇis and the
Andhakas arrived the blowing of Pāñca-
janya in their houses was accompanied by
the harsh braying of the asses 16. 3. 15
[नदन्तं पाञ्चजन्यं च वृष्ण्यन्धक-
निवेशने।समन्तात् प्रत्यवाश्यन्त रासभा
दारुणस्वराः॥ Does Pāñcajanya here refer
not to Kṛṣṇa's special conch, but to the conches
in general in the houses of the Vṛṣṇis and
the Andhakas ?].

पारमेष्ठ्य
Pārameṣṭhya (astra) nt.: Name of a
missile of Prajāpati.
According to Bhīṣma it was known to
Arjuna and perhaps to Kṛṣṇa 6. 116. 38-39.
[See Brahmāstra]

पार्जन्य
Pārjanya (astra) nt.: Name of a
missile 1. 125. 19 [See Parjanyāstra]

पार्वत
Pārvata (astra) nt.: Name of a missile.
When Arjuna displayed his skill in the
use of missiles, he released mountains by the
employment of the Pārvata astra (पार्व-
तेनासृजद् गिरीन्) 1. 125. 20. [See Parvata]

पाश
Pāśa m. (pl.): Noose used as a missile
(पाश generally used in pl., but also rarely
in sg. 1. 218. 31).
A. Association with Varuṇa: Listed as
a missile of Ambupa (Varuṇa) 8. 66. 15;
hence called वारुण अस्त्र 4. 56. 14; Varuṇa
has epithets like पाशभृत् 6. 46. 7; 6. 103.
17; पाशवन्त् 7. 64. 15; पाशिन् 8. 29. 28.
B. Description: Described as heavenly
(दिव्य) 3. 42. 31; 3. 89. 12; 12. 5. 13-14;
fierce (घोर) 3. 190. 60; 7. 53. 43; irresi-
stible (अनिवारण) 3. 42. 27.
C. Use
made by Varuṇa: (1) In battles: Varuṇa
bound thousands of Daityas with them in the
fight with Tārakāsura 3. 42. 28; during
Varuṇa's fight with the demons, Bali, son of
Virocana, was bound by the पाशस् 12. 220.
18; Bali would be free from these पाशस् at
the turn of time (मोक्षयन्ते वारुणाः
पाशास् तवेमे कालपर्ययात्) 12. 220. 110;
at a time only one पाश of Bali will be
released (एकैकस् ते तदा पाशः क्रमशः
प्रतिमोक्ष्यते) 12. 220. 114; Varuṇa equi-
pped himself with पाश (sg.) when he got
ready to help Indra in his fight with Kṛṣṇa
and Arjuna at the Khāṇḍava forest 1. 218. 31;
(2) To punish the sinners: Varuṇa has
one thousand पाशस् with which he binds a
liar; when the liar is to be released he is
freed of one पाश at the end of each year 2.
61. 67-68; sinners in general bound by the
पाशस् of Varuṇa 12. 96. 20; 3. 190. 60; one
who does not give what he has promised to
give, or one who takes back what has been
given, is bound by the पाशस् of Varuṇa 13.
61. 72; every one is afraid at the sight of
Varuṇa's पाशस् 12. 220. 89; Varuṇa binding
with पाशस् referred to as संयम (?)
(वारुणे चैव संयमे) 2. 69. 16 (Nī.
संयमे वशीकरणे on Bom. Ed. 2. 78. 19].
D. Pāśas obtained by Arjuna: Arjuna
received from Varuṇa the पाशस् along with
the secret of withdrawing them (प्रतिगृह्-
णीष्व कौन्तेय सरहस्यनिवर्तनान्); if
Arjuna used them on his stretched bow, even
Antaka could not get rid of them; with their
use Arjuna could destroy every Kṣatriya on
the earth 3. 42. 27, 29, 30; Arjuna's receiv-
ing the अस्त्र of Varuṇa, without naming it,
referred to 3. 89. 12; 3. 164. 29; 4. 56. 14;
7. 53. 43; 12. 5. 13-14. [See Vāruṇa1,
Vāruṇa2]

पाशुपत
Pāśupata nt., (m.): Name of the
missile of Śiva 7. 57. 16.
A. Description: Heavenly (दिव्य) 3.
41. 7; 3. 163. 51; 7. 41. 7; 7. 57. 62; 13.
14. 124; large, of huge shape (महत्) 3.
41. 13; 13. 14. 124; (महाकाय) 13. 14. 125;
(महास्त्र) 1. 1. 109; 8. 57. 44; (पर-
मास्त्र) 7. 57. 16; fierce (घोर) 3.
41. 7, 22; 5. 47. 100; 7. 57. 79; (सुघोर)
8. 57. 44; (महाघोर) 13. 14. 124;
(रौद्र) 3. 163. 48; eternal (सनातन)
3. 163. 49; burning (जाज्वलत्) 3. 41. 22;
(सस्फुलिङ्गं … विसृजन्तम् (mas.) इवान-
लम्) 13. 14. 125; (उद्गिरन्तम् (mas.)
इवानलम्) 13. 14. 126; itself irresistible
(अप्रतिहत) 3. 163. 51; (दूरासद) 3. 163.
52, but resisting all other missiles (सर्वा-
स्त्रप्रतिषेधन) 3. 163. 51; (सर्वशस्त्र-
विघातन) 13. 14. 127; unsurpassed, in-
describable (अद्वितीयम् अनिर्देश्यम्) 13. 14.
125; frightful to all beings (सर्वभूत-
भयावह) 13. 14. 125; difficult to be
endured even by gods, Dānavas, and Rākṣasas
(दुष्प्रसहं सुरदानवराक्षसैः) 3. 163.
52; destroying the enemies and their armies
(उत्सादनम् अमित्राणां परसेनानिकर्त-
नम्) 3. 163. 52; capable of destroying the
three worlds (त्रैलोक्यसंहारकर) 8. 57.
44; described as having a terrible bodily form
—having one foot, large teeth, a thousand
heads and bellies, and a thousand arms,
tongues, and eyes—(एकपादं महादं-
ष्ट्रं सहस्रशिरसोदरम्।सहस्रभुज-
जिह्वाक्षम्) 13. 14. 126.
B. Use by Śiva:
(1) Śiva killed with it all Daityas in the battle
7. 57. 16; (all the enemies of gods) 7. 57. 65;
(2) Śiva charged his arrow with the Pāśupata
missile and shot it to burn the त्रिपुरस् of the
three sons of Tāraka Asura 8. 24. 115, 120;
(8. 24. 4, 10-12); 13. 14. 128.
C. Śiva
gave it to (1) Arjuna: Two accounts:
(i) Arjuna desired to have Śiva's Pāśupata
missile so that he could burn the Dānavas,
the Rākṣasas, the Bhūtas, the Piśācas, the
Gandharvas and the mythical serpents
(पन्नगस्) in battle; he could then be a
match for Bhīṣma, Droṇa, Kṛpa, and Karṇa
3. 41. 7, 9, 11; Arjuna called it Brahma-
śiras which was terrific and of fierce power
(यत् तद् ब्रह्मशिरो नाम रौद्रं भीम-
पराक्रमम्) 3. 41. 8; Śiva ready to give
Pāśupata, his dear weapon (दयितम् अस्त्रम्),
to Arjuna as he was capable of possessing
(धारण), releasing (मोक्ष), and with-
drawing (संहार) it 3. 41. 13; to receive
it, Arjuna purified himself and remained fully
attentive (शुचिर् भूत्वा समाहितः); he
folded his hands and said to Śiva ‘recite (the
mantra)’ (अधीष्व); Śiva then taught it
to Arjuna together with its secrets and mode
of withdrawal (सरहस्यनिवर्तनम्) 3. 41.
17-18; the missile, like the God of Death in
bodily form, then waited on Arjuna; at that
time the earth trembled and there was a loud
sound of conches, drums and भेरिस् by thou-
sands; the gods and demons saw the missile
in bodily form standing near Arjuna 3. 41.
17-22; 1. 1. 109; 3. 163. 48, 51; 6. 116. 38;
8. 57. 44; (ii) During the night, after Arjuna
took the vow to kill Jayadratha the next
day before sunset, Kṛṣṇa advised Arjuna to
acquire the knowledge of the great Pāśupata
missile from Śiva in order to be able to
accomplish his vow; Kṛṣṇa advised Arjuna
to mentally approach god Śiva; Arjuna
touched water (संस्पृश्याम्भः), sat down
on the ground, and mentally went to Bhava
(Śiva) 7. 57. 17-19; Arjuna praised Śiva and
made him favourable to give the missile 7.
57. 59; Śiva told Arjuna and Kṛṣṇa that
nearby there was a lake of nectar where he
had left his divine bow and arrow; he asked
them to get his bow and arrow 7. 57. 64-
65; when they brought the bow and arrow,
a Brahmacārin came from the side of Śiva; he
held the bow and, putting the arrow on it,
drew it according the prescriptions (व्यकर्षच्
चापि विधिवत् सशरं धनुर् उत्तमम् 7.
57. 75); having seen how the Brahmacārin
held the bow in his grip, how he drew the
string, and the posture adopted by him
(तस्य मौर्वीं च मुष्टिं च स्थानं
चालक्ष्य पाण्डवः 7. 57. 76), and having
heard the मन्त्र recited by Śiva, Arjuna
understood the way how to employ Pāśupata;
the arrow was shot by the Brahmacārin in
the lake and the bow was again placed in
it; Arjuna then remembered the boon Śiva
granted to him during his stay in the forest
(आरण्यक) and his meeting Śiva, and wished
that he might now receive the boon; knowing
Ariuna's mind, Śiva gave him the boon, the
Pāśupata missile, and wished him success in
accomplishing his vow; Kṛṣṇa and Arjuna
bowed down to Śiva and, when permitted to
leave, delighted they returned to their camp,
7. 57. 73-81; (Śiva gave missile to Arjuna
7. 173. 100); (2) Besides Arjuna, Kṛṣṇa
knew the use of Pāśupata 7. 57. 79; 8.
57. 44; Bhīṣma is not so sure about Kṛṣṇa's
knowledge of the Pāśupata 6. 116. 39.
D. Effects: The missile, when released,
produced thousands of tridents (शूलस्),
fierce maces (गदाश् चोग्रप्रदर्शनाः),
and charmed arrows having the form of
serpents (शराश् चाशीविषाकाराः संभवन्त्य्
अनुमन्त्रिताः) 3. 41. 10.
E. Restrictions
on its use: Arjuna was specifically told by
Śiva that the missile was never to be used
against men (न प्रयोज्यं भवेद् एतन्
मानुषेषु कथंचन); Arjuna was to
use the missile only if he was under
severe pressure (पीड्यमानेन बलवत्),
or if he wished to ward off the missiles
used by his opponents (अस्त्राणां प्रति-
घाते च सर्वथैव प्रयोजयेः) 3. 163.
49-50; 3. 41. 15; if used against ordinary
persons it would burn the entire world
3. 41. 15.
F. Use in the epic war:
(1) Arjuna in his message to the Kauravas,
sent through Saṃjaya, threatened that he
would use the Pāśupata missile against them in
the war 5. 47. 100; Kṛṣṇa told Karṇa that in
the ‘sacrifice to be performed with the wea-
pons’ (शस्त्रयज्ञ 5. 139. 29), the मन्त्रस्
recited by Arjuna while releasing the Pāśupata
and other missiles would serve as the मन्त्रस्
used while performing a sacrifice 5. 139. 31;
(2) Droṇa used Pāśupata against Arjuna
and it was repelled (जघान) by Arjuna
presumably by using the same missile 7.
163. 28; (3) Karṇa used it against Yudhi-
ṣṭhira and hence Kṛṣṇa apprehended Yudhi-
ṣṭhira's death in the war 8. 43. 21, 18.
G. Status: The Pāśupata missile surpassed
all other missiles like Brāhma, Nārāyaṇa,
Aindra, Āgneya, and Vāruṇa; it could
destroy all weapons (सर्वशस्त्रविघातन)
13. 14. 127; even gods like Indra, Yama,
Kubera, Varuṇa, and Vāyu did not know it
3. 41. 14; there was none who could not be
killed by it; besides its use on an arrow,
it could be released even by mind, eye, and
speech (मनसा चक्षुषा वाचा धनुषा च
निपात्यते) 3. 41. 16.

पिनाक
Pināka1 nt.: Name of the bow of Śiva
(of Rudra, who killed cattle with it 6. 58.
58; 6. 59. 16; 10. 3. 29).
A. Association with Śiva: Śiva told
Umā that he held Pināka to accomplish the
objectives of the gods 13. 127. 48; 13. 128.
7; Upamanyu saw Śiva with his Pināka bow
13. 14. 122; considered as a special weapon
of Hara (Śiva) 8. 66. 15; hence Śiva is
called पिनाकिन् 1. 28. 20; 3. 39. 25; 3. 40. 31;
3. 42. 1, 3; 3. 104. 11; 3. 221. 18; 5. 168. 5;
6. 58. 52; 7. 69. 56; 7. 172. 59; 7. 173. 33;
8. 49. 93; 9. 43. 33; 12. 149. 110; 12. 278. 27;
13. 15. 11; पिनाकधृक् 3. 40. 27; 3. 93. 12;
3. 163. 5, 42; 4. 21. 59; 6. 58. 52; 7. 172.
73; 7. 173. 99; 12. 274. 31, 48; 13. 17. 72,
133; 13. 127. 50; 13. 132. 27; 13. 145. 10;
14. 77. 44; पिनाकपाणि 3. 40. 1; 8. 24. 102;
10. 3. 29 (Rudra); 13. 14. 151; 13. 128. 20;
पिनाकहस्त 12. 320. 31.
B. Origin: Śiva
wanted to tame sage Uśanas, a Bhārgava-
relative (भार्गवदायादो मुनिः 12. 278. 7)
because Uśanas had taken away the riches
of Kubera; so Śiva, with शूल in hand, went
to Uśanas; Uśanas using his Yogic powers
appeared on the tip of the शूल; Śiva then
bent the शूल to get Uśanas into his hand; the
शूल, bent by the hand (पाणि), was called by
Śiva ‘पिनाक’ (आनतेनाथ शूलेन पाणिना-
मिततेजसा।पिनाकम् इति चोवाच शूलम्
उग्रायुधः प्रभुः 12. 278. 18-19; Nīla.
uses this description to suggest a fanciful
etymology of पिनाक: शूलम् एव पिनाक-
पदेन उवाच।यतः पाणिना अनामयत्
अतः पिनाकम्।तेन आद्यपदस्याद्यन्त-
वर्णाभ्यां द्वितीयस्य मध्यमाभ्यां
कप्रत्यययुक्ताभ्यां पिनाकपदम् निष्प-
न्नम् इति योगप्रदर्शनं कृतम् Bom. Ed.
12. 289. 18).
C. Description: Illustrious
(श्रीमत्) 3. 40. 3 (not named); its splendour
like that of a thousand lightnings (इन्द्रा-
युधसहस्राभ 13. 14. 122).
D. Com-
parisons: (1) Bhīma's गदा compared with
Pināka (of Rudra) 6. 58. 58; 6. 59. 16;
or Bhīma with his गदा compared with
Pinākin (Śiva) holding his Pināka 6. 58.
52; (2) Arjuna's Añjalika arrow with which
he killed Karṇa compared with Pināka (i. e.
the arrow shot from Pināka) 8. 67. 18;
(3) The arrow of Karṇa with which he
removed the किरीट of Arjuna supposed to
have achieved something not possible for
Hara's (Śiva's) Pināka (i. e. for the arrow
shot from Pināka) 8. 66. 15. [See Pināka2]

पिनाक
Pināka2 m. (pl.): A kind of weapon
(a शूल with a bend and hence looking like
the staff of a strung bow ?)
Ghaṭotkaca and Alāyudha fought each
other using various weapons including Pinākas
(ततो नानाप्रहरणैर् अन्योन्यम् अभिवर्ष-
ताम्।आयसैः परिघैः … पिनाकैः … )
7. 153. 21-22; the Rākṣasas of Ghaṭotkaca
struck down the Kaurava warriors with
various weapons including Pinākas ( …
वज्रैः पिनाकैर् अशनिप्रहारैः) 7. 154.
36. [See Pināka1]

पैतामह
Paitāmaha adj.: of the missile of
Pitāmaha.
Arjuna was to learn it along with the
other divine missiles at the residence of Indra
in the heaven 3. 164. 30. [See Brahmāstra]

पैशाच
Paiśāca adj. (pl.): of व्यूह (arrange-
ment of the army) known to the Piśācas.
Every day Bhīṣma arranged the army
of the Kauravas in different व्यूहस्, some of
those being the Paiśācas (दिवसे दिवसे
प्राप्ते भीष्मः शान्तनवो युधि।आसुरान्
अकरोद् व्यूहान् पैशाचान् अथ राक्षसान्)
6. 104. 16.

पौण्ड्र
Pauṇḍra m.: Name of the conch of
Bhīmasena.
Large in size (महाशङ्ख), Bhīma
blew it at the start of the battle on the first
day 6. 23. 15; he blew it on the second day
6. 47. 25; (and presumably on every subse-
quent day, as also on many other occasions
during the war although not specifically
named each time).

पौरन्दर
Paurandara adj.: of the missile of
Purandara (Indra).
Arjuna told Karṇa that he was well-
versed in the use of this missile due to his
teacher's instruction (निष्ठितो गुरुशासनात्)
1. 181. 20.

प्रज्ञास्त्र
Prajñāstra nt.: Name of a missile.
Droṇa used Prajñāstra to bring the sons
of Dhṛtarāṣṭra back to consciousness (अथ
प्रत्यागतप्राणास् तव पुत्रा महारथाः 6.
73. 50), who had become unconscious due
to the Pramohanāstra of Dhṛṣṭadyumna 6.
73. 42-43, 47, 49; Vibhīṣaṇa brought Rāma
and Lakṣmaṇa to consciousness (बोधयाम्
आस तौ वीरौ; प्रबोधितौ; तौ लब्ध-
संज्ञौ) who were bound by the arrows
of Indrajit and who had apparently lost
consciousness 3. 273. 5, 7; (both Droṇa
and Vibhīṣaṇa recited only the मन्त्रस्
of Prajñāstra without using them on the
arrow ?).

प्रमोहनास्त्र
Pramohanāstra, Mohanāstra nt.:
Name of a missile.
Used by Dhṛṣṭadyumna to kill (जिघां-
सुः) the sons of Dhṛtarāṣṭra who showered
arrows on him; Dhṛṣṭadyumna employed
Pramohanāstra on them due to which they
lost consciousness 6. 73. 42, 43, 47; Droṇa
removed the effect of the missile (Moha-
nāstra) by using Prajñāstra 6. 73. 49.

प्रसृत
Prasṛta nt.: One of the twenty-one
movements (सो ऽचरद् विविधान् मार्गान्
प्रकारान् एकविंशतिम्) used while fighting
with a sword and a shield.
Dhṛṣṭadyumna used it when he, with a
sword and a shield in his hand, wanted to
attack Droṇa who shot arrows at him 7.
164. 145-148.

प्रस्वाप
Prasvāpa nt.: Name of a missile which
sent the adversary to sleep.
It was fashioned by Viśvakarman
(विश्वकृतम्) and it belonged properly to
Prajāpati (प्राजापत्यम्) 5. 184. 12; des-
cribed as ‘dear’ (सुदयित, दयित) 5. 184.
11; 5. 184. 15; 5. 185. 23; it was known
to Bhīṣma in his former life (पूर्वस्मिन्
देहधारणे); in his long-drawn fight with
Rāma Jāmadagnya, when Bhīṣma was deject-
ed, the eight Vipras (Vasus) reminded him
of this missile in a dream and told him
that it would flash upon him again (इदम्
अस्त्रम् सुदयितम् प्रत्यभिज्ञास्यते भ-
वान्); the missile was not known to Rāma
Jāmadagnya, and to no one else on the
earth; the Vipras advised Bhīṣma to employ
it forcefully (भृशं संयोजयस्व 5. 184.
13) against Rāma Jāmadagnya; as a result
Rāma would not die but just go to sleep;
in its use against his teacher Rāma, Bhīṣma
would incur no sin; Bhīṣma will have
thus defeated Rāma with Prasvāpāstra (to
be awakened by him later by using Saṃbo-
dhanāstra); since Rāma could not be killed
in battle, he was to be defeated by using
Prasvāpāstra; the Vipras told Bhīṣma that
a hero sent to sleep in battle and the
one killed were considered by them equal
(प्रसुप्तं वा मृतं वापि तुल्यं मन्या-
महे वयम् 5. 184. 16) 5. 184. 9-17; the
next day when Bhīṣma thought of the missile
for employing it, it flashed in his mind
(चिन्तितं च तद् अस्त्रं मे मनसि प्रत्य-
भात् तदा) 5. 185. 22-23; the gods, appear-
ing in the heaven, however, forbade Bhīṣma
from using Prasvāpa against Rāma; as
Bhīṣma put the arrow on his bow, Nārada
drew Bhīṣma's attention to what the gods
asked him and he told Bhīṣma not to insult
Rāma who was his teacher; the eight Vipras
also asked Bhīṣma to do what Nārada told
him, since therein lay the welfare of the worlds
(एतद् धि परमं श्रेयो लोकानाम्); hence
Bhīṣma withdrew the missile; when Rāma
saw Bhīṣma withdrawing the missile he
accepted defeat at the hands of Bhīṣma
(दृष्ट्वा तद् अस्त्रं विनिवर्तितं वै।जितो
ऽस्मि भीष्मेण सुमन्दबुद्धिर् इत्य् एव
वाक्यं सहसा व्यमुञ्चत्) 5. 186. 1-8.
[See Prājāpatya1 from which Prasvāpa is
different]

प्राजापत्य
prājāpatya1 nt.: A missile of Prajāpati.
(1) It was used by Bhīṣma and Arjuna
against each other during the cattle-raid
4. 59. 21; (2) Employed by Droṇa, along
with Aindra, against Yudhiṣṭhira to kill him
(जिघांसुः); both missiles were repelled by
Yudhiṣṭhira with Māhendrāstra 7. 132. 31-32.
[See Prasvāpa which, although प्राजापत्य,
is different from this missile].

प्राजापत्य
Prājāpatya2 adj.: of the missile Pras-
vāpa belonging to Prajāpati 5. 184. 12.
[Different from Prājāpatya missile. See
Prasvāpa and Prājāpatya1]

बार्हस्पत्य
Bārhaspatya m.: A particular arrange-
ment of the army (व्यूह) originating with
Bṛhaspati.
Described as chief of the व्यूहस्
(व्यूहराज) 8. 31. 25, great व्यूह (महा-
व्यूह) that caused fear to the enemies
8. 31. 26, 29; it consisted of ‘wings’
(पक्ष) and ‘extensions or extremities of
wings’ (प्रपक्ष) 8. 31. 6, 29; it was
used by Karṇa on the seventeenth day of
the war to attack the Parānīkabhid Vyūha
of the Pāṇḍavas 8. 31. 5, 1; its ‘right wing’
(दक्षिण पक्ष) was constituted by Kṛpa, the
Magadha warriors (मगधश् च (?) 8. 31.
11, v. l. मागधास् च), and Kṛtavarman;
the wing was further extended (प्रपक्ष)
by stationing there Śakuni and Ulūka, who
were guarded by horsemen from Gandhāra
country (सादिभिः … गान्धारिभिः 8. 31. 12-
13) and invincible warriors from highlands
(पार्वतीयैश् च दुर्जयैः 8. 31. 13); on the
‘left side’ (वाम पार्श्व) stood the Saṃ-
śaptakas with thirty-four thousand chariot-
fighters, who would not leave the battle,
together with the sons of Dhṛtarāṣṭra; the
left wing was further extended (प्रपक्ष)
by ordering the Kāmbojas, the Śakas and
the Yavanas to be there; they were there
with chariots and horse-men, and foot-soldiers;
in the middle of the front of the army stood
Karṇa himself to guard it; he was offered
protection by his sons; he looked suitable as
the leader of the व्यूह; the rear (पृष्ठतः)
of the army was taken care of by Duḥ-
śāsana, seated on a huge elephant (महा-
द्विपस्कन्धगतः 8. 31. 19) and surrounded
by different armies; he was followed by
Duryodhana with his brothers on horse-backs,
and the Madras and the Kekayas to protect
him; Aśvatthāman, the Kuru heroes, and
elephants mounted by the Mlecchas were
behind the army of the chariot-fighters (अन्व-
युस् तद् रथानीकम्); they were assisted
by horse-men (सादिभिश् चास्थिताः); many
thousands of brave warriors, who would not
show their backs, armed with पट्टिश and
swords, acted as foot-guards of elephants and
of foot-soldiers (?) (तेषां पदातिनागानां
पादरक्षाः सहस्रशः 8. 31. 24); the
Bārhaspatya vyūha shone like the army of
the gods or of the Asuras 8. 31. 11-25.

बाहुकण्टक
Bāhukaṇṭaka nt.: Name of a particular
manœuvre employed in a wrestling match.
Karṇa employed it to split the joint in
Jarāsandha's body while wrestling with him
(but did not kill him) (बाहुभिः समसञ्-
जेताम् उभाव् अपि बलान्वितौ॥बाहुकण्टक-
युद्धेन तस्य कर्णो ऽथ युध्यतः
बिभेद सन्धिं देहस्य) 12. 5. 3-4 [बाहु-
कण्टकं (बहु-कण्टकं ?) केतकपत्रम्
तद्वद् यत्र बलिना दुर्बलस्य शरीरं
पाट्यते तद् बाहुकण्टकं नाम युद्धम्
Nī. on 12. 5. 4 (Bom. Ed.)].

बिभीषिका
Bibhīṣikā f.: A kind of माया used by
the Gandharvas to frighten men.
Arjuna told the Gandharva Aṅgāraparṇa
that the Bibhīṣikā employed by him had no
effect on those who knew the use of the
अस्त्रस्; if employed, it vanished like foam
(अस्त्रज्ञेषु प्रयुक्तैषा फेनवत् प्रविली-
यते) 1. 158. 24.

ब्रह्मदण्ड
Brahmadaṇḍa m.: A weapon of Brah-
man (Nī., however, ब्रह्मदण्ड आभिचारि-
कविद्या on 2. 5. 122, Bom. Ed.).
Described as ‘very fierce’ (महाघोर),
‘having lustre like the fire on the Doom's
Day’ (कालाग्निसमतेजस्) 1. 49. 24; Nārada
asked Yudhiṣṭhira whether he knew the use
of the Brahmadaṇḍa 2. 5. 111; one of the
weapons placed by Śiva on his chariot when it
was made ready for the fight with the Tripuras
(other weapons placed on the chariot being
Kāladaṇḍa, Rudradaṇḍa) 8. 24. 79; Brahma-
daṇḍa used for various comparisons: (1) the
शक्ति hurled by Yudhiṣṭhira at Śalya and
which killed him was said to be ‘unfailing’
(अमोघा) like the Brahmadaṇḍa 9. 16. 42;
(2) the arrows of Arjuna which struck
Bhīṣma (6. 114. 57) had the touch of Brahma-
daṇḍa (ब्रह्मदण्डसमस्पर्शाः); and the
arrows with which Droṇa fought with Dhṛṣṭa-
dyumna had the lustre of Brahmadaṇḍa
(शरांश् च ब्रह्मदण्डाभान्) 7. 164. 122;
the arrows of Rāma that killed Rāvaṇa
looked like a raised Brahmadaṇḍa 3. 274. 27;
(3) the गदा of Bhīma compared with a
raised Brahmadaṇḍa 5. 50. 8; (4) Rāvaṇa
hurled a शूल at Rāma which looked like a
raised Brahmadaṇḍa 3. 274. 19; (5) Garuḍa,
flying in the sky, appeared to Kaśyapa, his
father, like a raised Brahmadaṇḍa 1. 26. 7;
(6) enraged Sudhanvan, the son of Aṅgiras,
looked like the burning Brahmadaṇḍa 2. 61.
62; (7) the fear of the sacrificial fire which
the snake Vāsuki entertained due to his
mother's curse compared with Brahmadaṇḍa
1. 49. 22-24; (1. 52. 22 ?); [Brahmadaṇḍa
also means ‘punishment inflicted by the curse
of a Brāhmaṇa’ 1. 2. 220; 16. 4. 38].

ब्रह्मशिरस्
Brahmaśiras1 nt.: Name of a missile
(once called ब्रह्मास्त्र 10. 15. 21).
A. History: Supposed to have arisen
from Brahman's lustre (ब्रह्मतेजोभव
10. 15. 7); Droṇa, after practising severe
austerities, received the missile Brahmaśiras
from Agastya 10. 12. 14; later it was taught
by Droṇa to Arjuna when he was satisfied
(प्रितिमान्, प्रीयमाणः) with him (Arjuna)
1. 123. 72; 10. 12. 5 and, not with great delight
(नातिहृष्टमनाः), to Aśvatthāman whom he
had apparently first refused to teach 10. 12. 6.
B. Description: powerful missile (पर-
मास्त्र) 1. 123. 78; 10. 15. 3, 6; famous as
‘uncomparable’ in the worlds (असामान्यम्
इदं तात लोकेष्व् अस्त्रं निगद्यते) 1. 123.
76; divine (दिव्य) 10. 15. 16; outstanding
(विशिष्ट) 1. 123. 74; highly irresistible (अति-
दुर्धर) 1. 123. 74; fiery (महार्चिष्मत्)
10. 14. 7; difficult to obtain (दुरवाप) 10.
15. 9; worshipped by gods and Gandharvas
(देवगन्धर्वपूजित) 10. 12. 14; capable of
burning the whole earth (दहेद् यद् पृथिवीम्
अपि) 10. 12. 4.
C. Restrictions on its
use: (1) while giving the अस्त्र to Arjuna,
Droṇa told him not to use it against men, but
to use it only if he was attacked in a battle
by a superhuman enemy (अमानुषः शत्रुः);
if released against an enemy of lesser mettle
(अल्पतेजस्), the missile would burn the
world 1. 123. 75, 77; (2) while teaching it
to Aśvatthāman, who was known to be rash
by nature, Droṇa warned him not to use it
even under dire circumstances in battle, espe-
cially not against men (परमापद्गतेनापि
न स्म तात त्वया रणे।इदम् अस्त्रं
प्रयोक्तव्यं मानुषेषु विशेषतः) 10. 12.
7-8.
D. Taught by Droṇa only to Arjuna
and Aśvatthāman: (1) It was given to
Arjuna since Droṇa considered him to be dis-
tinguished among his pupils (विशिष्टं सर्व-
शिष्येभ्यः) 1. 123. 72; 10. 15. 21; when
taught to Arjuna, he would be an unrivalled
archer (भविता त्वत्समो नान्यः पुमाल्̃ लोके
धनुर्धरः) 1. 123. 78; Droṇa taught
to Arjuna, both its use and withdrawal
(सप्रयोगनिवर्तनम्) 1. 123. 74; its with-
drawal very difficult; once released, no one
except Arjuna, not even Indra, was capable of
withdrawing it 10. 15. 5, 6; it could not be with-
drawn by one who had not observed celibacy;
if a non-qualified person tried to withdraw
it, it would cut his head and destroy his
belongings 10. 15. 7-8; Arjuna could with-
draw it as he was truthful, brave, had prac-
tised celibacy, and was obedient to his teacher
10. 15. 10, 20, 24; although fully qualified
to withdraw it, Arjuna never used it in the
epic war nor outside it, even under stress
(ब्रह्मचारी व्रती चापि दुरवापम् अवाप्य
तत्।परमव्यसनार्तो ऽपि नार्जुनो ऽस्त्रं
व्यमुञ्चत) 10. 15. 9, (ब्रह्मास्त्रम् अप्य्
अवाप्यैतद् … क्षत्रधर्मान् महाबाहुर्
नाकम्पत धनंजयः) 10. 15. 21; (2)
Envious of Arjuna, Aśvatthāman asked his
father to teach him Brahmaśiras; Droṇa gave
it to him but not with a pleased mind (नाति-
हृष्टमना इव) 10. 12. 6; (since Aśvatthā-
man could not make use of it) he wanted to
exchange it with Kṛṣṇa for his (Sudarśana)
Cakra so that Aśvatthāman could be invin-
cible 10. 12. 15, 36; Kṛṣṇa offered to give
any one of his weapons to Aśvatthāman with-
out receiving from him in return his Brahma-
śiras 10. 12. 18-19; Aśvatthāman chose
the Cakra but failed even so much as to move
it from its place 10. 12. 20-23.
E. Use:
As Aśvatthāman was cruel and rash, there
was every danger of his using Brahmaśiras
against Bhīma, who was chasing him 10. 12.
40; when Aśvatthāman actually used it on an
इषीका, Kṛṣṇa advised Arjuna to release his
Brahmaśiras to counter it; Arjuna got down
from the chariot with bow and arrow in
hand, wished ‘well’ (स्वस्ति 10. 14. 5; 1. 1.
155) first to Aśvatthāman, then to himself
and to his brothers (the Pāṇḍavas); then
bowing down to deities and teachers, he
released Brahmaśiras, wishing welfare, and
saying ‘may the missile pacify (Aśvatthā-
man's) missile’ (उत्ससर्ज शिवं ध्यायन्न्
अस्त्रम् अस्त्रेण शाम्यताम्) 10. 14. 4-6; 10.
15. 2, 20; 1. 1. 155; at that time fire broke
out like the fire at the end of the aeon; the fire
of Arjuna's missile matched the fire of Aśvat-
thāman's missile; as a result terror struck the
creatures, skies were filled with great sound
and were engulfed in fire, earth, with its
mountains and trees, shook; the two missiles
produced heat with their lustre 10. 14. 7-11;
just then Nārada and Kṛṣṇa Dvaipāyana, de-
siring welfare for all the people, appeared and
stood between the two missiles; they pointed
out that Brahmaśiras was never used by any
one before against men 10. 14. 16; in response
to their appeal, Arjuna immediately with-
drew his Brahmaśiras; but Aśvatthāman could
not 10. 15. 1-15; moreover, if Brahmaśiras
was pacified by the other powerful missile
(परमास्त्र) there would be no rain in the
land for twelve years 10. 15. 23; Aśvatthā-
man then directed his missile towards the
foetus of the Pāṇḍavas 10. 15. 31, 32; 10.
16. 9. [See Iṣīkā, Brahmaśiras2, Brahmā-
stra]

ब्रह्मशिरस्
Brahmaśiras2 nt.: Name of the missile
of Śiva (Rudra) (identified with the fierce
(घोर), divine (दिव्य) Pāśupatāstra 3.
41. 7).
A. Origin: It arose from अमृत 3.
89. 11; Rudra acquired it with austerities
3. 89. 10.
B. Description: great (महत्)
and unrivalled (अप्रतिम) 3. 89. 10, fierce,
of terrible power (रौद्रं भीमपराक्र-
मम्) 3. 41. 8; 3. 89. 11; it destroys the
whole world at the time of the युगान्त 3.
41. 8.
C. Given to Arjuna: Arjuna
requested Śiva to give his Brahmaśiras
(Pāśupata); armed with it, Arjuna wanted
to burn in battle the Dānavas, the Rākṣasas,
the Bhūtas, the Piśācas, the Gandharvas,
and the Pannagas; using it Arjuna wanted
to fight with Bhīṣma, Droṇa. Kṛpa, and
Karṇa 3. 41. 8-11; Arjuna received it from
Rudra together with the मन्त्रस् to be
recited at the time of its employment, the
mode of withdrawing it, and the benediction
meant for expiation (if wrongly used) सम-
न्त्रं ससंहारं सप्रायश्चित्तमङ्गलम्
3. 89. 11 (however, Nī. प्रायश्चित्तम् अस्त्रा-
ग्निना निरपराधानां दाहे यो दोषस् तस्य
शोधनम्।मङ्गलं दग्धानाम् एवारा-
मादीनां पुनर्विकसनम्। on Bom. Ed.
3. 91. 12).
D. Effect: When employed,
thousands of शूलस्, गदास्, and serpent-like
‘charmed’ arrows came out of it (शराश्
चाशीविषाकाराः संभवन्त्य् अनुमन्त्रिताः)
3. 41. 10. [See Pāśupata, Brahmaśiras1]

ब्रह्मास्त्र
Brahmāstra, Brāhma astra, (Paitā-
 maha) nt. (rarely pl. 7. 165. 22; 8. 29. 26):
Name of a missile.
A. Relationship with god Brahman:
Destined by god Brahman for repulsing all
other missiles (सर्वास्त्रप्रतिघाताय विहितं
पद्मयोनिना) 7. 172. 32; when withdrawn
by Kṛṣṇa from the stillborn Parikṣit, the
flaming missile returned to Pitāmaha
(Brahman) 14. 69. 1, 3.
B. Gods and
heroes who knew its use: (1) Among the
gods, Indra knew it 5. 47. 100; (2) Among
men: (i) Droṇa: He received it from Rāma
Jāmadagnya; when Droṇa received it, he
became distinguished among men 1. 154. 13;
Droṇa not equalled by any one in the use
of Brahmāstra; Drupada attributed his defeat
at the hands of Droṇa to Droṇa's know-
ledge of Brahmāstra 1. 155. 22; Droṇa un-
equalled in battle by any one because of his
knowledge of Brahmāstra (and other missiles)
( … ब्रह्मास्त्रादीनि यान्य् अपि।तानि सर्वाणि
तिष्ठन्ति भवत्य् एव विशेषतः) 7. 160. 5;
known for his knowledge of Brahmāstra,
Droṇa knew its use and remedy (सप्रयोग-
चिकित्सितम्) 3. 38. 5; 4. 46. 7, 9; 7. 166.
2; (ii) Arjuna: He was taught (निष्ठित)
Brāhma astra by his teacher (Droṇa) 1.
181. 20; 6. 116. 38; in its use, he never
violated the rules of the Kṣatriyas (क्षत्र-
धर्मान् महाबाहुर् नाकम्पत धनं-
जयः) 10. 15. 21; Arjuna was asked by
Indra to learn the Paitāmaha astra (identical,
or different from Brahmāstra ?) 3. 164. 29;
(iii-v) Bhīṣma, Kṛpa, and Aśvatthāman:
According to Yudhiṣṭhira, Bhīṣma, Kṛpa and
Aśvatthāman knew its use and remedy (स-
प्रयोगचिकित्सितम्) 3. 38. 5; 4. 46. 7 (Kṛpa
and Aśvatthāman); 4. 46. 9 (Aśvatthāmān);
(vi) Karṇa: Karṇa requested Droṇa to teach
him Brahmāstra together with its secret and
withdrawal, but Droṇa refused to oblige
12. 2. 10, 13; Karṇa, who coveted the Astra
(12. 3. 27, 30), then learnt it in its entirety
(कृत्स्नम्) from Rāma Jāmadagnya 12. 3.
2; 8. 5. 67; but since Karṇa had told a lie
to obtain its knowledge (12. 3. 30), Rāma
cursed him saying that the missile would flash
to him on all occasions except when he met
his equal and the time of his death had arrived
(ते … ब्रह्मास्त्रं प्रतिभास्यति।अन्यत्र
वधकातात् ते सदृशेन समेयुषः) 12. 3.
30-31; 5. 61. 2; returning, Karṇa reported
to Duryodhana that he had acquired the
missiles (from Rāma) (कृतास्त्रो ऽस्मि) 12. 3.
33; since Karṇa had pacified Rāma, knowledge
of Brahmāstra remained with him; hence
Karṇa assured Duryodhana that he was quite
capable of bearing the burden of the war
(ततस् तद् अस्त्रं मम सावशेषं तस्मात्
समर्थो ऽस्मि ममैष भारः) 5. 61. 2-4;
according to Yudhiṣṭhira, Karṇa knew the
use and remedy of Brahmāstra 3. 38. 5;
Karṇa boasted to Śalya that he knew the
Brāhma astras (pl. अस्त्राणि … ब्राह्माणी) 8.
29. 26; (vii) Kṛṣṇa: According to Bhīṣma,
perhaps Kṛṣṇa knew Brāhma and many
other heavenly weapons (कृष्णो वा देवकी-
पुत्रः) 6. 116. 39; (viii) Vibhīṣaṇa: He
prayed Brahman that the Brahmāstra might
flash to him although it was not duly taught
to him (अशिक्षितं च भगवन् ब्रह्मास्त्रं
प्रतिभातु मे) 3. 259. 30; [For its use also
by Yudhiṣṭhira, Kuvalāśva, Bṛhatkṣatra,
Pradyumna, Rāma (Dāśarathi), and Lakṣ-
maṇa see below section F].
C. Des-
cription: heavenly (दिव्य) 3. 271. 16; 7.
101. 12; 7. 160. 5; 7. 165. 22, 105; 8. 29. 27;
9. 61. 13, (19); great missile (महास्त्र)
3. 163. 33; 7. 165. 23; 8. 65. 23; (परम्
अस्त्रम्) 8. 66. 52; (परमास्त्र) 5. 185. 15;
best (उत्तम) 5. 185. 16; unrivalled (अप्र-
तिम) 8. 29. 27; dreadful (घोर) 3. 274.
27, (माहाघोर) 8. 5. 67; fierce (उग्र) 8.
65. 23; unbearable (असह्य) 8. 65. 24; of un-
matched strength (अप्रतिमौजस्) 3. 274. 27;
invincible even in thought (मनसा तद् ध्य्
अजय्यम्) 8. 29. 27; highly respected
(परमसंमत) 1. 154. 13; to be employ-
ed mentally (मनसा संविधेयम्) 8. 65.
24; cannot be withstood even by Indra 9.
61. 27.
D. Teaching of the अस्त्र: The
use of the missile was to be taught in full
(कृत्स्नम्), i. e. together with the mode of
its withdrawal; this is how Rāma Jāmadagnya
taught it to Karṇa after performing due rites
(तस्मै स विधिवत् कृत्स्नम् ब्रह्मास्त्रं
सनिवर्तनम्।प्रोवाच) 12. 3. 2; Droṇa
learnt from Rāma Jāmadagnya both—the
mode of its employment (प्रयोग) and with-
drawal (संहार) 1. 154. 11; when Karṇa
expressed his desire to learn it from Droṇa
he wanted to know it with its secrets and the
mode of its withdrawal (सरहस्यनिवर्तनम्)
12. 2. 10; Bhīṣma, Droṇa, Kṛpa, Karṇa and
Aśvatthāman reputed for their knowledge of
the employment of the अस्त्र and its remedy
(i. e. withdrawal) (सप्रयोगचिकित्सितम्) 3.
38. 5; it could be taught only to a Brāh-
maṇa who had duly observed the prescribed
vow (यथावत् चरितव्रतः), or a Kṣatriya
who had practised austerities (तपस्वी), but
to none else 12. 2. 13; hence Karṇa told a
lie to Rāma Jāmadagnya about his lineage
while declaring that he was a Bhārgava Brāh-
maṇa 12. 2. 15; 12. 3. 26-30.
E. Use
and withdrawal: At the time of its employ-
ment, मन्त्रस् related to Brahmāstra were
recited on an arrow to use it as a charged
missile (बाणवर्यं … ब्रह्मास्त्रेणाभि-
मन्त्रितम्) 3. 274. 24-25; (ब्रह्मास्त्र-
परिमन्त्रितैः सायकैः) 3. 167. 17; (सं-
मन्त्र्य) 8. 66. 52; these मन्त्रस् used
to charge the arrow with the Brāhma (and the
other अस्त्रस्) were supposed to serve as
the ritual मन्त्रस् for the ‘sacrifice to be
performed with weapons’ (शस्त्रयज्ञ, i. e.
in the war) 5. 139. 31; it was necessary
to support the bow and the arrow with great
might (बलेनाथ स संस्तभ्य ब्रह्मा-
स्त्रं समुदैरयत्) 8. 66. 48; at the time of
withdrawing the Brahmāstra (Iṣīkā) employ-
ed by Aśvatthāman, Kṛṣṇa touched water
(उपस्पृश्य) 14. 68. 16, 14. 69. 1, and also
made a सत्यक्रिया 14. 68. 19-23.
F.
Uses: (1) In the epic war: (i) by
Droṇa—(a) against Arjuna in order to cut
down the भल्ल arrows 7. 67. 9 (समु-
दीरय-); 7. 163. 43 (प्रादुष्कृ-); 9.
61. 27; (b) against Yudhiṣṭhira to burn his
शक्ति to ashes 7. 81. 32-33 (प्रादुष्कृ-);
7. 132. 33 (उदीरय-); (c) against Bṛhat-
kṣatra of the Kekayas 7. 101. 12 (प्रा-
दुष्कृ-); (d) against the Pāñcālas, killing
twenty thousand chariot-fighters, besides
many elephants and horses 7. 164. 79-83
(प्रादुष्कृ-); in addition, Droṇa killed
ten अयुतस् of the Pāñcāla soldiers with
Brāhma astra as if to destroy all the Kṣatriyas
(क्षत्रियाणाम् अभावाय ब्राह्मम् आत्मानम्
आस्थितः) 7. 165. 14-15; (e) against the
armies of the Pāṇḍavas, the Kekayas, the
Matsyas, specially of the Pāñcālas killing by
hundreds and thousands; Droṇa also burnt
one thousand chariot-fighters and two thousand
elephant-riders 7. 165. 100-102; (f) against
Dhṛṣṭadyumna while dashing the horses of
his chariot against those of Dhṛṣṭadyumna
(ब्राह्मम् अस्त्रम् उदीरयन्) 7. 164. 129;
(उदीरयेतां ब्राह्माणि दिव्यान्य् अस्त्राण्य्
अनेकशः) 7. 165. 22; (ब्राह्मम् अस्त्रं
विकुर्वाणः) 7. 165. 100; (दिव्यम् अस्त्रं
विकुर्वाणः) 7. 165. 105; (ii) by Arjuna:
(a) He assured Kṛṣṇa that by employing his
Brāhma astra he would repulse all the missiles
used against him by the protectors of Jaya-
dratha 7. 53. 44; (b) Arjuna cut down with
the rain of arrows released by the use of the
Brahmāstra the shower of arrows released
against him by Droṇa by using the same mis-
sile 7. 67. 12; 7. 163. 46; (c) Arjuna released
(उदीरय-) his Brāhma astra to nullify the
effect of the Āgneya astra (7. 172. 14) of
Aśvatthāman 7. 172. 14; (d) against Karṇa:
Arjuna thought of using it for the welfare of
the people (शिवाय लोकस्य) and the death of
Karṇa (वधाय सौतेः); to do this he sought
the permission of Kṛṣṇa, the gods, Brahman,
Śiva, and of all the knowers of ब्रह्मन् (ब्र-
ह्मविद्) 8. 65. 23-24; Arjuna advised to use
Brahmāstra by Kṛṣṇa 8. 66. 52 (विसृज्-, प्रयो-
जय।); he countered Karṇa's Brahmāstra by
using apparently the same missile (तद् अस्त्रम्
अस्त्रेणावार्य) 8. 67. 8; (iii) by Karṇa:
(a) when he was surrounded at once by many
Pāṇḍava warriors 8. 33. 25 (उदीरय-);
(b) against Arjuna 8. 66. 48 (समुदीरय-);
8. 67. 8; (9. 61. 27); (iv) by Yudhiṣṭhira: to
pacify the Brahmāstra of Droṇa used against
him 7. 81. 34; 7. 132. 35; (v) by Dhṛṣṭa-
dyumna: He and Droṇa used (उदीरय-)
heavenly Brāhma missiles (pl.) against each
other in many ways (ब्राह्माणि दिव्यान्य्
अस्त्राण्य् अनेकशः) 7. 165. 22; Dhṛṣṭdyumna
repelled successfully all missiles used by
Droṇa 7. 165. 23; (vi) by Bṛhatkṣatra (a
Kaikeya): he repulsed Droṇa's Brāhma astra
by the use of the same weapon 7. 101. 13,
(14); (2) Outside the epic war: (i) by
Arjuna: (a) against Kirāta (Śiva); but
it was destroyed by Kirāta 3. 163. 33,
35; (b) against the Nivātakavacas to blow
them away by hundreds and thousands with
the arrows released from the missile 3.
167. 17; (ii) by Aśvatthāman: the इषीका
directed by Aśvatthāman towards the foetus
of Uttarā (10. 15. 31, 33) identified with
Brahmāstra 14. 65. 9; 14. 67. 21; 14. 68. 16;
14. 69. 1; (14. 67. 13, 16); (iii) by Rāma
Jāmadagnya: he used it against Bhīṣma 5.
185. 15 (प्रादुष्कृ-); (iv) by Bhīṣma: to
counter with the same missile the use of the
Brahmāstra by Rāma Jāmadagnya 5. 185.
16 (प्रयुज्-); (v) by Pradyumna: against
Śālva to cut off half way his Daiteyāstra
(माया) 3. 20. 17; (vi) by Kuvalāśva:
against the Daitya Dhundhu who was burnt
with it 3. 195. 28; (vii) by Rāma (Dāśa-
rathi): against Rāvaṇa; Rāma, while using
it, recited मन्त्रस् on his arrow; with it,
Rāvaṇa, together with his chariot and the
charioteer, were burnt down 3. 274. 24-25,
28; (viii) by Lakṣmaṇa: against the demon
Kumbhakarṇa who was burnt with it 3. 271.
16.
G. Effects of Brahmāstra: When the
Brahmāstra was released: (i) it produced
a very large number of (flaming) arrows 3.
163. 33; 3. 167. 17; 7. 67. 9 (भल्ल), 12;
7. 165. 100 (भल्ल); 8. 33. 25; 8. 65. 24; 8.
66. 53; 8. 67. 8; (ii) it produced fire enough
to heat the worlds and fill the directions
and space with lustre (ततः संतापितो लोको
मत्प्रसूतेन तेजसा।क्षणेन हि दिशः
खं च सर्वतो ऽभिविदीपितम्) 3. 163.
34; (जज्वाल) 5. 185. 16; (व्योम्नि पादुर्-
अभूत् तेजः) 5. 185. 18; (दीपयां चक्रे)
5. 186. 7; (तद् अस्त्रं ज्वलितम्) 14. 69. 3;
or to burn the enemy with it 3. 195. 28; 3.
271. 16; 3. 274. 28; 7. 165. 102; or to burn
the enemy's weapon 7. 81. 33; or to burn
the enemy's chariot 9. 61. 18-19; or to burn
the chariot together with horses and charioteer
3. 274. 28; (iii) it produced smoke to fill the
directions 5. 185. 21; (iv) it produced
darkness all over which terrified creatures 7.
132. 33-34; (v) it removed the darkness
produced by the enemy's missile with the
result that cold winds blew and the directions
became clear 7. 172. 32; (vi) all life could
be threatened by it 5. 47. 101; 5. 185. 18,
20-21; 7. 163. 45; (vii) earth, with its
mountains, forests, and trees shook, winds
blew in the opposite direction, and the oceans
were agitated 7. 163. 44; 5. 185. 22; (viii)
gods and other divine and demoniac beings
were heated with its blaze 5. 185. 19; or they
could not remain in the mid-region and they
bewailed 5. 185. 21-22; (ix) under its
influence the Rakṣases infested the residence;
they disappeared when the missile was with-
drawn 14. 69. 2.
H. Withdrawal: Bra-
hmāstra, when employed, either served the
purpose for which it was used, or was
repulsed, or pacified by the counter-use of the
same missile (cf. above sections F and G);
it was only once destroyed by Kirāta (Śiva) 3.
163. 35; only once when the same missile was
employed by the opponents they clashed in-
between without reaching the respective targets
5. 185. 17; Arjuna withdrew it (= Brahma-
śiras) 10. 15. 1, 5, but it (Iṣīkā identified
with Brahmāstra) could not be withdrawn
by Aśvatthāman as he had not observed the
ब्रह्मचारिव्रत 10. 15. 7-8; later Kṛṣṇa
withdrew it after sipping water (and making
a सत्यक्रिया) to revive the still-born child
14. 68. 16, (19-23); 14. 69. 1; when Kṛṣṇa
withdrew the Brahmāstra, brilliant light
emanated from the body of Parikṣit to fill
the room; the evil spirits (रक्षांसि) then left
the house and disappeared, and the mid-region
was filled with the words ‘well-done’ (साधु
केशव साध्व् इति) 14. 69. 1-2.
I. Com-
parison: the missile compared with the raised
Brahmadaṇḍa 3. 274. 27;
J. Status:
Inferior to Pāśupatāstra of Śiva 13. 14. 127,
(124). [See Iṣīkā, Brahmaśiras1]

भार्गवास्त्र
Bhārgavāstra nt.: Name of a missile.
Obtained by Karṇa from Bhārgava
(Rāma Jāmadagnya) 8. 51. 101; described
as fearful (घोर, घोररूप) 8. 51. 101,
102, very fierce (सुदारुण) 8. 51. 102;
difficult to resist (दुर्निवार) 8. 51. 104;
cannot be resisted in war (नैतद् अस्त्रं
हि समरे शक्यं हन्तुं कथंचन) 8.
45. 46; flaming with its lustre (ज्वलति स्वेन
तेजसा) 8. 51. 102; hence burning the oppo-
nent's armies (तापनं सर्वसैन्यानाम्)
8. 51. 102; compared with the thunderbolt
of Indra (शक्रेणेव महाशनिम्) 8. 52. 6;
used by Karṇa against the Pāñcāla and the
Pāṇḍava armies when the Kaurava soldiers
took to their heels 8. 45. 34; as a result crores
and प्रयुतस् and अर्बुदस् of sharp arrows
were released from the Bhārgavāstra; the
armies were tortured by the arrows which were
burning and which were sped by their feathers
of the Kaṅka birds 8. 45. 35-37; thousands
of warriors, elephants, chariots and horses
fell down due to the impact of the missile
8. 45. 38; 8. 51. 99-100; Arjuna pointed
out to Kṛṣṇa the havoc created by the might
of the Bhārgavāstra 8. 45. 45-46; the
Pāñcāla army withdrew what they never had
done before 8. 51. 95-99; 8. 52. 5-6.

भास्कर
Bhāskara astra nt.: Name of a missile.
Abhimanyu employed (प्रादुष्कृ-) it to
dispel the dense darkness produced by the
great माया (महामाया) of the Rakṣas
Alambusa; the Bhāskara astra destroyed the
माया and there was light everywhere 6. 97.
21-24.

भौम
Bhauma astra nt.: Name of a missile.
While displaying his skill in the use of
missiles, Arjuna employed Bhauma astra and
entered the earth (भौमेन प्राविशद् भू-
मिं) 1. 125. 20.

भ्रान्त
Bhrānta nt.: One of the twenty-one
movements (मार्ग) used by a swordsman.
Dhṛṣṭadyumna used it when he, with a
sword and a shield in hand, wanted to
attack Drona who was shooting arrows at
him 7. 164. 145-148.

मकर
Makara, Mākara (8. 7. 14) m.: Name
of a particular way of arranging the army
(व्यूह).
A. Description: Tormentor of the
enemies (शत्रुतापन) 6. 71. 4; hard like
वज्र (वज्रकल्प) 6. 76. 5.
B. Its
use: (1) Bhīṣma arranged the Kaurava
army that way on the fifth day of the war
to counter the Śyenavyūha of the Pāṇḍavas
6. 65. 7; Bhīṣma guarded it on all sides 6.
6. 65. 4; Bhīma entered the Makaravyūha
from the front (मुखतः) and attacked
Bhīṣma with arrows 6. 65. 13; (2) On the
sixth day of the war Yudhiṣṭhira asked
Dhṛṣṭadyumna to arrange the army acco-
rding to the Makaravyūha 6. 71. 4; its
‘head’ (शीरस्) was formed by Drupada and
Arjuna; its ‘eyes’ (चक्षुषी) were Sahadeva
and Nakula; its ‘mouth’ (तुण्ड) was
Bhīmasena; its ‘neck’ (ग्रीवा) were
Abhimanyu, the sons of Draupadī, Ghaṭot-
kaca, Sātyaki and Yudhiṣṭhira; its ‘back’
(पृष्ठ) was formed by Virāṭa and Dhṛṣṭa-
dyumna with a large army; its ‘left side’
(वामपार्श्व) was formed by the five Kekaya
brothers, and the ‘right side’ (दक्षिण
पार्श्व) by Dhṛṣṭaketu and Karakarṣa; its
‘two feet’ (पादौ) were Kuntibhoja and Śatā-
nīka with a large army; its ‘tail’ (पुच्छ)
was Śikhaṇḍin, surrounded by Somakas, and
Irāvant 6. 71. 6-12; Duryodhana complained
to Bhīṣma that when he entered the Makara
vyūha (6. 75. 1) he was overpowered by
Bhīma with arrows 6. 76. 5; (3) Karṇa
arranged Kaurava army according to the
Mākara vyūha (8. 7. 14) on the sixteenth day
of the war; its ‘mouth’ (तुण्ड) was Karṇa;
its ‘eyes’ (नेत्रे) were Śakuni and Ulūka;
its ‘head’ (शिरस्) was Aśvatthāman; its
‘neck’ (ग्रीवा) was formed by Duryodhana's
brothers; at its ‘waist’ (मध्य) was
Duryodhana with a large army; at the ‘left
foot’ (वामपाद) was Kṛtavarman with
Gopālas from the army of Nārāyaṇa and
at the ‘right foot’ (दक्षिण पाद) Kṛpa
surrounded by the Trigartas and the Dākṣiṇā-
tyas; at the ‘left hind-foot’ (वाम अनुपाद)
was Śalya with a large Madra army; at the
‘right (hind-foot)’ (दक्षिण) was Suṣeṇa
with one thousand chariots and a hundred
elephants; at the ‘tail’ (पुच्छ) were the
brothers Citrasena and Citra (the Abhisāra
princes) who stood there with a large army;
8. 7. 15-21; to counter this Mākara vyūha
of the Kauravas, Arjuna used the Ardha-
candra vyūha 8. 7. 27.

मणिपुष्पक
Maṇipuṣpaka m.: Name of a conch.
It belonged to Sahadeva; he blew it on
the first day of the war when the two armies
were arrayed against each other 6. 23. 16;
he blew it the next day at the start of the
war 6. 47. 26, (and presumably on all the
following days).

मण्डल
Maṇḍala m.: Name of a particular
arrangement of the army (व्यूह).
Described as bristling with many weapons
(नानाशस्त्रसमाकुल) 6. 77. 12; very large
(सुमहाव्यूह); difficult to be penetrated
(दुर्भेद्य); difficult to be reached by the
enemies (अरीणां दुरासदः) 6. 77. 20;
very terrible (परमदारुण) 6. 77. 21;
Bhīṣma arranged the Kaurava army according
to this व्यूह on the seventh day of the war 6.
77. 11-12; it faced the west (प्रत्यङ्मुख)
6. 77. 20; it was surrounded on all sides by
many thousands of chariots, large troops of
horsemen holding ऋष्टिस् and तोमरस्; every
elephant was guarded by seven chariots, and
every chariot by seven horsemen; near every
horseman were stationed ten archers, and
seven swordsmen (चर्मिणः lit. ‘holding
shields’) stood guard near every archer 6.
77. 13-14; to counter the Maṇḍalavyūha the
Pāṇḍavas used the Vajravyūha 6. 77. 21.

मण्डलार्ध
Maṇḍalārdha m.: Name of a particular
arrangement of the army (व्यूह).
Yudhiṣṭhira arranged the army of the
Pāṇḍavas according to this व्यूह on the
twelfth day of the war to counter the Suparṇa-
vyūha of the Kauravas 7. 19. 4.

महाव्यूह
Mahāvyūha m.: Name of a particular
way of arranging the army (व्यूह).
Described as extremely invincible
(सुदुर्जय) 6. 95. 38; (1) Bhīṣma, Droṇa
and Duryodhana arranged on the second
day of the war the Kaurava army according
to Mahāvyūha to counter the Krauñca
vyūha of the Pāṇḍavas 6. 47. 1, 10;
6. 48. 10; in this arrangement Bhīṣma, sur-
rounded by a large army, was in the front;
he was followed by Droṇa, accompanied
by the Kuntalas, Daśārṇas, Māgadhas and
many others; Śakuni with his army, as
also the Gāndhāras, Sindhusauvīras, the
Śibis, and the Vasātis, moved with Droṇa to
protect him; Duryodhana, with his brothers,
and the Aśvātakas, the Vikarṇas, the Śar-
milas and the Kośalas, and many others took
positions to offer protection to the army of
Śakuni; Bhūriśravas, Śala, Śalya, Bhaga-
datta, Vinda and Anuvinda of the Avanti,
stood on the left side of the vyūha (वाम-
पार्श्व); Saumadatti (Bhūriśravas) Suśar-
man, Sudakṣiṇa of the Kāmboja country,
Śatāyu and Śrutāyu took care of the right side
(दक्षिण पार्श्व); Aśvatthāman, Kṛpa, and
Kṛtavarman with a large army guarded the
rear (सेनापृष्ठे व्यवस्थिताः); kings of
many countries, Ketumant, Vasudāna, and
the son of the Kāśī king acted as the rear-
guards of the army (पृष्ठगोपाः) 6. 47.
11-20; (2) Apparently the Kaliṅga king,
when asked by Duryodhana to protect Droṇa
and attack Bhīma (6. 49. 37, 38; 6. 50. 1,
3 ff.), had arranged his army in the Mahā-
vyūha way (महाव्यूहः कलिङ्गानाम् 6. 50.
113); in that vyūha many elephants, horse-
men, and chariot fighters took part (नागा-
श्वरथसंकुलः); Bhīma, by himself,
was able to crush it 6. 50. 113; (3) Bhīṣma
arranged the Kaurava army according to the
Mahāvyūha on the eighth day of the war 6.
83. 5, 13, 15; it looked like an ocean (सागर-
प्रतिम) 6. 83. 5, (सागरोपम) 6. 83. 16;
the vyūha was led by Bhīṣma, accompanied
by the Mālavas, Dākṣiṇātyas, and the Āvan-
tyas; he was followed by Droṇa, accompa-
nied by Pulindas, Pāradas, Kṣudrakas, and
the Mālavas; Droṇa was followed by Bhaga-
datta, accompanied by the Māgadhas, the
Kaliṅgas, and the Piśācas; behind him was
Bṛhadbala of the Kosala country, accompa-
nied by the Mekalas, the Traipuras, and the
Cicchilas; then came Trigarta (Suśarman),
the ruler of Prasthalas accompanied by many
Kāṃbojas and the Yavanas in thousands;
Aśvatthāman followed Trigarta; behind
Aśvatthāman marched Duryodhana surround-
ed by his brothers; Kṛpa followed Duryo-
dhana 6. 83. 6-13; (4) The Pāṇḍavas
arranged their army in the Mahāvyūha way
(6. 95. 38) on the ninth day of the war
to counter the Sarvatobhadravyūha of the
Kauravas (6. 95. 26); in the forefront of
this vyūha stood Bhīmasena (6. 95. 40),
along with Yudhiṣṭhira, Nakula and Saha-
deva; Dhṛṣṭadyumna, Virāṭa and Sātyaki
apparently followed them; they seem to have
been followed by Śikhaṇḍin, Vijaya (Arjuna),
the Rākṣasa Ghaṭotkaca, Cekitāna and Kunti-
bhoja, all of them encircled by large armies;
the rear seems to have been made up by
Abhimanyu, Drupada, and five Kekaya
brothers (6. 95. 34-38); (but Arjuna had
advised Dhṛṣṭadyumna to see that Śikhaṇḍin
confronted Bhīṣma and that he would pro-
tect Śikhaṇḍin (शिखण्डिनं नरव्याघ्र
भीष्मस्य प्रमुखे ऽनघ।स्थापय-
स्वाद्य पाञ्चाल्य तस्य गोप्ताहम् अप्य् उत
6. 95. 25; according to Duryodhana's infor-
mation, in that position Yudhāmanyu would
guard the left wheel of Arjuna and Utta-
maujas the right wheel 6. 95. 21).

महास्त्र
Mahāstra nt.: The ‘great’ missile, not
named, employed by Arjuna on his Añjalika
arrow (8. 67. 16).
Arjuna, who knew the मन्त्रस् of this
missile, charged his arrow with the Mahāstra
when he shot it at Karṇa to kill him (युक्त्वा
महास्त्रेण परेण मन्त्रवित्); he then
described his arrow as Mahāstra (अयम्
महास्त्रो ऽप्रतिमो धृतः शरः) 8. 67. 19;
he also strengthened it with the power of
truth by making a सत्यक्रिया (तपो ऽस्ति
तप्तं गुरवश् च तोषिता मया यद् इष्टं
सुहृदां तथा श्रुतम्।अनेन सत्येन नि-
हन्त्व् अयं शरः सुदंशितः कर्णं अरिं
ममाजितः) 8. 67. 20; the arrow was then
to work like a fierce अथर्वाङ्गिरसी magic
and bring victory to Arjuna (कृत्याम् अथर्-
वाङ्गिरसीम् इवोग्रां … अयं शरो मे विज-
यावहो ऽस्तु) 8. 67. 21-22.

माकर
Mākara adj.: of a व्यूह। [See
Makara].

माधव
Mādhava nt.: Name of a missile.
A favourite (दयित) missile of Deva-
rāja (Indra); described as great (परम)
and having sharp lustre (तिग्मतेजस्); used
by Arjuna while fighting with the demons
called the Nivātakavacas who were enemies of
Indra; with the might of this missile (अस्त्र-
वीर्य) Arjuna was able to cut the swords,
the tridents (त्रिशूलस्), and तोमरस् in
thousands hurled against him by the demons
3. 167. 19-20.

मारुत
Māruta nt.: Name of a missile.
Mentioned along with Āgni, i. e. the
Āgneyāstra (उभे चैवाग्निमारुते); it was
meant to be used by Arjuna against the
Kauravas in the war 5. 140. 6.

मानुष
Mānuṣa adj.: of missiles specific to
human beings.
They are not named but are distinguished
from such divine missiles as Vāruṇa, Āgneya
Brāhma, Aindra and Nārāyaṇa astra; Droṇa
reputed to have the knowledge of both these
kinds of missiles 7. 166. 2.

मानुष
Mānuṣa2 adj.: of व्यूहस् (arrange-
ments of the army) known to men.
Bhīṣma knew different kinds of व्यूहस्,
some of them known as Mānuṣa vyūhas
5. 162. 8. 10; 6. 19. 2; he arranged the
Kaurava army everyday in a different way,
one of the ways being Mānuṣa (vyūha) 6.
20. 18; Dhṛṣṭadyumna, who led the Pāṇḍava
army, also knew these different vyūhas
5. 56. 11.

माहेन्द्र
Māhendra1 adj.: of a missile belonging
to Mahendra (Indra), (different from
Aindra ?).
Yudhiṣṭhira employed this missile to
defeat the Aindra and the Prājāpatya missiles
used simultaneously against him by Droṇa
(प्रादुश्चकारास्त्रम् अहीनतेजा माहेन्द्रम्
अन्यत् स जघान ते ऽस्त्रे) 7. 132. 32.
[See Aindrāstra]

माहेन्द्र
Māhendra2 adj.: of the bow Vijaya
which belonged to Indra; used in the epic
war by Karṇa.
It is one of the only three divine bows
(the other two being Gāṇḍiva of Varuṇa and
Śārṅga of Viṣṇu) 5. 155. 5-6. [See Vijaya]

मुसल
Musala m., nt.: A weapon specially
mentioned in relation to Jaya.
Jaya held it when he came to the aid of
Indra in his fight with Kṛṣṇa and Arjuna at
the Khāṇḍava forest (जगृहे … मुसलं च
जयस् तथा) 1. 218. 32; (also Balarāma is
called मुसलायुध 9. 35. 2; 9. 48. 6).

मृत्युदण्ड
Mṛtyudaṇḍa m.: Missile of the god of
Death. [See Daṇḍa]

मोहनास्त्र
Mohanāstra nt.: Name of a missile.
[See Pramohanāstra]

यमदण्ड
Yamadaṇḍa m.: Name of the missile
specially related to Yama. [See Daṇḍa,
Yāmya astra]

याम्य
Yāmya astra nt.: A missile special to
Yama.
Described as heavenly (दिव्य) 12. 5.
14, and fierce (घोर) 7. 53. 43; Arjuna
had received it from Yama 7. 53. 43; 12.
5. 13-14; Arjuna's collection of missiles
(अस्त्रग्राम) included among other missiles,
Yāmya astra 5. 166. 32-33; (Bhīṣma, Droṇa
and Yudhiṣṭhira also knew it); Droṇa used
it agaisnt Yudhiṣṭhira in order to kill him
(जिघांसुः) but Yudhiṣṭhira repelled it
apparently by using the same missile 7. 132.
29-30; Bhīṣma and Arjuna used it against
each other at the time of the cattle-raid 4.
59. 21. [See Yamadaṇḍa]

रक्षसाम्
Rakṣasām astrāṇi nt. pl.: Missiles
special to Rakṣases.
Arjuna was to learn these after reaching
the residence of Indra 3. 164. 29-30.

राक्षस
Rākṣasa adj.: of the व्यूह (arrange-
ment of the army) known to the Rakṣases.
Bhīṣma knew these and is said to have
used them on different days along with those
known to the Asuras and the Piśācas 6.
104. 16.

रुद्राणाम्
Rudrāṇām astrāṇi nt. pl.: Missiles
special to the Rudras.
When Arjuna reached Indra's residence,
the Rudras, along with the other group-gods,
agreed to give their missiles to him 3. 164.
49-50; they figure in a bad omen: when
Garuḍa flew up from a mountain top to
fetch Soma from the heaven, there occurred
bad omens for the gods, one of them being
that the missile (प्रहरणम्) of the Rudras
clashed with those of the Vasus, the Ādityas,
the Sādhyas, the Maruts and the other hosts
of gods (ये चान्ये देवतागणाः); such a
thing had never happened before 1. 26. 29-30.

रुद्रास्त्र
Rudrāstra, Raudra astra nt.: Name
of a missile, special to Rudra (Śiva).
A. Description: Heavenly (दिव्य)
12. 5. 13-14; great (महास्त्र) 3. 170. 38;
fierce (घोर) 3. 170. 40; 7. 53. 43; eternal
(सनातन) 3. 170. 40; destroyer of all ene-
mies (सर्वामित्रविनाशन) 3. 170. 38; no
other weapon superior to it (अनुत्तम) 8. 66.
57.
B. Identified with the Pāśupata (and
the Brahmaśiras ?): When Arjuna prayed to
Śiva to give him the divine missiles, he agreed
to Arjuna's request and told him that his
Raudra missile would wait on him; he then
gave him his Pāśupata 3. 163. 47-48; Brahma-
śiras missile, which Arjuna received from
Rudra, also called Raudra (or adj. ‘fierce’
of Brahmaśiras (?)) 3. 41. 8.
C. Known
to Arjuna: Arjuna's collection of missiles
(अस्त्रग्राम 5. 166. 32) included Raudra
astra 3. 89. 10-11; Arjuna had received it
from Rudra 7. 53. 43; 12. 5. 13-14, and he
wanted to use it against the Kauravas at
the time of the cattle-raid 4. 56. 14.
D.
Mode of use: At the time of using it (against
Karṇa), Arjuna recited the मन्त्रस् (अनु-
मन्त्र्य) on the arrow on which he employed
it 8. 66. 58; at the time of charging his
arrow with the missile (to release it against
the Pauloma and the Kālakeya demons)
Arjuna bowed down to Rudra (रुद्राय
प्रणतो रणे) and wished well to the crea-
tures (स्वस्ति भूतेभ्यः); he bowed down
to Śarva (Rudra) again when he actually
released the missile from the bow (नमस्कृत्वा
त्रिनेत्राय शर्वायामिततेजसे) 3. 170. 38, 41.
E. Uses: 1. In the epic war: (i) Arjuna
wanted to employ it on a heavenly arrow,
resembling fire or snake's poison and which
was hard like a stone, and release it against
Kaṛṇa 8. 66. 58-59; there is no mention
of Arjuna having released it, but it seems
that he warded off Karṇa's Brahmāstra with it
(not named; तद् अस्त्रम् अस्त्रेणावार्य प्रज-
हारास्य पाण्डवः) 8. 67. 8; (ii) Aśva-
tthāman killed the followers of Dhṛṣṭadyumna
who surrounded him after he killed Dhṛṣṭa-
dyumna at night in the camp of the Pāṇḍavas
10. 8. 31-32; 2. Outside the epic war: (i)
Arjuna used it to burn with its fire the
Nivātakavaca demons 5. 136. 7; (ii) Arjuna
used it to kill the Pauloma and the Kālakeya
demons; Arjuna first used all his other missiles
without being able to defeat the demons, but
was himself oppressed by them; at that time he
was afraid; he bowed to Rudra and employed
the great Raudra missile on his arrow (महा-
स्त्रं समयोजयम्); he then saw a man
having three heads, nine eyes, three mouths,
six hands, burning, his hair bright like the
sun or fire, his head covered with big snakes
(ततो ऽपश्यं त्रिशिरसं पुरुषं नवलोच-
नम्।त्रिमुखं षड्भुजं दीप्तम् अर्क-
ज्वलनमूर्धजम्॥लेलिहानैर् महानागैः
कृतशीर्षम्) 3. 170. 38-39; when the missile
was next actually released (मुक्तमात्रे ततस्
तस्मिन्) thousands of different shapes—wild
animals like lions, tigers, bears, buffalos,
as also snakes, cows, elephants, सृमरस्,
शरभस्, bulls, boars, wild cats, शालावृकस्,
ghosts, भुरुण्डस्, vultures, eagles, crocodiles,
Piśācas, Yakṣas, demons, Guhyakas, Nairṛtas,
big fishes having mouths of elephants, owls,
hosts of fishes and tortoises, shapes holding
different weapons and swords, Yātudhānas
holding गदा and मुद्गर, and many
others—came out from the missile and filled
the space; the demons were killed by many
shapes having three heads, four tusks, four
mouths, four hands, as also by the arrows of
Arjuna which shone like the sun and the fire,
which were brilliant like the Vajra and
lightning, and hard like rocks; when the
demons were killed by the Raudrāstra, Arjuna
bowed down to Tripuraghna (Śiva) once
again 3. 170. 42-51.

रौद्र
Raudra astra: [See Rudrāstra].

लाङ्गल
Lāṅgala nt.: Plough used as a weapon
by Balarāma.
Hence Balarāma has epithets like
लाङ्गलिन् 1. 213. 49; 9. 36. 36; 9. 38. 2;
9. 45. 93, 94; 9. 46. 23; 9. 54. 4; लाङ्गल-
ध्वज 5. 3. 4.

वज्र
Vajra1 nt. (m. 4. 2. 13; 12. 273. 7;
12. 31. 29): A missile generally associated
with Indra, but also on a few occasions
with Kṛṣṇa and Śiva; also called Kuliśa
(कुलिशं मघवान् इव) 3. 12. 43; 8. 13. 20.
I. As Indra's missile:
A. Origin: Three
accounts: (1) when the Kāleya demons, under
the leadership of Vṛtra, attacked Indra and the
other gods, Brahman advised them to approach
the sage Dadhīca and ask him for his bones in
order to fashion a Vajra out of it; with that
Vajra, Indra was to kill Vṛtra 3. 98. 3-11;
when the gods received the bones of Dadhīca,
they took them to Tvaṣṭṛ and asked him to
fashion a Vajra out of the bones; Tvaṣṭṛ,
ritually ready (प्रयत) to receive the bones,
was glad to fashion the Vajra which he did
with great effort (प्रयत्नात्) 3. 98. 22; when
the Vajra was ready, Tvaṣṭṛ asked Indra
to reduce his enemies to ashes with the
excellent Vajra (वज्रप्रवर); Indra too
was happy and ritually ready (प्रयत)
to receive it 3. 98. 23-24; (2) Vajra created
from the bones of Dadhīca in order to kill the
three-headed Viśvarūpa, son of Tvaṣṭṛ; when
the Vajra was fashioned by Dhātṛ, Viṣṇu
entered it (विष्णुप्रविष्ट); with the Vajra,
thus fortified, Indra cut off the heads of
Viśvarūpa 12. 329. 25-27; 1. 127. 12; (3)
during a conflict between the gods and the
demons Indra searched the three worlds for a
suitable weapon, but did not find it; he asked
the gods to approach the sage Dadhīca to ask
for his bones; when the bones were received,
Indra got prepared out of them various
divine missiles like वज्रस् (pl.), discuses,
maces, and heavy दण्डस् (कारयाम् आस
दिव्यानि नानाप्रहरणान्य् उत।वज्राणि
चक्राणि गदा गुरुदंडांश् च पुष्कलान्);
with this Vajra produced from the lustre of a
Brāhmaṇa (Dadhīca) and employed with the
recitation of the मन्त्रस् (तेन वज्रेण …
मन्त्रयुक्तेन … ब्रह्मतेजोभवेन च),
Indra killed nine times ninety (नवतीर् नव
9. 50. 33) Daityas and Dānavas 9. 50. 25-33.
B. Description: Heavenly (दिव्य) 12. 31.
27; terrific, very terrific (घोर, घोररूप,
महाघोर) 1. 21. 10; 3. 98. 10; 3. 124. 15,
17; 5. 9. 22; 14. 11. 8; having a fierce form
(उग्ररूप, उग्र) 3. 98. 23; 8. 21. 32; fearful
(भयावह) 5. 9. 22; impenetrable (अभे-
द्य) 12. 329. 27; difficult to resist (दुरु-
त्सह) 3. 45. 4; unassailable (अप्रधृष्य)
12. 329. 27; hard (दृढ) 3. 98. 10; sharp
(तीक्ष्ण) 3. 98. 10; incomparable (अतुल) 1.
21. 10; unsurpassed (अनुत्तम) 3. 124. 15;
large (महत्) 3. 98. 10; fiery (वैश्वान-
रनिभ) 5. 9. 22; having great lustre
(सुमहातेजाः mas.) 12. 273. 7; (अमितते-
जस्) 14. 11. 15, 17; (भूरितेजस्) 14. 11.
9, 11, 13; called big lightning (महाशनि)
1. 218. 30; looking like the fire at the time of
the destruction of the world (कालाग्निसदृशो-
पमः mas.) 12. 273. 7; having six edges
(षडश्र) 3. 98. 10; producing terrific sound
(भीमनिस्वन) 3. 98. 10; produced from
the bones of a Brāhmaṇa (ब्रह्मास्थि-
संभूत) 12. 329. 27; produced from the
lustre of a Brāhmaṇa (ब्रह्मतेजोभव)
9. 50. 33; killer of the enemies (शत्रुहन्)
3. 98. 10; killer of the Dānavas (दानव-
सूदन) 1. 127. 12.
C. Indra's proper
weapon: Dear weapon of Indra (इन्द्रस्य
दयितं वज्रम्) 1. 26. 28; 3. 45. 4; 3. 169.
13; hence Indra has epithets like वज्रिन्
1. 26. 40; 1. 57. 3; 1. 185. 3; 1. 189. 12;
1. 199. 25; 1. 216. 27; 1. 218. 9; 2. 7. 13;
2. 58. 23; 2. 61. 63; 3. 99. 1; 3. 126. 28;
3. 213. 10; 3. 240. 21; 3. 276. 7; 3. 286.
9, 10; 3. 298. 3; 4. 22. 25; 4. 42. 18; 5. 13.
12; 5. 16. 15; 5. 74. 10; 7. 50. 73; 7. 173. 63;
8. 12. 9, 40, 44; 8. 14. 6; 8. 43. 67; 8. 45. 54;
8. 47. 12; 8. 69. 3; 9. 61. 27; 12. 217. 35;
12. 220. 11, 26; 12. 221. 7; 12. 273. 13;
13. 105. 62; 14. 10. 10; 14. 60. 18; वज्रभृत्
1. 51. 13; 1. 195. 17; 1. 215. 7; 1. 217. 18;
3. 22. 19; 3. 229. 13; 4. 34. 7; 4. 47. 10;
6. 15. 25; 6. 46. 41; 6. 60. 68; 6. 96. 11;
6. 114. 52; 7. 12. 11; 8. 5. 63; 9. 30. 5;
12. 217. 9; 13. 40. 29; वज्रस्य भर्ता
1. 3. 152; वज्रधर 1. 150. 16; 1. 207.
1 (वज्रधर°); 1. 215. 13 (pl. यैर्
अहं शक्नुयाम् योद्धुम् अपि वज्रधरान्
बहून्); 2. 4. 20; 3. 113. 23; 3. 121. 3;
3. 142. 14; 3. 154. 41; 3. 161. 19; 3. 216. 11;
3. 272, 3; 5. 21. 7; 6. 17. 36; 6. 79. 25; 6.
103. 69, 93; 7. 72. 30; 7. 94. 15; 7. 115. 10;
7. 167. 22; 9. 19. 5; 9. 47. 53; 12. 221. 88;
14. 78. 31 (वज्रधर°); 15. 26. 11; वज्र-
धारिन् 6. 95. 20; वज्रपाणि 1. 50. 12; 1.
134. 4; 1. 189. 21, 28; 3. 126. 39 (वज्र-
पाणिन्); 3. 163. 7; 3. 173. 14; 3. 276. 4
(वज्रपाणिन्); 3. 285. 10; 4. 33. 19; 4.
44. 21; 4. 56. 13; 6. 19. 7 (वज्रपाणिन्);
6. 46. 7; 6. 75. 26; 6. 78. 50; 6. 82. 37;
6. 103. 16; 6. 104. 33; 6. 112. 35; 7. 3. 14;
8. 26. 19, 42; 9. 23. 64; 10. 4. 1, 16; 13. 14.
88 (Śiva as Indra); 14. 54. 26; 14. 57. 27,
31; वज्रहस्त 5. 47. 5, 62, 63; 7. 69. 28;
7. 101. 70; 7. 167. 10; 8. 5. 31; 8. 10. 33;
8. 33. 40; 9. 31. 40; 13. 14. 151 (Śiva
as Indra); वज्रोद्यतकर 12. 273. 5;
वज्रायुध 5. 155. 32; 6. 58. 54; सवज्र
(Vāsava) 6. 58. 34; 6. 96. 11; 7. 64. 14
8. 29. 28; 12. 217. 38; प्रगृहीतवज्र
8. 55. 3; Indra's arm has a scar due to his
holding the वज्र (वज्रग्रहणचिह्नेन
करेण बलसूदनः) 3. 44. 25; Indra him-
self called Vajra 1. 21. 10; Indra boasts that
he does not strike his Vajra against the
weak (न दुर्बले वै विसृजामि वज्रम्)
14. 9. 29; that Vajra is the proper weapon
of Indra is also brought out by such ex-
pressions as: the armour with which Duryo-
dhana was equipped by Droṇa could not be
pierced by Indra with his Vajra 7. 78. 13;
Karṇa told Śalya that no one, not even
Indra with his raised Vajra, can dissuade
him from his resolve to fight with Arjuna
8. 27. 29; or Indra's telling Karṇa to ask
for anything except his Vajra 3. 294. 19.
D. Use by Indra: 1. Incidents related
to the epic: (i) Indra released his lustrous
missile (स्वम् अस्त्रम् असृजद् दीप्तम्), not
named, against Arjuna at the time of the
Khāṇḍava fire; it produced lightnings;
Arjuna repelled it by Vāyavya astra 1. 218.
13, 15-16; Indra took up a thunderbolt
(अशनि, महाशनि), and, charging it with
Vajra missile, released it against Kṛṣṇa and
Arjuna (अशनिं गृह्य तरसा वज्रम्
अस्त्रम् अवासृजत्), and told the gods that
the two were killed 1. 218. 29-30; Kṛṣṇa
paralysed Indra who wanted to strike him
with Vajra (reference to the Khāṇḍava fire ?)
13. 143. 26, 23; (ii) when Indra could not
dissuade Uttaṅka from desisting to dig the
earth with just a stick, he joined his Vajrāstra
with the stick; the earth, torn asunder by the
strokes of Vajra, made way for Uttaṅka to
go to the Nāgaloka 14. 57. 31-32; 2. Inci-
dents not related to the epic: (i) Indra
threatened king Marutta, first through Agni,
that in case the king did not forsake Saṃ-
varta who acted as his priest at the sacri-
fice, he would hurl his Vajra at him 14. 9. 24;
he again threatened Marutta, through the Gan-
dharva Dhṛtarāṣṭra, that he would use his
Vajra against the king 14. 10. 1, 2, 4, 7;
Saṃvarta, however, assured Marutta that if
Indra with his Vajra arrived to strike the
king, he would paralyse Indra, and that he
had destroyed before the weapons of all the
gods; Saṃvarta then said: “let the wind
blow and may it drive away the Vajra to the
directions; let there be rain and may it fall
on the forests; let waters float in the mid-
region and let there be lightning in the sky
(दिशो वज्रं व्रजतां वायुर् एतु वर्षं
भूत्वा निपततु काननेषु।आपः प्लवन्त्व्
अन्तरिक्षे वृथा च सौदामिनी दृश्यतां मा
बिभस् त्वम्॥) 14. 10. 13; (वज्रं तथा
स्थापयतां च वायुः) 14. 10. 14; Marutta
was still afraid of the sound of Vajra and of
the winds, and then Saṃvarta again assured
the king that he would become wind and
strike down the Vajra to dispel the king's
fear 14. 10. 15-16; (ii) Indra asked his
missile Vajra in the bodily form (मूर्तिसंस्-
थित) to turn into a tiger and kill Suvarṇa-
ṣṭhīvin, son of king Sṛñjaya, as he was
afraid of the prince's growing strength 12.
31. 27-28; when Vajra (वज्रः) was so
addressed, he began to look for a suitable
opportunity and when it arrived he, as tiger,
killed Suvarṇaṣṭhīvin; after killing the
prince, the tiger disappeared by the माया of
Indra 12. 31. 29-34; (iii) when the sage
Cyavana wanted to offer Soma to Aśvinā
Indra objected to it; in spite of the objec-
tion, when Cyavana was about to fill
the cup for the Aśvinā, Indra threatened
Cyavana to strike him with Vajra; when
Cyavana still proceeded to fill the cup, and
Indra was about to strike the Vajra, Cyavana
paralysed Indra's arm 3. 124. 8, 15-17; 14. 9.
31-32; 12. 329. 14(3); 3. Mythological
incidents: (i) Vṛtra episode: (a) in the
battle between the gods and Vṛtra, helped by
the Kālakeyas, Indra released his Vajra to kill
Vṛtra; when struck by the Vajra, Vṛtra was
killed 3. 99. 1-3, 13-14; however, Indra felt
as if he had not released the Vajra from his
hand and that Vṛtra was not killed 3. 99. 15;
(b) when the gods approached Viṣṇu for his
help in their fight against Vṛtra, Viṣṇu advised
them to establish peace for the time being
with Vṛtra, and when the proper time came he
would enter the Vajra of Indra 5. 10. 11-12;
Vṛtra was ready to make peace if he would
not be attacked by Indra or by the gods with
anything that was dry or wet, which was stone
or wood, which was a weapon (शस्त्र) or
Vajra, and if they would strike neither by
day nor by night 5. 10. 29; Indra killed Vṛtra
with foam which was fortified with Vajra;
Viṣṇu had entered that foam (सवज्रम्
अथ फेनं तं क्षिप्रं वृत्रे निसृष्ट-
वान्।प्रविश्य फेनं तं विष्णुर् अथ
वृत्रं व्यनाशयत्) 5. 10. 38; 3. 299. 15;
(c) Maheśvara told Indra to kill Vṛtra
with Vajra; Indra agreed 12. 272. 38-39; in
the fight that ensued, Indra came with Vajra
in his hand; he struck Vṛtra with Vajra; the
Vajra (m.) killed him; Viṣṇu had entered the
Vajra 12. 273. 5-7, 9; 12. 272. 31; 12. 274. 2;
(d) in the fight between Indra and Vṛtra,
when the latter covered the earth, Indra re-
leased his Vajra at him; Vṛtra then entered
successively water, fire, wind, and then ran
to ether (आकाश); each time Indra struck
him with Vajra; finally Vṛtra entered Śakra
(Indra); in that condition Indra struck Vṛtra
with an invisible Vajra (अदृश्येन वज्रेण)
14. 11. 6-19; (ii) Viśvarūpa-Triśiras
episode: (a) when the gods led by Indra
approached god Brahman complaining that
Viśvarupa (Triśiras), son of Tvaṣṭṛ, drank
away all Soma offered in sacrifices, and that
they were left without a share, Brahman
advised them to approach the sage Dadhīca
and request him to give up his body; the gods
should then fashion a Vajra from the bones
of Dadhīca 12. 329. 24-25; when Dadhīca
gave up his body, Dhātṛ fashioned a Vajra
out of the bones; with that Vajra, produced
from the bones of a Brāhmaṇa and in which
god Viṣṇu had entered, Indra killed Viśvarūpa
and cut off his heads 12. 329. 27; (b)
when Indra failed to tempt Triśiras, son of
Tvaṣṭṛ, with Apsarases while he was practis-
ing penance, he decided to strike Vajra at
him; when struck by Vajra, Triśiras fell down
like the summit of a mountain; Indra was
still afraid of Triśiras and he asked a wood-
cutter (तक्षन्) to cut off the heads of the
lying Triśiras assuring Takṣan that he would
make his axe Vajra-like (मत्प्रसादाद् धि
ते शस्त्रं वज्रकल्पं भविष्यति 5. 9. 27);
the woodcutter finally cut off the heads of
Triśiras with his axe 5. 9. 15-34; (iii) Meet-
ing of Bali and Indra: when Indra met Bali
in the form of a donkey (खर 12. 216. 12),
Bali told Indra that he could fell down Indra
with his fist although Indra was equipped with
Vajra, but that that was the time to show for-
bearance (क्षमा) and not valour (विक्रम)
12. 217. 38-39; 12. 220. 79-80; Indra told
Bali that since he was asked by god Brahman
not to kill Bali, he was not releasing his
Vajra at him (Bali) (12. 218. 33); Indra
asked Bali why he was not grieved although
he was formerly struck by Vajra 12. 220.
18; Bali told Indra that he was not afraid of
him (Indra) although he saw him with his
Vajra raised (वज्रम् उद्यम्य तिष्ठन्तम्)
12. 220. 21; Indra was surprised at the tran-
quility of Bali for he was not afraid of Indra
with Vajra raised in his hand 12. 220. 89;
(iv) Garuḍa episode: on his way to fetch
अमृत, when Garuḍa flew to the mountain
whose caves were blocked with snow, there
were bad omens for the gods; Indra's dear
missile Vajra blazed with pain (इन्द्रस्य
वज्रं दयितं प्रजज्वाल व्यथान्वितम्) 1.
26. 28; when Garuḍa was taking away अमृत,
Indra struck him with Vajra; Garuḍa smiled
and told Indra that just out of respect for the
sage (Dadhīca) from whose bones the Vajra
was fashioned, out of respect for Vajra itself,
and Indra, he would let fall just one of his
feathers; otherwise, due to the blow of the
missile, he felt no pain at all; surprised, Indra
sought friendship with Garuḍa 1. 29. 17-23;
(v) Fight between the gods and Skanda:
when during the fight between the gods and
Skanda, the gods abandoned Indra, he released
his Vajra at Skanda; it struck Skanda on his
right side and split it open; due to the impact
of Vajra was produced another young man
(पुरुषो ऽपरः।युवा) with golden armour,
wearing heavenly कुण्डलस्, and holding
शक्ति; he became Viśākha since he was pro-
duced due to वज्रविशन (यद् वज्रविशनाज्
जातो विशाखस् तेन सो ऽभवत्) 3. 216. 12-
14 [विशन ‘opening made by the Vajra’ ?
Nīla.: ‘digging up of the arm’ बाहोर्
आखननात् Bom. Ed. 3. 227. 17]; (vi)
Śiva and Indra: (a) Śiva, in the form of a
child in the lap of Umā, froze the arm of
Śakra which held Vajra (since apparently
Indra wanted to strike Vajra at the child
not realising that the child was Śiva); when
Brahmā and the other gods propitiated Śiva
(Rudra) and Umā, Indra's hand, holding the
Vajra, became as before 7. 173. 60-63; 13.
145. 30-34; (b) Indra once desirous to have
Maheśvara's glory hurled his Vajra at him;
it burnt Maheśvara's throat and departed;
that is why Śiva is called Śrīkaṇṭha (तेन
श्रीकण्ठता मम; Nīla. श्रकण्ठता = नील-
कण्ठता on Bom. Ed. 13. 127. 47) 13. 128.
8; (vii) Indra and Mandara: Mandara, son
of Hiraṇyakaśipu, fought with Indra for a
million years; due to the boon he had obtained
from Mahādeva (Śiva) Indra's Vajra was
shattered on the limbs of the “tormentor”
(ग्रह ?) Mandara 13. 14. 53-54 (Nī.
ग्रहस्य मन्दारनाम्नः on Bom. Ed.
13. 14. 75).
E. Knowledge of Vajra by
Arjuna and its use by him: Arjuna learnt
(अधीतवान्) the Vajra missile from Indra
(and other missiles from Yama, Kubera,
and Varuṇa) 3. 89. 12; (i) Mātali advised
Arjuna to use Indra's favourite missile
against the Nivātakavaca demons; Arjuna
released (उदीरय-) it after resorting to a
firm place (अचलं स्थानम् आसाद्य) and
after reciting the मन्त्रस् on the Gāṇḍīva
bow (गाण्डीवम् अनुमन्त्र्य च); the result
was that the sharp, iron arrows released from
his bow had the impact of Vajra (अमुञ्चं
वज्रसंस्पर्सान् आयसान् निशिताञ् शरान्);
the arrows, propelled by the Vajra and which
had themselves become Vajra-like (ते वज्र-
चोदिता बाणा वज्रभूताः) pierced the मायास्
of the demons and the demons themselves;
they all fell down on the ground when struck
by the impact (वेग) of Vajra; the arrows
killed also those demons who had entered the
ground 3. 169. 12-17; (ii) Arjuna used the
Vajra missile to kill the Saṃśaptaka warriors
who showered arrows at Kṛṣṇa and Arjuna
to completely cover them 7. 26. 19-20.
F. As standard of comparison; Various things
compared with Vajra: 1. arrows: of Arjuna
6. 114. 55, 57; 7. 68. 56; 7. 78. 10; 8. 21. 32;
8. 55. 3; 8. 67. 16; 14. 73. 29; 14. 78. 27;
of Arjuna and Karṇa 8. 65. 7; of Sātyaki
7. 91. 20; 7. 94. 14; 7. 95. 42; of Abhi-
manyu 6. 75. 24; of the Pāṇḍya king 8. 15. 8;
of Droṇa 7. 72. 30; of Bhūriśravas 6. 70. 9;
of Aśvasena 7. 171. 49; 2. गदा: of Bhīma
6. 58. 34; 7. 109. 11; 7. 110. 13 (गदा not
mentioned); 7. 152. 27; of Sātyaki 7. 169. 19;
of Karṇa 8. 27. 29; 3. चक्र of Kṛṣṇa 6. 55.
86; 4. मुसल: 16. 4. 35, 39, 37 (एरका);
5. Arjuna's banner with monkey on it 9.
3. 18; 6. strong built of Karṇa 8. 5. 11; of
the Pāṇḍya king 8. 15. 13; 7. strong arms
8. 23. 26; 8. hard heart 7. 50. 49; 8. 5. 24;
9. 2. 4; 12. 171. 23; 9. the Makaravyūha
6. 76. 5 (वज्रकुल्पः; Vajra = the missile or
the Vajravyūha ?) 10. sound produced while
fighting with different objects compared with
that of the Vajra: (i) sound produced by
arrows 7. 141. 21; (ii) by various wea-
pons 7. 141. 23; (iii) by गदा 9. 56. 60;
(iv) by summits of mountains hurled as
missiles 7. 153. 26; (v) by fists 7. 152.
44; (vi) by bow-string 5. 47. 47; 7. 73.
16; 9. 16. 14; 11. warriors or elephants
falling on the battle-field compared with the
mountains (or their summits) falling down
when struck by (Indra's) Vajra: (i) warriors
(or their heads, or head-gears) 6. 42. 19;
7. 53. 40; 8. 15. 38; 8. 40. 105; 8. 66. 17;
8. 66. 31 (only distressed); 8. 67. 26; 12. 27.
5 (only shaking); (ii) elephants (some-
times along with their riders) 4. 60. 10;
(4. 60. 12); 6. 58. 34; 6. 112. 35; 7. 28. 38;
7. 48. 43; 7. 66. 18; 7. 68. 51; 7. 123. 39; 8.
8. 44; 8. 12. 40; (8. 12. 44); 8. 13. 15; 8. 13.
20 (कुलिश); 8. 17. 27; 8. 14. 12; 8. 33. 51;
8. 43. 67; 8. 54. 5; 8. 59. 13; 8. 62. 43, 45, 46;
8. 68. 16; 9. 8. 27; 9. 19. 26; (iii) heroes
struck by arrows compared with trees struck
by Vajra 6. 70. 24; 6. 103. 91; 7. 172. 23;
12. fight between two heroes compared
with that between Vajra and the mountain:
between Bhīma and Jarāsandha 2. 21. 11;
between Yuyudhāna (Sātyaki) and the
Kauravas 5. 3. 15; between Pradyumna and
his opponents 5. 3. 19; between Ghaṭotkaca
and Alaṃbala 7. 149. 26; 13. fear, like
the burning Vajra, torments the timid ones
in the army 12. 103. 23.
G. Its use
for punishment and not as a missile:
(1) Sudhanvan warned Prahlāda that if,
in reply to a question, he told what was
false, Indra would pound his head with Vajra
into hundred pieces 2. 61. 63; (2) Bṛha-
spati told the gods what had been proclaimed
by Brahman in ancient times (पुरा गीतं
ब्रह्मणा 5. 12. 18): if one hands over
to the enemy the person who has sought
refuge, the gods with Indra strike him with
Vajra 5. 12. 21.
H. Status: The best
among the weapons (आयुधानां वरो वज्रः
(m.)) 4. 2. 13; an object of worship and
honour: (i) when Vajra struck Vṛtra's
head, it (the Vajra) was shattered into ten,
and then into hundred pieces; the gods shared
the pieces of Vajra among themselves and
worshipped them; (ii) whatever is efficaci-
ous in the world is supposed to have the
built of Vajra (लोके यत् साधनं किंचित्
सा वै वज्रतनुः स्मृता 1. 158. 48);
hence a Brāhmaṇa's hand is considered
to be made of Vajra, a Kṣatriya has his
chariot of Vajra, a Vaiśya's gift is as
efficacious as Vajra, and those junior to a
Vaiśya (the Śūdras) are supposed to have
Vajra's strength in their service; the horses
of a Kṣatriya are as good as Vajra and
hence they are inviolable (वज्रपाणिर् ब्राह्-
मणः स्यात् क्षत्रं वज्ररथं स्मृतम्।
वैश्या वै दानवज्राश् च कर्मवज्रा यवी-
यसः॥वज्रं क्षत्रस्य वाजिनो अवध्या
वाजिनः स्मृताः) 1. 158. 49-50; however,
Vajra made ineffectual when Nīlakaṇṭha
(Śiva) granted a boon to Nārāyaṇa that
Vajra will not have any effect on him 7.
172. 77-78.
II. As Kṛṣṇa's missile: Kṛṣṇa cut off
all the mountains hurled at him by a demon
fighting from the side of Śālva, with his
dear missile Vajra which was capable of
breaking all rocks (सर्वपाषाणभेदन)
3. 23. 17.
III. As Śiva's missile: Śiva is called
वज्रिन् 7. 172. 59; 13. 15. 11; 13. 17. 128;
and वज्रहस्त 13. 17. 70.
IV. Vajra as a general missile, not
associated with any individual: Many Vajras
were used during the fight between Bhīma
and Karṇa 7. 113. 20; Vajras were used by the
Rākṣasas of Ghaṭotkaca against the Kaurava
army 7. 154. 36; even the blades of grass
acted like Vajras when the time was ripe
(mode of expression) (पक्वानां हि वधे
सूत वज्रायन्ते तृणान्य् अपि) 7. 10. 47.

वज्र
Vajra2 m.: Name of a व्यूह (a parti-
cular arrangement of the army).
A. Origin: It was designed by Indra
(विहितं वज्रपाणिना) 6. 19. 7.
B. Des-
cription: highly invincible (परमदुर्-
जय) 6. 19. 7; (अजेयो मानुषे लोके) 6. 19.
35; immovable (अचल) 6. 19. 7; difficult
to penetrate (दुर्भिद), watching on all
sides (सर्वतोमुख), and terrible (घोर)
6. 19. 34.
C. Use in the epic war:
(1) Arjuna arranged the Pāṇḍava army
according to this Vyūha on the first day of
the war 6. 19. 6-7, 35; Bhīma led it
(भीमसेनो ऽग्रणीस् तेषाम्) 6. 19. 18,
(दृष्ट्वाग्रतो भीमसेनम्) 6. 19. 44,
(भीमसेनो … प्रचकर्ष महत् सैन्यम्)
6. 19. 32; 6. 19. 8, 9; also in the forefront
stood Dhṛṣṭadyumna, Nakula, Sahadeva, and
Dhṛṣtaketu; Nakula and Sahadeva acted as
the protectors of the wheels of Bhīma's
chariot (चक्ररक्षौ 6. 19. 20), and the
sons of Draupadī and Abhimanyu protected
Bhīma from behind (पृष्ठगोपाः 6. 19. 20);
Dhṛṣṭadyumna, helped by the Prabhadrakas,
offered protection to all of them (6. 19. 21);
the king (Virāṭa ?), surrounded by an army,
अक्षौहिणी strong, together with his brothers
and sons guarded them from behind;
Śikhaṇḍin, guarded by Arjuna, followed them;
Yuyudhāna (Sātyaki) protected Arjuna
from behind (पृष्ठगोप) and Yudhā-
manyu and Uttamaujas acted as his wheel-
protectors (चक्ररक्षौ); Yudhiṣṭhira, with
elephants, took position in the middle; the
Pāñcāla king Yajñasena with an army,
अक्षौहिणी strong, marched behind Virāṭa;
Dhṛṣṭadyumna, having moved from
his position, with his brothers and sons,
protected Yudhiṣṭhira from behind; hundreds
and thousands of foot-soldiers moved in the
front to protect Bhīmasena, while ten thou-
sand elephants followed Yudhiṣṭhira 6. 19.
18-31; according to 6. 22. 1-6, where the
name of the Vyūha is not mentioned but
the description of which apparently applies to
the arrangement of the Pāṇḍava army on the
first day, Yudhiṣṭhira himself directed the
contingents (अनीकानि) of his army to counter
the Vyūha (Sarvatobhadra) of Bhīṣma;
Śikhaṇḍin's contingent stood in the middle,
protected by Arjuna (also 6. 22. 14); Dhṛṣṭa-
dyumna's contingent was protected by Bhīma
himself; the contingent on the right side of the
Vyūha (अनीकं दक्षिणम्) was protected by
Yuyudhāna (Sātyaki); Yudhiṣṭhira's chariot
was stationed in the midst of elephants;
Bhīma, along with Nakula and Sahadeva, is
said to be the guard of the chariot of the hero
(वीररथस्य गोप्ता i. e. Arjuna ? Dhṛṣṭa-
dyumna ?), but his position seems to be in
the front of the army (सेनाग्रगतम्) 6.
22. 12-13; in many respects, this description
of the Vyūha agrees with that of the Vajra
given above (6. 19. 18-31); (2) On the
seventh day of the war Yudhiṣṭhira himself
used the Vajravyūha for his army (of which
no details are available) to counter the
Maṇḍalavyūha of the Kaurava army 6. 77. 21.

वसूनाम्
Vasūnām astram (or astrāṇi) nt.
(sg. or pl.): A missile (or missiles), not
named, special to the Vasus.
Arjuna was to learn them from the
Vasus after reaching the residence of Indra
3. 164. 29; Vasus agreed to give their missiles
to him 3. 164. 49-50. [See Vasūnāṃ
praharaṇam]

वसूनां
Vasūnāṃ praharaṇam nt.: The weapon
of the Vasus, not named.
When Garuḍa flew up from the moun-
tain top to fetch the Soma from the heaven,
bad omens occurred for the gods, one of them
being that the weapon of the Vasus clashed
with that of the Rudras, the Ādityas, the
Sādhyas, the Maruts and the other hosts of
gods (ये चान्ये देवतागणाः); such a
thing had never happened before 1. 26.
29-30. [See Vasūnām astram]

वायव्यास्त्र
Vāyavyāstra, (Vāyavya) nt. (rarely pl.
1. 225. 12): Name of a missile related to
god Vāyu 3. 164. 29; to Vāta 3. 161. 28;
to Mātariśvan 4. 56. 14.
A. Description: heavenly (दिव्य)
5. 181. 13; 7. 132. 28; best (उत्तम) 1. 218.
15; very fierce (सुदारुण) 6. 98. 20.
B. Its
knowledge: Arjuna learnt it from god Vāyu
when he, after satisfying Mahādeva (Śiva),
received it in the heaven along with many
other heavenly weapons 1. 225. 12 (pl.
वायव्यानि); 3. 164. 29; 3. 161. 28 (Vāta);
4. 56. 14 (Mātariśvan); 6. 116. 38; but
apparently he had also learnt it earlier
from Droṇa since he used it while displaying
his skill in archery (1. 125. 19), and at
the time of burning the Khāṇḍava forest
(1. 218. 15); Droṇa, of course, knew it,
and it was known to many other epic heroes,
viz. Bhīṣma, Droṇa, Karṇa, Aśvatthāman,
Yudhiṣṭhira, and the Pāṇḍya king (see the
next section); it was known also, perhaps, to
Kṛṣṇa 6. 116. 39.
C. Use: (1) In the epic
war: (i) by Arjuna, agaisnt the Trigartas;
noticing its employment, Droṇa repelled it
with the Śaila astra 6. 98. 18-20; against
the Saṃśaptakas, to scatter their shower of
arrows, when they covered Kṛṣṇa and Arjuna
with their arrows; the two, therefore, could
not be seen and were mistaken to be dead
7. 18. 17-22; god Vāyu carried away
the Saṃśaptakas together with their horses,
elephants, chariots and weapons like dried
leaves; they looked like birds flying from
trees 7. 18. 17-23; agaisnt Droṇa to repel
the Vāyavyāstra released by him 7. 163. 28
(here not specifically named: अस्तृआण्य् अस्त्रैर्
यदा तस्य विधिवद् धन्ति पाण्डवः);
against Karṇa, to scatter the clouds created
by his Vāruṇāstra 8. 67. 11; (ii) by
Droṇa, against Yudhiṣṭhira 7. 132. 28; again
against Yudhiṣṭhira, when Droṇa was for
a moment distressed by Yudhiṣṭhira's arrow
and had to sit down in the chariot 7. 137.
40-42; against the army of king Drupada
to blow it away, as wind blows away the
clouds 7. 136. 10; 7. 132. 37; against Arjuna
7. 163. 28; (iii) by Yudhiṣṭhira, to combat
successfully the same Astra used against him
by Droṇa (अस्त्रम् अस्त्रेण जघ्निवान्)
7. 132. 28; again to halt the same Astra used
against him by Droṇa (तद् अस्त्रम् अस्त्रेण
रणे स्तम्भयाम् आस) 7. 137. 42; (iv) by
Aśvatthāman, against Ghaṭotkaca to blow him
away (व्यधमत्) when Ghaṭotkaca em-
ployed his माया to become a dark cloud to
attack Aśvatthāman 7. 131. 71-72; (v) by
Karṇa, against Ghaṭotkaca under similar
conditions 7. 150. 70-71; (vi) by the
Pāṇḍya king, to obstruct (रुध्-) the shower
of arrows released by Aśvatthāman
on his army 8. 15. 30-31; (2) Outside the
epic war—(i) Arjuna used it by reciting
मन्त्रस् (अभिमन्त्र्य) to dispel the clouds
and the lightning created by Vāyu and Indra
at the time of burning the Khāṇḍava forest
1. 218. 15; Arjuna used it against Kirāta
(Śiva), but the missile had no effect on
him 3. 163. 29-30; against Droṇa at the
time of the cattle-raid to swallow the Vāya-
vyāstra used by Droṇa (वायव्यं …
अस्त्रम् अस्त्रेण पाण्डवः। … ग्रसते
स्म … ) 4. 53. 48; against Bhīṣma at the
time of the cattle raid 4. 59. 21; at the
time of displaying his skill in the use of
missiles 1. 125. 19; (ii) by Bhīṣma, against
Arjuna at the time of the cattle-raid 4. 59.
21; against Rāma Jāmadagnya who combated
it with the use of the Guhyakāstra 5. 181.
11; (iii) by Droṇa, against Arjuna at the
time of the cattle-raid 4. 53. 48; (iv) the
effect of the Vāyavyāstra was produced by
the Nivātakavaca demons by employing
their माया while fighting with Arjuna; it
produced wind, the velocity of which was
obstructed by Arjuna by the use of the Śaila
astra (शैलेन च महास्त्रेण वायोर् वेगम्
अधारयम्) 3. 168. 9-10; the demons again
practised their different मायास् simultaneously
(प्राकुर्वन् विविधा माया यौगपद्येन)
and produced the Astra of Vāyu (along
with that of Agni and the Aśmavarṣa); it
oppressed Arjuna and produced darkness all
around, which was dispelled by Arjuna
by employing his Astramāyā 3. 168.
11-13, 25-26.
D. Effects: Arjuna
created wind by the use of the Vāyavya astra
(वायव्येनासृजद् वायुम्) 1. 125. 19; the
wind that was released by the use of the
missile agitated the sky, felled the trees, and
killed soldiers 6. 98. 18-20; when used against
the Saṃśaptakas, god Vāyu (भगवान्
वायुः) swept them away together with their
horses, elephants, chariots and weapons, like
dried leaves; they appeared like birds flying
away from trees 7. 18. 22-23. [See
Vāyuvarṣa]

वायुवर्ष
Vāyuvarṣa nt.: A missile (?) of the
Nivātakavaca demons produced by their
माया।
The Nivātakavaca demons employed
their various मायास् simultaneously (प्राकुर्-
वन् विविधा माया यौगपद्येन) against
Arjuna which produced, besides other missiles,
the Vāyuvarṣa; it afflicted Arjuna; as a
result of the simultaneous use of these
missiles there was darkness all around 3. 168.
11-13; Arjuna used his Astramāyā to defeat
the मायास् of the demons 3. 168. 25-26;
earlier also the Nivātakavaca demons
had produced wind blowing with velocity
apparently by using the same Vāyuvarṣa
missile produced by the माया; Arjuna
obstructed the velocity of the wind (वायोर्
वेगम् अधारयम्) by using the Śaila astra
3. 168. 9-10. [See Vāyavyāstra]

वारुण
Vāruṇa1 adj. (pl.): of the Pāśas of
Varuṇa 12. 220. 18. [See Pāśa]

वारुण
Vāruṇa2 adj.: of Gāṇḍiva bow, originally
belonging to Varuṇa.
It is one of the three divine bows
belonging to celestial beings (दिव्यानि
धनूंषि दिविचारिणाम्), the other two
being Vijaya of Mahendra and Śārṅga of
Viṣṇu 5. 155. 5-6. [See Gāṇḍīva]

वारुण
Vāruṇa3 adj. (du.): of the two quivers
of Varuṇa.
Described as heavenly (दिव्यौ) 5. 59. 12,
(दिव्यरूपौ) 8. 57. 42; great (महेषुधी)
1. 216. 7; 5. 59. 12; 8. 57. 42; inexhaustible
(अक्षय्यौ) 1. 216. 7; (अक्षयौ) 5. 59.
12; 8. 57. 42; full of arrows (शरपूर्णौ)
5. 59. 12; Varuṇa gave them to Arjuna
at the time of burning the Khāṇḍava
forest (प्रादाद् वै … अक्षय्यौ च महेषुधी)
1. 216. 7; according to Karṇa, however, these
were given by Havyavāha (Agni) himself to
Arjuna (महेषुधी … हव्यवाहात्) 8. 57. 42.

वारुण
Vāruṇa4 adj.: of the conch Devadatta
2. 3. 7. [See Devadatta and Vāruṇa5]

वारुण
Vāruṇa5 adj.: of the conch of
Varuṇa (?).
Prajāpati in a previous age got it for
Indra; the ocean (कलशोदधि) brought it
for Yudhiṣṭhira for his anointment at the
Rājasūya (कलशोदधिः समुद्रः Nī. on
Bom. Ed. 2. 53. 15; however Nī. on Bom.
Ed. 2. 49. 26. कलश इव कलशो जलपूर्ण-
त्वात् समुद्रः। … अन्ये तु कलशोदधिः
समुद्रः); it was well-fashioned by
Viśvakarman and was set with a thousand
निष्कस् (सिक्तं निष्कसहस्रेण सुकृतं
विश्वकर्मणा); with this Vāruṇa conch
Kṛṣṇa anointed Yudhiṣṭhira 2. 49. 14-15;
however, according to 2. 45. 26-27 the ocean
(कलशोदधि) brought a Vāruṇa drinking
vessel made of brass (कांस्यं … वारु-
णं) to Yudhiṣṭhira; it was probably
brought in a sling made of a thousand
रुक्मस् and adorned with many jewels 2.
45. 26-27.

वारुणास्त्र
Vāruṇāstra, Vāruṇa astra nt.: Name
of the missile related to Varuṇa.
A. Description: heavenly (दिव्य) 5.
181. 13; 6. 116. 38; 7. 73. 46; 12. 5.
13-14; fierce (घोर) 7. 53. 43.
B.
Knowledge: (1) Droṇa knew the use of
the Vāruṇa astra 7. 166. 2; (2) Arjuna,
after reaching the residence of Indra, was to
learn the Astra from Varuṇa 3. 164. 29;
Arjuna told Uttara that he received the Vāruṇa
astra from Varuṇa 4. 56. 14; 7. 53. 43; 12. 5.
13-14; Vāruṇa astra included among the group
of missiles (अस्त्रग्रामः) known to Arjuna
5. 181. 11; according to Bhīṣma known only
to Arjuna, and perhaps to Kṛṣṇa 6. 116.
38-39; but it was apparently also known to
Rāma Jāmadagnya, Bhīṣma, Droṇa, Sātyaki,
Śikhaṇḍin, Yudhiṣṭhira (?) and Karṇa (see
the next section C);
C. Use: (1) In
the epic war: (i) by Droṇa: one of the
missiles used against Yudhiṣṭhira with the inte-
ntion of killing him (जिघांसुः) 7. 132. 29;
against Arjuna 7. 163. 28; (ii) by Arjuna:
used by Arjuna, according to prescriptions,
to repel the same (?) missile used by Droṇa
against him (मुक्तं मुक्तं द्रोणचापात्
तज् जघान धनंजयः॥अस्त्राण्य् अस्त्रैर्
यदा तस्य विधिवद् धन्ति पाण्डवः)
7. 163. 28-29; to protect Bhīma from the fire
of the Nārāyaṇāstra 7. 171. 1; (iii) Sātyaki
employed the Vāruṇa astra to pacify the
Āgneya astra, used by Droṇa (तद्
आग्नेयं महाघोरं रिपुघ्नम् उपलक्ष्य
सः।अस्त्रं दिव्यं महेष्वासो वारुणं
समुदैरयत् … अस्त्रे ते वारुणाग्नेये ताभ्-
यां बाणसमाहिते) 7. 73. 46, 48; (iv)
Śikhaṇḍin used it to repel a powerful missile
used agaisnt him by Śalya 6. 81. 25-27;
(v) Karṇa used this missile to extinguish the
fire caused by the Astra of Jātavedas
(Āgneyāstra) employed by Arjuna 8. 67. 10;
Arjuna nullified its effects by the Vāyavyāstra
8. 67. 11; (vi) Yudhiṣṭhira successfully
combated the different missiles-one of
them being Vāruṇa-used agaisnt him by
Droṇa by using the same (?) missiles
(तानि चास्त्राणि धर्मजः।जघानास्त्रैर्
महाबाहुः) 7. 132. 30. (2) Outside the
epic war: used by Rāma Jāmadagnya
against Bhīṣma to repulse his Āgneya
astra 5. 181. 12; (ii) Bhīṣma used this
missile against Śālva and with it crushed
the four horses of Śālva 1. 96. 37; against
Arjuna at the cattle-raid 4. 59. 21; (iii)
Arjuna used it against Bhīṣma on the same
occasion 4. 59. 21; Arjuna demonstrated it at
the time of showing his skill in the use of
missiles (अस्त्रलाघव) 1. 125. 18-19.
D.
Effects: (1) When Karṇa released the Vāruṇa
astra to pacify the fire of the Āgneyāstra, the
directions were covered with clouds and it
became dark (जीमूतैश्च दिशः सर्वाश् चक्रे
तिमिरदुर्दिनाः) 8. 67. 10; the clouds were
driven away by Arjuna by using the Vāyavyā-
stra 8. 67. 11; (2) when used by Arjuna to
cover Bhīma, who was surrounded by the
fire of the Nārāyaṇāstra (तेजसः प्रतिघा-
तार्थं वारुणेन समावृणोत्), Bhīma could
not be seen by others (नालक्षयत तं
कश्चिद् वारुणास्त्रेण संवृतम्) 7. 171.
1-2; when Kṛṣṇa and Arjuna went through
the fire produced by the Nārāyaṇāstra, it
did not burn them on account of the Vāruṇa
astra employed by Arjuna (as also due to
the prowess of Kṛṣṇa and Arjuna) 7. 171.
12; (3) at the time of the display of the
use of missiles, Arjuna produced water by
using Vāruṇa astra (वारुणेनासृजद् पयः)
1. 125. 19; for its use to combat the missiles
of others see the section C. E. Status:
Inferior to the Pāśupata astra 13. 14. 127.

वासवी
Vāsavī adj. (f.): of the unfailing
(अमोघा) Śakti of Vāsava (Indra) 3. 294.
34; 7. 122. 33; 7. 148. 34; 7. 158. 9, 10, 56,
58; (3. 286. 20). [See Śakti]

विचक्र
Vicakra nt.: Name of the weapon
(शस्त्र 1. 218. 31) of Śiva.
Śiva became ready with it when other
gods picked up their weapons to help Indra
in his fight with Kṛṣṇa and Arjuna at the
burning of the Khāṇḍava forest 1. 218. 31.

विजय
Vijaya1 nt.: Name of the bow of Indra.
A. History: It was fashioned by
Viśvakarman for the use of Indra 8. 22. 36;
Śakra (Indra) gave it to Bhārgava (Rāma
Jāmadagnya), and Rāma gave it to Karṇa
8. 22. 37-38, 40.
B. Description: Ancient
(पुरातन) 8. 45. 33; heavenly (दिव्य) 8.
22. 38, 46; large, larger than all weapons
(महत्, सर्वायुधमहामात्र) 8. 22. 46,
36; best, the best bow (उत्तम, धनुः-
श्रेष्ठ) 8. 22. 38, 45; 8. 45. 33; highly
honoured (परमसंमत) 8. 22. 37.
C. Use: (1) By Indra: Śatakratu (Indra)
conquered hosts of Daityas with it; due to
its sound the Daityas lost sense of directions
(यस्य घोषेण दैत्यानां विमुह्यन्ति
दिशो दश) 8. 22. 37; Rāma Jāmadagnya
narrated to Karṇa the divine acts (not
detailed) performed with Vijaya (by
Indra ?) 8. 22. 40; (2) By Rāma Jāma-
dagnya: Rāma conquered earth twentyone
times using Vijaya 8. 22. 39; (3) By Karṇa:
Karṇa wanted to use Vijaya while fighting
with Arjuna 8. 22. 38; Karṇa's desire for a
duel with Arjuna indicated by him by
stretching the bow-string of his Vijaya
(व्याक्षिपद् विजयं धनुः) 8. 42. 52;
Karṇa must have used it on other
occasions too; specific mention is found in
Karṇa's fight with Dhṛṣṭadyumna when,
while using, he shook it (विजयं तु धनुः-
श्रेष्ठं विधुन्वानः) 8. 42. 8; when
Duryodhana drew Karṇa's attention to the
rout of the Kaurava army, he strung
his Vijaya bow, wiped it (संमृज्य), and
discharged Bhārgavāstra from it 8. 45.
33-34.
D. Status: According to Karṇa
Vijaya was superior to Gāṇḍīva of Arjuna
(गाण्डीवात् तद् विशीष्यते) 8. 22. 39; 8. 22. 46.
[Apparently different from Vijaya2]

विजय
Vijaya2 nt.: Name of the bow of
Mahendra.
A. History: It belonged to Mahendra,
hence called माहेन्द्रं धनुः 5. 155.
4-5; Rukmin, the son of Bhīṣmaka Hiraṇya-
loman, received this Vijaya bow from his
teacher Druma, the lion among the Kiṃpuruṣas
living on the Gandhamādana mountain 5. 155.
7, 10, 3; when Rukmin moved with it, he, as
though, terrified the world (व्त्भीषयन्न् इव
जगत्) 5. 155. 10.
B. Description:
Divine (दिव्य) 5. 155. 4, 5; indestructible
(अक्षय) 5. 155. 4; producing sound like that
of a cloud (मेघसमस्वन) 5. 155. 10.
C. Status: Equal to Gāṇḍīva of Arjuna in
strength (तुल्यं गाण्डीवतेजसा) 5. 155. 4;
also comparable with Śārṅga bow of Viṣṇu
(शार्ङ्गेण च संमितम्) 5. 155. 4; Vijaya
was considered to be one of the three
heavenly bows of gods (the other two being
Gāṇḍiva of Varuṇa and Śārṅga of Viṣṇu) 5.
155. 5-6. [Apparently different from
Vijaya1]

विजय
Vijaya3 m.: Name of the trident (शूल)
of Rudra.
Present in the procession of Śiva to
Bhadravaṭa (after Skanda was anointed as
the सेनापति of the gods); in the procession,
Vijaya followed Yama; and Vijaya, in turn,
was followed by Varuṇa and his acquatic
creatures, as also by the पट्टिश of Rudra;
Vijaya is described as fierce (घोर), sharp
(शित), having three points (त्रिशिखर), and
well-decorated (स्वलङ्कृत) 3. 221. 10-12, 1.

विशोषण
Viśoṣaṇa nt.: Name of a missile.
Described as heavenly (दिव्य), fierce
(घोर), and burning (दीप्त); it was taught
by Indra to Arjuna; Arjuna used it to dry up
the torrential rain-water released with माया
by the Nivātakavaca demons 3. 168. 8.

वैजयन्ती
Vaijayantī f. (du.): Name of the two
bells of Airāvata, the elephant of Indra.
Śakra (Indra) gave them to Guha
(Skanda), as a toy (क्रीडनक) to play with;
one of the two bells was with Viśākha, the
other remained with Skanda 3. 220. 18-20.

वैष्णव
Vaiṣṇava1 adj.: of the Cakra belonging
to Viṣṇu.
In the world of Varuṇa, the Cakra,
permeated by smokeless fire, lay in his
lake (वरुणह्रदे।वैष्णवं चक्रम्
आविद्धम् विधूमेन हविष्मता) 5. 96. 18.
[See Sudarśana, Āgneyāstra]

वैष्णव
Vaiṣṇava2 adj.: of the bow Śārṅga
belonging to Viṣṇu.
One of the three divine bows, described
as lustrous (तेजोमय), (the other two being
Vāruṇa Gāṇḍiva and Māhendra Vijaya)
5. 155. 5-6. [See Śārṅga]

वैष्णवास्त्र
Vaiṣṇavāstra, Vaiṣṇava (astra): nt.
(sg.; pl. 3. 164. 30) Name of a missile
belonging to Viṣṇu (तद् अस्त्रं पार्थ
मामकम् 7. 28. 33).
A. History: In the bygone days, Earth
(पृथिवी, जगती, क्षमा) asked for her son
Naraka the following boon from the fourth
form of Kṛṣṇa (Viṣṇu) which wakes up once
after thousand years: “May he be equipped
with the Vaiṣṇavāstra so that he cannot be
killed by the gods and the Asuras”; accord-
ingly Viṣṇu gave the missile to Naraka and
said: “May this missile be unfailing in
protecting Naraka; no one shall kill him;
protected by the missile, Naraka will be
unassailable in the worlds for all times”;
from Naraka, the missile went to Prāgjyotiṣa
(Bhagadatta) 7. 28. 26-33.
B. Descrip-
tion: heavenly (दिव्य) 6. 116. 38; great
missile (परमास्त्र) 7. 28. 34; unfailing
(अमोघ) 7. 28. 29, 30; killer of all
(सर्वघातक) 7. 28. 17.
C. Know-
ledge: Indra told Arjuna to go to his residence
in the heaven to learn all the Vaiṣṇava
missiles (वैष्णवानि च सर्वाणि) together
with other heavenly missiles 3. 164. 29-30;
according to Bhīṣma, all the heavenly missiles
including the Vaiṣṇava astra, known to
Arjuna and perhaps to Kṛṣṇa, and to no one
else in the world of the mortals (सर्वस्मिन्
मानुषे लोके वेत्त्य् एको हि धनंजयः।
कृष्णो वा देवकीपुत्रो नान्यो वै वेद
कश्चन) 6. 116. 38-39.
D. Use in
the epic war: Bhagadatta, wishing to
release the Vaiṣṇavāstra (उदीरयन्) recited
मन्त्रस् (अभिमन्त्र्य) on his hook
(अङ्कुश) and hurled it aiming it on Arjuna's
chest; Kṛṣṇa covered Arjuna and received the
missile on his chest, where it turned into the
garland Vaijayantī 7. 28. 16-18; since there
was no one in the worlds, including even Indra
and Rudra, who could not be killed by the
missile, Kṛṣṇa covered Arjuna to save him
(नास्यावध्यो ऽस्ति लोकेषु सेन्द्ररुद्रेषु
मारिष) 7. 28. 33-34.

व्याल
Vyāla m.: Name (?) of a particular
kind of the arrangement of army (व्यूह).
On the fourth day of the war the Kau-
ravas arranged their army according to this
Vyūha; Bhīṣma led it, and he was followed
all around by Droṇa, Duryodhana, Bāhlika
(Somadatta), Durmarṣaṇa, Citrasena, Jayad-
ratha and other kings with their armies;
the Kaurava army looked like the sky full
of clouds at the advent of the rainy season;
that army, protected by Bhīṣma, rushed
towards Arjuna like a mighty current of a
river; its great strength lay concealed in
various ways and it had a large number of
elephants, horses, foot-soldiers and chariots
on either side (तं व्यालनानाविधगू-
ढसारां गजाश्वपादातरथौघपक्षम्।
व्यूहम् … ॥ Nī. व्यालो व्यूहविशेषस् तेन
नानाविधं गूढसारं च on Bom. Ed.
6. 60. 7) 6. 56. 1-7; it appears that this
Vyūha was opposed by the Pāṇḍavas with
their Ardhacandravyūha (not directly
mentioned) which they had adopted on the
previous day and in which the Pāñcāla and
the Cedi chiefs took their positions as before
(यथा हि पूर्वे ऽहनि धर्मराज्ञा व्यूहः
कृतः कौरवनन्दनेन।तथा तथोद्देशम्
उपेत्य तस्थुः पाञ्चालमुख्यैः सह
चेदिमुख्याः) 6. 56. 11.

व्यूह
Vyūha m.: A particular way of arrang-
ing the army for war; most of the Vyūhas
used by the Kauravas and the Pāṇḍavas are
named (Ardhacandra, Krauñca, Garuḍa,
Cakra, Cakraśakaṭa, Candrārdha, Padma,
Parānīkabhid (?), Bārhaspatya, Makara,
Maṇḍala, Maṇḍalārdha, Mahāvyūha, Vajra,
Vyāla (?), Śakaṭa (= Cakraśakaṭa), Śṛṅgāṭaka,
Śyena, Sarvatobhadra and Sūcī).
Some of the Vyūhas used by the two
sides on certain days are neither described
in detail nor named; on the other hand,
details of those used by the two sides on the
tenth day of the war are available, but they
are not named. (1) The Vyūha used by
the Pāṇḍavas: Described as overpowering
all the foes (सर्वशत्रुनिबर्हण) 6. 104.
4; Śikhaṇḍin was in the front of the entire
army (सर्वसैन्यानाम् अग्र आसीत्); Bhīma-
sena and Dhanaṃjaya acted as the protectors
of his wheel (चक्ररक्षौ); behind them
marched the sons of Draupadī and Abhi-
manyu, Sātyaki and Cekitāna; Dhṛṣṭadyumna,
guarded all around by the Pāñcāla army,
acted as their protector; behind them was
Yudhiṣṭhira with Nakula and Sahadeva;
behind them moved Virāṭa surrounded by
his own army, and he was followed by
Drupada; the five Kekaya brothers and
Dhṛṣṭaketu guarded the rear (जघनं
पालयाम् आस) 6. 104. 3-10; this Vyūha
could be one of the Mānuṣa, Daiva,
Gāndharva or Āsura Vyūhas known to
Dhṛṣṭadyumna 5. 56. 11; (2) The counter-
Vyūha of the Kauravas used on that day:
the entire Kaurava army was led by Bhīṣma
(अग्रटः सर्वसैन्यानाम्); he was guarded
by the sons of Dhṛṭarāṣṭra; they were
followed by Droṇa and his son Aśvatthāman;
Bhagadatta, with his army of elephants,
followed them; Kṛpa and Kṛtavarman followed
Bhagadatta; next came Sudakṣiṇa, the king
of the Kāmbojas, Jayatsena, the king of the
Magadhas, and Bṛhadbala, the son of Subala;
other kings headed by Suśarman guarded
the rear (जघनं पालयाम् आसुः)
6. 104. 15; similarly, during the war
at night (between the fourteenth and
the fifteenth day), the Kaurava army
was rearranged (पुनर् व्यूहम् अकल्-
पयत् 7. 138. 10) by Duryodhana (?, by
Droṇa ?); this Vyūha is also not named;
Droṇa was in the front, Aśvatthāman and
Śakuni on either side, and Śalya in the rear;
Duryodhana himself protected all the wings
of the army 7. 138. 11; this Vyūha in which
the chariots, horses, and elephants took up
their positions looked like (the armies in)
the Vyūha of the gods and the demons
7. 138. 32.

शकटव्यूह
Śakaṭavyūha m.: Name of a व्यूह
(a particular arrangement of the army)
7. 6. 15.
Droṇa arranged the Kaurava army in the
form of the Śakaṭavyūha on the eleventh day
of the war; Jayadratha, the Kaliṅga king (not
named), and Vikarṇa stood on the right side
(दक्षिण पार्श्व); at the extremity of the
right wing (प्रपक्ष) was Śakuni, assisted
by excellent horsemen from the Gandhāra
country who fought with sharp प्रासस्; Kṛpa,
Kṛtavarman, Citrasena, and Viviṃśati, with
Duḥśāsana to lead them (दुःशासनमुखाः),
stood on its left side (सव्य पार्श्व); at the
extremity of the left wing (प्रपक्ष) stood
the Kāmbojas, led by Sudakṣiṇa, who fought
on horses, as also the Śakas and the Yavanas;
apparently in between the two sides were
stationed the Madras, the Trigartas, the
Ambaṣṭhas, warriors who came from the west
and the north, the Śibis, the Śūrasenas, the
Śūdras, the Maladas, the Sauvīras, and the
Kitavas, all of whom were led by Duryo-
dhana (तवात्मजं पुरस्कृत्य); Karṇa
took position in front of Duryodhana
and was at the head of all the archers
(प्रमुखे सर्वधन्विनाम्) 7. 6. 1-8;
in this Vyūha, Karṇa was in front of the army
(तावकानां मुखं कर्णः) 7. 6. 21;
from the description of the start of that
day's battle it is clear that Droṇa also stood
at the head of the army 7. 6. 32-36; this
Vyūha of the Kauravas was opposed by the
Pāṇḍavas with the Krauñcavyūha 7. 6. 15.
[See Cakraśakaṭa]

शक्ति
Śakti1 f.: A missile special to Vāsava
(Indra), hence called वासवी 3. 294. 34;
7. 122. 33; 7. 148. 34; 7. 158. 9, 10, 56,
58; given by Vāsava 3. 286. 20; 7. 154. 50;
7. 155. 21; or by Śakra (Indra) 3. 294. 1ff.;
7. 154. 53, 58 (शक्रशक्ति); 7. 155. 27;
1. 7. 156. 27; 7. 157. 4.
A. Description: unfailing (अमोघा)
3. 286. 14; 3. 294. 20, 21, 24, 29, 33; 7. 157.
7, 12, 16, 29; heavenly (दिव्या) 8. 5. 65;
best, excellent (श्रेष्ठा) 7. 154. 52;
(उत्तमा) 7. 154. 55; (परमा) 7. 157. 6;
(प्रवरा) 3. 294. 29; honoured (सत्कृता) 7.
154. 53; (पूज्यमाना) 7. 122. 33; irresisti-
ble (अनिवार्या) 7. 158. 2; unbearable (असह्या)
7. 154. 52; 7. 158. 2; burning, shining (like a
lightning) (प्रज्वलन्ती) 7. 122. 33; (ज्व-
लन्ती) 7. 154. 57; (प्रज्वलिता) 3. 294. 35;
(प्रदीप्ता) 7. 154. 54; दीप्यमाना 7. 148. 34;
7. 154. 57; (विद्युत्प्रभा) 8. 5. 65; deco-
rated with gold (कनकभूषणा) 8. 5. 65;
victorious (वैजयन्ती) 7. 154. 52; the
highway to victory (जयस्य च परायणम्)
7. 157. 6; killer of one opponent (when used
by Karṇa) (एकघ्नी) 7. 158. 2; destroyer of
the body of the enemy (परकायापहन्त्री)
7. 154. 55; killer of many enemies (when
used by Indra) (द्विषतां हन्त्री)
8. 5. 65; (अमित्रविनिबर्हिणी) 3. 286. 14;
(शत्रुसङ्घानां घातिनीम्) 3. 294. 21;
having a terrible form (रौद्ररूपं
बिभर्ति च) 7. 148. 34.
B. Exchanged
by Indra for Karṇa's armour and ear-rings:
God Sūrya advised Karṇa to obtain from
Indra his unfailing Śakti in exchange for
(नियमेन) the armour (कवच) and
the ear-rings (कुण्डलस्) which Indra
would ask Karṇa to part with 3. 286.
14-15; after receiving this hint, Karṇa long-
ing for the Śakti waited for Vāsava (Indra)
3. 286. 20; when Indra came and begged
Karṇa of his कवच and कुण्डलस्, Karṇa
asked Indra's unfailing Śakti in return 3. 294.
20-21; Indra agreed to part with his Śakti
under the stipulation that although the Śakti,
when used by Indra, would unfailingly kill
Indra's enemies ब्य् हुन्द्रेद्स् and return to
Indra's (user's) hand, when it reached Karṇa
it would kill only ओने illustrious, roaring and
tormenting enemy of Karṇa and return, not to
Karṇa, but to Indra (सेयं तव करं प्रा-
प्य हत्वैकं रिपुम् ऊर्जितम्।गर्जन्तं
प्रतपन्तं च माम् एवैष्यति सूतज॥)
3. 294. 23-25; the Śakti, as long as it was
with Karṇa, would fail after killing one hero
and would lose its quality of being unfailing
(एकवीरवधे मोघा) 7. 157. 1, 7; (अमो-
घाया विघातार्थम्) 7. 157. 12; Karṇa
agreed to receive the Śakti on that condition
for he feared danger in battle only from one
enemy 3. 294. 26, 29; Indra also warned
Karṇa not to use the Śakti when other missiles
were available with him and when he was
not in danger; if used negligently the
Śakti would boomerang on Karṇa (विद्य-
मानेषु शस्त्रेषु यद्य् अमोघाम् असंशये।
प्रमत्तो मोक्ष्यसे चापि त्वय्येवैषा
पतिष्यति॥) 3. 294. 33; Karṇa vowed to
Indra (सत्यम् एतद् ब्रवीमि ते) that
he would release the Vāsavī (Śakti) only
when he was in great danger 3. 294. 34;
Karṇa then received the burning Sakti in
exchange of his कवच and कुण्डलस् 3. 294.
35, 38; 8. 5. 65.
C. What the Śakti meant
to Karṇa: Karṇa had great confidence due to
the Śakti (अयं च प्रत्ययः कर्णे शक्त्या)
7. 157. 31; when Vāsava (Indra) gave the
Śakti to Karṇa, he (Karṇa) felt that Arjuna
was as good as dead 7. 155. 21-22; with
Śakti in Karṇa's hand, no one in the world
dare oppose him 7. 155. 13; Karṇa had
preserved the Śakti to kill Arjuna 7. 122. 33;
7. 148. 34; 7. 154. 53; the Śakti meant
death for Arjuna 7. 157. 38; Duḥśāsana,
Śakuni, Jayadratha and Duryodhana always
counselled Karṇa not to use the Śakti against
any one except Arjuna 7. 157. 32-34; (cf.
7. 157. 19-21 for the use of Śakti (not named)
only against Arjuna or Kṛṣṇa); if on any
occasion Karṇa's other missiles had failed and
if he was pressed (पीडितः) by the circums-
tances, he would certainly have used his
Vāsavī Śakti against Arjuna 7. 158. 54;
hence Kṛṣṇa protected Arjuna particularly
from the unfailing Śakti which, if released,
would certainly have killed him like the light-
ning striking down a tree 7. 157. 16;
according to Vyāsa too if Arjuna and
Karṇa had clashed, the latter, after exhaus-
ting all other missiles, would have surely
used Vāsavī against Arjuna 7. 158. 56;
Kṛṣṇa was therefore always looking for a
way to render the unfailing Śakti futile
(अमोघां तां कथं शक्तिं मोघां
कुर्याम्) 7. 157. 29; when the Śakti was
diverted on Ghaṭotkaca, Karṇa, in the
opinion of Kṛṣṇa, was as good as dead
7. 155. 12; when Karṇa was relieved
of his Śakti, he became an ordinary
human being (सो ऽद्य मानुषतां
प्राप्तो विमुक्तः शक्रदत्तया 7. 155. 27),
and Arjuna could dare attack him 8. 22. 33.
D. Why the Śakti was not used against
Arjuna: Both Dhṛtarāṣṭra and Sātyaki asked
Saṃjaya and Kṛṣṇa respectively why the Śakti
was not used by Karṇa against Arjuna 7.
157. 1; 7. 158. 2-3; 7. 157. 31; (1) accor-
ding to Saṃjaya's reporting, Duryodhana,
Śakuni, Duḥśāsana, and he himself urged
Karṇa every night after the day's war to use
his Śakti the next day against Arjuna or
Kṛṣṇa (7. 157. 19-21), but that counsel was
forgotten the next day during the fight due
to the watchfulness of Kṛṣṇa (सा तु बुद्धिः
कृताप्य् एवं जाग्रति त्रिदशेश्वरे।अप्रमेये
हृषीकेशे युद्धकाले व्यमुह्यत) 7. 157. 27;
Kṛṣṇa also never brought Arjuna face to face
with Karṇa as long as the latter was equipped
with Śakti; Kṛṣṇa managed to see that
other warriors faced Karṇa 7. 157. 28-29;
according to Saṃjaya, again, the previous
night's counsel (7. 158. 4-5) was forgotten
by Karṇa the next day due to the deities
(unfavorable) to him and to the other heroes
(on the side of the Kauravas), and thus
it was primarily due to the working of the
fate that Karṇa did not employ his Śakti
against Arjuna or Kṛṣṇa to kill any one of
them (ततः प्रभातसमये राजन् कर्णस्य
दैवतैः।अन्येषां चैव योधानां सा
बुद्धिर् नश्यते पुनः॥दैवम् एव परं
मन्ये यत् कर्णो हस्तसंस्थया।न
जघान रणे पार्थं कृष्णं वा देवकी-
सुतम्॥ 7. 158. 6-7; also 8-9; (2) accor-
ding to Vyāsa too it was due to fate
(दिष्ट्या) that Arjuna was not locked in
a duel with Karṇa prior to the latter's being
relieved of the Śakti 7. 158. 54; according
to him Ghaṭotkaca was killed by Time
using Vāsavī as his means (वासवीं
कारणं कृत्वा कालेनापहतो ह्य् असौ)
7. 158. 58; (3) according to Kṛṣṇa he
deluded the mind of Karṇa and hence he did
not use his Śakti against Arjuna (अहम्
एव तु राधेयं मोहयामि युधां वर
7. 157. 37; (4) according to Dhṛtarāṣṭra
both fate and the intelligence of Kṛṣṇa
came together to defeat the purpose of the
Kauravas and hence the Vāsavī (Śakti)
killed Ghaṭotkaca instead of Arjuna
(दैवेनैव हता यूयं स्वबुद्ध्या
केशवस्य च।गता हि वासवी हत्वा
तृणभूतं घटोत्कचम्) 7. 158. 10.
E. Use: (1) By Karṇa: All the Kuru
warriors urged Karṇa to kill the demon
Ghaṭotkaca by using the Śakti given to him
by Vāsava and save the Kauravas and their
warriors from destruction; hearing that call,
Karṇa held the Śakti desiring to kill Ghaṭot-
kaca, that Śakti given to him by Śakra
and which he had preserved for Arjuna
for years; when the missile was released,
Ghaṭotkaca, afraid, assumed a huge form
of the foot of the Vindhya mountain and
fled; the beings in the mid-region wailed
at the sight of the Śakti; the released Śakti
first burnt the माया of Ghaṭotkaca, and
then broke open deeply the chest of Ghaṭot-
kaca and went up in the sky, shining at night,
to enter the spaces between the नक्षत्रस्
(ऊर्ध्वं ययौ दीप्यमाना निशायां
नक्षत्राणाम् अन्तराण्य् आविशन्ती 7. 154. 57);
Ghaṭotkaca, with his vitals pierced by the
Śakti, was killed 7. 154. 48-59; 7. 156. 24;
7. 158. 10; 8. 5. 71; by asking Ghaṭotkaca
to fight with Karṇa, Kṛṣṇa diverted the Śakti
on him 7. 156. 27; 7. 157. (5), 6, 39;
7. 155. 12, 14; (Kṛṣṇa said that if
Karṇa had not killed Ghaṭotkaca with his
Śakti, he would have killed Ghaṭotkaca
7. 156. 25); (2) By Indra: When used
by Indra while fighting with the Daityas,
the Śakti, after killing his enemies by hun-
dreds, returned to Indra's hand 3. 294. 24;
3. 286. 16 (killing of the enemies by
hundreds and thousands). [See Śakti2-5]

शक्ति
Śakti2 f., Śaktyastra nt.: missile of
Skanda.
Described as terrific (भीमम् nt.) 9.
45. 60, (सुघोरा f.) 9. 45. 62; its association
with Skanda noticed when it is described that
in the entourage of Śiva, Skanda, on his
peacock, stood on the side of Devī,
holding Śakti on his neck (शक्तिम् कण्ठे
समादाय) 13. 14. 143; it was used by
Skanda against the demon Tāraka and his
associates; Skanda released it again and again,
imbibing it with his own lustre (आदधच्
चात्मनो तेजः 9. 45. 60); when released, the
flame of the meteor and resounding thunder-
bolts struck the earth as would happen at the
time of the end of the world; when one
Śakti was hurled by Skanda, crores of Śaktis
fell out from it; Skanda killed with his
missile the demons Tāraka, Mahiṣa, Tripāda
and Hradodara together with innumerable
Daityas; they were burnt by the flames
of the Śaktyastra 9. 45. 60-70. [See
Śakti1, 3-5]

शक्ति
Śakti3 f.: Missile, special to Viśākha.
When Viśākha came out of the right side
of Skanda's body he appeared armed with
Śakti (शक्तिधृक्) 3. 216. 13. [See
Śakti1-2, 4-5]

शक्ति
Śakti4 f.: Missile of Kṛṣṇa.
Along with other missiles and weapons
(प्रहरणानि), Śakti appeared on one of the
arms of Kṛṣṇa when he manifested his fierce
form in the Sabhā of the Kauravas 5. 129.
9-10; Kṛṣṇa asked his charioteer Dāruka to
place in his chariot the divine (दिव्या) Śakti
when the chariot was to be made ready for
Kṛṣṇa's eventual intervention in the war 7.
56. 32 [See Śakti1-3, 5]

शक्ति
Śakti5 f.: Missile of Aṃśa.
When Indra got ready to fight with Kṛṣṇa
and Arjuna at the time of burning the
Khāṇḍava forest, Aṃśa, to help Indra, picked
up his Śakti 1. 218. 33. [See Śakti1-4]

शतघण्टा
Śataghaṇṭā1 f.: Name of the गदा of
Ghaṭotkaca (or adj. of his गदा, meaning
‘decorated with a hundred bells’ ?).
Described as bright like burning fire,
decorated, adorned with gold ornaments and
making loud noise (दीप्ताग्निसंकाशा,
अलंकृता, काञ्चनभूषणा, महास्वना);
Ghāṭotkaca, when struck on his head by
Alāyudha with a huge परिघ, hurled at his
opponent his Śataghaṇṭā गदा which crushed
Alāyudha's horses, chariot, and the charioteer
7. 153. 13-14. [See Śataghaṇṭā2]

शतघण्टा
Śataghaṇṭā2 f.: Name of the गदा of
Vibhīṣaṇa (or adj. of his गदा, meaning
‘decorated with a hundred bells’ ?).
Described as large (विपुला), of great
strength (महाशक्ति); when Vibhīṣaṇa was
struck by Prahasta with a गदा, he took up
his Śataghaṇṭā गदा and after reciting
मन्त्रस् over it (अभिमन्त्र्य), threw it on
Prahasta's head; the गदा, falling swiftly
with the rear of a lightning, cut off the head
of Prahasta 3. 270. 2-4. [See Śataghaṇṭā1]

शरवर्ष
Śaravarṣa nt.: Name of a missile (so
called because it produced, when released, a
shower of arrows ?).
Used, among other missiles (अस्त्रपूग
3. 163. 31) by Arjuna against Kirāta
(Śiva); Śiva swallowed all those अस्त्रस्
(जग्रास … तानि सर्वाण्य् अस्त्राणि) 3. 163. 32.
[See Śarolbaṇa]

शरोल्बण
Śarolbaṇa nt.: Name of a missile (so
called because it produced, when released,
excessive number of arrows ?).
Used, among other missiles (अस्त्रपूग
3. 163. 31) by Arjuna against Kirāta (Śiva);
Śiva swallowed all those अस्त्रस् (जग्रास …
तानि सर्वाण्य् अस्त्राणि) 3. 163. 32. [See
Śaravarṣa].

शाक्र
Śākra astra nt.: See Aindrāstra.

शार्ङ्ग
Śārṅga nt.: Name of the bow of Viṣṇu,
Kṛṣṇa (शार्ङ्गं तु वैष्णवं प्राहुः …
धारयाम् आस यत् कृष्णः 5. 155. 6).
A. Acquisition: In his fight against
Naraka, Kṛṣṇa cut off the nooses of the
demon Muru, killed him, then conquered the
demon Naraka, son of Bhūmi (भौम),
and brought back with him the jewelled
कुण्डलस्, sixteen thousand excellent women
and various jewels; he then received the best
Śārṅga bow (प्रतिपेदे हृषीकेशः शार्ङ्गं
च धनुर् उत्तमम्) 5. 155. 8-9.
B. Des-
cription: heavenly (दिव्य) 5. 155. 6; 3. 21.
24 (धनुषा दिव्येन not named); splendid
(रुचिर) 3. 23. 1; best (उत्तम) 5. 155. 9;
lustrous (तेजोमय) 5. 155. 6; causing fear to
the army of the enemy (परसेनाभयावह)
5. 155. 6.
C. Association with Kṛṣṇa: As
Kṛṣṇa's bow, it is mentioned among the
weapons placed on his chariot when he started
from the Khāṇḍavaprastha to Dvārakā 2. 2.
12; Kṛṣṇa asked his charioteer Dāruka to
place the bow (not named) in his chariot
when it was to be made ready for Kṛṣṇa's
eventual intervention in the war 7. 56. 32;
Śārṅga bow, along with conch, disc, mace and
Śakti appeared on Kṛṣṇa's different arms
when he manifested his fierce form, as a great
wonder, in the Sabhā of the Kauravas 5. 129.
9-10; Kṛṣṇa (and Viṣṇu) have epithets like
शार्ङ्गधन्वन् 3. 120. 6; 3. 189. 30; 5. 73.
2; 5. 135. 30; 6. 61. 35; 7. 9. 71; 8. 5. 16
(शार्ङ्ग° °धन्वन्); 10. 13. 6, 9; 12. 200.
6; 13. 135. 120; 14. 52. 6; 16. 9. 14; शार्ङ्ग-
धनुर्धर 6. 61. 45; शार्ङ्गरथाङ्गपाणि
6. 55. 94; शार्ङ्गगदाधर 2. 41. 33;
शार्ङ्गचक्रगदाधर 2. 42. 34; 16. 4. 44;
शार्ङ्गचक्रासिपाणि 12. 43. 16.
D. Use:
Kṛṣṇa used it in his fight with Śālva;
Kṛṣṇa's arrows released from Śārṅga first
failed to reach the Saubhapura of Śālva 3.
21. 18; he again released अयुतस् of arrows
against Śālva from his heavenly bow 3. 21.
24; the arrows released from Śārṅga pierced
the bodies of the demons in the Saubhapura
and they fell down in the ocean 3. 21. 28;
due to the माया of Śālva, Kṛṣṇa saw the
son of Śūra (Vasudeva) falling down from
the Saubha; as a result, he was confused and
the Śārṅga slipped down from his hand 3.
22. 22-25; when Kṛṣṇa knew the truth, he
picked up the splendid bow and shot arrows
from it which cut off the heads of the
enemies 3. 23. 1-2.
E. Status: The
Śārṅga bow of Viṣṇu counted among the only
three heavenly bows of divine beings, the
other two being Gāṇḍiva of Varuṇa and
Vijaya of Mahendra (त्रीण्य् एवैतानि दिव्यानि
धनूंषि दिविचारिणाम्) 5. 155. 5; hence the
Vijaya bow obtained by Rukmin is said to
be comparable with the Śārṅga 5. 155. 4.

शिबिका
Śibikā f.: Name of a weapon (शस्त्र)
of Kubera.
When Indra started for the fight with
Kṛṣṇa and Arjuna at the time of the burning
of the Khāṇḍava forest, Dhaneśvara (Kubera)
picked up his Śibikā to help him 1. 218. 31.
(According to a view cited by Nīlakaṇṭha,
शिबिका means गदा। Nīlakaṇṭha's reading is
गदां चैव, but he adds शिबिकाम् इति पाठे
शिबिका गदेति प्राञ्चः on Bom. Ed. 2. 227.
32). [See Antardhāna2; Kaubera astra in
the Addenda].

शुक
Śuka nt.: Name of a missile.
One of the eight missiles known to
Arjuna; enumerated by Rāma Jāmadagnya
for the information of Duryodhana; Arjuna
was likely to employ these missiles during the
war 5. 94. 38; for the effects produced by
these missiles see Akṣisaṃtarjana.

शूल
Śūla m.: A missile (अस्त्र 13. 14. 131,
136), specially related to Śiva (Rudra)
but also to Naṇdi(n), and Viṣṇu (Kṛṣṇa).
I. Missile of Śiva: Upamanyu saw Śiva
together with his missiles in bodily form
(मूर्तिमन्ति तथास्त्राणि सर्वतेजोमयानि
च।मया दृष्टानि गोविन्द भवस्यामित-
तेजसः 13. 14. 121), one of them being
the one which is known as Śūla in the three
worlds 13. 14. 131; hence Śiva (Rudra)
has epithets like शूलपाणि 1. 44. 22; 3. 40.
34; 3. 81. 71; 3. 104. 11; 3. 163. 43; 3.
261. 54; 5. 188. 7; 7. 64. 15; 9. 31. 38;
12. 122. 34; 12. 160. 48; 12. 283. 16; 13.
14. 132, 172; 13. 15. 11; 13. 61.
45; 13. 83. 40; 13. 127. 40; 18. 4. 10;
शूलपाणिन् (m. c. for शूलपाणि ?) 3. 40. 55;
4. 40. 11; 5. 49. 24; 5. 190. 4; 10. 6. 34;
शूलिन् 7. 57. 35, 52; 8. 24. 46, 136, 153;
13. 1. 25; 13. 14. 131, 139; 14. 8. 3;
शूलहस्त 9. 31. 40; 9. 43. 33; शूलधृक् 2.
10. 20; 3. 81. 108; 9. 37. 43; शूलभृत् 6.
58. 61; शूलधर 3. 38. 43; खड्गशूल-
धर 13. 14. 151; शूलाङ्क 10. 7. 44;
दीप्तशूल 7. 172. 59; त्रिशूलपाणि 3. 80.
111; 7. 173. 33; 14. 8. 25.
A. Des-
cription: mysterious (गुह्य) 13. 14. 131;
indescribable (अनिर्देश्य) 13. 14. 136; having
very sharp points (अतितीक्ष्णाग्र); very fright-
ful (सुभीम); causing the opponent's hair
stand on ends (लोमहर्षण), as if threat-
ening him with its eye-brow knit in three
wrinkles (त्रिशिखां भ्रुकुटीं कृत्वा तर्ज-
मानम् इव स्थितम्) 13. 14. 135; it was like
fire without smoke, black in colour, appearing
like the sun risen at the time of the end of
the universe; it held a serpent in hand, and
hence looking like the god of Death with his
पाश in hand (विधूमं सार्चिषं कृष्णं
कालसूर्यम् इवोदितम्।सर्पहस्तम् … पाश-
हस्तम् इवान्तकम्) 13. 14. 136.
B.
Strength: If released by Śūlapāṇi (Śiva) it
was capable of tearing open the whole earth,
or dry up the great ocean, or destroy the entire
world 13. 14. 132.
C. Status: It was
equal or even superior to Pāśupata (तत्-
(= Pāśupata) तुल्याधिकम् एव वा) 13. 14.
131.
D. Use: The demon Lavaṇa,
holding this Śūla in hand, killed the very
strong and universal monarch Māndhātṛ, the
son of Yuvanāśva 13. 14. 133-134.
E.
Part in the epic war: Arjuna told Vyāsa,
after the death of Droṇa, that when on the
battle-field he shot arrows at his enemies he
saw an excellent person (पुरुषोत्तम) of
fiery lustre, looking like the sun, moving in
front of him with his raised burning Śūla; the
person did not touch the ground with his feet
and never released the Śula, but thousands of
Śūlas fell out from it; the direction in which
the excellent person moved, Arjuna's enemies
were destroyed; thus, actually the excellent
person first burnt Arjuna's enemies and Arjuna
burnt them afterwards, but people thought
Arjuna did it; Vyāsa told Arjuna that the
excellent person was none else but Śaṅkara
with his Śūla 7. 173. 3-10.
II. Association
with Nandi(n), one of the attendants of Śiva:
Nandin waited on Śiva holding the burning
Śūla, shining with its lustre (प्रगृह्य
ज्वलितम् शूलं दीप्यमानं स्वतेजसा) 12.
274. 15; when Upamanyu saw Śiva, Nandi
stood in front of Śiva having fixed his Śūla
(शूलं विष्टभ्य तिष्ठन्तम्) and hence
looking like another Śaṅkara 13. 14. 144.
III. Association with Viṣṇu (Kṛṣṇa):
Viṣṇu, when he on request by Brahman creat-
ed दण्डनीति, is described as one having the
excellent Śūla as his weapon (शूलवरायुध)
12. 122. 26 (commentator Vādirāja, however,
takes it to mean as ‘one who has a weapon
(चक्र) which is superior to Śūla (शूलाद्
वरं श्रेष्ठं चक्रम् आयुधं यस्य, see
Cr. edn. 12. 122. 24 f. n.); Viṣṇu is also called
there शूल (जटा) धर 12. 122. 24; Bhīṣma,
while praising Kṛṣṇa as the highest god, uses
the epithet ‘bearer of Śūla’ (शूलभृत्) to
describe him 13. 143. 13.

शृङ्गाटक
Śṛṅgāṭaka m.: Name of a particular
arrangement of the army (व्यूह).
On the eighth day of the war, when
Yudhiṣṭhira pointed out to Dhṛṣṭadyumna
the Mahāvyūha of the Kauravas, to counter it
Dhṛṣṭadyumna arranged the Pāṇḍava army
according to the Śṛṅgāṭaka vyūha; described
as very fearful (सुदारुण) 6. 83. 17; great
(महाव्यूह) 6. 83. 22; destroyer of the
enemy's Vyūha (परव्यूहविनाशन) 6.
83. 17; at its ‘horns’ (शृङ्गेभ्यः pl.)
were stationed Bhīmasena and Sātyaki with
many thousands of chariot-fighters as well as
horse-soldiers and foot-soldiers; at its ‘nave’
(नाभि) stood Arjuna; its ‘centre’
(मध्य), was filled by Yudhiṣṭhira,
Nakula, and Sahadeva, as also by other
kings fighting with bows, and their armies;
they were followed (ततः पश्चात्) by
Abhimanyu, Virāṭa, the five sons of
Draupadī, and Ghaṭotkaca 6. 83. 16-22.

शैलास्त्र
Śailāstra nt.: Name of a missile.
Described as fierce (घोर) 6. 98. 20,
and mighty (महास्त्र) 3. 168. 10; when
Arjuna released the Vāyavyāstra against the
Trigartas, Droṇa released the Śailāstra; as a
result the force of the wind abated and the
directions became clear (प्रशशाम ततो
वायुः प्रसन्नाश् चाभवन् दिशः) 6. 98.
20-21; Arjuna used the Śailāstra against
Kirāta (Śiva) which was swallowed
(जग्रास) by the latter 3. 163. 32; when
the Nivātakavaca demons produced wind
with their माया, Arjuna used the mighty
Śaila astra to hold the speed of the wind and
defeat the माया (शैलेन च महास्त्रेण
वायोर् वेगम् अधारयम्) 3. 168. 10.

श्येन
Śyena m.: Name of a व्यूह (a
particular way of arranging the army).
Described as the king of the Vyūhas
(व्यूहराज), and invincible in battle
(अजय्येन संयुगे) 6. 65. 7; on the fifth
day of the war, the Pāṇḍava army was
arranged according to the Śyenavyūha to
counter the Makaravyūha (6. 65. 4) of the
Kauravas; its ‘mouth’ (मुख) was formed
by Bhīmasena, ‘eyes’ (नेत्रे) by Śikhaṇḍin
and Dhṛṣṭadyumna, ‘head’ (शीर्ष) by
Sātyaki, ‘neck’ (ग्रीवा) by Pārtha
(Arjuna), ‘left wing’ (वामपक्ष) by
Drupada and his son (not named) together
with a full अक्षौहिणी army, ‘right wing’
(दक्षिण पक्ष) by Kaikeya, the leader of
an अक्षौहिणी army (अक्षौहिणीपतिः), at its
back (पृष्ठतः) stood the sons of Draupadī
and Saubhadra (Abhimanyu), and the ‘back’
(पृष्ठ) was formed by Yudhiṣṭhira with
Nakula and Sahadeva 6. 65. 7-12.

सन्तान|संतान
Saṃtāna nt.: Name of a missile.
One of the eight missiles known to
Arjuna, enumerated by Rāma Jāmadagnya
for the information of Duryodhana; Arjuna
was likely to employ them in the war 5. 94.
38; for the effects produced by these missiles
(5. 94. 39-40) see Akṣisaṃtarjana.

समुदीर्ण
Samudīrṇa nt.: One of the twenty-one
movements (मार्ग) used while fighting
with a sword and a shield.
Dhṛṣṭadyumna used it and the others when
he, with a sword and a shield in hand,
wanted to attack Droṇa who was shooting
arrows at him (सो ऽचरद् विविधान् मार्गान्
प्रकारान् एकविंशतिम्) 7. 164. 145-148.

सम्पात|संपात
Saṃpāta m.: One of the twenty-one
movements (मार्ग) used while fighting
with a sword and a shield.
Dhṛṣṭadyumna used it and the others
when he, with a sword and a shield in hand,
wanted to attack Droṇa who was shooting
arrows at him (सो ऽचरद् विविधान् मार्गान्
प्रकारान् एकविंशतिम्) 7. 164. 145-148.

सम्बोधन|संबोधन
Saṃbodhana nt.: Name of a missile.
Vipras (Vasus) advised Bhīṣma in a
dream first to use the Prasvāpa astra against
Rāma Jāmadagnya to send him to sleep and,
thus having conquered him, awaken him by
using the dear Saṃbodhana astra (ततो
जित्वा त्वम् एवैनम् पुनर् उत्थापयिष्यसि।
अस्त्रेण दयितेनाजौ भीष्म संबोधनेन
वै) 5. 184. 15. [See Prasvāpa]

सम्मोहन|संमोहन
Saṃmohana nt.: Name of a missile.
Described as ‘irresistible’ (अपारणीय);
when Arjuna, at the time of the cattle-raid,
was encircled by Bhīṣma, Droṇa and the
other Kaurava warriors, he employed his
Saṃmohanāstra due to which, as also due to
the sound of his bow Gāṇḍīva and the conch,
the Kaurava heroes were stupefied and
became calm (संमोहिताः … शान्तिपरा
बभूवुः) 4. 61. 8-11.

सर्वतोभद्र
Sarvatobhadra nt.: Name of a व्यूह
(a particular arrangement of the army).
Described as great (महत्) 6. 95. 26,
successful (ऋद्धिमत्) 9. 7. 19; (1) Bhīṣma
arranged the Kaurava army in this way on
the ninth day of the war; at its front and
at the head of all the army (व्यूहस्य
प्रमुखे; अग्रतः सर्वसैन्यानाम्) stood
Kṛpa, Kṛtavarman, the Śaibya king, Śakuni,
Jayadratha, and Sudakṣiṇa (the Kāmboja)
together with Bhīṣma and the sons of
Dhṛtarāṣṭra; on the right side (दक्षिण
पक्ष) stood Droṇa, Bhūriśravas, Śalya,
and Bhagadatta; on the left side (वाम
पक्ष) stood Aśvasena, Somadatta, and two
princes from Avanti (Vinda and Anuvinda)
with large armies on all sides; in the middle
(व्यूहमध्ये) was stationed Duryodhana,
surrounded on all sides by the Trigartas; in
the rear (पृष्ठतः) were Alambusa and
Śrutāyu 6. 95. 26-32; this Vyūha of the
Kauravas was countered by the Mahāvyūha of
the Pāṇḍavas 6. 95. 38; (2) Śalya arranged
the Kaurava army according to the Sarvato-
bhadra Vyūha on the eighteenth day of the war
9. 7. 19; at its front (मुख) was Śalya,
together with the Madra warriors and the sons
of Karṇa; at the left (सव्य) stood
Kṛtavarman, surrounded by the Trigartas; at
the right side (दक्षिण पार्श्व), stood
Gautama (Kṛpa), with the Śakas and the
Yavanas; in the middle (मध्य) was
stationed Duryodhana protected by the Kuru
warriors; probably in the rear were Śakuni
with a large cavalry and Kaitavya (Ulūka)
with all his army 9. 7. 23-26; this Vyūha
was countered by the Pāṇḍavas by dividing
their army in three divisions which were
apparently led by Dhṛṣṭadyumna, Śikhaṇḍin
and Sātyaki 9. 7. 27-28.

सलिलास्त्र
Salilāstra nt.: Name of a missile.
Employed by Arjuna in his fight with
the Nivātakavaca demons to blow away the
fire produced by them with their माया 3.
168. 9-10.

सवितुर्
Savitur astram nt.: A missile 6. 116.
38. [See Sāvitra]

सहस्रघ्नी
Sahasraghnī f.: Name of a missile.
Described as a lightning coming out of
a cloud (बलाहकाद् उच्चरन्तीव विद्युत्);
Arjuna would employ it in the war; when
employed, it would emit arrows to cut the
bones and pierce the vitals of the enemies
5. 47. 49.

साध्य
Sādhya (astra) nt.: A missile special
to the Sādhyas.
Arjuna was to learn it after reaching
the residence of Indra 3. 164. 29-30; the
Sādhyas agree to teach it to him 3. 164.
49-50. [See Sādhyānāṃ praharaṇam]

साध्यानां
Sādhyānāṃ praharaṇam nt.: The
weapon of the Sādhyas, not named.
When Garuḍa flew up from a mount-
ain-top to fetch the Soma from the heaven,
there occurred bad omens for the gods, one
of them being that the weapon of the
Sādhyas clashed with that of the Vasus, the
Rudras, the Ādityas, the Maruts and the
other hosts of gods (ये चान्ये देवतागणाः);
such a thing had never happened before 1.
26. 29-30. [See Sādhya astra]

सावित्र
Sāvitra (astra) nt.: Name of a
missile of Savitṛ.
Described as heavenly (दिव्य) 6. 116.
38; Droṇa employed it (as also other
missiles) against Yudhiṣṭhira in order to
kill him (जिघांसुः) 7. 132. 29; Yudhiṣṭhira
defeated it by the use of the same (?)
missile (तानि चास्त्राणि धर्मजः।जघाना-
स्त्रैर् महाबाहुः कुम्भयोनेर् अवित्रसन्)
7. 132. 30; however, according to Bhīṣma,
among men, the use of this missile (सवितुर्
अस्त्रम्) was known only to Arjuna, and
perhaps to Kṛṣṇa, and to none else (नान्यो
वै वेद कश्चन) 6. 116. 38-39.

सीर
Sīra m.: A plough used as a weapon
by Balarāma. Hence his epithet सीरायुध
9. 48. 15.

सुघोष
Sughoṣa m.: Name of the conch of
Nakula.
On the first day of the war, when the
Kaurava and the Pāṇḍava armies were
arranged against each other, Nakula blew
his Sughoṣa conch 6. 23. 16; he blew it also
before the start of the war on the next day
6. 47. 26, (and very likely on all the following
days).

सुदर्शन
Sudarśana cakra nt.: Name of the
discuss used as a missile (अस्त्र 1. 216. 28;
10. 12. 15, 16, 18) by Kṛṣṇa (or Viṣṇu
वैष्णवम् चक्रं 5. 96. 18), often referred
to simply as Cakra; called Āgneya astra 1.
216. 21; 3. 23. 28; 7. 10. 21.
A. History: Fire in high flames,
permeated by smokeless fire, remains awake
in the form of Viṣṇu's cakra (वैष्णवं
चक्रम्) in Varuṇa's lake 5. 96. 18; at the
time of burning the Khāṇḍava forest, god
Agni asked Varuṇa to give for his sake the
Cakra to Vāsudeva (Kṛṣṇa) with which he
would execute a great deed (cf. also 16. 4. 3);
Varuṇa agreed to Agni's request (1. 216. 4)
and gave the Cakra, here called Āgneya
astra, to Kṛṣṇa; Agni told Kṛṣṇa that,
equipped with the Cakra, he would defeat
even superhuman beings in battle; he would
be superior to men, gods, demons, Piśācas,
Daityas and serpents when in battle he
was opposed by a very strong enemy; when-
ever Kṛṣṇa hurled in battle the Cakra
against his enemies, it would kill the enemy
without resistance and return to Kṛṣṇa's hand
1. 216. 21-24; Kṛṣṇa felt fully prepared to
fight with all the gods and demons when he
received the Cakra 1. 216. 26-27, 30, 21;
Arjuna felt confident that there was nothing
which Kṛṣṇa would not conquer when he had
the Cakra for use in battle 1. 216. 28;
according to the information of Dhṛtarāṣṭra,
Kṛṣṇa received the Cakra, identified with the
Āgneya astra, from the satisfied Agni after,
and not before, the burning of the forest 7.
10. 21.
B. Description: heavenly (दिव्य)
3. 23. 28 (Āgneya astra), 10. 12. 31; 18. 4.
3; great (महत्) 3. 23. 29 (Āgneya astra),
10. 12. 31; spotless (अमल) 3. 23. 30;
incomparable (अतुल) 3. 23. 30, (अप्रतिम)
10. 12. 31; invincible (अजय्य) 1. 17. 20; best,
best among the discusses (उत्तम) 1. 17. 20;
(चक्ररत्न) 17. 1. 38; (वरम् … चक्राणां
सुदर्शनं) 5. 53. 12; 7. 6. 19; irresistible
(दुर्धर्ष) 7. 10. 21; never repulsed
(अप्रतिहत) 3. 23. 28 (Āgneya astra);
impenetrable (अभेद्य) 3. 23. 28 (Āgneya
astra); having razor-like or unblunted edge
(क्षुरान्त) 3. 23. 30; 6. 55. 86; (क्षुर-
नेमि) 8. 65. 19; (अकुण्ठमण्डल) 1. 17.
20; fierce, terrible (उग्र) 6. 55. 83
(रथाङ्ग); (भीम) 1. 17. 20; (भय-
ंकर) 1. 17. 21; agile, speedy, very speedy
(चपल) 1. 17. 21; (वेगवत्) 1. 17. 22;
(उदग्रवेगवत्) 1. 17. 21; very strong
(अतिवीर्यवत्) 3. 23. 28 (Āgneya astra);
overpowering all (सर्वसाह) 3. 23. 28
(Āgneya astra); having the strength of
Vajra (वज्रसमप्रभाव) 6. 55. 86;
deadly (कालान्तकयमोपम) 3. 23. 30;
highly lustrous (महाप्रभ) 1. 17. 20-21;
3. 23. 28 (Āgneya astra); having the lustre
of the sun (at the end of the aeon) or
blazing like fire (on the Doom's day) (सूर्य-
प्रभ) 6. 55. 86; (रूपम् … द्वितीयस्येव
सूर्यस्य युगान्ते परिविष्यतः) 3. 23. 32;
(विभावसोस् तुल्यम्) 1. 17. 20; (ज्वलित-
हुताशनप्रभ) 1. 17. 21; (अन्तकज्वल-
नसमानवर्चस्) 1. 17. 22; counted among
the four lustres stationed on Arjuna's chariot
(the other three being Arjuna, the Gāṇḍīva
bow and Vāsudeva) (चत्वार्य् एतानि तेजांसि)
7. 6. 20; made of metal (अयस्मय) 10. 12.
20; 16. 4. 3; having a thousand spokes
(सहस्रार) 10. 12. 20; having a good nave
or a nave hard like Vajra (सुनाभ) 6. 55.
86; 10. 12. 20; 10. 12. 38; (वज्रनाभ)
1. 216. 21; 10. 12. 20; 16. 4. 3; razing the
town of enemies (परनगरावदारण) 1.
17. 21; tormentor or killer of enemies
(अमित्रतापन) 1. 17. 20; (द्विषतां च
निबर्हणं) 3. 23. 30; (रिपुहरं रणे)
10. 12. 15; killer of the demons (दानव-
सूदन) 1. 17. 19, or reducing to ashes the
Yakṣas, the Rākṣasas, the Dānavas, and the
hostile kings in battle (यक्षाणां राक्ष-
सानां च दानवानां च संयुगे।राज्ञां च
प्रतिलोमानां भस्मान्तकरणं महत्)
3. 23. 29 (Āgneya astra); honoured by
gods and demons (देवदानवपूजित) 10.
12. 36; dear (missile of Varuṇa) 1. 216. 21;
3. 23. 28 (Āgneya astra); described as a
lotus having razor-like sharp-edged, well-
developed petals and Kṛṣṇa's arm serving
as a stalk and hence compared with the
primeval lotus which arose from the navel
of Nārāyaṇa (सुदर्शनं … चक्रपद्मं
सुभुजोरुनालम्। … क्षुरान्ततीक्ष्णाग्र-
सुजातपत्रम् … यथादिपद्मं … नारा-
यणनाभिजातं … नारायणबाहुनालम्)
6. 55. 89-90.
C. Kṛṣṇa's missile:
Kṛṣṇa's different weapons, Cakra one of
them, appeared on his arms when he showed
his fierce form to the Kauravas in their
Sabhā 5. 129. 9-10; Vāsudeva's (Kṛṣṇa's)
Cakra rotates due to his माया resorting to
the space between the sky and (the earth ?)
as directed by him (द्याम् अन्तरं समा-
स्थाय यथायुक्तं मनस्विनः।चक्रं
तद् वासुदेवस्य मायया वर्तते विभो) 5.
66. 2; Kṛṣṇa asked Sātyaki to place, among
other things, his Cakra in the chariot when he
was to proceed to Hāstinapura 5. 81. 12;
Yudhiṣṭhira saw Govinda (Kṛṣṇa) in heaven
together with his heavenly missiles, the Cakra
and the rest, in the bodily form (चक्र-
प्रभृतिभिः … पुरुषविग्रहैः) 18. 4. 3.
D. Use of Cakra in epithets: Kṛṣṇa (Viṣṇu)
has epithets like चक्रिन् 13. 135. 110. 120
(Viṣṇu); सचक्रः 6. 55. 101; चक्रायुध
1. 17. 6 (Viṣṇu); 5. 3. 16; 15. 32. 10; चक्र-
धर 7. 115. 17 (Sātyaki called चक्र-
धरप्रभाव); रथाङ्गपाणि 13. 135. 120
(Viṣṇu); रथचक्रभृत् 5. 103. 18; चक्र-
गदाभृत् 5. 81. 14; चक्रगदाधर 5. 89.
15; 5. 103. 35 (Viṣṇu ?); 11. 25. 39; 13. 135.
71 (Viṣṇu); 14. 2. 11; 14. 90. 8; 16. 9. 28;
चक्रगदापाणि 1. 58. 50 (Nārāyaṇa); शङ्ख-
चक्रगदाधर 3. 19. 27; 3. 187. 38 (Nārā-
yaṇa); 3. 256. 29; 6. 62. 14; 13. 14. 142;
13. 153. 37; 14. 54. 22; 16. 9. 19; शाङ्ख-
चक्रगदाहस्त 5. 48. 23; शङ्खचक्रासि-
पाणि 8. 57. 48 (Viṣṇu, Kṛṣṇa); शार्ङ्ग-
रथाङ्गपाणि 6. 55. 94; शार्ङ्गचक्रगदा-
धर 2. 42. 34; 16. 4. 44; शार्ङ्गचक्रासि-
पाणि 12. 43. 16.
E. Aśvatthāman incident:
Aśvatthāman was forbidden to use the
Brahmaśiras astra on any occasion whatso-
ever; so he wanted to exchange Brahmaśiras
for Kṛṣṇa's Sudarśana; Kṛṣṇa allowed Aśva-
tthāman to choose any one of his missiles,
including the Cakra, which he felt he could
wield and use in the battle; Aśvatthāman opted
for the Cakra, and when allowed by Kṛṣṇa
to take it, he first tried to pick it up with his
left hand; failing to move it, he tried his right
hand; when he could not move the Cakra
even with his right hand, he used all his might
(i. e. probably used both his hands together);
having failed in this attempt too, Aśvatthāman
in despair abandoned the attempt; Kṛṣṇa then
told him that he had asked for something very
unusual, for not even Arjuna, Pradyumna,
(Bala)rāma, Gada, Sāmba, nor any one of
the Vṛṣṇi and Andhaka heroes living in
Dvārakā had asked for it; Kṛṣṇa, out of
curiosity, asked Aśvatthāman whom he wanted
to fight with equipped with Sudarśana; Aśva-
tthāman admitted that he wanted to fight
with Kṛṣṇa himself and become invincible;
Aśvatthāman realised that the Cakra would
not leave Kṛṣṇa and hence he left Dvārakā
without it 10. 12. 14-38.
F. Its use:
(1) In wars or events not related to the
epic: (i) when Viṣṇu was distributing the
अमृत among the gods, Rāhu cunningly
managed to get it; as the अमृत had
reached Rāhu's throat, Viṣṇu used the Cakra
to cut off his head; when severed by the
Cakra, the head fell on the ground and shook
the earth 1. 17. 5-7; (ii) in the war that
ensued between the gods and the demons
after the above incident Nara and Nārāyaṇa
appeared on the scene; Viṣṇu (Narāyaṇa)
then thought of his Sudarśana cakra; as soon
as thought of, it arrived from the sky (ततो
ऽम्बराच् चिन्तितमात्रम् आगतम् 1. 17. 20);
armed with it, Viṣṇu used it against the
demons; it struck them again and again and
cut off the Daityas to pieces in thousands;
sometimes it licked the Dānavas and, over-
powering them, cut them off; sometimes it
burnt them like fire; hurled now in the sky
and then on the ground it drunk their blood
like a Piśāca; having heard that the Sudar-
śana cakra was angry, the demons disappeared
entering the earth and the ocean 1. 17. 18-28;
(iii) in Kṛṣṇa's war with Śālva who was
fighting from his Saubhapura, Kṛṣṇa released
his sharp-edged discuss, here called his dear
(दयित) Āgneya astra (3. 23. 28), after
reciting मन्त्रस् over it (अभिमन्त्र्य 3.
23. 30) and using the strength of his arm
(भुजवीर्येण 3. 23. 31); Kṛṣṇa directed
his Cakra to strike down with its might the
Saubha and all the enemies living there; the
missile cut into two the Saubha town in the
middle as a saw might cut a pillar; after
achieving its objective the missile returned to
Kṛṣṇa's hand; Kṛṣṇa again shook it upwards
with great speed and released it with the
words: “(now) for Śālva” (पुनश् चोद्-
धूय वेगेन शाल्वायेत्य् अहम् अब्रुवम् 3. 23.
35); the discuss instantly cut Śālva into two,
who was then wielding a heavy गदा, and
then it blazed with its lustre 3. 23. 28-36;
(2) In wars or events related to the epic:
(1) at the time of the Khāṇḍava fire, Kṛṣṇa
killed many hosts of Daityas and Dānavas
with his Cakra; many others, were blown
away by the speed of the Cakra (चक्र-
वेगेरिताः) 1. 218. 26-27; in this incident
Kṛṣṇa released his Cakra on animals and
other beings (तथान्या भूतजातयः 1. 219.
2) so that these, along with the Dānavas and
the night-stalkers (सदानवनिशाचराः 1. 219.
4) were cut into pieces by hundreds and they
fell into the fire; the Rākṣasas, cut by the
Cakra of Kṛṣṇa, looked like evening clouds;
Kṛṣṇa moved there like the god of Death kill-
ing by thousands Piśācas, birds, serpents and
animals with his Cakra; the Cakra, repeatedly
hurled, killed many beings and returned to
Kṛṣṇa's hand 1. 219. 2-7; if the Rākṣasas,
Dānavas and serpents tried to escape to-
gether (एकायनगताः सङ्घीभूताः Nī. on
1. 228. 34 Bom. Ed.) even then Kṛṣṇa killed
them and they fell into the flaming fire 1. 219.
30-31; Kṛṣṇa saw Asura Maya fleeing from
the house of Takṣaka and when Agni showed
his desire to burn him, Kṛṣṇa stood ready with
his raised Cakra to kill him; but Maya sought
help from Arjuna and was saved 1. 219.
35-39; (2) Enraged Kṛṣṇa cut off the head
of Śiśupāla with Cakra at the time of the
Rājasūya 2. 42. 21; 3. 15. 3-4; 12-13 (use
of Cakra not mentioned).
G. Threatened
or eventual use in the epic war: (1) Dis-
appointed at Arjuna's softness (मृदुयुद्ध-
ताम् 6. 55. 63, 80) while fighting with Bhīṣma,
Kṛṣṇa took up his discuss (रथाङ्गम्) with
a view to killing Bhīṣma; raising his Cakra he
jumped down from the chariot and proceeded
on foot to attack Bhīṣma; the Sudarśana,
lotus-like and having a beautiful nave, shone
like the primeval lotus (आदिपद्म) rising
from the navel of Nārāyaṇa; seeing Kṛṣṇa
equipped with Cakra all beings cried aloud
thinking that that was the end of the Kurus;
Kṛṣṇa, holding the Cakra and jumping along,
looked as if he was revolving the world, or
he looked like the god of Death in the form of
Fire burning the creatures (संवर्तयिष्यन्न्
इव जीवलोकम्। … भूतानि धक्ष्यन्न् इव
कालवह्निः) 6. 55. 92); (2) seeing Kṛṣṇa
rushing towards him with Cakra in hand,
Bhīṣma invited him from his chariot to put
an end to his life; when Arjuna, coming
from behind, assured Kṛṣṇa that he would
destroy the Kurus, Kṛṣṇa returned and holding
the discuss, mounted the chariot 6. 55. 83,
86-87, 89-94, 100-101; (3) Apprehending
that Arjuna might not be able to fulfil his vow
to kill Jayadratha before sunset, Kṛṣṇa thought
that his intervention in the war might become
necessary and he therefore asked Dāruka, his
charioteer, to keep his chariot ready with all
the missiles in it, including Cakra, so that he
would destroy the enemy's army with it 7.
56. 32, 28. (4) Kṛṣṇa, in order to incite
Arjuna who was somewhat overpowered
by Karṇa, showed readiness to give his
Cakra to him to cut off Karṇa's head with
it 8. 65. 19.
H. Actual or possible defeat
of Sudarśana: (1) Viṣṇu's Cakra was
shattered on the limbs of Mandara, the son
of Hiraṇyakaśipu, owing to a boon Mandara
had received from Mahādeva (Śiva) 13. 14.
54; (2) even Kṛṣṇa with his Sudarśana
would not be able to vanquish Karṇa as long
as he was armed with Indra's (वासवी)
Śakti and was protected by his armour and
कुण्डलस् 7. 155. 17, (13-15).
I. End
When the end of the Yādavas had arrived and
when they started for the तीर्थयात्रा on the
shore of the ocean, the Cakra, given to
Kṛṣṇa by Agni, left him and rose to the sky
even as the Vṛṣṇis watched it 16. 4. 3; when
Yudhiṣṭhira relinquished the kingdom to
Parikṣit and the Pāṇḍavas started for the
forest, god Agni appeared in bodily form
(17. 1. 33) and told them that the excellent
Cakra which stayed with Kṛṣṇa had dis-
appeared and that it would return to his hand
at the proper time (चक्ररत्नं तु यत्
कृष्णे स्थितम् आसीन् महात्मनि।गतं तच्
च पुनर् हस्ते कालेनैष्यति तस्य ह॥)
17. 1. 38.

सुदर्शन
Sudarśana2 nt.: Name of Indra's aerial
car (विमान 4. 51. 7).
Śakra (Indra), with many other gods,
came to watch the war between Arjuna and
the Kaurava heroes at the time of the
cattle-raid riding his Sudarśana Vimāna 4.
51. 3.

सुपर्ण
Suparṇa m.: Name of a Vyūha (7. 19.
4-5). [See Garuḍa]

सूची
Sūcī (Sūcī̆°) f.: Name of a particular
arrangement of the army (व्यूह).
A. When to be used: According to
the great sage Bṛhaspati if the number
of warriors in one's army was small it
should be gathered together, but if it was
large it might be spread out as much as
desired; in the former case the contingent in
the front should be arranged according to the
Sūcī vyūha (महर्षेर् वचनात् तात वेद-
यन्ति बृहस्पतेः।संहतान् योधयेद् अल्पान्
कामं विस्तारयेद् बहून्॥सूचीमुखम्
अनीकं स्याद् अल्पानां बहुभिः सह।) 6.
19. 4-5; 12. 101. 44.
B. Its use in the
epic war: (1) In the opinion of Yudhiṣṭhira,
since the Pāṇḍava army was smaller in
number than that of their opponent, it was to
be arranged as directed by the great sage
(Bṛhaspati); this was his suggestion to
Arjuna at the beginning of the war
on the first day (अस्माकं च तथा सैन्यम्
अल्पीयः सुतरां परैः॥एतद् वचनम्
आज्ञाय महर्षेर् व्यूह पाण्डव) 6. 19.
5-6; (Arjuna, however, chose to arrange the
Pāṇḍava army according to the Vajravyūha 6.
19. 7); (2) When the contingent compris-
ing the Kekaya princess the sons of Draupadī,
and Dhṛṣṭaketu and which was led by Abhi-
manyu with a large force was asked by
Yudhiṣṭhira to rush to the aid of Bhīmasena
and Dhṛṣṭadyumna, they arranged themselves
in such a way that its front formed the
Sūcī 6. 73. 51, 54-55; (3) In order to
protect Jayadratha a small contingent was
arranged in the form of Sūcī which was
concealed in the middle of the Padma vyūha,
which itself formed the rear half of the main
Śakaṭa (7. 53. 27) or the Cakraśakaṭa vyūha
7. 63. 21; 7. 63. 23; the front of the Sūcī
(सूचीमुख) was formed by Kṛtavarman,
followed by Jalasandha, the Kāmboja;
Duryodhana with his Amātyas stood behind
them; behind them, at the position of the
‘eye’ of the Sūci (? सूचिपाश 7. 63. 27),
stood Jayadratha surrounded by a large force
7. 63. 24-27; 7. 53. 27; a hundred thousand
warriors who would not turn away from the
battle-field were distributed in the Śakaṭa
vyūha to guard the Sūci vyūha (योधानाम्
अनिवर्तिनाम्।व्यवस्थितानि सर्वाणि शकटे
सूचिरक्षिणः) 7. 63. 26.

सृत
Sṛta nt.: One of the twenty-one move-
ments (मार्ग) used while fighting with a
sword and a shield.
Dhṛṣṭadyumna used it when he, with a
sword and a shield in hand, wanted to avoid
the arrows of Droṇa and also attack him
(सो ऽचरद् विविधान् मार्गान् प्रकारान्
एकविंशतिम्) 7. 164. 145-148.

सौपर्ण
Sauparṇa astra nt.: Name of a
missile.
It was used (प्रादुष्कृ) by Suśarman
to free the feet of his army which were tied
up by the snakes released by the Nāga astra
of Arjuna; from the Sauparṇa astra came out
the Suparṇas which started eating up the
snakes; then the snakes, seeing those birds,
crept away and the army was freed from the
ties on their feet 8. 37. 25-27; 21-22.

सौम्य
Saumya astra nt.: Name of a missile
related to Soma.
Described as heavenly (दिव्य) 6. 116.
38; used by Arjuna against the Gandharvas,
who had captured the Kauravas, to ward off
the showers of arrows released by them; the
Gandharvas felt burnt by the arrows (दह्य-
मानाः) of Arjuna 3. 234. 17-18; according
to Bhīṣma's information, only Arjuna, among
men, knew this missile, and perhaps Kṛṣṇa
6. 116. 38-39.

सौर
Saura astra nt.: Name of a missile
related to Sūra.
Used by Arjuna against the Gandharvas,
who had captured the Kauravas, to ward off
the showers of arrows released by them; the
Gandharvas felt burnt by the arrows (दह्य-
मानाः) of Arjuna 3. 234. 17-18; [See
Bhāskara astra].

स्थूणाकर्ण
Sthūṇākarṇa nt.: Name of a missile,
apparently known to very few heroes.
According to Nīlakaṇṭha, it is related
to Śaṅkukarṇa, one of the incarnations of
Rudra (स्थूणाकर्ण इति शङ्कुकर्णाख्यो
रुद्रावतारभेदस् तद्दैवत्यम् अस्त्रम् on
3. 167. 33 Bom. Ed.); it seems to have been
a very important missile since it is mentioned
along with the Pāśupata and the Brahmāstra
5. 47. 100; 5. 139. 31 (also Aindra); Arjuna,
in his message sent through Saṃjaya,
threatened to use Sthūṇākarṇa against the
Kaurava warriors in the war 5. 47. 100;
Karṇa, too, was sure that Arjuna would use
Sthūṇākarṇa in the war with the employment
of proper मन्त्रस् on his arrow (मन्त्रास्
तत्र भविष्यन्ति प्रयुक्ताः सव्यसाचिना) 5.
139. 31; but its use by Arjuna in the war is
not recorded; on the other hand Karṇa him-
self, while inciting the sons of Dhṛtarāṣṭra
who were attacking Yudhiṣṭhira to kill him,
released Sthūṇākarṇa, along with Indrajāla
and Pāśupata, to overpower Yudhiṣṭhira 8.
43. 20-21; outside the epic war, Arjuna used
it against the Kirāta (Śiva) who swallowed it
up 3. 163. 32; Arjuna used it also against
the Gandharvas who had captured the
Kauravas; the Gandharvas were tormented
by the heat (दह्यमानाः) of the arrows
released by the use of the missile 3. 234.
17-18; Balarāma had released Sthūṇākarṇa
missile to repulse a very powerful गदा
hurled against him and Kṛṣṇa by Jarāsandha;
the गदा, when met with force by the missile,
fell on the earth tearing it open and the impact
produced by it shook the mountains; the
Rākṣasī Jarā (who had joined the two parts
of the body of Jarāsandha) lay concealed
under the ground; she, together with
her sons and relatives, was killed due to
the impact of the गदा and the Sthūṇākarṇa
missile on the earth 7. 156. 10-14.

हल
Hala m. nt.: A plough used as a weapon
by Balarāma.
Hence Balarāma has epithets like
हलायुध 1. 178. 8; 1. 180. 17, 22; 3. 180.
32; 4. 67. 20; 5. 7. 28; 5. 154. 15, 20, 22;
9. 33. 2, 6, 7; 9. 34. 79; 9. 35. 1, 52; 9. 36.
1, 26, 63; 9. 38. 1, 4, 30; 9. 51. 24; 9. 52.
17; 9. 53. 4, 12; 9. 59. 4; 16. 2. 10; हलिन्
3. 119. 4; 5. 129. 7; 7. 10. 31; 9. 33. 12;
हलधर 1. 211. 7; 1. 213. 49; 2. 20. 34;
9. 34. 12; 9. 36. 12; 9. 38. 23; हलभृत् 9.
34. 29; 9. 49. 65; हलायुध also appears as
a name of Viṣṇu 13. 135. 73.

अंशावतरण
Aṃśāvataraṇa nt.: Name of a section
of the Ādiparvan describing the incarnations
of portions of gods (त्वयैवांशावतरणे
देवभागाः प्रकीर्तिताः) 1. 109. 3.
A part of the Saṃbhavaparvan where
partial descent of gods is described (सं-
भवपर्वणि … अंशावतरणं चात्र देवा-
नां परिकीर्तितम्) 1. 2. 75-76; Brahman
asked the gods, the Gandharvas, and the
Apsarases to be partially born separately
among men in order to lessen the burden of
the earth (अस्या भूमेर् निरसितुं भारं
भागैः पृथक् पृथक्।अस्याम् एव प्रसूय-
ध्वम् … स्वैर् अंशैः संप्रसूयध्वम्
यथेष्टं मानुषेष्व् इति) 1. 58. 46-47;
Indra then requested Nārāyaṇa (Hari)
to be partially born, to which request he
agreed (अंशेनावतरस्वेति तथेत्याह च
तं हरिः) 1. 58. 51; Nārada, seeing the
kings who had assembled for the Rājasūya
of Yudhiṣṭhira, remembered the conversation
which in the bygone days took place
(पुरावृत्तां कथाम्) in the residence
of Brahman in regard to the partial incar-
nations on the earth and recognized that
what he saw before him was in fact the
assembly of the gods (देवानां संगमम्)
2. 33. 11-13; at the request of Janamejaya,
Vaiśayṃpāyana narrated to him the incarna-
tions of the Dānavas and the gods 1. 61. 1-2;
this is the narration of Aṃśāvataraṇa 1. 61.
99; one is advised to listen to the recitation
of the Aṃśāvataraṇa since it brought to the
listener wealth, fame, sons, long life and
victory; one who listened to the recitation
did not perish in adverse circumstances 1. 61.
101-102.

अघमर्षण
Aghamarṣaṇa nt.: Name of a sacred
text (Ṛgveda 10. 190. 1-3) composed by the
sage Aghamarṣaṇa, son of Madhucchandas.
According to Manu, one who takes a
dip into water and recites the Aghamarṣaṇa
मन्त्रस् thrice (a day) acquires the fruit of
an Aśvamedha sacrifice; such a person drives
away quickly his sin, is honoured, and all
beings try to please him (अपि चैनं प्रसी-
दन्ति भूतानि) 12. 148. 26-27; one who bathes
in the water of the Kulyātīrtha and repeats
the Aghamarṣaṇa मन्त्रस् and, remaining
undefiled, fasts for three nights gets the fruit
of an Aśvamedha sacrifice 13. 26. 53; while
observing the ब्रह्मचर्य vow, if one slips
(makes a fault) in sleep he should recite
mentally the Aghamarṣaṇa मन्त्रस् thrice;
this way he burns the sin within himself
which was the result of the quality of passion
(मग्नः स्वप्ने च मनसा त्रिर् जपेद्
अघमर्षणम्॥पाप्मानं निर्दहेद् एवम्
अन्तर्भूतं रजोमयम्) 12. 207. 13-14.

अथर्वन्
Atharvan (sg., pl.), Atharvaṇa,
Atharvaveda, Atharvāṇa m.: Name of one
of the four vedas; मन्त्रस् of this Veda.
A. Origin: The god of gods (Nārā-
yaṇa) told Mārkaṇḍeya that the three Vedas
and the Atharvaṇa arise out of him and
enter into him again (यजुर्वेदो ऽप्यथर्-
वणः।मत्तः प्रादुर्भवन्त्य् एते माम् एव
प्रविशन्ति च) 3. 187. 14.
B. What it
does and does not contain: Vyāsa told his
son Śuka that one should study the त्रयी
विद्या contained in the Ṛk, the Yajus, and
the Sāman, as also in the Atharvan
(त्रयीविद्याम् अवेक्षेत वेदेषूक्ताम् अथाङ्ग-
तः।ऋक्सामवर्णाक्षरतो यजुषोऽथर्वणस्
तथा) 12. 227. 1; Bhagavān (Kṛṣṇa) told
Arjuna that the great sages had mentioned
many of his names in the Atharvan as well
as in the other vedas (ऋग्वेदे सयजुर्वेदे
तथैवाथर्वसामसु … बहूनि मम
नामानि कीर्तितानि महर्षिभिः) 12. 328. 8-9;
the sage Sanatsujāta told Dhṛtarāṣṭra that
the highest principle (ब्रह्मन्) was not to
be found in the Atharvan मन्त्रस्, nor in the
ऋक्स्, the यजुस्, or the सामन्स् (नैवर्क्षु
तन् न यजुःषु नाप्य् अथर्वसु न चैव
दृश्यत्य् अमलेषु सामसु) 5. 44. 21.
C.
Object of study: Sages versed in the Atha-
rvaveda recited this Saṃhitā in accordance
with the पद and the क्रम mode of
recitation (अथर्ववेदप्रवराः … संहि-
ताम् ईरयन्ति स्म पदक्रमयुतां तु ते) 1.
64. 33; a certain Ṛṣi, born in the family of
a Purohita (not named), when grew up
learnt, among other sciences, the Veda and
the Atharvaveda (अथर्ववेदे वेदे च
बभूवर्षिः सुनिश्चितः) 13. 10. 34; Bhaga-
vān (Kṛṣṇa) told Arjuna that the Vipras
who had learnt the Atharvāṇa looked upon
him as Atharvan consisting of five कल्पस्,
enlarged by कृत्यास् (पञ्चकल्पम् अथर्वा-
णं कृत्याभिः परिबृंहितम्।कल्पयन्ति हि
मां विप्रा अथर्वाणविदस् तथा) 12. 330.
34.
D. Use: 1. For worship: When
the sage Aṅgiras visited Indra he used for
worshipping the god the मन्त्रस् from the
Atharvaveda (अथर्ववेदमन्त्रैश् च);
Indra, while giving the sage a boon addressed
him as Atharvāṅgiras and said that the
मन्त्रस् from the Atharvaveda used by him
for his praise would be known as the
Atharvāṅgirasa section of that Veda
(अथर्वाङ्गिरसं नाम अस्मिन् वेदे भ-
विष्यति।उदाहरणम् एतद् धि) 5. 18. 5-7;
2. For magic: the Daityas and the Dānavas
residing in the Pātāla and who had studied
the different मन्त्रस् performed a sacrificial
rite (कर्म वैतानसंभवम्) by using
मन्त्रस् which included those known from
the Atharvaveda (बृहस्पत्युशनोक्तैश् च
मन्त्रैर् मन्त्रविशारदाः।अथर्ववेद-
प्रोक्तैश् च) in order to produce a कृत्या who
was commissioned to fetch Duryodhana who
had decided to fast unto death 3. 239. 20.
E. Personified: the Atharvaveda, along with
the other three Vedas, seen by Nārada in the
Sabhā of god Brahmadeva (अथर्ववेदश्
च तथा … सर्वं तस्यां मया दृष्टम्) 2.
11. 23, 33, [See Atharvaśiras, Atharvāṅgi-
rasa, Ātharvaṇa]

अथर्वशिरस्
Atharvaśiras nt.: Name of an
Upaniṣad ?
A Brahmacārī who had observed the
vows (यतव्रत) and who had studied the
Atharvaśiras (अथर्वतिरसोऽध्येता) was to
be looked upon as respectable (पङ्क्तिपावन
‘who purifies those who sit along with him in
a line to take food’) 13. 90. 22 [cf. य इदम्
अथर्वशिरो ब्राह्मणोऽधीते अश्रोत्रियः
श्रोत्रियो भवति section 7 of the Atharva-
śiras Upaniṣad]; A Brāhmaṇa taught
Kuntī a group of मन्त्रस् which were
revealed in the Atharvaśiras (ततस् ताम्
अनवद्याङ्गीम् ग्राहयाम् आस वै द्विजः।
मन्त्रग्रामं तदा राजन्न् अथर्वशिरसि
श्रुतं); whichever deity Kuntī chose to
invite with one of the मन्त्रस् from this
मन्त्रग्राम was sure to arrive and be
under her control 3. 289. 20. [See
Atharvan, Atharvāṅgirasa, Ātharvaṇa]

अथर्वाङ्गिरस
Atharvāṅgirasa m. nt. (sg., pl.),
Atharvāṅgīrasī f.: Name of one of the
four Vedas, or of an extract from that Veda.
Bhagavān (Nārāyaṇa) told the seven
sages (Marīci, Atri and others 12. 322. 27)
that the शास्त्र composed by them in a
hundred thousand श्लोकस् and from which the
धर्म proceeds is one which is approved
by (i. e. is in accordance with) the Ṛks,
Yajus and Sāmans, as also the Atharvāṅgi-
rasas (कृतं शतसहस्रं हि श्लोकानाम्
इदम् उत्तमम्। … यस्माद् धर्मः
प्रवर्तते॥ … ऋग्यजुःसामभिर् जुष्टम्
अथर्वाङ्गिरसैस् तथा) 12. 322. 36-37; when
Kṛṣṇa asked Arjuna to insult Yudhiṣṭhira
which was as good as ‘killing’ him, he told
Arjuna that his instruction was according
to the Atharvāṅgirasī Śruti which was the
best among the Śrutis and which should be
practised without hesitation by those who
desired welfare (अथर्वाङ्गिरसी ह्य् एषा
श्रुतीनाम् उत्तमा श्रुतिः।अविचार्यैव
कार्यैषा श्रेयःकामैर् नरैः सदा॥) 8. 49.
69; an extract (उदाहरणम्) from the
Atharvaveda used by the sage Aṅgiras (or
Atharvāṅgiras 5. 18. 6, 8) to praise Indra was
to be known as Atharvāṅgirasa (अथर्वाङ्-
गिरसं नाम अस्मिन् वेदे भविष्यति।
उदाहरणम् एतद् धि) 5. 18. 5-7; the
Śakti hurled by Yudhiṣṭhira at Śalya is
compared with the कृत्या produced by the
मन्त्रस् from the Atharvāṅgirasa (कृत्याम्
अथर्वाङ्गिरसीम् इवोग्राम्) 9. 16. 43. [See
Atharvan, Atharvaśiras, Ātharvaṇa]

अनुक्रमणी
Anukramaṇī (-ṇi m. c.), Parvānu-
kramaṇī f.: Name of the first अध्याय
(अनुक्रमणिम् अध्यायम् 1. 1. 62, 199) or
पर्वन् in the list of a hundred sub-पर्वन्स्
of the Bhārata supposed to have been made
by Vyāsa in the Parvasaṃgraha (भारत-
स्त्येतिहासस्य श्रूयतां पर्वसंग्रहः।
पर्वानुक्रमणी पूर्वम्) 1. 2. 33-34, 70.
In this अध्याय the sage (Vyāsa) is
supposed to have made a summary of his
Bhārata listing the पर्वन्स् and their (main)
events in one hundred and fifty stanzas
(ततो ऽध्यर्धशतं ब्यूयः संक्षेपं
कृतवान् ऋषिः।अनुक्रमणिम् अध्यायं
वृत्तान्तानां सपर्वणाम्) 1. 1. 62; [actually
the first अध्याय does not list the पर्वन्स्,
which is done in the second अध्याय, but
gives an outline of the contents of the epic
from the conquests of Pāṇḍu to the end of the
war in श्लोकस् 65-158]; one who is faithful
(श्रद्दधानः), always striving, and truth-
ful and honours this अध्याय (not named
here) is freed from sin; one who always
hears this Anukramaṇi Adhyāya (अनुक्र-
मणिम् अध्यायम्) from the beginning with
faith (आस्तिकः) never perishes in adverse
circumstances; one who recites some portion
of Anukramaṇī at both the twilights is
freed from the guilt accumulated during the
day and the night 1. 1. 198-200; if one who
is pure recites this Adhyāya (not named) on
every पर्वन् day he has as good as recited
the whole of the Bhārata; one who with faith
constantly listens to this अध्याय (not named)
declared by the Ṛṣi (आर्षम्) shall obtain
long life, fame and heaven 1. 1. 206-207.

अनुगीता
Anugītā f.: Name of the 92nd पर्वन्
in the list of a hundred sub-पर्वन्स् of the
Bhārata supposed to have been made by
Vyāsa in the Parvasaṃgraha. It explains
matters related to the knowledge of the soul
(अनुगीता ततः पर्व ज्ञेयम् अध्यात्म-
वाचकम्) 1. 2. 66, 33, 70.
Related to Adhyāyas 14. 16-50 (some of
the Adhyāyas are also called Brāhmaṇagītā
or Guruśiṣyasaṃvāda).

अनुद्यूत
Anudyūta nt.: Name of the 28th पर्वन्
in the list of a hundred sub-पर्वन्स् of the
Bhārata supposed to have been made by
Vyāsa in the Parvasaṃgraha 1. 2. 41,
33, 70.
Referred to in the contents of the Sabhā-
pavan 1. 2. 102; related to Adhyāyas 2. 66-72.

अनुशासन
Anuśāsana, Ānuśāsana (1. 2. 201)
nt.: Name of the 13th पर्वन् of the
Bhārata (1. 2. 201, 204-205) among the
eighteen major पर्वन्स् 1. 2. 71.
According to the Parvasaṃgrahaparvan
it has 146 chapters (अध्यायस्) and 6700
stanzas (श्लोकस्) 1. 2. 205; it is described
as the best (उत्तम) 1. 2. 201, and having
many topics (सुबहुवृत्तान्त); considered
to be the best instruction (उत्तमं चानुशा-
सनम्) 1. 2. 204, leading to firm decisions
in matters of धर्म (धर्मनिश्च-
यकारक) 1. 2. 205; Yudhiṣṭhira, having
heard from Bhīṣma in this पर्वन् his deci-
sions on धर्म, regained composure (यत्र
प्रकृतिम् आपन्नः श्रुत्वा धर्मविनिश्च-
यम्) 1. 2. 201; here the matters related to
धर्म and अर्थ are fully described, as also
the fruits of different gifts, the nature of
those who deserve gifts, and the rules of
giving gifts; it deals with what is (good)
conduct and what one ultimately achieves
by observing truth 1. 2. 202-203; in this
पर्वन् is narrated also the attainment of
heaven by Bhīṣma 1. 2. 204. [See
Ānuśāsanika]

अभय
Abhaya m. Name of a dialogue
(संवाद) (संवादम् अभयं नाम
नामतः) that took place between a Brāh-
maṇa who was versed in ज्ञान and विज्ञान
and his wife Brāhmaṇī.
Called इतिहासम् पुरातनम् 14. 20. 1;
the dialogue started when the Brāhmaṇī
asked the Brāhmaṇa which world she would
go to (after death) having obtained him
for husband (14. 20. 4); in this dialogue the
Brāhmaṇa stands for mind (मनस्) and
the Brāhmaṇī for understanding (बुद्धि)
of Vāsudeva (Kṛṣṇa) 14. 34. 12; this
संवाद was narrated by Vāsudeva to Pārtha
(Arjuna); it comprises अध्यायस् 14. 20-34.

अभिमन्युवध
Abhimanyuvadha m.: Name of the 67th
पर्वन् in the list of a hundred sub-पर्वन्स्
of the Bhārata supposed to have been made
by Vyāsa in the Parvasaṃgraha 1. 2. 57,
33, 70; mentioned in the narration of the
contents of the Droṇaparvan 1. 2. 162; also
in the summary of the epic 1. 1. 132-134;
related to Adhyāyas 7. 32-51.

अम्बोपाख्यान
Ambopākhyāna nt.: Name of the 59th
पर्वन् in the list of a hundred sub-पर्वन्स्
of the Bhārata supposed to have been made
by Vyāsa in the Parvasaṃgraha 1. 2. 54,
33, 70; listed as one of the topics of the
Udyogaparvan 1. 2. 150; it comprises
Adhyāyas 5. 170-197.

अर्घाभिहरण
Arghābhiharaṇa nt.: Name of the 25th
पर्वन् in the list of a hundred sub-पर्वन्स्
of the Bhārata supposed to have been made
by Vyāsa in the Parvasaṃgraha 1. 2. 41,
33, 70; alluded to as अर्घसंवाद in the
narration of the contents of the Sabhāparvan
1. 2. 99; it comprises Adhyāyas 2. 33-36.

अर्जुनस्य
Arjunasya vane vāsaḥ m.: Name of
the 17th पर्वन् in the list of a hundred sub-
पर्वन्स् of the Bhārata supposed to have
been made by Vyāsa in the Parvasaṃgraha 1.
2. 38, 33, 70; alluded to as पार्थस्य वन-
वासः in the contents of the Ādiparvan
1. 2. 91; it comprises Adhyāyas 1. 205-210.

अश्मगीत
Aśmagīta nt.: Name of an ancient
Itihāsa 12. 28. 2.
In this Itihāsa, the Brāhmaṇa Aśman,
when questioned by king Janaka of Videha
who was overcome by grief how one should
face the acquisition and loss of relatives and
wealth, instructed him 12. 28. 2-57.

अश्वमेधिक
Aśvamedhika nt.: (1) Name of the 91st
पर्वन् in the list of a hundred sub-पर्वन्स्
of the Bhārata supposed to have been made
by Vyāsa in the Parvasaṃgraha 1. 2. 66, 33,
70; described as ‘the one that destroys all
sins’ (सर्वपापप्रणाशनम्) 1. 2. 66;
(2) Aśvamedhika (Āśvamedhika 1. 2. 210)
nt.: Name of the fourteenth पर्वन् among
the eighteen major पर्वन्स् of the Bhārata 1.
2. 206; 1. 2. 71; according to the Parvasaṃ-
grahaparvan it has 133 chapters (अध्यायस्)
and 3320 stanzas (श्लोकस्) as counted by
(Vyāsa) who sees the truth (संख्यातास्
तत्त्वदर्शिना) 1. 2. 210-211; described as
highly wonderful (महाद्भुत) 1. 2. 210;
this पर्वन् contains the following topics: the
excellent narrative of Saṃvarta and Marutta;
the acquisition of gold treasures (by the
Pāṇḍavas); the birth of Parikṣit; Parikṣit,
who was burnt by the fire of the missile,
brought back to life by Kṛṣṇa; the horse
(of the Aśvamedha sacrifice) set free for
wanderings; Arjuna who followed the horse
fought various battles with enraged princes;
Arjuna's life in danger in his battle with
Babhruvāhana, son of Citrāṅgadā; the story
narrated by the mongoose at the Aśvamedha
sacrifice 1. 2. 206-209.

अष्टावक्रीय
Aṣṭāvakrīya nt.: Name of an आख्यान
listed in the contents of the Āraṇyakaparvan
1. 2. 120.
Here is told how the sage Aṣṭāvakra
in a contest (विवाद) defeated Bandin and
brought back his father who was plunged into
the ocean water 1. 2. 120; comprises Adhyāyas
3. 132-134.

असित
Asita m.: Name of a मन्त्र (?) (of
a sage ?)
One who remembers the Asita मन्त्र
along with the Ārtimant and the Sunītha has
no fear from serpents by day or at night 1. 53.
23 (असितं चार्तिमन्तं च सुनीथं चापि
यः स्मरेत्।दिवा वा यदि वा रात्रौ नास्य
सर्पभयं भवेत्॥ Nī. on Bom. Ed. 1. 58.
23 says: प्रसङ्गात् सर्पभयनिवर्तकान्
मन्त्रान् पठति।असितम् इत्यादीन्). [See
Ārtimant and Sunītha].

आगस्त्य
Āgastya nt.: Name of an आख्यान।
Listed among the contents of the
Āraṇyakaparvan; the आख्यान narrates
incidents in Agastya's life which include
devouring of the demon Vātāpi and the
sage's approaching his wife Lopāmudrā for a
child 1. 2. 114; 3. 108. 19; related to the
incidents narrated in the Adhyāyas 3. 94-103.

आजगर
Ājagara nt.: Name of the 36th पर्वन्
in the list of a hundred sub-पर्वन्स् of the
Bhārata supposed to have been made by
Vyāsa in the Parvasaṃgraha 1. 2. 44, 33, 70.
Related to Adhyāyas 3. 173-178.

आथर्वण
Ātharvaṇa1 adj.: related to Atharvan,
i. e. the Atharvaveda.
When all the sages took the oath to
prove that they had not stolen Agastya's
lotus stalks, Śakra, when his turn came,
uttered a benediction (instead of a curse)
and said, among other things, “Let him
who has stolen your stalks be like a Brāh-
maṇa (विप्र) who takes bath after com-
pleting the study of the Ātharvaṇa Veda”
(आथर्वणं वेदम् अधीत्य विप्रः स्नायेत
यः पुष्करम् आददाति) 13. 96. 44.

आथर्वण
Ātharvaṇa2 adj.: A मन्त्र related to
the Atharvaveda.
These मन्त्रस् were used to cure the
poison of a scorpion, or various other kinds
of poisons (मद्रके संगतं नास्ति हतं
वृश्चिकतो भवेत्।आथर्वणेन मन्त्रेण
सर्वा शान्तिः कृता भवेत्॥इति वृश्चिकद-
ष्टस्य नानाविषहतस्य च।कुर्वन्ति
भेषजं प्राज्ञाः सत्यं तच् चापि दृश्यते॥)
8. 27. 83, 84.

आथर्वण
Ātharvaṇa3 adj.: A remedy prescribed
in the Atharvaveda.
प्रज्ञाशरेणाभिहतस्य जन्तोः … नाथ्-
अर्वणा नाप्य् अगदाः सुसिद्धाः 5. 37. 54
[Nī., however, आथर्वणा वेदमन्त्राः
on Bom. Ed. 5. 37. 58].

आदिपर्वन्
Ādiparvan nt.: Name of the first
पर्वन् of the Bhārata in a total of eighteen
major पर्वन्स् 1. 2. 95, 71.
Its contents are summarized in 1. 2.
71-95; (1. 1. 67-83; 1. 55. 6-37); accord-
ing to the Parvasaṃgrahaparvan it has 218
अध्यायस् and 7984 श्लोकस् as counted by
the great sage Vyāsa (संख्याते परमर्-
षिणा … व्यासेन) 1. 2. 95-96.

आदिवंशावतारण
Ādivaṃśāvatāraṇa nt.: Name of the
6th पर्वन् in the list of a hundred sub-
पर्वन्स् of the Bhārata supposed to have been
made by Vyāsa in the Parvasaṃgraha 1.
2. 34, 33, 70.
It narrates the origins of various Vipras,
as also of the sage Dvaipāyana (Vyāsa), the
partial descent of the gods, and the origins
of the Daityas, Dānavas, and of mighty
Yakṣas, also of Nāgas, serpents, Gandharvas,
and birds, and of various other beings 1. 2.
75-77; it comprises Adhyāyas 1. 54-61.

आनुशासनिक
Ānuśāsanika nt.: Name of the 89th
पर्वन् in the list of a hundred sub-पर्वन्स्
of the Bhārata supposed to have been made
by Vyāsa in the Parvasaṃgraha 1. 2. 65,
33, 70.
This is the 13th पर्वन् in the list of
the 18 parvans of the Bhārata [See
Anuśāsana]

आपद्धर्म
Āpaddharma m.: Name of the 87th
पर्वन् in the list of a hundred sub-पर्वन्स्
of the Bhārata supposed to have been made
by Vyāsa in the Parvasaṃgraha 1. 2. 64,
33, 70.
It forms a sub-पर्वन् of the 12th
Śāntiparvan and comprises Adhyāyas 12.
129-167; it lays down the emergency
duties which point to particular time as the
cause for their prescription; knowing these
a man becomes perfectly omniscient (आपद्-
धर्माश् च तत्रैव कालहेतुप्रदर्शकाः।
यान् बुद्ध्वा पुरुषः सम्यक् सर्वज्ञत्वम्
अवाप्नुयात्॥) 1. 2. 198 [Nī., however,
says कालो दुर्भिक्षादिर् हेतुर् वैररोगादिश्
च तत्प्रदर्शिनः देशकालाद्यपेक्षया वर्-
तितव्यम् इत्य् अर्थः Bom. Ed. 1. 2. 327].

आभिषेचनिक
Ābhiṣecanika nt.: Name of the 83rd
पर्वन् in the list of a hundred sub-पर्वन्स्
of the Bhārata supposed to have been made
by Vyāsa in the Parvasaṃgraha 1. 2. 62,
33, 70.
It deals with the consecration of Dhar-
marāja (Yudhiṣṭhira) 1. 2. 62 (cf. Śānti-
parvan Adhyāya 40).

आयुर्वेद
Āyurveda m.: Name of the science of
medicine.
Even the physicians studying the Āyur-
veda themselves or their families are afflicted
by diseases and although they take various
decoctions (कषायस्) and clarified butter
(सर्पींषि) for cure, they cannot avoid death
12. 28. 44-45;—Kṛṣṇa tells Arjuna that
his many names have been recounted by
great sages in the Sāṃkhya, the Yogaśāstra
and the Āyurveda 12. 328. 9; those versed
in the Āyurveda give the name Tridhātu to
Kṛṣṇa, since the body has three constituents
[bile (पित्त), phlegm (श्लेष्मन्) and
wind (वायु)] and is sustained by them
and when they are wasted away the body
is emaciated 12. 330. 21-22 [Nī. explains
Tridhātu as त्रयो धातव उपाधिभुताः
सन्त्य् अस्य स त्रिधातुः on Bom. Ed. 12.
342. 87].

आरणेय
Āraṇeya nt.: Name of the 44th पर्-
वन् in the list of a hundred sub-पर्वन्स् of
the Bhārata supposed to have been made by
Vyāsa in the Parvasaṃgraha 1. 2. 48, 33, 70.
In the brief enumeration of the contents
of the Āraṇyakaparvan it is called an
उपाख्यान where god Dharma instructed his
son (Yudhiṣṭhira), and then the Pāṇḍavas
having received the boon (from him) went
towards the west 1. 2. 127; related to the
अध्यायस् 3. 295-299.

आरण्यक
Āraṇyaka1 nt.: Name of the 29th पर्-
वन् in the list of a hundred sub-पर्वन्स् of
the Bhārata supposed to have been made by
Vyāsa 1. 2. 42, 33, 70.
Referred to as ‘where the citizens follow-
ed Yudhiṣṭhira (when he started to go to the
forest)’ while narrating the contents of the
Āraṇyakaparvan 1. 2. 105; it comprises
अध्यायस् 3. 1-11.

आरण्यक
Āraṇyaka2 nt.: Name of the third
पर्वन् among the eighteen major पर्वन्स्
of the Bhārata 1. 2. 105, 128.
Described as large (महत्) 1. 2. 105;
according to the Parvasaṃgrahaparvan it
contains 269 अध्यायस् and 11664 श्लोकस् as
counted by the great sage (Vyāsa) (सं-
ख्याते परमर्षिणा) 1. 2. 128-129; its
contents are summarized in 1. 2. 105-127;
Arjuna, when he vowed to kill Jayadratha
and then received the Pāśupata astra from
Śiva, remembered the boon he had received
from him and the sight he had obtained in
the Āraṇyaka (i. e. in the Āraṇyakaparvan
or during the stay in the forest ?) (ततः
प्रीतं भवं ज्ञात्वा स्मृतिमान् अर्जुनस्
तदा।वरम् आरण्यके दत्तं दर्शनं
शङ्करस्य च) 7. 57. 78.

आर्तिमत्|आर्तिमन्त्
Ārtimant m.: Name of a मन्त्र (?),
of a sage (?).
One who remembers the Ārtimant
मन्त्र along with the Asita and the Sunī-
tha has no fear from serpents either by
day or at night 1. 53. 23 (असितम् चार्तिमन्-
तं च सुनीथं चापि यः स्मरेत्।दिवा वा
यदि वा रात्रौ नास्य सर्पभयं भवेत्
(cf. Nī. Bom Ed. 1. 58. 23: प्रसङ्गात्
सर्पभयनिवर्तका मन्त्रान् पठति।
असितम् इत्यादीन्). [See Asita and Sunītha]

आश्रमवास
Āśramavāsa1 m.: Name of the 93rd
पर्वन् in the list of a hundred sub-पर्वन्स्
of the Bhārata supposed to have been made by
Vyāsa in the Parvasaṃgraha 1. 2. 67 (पर्व
चाश्रमवासाख्यम्), 33, 70.
It comprises अध्यायस् 15. 1-35.

आश्रमवास
Āśramavāsa2 m. (= Āśramavāsika nt.
so called in the colophons to the अध्यायस्
15, 30, 32, 35, 36, 37, 40, 43, 44, 46):
Name of the 15th पर्वन् among the 18
major पर्वन्स् of the Bhārata (तत आश्र-
मवासाख्यं पर्व पञ्चदशं स्मृतम्)
1. 2. 212, 218.
According to the Parvasaṃgrahaparvan it
has 42 chapters (अध्यायस्) and 1506 stanzas
(श्लोकस्) as counted by (Vyāsa) who sees
the truth (संख्यातास् तत्त्वदर्शिना) 1. 2.
218-219; in this पर्वन् Dhṛtarāṣṭra, with
Gāndhārī and Vidura, left the capital and
went to the hermitage; they were followed
by Pṛthā (Kuntī); in this hermitage the
king saw, by the favour of the sage Kṛṣṇa
(Vyāsa), his sons, grand-sons, and other
kings and heroes, who were killed in battle,
come back again; that was a wonder
unsurpassed (आश्चर्यम् अनुत्तमम् 1. 2.
215); seeing it Dhṛtarāṣṭra and Gāndhārī
abandoned grief and obtained high perfection
(सिद्धिं परमिकां गतः 1. 2. 215); in
this पर्वन्, we hear of Vidura and Saṃjaya
going to the next world; in this पर्वन्,
Yudhiṣṭhira met Nārada and heard from him
the great killing of the Vṛṣṇis (the Yādavas)
1. 2. 212-217.

आश्वमेधिक
Āśvamedhika nt.: Name of the 14th
पर्वन् in the list of the 18 major पर्वन्स्
of the Bhārata (1. 2. 210) [See Aśva-
medhika]

आस्तीक
Āstīka nt.: Name of the 5th पर्वन्
(also referred to as आख्यान, कथा and
पुराण इतिहास) in the list of a hundred
sub-पर्वन्स् of the Bhārata supposed to
have been made by Vyāsa in the Parva-
saṃgraha 1. 2. 34, 33, 70.
Described as great (महद् आख्यानम्
आस्तीकम्) 1. 13. 4, and attractive (कथाम्
एताम् मनोरमाम्।आस्तीकस्य) 1. 13. 5;
it comprises Adhyāyas 1. 13-53; in this
sub-पर्वन् we are told about the birth of
the snakes and of Garuḍa, the churning of
the milky ocean, the origin of Uccaiśravas;
it provides the setting for the narration of
the story of the Bhāratas to Janamejaya,
son of Parikṣit, who was offering the snake-
sacrifice 1. 2. 73-74; according to some the
Bhārata begins with the Āstīka (parvan)
(मन्वादि भारतं केचिद् आस्तीकादि
तथापरे) 1. 1. 50; Ruru wanted to
know the life story of Āstīka (आस्तीक-
चरित), and the narrative (आख्यान) was
told to him by his father Pramati 1. 12. 3,
5; the elders called it an ancient इतिहास
which was narrated by Kṛṣṇa Dvaipāyana
(Vyāsa) to the sages in the Naimiṣa forest
(इतिहासम् इमं वृद्धाः पुराणं परि-
चक्षते) 1. 13. 6; narrated by Sūta Loma-
harṣaṇa, pupil of Vyāsa, to the Brāhmaṇas
at their request; his son Sūta Ugraśravas
heard it from Lomaharṣaṇa and he, in turn,
narrated it to Śaunaka 1. 13. 7-8, 45;
Śaunaka again requested Sūta Ugraśravas
to tell the story (कथा) of Āstīka in
detail (सौते कथय ताम् एताम् विस्तरेण
कथां पुनः।आस्तीकस्य कवेः साधोः
शुश्रूषा परमा हि नः॥) 1. 14. 1; the
narrative of Āstīka confers long life (आयुष्-
यम् इदम् आख्यानम् आस्तीकम्) 1. 14. 4; the
आख्यान of Āstīka, his life-story (चरित),
is exceedingly pious (धर्मिष्ठ), increases
merit (of the listener) (पुण्यवर्धन),
and is illustrious (श्रीमत्); one who recites
it or listens to it from the very beginning
shall have no danger from the snakes 1. 53.
25-26.

इन्द्रलोकाभिगमन
Indralokābhigamana nt.: Name of the
32nd पर्वन् in the list of a hundred sub-
पर्वन्स् of the Bhārata supposed to have
been made by Vyāsa in the Parvasaṃgraha
1. 2. 43, 30, 70.
Alluded to in the contents of the Āraṇya-
kaparvan (दर्शनं लोकपालानां स्वर्गा-
रोहणम् एव च 1. 2. 107; it comprises the
अध्यायस् 3. 43-49; 79.

इन्द्रविजय
Indravijaya, Śakravijaya, Vijaya nt.:
Name of an आख्यान 5. 18. 19 or उपाख्यान
5. 18. 16; also called Śakravijaya (उपा-
ख्यानम् इदं शक्रविजयम्) 5. 18. 16,
or Vijaya (for short) 5. 18. 17.
It comprises अध्यायस् 5. 9-18; described
as an incident that occurred in the past, an
ancient इतिहास (पुरा वृत्तम् इतिहासं पुरा-
तनम्) 5. 9. 2; comparable to the Veda (in
importance) (वेदसंमितम्) 5. 18. 16; it
should be heard by a king desiring victory
when his army and that of his enemy are
arrayed (for a battle) 5. 18. 16; that is why
Śalya narrated the आख्यान Vijaya, in which
Indra's victory over Vṛtra and the downfall
of Nahuṣa were described, to Yudhiṣṭhira
before the start of the war 5. 18. 17; one who
diligently (नियतः) recites this Indravijaya
Ākhyāna is washed of all his sins, wins
heaven, and rejoices in this as well as in
the next world; he has no danger from the
enemy, and is never without a son (i. e. he
does not lose his sons in war ? न चारिजं
भयं तस्य न चापुत्रो भवेन् नरः); he
does not meet with adversity and gets long
life; he is victorious in all battles and never
knows defeat 5. 18. 19-20.

उद्योगपर्वन्
Udyogaparvan1 nt.: Name of the 49th
पर्वन् in the list of a hundred sub-पर्वन्स्
of the Bhārata supposed to have been made
by Vyāsa in the Parvasaṃgraha 1. 2. 49,
33, 70.
Described as highly wonderful (महा-
द्भुत) 1. 2. 49; alluded to briefly in the
narration of the contents of the Udyoga-
parvan—where Duryodhana and Arjuna
waited on Vāsudeva (Kṛṣṇa) for help in the
ensuing war and where Duryodhana opted for
the army, अक्षौहिणी strong, of Kṛṣṇa, while
Arjuna opted for Kṛṣṇa as a non-combatant
counsellor (अयुध्यमानं सचिवं) 1. 2.
136-139; (also 1. 1. 118); it comprises
अध्यायस् 5. 1-21.

उद्योगपर्वन्
Udyogaparvan,2 Udyoga nt.: Name of
the fifth पर्वन् in the list of the eighteen
major पर्वन्स् of the Bhārata 1. 2. 136, 151,
71; called Udyoga (for short) 6. 41. 81;
6. 95. 11.
It contains many events (सुबहुवृत्तान्त)
and is concerned with the efforts for peace
and war (संधिविग्रहसंश्रित) 1. 2. 151;
according to the Parvasaṃgraha it has 186
अध्यायस् and 6698 श्लोकस् as told by
Vyāsa (प्रोक्ताः … महात्मना।व्यासेनोदार-
मतिना) 1. 2. 152-153; summary of its con-
tents: when the Pāṇḍavas resided in Upa-
plavya, Duryodhana and Arjuna approached
Vāsudeva (Kṛṣṇa) to seek his help in the com-
ing war; when Kṛṣṇa asked them to choose
between himself and his army, Duryodhana
chose the latter, while Dhanaṃjaya chose
the former; Dhṛtarāṣṭra sent Saṃjaya as his
envoy to the Pāṇḍavas for conciliation; Dhṛta-
rāṣṭra having come to know (from Saṃjaya)
that the Pāṇḍavas would be led by Kṛṣṇa lost
sleep due to anxiety; Vidura gave Dhṛta-
rāṣṭra much sound advice; the sage Sanat-
sujāta gave him an excellent discourse on
the doctrine of soul (अध्यात्मम् अनुत्त-
मम् … श्रावितः); Saṃjaya told Dhṛta-
rāṣṭra about the close association of Vāsu-
deva and Arjuna; Kṛṣṇa himself left for
Hāstinapura to seek conciliation with the
Kauravas; Duryodhana's rejection of Kṛṣṇa's
proposal which would be for the benefit
of both the parties; Kṛṣṇa sensing the
evil intention of Karṇa, Duryodhana and
the rest (to imprison him) displayed his
prowess as a योगेश्वर to the kings; Kṛṣṇa
tried to win over Karṇa to the side of the
Pāṇḍavas but Karṇa, due to his sense of
pride, did not oblige; the army consisting of
chariots, horses, soldiers and elephants,
marched out of Hāstinapura; counting of
the forces; Ulūka sent as a messenger to
the Pāṇḍavas a day before the war; counting
of the रथिन्स् and अतिरथिन्स्; the narrative
of Ambā 1. 2. 136-150 (also 1. 1. 116-120);
Yudhiṣṭhira asked Śalya to fulfil the boon he
gave to Yudhiṣṭhira in the Udyoga (i. e. in
the Udyogaparvan) and weaken the vigour
(तेजोवध) of Karṇa during the war (a
reference to 5. 18. 22-24) 6. 41. 81; that
Śikhaṇḍin was first born as a woman was
told by Bhīṣma in the Udyoga (reference to
5. 189-193) 6. 95. 11.

उलूकदूतागमन
Ulūkadūtāgamana (also known as
Ulūkayāna) nt.: Name of the 58th पर्वन्
in the list of a hundred sub-पर्वन्स् of the
Bhārata supposed to have been made by Vyāsa
in the Parvasaṃgraha 1. 2. 53, 33, 70.
Counted in the contents of the Udyoga-
parvan; it relates to the dispatch Ulūka as
a messenger to the Pāṇḍavas on the eve of
the battle 1. 2. 150; comprises अध्यायस्
5. 157-161.

ऋग्वेद
Ṛgveda m.: Name of one of the four
Vedic Saṃhitās.
A. Relationship with Kṛṣṇa-Nārāyaṇa:
Nārāyaṇa, the greatest of the gods (देव-
देव 3. 186. 129), told the sage Mārkaṇḍeya
that the Ṛgveda and the other Vedas arise
from him and enter into him (मत्तः
प्रादुर्भवन्त्य् एते माम् एव प्रविशन्ति च)
3. 187. 14; Bhagavān (Kṛṣṇa) told Arjuna
that in the Ṛgveda and in many other texts
his names have been enumerated by great
sages (ऋग्वेदे … बहूनि मम नामानि
कीर्तितानि महर्षिभिः) 12. 328. 8-9; those
versed in the Vedas call Bhagavān as the
Ṛgveda of twentyone branches (एकविंशति-
शाखं च ऋग्वेदं मां प्रचक्षते। …
ये वै वेदविदो जनाः) 12. 330. 32.
B.
Source of mythology and व्रतस्: Gṛtsamada,
son of Vītahavya, who in appearance was
like another Indra, was once caught hold
of by the Daityas; this incident is referred to
in the Ṛgveda (cf. ṚV. 2. 12) where Gṛtsa-
mada is glorified by the Brāhmaṇas (ऋग्वेदे
वर्तते चाग्र्या श्रुतिर् अत्र विशां पते
यत्र गृत्समदो ब्रह्मन् ब्राह्मणैः स
महीयते) 13. 31. 56; a व्रत called Trisau-
parṇavrata, difficult to observe, is found in
the Ṛgveda (ऋग्वेदपाठपठितं व्रतम्
एतद् धि दुश्चरम्) 12. 336. 20.
C.
Ṛgveda personified: (1) Ṛgveda, along
with the Sāmaveda and the Purāṇas, move
in front of the chariot of Mahādeva to
protect it (when Śiva got ready to fight
with the Tripuras) 8. 24. 80; (2) Ṛgveda
together with the other three Vedas, visit the
Sabhā of Brahmadeva (2. 11. 19) and wait
on him 2. 11. 23, 31; (3) Ṛgveda, adorned
with क्रम and पद, came to the sacrifice
of Mahādeva (Śiva) who had assumed the
form of Varuṇa 13. 85. 4, 2. [See Ṛc]

ऋच्
Ṛc f. (mostly plural): Often stands
for the Ṛgveda or stanzas in it; in such
contexts Ṛc often occurs along with Yajus
and Sāman.
A. Number: their number given as
ten thousand (दशेदम् ऋक्सहस्राणि) 12.
238. 14 (दश किंचिदधिकानि ऋक्सहस्राणि)
Nī. on Bom. Ed. 12. 246. 14).
B. Their
study recommended and their chanting
referred to: the Brāhmaṇas are enjoined to
study the ऋच्स्, the यजुसेस् and the सामन्स्
(सर्वान् वेदान् अधीयीत … ऋचो यजूंषि
सामानि) 12. 243. 2; 12. 260. 36; these are
to be studied with due respect for the
teacher; hence, while taking an oath to prove
his innocence, Bharadvāja said: “who steals
the lotus-stalks, may he study ऋच्स् and
यजुसेस् disrespecting his teacher” (उपाध्या-
यम् अधः कृत्वा ऋचो ऽध्येतु यजूंषि च।
 … बिसस्तैन्यं करोति यः) 13. 95. 62; a
Brāhmaṇa who can recite the ऋच्स्, the यजुसेस्
and sing the सामन्स् is considered to be the
proper person to receive gifts (ऋग्यजुःसामगो
विद्वान् … पात्रम् उच्यते) 12. 297. 15; such
a learned Brāhmaṇa is to be honoured as
a god (ऋग्यजुःसामविद् पूज्यो नित्यं स्याद्
देववद् द्विजः) 12. 60. 42; Brāhmaṇas, ac-
companying the Pāṇḍavas to the Dvaitavana,
recited ऋच्स्, यजुसेस्, and सामन्स् (यजुषां
ऋचां च साम्नां च … आसीद् उच्चार्यमा-
णानाम् निस्वनो हृदयंगमः) 3. 27. 3;
those who had studied the ऋच्स्, recited them
according to the पद- and the क्रम-पाठ
in the sacrificial rites performed in Kaṇva's
hermitage (ऋचो बह्वृचमुख्यैश् च प्रेर्-
यमाणाः पदक्रमैः।शुष्राव … विततेष्व्
इह कर्मसु) 1. 64. 31; one should study
त्रयी विद्या (threefold knowledge), detailed
in the Vedas, from ऋच्, यजुस्, सामन्, and
अथर्वन् (त्रयीविद्याम् अवेक्षेत वेदेषूक्ताम्
अथाङ्गतः।ऋक्सामवर्णाक्षरतो यजुषो
ऽथर्वणस् तथा) 12. 227. 1.
C. Their
importance for Dharmaśāstra and Adhyātma-
śāstra: the शास्त्र, consisting of a hundred
thousand श्लोकस्, produced by the seven
sages, Marīci, Atri and others (12. 322.
26-27), and which is approved by the
ऋच्स्, यजुसेस् and सामन्स्, as well as by the
अथर्वाङ्गिरसस् will be the source of
धर्म (कृतं शतसहस्रं हि श्लोकानाम्
इदम् उत्तमम्। … प्रवृत्तौ च निवृत्तौ च
योनिर् एतद् भविष्यति।ऋग्यजुःसामभिर्
जुष्टम् अथर्वाङ्गिरसैस् तथा॥) 12. 322.
36-37; Bhagavān (Kṛṣṇa) identifies himself
with ऋच्, सामन् and यजुस् (अहम् … ऋक्
साम यजुर् एव च) 6. 31. 17; the शास्त्र
constituting the secret of all the Vedas and
leading to the knowledge of आत्मन् was
churned out like nectar from the ten thou-
sand ऋच्स् (रहस्यं सर्ववेदानां … आत्म-
प्रत्ययिकं शास्त्रं … दशेदम् ऋक्सह-
स्राणि निर्मथ्यामृतम् उद्धृतम्) 12. 238.
13-14; there is only one सामन्, one यजुस्
and one ऋच् (एकं साम यजुर् एकम् ऋग्
एका) 12. 60. 45 (Nī. on 12. 60. 47 Bom.
Ed. अकारो वै सर्वा वाक् … इति श्रुतेर् एकम्
अकाररूपम् एव अक्षरं यथा सामादिरू-
पम्).
D. Their use and importance for
rites (real or metaphorical): ऋच्स् and
सामन्स् were chanted at the cremation
rites of those fallen in the war (साम्नां
ऋचां च नादेन) 11. 26. 40; those who know
Nārāyaṇa recite ऋच्स् (= stanzas as holy ऋच्स् ?)
to the effect that when formerly animals were
bound for the god Nārāyaṇa सामन्स् were
sung 14. 25. 16-17 (Nī. on 14. 25. 16
Bom. Ed.: ऋचः ‘तप आसीद् गृहपतिर्’
(Tai. Br. 3. 12. 9. 3) इत्याद्याः … शंसन्ति
योगयज्ञे प्रमाणत्वेन कथयन्ति तैत्तिरी-
यादयः।नारायणविदः वेदविद आत्मविदो
वा।नारायणाय आत्मप्राप्त्यर्थं यत्
यदा पशून् इन्द्रियाणि अविन्दन् वश्यत्वेन
प्राप्तवन्तः); a sacrifice has seventeen
constituents three of which are ऋच्स्, यजुसेस्
and सामन्स् (ऋचो यजूंषि सामानि … अङ्गान्य्
एतानि यज्ञस्य) 12. 260. 26.
E. Ṛcs used
for praising various deities: In this context
ऋच् does not always mean a stanza from
the Ṛgveda, but also one similar to it, or a
stanza in general: (1) Excellent Brāh-
maṇas praised Indra with praises consisting
of ऋच्स्, यजुसेस् and सामन्स् (स्तूयमानं
द्विजाग्र्यैश् च ऋग्यजुःसामसंस्तवैः) 3.
44. 18; (2) son of Ṛcīka (Śunaḥśepa),
having praised with ऋच्स् gods who receive
shares in sacrifices, became Viśvāmitra's
son (ऋग्भिः स्तुत्वा महाभागो देवान् वै
यज्ञभागिनः) 12. 281. 13; (3) various
sages (Asita Devala and others 12. 281.
15-16) praised Viṣṇu with ऋच्स् and obtained
सिद्धि by practising तपस् due to his favour
(स्तुत्वा विष्णुम् ऋग्भिः) 12. 281. 17; (4)
Vyāsa, his pupils, and his son Śuka praised
Hari with ऋच्स् from all the four Vedas (स
चास्माकम् उपाध्यायः सहास्माभिर् विशां
पते।चतुर्वेदोद्गताभिश् च ऋग्भिस् तम्
अभितुष्टुवे) 12. 327. 100; Vyāsa and other
sages worshipped Kṛṣṇa with praises consi-
sting of ऋच्स्, यजुसेस् and सामन्स् (ऋग्यजुः-
सामसंयुक्तैर् वचोभिः कृष्णम् अर्चयन्)
12. 52. 22; sages praised Madhusūdana with
praises adorned with the contents of ऋच्स्
(वाग्भिर् ऋग्भूषितार्थाभिः) 13. 126. 46;
(5) Upamanyu, as directed by his teacher
Dhaumya, praised Aśvins with the ऋच्
stanzas (1. 3. 60-70 which actually are not
from the Ṛgveda) to regain his eye-sight
(वाग्भिर् ऋग्भिः) 1. 3. 59; (6) Śiva is
praised with ऋच्स् in Tantric rites by those
who are versed in the Ṛgveda (ऋग्भिर् यम्
अनुशंसन्ति तन्त्रे कर्मणि बह्वृचः)
(? बह्वृचाः)) 13. 16. 48; sages praised
goddess Umā with praises adorned with the
contents of the ऋच्स् (वाग्भिर् ऋग्भूषितार्था-
भिः) 13. 128. 24.
F. Their importance
and utility limited: Sage Sanatsujāta told
Dhṛtarāṣṭra that the छन्दस् (ऋच्), यजुस्
and सामन् did not save one from sin 5. 43.
1-3; the ऋच्स्, the सामन्स् and the यजुसेस्
have a beginning and therefore an end i. e.
they are not eternal (12. 199. 16-18); the
अक्षर पद is not to be found in the ऋच्स्,
यजुसेस्, अथर्वन्स्, and सामन्स् 5. 44. 21;
even after studying the collections of the
ऋच्स् and the सामन्स्, and the यजुसेस्
Bṛhaspati did not know the source of beings
(ऋक्सामसंघांश् च यजूंषि चाहम् …
अधीत्य … भूतप्रकृइत्ं न वेद्मि) 12.
194. 8; mortals who believed in non-
distinction (between ब्रह्मन् and आत्मन्)
having seen that the ऋच्स्, the सामन्स्,
the यजुसेस् and the prosperity desired
(through them) was something distinct (from
the highest self) (resorted) to तपस् by
practising austerities (अपृथग्धर्मिणो
मर्त्या ऋक्सामानि यजूंषि च।काम्यां
पुष्टिम् पृथग् दृष्ट्वा तपोभिस् तप एव
च) 12. 224. 63 (अद्वैतनिष्ठा मर्त्यास्
तप एव योगम् एव कृतयुगे ऽनुतिष्ठन्तीति
शेषः।ऋगादीनि काम्या इष्टीश् च … पृथक्
तपोभिर् आलोचनैः दृष्ट्वा … तत् परित्यज्य
योगपरा एव बभूवुर् इत्य् अर्थः Nī. on
Bom. Ed. 12. 232. 33); also cf. तपोयज्ञा
द्विजातयः 12. 224. 61; all those who see
the non-distinction (between पौरुष कर्म
दैव, and स्वभाव 12. 230. 4-5), keep away
(दृष्ट्वा = कृत्वा) their love and hatred for
ऋच्स्, सामन्स् and यजुसेस्, and practise तपस्
in the Kṛta age (अपृथग्दर्शिनः सर्वे
ऋक्सामसु यजुःषु च।कामद्वेशौ पृथग्
दृष्ट्वा तपः कृत उपासते) 12. 230. 8 (Nī.
however, on Bom. Ed. 12. 238. 8: वेदत्रये ऽपि
भेदम् अपश्यन्तः काम्यादीन् (? कामादीन्)
पृथक्कृत्य तपो ज्ञानम् उपासते श्रयन्ति).
[See Ṛgveda]

ऋषिवंश
Ṛṣivaṃśa m.: Name of a passage in
the Anuśāsanaparvan listing the names of
sages and also of kings, some of whom are
royal sages (राजर्षि) 13. 151. 30-51.
The names of sages, rich in austerities,
who having practised austerities had attained
perfection (विप्रांस् तपःसिद्धांस् तपोधि-
कान् 13. 151. 30) are listed according to the
quarters they occupy: Yavakrīta, Raibhya,
Kakṣīvān and some others in the east;
Ulmucu, Pramucu, Mumucu and some
others in the south; Uṣadgu and his brothers,
Parivyādha, Dīrghatamas and some others
in the west; Atri, Vasiṣṭha, Śakti and some
others in the north 13. 151. 31-40; the
recitation of the Ṛṣivaṃśa, along with that
of the Daivatavaṃśa, at two twilights is
very effective in removing sins (द्विसं-
ध्यं पठितः पुत्र कल्मषापहरः
परः) 13. 151. 2; (कीर्तितान् … सर्वपापप्र-
मोचनान्) 13. 151. 30; then follow names of
kings beginning with Nṛga and ending with
Kakṣasena 13. 151. 41-50; some of these
kings are royal sages, viz. Mucakunda
(राजर्षिः) 13. 151. 46; Śveta (राजर्षिसत्-
तमः) 13. 151. 47, Kṣupa (राजर्षिः) 13.
151. 48, Nala (राजर्षिः) 13. 151. 49, and
Kakṣasena (राजर्षिः) 13. 151. 50; the list
is apparently intended to be recited by one
who does not wish to meet with difficulties, nor
incur sin, nor encounter enemies, and by one
who wishes to have sure victory and great
happiness after death (मा विघ्नं मा
च मे पापं मा च मे परिपन्थिनः।
ध्रुवो जयो मे नित्यं स्यात् परत्र च परा
गतिः) 13. 151. 51.

ऐषीक
Aiṣīka nt.: Name of the 79th पर्वन्
in the list of a hundred sub-पर्वन्स् of the
Bhārata supposed to have been made by
Vyāsa in the Parvasaṃgraha 1. 2. 61, 30, 70.
Described as very frightful (सुदारुण)
1. 2. 61; it is said to be the continuation of
the Sauptikaparvan (सौप्तिकैषीकसं-
बन्धे पर्वणि) 1. 2. 190; referred to in
Dhṛtarāṣṭra's summary made for Saṃjaya 1. 1.
154-156; it comprises the last nine अध्यायस्
of the Sauptikaparvan 10. 10-18.

ओङ्कार|ॐकार
Oṃkāra m.: Name of the sacred
syllable.
Suparṇa (Garuḍa) told Gālava that in
the east ॐकार was produced 1000 times
(? ॐकारस्यात्र जायन्ते सूतयो दशतीर्
दश) 5. 106. 14 (Nī., however, takes
दशती to mean ‘one thousand’ and reads
सृतयो for सूतयो; he explains the line as:
दशशतीशब्दस्य पृषोदरादिशकारलोपेन
दशतीशब्दः सहस्रवाची सृतयो मार्गाः।
‘ॐकारो वै सर्वा वाक्’ इति श्रुतेर् वेदस्य
शाखाप्रशाखादिभेदो ऽत्रैव जात इत्य्
अर्थः on Bom. Ed. 5. 108. 14); the शास्त्र
that was proclaimed unanimously by the
seven sages Marīci, Atri, Aṅgiras, Pulastya,
Pulaha, Kratu and Vasiṣṭha (12. 322. 27) was
at the very beginning adorned with the syllable
ओम् (आदाव् एव हि तच्छास्त्रम् ॐकारस्वर-
भूषितम्) 12. 322. 34; when Agni was
cursed by Bhṛgu, he disappeared; then the
people, since they could not give offerings
in the fire became devoid of ॐकारस् and
वषट्कारस् (निर्ॐकारवषट्काराः … विना-
ग्निना प्रजाः सर्वास् तत आसन् सुदुःखिताः)
1. 7. 13.

औद्दालकीय
Auddālakīya nt.: Name of an आख्यान
mentioned while listing the contents of the
Āraṇyakaparvan (सावित्र्यौद्दालकीयं च)
1. 2. 126.
Not found as an independent आख्यान in
the Āraṇyakakaparvan; reference to 3. 132 ?

और्व
Aurva nt.: Name of an आख्यान
mentioned while listing the contents of the
Ādiparvan 1. 2. 87.
Described as best (1. 2. 87); it occurs
as a section (1. 169-172) of the Caitra-
rathaparvan 1. 153-173.

औशनस
Auśanasa adj.: of a शास्त्र proclaimed
by Uśanas; mentioned along with Bṛhaspati-
mata 12. 122. 11.
Uśanas and Bṛhaspati were to revive
the शास्त्र proclaimed by the seven sages
(Marīci, Atri, Aṅgiras, Pulastya, Pulaha,
Kratu and Vasiṣṭha 12. 322. 26-27, 29; (its
contents 12. 322. 30); 12. 322. 42-43 (उशना
बृहस्पतिश् चैव यदोत्पन्नौ भविष्यतः।
तदा प्रवक्ष्यतः शास्त्रम् युष्मन्मतिभिर्
उद्धृतम्); it was learnt by king Vasuhoma,
who had also learnt the शास्त्र (मत)
of Bṛhaspati (बृहस्पतेर् मतं राजन्न्
अधीतं सकलं त्वया।तथैवौशनसं
शास्त्रं विज्ञातं ते नराधिप॥), and there-
fore king Māndhātṛ wanted to know from
Vasuhoma how दण्ड came into existence
for the maintenance of discipline among the
subjects (प्रजाविनयरक्षार्थम्) 12. 122.
12-14. [See Bṛhaspatimata]

कर्णपर्वन्
Karṇaparvan nt.: Name of the 73rd
पर्वन् of the Bhārata in the list of a hundred
sub-पर्वन्स् supposed to have been made by
Vyāsa in the Parvasaṃgraha 1. 2. 59, 33, 70;
it is listed as the eighth पर्वन् in the list
of the eighteen major parvans by those
who have thought about Bhārata (भारत-
चिन्तकैः) 1. 2. 169, 172, 233, 71.
Described as containing great wonders
(परमाद्भुतम्); it has 69 Adhyāyas and
4900 Ślokas 1. 2. 169, 172; in this पर्वन् we
are told the following: (1) the Madrarāja
(Śalya) was asked to act as a charioteer;
(2) an ancient आख्यान about the destruction
of the Tripuras; (3) harsh dispute between
Karṇa and Śalya; (4) the story of the
swan and the crow; (5) Yudhiṣṭhira and
Arjuna getting angry with each other; (6)
Karṇa's death at the hands of Arjuna in
a duel that was fought from chariots
(द्वैरथ) 1. 2. 169-171; the last incident
is referred to in Dhṛtarāṣṭra's summary made
for Saṃjaya 1. 1. 146.

कर्णस्य
Karṇasya vivādaparva: Name of the
55th पर्वन् in the list of a hundred sub-
पर्वन्स् of the Bhārata supposed to have
been made by Vyāsa in the Parvasaṃgraha
(ज्ञेयं विवादपर्वात्र कर्णस्यापि महात्-
मनः) 1. 2. 52, 33, 70; (कृष्णकर्णसं-
वादरूपं पर्व Nī. on Bom. Ed. 1. 2. 64).
Referred to in the listing of the contents
of the Udyogaparvan (रथम् आरोप्य
कृष्णेन यत्र कर्णोनुमन्त्रितः) 1. 2. 148
(अनुमन्त्रितः उपजापितः उपायपूर्वं
भेदपूर्वम् Nī. on Bom. Ed. 1. 2. 236);
related to the incidents narrated in the
Adhyāyas 5. 138-148.

कापव्यचरित
Kāpavyacarita nt.: The story of
Kāpavya, born of a Niṣāda woman from a
Kṣatriya father 12. 133. 25, 3.
This is cited by Bhīṣma as an ancient
narrative (इतिहासं पुरातनम्) 12. 133. 1;
it describes how Kāpavya instructed the
Dasyus to follow the right path 12. 133.
13-22; one who narrates this Kāpavyacarita
need have no fear from the forest-dwellers,
nor from human beings, nor immortal ones
12. 133. 25-26.

कामशास्त्र
Kāmaśāstra nt.: A text dealing with
the art of love.
One who knows how to destroy the
(teachings of the) Kāmaśāstra gets over all
miseries (एवं यो वेद … वधं वै
कामशास्त्रस्य स दुःखान्य् अतिवर्तते 12.
246. 8; Nī. who reads बन्धं वै काम-
शास्त्रस्य adds वधम् इति पाठे त्यागम्
on Bom. Ed. 12. 254. 8).

कार्ष्ण
Kārṣṇa adj.: of the Veda; the Bhārata
or the Mahābhārata so called because it was
composed by Kṛṣṇa (Dvaipāyana).
One, who having known the Veda of
Kṛṣṇa, i. e. the Mahābhārata, recites it to
those that are noble-minded, generous, truth-
ful, and who are not atheists achieves his
objective (अक्षुद्रान् दानशीलांश् च सत्य-
शीलान् अनास्तिकान्।काऋष्णं वेदम् इमं
विद्वाञ् छ्रावयित्वार्थम् अश्नुते) 1. 56. 17;
the reciter is also no doubt freed of the sin of
killing an embryo (भ्रूणहत्याकृतं चापि
पापं जह्यान् न संशयः) 1. 56. 17; 1.
1. 205. [See Bhārata, Mahābhārata]

किर्मीरवध
Kirmīravadha m.: Name of the 30th
पर्वन् of the Bhārata in the list of a
hundred sub-पर्वन्स् supposed to have been
made by Vyāsa in the Parvasaṃgraha 1. 2.
42, 33, 70.
Referred to in the listing of the contents
of the Āraṇyakaparvan 1. 2. 106; related
to the incidents narrated in the Adhyāya
3. 12.

कीचकानां
Kīcakānāṃ vadhaḥ: Name of the
46th पर्वन् of the Bhārata in the list of a
hundred sub-पर्वन्स् supposed to have been
made by Vyāsa in the Parvasaṃgraha 1. 2.
48, 33, 70.
Referred to in the listing of the con-
tents of the Virāṭaparvan 1. 2. 131; related
to the incidents of the Adhyāyas 4. 13-23.

कुण्डलाहरण
Kuṇḍalāharaṇa nt.: Name of the 43rd
पर्वन् of the Bhārata in the list of a
hundred sub-पर्वन्स् supposed to have been
made by Vyāsa in the Parvasaṃgraha 1. 2.
47, 33, 70.
Referred to in the listing of the contents
of the Āraṇyakaparvan 1. 2. 127; related to
the incidents narrated in Adhyāyas 3. 284-
294.

कैरात
Kairāta nt.: Name of the 31st पर्वन्
in the list of a hundred sub-पर्वन्स् of the
Bhārata supposed to have been made by
Vyāsa in the Parvasaṃgraha 1. 2. 42, 33, 70.
Referred to in the listing of the con-
tents of the Āraṇyakaparvan 1. 2. 107;
alluded to in 5. 195. 12 (यत् तद् घोरं
पशुपतिः प्रादाद् अस्त्रं महन् मम।
कैराते द्वन्द्वयुद्धे वै तद् इदं मयि
वर्तते); the incident in this पर्वन् men-
tioned by Dhṛtarāṣṭra in his summary made
for Saṃjaya 1. 1. 109; related to the incidents
narrated in the Adhyāyas 3. 24-42.

क्षेमदर्शीय
Kṣemadarśīya nt.: Name of an Itihāsa
(अत्रायं क्षेमदर्शीयम् इतिहासो ऽनुगीयते)
12. 105. 2.
It was narrated by Bhīṣma to Yudhiṣ-
ṭhira in reply to his question how a righte-
ous king, when oppressed by his ministers
and deprived of his treasure and authority
(च्युतः कोशाच् च दण्डाच् च), should act if
he sought happiness 12. 105. 1-2; this advice
was earlier sought by prince Kṣemadarśa
(and hence so called) from the sage Kālaka-
vṛkṣīya 12. 105. 3 ff.

खड्गसाधन
Khaḍgasādhana nt.: Name (?) of a
chapter (12. 160) in the Śāntiparvan in
which the acquisition of the sword is narra-
ted 12. 160. 87; also described as ‘acquain-
ting (the hearer) with the creation of the
sword’ (?) (इत्य् एष प्रथमः कल्पो व्या-
ख्यातस् ते सुविस्तरः।असेर् उत्पत्तिसंसर्-
गः) 12. 160. 86.
Described as best (उत्तम) 12. 160.
87; the origin of the sword was narrated by
Bhīṣma, lying on the bed of arrows, to
Nakula, who was expert in wielding a sword,
at the latter's request 12. 160. 1, 8, 9; a
‘being’ (भूतम्) called ‘sword’ (असि) was
conceived by Pitāmaha (मयैतच् चिन्तितं
भूतम् असिर् नाम) for the protection of
the world and destruction of the enemies of
gods; the ‘being’ then gave up its form and
became निस्त्रिंश (ततस् तद् रूपम् उत्षृज्य
बभौ निस्त्रिंश एव सः) 12. 160. 42-43;
the असि or निस्त्रिंश is described as spot-
less (विमल) 12. 160. 43, shining (दीप्त)
12. 160. 44; sharp-edged (तीक्ष्णधार) 12.
160. 43; strong (वीर्यवन्त्) 12. 160. 42;
warding off अधर्म (अधर्मप्रतिवारण)
12. 160. 44; great (परम) 12. 160. 79;
ready to strike like a Kālāntaka (कालान्तक
इवोद्यतः) 12. 160. 43; foremost among
weapons (अग्र्यः प्रहरणानां च) 12.
160. 83; protector of धर्म (धर्मस्य
गोप्तारम्) 12. 160. 64; the interior of which
was धर्म (धर्मगर्भ) 12. 160. 67;
the असि, after its creation, was given by
god Brahman first to Rudra 12. 160. 42, 44;
with that निस्त्रिंश in hand Rudra cut off,
broke, wounded, tore asunder, split open, and
destroyed the Daityas (छिन्दन् भिन्दन्
रुजन् कृन्तन् दारयन् प्रमथन्न् अपि।
अचरद् दैत्यसंघेषु रुद्रः) 12. 160.
55; god Rudra then honoured Viṣṇu and
handed over the sword to him; from Viṣṇu
it passed successively through various
hands to different persons until from the
guardians of the world (लोकपालस्) it
came to Manu, the son of Sūrya and lord
of men; Manu was asked to protect his
subjects with the sword 12. 160. 64-67;
from Manu it again changed hands through
successive generations of kings until it came
from Bharadvāja to Droṇa, then to Kṛpa, and
finally from him to Nakula and his brothers
(ततस् त्वं भ्रातृभिः सार्धं परमासिम्
अवाप्तवान्) 12. 160. 71-79; the असि is
governed by the नक्षत्र Kṛttikā, its deity
is Agni, its गोत्र is Rohiṇis, and its गुरु
is Rudra 12. 160. 80; असि has eight secret
names (नामानि रहस्यानि) which were told
by Bhīṣma to Nakula: असि, विशसन, खड्ग,
तीक्ष्णवर्त्मन्, दुरासद, श्रीगर्भ, विजय,
and धर्मपाल 12. 160. 81-82; one who
recites the eight secret names of असि gets
victory 12. 160. 81; असि should always be
worshipped by those who are expert in fight-
ing 12. 160. 85; one who listens to this
खड्गसाधन obtains fame (in this life)
and eternal happiness (in the next world)
(लभते पुरुषः कीर्तिं प्रेत्य चानन्त्यम्
अश्नुते) 12. 160. 87.

खाण्डवदाह
Khāṇḍavadāha m.: Name of the 19th
पर्वन् (खाण्डवदाहाख्यम्) in the list
of a hundred sub-पर्वन्स् of the Bhārata
supposed to have been made by Vyāsa in
Parvasaṃgraha 1. 2. 39, 33, 70.
It is mentioned (खाण्डवस्य च
दाहनम्) in the list of the contents of the
Ādiparvan 1. 2. 93; it also narrates the release
of Maya from fire and the escape of the snake
1. 2. 94; the incident is referred to by Dhṛta-
rāṣṭra in his summary made for Saṃjaya 1.
1. 104 and by Vaiśaṃpāyana in his summary
made for Janamejaya 1. 55. 35-38; these
incidents form the contents of the अध्यायस्
1. 214-225.

गदायुद्ध
Gadāyuddha nt.: Name of the 76th
पर्वन् in the list of a hundred sub-पर्वन्स्
of the Bhārata supposed to have been made
by Vyāsa in the Parvasaṃgraha 1. 2. 59.
Mentioned in the list of the contents of
the Śalyaparvan 1. 2. 175; the incident is
referred to by Dhṛtarāṣṭtra in his summary
of the events made for Saṃjaya 1. 1. 150-
152; related to the incidents narrated in the
अध्यायस् 9. 31-33, 54-64.

गान्धर्ववेद
Gāndharvaveda m.: Name of the Veda
related to the Gandharvas.
Arjuna, during his stay in the heaven,
learnt it correctly and according to the rules
(यथान्यायं … यथाविधि) from the Gan-
dharva Viśvāvasu; the Veda comprised the
skills in singing (गीतम्), dancing (नृत्तम्),
melody (साम), and instrumental music
(वादित्रम्) 3. 89. 13-14.

गृहाणां
Gṛhāṇāṃ pravibhāgaḥ: Name of
the 85th पर्वन् in the list of a hundred sub-
पर्वन्स् of the Bhārata supposed to have
been made by Vyāsa in the Parvasaṃgraha
(प्रविभागो गृहाणां च) 1. 2. 63.
Apparently this refers to the assigning
of the houses, after the war, of Duryodhana,
Duḥśāsana, Durmarṣana and Durmukha to
Bhīma Arjuna, Nakula and Sahadeva res-
pectively 12. 44. 6-13. [Yuyutsu, Vidura,
Saṃjaya, Sudharman (Duryodhana's Purohita
cf. Nī. on Bom. Ed. 11. 26. 24: सुधर्मा-
णम् दुर्योधनपुरोहितम्) and Dhaumya
retained their old houses 12. 44. 14].

गोग्रहण
Gograhaṇa nt.: Name of the 47th
पर्वन् in the list of a hundred sub-पर्वन्स् of
the Bhārata supposed to have been made by
Vyāsa in the Parvasaṃgraha 1. 2. 48, 33, 70.
Referred to while listing the contents of
the Virāṭaparvan as गोग्रह (cattle-raid) in
which Arjuna defeated the Kauravas, and the
Pāṇḍavas got back the cows of Virāṭa 1. 2.
132; referred to in Dhṛtarāṣṭra's summary
of the incidents made for Saṃjaya 1. 2. 114;
it is related to the incidents narrated in the
अध्यायस् 4. 24-62.

घटोत्कचवध
Ghaṭotkacavadha m.: Name of the
70th पर्वन् in the list of a hundred sub-
पर्वन्स् of the Bhārata supposed to have
been made by Vyāsa in the Parvasaṃgraha
1. 2. 57.
Ghaṭotkaca's death referred to in the
list of the contents of the Droṇaparvan 1.
2. 164; referred to in Dhṛtarāṣṭra's summary
of the incidents made for Saṃjaya 1. 1.
141-142; related to the incidents narrated in
the अध्यायस् 7. 122-154.

घोषयात्रा
Ghoṣayātrā f.: Name of the 39th
पर्वन् in the list of a hundred sub-पर्वन्स्
of the Bhārata supposed to have been made
by Vyāsa in the Parvasaṃgraha 1. 2. 46,
33, 70.
Mentioned in the list of the contents of
the Āraṇyakaparvan (in this sub-पर्वन्
Arjuna fought with the Gandharvas) 1. 2.
122; referred to in Dhṛtarāṣṭra's summary of
the incidents made for Saṃjaya 1. 1. 112;
also cf. 5. 23. 25; 5. 48. 39; 5. 136. 8; 5. 155.
25; 7. 160. 17; it is related to the incidents
narrated in the अध्यायस् 3. 225-243.

चार्वाकनिग्रह
Cārvākanigraha m.: Name of the 84th
पर्वन् in the list of a hundred sub-पर्वन्स् of
the Bhārata supposed to have been made by
Vyāsa in the Parvasaṃgraha 1. 2. 63, 33, 70.
Alluded to in 9. 63. 38; related to the
incident told in the अध्यायस् 12. 39. 22-47.

चैत्ररथ
Caitraratha nt.: Name of the 11th
पर्वन् in the list of a hundred sub-पर्वन्स्
of the Bhārata supposed to have been made
by Vyāsa in the Parvasaṃgraha 1. 2. 36,
33, 70.
Referred to as the defeat of Aṅgāra-
parṇa (अङ्गारपर्णं निर्जित्य) in the list of
the contents of the Ādiparvan 1. 2. 86; the
following अध्यायस् are considered to belong
to the Caitrarathaparvan 1. 153-173; the
actual encounter with Aṅgāraparṇa is found
in the अध्याय 1. 158.

जटासुरवध
Jaṭāsuravadha m.: Name of the 34th
पर्वन् in the list of a hundred sub-पर्वन्स्
of the Bhārata supposed to have been made
by Vyāsa in the Parvasaṃgraha 1. 2. 44,
33, 70.
Referred to while detailing the contents
of the Āraṇyakaparvan 1. 2. 111; related
to the incidents narrated in the अध्याय
3. 154.

जतुगृहस्य
Jatugṛhasya dāhaḥ: Name of the 8th
पर्वन् in the list of a hundred sub-पर्वन्स्
of the Bhārata supposed to have been made
by Vyāsa in the Parvasaṃgraha (दाहो
जतुगृहस्यात्र) 1. 2. 35.
Alluded to, though not directly by this
name, in the list of contents of the Ādipar-
van 1. 2. 83; also listed by Vaiśaṃpāyana
in his very brief enumeration of the main
incidents for Janamejaya 1. 55. 16-18; related
to the incidents narrated in the अध्यायस्
1. 124(? 129)-138.

जन्तूपाख्यान
Jantūpākhyāna nt.: Name of a narra-
tive occurring in the Āraṇyakaparvan 1.
2. 119.
In this narrative it is told that king
Somaka sacrificed his son (Jantu) and got
a hundred sons 1. 2. 119; the narrative occurs
in the अध्यायस् 3. 127-128.

जम्बूखण्डविनिर्माण
Jambūkhaṇḍavinirmāṇa nt.: Name of
the 61st पर्वन् in the list of a hundred sub-
पर्वन्स् of the Bhārata supposed to have been
made by Vyāsa in the Parvasaṃgraha 1. 2.
55, 33, 70.
Referred to as an item in the list of the
contents of the Bhīṣmaparvan 1. 2. 154;
related to the अध्यायास् 6. 1-11.

जय
Jaya m.: Name of a type of Itihāsa
(जयो नामेतिहासो ऽयम्) 1. 56. 19; 5. 134.
17; 18. 5. 39.
Usually this is considered to be the desi-
gnation of that text which was originally
composed by Vyāsa and later, with gradual
additions, grew to become the Bhārata and the
Mahābhārata at the hands of Vaiśāṃpāyana
and Sūta Ugraśravas respectively; as the name
of the Mahābhārata it probably occurs in the
opening मङ्गल श्लोक found at the begin-
ning of the different पर्वन्स् (नारायणं
नमस्कृत्य नरं चैव नरोत्तमम्।
देवीं सरस्वतीं चैव ततो जयम् उदीर-
येत्॥) which is not found in all the versions;
according to V. S. Sukthankar, however,
“ … Jaya is a गेनेरिच् name applicable to
different works, and not a specific name of
the Mahābhārata at all as believed by some
writers” (Ādiparvan, p. 989, note on 56. 19);
the recitation of this kind of Itihāsa should
be heard by a king who desires victory; he
then conquers the earth and shall defeat his
enemies; it should also often be heard by a
chief queen since it is as good as a rite
calculated to lead to the birth of a son (पुं-
सवनम्) and by a crown prince since it
is the royal road to welfare (स्वस्त्ययनं
महत्) 1. 56. 19-20; its recitation is re-
commended for a king desiring prosperity
(भूतिम्), for princes in general, and for
any pregnant woman; it is also said that
hearing it one who desires heaven will
go to heaven, one who wants victory will
win victory, and a pregnant woman will
deliver a son or a fortunate girl (पुत्रं
कन्यां वा बहुभागिनीम्) 18. 5. 39-40; the
narrative called the Vidurāputrānuśāsana
(5. 131-135) is also classed as the Jaya
type of Itihāsa 5. 134. 17; a minister should
recite this to a king who is oppressed by his
enemies and who is dejected since this tract,
being a powerful exhortation, is best suited
to cause increase in energy (इदम् उद्ध-
रणं भीमं तेजोवर्धनम् उत्तमम्);
the rest of the श्रवणफल given here is
the same as for the Mahābhārata (as a Jaya
type of composition) with the addition which
gives the qualities of the son to be born to
a woman 5. 134. 16-21.

जयद्रथवध
Jayadrathavadha m.: Name of the
69th पर्वन् in the list of a hundred sub-
पर्वन्स् of the Bhārata supposed to have been
made by Vyāsa in the Parvasaṃgraha 1. 2.
57, 33, 70.
Referred to in the list of the contents of
the Droṇaparvan 1. 2. 163; the incident is
included by Dhṛtarāṣṭra in his summary of
the chief events made for Saṃjaya 1. 1. 135-
140; related to the incidents narrated in the
अध्यायस् 7. 61-121.

जरासन्धवध
Jarāsandhavadha m.: Name of the
22nd पर्वन् in the list of a hundred sub-
पर्वन्स् of the Bhārata supposed to have been
made by Vyāsa in the Parvasaṃgraha 1. 2.
40, 33, 70.
Listed in the contents of the Sabhāparvan
1. 2. 98, (99); referred to by Sūta in his
summary of the events made for the sages as-
sembled in the Naimiṣa forest 1. 1. 86; related
to the incidents narrated in the अध्यायस् 2.
18-22.

जलप्रदानिक
Jalapradānika nt.: Name of the 80th
पर्वन् in list of a hundred sub-पर्वन्स् of
the Bhārata supposed to have been made by
Vyāsa in the Parvasaṃgraha 1. 2. 61,
33, 70.
Alluded to in the contents of the Sau-
ptikaparvan (?) 1. 2. 187 (तोयकर्मणि
सर्वेषां राज्ञाम् उदकदानिके); related to
the अध्याय 11. 27.

तापत्य
Tāpatya nt.: Name of an आख्यान
(related to Tapatī).
Listed in the contents of the Ādipar-
van 1. 2. 87; related to the incidents narra-
ted in the अध्यायस् 1. 160-163.

तीर्थयात्रा
Tīrthayātrā f.: Name of the 33rd
पर्वन् in the list of a hundred sub-पर्वन्स्
of the Bhārata supposed to have been made
by Vyāsa in the Parvasaṃgraha 1. 2. 43,
33, 70.
Mentioned while listing the contents of
the Āraṇyakaparvan 1. 2. 111; also referred
to in 11. 26. 19; related to the अध्यायस्
3. 80-153.

त्रिणाचिकेत
Triṇāciketa m.: Name of a section of
the Yajurveda (Tai. Br. 3. 11 ?); in the Mahā-
bhārata it occurs as an adj. of a Brāhmaṇa
who has studied this section 13. 90. 20.
According to an unknown commentator
it is a particular section of the Yajurveda
(अध्वर्युवेदभागविशेष-), cf. Critical
Notes on 13. 90. 20 (p. 1091. 1); so also
Kullūka on Manu 3. 185: त्रिणाचिकेतः
अध्वर्युवेदभागः, and Nī. on Bom. Ed.
13. 90. 26: त्रिणाचिकेतः त्रिणाचिकेताख्य-
मन्त्राध्येता।

त्रिपुरस्य
Tripurasya nipātanam: A narrative (?)
from a Purāṇa describing the destruction
of the Tripuras (आख्यातं यत्र पौराणं
त्रिपुरस्य निपातनम्) 1. 2. 169.
Refers to the mythical incidents narrated
in the अध्याय 8. 24.

त्रिसुपर्ण
Trisuparṇa m., nt.: Name of a Vedic
text; in the Mahābhārata the word occurs as
an adj. of a Brāhmaṇa who has studied this
text 13. 90. 20.
According to Nī. the term applies to
the three मन्त्रस् from the Ṛgveda (10. 114.
3-5 which contain the word सुपर्ण) or to
those in the Taitt. Ār. 10. 48-50: त्रिसुपर्णं
चतुष्कपर्दा युवतिः सुपेषा इति बह्वृचानां
मन्त्रत्रयं वा ब्रह्मम् एतु माम् इत्यादि
तैत्तिरीयप्रसिद्धं वा on Bom. Ed. 13.
90. 26; the unknown commentator simply
says: त्रिसुपर्णः बह्वृचां वेदभाग-
वीशेषाध्यायी—see Critical Notes on 13. 90.
20 (p. 1091. 1); so also Kullūka on Manu
3. 185: त्रिसुपर्णो बह्वृचां वेदभागः।

दिग्विजय
Digvijaya m.: Name of the 23rd पर्-
वन् in the list of a hundred sub-पर्वन्स् of
the Bhārata supposed to have been made by
Vyāsa in the Parvasaṃgraha 1. 2. 40, 33, 70.
Referred to in Sūta's summary of the
events for the sages assembled in the Naimiṣa
forest 1. 1. 84; also in Vaiśaṃpāyana's
summary of the events for Janamejaya 1. 55.
28, 29; related to the अध्यायस् 2. 23-29.

दैवतवंश
Daivatavaṃśa m.: Name of a passage
in the Anuśasanaparvan listing the names
of gods, goddesses, and other beings (अयं
दैवतवंशो वै) 13. 151. 2.
Besides listing names of gods like
Pitāmaha (Brahmadeva) with Sāvitrī,
Viṣṇu-Nārāyaṇa, Umāpati (Śiva), Virūpā-
kṣa, Skanda, Viśākha and others, it contains
also such names like Surabhi (cow), Sāgara
(ocean), and Gaṅgā (river); it has names
of sages like the Vālakhilyas, Kṛṣṇa-dvai-
pāyana, Nārada and Parvata; of Gandhar-
vas like Viśvāvasu Hahāhuhū and others;
of Apsarases like Urvaśī, Menakā, Rambhā
and others; it mentions also group-gods like
the Ādityas, the Vasus, the Rudras, the
Aśvinā, and also the Pitṛs; personified
concepts like धर्म, सत्य; divisions of
time like nights and days, seasons, months,
twilights; names of planets (Śukra, Brhaspati
and the rest) and Nakṣatras (not listed);
mythical birds (Vainateyas) and serpents
(कद्रुजाः); rivers like Śatadrū, Vipāśā
and others; holy places of pilgrimage like
Prayāga, Prabhāsa and others; mountains like
Himavant, Vindhya and the rest—all these
also find a place in this list 13. 151. 3-28;
together with the Ṛṣivaṃśa, this Daivata-
vaṃśa is described as the ‘first collection’
of its kind (एष वै समवायस् ते ऋषि-
देवसमन्वितः।आद्यः प्रकीर्तितो राजन्)
13. 151. 40; also अयं दैवतवंशो वै
ऋषिवंशसमन्वितः 13. 151. 2; the recita-
tion of the two वंशस् together at two
twilights is very effective in removing sins
(द्विसंध्यं पठितः पुत्र कल्माषा-
पहरः परः) 13. 151. 2; (सर्वपाप-
प्रमोचनः) 13. 151. 40; (मुच्यते सर्व-
किल्बिशैः) 13. 151. 29; one who recites these
names of gods or welcomes their recitation
is freed of dangers from all quarters and
from sins arising from all kinds of promis-
cuous behaviour (स्तुवंश् च प्रतिनन्दंश्
च मुच्यते सर्वतो भयात्।सर्वसंकर-
पापेभ्यो देवतास्तवनन्दकः॥) 13. 151.
29. [See Ṛṣivaṃśa]

द्यूतपर्वन्
Dyūtaparvan nt.: Name of the 27th
पर्वन् in the list of a hundred sub-पर्वन्स्
of the Bhārata supposed to have been made
by Vyāsa in the Parvasaṃgraha 1. 2. 41,
33, 70.
The incidents of this पर्वन् briefly
listed in the contents of the Sabhāparvan (1.
2. 100-102): Bhīma derided Duryodhana in
the Sabhā; the game of dice traced to the
wrath of Duryodhana aroused due to his
derision by Bhīma; in the द्यूत that followed,
Śakuni defeated Dharmasuta (Yudhiṣṭhira);
Draupadī came to their rescue; referred to
also by Dhṛtaraṣṭra in his summary made
for Saṃjaya 1. 1. 99-100; 105-106; and
still more briefly by Vaiśaṃpāyana in his
summary for Janamejaya 1. 55. 39; related
to the अध्यायस् 2. 43-65.

द्रोणपर्वन्
Droṇaparvan nt.: Name of the 7th
पर्वन् in the list of the 18 major पर्वन्स्
of the Bhārata 1. 2. 160, 166, 233.
Described as wonderful and full of in-
cidents (चित्रम्, बहुवृत्तान्तम्) 1. 2. 160,
great (महत्) 1. 2. 166; most of the heroic
kings were killed in the Droṇaparvan 1. 2. 66;
the main incidents in this पर्वन् are listed as
follows: the Saṃśaptakas removed Arjuna
from the main battle-field; Bhagadatta, with
his elephant Supratīka, killed by Arjuna;
young Abhimanyu killed by many heroes
who were led by Jayadratha; angered Arjuna
killed seven Akṣauhiṇīs and Jayadratha; all
the Saṃśaptakas destroyed without a re-
mainder; Alambusa, Śrutāyus, Jalasaṃdha,
Saumadatti, Virāṭa, Drupada, Ghaṭotkaca
and many others killed in this पर्वन्;
Aśvatthāman, enraged at the fall of Droṇa,
released his frightful Nārāyaṇāstra 1. 2. 160-
165; the अध्यायस् of the Droṇaparvan, as
counted by Vyāsa, the seer of truth (तत्त्व-
दर्शिना) after due thought (संचिन्त्य) are
170 and its श्लोकस् 8909 (1. 2. 167-168).

द्रोणवध
Droṇavadha m.: Name of the 71st
पर्वन् in the list of a hundred sub-पर्वन्स्
of the Bhārata supposed to have been made
by Vyāsa in the Parvasaṃgraha 1. 2. 58,
33, 70.
Described as hair-raising (लोमहर्-
षण) 1. 2. 58; fall of Droṇa referred to
while listing the major events of the Droṇa-
parvan 1. 2. 165, and in the summary of the
events made by Dhṛtarāṣṭra for Saṃjaya
1. 1. 143; the पर्वन् is related to the inci-
dents narrated in the अध्यायस् 7. 155 (or
159)-165.

द्रोणाभिषेक
Droṇābhiṣeka m.: Name of the 65th
पर्वन् in the list of a hundred sub-पर्वन्स्
of the Bhārata supposed to have been made
by Vyāsa in the Parvasaṃgraha 1. 2. 56,
33, 70.
Related to the अध्यायस् 7. 1-15 (7. 5.
5-40).

द्रौपदीसत्यभामयोः
Draupadīsatyabhāmayoḥ saṃvādaḥ:
Name of the 38th पर्वन् in the list of a
hundred sub-पर्वन्स् of the Bhārata supposed
to have been made by Vyāsa in the Parva-
saṃgraha (संवादश् च ततः पर्व द्रौ-
पदीसत्यभामयोः) 1. 2. 45, 33, 70.
The incident is mentioned while listing
the contents of the Āraṇyakaparvan
(संवादश् चैव सत्यया) 1. 2. 125; the
पर्वन् is related to the अध्यायस् 3. 222-
224.

द्रौपदीस्वयंवर
Draupadīsvayaṃvara m.: This name does
not occur in the text. [See Pāñcālyāḥ
svayaṃvaram]
Related to the अध्यायस् 1. 174-189.

द्रौपदीहरण
Draupadīharaṇa nt.: Name of the 42nd
पर्वन् in the list of a hundred sub-पर्वन्स्
of the Bhārata supposed to have been made
by Vyāsa in the Parvasaṃgraha 1. 2. 47,
33, 70.
Draupadī's abduction was attempted by
the Sindhu king (Jayadratha) 1. 2. 47; the
incident is mentioned while listing the con-
tents of the Āraṇyakaparvan 1. 2. 123-124;
the पर्वन् is related to the incidents of the
अध्यायस् 3. 248-256.

धौन्धुमार
Dhaundhumāra adj.: Of an उपाख्यान,
so called because it describes the killing of
the demon Dhundhu by king Kuvalāśva who
then came to be known as Dhundhumāra
(धौन्धुमारम् उपाख्यानं प्रथितं
यस्य कर्मणा) 3. 195. 37, 13, 36; 3.
192. 4, 7.
Described as most meritorious (धर्-
मिष्ठम् इदम् आख्यानं धुन्धुमारस्य)
3. 192. 6, and holy (पुण्यम्) 3. 195. 38; it
is also the praise of Viṣṇu (विष्णोः सम-
नुकीर्तनम्) 3. 195. 38; one who listens to
it on पर्वन् days becomes religious-minded
(धर्मात्मा), gets sons, long life and
fortitude; he has no fear from diseases and
is free of anguish (विगतज्वरः) 3. 195.
38-39; the incident is narrated in the
अध्यायस् 3. 192-195.

नकुलाख्यान
Nakulākhyāna nt.: Name of an
आख्यान mentioned in the list of the contents
of the Āśvamedhikaparvan 1. 2. 209.
The incident which occurred at the
conclusion of the Aśvamedha sacrifice of
Yudhiṣṭhira is narrated in the अध्यायस् 14.
92-96.

नलोपाख्यान
Nalopākhyāna nt.: Name of an उपा-
ख्यान mentioned in the list of the contents
of the Āraṇyakaparvan 1. 2. 109.
Described as most pious (धर्मिष्ठ)
and which causes the rise of compassion (in
the hearer) (करुणोदय); here is described
the condition of Damayantī when Nala was
overpowered by calamity (दमयन्त्याः
स्थितिर् यत्र नलस्य व्यसनागमे) 1. 2.
109; the उपाख्यान is narrated in the
अध्यायस् 3. 50-78.

नारदागमन
Nāradāgamana nt.: Name of the 95th
पर्वन् in the list of a hundred sub-पर्वन्स्
of the Bhārata supposed to have been made
by Vyāsa in the Parvasaṃgraha 1. 2. 67.
The incident is mentioned in the narra-
tion of the contents of the Āśramavāsa-
parvan; Nārada came to visit Yudhiṣṭhira
and told him about the great destruction of
the Viṛṣṇis 1. 2. 217; (Actually Nārada re-
ported to Yudhiṣṭhira about the death of
Dhṛtarāṣṭra, Gāndhārī and Kuntī in the
forest-fire (15. 45. 9-38); it was Dāruka who
reported to the Pāṇḍavas about the destruc-
tion of the Vṛṣṇis 16. 6. 1); the पर्वन् is
related to the अध्यायस् 15. 45-47.

नारायणकथा
Nārāyaṇakathā f.: See Nārāyaṇīya.

नारायणास्त्रस्य
Nārāyaṇāstrasya mokṣaḥ: Name of
the 72nd पर्वन् in the list of a hundred
sub-पर्वन्स् of the Bhārata supposed to
have been made by Vyāsa in the Parvasaṃ-
graha 1. 2. 58 (मोक्षो नारायणास्त्रस्य
पर्वानन्तरम् उच्यते).
The incident of the release of the
Nārāyaṇāstra by Aśvatthāman, enraged at
the death of his father Droṇa, is mentioned
in the narration of the contents of the
Droṇaparvan 1. 2. 165, and in Dhṛtarāṣṭra's
summary of the events made for Saṃjaya
1. 1. 145; the पर्वन् is related to the
अध्यायस् 7. 166-173.

नारायणीय
Nārāyaṇīya nt., Nārāyaṇakathā f.:
Name of an आख्यान 12. 334. 12, or of a
कथा 12. 327. 4; 12. 331. 7, 19; it comprises
the अध्यायस् 12. 321-337.
A. Characterizations: This section (or
its parts) generally referred to as आख्यान
12. 326. 113; 12. 331. 1; 12. 326. 121
(आख्यानवर, also 12. 337. 16); 12.
334. 2 (भगवदाख्यान); 12. 334. 11
(महदाख्यान), or as कथा 12. 326.
118; 12. 326. 115 (कथामृत) 12. 331. 4
(कथामृत) 12. 334. 4; 12. 335. 6; but
occasionally also as पूराण 12. 326. 112; 12.
329. 2; or पुराण equal to Veda (in import-
ance) (पुराणं वेदसंमितम्) 12. 326.
106; as old इतिहास (इतिहासं पुरातनम्)
12. 321. 7; as धर्मसंहिता 12. 327. 4;
as ब्रह्म 12. 326. 107; as a great उप-
निषद्(अ), together with the four Vedas, com-
posed by Nārāyaṇa (इदं महोपम्षदं
चतुर्वेदसमन्वितम् … नारायणमुखोद्-
गीतम्) 12. 326. 100-101; as ज्ञान pertain-
ing to all the three times (past, present and
future) which dawned on Vyāsa by the favour
of Nārāyaṇa (नारायणप्रसादेन … त्रैकालि-
कम् इदं ज्ञानं प्रादुर्भूतम्) 12. 327.
22-23, 97; as सात्वत धर्म 12. 336. 78,
(51), or simply as धर्म 12. 336. 9 ff.
B. Description: The आख्यान (or its parts)
described as great (महत्) 12. 334. 11,
very great (सुमहत्) 12. 331. 1; best
(उत्तम) 12. 337. 16, unparalleled (अनु-
त्तम) 12. 331. 4; difficult to be understood
(गहन) 12. 321. 6; pious (पुण्या) 12.
335. 6; destroying all sins (सर्वपाप-
प्रणाशनी) 12. 331. 8; proceeding directly
from the mouth of Nārāyaṇa (नारायन-
मुखोद्गीत) 12. 326. 101; originating from
the Ṛṣi (Nārāyaṇa) and transmitted by
tradition (आर्षेयम् पारंपर्यागतम्) 12.
326. 113; related to the origin of Ṛṣi (Vyāsa
from Nārāyaṇa) (आर्षेय) 12. 337. 16; of
great importance as a prayer to be muttered
(परमं जप्यम्) 12. 326. 123; based on
the Nārāyaṇakathā (नारायणकथाश्रय)
12. 331. 4; churned out of the Bhāratā-
khyāna of a hundred thousand stanzas (as
butter from curds etc.) 12. 331. 2-4; 12.
326. 115; essence of all the hundreds of
religious उपाख्यानस् heard by Yudhiṣṭhira
from Bhīṣma 12. 326. 114.
C. Glorifica-
tion and importance: Contains a स्तोत्र of
Bhagavān (12. 326. 1) who is विश्व, निर्गुण
and महात्मन् 12. 325. 3; constitutes the
praise of the high-souled excellent Puruṣa
(महात्मनः पुरुषवरस्य कीर्तनम्) 12.
327. 107; and describes the greatness of the
Paramātman (माहात्म्यं परमात्मनः)
12. 334. 8; neither a visit to all the आश्रमस्
nor bathing in all the तीर्थस् yields as much
fruit as does the Nārāyaṇakathā 12. 331. 7;
it has the purifying effect on listeners
(पावितात्माद्य संवृत्वः श्रुत्वेमाम् आदितः
कथाम् 12. 334. 4; पाविताः स्म त्वया
ब्रह्मन् पुण्यां कथयता कथाम् 12.
335. 6); it should not be narrated to one
who is not devoted to Vāsudeva 12. 326. 113.
D. Nature and form: It is a glorification
of Nārāyaṇa in different contexts and is
in many places in the form of dialogues
(1) between Nārāyaṇa and Nārada in the
Badaryāśrama 12. 321. 23-43; 12. 331. 20-
32; 12. 332. 1-23; 12. 333. 2-25 (11-25
speakers Nara and Nārāyaṇa); at the
Śvetadvīpa 12. 326. 10-98; (2) Bhagavān
and Arjuna अध्य्स्। 12. 328-330; (3) Vyāsa
and Vaiśaṃpāyana 12. 327. 20-98; 12. 337.
15. 57; (4) Bhīṣma and Yudhiṣṭhira 12.
322. 13-52; 12. 323. 1-57; 12. 324. 1-39; 12.
326. 102-120; (5) Vaiśaṃpāyana and Jana-
mejaya 12. 327. 1-19; 99-101; 12. 336-337.
E. Etymologies: Arjuna requested Bhaga-
van to tell him etymologies of his names
based on qualities and activities (निरुक्तं
गुणकर्मजम् 12. 328. 3, 10; 12. 328. 6-7
(यानि नामानि ते देव कीर्तितानि महर्षि-
भिः। … तेषां निरुक्तम् त्वत्तोऽहं स्रोतुम्
इच्छामि केशव); also 12. 328. 1-4; Bhaga-
vān then explained these etymologies to
Arjuna 12. 328. 8-51; 12. 330. 1-31.
F. Narrations: Various portions of this
आख्यान are narrated (1) (उपनिषद) by
Nārāyaṇa himself to Nārada 12. 326. 100-
101 (इदं महपनिषदम् … पञ्चरात्रा-
नुशब्दितम्॥नारायणमुखोद्गीतम्);
Nārada narrated it to Brahman 12. 326. 101-
102, from whom it passed on successively to
the Siddhas, Sūrya, 66000 ऋषिस्, gods द्विज
Asita manes (पितृस्) (including Śaṃtanu);
from Śaṃtanu it went to Bhīṣma and then to
Yudhiṣṭhira 12. 326. 105-111; (2) (धर्म)
narrated by Nārāyaṇa himself to Narada
12. 336. 50, and then by Nārada to Pārtha
(Yudhiṣṭhira) in the presence of the sages
(including Vyāsa), and within the hearing of
Kṛṣṇa and Bhīṣma 12. 336. 11 (or by Nārada
to Vyāsa and then by Vyāsa to Yudhiṣṭhira,
the sages, Kṛṣṇa and Bhīṣma 12. 336. 59-
60), and also by Vyāsa to Vaiśaṃpāyana
and then by the latter to Janamejaya 12.
336. 12, 57, 80; (3) (आख्यान) narrated
by Nārada to Vyāsa seated among the sages,
and to the Pāṇḍavas within the hearing of
Kṛṣṇa and Bhīṣma 12. 334. 12, and further
by Vyāsa to Vaiśaṃpāyana and by the latter
to Janamejaya 12. 334. 8, 12; 12. 331. 19
(नारायणकथा); (4) (ज्ञान) Vyāsa
narrated the ज्ञान which dawned on him
by the favour of Nārāyaṇa to his pupils
Vaiśaṃpāyana and others, and to Śuka 12.
327. 15-23, 97, 99, 101, and then Vaiśaṃ-
pāyana to Janamejaya 12. 327 15, 19, 101.
G. स्रवणफल: (of the आख्यान or the
कथा) One who always recites this आख्यान
or listens to it, being devoted to one object,
and very attentively, in a secluded place
(एकान्तभावोपगत एकान्ते सुसमाहितः),
reaches the Śvetadvīpa and, having obtained
the lustre of the moon, would no doubt enter
the god of thousand flames (स सहस्रार्-
चिषम् देवं प्रविशेन् नात्र संशयः) 12.
326. 116-17; (12. 327. 6); it one, afflicted
(by diseases) listens to this कथा from the
beginning, he will be freed from the disease;
one who listens to it out of curiosity
(जिज्ञासुः) obtains his desires, and a devotee
(after death) would go along the course of a
devotee (भक्तो भक्तगतिं व्रजेत्) 12. 326.
118; (of the ज्ञान expounded by Vyāsa) one
who listens to it or one who recites it, having
bowed down to Bhagavān and with attentive
mind, is freed from disease, becomes lustrous,
and gets strength and good complexion; one
who is suffering from illness is freed of
illness, one held in captivity is released from
bonds, one who entertains desires obtains them
and long life; a Brāhmaṇa thereby knows all,
a Kṣatriya is victorious, a Vaiśya obtains
much profit and a Śūdra becomes happy; one
who is devoid of a son has a son; a maiden
gets the cherished husband, the woman who
experiences difficulty in delivery delivers easily
(लग्नगर्भा विमुच्यते), a pregnant woman
delivers a son, a barren woman has abundant
progeny consisting of sons and grandsons;
one who recites this while on journey reaches
his destination safely; (in short) whatever
desire a person entertains that he definitely
gets; this is the considered assurance of the
great sage (इदं महर्षेर् वचनं विनिश्-
चितम्) that by listening to the praise of the
Excellent Person (पुरुषवर) the devotees
are very comfortable (निशम्य भक्ताः सु-
सुखं लभन्ते) 12. 327. 102-107.
H.
End: After listening to this great Nārāyaṇīya
आख्यान, king Janamejaya resumed all the
rites necessary for the completion of the
(snake) sacrifice (एतद् तु महद् आख्यानं
श्रुत्वा पारिक्षितो नृपः।ततो यज्ञसमा-
प्त्यर्थं क्रियाः सर्वाः समारभत्॥ 12.
334. 11). [See Puruṣasukta, Hayaśiras]

निरुक्त
Nirukta nt.: Name of the text dealing
with etymologies.
The sage Yāska is credited to have
rescued by the favour of Kṛṣṇa the lost
Nirukta when he praised Kṛṣṇa as शिपिविष्ट
12. 330. 8 (स्तुत्वा मां शिपिविष्टेति यास्को
मुनिर् उदारधीः।मत्प्रसादाद् अधो
नष्टं निरुक्तम् अभिजग्मिवान्; Nī. अधो
नष्टं वेदहरणवेलायां पाताले ऽन्तर्हि-
तम् on Bom. Ed. 12. 342. 73); those who
know the Nirukta (name of the text ?) and
the Veda praise Kṛṣṇa as Adhokṣaja in the
ritual context 12. 330. 18 (निरुक्तम् वेद-
विदुषो … ते मां गायन्ति प्राग्वंशे अधो-
क्षज इति स्थितिः; Nī. प्राग्वंशे यज्ञशा-
लैकदेशे on Bom. Ed. 12. 342. 83); gods
long for him who knows the Vedas, the
Vedāṅgas (?), the whole sacrificial proce-
dure, the Nirukta (text ?), and the highest
truth to be in the शरीरात्मन् (वेदांश् च
वेद्यं च विधिं च कृत्स्नम् अथो निरुक्तं
परमार्थतां च।सर्वं शरीरात्मनि
यः प्रवेद तस्मै स्म देवाः स्पृहय-
न्ति नित्यम् 12. 237. 30; but Nī. on Bom.
Ed. 12. 245. 30: वेद्यं वियदादि, विधिं
कर्मकाण्डम्, निरुक्तं शब्दैकगम्यं
परलोकादि परमार्थताम् सत्यस्वभाव-
तां चात्मनः); Bṛhaspati told Prajāpati
that even after studying the Vedas and the
other texts like the Nirukta and the
Vyākaraṇa he does not know the ultimate
source of beings (भूतप्रकृतिं न वेद्मि)
12. 194. 8; the Nirukta (personified, among
other personified texts) came to the sacrifice
of Rudra who had assumed the form of
Varuṇa 13. 85. 5, 2, 7-8.

निर्याण
Niryāṇa nt.: Name of the 56th पर्वन्
in the list of a hundred sub-पर्वन्स् of the
Bhārata supposed to have been made by
Vyāsa in the Parvasaṃgraha 1. 2. 52, 33, 70.
Referred to as marching out of the
chariots, the horses, the footsoldiers, and the
elephants from the city Hāstinapura and the
mention of their total count (बलसंख्या-
नम्) while listing the contents of the
Udyogaparvan 1. 2. 149; related to the
अध्यायस् 5. 149-152 (अभिनिर्याणपर्वन्).

नैघण्टुक
Naighaṇṭuka nt.: Name of a text giving
synonyms (?).
Supposed to have been composed by
Prajāpati Kaśyapa 12. 330. 24; in it Kṛṣṇa
is called Vṛṣākapi (because Vṛṣa is Dharma
and कपि means ‘the best, the highest’;
Vṛṣākapi thus means ‘the highest Dharma’)
12. 330. 23-24.

पञ्चेन्द्राणाम्
Pañcendrāṇām upākhyānam: Name of
an Upākhyāna occurring in the पर्वन् called
Pāñcālyāḥ svayaṃvaram.
Described as wonderful (पञ्चेन्द्रा-
णाम् उपाख्यानम् अत्रैवाद्भुतम् उच्यते)
1. 2. 87; it comprises the अध्याय 1. 189
(Pañcendropākhyāna).

पर्वसंग्रह
Parvasaṃgraha1 m.: Collection of a
hundred sub-पर्वन्स् of the Bhārata 1. 2.
33-70.
The number of these sub-पर्वन्स् is
hundred (including the Harivaṃśa parvan
and the Bhaviṣyat parvan called as the
खिलस्) and it is supposed to have been made
by Vyāsa himself (एतत् पर्वशतं पूर्णं
व्यासेनोक्तं महात्मना) 1. 2. 70; it
was then exactly repeated by Lomaharṣaṇin
(Ugraśravas) 1. 2. 70; the collection of the
sub-पर्वन्स् and the listing of the main
events in each sub-पर्वन्स् which make up the
major eighteen पर्वन्स् (1. 2. 72-233) consti-
tute the summary of the Bhārata (समासो
भारतस्यायं तत्रोक्तः पर्वसंग्रहः)
1. 2. 71, (एतद् अखिलम् आख्यातं भारतं
पर्वसंग्रहात्) 1. 2. 234.

पर्वसंग्रह
Parvasaṃgraha2 m.: Name of the 2nd
पर्वन् in the list of a hundred sub-पर्वन्स्
of the Bhārata supposed to have been made
by Vyāsa in the Parvasaṃgraha 1. 2. 34, 33,
70, 243.
It constitutes the second अध्याय of
the Ādiparvan in which the sub-पर्वन्स् are
listed (1. 2. 34-70) and the contents of the
18 major पर्वन्स् are summarized (1. 2.
71-234); thus the Parvasaṃgraha forms the
layout of the grand narrative of the Mahā-
bhārata (आख्यानं तद् इदम् अनुत्तमं
महार्थम् विन्यस्तं महद् इह पर्व-
संग्रहेण) 1. 2. 243; if one first listens
to this summary of the contents, it becomes
easy for him to go through the Bhārata as
one can easily float over the extensive ocean
with a small boat 1. 2. 243.

पर्वानुक्रमणी
Parvānukramaṇī f.: See Anukramaṇī.

पाञ्चाल्याः
Pāñcālyāḥ svayaṃvaram: Name of the
12th पर्वन् in the list of a hundred sub-
पर्वन्स् of the Bhārata supposed to have
been made by Vyāsa in the Parvasaṃgraha
(ततः स्वयंवरं देव्याः पाञ्चाल्याः
पर्व चोच्यते) 1. 2. 36, 33, 70.
In this पर्वन् Draupadī was won follow-
ing the क्षत्रधर्म 1. 2. 37; it is referred
to in the summary of the contents of the
Ādiparvan where it is said that it contains the
wonderful Pañcendra upākhyāna, Drupada's
deliberation on the wedding of five (brothers)
with one woman, and Draupadī's unusual
marriage ordained by the gods (पञ्चेन्द्रा-
णाम् उपाख्यानम् अत्रैवाद्भुतम् उच्यते॥
पञ्चानाम् एकपत्नीत्वे विमर्शो द्रुपदस्य
च।द्रौपद्या देवविहितो विवाहश् चाप्य्
अमानुषः॥) 1. 2. 87-88; referred to by
Dhṛtarāṣṭra in his summary of the events
made for Saṃjaya 1. 1. 102, and by Vaiśaṃ-
pāyana in his summary made for Janame-
jaya 1. 55. 22; related to the अध्यायस्
1. 174-189 (Draupadīsvayaṃvaraparvan).

पुत्रदर्शन
Putradarśana nt.: Name of the 94th
पर्वन् of the Bhārata supposed to have been
made by Vyāsa in the Parvasaṃgraha 1. 2.
67, 33, 70.
The incident is mentioned while narrating
the contents of the Āśramavāsaparvan;
Dhṛtarāṣṭra, by the grace of Vyāsa, saw
for a while the miracle of the return of his
sons, grandsons, and other kings who were
killed in the battle 1. 2. 214-215; it is related
to the अध्यायस् 15. 36-44.

पुरुषसूक्त
Puruṣasūkta nt.: Name of a section
(अध्यायस् 12. 338-339) in the Śāntiparvan
12. 338. 5 (perhaps part of the Nārāyaṇīya
since the Puruṣa, also called पुरुषः विराट्
12. 338. 21, is identified with Nārāyaṇa 12.
339. 14).
Vaiśaṃpāyana narrated it to Janamejaya
when the latter asked him: “Who is the
foremost Puruṣa and who is the source (of
the universe) ? (को ह्य् अत्र पुरुषः श्रेष्ठः
को वा योनिर् इहोच्यते) 12. 338. 1; Vaiśaṃ-
pāyana narrated it to Janamejaya by the
favour of his teacher Vyāsa to whom he paid
obeisance 12. 338. 7, 4; the Puruṣasūkta is
known in the Vedas as ऋत and सत्य 12.
338. 5; Vyāsa, the best among the sages
(ऋषिसिंह 12. 338. 5), has summarized in it
what the sages Kapila and others have ex-
pounded in their शास्त्रस् 12. 338. 6-7; origi-
nally the Puruṣottama (12. 338. 23) was
described by the four-faced Brahman to his
three-eyed son Rudra, hence called an old
Itihāsa (इतिहासं पुरातनम्) 12. 338. 8-25;
12. 339. 1-21.

पूरोर्
Pūror vaṃśaḥ: Name (?) of a section
of the sub-पर्वन् called Saṃbhavaparvan
1. 90. 96.
It comprises the अध्यायस् 1. 89-90 in
which Vaiśaṃpāyana, at the request of Jana-
mejaya (1. 90. 1), informed him about the
kings born in the family of Pūru; one who
listens to this Pūruvaṃśa is released of all
sins 1. 90. 96.

पैतामहशास्त्र
Paitāmahaśāstra nt.: Characterization
of a नीतिशास्त्र (12. 59. 74) originally com
posed by Lokapitāmaha (Brahmadeva) 12.
59. 29, 23.
Described as auspicious (शुभ) 12. 59.
75; originally it consisted of one hundred
thousand अध्यायस् 12. 59. 29; it was com-
posed by Brahmadeva to allay the fear of
gods who complained to him about the destru-
ction of ब्रह्मन् and धर्म in the world
due to which gods became equal of men (ब्रह्-
मणश् च प्रणाशेन धर्मो ऽप्य् अनशद्
ईश्वर।ततः स्म समतां याता मर्त्यैश्
त्रिभुवनेश्वर) 12. 59. 25. 22-24; its
contents are detailed in 12. 59. 29-74;
80-85; it was composed for the benefit of
the world and for the establishment of the
त्रिवर्ग (i. e. धर्म अर्थ and काम
12. 59. 29-30) 12. 59. 76; along with
दण्डनीति, it would protect the world 12. 59.
77-79; it was first taught to Śaṅkara who
abridged it to ten thousand अध्यायस् called
Vaiśālākṣa 12. 59. 86-88. [See Barhas-
patya, Bāhudantaka, Vaiśālākṣa]

पौलोम
Pauloma nt.: Name of the 4th पर्वन्
in the list of a hundred sub-पर्वन्स् of the
Bhārata supposed to have been made by
Vyāsa in the Parvasaṃgraha 1. 2. 34, 33, 70.
In the Pauloma parvan is narrated the
extension of the lineage of Bhṛgu (भृगुवं-
शस्य विस्तारः) from Bhṛgu to Śunaka 1. 2.
72; 1. 5. 7-8; 1. 8. 1-2; Sūta Ugraśravas is
supposed to say that he would narrate the
Pauloma Ākhyāna immediately after the
beginning (यत् तु शौनकसत्रे ते भारता-
ख्यानविस्तरम्।आख्यास्ये तत्र पौलोमम्
आख्यानं चादितः परम्) 1. 2. 29 [this
statement apparently refers to the occurrence
of the Pauloma parvan (अध्यायस् 1. 4-12)
in the present text of the Mahābhārata where
at the beginning of the अध्याय 1. 4 the words
लोमहर्षणपुत्र उग्रश्रवाः etc. occurring
at 1. 1 are repeated; आदितः परम् seems
to mean ‘from the beginning onwards’;
V. S. Sukthankar, however, renders the line
आख्यास्ये etc. as ‘then shall I narrate, to
begin with, the excellent story of Pauloma’
ABORI 11. 183 (1930) = Sukthankar Memo-
rial Edition I. 219 (1944)]; the Pauloma
parvan comprises the अध्यायस् 1. 4-12.

पौष्य
Pauṣya nt.: Name of the 3rd पर्वन्
in the list of a hundred sub-पर्वन्स् of the
Bhārata supposed to have been made by
Vyāsa in the Parvasaṃgraha 1. 2. 34, 33, 70;
It describes the greatness of Uttaṅka
(माहात्म्यम् उत्तङ्कस्योपवर्णितम्) 1. 2.
72; related to the अध्याय 1. 3.

प्रजागर
Prajāgara nt.: Name of the 51st
पर्वन् in the list of a hundred sub-पर्वन्स्
of the Bhārata supposed to have been made by
Vyāsa in the Parvasaṃgraha 1. 2. 50.
It was occasioned by the anxiety of
Dhṛtarāṣṭra (धृतराष्ट्रस्य चिन्तया) 1. 2.
50; Dhṛṭarāṣṭra was worried and lost sleep
when he heard that the Pāṇḍavas would be
led by Vāsudeva (Kṛṣṇa) (श्रुत्वा च
पाण्डवान् यत्र वासुदेवपुरोगमान्।प्र-
जागरः संप्रजज्ञे धृतराष्ट्रस्य चिन्-
तया) 1. 2. 141; (5. 33. 6); in this पर्वन्
Vidura gives all sort of beneficial advice to
Dhṛtarāṣṭra (वाक्यानि विचित्राणि हितानि च)
1. 2. 142; alluded to in Dhṛtarāṣṭra's summary
of the events made for Saṃjaya 1. 1. 118;
the पर्वन् comprises the अध्यायस् 5. 33-41.

प्रतिज्ञापर्वन्
Pratijñāparvan nt.: Name of the 68th
पर्वन् in the list of a hundred sub-पर्वन्स्
of the Bhārata supposed to have been made
by Vyāsa in the Parvasaṃgraha 1. 2. 57,
33, 70.
The event of प्रतिज्ञा (Arjuna's vow
to kill Jayadratha) referred to in the sum-
mary of events made by Dhṛtarāṣṭra for
Saṃjaya 1. 1. 134-135; related to the
Adhyāyas 7. 52-60.

बकवध
Bakavadha m.: Name of the 10th
पर्वन् in the list of a hundred sub-पर्वन्स्
of the Bhārata supposed to have been made by
Vyāsa in the Parvasaṃgraha 1. 2. 36, 33, 70.
Mentioned in the narration of the con-
tents of the Ādiparvan (बकस्य निधनं
चैव) and referred to in the summary of
the events made by Vaiśaṃpāyana for Jana-
mejaya 1. 55. 21; related to the अध्यायस्
1. 143-152.

बार्हस्पत्य
Bārhaspatya nt.: Name of a शास्त्र in
the form of an abridgement made by Bṛhas-
pati 12. 59. 90.
The original Nītiśāstra composed by
Lokapitāmaha (Brahmadeva) was succes-
sively abridged by Śiva, Indra, Bṛhaspati,
and Kāvya; Bṛhaspati apparently received
the abridged form known as Bāhudantaka
from Indra; he then further abridged it to
three thousand अध्यायस्; (this was further
abridged by Kāvya, the teacher of the Yoga
(योगाचार्य) into one thousand अध्यायस्-
the name of this last abridgement not given
12. 59. 91). [See Paitāmahaśāstra, Bāhu-
dantaka, Vaiśālākṣa].

बाहुदन्तक
Bāhudantaka nt.: Name of a शास्त्र
in the form of an abridgement made by
Indra 12. 59. 89.
The Nītiśāstra originally composed by
Lokapitāmaha (Brahmadeva) was first
abridged by Śiva and was then called
Vaiśālākṣa; Indra received it in this form
and abridged it further to five thousand
अध्यायस्; it was called Bāhudantaka 12.
59. 88-89. [See Paitāmahaśāstra, Bārhas-
patya, Vaiśālākṣa]

बृहस्पतिमत
Bṛhaspatimata nt.: Name of a Śāstra
12. 322. 43; referred to as बृहस्पतेर् मतम्
in 12. 122. 11.
The Śāstra was originally composed by
the seven sages (Marīci, Atri and others
12. 322. 27) dealing with धर्म, अर्थ,
काम, and subsequently with मोक्ष and
other regulations (तत्र धर्मार्थकामा हि
मोक्षः पश्चाच् च कीर्तितः।मर्यादा विवि-
धाश् चैव 12. 322. 30); Manu Svāyaṃbhuva,
and Uśanas and Bṛhaspati when the two
would be born, were to propound the शास्त्र
of the seven sages; the शास्त्र will be
received by king Vasu 12. 322. 26-30;
35-37; 41-44; it was studied, along with
the Auśanasa śāstra, also by king Vasuhoma
of the Aṅgas; hence king Māndhātṛ asked
Vasuhoma to tell him how दण्ड came into
existence and how afterwards it came to be
established among the Kṣatriyas (तद् अहं
श्रोतुम् इच्छामि दण्ड उत्पद्यते कथम्।
 … कथं क्षत्रियसंस्थश् च दण्डः
संप्रत्य् अवस्थितः) 12. 122. 11-13. [See
Auśanasa]

ब्रह्मसूत्र
Brahmasūtra nt.: Name of a सूत्र-
text ?
The sages in ancient times are said to
have sung individually in the Brahma-
sūtra in different metres and with words
which provide well-determined grounds their
observations (viz. that this body is known
as क्षेत्र and one who knows it is known
as क्षेत्रज्ञ; and the Bhagavān is the
क्षेत्रज्ञ residing in all क्षेत्रस् 6. 35. 1-2)
6. 35. 4 (ऋषिभिर् बहुधा गीतं छन्दोभिर्
विविधैः पृथक्।ब्रह्मसूत्रपदैश् चैव
हेतुमद्भिर् विनिश्चितैः).

ब्रह्मोपनिसद्
Brahmopanisad f.: Name of a text (?)
(or ‘a secret doctrine related to ब्रह्मन्’ ?)
At the end of the war, Dhṛtarāṣṭra, when
he met the sage Vyāsa, learnt it, along with
the duties of a king 15. 43. 2-3 (स राजा
राजधर्मांश् च ब्रह्मोपनिषदं तथा।
अवाप्तवान् नरश्रेष्ठः … धृतराष्ट्रः
समासाद्य व्यासं चापि तपस्विनम्॥).

भगवद्गीता
Bhagavadgītā f.: Name of the 63rd
पर्वन् in the list of a hundred sub-पर्वन्स्
of the Bhārata supposed to have been made
by Vyāsa in the Parvasaṃgraha 1. 2. 56,
33, 70.
In it the highly intelligent Vāsudeva
destroyed the turbidity of mind of Pārtha
(Arjuna), arising out of confusion, by advanc-
ing arguments which taught the way that led
to liberation (कश्मलं यत्र पार्थस्य
वासुदेवो महामतिः।मोहजं नाशयाम्
आस हेतुभिर् मोक्षदर्शनैः) 1. 2. 156;
the incident is referred to in the summary of
the events made by Dhṛtarāṣṭra for Saṃjaya
1. 1. 124 and by Vaiśaṃpāyana at 12. 336.
8 (समुपोढेष्व् अनीकेषु कुरुपाण्डवयोर्
मृधे।अर्जुने विमनस्के च गीता भग-
वता स्वयम्); the पर्वन् is related to the
अध्यायस् 6. 14 (in fact 23)-40.

भगवद्यान
Bhagavadyāna nt.: Name of the 54th
पर्वन् in the list of a hundred sub-पर्वन्स्
of the Bhārata supposed to have been made
by Vyāsa in the Parvasaṃgraha 1. 2. 51,
33, 70.
Listed in the contents of the Udyoga-
parvan as follows: where Kṛṣṇa, overcome
by compassion and desiring peace, himself
went to Hāstinapura, but his proposal,
which was beneficial to both the parties, was
rejected by Duryodhana; where, having come
to know the evil design of Karṇa, Duryodhana
and others, Kṛṣṇa manifested his mastery
over the divine power to the assembled
kings (योगेश्वरत्वं कृष्णेन यत्र राजसु
दर्शितम्) 1. 2. 145-147; referred to by
Dhṛtarāṣṭra in his summary of the events
made for Saṃjaya 1. 1. 118-120; the sub-
पर्वन् comprises the अध्यायस् 5. 70-137.

भविष्यत्
Bhaviṣyat nt.: Name of the 100th
पर्वन् in the list of a hundred sub-पर्वन्स्
of the Bhārata supposed to have been made
by Vyāsa in the Parvasaṃgraha 1. 2. 69,
33, 70.
Also mentioned at the end of the listing
of the contents of the eighteen major पर्वन्स्
as one of the two supplements of the
Bhārata (खिलेषु हरिवंशश् च भविष्यच्
च प्रकीर्तितम्) 1. 2. 233; described as
highly wonderful among the Khilas (खिलेष्व्
एवाद्भुतं महत्) 1. 2. 69; related to the
अध्यायस् 114-118 of the Harivaṃśa.

भारत
Bhārata, Mahābhārata nt.: Name of
the great epic composed by Vyāsa, who was
also known as Kṛṣṇa Dvaipāyana; the title
Bhārata once given to an abridgement of
the original in 24000 श्लोकस् made by
dropping the उपाख्यानस् (चतुर्विंशति-
साहस्रीम् चक्रे भारतसंहिताम्।उपा-
ख्यानैर् विना तावद् भारतं प्रोच्यते
बुधैः॥) 1. 1. 61; also called Bhāratī
kathā (श्रोतुं पात्रं च राजंस् त्वं
प्राप्येमां भारतीं कथाम्) 1. 55. 3.
A. Contents and definition: It nar-
rates the extensive life-story of the Kurus
(कुरूणां चरितं महत्) 1. 56. 1, or the
full story of the Kurus and the Pāṇḍavas
(कुरूणां चरितं कृत्स्नम् पाण्डवानां
च भारत) 18. 5. 25; or the history of
Śaṃtanu (यस्य (i. e. शंतनोः) इतिहासो
द्युतिमान् महाभारतम् उच्यते) 1. 93.
46; Vaiśaṃpāyana summarized for Jana-
mejaya its contents in three words, ‘breach,
loss of kingdom, and victory’ (एवम्
एतत् पुरावृत्तं तेषाम् अक्लिष्टकर्मणाम्।
भेदो राज्यविनाशश् च जयश् च
जयतां वर) 1. 55. 43 (also cf. 1. 55.
4-5 where the three events are referred to
as भेद, वनवास and युद्ध); earlier the
three events are referred to by a single
word भेद (कुरूणां पाण्डवानां च
यथा भेदो ऽभवत् पुरा) 1. 54. 22, or
by two भेद and राज्यविनाश (भेदं
राज्यविनाशं च कुरुपाण्डवयोस् तदा)
1. 54. 24; the sage (Vyāsa) examined
together the शास्त्रस् related to Dharma,
Kāma and Artha, as also other शास्त्रस्, and
the laws that govern the affairs of the world;
next also the histories with their commen-
taries and different revealed texts; all that
is included here—this defines the text
(of the Mahābhārata) (धर्मकामार्थ-
शास्त्राणि शास्त्राणि विविधानि च।लोकयात्रा-
विधानं च संभूतं दृष्टवान् ऋषिः॥
इतिहासाः सवैयाख्या विविधाः श्रुतयो ऽपि
च।इह सर्वम् अनुक्रान्तम् उक्तं ग्रन्-
थस्य लक्षणम् 1. 1. 47-48.
B. Charac-
terizations: (i) आख्यान (once उपाख्यान
1. 2. 236) 1. 1. 16 (°वरिष्ठ); 1. 2. 29, 30,
195, 235, 238-241, 243; 1. 53. 31, 32, 35;
1. 56. 1, 30, 32; 12. 331. 2; 12. 334. 11; 12.
337. 10; 18. 5. 53; (ii) इतिहास 1. 1. 17,
24, 52; 1. 2. 31, 32 (°उत्तम), 33, 237
(°उत्तम) 1. 54. 23 (पुरातन); 1. 56.
16, 18, 1. 93. 46 (द्युतिमन्त्); 18. 5. 31
(पुण्यो ऽयम् इतिहासाख्यः), 43 (पुण्य);
(iii) पुराण 1. 1. 15; 1. 56. 15 (पुराणं
ऋषिसंस्तुतम्); (iv) कथा 1. 53. 28, 33;
1. 55. 3 (Bhāratī kathā); 1. 56. 2 (चित्रार्-
था); 12. 334. 4; (v) चरित (कुरूणां
चरितं महत्) 1. 56. 1; (vi) (fifth)
Veda 1. 1. 204, 205 (कार्ष्ण वेद); 1. 56.
17 (कार्ष्ण वेद); 1. 57. 74 (वेदान् …
महाभारतपञ्चमान्); (vii) संहिता
1. 1. 19 (व्यासस्याद्भुतकर्मणः।सं-
हिताम्); 1. 1. 61 (भारतसंहिता); 1. 57.
75 (संहितास् तैः पृथक्त्वेन भारतस्य
प्रकाशिताः; Nī., however on Bom. Ed.
1. 63. 90; भारतस्य मूलभूताः संहिताः
मन्त्रब्राह्मणरूपा वेदाः।तैः सुमन्तु-
प्रभृतिभिः प्रकाशिताः इदम् अस्य मूलम्
इदम् अस्य मूलं इति स्पष्टीकृतास् तेन प्र-
त्यक्षवेदमूतम् एतद् इति भावः); 18. 5.
46; (viii) पुण्या उपनिषद् (अत्रोपनिष-
दं पुण्यां कृष्णद्वैपायनो ऽब्रवीत्)
1. 1. 191 (Nī. on Bom. Ed. 1. 1. 253:
ब्रह्मात्मैकत्वविद्याप्रतिपादकं ग्रन्-
थं सूत्रवृत्त्योः प्राग् उक्तयोर् वार्तिकस्था-
नीयम् उपनिषच्छब्दवाच्यम् अब्रवीत्);
(ix) मत 1. 1. 23 (प्रवक्ष्यामि मतं
कृत्स्नं व्यासस्यामिततेजसः); 1. 55. 2; 1.
56. 12; 1. 53. 35 (कृष्णद्वैपायनमतं
महाभारतम्); (x) composition (सन्दर्-
भ) described as ‘not received by tradition’
i. e. ‘original’ (?) (अनागतं … कृष्णद्वै-
पायनः प्रभुः।संदर्भं भारत-
स्यास्य कृतवान् धर्मकाम्यया) 18. 5. 41.
C. Author: The great epic composed by
the great sage Kṛṣṇa Dvaipāyana, also
called Vyāsa, the son of Satyavatī 1. 1.
9-10 (कृष्णद्वैपायनप्रोक्ताः … कथाः …
महाभारतसंश्रिताः); 1. 1. 15 (द्वै-
पायनेन यत् प्रोक्तं पुराणम्); 1. 1. 19
(व्यासस्याद्भुतकर्मणः।संहिताम्);
1. 1. 52 (इतिहासम् इमं चक्रे पुण्यं
सत्यवतीसुतः); 1. 1. 56 (महान् ऋषिः not
named); 1. 1. 60 (भगवान् ऋषिः not
