महात्मना) 1. 2. 70.
D. Etymology:
So called because of its extent (? impor-
tance ?) and weight (महत्त्वाद् भारवत्त्वाच्
च महाभारतम् उच्यते।निरुक्तम् अस्य
यो वेद) 1. 1. 209; so called because it
contains the great life-story (?) of the
Bhāratas (भारतानां महज् जन्म महा-
भारतम् उच्यते।निरुक्तम् अस्य यो वेद)
1. 56. 31.
E. Extent: One hundred
thousand श्लोकस् 1. 56. 13 (इदं शतसहस्-
रं हि श्लोकानां पुण्यकर्मणाम्); 12.
331. 2 (इदं शतसहस्राद् धि भारता-
ख्यानविस्तरात्).
F. Abridgements: Its
abridgements are referred to in 1. 1. 25
(विस्तरैश् च समासैश् च धार्यते यद्
द्विजातिभिः); the sage himself is credited
with an abridgement of the store of know-
ledge after he had first expounded it in full;
learned men desire to preserve it in full as
well as in abridgement (विस्तीर्यैतन् महज्
ज्ञानम् ऋषिः संक्षेपम् अब्रवीत्।इष्तं हि
विदुसां लोके समासव्यासधारनम्) 1. 1.
49; the sage Dvaipāyana abridged (the full
extent of one hundred thousand श्लोकस् into
24000 श्लोकस् by omitting the उपाख्यानस्-
this is known as Bhārata (चतुर्विंशतिसा-
हस्रीं चक्रे भारतसंहिताम्।उपाख्या-
नैर् विना तावद् भारतं प्रोच्यते बुधैः)
1. 1. 61; it was further abridged into 150
श्लोकस् in the form of a table of contents of all
the incidents of the sub-पर्वन्स् (this could
refer to 1. 2. 71-233) (ततो ऽध्यर्धशतं
भूयः संक्षेपं कृतवान् ऋषिः।अनुक्रम-
णिम् अध्यायं वृत्तान्तानां सपर्वणाम् 1. 1.
62; एतद् अखिलम् आख्यातं भारतं पर्व-
संग्रहात् 1. 2. 234); the list of the hundred
sub-पर्वन्स् of the Bhārata (1. 2. 34-1. 2.
70) is included in its abridgement (समासो
भारतस्यायं तत्रोक्तः पर्वसंग्रहः)
1. 2. 71; before narrating in all details, the
Mahābhārata was first summarized by
Vaiśampāyana for Janamejaya (कथितं
वै समासेन त्वया सर्वं द्विजोत्तम।
महाभारतं आख्यानम्) 1. 56. 1;
this summary began with the return of
the Pāṇḍavas to Hāstinapura after the
death of Pāṇḍu and it ended with the death
of Duryodhana and the Pāṇḍavas obtaining
the kingdom 1. 55. 6-42; a sort of a sum-
mary which began with Pāṇḍu's conquering
many countries and then retiring to the forest
and ended with the great destruction after the
war leaving only ten heroes alive is made by
Sūta Ugraśravas for the sages assembled in
the Naimiṣa forest 1. 1. 67-158.
G. Three
beginnings: According to Sūta Ugraśravas
there were three different views regarding the
beginning of the Bhārata: (1) according
to one view it began with Manu Vaivasvata
(मन्वादि भारतं केचित्) 1. 1. 50 (i. e.
with प्रजापतेस् तु दक्षस्य मनोर् वैवस्-
वतस्य च। … अन्वये॥यादवानाम् इमं
वंशं पौरवाणां च सर्वशः।तथैव
भारतानां च (?) 1. 70. 1-2); Devabodha
on 1. 1. 50 explains मनुः as आदिराजः;
according to Nī. on Bom. Ed. 1. 1. 52, in
the opinion of the easterners, मनु means
मन्त्र and hence मन्वादि refers to the
मङ्गल stanza नारायणं नमस्कृत्य etc.
or ओम् नमो भगवते etc. found at the
beginning of the epic in some manuscripts;
in his own opinion, however, मनु refers to
Manu Vaivasvata, the son of the heaven, cf.
मनुर् मन्त्रः नारायणं नमस्कृत्येति।
ओम् नमो भगवते वासुदेवायेति वा तदादि
इति प्रञ्चः।दिवः पुत्रो वैवस्वतमह्य-
संज्ञो मनुस् तदादीति तत्त्वम्।); (2)
according to another view the Bhārata
begins with आस्तीक (आस्तीकादि तथापरे)
1. 1. 50 (i. e. with the अध्याय 1. 13
beginning of the Āstīkaparvan); (3) accor-
ding to a third view it begins with उपरिचर
(तथोपरिचराद् अन्ये) 1. 1. 50 (i. e. with
राजोपरिचरो नाम 1. 57. 1).
H. Its
first teaching and subsequent narrations:
(1) Teaching: Dvaipāyana (Vyāsa) first
taught it to his son Śuka and then handed
it over to his other deserving pupils 1. 1. 63;
he taught it to Śuka together with the four
श्लोकस् (18. 5. 47-50) known as the Bhārata-
sāvitrī 18. 5. 51; Vyāsa taught the Mahabhā-
rata to his pupils Sumantu, Jaimini, Paila,
Vaiśaṃpāyana and to his son Śuka 1. 57.
74-75; Vyāsa taught it to them on the mount
Meru 12. 327. 16-18; on the slope of the
Himavant mountain (हिमवत्पादे) 12. 337.
9, 12, 14-15 (वेदार्थान् भारतार्थांश् च
 … व्याहर्तुम् उपचक्रमे); (2) Narra-
tions: (i) Nārada recited it for the gods,
Asita Devala for the manes (पितृन्), and
Śuka for the Gandharvas, the Yaksas and the
demons 1. 1. 64; 18. 5. 42; (ii) The pupils
of Vyāsa made separate public recitations of
the Bhārata saṃhitā received by them from
him (संहितास् तैः पृथक्त्वेन भारतस्य
प्रकाशिताः) 1. 57. 75; (iii) one such reci-
tation by his pupil Vaiśaṃpāyana is recorded
in the epic: When Kṛṣṇa Dvaipāyana arrived
at the snake-sacrifice of Janamejaya he was
requested by the king to narrate to him the
life-story of the Kurus and the Pāṇḍavas
(1. 54. 18 ff.); Kṛṣṇa Dvaipāyana then
asked his pupil Vaiśaṃpāyana to narrate it
as the latter had heard it from him; Vaiśaṃ-
pāyana then narrated the whole पुरातन
इतिहास to the king, and to those who had
assembled in the सदस्, and to all other
Kṣatriyas (तस्मै राज्ञे सदस्येभ्यः
क्षत्रियेभ्यश् च सर्वशः) 1. 54. 21-24;
1. 1. 8-10; 1. 1. 18; 1. 1. 57-58; 1. 55. 2-3;
1. 55. 4-43 (summary); 18. 5. 26, 30, 42;
18. 1. 2; (iv) but in one place the आख्यान
is said to have been narrated by Vyāsa
himself to Janamejaya continuously (व्यासस्
त्व् अकथयन् नित्यम् आख्यानं भारतं
महत्) 1. 53 31; he narrated it in intervals
(महाभारतम् आख्यानं … जनमेजयेन
यत् पृष्टः कृष्णद्वैपायनस् तदा॥श्रा-
वयाम् आस विधिवत् तदा कर्मान्तरेषु
सः।) 1. 53. 32-33; (v) it was further
narrated by Sūta Ugraśravas, son of Loma-
harṣaṇa, to Śaunaka and the other sages
assembled in the Naimiṣa forest for the
twelve-yearly sacrificial session of Śaunaka
as the Sūta had heard the composition of
Vyāsa being told by Vaiśaṃpāyana to Jana-
mejaya in the latter's snake sacrifice 1. 1.
8-10, 23; 1. 4. 1; 1. 2. 74; 1. 1. 67-158
(summary); 1. 2. 29; Ugraśravas recounted
the Parvasaṃgraha (1. 2. 34-69) made by
Vyāsa as also the eighteen major पर्वन्स्
(एतत् पर्वशतं पूर्णं व्यासेनोक्तं
महात्मना।यथावत् सूतपुत्रेण लोम-
हर्षणिना पुनः॥कथितं नैमिषारण्ये
पर्वाण्य् अष्टादशैव तु) 1. 2. 70-71; the
Sūta also narrated the summary of the
eighteen major पर्वन्स् (based on the
hundred sub-पर्वन्स्) together with the
number of the अध्यायस् and the श्लोकस्
in each पर्वन् 1. 2. 72-234; 1. 53. 27-
36; 18. 5. 30.
I. Purpose: To spread
the fame of the Pāṇḍavas in the world
(पाण्डवानां यशस्करम्) 1. 53. 32; of
the Kurus and the Pāṇḍavas 6. 2. 13;
and also of the other Kṣatriyas possessing
ample wealth and lustre (कीर्तिम् प्रथयता
लोके पाण्डवानां महात्मनाम्।अन्येषां
क्षत्रियाणां च भूरिद्रविणतेजसाम्)
18. 5. 34.
J. Description: Described as
unfathomable (अप्रमेय) 1. 2. 242 (Nī.
on Bom. Ed. 1. 2. 392: नास्ति प्रकृष्टं
मेयं यस्माद् इत्य् अप्रमेयम्। … यद् वा
आशयस्य गंभीरत्वाद् अगाधम्); 18. 5.
54; best (उत्तम) 1. 53. 35; 1. 56. 15, 32;
18. 5. 31, 54, (अनुत्तम) 1. 2. 243; most
exquisite (वरिष्ठ) 1. 1. 202; superior
among all आगमस् (श्रेष्ठः सर्वाग-
मेषु) 1. 2. 31; great (महत्) 1. 2. 243;
1. 53. 31, 35; 12. 334. 11; seen by the
seer (Vyāsa) (आर्ष) 1. 1. 207; having
great import (महार्थ) 1. 2. 243; 18. 5.
43; holy (पुण्या̆) 1. 1. 17, 52; 1. 1. 191;
1. 2. 242 (Nī. on Bom. Ed. 1. 2. 392:
पुण्यं पुण्यहेतुः। … यद् वा … पुण्यं
ज्योतिष्टोमादिवत् स्वर्ग्यम्); 1. 53. 33; 1. 56.
52; 18. 5. 31, 43, 45, 54; (सुपुण्या) 1. 1. 9;
(महापुण्या) 1. 56. 16; conferring merit
(पुण्य) 1. 56. 25; purifying (पवित्र)
1. 2. 242 (however, Nī. on Bom. Ed. 1. 2.
392; पविर् इव पविर् वज्रतुल्यो मृत्युस्
तस्मात् त्रायत इति पवित्रं मृत्युतरणम्
इत्य् अर्थः। … (यद् वा) पवित्रं संध्यो-
पासनादिवच् चित्तशुद्धिकरम्); 1. 56. 15;
18. 5. 31; 18. 5. 54; related to righteousness
(संहितां … धर्म्याम्) 1. 1. 19; auspi-
cious (शिव) 1. 2. 242 (Nī. on Bom. Ed.
1. 2. 392 शिवं कल्याणम् … (यद् वा)
शिवं योगाभ्यासवत् सर्वकल्याणप्रदम्);
18. 5. 54; bringing wealth (धन्य) 1. 56.
25; bringing fame (यशस्य) 1. 56. 25; con-
ferring long life (आयुष्य) 1. 56. 25; leading
to heaven (स्वर्ग्य) 1. 56. 25; destroying
sin (पापहर) 1. 2. 242 (Nī. on Bom.
Ed. 1. 2. 392: पापहरं पुण्यहेतुत्वाद्
एव … (यद् वा) प्रायश्चित्तवद् ब्रह्मह-
त्यादिदोषघ्नम्); 18. 5. 54; removing sin
and danger (संहिताम् … पापभयापहाम्)
1. 1. 19 (however, Nī. on Bom. Ed. 1. 1. 21:
पापभयापहां चित्तशोधिकाम्); having
the same measure as, i. e. equal to, the four
Vedas (वेदैश् चतुर्भिः समिताम् … संहि-
ताम्) 1. 1. 19 (Nī. who reads संयुक्ताम् says
on Bom. Ed. 1. 1. 21: संमिताम् इति पाठे
तुल्याम् इत्य् अर्थः); 1. 56. 15 (इदं हि वेदैः
समितम्); 18. 5. 43 (इतिहासं … वेदसं-
मितम्); (however cf. 1. 1. 208 in the next
section where it is said that the Mahābhārata
outweighs the four Vedas taken together);
adorned with the thoughts of the Veda (वेदार्-
थैर् भूषितस्य च।भारतस्येतिहासस्य)
1. 1. 16-17 (Nī. on Bom. Ed. 1. 1. 18: वेदार्-
थैः वेदतात्पर्यविषयभूतैर् अर्थैः);
enlarged with various शास्त्रस् (नानासास्त्रो-
पबृंहिता … संहिता) 1. 1. 17 (but Nī.
on Bom. Ed. 1. 1. 19 नानाशास्त्रैर् उपबृ-
ंहिताम् उद्दीपितां शास्त्रान्तराविरुद्धाम्);
(cf. 1. 1. 204 in the next section); where
the best intellect is at work (इतिहासोत्तमे
ह्यस्मिन्न् अर्पिता बुद्धिर् उत्तमा) 1. 2. 32;
accomplished with the intellect (प्रज्ञाभि-
पन्नस्य … इतिहासस्य) 1. 2. 33 (Nī. on
Bom. Ed. 1. 2. 40: प्रज्ञयाभिपन्नं
प्राप्तम्); approached by wise men (अभि-
पन्नं नरैः प्राज्ञैः) 1. 2. 30; loved
by the learned (विदुषां प्रियम्) 1. 1. 26;
adorned with divine and human conventions
(अलंकृतं … समयैर् दिव्यमानुषैः)
1. 1. 26 (Nī. on Bom. Ed. 1. 1. 28: सम-
यैः संकेतैः … दिव्यमानुषैः वैदिक-
लौकिकैः); following many conventions (अने-
कसमयान्वित 1. 2. 30); composed in varied
words and consisting of various पर्वन्स्
(विचित्रपदपर्वणः) 1. 1. 16 (Nī. on Bom.
Ed. 1. 1. 18: विचित्राणि स्वरूपतो ऽर्थतश् च
रम्याणि पदानि वाक्यादेर् उपलक्षणं
पर्वाणि पौष्यपौलोमादीनि आदिसभादीनि
वा); 1. 2. 33; an आख्यान composed in
varied words of varied import (विचित्रार्थ-
पदाख्यानम्) 1. 2. 30; has many stories
of various import (विविधाः कथाः … विचि-
त्रार्था महाभारतसंश्रिताः) 1. 1. 9-10;
(कथाश् चित्राः) 1. 53. 30; exhibiting subtle
meaning and logic (सूक्ष्मार्थन्याययुक्त)
1. 1. 16; constituting as though the whole
speech made up of vowels and consonants
that are used in the world and in the
Vedas (स्वरव्यञ्जनयोः कृत्स्ना लोकवेदा-
श्रयेव वाक्) 1. 2. 32; the speech (related
to Brahman) in its refined form संस्कारो-
पगतां ब्राह्मीम्) 1. 1. 17 (Nī. on Bom.
Ed. 1. 1. 19; ब्राह्मीम् वाचम्); adorned
with auspicious words (अलंकृतं शुभैः
शब्दैः) 1. 1. 26; composed in many metres
(छन्दोवृत्तैश् च विविधैर् अन्वितम्) 1. 1.
26; (see also the next section).
K.
Importance: In this epic Kṛṣṇa Dvaipāyana
has expounded a holy उपनिषद् (अत्रोपनि-
षदं पुण्यां कृष्णद्वैपायनो ऽब्रवीत्)
1. 1. 191; truth and nectar constitute the
body of the Bhārata (as the butter of
curds and the Brāhmaṇa of the bipeds)
भारतस्य वपुर् ह्य् एतत् सत्यं चामृतम्
एव च) 1. 1. 201 (Nī. on Bom. Ed. 1. 1.
264: सत्यं ब्रह्म अमृतं देवभावश्
च अत्रैवास्तीत्य् अर्थः); as ocean is the
best of the reservoirs of water, a cow of
the quadrupeds, so is the Bhārata (among
the literary works) 1. 1. 201-202; one should
expand this Veda (of Kṛṣṇa) with the help
of the Itihāsa and Purāṇa for, with the
thought: “he may (easily) go over me” the
Veda is afraid of one who has not studied
much (इतिहासपुराणाभ्यां वेदं समुप-
बृंहयेत्।बिभेत्य् अल्पश्रुताद् वेदो माम्
अयं प्रतरिष्यति) 1. 1. 204 (Devabodha:
उपबृंहणम् अर्थान्तरकल्पनया क्षीण-
स्य यथावद् व्याख्यानेन परिपोषः; Nī.,
however, on Bom. Ed. 1. 1. 268: “यद् ध
त्यं मायिनं मृगम् तम् उ त्यं मायया-
वधीर्” (ṚV. 1. 80. 7) इति मन्त्रावयवो
हि रामायणीयमारीचवधज्ञेनैवोपबृं-
हितुं शक्यो न त्व् अन्येनातस् तस्माद्-
अल्पश्रुताद् वेदस्य भयम् उचितम् एव।
वेदार्थजिज्ञासुना इदम् अवश्यम् अध्येत्-
अव्यम् इत्य् अर्थः); when the sages once
weighed the Bhārata in a balance against
the four Vedas put together it outweighed
them in largeness and heaviness (महत्त्वे
च गुरुत्वे च ध्रियमाणं ततो ऽधिकम्)
1. 1. 208 (Nī. on Bom. Ed. 1. 1. 273:
महत्त्वे ग्रन्थत आधिक्ये गुरुत्वे
अर्थत आधिक्ये); best among the works
which deserve to be heard (when recited)
(श्राव्याणाम् उत्तमं चेदं) 1. 56. 15;
having heard this Purāṇa, composed by
the great sage Dvaipāyana, it was honoured
(अभिपूजितम्) by gods and Brahmarṣis
1. 1. 15; here are glorified holy divine
sages (देवर्षयः पुण्याः), brahmanical
and royal sages of auspicious deeds (पुण्या
ब्रह्मराजर्षयस् तथा।कीर्त्यन्ते शुभ-
कर्माणः), the Yakṣas and the great
snakes, as also lord Vāsudeva 1. 1. 192-193;
in this Purāṇa are expounded fully the two
Puruṣārthas अर्थ and धर्म (अस्मिन्न्
अर्थश् च धर्मश् च निखिलेनोपदिश्यते)
1. 56. 16; in respect of all the four Puruṣārthas
viz. धर्म, अर्थ, काम and मोक्ष, what-
ever is here will be found elsewhere, what is
not here cannot be found anywhere (धर्मे
चार्थे च कामे च मोक्षे च भरतर्षभ।
यद् इहास्ति तद् अन्यत्र यन् नेहास्ति न तत्
क्वचित्।) 1. 56. 33 = 18. 5. 38; in this highly
sacred Itihāsa one finds the exposition lead-
ing to emancipation (बुद्धिश् च परिनै-
ष्ठिकी) 1. 56. 16; (Nī. on Bom. Ed. 1.
62. 17: परिनिष्ठा मोक्षस् तदुचिता); this
is a text on profit (अर्थशास्त्रम्), a holy
treatise on law (पुण्यं धर्मशास्त्रम्),
a way to liberation (मोक्षशास्त्र) as ex-
pounded by Vyāsa 1. 56. 21; this is a great
store of knowledge of the three worlds which
is committed to memory by the twice-born
fully and in abridgements (इदं तु त्रिषु
लोकेषु महज् ज्ञानं प्रतिष्ठितम्।विस्त-
रैश् च समासैश् च धार्यते यद् द्विजाति-
भिः) 1. 1. 25; 1. 1. 49; storehouse of choice
objects (रत्ननिधि) 1. 56. 27 = 18. 5. 52;
the unsurpassed ocean of knowledge-having
churned it with his intellect Vaiśaṃpāyana
collected the आख्यान based on the Nārāyaṇa-
kathā (इदं (i. e. आख्यानं)  … आमथ्य
दधिमन्थेन ज्ञानोदधिम् अनुत्तमम्।
नवनीतं यथा दध्नो … समुद्धृतं …
नारायणकथाश्रयम्) 12. 331. 1-4; some
poets have narrated this इतिहास (composed
by Vyāsa) before (Sūta Ugraśravas did
it), some of the contemporaries of Ugra-
śravas were narrating it in his times, and
others will narrate it in future (आचख्युः
कवयः केचित् संप्रत्य् आचक्षते परे।
आख्यास्यन्ति तथैवान्ये इतिहासम् इमम्
भुवि) 1. 1. 24; 1. 56. 22; even if one knew
the four Vedas together with their अङ्गस्
and the Upaniṣads, but did not know this
आख्यान, he could not be called learned
(विचक्षण) 1. 2. 235; having once listened
to this आख्यान one does not like to listen
to any other composition although worth
hearing 1. 2. 236; the intellects of the poets
take their start from this excellent इतिहास
(इतिहासोत्तमाद् अस्माज् जायन्ते कविबुद्ध-
यः) 1. 2. 237; there is no narrative on this
earth which does not have its basis in this
आख्यान (अनाश्रित्यैतद् आख्यानं कथा
भुवि न विद्यते) 1. 2. 240; all great poets
live on this आख्यान (इदं सर्वैः कवि-
वरैर् आख्यानम् उपजीव्यते) 1. 2. 241; the
whole Purāṇa is included in the scope of this
आख्यान (अस्याख्यानस्य विषये पुराणं
वर्तते द्विजाः) 1. 2. 238; all good qualities
of actions have this आख्यान for their rest-
ing place (i. e. they are motivated by this
आख्यान) (क्रियागुणानां सर्वेषाम् इदम्
आख्यानम् आश्रयः) 1. 2. 239 (Nī. on Bom.
Ed. 1. 2. 387: क्रियाः लौकिक्यो वैदिक्यश् च
तासां गुणाः उत्कृष्टफलसाधनानि।अथवा
क्रियाः दानध्यानादयः।गुणाः शमाद-
यः).
L. फलश्रुति: If one recites
with devotion even a quarter of the Bhārata
all his sins, without a remainder, get puri-
fied (भारताध्ययनात् पुण्यद् अपि पादम्
अधीयतः।श्रद्दधानस्य पूयन्ते सर्व-
पापान्य् अशेषतः) 1. 1. 191 (but Nī. on
Bom. Ed. 1. 1. 254: अस्य श्लोकस्य चतुर्-
थांशोच्चारणमात्राद् अपि सर्वपापनाशः
किं वाच्यं कृत्स्नाध्ययनात् तदर्थस्य
ज्ञानात् साक्षात्काराद् वेति भावः); 18. 5.
45 (here, Nī. on Bom. Ed. 18. 5. 59:
पादं श्लोकपादं ग्रन्थपादं वा); if
one were to recite a quarter of the Bhā-
rata for the Brāhmaṇas at the end of a
श्राद्ध he will ensure for the manes
inexhaustible food and drink (यश् चैनं
(? इदम् cf. 1. 56. 29) श्रावयेच् छ्राद्धे
ब्राह्मणान् पादम् अन्ततः।अक्षय्यम्
अन्नपानम् तत् पितॄंस् तस्योपतिष्ठति) 1. 1.
203; 18. 5. 36 (Nī. on Bom. Ed. 18. 5. 42:
अन्ततः निकटे); 1. 56. 29 (अक्षय्यं तस्य
तच् छ्राद्धम् उपतिष्ठेत् पितॄन् अपि); after
reciting the whole of this Veda of Kṛṣṇa
(i. e. the Bhārata) one attains profit, and one
will undoubtedly get rid of even the sin of
killing an embryo 1. 1. 205; one who recites
it for those that are not low, are generous,
truthful and believers attains profit 1. 56. 17;
even a very cruel person after hearing this Iti-
hāsa will be rid of the sin of killing an embryo
1. 56. 18; one who learns the Bharata when
it is being recited need not bathe in the waters
of Puṣkara 1. 2. 242; 18. 5. 54; one who
recites for others the composition of Vyāsa
and one who listens to it, all of them having
attained to the place of Brahman become
equal to gods 1. 56. 14; this (i. e. listening
to the recitation of the Bhārata) is the best
 means for obtaining a male child (पुंसव-
नं श्रेष्ठम्), a high road to one's well-
being (स्वस्त्ययनं महत्), it should be
listened to by the chief queen and the crown
prince 1. 56. 20; (of one who narrates this),
his sons are obedient to him and his servants
do him good (पुत्राः शुश्रूषवः सन्ति
प्रेष्याश् च प्रियकारिणः) 1. 56. 22; one
who listens to it divests himself quickly of
all sins incurred by body, speech, and mind
1. 56. 23; those who listen, without envy, to
the great life (story) of the Bhāratas have
no fear from disease (in this world), and
need have no fear of the next world at all
1. 56. 24; Kṛṣṇa Dvaipāyana has composed
it which helps to acquire wealth, fame, long
life, heaven and merit 1. 56. 25; the one who
having known it recites it for the Brāhmaṇas
on the पर्वन् days is cleansed of his sins,
wins heaven for himself and becomes one
with Brahman (ब्रह्मभूयं स गच्छति)
1. 56. 28; 18. 5. 35; the sin that one inad-
vertently commits by day in one's activities
disappears if he listens to the Mahābhārata
Ākhyāna 1. 56. 30, or is released from it
by narrating it in the evening 18. 5. 37
(Nī. on Bom. Ed. 18. 5. 43: पश्चिमायां
सन्ध्यायां पठ्यते चेद् दिनकृतं पापं
नश्यति); one who recites it for the three
वर्णस् with Brāhmaṇas at their head is
cleansed of his sins, obtains fame and
undoubtedly achieves the greatest perfection
(गच्छेत् परमिकां सिद्धिम्) 18. 5. 43-
44; or one who studies attentively (पठेत्
सुसमाहितः) the Mahābhārata Ākhyāna will
undoubtedly attain the greatest perfection
18. 5. 53. [See Kārṣṇa, Jaya, Bhārata-
sāvitrī]

भारतसावित्री
Bhāratasāvitrī f.: Name of the four
stanzas (18. 5. 47-50) occurring towards
the end of the Mahābhārata 18. 5. 51.
The great sage Vyāsa having composed
in the bygone days this Bhārata Saṃhitā,
taught it to his son along with the four
stanzas 18. 5. 46; contents of these stanzas
(18. 5. 47-50): thousands of parents and
hundreds of sons and wives with whom one
lives in this world pass away and (many)
others will pass away (in future) (47);
only an ignorant, and not a wise person,
experiences day by day thousands of occasions
for delight and hundreds of occasions for
fear (48); here I, (i. e. Vyāsa himself)
with upraised hands, speak loudly (to
people): why do you not practise धर्म
since from it proceed acquisition of profit
and fulfilment of desire (ऊर्ध्वबाहुर्
विरौम्य् एष न च कश्चिच् छृणोति मे।
धर्माद् अर्थश् च कामश् च स किमर्-
थं न सेव्यते॥) (49); one should not
forsake धर्म for the fulfilment of desire,
nor out of fear, nor greed, nor even for
saving one's life; (for), धर्म is eternal,
while happiness and misery are not eternal,
जीव (soul) is eternal its cause (हेतु i. e.
body) is not eternal (न जातु कामान् न
भयान् न लोभाद् धर्मं त्यजेज् जीवि-
तस्यापि हेतोः।नित्यो धर्मः सुखदुःखे
त्व् अनित्ये जीवो नित्यो हेतुर् अस्य त्व् अनित्यः)
(50); one who recites the Bhāratasāvitrī on
waking up in the morning obtains the fruit
of (reciting) the Bhārata and attains the
highest ब्रह्मन् (स भारतफतं प्राप्य
परं ब्रह्माधिगच्छति); (according to
Nīlakaṇṭha on Bom Ed. 18. 5. 60 these
stanzas bring together the essence of the
Bhārata and therefore deserve to be recited
(तत्र पठनयोग्यं भारतसारसं-
ग्रहं चतुःश्लोकीरूपम्).

भीष्मपर्वन्
Bhīṣmaparvan nt.: Name of the 6th
पर्वन् in the list of the 18 major पर्वन्स्
of the Bhārata 1. 2. 154, 158, 159.
Described as full of varied contents
(विचित्रार्थ) 1. 2. 154 and large (महा-
पर्वन्) 1. 2. 158; it has 117 अध्यायस्
and 5884 श्लोकस् as counted by Vyāsa
(व्यासेन वेदविदुषा संख्याता भीष्म-
पर्वणि) 1. 2. 159; in this पर्वन् Saṃjaya
has described for Dhṛtarāṣṭra the creation of
the Jambūkhaṇḍa; the terrible war lasted for
ten days during which the army of Yudhiṣ-
ṭhira was highly dejected; in it the highly
intelligent Vāsudeva (Kṛṣṇa) removed the
dejection arising out of confusion of Arjuna
with arguments expounding salvation (कश्-
मलं यत्र पार्थस्य वासुदेवो महा-
मतिः।मोहजं नाशयाम् आस हेतुभिर्
मोक्षदर्शनैः) 1. 2. 156 (Nī. on Bom.
Ed. 1. 2. 46-47: कशमलं विषादम्।
मोहजं ममतोत्थम्); in this पर्वन्
Pārtha (Arjuna), placing Śikhaṇḍin in front,
shot sharp arrows at Bhīṣma and felled him
down from the chariot 1. 2. 155-157.

भीष्मवध
Bhīṣmavadha m.: Name of the 64th
पर्वन् in the list of a hundred sub-पर्वन्स्
of the Bhārata supposed to have been made
by Vyāsa in the Parvasaṃgraha 1. 2. 56,
33, 70.
Referred to in the list of the contents
of the Bhīṣmaparvan 1. 2. 157; also by
Dhṛtarāṣṭra in his summary of the events
made for Saṃjaya 1. 1. 125-126; related to
the अध्यायस् 6. 41-117.

भीष्मस्य
Bhīṣmasya svargārohaṇikam: Name
of the 90th पर्वन् in the list of a hundred
sub-पर्वन्स् of the Bhārata supposed to
have been made by Vyāsa in the Parvasaṃ-
graha (स्वर्गारोहणिकं पर्व ततो भीष्म-
स्य धीमतः) 1. 2. 65, 33, 70.
Referred to in the listing of the contents
of the Anuśāsanaparvan (भीष्मस्यात्रैव
संप्राप्तिः स्वर्गस्य परिकीर्तिता) 1. 2.
204; related to the अध्यायस् 13. 153-154.

भीष्माभिषेचन
Bhīṣmābhiṣecana nt.: Name of the
60th पर्वन् in the list of a hundred sub-
पर्वन्स् of the Bhārata supposed to have been
made by Vyāsa in the Parvasaṃgraha 1. 2.
54, 33, 70.
Described as the cause of wonder
(अद्भुतकारण) 1. 2. 54; related to the
अध्यायस् 5. 153-156.

भूमिपर्वन्
Bhūmiparvan nt.: Name of the 62nd
पर्वन् in the list of a hundred sub-पर्वन्स्
of the Bhārata supposed to have been made
by Vyāsa in the Parvasaṃgraha 1. 2. 55,
33, 70.
Described as attractive (मनोनुग)
6. 13. 48; in this पर्वन् the extent of the
islands was described (द्वीपविस्तरकीर्तनम्)
by Saṃjaya to Dhṛtarāṣṭra 1. 2. 55; related
to Saṃjaya's narration in the अध्यायस् 6.
12-13; listening to the Bhūmiparvan a king
becomes illustrious, achieves his objective,
is honoured by the pious (श्रीमान् भवति
राजन्यः सिद्धार्थः साधुसंमतः);
his life, strength, energy and lustre increase
(आयुर् बलं च वीर्यं च तस्य तेजश् च
वर्धते) 6. 13. 48; the ancestors and grand-
fathers of one who, while observing the व्रत,
listens to it on the पर्वन् days are deligh-
ted (प्रीयन्ते पितरस् तस्य तथैव च
पितामहाः) 6. 13. 49.

मन्त्रपर्वन्
Mantraparvan nt.: Name of the 21st
पर्वन् in the list of a hundred sub-पर्वन्स्
of the Bhārata supposed to have been made
by Vyāsa in the Parvasaṃgraha 1. 2. 39,
33, 70.
Referred to as ‘the beginning of the
Rājasūya’ (राजसूयस्य चारम्भः) while
listing the contents of the Sabhāparvan 1. 2.
98; comprises the अध्यायस् 2. 12-17.

महाप्रस्थानिक
Mahāprasthānika nt.: Name of the
97th पर्वन् in the list of a hundred sub-
पर्वन्स् of the Bhārata supposed to have been
made by Vyāsa in the Parvasaṃgraha 1. 2. 68,
33, 70; name of the 17th पर्वन् among the
18 major पर्वन्स् of the Bhārata. 1. 2. 230.
In this पर्वन् the Pāṇḍavas, having
abandoned the kingdom, attained, along with
Draupadī, the highest perfection (सिद्धिं
परमिकां गताः) 1. 2. 230; the sage who
sees the truth (i. e. Vyāsa, not named) has
said that the पर्वन् has three अध्यायस् and
has counted its stanzas to be one hundred and
twenty (सांख्यातास् तत्त्वदर्शिना) 1. 2.
231; related to the अध्यायस् 17. 1-3.

महोपनिषद्
Mahopaniṣad f.: Name (?) of a sacred
text 6. 114. 12.
(1) Bhīṣma, when he fell down from
his chariot, resorted to Yoga and started
reciting Mahopaniṣad; in that condition he
waited for the arrival of proper time for giv-
ing up his life (महोपनिषदं चैव योगम्
आस्थाय वीर्यवान्।जपञ् शान्तनवो धीमान्
कालाकाङ्क्षी स्थितो ऽभवत्॥) 6. 114. 112;
(2) Bhūriśravas, when his right hand was
cut off by Arjuna, gave up fighting with
Sātyaki and started meditating on the
Mahopaniṣad; he then became a sage engaged
in Yoga (ध्यायन् महोपनिषदं योग-
युक्तो ऽभवन् मुनिः) 7. 118. 18. [See
Mahopaniṣada]

महोपनिषद
Mahopaniṣada nt.: Name (?) of a
section (12. 326. 20-99) in the Śāntiparvan
12. 326. 100.
Described as being in conformity with
the four Vedas and composed according to
Sāṃkhya and the Yoga, and following the
Pañcarātra (इदं महोपनिषदं चतुर्-
वेदसमन्वितम्।सांख्ययोगकृतं तेन
पञ्चरात्रानुशब्दितम्॥) 12. 326. 100: it
was sung by Nārāyaṇa (नारायणमुखोद्-
गीत 12. 326. 101) to Nārada when he visited
the great Śvetadvīpa (12. 325. 1); in it
Nārāyaṇa is described to Nārada as one eternal
Person, Vāsudeva (एकं पुरुषं वासुदेवं
सनातनम् 12. 326. 31), who is called the
soul of the world (लोकस्यांएति कथ्यते
12. 326. 21) or the soul of all beings
(सर्वभूतात्मभुतो हि वासुदेवः 12. 326.
31); that Puraṣa is devoid of activity and
can be seen only through knowledge; there is
nothing beyond that eternal Puruṣa (पुरुषो
निष्क्रियश् चैव ज्ञानदृश्यश् च कथ्यते
12. 326. 23; अव्यक्तं पुरुषे ब्रह्मन्
निष्क्रिये संप्रलीयते।नास्ति तस्मात् पर-
तरं पुरुषाद् वै सनातनात् 12. 326. 30);
one should know him to be the eternal,
highest self Vāsudeva (12. 326. 24);
he, the क्षेत्रज्ञ, enjoys the three गुणस्
सत्त्व, रजस् and तमस्, but is not
affected by them (12. 326. 27, 21); that
Vāsudeva himself (क्षेत्रज्ञ) is Saṃkar-
ṣaṇa (जीव), from whom arises Pradyumna
(मनस्), and from Pradyumna arises Ani-
ruddha (अहंकार) (12. 326, 38-39; 35-
37, 68-69); all gods and sages resort to him
and the entire world is contained in him
(12. 326, 47-55); his incarnations from
Varāha to Kṛṣṇa are narrated in 12. 326.
71-93; having thus told Nārada all that was
past. and also the future, with its secret the
blessed God disappeared (एतत् ते सर्वम्
आख्यातं ब्रह्मन् भक्तिमतो मया।
पुराणं च भविष्यं च सरहस्यं च
सत्तम॥एवं स भगवान् देवो विश्व-
मूऋतिधरो ऽव्ययः।एतावद् उक्त्वा वचनं
तत्रैवान्तरधीयत॥) 12. 326. 97-98;
Nārada narrated what he heard from Nārā-
yaṇa again to Brahman in his abode (नाराय-
णमुखोद्गीतं नारदो ऽस्रावयत् पुनः।
ब्रह्मणः सदने तात यथा दृष्टं यथा
श्रुतम्॥) 12. 326. 101. [See Mahopa-
niṣad]

मातङ्गवचन
Mātaṅgavacana nt.: A stanza attribu-
ted to Mātaṅga 5. 125. 19-20.
Duryodhana, when under pressure from
all quarters to come to terms with the
Pāṇḍavas, while replying to Kṛṣṇa quoted
the authority of Mātaṅga in support of the
course of action chosen by him (viz. not
bowing down before the enemy for fear of
losing life); Mātaṅga had said: “One should
rise up and not bow down, for rising up
means manliness; one may break one's bone
(lit. ‘which has no joints’), but not bow
down before any one” (उद्यच्छेद् एव
न नमेद् उद्यमो ह्य् एव पौरुषम्।अप्य्
अपर्वण्त् भज्येत न नमेद् इह कस्यचित्।)
5. 125. 19 (However Nī. on Bom. Ed. 5.
127. 19: अपर्वणि अप्रस्तावे); this dictum
of Mātaṅga is cherished by those who seek
their welfare (इति मातङ्गवचनं परी-
प्सन्ती हितेप्सवः) 5. 125. 20.

मात्स्यक
Mātsyaka adj.: of a Purāṇa (इत्य् एतन्
मात्स्यकं नाम पुराणं परिकीर्तितम्।
3. 185. 53.
Also called आख्यान which removes all
sins (आख्यानम् इदम् आख्यातं सर्व-
पापहरं मया) 3. 185. 53; the Purāṇa
narrates the story of Manu and the fish
3. 185. 1-54; one who always listens to the
story of Manu from the very beginning
becomes happy, all his objectives are ful-
filled, and he goes to heaven 3. 185. 54.

मानवी
Mānavī adj.: of Arthavidyā proclaimed
by Manu 7. 5. 34.
Droṇa, while accepting Duryodhana's
proposal to lead the army after the fall of
Bhīṣma, informed him that besides knowing
the Veda with its six auxiliary sciences, he
knew the Arthavidyā proclaimed by Manu
(वेदं षडङ्गं वेदाहं अर्थविद्यां
च मानवीम्) 7. 5. 34.

मार्कण्डेयसमस्या
Mārkaṇḍeyasamasyā f.: Name of the
37th पर्वन् in the list of a hundred sub-
पर्वन्स् of the Bhārata supposed to have
been made by Vyāsa in the Parvasaṃgraha
1. 2. 45, 33, 70.
Listed in the contents of the Āraṇyaka-
parvan; many narratives (उपाख्यानस्) are
told in this समस्या 1. 2. 124 (मार्कण्डेय-
समस्यायाम् उपाख्यानानि भागशः);
related to the अध्यायस् 3. 179-221.

म्र्गस्वप्नभय
Mrgasvapnabhaya nt.: Name of the
40th पर्वन् in the list of a hundred sub-
पर्वन्स् of the Bhārata supposed to have
been made by Vyāsa in the Parvasaṃgraha
1. 2. 46, 33, 70.
Not listed in the contents of the Āraṇya-
kaparvan (i. e. at 1. 2. 125); related to the
अध्याय 3. 244.

मोक्षधर्म
Mokṣadharma m.: Name of the 88th
पर्वन् in the list of a hundred sub-पर्वन्स्
of the Bhārata supposed to have been made
by Vyāsa in the Parvasaṃgraha 1. 2. 64.
Described as the best among the धर्मस्
followed by those who observe rhe four
religious stages of life (धर्मम् आश्रमिणां
श्रेष्ठम्) 12. 168. 1; referred to in the brief
mention of the contents of the Śāntiparvan as
one where various मोक्षधर्मस् are exten-
sively detailed (मोक्षधर्माश् च कथिता
विचित्रा बहुविस्लराः) 1. 2. 198; related to
the अध्यायस् 12. 168-353.
Mausala nt.: Name of the 96th पर्वन्
in the list of a hundred sub-पर्वन्स् of the
Bhārata supposed to have been made by
Vyāsa in the Parvasaṃgraha 1. 2. 68, 33, 70;
name of the 16th पर्वन् in the list of the
eighteen major पर्वन्स् of the Bhārata 1. 2.
220, 229.
Described as frightful (घोर) 1. 2. 68,
(दारुण) 1. 2. 220; in this पर्वन् is
described how the great heroes (the Yāda-
vas), in a drunken state, crushed by the
Brahmadaṇḍa and incited by fate, killed
one another near the ocean with the वज्रस्
in the form of एरका grass; how Rāma
(i. e. Balarāma) and Keśava could not go
beyond Time when it arrived (नातिचक्रमतुः
कालम् प्राप्तं 1. 2. 222); how Arjuna hav-
ing seen the Dvāravatī without the Vṛṣṇis
(the Yādavas) was dejected and excessively
grieved; he cremated his maternal uncle
Śauri (Vasudeva) and saw the great
destruction of the Yadus at the drinking
party near the ocean (समीपे लवणाम्-
भसः।आपाने) 1. 2. 220-224; Arjuna
cremated the bodies of Vāsudeva, Rāma and
the principal Vṛṣṇis; he then took with him
the aged and the children and after leaving
Dvāravatī experienced the defeat of this
Gāṇḍīva bow in an adverse calamity; he
also experienced non-availablity to him of
all his heavenly missiles (ददर्शापदि
कष्टायाम् गाण्डीवस्य पराभवं॥सर्-
वेषां चैव दिव्यानाम् अस्त्राणाम् अप्रसन्-
नताम् 1. 2. 226-227; Nī. on Bom. Ed.
1. 2. 361.: अप्रसन्नताम् अस्फुरणम्); (on
way) the Vṛṣṇi women were lost; having thus
realized the transient nature of this powers
(नाशं वृष्णिकलत्राणाम् प्रभावानाम्
अनित्यताम्।दृष्ट्वा 1. 2. 227-228), Arjuna,
overcome by the feeling of disregard for the
world and urged by the advice of Vyāsa
(निर्वेदम् आपन्नो व्यासवाक्यप्रचोदितः)
1. 2. 228) recommended संन्यास to Dharma-
rāja when he met him (Nī. on Bom. Ed.
1. 2. 362: संन्यासं राज्यत्यागम्) 1. 2.
220-228; according to the Parvasaṃgraha,
the Mausala parvan has eight अध्यायस् and
three hundred श्लोकस् 1. 2. 229.

यक्षयुद्ध
Yakṣayuddha nt.: Name of the 35th
पर्वन् of the Bhārata in the list of a hundred
sub-पर्वन्स् supposed to have been made by
Vyāsa in the Parvasaṃgraha 1. 2. 44, 33, 70.
The incident is mentioned while listing
the contents of the Āraṇyakaparvan: Drau-
padī asked Bhīmasena to get the Mandāra
flowers; for these he went to the Gandha-
mādana mountain and dared approach the
lotus pond; a great war ensued between him
and the Rākṣasas and the Yakṣas headed
by Maṇibhadra (who guarded the pond)
1. 2. 112-113; alluded to by Dhṛtarāṣṭra
in his summary of the events made for Saṃ-
jaya 1. 1. 111; related to the अध्यायस् 3.
155-172.

यजुर्वेद
Yajurveda m.: Name of one of the
four Vedic Saṃhitās.
A. Relationship with Kṛṣṇa-Nārāyaṇa:
Nārāyaṇa, the greatest among the gods, told
the sage Mārkaṇḍeya that the Yajurveda
and the other three Vedas arise from him
(at the beginning) and enter into him (at
the end) (मत्तः प्रादुर्भवन्त्य् एते माम्
एव प्रविशन्ति च) 3. 187. 14; Bhagavān
(Kṛṣṇa) told Arjuna that in the Yajur-
veda and in the other three Vedas the great
sages have listed his many names 12. 328. 8-
9; he also told Arjuna that he was described
in the ritual texts to be the Yajurveda of one
hundred and one branches (षट्पञ्चाशतम्
अष्टौ च सप्तत्रैंशतम् इत्य् उत।यस्मिञ्
शाखा यजुर्वेदे सो ऽहम् आध्वर्यवे
स्मृतः) 12. 330. 33.
B. Personified:
(i) Yajurveda and Itihāsa acted as rear-
guards (पृष्ठरक्षौ) of the chariot of
Mahādeva (when he got ready to destroy
the Tripuras) 8. 24. 81; (2) Yajurveda,
along with the other Vedas, was seen by
Nārada, waiting on Pitāmaha (Brahmadeva)
in his Sabhā 2. 11. 23, 31. [See Yajus]

यजुस्
Yajus nt. (sg. or pl.): Sacrificial prose
formula from the Yajurveda; when used in
plural it stands also for the Yajurveda; when
in plural, it mostly occurs with ऋच्स् and
सामन्स्।
A. Gift of Āditya to Yājñavalkya:
The sage Yājñavalkya told king Janaka that
while he was practising the prescribed rite,
(although) he was despised (? अवमतेन),
he propitiated the god Sun with severe
austerity; he then received from Āditya the
यजुसेस् (यथार्षेणेह विधिना चरतावम-
तेन ह।मयादित्याद् अवाप्तानि यजूंषि
मिथिलाधिप॥महता तपसा देवस् तपिष्-
ठः सेवितो मया) 12. 306. 2-3; when the
pleased god Sūrya offered a boon to Yājña-
valkya, the latter requested the god to grant
him the यजुसेस् which had not been used
before (? यजूंषि नोपयुक्तानि क्षिप्रम्
इच्छामि वेदितुम्) 12. 306. 4-5; the god
agreed to Yājñavalkya's request; Sarasvatī
then in the form of speech entered Yājña-
valkya's mouth 12. 306. 6-7; the God said
that as a result of that, the whole of Veda
(i. e. the Yajurveda) together with its latter
half and the खिल would be established in
him (Yājñavalkya) (प्रतिष्ठास्यति ते वेदः
सोत्तरः सखिलो द्विजा) 12. 306. 10 (Nī. on
Bom. Ed. 12. 318. 10: खिलं परशाखीयं
स्वशाख्यायाम् अपेक्षावशात् पठ्यते तत्
खिलम् इत्य् उच्यते। … सखिलम् तत्सहितम्।
सोत्तरं सोपनिषत्कम्।); Yājñavalkya
received fifteen यजुसेस् from Arka (Sūrya)
(दश पञ्च च प्राप्तानि यजूंष्य् अर्कान्
मयानघ) 12. 306. 21; Sūrya gave the
यजुसेस् (to Yājñavalkya) in the east (अत्र
(i. e. in the east) दत्तानि सूर्येण यजूंषि)
5. 106. 11 (Nī on Bom. Ed. 5. 108. 11:
याज्ञवल्क्यायेति शेषः).
B. Relationship
with deities: Nārāyaṇa has his abode in the
ऋच्स्, the यजुसेस् and the सामन्स् (ऋग्यजुः-
सामधामानम्) 12. 47. 27; Bhīṣma while
praising Kṛṣṇa-Nārāyaṇa said that he was
of the nature of a स्तोत्र and, as a bird
named Yajus, had metres for its limbs,
Trivṛt (स्तोम) for its head, and Ratha-
ntara and Bṛhatī sāmans for its eyes (यः
सुपर्णो यजुर् नाम छन्दोगात्रस् त्रि-
वृच्छिराः।रथन्तरबृहत्यक्षस् तस्मै
स्तोत्रात्मने नमः॥) 12. 47. 28; (Nī.,
however, on Bom. Ed. 12. 47. 44: सु-
पर्णः वेदपुरुषःअ यजुर् इति यस्य नाम
छन्दांसि गायत्र्यादीनी यस्य गात्राणि हस्-
तादीनि।त्रिवृत् त्रिभिर् ऋग्यजुःसामभिर् वर्-
तत इति योगाद् यज्ञाः स एव शिरो यस्य।
यस्य रथन्तरं बृहच् च वैकल्पिकं
साम प्रीतिवाक्यम्); (2) Upamanyu while
praising Śiva said that he was Śatarudriya
among the यजुसेस् 13. 14. 159.
C. यजुस्
and sacrifice (real or metaphorical): The
sage Taṇḍi while praising Mahādeva said
that the Adhvaryu priests give offerings to
him in sacrifice with the repetition of यजुस्
formulae 13. 16. 48; Trita, fallen in a well,
mentally thought of the ऋच्स्, the यजुसेस् and
the सामन्स् for offering a Soma sacrifice
(ऋचो यजूंषी सामानि मनसा चिन्तयन्
मुनिः) 9. 35. 33; the Yakṣa asked Yudhi-
ṣṭhira: “which is the one यजुस् suited for
sacrifice ?” (किम् एकं यज्ञ्यं यजुः);
the reply was: “mind is the (one) यजुस्
suitable for sacrifice” (मनो वै यज्ञियं
यजुः) 3. 297. 34-35; one who dwells in a
forest (वानप्रस्थाश्रमे वसेत् 12. 236. 5)
should, till death, give five (offerings) to the
प्राणस् in the three fires in himself with the
यजुस् formula, (and) eat six (morsels) with-
out criticizing (the food) 12. 236. 25 (त्रींस्
चैवाग्नीन् यजेत् सम्यग् आत्मन्य् एवात्म-
मोक्षणात् (?)।प्राणेभ्यो यजुषा पञ्च षट्
प्राश्नीयाद् अकुत्सयन्॥ Nī., however, on
Bom. Ed. 12. 244. 26: ‘हृदयं गार्ह-
पत्यो मोनो ऽन्वाहार्यपचन आस्यम् आह-
वनीयः’ इति वैश्वानरविद्योक्तप्रकारेण
आत्ममोक्षणाद् देहपातावधि आत्मनि देहे
एवाग्नीन् यजेत् … यजुष उच्चारणानन्तरम्
पञ्च ग्रासान् प्राश्नीयात् षड् वा।अकुत्सयन्
अन्नम् अनिन्दन्).
D. यजुस् and meat-
eating: One who eats meat which is sancti-
fied by the यजुस् formula (i. e. sacrificial
meat) incurs no sin (यजुषा संस्कृतं
मांसम् उपभुञ्जन् न दुष्यति) 13. 148.
17; consecration by the यजुस् formula is
extended even to ordinary food which does
not involve killing (नात्मार्थं पाचयेद्
अन्नं न वृथा घातयेत् पशून्।प्राणी वा
यदि वाप्राणी संस्कारं यजुषार्हति) 12.
235. 5 (Nī., however, on Bom. Ed. 12. 243.
6: प्राणी छागादिः अप्राणी अश्वथादिः
यजुषा छेदनमन्त्रेणैव क्रत्वर्थम् एव
संस्कारम् अर्हति न तु भक्षणमात्रा-
र्थम्); according to 12. 186. 13, however,
one who has abstained from meat should
not eat (even) meat which is sanctified by
the यजुस् formula (i. e. should not eat even
sacrificial meat) (यजुषा संस्कृतं मांसम्
निवृत्तो मांसभक्षणात्।न भक्षयेत्;
Nī. on Bom. Ed. 12. 193. 14: यजुषा
यजुर्वेदविदाध्वर्युणा मांसम् यज्ञ्यम्
अपि निवृत्तो न भक्षयेत्).
E. The study
of ऋच्स्, यजुसेस् and सामन्स्: One who does
not know the ऋच्स्, the यजुसेस् and the
सामन्स् is to be considered as a calamity
brought about by Prajāpati (अनृग्यजुर्
असामा तु प्राजापत्य उपद्रवः) 12. 60. 42
(Commentator Vimalabodha: अनृग्यजुर्
असामा ऋग्वेदादिशून्यः प्राजापत्य उप-
द्रवः विधातृकृत उपद्रवः उपघातः।
एवंविधो ब्राह्मणो निष्फलजन्मेति भावः
cited in the footnote to the stanza in the Cr.
Ed.; Nī., however, on Bom. Ed. 12. 60. 44:
शूद्रेण उपद्रवतीति तत्समीपगामित्वाद्
उपद्रवो दासः शूद्रः स वेदहीनो ऽपि
प्राजापत्यः प्रजापतिदेवताकः यथाग्नेयो
ब्राह्मण ऐन्द्रोः क्षत्रियस् तद्वत्).
F.
Personified: यजुसेस् in thousands in the
bodily form attended the sacrifice of Mahā-
deva who had assumed the body of Varuṇas
13. 85. 4.
G. Limitations: Hanūmān
told Bhīma that in the Kṛta age there were
no सामन्स्, यजुसेस् अन्द् ऋच्स् (नासन् कृतयुगे
तात … न सामयजुऋग्वर्णाः) 3. 148. 12-13
(Nī. on Bom. Ed. 3. 149. 14: त्रयीध-
र्मस्य चित्तशुद्ध्यर्थत्वात् तस्याश् च
तदानीम् स्वभावसिद्धत्वान् न सामादीन्य्
आसन्) [for other information on यजुस् which
is common to the ऋच्स्, the यजुसेस् and the
सामन्स् see Ṛc above].

यानसन्धि
Yānasandhi m.: Name of the 53rd
पर्वन् in the list of a hundred sub-पर्वन्स्
of the Bhārata supposed to have been made
by Vyāsa in the Parvasaṃgraha 1. 2. 51,
33, 70.
Referred to in the listing of the contents
of the Udyogaparvan as: where Saṃjaya,
in the assembly of the kings, spoke to Dhṛta-
rāṣṭra on the identity of Vāsudeva and
Arjuna (ऐकात्म्यं वासुदेवस्य प्रोक्तवान्
अर्जुनस्य च) 1. 2. 144; the event is also
mentioned in the summary made by Dhṛta-
rāṣṭra for Saṃjaya 1. 1. 117-118; related to
the अध्यायस् 5. 46-69.

रथातिरथसङ्ख्या|रथातिरथसंख्या
Rathātirathasaṃkhyā f.: Name of the
57th पर्वन् in the list of a hundred sub-
पर्वन्स् of the Bhārata supposed to have
been made by Vyāsa in the Parvasaṃgraha
1. 2. 53, 33, 70.
Referred to as ‘counting of the Rathas
and Atirathas’ (रथातिरथसंख्यानम्)
in the listing of the contents of the Udyoga-
parvan 1. 2. 150; during the war the Kaurava
army remembered Karṇa (who was absent
from the battle-field for the first ten days of
the war) at the fall of Bhīṣma and recollected
that in the incident of counting the Rathas
and the Atirathas Bhīṣma had rated Karaṇa as
Ardharatha although he was twice as good as
that kind of a warrior (संख्यातो ऽर्धरथः
कर्णो द्विगुणः सन् नरषभ) 7. 1. 33-
35; referred to in the summary of the events
made by Dhṛtarāṣṭra for Saṃjaya 1. 1. 122;
related to the अध्यायस् 5. 161-169.

राजधर्म
Rājadharma m.: Name of the 86th
पर्वन् in the list of a hundred sub-पर्वन्स्
of the Bhārata supposed to have been made
by Vyāsa in the Parvasaṃgraha (राजधर्-
मानुकीरतनम्) 1. 2. 64, 33, 70.
Referred to in the listing of the contents
of the Śāntiparvan as describing the duties
which must be understood by kings who wish
to know the correct policy (राजभिर् वेदि-
तव्या ये सम्यङ्नयबुभुत्सुभिः) 1. 2.
197; related to the अध्यायस् 12. 1-128.

राजसूयिक
Rājasūyika nt.: Name of the 24th
पर्वन् in the list of a hundred sub-पर्वन्स्
of the Bhārata supposed to have been made
by Vyāsa in the Parvasaṃgraha; it occurs
after the Digvijaya parvan 1. 2. 40, 33, 70.
Referred to in the listing of the contents
of the Sabhāparvan as राजसूये ऽर्घसं-
वादे 1. 2. 99; mentioned in the summary
of the events made by Sūta Ugraśravas for
the sages assembled at the सत्र of Śaunaka
1. 1. 84-85, and in the summary of Dhṛta-
rāṣṭra made for Saṃjaya 1. 1. 99; related
to the अध्यायस् 2. 30-32.

राज्यलम्भ
Rājyalambha m.: Name of the 15th
पर्वन् in the list of a hundred sub-पर्वन्स्
of the Bhārata supposed to have been made
by Vyāsa in the Parvasaṃgraha 1. 2. 37,
33, 70.
Described in the listing of the contents
of the Ādiparvan as: “Pāṇḍavas starting
their life in the Khāṇḍavaprastha and ruling
over half the kingdom; entering into an agree-
ment regarding Draupādī at the instance of
Nārada (नारदस्याज्ञाया चैव द्रौपद्याः
समयक्रिया); the narration of the उपा-
ख्यान related to Sunda and Upasunda”
1. 2. 89-90; referred to in the summary of
the events made by Vaiśaṃpāyana for Jana-
mejaya 1. 55. 23-27; related to the अध्याय
1. 199.

रामचरित
Rāmacarita nt.: Name of an आख्यान (?)
(आख्याते रामचरिते) composed by Bhārgava
12. 57. 40.
Bhīṣma while discoursing on the duties
of a king to Yudhiṣṭhira cities a श्लोक sung
in the bygone days by Bhārgava in the
Rāmacarita (श्लोकश् चायं पुरा गीत्ō भार्-
गवेण महात्मना।आख्याते रामचरिते।)
12. 57. 40; according to this श्लोक one
should first seek a king and next a wife and
riches; in the absence of a king, people
can have neither wife nor riches (राजानं
प्रथमं विन्देत् ततो भार्यां ततो ध-
नम्।राजन्य् असलि लोकस्य कुतो भार्या
कुतो धनम्॥) 12. 57. 41.

रामायण
Rāmāyaṇa1 nt.: Name of an उपा-
ख्यान।
It is narrated in great details (बाहु-
विस्तरम्); listed in the contents of the
Āraṇyakaparvan 1. 2. 126; related to the
अध्यायस् 3. 258-276.

रामायण
Rāmāyaṇa2 nt.: Name of the epic.
Referred to by Bhīma in his conversation
with Hanūmān 3. 147. 11.

वसुहोमस्य
Vasuhomasya matam: Name (?) of a
tract occurring in the Śāntiparvan 12. 122. 54.
In this tract (12. 122) Vasuhoma, the
king of the Aṅgas, told his royal guest Mān-
dhātṛ the origin of दण्ड,—how Mahādeva
created it to put an end to promiscuous be-
haviour of the people (संकरो न भवेद्
अत्र तथा वै तद् विधीयताम् 12. 122. 23);
Mahādeva having created it gave it to Viṣṇu,
from whom it passed on successively to Manu
and his sons; when people remain awake in
this world (i. e. are not negligent about their
duties), it means that the दण्ड is awake
in them (प्रजा जाग्रति लोके ऽस्मिन् दण्डो
जाग्रति तासु च) 12. 122. 50; the king who
listens to this tract and behaves properly will
get all his desires 12. 122. 54.

वासिष्ठ
Vāsiṣṭha nt.: Name of an आख्यान 1.
2. 87.
Listed in the contents of the Ādiparvan
1. 2. 87; called पुराअण in all the (three)
worlds (इदं वासिष्ठम् आख्यानं पुराणं
परिचक्षते।पार्थ सर्वेषु लोकेषु) 1.
165. 2; it occurs, as part of the Caitraratha-
parvan, in the अध्यायस् 1. 164-168, 173.

विजय
Vijaya nt.: See Indravijaya.

विदुरागमन
Vidurāgamana nt.: Name of the 14th
पर्वन् in the list of a hundred sub-पर्वन्स्
of the Bhārata supposed to have been made
by Vyāsa in the Parvasaṃgraha 1. 2. 37,
33, 70.
Referred to as विदुरस्य च संप्राप्तिः
while listing the contents of the Ādiparvan
1. 2. 89; related to the अध्यायस् 1. 192-198.

विदरायाश्
Vidarāyāś ca saṃvādaṃ putrasya ca:
Name (?) of a dialogue between Vidurā and
her son (Saṃjaya) 5. 131. 1.
Described as old Itihāsa (इतिहासं पुरा-
तनम्) 5. 131. 1; the Itihāsa is of the type
of Jaya (जयो नामेतिहासो ऽयम्) 5. 134. 17;
it contains what is beneficial (for a king)
and what leads to his prosperity (अत्र श्रेयश्
च भूयश् च) 5. 131. 2; it is a powerful
exhortation, best calculated to raise the spirits
(of a king); a minister should narrate it to
his king who is sinking (in spirits) and is
oppressed by enemies (इदम् उद्धर्षणं
भीमं तेजोवर्धनम् उत्तमम्।राजानं
श्रावयेन् मन्त्री सीदन्तन्ं शत्रुपीडितम्॥)
5. 134. 16; in it Vidurā, the queen mother,
instructed her dejected son Saṃjaya regar-
ing the duties of a Kṣatriya and exhorted
him to rise up and fight with his enemies to
get back the lost kingdom; Kuntī told it to
Kṛṣṇa and wanted him to report it to her
sons; the narrative is contained in the
अध्यायस् 5. 131-134; alluded to in 15. 22.
20; 15. 23. 1-18 (esp. 14, 18). [See Jaya]

वैन्योपाख्यान
Vainyopākhyāna nt.: Name of an
उपाख्यान।
Listed in the contents of the Āraṇyaka-
parvan 1. 2. 126; related to the अध्याय
3. 183 (?)

वैराट
Vairāṭa1 nt.: Name of the 45th पर्वन्
in the list of a hundred sub-पर्वन्स् of the
Bhārata supposed to have been made by
Vyāsa in the Parvasaṃgraha 1. 2. 48, 33, 70.
Related to the अध्यायस् 4. 1-12.

वैराट
Vairāṭa2 nt.: Name of the 4th पर्वन्
among the eighteen major पर्वन्स् of the
Bhārata 1. 2. 130, 134.
Described as extensive (विपुल) 1. 2.
134; the great sage (Vyāsa) has counted of
this पर्वन् sixty-seven अध्यायस् (4. 1-67)
and two thousand and fifty श्लोकस् 1. 2. 134-
135; the events of this पर्वन् are summar-
ized as follows: the Pāṇḍavas after reaching
the Virāṭanagara left their weapons on a
big Śamī tree; concealing their identity, the
Pāṇḍavas lived in the Virāṭanagara; wicked
Kīcaka was killed by Vṛkodara (Bhīma);
the Kurus, when they attempted a raid on
Virāṭa's cattle, were defeated by Pārtha
(Arjuna); the cattle were brought back by
the Pāṇḍavas; Virāṭa gave Uttarā to Arjuna
as his daughter-in-law to be wedded to Abhi-
manyu 1. 2. 130-133; the incidents of this
पर्वन् are referred to by Dhṛtarāṣṭra in his
summary made for Saṃjaya 1. 1. 114-115.

वैवाहिक
Vaivāhika1 nt.: Name of the 13th
पर्वन् in the list of a hundred sub-पर्वन्स्
of the Bhārata supposed to have been made
by Vyāsa in the Parvasaṃgraha 1. 2. 37,
33, 70.
Referred to while summarizing the con-
tents of the Ādiparvan as: here takes place
the marriage of Draupadī, not common among
men, as ordained by the gods (द्रौपद्या
देवविहितो विवाहश् चाप्य् अमानुषः) 1. 2. 88;
related to the अध्यायस् 1. 190-191.

वैवाहिक
Vaivāhika2 nt.: Name of the 48th
पर्वन् in the list of a hundred sub-पर्वन्स्
of the Bhārata supposed to have been made
by Vyāsa in the Parvasaṃgraha 1. 2. 49,
33, 70.
In this पर्वन् Abhimanyu was married
to Vairāṭī (Uttarā) 1. 2. 49; referred to
while summarizing the contents of the Vai-
rāṭaparvan 1. 2. 133; also by Dhṛtarāṣṭra in
his summary made for Saṃjaya 1. 1. 115;
related to the अध्यायस् 4. 63-67.

वैशालाक्ष
Vaiśālākṣa nt.: Name of a शास्त्र 12.
59. 88.
The शास्त्र which was first composed by
Pitāmaha Brahman was received from him
by Viśālākṣa Śaṃkara, the husband of Umā;
Śiva, having regard to (the shorter duration
of) the (successive) युगस्, abridged the
शास्त्र and it then came to be known as
Vaiśālākṣa; this abridged version of ten
thousand अध्यायस् was received by Indra
from Śiva 12. 59. 86-88. [See Paitāmaha-
śātra, Bārhaspatya, Bāhudantaka]

व्रीहिद्रौणिक
Vrīhidrauṇika nt.: Name of the 41st
पर्वन् in the list of a hundred sub-पर्वन्स्
of the Bhārata supposed to have been made
by Vyāsa in the Parvasaṃgraha 1. 2. 46,
33, 70.
The पर्वन् is called an आख्यान (व्रीहि-
द्रौणिकम् आख्यानम्) 1. 2 46; referred to
while listing the contents of the Āraṇyaka-
parvan 1. 2. 125; related to the अध्यायस्
3. 245-247.

शक्रविजय
Śakravijaya nt.: See Indravijaya.

शतपथ
Śatapatha nt.: Name of a Vedic text
belonging to the White Yajurveda.
Described as a new Veda (lit. ‘which
did not exist before’) (वेदम् अपूर्वम्) 12.
306. 23; God Sūrya blessed Yājñavalkya
with a boon and told him that goddess
Sarasvatī, in the form of speech, would enter
his body; he then asked Yājñavalkya to open
his mouth (सरस्वतीह वाग्भूता शरीरं
ते प्रवेक्ष्यति।ततो माम् आह भगवान्
आस्यं स्वं विवृतं कुरु।) 12. 306. 6-7;
Yājñavalkya was then to promulgate
the entire Śatapatha at the end of which
activity his mind would seek liberation
(कृत्स्नं शतपथं चैव प्रणेष्यसि द्वि-
जर्षभ।तस्यान्ते चापुनर्भावे बुद्धिस्
तव भविष्यति) 12. 306. 11; (Nī. on Bom.
Ed. 12. 319. 11: अपुनर्भावे मोक्षे); later,
Yājñavalkya meditated on Sarasvatī and when
the goddess, adorned with vowels and conso-
nants, flashed before him, he offered her and
the god Sūrya a guest offering; he then
composed with great delight the entire Śata-
patha along with its secrets, and abstracts,
and supplements; he taught it to his hundred
pupils (ततः शतपथं कृत्स्नं सर-
हस्यं ससंग्रहम्।चक्रे सपरिशेषं
च हर्षेण परमेण च॥कृत्वा चाध्यय-
नं तेषां शिष्याणां शतम् उत्तमम्) 12.
306. 16-17; Yājñavalkya embarked on this
activity keeping before his mind the seed (in
the form of the fifteen यजुसेस् which he had
obtained from god Sun (दश पञ्च च
प्राप्तानि यजूंष्य अर्कान् मयानघ 12.
306. 21) and goddess Sarasvatī, and on
the strength of the authority conferred on
him by god Sūrya (बीजम् एतत् पुरस्कृत्य
देवीम् चैव सरस्वतीम्।सूर्यस्य चानु-
भावेन प्रवृत्तो ऽहं नराधिप॥) 12.
306. 22; he taught the whole of it to his
pupils and established fifteen branches of
learning revealed to him by Bhāskara (god
Sūrya) 12. 306. 24-25; a passage to the effect
that ‘if one who knows (the real significance)
gives an offering as a gift in the mouth of
a Brāhmaṇa it is as good as giving an
offering in kindled fire’ is supposed to occur
in the Śatapatha Brāhmaṇa (शतपथे हि
ब्राह्मणं भवति।अग्नौ समिद्धे स
जुहोति यो विद्वान् ब्राह्मणमुखे दाना-
हुतिं जुहोति) 12. 329. 8.

शतरुद्रीय
Śatarudrī̆ya1 nt.: Name of a स्तोत्र
glorifying Śiva (7. 173. 103) communicated
by Vyāsa to Arjuna (देवदेवस्य ते पार्थ
व्याख्यातं शतरुद्रियम्) 7. 173, 101; 7.
173. 104 (शतरुद्रीयम्).
A. Description: Described as winning
wealth (धन्य), fame (यशस्य), long life
(आयुष्य), and merit (पुण्य), and made
known by the Vedas (वेदैश् च संज्ञितम्)
7. 173. 101; fulfilling all aims (सर्वार्थ-
साधक), holy (पुण्य), destroying all blemi-
shes (सर्वकिल्बिषनाशन), destroying all sins
(सर्वपापाप्रशमन), driving away all
misery and fear (सर्वदुःखभयापह)
7. 173. 102; four-fold (चतुर्विध, probably
because the स्तोत्र (1) enumerates the attri-
butes of Śiva (7. 173. 9-14; 20-39), (2)
describes his greatness (7. 173. 15-19; 61-81;
93-100), (3) glorifies his deeds (7. 173.
40-60), and (4) gives etymologies of his
names (7. 173. 82-92); but Nī. on Bom. Ed.
7. 202. 50: शुद्धशबलसूत्रविराट्भेदेन
भगवद्रूपस्य चातुर्विअध्यात् स्तोत्रम् अप्य्
अस्य चतुर्विधम्); describes the divine deeds
of the high-souled Śiva (चरितं महात्मनो
दिव्यम्), of help in war (साङ्ग्रामिक), and
auspicious (शुभ) 7. 173. 104.
B. फल-
श्रुति: One who always listens to Śatarudrīya
defeats all his enemies and is highly esteemed
in the Rudraloka 7. 173. 103; one who recites
it or, always exerting himself, listens to it,
and is devoted to god Viśveśvara obtains,
when god Tryambaka is pleased, all his chosen
desires 7. 173. 104-105; the स्तोत्र comprises
the stanzas 7. 173. 1-101.

शतरुद्रीय
Śatarudrī̆ya2 nt.: Name of a Vedic
text (ब्रह्म) 7. 57. 71 (Vāj. Saṃ. 16 =
Tai. Saṃ. 4. 5. 1-11).
A. Origin: It was created by Prājā-
pati at the end of his तपस् 13. 145. 5.
B. Importance: Śiva was identified by
Upamanyu as Śatarudriya of Yajurveda
(यजुषां शतरुद्रियम्) 13. 14. 159; Vyāsa
told Arjuna that in the Veda is transmitted
the excellent Śatarudrīya as a means of
worship of Śiva (रेदे चास्य समाम्नातं
शतरुद्रीयम् उत्तमम्। … उपस्थानं
महात्मनः) 7. 173. 79; Kṛṣṇa told Yudhi-
ṣṭhira that the excellent Śatarudrīya was
known from the Veda and that it was a
means of worshipping Śiva, which became
known immediately after the one known to
Vyāsa (? reference to Satarudriya1 ?) (वेदे
चास्य विदुर् विप्राः शतरुद्रीयम् उत्तमम्।
व्यासाद् अनन्तरं यच् चाप्य् उपस्थानं
महात्मनः॥) 13. 146. 23.
C. Des-
cription: Described as ‘special knowledge’
(विज्ञान), which constitutes the high ex-
cellence and the names of Śiva, obtained by
Kṛṣṇa from Durvāsas (दुर्वाससः प्रसादात्
ते यत् तोदा मधुसादन।अवाप्तम् इह
विज्ञानम् … महाभाग्यं च यत् तस्य
नामानि च महात्मनः) 13. 145. 1-2.
D. Use: Kṛṣṇa recited it every morning
with folded hands 13. 145. 4; it was used
to worship Rudra-Śiva on various occasions:
(1) the gods gathered at Dakṣa's sacrifice
tried to pacify enraged Rudra by reciting
with folded hands the Śatarudrīya 13. 145. 21;
(2) when different gods praised Śiva (called
परं ब्रह्म) with स्तोत्रस्, Indra praised
him with the excellent Śatudrīya 13. 14. 147;
(3) Kṛṣṇa and Arjuna, who knew the
Veda, touched water, folded their hands, and
worshipped the two Nāgas protecting the bow
and arrow of Śiva, and recited the Śata-
rudrīya in praise of Śiva 7. 57. 71.

शल्यपर्वन्
Śalyaparvan1 nt.: Name of the 74th
पर्वन् in the list of a hundred sub-पर्वन्स्
of the Bhārata supposed to have been made
by Vyāsa in the Parvasaṃgraha 1. 2. 59,
33, 70.
Reterred to in the summary of the events
made by Dhṛtarāṣṭra for Saṃjaya 1. 1. 148;
related to the अध्यायस् 9. 1-16 (Śalya-
vadhaparvan).

शल्यपर्वन्
Śalyaparvan2 nt.: Name of the 9th
पर्वन् among the eighteen major पर्वन्स्
of the Bhārara 1. 2. 173, 174, 176.
Described as wonderful (अद्भुत) 1.
2. 176, full of import (अर्थवत्) 1. 2. 176,
having varied topics (विचित्रार्थ) 1. 2. 173;
its अध्यायस् are said to describe many events
(बहुवृत्तान्ताः) 1. 2. 177; the contents of
the पर्वन् are summarized as follows: at
the death of the excellent hero (Karṇa),
the king of the Madras (Śalya) became the
leader; there occurred many chariot battles
(during his leadership) which are described at
various places (वृत्तानि रथयुद्धानि कीर्त्-
यन्ते यत्र भागशः); many principal Kuru
warriors met with death; Śalya was killed
by Dharmarāja; the fierce duel with maces
also occurred in that पर्वन्; the holiness
of the river Sarasvatī and of the तीर्थस् is
described in it 1. 2. 173-175; those expert
in counting numbers (संख्याविशारद)
had counted its अध्यायस् to be fifty-nine 1. 2.
176 (actually the critical edition has sixty-
four अध्यायस् 9. 1-64); the sage (Vyāsa)
composed three thousand two hundred and
twenty श्लोकस् for this पर्वन् 1. 2. 177.

शान्तिपर्वन्
Śāntiparvan nt.: Name of the 12th
पर्वन् among the eighteen major पर्वन्स् of
the Bhārata 1. 2. 64, 196, 197.
Described as one which enhances
wisdom (बुद्धिवर्धन) 1. 2. 196, and
one which is liked by intelligent persons
(प्राज्ञजनप्रिय) 1. 2. 199; it has three
sub-पर्वन्स्: Rājadharma, Āpaddharma,
and Mokṣadharma (शान्तिपर्व ततो यत्र
राजधर्मानुकीर्तनम्।आपद्धर्मश् च
पर्वोक्तं मोक्षधर्मस् ततः परम्।)
1. 2. 64; these धर्मस् were expounded by
Bhīṣma, lying on the bed of arrows (शान्ति-
पर्वणि धर्माश् च व्याख्यातः शरतल्पि-
काः) to Yudhiṣṭhira who felt dejected as he
was responsible for the deaths of fathers,
brothers, sons, kinsmen and relatives 1. 2.
196-197; the पर्वन् has 339 अध्यायस् and
it is reported that it has 14525 stanzas 1. 2.
199-200. [See Āpaddharma, Mokṣadharma,
Rājadharma]

शिशुपालवध
Śiśupālavadha m.: Name of the 26th
पर्वन् in the list of a hundred sub-पर्वन्स्
of the Bhārata supposed to have been made
by Vyāsa in the Parvasaṃgraha 1. 2. 41,
33, 70.
The incident is mentioned while listing
the contents of the Sabhāparvan 1. 2. 99;
it is referred to in Sūta's summary of the
events made for the sages assembled in the
Naimiṣa forest as ‘where (was killed) the
arrogant king of the Cedis’ (घातयित्वा …
चैद्यं च बलगर्वितम्) 1. 1. 86; related
to the अध्यायस् 2. 37-42.

श्येनकपोतीय
Śyenakapotīya nt.: Name of an उपा-
ख्यान।
Listed in the contents of the Āraṇyaka-
parvan 1. 2. 115; in it Indra, Agni and
Dharma put king Śibi to test (ततः श्येनक-
पोतीयम् उपाख्यानम् अनन्तरम्।इन्द्रो
ऽग्निर् यत्र धर्मश् च अजिज्ञासञ् शिबिं नृ-
पम्॥) 1. 2. 115; (actually in the narrative
only Indra and Agni appear and the two put
Śibi to test regarding his steadfastness in
धर्म (इन्द्रो ऽहम् अस्मि धर्मज्ञ
कपोतो हव्यवाड् अयम्।जिज्ञासमानौ
धर्मे त्वाम् यज्ञवाटम् उपागतौ॥)) 3.
131. 28); related to the अध्याय 3. 131
(also 3. 130. 18-20).

श्राद्धपर्वन्
Śrāddhaparvan nt.: Name of the 82nd
पर्वन् in the list of a hundred sub-पर्वन्स्
of the Bhārata supposed to have been made
by Vyāsa in the Parvasaṃgraha 1. 2. 62,
33, 70.
In it the funeral rites of the Kurus
were performed (कुरूणाम् और्ध्वदेहिकम्)
1. 2. 62; alluded to in the listing of the
contents of the Strīparvan as one in which
Yudhiṣṭhira got the bodies of the kings
cremated according to the rites (राज्ञां तानि
शरीराणि दाहयाम् आस शास्त्रतः) 1. 2. 193;
related to the अध्याय 11. 26.

संवर्तमरुत्तीय
Saṃvartamaruttīya nt.: Name of an
आख्यान 1. 2. 206.
Described as one not excelled by any
other आख्यान (अनुत्तम), it occurs as a
part of the 14th Aśvamedhika parvan 1. 2.
206; in the Āśvamedhikaparvan it is alluded
to as a कथा 14. 4. 1, or an old इतिहाष
and a संवाद between Bṛhaspati and
Marutta (अत्राप्य् उदाहरन्तीमम् इतिहासं
पुरातनम्।बृहस्पतेश् च संवादं
मरुत्तस्य च भारत) 14. 6. 1; related
to the अध्यायस् 14. 4-10; also cf. 14. 3.
20-22.

संशप्तकवध
Saṃśaptakavadha m.: Name of the
66th पर्वन् in the list of a hundred sub-
पर्वन्स् of the Bhārata supposed to have
been made by Vyāsa in the Parvasaṃgraha
1. 2. 56, 33, 70.
The incident is referred to while listing
the contents of the Droṇaparvan as: where
the Saṃśaptakas took Arjuna away from the
battle-field (यत्र शंशप्तकाः पार्थम्
अपनिन्यू रणाजिरात्) 1. 2. 160, and where
Arjuna completely annihilated what remained
of the Saṃśaptakas after he killed Jayadratha
(हतो राजा जयद्रथः।संशप्तकाव-
शेषं च कृतं निःशेषम् आहवे) 1. 2. 163;
the incident is referred to by Dhṛtarāṣṭra in
his summary of the events made for Saṃjaya
1. 1. 131; related to the अध्यायस् 7. 16-31.

सञ्जययान|संजययान
Saṃjayayāna nt.: Name of the 50th
पर्वन् in the list of a hundred sub-पर्वन्स्
of the Bhārata supposed to have been made
by Vyāsa in the Parvasaṃgraha (ततः
संजययानाख्यं पर्व ज्ञेयम् अतः
परम्) 1. 2. 50, 33, 70.
The incident is mentioned in the summary
of the contents of the Udyogaparvan as
follows: where Dhṛtarāṣṭra sent Saṃjaya as
his messenger to make peace with the Pāṇḍa-
vas 1. 2. 140; related to the अध्यायस् 5.
22-32.

सभापर्वन्
Sabhāparvan1 nt.: Name of the 20th
पर्वन् in the list of a hundred sub-पर्वन्स्
of the Bhārata supposed to have been made
by Vyāsa in the Parvasaṃgraha 1. 2. 39,
33, 70.
Related to the अध्यायस् 2. 1-11. [See
Sabhāparvan2]

सभापर्वन्
Sabhāparvan2 nt.: Name of the 2nd
पर्वन् among the 18 major पर्वन्स् of the
Bhārata 1. 2. 97, 103.
Described as having many events (बहु-
वृत्तान्त) 1. 2. 97; its contents are summa-
rized as follows: (where we hear) the con-
struction of the सभा of the Pāṇḍavas; the
appearance of the किङ्करस्; the description
by Nārada of the सभास् of the guardians
of the world; the undertaking of the Rāja-
sūya; the killing of Jarāsandha; the release
by Kṛṣṇa of the kings imprisoned in the
Girivraja; the killing of Śiśupāla over the
dispute regarding the guest worship at the
Rājasūya; derision of Duryodhana by Bhīma
on the floor of the सभा; Duryodhana griev-
ed and angered at the riches gathered by
the Pāṇḍavas for the sacrifice; where angry
Duryodhana forced a game of dice (on the
Pāṇḍavas); where gambler Śakuni defeated
Yudhiṣṭhira at the game of dice; where
Draupadī saved the Pāṇḍavas, as a boat
(saves one) in an ocean; where Duryodhana
challenged the Pāṇḍvas to a second game
of dice 1. 2. 97-102; all this constitutes the
Sabhāparvan and it was narrated by the great
sage (एतत् सर्वं सभापर्व समाख्यातं
महात्मना) 1. 2. 103; its अध्यायस् are
known to be 72 (अध्यायाः … ज्ञेयाः) and
the number of श्लोकस् are declared to be 2511
(श्लोकाश् च … ज्ञेयाः पर्वण्य् अस्मिन् प्रकी-
र्तिताः) 1. 2. 103-104; the incidents of the
Sabhāparvan are referred to in Dhṛtarāṣṭra's
summary of the events made for Saṃjaya
1. 1. 105-107, and by Vaiśaṃpāyana in his
summary made for Janamejaya 1. 55. 38-40.
[See Sabhāparvan1]

सम्भवपर्वन्|संभवपर्वन्
Saṃbhavaparvan nt.: Name of the 7th
पर्वन् in the list of a hundred sub-पर्वन्स्
of the Bhārata supposed to have been made
by Vyāsa in the Parvasaṃgraha 1. 2. 35,
33, 70.
Described as wonderful (अद्भुत) and
created by the gods (देवनिर्मित) 1. 2. 35;
its contents are summarized as follows:
(where we are told) the birth of the Vasus
as sons of Bhāgīrathī (Gaṅgā) in the
house of Śaṃtanu and their rise to heaven
again; birth of Bhīṣma from the combi-
nation of the portions of the lustre of the
Vasus (तेज्ॐशानां च संघाताद् भीष्म-
स्याप्य् अत्र संभवः 1. 2. 79); Bhīṣma's
renouncing the kingdom and his determina-
tion to remain celibate; Bhīṣma's fulfilling
his vow and his guardianship of Citrāṅgada;
at the death of Citrāṅgada, Bhīṣma's giving
protection to the younger brother (Vicitra-
vīrya) and putting him on to the throne;
birth of Dharma among men as a result of
the curse of sage Aṇīmāṇḍavya and birth of
Dhṛtarāṣṭra and Pāṇḍu from Kṛṣṇa-dvaipā-
yana as a result of a boon, and birth of the
Pāṇḍavas 1. 2. 78-82; the incidents are referr-
ed to in Sūta's summary of the events made
for the sages assembled in the Naimiṣa forest
1. 1. 53-55; 67-69; the पर्वन् is related to
the अध्यायस् 1. 62-123.

सम्यङ्मनस्
Samyaṅmanas nt.: Name of a शास्त्र
dealing with renunciation (तत्र सम्यङ्-
मनो नाम त्यागशास्त्रम्) 12. 212. 16.
Described as unexcelled (अनुत्तम)
12. 212. 16; it was taught to Janaka
Janadeva, king of Mithilā, (12. 212. 1;
12. 211. 1) by कवि Pañcaśikha Kāpileya
(12. 211. 6, 15-16), the pupil of Āsuri
(12. 211. 10); the nature of त्याग was
expounded by Pañcaśikha to the king so that
he might attain emancipation (शृणु यत् तव
मोक्षाय भाष्यमाणं भविष्यति) 12. 212.
16; the exposition of the शास्त्र is found in
12. 212. 17-43; one who knows this knowledge
leading to emancipation and one who, with-
out making a mistake, seeks the soul is not
tainted by the undesirable fruits of his
acts (इमां तु यो वेद विमोक्षबुद्धिम्
आत्मानम् अन्विच्छति चाप्रमत्तः।न
लिप्यते कर्मफलैर् अनिष्टैः पत्रं बिस-
स्येव जलेन सिक्तम्) 12. 212. 44; the condi-
tion of such a person is described in 12.
212. 45-50; when the king of Videha
(Janaka Janadeva) was taught the state of
immortality (अमृतपदम्), he lived very
happily and was freed from sorrow 12. 212,
51; one who reads this established doctrine
on emancipation (विमोक्षनिश्चय) does not
experience calamities and is freed (of all
bonds, cf. 12. 212. 45) 12. 212. 52.

सानत्सुजात
Sānatsujāta nt.: Name of the 52nd
पर्वन् in the list of a hundred sub-पर्वन्स्
of the Bhārata supposed to have been made
by Vyāsa in the Parvasaṃgraha 1. 2. 51,
33, 70.
A section of the Udyogaparvan is so
called; in this sub-पर्वन् the grieved king
Dhṛtarāṣṭra was instructed by Sanatsujāta
in the excellent doctrine concerning आत्मन्
(तथा सनत्सुजातेन यत्राध्यात्मम् अनु-
त्तमम्।मनस्तापान्वितो राजा श्रावितः
शोकलालसः) 1. 2. 143; related to the
अध्यायस् 5. 42-45.

सामन्
Sāman nt. (mostly plural): Stands for
the Sāmaveda, or a hymn or stanzas of that
Veda (in this sense it often occurs along with
ऋच् and यजुस्); a melody in which the stanzas
of the Sāmaveda are sung.
A. Relationship with Bhagāvān: Bhaga-
vān told Arjuna that those who knew the
Veda called him the Sāmaveda of a thousand
branches (मां प्रचक्षते।सहस्रशाखं
यत् साम ये वै वेदविदो जनाः) 12. 330.
32; in the stanzas of the Sāmaveda, as in the
other three Vedas and many other texts, many
names of Bhagavān have been enumerated by
the great sages (ऋग्वेदे सयजुर्वेदे तथै-
वाथर्वसामसु। … बहूनि मम नामानि
कीर्तितानि महर्षिभिः) 12. 328. 8.
B. Sing-
ing of सामन् as daily routine: The आश्रम
of Dadhīca on the other bank of Sarasvatī
hummed with the sound of bees as with the
chantings of सामन्- singers (षट्पदोद्गीत-
निनदैर् विघुष्ट्ं सामगैर् इव) 3. 98. 13;
on the Gandhamādana mountain the Pāṇḍavas
could hear the sound of the songs and of the
clapping of hands (by the Gandharvas and the
Kiṃpuruṣas) which sounded like the melody
of the सामन् chants (गीतानां तलतालानां
यथा साम्नां च निस्वनः) 3. 155. 84; the
precincts of the आश्रम of Upamanyu
resounded with the auspicious melodies of
सामन्-singers (शुभैः सामगानां
च वीर) 13. 14. 35.
C. Employment
in sacrifices: In the Rājasūya of Yudhiṣṭhira
the six fires were piled up with the chanting
of सामन् by those who had observed the
vows (साम्ना षडग्नयो यस्मिंश् चीयन्ते
संशितव्रतैः) 2. 12. 13; in this sacrifice
Susāman, the chief of the Dhanaṃjayas,
acted as the chanter of the सामन्स् 2. 30. 34
(धनंजयानां ऋषभः सुसामा सामगो
ऽभवत्।) Nī. on Bom. Ed. 2. 33. 34:
धनंजयानां धनंजयगोत्राणां म-
ध्ये श्रेष्ठः सुसामा नाम आङ्गिरसः);
in the sacrifice of Janaka the excellent Ukthya
sāman was sung 3. 134. 36; Bhīṣma told
Yudhiṣṭhira that in a sacrifice the सामन्-
singers praise employing the Rathantara
melody (रथन्तरे सामगाश् च स्तुवन्ति)
13. 143. 15; Ṛṣi Gṛtsamada told Yudhiṣṭhira
that once, when Indra's long sacrificial session
lasting for a thousand years was in progress,
Vasiṣṭha, the son of Manu Cākṣuṣa, found
fault the way Gṛtsamada was singing the
Rathantara chant; Vasiṣṭha asked Gṛtsamada
to set his jubilation aside and again think
over what he had done (रथन्तरं द्विज-
श्रेष्ठ न सम्यग् इति वर्तते।समीक्षस्व
पुनर् बुद्ध्या हर्षं त्यक्त्वा द्विजोत्तम);
(he charged Gṛtsamada that by his in-
correct singing he had committed a sin which
would not carry the sacrifice to the gods;
for this fault Gṛtsamada was cursed to be
a deer) 13. 18. 15-17; Vālmīki told Yudhi-
ṣṭhira that in a certain dispute regarding
सामन् (-chanting) the sages pronounced the
judgement that Vasiṣṭha had incurred the sin
of killing a Brāhmaṇa and he was instantly
seized by that sin (वीवादे साम्नि मुनिभिर्
ब्रह्मघ्नो वै भवान् इति।उक्तः क्षणेन
चाविष्टस् तेनाधर्मेण भारत) 13. 18. 7.
Trita, when he wanted to offer a sacrifice in
the well, thought of ऋच्स्, यजुसेस् and सामन्स्
for using them in the rites 9. 35. 33; in the
metaphorical sacrifice (संग्रामयज्ञ 12.
99. 12) performed by a warrior (i. e. in a
war) the words ‘cut, break’ uttered by the
fighters in a war serve the purpose of the
सामन्स् chanted by the सामन्- singers in the
abode of Yama (cf. the next section D)
(छिन्धि भिन्धीति यस्यैतच् छ्रूयते वाहिनी-
मुखे।सामानि सामगास् तस्य गायन्ति
यमसादने) 12. 99. 22; सामन्स् were sung
when formerly animals were bound for god
Nārāyaṇa—this is mentioned in the ऋच्स्
recited by those who know Nārāyaṇa and
these are cited as an instance (ऋचश् चाप्य्
अत्र शंसन्ति नारायणविदो जनाः नारा-
यनाय देवाय यद् अब्दह्नन् पशून् पुरा॥
तत्र सामानि गायन्ति तानि चाहुर् निदर्श-
नम्॥) 14. 25. 16-17 (see however Nī. cited
under ऋच् p. 175. 2 above).
D. Employ-
ment in funeral rites: When the Pāṇḍavas
set out for the forest Dhaumya, their Puro-
hita, accompanied them chanting on the way
the terrible सामन्स् addressed to Yama and
holding in his hand कुश grass directed to-
wards the Nairṛtya direction (धौम्यो
याम्यानि सामानि रौद्राणि च विशां पते।
गायन् गच्छति मार्गेषु कुशान् आदाय
पाणिना॥) 2. 71. 7 (Nī. on Bom. Ed. 2. 80.
7: याम्यानि यमदैवत्यानि); (कृत्वा तु
नैरृतान् दर्भान् धीरो धौम्यः पुरो-
हितः।सामानि गायन् याम्यानि पुरतो याति
भारत) 2. 71. 21 (Nī. on Bom. Ed. 2. 80.
22: नैरृतान् निरृतिकोणगान्); he thereby
wanted to indicate that when the Bhāratas will
be killed in the war the priests of the Kurus
will similarly chant the सामन्स् (addressed to
Yama) 2. 71. 22; at the cremation of Droṇa
the सामन्-singers sang three सामन्स् when
his body was placed on the funeral pyre
(द्रोणम् आधाय गायन्ति त्रीणि सामानि
सामगाः) 11. 23. 38; when the pyre was lit,
others followed them reciting the three सामन्स्
in subdued voices (see Cr. Ed. Vol. 12.
p. 119 note on 11. 23. 41) (सामभिस् त्रिभिर्
अन्तःस्थैर् अनुशंसन्ति चापरे।अग्नाव्
अग्निम् इवाधाय द्रोणं हुत्वा हुताशने)
11. 23. 41; सामन्स् were sung at the Pitṛ-
medha rites of some of those fallen in the war;
due to the sound of the सामन्स् and the ऋच्स्,
as also due to the lamentations of women, all
beings were stupefied during the night (पितृ-
मेधाश् च केषांचिद् अवर्तन्त महात्मनाम्।
सामभिश् चाप्य् अगायन्त … ॥ साम्नां ऋचां
च नादेन स्त्रीणां च रुदितस्वनैः।कश्म-
लं सर्वभूतानां निशायाम् समपद्यत)
11. 26. 39-40; at the Pitṛmedha rites of
Bhīṣma the सामन्-singers sang the chants
13. 154. 12; during the Pitṛmedha rites, at
the cremation of Vasudeva, when the funeral
pyre was lit there was a loud sound produced
by the सामन्-singers (सामगानां च
निर्घोषः) 16. 8. 23, 25-26.
E. Use in
the praise of deities: (1) Indra: Arjuna saw
Indra praised by excellent द्विजस् with praises
consisting of ऋच्स्, यजुसेस् and सामन्स् 3. 44.
18; when Arjuna and Indra sat on the same
throne, Gandharvas led by Tumburu, skilled
in songs and chants, sang गाथास् in very
agreeable melody (तत्र स्म गाथा गायन्ति
साम्ना परमवल्गुना।गन्धर्वास् तुम्बु-
रुश्रेष्ठाः कुशला गीतसामसु) 3. 44. 28;
(2) Kubera: On the Gandhamādana
mountain the sound of सामन्- singing by
Tumburu, who waits on Dhanada (Kubera)
was heard on the junctions of the four changes
of the moon (पर्वसधिषु) 3. 156. 28;
(3) Śiva: Upamanyu in his praise of Śiva
said that the god was sung with chants by the
सामन्-singers (सामभिर् यं च गायन्ति
सामगाः शुद्धबुद्धयः) 13. 16. 49;
Śatakratu (Indra) and Viṣṇu (who are the
two sons of Aditi), and god Brahman sing the
Rathantara melody near Bhava (Śiva) (शत-
क्रतुस् च भगवान् विष्णुश् चादितिनन्दनौ।
ब्रह्मा रथन्तरं साम ईरयन्ति भावा-
न्तिके) 13. 15. 16; (however, the Editor's note,
Cr. Ed. Vol. 17, p. 1061 on 13. 15. 16, says:
अदितिनन्दनौ = Mitra and Varuṇa ?) (4)
Deity not named: in the south, in the bowers
of Mandara mountain and in the houses of
the Viprarṣis, the Gandharvas sing enchanting
गाथास् sung in different melodies (गन्ध-
र्वा गान्ति गाथा वै चित्तबुद्धिहरा द्विज।
अत्र सामानि गाथाभिः श्रुत्वा गीतानि॥)
5. 107. 9-10.
F. Importance: While des-
cribing his विभूतिस्, Bhagavān told Arjuna
that he was the Bṛhatsāman chant among the
melodies (बृहत्साम् तथा साम्नाम्) 6. 32.
35; Bhīṣma praised Kṛṣṇa-Nārāyaṇa, who is
sung in सामन्स् that are true, as one whose
actions are true and who is truth (यं …
गृणन्ति सत्यकर्माणं सत्यं सत्येषु
सामसु) 12. 47. 16 (Nī. on Bom. Ed.
12. 47. 26: गृणन्ति ध्यायन्ति सत्यम् अबा-
धितं सत्येषु अबाधितार्थेषु सामसु
ज्येष्ठसामादिषु).
G. Personfication:
The Sāmans along with the Yajuses and the
Ṛgveda, in bodily form, attended the sacrifice
of Mahādeva (Śiva) who had assumed the
form of Varuṇa (मूर्तिमन्ति च सामानि
यजूंषि च सहस्रश्ः।ऋग्वेदश् चागमत्
तत्र) 13. 85. 4, (देवस्य महतस् तात
वारुणीं बिभ्रतस् तनुम्) 13. 85. 2, (आज-
ग्मुः … यज्ञं पशुपतेः प्रीता वरुणस्य
महात्मनः) 13. 85. 7-8.
H. Mystic
interpretation: The Yakṣa asked Yudhi-
ṣṭhira: “What is the one सामन् suited for
sacrifice ?” Yudhiṣṭhira replied: “Prāṇa is
the one सामन् suited for sacrifice” (किम्
एकम् यज्ञियं साम) 3. 297. 34, (प्राणो वै
यज्ञियं साम) 3. 297. 35; Bhīṣma declared
to Yudhiṣṭhira: There was but one सामन्
(एकं साम) 12. 60. 45 (Nī. on 12. 60
47: अकारो वै सर्वा वाक् सैषा स्पर्शोष्म-
भिर् व्यज्यमाना भवी नानारूपा भवतीति
श्रुतेर् एकं अकाररूपम् एव अक्षरं
यथा सामादिरूपं)
I. Relationship
with Yugas: According to Hanūmant there
were neither सामन्स्, यजुसेस् nor ऋच्स् in the
Kṛtayuga (नासन् कृतयुगे तात … न साम-
यजुऋग्वर्णाः) 3. 148. 12-13 (See Nīla-
kaṇṭha on this passage cited under Yajus
p. 207. 1; for such other information common
to ऋच्स् and यजुसेस् see Ṛc, especially 3. 27.
3; 5. 43. 1-3; 5. 44. 21; 6. 31. 17; 12. 52.
22; 12. 60. 42; 12. 194. 8; 12. 199. 16-
18; 12. 224. 63; 12. 227. 1; 12. 230. 8; 12.
243. 2; 12. 260. 26, 36; 12. 297. 15; 12.
322. 37). [See Sāmaveda]

सामवेद
Sāmaveda m.: Name of one of the
four Vedic Saṃhitās.
A. Relationship with Kṛṣṇa Nārāyaṇa:
Nārāyaṇa told the sage Mārkaṇḍeya that the
Sāmaveda, along with the other three Vedas,
arise from him and enter into him (मत्तः
प्रादुर्भवन्त्य् एते माम् एव प्रविशन्ति च)
3. 187. 14.
B. Importance: (1) In
the Vibhūtiyoga of the Gītā, Bhagavān told
Arjuna that he was the Sāmaveda of the
(four) Vedas (वेदानाम् सामवेदो ऽस्मि)
6. 32. 22; (2) Upamanyu, in his praise of
Śiva, described Śiva as the Sāmaveda of the
(four) Vedas (सामवेदश् च वेदानाम्)
13. 14. 159; (3) The धर्म of the एका-
न्तिन्स् (12. 336. 7, 57), expounded by Nārada
for the benefit of Yudhiṣṭhira, was equal to
the Sāmaveda and was preserved by god
Nārāyaṇa himself (गहनो ह्य् एष धर्मो
वै … संमितः सामवेदेन।धार्यते
स्वयम् ईशेन राजन् नारायणेन ह॥)
(12. 336. 9-10); this धर्म was learnt
and taught by Brahman to the Barhiṣad
sages from whom it went to a द्विज called
Jyeṣṭha who was versed in the Sāmaveda
(अऋहीतो ब्रह्मणा राजन् … अध्यापिताश् च
मुनयो नाम्ना बर्हिषदो नृप॥बर्हिष-
द्भ्यश् च संक्रान्तः सामवेदान्तगं
द्विजम्।ज्येष्ठं नाम्नाभिविख्यातम् … )
12. 336. 41-42.
C. Personified: (1)
Sāmaveda, along with the Ṛgveda and the
Purāṇas, moved in front of the chariot of
Śiva when he got ready to destroy the
Tripuras 8. 24. 80; (2) Sāmaveda, along
with the other three Vedas, visit the Sabhā
of Brahmadeva 2. 11. 23.
D. Limita-
tions: Dhṛtarāṣṭra asked Sanatsujāta
whether one who committed sin was absolved
of it if he studied the Sāmaveda (and the
ऋच्स् and यजुसेस्) 5. 43. 1 (the reply was in
the negative 5. 43. 2). [See Sāman]

सारस्वत
Sārasvata nt.: Name of the 77th
पर्वन् in the list of a hundred sub-पर्वन्स्
of the Bhārata supposed to have been made
by Vyāsa in the Parvasaṃgraha 1. 2. 60,
33, 70.
Described as detailing the merits of a
group of तीर्थस् (तीर्थवंशगुणान्वित) 1.
2. 60; referred to while listing the contents of
the Śalyaparvan as one in which was describ-
ed the holiness of river Sarasvatī and of the
तीर्थस् (सरस्वत्याश् च तीर्थानां पुण्यता
परिकीर्तिता) 1. 2. 175; related to the
अध्यायस् 9. 29-53 (called Tīrthayātrā-
parvan in the colophon; actually this पर्वन्
precedes the Gadāyuddhaparvan and does not
follow it as stated in 1. 2. 60 (गदायुद्धम्
अतः परम्।सारस्वतं ततः पर्व) and
in 1. 2. 175).

सावित्री
Sāvitrī1 f.: Name of a मन्त्र (ṚV,
3. 62. 10) so called because it is related to
god Savitṛ; also called Gāyatrī (3. 83. 27:
6. 5. 18-19) because the मन्त्र is composed
in the Gāyatrī metre.
A. Description: holy (पुण्या) 6. 5. 18;
best (उत्तमा) 13. 145. 27; having all quali-
ties (सर्वगुणान्विता) 6. 5. 18; enabling the
reciter to get over difficult situations (दुर्ग-
तरणी) 2. 11. 25; highly honoured in the
worlds (लोकसंमता) 6. 5. 18.
B. Im-
portance and significance: Sāvitrī was con-
sidered to be the beginning of all sciences
(आदिर् इष्यते।सावित्री सर्वविद्यानाम्) 14.
44. 4-5; the nineteen classes of beings (7
ग्राम्य पशुस्, 7 आरण्य पशुस्, 5 उद्-
भिज्जस्) and the five महाभूतस्, which
make a total of twenty-four are identi-
fied with (the twenty-four syllables of) the
Gāyatrī (एषां विंशतिर् एकोना महाभूतेषु
पञ्चसु।चतुर्विंशतिर् उद्दिष्टा गायत्री
लोकसंमता॥) 6. 5. 15-18.
C. Its
close association with the Vedas used for
a simile: As the Sāvitrī मन्त्र does not
forsake the Vedas, so did Yājñasenī (Drau-
padī) not forsake the Pāṇḍavas 3. 80. 4.
D. Relationship with deities: (1) Savitṛ:
Sāvitrī was (first) pronounced in the east by
god Savitṛ to the ब्रह्मवादिन्स् 5. 106. 10;
3. 110. 5 (? सावित्रीं सविता यथा (ददौ));
(2) Nārāyaṇa: On the Śveta Dvīpa, Nārada
saw ॐकार, followed by Sāvitrī, coming out
of the mouth of Nārāyaṇa 12. 326. 7; (3)
Śiva: when Rudra got ready to destroy the
Tripuras he made the Vedas his bow and the
Sāvitrī मन्त्र his bow-string 13 145. 27;
E. Personification: (1) Sāvitrī, in bodily
form, present in the Sabhā of Brahmadeva 2.
11. 25; Sāvitrī, along with the Vedas and the
Upaniṣads attended the sacrifice of Śiva when
he had assumed the form of Varuṇa 13. 85. 6.
F. Uses: (1) In श्राद्ध: One should atten-
tively recite the Sāvitrī prayer at each oblation
given to the manes at the श्राद्ध (ब्रूयाच्
छ्राद्धे च सावित्रीं पिण्डे पिण्डे समा-
हितः) 13. 92. 14; (cf. Śāṅkh Gṛ. Sū. 4. 1. 8
for a slightly different use: भुञ्जानेषु
महाव्याहृतीः सावित्रीम् मधुवातीयाः पितृ-
देवत्याः पावमानीश् च जपेत्); (2) for use
as a test (?): If a person born of a mixture of
castes recites Gāyatrī at the renowned तीर्थ
called Gāyatryāḥ sthānam it sounds like a
गाथा (a non-Vedic stanza) or an ordinary
song. This was a direct proof available for a
Brāhmaṇa to prove that he was not of mixed
origin (निदर्शनं च प्रत्यक्षं ब्राह्-
मणानां नराधिप।गायत्रीं पठते यस्
तु योनिसंकरजस् तथा।गाथा वा गीतिका
वापि तस्य संपद्यते नृप॥ Nī., however,
on Bom. Ed. 3. 85. 29: निदर्शानम् उदा-
हरणम्); (3) As a benediction: Jāmbavatī
invoked Sāvitrī mantra for the protection
of Kṛṣṇa when he set out for the Himavant
to meet Śiva (सावित्री ब्रह्मविद्या च ऋतवो
वत्सराः क्षपाः। … रक्षन्तु सर्वत्र गतं
त्वाम् यादव सुखावहम्॥ 13. 14. 22-23).
G. Qualifications and rewards obtained by
its knowledge and recitation: Brāhmaṇas who
know Sāvitrī, so also the one who recites
Sāvitrī three times a day, are worthy of being
invited for a श्राद्ध (सावित्रीज्ञाः क्रिया-
वन्तस् ते राजन् केतनक्षमाः) 13. 24. 25,
(सावित्रीं जपते यस् तु त्रिकालम् … स राजन्
केतनक्षमः) 13. 24. 28; one who recites
Sāvitrī on a sacred spot, eating limited food,
not injuring others, alert (? अमन्दकः), not
talking to any one is freed of all sins 12. 36.
33 (Nī., however, on Bom. Ed. 12. 35. 37:
मन्द इव मन्दकः रागद्वेषमानाप-
मानशून्यः); one who knows the real nature
of Gāyatrī (i. e. the identification of its 24
syllables with 19 kinds of beings and 5
महाभूतस्) is never deprived of the world
due to him (य एतां वेद गायत्रीं …
तत्त्वेन भरतश्रेष्ठ स लोकान् न प्रण-
श्यति) 6. 5. 19. [See Sāvitrī2, Bhārata-
sāvitrī]

सावित्री
Sāvitrī2 f.: Name of a मन्त्र related
to god Savitṛ.
The मन्त्र is recited in the ceremony to
be performed after the birth of a child and
before cutting the navel string; at that time
the Sāvitrī mantra is the child's mother and
the teacher is its father (प्राङ्नाभिवर्ध-
नात् पुंसो जातकर्म विधीयते।तत्रास्य
माता सावित्री पिता त्व् आचार्य उच्यते) 3. 177. 29
(cf. Āśva. Gṛ. Sū. 1. 15. 1: प्र ते ददामि
मधुनो घृतस्य वेदं सवित्रा प्रसूतं
मघोनाम्।आयुष्मान् गुप्तो देवताभिह्
शतं जीव शरदो लोके अस्मिन्; Śāṅkh. Gṛ.
Sū. 1. 24. 4: प्र ते यच्छामि मधु-
मन् मखाय वेदं प्रसूतं सवित्रा
मघोना। … ). [See Sāvitrī1]

सावित्री
Sāvitrī°3: Name of an Upākhyāna.
Mentioned in the contents of the
Āraṇyakaparvan (सावित्र्यौद्दालकीयं च)
1. 2. 126; related to the अध्यायस् 3. 277-283
(occurs as a section of the Draupadīharaṇa-
parvan).

सुनीथ
Sunītha m.: Name of a मन्त्र (? or
of a sage ?) 1. 53. 23.
One who brings to mind the Sunītha
मन्त्र along with Asita and Ārtimant need
have no fear from serpents either by day or at
night 1. 53. 23 (असितं चार्तिमन्तं च
सुनीथम् चापि यः स्मरेत्।दिवा वा यदि
वा रात्रौ नास्य सर्पभयं भवेत्);
cf. Nī. on Bom. Ed. 1. 58. 23 cited under
Asita on p. 169 above. [See Asita,
Ārtimant]

सुन्दोपसुन्दयोर्
Sundopasundayor upākhyānam nt.:
Designation of an उपाख्यान।
Mentioned in the list of the contents of
the Ādiparvan (सुन्दोपसुन्दयोस् तत्र उपा-
ख्यानं प्रकीर्तितम्) 1. 2. 90; related to
the अध्यायस् 1. 201-204.

सुभद्राहरण
Subhadrāharaṇa nt.: Name of the 17th
पर्वन् in the list of a hundred sub-पर्वन्स्
of the Bhārata supposed to have been made by
Vyāsa in the Parvasaṃgraha 1. 2. 38, 33, 70.
Referred to in the list of the contents of
the Ādiparvan as ‘where at Dvārakā the
loving Subhadrā was obtained by Kirīṭin
(Arjuna), who longed for her, with the
consent of Vāsudeva’ 1. 2. 92; the incident
is mentioned by Dhṛtarāṣṭra in his summary
of the events made for Saṃjaya 1. 1. 103
and by Vaiśaṃpāyana in his summary made
for Janamejaya 1. 55. 32-34.

सौकन्य
Saukanya nt.: Name of an आख्यान।
Mentioned while listing the contents of
the Āraṇyakaparvan; in this Ākhyāna we
are told that the sage Cyavana of the Bhṛgu
family enabled the Nāsatyā (the Aśvinā) to
have a share in Soma in the sacrifice of
Śaryāti and in return the deities conferred
youth on the sage. 1. 2. 117-118; related
to the अध्यायस् 3. 122-125.

सौप्तिक
Sauptika1 nt.: Name of the 78th
पर्वन् in the list of a hundred sub-पर्वन्स्
of the Bhārata supposed to have been made
by Vyāsa in the Parvasaṃgraha 1. 2. 60,
33, 70.
Described as disgusting (बीभत्स) 1.
2. 60; referred to in the summary of the
events made by Dhṛtarāṣṭra for Saṃjaya 1.
1. 153; related to the अध्यायस् 10. 1-9.

सौप्तिक
Sauptika2 nt.: Name of the tenth
पर्वन् among the eighteen major पर्वन्स्
of the Bhārata 1. 2. 178, 188.
Described as dreadful (दारुण) 1. 2.
178; its contents are summarized as follows:
where Duryodhana, whose thighs were
broken, was approached after the Pāṇḍavas
had left, by Kṛtavarman, Kṛpa and Drauṇi
(Aśvatthāman); where the enraged Drauṇi
vowed that he would not take off his armour
unless he had killed all the Pāñcālas led by
Dhṛṣtadyumna and the Pāṇḍavas with their
house attendants (अहत्वा सर्वपाञ्चालान्
धृष्टद्युम्नपुरोगमान्।पाण्डवांश् च
सहामात्यान् न विमोक्ष्यामि दंशनम्) 1.
2. 180; where the trio, led by Drauṇi, killed
the Pāñcālas and their attendants while they
were confidently asleep at night; where the
five Pāṇḍavas and Sātyaki were saved as
they were protected by the might of Kṛṣṇa
(कृष्णबलाश्रयात् 1. 2. 182) and all the
rest perished; where Draupadī, grieved by
the death of her sons, and pained at the
killing of her father and brothers, resolved
to fast unto death; where, at the instance
of Draupadī, Bhīma pursued Aśvatthāman;
where Aśvatthāman, afraid of Bhīmasena,
released the missile (Brahmaśiras) against
him saying it was for the destruction of the
Pāṇḍava’ (अपाण्डवायेति रुषा द्रौणिर्
अस्त्रम् अवासृजत् 1. 2. 185); but Kṛṣṇa,
wanting to neutralize (the effect of) those
words said ‘let that not happen’ (मैवम्
इत्य् अब्रवीत् कृष्णः शमयंस् तस्य तद्
वचः 1. 2. 186); whereupon Phālguna
(Arjuna) neutralized Aśvatthāman's missile
by his missile (Brahmaśiras) (यत्रास्त्रम्
अस्त्रेण च तच् छमयाम् आस फाल्गुनः
1. 2. 186); Aśvatthāman, (Kṛṣṇa) Dvai-
pāyana and others uttered curses provoked
by one another (द्रौणिद्वैपायनादीनां
शापाश् चान्योन्यकारिताः) 1. 2. 187); where
the oblations of water to all kings (killed in
the war) were offered (तोयकर्माणि सर्वेषां
राज्ञाम् उदकदानिके 1. 2. 187); where Pṛthā
(Kuntī) narrated the birth of her son who
was secretly born 1. 2. 188; the high-souled
sage of infinite intelligence (Vyāsa) has
declared that the Sauptika and the Aiṣilka
parvans together (सौप्तिकैषीकसंबन्धे)
have eighteen अध्यायस् and he has counted
the श्लोकस् to be eight hundred and seventy
1. 2. 189-190; the पर्वन् (? or the incident
described in it ?) is referred to by Sātyaki
while blaming Kṛtavarman who, in association
with the son of Droṇa (Aśvatthāman), killed
those who were asleep (सौप्तिके ये च निहताः
सुप्तानेन दुरात्मना॥द्रोणपुत्रसहायेन
पापेन कृतवर्मणा) 16. 4. 25-26.

सौभवधाख्यान
Saubhavadhākhyāna nt.: Name of an
आख्यान।
Mentioned while listing the contents of
the Āraṇyakaparvan 1. 2. 106; related to
the अध्यायस् 3. 15-23.

स्तवराज
Stavarāja m.: Name (?) of a collect-
ion of names (नामसंहारम् 13. 17. 1;
नामसमुद्देशम् 13. 17. 12, 11) of Śiva
13. 17. 21; these are one thousand and
eight names of Śarva 13. 17. 29; the names
are listed in 13. 17. 30-150.
A. Original composer and transmission:
Originally Brahmā sang the Stava (यत्
पुरा लोककृज् जगौ) 13. 16. 66; यद् उक्तं
पद्मयोनिना 13. 17. 12) and himself
preserved the Stava of Bhagavān (Śiva)
(स्तवम् एतं भगवतो ब्रह्मा स्वयम्
अधारयत्) 13. 17. 164; 13. 17. 154; 13.
17. 5; 13. 16. 66; from him it went
successively to Śakra (Indra) and others 13.
17. 164-168; one of the receivers in this
line was Taṇḍi who obtained it in the abode
of Brahman after he had performed severe
austerities 13. 17. 165; he handed it over to
Śukra Bhārgava 13. 16. 66; 13. 16. 75 (?);
at the end of the line of transmission stood
Mārkaṇḍeya who taught it to Upamanyu
when the latter had observed certain rules
(मार्कण्डेयान् मया प्राप्तं नियमेन
जनार्दन 13. 17. 169) and Upamanyu
gave it to Janārdana (Kṛṣṇa) 13. 17. 168-
169; 13. 17. 1, 5-6; since, in bygone days,
it was once taught by Taṇḍi it also came
to be looked upon as composed by Taṇḍi;
moreover Taṇḍi had brought it down from
heaven to this world (यस्मात् तण्डिः पुरा
प्राह तेन तण्डिकृतो ऽभवत्।स्वर्गाच्
चैवात्र भूलोकं तण्डिना ह्य् अवतारि-
तः॥) 13. 17. 22; 13. 16. 66. 75; 13. 17.
3; the Stavarāja was brought down (to
this world) from the Brahmaloka 13. 17.
21, 4; Upamanyu is also said to have
received it directly from Taṇḍi (तण्डिर्
आख्यातवान् मम।नामानि) 13. 16. 73,
72.
B. Activity of Upamanyu: Pitāmaha
(Brahmadeva) had mentioned ten thousand
names of Sarva (Śiva) in the Vedas and
one thousand names of Śarva (Śiva) in the
Śāstras (दश नामसहस्राणि वेदेष्व् आह
पितामहः।शर्वस्य शास्त्रेषु तथा दश
नामशतानि वै॥) 13. 16. 74; 13. 17. 13;
Upamanyu made an abridgement (in the
form of Stavarāja) out of the ten thousand
names as one churns घृत from curds
(नाम्नां कंचित् समुद्देशं वक्ष्ये ह्य्
अव्यक्तयोनिनः … दश नामसकस्राणि यान्य्
आह प्रपितामहः।तानि निर्मथ्य मनसा
दध्नो घृतम् इवोद्धृतम्) 13. 17. 11, 13.
(for other similes cf. 13. 17. 14); Upa-
manyu gave to Kṛṣṇa this form of the
स्तव, which constituted Mahādeva's (Śiva's)
चरित, having fewer words (and syllables)
and being concise in meaning (किं तु दे-
वस्य महतः संक्षिप्तार्थपदाक्षरम्।
शक्तितश् चरितं वक्ष्ये) 13. 17. 9; this
abridged form looked upon as the essence of
the original (तथैतत् सारम् उद्धृतम्)
13. 17. 14.
C. Its name: After its
composition Brahmā destined it to be the
king of all the divine स्तवस्; since then
it came to be known as Stavarāja of
Īśvara (सर्वस्तवानां दिव्यानां राजत्वे
समकल्पयत्॥तदाप्रभृति चैवायम् ईश्व-
रस्य महात्मनः।स्तवराजेति वीख्यातः)
13. 17. 20-21.
D. Description: The
best of all स्तवस् (स्तवानाम् उत्तमं
स्तवम्) 13. 17. 19, 23; famous (विश्रुत)
13. 17. 169; excellent (प्रवर) 13. 17. 4;
of the first rank (प्रथम) 13. 17. 4;
associated with the four vedas (चतुर्वेद-
समन्वित) 13. 17. 15; means of purifying
(पावन) 13. 17. 15; (पवित्र) 13. 17. 19;
destroyer of all sins (सर्वपापामापह) 13.
17. 15; (सर्वपापप्रणाशन) 13. 17. 23;
killer of demons (रक्षोघ्न) 13. 17. 15;
auspicious (मङ्गल) 13. 17. 19; holy
(शुभ) 13. 17. 4; the best among auspicious
(सर्वमङ्गलमङ्गल्य) 13. 17. 23; holy
(पुण्य) 13. 17. 19; most beneficial
(कल्याणम् उत्तमम्) 13. 17. 19; leading
to heaven (स्वर्ग्य) 13. 17. 4, 169; giving
calmness of mind (शान्तिद) 13. 17. 15; con-
ferring health (आरोग्य), long life (आयुष्य),
wealth (धन्य) and strength (बल्य) 13.
17. 169; conferring welfare (पौष्टिक) 13.
17. 15; beneficial to all beings (सर्वभूत-
हित) 13. 17. 4; looked upon as the highest
ब्रह्मन् (परमं ब्रह्म) 13. 17. 154;
13. 16. 66, as eternal ब्रह्मन् (ब्रह्म सना-
तनम्) 13. 17. 6.
E. Importance: This
Stavarāja is equal to meditation, practice of
Yoga, the best thing to meditate on; it
deserves to be recited; it is itself knowledge
and the highest secret; if one knows it even
at the end of one's life one can attain the
highest state after life (इदं ध्यानम्
इदं योगम् इदं ध्येयम् अनुत्तमम्।
इदं जप्यम् इदं ज्ञानं रहस्यम् इदम्
उत्तमम्।इदं ज्ञात्वान्तकाते ऽपि गच्छेद्
धि परमां गतिम्॥) 13. 17. 18; this
great, eternal secret was proclaimed by
Brahman himself (यत् तद् रहस्यं पर-
मं ब्रब्मप्रोक्तं सनातनम्) 13. 17. 5.
F. Who may receive the Stavarāja: It may
be taught to one who is devoted (to god), to
one who has faith, and one who believes in
god; but it should not be taught to a non-
believer who is lack of faith in the bodily
form and who has not controlled his self
(इदं भक्ताय दातव्यं श्रद्दधानास्ति-
काय च।नाश्रद्दधानरूपाय नास्तिकाया-
जितामने) 13. 17. 16 (Unknown commenta-
tor: वेदबोधितफलावश्यंभावनिश्चयः
श्रद्धा।वेदाः प्रमाणम् इति ज्ञानवान्
आस्तिकः।उक्तविपरीतो नास्तिकः Cr. Ed. 17(2).
1062. on 13. 17. 6); it should not be taught
to one who scorns god Pinākin (Śiva); such
a person goes to hell with his ancestors and
descendants 13. 17. 17; it should be learnt
with due effort and then be preserved by one
who has controlled his mind (प्रयत्नेनाध्-
इगन्तव्यं धार्यं च प्रयतात्मना) 13.
17. 15.
G. Rewards obtained: By listen-
ing to the name of Śarva listed in the Stava-
rāja one obtains all desires 13. 17. 29; by
reciting this Stava the sage Kṛṣṇadvaipāyana
obtained all his desires while he was practis-
ing austerities on mount Meru for a son; he
therefore advised Yudhiṣṭhira to recite the
स्तव so that he would also obtain all his
desires by the grace of Maheśvara 13. 18. 1-3;
by praising Śiva with the names in this स्तव
one obtains one's Self (प्राप्नोत्य् आत्मानम्
आत्मना) 13. 17. 153; god Mahādeva is
pleased by the recitation of his names and he
establishes his devotees in himself (भक्ता-
नुकम्पी भगवान् आत्मसंस्थान् करोति
तान्) 13. 17. 155; by its recitation a person
who is cleansed of his sins becomes devoted
to Bhava (Śiva) which (devotion) leads
him to attain the highest perfection (जन्तोर्
विशुद्धपापस्य भवे भक्तिः प्रजायते। …
तस्यैव च प्रसादेन भक्तिर् उत्पद्यते
नृणाम्।यया याति परां सिद्धिम्) 13. 17.
158, 160; the demons, the Yakṣas, the
Rākṣasas, the Piśācas, the Yātudhānas, the
Guhyakas and the snakes do not put
obstacle in the way (of one who recites this
स्तव) 13. 17. 170; he who observing rules
of purity and celibacy, with controlled sense-
organs, recites this स्तव for one year with-
out a break in application obtains the fruit
of performing an Aśvamedha sacrifice (यः
पठेत शुचिर् भूत्वा ब्रह्मचारी जितेन्द्रि-
यः।अभग्नयोगो वर्षं तु सोऽ श्वमेध-
फलं लभेत्॥) 13. 17. 171; by praising
god Mahādeva with the names (in this
Stava) Jāmadagnya, who was afflicted by
the sin of killing his father and the
Brāhmaṇas (? पितृविप्रवधेनाहम् आर्तः;)
13. 18. 10 (Nī. on Bom. Ed. 13. 18. 12: पितृ-
तुल्या विप्राः ‘ज्येष्ठो भ्राता पितुः समः’
इति स्मृतेर् ज्येष्ठा भ्रातरस् तेषां वधेन),
was freed of the sin; in addition the god
gave him an axe and divine missiles and made
him invincible; god of death would not over-
power Jāmadagnya and he would be famous
13. 18. 9-12 (पापं न भविता ते ऽद्य
अजेयश् च भविष्यसि।न ते प्रभविता
मृत्युर् यशस्वी च भविष्यसि॥ 12).

स्त्रीपर्वन्
Strīparvan1 nt.: Name of the 81st
पर्वन् in the list of a hundred sub-पर्वन्स्
of the Bhārata supposed to have been made
by Vyāsa in the Parvasaṃgraha 1. 2. 61,
33, 70.
Referred to among the contents of the
major Strīparvan 1. 2. 191-192; related to
the अध्यायस् 11. 9-25 (or 1-25 if one includes
the Viśokaparvan mentioned in the colophon
at the end of the eighth अध्याय 11. 1-8).
[See Strīparvan2]

स्त्रीपर्वन्
Strīparvan2 nt.: Name of the eleventh
पर्वन् among the eighteen major पर्वन्स्
of the Bhārata 1. 2. 191, 194.
Described as one in which one finds the
rise of compassion (करुणोदय) 1. 2. 191
and one which is very pitiful (अतिकरुणम्
महत्) 1. 2. 194; the author of Bhāratākh-
yāna has so composed it as to cause distress to
the hearts of good people and make them shed
tears (सज्जनमनोवैक्लव्याश्रुप्रवर्तक)
1. 2. 195; the contents of the पर्वन् are
summarized as follows: where one finds the
highly pitiful lamentation of the wives of
the (fallen) heroes and the upsurge of anger
and the tranquility of mind of Dhṛtarāṣṭra
and Gāndhārī respy. (क्रोधावेशः प्रसादश्
च गान्धारीधृतराष्ट्रयोः 1. 2. 191); where
one saw those brave Kṣatriyas who would
not turn back and who were destined to die,
sons, brothers, fathers-killed in battle
(यत्र तान् क्षत्रियाञ् शूरान् दिष्टान्तान्
अनिवर्तिनः।पुत्रान् भ्रातॄन् पितॄंश् चैव
ददृशुर् निहतान् रणे 1. 2. 192); where the
king, excellent among all those who upheld
the law (viz. Yudhiṣṭhira 11. 26. 24-26),
ordered cremation of kings to be done in
accordance with the prescribed rites
(शास्त्रतः) 1. 2. 191-193; the number of
the अध्यायस् in this पर्वन् is said to be
twentyseven, and the number of श्लोकस्
seven hundred and seventy five 1. 2. 194-
195. [See Strīparvan1]

स्वयंवर
Svayaṃvara See पाञ्चाल्याः स्वयं-
वरम्।

स्वर्गपर्वन्
Svargaparvan nt.: Name of the
eighteenth पर्वन् among the eighteen major
पर्वन्स् of the Bhārata 1. 2. 232-233 (अश्ता-
दशैवम् एतानि पर्वाण्य् उक्तान्य् अशेषतः).
Described as heavenly (दिव्य) and super-
human (अमानुष) 1. 2. 232; its अध्यायस्
are counted to be five and श्लोकस् two hundred
1. 2. 232. [See Svargārohaṇika with which
this is identical]

स्वर्गारोहणिक
Svargārohaṇika nt.: Name of the 98th
पर्वन् in the list of a hundred sub-पर्वन्स्
of the Bhārata supposed to have been made
by Vyāsa for the Parvasaṃgraha 1. 2. 68
[See Svargaparvan with which this is
identical]

हंसकाकीय
Haṃsakākīya nt.: Name of an
आख्यान 1. 2. 170.
Listed in the contents of the Karṇaparvan
where it occurs as a part of the harsh
dialogue which took place between Karṇa
and Śalya when they started out for war;
the dialogue was full of abuse (प्रयाणे
परुषश् चात्र संवादः कर्णशल्ययोः।
हंसकाकीयम् आख्यानम् अत्रैवाक्षे-
पसंहितम्) 1. 2. 170; related to the
अध्याय 8. 28.

हयशिरस्
Hayaśiras nt.: Name of an आख्यान
(forming part of the Nārāyaṇīya) 12. 335.
72; it occurs in stanzas 12. 335. 3-70.
A. Description: Described as a Purāṇa
equal in importance to the Veda (पुराणं
वेदसंमितम्) 12. 335. 7; (पुराणम्
वेदसंमितम्) 12. 335. 72; (पौराणम्
एतद् आख्यातम् रूपं वरदम् ऐश्वरम्
12. 335. 69).
B. Narration: It was
originally narrated by Vyāsa to king
Yudhiṣṭhira (12. 335. 7), at the latter's
request (12. 335. 8-9), and next by Vaiśaṃ-
pāyana to Janamejaya 12. 335. 6-7, 72.
C. Contents: The आख्यान narrates how
Hari-Nārāyaṇa (12. 335. 21, 23, 33, 53, 62-
63, 67-69), also called Madhusūdana (12.
335. 64), Viśveśa (12. 335. 49), Īśāna (12.
335. 28), Bhagavant Puruṣa (12. 335. 43,
56), Puruṣottama 10. 335. 62, 65, Puruṣa
(12. 335. 56), Śveta Puruṣa (12. 335. 60),
and Prabhu 12. 335. 44, 49, 56 (आदिकरं
प्रभुम्), assumed the form of a horse's
head (हयशिरस्) to retrieve the Vedas which
were forcibly taken away by the demons
Madhu and Kaiṭabha from Brahman 12. 335.
21-69.
D. फलश्रुति: The studies
of a Brāhmaṇa who listens or commits to
memory this आख्यान are never lost to him
12. 335. 70 (यो ह्य् एतद् ब्राह्मणो नित्यं
शृणुयाद् धारयेत वा।न तस्याध्ययनं
नाशम् उपगच्छेत् कदाचन॥).

हरणहारिक
Haraṇahārika nt.: Name of the 18th
पर्वन् in the list of a hundred sub-पर्वन्स्
of the Bhārata supposed to have been made
by Vyāsa in the Parvasaṃgraha 1. 2. 38,
33, 70.
The title is explained by Nīla. on Bom.
Ed. 1. 2. 46. as: हरणं दायः पारिबर्हम्
इति यावत्।तस्य हारिका समानयनम्;
it occurs after the Subhadrāharaṇaparvan
1. 2. 38; referred to while listing the
contents of the Ādiparvan as “where
Kṛṣṇa brought with him nuptial gifts (for
the Pāṇḍavas)” (हरणं गृह्य सं-
प्राप्ते कृष्णे देवकिनन्दने) 1. 2. 93;
related to the अध्याय 1. 213. (Nī. on
Bom. Ed. 1. 2. 126 cites the following
stanza: मानघ्नस्यापि जामातुर् मानं
संवर्धयेद् बुधः।स्वसुर् हर्त्रे
ऽर्जुनायापि ददुर् वित्तानि वृष्णयः॥)

हरिगीता
Harigītā f. (pl.): Name of the tract (?)
12. 336. 49.
The धर्म to be practised by the
Vratins was once told, with all the injun-
ctions to be observed (?), by Vaiśaṃpāyana
to Janamejaya in the Harigītās (व्रतिनां
चापि यो धर्मः स ते पूर्वं नृपोत्तम।
कथितो हरिगीतासु समासविधिकल्पितः)
12. 336. 49; this dharma, together with its
secrets and complete collection, was obtained
by Nārada from Nārāyaṇa himself (नारदेन
तु संप्राप्तः सरहस्यः ससंग्रहः।
एष धर्मो जगन्नाथात् साक्षान् नारायणान्
नृप) 12. 336. 50.

हरिवंश
Harivaṃśa m.: Name of the 99th
पर्वन् in the list of a hundred sub-पर्वन्स्
of the Bhārata supposed to have been made
by Vyāsa in the Parvasaṃgraha 1. 2. 69,
33, 70.
Also called पुराण 1. 2. 69; it is
known as an appendix (खिलसंज्ञित) 1.
2. 69, and hence is counted among the
खिलस् (खिलेषु … प्रकीर्तितम्) which are
mentioned at the end of the eighteen major
पर्वन्स् of the Bhārata 1. 2. 233.

हैडिम्ब
Haiḍimba nt.: Name of the 9th पर्वन्
in the list of a hundred sub-पर्वन्स् of the
Bhārata supposed to have been made by
Vyāsa in the Parvasaṃgraha 1. 2. 35, 33, 70.
The contents of the पर्वन् are alluded
to as: here are narrated the meeting of the
Pāṇḍavas with Hiḍimbā in the forest and
the birth of Ghaṭotkaca 1. 2. 84; the
incident is referred to in Vaiśaṃpāyana's
summary of the events made for Janamejaya
(where angered Bhīma killed Hiḍimba in the
terrifying forest) 1. 55. 19; the पर्वन् is
related to the अध्यायस् 1. 139-142 (the birth
of Ghaṭotkaca is actually narrated in the first
अध्याय of the next sub-पर्वन् entitled
Bakavadhaparvan 1. 143. 27-34).

ह्रदप्रवेशन
Hradapraveśana nt.: Name of the 75th
पर्वन् in the list of a hundred sub-पर्वन्स्
of the Bhārata supposed to have been made
by Vyāsa in the Parvasaṃgraha 1. 2. 59,
33, 70.
The incidents of this sub-पर्वन्स् are
referred to in Dhṛtāṣṭra's summary of the
events made for Saṃjaya 1. 1. 149-150
(Saubala (Śakuni), the cause of the game
of dice which led to disharmony, was killed
by Sahadeva; then the tired Duryodhana,
who had lost his chariot, went to a pond
and having blocked its water rested there);
the पर्वन् is related to the अध्यायस्
9. 17-28.

अकालकौमुदी
Akālakaumudī f.: See Kaumudī.

अङ्गारक
Aṅgāraka m.: Name of the planet
Mars; also called Bhauma (13. 151. 12),
Lohitāṅga (6. 3. 17; 7. 141. 12).
Described as great (महाग्रह) 6. 3.
13; having the lustre of fire (पावकप्रभ)
6. 3. 17; having bright rays (दीप्तरश्मि)
7. 141. 12; Nārada saw Aṅgāraka, along
with other Grahas, in the Sabhā of Brahma-
deva 2. 11. 20; listed (Bhauma) with other
Grahas in the Daivataṃśa 13. 151. 12;
by bathing in Mahāgaṅgā at the conjunction
of Mars with the Kṛttikās (कृत्तिकाङ्गारके)
and by fasting for a fortnight one is purified
and obtains heaven 13. 26. 20; Aṅgāraka
figures in similes and bad omens: 1. Similes:
Droṇa's entry in the arena in the company of
Aśvatthāman compared with the appearance
of the Moon and Mars in the sky without
clouds 1. 124. 18; Bāhlīka and Dhṛṣṭaketu,
the king of the Cedis, fought each other
as would Aṅgāraka and Budha 6. 43. 38;
Drupada and Jayadratha fought each other
as would Śukra and Aṅgāraka 6. 43.
54; Arjuna killed many Saṃśaptakas by
adopting repeatedly oblique movements like
Aṅgāraka (वक्रानुवक्रगमनाद् अङ्गारक
इव ग्रहः) 8. 14. 1; Alambusa, in his duel
with Ghaṭotkaca, fell down on the ground
as would Aṅgāraka by chance (यदृच्छया
निपतितम् अलम्बुसम् (7. 84. 26), भूमाव्
अङ्गारकं यथा) 7. 84. 27; Bhūri, a
Kaurava, when struck by the शक्ति of
Sātyaki fell down on the ground from his
chariot as would Mars, by chance, from the
sky (लोहिताङ्ग इवाकाशाद् दीप्तरश्मिर् यद्-
ऋच्छया) 7. 141. 12. 2. Omens: Vyāsa
told Dhṛtarāṣṭra that Aṇgāraka making re-
trograde (वक्र) movement in the con-
stellation Maghā indicated fierce destruction
of the two armies (सेनयोर् अशिवं घोरं
करिष्यति महाग्रहः।मघास्व् अङ्गारको
वक्रः) 6. 3. 13; another bad omen pointed
out by Vyāsa to Dhṛtarāṣṭra before the war
was that Mars, the red-bodied one (लोहि-
ताङ्ग), after making repeated retrograde
movements and returning to the Brahmarāśi
was established in the Śravaṇa नक्षत्र
(वक्रानुवक्रं कृत्वा च श्रवणे पावक-
प्रभः।ब्रह्मराशिं समावृत्य लोहिताङ्गो
व्यवस्थितः।) 6. 3. 17 (Nī. on Bom. Ed. 6.
3. 18: तत्रैव सर्वतोभद्रचक्रे मघा-
स्थो लोहिताङ्गो ऽङ्गारको वक्रानुवक्रं
पुनःपुनर् वक्रीभूय ब्रह्मणा बृहस्-
पतिनाक्रान्तम् राशिं नक्षत्रं श्रवणं
समावृत्य सम्यक् पूर्णदृष्ट्या विद्ध्वा
तिष्ठति); among the bad omens noticed by
Karṇa and pointed out to Kṛṣṇa one referred to
the retrograde motion of Mars in Jyeṣṭhā and
his wooing Anurādhā thereby as though tran-
quilizing the Maitra Nakṣatrayoga (कृत्वा
चाङ्गारको वक्रं ज्येष्ठायां मधु-
सूदन।अनुराधां प्रार्थयते मैत्रं
संशमयन्न् इव॥) 5. 141. 8 (Nī., however,
on Bom. Ed. 5. 143. 9: ज्येष्ठाम् अप्राप्य
यदि भौमो वक्रीभवेत् तर्हि ज्येष्ठस्य
राज्ञः ये ऽमित्रभूतास् ते सर्वे नश्येयुर्
इति भावः।मैत्रं [मित्रसमूहं सं-
गमयन् नाशयन्।“वैवस्वतं सं-
गमनं जनानाम्” (RV. 10. 14. 1) इत्य्
आदौ संपूर्वस्य गमेर् मारणार्थत्व-
दर्शनात्).

अनुमति
Anumati f.: Name of the first Paurṇa-
māsī day (when the Paurṇamāsī extends to
two days; see Ait. Br. 32. 9 and Nirukta
11. 29).
She, personified, arrived at the river
Sarasvatī to be present at the investiture of
Kumāra as the general of the gods 9. 44. 12,
16; she served as one of the reins (योक्त्राणि)
of the horses of Śiva's chariot when it was
made ready for his fight with the Tripuras 8.
24. 74.

अनुराधा
Anurādhā f.: Name of the seventeenth
Nakṣatra.
A. Religious rites: If one gives under
the Nakṣatra Anurādhā, after observing fast,
a gift of a covering (प्रावार) and another
cloth (वस्त्रान्तर), he is glorified in the
heaven for a hundred Yugas 13. 63. 22; if
one offers a श्राद्ध under Anurādhā he
establishes a line of kings (?राजचक्रम्
प्रवर्तयेत्) 13. 89. 8.
B. Bad omens:
Among the bad omens reported by Karṇa to
Kṛṣṇa there was one which referred to the
retrograde motion of Mars (Aṅgāraka) in
Jyeṣṭhā and his wooing Anurādhā thereby as
though tranquilizing the Maitra Nakṣatra-
yoga (कृत्वा चाङ्गारको वक्रं ज्येष्ठायां
मधुसूदन।अनुराधां प्रार्थयते
मैत्रं संशमयन्न् इव) 5. 141. 8 (For
Nī. comm. see Aṅgāraka).

अभिजित्
Abhijit f.: Name of the twentieth
Nakṣatra.
Described as heavenly (देवी) 3. 219.
8; Indra reported to Skanda that Abhijit,
the younger sister vying with Rohiṇī as she
desired higher rank, went to the forest to
practise austerities; Indra was, therefore, con-
fused (in reckoning time) due to the dropping
down of one Nakṣatra from the sky (अभिजित्
स्पर्धमाना तु रोहिण्या कन्यसी स्वसा।
इच्छन्ती ज्येष्ठतां देवी तपस् तप्तुं
वनं गता॥तत्र मूढो ऽस्मि … नक्षत्रं
गगनाच् च्युतम्।कालं त्व् इमं परं
स्कन्द ब्रह्मणा सह चिन्तय) 3. 219. 8-9;
(to fill the gap, the Kṛttikās went to the heaven
3. 219. 11) (Nī. on Bom. Ed. 3. 230. 8-9, 11:
कन्यसी कनिष्ठा वनं गता अधिकारं
त्यक्त्वेति शेषः॥८॥सा च ज्येष्ठतास्पर्-
धया गगनात् च्युता अतो ऽहं मूढो ऽस्मि
नक्षत्रसंख्यापूरणप्रकारस्याज्ञानाद्
इति भावः॥९॥तथा च कृत्तिकाभिर् एव
नक्षत्रसंख्यापूर्तिं कुर्व् इति शक्राशयं
ज्ञात्वा तास् त्रिदिवं गताः॥११॥); if one
offers a श्राद्ध under the constellation
Abhijit he attains superior knowledge (विद्यां
श्रेष्ठाम् अवाप्नुयात्) 13. 89. 11. [See
Abhijita1]

अभिजित
Abhijita1 m.: Name of a Nakṣatra
(= Abhijit ?)
Here called योग; if a righteous person
(धर्मनित्य) gives the gift of milk mixed
with honey and घृत to learned men under
the constellation Abhijita (अभिजिते योगे)
he is honoured in heaven 13. 63. 27.

अभिजित
Abhijita2 m.: Name of the eighth
part of the day (मुहूर्त), about mid-day
(twenty-four minutes before and twenty-four
minutes after midday).
Yudhiṣṭhira was born at the Abhijita
मुहूर्त (मुहूर्ते ऽभिजिते ऽष्टमे) 1. 114. 4
(Nī, however, on Bom. Ed. 1. 123. 6, takes
अष्टमे to identify the नक्षत्र Jyeṣṭhā:
ज्येष्ठानक्षत्रे अष्टमे संवत्सरारम्भात्)

अश्वयुज
Aśvayuja m.: Name of a constellation.
Yama told Śaśabindu (13. 89. 1) that by
offering a श्राद्ध (which is काम्य) under
this constellation one got horses (अश्वांश्
चाश्वयुजे वेत्ति) 13. 89. 14. [See Aśvinī]

अश्विनी
Aśvinī f.: Name of a constellation.
Nārada told Devakī (13. 63. 2-4) that
one who gave as gift a chariot with horses
under the Aśvinī नक्षत्र, was born in a
family that had many elephants, horses and
chariots 13. 63. 34. [See Aśvayuja]

अषाढा
Aṣāḍhā f.: See Uttarāṣāḍhā and
Pūrvāṣāḍhā.

आग्नेय
Āgneya nt.: Name of the constellation
Kṛttikā.
One should not perform any rite for
gods or पितृस् under the Āgneya constellation
(दैवं पित्र्यम् अथापि च।न … कार्यं
तथाग्नेये च भारत) 13. 107. 119.
[See Kṛttikā]

आङ्गिरस
Āṅgirasa m.: Name of the planet
Jupiter.
Arjuna and Aśvatthāman, who had
the lustre of Śukra and Āṅgirasa, fought
with each other as the two planets would
do in heaven for a नक्षत्र (ततः सम-
भवद् युद्धम् शुक्राङ्गिरसवर्चसोः।
नक्षत्रम् अभितो व्योम्नि शुक्राङ्गिरसयोर्
इव॥) 8. 12. 48 (Nī. on Bom. Ed. 8. 17. 1:
नक्षत्रम् अभितः नक्षत्रम् लक्षीकृत्य).

आदियुग
Ādiyuga nt.: [See Kṛtayuga]

आर्द्रा
Ārdrā f.: Name of a constellation.
Nārada told Devakī (13. 63. 2-4) that
if one gave as a gift, after fasting, कृसर
mixed with sesamum oil, under the constella-
tion Ārdrā one could get over difficulties and
cross mountains having edges as sharp as a
razor (आर्द्रायां कृसरं दत्त्वा तैलमि-
श्रम् उपोषितः।नरस् तरति दुर्गाणि क्षुर-
धारांश् च पर्वतान्) 13. 63. 8; Yama
told Śaśabindu (13. 89. 1) that by offering a
श्राद्ध (which is काम्य) under Ārdrā one
could perform terrible deeds (क्रूरकर्मा …
मानवो भवेत्) 13. 89. 3.

आश्लेषा
Āśleṣā f.: Name of a constellation.
Nārada informed Devakī (13. 63. 2-4)
that one who gave as a gift under the con-
stellation Āśleṣā silver (रूप्य) or a bull he
became free from all dangers and overpowered
his enemies 13. 63. 11; Yama told Śaśabindu
(13. 89. 1) that by offering a श्राद्ध (which
is काम्य) under the constellation Āśleṣā one
got heroic sons 13. 89. 5.

आश्वयुज्
Āśvayuj m.: Name of the month
(Āśvina).
Bhīṣma told Yudhiṣṭhira that if one,
remaining pure and composed (शुचिर् आत्म-
वान्), gave घृत to Vipras in the month of
Āśvayuj the pleased Aśvinau gave him a
handsome form (तस्मै प्रयच्छतो रूपम्
प्रीतौ देवाव् इहाश्विनौ) 13. 64. 10; the
sage Aṅgiras told Bhīṣma (13. 109. 9-10)
that if one passed the month of Āśvayuj
eating once a day he would have a large
progeny, many vehicles, and many sons
(तथैवाश्वयुजं मासम् एकभक्तेन यः
क्षपेत्।प्रजावान् वाहनाढ्यश् च बहु-
पुत्रश् च जायते) 13. 109. 28.

आषाढ
Āṣāḍha m.: Name of a month.
Aṅgiras had told Bhīṣma (13. 109. 9-
10) that if one diligently (अतन्द्रितः) took
only one meal a day in the month of Āṣāḍha
he had ample field produce, wealth and many
sons (बहुधान्यो बहुधनो बहुपुत्रश्
च जायते) 13. 109. 25.

आषाढी
Āṣāḍhī f.: Name of the full moon day
in the month of Āṣāḍha.
Virūpākṣa, the king of the Rākṣasas,
used to give excellent and well-garnished food,
as desired, to many Brāhmaṇas on every full
moon day (पौर्णमास्याम् 12. 165. 16) of
the month of Āṣāḍha (तस्य नित्यं तथा-
षाढ्यां … बहवो द्विजाः।ईप्सितं भोजन-
वरं लभन्ते सत्कृतं सदा) 12. 165. 15.

उत्तर
Uttara Proṣṭhapada m.: Name of a
नक्षत्र। [See Uttarā Bhādrapadā]

उत्तरा
Uttarā Phalgunī f. (sg., du, pl.):
Name of a नक्षत्र।
A. Epic event: Arjuna was born on
the mountain Himavant under the junction
of the two constellations Pūrvā and Uttarā
Phalgunī, hence called Phalguna (उत्तरा-
भ्यां च पूर्वाभ्यां फल्गुनीभ्याम्
अहं दिवा।जातो हिमवतः पृष्ठे तेन
मां फल्गुनं विदुः) 4. 39. 14. (Nī. on
Bom. Ed. 4. 44. 16: उत्तराभ्यां च
पूर्वाभ्याम् इति पाठे नक्षत्रसन्धौ इत्य्
अर्थः).
B. Religious rites: Nārada told
Devakī (13. 63. 2-4) that if, after ob-
serving fast (उपोषितः 13. 63. 13), one gave,
according to the rites (विधिवत्), under this
नक्षत्र (उत्तराविषये) gift of cooked rice
made of grains that ripen in sixty days (षष्टि-
कौदन) mixed with घृत and milk, he
was honoured in heaven 13. 63. 14; whatever
gift one gave under this नक्षत्र it produced
ample benefit that became everlasting (यद्
यत् प्रदीयते दानम् उत्त्राविषये नरैः।
महाफलम् अनतं च भवतीति विनिश्-
चयः) 13. 63. 15; Yama told Śaśabindu (13.
89. 1) that if one offered a काम्य श्राद्ध
under this नक्षत्र one got progeny (अपत्य-
भाग् उत्तरासु) 13. 89. 6.

उत्तरा
Uttarā Bhādrapadā f. (sg., pl), Uttara
Proṣṭhapada m. (sg.): Name of a con-
stellation.
A. Religious rites: Nārada told Devakī
(13. 63. 2-4) that if one gave as a gift
meat of a ram or a sheep under the conste-
llation Uttarā Bhādrapadā he gave delight to
the manes and obtained infinite (happiness)
after death (औरभ्रम् उत्तरायोगे यस् तु
मांसं प्रयच्छति।स पितॄन् प्रीणयति
वै प्रेत्य चानन्त्यम् अश्नुते) 13. 63. 32;
Yama told Śaśabindu (13. 89. 1) that
by offering a काम्य श्राद्ध under this
नक्षत्र one got a thousand cows (उत्तरास्व्
अथ कुर्वाणः) 13. 89. 13.
B. Bad
omens: Among the bad omens which oc-
curred before the start of the war and
which were reported by Vyāsa to Dhṛtarāṣṭra
there was one according to which the planet
Śukra after ascending Pūrva Proṣṭhapada and
then having gone to the Uttara Proṣṭhapada
was, together with it (?) looking back at
(the Pūrva Preṣṭhapada) (शुक्रः प्रोष्ठ-
पदे पूर्वे समारुह्य विशां पते।उत्तरे
तु परिक्रम्य सहितः प्रत्युदीक्षते॥)
6. 3. 14 (Nī., however, on Bom. Ed. on 6.
3. 15: पूर्वे प्रोष्ठपदे पूर्वाभाद्रपदा-
नक्षत्रं समारुह्य परिक्रम्य परि-
घाख्य उपग्रहस् तेन सहितः उत्तरे
उत्तराभाद्रपदानक्षत्रम् उदीक्षते आक्रा-
न्तुम् इच्छति).

उत्तरायण
Uttarāyaṇa nt.: Name of the period in
which the sun moves to the north, the summer
solstice; also called Udagā̆yana (-आ- म्। च्।)
(6. 114. 98; 12. 224. 16).
A. Sun's courses fixed by Brahman:
Śakra told Bali that the self-born god (Sva-
yaṃbhū) had fixed the movements of the
sun following which the sun moved towards
the north for six months and towards the
south for six months 12. 218. 35-36.
B.
Its duration: The calculators of the divi-
sions of time say that the year consists of
two अयनस् (sun's courses), viz. दक्षिण
and उत्तर (संवतसरं द्वे अयने वदन्ति
संख्याविदो दक्षिणम् उत्तरम् च) 12.
224. 13; (12. 47. 42); 13. 16. 46; Nārada
told Devamata that the two अयनस् (दक्षिण
and उत्तर) form a pair and between them
is fire; Brāhmaṇas knew that that is the
highest form of उदान (? उभे चैवायने
द्वंद्वं तयोर् मध्ये हुताशनः।एतद्
रूपम् उदानस्य परमं ब्राह्मना विदुः)
14. 24. 15; Vyāsa had told Śuka that the night
and the day of the gods was equal to one
human year of which the उत्तरायण form-
ed the day and the दक्षिणायन the night
(दैवे रात्र्यहनी वर्षम् प्रविभागस् तयोः
पुनः।अहस् तत्रोदगयनं रात्रिः स्याद्
दक्षिणायनम्) 12. 224. 16.
C. Effects
on the earth: The sun, during its two
courses, northern and southern, distributes
cold and heat among the people (अयनं
तस्य षण्मासा उत्तरं दक्षिणं तथा।
येन संयाति लोकेषु शीतोष्णे विसृजन् रविः॥)
12. 218. 36; the sun, having traversed its
northern course and having collected with his
rays the heated waters, turns for the southern
course and enters the earth; there, lying in
the earth and sprinkled with the energies of
the moon, it produces plants which serve as
food for living beings (गत्वोत्तरायणं
तेजोरसान् उद्धृत्य रश्मिभिः।दक्षिणा-
यनम् आवृत्तो महीं निविशते रविः॥ …
निषिक्तश् चन्द्रतेजोभिः सूयते भूगतो
रविः।ओषध्यः षड्रसा मेध्यास् तद्
अन्नं प्राणिनां भुवि॥) 3. 3. 6, 8 (Nī.
on Bom. Ed. 3. 3. 6: तेजोरसान् जलानि).
D. Importance: Mahādeva (13. 16. 13)
identified with both the Uttara and the
Dakṣiṇa ayana 13. 16. 46.
E. Considered
holy: The night in the Uttarāyaṇa is con-
sidered holy and divine; Śacī bowed down
to this goddess Rātri so that her wish to see
her husband was fulfilled (पुण्यां चेमाम्
अहं दिव्यां प्रवृत्ताम् उत्तरायणे।देवीं
रात्रिम् नमस्यामि सिध्यतां मे मनोर-
थः॥) 5. 13. 23; from Dakṣiṇāyana (which
symbolizes darkness) proceeds Uttarāyaṇa
(which stands for light); (hence) the gift of
light is praiseworthy (अन्धं तमस् तमि-
स्रं च दक्षिणायनम् एव च।उत्तरायणम्
एतस्माज् ज्योतिर्दानं प्रशस्यते॥) 13. 101.
46 (perhaps what is meant is that giving
gifts of light helps the bringing in of the
Uttarāyaṇa. Nī. on Bom. Ed. 13. 98. 47:
तमिस्रं अन्धकारः।अन्धंतमो नाम
नरकरूपं तथा दक्षिणायनम् अप्य्
अन्धंतम एव।अत उत्तरायणे रात्रौ
तमोनाशकं ज्योतिर् देयं नरकनिवृत्त्यर्-
थम्। Editor, Cr. Ed., Vol. 17. (part II),
p. 1098 on 13. 101. 46, however,: “Does this
suggest the origin of the Dīpāvali festival ?”).
F. Bhīṣma's death in Uttarāyaṇa: Bhīṣma
when he fell on the ground in the war did not
give up his life as he wished to wait till the
setting in of the Uttarāyaṇa 6. 114. 89; he
assured the sages, sent to him by Gaṅgā, when
they came to him in the form of swans, that
he would sustain his life and go to his ori-
ginal place when the sun had turned towards
the north 6. 114. 97; he told them that he
would sustain his life longing for the Uttarā-
yaṇa; established in complete sway (over his
life), he could control the act of giving up
life; he would therefore hold life for some
time since he wished to die in the Udagāyana
(धारयिष्याम्य् अहं प्राणान् उत्तरायण-
काङ्क्षया।ऐश्वर्यभूतः प्राणानाम्
उत्सर्गे नियतो ह्य् अहम्।तस्मात् प्राणान्
धारयिष्ये मुमूर्षुर् उदगायने॥) 6.
114. 98 (Nī. on Bom. Ed. 6. 119. 106:
स्वसामर्थ्येन भूतः प्राप्तः स्वच्छ-
न्दमृत्युत्वात्); Bhīṣma's future death in
the Uttarāyaṇa alluded to by Yudhiṣṭhira 12.
291. 4 (आवृत्ते भगवत्य् अर्के गनतासि पर-
मां गतिम्); Bhīṣma asked Yudhiṣṭhira to
come back to him when the sun had returned
from the Dakṣiṇāyana and the Uttarāyaṇa
had set in 13. 152. 10; when the Uttarāyaṇa
set in, Yudhiṣṭhira started from Hāstinapura
to meet Bhīṣma (for the remembered what
Bhīṣma had told him) 13. 153. 6; Bhīṣma
greeted Yudhiṣṭhira and said that the sun had
turned back (from the Dakṣināyana) 13.
153. 26; as soon as the sun had returned to
its northerly course Bhīṣma, well composed,
placed himself in his soul (to he ready to
abandon the body) 12. 47. 3; Bhīṣma gave
up his life when the Uttarāyaṇa had set in
14. 59. 12.

उत्तराषाढा
Uttarāṣāḍhā f. (pl.): Name of a con-
stellation.
Nārada told Devakī (13. 63. 2-4) that if
one gave under the Uttarā Aṣāḍhā a pot of
barley-preparation (?) mixed with clarified
butter and thickened with plenty of honey
one obtained all desires 13. 63. 26. (उदमन्-
थं ससर्पिष्कं प्रभूतमधुफाणि-
तम्।दत्त्वोत्तरास्व् अषाढासु सर्वकामान्
अवाप्नुयात्॥ Nī. on Bom. Ed. 13. 64. 26:
(उदमन्थम्) उदकुंभयुक्तं सक्तु-
विकारम्; Unknown commentator: उदमन्-
थं नवनीतम्, cf. Cr. Ed., Vol. 17, part II.
p. 1080 note on 13. 63. 26); Yama told Śaśa-
bindu (13. 89. 1) that by offering a काम्य
श्राद्ध under the Uttarā Aṣāḍhā one was
freed of all sorrow (उत्तरासु त्व् अषाढासु
वीतशोकश् चरेन् महीम्) 13. 89. 10.

उद्गायन
Udgā̆yana nt.: See Uttarāyaṇa.

ऐन्द्र
Aindra adj.: See Jyeṣṭhā.

कलि
Kali m., Kaliyuga nt.: Name of one
of the four Yugas or ages; also called Puṣya
(6. 11. 3-4, 7, 12, 13) and Tiṣya (is कलि-
पुरस्कृत 12. 327. 76; 12. 337. 42; Nī. on
Bom. Ed. 6. 10. 3. (= Cr. Ed. 6. 11. 3
reads तिष्यम् (in place of Cr. Ed. पुष्यम्)
and explains it as कलियुगम्).
A. Characterization: Characterized as
कृष्णयुग (12. 337. 44) and तामसयुग
(3. 148. 33).
B. Place among the four
Yugas: Fourth and the last Yuga, hence
referred to as the चतुर्थ युग (युगस्य
च चतुर्थस्य राजा भवति कारणम्)
5. 130. 16; 12. 70. 25, or as पश्चिम
युगकाल 3. 189. 13; it comes at the close
of the Dvāpara Yuga (संक्षेपाद् द्वाप-
रस्याथ ततः पुष्यं प्रवर्तते) 6. 11.
4; hence referred to after the Dvāpara as
अपर युग 12. 259. 32; Hanūmant told
Bhīma that the Kaliyuga will commence
soon (after the Dvāpara) (एअतत् कलियुगं
नाम अचिराद् यत् प्रवर्तते) 3. 148. 37;
after the Kaliyuga commences again the
Kṛtayuga (क्षीणे कलियुगे चैव प्रवर्तति
कृतं युगम्) 3. 186. 22.
C. Duration:
Mārkaṇḍeya told Yudhiṣṭhira that the Kali
Yuga lasts for 1000 years; it is preceded by
dawns of 100 years and followed by evenings
of equal duration (सहस्रम् एकं वर्षाणां
ततः कलियुगं स्मृतम्।तस्य वर्षशतं
संध्या संध्यांशश् च ततः परम्।
संध्यासंध्यांशयोस् तुल्यं प्रमाणम्
उपधारय) 3. 186. 21 (Nī. on Bom. Ed.
3. 188. 23: सन्ध्या पूर्वस्मिन् युगे उत्तर-
युगधर्माणाम् उपसर्जनतया संक्र-
मः।सन्ध्यांशस् तूत्तरस्मिन् पूर्वयुग-
धर्माणाम्); the same duration for Kaliyuga
was narrated by Vyāsa to Śuka 12. 224. 20.
D. Events marking the advent of the Kali
Yuga: (1) The armies of the Kurus and the
Pāṇḍavas fought each other near the Samanta-
pañcaka at the junction of the Dvāpara
and the Kali Yuga (अन्तरे चैव सं-
प्राप्ते कलिद्वापरयोर् अभूत्।समन्त-
पञ्चके युद्धं कुरुपाण्डवसेनयोः)
1. 2. 9; (2) Nārāyaṇa told Apāntaratamas
that when the Tiṣyayuga will have set in the
kings born in the line of Bharata, known as
the Kurus, will be born of him (i. e. of Apān-
taratamas then born as Vyāsa) and that
there will be a feud in the family leading to
mutual destruction (here Tiṣya, i. e. Kali,
is mentioned in place of Dvāpara due to
close proximity ?) (पुनस् तिष्ये च संप्रा-
प्ते कुरवो नाम भारताः।भविष्यन्ति
महात्मानो राजानः प्रथिता भुवि॥तेषां
त्वत्तः प्रसूतानां कुलभेदो भविष्यति।
परस्परविनाशार्थं) 12. 337. 42-43;
(3) Nārāyaṇa told Nārada that at the end
of the junction of the Dvāpara and the
Kali age he would appear in Mathurā for
the killing of Kaṃsa (द्वापरस्य कलेश्
चैव संधौ पर्यवसानिके।प्रादुर्भा-
वः कंसहेतोः मथुरायां भविष्यति)
12. 326. 82; (4) at the end of the Dvā-
para and the beginning of the Kali age
Vāsudeva (Kṛṣṇa), along with Saṃkarṣaṇa,
is sung according to the Sātvata mode of
worship (द्वापरस्य युगस्यान्ते आदौ
कलियुगस्य च।सात्वतं विधिस्म् आस्थाय
गीतः संकर्षणेन यः) 6. 62. 39.
E.
Kaliyuga and Nārāyaṇa and Vyāsa: (1)
Bhīṣma told Yudhiṣṭhira that in the Kali
Yuga Kṛṣṇa came down to the earth as
अधर्म (कृष्णः।कलाव् अधर्मः क्षितिम्
आजगाम 13. 143. 9; Nī. on Bom. Ed. 13.
158. 10: कलौ त्व् अधर्म एव बलवान् इति
भावः); the god (Nārāyaṇa i. e. Kṛṣṇa-
Janārdana 3. 187. 52, 50) told Mārkaṇḍeya
that he has dark colour in the Kaliyuga
(कृष्णः कलियुगे तथा) 3. 187. 31;
तामसं युगम् आसाद्य कृष्णो भवति
केशवः) 3. 148. 33; (2) Hari-Nārāyaṇa
told Apāntaratamas (12. 337. 38) that when
Kṛṣṇayuga (i. e. Kaliyuga) sets in he (as
Vyāsa) will have dark colour (कृष्णे युगे
च संप्राप्ते कृष्णवर्णो भविष्यसि) 12.
337. 44.
F. King and the Kali Yuga:
All the Yugas are dependent on the king's
behaviour, hence a king is called a युग
(राजवृत्तानि सर्वाणि राजैव युगम् उच्यते)
12. 92. 6; according to Bhīṣma all the
Yugas, including Kali, are rooted in a king
(राजमूलानि सर्वाणि) 12. 139. 10; it is the
king who makes the Yugas what they are and
hence he is also the cause of the fourth Yuga
(i. e. the Kaliyuga) (युगस्य च चतुर्थ-
स्य राजा भवति कारणम्) 5. 130. 16; 12.
70. 25; by bringing about the Kali age the
king incurs immense sin (कलेः प्रवर्तनाद्
राजा पापम् अत्यन्तम् अश्नुते) 12. 70. 27;
by bringing about the Kaliyuga (not directly
stated) the evil-doer (i. e. the king) lives
eternally in the hell (ततो वसति दुष्कर्मा
नरके शाश्वतीः समाः) 5. 130. 18; when
the king wholly gives up दण्डनीति and
oppresses his subjects unjustly the Kali age
makes its appearance (दण्डनीतिं परित्य-
ज्य यदा कार्त्स्न्येन भूमिपः।प्रजाः
क्लिश्नात्य् अयोगेन प्रविश्यति तदा कलिः)
12. 70. 18; where the sinful ones move about
freely among the righteous, there the Kali
age (? or the evil spirit ?) meets the kings
(? यत्र पापा ज्ञायमानाश् चरन्ति सतां
कलिर् विन्दति तत्र राज्ञाः) 12. 92. 27
(Nī. on Bom. Ed. 12. 91. 28: राज्ञः
नृपान्).
G. Kali Yuga and धर्म:
While describing the four Yugas Hanūmant
told Bhīma that in the Kali Yuga धर्म
stands only on one foot (पादेनैकेन
कौन्तेय धर्मः कलियुगे स्थितः) 3.
148. 32; (पादेन त्व् अपरे (i. e. कलौ)
युगे) 12. 259. 32; (ततस् तिष्ये ऽथ सं-
प्राप्ते युगे कलिपुरस्कृते।एकपाद-
स्थितो धर्मो यत्र तत्र भविष्यति) 12.
327. 76 (however, commentator Vādirāja:
तिष्ये पुष्यनक्षत्रे, note on this stanza in
the Cr. Ed.); 12. 224. 23; gods asked
Bhagavān Nārāyaṇa what they should do
when the धर्म in the Tiṣya Yuga stood
on one foot 12. 327. 77; in the Kali Yuga
(not directly mentioned) अधर्म rules
over men in three parts while धर्म attends
men only in one part (त्रिभिर् अंशैर्
अधर्मस् तु लोकान् आक्रम्य तिष्ठति।चतुर्-
थांशेन धर्मस् तु मनुष्यान् उपति-
ष्ठति) 3. 188. 12; in the Kali Yuga धर्म
is reduced to its sixteenth कोला on account
of the misbehaviour of kings (तथा कलियुगे
प्राप्ते राज्ञां दुश्चरितेन ह।भवेत्
कालविशेष्ण कला धर्मस्य षोडशी) 12.
259. 33.
H. Nature of the Kali Yuga
and its effects on men: Vedic practices dwin-
dle, so also the religious and the sacrificial
rites; on the other hand, seasonal calamities,
diseases, lassitude, vices like anger and
others, calamities and mental agonies are ex-
perienced (वेदाचाराः प्रशाम्यन्ति धर्म-
यज्ञक्रियास् तथा॥ईतयो व्याधयस्
तन्द्री दोषाः क्रोधादयस् तथा।उपद्रवाश्
च वर्तन्ते आधयो व्याधयस् तथा॥ 3.
148. 33-34; also cf. 3. 186. 24-55; 3. 188.
5-6, 13-84; 12. 224. 62; in the Kali Yuga
the Vedas are seen (i. e. practised) by some
and not by others; they, which alone serve as
dams of धर्म, fall into ruin along with
the sacrifices (दृश्यन्ते नापि दृश्यन्ते वेदाः
कलियुगे ऽखिलाः।उत्सीदन्ते सयज्ञाश् च
केवला धर्मसेतवः॥) 12. 224. 66; 12.
230. 15-17; the study of the Vedas dwindles
gradually in each succeeding Yuga (वेद-
वादाश् चानुयुगं ह्रसन्तीति च नः श्रुतम्)
12. 224. 25; the अधर्म in the Yugas
other than the Kṛta is on increase due to the
practice of theft, falsehood and deceipt 12.
224. 23; the duties (धर्माः) to be followed
in the Kali Yuga are different (from those of
the other Yugas); they have been prescribed
as if keeping in mind the (lowered) capacity
of men in that age (अन्ये कलियुगे धर्मा
यथाशक्तिकृता इव) 12. 224. 26 = 12. 252. 8;
giving gifts is specially recommended for the
Kali Yuga (दानम् एव कलौ युगे) 12.
224. 27; in the Kali age अधर्म is practised
by many, and धर्म only by a few; all
the Varṇas are disinclined to follow धर्म
proper to them 12. 70. 19; also 20-24; the
nature of men in the Puṣyayuga is describ-
ed also in 6. 11. 12-13; strict adherence
to धर्म is not to be expected in the Kali
Yuga-this is what Kṛṣṇa implied in his
words addressed to Balarāma to assuage his
wrath (प्राप्तं कलियुगं विद्धि) 9. 59.
21; in the Kali age (as in the Dvāpara) it
is necessary for people to he paired to beget
children (द्वापरे मैथुनो धर्मः प्रजा-
नाम् अभवन् नृप।तथा कलियुगे राजन्
द्वन्द्वम् आपेदिरे जनाः॥) 12. 200. 37;
the ascetics born in the Kali age (as also in
the Tretā and the Dvāpara) are beset with
doubts (त्रेतायां द्वापरे चैव कलिजाश् च
ससंशयाः।तपस्विनः) 12. 230. 7; evil
tribes like the Talavaras, the Andhrakas and
others which originate in the south (दक्षिणा-
पथजन्मानः) and those like the Yaunas,
the Kāmbojas, and other which have their
origin in the north (उत्तरापथजन्मानः)
roam on the earth in the Tretā and the follow-
ing Yugas (i. e. also in the Kali) (त्रेता-
प्रभृति वर्तन्ते ते जना भरतर्षभ)
12. 200. 39-42; Dyumatsena told Satyavān
that if the Dasyus were not killed then
in the Kaliyuga people would say to each
other: “this is mine, not his”, it would
then be difficult to carry on every day life
(ममेदम् इति नास्यैतत् प्रवर्तेत कलौ
युगे।लोकयात्रा न चैव स्यात्) 12. 259. 6; if
one always recites the description of the origin
of cows he is freed of the impurity of the Kali
age (? or of evil spirit ?) (इमं गवां प्र-
भवविधानम् उत्तमं पठन् सदा …
विमुच्यते कलिकलुषेण मानवः) 13. 76. 32.
I. Span of life: In the Puṣya (i. e. the Kali)
Yuga there is no fixed span of life; people die
(even) in the womb or immediately after
they are born (न प्रमाणस्थितिर् ह्य् अस्ति
पुष्ये ऽस्मिन् भरतर्षभ गर्भस्थाश् च
म्रियन्ते ऽत्र तथा जाता म्रियन्ति च॥)
6. 11. 7; the life-span, as also other faculties,
of human beings decrease successively in
each following Yuga (आयुर् वीर्यम् … ।
मनुस्याणाम् अनुयुगं ह्रसतीति निबोध
मे॥) 3. 188. 13; however, life is expected
to be of a hundred years ( … त्रेतादिष्व् एते-
सां पादशो ह्रसते वयः) 12. 224. 24, 25.
J. Kali as a name of Sūrya: Kali occurs
among the 108 names of Sūrya taught by
Dhaumya to Yudhiṣṭhira 3. 3. 22 (Nī. on
Bom. Ed. 3. 3. 20: कलिः सर्वमलाश्रय
इत्य् एकं नाम).

काम्याष्टमी
Kāmyāṣṭamī f.: Name of the eighth
day (of the bright or the dark fortnight ?) of
the month (?)
One should give cows and then observe
the गोव्रत (live like a cow ?) for three
nights, spending one of the nights with cows;
then from the Kāmyāṣṭamī he should live
three nights on milk or on cow-dung and cow-
urine (गा वै दत्त्वा गोव्रती स्यात् त्रिरात्रं
निशां चैकां संवसेतेह ताभिः।काम्या-
ष्टम्यां वर्तितव्यं त्रिरात्रं रसैर् वा
गोः शकृता प्रस्नवैर् वा॥) 13. 75. 19.

कार्तयुग
Kārtayuga: See Kṛtayuga.

कार्तिक|कार्त्तिक
Kārttika m.: Name of a month.
A. Epic event related with this month:
The wrestling match between Bhīma and
Jarāsandha began on the first day of Kārttika
2. 21. 17.
B. Religious rite performed in
this month: Aṅgiras told Bhīṣma that if one
took food only once a day in Kārttika he
became brave, got many wives, and became
famous (कार्त्तिकं तु नरो मासं यः
कुर्याद् एकभोजनम्।शूरश् च बहु-
भार्यश् च कीर्तिमांश् चैव जायते॥) 13.
109. 29. [See Kaumuda]

कार्त्तिकी
Kārttikī (Cr. Ed. also Kārtikī) f.:
The night of full moon in the month of
Kārttika.
A. Description: Most holy among the
पर्वन्स् (पुण्यतमा रात्रिः पर्वसन्धौ)
3. 179. 16; the best conjunction (योगम्
उत्तमम्) 3. 179. 17.
B. Epic events
connected with this तिथि: (1) When the
Pāṇḍavas lived near the river Sarasvatī there
occurred the Kārttikī of the autumn season;
the Pāṇḍavas spent that night of best con-
junction in the company of the holy ascetics
and when the darkness set in (तमिस्राभ्य्-
उदये) they, with Dhaumya, went to the
Kāmyaka forest 3. 179. 16-18; (2) Vidura
reported to Yudhiṣṭhira that Dhṛtarāṣṭra
had decided to retire to the forest on the
following Kārtikī (गमिष्यति वनं राजन्
कार्तिकीम् आगताम् इमाम्) 15. 17. 3; before
setting for the forest Dhṛtarāṣṭra wished to
give rich gifts on the Kārtikī (कार्तिक्याम्) 15.
19. 15; he gave those gifts for ten days preced-
ing (the Kārttikī) (दशाहम् एवं दानानि
दत्त्वा राजाम्बिकासुतः) 15. 20. 17; gifts
given by him detailed in 15. 20. 3-16; the
gifts were intended as a श्राद्ध or an
और्ध्वदेहिक for Bhīṣma and the rest 15.
17. 4-5, 9, 17; 15. 19. 11; Dhṛtarāṣṭra there-
by wanted to pay back the debt he owed to
his sons and friends (बभूव पुत्रपौत्रा-
णाम् अनृणो भरतर्षभ) 15. 20. 17; 15.
18. 11; he started for the forest when the
Brāhmaṇas, at his instance, offered an इष्टि
on the Kārttikī 15. 21. 2.
C. Bad omens:
Among the bad omens reported by Vyāsa to
Dhṛtarāṣṭra before the start of the great war
one was related to the night of the Kārttikī
full moon when the moon having the colour
of fire, shining in the sky of the same colour,
became lustreless and could not be noticed
(अलक्ष्यः प्रभया हीनः पौर्णमासीं
च कार्त्तिकीम्।चन्द्रो ऽभूद् अग्निवर्णश्
च समवर्णे नभस्तले॥) 6. 2. 23.
D. Religious importance: (1) Merit of a
person who visits Puṣkara on the Kārtikī
grows undecayingly 3. 80. 52; spending one
full moon Kārtikī night at Puṣkara was
equal to offering अग्निहोत्र for full hundred
years 3. 80. 57; (2) Pilgrims bathe in the
river Sarasvatī for a year following the
occurrence of the Kārtikī (सरस्वत्यां
महाराज अनु संवत्सरं हि ते।स्नायन्ते
भरतश्रेष्ठ वृत्तां वै कार्तिकीं सदा)
3. 80. 121; with this bath one shone like a
moon and obtained fruit of giving a thousand
cows 3. 80. 122; (3) Virūpākṣa, the king
of the Rākṣasas used to feed a thousand
excellent Brāhmaṇas on the autumnal full
moon day of the Kārttika; according to the
श्रुति texts Brāhmaṇas should be given preci-
ous stones (रत्नानि) on that day; Virūpākṣa
assured the Brāhmaṇas that they need have
no fear from the Rākṣasas on that one day
of Kārttikī and they need not be in a hurry
to go away 12. 165. 9, 16, 23; details of
how Virūpākṣa honoured Brāhmaṇas 12
165. 10-14, 17-19.

कुहू
Kuhū f.: Name of the second Amā-
vāsyā day (if the Amāvāsyā extends over
two days (see Ait. Br. 32. 9, Nirukta 11. 31)
and on which the moon is not seen.
Described as venerable (भगवती) and
one whose only digit is very small (एकानंशा)
3. 208. 8 (Nī. on Bom. Ed. 3. 218. 8: एका
कला अनंशा अल्पांशवती); personified, she
was the eighth daughter of Aṅgiras, and
was called Kuhū because people, having seen
her, were struck with wonder (यां तु दृष्ट्वा
भगवतीं जनः कुहुकुहायते) 3. 208. 8
(Nī. on Bom. Ed. 3. 218. 8: कुहुकुहायते
विस्मितो भवति); Kuhū formed one of the
four reins (योक्त्र) for the horses yoked
to the chariot of Mahādeva when it was
made ready for his fight with the Tripuras
8. 24. 74; she attended the investiture of
Kumāra (Skanda) as the general of the gods
which took place near the river Sarasvatī 9.
44. 12, 16; Brāhmaṇas call Devasenā, chief
queen of Skanda, by different names, one
of them being Kuhū (स्कन्दस्य महिषीम्
 … षष्ठीं यां ब्राह्मणाः प्राहुः … सिनी-
वालीं कुहूं चैव) 3. 218. 47.

कृत
Kṛta, Kṛtayuga nt.: Name of the first
among the four Yugas; also called Devayuga
(1. 14. 5; 2. 11. 1; 3. 92. 6; 10. 18. 1; 12.
3. 19; 13. 82. 24, Ādiyuga (6. 76. 18; 13.
135. 11), Prājāpatyayuga (12. 113. 4), and
Dharmayuga (12. 308. 7).
A. Description: Auspicious (शुभ)
1. 14. 5; 12. 336. 31; completely free from
the three गुणस् (सत्त्व, रजस् and तमस्),
(त्रैगुण्यपरिवर्जित) 13. 148. 22; the best
period (श्रेष्ठः कालः) 5. 130. 14; 12.
324. 5; 12. 327. 73; the best among the
Yugas (युगोत्तम) 13. 148. 11.
B. Place
among the Yugas: When Brahmā created
the worlds, the first Yuga to occur was the
Kṛta (ततः प्रावर्तत तदा आदौ कृत-
युगं शुभम्) 12. 336. 31; 6. 11. 4; 14.
44. 8; first Yuga after the dissolution of the
entire world (आदितः मनुजव्याघ्र कृत्-
स्नस्य जगतः क्षये … ततो कृतं युगं)
3. 186. 17-18; hence called आदियुग and
प्रथमकल्पित 12. 322. 51; hence also the
words आदौ and पुरा (or पूर्वम्) often
used with Kṛta (12. 59. 13; 12. 336. 31,
and many other citations in section D
below); Kṛta sets in again at the end of
the fourth Kali Yuga; Yudhiṣṭhira asked
Mārkaṇḍeya what would be the (final)
stage of Kali when its end will have arrived
and after which Kṛta will commence again
(युगक्षये॥कां च काष्ठां समा-
साद्य पुनः संपत्स्यते कृतम्) 3. 188.
6-7; 3. 186. 22.
C. Duration: Mārka-
ṇḍedya told Yudhiṣṭhira that the duration of
the Kṛta Yuga was 4000 years; it had dawns
of 400 years and twilights of the same
duration (चत्वार्य् आहुः सहस्राणि वर्षाणां
तत् कृतं युगम्।तस्य तावच्छती संध्या
संध्यांशश् च ततः परम्॥) 3. 186.
18 (cf. Nī. on Bom. Ed. 3. 188. 23 above
Kali, section C, p. 234); the same duration
of Kṛta told by Vyāsa to Śuka 12. 224.
18-19.
D. Events occurring in the Kṛta
Yuga: (1) All beings are produced from
Viṣṇu at the advent of the Kṛta Yuga and
are reabsorbed into him at the end of that
Yuga 13. 135. 11; (2) The creation of the
world, the creation of Saṃkarṣaṇa, Prad-
yumna, Aniruddha and Brahman, Nārāyaṇa's
incarnation as Varāha to reestablish the earth
and kill Hiraṇyākṣa, as Nṛsiṃha to kill
Hiraṇyakaśipu, and as Vāmana to make
Bali a resident of Pātāla—all these events
are said to have occurred in the Kṛta Yuga
which is not named 12. 326. 67-76; (also
cf. 12. 337. 29-36 where these three incarna-
tions are mentioned without naming Kṛta-
yuga); (3) Formerly, in the Kṛta Yuga
of the Svāyaṃbhuva Manvantara, Nārā-
yaṇa was born as Nara, Nārāyaṇa, Hari
and Kṛṣṇa (नारायणो हि विश्वात्मा चतुर्-
मूरतिः सनातनः।धर्मात्मजः संब-
भूव … ॥कृते युगे महाराज पुरा स्वा-
यंभुवे ऽन्तरे।नरो नारायणश् चैव
हरिः कृष्णस् तथैव च॥) 12. 321. 8-9;
(4) In the Devayuga when the Daityendras
ruled the three worlds Viṣṇu entered the
womb of Aditi (पुरा देवयुगे तात … ) 13.
82. 24-25; (5) In the Devayuga Prajā-
pati had two daughters (पुरा देवयुगे … )
1. 14. 5 (Nī. on Bom. Ed. 1. 16. 5: देव-
युगे सत्ययुगे); (6) In the Kṛta Yuga
all gods approached Varuṇa and requested
him to be the ruler of waters 9. 46. 5-6;
(7) In the Devayuga, Āditya came down
from the heaven to visit the world of mortals
when he met Nārada (पुरा देवयुगे
राजन् … ) 2. 11. 1; (8) In one of the past
Devayugas, the gods, desirous of giving
offerings, arranged the sacrifice following the
prescriptions of the Vedas (ततो देवयुगे
ऽतीते देवा वै समकल्पयन्।यज्ञम् वेद-
प्रमाणेन विधिवद् यष्टुम् ईप्सवः) 10.
18. 1; (9) Lomaśa told Yudhiṣṭhira that
formerly in the Devayuga he had seen that
the gods liked the धर्म and the Asuras
deserted it (पुरा देवयुगे चैव दृष्टं
सर्वं मया विभो।अरोचयन् सुरा धर्-
मं धर्मं तत्यजिरे ऽसुराः) 3. 92. 6;
(10) Gods and demons churned the ocean
in the Ādiyuga 6. 76. 18; (11) There were
fierce Dānavas, known as Kāleyas, in the
Kṛta Yuga 3. 98. 3; (12) Asura Gṛtsa
carried away the wife of Bhṛgu in the Deva-
yuga (पुरा देवयुगे तात … ) 12. 3. 19;
(13) In the Kṛta Yuga Manu held the
दण्ड (आसीत् कृतयुगे पूर्वं मनुर्
दण्डधरः प्रभुः) 14. 4. 2; (14)
God Nārāyaṇa told the seven sages (12. 322.
27, 31) that the अनुशासन promulgated by
him and the शास्त्र, together with the अङ्गस्
and the Upaniṣad, will be established by
them in Bṛhaspati Āṅgirasa in the Kṛta Yuga
(not directly named) (उत्पन्ने ऽङ्गिरसे चैव
युगे प्रथमकल्पिते।साङ्गोपनिषदं
शास्त्रं स्थापयित्वा बृहस्पतौ) 12. 322.
51; (15) In the Kṛta there was a famous
sage Taṇḍi who, as a devotee, propitiated
god for ten thousand years by practising
समाधि 13. 16. 12; (16) Formerly in the
the Kṛta Yuga an excellent Brāhmaṇa called
Ārṣṭiṣeṇa lived in a गुरुकुल; he studied
diligently, but could not complete the study
of either the विद्यास् or the Vedas (पुरा
कृतयुगे … ) 9. 39. 3-4; (17) Formerly in
the Kṛta Yuga there lived a king Avikam-
paka who was overpowered in battle by
enemies (पुरा कृतयुगे तात … ) 12. 248. 7;
(18) In the Kṛta Yuga there was a famous
sage Sāvarṇi who practised austerities for
six thousand years to satisfy Rudra 13.
14. 70; (19) Formerly in the Kṛta
Yuga there was a sage Vyāghrapāda who
was versed in the Vedas and the Vedāṅgas
(पुरा कृतयुगे तात … ) 13. 14. 75;
(20) In the Dharmayuga, when Janaka
ruled Mithilā, a certain भिक्षुकी called
Sulabhā roamed alone on the earth 12. 308.
7; (21) In the Prājāpatyayuga (i. e. the
Kṛtayuga) there once lived a large camel
who remembered his previous lives (जातिस्-
मरः); he observed scrupulously the vows
and practised severe austerities in a forest
12. 113. 4; (22) Formerly in the Kṛta
Yuga a Rākṣasa called Cārvāka practised
austerities in the Badarī Āśrama and was
blessed with a boon by Brahman (पुरा
कृतयुगे … ) 12. 39. 39; (23) Nārāyaṇa
told Nārada that formerly in the Kṛta Yuga
when the Veda and the श्रुति were lost, he
retrieved them and (the worlds) were again
supplied with the Vedas and the श्रुतिस् (?)
(यदा वेदश्रुतिर् नष्टा मया प्रत्याहृता
पुरा।सवेदाः सश्रुतीकाश् च कृताः पूर्वं
कृते युगे॥) 12. 326. 94; (24) Formerly,
during the second birth of Brahmā from the
eyes of Nārāyaṇa in the Kṛta Yuga, Rudra,
who received the धर्म of the Ekāntins
from Soma and who practised योग, taught
it to the Vālakhilyas ( … पुरा कृतयुगे
नृप) 12. 336. 15-16; the practice of the
धर्म of the Ekāntins formed such an
important characteristic of the Kṛta Yuga
that if in any other Yuga the world became
full of the Ekāntins that would mean the
advent of the Kṛta Yuga—this is what
Vaiśaṃpāyana told Janamejaya (यद्य् एकान्-
तिभिर् आकीर्णं जगत् स्यात् कुरुनन्दन।
 … भवेत् कृतयुगप्राप्तिः) 12. 336. 58;
(25) Hari-Nārāyaṇa told Brahmā, born
for the fourth time from his ears (12. 336.
23), to learn the Sātvata Dharma, from
him and establish it in the Kṛta Yuga
12. 336. 27; this धर्म was hence called
Kārtayugadharman 12. 336. 29; Brahmā, as
instructed by Nārāyaṇa, initiated first the
Kṛta Yuga and then the Sātvata धर्म
spread among the people 12. 336. 31; (26)
In the fifth birth of Brahman from the nose
of Nārāyaṇa (12. 336. 36), at the beginning
of the Kṛtayuga, Prajāpati Vīraṇa learnt the
Sātvata Dharma from Sanatkumāra 12. 336.
37; (27) In the seventh birth of Brahman
from a lotus (12. 336. 44), Nārāyaṇa him-
self instructed Pitāmaba in the Sātvata
धर्म at the beginning of the Kṛta Yuga
(not named) तत्रैष धर्मः कथितः
स्वयं नारायणेन हि॥पितामहाय शुद्-
धाय युगादौ लोकधारिणे) 12. 336.
44-45; (28) At the request of Yudhiṣṭhira
Bhīṣma told him how at the beginning,
in the Kṛta Yuga, a kingdom first came
into existence (यथा राज्यं समुत्पन्-
नम् आदौ कृतयुगे ऽभवत्) 12. 59. 13;
(29) Formerly in the Kṛta Yuga the ascetics
residing in the Naimiṣa forest were engaged
in a twelve-yearly sacrificial session (पूर्वं
कृतयुगे राजन् … ) 9. 36. 39.
F. Nārāyaṇa
(Kṛṣṇa) and the Kṛta Yuga: Bhagavān
Nārāyaṇa (who was the same as Kṛṣṇa-
Janārdana 3. 187. 52, 50) told Mārkaṇḍeya
that his colour in the Kṛta Yuga was white
(श्वेतः कृतयुगे वर्णः) 3. 187. 31; Bhīṣma
told Yudhiṣṭhira that Kṛṣṇa was complete
Dharma in the Kṛta Yuga (कृते युगे धर्म
आसीत् समग्रः) 13. 143. 9.
G. King and
the Kṛta Yuga: The king is the creator of
the Kṛta Yuga (राजा कृतयुगस्रष्टा) 5.
130. 16 = 12. 70. 25, (also cf. राजा कालस्य
कारणम् 12. 70. 6); Kṛta and the remaining
three Yugas depend on the conduct of the
king and hence the king is identical with
Yuga (राजवृत्तानि सर्वाणि राजैव युगम्
उच्यते) 12. 92. 6; (राजमूलानि सर्वाणि)
12. 139. 10; when the king fully followed
दण्डनीति then prevailed the Kṛta Yuga, the
best of time (दण्डनीत्यां यदा राजा सम्यक्
कार्त्स्न्येन वर्तते।तदा कृतयुगं नाम
कालः श्रेष्ठः प्रवर्तते॥) 5. 130. 14 =
12. 70. 7; Dyumatsena told Satyavān that in
the Kṛta Yuga the king followed the instruc-
tion (how a king should rule 12. 259. 24-30)
as his primary principle (एतत् प्रथम-
कल्पेन राजा कृतयुगे ऽभजत्) 12. 259. 32;
a king, as the creator of Kṛta, enjoyed in
the heaven endlessly (कृतस्य करणाद् राजा
स्वर्गम् अत्यन्तम् अश्नुते) 5. 130. 17 =
12. 70. 26; king Yayāti was described by
Aṣṭaka as the best among those born in the
Kṛta Yuga (कार्तयुगप्रधान) 1. 85. 1
(Nī. on Bom. Ed. 1. 90. 1: कार्तयुगप्र-
धान।कृतयुगे भवाः कार्तयुगाः।अत्य-
न्तनिष्पापा तेषां मुख्यतमेत्य् अर्थः).
H. Kṛta and धर्म: In the Kṛta Yuga
the ancient धर्म prevails (यत्र धर्मः
सनातनः) 3. 148. 10; in that Yuga the eternal
धर्म of the four वर्णस् stands on all its
four feet (i. e. is in no way deficient) (कृते
युगे चतुष्पादश् चातुर्वर्ण्यस्य शाश्वतः)
3. 148. 21; formerly in the Kṛta Yuga Dharma,
the bull, without deceit and free from vices
stood established in its entirety among men
(कृते चतुष्पात् सकलो निर्व्याजोपाधिवर्-
जितः।वृषः प्रतिष्ठितो धर्मो मनुष्येष्व्
अभवत् पुरा॥) 3. 188. 10 (Nī. on 3.
190. 9: वृष इव चतुष्पात्); 12. 327. 73;
both धर्म, on its four feet, and truth
are fully established in the Kṛta Yuga
(चतुष्पात् सकलो धर्मः सत्यं चैव
कृते युगे) 12. 224. 22; since धर्म is not
contaminated by अधर्म (नाधर्मेणा-
गमः कश्चित् 12. 224. 22) it does not get
diminished (धर्मो न ह्रसते क्वचित्) 1.
58. 22; धर्म always prospers and अधर्म
is destroyed 3. 189. 7; 12. 70. 8; धर्म
in the Kṛta Yuga was established among
the Brāhmaṇas who had mastered their self,
who had practised austerities and who had
studied the Vedas (आत्मवत्सु तपोवत्सु
श्रुतवैसु प्रतिष्ठितः) 12. 224. 67; धर्म
in different Yugas is different 12. 224. 26 =
12. 252. 8; austerity is the best धर्म
for the Kṛta (तपः परं कृतयुगे) 12.
24. 27; in the Kṛta Yuga the only धर्म
is renunciation (धर्मः संन्यास एव
च) 3. 148. 13; one is not supposed to
get angry in the Kṛta Yuga (न रोषं
कर्तुम् अर्हसि।नैष धर्मः कृतयुगे
यस् त्वं रोषम् अचीकृथाः) 12. 323. 17.
I. Kṛta and the sacrifice: In the Kṛta
Yuga performance of sacrifices is not pre-
scribed (त्रेतायुगे विधिस् त्व् एषां यज्ञा-
नां न कृते युगे) 12. 224. 62; the sages
who assembled for a sacrifice told gods who
wanted a goat to be killed that that was
not the धर्म of good people; they reminded
the gods that they were in the Kṛta Yuga
when an animal was not offered (नैष
धर्मः सतां देवा यत्र वध्येत वै
पशुः।इदं कृतयुगं श्रेष्ठं कथं
वध्येत वै पशुः॥) 12. 324. 5; (अहिंस्या
यज्ञपशवो युगे ऽस्मिन् नैतद् अन्यथा) 12.
327. 73; the offerings offered by Brahman and
others to Viṣṇu in a Vaiṣṇava Kratu were
offered according to the prescriptions meant
for the Kṛta Yuga and, as a result, they reach-
ed the Puruṣa who had the brightness of the
sun and who was above darkness (ते कार्त-
युगधर्माणो भागा परमसत्कृताः।
प्रापुर् आदित्यवर्णं तं पुरुषं तमसः
परम्॥) 12. 327. 50 (commentator Vidyā-
sāgara: कार्तयुगधर्माणः अहिंसादि-
लक्षणकृतस्वभावाः मन्त्रलोपतन्त्रलोप-
क्रियालोपहिंसादिरहिताः परमसंस्कृताः,
cf. the note on this stanza in the Cr. Ed.);
but according to Bhīṣma when the king, in
any other Yuga, employed दण्डनीती properly,
condition was as good as in the Kṛta Yuga
(12. 70. 7); in such a Kṛta Yuga, all the
three Varṇas offered Soma sacrifices according
to rites (सोमे प्रयत्नं कुर्वन्ति त्रयो
वर्णा यथाविधि) (Editor's note on the
stanza: सोमे = देवतादीन् उद्दिश्य सोमयागे)
and the Vedic rites were faultlessly performed
(वैदिकानि च कर्माणि भवन्त्य् अविगुणान्य्
उत) 12. 70. 9.
J. Nature of the Kṛta
Yuga, its effects on men: Hanūmant told
Bhīma that the times in the Kṛta Yuga were
different from those in the other Yugas
(अन्यः कृतयुगे कालस् त्रेतायां द्वापरे
परः) 3. 148. 6; Kṛta Yuga described by
different persons: (1) by Hanūmant to
Bhīma 3. 148. 11-22 (Kṛta Yuga was com-
pletely free from the three qualities (viz.
सत्त्व, रजस् and तमस्) (त्रैगुण्यपरि-
वर्जितम् 3. 148. 22); (2) by Vaiśaṃpāyana
to Janamejaya 1. 58. 8-24 (काले गावः
प्रसूयन्ते नार्यश् च भरतर्षभ।
फलन्त्य् ऋतुषु वृक्षाश् च पुष्पाणि च
फलानि च॥ 1. 58. 23); (3) by Mārka-
ṇḍeya to the Pāṇḍavas 3. 189. 8-13 (षट्-
कर्मनिरता विप्राः क्षत्रिया रक्षणे रताः॥
शुस्रूषायां रताः शूद्रास् तथा वर्णत्र-
यस्य च।एष धर्मः कृतयुगे … ॥ 3.
189. 12-13); (4) by Bhīṣma to Yudhi-
ṣṭhira (when a king in any Yuga practised
दण्डनीति properly) 12. 70. 8-13 (the quali-
ties of Kṛta age are called कार्तयुगान् गुण्गान्
12. 70. 13, also कार्तयुगधर्माणो भागाः
12. 327. 50); (5) by Saṃjaya to Dhṛta-
rāṣṭra 6. 11. 8-9; in general the people of
the Kṛta Yuga were possessed of fortitude,
were diligent in their duties, knew the proper
time for the use of valour (धृतिमन्तश् च
दक्षाश् च स्वे स्वे कर्मणि भारत।परा-
क्रमविधानज्ञा नराः कृतयुगे ऽभवन्)
3. 159. 2; the ascetics of the Kṛta Yuga were
calm and they remained steady in the सत्त्व
quality (तपस्विनः प्रशान्ताश् च सत्त्वस्थाश्
च कृते युगे) 12. 230. 7 (Nī. on Bom. Ed.
12. 238. 7: प्रशान्ताः निःसंशयाः); all the
ascetics then made no distinction between
पौरुष, दैव and स्वभाव as the cause
of the success in कर्म and had neither love
nor hatred for the ऋच्स्, the यजुसेस् and the
सामन्स्; hence they practised austerities (and
did not perform sacrifices) अपृथग्दर्शिनः
सर्वे ऋक्सामसु यजुःषु च।कामद्वेषौ
पृथग् दृष्ट्वा तपः कृत उपासते॥) 12.
230. 8 (Nī., however, on Bom. Ed. 12.
238. 8: वेदत्रये ऽपि भेदम् अपश्यन्तः
काम्यादीन् पृथक्कृत्य तपो ज्ञानम् उपासते
श्रयन्ति); 12. 224. 63 (Kṛta not mentioned,
but Nī., on Bom. Ed. 12. 232. 33 supplies it:
अद्वैतनिष्ठा मर्त्यास् तप एव योगम् एव
कृतयुगे ऽनुतिष्ठन्तीति शेषः); when Dhṛta-
rāṣṭra, Pāṇḍu and Vidura were born the
country of the Kurus (कुरुजाङ्गलम्), the
Kurus themselves and the Kurukṣetra, all
prospered 1. 102. 1; at that time a condition
similar to the Kṛta Yuga prevailed in the
regions of the different kingdoms (प्रदे-
शेष्व् अपि राष्ट्राणां कृतम् युगम् अवर्तत)
1. 102. 5; this condition is described in 1.
102. 2-11; people in the Kṛta Yuga did not
have to cohabit to beget children, they could
have them by mere thought (न चैषां
मैथुनो धर्मो बभूव भरतर्षभ।
संकल्पाद् एव चैतेषाम् अपत्यम् उदपद्-
यत॥) 12. 200. 35; in the Kṛta Yuga evil
tribes like the Talavaras, the Andhrakas etc.
in the south and the Yaunas (Yavanas),
Kāmbojas etc. in the north did not exist on the
earth 12. 200. 39-43; there were no भिक्षुस्
and those who have sectarian marks (लिङ्गि-
नः); similarly there were no alternatives to
the four आश्रमस्; all this happened when the
Kṛta Yuga passed away and the दण्डनीति
was no longer practised—thus Indra told to
Māndhātṛ 12. 65. 24-25.
K. Expecta-
tion of life: In the Kṛta Yuga people were
free from diseases, succeeded in achieving all
objectives and lived for four hundred years
(अरोगाः सर्वसिद्धार्थाश् चतुर्वर्षशता-
युषः।कृते) 12. 224. 24; however, according
to Saṃjaya people lived for four thousand
years (चत्वारि च सहस्राणि वर्षाणां
कुरुसत्तम।आयुःसंख्या कृतयुगे सं-
ख्याता राजसत्तम॥) 6. 11. 5 (apparently
there is confusion between the duration of
the Kṛta Yuga (above section C) and life-
expectancy of human beings); also cf.
सहस्रशतजीविनः ताः प्रजाः … ॥ … एवं
कृतयुगे सम्यग् वर्तमाने तदा नृप)
1. 58. 10, 24; men lived as long as they liked
and they had no fear of Yama 12. 200. 34;
(न क्षीयन्ते च वै प्रजाः) 3. 148. 11;
(नाल्पायुर् दृश्यते नरः) 12. 70. 11; but
the life expectation, virility etc. decrease
successively in the Yugas that follow the
Kṛta (आयुर् वीर्यम् अथो बुद्धिर् … मनु-
ष्याणाम् अनुयुगं ह्रसतीति निबोध मे) 3.
188. 13.
L. Kṛta as the name of Sūrya:
Kṛta appears among the 108 names of Sūrya
taught by Dhaumya to Yudhiṣṭhira 3. 3. 22.
M. Etymology: The etymology is implied
when it is said that in the Kṛta Yuga
(whatever needs be done) is done and does
not remain undone (कृतम् एव न कर्त-
व्यं तस्मिन् काले युगोत्तमे) 3. 148. 10
[Nī. on Bom. Ed. 3. 149. 11: कृतम् एव
सर्वे कृतकृत्या एवेत्य् अर्थः।तत एव
हेतोः कृतयुगं नाम॥). [Nī., Bom. Ed.
3. 191. 3, who reads विप्रैश् चोरक्षयश्
चैव कृते क्षेमं भविष्यति in place of
the Cr. Ed. विप्रैश् चोरक्षये चैव कृते (3.
189. 3) interprets कृते युगे; the words कृत,
त्रेता etc. occurring in 5. 140. 7-15 (= Bom.
Ed. 5. 142. 7-15) are interpreted by Nī. as
the Yuga names and not as names of the
throws of dice in a dice game].

कृत्तिका
Kṛttikā f. (pl.): Name of a conste-
llation (the Pleiads); (personified as the
mothers of Skanda, said to be the wives of
the six seers Aṅgiras and others 3. 214.
1-16; 3. 218. 30; 3. 207. 4; 3. 218. 27;
9. 43. 10-13; 9. 45. 86; 13. 84. 76; 13. 86.
5, 8, 10, 13; hence Skanda known as Kārtti-
keya (कृत्तिकाभ्युपपत्तेश् च कार्त्तिकेय इति
स्मृतः) 1. 60. 23; 9. 43. 16; 13. 84. 77; 13.
86. 14, 32).
A. Formation of the constellation:
When the constellation Abbhijit left her place
in the sky and went to the forest to practise
austerities there was confusion in the calcula-
tion of time; Kṛttikās then went up to the
heaven to fill in the gap; there they shine as
a constellation, having the form of a cart,
with god Fire as their regent (एवम् उक्ते तु
शक्रेण त्रिदिवं कृत्तिका गताः।नक्षत्रं
शकटाकारं भाति तद् वह्निदैवतम्॥)
3. 219. 11.
B. Number: Their number
is six 3. 134. 12.
C. Rites performed
under the Kṛttikās: (1) Nārada told Devakī
(13. 63. 2-4) that if one satisfied the Brāh-
maṇas under the Kṛttikās by feeding them
with rice boiled with milk and sprinkled with
clarified butter (पायसेन ससर्पिषा) one
obtained the highest worlds 13. 63. 5; (2)
Yama told Śaśabindu (13. 89. 1) that if
one offered a काम्य श्राद्ध regularly under
the Kṛttikās that was as good as perform-
ing a sacrifice after establishing the fires;
such a person was blessed with progeny and
was free from affliction (विगतज्वरः) 13.
89. 2; (3) By bathing in Māhāgaṅgā at
the conjunction of Mars with the Kṛttikās
(महागङ्गाम् उपस्पृश्य कृत्तिकाङ्गारके
तथा) and by fasting for a fortnight one
was purified and obtained heaven 13. 26. 20;
(4) Aṅgiras told Gautama that if one who
was well composed went on the Urvaśī-
kṛttikāyoga (?) to the Lauhitya तीर्थ and
bathed there according to the rites one
obtained the fruit of performing the Puṇḍa-
rīka sacrifice (उर्वशीकृत्तिकायोगे गत्वा यः
सुसमाहितः।लौहित्ये विधिवत् स्नात्वा
पुण्डरीकफलं लभेत्॥) 13. 26. 43
(Nī. reads उर्वशीं कृत्तिकायोगे (Bom. Ed.
13. 25. 46) and explains: उर्वशीं उर्वशी-
तीर्थं कृत्तिकायोगे कार्तिक्यां पौर्णमा-
स्याम्);
D. Places named after the
Kṛttikās: (1) An आश्रम (आश्रमे कृत्तिका-
नां तु); if one, after bathing at this
आश्रम and delighting Mahādeva, satisfied
the पितृस् he obtained heaven 13. 26. 23;
(2) A तीर्थ named jointly after the
Kṛttikās and the Maghā (कृत्तिकामघयोश्
चैव तीर्थम्); by visiting this तीर्थ one
obtained the fruits of Agniṣṭoma and Atirātra
sacrifices 3. 82. 46.
E. The Kṛttikās
and the sword: When Brahmā created the
sword as a weapon the day was presided over
by the Kṛttikās (कृत्तिकाश् चास्य नक्षत्रम्
असेः) 12. 160. 80.
F. Relationship with
omens: Among the bad omens reported by
Vyāsa to Dhṛtarāṣṭra before the war, there
was one according to which the fierce ग्रह
(i. e. Rāhu) blazed in the Kṛttikās, wiped
out their appearance by its lustre and stood
like a comet (कृत्तिकासु ग्रहस् तीव्रो नक्षत्रे
प्रथमे ज्वलन्।वपूंष्य् अपहरन् भासा
धूमकेतुर् इव स्थितः॥) 6. 3. 26 (Nī.
who reads कृत्तिकां पीडयंस् तीक्ष्णैः (Bom.
Ed. 6. 3. 30) explains: तीक्ष्णैः क्रूरैः
कर्मभिर् उपलक्षितो राहुर् इत्य् अर्थः).
G. Simile: The king of the Prāgjyotiṣa
(Bhagadatta), riding on an elephant, was
covered with a parasol decorated with gar-
lands of flowers and hence looking like a
moon on the full moon night in conjunction
with the Kṛttikās (कृत्तिकायोगयुक्तेन
पौर्णमास्याम् इवेन्दुना) 7. 19. 18. [See
Āgneya]

कौमुद
Kaumuda m.; adj.: Name of the month
Kārttika; of the month of Kaumuda.
Described as occurring in the autumn
season (शारद) 13. 116. 70; Kṛṣṇa set out
for Hāstinapura on his peace mission towards
the end of the autumn season and at the ad-
vent of the winter, in the month of Kaumuda,
and under the constellation Revatī (कौमुदे
मासि रेवत्यां शरदन्ते हिमागमे) 5. 81. 7;
according to Bhīṣma, observance of धर्म
consisted in avoiding all kind of meat in the
Kaumuda month, especially in the bright fort-
night (कौमुदे तु विशेषेण शुक्लपक्षे
नराधिप।वर्जयेत् सर्वमांसानि धर्मो
ह्य् अत्र विधीयते) 13. 116. 60; Bhīṣma told
Yudhiṣṭhira that many kings in the past like
Nābhāga, Ambarīṣa and others (13. 116.
65-70) had given up meat in the (bright) fort-
night of the month of Kaumuda (कौमुदं
पक्षम्) 13. 116. 64; they gave up meat in
the month of Kaumuda and attained heaven
13. 116. 70.

कौमुदी
Kaumudī f.: The full moon day of the
Kaumuda month (i. e. of Kārttika).
One who gives food on the full moon day
of the bright half of the month of Kaumuda
gets over difficulties and attains immense
happiness after death (कौमुद्यां शुक्ल-
पक्षे तु यो ऽन्नदानं करोत्य् उत) 13. 65.
60; also a festival celebrated on that day is
called Kaumudī; the demons Sunda and Upa-
sunda, when the two received the boon from
Pitāmaha, observed it out of time with their
friends and fulfilled every desire of the parti-
cipant (अकालकौमुदीं चैव चक्रतुः
सार्वकामिकीम्।दैत्येन्द्रौ परमप्रीतौ
तयोश् चैव सुहृज्जनः) 1. 201. 29.

गुरु
Guru m.: The planet Jupiter. See
Bṛhaspati.

चित्रा
Citrā f.: Name of a constellation.
A. Religious rites: (1) Nārada told
Devakī (13. 63. 2-4) that if one gave as a
gift a bull and auspicious perfumes under
Citrā (चित्रायाम्) one moved in the world
of the Apsarases and enjoyed in the Nandana-
vana 13. 63. 17; (2) Yama told Śaśabindu
(13. 89. 1) that by offering a काम्य श्राद्ध
under Citrā one got handsome sons 13. 89.
7.
B. Bad omens: (1) Karṇa pointed
out to Kṛṣṇa that the Kauravas were facing
great danger because the planet (Mahāpāta)
was severely afflicting Citrā (नूनं महद्
भयं कृष्ण कुरूणां समुपस्थितम्।
विशेषेण हि वार्ष्णेय चित्रां पीडयते ग्र-
हः॥) 5. 141. 9 (Nī. on Bom. Ed. 5. 143.
10: चित्रां ग्रहो महापाताख्यो ज्योतिः-
शास्त्रप्रसिद्धः।तेन राकारस्य वेधाद्
राजजातीयानां क्षयो भवितेति भावः।);
(2) Among the bad omens pointed out by
Vyāsa to Dhṛtarāṣṭra there was one according
to which a Śvetagraha (also called a harsh
ग्रह = Ketu) had gone beyond Citrā and
was at the beginning of Svāti (श्वेतो ग्रहस्
तथा चित्रां समतिक्रम्य तिष्ठति) 6. 3. 11
(Nī. on Bom. Ed. 6. 3. 12: श्वेतो ग्रहः
केतुश् चित्राम् अतिक्रामति स्वात्यादौ वर्तते);
(चित्रास्वात्यन्तरे चैव धिष्ठितः परुषो
ग्रहः) 6. 3. 16.

चैत्र
Caitra m.: Name of a month.
Aṅgiras had told Bhīṣma (13. 109. 9-
10) that if one, with restrained mind, spent
the month of Caitra eating only once a day
he was born in a noted family that was rich
with gold, gems and pearls 13. 109. 22;
Nārada told the Pāṇḍavas that Brahmadeva
and other gods, the Seers, the Siddhas and the
Cāraṇas visit the famous and very holy con-
fluence of the river Sarasvatī where Janārdana
was worshipped (सङ्गमं लोकविश्रुतम्।
सरस्वत्या महापुण्यम् उपासन्ते जनार्-
दनम्॥ 3. 80. 130) on the fourteenth day
of the bright half of Caitra (3. 80. 131);
if a king was threatened by a stronger adver-
sary (12. 69. 32) he should, in the month
of Caitra when there was fear of fire, get in
advance all houses, that were covered with
grass, smeared with mud and remove the
grass from them (तृणच्छन्नानि वेश्मानि
पङ्केनापि प्रलेपयेत्।निर्हरेच् च तृणं
मासे चैत्रे वह्निभयात् पुरः) 12. 69. 45.

चैत्री
Caitrī f.; adj.: Name of the day of the
full moon in the month of Caitra; occurring
in Caitra.
Vyāsa told Yudhiṣṭhira that he will be
consecrated for the Aśvamedha sacrifice on
the full moon day of Caitra (चैत्र्यां हि
पौर्णमास्यां च तव दीक्षा भविष्यति)
14. 71. 4; after defeating Vajradatta, son of
Bhagadatta of the Prāgjyotiṣa, Arjuna invited
him to attend the Aśvamedha sacrifice of
Dharmarāja which would take place on the
following full moon day of Caitra (आगच्-
छेत्था महाराज परां चैत्रीम् उपस्थि-
ताम्।तदाश्वमेधो भविता धर्मराजस्य
धीमतः) 14. 75. 25; he similarly invited
Babhruvāhana 14. 82. 24, Meghasaṃdhi
(grandson of Jarāsaṃdha, son of Sahadeva)
14. 83. 27, and Śakuni's son 14. 85. 23;
marching out of an army for attack is re-
commended on the full moon day of Caitra
or Mārgaśīrṣa for the crops are then ripe and
there is ample water; it is also then neither
too hot nor too cold (चैत्र्यां वा मार्ग-
शीर्ष्यां वा सेनायोगः प्रशस्यते।पक्व-
सस्या हि पृथिवी भवत्य् अम्बुमती तथा॥
नैवातिशीतो नात्युष्णः कालो भवति भारत।
तस्मात् तदा योजयेत) 12. 101. 9-10.

जय
Jaya m.: Name of a मुहूर्त।
Drupada asked his Purohita, whom he
dispatched as his दूत to the Kauravas, to
start for Hāstinpura at the time of the con-
junction of the moon with Puṣya नक्षत्र
and under the मुहूर्त Jaya (स भवान्
पुष्ययोगेन मुहूर्तेन जयेन च।कौर-
वेयान् प्रयात्व् आशु) 5. 6. 17.

ज्येष्ठा
Jyeṣṭhā f.: Name of a constellation,
also called Aindra (1. 114. 4; 6. 3. 15).
A. Epic event related to this नक्षत्र:
Kuntī gave birth to Yudhiṣṭhira on the day
when the moon was in conjunction with the
Aindra नक्षत्र (लेभे पुत्रं वरारोहा
 … ऐन्द्रे चन्द्रसमायुक्ते) 1. 114. 3-4
(Nī. on Bom. Ed. 1. 123. 6: ऐन्द्रे ज्ये-
ष्ठानक्षत्रे अष्टमे संवत्सरारम्भात्).
B. Religious rites performed under this
नक्षत्र: Nārada told Devakī (13. 63.
2-4) that if one gave to the Brāhmaṇas
कालशाक with roots under Jyeṣṭhā one ob-
tained prosperity wished for and cherished
condition after death (कालशाकं तु विप्रे-
भ्यो दत्त्वा मर्त्यः समूलकम्।ज्येष्ठा-
याम् ऋद्धिम् इष्टां वै गतिम् इष्टां च
विन्दति) 13. 63. 23; Yama told Śaśabindu
(13. 89. 1) that if a man, with faith and
self-control, offered a काम्य श्राद्ध under
Jyeṣṭhā he got overlordship (आधिपत्यं
व्रजेन् मर्त्यः) 13. 89. 9.
C. Bad
omens: Among the bad omens pointed out
by Vyāsa to Dhṛtarāṣṭra there was one
according to which the blazing black planet
(i. e. Ketu), full of fire and smoke, had taken
hold of Jyeṣṭhā, which was the bright Aindra
नक्षत्र, and had remained there (श्यामो
ग्रहः प्रज्वलितः सधूमः सहपावकः।
ऐन्द्रं तेजस्वि नक्षत्रं ज्येष्ठाम् आक्र-
म्य तिष्ठति) 6. 3. 15 (Nī., who reads श्वेतो
ग्रहः in place of श्यामो ग्रहः, on Bom.
Ed. 6. 3. 16 also explains it as Ketu: श्वेतो
द्वितीय उपरहः केतुसंज्ञः ऐन्द्रं
ज्येष्ठानक्षत्रम् इति योज्यम्; among the
bad omens pointed out by Karṇa to Kṛṣṇa one
was related to the retrograde movement of
Mars in Jyeṣṭhā and his coveting Anurādhā
as though thereby tranquilizing the Maitra
Nakṣatrayoga (कृत्वा चाङ्गारको वक्रं
ज्येष्ठायां मधुसूदन।अनुराधां
प्रार्थयते मैत्रं संशमयन्न् इव॥)
5. 141. 8 (For Nī.'s commentary on Bom.
Ed. 5. 143. 9 See under Aṅgāraka, p. 229
above).

ज्येष्ठामूल
Jyeṣṭhāmūla m.: Name of the month
Jyaiṣṭha.
A. Religious rite performed in this
month: Aṅgiras had told Bhīṣma that if
a man or a woman passed the Jyeṣṭhāmūla
month eating only once a day, he or she
attained to prosperity which was incomparable
and best 13. 109. 24 (Nī. on Bom. Ed.
13. 106. 25: ज्येष्थामूलं ज्येष्ठमासम्).
B. Past event connected with this month:
Jamadagni shot arrows at midday in the
month Jyeṣṭhāmūla and asked his wife
Reṇukā to fetch them (ततो मध्याह्नम्
आरूढे ज्येष्ठामूले दिवाकरे।स सायकान्
द्विजो विद्ध्वा रेणुकाम् इदम् अब्रवीत्॥
गच्छानय विशालाक्षि शरान् एतान् धनु-
श्च्युतान्) 13. 97. 9-10 (Unknown commen-
tator: ज्येष्ठामूले ज्येष्ठमासे ज्येष्ठमा-
सस्य मध्याह्ने अतितीक्ष्णः [दिवाकरः] इति
सूचितम्। (cf. Cr. Edn. vol. 17, p. 1097, note
on this stanza; Nī., however, on Bom. Ed.
13. 95. 9: ज्येष्ठामूले दक्षिणावर्ते भ्र-
ममाणे भचक्रे ज्येष्ठानां समसूत्रे
पतितं रोहिणीनक्षत्रं तद् एव ज्येष्ठा-
नां मूलम्।यथाश्रुतार्थग्रहणं तु
न ज्येष्ठामूलस्थे ऽर्के हेमन्ते शिरःपाद-
दाहस्यानवसरात्॥).

तारामृग
Tārāmṛga m.: See Mṛgaśiras.

तिष्य
Tiṣya1: See Kaliyuga.

तिष्य
Tiṣya2: See Puṣya1.

त्रेता
Tretā f., Tretāyuga nt.: Name of the
second Yuga among the four Yugas.
A. Place among the four Yugas:
Second, occurs after Kṛta, hence mentioned
after it (पूर्वं कृतयुगं नाम ततस्
त्रेतायुगं विभो) 6. 11. 4; 6. 11. 3; 12.
224. 18; 12. 323. 50-51; after Tretā follows
Dvāpara (त्रेतानिर्मोक्षसमये द्वापर-
प्रतिपादने) 12. 139. 14; hence the junction
of these two युगस् is referred to (त्रेता-
द्वापरयोः सन्धौ) 1. 2. 3; 12. 139. 13;
12. 326. 78.
B. Duration: Mārkaṇḍeya
told Yudhiṣṭhira that the duration of the
Tretā Yuga was three thousand years, with
dawns of three hundred years and twilights
of the same duration (त्रीणि वर्षसहस्राणि
त्रेतायुगम् इहोच्यते।तस्य तावच्छती
संध्या संध्यांशस् च ततः परम्॥ …
संध्यासंध्यांशयोस् तुल्यं प्रमाणम्
उपधारय) 3. 186. 19, 21 (for Nī.'s ex-
planation of संध्या and संध्यांश, see
Kali, Section C); the same duration was
told by Vyāsa to Śuka without specifically
naming the Yuga but in relation to Kṛta
(इतरेषु ससंध्येषु ससंध्यांशेषु च
त्रिषु।एकापायेन संयान्ति सहस्राणि शतानि
च॥) 12. 224. 20.
C. Events: (1)
Bhagavān (Nārāyaṇa) told Nārada that in
the Tretāyuga, (first), he will be born as
Rāma in the family of the Bhṛgus and will
destroy the Kṣatriyas; and, (next), when the
junction of the Tretā and the Dvāpara will
have arrived he will be born as Rāma, son
of Daśaratha, to be the king of the world
(त्रेतायुगे भविष्यामि रामो भृगुकुलोद्-
वहः।क्षत्रं चोत्सादयिष्यामि … ॥सं-
धौ तु समनुप्राप्ते त्रेतायां द्वापर्-
अस्य च।रामो दाशर्थिर् भूत्वा भवि-
ष्यामि जगत्पतिः॥) 12. 326. 77-78; 1. 2. 3;
(2) A being without bodily form informed
from the sky (12. 323. 46) Ekata, Dvita
and Trita that when the Kṛtayuga had passed
and the Tretāyuga of the 7th मन्वन्तर
presided over by Manu Vaivasvata will have
arrived they will work as helpers of gods
for achieving a great purpose (वैवस्वते
ऽन्तरे विप्राः प्राप्ते त्रेतायुगे ततः।
सुराणां कार्यसिद्ध्यर्थं सहाया वै
भविष्यथ) 12. 323. 51; (cf. 12. 326. 79-
80); (3) Vyāsa told Yudhiṣṭhira that
Karaṃdhama's son (Avikṣit) was born at
the commencement of the Tretāyuga—he
was glorious, not inferior to Indra, and invin-
cible even by the gods 14. 4. 17; (4) Bhīṣma
told Yudhiṣṭhira that formerly at the junction
of the Tretā and the Dvāpara, a terrible
drought, lasting for twelve years, occurred
due to the working of the fate (दैवविधि-
क्रमात्) 12. 139. 13; when the Tretā was
about to end and the Dvāpara was about
to set in and when the end of the eon was at
hand Indra did not release rain (युगान्ते पर्-
युपस्थिते।त्रेतानिर्मोक्षसमये द्वापर-
प्रतिपादने॥न ववर्ष सहस्राक्षः)
12. 139. 14-15.
D. Nārāyaṇa-Kṛṣṇa and
Tretā: Bhagavān (Nārāyaṇa) told Mārka-
ṇḍeya that his colour in the Tretāyuga was
yellow (पीतस् त्रेतायुगे मम) 3. 187. 31;
but according to Hanūmant, Acyuta was
red in the Tretā (रक्ततां याति चाच्युतः)
3. 148. 23; Bhīṣma told Yudhiṣṭhira that
Kṛṣṇa conformed to ज्ञान in the Tretā
(त्रेताकाले ज्ञानम् अनुप्रपन्नः) 13. 143.
9 (Nī. on Bom. Ed. 13. 158. 10: ज्ञानम्
अकर्तव्यकोटेर् अपि उपस्थानात् त्रेतायां
विवेक आसीत्).
E. King and Tretā: When
the king observes दण्डनीति only in three
parts and leaves out the fourth, the Tretā-
yuga sets in; the place of the fourth part is
then made up by what is inauspicious and this
part gets associated with the other three,
hence the earth has to be ploughed for the
growth of the plants (दण्डनीत्या यदा राजा
त्रीन् अंशान् अनुवर्तते।चतुर्थम् अंशम्
उत्सृज्य तदा त्रेता प्रवर्तते॥अशुभस्य
चतुर्थांशस् त्रीन् अंशान् अनुवर्तते।कृष्ट-
पच्यैव पृथिवी भवन्त्योषध्यस् तथा॥)
12. 70. 14-15; (पादोनेनापि धर्मेण गच्-
छेत् त्रेतायुगे तथा) 12. 259. 32; a king is
the cause of the Tretā (as also of the other
three Yugas) (त्रेतायाः … । … राजा भवति
कारणम्) 5. 130. 16 = 12. 70. 25; (also cf.
राजा कालस्य कारणम् 12. 70. 6 = 5. 130. 15);
Tretā, like the other three Yugas, depends
on the conduct of the king and hence the
king is called a Yuga (राजवृत्तानि सर्वाणि
राजैव युगम् उच्यते) 12. 92. 6; (राज-
मूलानि सर्वाणि) 12. 139. 10; a king obtains
heaven, but not endlessly, because he intro-
duces Tretā (त्रेतायाः करणाद् राजा स्वर्गं
नात्यन्तम् अश्नुते) 5. 130. 17 = 12. 70. 26;
description of the people in the Tretā in the
absence of दण्डनीति 12. 65. 24-27;
F. Tretā and धर्म: In the Tretāyuga
Dharma loses one of its four feet (तत्र
(i. e. त्रेतायुगे) पादचतुर्थो वै धर्म्-
अस्य न भविष्यति) 12. 327. 74; (पादेन
ह्रसते धर्मः) 3. 148. 22-23; in the
Tretā, Dharma is established in three parts
and the remaining one part is affected by
अधर्म (अधर्मपादविद्धस् तु त्रिभिर्
अंशैः प्रतिष्ठितः।त्रेतायाम्) 3. 188. 11;
also of 12. 259. 32; in the Tretā and the
other two following Yugas the धर्म is
displaced from tradition successively by one
quarter and the अधर्म is on increase due
to thefts, falsehood and deceit (इतरेष्व्
(i. e. युगेषु) आगमाद् धर्मः पादशस्
त्व् अवरोप्यते।चौरिकानृतमायाभिर्
अधर्मश् चोपचीयते) 12. 224. 23; the
धर्मस् in the Tretā were different from
those in the Kṛta 12. 224. 26 = 12. 252. 8;
ज्ञान was considered to be the best धर्म
for the Tretā (त्रेतायां ज्ञानम् उत्तमम्)
12. 224. 27; Hanūmant told Bhīma that times
in the different Yugas were different 3. 148.
6; Vyāsa told his son Śuka that he had
heard that the study of the Vedas decreased
in every following Yuga and so also the
benefit derived by people from the Veda
(वेदवादाश् चानुयुगं ह्रसन्तीति च नः
श्रुतम्। … वेदस्यैव च यत् फलम्) 12.
224. 25; the Sātvata धर्म, which flourished
in the Kṛtayuga of the fourth birth of Brah-
man (12. 336. 25), disappeared when the
Tretā returned (ततः सो ऽन्तर्दधे भूयः
प्राप्ते त्रेतायुगे पुनः) 12. 336. 35; but
in the seventh birth of Brahman (12. 336.
44) the same Sātvata धर्म was taught
by Vivasvān to Manu 12. 326. 47; according
to Mārkaṇḍeya, however, the धर्म for
the Kṛta, the Tretā and the Dvāpara was
the same 3. 189. 13.
G. Tretā and the
sacrifice: There were no sacrifices in the
Kṛtayuga, but they all, very strong, collected
together appeared in the Tretā and be-
came controllers of those that move (living
beings) and those that do not (non-living
beings) (त्रेतायुगे विधिस् त्व् एषां यज्ञानां
न कृते युगे … त्रेतायां तु समस्तास् ते
प्रादुरासन् महाबलाः।संयन्तारः
स्थावराणां जङ्गमानां च सर्वशः॥
त्रेतायां संहता ह्य् एते यज्ञाः … ) 12.
224. 62, 64, 65 (Nī., however, on Bom. Ed.
12. 232. 34: त्रेतायां धर्मे नृणां स्वतः
प्रवृत्त्यभावात् तत्र संयन्तारो धर्म-
शास्तारो वेदाश् च संहता यज्ञाद्यनुष्ठा-
पनाय सन्नद्धा आसन्); Bhagavān (Nārā-
yana) told the gods that the three Vedas
will rule the Tretāyuga and then the animals,
consecrated for the sacrifice, will be killed
(ततस् त्रेतायुगं नाम त्रयी यत्र भवि-
ष्यति।प्रोक्षिता यत्र पशव वधं
प्राप्स्यन्ति वै मखे।) 12. 327. 74;
(त्रेताम् अपि निबोध त्वम् यस्मिन् सत्रं
प्रवर्तते) 3. 148. 22; (ततो यज्ञाः प्र-
वर्तन्ते धर्माश् च विविधाः क्रियाः।
त्रेतायां भावसंकल्पाः क्रियादानफलो-
दयाः॥) 3. 148. 24 (Nī. on Bom. Ed. 3.
149. 23: सत्रं यज्ञक्रिया रजोमिश्रत्वात्;
on 3. 149. 25: भावसंकल्पाः भावो
भावना क्रिया अहम् अनेन कर्मणा
इदं फलं अनेन प्रकारेण करिष्यामीत्य्
एवंरूपा तद्विषय एव संकल्पो येषाम्);
Vyāsa told Śuka that at the commencement
of the Tretā the Vedas and the sacrifices
are complete in form (त्रेतादौ सकला वेदा
यज्ञा वर्णाश्रामास् तथा) 12. 230. 14;
(also cf. Maheśvara (Viṣṇu) recommending
the performance of sacrifices for the benefit of
gods, and the gods, on their part, sustaining
the worlds in the Yugas (not named) other
than the Kṛta 12. 327. 53-60).
H. Nature
of the Tretāyuga: Hanūmant told Bhīma
that the times in the Tretā were different from
those in the Kṛta (अन्यः कृतयुगे कालस्
त्रेतायां द्वापरे ऽपरः) 3. 148. 6; Hanū-
mant then described to Bhīma the condition
of the world in the Tretāyuga 3. 148. 22-25
(men are truthful (सत्यप्रवऋत्ताश् च नराः),
they do not deviate from the path of धर्म,
are given to the practice of austerities and to
giving gifts); the Tretāyuga also described
by Saṃjaya to Dhṛtarāṣṭra (Kṣatriyas are
long-lived, they are great warriors, excellent
archers in war, brave and emperors) 6. 11. 10
(जायन्ते क्षत्रियाः शूरास् त्रेतायां चक्र-
वर्तिनः); according to Mārkaṇḍeya the
condition of धर्म in the Tretā is not
different from the one in the Kṛta described
by him (एष धर्मः कृतयुगे त्रेआयाम्)
3. 189 13; the ascetics in the Tretā, who
are steady in the सत्त्व गुण, have no
doubt whatever whether पुरुष, दैव
or स्वभाव is the cause of a man's success
in his activities; they see no distinction,
as same people for want of judgement do,
between them (पौरुषं कारणं केचिद्
आहुः कर्मसु मानवाः।दविअम् एके
प्रशंसन्ति स्वभावं चापरे जनाः॥ …
त्रयम् एतत् पृथग्भूतम् अविवेकं तु
केचन। … कर्मस्था विषमं ब्रूयुः
सत्त्वस्थाः समदर्शिनः॥ त्रेतायां …
तपस्विनः … ) 12. 230. 4, 6-7; in the Tretā,
as in the Kṛta, people could get progeny by
mere thought and did not have to cohabit
for this purpose (तत्र त्रेतायुगे काले सं-
कल्पाज् जायते प्रजा।न ह्य् अभूत् मैथुनो
धर्मस् तेषाम् अपि नराधिप॥) 12. 200.
36; evil tribes like the Talavaras, the
Andhrakas and others in the south and the
Yaunas (Yavanas), the Kāmbojas and others
in the north, unlike in the Kṛtayuga, begin
to roam about on the surface of the
earth from the Tretāyuga onwards (नैते
कृतयुगे तात चरन्ति पृथिवीम् इमाम्।
त्रेताप्रभृति वर्तन्ते ते जना भरतर्-
षभ॥) 12. 200. 42.
I. Span of life:
Vyāsa told Śuka that people in each suc-
ceeding Yuga lived a quarter years less
than those in the Kṛtayuga who lived for
four hundred years, i. e. in the Tretā they
lived for three hundred years (चतुर्वर्ष-
शतायुषः।कृते त्रेतादिष्व् एतेषां पादशो
ह्रसते वयः) 12. 224. 24; Vyāsa had heard
that life gradually decreased in each succes-
sive Yuga (अनुयुगं ह्रसन्तीति च नः
श्रुतम्।आयूंषि) 12. 224. 25; the same
thing was told by Mārkaṇḍeya to Yudhi-
ṣṭhira (आयुर् वीर्यम् अथो बुद्धिर् बलं
तेजश् च पाण्डव।मनुष्याणाम् अनुयुगं
ह्रसतीति निबोध मे) 3. 188. 13; however,
Saṃjaya, told Dhṛtarāṣṭra that people lived
for three thousand years in the Tretā (आयुः-
संख्या … संख्याता राजसत्तम।तथा
त्रीणि सहस्राणि त्रेतायां मनुजाधिप॥)
6. 11. 5-6 (apparently, in Saṃjaya's narra-
tion, there is confusion between the dura-
tion of the Tretāyuga (cf. section
B. above)
and the life expectancy of the people in this
Yuga).
J. Simile: The region where
the river Narmadā (f.) passes along the
Vaiḍūrya mountain (m.) is compared with
the conjunction of the Tretā (f.) and the
Dvāpara (m) (वैडूर्यपर्वतं दृष्ट्वा
नर्मदाम् अवतीर्य च।सन्धिर् एष नर-
श्रेष्ठ त्रेताया द्वापरस्य च॥) 3. 121.
18-19.
K. Name of Sūrya: Tretā
appears as the 47th name among the hundred
and eight names of Sūrya taught by Dhaumya
to Yudhiṣṭhira 3. 3. 22. [The words Kṛta,
Tretā and Dvāpara occurring in 5. 140. 7-
15 are wrongly interpreted by Nī. (Bom.
Ed. 5. 142. 7-15) as names of the three
Yugas and not as the names of the throws
of dice in a dice-game].

दक्षिणायन
Dakṣiṇāyana nt.: Name of the period
of six months in which the sun moves towards
the south (also expressed as दक्षिणावृत्त
आदित्ये 6. 114. 96).
A. Duration: It lasts for six months
(षण्मासा दक्षिणायनम्) 6. 30. 25.
B.
Association with darkness: Vyāsa told Śuka
that Dakṣiṇāyaṇa formed the night of the
gods (रात्रिः स्याद् दक्षिणायनम्) 12. 224.
16; Dakṣiṇāyana is associated with blind
darkness and the dark night (अन्धं तमस्
तमिस्रं च दक्षिणायनम् एव च) 13.
101. 46.
C. Bhīṣma's falling down in the
Dakṣiṇāyana and his death in the Uttarā-
yaṇa: When Bhīṣma fell down on the battle-
field he heard a heavenly voice in the mid-
region resounding all around saying “how
should the high-souled Gāṅgeya (Bhīṣma)
die when it was Dakṣiṇāyana ?” (कथं
महात्मा गाङ्गेयः … ।कालं कर्ता नर-
व्याघ्रः संप्राप्ते दक्षिणायने) 6. 114.
88; the great sages who, in the form of the
swans, were sent by Gaṅgā observed that the
sun was in the south when Bhīṣma fell from
the chariot (दक्षिणेन च भास्करम् 6. 114.
93); they said to each other: (it seems)
Bhīṣma, though high-souled, shall die when
it was Dakṣiṇāyaṇa (इतरेतरम् आमन्त्र्य
प्राहुस् तत्र मनीषिणः।भीष्म एव महा-
त्मा सन् संस्थाता दक्षिणायने॥) 6. 114.
94 (Nī. on Bom. Ed. 6. 119. 102: सं-
स्थाता मरिष्यति); Bhīṣma then assured the
sages that he had resolved that in no case
would he go (from this world) when the
sun was turned towards the south (तान्
अब्रवीच् छान्तनवो नाहं गन्ता कथं-
चन।दक्षिणावृत्त आदित्ये एतन् मे मनसि
स्थितम्॥) 6. 114. 96; Yudhiṣṭhira became
anxious when the realized that Bhīṣma had only
a few days to live in the Dakṣiṇāyana and
that he would soon leave for the highest state
when the sun had started moving (north-
wards) (शेषम् अल्पं द्मानां ते दक्षिणा-
यनभास्करे।आवृत्ते भगवत्य् अर्के गन्त्-
आसि परमां गतिम्॥) 12. 291. 4; the period
of Dakṣiṇāyaṇa, when Bhīṣma fell, is alluded
to in Bhīṣma's instruction to Yudhiṣṭhira to
come back to him when the sun had return-
ed (from the southerly course) (विनिवृत्ते
दिनकरे) 13. 152. 10; it is also alluded to
when Yudhiṣṭhira returned to meet Bhīṣma
(दृष्ट्वा निवृत्तम् आदित्यम् प्रवृत्तं चोत्तरा-
यणम्) 13. 153. 6; when Bhīṣma, on seeing
Yudhiṣṭhira, greeted him and said that the sun
had, indeed, returned (from the southerly
course) (परिवृत्तो हि भगवान् सहस्रांशुर्
दिवाकरः) 13. 153. 26; and when Bhīṣma,
composed in attitude, put his entire bodily
function in his self as soon as the sun had
returned (from the south) (निवृत्तमात्रे त्व्
अयने उत्तरे वै दिवाकरे।समावेशयद्
आत्मानम् आत्मन्य् एव समाहितः॥) 12. 47.
3; Bhīṣma finally died when the sun left the
southerly course and the Uttarāyaṇa had start-
ed (अकरोत् स ततः कालं शरतल्पगतो
मुनिः॥अयनं दक्षिणं हित्वा संप्राप्ते
चोत्तरायणे॥) 14. 59. 12.
D. Death in
the Dakṣiṇāyana: If a Yogī dies during the six
months of the Dakṣiṇāyana he, after reaching
the moon's realm of light, returns to this
world (षण्मासा दक्षिणायनम्।तत्र चान्-
द्रमसं ज्योतिर् योगी प्राप्य निवर्तते॥)
6. 30. 25; Nārada, while consoling Sṛñjaya
lamenting over the death of his son, told
him that Ambarīṣa, son of Nābhāga, and
hundreds of other kings who performed the
Aśvamedha, went towards the Dakṣiṇāyana
(i. e. died during the Dakṣiṇāyana) (सर्वे
ऽश्वमेधैर् ईजानास् ते ऽभ्ययुर् दक्षिणाय-
नम्) 12. 29. 96; (Nī., however, who reads
अन्वयुः, on Bom. Ed. 12. 29. 103: सर्वे
राजानः … दक्षिणायनम् अनु पश्चात् अयुर्
गताः।उत्तरायणमार्गेण हिरण्यगर्भ-
लोकं प्राप्ताः इत्य् अर्थः); but men who
perform bad deeds and who die in the
Dakṣiṇāyana wait upon Dharmarāja (Yama)
in his सभा (नरा दुष्कृतकर्माणो दक्षि-
णायनमृत्यवः। … उपासते धर्मराजम्)
2. 8. 28-29. [For most of the information
which is common to both the अयनस् the
Uttara and the Dakṣiṇa, see Uttarāyaṇa].

देवयुग
Devayuga nt.: See Kṛtayuga.

द्वापर
Dvāpara m., nt.: Name of the third
Yuga among the four Yugas.
A. Place among the four Yugas:
Its place is third, mentioned after the Tretā
and before the Kali (कृतं त्रेता द्वा-
परं च पुष्यं च कुरुवर्धन) 6.
11. 3; 12. 224. 18; the Dvāpara starts
when the Tretā ends (त्रेतानिर्मोक्षसमये
द्वापरप्रतिपादने) 12. 139. 14; and
the Kali starts when the Dvāpara ends
(सङ्क्षेपाद् द्वापरस्याथ ततः पुष्यं
प्रवर्तते) 6. 11. 4; hence also the junctions
of the Tretā and the Dvāpara on the one
hand and of the Dvāpara and the Kali
on the other are referred to 1. 2. 3; 12.
139. 13; 12. 326. 78; 1. 2. 9; 12. 326. 82.
B. Duration: Mārkaṇḍeya told Yudhiṣṭhira
that the duration of the Dvāpara Yuga was
two thousand years with dawns and twilights
of two hundred years each at both ends (तथा
वर्षसहस्रे द्वे द्वापरं परिमाणतः।
तस्यापि द्विशती संध्या संध्यांशस् च
ततः परम्॥संध्यासंध्यांशयोस् तुल्-
यं प्रमाणम् उपधारय) 3. 186. 20-
21 (for Nī's explanation of संध्या and
संध्यांश see above Kali, section C,
p. 234); the same duration for the Dvāpara
was told by Vyāsa to Śuka without naming
the Yuga, but indicating it in relation to the
Kṛta 12. 224. 20.
C. Events occurring
in the Dvāpara: (1) Bhīṣma told Yudhi-
ṣṭhira that formerly, at the junction of the
Tretā and the Dvāpara, there occurred a
terrible drought lasting for twelve years due
to the working of the fate (दैवविधि-
क्रमात्); when the Tretā was about to end
and the Dvāpara was to set in Indra did
not release rain for twelve years (त्रेतानिर्-
मोक्षसमये द्वापरप्रतिपादने॥न
ववर्ष सहस्राक्षः) 12. 139. 13-15; (2)
Sūta Ugraśravas told the sages assembled in
the Naimiṣa forest that at the junction of
the Tretā and the Dvāpara (त्रेताद्वापरयोः
संधौ) Rāma destroyed the princely
Kṣatriyas again and again 1. 2. 3 (but
see the next event); (3) Bhagavān (Nārā-
yaṇa) told Nārada that at the junction
of the Tretā and the Dvāpara (संधौ
तु समनुप्राप्ते त्रेतायां द्वापरस्य
च) he would be born as Rāma, son of
Daśaratha 12. 326. 78; (4) Bhagavān
(Nārāyaṇa) told Nārada that towards the end
of the junction of the Dvāpara and the Kali
(द्वापरस्य कलेश् चैव संधौ पर्यव-
सानिके) he would be born in Mathurā for (the
killing of) Kaṃsa 12. 326. 82; (5) at the
junction of the Dvāpara and the Kali the
armies of the Kurus and the Pāṇḍavas fought
each other near Samantapañcaka 1. 2. 9.
D.
Kṛṣṇa-Nārāyaṇa (Viṣṇu) and the Dvāpara:
(1) Bhagavān (Nārāyaṇa) told Mārka-
ṇḍeya that he has red colour in the Dvāpara
Yuga (रक्तो द्वापरम् आसाद्य) 3. 187. 31;
but according to Hanūmant Viṣṇu becomes
yellow in the Dvāpara (द्वापरे ऽपि युगे …
विष्णुर् वै पीततां याति) 3. 148. 26; (3)
Bhīṣma told Yudhiṣṭhira that Kṛṣṇa was
strength in the Dvāpara (बलं त्व् आसीद् द्वा-
परे पार्थ कृष्णः) 13. 143. 9.
E. King
and the Dvāpara: According to Utathya
Aṅgiras all the four Yugas depend on the
king's behaviour, hence a king himself is
called Yuga (राजवृत्तानि सर्वाणि राजैव
युगम् उच्यते) 12. 92. 6; Bhīṣma had no
doubt that all the Yugas were rooted in
a king (राजमूलानि सर्वाणि मम नास्त्य्
अत्र संशयः) 12. 139. 10; it is the king
who created a Yuga—whether it was the
Kṛta, the Tretā, or the Dvāpara 5. 130. 16 =
12. 70. 25 (also cf. राजा कालस्य कारणम्
5. 130. 15 = 12. 70. 6); when a king gives
up half of the दण्डनीति and practises only
one half of it, then the Dvāpara age sets
in (अर्धं त्यक्त्वा यदा राजा नीत्यर्धम्
अनुवर्तते।ततस् तु द्वापरं नाम स
कालः संप्रवर्तते॥) 12. 70. 16; the
धर्म practised by the king in the Dvāpara
is deficient in two quarters (द्वापरे तु
द्विपादेन (ऊनः)) 12. 259. 32; by bringing
about the Dvāpara a king lives in heaven
only according to his share (i. e. not for a long
time) (प्रवर्तनाद् द्वापरस्य (स्वर्गम्)
यथाभागम् य्पाश्नुते) 5. 130. 17 = 12. 70.
27; (description of the behaviour of people in
the Dvāpara in the absence of the दण्डनीति
12. 65. 24-27).
F. Dvāpara and धर्म:
In the Dvāpara Yuga, धर्म will lose two
of its four feet and the age will be marked
by a mixture (of धर्म and अधर्म)
(ततो वै द्वापरं नाम मिश्रः कालो
भविष्यति।द्विपादहीनो धर्मश् च युगे
तस्मिन् भविष्यति) 12. 327. 75; (द्वापरे
ऽर्धेन व्यामिश्रो धर्म उच्यते) 3. 188.
11 (Nī. on Bom. Ed. 3. 190. 10: अर्धेन
अधर्मेण); (अशुभस्य तदा अर्धं द्वाव्
अंशाव् अनुवर्तते) 12. 70. 17; (द्वापरे ऽपि
युगे धर्मो द्विभागोनः प्रवर्तते) 3.
148. 26; 12. 259. 32; in the Yugas that
follow the Kṛta the traditional धर्म is
displaced successively by one quarter and in-
stead अधर्म increases due to the practice
of theft, falsehood and deceit 12. 224. 23; the
धर्मस् in the Dvāpara are different from
those in the Kṛta and the Tretā 12. 224. 26 =
12. 252. 8; according to Mārkaṇḍeya, however,
the धर्म for the Kṛta, the Tretā and the
Dvāpara was the same (एष ढर्मः कृत-
युगे त्रेतायां द्वापरे तथा) 3. 189. 13;
sacrifice was considered to be the best धर्म
for the Dvāpara (द्वापरे यज्ञम् एवाहुः
(उत्तमम्)) 12. 224. 27; Hanūmant told
Bhīma that the times in different Yugas were
different; he and Bhīma lived at a time when
the Dvāpara was about to end and hence he
could not assume the form he had taken in
the earlier Yuga (अयं प्रध्वंसनः कालो
नाद्य तद् रूपम् अस्ति मे) 3. 148. 6;
Kṛṣṇa-Vāsudeva, along with Saṃkaraṣṇa, is
praised following the Sātvata rites when the
Dvāpara ends, and the Kali begins (द्वाप-
रस्य युगस्यान्ते आदौ कलियुगस्य च।
सात्वतं विधिं आस्थाय गीतः संकर्षणेन
यः (i. e. कृष्णः) 6. 62. 39.
G. Dvāpara,
sacrifice and the Vedas: Vyāsa told his son
Śuka that on account of the limitation on the
life expectancy (of human beings) sacrifices,
in the Dvāparayuga, get into disarray (संर्च्-
धाद् आयुषस् त्व् एते (i. e. यज्ञाः) व्यस्यन्ते
द्वापरे युगे) 12. 224. 65 = 12. 230. 14;
they fall into ruin (द्वापरे विप्लवं यान्ति
यज्ञाः) 12. 224. 62 = 12. 230. 15 (विप्लवं
यान्ति वेदाः); however, sacrifice considered
to be the best धर्म for the Dvāpara
(द्वापरे यज्ञम् एवाहुः (उत्तमम्) 12.
224. 27; Hanūmant told Bhīma that in the
Dvāpara the Veda is foretold; hence some
study all the four Vedas, others three, two,
or one; but some do not study a single ऋच्; as
men did not realize the sacred text to be one
Veda, the Veda was divided into many
(Vedas) (द्वापरे ऽपि युगे … चतुर्धा
वेद एव च॥ततो ऽन्ये च चतुर्वेदास्
त्रिवेदाश् च तथापरे।द्विवेदाश् चैकवेदाश्-
चाप्य् अनृचश् च तथापरे॥ … एकवेदस्य
चाज्ञानाद् वेदास् ते बहवः कृताः) 3. 148.
26-27, 29 (Nī., on Bom. Ed. 3. 149. 28,
offers an alternative explanation: यद् वा
चतुर्वेदा इति वेदत्रयोक्तं कर्म ज्योतिष्टो-
मादिकम्।अथर्वणोपनिषदुक्तम् ध्या-
नं च सहैव वानुतिष्ठन्तीति कर्मोपास्ति-
समुच्चय उक्तः।त्रिवेदा इति केवलकर्-
मठाः।द्विवेदा इति स्वशाखोक्तं सं-
ध्यावन्दनादि कर्म ध्यानं चानुति-
ष्ठन्ति।एकवेदा ध्यानैकनिष्ठाः।
अनृचः कृतकृत्याः।); (also cf. Maheśvara
(Viṣṇu) recommending the performance of
sacrifices to satisfy the gods and the gods,
on their part, sustaining the worlds in the
(three) Yugas other than the Kṛta 12. 327.
53-60).
H. Nature: According to the
description of the Dvāpara given by Hanū-
mant to Bhīma, since in that age the Vedas
become fourfold and the शास्त्रस् multiply,
the Vedic rites are variously performed;
people, given to austerities and gifts, become
राजस by nature; since truth falls down,
rarely any one abides by truth (एवं
शास्त्रेषु भिन्नेषु बहुधा नियते कृइया।
तपोदानप्रवृत्ता च राजसी भवति प्रजा॥
 … सत्यस्य चेह विभ्रंशात् सत्ये कश्चिद्
अवस्थितः॥) 3. 148. 28-29; for further
description of the Dvāpara cf. 3. 148. 30-31;
Hanūmant concludes that people in the
Dvāpara perish due to the practice of
अधर्म (एवं द्वापरम् आसाद्य प्रजाः
क्षीयन्त्य् अधर्मतः) 3. 148. 32; according
to Saṃjaya, in the Dvāpara all the four
वर्णस् are full of energy; they are great
heroes, desirous of killing each other; on the
whole, the Dvāpara in which Saṃjaya lived
was characterized by contraction (of the me-
rits in all respects) (सर्ववर्णा महाराज
जायन्ते द्वापरे सति।महोत्साहा महावीर्-
याः परस्परवधैषिणः॥ … संक्षेपो
वर्तते राजन् द्वापरे ऽस्मिन् नराधिप)
6. 11. 11, 14 (Nī. on Bom. Ed. 6. 10. 15:
संक्षेपो गुणानाम् इति शेषः); Vyāsa told
Śuka that all the वर्णस् and the आश्रमस्
fall into disarray due to the limitation on
the life-span (वर्णाश्रमास् तथा।संर्च्-
धाद् आयुषस् त्व् एते व्यस्यन्ते द्वापरे
युगे) 12. 230. 14; he also said that people
in the Dvāpara (as in the Tretā and the Kali)
entertain doubt (त्रेतायां द्वापरे चैव
कलिजाश् च ससंशयाः 12. 230. 7) as to
what is at the root of a man's success—
his effort, fate, or nature 12. 230. 4; in the
Dvāpara, the earth has to be ploughed and
even then it does not yield much harvest
(कृष्टपच्यैव पृथिवी भवत्य् अल्पफला
तथा) 12. 70. 17; in this Yuga people have to
copulate to beget progeny (द्वापरे मैथुनो
धर्मः प्रजानाम् अभवन् नृप) 12. 200.
37; evil tribes like the Talavaras and the
Andharkas from the south and the Yaunas
(Yavanas) and the Gāndhāras from the
north move on earth from the Tretā onwards
(i. e. also in the Dvāpara) 12. 200. 39-40, 42.
I. Life expectancy: Vyāsa told his son
Śuka that the life expectancy of people dimini-
shes by a quarter in each succeeding Yuga
after the Kṛta, hence in the Dvāpara they
live for two hundred years ( … त्रेतादिष्व्
एतेषां पादशो ह्रसते वयः) 12. 224. 24;
Vyāsa also told Śuka that according to his
information life expectancy of people, along
with other things, gradually decreased in the
successive Yugas ( … अनुयुगं ह्रसन्तीति
च नः श्रुतम्।आयूंषि … ) 12. 224. 25;
this is also what Mārkaṇḍeya told Yudhi-
ṣṭhira (आयुर् … मनुष्याणाम् अनुयुगं
ह्रसतीति निबोध मे) 3. 188. 13; according
to Saṃjaya, however, the life expectancy of
people in the Dvāpara was two thousand
years (आयुःसंख्या … संक्त्याता … ।द्वि-
सहस्रं द्वापरे तु) 6. 11. 5-6 (ap-
parently Saṃjaya made confusion between
the duration of the Dvāpara age and the
life expectancy of people in that Yuga).
J. Simile: The place where the river
Narmadā passes along the Vaiḍūrya moun-
tain is compared to the junction of the Tretā
(f.) and the Dvāpara (m.) 3. 121. 18-19.
K. Name of Sūrya: Dvāpara appears as
48th name among the hundred and eight
names of Sūrya taught by Dhaumya to
Yudhiṣṭhira 3. 3. 22. [The words कृत, त्रेता,
द्वापर and कलि occurring in 5. 140. 7-15
are wrongly interpreted by Nīlakaṇṭha (Bom.
Ed. 5. 142. 7-15) as names of the four Yugas,
and not as the names of the throws in the
game of dice].

धनिष्ठा
Dhaniṣṭhā f. (sg., pl.): Name of a
नक्षत्र।
A. Computation of time began with it:
When the Abhijit नक्षत्र dropped down from
the sky and Indra was confused in calculating
time, Brahman ordained that time (काल =
युग) began with Dhaniṣṭhā, whereas for-
merly it began with Rohiṇī (धनिष्ठादिस्
तदा कालो ब्रह्मणा परिनिर्मितः।रोहिण्या-
द्यो ऽभवत् पूर्वम्) 3. 219. 10 (Nī. on
Bom. Ed. 3. 230. 10: यस्य नक्षत्रस्या-
द्यक्षणे चन्द्रसूर्यगुरूणां योगस् तद्
युगादिनक्षत्रम्।तच् च पूर्वं रोहिण्य्
अभूत्।तदा ऽभिजित्पतनकाले तु एकन्यूनैर्
अहोरात्रैर् भगणस्य भोगात् कृतयुगादि-
नक्षत्रं धनिष्ठैवाभद् इत्य् अर्थः).
B. Religious rites: (1) Nārada told Devakī
(13. 63. 2-4) that if one, with composed
mind, gave a cart, yoked with bulls and filled
with garments and food (?) under the con-
stellation Dhaniṣṭhā he, in the next life,
instantly attained kingdom (गोप्रयुक्तं
धनिष्ठासु यानं दत्त्वा समाहितः।
वस्त्ररश्मिधरं सद्यः प्रेत्य राज्यम्
प्रपद्यते) 13. 63. 29; (2) Yama told
Śaśabindu (13. 89. 1) that if one offered a
काम्य श्राद्ध under the Dhaniṣṭhā (धनि-
ष्थायाम्) he obtained a share in kingdom
and did not meet with difficulties 13. 89. 12.

धर्मयुग
Dharmayuga: See Kṛtayuga.

धूमकेतु
Dhūmaketu m.: A comet; or planet
Rāhu (?); according to Nī., name of a sub-
ordinate planet (उपग्रह).
Among the bad omens which betokened
the annihilation of the Kauravas, and which
were pointed out by Vyāsa to Dhṛtarāṣṭra,
one was related to a very fierce comet taking
hold of the Puṣya constellation (अभावं
हि विशेषेष्ण कुरूणां प्रतिपश्यति।धूम-
केतुर् महाघोरः पुष्यम् आक्रम्य
तिष्ठति॥) 6. 3. 12; (महाघोर धूम-
केतु may stand for Rāhu, cf. 6. 3. 26
where a तीव्रग्रह which very probably
means Rāhu, is compared to धूमकेतु; ac-
cording to Nī. on Bom. Ed. 6. 3. 13 Dhūma-
ketu is a particular उपग्रह (उपग्रह-
विशेषः); he looks upon both Rāhu and Ketu
as subordinate planets, cf. his Comm. on Bom.
Ed. 6. 17. 2). [See Rāhu]

ध्रुव
Dhruva1 m.: Name of the polar star.
A. Described as the best among the
heavenly bodies (ज्योतिषां श्रेष्ठम्) 12.
326. 53; identified as the son of king Uttāna-
pāda (औत्तानपाद) 13. 3. 15.
B. Bad
omen: Among the bad omens reported by
Vyāsa to Dhṛtarāṣṭra one was related to the
blazing Dhruva's movement towards left
which foretold terrible happenings (ध्रुवः
प्रज्वलितो घोरम् अपसव्यं प्रवर्तते)
6. 3. 16.
C. Relation with Nārāyaṇa:
Bhagavān (Nārāyaṇa) pointed out to Nārada
that Dhruva, the best among the luminous
heavenly bodies moving in the sky, was
within him (ध्रुवं च ज्योतिषां श्रेष्ठं
पश्य नारद खेचरं (मत्स्थं) 12.
326. 53.
D. Relation with the star
Viśvāmitra: Viśvāmitra, stationed between
Dhruva Auttānapāda and the Brahmarṣis
(the seven stars forming the constellation
Ursa Major), shines constantly in the north
(ध्रुवस्यौत्तानपादस्य ब्रह्मर्षीणां
तथैव च।मध्ये ज्वलति यो नित्यम्
उदीचीम् आश्रितो दिशम्) 13. 3. 15.
E. Neg-
lecting Dhruva harmful: Yājñavalkya told
Janaka that those who fail to see Dhruva,
having seen it once before, have only a year
to live (संवत्सरवियोगस्य संभवेयुः
शरीरिणः॥यो ऽरुन्धतीं न पश्येत
दृष्टपूर्वां कदाचन।तथैव ध्रुवम्
इत्य् आहुः) 12. 305. 8-9.
F. Simile: All
ascetics of the Naranārāyaṇāśrama (12. 126.
2) sat round king Vīradyumna as do the
seven sages round Dhruva 12. 126. 25. [For
Dhruva also see Section 1. 7]

ध्रुव
Dhruva2 nt.: Designation of the four
नक्षत्रस् (Rohiṇī, Pūrvā Phalgunī, Pūrvā
Bhādrapadā and Pūrvāṣāḍhā).
When the Pāṇḍavas decided to get the
wealth of king Marutta Āvikṣita, left on the
mountain Himavant, they ordered their army
to march out on the day (i. e. Sunday ?, see the
next) which was presided over by the Dhruva
नक्षत्र (कृत्वा तु पाण्डवाः सर्वे रत्ना-
हरणनिश्चयम्।सेनाम् आज्ञापयाम् आसुर्
नक्षत्रे ऽहनि च ध्रुवे) 14. 62. 17 (Nī.
on Bom. Ed. 14. 63. 18: ध्रुवे नक्षत्रे
रोहिण्याम् उत्तरात्रये च). [See Dhruva3]

ध्रुव
Dhruva3 nt.: Designation of the day
presided over by Dhruva (? i. e. Sunday ?).
The Pāṇḍavas ordered their army to
march out on the ध्रुव day (सेनाम् आज्ञा-
पयाम् आसुर् नक्षत्रे ऽहनि च ध्रुवे) 14.
62. 17 (Nī. on Bom. Ed. 14. 63. 18: अहनि
वारे ध्रुवे रविवारे। But Nī.'s explanation
amounts to anachronism). [See Dhruva2]

पुनर्वसु
Punarvasu m. (sg., du.): Name of a
नक्षत्र।
A. Religious rites: (1) Gifts under
this नक्षत्र: Nārada told Devakī (13. 63.
2-4) that if one gave as gifts cakes
(अपूपान्) and food (अन्नानि) under Punar-
vasu (पुनर्वसौ) one obtained fame and
good look and was born in a family that had
ample food (बह्वन्ने जायते कुले) 13. 63. 9;
(2) श्राद्ध: Yama told Śaśabindu (13.
89. 1) that if one offered a काम्य श्राद्ध
under Punarvasu he reaped (ample) harvest
(कृषिभागी भवेन् मर्त्यः कुर्वञ् श्राद्-
धं पुनर्वसौ) 13. 89. 4.
B. Smile:
The two Pāñcāla warriors (Candradeva and
Daṇḍadhara cf. the various readings under
8. 33. 15) guarding the wheels of Yudhiṣṭhira
shone on his two sides as do the two Punar-
vasu stars seen on the two sides of the moon
(रथाभ्याशे चकासेते चन्द्रस्येव पुनर्-
वसू) 8. 33. 16.

पुष्य
Puṣya1 m.: Name of a नक्षत्र, and
of the moon's conjunction with this नक्षत्र
(Puṣyayoga); also called Tiṣya (3. 188. 87).
A. Description: auspicious (पुण्य-
योग) 3. 261. 15.
B. Considered favour-
able for marching out of the army or for
going out on a pilgrimage: (1) Duryodhana
urged again and again the assembled kings
to march towards Kurukṣetra on that very
day since it was presided over by the Puṣya
नक्षत्र (आज्ञापयच् च राज्ञस् तान् पार्थि-
वान् दुष्टचेतसः।प्रयाध्वं वै कुरु-
क्षेत्रं पुष्यो ऽद्येति पुनः पुनः) 5. 148.
3 (Nī. on Bom. Ed. 3. 150. 3: पुष्यनक्-
षत्रं हि अश्विन्याः पौरणमास्या उपरि
अष्टम्यां भवति; cf. 5. 140. 18: सप्तमाच्
चापि दिवसाद् अमावास्या भविष्यति); (2)
Kṛṣṇa too, with the Pāṇḍavas, started towards
Kuru (kṣetra) when Rauhiṇeya (Balarāma)
went away on the day which was presided
over by Puṣya (पुष्येण) 9. 34. 14; 9.
34. 9; (3) When the Mārgaśīrṣī (full
moon day of the month Mārgaśīrṣa) had
passed and the Puṣya had set in, the Pāṇḍa-
vas, together with Dhaumya and other
ascetics, started from the Kāmyaka forest
towards the east (3. 91. 28) to visit the तीर्थस्
(मार्गशीर्ष्याम् अतीतायां पुष्येण प्रययुस्
तदा) 3. 91. 25; (4) Balarāma started for
his तीर्थयात्रा under the Puṣya and returned
to Kurukṣetra under the Śravaṇa; he was
out for 42 days (चत्वारिंशद् अहान्य् अद्य
द्वे च मे निःसृतस्य वै।पुष्येण सं-
प्रयातो ऽस्मि श्रवणे पुनर् आगतः) 9 33.
5 (see Editor's note on the stanza, Cr. Ed.
Vol. 11, p. 489); 9. 34. 14; (5) Drupada
asked his Purohita, whom he sent as his mes-
senger to the Kauravas, to start when the
moon was in conjunction with the Puṣya so
that he might achieve the objective of Yudhi-
ṣṭhira (स भवान् पुष्ययोगेन … कौरवेयान्
प्रयात्व् आशु कौन्तेयस्यार्थसिद्धये) 5.
6. 17; (6) Daśaratha asked his Purohita
to make the necessary preparations in connec-
tion with the consecration of Rāma as hair-
apparent since on that night Puṣya was to
enter into the auspicious conjunction (with the
moon) (अद्य पुष्यो निशि ब्रह्मन् पुण्यं
योगम् उपैष्यति) 3. 261. 15.
C. Advent
of the Kṛta Yuga: When the moon, the sun,
the Tiṣya and the Bṛhaspati will come in
one राशि, the Kṛta Yuga will commence
(यदा चन्द्रश् च सूर्यश् च तथा तिष्य-
बृहस्पती।एकराशौ समेष्यन्ति प्रपत्-
स्यति तदा कृतम्॥) 3. 188. 87 (Nī., how-
ever, on Bom. Ed. 3. 190. 90: गुरुसूर्य-
चन्द्राः यदा युगपत् पुष्यनक्षत्रम्
एष्यन्ति तदा कृतयुगप्रवृत्तिर् इत्य् अर्थः).
D. Religious rites: (1) Gifts under this
नक्षत्र: Nārada told Devakī (13. 63. 2-4)
that by giving gold, whether wrought or
unwrought, as gift under Puṣya (पुष्ये)
one shone like Soma (i. e. moon ?) in the
worlds which have no (other) light (अनालो-
केषु लोकेषु सोमवत् स विराजते) 13. 63. 10
(Nī. on Bom. Ed. 13. 64. 10: अनालोकेषु
आलोकान्तरवर्जितेषु स्वयंप्रकाशेष्व् इत्य्
अर्थः); (2) श्राद्ध: Yama told Śaśabindu
(13. 89. 1) that one who desired prosperity
should think of offering a काम्य श्राद्ध
under the Puṣya नक्षत्र (पुष्टिकामो ऽथ
पुष्येण श्राद्धम् ईहेत मानवः) 13. 89.
4.
E. Bad omen: Among the bad omens
for the Kauravas, pointed out by Vyāsa to
Dhṛtarāṣṭra, one was related to a fierce comet
(Rāhu ?) that had taken hold of Puṣya
(धूमकेतुर् महाघोरः पुष्यम् आक्रम्य
तिष्ठति) 6. 3. 12. [See Dhūmaketu, Pauṣya]

पुष्य
Puṣya2 m.: See Kaliyuga.

पूर्वा
Pūrvā Proṣṭhapadā f.: See Pūrvā
Bhādrapadā.

पूर्वा
Pūrvā Phalgunī f. (du., pl.): Name of
a double नक्षत्र distinguished as Pūrvā
and Uttarā. [Referred to also simply as
Phalgunī 13. 89. 6].
A. Epic event: Arjuna was born on
mountain Himavant under the junction of
the two constellations Pūrvā Phalgunī and
Uttarā Phalgunī and hence he was called
Phalguna (उत्तराभ्यां च पूर्वाभ्यां
फल्गुनीभ्याम् अहं दिवा।जातो … तेन
मां फल्गुनं विदुः) 4. 39. 14 (Nī., who
reads (Bom. Ed. 4. 44. 16) उत्तराभ्यां
फलगुनीभ्यां नक्षत्राभ्याम् explains it
as नक्षत्राभ्यां ताराभ्यां तत्र स्थिते
चन्द्रे इत्य् अर्थः).
B. Religious rites:
(1) दान: Nārada told Devakī (13. 63. 2-4)
that if one, after observing fast, gave to Brāh-
maṇas under Pūrvā Phalgunī (फल्गुनी-
पूर्वसमये) food mixed with condensed
sugar cane juice (भक्षान् फाणितसंयुक्-
तान्), one obtained prosperity (सौभाग्यम्
ऋच्छति) 13. 63. 13; (2) श्राद्ध: Yama
told Śaśabindu (13. 89. 1) that if one offered
a काम्य श्राद्ध under (Pūrvā) Phalgunī
one became prosperous (फल्गुनीषु ददच्
छ्राद्धं सुभगः श्राद्धदो भवेत्) 13.
89. 6.

पूर्वा
Pūrvā Bhādrapadā f.; also called
Pūrvā Proṣṭhapadā (du., pl.); Pūrva Pro-
ṣṭhapada m. (sg.) (6. 3. 14): Name of a
double नक्षत्र distinguished as Pūrvā and
Uttarā.
A. Religious rites: (1) दान: Nārada
told Devakī (13. 63. 2-4) that by offering the
राजमाषस् (kind of beans) as a gift under
the Pūrvabhādrapadā conjunction one enjoys
all kinds of food and becomes happy in next
life (पूर्वभाद्रपदायोगे राजमाषान् प्र-
दाय तु।सर्वभक्षफलोपेतः स वै
प्रेत्य सुखी भवेत्॥) 13. 63. 31; (2)
श्राद्ध: Yama told Śaśabindu (13. 89. 1)
that by offering a काम्य श्राद्ध under
Pūrvaproṣṭhapadā one obtained many goats
and sheep (पूर्वप्रोष्ठपदाः कुर्वन् बहु
विन्देद् अजाविकम्) 13. 89. 13; but in general
one is not supposed to offer any rites to
gods and manes under the two Proṣṭhapadā
नक्षत्रस् (दैवं पित्र्यम् अथापि च। …
न प्रोष्ठपदयोः कार्यम्) 13. 107. 119.
B. Bad effect: Śukra, when in conjunction
with the two Proṣṭhapadās has always wealth,
so also the Lord of riches (i. e. Kubera);
Śukra (when in conjunction with the two
नक्षत्रस्) takes away from men what-
ever wealth they had earned as desired
(नित्यं प्रोष्ठपदाभ्यां च शुक्रे
धनपतौ तथा।मनुष्येभ्यः समा-
दत्ते शुक्रश् चित्तार्जितं धनम्॥) 5. 112.
3 (Nī., however, on Bom. Ed. 5. 114. 3:
प्रोष्ठपदाभ्याम् इति तृतीया … सप्तम्यर्थे
तेन तस्मिन् नक्षत्रद्वये शुक्रे शुक्रवा-
सरे तद्योगे सति शुक्रो ऽग्निः धनपतौ
कुबेरस्य वृद्ध्यर्थं मनुष्येभ्यः
संप्रदानेभ्यः धनं दत्ते ददाति।
शुक्रश् चित्तार्जितम् इत्य् अनेन वह्निरेतस्-
त्वं तस्य प्रदर्श्यते।धनार्थी उक्तन-
क्षत्रवारयोगे वह्निं प्रार्थयेत्।तच् च
धनं यागादिद्वारा वा भूमौ निखनेन
वा सर्वं कुबेरं प्रत्य् एव गच्छतीति
भावः).
C. Bad omen: Among the
bad omens pointed out by Vyāsa to Dhṛtarā-
ṣṭra one referred to Śukra's having ascended
the Pūrva Proṣṭhapada constellation and then
having gone over to the Uttara Proṣṭhapada,
was still looking at it (i. e. looking at the
Pūrva Proṣṭhapada) 6. 3. 14 (for the citation
and Nī.'s commentary on it see above
Uttarā Bhādrapadā p. 232. 2). [See Uttarā
Bhādrapadā]

पूर्वाषाढा
Pūrvāṣāḍhā f. (pl.): Name of a double
नक्षत्र distinguished as Pūrvā and Uttarā.
Religious rites: (1) दान: Nārada
told Devakī (13. 63. 2-4) that if one, after
observing fast, gave as a gift under the
Pūrvāṣāḍhā (पूर्वास्व् अषाढासु) pots full
of curds (दधिपात्राणि) to a Brāhmaṇa
born in good family and of good conduct and
who was proficient in the Vedas, the giver,
after death, was born in a family that was
rich in cows 13. 63. 25; (2) श्राद्ध: Yama
told Śaśabindu (13. 89. 1) that by offering a
काम्य श्राद्ध under the Pūrvāṣāḍhā (the
word पूर्वा does not occur but is easily
inferred) one obtained excellent fame (यशो
ऽषाढास्व् अनुत्तमम्) 13. 89. 10.

पौष
Pauṣa m.: Name of a month
Aṅgiras had told Bhīṣma that if one
spent the month of Pauṣa eating only once a
day (भक्तेनैकेन यः क्षपेत्) he was born
fortunate, handsome and famous 13. 109. 19.

पौष्य
Pauṣya adj.: (of a योग) related to the
नक्षत्र Puṣya.
The sage Vyāsa asked first Yudhiṣṭhira
to hold the hand (in marriage) of Kṛṣṇā
since that was an auspicious day when the
moon was going to have the Pauṣya yoga i. e.
be in conjunction with Puṣya (अद्य पुण्या-
हम् उत पाण्डवेय।अद्य पौष्यं योगम्
उपैति चन्द्रमाः) 1. 190. 5 (Nī., however,
on Bom. Ed. 1. 198. 5: पौष्यं पुष्यत्य्
अनेनेति तं न तु पुष्यं तस्यावैवाहिक-
त्वात्). [See Puṣya]

प्राजापत्य
Prājāpatya1 nt.: See Kṛtayuga.

प्राजापत्य
Prājāpatya2 nt.: Name of an asterism.
Among the bad omens pointed out by
Karṇa to Kṛṣṇa one was related to the
lustrous, sharp planet Śanaiścara afflicting
the Prājāpatya नक्षत्र (= Rohiṇī?) while
simultaneously afflicting living beings all the
more (प्राजापत्यं हि नक्ष्त्रं ग्रहस्
तीक्ष्णो महाद्युतिः।शनैश्चरः पीडयति
पीडयन् प्राणिनो ऽधिकम्) 5. 141. 7 (Nī.
on Bom. Ed. 5. 143. 8: प्राजापत्यं
रोहिणीनक्षत्रम्।प्रजानां पतिर् दुर्यो-
धनस् तदीयं नाम नक्षत्रम् उत्तरा-
भाद्रपदाख्यम् इति वा।तेन पत्युः
पीडया प्राणिनाम् अपि पीडेति युक्तम्।यद् वा
पृथ्वीकूर्मोदरस्थां रोहिणीम् शनैश्चरः
पीडयति तेन मध्यदेशे महान् क्षयो
राज्ञो नाशश् चेति भावः।)

प्रोष्ठपदा
Proṣṭhapadā: See Pūrvā Bhādrapadā
and Uttarā Bhādrapadā.

प्रौष्ठपद
Prauṣṭhapada m.: Name of the month
Bhādrapada.
Aṅgiras had told Bhīṣma (13. 109. 9)
that one who spent the month of Prauṣṭha-
pada taking food only once a day obtained
rich, prosperous and steady power (प्रौष्ठ-
पदं तु यो मासम् एकाहारो भवेन् नरः।
धनाढ्यं स्फीतम् अचलम् ऐश्वर्यं
प्रतिपद्यते) 13. 109. 27.

फल्गुन
Phalguna m.: Name of a month.
A. Epic event: The Pāṇḍavas procee-
ded from Hāstinapura to Vāraṇāvata on
the eighth day of the month of Phalguna
and under the constellation Rohiṇī (अष्टमे
ऽहनि रोहिण्यां प्रयाताः फल्गुनस्य ते)
1. 133. 30. [See Bhagadaiva]

फल्गुनी
Phalgunī: See Pūrvā Phalgunī and
Uttarā Phalgunī.

बुध
Budha m.: Name of a planet (Mer-
cury).
A. Importance: Budha, along with
other planets, visits the सभा of Brahmadeva
2. 11. 20; mentioned, along with other
planets, in the Daivatavaṃśa 13. 151. 12.
B. Name of Sūrya: Budha appears as
the 24th name among the 108 names of
Sūrya taught by Dhaumya to Yudhiṣṭhira
3. 3. 19.
C. Smile: (1) Droṇa and
and Arjuna confronted each other in battle
like Budha and Śukra in the sky 6. 97.
57; (2) The confronting of Duḥśāsana
and Prativindhya appeared like that of
Budha and Bhārgava (i. e. Śukra) in a
cloudless sky 7. 143. 30; (3) Dhṛṣṭaketu
and Bāhlīka fought each other like angry
Aṅgāraka (Mars) and Budha 6. 43. 38;
(4) Abhimanyu and Citrasena, when they
met each other on the battlefield, shone like
Budha and Śanaiścara in the sky 6. 100. 20;
(5) Arjuna, marching out on his excellent
chariot in the company of Kṛṣṇa and Sātyaki
looked like moon, accompanied by Budha
and Śukra, destroying the darkness 7. 60. 20.
[For Budha also see Section 1. 7]

बृहस्पति
Bṛhaspati m.: Name of a planet
(Jupiter), also called Guru (12. 139. 15).
A. Description: Very bright (प्रज्व-
लित) 6. 3. 25.
B. Importance: Bṛhas-
pati, along with other planets, visits the सभा
of Brahmadeva 2. 11. 20; Bṛhaspati, with
other planets, finds place in the Daivata-
vaṃśa 13. 151. 12.
C. Name of Sūrya:
Bṛhaspati appears as the 22nd name among
the 108 names of Sūrya taught by Dhaumya
to Yudhiṣṭhira 3. 3. 19.
D. Bad omen: (1)
Among the bad omens pointed out by Vyāsa
to Dhṛtarāṣṭra one was related to Bṛhaspati
making retrograde movement in the constella-
tion Śravaṇa (मघास्व् अङ्गारको वक्रः
श्रवणे च बृहस्पतिः) 6. 3. 13; (2) The
other omen observed by Vyāsa was that the
planets Bṛhaspati and Śanaiścara were
stationed near the two stars Viśākhā and
were in that position for a year (संवत्स-
रस्थायिनौ च ग्रहौ प्रज्वलिताव् उभौ।
विशाखयोः समीपस्थौ बृहस्पतिशनैश्च-
रौ) 6. 3. 25 (Nī. on Bom. Ed. 6. 3. 27:
पूर्वं श्रवणस्थो बृहस्पतिर् (reference
to 6. 3. 13) भगनक्षत्रस्थः सूर्यपुत्र
(reference to 6. 3. 14) इत्य् उक्तम्।ताव्
उभौ विशाखासमीपे तिर्यग्वेधेन शत-
पदे चक्रे विशाखानक्षत्रं विध्यत इत्य्
अर्थः); (3) At the time of the death of
Karṇa, Bṛhaspati afflicted Rohiṇī constellation
and looked like moon and sun (बृहस्पती
रोहिणीं संप्रपीड्य बभूव चन्द्रार्क-
समानवर्णः) 8. 68. 49.
E. Events
connected with Bṛhaspati: (1) Formerly,
when the Tretā was about to end and the
Dvāpara was about to commence, as the
Guru (Bṛhaspati) was not favourable it did
not rain for twelve years (न ववर्ष सह-
स्राक्षः प्रतिलोमो ऽभवद् गुरुः) 12. 139.
15, 13-14; (2) Mārkaṇḍeya told the Pāṇḍa-
vas that when the moon, the sun, the Tiṣya
(Puṣya) and Bṛhaspati will come together
in the same sign of the zodiac (राशि), the
Kṛtayuga will commence (यदा चन्द्रश् च
सूर्यश् च तथा तिष्यबृहस्पती।एकराशौ
समेष्यन्ति प्रपत्स्यति तदा कृतम्) 3. 188.
87 (Nī., however, on Bom. Ed. 3. 190. 90:
गुरुसूर्यचन्द्राः यदा युगपत् पुष्य-
नक्षत्रम् एष्यन्ति तदा कृतयुगप्रवृत्तिर्
इत्य् अर्थः). [For Bṛhaspati see Section 1. 7]

ब्रह्मकल्प
Brahmakalpa m.: A cosmic period of
Brahman.
In a former Brahmakalpa, when the
ब्रह्मर्षिस् met, they entertained doubt about
the creation of the world (ब्रह्मकल्पे
पुरा ब्रह्मन् ब्रह्मर्षीणां समागमे।
लोकसंभवसन्देहः समुत्पन्नो महात्-
मनाम्) 12. 176. 6.

ब्रह्मराशि
Brahmarāśi m.: Name of a constellation
(identical with Śravaṇa ?).
One of the bad omens pointed out by
Vyāsa to Dhṛtarāṣṭra was related to the
planet Mars who made repeated retrograde
movements and then returned to Brahmarāśī
to remain steady in the constellation Śra-
vaṇa (वक्रानुवक्रं कृत्वा च श्रवणे
पावकप्रभः।ब्रह्मराशिं समावृत्य
लोहिताङ्गो व्यवस्थितः॥ 6. 3. 17) (Nī. on
Bom. Ed. 6. 3. 18: तत्रैव सर्वतोभद्र-
चक्रे मघास्थो लोहिताङ्गो ऽङ्गारको वक्रा-
नुवक्रं कृत्वा पुनःपुनर् वक्रीभूय
ब्रह्मणा बृहस्पतिनाक्रान्तं राशिं
नक्षत्रम् श्रवणं समावृत्य सम्यक्
पूऋनदृष्ट्या विद्ध्वा तिष्ठति).

ब्राह्म
Brāhma1, (Brāhmī f.) adj.: of the day
and night of Brahman.
A day and night each of Brahman is
equal to one thousand Yugas (a Yuga or a
Kalpa being equal to twelve thousand years
which is the total duration of the Kṛta,
the Tretā, the Dvāpara and the Kali taken
together) (एषा द्वादशसाहस्री युगाख्या
परिकीर्तिता॥एतत् सहस्रपर्यन्तम् अहो
ब्राह्मम् उदाहृतम्) 3. 186. 22-23; 12.
224. 28; 12. 224. 17; सहस्रयुगपर्यन्तम्
अहर् यद् ब्रह्मणो विदुः।रात्रिं युगस-
हस्रान्तां ते ऽहोरात्रविदो जनाः॥) 6. 30.
17 = 12. 224. 30; at the beginning of his
night, i. e. during the Pralaya, Brahman
enters into himself and sleeps; at the end of
the night he is awakened from his sleep and
creates the great भूत (i. e. Hiraṇya-
garbha) (रात्रिस् तावत्तिथी ब्राह्मी तदादौ
विश्वम् ईश्वरः।प्रलये ऽध्यात्मम् आविश्य
सुप्त्वा सो ऽन्ते विबुध्यते॥प्रतिबुद्धो
विकुरुते ब्रह्माक्षय्यं क्षपाक्षये।
सृजते च महद् भूतम्) 12. 224. 29, 31;
(सृजत्य् अनन्तकर्माणं महान्तं भू-
तम् अग्रजम्) 12. 291. 15 (Nī. on Bom. Ed.
12. 302. 15: अग्रजं हिरण्यगर्भम्);
युगं द्वादशसाहस्रं कल्पं विद्धि
चतुर्गुणम्।दशकल्पशतावृत्तं तद्
अहर् ब्राह्मम् उच्यते।रात्रिश् चैतावती
राजन् यस्यान्ते प्रतिबुध्यते 12. 291. 14
(Nī. on Bom. Ed. 12. 302. 14: तद् एव
चतुर्युगं दशशतावृत्तं कल्पं तद् एव
च ब्राह्मम् अहर् उच्यते); at the end of
Brahman's night there arises due to the
kindness of the god of boundless lustre
(i. e. of god Nārāyaṇa 12. 328. 12) a lotus,
where again by the god's kindness Brahman
is born; at the end of Brahman's day,
from the forehead of the god, who is angry,
arises his son, Rudra, the destroyer (ब्राह्मे
रात्रिक्षये प्राप्ते तस्य ह्य् अमिततेजसः।
प्रसादात् प्रादुरभवत् पद्मं पद्म-
निभेक्षण।तत्र ब्रह्मा समभवत् स
तस्यैव प्रसादतः॥अह्नः क्षये ललाटाच्
च सुतो देवस्य वै तथा।क्रोधाविष्टस्य
संजज्ञे रुद्रः संहारकारकः) 12. 328.
15-16; at the beginning of the Brahman's
day all manifestations arise from the non-
manifest; at the beginning of his night the
manifestations are dissolved into the same
non-manifest (अव्यक्ताद् व्यक्तयः सर्वाः
प्रभवन्त्य् अहरागमे।रात्र्यागमे प्र-
लीयन्ते तत्रैवाव्यक्तसंज्ञके) 6. 30. 18.

ब्राह्म
Brāhma2 adj.: of a मुहूर्त (time
before sunrise, early morning).
A. Epic event: when Arjuna sat on
the ground and mentally thought of Bhava,
he, at the auspicious ब्राह्म मुहूर्त, with
his (mind) concentrated, saw himself in
the sky in the company of Keśava (भूमाव्
आसीन एकाग्रो जगाम मनसा भवम्॥
ततः प्रणिहिते ब्राह्मे मुहूर्ते शुभलक्-
षणे।आत्मानम् अर्जुनो ऽपश्यद् गगने
सहकेश्वम्॥) 7. 57. 19-20 (Nī. who
reads प्रणिहितो (Bom. Ed. 7. 80. 23) explains
समाहितमनाः).
B. Time for perfor-
ming the संध्या ceremony: Bhīṣma
advised Yudhiṣṭhira that one who wanted
long life should wake up at the ब्राह्म
मुहूर्त, think of धर्म and काम (the
two पुरुषार्थस्), and after sipping water
for purification, should, with folded hands,
perform the first संध्या (ब्राह्मे मुहूर्ते
बुध्येत धर्मार्थौ चानुचिन्तयेत्।उत्था-
याचम्य तिष्ठेत पूर्वां संध्यां कृताञ्-
जलिः॥) 13. 107. 16.

भगदैव
Bhagadaiva m.: Name of the month
Phalguna.
Aṅgiras told Bhīṣma that one who eats
only once a day in the month of Bhagadaiva
(Phalguna) is loved by women and they
remain under his control (भगदैवं तु
यो मासम् एकभक्तेन यः क्षपेत्।स्त्रीषु
वल्लभतां याति वश्याश् चास्य भवन्ति ताः)
13. 109. 21. [See Phalguna]

भगदैवत
Bhagadaivata nt.: Name of the Uttarā
Phalgunī नक्षत्र; also called Bhāgya
(6. 3. 14).
A. Auspicious for marriage: Sage
Sthūlakeśa gave Pramadvarā to Ruru fixing
the marriage on the following Bhagadaivata
नक्षत्र (i. e. the Uttarā Phalgunī) (विवा-
हं स्थापयित्वाग्रे नक्षत्रे भगदैवते)
1. 8. 13 (Nī. on Bom. Ed. 1. 8. 16:
भगदैवते पूर्वयोः फल्गुन्योर् इति
लौकिकाः।फल्गुनीनक्षत्रम् अर्यमा
देवता फल्गुनीनक्षत्रं भगो देवतेति
श्रुतेर् उत्तराफल्गुन्योर् वा विवाहं स्था-
पयित्वा निश्चित्य।).
B. Bad omen: Among
the bad omens noticed by Vyāsa there was
one according to which the planet Śanaiścara
was afflicting the Bhāgya (i. e. the Uttarā
Phalgunī) नक्षत्र (भाग्यं नक्षत्रम्
आक्रम्य सूर्यपुत्रेण पीड्यते) 6. 3. 14
(Nī. who reads भगं नक्षत्रं comments
on Bom. Ed. 6. 3. 14: भगं नक्षत्रं
पूर्वाफल्गुनी श्रुतिमते तूत्तराफल्गुनी).
[See Uttarā Phalgunī]

भरणी
Bharaṇī f. (pl.): Name of a constella-
tion.
Religious rites: (1) दान: Nārada
told Devakī (13. 63. 2-4) that by offering
sesame and cow (?तिलधेनुं प्रदाय वै)
to Brāhmaṇas under Bharaṇī (भरणीषु),
one obtained many cows and fame in next
life 13. 63. 35 (cf., however, the note printed
at the end of the अध्याय 13. 64 of the
Bom. Ed.: यावता वस्त्रेण कृत्स्ना धेनुर्
आच्छादिता भवति तद्वस्त्रपूरिततिलास् तिल-
धेनुः); (2) श्राद्ध: Yama told Śaśa-
bindu (13. 89. 1) that by offering a काम्य
श्राद्ध under Bharaṇī one enjoyed excellent
life (आयुर् उत्तमम्) 13. 89. 14.

भाग्य
Bhāgya nt.: See Bhagadaivata.

भाद्रपदा
Bhādrapadā f.: See Pūrvā Bhādrapadā
and Uttarā Bhādrapadā.

भार्गव
Bhārgava m.: See Śukra1.

भृग्वङ्ग
Bhṛgvaṅga(?gi)rasaka adj.: of a certain
period of time.
Yudhiṣṭhira asked Bhīṣma the name of
the sage who first conceived of the श्राद्ध
ceremony, its appropriate time and nature, in
the period that was influenced by the Bhṛgus
and the Aṅgirases (केन संकल्पितं श्राद्-
धं कस्मिन् काले किमात्मकम्।भृग्व-
ङ्ग(? गि)रसके काले मुनिना कतरेण वा)
13. 91. 1 (Nī., however, on Bom. Ed. 13. 91.
1: भृग्वङ्गिरसके यदा भृगवो ऽङ्गिरसश्
च वर्तन्ते नान्ये).

भौम
Bhauma m.: See Aṅgāraka.

मघा
Maghā f. (pl.): Name of a नक्षत्र।
A. Event: Mythological: Sunda and
Upasunda, after performing at night the
ceremonies suitable for moving out, marched
out under the constellation Maghā for their
conquest of the three worlds (कृत्वा प्रास्था-
निकं रात्रौ मघासु ययतुस् तदा) 1.
202. 2 (Nī. on Bom. Ed. 1. 210. 2: मघासु
गमनार्थं निषिद्धे ऽपि नक्षत्रे असुर-
त्वाद् ययतुः).
B. Importance: A cer-
tain तीर्थ named jointly after the Kṛttikā
and the Maghā; by visiting this तीर्थ one ob-
tained the merit of performing the Agniṣṭoma
and the Atirātra sacrifices (कृत्तिकामघयोश्
चैव तीर्थम्) 3. 82. 46.
C. Omens:
(1) Vyāsa told Dhṛtarāṣṭra before the start of
the war that a calamity was predicted for the
two armies by the planet Mars making retro-
grade movement under the Maghā (मघास्व्
अङ्गारको वक्रः) 6. 3. 13; (2) Saṃjaya
told Dhṛtarāṣṭra that rhe armies of the
Kauravas gathered for war at Kurukṣetra on
the day when the moon entered the Maghā
and the seven principal planets, shining, came
together in the sky (मघाविषयगः सोमस्
तद् दिनं प्रत्यपद्यत।दीप्यमानाश् च
संपेतुर् दिवि सप्त महाग्रहाः॥) 6. 17. 2
(Nī. on Bom. Ed. 6. 17. 2 has a long com-
mentary trying to reconcile the astronomical
statements. He does not interpret मघा-
विषय as the region of the constellation
Maghā but as पितृदेश: मघा पित्रयं नक्-
षत्रं तस्य विषयो देशः पितृलोकस् तद्गतः
सोमः। … एतेन युद्धारंभं प्रकृत्य
‘मघाविषयगः सोमस् तद् दिनं प्रत्य-
पद्यत’ इति भीष्मपर्वणि सञ्जयवाक्यान्
मघायां युद्धारंभ इत्य् अपि निरस्तम्।
 … महाग्रहाः राहुकेत्वोर् उपग्रहत्वात्
सप्तैव).
D. Religious rites: (1) दान:
Nārada told Devakī (13. 63. 2-4) that by
offering plates (? rather ‘heaps’) full of
sesame one had many sons and cattle in this
life and enjoyed life after death (मघासु
तिलपूर्णानि वर्धमानानि मानवः।प्र-
दाय पुत्रपशुमान् इह प्रेत्य च मोदते)
13. 63. 12; (2) श्राद्ध: Yama told
Śaśabindu (13. 89. 1) that by offering a
काम्य श्राद्ध under the Maghā (मघासु)
one became eminent among kinsmen 13. 89.
5; (3) Bhīṣma recited for Yuḍhiṣṭhira the
गाथास् sung by the manes which were
recited for him formerly by the venerable
Sanatkumāra; according to these गाथास् the
manes cherished a wish that some one would
be born in their line who would offer to them
on the thirteenth day under the Maghā, during
the Dakṣiṇāyana, rice boiled in milk, together
with clarified butter or meat of red goat,
that was fanned, according to the rites, by
the (elephant's) ear, under the shadow of
an elephant (गाथाश् चाप्य् अत्र गायन्ति
पितृगीता युधिष्ठिर।सनत्कुमारो भग-
वान् पुरा मय्य् अभ्यभाषत॥अपि
नः स कुले जायाद् यो नो दद्यात् त्रयो-
दशीम्।मघासु सर्पिषा युक्तं पायसं
दक्षिणायने॥आजेन वापि लौहेन मघास्व्
एव यतव्रतः।हस्तिच्छायासु विधिवत्
कर्णव्यजनवीजितम्॥) 13. 88. 11-13. (In-
terpretation of हस्तिच्छाया as an eclipse in
this context is not favoured by the commen-
tators on the Manusmṛti; on Manu 3. 274,
which has the reading प्राक्छाये कुञ्जरस्य
च, Kullūka observes: हस्तिनः पूर्वां
दिशं गतायां छायायाम् … न तु त्रयो-
दशीहस्तिच्छाययोः समुच्चयः।; Medhātithi
on the same stanza: तथा कुञ्जरस्य
हस्तिनः प्राक्छाये प्राच्यां दिशि गतायां
छायायाम् अपराण्हेतरे काल इत्य् अर्थः। …
यत् तु व्याचक्षते राहूपरागो हस्तिच्छायो-
च्यते … तद् अयुक्तम्।; Rāghavānanda:
कुञ्जरस्यैव छाया विवक्षिता न तु योग-
विशेषः।कर्णव्यजनवीजितम् इति वाक्यान्-
तराच् चेति which latter is an obvious reference
to the Mbh. passage).

माघ
Māgha, Māghamāsa m.: Name of a
month.
A. Description: Holy (पुण्य) 13.
153. 28.
B. Epic Event: Bhīṣma, lying
on the bed of arrows, realized that the holy
month of Māgha had arrived (मासो ऽयं
समनुप्राप्तो मासः पुण्यो युधिष्ठिर);
he guessed that it must be the eighth day
of the bright fortnight of that month (त्रि-
भागशेषः पक्षो ऽयं शुक्लो भवितुम्
अर्हति) 13. 153. 28 (Nī. on Bom. Ed.
13. 167. 28: तेनाद्याष्टमीत्य् अर्थः).
C.
Religious rites: (1) Vedic: Aśvamedha:
when the return of the horse, wandering on
the earth, was reported to Yudhiṣṭhira, he,
noticing that the day was the twelfth of the
(bright) fortnight of the month of Māgha
and that the constellation (viz. Puṣya) was
favourable, he asked Bhīma to make prepa-
rations for the horse sacrifice (एतस्मिन्न् एव
काले तु द्वादशीं माघपाक्षिकीम्।इष्टम्
गृहीत्वा नक्षत्रं) 14. 86. 4 (Nī. on Bom.
Ed. 14. 85. 4: इष्टं नक्षत्रं पुष्यम्);
(2) Non-Vedic: (a) स्नान: Aṅgiras told
Gautama that if one who had controlled his
mind and had strictly observed the vows
bathed at Prayāga in Māgha he was puri-
fied of the sins and went to heaven 13. 26. 36;
(b) दान: One who offered sesame to Brāh-
maṇas in Māgha did not go to hell 13. 65. 7;
(c) उपवास: If one, who is devoted to father
(पितृभक्तः), spends the month of Māgha
taking food only once a day he becomes
eminent in his illustrious family and among
his kinsmen (श्रीमत्कुले ज्ञातिमध्ये स
महत्त्वं प्रपद्यते) 13. 109. 20.
D.
Smile: Bhīṣma said that the arrows which
pierced his vitals, as (the winter time
शैशिरः कालः 6. 113. 7) in the month of
Māgha pierced the vitals of cows, were those
of Arjuna and not of Śikhaṇḍin (कृन्तन्ति
मम गात्राणि माघमासे गवाम् इव।
अर्जुनस्य इमे बाणा नेमे बाणाः शिखण्डि-
नः) 6. 114. 60 (see the Editor's note on the
stanza, Cr. Ed. Vol. 7, p. 795; for the reading
माघमा (or मागमा) सेगवाम् इव and
the commentator's explanations of it, see the
Critical Apparatus on the stanza (p. 677),
and for Nī.'s expl. see Bom. Ed. 6. 119. 66).
[See Māghī]

माघी
Māghī f.; adj.: The day of full moon
in the month of Māgha; of the month of
Māgha.
A. Importance: Aṅgiras told Gautama
that on the Māghī (माघ्याम्) three crores and
ten thousand तीर्थस् visit Prayāga 13. 26. 35.
B. Auspicious: (1) for Vedic rites: Yudhi-
ṣṭhira asked his brothers to make prepara-
tions for the Aśvamedha since the roaming
horse had returned and the day was the full
moon of the month of Māgha (अभितो वर्-
तते हयः।माघी च पौर्णमासीयम्)
14. 86. 8; (2) for non-Vedic rites: (a)
The sages, Aṅgiras and others, while on a
तीर्थयात्रा, went to the holy river Kauśikī
on the Māghī (माघ्याम्) 13. 96. 6 (for the
river Kauśiki see the Editor's note on 13.
3. 10, Cr. Ed. Vol. 17, part II, p. 1054);
(b) On every Māghī (as well as on the
Āṣāḍhi) Virūpākṣa, the king of the Rākṣasas
used to give excellent and well-garnished
food, as desired, to the Brāhmaṇas (तस्य
(i. e. of Virūpākṣa) नित्यं तथाषाष्ह्यां
माघ्यां च बहवो द्विजाः।ईप्सितं भोज-
नवरं लभन्ते सत्कृतं सदा॥) 12.
165. 15. [See Māgha]

माधव
Mādhava m.: Name of a month.
[See Vaiśākha].

मार्गशीर्ष
Mārgaśīrṣa m.: Name of a month.
A. Importance: Bhagavān, while
describing his विभूतिस् to Arjuna, said that
he was the Mārgaśīrṣa among the months
(मासानां मार्गशीर्षो ऽहम्) 6. 32. 35.
B. Religious rites: उपवास: Bhīṣma told
Yudhiṣṭhira that one who spent the month of
Mārgaśirṣa taking food only once a day
and fed the twice-born with devotion would
be freed from diseases and sins; he would
also be born enjoying all blessings, possess-
ing all medicinal herbs, reaping good harvest,
wealthy, and would have many sons (सर्व-
कल्याणसंपूर्णः सर्वौषधिसमन्वितः।
कृषिभागी बहुधनो बहुपुत्रश् च जायते)
13. 109. 18.

मार्गशीर्षी
Mārgaśīrṣī f.: The full moon day of the
month of Mārgaśirṣa.
A. Epic event: The Pāṇḍavas, toge-
ther with Dhaumya and other forest dwellers,
started on their pilgrimage from the Kāmyaka
forest under the constellation Puṣya when
the full moon day of the month of Mārgaśīrṣa
had passed (मार्गशीर्ष्याम् अतीतायां पुष्येण
प्रययुस् ततः) 3. 91. 25.
B. Proper
time for army manoeuvre: Marching out of
the army for attack on the full moon day
of the month of Caitra or of Mārgaśīrṣa is
recommended since the crops the are ripe
and water is ample; it is then also neither
too hot nor too cold 12. 101. 9-10 (for the
citation, see above Caitrī, p. 246. 1).

मूल
Mūla m., nt.: Name of a constellation.
Religious rites: (1) दान: Nārada
told Devakī (13. 63. 2-4) that by giving as
a gift with composed mind (समाहितः) roots
and fruits to the Brāhmaṇas under the con-
stellation Mūla (मूले मूलफलं दत्त्वा)
one delights the manes, and gets the desired
state after death (गतिम् इष्टां च गच्छति)
13. 63. 24; (2) श्राद्ध: Yama told
Śaśabindu (13. 89. 1) that by offering a
काम्य श्राद्ध under the Mūla one becomes
healthy (मूले त्व् आरोग्यम् अर्च्छेत) 13.
89. 10.

म्र्गोत्तम
Mrgottama nt.: Name of the constella-
tion Mṛgaśiras; also called Tārāmṛga (m.)
(3. 262. 19) and Somadaivata (13. 63. 7).
A. Religious rites: (1) दान: Nārada
told Devakī (13. 63. 2-4) that those who
gave as a gift a milch cow with a calf under
the constellation Somadaivata (नक्षत्रे
सोमदैवते) went to the excellent heaven
from the world of mortals (गच्छन्ति मानु-
षाल् लोकात् स्वर्गलोकम् अनुत्तमम्) 13.
63. 7 (Nī. on Bom. Ed. 13. 64. 7: सौम्य-
नक्षत्रे मृगशिरसि); (2) श्राद्ध: Yama
told Śaśabindu (13. 89. 1) that one desirous
of vigour should offer a श्राद्ध under the
constellation Mṛgottama (ओजस्कामो मृगोत्-
तमे) 13. 89. 3 (Unknown commentator:
मृगोत्तमे मृगशिरसि, cf. Editor's note on
the stanza Cr. Ed. Vol. 17, p. 1090).
B.
Simile: Rāma ran after the deer as did
Rudra after the Tārāmṛga (अन्वधावन्
मृगं रामो रुद्रस् तारामृगं यथा)
3. 262. 19 (Nī. on Bom. Ed. 3. 278. 20:
तारामृगं तारारूपं मृगम् … तद् एतन्
मृगशीर्षं नाम नक्षत्रम्).

मैत्र
Maitra1 nt.: Name of the constellation
Anurādhā.
Balarāma, angered, left for the तीर्थयात्रा
on the river Sarasvatī under the sun's con-
junction with Maitra (ततो मन्युपरीतात्मा
जगाम … ।तीर्थयात्रां हलधरः सरस्-
वत्यां महायशाः।मैत्रे नक्षत्रयोगे
स्म … ॥) 9. 34. 12 (Nī. on Bom. Ed.
9. 35. 14 मैत्रनक्षत्रयोगे अनुराधायाम्;
see Puṣya1 B (4) above p. 256; however,
see the Editor's note on this stanza: “There
is no real inconsistency between this passage
on the one hand and 9. 33. 5 and 9. 34. 14
on the other. The latter evidently refer to
the Nakṣatra (that is, Puṣya) occupied by
the moon, while मैत्रे नक्षत्रयोगे refers
to the sun's conjunction with the Nakṣatra
Maitra (= Anurādhā)” Cr. Ed. Vol. 11,
p. 489). [See Anurādhā]

मैत्र
Maitra2 m.: Name of a मुहूर्त।
On the day when Kṛṣṇa wanted to go to
Hāstinapura he woke up and finished his early
morning rites when sun rose and the Maitra
Muhūrta had set in (सूर्ये विमल उद्गते।
मैत्रे मुहूर्ते संप्राप्ते। … कृत्वा पौर्-
वाण्हिकं कृत्यम्) 5. 81. 6, 9 (Nī., however,
on Bom. Ed. 5. 83. 6: मैत्रे जन्मर्क्षाद्
अष्टमतारायाम् दूतस्य हि स्वामिबलेनैव
बलवत्त्वम् इत्य् अर्थः).

यमस्य
Yamasya Putraḥ m.: Name of a planet
(Ketu ?).
When Karṇa fell, the rivers stood still,
the sun, with a turbid hue set, and the planet,
the son of Yama, having the colour of blazing
sun arose obliquely (ग्रहश् च तिर्यग् ज्वलि-
तार्कवर्णो यमस्य पुत्रो ऽभ्युदियाय
राजन्) 8. 68. 47 (one Telugu (T2) ms.
actually reads केतुः for राजन्; most Bengali
mss., few Devanāgarī and one Grantha read
सोमस्य पुत्रो i. e. Budha).

राका
Rākā f.: Name of the second Paurṇa-
māsī when the full moon day extends to two
days (cf. या पूर्वा पौर्णमासी सानुमतिर्
योत्तरा सा राका Ait. Br. 32. 9; Nir. 11. 29).
A. Description: Observing her vows
strictly (सुव्रता) 8. 24. 74.
B. Mytholo-
gical events: (1) Rākā, personified, along with
Anumatī and many others arrived at the
river Sarasvatī to attend the investiture of
Kumāra as the general of the gods 9. 44.
12, 16; (2) she served as one of the reins
of the horses of Śiva's chariot when it was
made ready for Śiva's fight with the Tripuras
(कुहूं राकां च सुव्रताम्।योक्त्राणि
चक्रुर् वाहानाम्) 8. 24. 74.

राहु
Rāhu m.: Name of a planet, also called
Svarbhānu (6. 13. 39-40; 13. 17. 37).
A. Description: Described as round
(परिमण्डल) 6. 13. 40; fierce (तीव्र)
6. 3. 26; dark (श्याम) 6. 3. 15; blazing,
(प्रज्वलित) 6. 3. 15; having smoke and fire
सधूमः सहपावकः) 6. 3. 15; having
copper-red crest (? ताम्र° °शिख) 6. 3. 24.
B. Importance: Chief among the planets
(ग्रहपतिर् वरः) 13. 17. 37; Rāhu, along
with other planets, visits the सभा of Brah-
man 2. 11. 20, 19; Rāhu, not directly named
but probably referred to as Grahapati, finds
place in the list of a thousand names of
Śiva (केतुग्रहो ग्रहपतिर् वरः) 13. 17.
37 (however, Nī. on Bom. Ed. 13. 17. 38,
interprets ग्रहः as राहुः: केतुश् च प्रसिद्-
धः।चन्द्राक्रौ गृह्णातीति ग्रहो राहुः।
ग्रहाणां पतिः [ग्रहपतिः] क्रूरत्वात्
मंगलः); Rāhu finds place also in the
Daivatavaṃśa 13. 151. 12.
C. Measure-
ment: Dhṛtarāṣṭra asked Saṃjaya to tell
him complete extent (सर्वं (प्रमाणं))
of Rāhu, to which Saṃjaya agreed 6. 12.
3-4; according to the information of Saṃ-
jaya his diameter (विष्कम्भ) was 12000
योजनस्, and his circumference (परिणाह)
36000 योजनस्; according to the learned
Paurāṇikas his expanse (? विपुलत्व) was
6000 योजनस् (परिमण्डलो महाराज स्वर्-
भानुः श्रूयते ग्रहः।योजनानां सह-
स्राणि विष्कम्भो द्वादशास्य वै॥परिणा-
हेन षट्त्रिंशद् विपुलत्वेन चानघ।
षष्टिम् आहुः शतान्य् अस्य बुधाः पौरा-
णिकास् तथा) 6. 13. 40-41 (Nī. on Bom.
Ed. 6. 12. 41 interprets विपुलत्वेन as
ततो ऽप्य् आधिक्येन, इदम् उत्तरान्वयि; in
that case the circumference of Rāhu will be
36000 + 6000 = 42000 योजनस्; see also
Editor's note on the stanza, Cr. Ed. Vol. 7,
p. 765: “Saṃjaya is here relying upon his
studies, and not upon the Eye Divine”);
owing to its being larger in size than the sun
and the moon, Rāhu covers them both at
proper times (स राहुश् छादयत्य् एतौ
(i. e. चन्द्रादित्यौ) यथाकालं महत्तया)
6. 13. 45.
D. Omens: (1) Among the
bad omens for the Kurus reported by Vyāsa
to Dhṛtarāṣṭra one was related to Rāhu's
swallowing the sun 6. 3. 11; this event is
again referred to by Vyāsa as occurring
at an improper time, i. e. on the thirteenth
day of the month and in which Rāhu swa-
llowed both Candra and Sūrya together;
this meant destruction of the subjects 6. 3.
28-29 (for citation and Nī.'s commentary
see Sūrya below); also cf. 14. 76. 15; 2. 71.
26; 9. 55. 10; the same was also noted by
Karṇa and reported to Kṛṣṇa (राहुर् अर्कम्
उपैष्यति) 5. 141. 10 (Nī. on Bom. Ed. 5. 143.
11: अयं कर्तरीयोगः सोमवंश्यानां
सूर्यवंश्यानां च राज्ञां क्षयकर
इत्य् अर्थः); (reference to Rāhu implied in
6. 73. 10: प्रजासंहरणे सूर्यः क्रूरैर्
इव महाग्रहैः (परिवृतः); (2) Among
the omens noticed by Vyāsa there was also
another according to which a black planet
(= Rāhu) blazing, and full of smoke and
fire had gone over to Jyeṣṭhā and remained
there (श्यामो ग्रहः प्रज्वलितः सधू-
मः सहपावकः। … ज्येष्ठाम् आक्रम्य
तिष्ठति॥)) 6. 3. 15 (Nī. on Bom. Ed. 6. 3.
16 reads श्वेतो ग्रहः in place of श्यामो
ग्रहः and explains it as Ketu: श्वेतो द्वितीय
उपग्रहः केतुसंज्ञः); (3) Vyāsa
had also noticed that the two Grahas
(Rāhu and Ketu ?) having copper-red and
ruddy crests (respy. ?) appear blazing in the
sky and cover up the lustre of the seven
sages (i. e. the constellation Ursa Major)
(ग्रहौ ताम्रारुणशिखौ प्रज्वलन्ताव् इव
स्थितौ।सप्तर् षीणाम् उदाराणां समवच्-
छाद्य वै प्रभाम्॥) 6. 3. 24; (4)
Kṛṣṇa observed that the अमावास्या had
already set in on the thirteenth day of the
dark half of the month and that Rāhu had
turned the fourteenth day into the fifteenth
(which was looked upon as bad); he told the
Yādavas that such an event had happened
only once before at the time of the Bhārata
war (a reference to 6. 3. 28-29 above) and
that it had now occurred again to foretell
the destruction of the Yādavas (त्रयो-
दश्याम् अमावास्या तान् दृष्ट्वा प्राब्रवीद्
इदम्॥चतुर्दशी पञ्चदशी कृतेयं राहुणा
पुनः।तदा च भारते युद्धे प्राप्ता
चाद्य क्षयाय नः॥) 16. 3. 16-17 (Nī. on
Bom. Ed. 16. 2. 19, notices a hint of a solar
eclipse in this statement: एवं सत्य् अग्रिम-
पक्षे वृद्ध्या भाव्यं तन् न जातं
प्रत्य् उत एका तिथिः क्षीणा तत्र ग्रहणं
च जातम्). [See Dhūmaketu; for Rāhu,
also see Section 1. 7]

रेवती
Revatī f.: Name of a constellation.
A. Placement in the Śākadvīpa: In
the Śākadvīpa, the constellation Revatī has
been permanently stationed in the sky by an
arrangement made by Pitāmaha (Brahman)
(रेवती दिवि नक्षत्रम् (नित्यं) पितामह-
कृतो विधिः॥) 6. 12. 16 (Nī. on Bom. Ed.
6. 11. 18: रेवती ज्योतिर्मण्डलरूपेण दिवि
विभ्रम्यमाणापि दिव्येन रूपेण अत्रापि
वर्तते एवं विधिर् मर्यादा पितामहेन
कृता).
B. Auspicious constellation: Kṛṣṇa
started for Hāstinapura on his peace mission
under the constellation Revatī (रेवत्याम्)
5. 81. 7.
C. Religious rites: (1) दान:
Nārada told Devaki (13. 63. 2-4) that if
one gave as a gift a milch cow together with
a milk-pail made of white copper under
Revatī, the cow waited upon the giver in his
next life and fulfilled his wishes (कांस्यो-
पदोहनां धेनुं रेवत्यां यो प्रयच्-
छति।सा प्रेत्य कामान् आदाय दातारम् उप-
तिष्ठति) 13. 63. 33; (2) श्राद्ध: Yama
told Śaśabindu (13. 89. 1) that by offering
a काम्य श्राद्ध under the Revatī one
obtained wealth consisting of much silver
(बहुरूप्यकृतं वित्तं विन्दते रेवतीं
श्रितः) 13. 89. 14 (For Revatī also see
Section 1. 7).

रोहिणी
Rohiṇī f. (sg., once pl. 12. 160. 80):
Name of a constellation.
A. Computation of time: Abhijit, youn-
ger sister of Rohiṇī, vying with her and
desiring for a higher rank went to forest to
practise austerities; Indra was then confused
in calculating time (due to the loss of
a नक्षत्र) 3. 219. 8-9; hence Brahman
ordained that time (काल) would commence
with Dhaniṣṭhā, while formerly it commenced
with Rchiṇī; this made good the loss of one
नक्षत्र (रोहिण्याद्यो ऽभवत् पूर्वम् एवं
संख्या समाभवत्) 3. 219. 10 (for full
citation and Nī.'s commentary see Abhijit and
Dhaniṣṭhā).
B. Auspicious constellation:
The Pāṇḍavas left for Vāraṇāvata on the
eighth day of Phalguna and under the con-
stellation Rohiṇī (रोहिण्याम्) 1. 133. 30.
C. Religious rites: (1) दान: Nārada
told Devakī (13. 63. 2-4) that in order to
be free from debt (to the manes ?) one
should, under the constellation Rohiṇī, feed
the Brāhmaṇas with known kinds of meat,
beans, cooked rice and clarified butter, and
give them milk at the end of the meal
(रोहिण्यां प्रथितैर् मांसैर् माषैर्
अन्नेन सर्पिषा।पयो ऽनुपानं दातव्यम्
आनृण्याय द्विजातये॥ 13. 63. 6 (Nī. who
reads प्रसृतैर् मार्गैर् मांसैर् explains
मार्गैर् as मृगसंबन्धिभिः); (2)
श्राद्ध: Yama told Śaśabindu (13. 89. 1)
that one desirous of offspring should offer a
श्राद्ध under Rohiṇī (रोहिण्याम्) 13. 89.
3.
D. Rohiṇī and the असि: The sword
which was created by Brahman as a weapon
(12. 160. 42) had the Rohiṇī stars for their
गोत्र (रोहिण्यो गोत्रम् अस्य (असेः)) 12.
160. 80.
E. Omens: (1) Among the
omens noticed by Vyāsa before the start of
the war there was one according to which
Śanaiścara was afflicting Rohiṇī (रोहिणीं
पीडयन्न् एष स्थितो राजञ् शनैश्चरः) 6.
2. 32 (also cf. the next section F (3); also 5.
141. 7 ? see Prājāpatya2) (2) At the time
of Karṇa's death, Bṛhaspati was afflicting
Rohiṇī (बृहस्पती रोहिणीं संप्रपीड्य)
8. 68. 49.
F. Similes: (1) Yudhiṣṭhira
saw Gāndhārī surrounded by her daughters-
in-law as is Rohiṇī by the stars (ताराभिर् इव
रोहिणीम्) 2. 52. 27; (2) Lopāmudrā, sur-
rounded by her hundred दासीस् and a hundred
maidens, sat like Rohiṇī in the sky (रोहिणीव
दिवि प्रभो) 3. 94. 24; (3) Rāvaṇa draw-
ing near Sītā looked like the planet Śanaiś-
cara when it approached Rohiṇī (ददृशे
रोहिणीम् एत्य शनैश्चर इव ग्रहः) 3.
265. 6; (4) Śāntā waited on Ṛśyaśṛnga
like Rohiṇī on Soma (रोहिणी सोमम् इवानु-
कूला) 3. 113. 22; (5) Sudeva wondered
when would Damayanti be united with Nala
and reach the end of her hardship as Rohiṇī
on meeting the moon (रोहिणी शशिनो यथा)
3. 65. 21. [See Prājāpatya2; for Rohiṇī
also see Section 1. 7]

रौद्र
Raudra m.: Name of a मुथूर्त।
Relationship with events: (1) Epic:
(a) Arjuna warned Bhīma during his noctu-
ral fight with Hiḍimba that with the advent
of the Raudra मुहूर्त the Rākṣasas grew
stronger (रौद्रे मुहूर्ते रक्षांसि प्रब-
लानि भवन्ति च) 1. 142. 22; (b) On the
fourteenth day of the war Arjuna appeared on
the scene under the Raudra मुहूर्त when
the two armies were about to clash (रौद्रे
मुहूर्ते संप्राप्ते सव्यसाची व्यदृश्यत)
7. 64. 3; (रौद्र मुहूर्त very probably
‘terrible hour’ 8. 68. 35); (2) Mytho-
logical: During his conversation with Deva-
senā, Indra observed that the Raudra मुहूर्त
had commenced on a new-moon day (अमा-
वास्यां संप्रवृत्तं मुहूर्तं रौद्रम्
एव च) 3. 213. 27; (धर्मगतं रौद्रम् ?
3. 213. 30).

वसिष्ठ
Vasiṣṭha m.: Name of one of the seven
stars of the constellation Ursa Major.
Among the bad omens noticed by Vyāsa
before the war there was one according
to which the star Arundhatī shone more
brightly than the star Vasiṣṭha (अरुन्धती
तयाप्य् एष वसिष्ठः पृष्ठतः कृतः) 6. 2.
31 (see Editor's note on the stanza, Cr.
Ed. Vol. 7, p. 757). [For Vasiṣṭha, also
see Section 1. 7]

वह्निदैवत
Vahnidaivata nt.: Name of the नक्षत्र
Kṛttikā (whose regent is god fire).
Events: (1) Epic: Kṛṣṇā (Draupadī)
bore a son Śrutasena by Sahadeva under the
constellation Vahnidaivata (नक्षत्रे वह्नि-
दैवते) 1. 213. 78; (2) Mythological: When
the Kṛttikās went to the heaven to fill in the
gap caused by the dropping down of Abhijit,
they began to shine there as the Vahnidai-
vata नक्षत्र having the shape of a cart
(त्रिदिवं कृत्तिका गताः।नक्षत्रं शकटा-
कारं भाति तद् वह्निदैवतम्) 3. 219.
11. [See Āgneya, Kṛttikā]

वारुण
Vāruṇa nt.: Name of the नक्षत्र
Śatabhiṣaj (sacred to Varuṇa).
Yama told Śaśabindu (13. 89. 1) that
by offering a काम्य श्राद्ध under the नक्ष-
त्र Vāruṇa a physician became successful
(नक्षत्रे वारुणे कुर्वन् भिषक् सिद्धिम्
अवाप्नुयात्) 13. 89. 12 (Nī. on Bom. Ed.
वारुणे शतभिषजि; unknown commentator:
शतभिषायाम्, see Ed.'s note on the stanza,
Vol. 17, p. 1090). [See Śatabhiṣaj]

विशाखा
Viśākhā f. (sg., du., pl.): Name of a
नक्षत्र।
A. Religious rites: (1) दान: Nārada
told Devakī (13. 63. 2-4) that if one gave to
Brāhmaṇas under the constellation Viśākhā
a bull, a milch cow, a cart supplied with
an iron yoke (? or a four-cornered cover-
ing ?) and filled with grain and clothes, he
satisfied the manes and the gods and enjoyed
infinite bliss after death; he met with no
adversities, went to heaven, obtained by
giving this gift as prescribed the desired
means of maintenance, and he certainly
never experienced sufferings of the hell and
similar places (विशाखायाम् अनड्वाहं
धेनुम् दत्त्वा च दुग्धदाम्।सप्रासङ्गं
च शकटं सधान्यं वस्त्रसंयुतम्॥ …
दत्त्वा यथोक्तं विप्रेभ्यो वृत्तिम् इष्टां
च विन्दति।नरकादींश् च संक्लेशान् नाप्-
नोतीति विनिश्चयः) 13. 63. 19-21 (unknown
commentator: सप्रासङ्गं लोहयुगादि-
युक्तम् इत्य् अर्थः, see Editor's note on the
stanza, Vol. 17, p. 1080; Nī., however, on
Bom. Ed. 13. 64. 19: प्रासङ्गो धान्यादि-
पिधानयोग्यं चतुरस्रम्); (2) श्राद्ध:
Nārada told Devakī (13. 89. 1) that one who
desired to give an offering to the manes (पित्र्-
यम् ईहन्) under the Viśākhās (विशाखासु)
obtained many sons 13. 89. 8.
B. Omens:
Among the omens noticed by Vyāsa before
the start of the war and reported to Dhṛta-
rāṣṭra there was one according to which
the planets Bṛhaspati and Śanaiścara were
stationed near the two Viśākhās (विशाख-
योः) and they stayed in that position for a
year (for the citation and Nī.'s commentary
see Bṛhaspati).
C. Simile: (1) Karṇa's
face, adorned with the कुण्डलस् on two sides
shone like the moon stationed between the two
Viśākhā stars (विशाखयोर् मध्यगतः
शशीव) 3. 285. 11; (2) also the head of
the Pāṇḍya king 8. 15. 42.

विश्वामित्र
*Viśvāmitra m.: Name of a star (not
directly named).
The star Viśvāmitra shines in the north
between the polar star and the Brahmarṣis
(i. e. the seven sages forming the Ursa
Major) (ध्रुवस्यौत्तानपादस्य ब्रह्मर्-
षीणां तथैव च।मध्ये ज्वलति यो
नित्यम् उदीचीम् आश्रितो दिशम्) 13. 3. 15 (See
Ed.'s note on the stanza, Vol. 17, p. 1054).

वैवस्वत
Vaivasvata nt.: Name of the 7th मन्-
वन्तर (i. e. the present age) which is pre-
sided over by Manu Vaivasvata.
An unknown being without a bodily
form, stationed in the sky, told Ekata, Dvita
and Trita (उवाच खस्थं किम् अपि भूतं
तत्राशरीरकम् 12. 323. 46) that in the
Tretāyuga of the Vaivasvata Antara they
would work as helpers of gods for achieving
their (gods') purpose (वैवस्वते ऽन्तरे
विप्राः प्राप्ते त्रेतायुगे ततः।सुराणां
कार्यसिद्ध्यर्थं सहाया वै भविष्यथ)
12. 323. 51.

वैसाख
Vaisākha m.: Name of a month, also
called Mādhava.
A. Event: Yavakrī, the son of Bhara-
dvāja, in his wanderings once went to Rai-
bhya's आश्रम in the month of Mādhava
(माधवे मासि) 3. 137. 1 (Nī. on Bom. Ed.
3. 136. 1: माधवे वैशाखे).
B. Reli-
gious rite: उपवास: Aṅgiras told Bhīṣma
that if one, with controlled sense organs, spent
the month of Vaiśākha eating only once a
day (निस्तरेद् एकभक्तेन वैशाखम्),
whether he be a man or a woman, became
eminent among his kinsmen 13. 109. 23.
C. Use in a Simile: Description of a “Brah-
macārī” who visited Ṛśyaśṛṅga's hermitage:
just as the forest, in the month of Mādhava
(माधवमासि), when stirred by the wind,
wafts (fragrance), so does ‘he’, when
attended by wind, emits (fragrance) 3.
112. 8.

वैष्णव
Vaiṣṇava nt.: Name of the Śravaṇa
नक्षत्र presided over by Viṣṇu.
Vasiṣṭha and Vāmadeva together conse-
crated Rāma on the throne under the constel-
lation Vaiṣṇava and on an agreeable day
(ततस् तं वैष्णवे शूरं नक्षत्रे
ऽभिमते ऽहनि) 3. 275. 65 (Nī. on Bom.
Ed. 3. 291. 66 वैष्णवे नक्षत्रे श्रवणे)
[See Śravaṇa].

शतभिषज्
Śatabhiṣaj m.: Name of a नक्षत्र।
Nārada told Devakī (13. 63. 2-4) that
by giving gift of fragrant substances along
with अगुरु and sandal wood one went after
death to the world of the Apsarases and
acquired permanent fragrances (गन्धाञ्
शतभिषग्योगे दत्त्वा सागुरुचन्दनान्।
प्राप्नोत्य् अप्सरसां लोकान् प्रेत्य गन्-
धांश् च शाश्वतान्) 13. 63. 30. [See
Vāruṇa]

शनैश्चर
Śanaiścara m.: Name of the planet
Saturn, son of the Sun (सूर्यपुत्र 6. 3. 14;
12. 337. 52).
A. Description: sharp (तीक्ष्ण) 5.
141. 7; very fierce (महाघोर) 6. 100.
20; having great lustre (महाद्युति) 5. 141.
7; blazing (प्रज्वलित) 6. 3. 25.
B.
Importance: Nārāyaṇa told the sage Apa-
rāntatama(s) that in the Vaivasvata Man-
vantara (12. 337. 41) Śanaiścara, the son
of Sūrya, will be the great Manu (शनैश्-
चरः सूर्यपुत्रो भविष्यति मनुर् महान्।
तस्मिन् मन्वन्तरे चैव) 12. 337. 52;
Śanaiścara, along with the other planets,
visits the सभा of Brahman (2. 11. 20);
mentioned in the Daivatavaṃśa (13. 151.
12).
C. Name of Sūrya: Śanaiścara
appears as the 31st name in the list of a
hundred names of Sūrya taught by Dhau-
mya to Yudhiṣṭhira 3. 3. 20.
D. Omens:
Among the bad omens observed by Vyāsa
before the war and reported to Dhṛtarāṣṭra
there was one according to which the planet
Śanaiścara was afflicting the constellation
Rohiṇī (रोहिणीं पीडयन्न् एष स्थितो राजञ्
शनैश्चरः) 6. 2. 32; but in another state-
ment Vyāsa said that Sūryaputra (i. e.
Śanaiścara) was afflicting the constellation
Bhāgya i. e. the Uttarā Phalgunī (भाग्यं
नक्षत्रम् आक्रम्य सूर्यपुत्रेण पीड्यते)
6. 3. 14 (Nī. on Bom. Ed. 6. 3. 14:
भगं नक्षत्रं पूर्वाफल्गुनी श्रुति-
मते तूत्तरा फल्गुनी); still according to
another observation of Vyāsa the two blaz-
ing planets Bṛhaspati and Śanaiścara were
stationed near the two Viśākhā stars and
had remained there for a year (संवत्सर-
स्थायिनौ च ग्रहौ प्रज्वलिताव् उभौ।
विशाखयोः समीपस्थौ बृहस्पतिशनैश्-
चरौ॥) 6. 3. 25 (for Nī.'s comm. see
Bṛhaspati); (2) According to one of the
bad omens observed by Karṇa and reported
to Kṛṣṇa, Śanaiścara was afflicting the con-
stellation Prājāpatya, i. e. Rohiṇī and as a
result was afflicting the living beings all the
more (प्राजापत्यं हि नक्षत्रं ग्रहस्
तीक्ष्णो महाद्युतिः।शनैश्चरः पीडयति
पीडयन् प्राणिनो ऽधिकम्) 5. 141. 7.
D.
Simile: (1) Śalya, fighting with Yudhi-
ṣṭhira, looked like Śanaiścara in the vicinity
of Candramas 9. 15. 10; (2) Ārjuni
(Abhimanyu) and Citrasena who came close
to each other in a duel looked like the
planets Budha and Śanaiścara in the sky
6. 100. 20; (3) Rāvaṇa approaching Sītā
looked like Śanaiścara moving near Rohiṇī
3. 265. 6.

शिशुमार
Śiśumāra m.: Designation of a group of
stars (having the shape of a dolphin), occurs
in the name of a town (?), a direction (?)
The kings and the Brāhmaṇas who came
to attend the स्वयंवर of Draupadī went
to Śiśumārapura and took residence there
(ब्राह्मणाश् च महाभागाः … शिशुमार-
पुरं प्राप्य न्यविशंस् ते च पार्थिवाः)
1. 176. 14-15 (Nī., who reads शिशुमार-
शिरः प्राप्य observes on Bom. Ed. 1. 185.
16: शिशुमारो जलजन्तुः तदाकारस् तारा-
समूहात्मको विष्णुः तस्य शिरःप्रदेशे
ऐशान्यां दिशि).

शुक्र
Śukra1 m.: Name of the planet Venus,
also called Bhārgava (7. 143. 30).
A. Description: lustrous (तेजस्विन्)
12. 278. 5.
B. History: (1) Yudhiṣṭhira
once asked Bhīṣma how Uśanas of im-
perishable lustre became Śukra and how he
acquired prosperity (कथं चाप्य् उशना
प्राप शुक्त्रत्वम् अमरद्युतिः।ऋद्धिं
स च कथं प्राप्तः) 12. 278. 4 (Nī.,
however, on Bom. Ed. 12. 289. 5 explains
शुक्रत्वं अस् शुक्रोत्पन्नत्वम्, cf. स विनिष्-
क्रम्य शिश्नेन शुक्रत्वम् अभिपेदिवान् 12.
278. 32); Yudhiṣṭhira also asked Bhīṣma
why does Śukra not move through the middle
of the sky (न याति च स तेजस्वी मध्येन
नभसः कथम्) 12. 278. 5; 12. 278. 32
(Nī., however, on Bom. Ed. 12. 289. 5:
तस्य आकाशगतिः कुतः कुण्ठितेत्य् अर्थः।
सप्तर्षिवद् द्वीरूपेण स्थितस्य शुक्रस्य
भूस्थमूर्तिविषयक एवायं प्रश्नो न
भचक्रस्थमूर्तिविषयः तेन यथा भौ-
मानां वसिष्ठादीनां स्वर्गे ऽपि गतिर् अस्ति
नैवं भौमस्य शुक्रस्यास्तीति गम्यते।);
(2) Parāśara told Janaka that Uśanas be-
came Śukra by propitiating Devadeva (Śiva);
and by praising Devī (Umā) he, covered
with lustre, delights in the sky (गतः
शुक्रत्वम् उशना देवदेवप्रसादनात्।
देवीं स्तुत्वा तु गगने मोदते तेजसा वृतः)
12. 281. 14 (a reference to 12. 278. 13-37);
(3) Planet Śukra is the son of Kavi
(शुक्रः कविसुतो ग्रहः) 1. 60. 40 (Nī.
on Bom. Ed. 1. 66. 42: शुक्रो ग्रह-
त्वाद् एव लोकानां प्राणयात्रायां वर्षा-
वर्षादिकार्ये नियुक्तः)
C. Importance:
(1) Śukra, along with other planets, visits
the सभा of Brahman 2. 11. 20; (2) finds
place in the Daivatavaṃśa 13. 151. 12.
D. Name of Sūrya: Śukra appears as the 23rd
name in the list of the 108 names of Sūrya
taught by Dhaumya to Yudhiṣṭhira 3. 3. 19.
E. Auspicious: (1) When Dhṛtarāṣṭra
heard that the planet Śukra and Sūrya
both together were favourable to the sons
of Kuntī for their victory in war he did
not hope to win (यदाश्रौषं शुक्र-
सूर्यौ च युक्तौ कौन्तेयानाम् अनुलोमौ
जयाय … तदा नासंसे विजयाय संजय॥)
1. 1. 129; (2) Bhīṣma told Yudhiṣṭhira
that in wars, victory was on that side for
which wind, Sūrya and the planet Śukra were
favourable; if they all were simultaneously
present, each time the former was stronger
than the latter (यतो वायुर् यतः सूर्यो
यतः शुक्रस् ततो जयः।पूर्वं पूर्वं
ज्याय एषां संनिपाते युधिष्ठिर 12. 101.
17.
F. Bad effect: While Śukra is in
conjunction with the two Proṣṭhapadās it has
wealth (as Kubera, the lord of riches, also
has); Śukra in that position takes away from
men whatever they have earned according to
their desires 5. 112. 3 (for citation and Nī.'s
comm. see Pūrvā Bhādrapadā); (for Śukra
as a great sage and perfect in योग depriv-
ing also Kubera of his wealth see 12. 278.
7-9).
G. Omens: Among the bad omens
noticed by the Vyāsa before the war one was
related to Śukra's ascending the Pūrva
Proṣṭhapada and then, after going over to the
Uttara Proṣṭhapada, both looking back at
the Pūrva Proṣṭhapada 6. 3. 14 (for citation
see Uttarā Bhādrapadā).
H. Similes:
(1) The battle between Drupada and Jaya-
dratha, delightful to the spectators (ईक्षितृ-
प्रीतिजननम्), was like the one between
Śukra and Aṅgāraka 6. 43. 54; (2) Droṇa
and Arjuna met in battle like Budha and
Śukra in the sky (नभस्तले) 6. 97. 57;
(3) The battle between Prativindhya and
Duḥśāsana was like the one between Budha
and Bhārgava (Śukra) in a cloudless sky
(व्यपेतजलदे व्योम्नि) 7. 143. 30; (4)
Arjuna, with Kṛṣṇa and Sātyaki by his
side in the chariot, looked like the darkness-
destroying Śaśin with Budha and Śukra 7.
60. 20. [For Śukra also see Section 1. 7]

शुक्र
Śukra2 m.: Name of the month Jyaiṣṭha,
mentioned mostly along with Śuci.
Similes: (1) When Bhīma strode fast,
wind generated by the speed of his thighs
blew as it does at the advent of the months
Śukra (Jyaiṣṭha) and Śuci (Āṣāḍha) (प्र-
ववाव् अनिलो राजञ् शुचिशुक्रागमे यथा)
1. 138. 1. (Nī. on Bom. Ed. 1. 151. 2:
शुचिशुक्रागमे ज्येष्ठाषाढयोः समये);
(2) Duryodhana, burning with anger after
witnessing the Rājasūya of the Pāṇḍavas, was
drying up as does scanty water at the advent
of Jyaiṣṭha and Āṣāḍha (शुचिशुक्रागमे काले
शुष्ये तोयम् इवाल्पकम्) 2. 43. 21 (Nī. on
Bom. Ed. 2. 47. 24: शुचिशुक्रौ ज्येष्ठा-
षाढौ तयोर् आगमे ग्रीष्मर्तौ); (3)
Arjuna, tormenting his enemies with his
Gāṇḍīva bow drawn full circle and his
arrows issuing from it like hot rays, shone
like the haloed sun in the middle of the
months Jyaiṣṭha and Āṣāḍha (तपन् रिपून्
अर्जुनभास्करो बभौ।शरोग्ररश्मिः
शुचिशुक्रमध्यगो यथैव सूर्यः परि-
वेषगस् तथा॥) 8. 57. 57. [See Jyeṣṭhā-
mūla]

शुचि
Śuci m.: Name of the month Āṣāḍha,
mentioned mostly with Śukra2.
Simile: Droṇa, showering (arrows) like
hail stones frightened his enemies as does the
roaring and windly Parjanya at the end of
the month Śuci (i. e. at the end of Āṣāḍha,
or at the end of the hot season ?) (नान-
द्यमानः पर्जन्यः सानिलः शुचिसंक्षये।
अश्मवर्षम् इवावर्षत् परेषाम् आवहद्
भयम्॥) 7. 13. 5 (Nī. on Bom. Ed. 7.
14. 5: शुचिसंक्षये ग्रीष्मान्ते); for other
similes, see Śukra2. [See Āṣāḍha]

श्याम
Śyāma adj.: Designation of the planet
Rāhu. [See Rāhu]

शवण
Śavaṇa m.: Name of a constellation.
A. Importance: Menakā, while descri-
bing to Indra the exploits of Viśvāmitra,
said that he, enraged by the abundance of
constellations, started to create, in addition
to the existing galaxies of constellations,
counter-constellations starting with Śravaṇa
(अति नक्षत्रवंशांश् च क्रुद्धो नक्षत्र-
संपदा।प्रति श्रवणपूर्वाणि नक्षत्राणि
ससर्ज यः॥) 1. 65. 34.
B. Auspi-
cious: Balarāma left for his तीर्थयात्रा
under the constellation Puṣya and returned,
after forty days, under the constellation
Śravaṇa (चत्वारिंशद् अहान्य् अद्य द्वे च
मे निःसृतस्य वै।पुष्येण संप्रयातो
ऽस्मि श्रवणे पुनर् आगतः॥) 9. 33. 5
(see the Editor's note on the stanza Cr. Ed.
Vol. 11, p. 489).
C. Religious rites:
(1) दान: Nārada told Devakī (13. 63. 2-4)
that if one gave under the constellation
Śravaṇa a gift of a woolen blanket with a
piece of a cloth attached from inside, he
could reach to all the worlds which remained
unconcealed from him (?) in a bright con-
veyance (श्रवणे कम्बलं दत्त्वा वस्त्रान्-
तरितम् एव च।श्वेतेन याति यानेन सर्वान्
लोकान् असंवृतान्) 13. 63. 28; (2) श्राद्ध:
Yama told Śaśabindu (13. 89. 1) that by
performing a काम्य श्राद्ध under Śravaṇa
one obtained excellent condition after death
(प्रेत्य गच्छेत् परां गतिम्) 13. 89. 11.
D. Omens: (1) According to one of the
bad omens for the armies noticed by Vyāsa
before the war, the planet Bṛhaspati was
taking retrograde step under Śravaṇa
(मघास्व् अङ्गारको वक्रः श्रवणे च
बृहस्पतिः) 6. 3. 13; (2) According to
another omen noticed by Vyāsa the planet
Mars, after taking repeated retrograde steps
(under Maghā ?), had returned to Brahma-
rāśi and remained steady in Śravaṇa 6. 3. 17
(for the citation and Nī.'s comm. see Bra-
hmarāśi p. 260 above). [See Brahmarāśi,
Vaiṣṇava and Śraviṣṭhā]

श्रविष्ठा
Śraviṣṭhā f.: Name of a constellation.
According to Brahmadeva the constella-
tions began with Śraviṣṭhā (श्रविष्ठादीनि
ऋक्षाणि) 14. 44. 2 (व्। ल्। श्रवणादीनि, see
Śravaṇa above, section A).

श्रावण
Śrāvaṇa m.: Name of a month.
Aṅgiras had told Bhīṣma that if one
remained controlled and spent the month of
Śrāvaṇa taking food only once a day he was
given the honour of अभिषेक (ceremonial
bath ?) wherever he went and became the
prosperer of his kinsmen (श्रावणं नियतो
मासम् एकभक्तेन यः क्षपेत्।यत्र
तत्राभिषेकेण युज्यते ज्ञातिवर्धनः॥)
13. 109. 26.

श्रीपञ्चमी
Śrīpañcamī f.: Name of the fifth day
(of the bright fortnight of the month of
Māgha).
When Devasenā received Skanda for her
husband, Lakṣmī, in person, attended on him;
since Skanda was chosen by Śri (Lakṣmī) on
the fifth day (of the month of Māgha), that
day became known as Śrīpañcamī. (यदा
स्कन्दः पतिर् लब्धः शाश्वतो देवसेनया।
तदा तम् आश्रयल् लक्ष्मीः स्वयं देवी
शरीरिणी॥श्रीजुष्टः पञ्चमीं स्कन्दस्
तस्माच् छ्रीपञ्चमी स्मृता) 3. 218. 48-49.

श्वेत
Śveta, Śvetagraha m.: Designation of
the planet Ketu. [See Ketu in the Addenda]

षष्ठी
Ṣaṣṭhī f.: Name of the sixth day of the
bright half of the month of Māgha (?).
A. Description: important (महातिथि)
3. 218. 49.
B. Mythological Event:
Skanda married Devasenā on the fifth day
of the month of Māgha, and on the sixth
day he achieved his objective; hence Ṣaṣṭhī
is an important day (षष्ट्यां कृतार्थो
ऽभूद् यस्मात् तस्मात् षष्ठी महातिथिः)
3. 218. 49.

सप्तर्षि
Saptarṣi m.: (pl.): The seven stars
forming the constellation Ursa Major.
A. Description: lofty (उदार) 6. 3.
24.
B. Placement in the sky: Suparṇa
told Gālava that the place of the Seven Sages
was in the north (अत्र (i. e. उत्तरायां
दिशि 5. 109. 3) ते ऋषयः सप्त) 5. 109. 12;
Mārkaṇḍeya, while instructing Yudhiṣṭhira,
told him that to honour the old injunction
laid down by Brahman the Saptarṣis shine
in the sky; hence no one should violate the
injunction considering himself to be strong
(धात्रा विधिर् यो विहितः पुराणस् तं
पूजयन्तो नरवर्य सन्तः।सप्तर्षयः
पार्थ दिवि प्रभान्ति नेशे बलस्येति चरेद्
अधर्मम्) 3. 26. 13.
C. Auspicious in
wars: Bhīṣma told Yudhiṣṭhira that the
soldiers in the army, while fighting, should
keep the constellation Ursa Major at the
back and remain steady like mountains;
this way one could wish to win even the
unconquerable opponents (सप्तर्षीन् पृष्ठ-
तः कृत्वा युध्येरन्न् अचला इव।अनेन
विधिना राजञ् जिगीषेतापि दुर्जयान्) 12. 101.
16.
D. Omens: Among the omens
noticed by Vyāsa before the war one was
related to the position of the two planets
having copper-red and ruddy crests (Rāhu
and Ketu ?) who obscured the brilliance of
the lofty stars of the Ursa Major (ग्रहौ
ताम्रारुणशिखौ प्रज्वलन्ताव् इव स्थितौ।
सप्तर्षीणाम् उदाराणां समवच्छाद्य वै
प्रभाम्) 6. 3. 24.
E. Similes: (1)
The sages in the आश्रम of Tanu sat
around the king, father of Bhūridyumna,
placing him in front as do the stars of the
constellation Ursa Major the Polar star
(ततस् ते मुनयः सर्वे परिवार्य नरर्-
षभम्।उपाविशन् पुरस्कृत्य सप्तर्षय
इव ध्रुवम्॥) 12. 126. 25; (2) The
Brāhmaṇa instructed his wife that there was
only one relative, no other; he dwelt in our
heart; (in saying this) the Brāhmaṇa was only
repeating what the relative within had said
to him: instructed by the relative within
people have relatives; they shine (like ?) the
stars of the Ursa Major (एको बन्धुर् नास्ति
ततो द्वितीयो यो हृच्छयस् तम् अहम् अनु-
ब्रवीमि।तेनानुशिष्टा बान्धवा बन्धुमन्-
तः सप्तर्षयः सप्त दिवि प्रभान्ति) 14.
26. 3. [For Saptarṣi also see Section 1. 7]

सावित्र
Sāvitra nt.: See Hasta.

सिनीवाली
Sinīvālī f.: Name of the first Amāvā-
syā day (when the Amāvāsyā extends to
two days (see Ait. Br. 32. 9: या पूर्वामा-
वास्या सा सिनीवाली योत्तरा सा कुहूः; also
cf. Nirukta 11. 31).
A. Personification: Personified as the
third daughter of Aṅgiras, of matted hair;
on account of her thinness people said that
she vanished no sooner she was seen (यां
कपर्दिसुताम् आहुर् दृश्यादृश्येति देहिनः।
तनुत्वात् सा सिनीवालि तृतीयाङ्गिरसः सुता॥)
3. 208. 5 (Nī., however, on Bom. Ed. 3. 218.
5: कपर्दिनो रुद्रस्य सुताम् इव सुतां
चन्द्रकलां ललाटे धृतत्वात्। … चतुर्दशी-
युक्तामावास्या सिनीवाली).
B. Name of
Devasenā: Brāhmaṇas called Devasenā, the
chief queen of Skanda, by different names,
one of them being Sinīvālī (देवसेनां …
यां ब्राह्मणाः प्राहुः … सिनीवालीम्)
3. 218. 47.
C. Mythological events: (1)
Sinīvālī formed one of the reins (योक्त्राणी)
of the chariot of Śiva when it was made ready
for fight with the Tripuras 8. 24. 74; (2)
she was one of those who attended the
investiture (अभिषेक) of Kumāra (Skanda)
9. 44. 12.

सूर्य
Sūrya m.: Name of the planet Sun,
referred to also as Āditya and by its other
synonyms like Arka, Ravi, Bhāskara,
Bhānu, Pataṃga.
A. Origin and activity: According to
Bhīṣma, Āditya, along with Candra, other
planets, constellations and stars were born
from Viṣvaksena (i. e. Kṛṣṇa) (चन्द्रादि-
त्यौ ग्रहनक्षत्रताराः … विष्वक्सेनात्
सर्वम् एतत् प्रसूतम्) 13. 143. 31; Puru-
sottama (Nārāyaṇa) told the seven sages,
Marīci and others, that Sūrya, Candramas,
all constellations act in their own prescribed
way in their respective spheres and are
considered an authority (सुर्याचन्द्रमसौ
 … सर्वे च नक्षत्रगणाः … अधिकारेषु
वर्तन्ते यथास्वम् … सर्वे प्रमाणं हि
12. 322. 39-40.
B. Description: Radiant
(गभस्तिमन्त्) 2. 11. 17; (अंशुमन्त्)
6. 32. 21; rich in light (विभारसु) 6. 13.
44; very generous (परमोदार) 6. 13. 44.
C. Extent: Dhṛtarāṣṭra asked Saṃjaya to
tell him everything about the extent (सर्वं
प्रमाणम्) of Arka, to which Saṃjaya agreed
6. 12. 3-4; according to Saṃjaya's information
the diameter (विष्कम्भ) of Sūrya was 1000
योजनस् and the circumference (मण्डल)
was 30000 योजनस्; (according to the
learned Pauraṇīkas) Sūrya's expanse (?
विपुलत्व) was 5800 योजनस् (सूर्यस् त्व्
अष्टौ सहस्राणि द्वे चान्ये कुरुनदन।
विष्कम्भेण, ततो राजन् मण्डलं त्रिंश-
तं समम्॥अष्टपञ्चाशतं राजन् विपुल्-
अत्वेन चानघ।श्रूयते परमोदारः
पतंगो ऽसौ विभावसुः।एतत् प्रमाणम्
अर्कस्य निर्डिष्टम् इह भारत) 6. 13. 43-
44 (Nī. on Bom. Ed. 6. 12. 41 interprets
विपुलत्वेन as ततो ऽप्य् आधिकेयेन; in that
case the circumference of Sūrya will be
30000 + 5800 = 35800 योजनस्; see also the
Editor's note on the stanza 6. 13. 41, Vol.
7, p. 765); on account of the larger extent
of Rāhu, it covers Candra and Āditya at
proper times (स राहुश् छादयत्य् एतौ
यथाकालं महत्तया।चन्द्रादित्यौ)
6. 13. 45.
D. Importance: (1) Upamanyu
while praising Śiva said that he (Śiva) was
Sūrya among the planets (ग्रहाणां सूर्य
उच्यसे) 13. 14. 156; Sūrya appears in a
complex name of Śiva (चन्द्रसूर्यगतिः)
13. 17. 37; (2) Śiva made Bhāskara the
chief of the luminous bodies (तेजसां
भास्करं चक्रे (ईशम्)) 12. 122. 31;
Brahmā told the sages that Sūrya was the
chief of the planets (सूर्यो ग्रहाणाम् अधि-
पः) 14. 43. 6; Arka was known as the
chief of the hot luminaries (अर्को ऽधिपतिर्
उष्णानाम्) 14. 43. 7; also cf. आदित्यो ज्योति-
षाम् पतिः 6. 7. 14; खेचराणां प्रवरो
यथार्कः 1. 83. 7; (3) Bhagavān, while
narrating his विभूतिस्, said that he was
Ravi among the luminous bodies (ज्योतिषां
रविर् अंशुमान्) 6. 32. 21; (4) The
divine sages, the Siddhas, and the great
sages saw Candra, Āditya and Budha, among
others, in the abode of Brahman 1. 203. 4;
Āditya, along with Candra and constellations,
wait on Brahmadeva in his सभा 2. 11. 17;
E. Advent of the Kṛtayuga: Mārkaṇḍeya
told the Pāṇḍavas that when Candra, Sūrya,
the constellation Tiṣya (Puṣya) and Bṛhas-
pati will come together in one राशि, the
Kṛtayuga will set in 3. 188. 87 (for citation
and Nī.'s commentary on it, see above
Puṣya1, p. 257. 1).
F. Mythological
events: (1) Candra, Āditya, the planets,
the stars, the constellations and the denizens
of the heaven felt dejected due to the
destruction caused by Sunda and Upasunda
(चन्द्रादित्यौ ग्रहास् तारा नक्षत्राणि
दिवौकसः।जग्मुर् विषादम्) 1. 202. 26;
(2) when the gods made ready a chariot for
Śiva's fight with the Tripuras, Sūrya and
Candramas were made the two wheels of the
excellent chariot (सूर्याचन्द्रमसौ कृत्वा
चक्रे रथवरोत्तमे) 8. 24. 71.
G.
Auspicious: (1) Bhīṣma told Yudhiṣṭhira
that in war the side which had wind, Sūrya
and Śukra favourable to it became victorious;
if they were simultaneously present, the former
of the two proved stronger (यतो वायुर्
यतः सूर्य्ō यतः शुक्रस् ततो जयः।
पूर्वं पूर्वं ज्याय एषां संनिपाते
युधिष्ठिर॥) 12. 101. 17; (2) Dhṛta-
rāṣṭra told Saṃjaya that when he heard that
both Śukra and Sūrya were favourable to
Pāṇḍavas indicating their victory, he lost
all hopes of winning the war (यदा श्रौ-
षम् शुक्रसूर्यौ च युक्तौ कौन्तेयानाम्
अनुकूलौ जयाय। … तदा नाशंसे विज-
याय संजय॥) 1. 1. 129.
H. Omens:
(1) According to an astronomical event
which took place before the war and which
was noticed by Vyāsa, अमावास्या occurred
on the thirteenth day of the month which
was very unusual; on that occasion Candra
and Sūrya were untimely swallowed the same
month by Rāhu which indicated destruction
of the subjects (चतुर्दशीं पञ्चदशीम्
भूतपूर्वां च षोडशीम्।इमां तु नाभि-
जानामि अमावास्यां त्रयोदशीम्॥चन्द्र-
सूर्याव् उभौ ग्रस्ताव् एकमासे त्रयोदशीम्।
अपर्वणि ग्रहाव् एतौ प्रजाः संक्षपयि-
ष्यतः॥) 6. 3. 28-29 (Nī. on Bom. Ed.
6. 3. 28: पर्व दर्शाख्यं पञ्चदशे
ऽह्नि भवति।एकतिथिवृद्धौ षोडशे वा
एकतिथिक्षये चतुर्दशे वाह्नि भवति।
तिथिद्वयक्षयस् तु लोके ऽत्यन्तम् अप्रसिद्-
ध इत्य् अपर्वणित्य् उक्तम्।ग्रहं यातौ
राहुणा ग्रहणं प्राप्तौ एतद् एव प्रजा-
संक्षयहेतुत्वेन शास्त्रे दृष्टम्।); a
similar event—Rāhu swallowing both Āditya
and Soma simultaneously—also occurred
when the Sindhu heroes fought Arjuna and
at that time the meteors struck Sūrya and
were scattered (उल्काश् च जघ्निरे सूर्यं
विकीर्यन्त्यः समन्ततः) 14. 76. 15-16;
for Rāhu's swallowing Āditya out of time
(अपर्वणि) also cf. 2. 71. 26, and 9. 55.
10; also cf. 5. 141. 10; and 6. 3. 11 (in the
last two references अपर्वणि does not occur);
(for Nī.'s comment on Bom. Ed. 5. 143. 11
see Rāhu above p. 267. 1 and on Bom. Ed.
6. 3. 11 he says: तत्र तुलास्थम् अर्कं
राहुर् उपैति); (2) According to another
omen noticed by Vyāsa, Arka, Indu and the
constellations were blazing day and night
irrespective of the fact whether it was day
time or night time; that also indicated des-
struction (ज्वलितार्केन्दुनक्षत्रम् निर्विशे-
षदिनक्षपम्।अहोरात्रं मया दृष्तं
तत् क्षयाय भविष्यति) 6. 2. 22; (3)
According to an omen noticed by Karṇa, a
line of black clouds covered Bhānu at dawn
and dusk which foretold great danger (कृष्णश्
च परिघस् तत्र भानुम् आवृत्य तिष्ठति।
उदयास्तम्ये संध्ये वेदयानो महद्
भयम्॥) 5. 141. 22 (but Nī. on Bom.
Ed 5. 143. 23: परिघः परिवेशः); (4)
According to the omens noticed by Saṃjaya,
when the two armies faced each other at
Kurukṣetra, Āditya at its rise appeared as
though split into two (द्विधाभूत इवादित्य
उदये प्रत्यदृश्यत) 6. 17. 3; (5) When
Karṇa marched out for war many unusual
happenings (उत्पातस्) occurred, one of them
being that seven major planets were seen
issuing out of Sūrya (निश्चरन्तो व्यदृश्यन्त
सूर्यात् सप्त महाग्रहाः) 8. 26. 34 (Nī.,
however, on Bom. Ed. 8. 37. 4: निश्चरन्तो
युद्धार्थम् इति शेषः।सुआर्यात् सूर्यम्
आरभ्य सूर्यादयो ऽन्योन्यम् युध्यन्तीत्य्
अर्थः); (6) Yājñavalkya told Janaka that
if one saw the moon (Soma) or the sun (Saha-
srāṃśu) with a hole (in the middle) like a
wheel with a broken nave he had only a week
to live (शीर्णनाभि यथा चाक्रं छिद्रं
सोमं प्रपश्यति।तथैव च सहस्रां-
शुं सप्तरात्रेण मृत्युभाक्) 12. 305. 13.
I. Similes: (1) Draupadī's five sons rushed
at the demon Ārśyaśṛṅgi (Alambusa) as five
planets rush at Ravi (ग्रहाः पञ्च यथा
रविम्) 6. 96. 35; (2) Bhīmasena, encircled
by the sons of Dhṛtarāṣṭra, looked like Sūrya
encircled by fierce planets at the time of the
destruction of the people (प्रजासंहरणे
सूर्यः क्रूरैर् इव महाग्रहैः) 6. 73. 10;
(3) Lakṣmaṇa and Rāma, surrounded by
the monkey-chiefs, looked like Candra and
Sūrya surrounded by the planets (चन्द्र-
सूर्यौ ग्रहैर् वृतौ) 3. 267. 17. [For
Sūrya also see Section 1. 7 where other re-
ferences to the sun's eclipse can be found]

सूर्यपुत्र
Sūryaputra m.: See Śanaiścara.

सोम
Soma m.: Name of the planet moon,
referred to also as Candra or Candramas
and by its other synonyms such as Indu,
Śaśin, Niśākara.
A. Origin and activity: According to
Bhīṣma, Candra, Āditya and other planets,
the constellations and stars were born from
Viṣvaksena (i. e. Kṛṣṇa) (चन्द्रादित्यौ
ग्रहनक्षत्रताराः … विष्वक्सेनात् सर्वम्
एतत् प्रसूतम्) 13. 143. 31; Puruṣottama
(Nārāyaṇa) told the seven sages, Marīci
and others, that the sun, the moon, all con-
stellations act in their own prescribed way in
their respective spheres and are considered an
authority (सूर्याचन्द्रमसौ … अद्निकारेषु
वर्तन्ते यथास्वं … सर्वे प्रमाणं हि)
12. 322. 39-40.
B. Born repeatedly,
its waxing and waning: The moon is born
repeatedly (चन्द्रमा जायते पुनः) 3. 297.
47; vanishes thousands of times (चन्द्रमा
इव … सहस्रशः।लीयते) 12. 293. 3; the
moon waxes and wanes (क्षयं वृद्धिं च
चन्द्रस्य) 12. 290. 46; the moon on the
new moon day remains only as a very thin
digit (विद्धि चन्द्रमसं दर्शे सूक्ष्मया
कलया स्थितम्) 12. 233. 15; the fifteen
digits of the moon are its source and abode;
the moon also has a sixteenth digit, which
is very thin, and that is the real moon; that
digit is not used by gods but it favours
gods (?) (कलाः पञ्चदशा योनिस् तद्
धाम इति पठ्यते।नित्यम् एतद् विजानीहि
सोमः षोडशमी कला। … षोडशा तु कला
सूक्ष्मा स सोम उपधार्यताम्।न तूप-
युज्यते देवैर् देवान् उपयनकति सा॥)
12. 293. 4, 6 (Nī. on Bom. Ed. 12. 304. 6:
देवैर् इन्द्रियैर् न उपयुज्यते पाल्यते किं-
तु देवान् एव सत्तास्फूर्तिप्रदानेन उप-
युनक्ति पालयति).
C. Description: high-
souled (महात्मन्) 6. 13. 42; whose rays
are cool (शीतरश्मि) 6. 13. 42;
D. Ex-
tent: Dhṛtarāṣṭra asked Saṃjaya to tell
him everything about the extent (सर्वं
प्रमाणम्) of Soma, to which Saṃjaya
agreed 6. 12. 3-4; according to Saṃjaya's
information the diameter (विष्कम्भ) of
Candramas was 11000 योजनस् and its cir-
cumference (मण्डलम्) 33000 योजनस्;
(according to the learned Paurāṇikas) the
expanse (वैपुल्य) of the moon was 5900
योजनस् (चन्द्रमास् तु सहस्राणि राजन्न्
एकादश स्मृतः।विष्कम्भेण कुरुश्रेष्ठ
त्रयस्त्रिंशत् तु मण्डलम्॥एकोनशष्टिर्
वैपुल्याच् छीतरश्मेर् महात्मनः) 6. 13.
42 (Nī. on Bom. Ed. 6. 12. 41 interprets
विपुलत्वेन as ततो ऽप्य् आधिक्येन; in that
case moon's circumference will be 33000 +
5900 = 38900; see also the editor's note on
the stanza 6. 13. 41, Vol. 7, p. 765); on
account of the larger extent of Rāhu, it covers
the sun and the moon at proper times (स
राहुश् छादयत्य् एतौ यथाकालं महत्-
तया।चन्द्रादित्यौ) 6. 13. 45.
E.
Importance: (1) Upamanyu, while praising
Śiva, said that he (Śiva) was Candramas
among the नक्षत्रस् (नक्षत्राणां च
चन्द्रमाः) 13. 14. 156; Soma appears
among the names of Śiva (सोमो नक्षत्र-
साधकः) 13. 17. 36; also Candra in a com-
plex form (चन्द्रसूर्यगतिः) 13. 17. 37;
(2) Soma appears as one of the names of
Sūrya taught by Dhaumya to Yudhiṣṭhira 3.
3. 19; (3) God Śiva made moon (Niśā-
kara) the chief of the constellations (चक्रे
नक्षत्राणां निशाकरम् (ईशम्)) 12. 122.
31; Candramas is known as the chief of the
constellations (नक्षत्राणां च चन्द्रमाः
(अधिपः)) 14. 43. 6; Indu is known as
the chief of the luminous bodies (ज्योतिषाम्
इन्दुर् (अधिपतिः) उच्यते) 14. 43. 7; hence
Soma is called ग्रहगणेश्वर 13. 66. 12;
ग्रहपति 12. 118. 15; 12. 162. 24; Candra
and Sūrya are surrounded by the planets
(चन्द्रसूर्यौ ग्रहैर् वृतौ) 3. 267. 17;
moon is नक्षत्रराज् 3. 226. 10; 12. 29.
123; it is surrounded by the नक्षत्रस् 5.
138. 27; it is accompanied by the नक्षत्रस्
(सनक्षत्रः) 6. 7. 14; followed by the
planets, constellations and stars 3. 266. 2;
shines along with the planets and many con-
stellations 3. 179. 12; called ताराधिप 1. 61.
30; 3. 264. 18, 20; 11. 19. 17; 12. 289. 60;
12. 327. 8; 13. 124. 4; तारापति 3. 264. 38;
3. 277. 22; 3. 292. 1; तारकाराज 3. 42. 14.
उडुराज् 9. 34. 36; 12. 52. 18; 13. 14. 110;
14. 63. 3; उडुपति 9. 50. 1; उडुप 3. 146.
68; (4) Soma is also the lord of the plants
(ओषधीनां पतिः) 14. 43. 8; (5) Candra,
along with Āditya and Budha, present in the
abode of Brahmadeva 1. 203. 4; Candramas
and the constellations wait on Brahmadeva
in his सभा 2. 11. 17-18.
F. Advent of
Kṛta Yuga: When the Moon, the Sun, the
Tiṣya (Puṣya) and Bṛhaspati will come in
one राशि, the Kṛta age will commence 3.
188. 87 (for the citation and Nī.'s com,
on it see Puṣya1, p. 257. 1).
G. Mytho-
logical events: (1) Pained due to the des-
truction indulged in by Sunda and Upasunda,
the moon, the sun, the planets, the stars, the
constellations and the denizens of the heaven
felt dejected (चन्द्रादित्यौ ग्रहास् तारा
नक्षत्राणि दिवौकसः।जग्मुर् विषादम्)
1. 202. 26; (2) When the gods made
ready an excellent chariot for Śiva's fight
with the Tripuras, Sūrya and Candramas
were made its wheels (सूर्याचन्द्रमसौ
कृत्वा चक्रे रथवरोत्तमे) 8. 24. 71.
H. Auspicious conjunction: (1) Kuntī
gave birth to Yudhiṣṭhira when the moon
was in conjunction with the Aindra (Jyeṣṭhā)
नक्षत्र (ऐन्द्रे चन्द्रसमायुक्ते) 1.
114. 4-5; (2) Vyāsa asked first Yudhi-
ṣṭhira to take the hand of Draupadī (in
marriage) since that was an auspicious
day on which Candramas would he in con-
junction with the Puṣya constellation (for
the citation and Nī.'s comment on it see
above Pauṣya p. 259. 1); (3) Daśaratha
asked his Purohita to make preparations for
the consecration of Rāma as heir-apparent
since on that night the moon would be
in conjunction with the Puṣya which was an
auspicious योग (अध्य पुष्यो निशि ब्रह्मन्
पुण्यं योगम् उपैष्यति) 3. 261. 15;
I. Omens: (1) While pointing out different
bad omens to Kṛṣṇa, Karṇa said that the
mark on Soma had disappeared (सोमस्य
लक्ष्म व्यावृत्तम्) 5. 141. 10 (But Nī. on
Bom. Ed. 5. 143. 11: लक्ष्म व्यावृत्तं
क्षीणत्वाद् अमावास्यासान्निध्यात् क्षीणचन्द्रो
ऽपि पाप एव); the same bad omen was
noticed by Vyāsa also which, according to him,
indicated great danger (व्यावृत्तं लक्ष्म
सोमस्य भविष्यति महद् भयम्) 6. 2.
32 (Here Nī. on Bom. Ed. 6. 2. 32: व्या-
वृत्तं नष्टं लक्ष्महीनश् चन्द्र दृश्यत
इत्य् अर्थः); a similar sight was noticeable
at the junction of the Tretā and the Dvāpara
when there occurred a drought for twelve
years; at that time Soma, with its mark
disappeared, receded to the south (जगाम
दक्षिणं मारगं सोमो व्यावृत्तलक्षणः)
12. 139. 15 (Nī. on Bom. Ed. 12. 141. 15:
व्यावृत्तं अन्यथाभूतं लक्षणं चिह्नं
यस्य); (2) According to another omen
noticed by Vyāsa and reported to Dhṛtarāṣṭra
the moon on the Kārttikī full moon night,
being without lustre, was (sometimes ?) not
visible, and (at other times ?) with the
colour of fire appeared in the sky which had
the same colour (अलक्ष्यः प्रभया हीनः
पौर्णमासीं च कार्त्तिकीम्।चन्द्रो ऽभूद्
अग्निवर्णश् च समवर्णे नभस्तले) 6.
2. 23; (3) According to a third omen
noticed by Vyāsa, whether it was day or
night, the sun, the moon and the constellations
appeared blazing; that indicated destruction
(ज्वलितार्केन्दुनक्षत्रं निर्विशेषदिनक्ष-
पम्।अहोरात्रं मया दृष्टं तत् क्षयाय
भविष्यति॥) 6. 2. 22; (4) According to
another astronomical event, Vyāsa noticed
that the अमावास्या had occurred on the
thirteenth day of the month which was very
unusual; on that day Candra and Sūrya
both were swallowed the same month by
Rāhu at an improper time 6. 2. 28-29 (for
citation and Nī.'s commentary see Sūrya
p. 276. 2); (5) A similar event-Rāhu
swallowed Āditya and at the same time
Soma-occurred when the Sindhu heroes
fought with Arjuna (राहुर् अग्रसद् आदित्यं
युगपत् सोमम् एव च) 14. 76. 15; (6)
Saṃjaya told Dhṛtarāṣṭra that the day on
which the two armies gathered at Kurukṣetra,
Soma was in the constellation Maghā and the
seven principal planets gathered in the sky
blazing (for the citation and Nī.'s commen-
tary on it see above Maghā, p. 263. 1);
(7) Yājñavalkya told Janataka that one to
whom the full moon appeared broken towards
the south had only a year to live (पुर्णेन्-
दुं (दीपम् एव च)।खण्डाभासं दक्षि-
णतस् ते ऽपि संवत्सरायुषः॥) 12. 305. 9;
(8) He also told Janaka that one who saw
Soma with a hole like a wheel with a broken
nave had only a week to live (शीर्णनाभि
यथा चक्रं छिद्रं सोमं प्रपश्यति।
सप्तरात्रेण मृत्युभाक्) 12. 305. 13.
J. Similes: (1) Rohiṇī's association with
the moon: Sudeva wondered when would
Damayantī be associated with Nala, as
Rohiṇī with Śaśin, and end her miseries
(रोहिणी शशिनो यथा) 3. 65. 21; Śāntā
waited on Ṛśyaśrṅga as Rohiṇī on Soma
(खे रोहिणी सोमम् इवामुकूला) 3. 113. 22;
Kuntī blessed Draupadi after her marriage
saying that she might be united with her
husbands as Rohiṇī with Soma (रोहिणी च
यथा सोमे) 1. 191. 5; also cf. चन्द्रश् च
रोहिण्याम् 5. 115. 9; रोहिणी शशिनः 13. 134.
4; (2) Moon's association with the other
नक्षत्रस्: (i) Kṛttikās: The king of the
Prāgjyotiṣa with a white parasol decorated
with garlands (मालयदामवता … श्वेतच्छ-
त्रेण) shone like the moon on a full moon
day in conjunction with the Kṛttikās (कृ-
त्तिकायोगयुक्तेन पौर्णमास्याम् इवेन्दुना)
7. 19. 18; (ii) Sāvitra: Droṇa in the
company of the five Pāṇḍava brothers looked
like the moon in association with the constel-
lation Sāvitra (i. e. Hasta) consisting of
five stars (पञ्चतारेण संयुक्तः सावित्रे-
णेव चन्द्रमाः) 1. 125. 30 (Nī. on Bom.
Ed. 1. 135. 30: सावित्रेण हस्तनक्षत्रेण);
(iii) Punarvasū: the two Pāñcāla heroes
(पाञ्चाल्यौ), guarding the wheels of Yudhi-
ṣṭhira, shone like the two Punaravasu stars
on the two sides of the moon (रथाभ्याशे
चकाशेते चन्द्रस्येव पुनर्वसू) 8. 33. 16;
(iv) Viśākhā: Karṇa with the two shin-
ing कुण्डलस् in his ears appeared like the
bright moon in the sky with two Viśākhā
stars on each side (विशाखयोर् मध्य-
गतः शशीव विमलो दिवि) 3. 285. 11; the
head of the Pāṇḍya king wearing the
कुण्डलस् shone like the moon with two
Viśākhā stars on two sides 8. 15. 42; also
8. 14. 50; (v) Constellations or stars in
general: Balarāma of white complexion and
wearing a blue garment (नीलवासाः सित-
प्रभः), seated among the kings, appeared
like the moon among the constellations
(नक्षत्रगणैः परिकीर्णो निशाकरः) 9.
33. 17; 9. 54. 42; Kṛṣṇa told Karṇa that he,
among the Pāṇḍavas, would appear like the
moon among the नक्षत्रस् 5. 138. 27; the
sons of Draupadī, with their followers, stood
round Dhṛṣṭadyumna like the multitude of
stars around the moon (चन्द्रं तारागणा
इव) 8. 32. 6; when king Sagara, followed
by his 60000 sons, moved he looked liked
the king of the नक्षत्रस् (i. e. the moon)
followed by luminous bodies in a cloudless
sky at the end of the rainy season (नक्ष-
त्रराजं वर्षान्ते व्यभ्रे ज्योतिर्गणा इव)
12. 29. 123; (3) Moon's association with
planets: (i) Aṅgāraka: Droṇa entered the
arena with Aśvatthāhman as the moon enters
a cloudless sky in the company of Aṅgāraka
(नभो जलधरैर् हीनं साङ्गारक इवां-
शुमान्) 1. 124. 18; (ii) Budha and
Śukra: Arjuna, with Kṛṣṇa and Sātyaki by
his side in the chariot, looked like the moon
destroying the darkness in the company of
Budha and Śukra (सहितो बुधशुक्राभ्यां
तमो निघ्नन् यथा शशी) 7. 60. 20; (iii)
Śanaiścara: Śalya drawing near Yudhi-
ṣṭhira looked like the planet Śanaiścara
drawing near the moon (चन्द्रमसो
ऽभ्याशे शनैश्चर इव ग्रहः) 9. 15. 10;
(iv) Planets in general: Lakṣmaṇa and
Rāma surrounded by the monkey chiefs look-
ed like the moon and the sun surrounded by
the planets (चन्द्रसूर्यौ ग्रहैर् इव) 3.
267. 17; the seven Kaurava brothers tormented
Bhīmasena (by showering arrows) as do the
seven planets the moon at the time of the
destruction of the creatures (प्रजासंह-
रणे राजन् सोमं सप्त ग्रहा इव) 7. 112.
22; the five sons of Draupadī tormented
Ārśyaśṛṅgī as do the five planets the moon at
the end of the Yuga (यथा युगक्षये
घोरे चन्द्रमाः पञ्चभिर् ग्रहैः) 6.
96. 36; (4) Moon by itself (i) Kaca,
coming out of the belly of his teacher, is
compared with the moon on the full moon
day on the last day of the bright fortnight
(शूक्लात्यये पौर्णमास्याम् इवेन्दुः) 1.
71. 49; (ii) The fierce fight of Droṇa and
Karṇa with the army of Yudhiṣṭhira appeared
like the one between the two oceans which
grow large due to rise of the moon (यथा
सागरयो राजंश् चन्द्रोदयविवृद्धयोः)
7. 147. 32. [For Soma also See section 1. 7]

सोमदैवत
Somadaivata nt.: See Mṛgottama.

स्वर्भानु
Svarbhānu m.: See Rāhu.

स्वाति
Svāti f.: Name of a star.
A. Placement: Suparṇa told Gālava
that the Svāti was stationed in the north and
there it arose (अत्र तिष्ठति वै स्वातिर् अत्रा-
स्या उदयः स्मृतः) 5. 109. 12.
B. Reli-
gious rites: (1) दान: Nārada told
Devakī (13. 63. 2-4) that by giving away
riches, which one cherished most, under Svāti
(स्वाताव् अथ धनं दत्त्वा यद् इष्टतमम्
आत्मनः) one obtained auspicious worlds
(लोकान् … शुभान्) after death and great
fame in this world 13. 63. 18; (2) श्राद्-
ध: Yama told Śaśabindu (13. 89. 1) that
by offering a काम्य श्राद्ध under the
lunar conjunction with Svāti (स्वातियोगे)
one (was successful) deriving profit from
trade (वाणिज्यम् उपजीवति) 13. 89. 7.
C. Omen: According to one of the omens
noted hy Vyāsa before the war the harsh
planet (Ketu) was stationed between Citrā
and Svāti (चित्रास्वात्यन्तरे चैव धिष्ठि-
तः परुषो ग्रहः) 6. 3. 16.

स्वायम्भुव|स्वायंभुव
Svāyaṃbhuva nt.: Name of the first
मन्वन्तर (a long period of time) presided
over by Manu Svāyaṃbhuva.
Events: (1) Bhīṣma had heard from
his father that the eternal Nārāyaṇa, the
world-soul, was born as the son of Dharma
and had assumed four forms, viz. Nara,
Nārāyaṇa, Hari and Kṛṣṇa; this had happen-
ed formerly in the Kṛtayuga of the Svāyaṃ-
bhuva Manvantara (नारायणो हि विश्वात्मा
चतुर्मूर्तिः सनातनः।धर्मात्मजः
संबभूव पितैवं मे ऽभ्यभाषत॥
कृते युगे महाराज पुरा स्वायंभुवे
ऽन्तरे।नरो नारायणश् चैव हरिः कृष्णस्
तथैव च॥) 12. 321. 8-9 (Nī. on Bom.
Ed. 12. 334. 8: चतस्रो मूर्तयः नराद्याः);
(2) According to one view Rudra's throat
became blue because it was held tightly by
Nārāyaṇa in the bygone Svāyaṃbhuva
Manvantara (पूर्वे च मन्वन्तरे स्वा-
यंभुवे नारायणहस्तबन्धग्रहणान्
नीलकण्ठत्वम् एव वा) 12. 329. 15; (3)
Hari-Nārāyaṇa asked his speech-born son
Apāntaratamas (सुतो वाक्संभवो विभोः
12. 337. 38) to prepare श्रुति for making
the Vedas known; accordingly Apāntara-
tamas divided the Vedas in the Svāyaṃ-
bhuva Manvantara; when this was done the
god Hari was pleased with him (वेदाख्याने
श्रुतिः कार्या त्वया मतिमतां वर। …
तेन भिन्नास् तदा वेदा मनोः स्वायं-
भुवे ऽन्तरे।) ततस् तुतोष भगवान् हरिस्
तेनास्य कर्मणा) 12. 337. 39-40.

हस्त
Hasta m.: Name of a constellation,
also called Sāvitra (1. 125. 30).
A. Description: Consisting of five stars
(पञ्चतार) 1. 125. 30.
B. Religious
rites: (1) दान: Nārada told Devakī
(13. 63. 2-4) that by observing fast and
giving a gift under the Hasta constellation of
a chariot to which four elephants were yoked,
one obtained the highest worlds where all
pious wishes were fulfilled (हस्ते हस्तिरथं
दत्त्वा चतुर्युक्तम् उपोषितः।प्राप्नोति
परमा̆ल् लोकान् पुण्यकामसमन्वितान्) 13.
63. 16; (2) Yama told Śaśabindu (13. 89.
1) that by offering a काम्य श्राद्ध under
Hasta one obtained the desired fruit (हस्तेन
फलभाग् भवेत्) 13. 89. 6 (Nī. on Bom.
Ed. 13. 89. 6: फलभाक् इष्टार्थभाक्).
C. Simile: Droṇa standing in the arena
with the five Pāṇḍava brothers appeared like
the Moon in conjunction with the constella-
tion Sāvitra (Hasta) consisting of five stars
(पञ्चतारेण संयुक्तः सावित्रेणेव चन्द्-
रमाः) 1. 125. 30 (Nī. on Bom. Ed. 1.
135. 30: सावित्रेण हस्तनक्षत्रेण).

अक्षयवट
Akṣayavaṭa m.: Name of a tree, also
referred to as अक्षय्यकरणो वटः (3. 85.
8; 13. 88. 14).
A. Location: Near Gayā (3. 82. 71-
72; 13. 88. 14; 3. 85. 8); near the river
Mahānadī and the lake Gayaśiras 3. 85. 8;
3. 93. 10 (where the lake Brahmasaras is
also mentioned).
B. Description: great
(महन्त्) 3. 93. 13; famous in the three
worlds (त्रिषु लोकेषु विश्रुतः) 3. 82. 72;
famous in the worlds (प्रथितो लोकेषु) 13.
88. 14; praised by the Vipras (कीर्त्यते
विप्रैः) 3. 85. 8.
C. Explanation of the
name: Since food offered to manes near
this tree becomes inexhaustible (अक्षय),
the tree is so called 13. 85. 8 (for citation
see below section
D.).
D. Importance:
Food offered to manes near this tree becomes
inexhaustible (पितॄणां तत्र वै दत्तम्
अक्षयं भवति प्रभो) 3. 82. 72; (यत्रा-
सौ कीर्त्यते विप्रैर् अक्षय्यकरणो वटः।
यत्र दत्तं पितृभ्यो ऽन्नम् अक्षयं
भवति प्रभो॥) 3. 85. 8; the Brāhmaṇas
who came there in hundreds offered the Cātur-
māsya sacrifices according to the ancient
prescription (आर्षेण विधिना) and told pious
tales of the high-souled in the सदस् (कथाः
प्रचक्रिरे पुण्याः सदैसिथा महात्म-
नाम्) 3. 93. 14-15.
E. Epic event:
The Pāṇḍavas offered there the Cāturmāsya
sacrifices and the great sacrifice to the ऋषिस्
(तत्र ते पाण्डवा वीरा चातुर्मास्यैस् तदे-
जिरे।ऋषियज्ञेन महता यत्राक्षयवटो
महान्) 3. 93. 13.

अगस्त्यतीर्थ
Agastyatīrtha nt.: Name of a तीर्थ
(different from Agastyasaras).
A. Location: One of the तीर्थस् on the
southern ocean (समुद्रे तीर्थानि दक्षिणे)
1. 208. 3; on the ocean in the Draviḍa country
(द्रविडेषु राजन् समुद्रम् आसाद्य …
अगस्त्यतीर्थम् … ददर्श) 3. 118. 4; in the
counry of the Pāṇḍyas (अगस्त्यतीर्थं
पाण्ड्येषु) 3. 86. 10.
B. Description:
sanctifying and holy (पवित्रपुण्य) 3. 118.
4; holy for the worlds (लोकपुण्य) 3. 118. 4;
very holy (सुपुण्य) 1. 208. 1; worshipped
by the ascetics (सुपूजितानि तपस्विभिः) 1.
208. 1.
C. History: It was once thronged
by ascetics, but later avoided by them as the
five crocodiles in the तीर्थ dragged some
of them away; it then became isolated (विवि-
क्तानि) 1. 208. 2, 4-6.
D. Epic event:
(1) Arjuna visited the five तीर्थस् and freed
them of the crocodiles 1. 208. 7-21; 1. 209.
1-23; (2) Yudhiṣṭhira, with his brothers
and wife, reached the तीर्थ and heard there
the exploits of Arjuna and was highly grati-
fied; he bathed there with his wife and bro-
thers and extolled the heroism of Arjuna; he
gave as gift a thousand cows and praised
the gift of cows given by Arjuna (this gift of
Arjuna is not reported earlier in the Adhyāyas
1. 208 and 209) (अर्जुनस्य संकीर्तयाम्
आस गवां प्रदानम्) 3. 118. 4-7.

अगस्त्यवट
Agastyavaṭa m.: Name of a tree.
A. Location: On the slope of the
mountain Himavant (हिमवत्पार्श्वम्) and
near the Vasiṣṭhaparvata and the Bhṛgutuṅga
1. 267. 1-2.
B. Epic event: Arjuna,
during his exile, reached there form the
Gaṅgādvāra 1. 206. 6; 1. 207. 1-2.

अगस्त्यसरस्
Agastyasaras nt.: Name of a तीर्थ
(different from Agastyātīrtha).
A. Location: One can reach the Taṇ-
ḍulikāśrama from the Jambūmārga, and from
that आश्रम proceed to Agastyasaras 3. 80.
62-63.
B. Importance: Pulastya told
Bhīṣma that if one was engaged in the
worship of manes and gods (पितृदेवार्चने
रतः) at the Agastyasaras and observed
fast for three nights he obtained the fruit of
performing an Agniṣṭoma sacrifice; and if
one lived there on vegetables and fruits he
obtained the place of Kumāra (कौमारं
विन्दते पदम्) 3. 80. 63-64.

अग्नितीर्थ
Agnitīrtha nt.: Name of a तीर्थ।
A. Epic event: Balarāma in his तीर्थ-
यात्रा, proceeded from Śamītīrtha to Agni-
tīrtha; he bathed there and proceeded to the
Brahmayoni तीर्थ 9. 46. 12, 20.
B. My-
thological event (which explains the name of
the तीर्थ): God Fire, afraid of Bhṛgu's
curse, entered a Śamī tree at this तीर्थ
and disappeared (भृगोः शापाद् भृशं
भीतो जातवेदाः प्रतापवान्।शमीगर्भम्
अथासाद्य ननाश भगवांस् ततः॥) 9.
46. 16; (नष्टो न दृश्यते यत्र शमीगर्भे
हुताशनः) 9. 46. 12; the gods, in their
search for Fire, reached Agnitīrtha and found
Fire lying within the Śamī tree 9. 46. 12.
C. Importance: Pulastya told Bhīṣma that
by bathing at Agnitīrtha one reached the
world of Agni and lifted up his family
(अग्निलोकम् अवाप्नोति कुलं चैव समुद्-
धरेत्) 3. 81. 119.

अग्निधारा
Agnidhārā f.: Name of a तीर्थ।
Famous in the three worlds 3. 82. 127;
by visiting it one acquired the fruit of Agni-
ṣṭoma sacrifice and did not return (to this
world) from heaven (न च स्वर्गान् निवर्-
तते) 3. 82. 127.

अग्निशिरस्
Agniśiras nt.: Name of a तीर्थ।
A. Location: On the river Yamunā
3. 88. 2, 6.
B. Description: holy (पुण्य),
heavenly (दिव्य), auspicīous (शिव) 3. 88. 4.
C. Past events: (1) Sahadeva offered
there sacrifices by measuring the sacrificial
ground with the throw of a peg; with regard
to this a गाथा, sung by Indra, was current
in this world among the twice-born; it said
that Sahadeva performed Agnicayana a hund-
red hundred-thousand times along the river
Yamunā and gave hundreds of thousands as
दक्षिणा (सहदेवो ऽयजद् यत्र शम्याक्षे-
पेण भारत॥एतस्मिन्न् एव चार्थेयम्
इन्द्रगीता युधिष्ठिर।गाथा चरति लोके
ऽस्मिन् गीयमाना दिविजातिभिः॥अग्नयः
सहदेवेन ये चिता यमुनाम् अनु।शतम्
शतसहस्राणि सहस्रशतदक्षिणाः॥) 3.
88. 4-6 (Nī. on Bom. Ed. 3. 90. 5: शम्या-
क्षेपेण बलवता क्षिप्ता शम्या लगुडविशेषो
यावद् दूरं पतेत् तावान् यज्ञमण्डपो
यस्मिन् यज्ञे स शम्याक्षेपः); (2) King
Bharata, the famous emperor, offered there
35 horse sacrifices 3. 88. 7.

अग्नेः
Agneḥ puram nt.: Name of a तीर्थ।
Aṅgiras told Gautama that by bathing
in this तीर्थ one becomes identical with
ब्रह्मन् (अग्नेः पुरे नरः स्नात्वा …
ब्रह्मभूतो विराजते) 13. 26. 41.

अङ्गारपर्ण
Aṅgāraparṇa nt.: Name of a forest.
Located on the rivers Gaṅgā and Vākā;
described as variegated (चित्र) 1. 158. 13;
it belonged to the Gandharva Aṅgāra-
parṇa, the beloved friend of Kubera, and he
lived there; it was visited neither by corpses
nor horned animals, nor gods, nor men (न
कुणपाः शृङ्गिण्ō वा न देवा न च मानु-
षाः।इदम् समुपसर्पन्ति) 1. 158. 13-14;
the Pāṇḍavas encountered the Gandharva
there while they were proceeding to the city
of the Pāñcālas 1. 157. 15; 1. 158. 14.

अञ्जन
Añjana m.: Name of a mountain.
Yudhiṣṭhira was instructed by the great
sage Asita near the mountain Añjana (अश्रौ-
षीर् असितस्यापि महर्षेर् अञ्जनं प्रति) 2.
69. 13. [See Añjanābha]

अञ्जनाभ
Añjanābha m.: Name of a mountain.
Finds place, with other mountains, in the
Daivata-Ṛṣi-Vaṃśa 13. 151. 27; (13. 151. 2).
[See Añjana]

अतिकृष्णा
Atikṛṣṇā f.: Name of a river.
Listed by Saṃjaya among the rivers of
the Bhāratavarṣa 6. 10. 23, 5; people use its
water for drinking 6. 10. 13; all the rivers
are described as very strong and the mothers
of the universe (विश्वस्य मातरः सर्वाः
सर्वाश् चैव महाबलाः) 6. 10. 35.

अद्रिजा
Adrijā f.: Name of a river (or an
epithet of Kṛṣṇaveṇā ?)
Finds place among the rivers listed in the
Daivata-Ṛṣi-Vaṃśa (गोदावरी च वेण्णा च
कृष्णवेणा तथाद्रिजा) 13. 151. 17, 2.

अधिवंश्य
Adhivaṃśya nt.: Name of a sacred
grove.
By entering this sacred grove (तपोवन)
one rejoiced among the Guhyakas; there was
no doubt about this (गुह्यकेषु महाराज
मोदते नात्र संशयः) 3. 82. 98.

अधृष्या
Adhṛṣyā f.: Name of a river.
Listed by Saṃjaya among the rivers of
the Bhāratavarṣa 6. 10. 23, 5; people use its
water for drinking 6. 10. 13; all rivers descri-
fied as very strong and the mothers of the
universe (विश्वस्य मातरः सर्वाः सर्वाश्
चैव महाबलाः) 6. 10. 35.

अनरक
Anaraka nt.: Name of a तीर्थ।
A. Description: A तीर्थ of all gods
(तीर्थे तु सर्वदेवानाम्) 3. 81. 151, be-
cause (1) there Brahmā himself is always
waited upon (अन्वास्यते) by gods led by
Nārāyaṇa 3. 81. 147; (2) Rudra's wife
remains in vicinity; by paying a visit to the
goddess one never meets with misfortunes (न
दुर्गतिम् अवाप्नुयात्) 3. 81. 148; (3)
There is also god Viśveśvara (Śiva), husband
of Umā; by paying a visit to him one is
freed of all sins (मुच्यते सर्वकिल्बिशैः)
3. 81. 149; (4) By visiting there Padma-
nābha Nārāyaṇa one shines and obtains the
world of Viṣṇu (शोभमानो महाराज
विष्णुलोकं प्रपद्यते) 3. 81. 150.
B.
Holiness: By bathing at Anaraka one
does not meet with misfortunes (न दुर्-
गतिम् अवाप्नुयात्) 3. 81. 146, and, freed of
all sorrow, he always shines like the moon
(सर्वदुःखैः परित्यक्तो द्योतते शशिवत्
सदा) 3. 81. 151.

अनाजन्मन्
Anājanman nt.: Name of a तीर्थ।
Situated to the east of the तीर्थ Saraka,
it is famous (विश्रुत) and sacred to Nārada
(नारदस्य महात्मनः।तीर्थम्); by
bathing there and by giving up one's life, one
goes, with the consent of Nārada, to the
worlds that are difficult to obtain (नारदेना-
भ्यनुज्ञातो लोकान् प्राप्नोति दुर्लभान्) 3.
81. 67-68.

अन्तःशिला
Antaḥśilā f.: Name of a river.
Listed by Saṃjaya among the rivers of
the Bhāratavarṣa 6. 10. 29, 5; its water is
used by people for drinking 6. 10. 13; all
these rivers are described as very strong
(महाबलाः) and the mothers of the universe
(विश्वस्य मातरः) 6. 10. 35.

अन्तर्गिरि
Antargiri m.: Name (?) of a mountain.
Situated in the north, it was conquered
by Arjuna 2. 24. 2, 1.

अन्धकार
Andhakāra(ka) m.: Name of a moun-
tain.
Andhakāraka is situated in the Krauñca-
dvīpa, beyond the mountain Vāmana(ka);
beyond Andhakāra is the mountain Maināka
6. 13. 17-18.

अपरनन्दा
Aparanandā f.: Name of a river.
A. Description: Destroying sin and
danger (पापभयापहा) 3. 109. 1.
B. Epic connections: (1) Arjuna, during
his exile in the forest, saw it (1. 207. 7)
while proceeding to the east (प्राचीं दिशम्
अभिप्रेप्सुः) 1. 207. 5; after visiting these
holy places Arjuna purified himself and gave
wealth to Brāhmaṇas 1. 207. 8; (2) Yudhi-
ṣṭhira reached it (3. 109. 1) from the Aga-
styāśrama (3. 94. 1).
C. Importance:
Finds mention in the Daivata-Ṛṣi-Vaṃśa 13.
151. 23, 2.

अपरान्त
Aparānta m.: Name of a mountain.
Brave Ketumant killed prince Sudar-
śana at the mountain pass of the Aparānta
(अपरान्तगिरिद्वारे) 7. 9. 40.

अपां
Apāṃ hradaḥ m.: Name of a तीर्थ।
Aṅgiras told Bhīṣma that one who
practises chastity, has controlled his anger, is
devoted to truth and does not cause injury
to others (ब्रह्मचारी जितक्रोधः सत्य-
संधस् त्व् अहिंसकः) bathes (उपस्पृश्य)
at this तीर्थ, he obtains the merit of per-
forming a Vājapeya sacrifice 13. 26. 13.

अमराणाम्
Amarāṇām hradaḥ m.: Name of a
तीर्थ।
By bathing at this तीर्थ one obtains
the prowess of gods and is glorified among
them in heaven (अमराणां ह्रदे स्नात्वा
अमरेषु नराधिप।अमराणां प्रभा-
वेन स्वर्गलोके महीयते) 3. 81. 89.

अम्बुवश्य
Ambuvaśya nt.: Name of a sacred
place.
The तीर्थस् sacred to Kośeśvara (Kubera ?)
are located there (ततो ऽम्बुवश्यं धर्-
मज्ञ समासाद्य यथाक्रमम्।कोशेश्व-
रस्य तीर्थेषु); by bathing in these तीर्थस्
one is freed of all diseases and is glorified
in the Brahmaloka 3. 81. 46.

अम्बुवाहिनी
Ambuvāhinī f.: Name of a river.
Listed by Saṃjaya among the rivers of
the Bhāratavarṣa 6. 10. 26, 5; its water used
for drinking by people 6. 10. 13; all these
rivers are described as very strong (महा-
बलाः) and mothers of the universe (विश्वस्य
मातरः) 6. 10. 35; finds place in the Daivata-
Ṛṣi-Vaṃśa 13. 151. 15, 2.

अरण्या
Araṇyā f.: Name of a river.
Listed by Saṃjaya among the rivers of
the Bhāratavarṣa 6. 10. 33, 5; its water used
by people for drinking 6. 10. 13; all these
rivers are described as very strong (महा-
बलाः) and the mothers of the universe
(विश्वस्य मातरः) 6. 10. 35.

अरन्तुकस्य
Arantukasya tīrtham nt.: Name of a
तीर्थ।
This तीर्थ sacred to Arantuka, lord of
the Yakṣas, was situated on the river Sara-
svatī (ततो गच्छेत राजेन्द्र द्वारपालम्
अरन्तुकम्।तस्य तीर्थं सरस्वत्यां
यक्षेन्द्रस्य महात्मनः); by bathing
there one obtains the fruit of performing
an Agniṣṭoma sacrifice 3. 81. 42.

अरुणा
Aruṇā f.: Name of a river; also called
तीर्थ (9. 42. 26, 27).
A. Description: An excellent तीर्थ
(तीर्थवर) 9. 42. 26; the confluence of the
river Sarasvatī and Aruṇā was world famous
(लोकविश्रुत) 3. 81. 131.
B. Relation
with other तीर्थस्: (1) The Devītīrtha
(तीर्थं देव्याः) was situated near it 3.
81. 131; (2) The confluence of the rivers
Kauśikī and Aruṇā was known as the Kālikā-
saṃgama 3. 82. 135.
C. Importance:
(1) A bath in the river Aruṇā frees one
of the sin of killing a Brāhmaṇa (ब्रह्म-
हत्यापहा हि सा) 9. 42. 25, 34; (2) If
one fasts for three nights and bathes at the
confluence of Aruṇā and Sarasvatī one is
freed of the sin of killing a Brāhmaṇa and
he obtains the fruit of performing an Agni-
ṣṭoma and an Atirātra sacrifice; he also
purifies his lineage for seven generations 3.
81. 131-32; he is also freed of all sins 3. 82.
135; (3) Aruṇā finds mention in the Dai-
vata-Ṛṣi-Vaṃśa 13. 151. 16.
D. Events:
(1) Epic: (a) Before starting the war on
the eighteenth day, the Kaurava warriors
went to the rivers Aruṇā and Sarasvatī and
bathed there and drank their water; the place
was situated on the slope of Himavant a
little less than two योजनस् from the Kuru-
kṣetra (ऊने द्वियोजने गत्वा प्रत्यतिष्ठन्त
कौरवाः। … प्रस्थे हिमवतः शुभे) 9.
4. 48-49; the warriors returned from there
for war with their energies restored (कृतोत्-
साहाः) 9. 4. 50; (b) Balarāma bathed in
Aruṇā, gave varied gifts and acquired religi-
ous merit (अवाप्य धरमम्) 9. 42. 38;
(2) Mythological; (a) when the ascetics
requested Sarasvatī for the मोक्ष of the
Rākṣasas, it brought to its body the river
Aruṇā (अरुणाम् आनयाम् आस स्वां तनुं
पुरुषर्षभ) 9. 42. 24; when the Rākṣasas
bathed in Aruṇā they left their bodies and
went to heaven (तनूस् त्यक्त्वा दिवं गताः)
9. 42. 25; (b) Indra was advised by
Brahmadeva to perform a sacrifice on the
river Sarasvatī and to bathe in Aruṇā
according to the prescribed rites (यथाविधि
9. 42. 34); he was then freed of the sin
arising out of killing a Brāhmaṇa (अरुणा-
याम् उपास्पृशत्।स मुक्तः पाप्मना
तेन ब्रह्मह्यत्याकृतेन ह) 9. 42. 35-36;
9. 42. 26; (c) Namuci's head too reached
the eternal, wish-yielding worlds by plung-
ing (आप्लुत्य) into Aruṇā (शिरश् तच्
चापि नमुचेः लोकान् कामदुघान् प्राप्तम्
अक्षयान्) 9. 42. 37.

अरुन्धतीवाट
Arundhatīvāṭa m.: Name of a तीर्थ (?)
One who is on a pilgrimage (तीर्थ-
सेवी) is advised by Pulastya to visit Arun-
dhatīvaṭa 3. 82. 37 (Name of a banyan tree
situated near the Sāmudraka तीर्थ ?).

अर्बुद
Arbuda m.: Name of a mountain.
Described as the ‘son of Himavant’
(हिमवत्सुतम् अर्बुदम्); the mountain
stands now, where formerly there was a hole
in the earth (पृथिव्यां यत्र वै छिद्रं
पूर्वम् आसीद् युधिष्ठिर) 3. 80. 74; on
this mountain there is the world famous
आश्रम of Vasiṣṭha; by living there for a
night one obtained the fruit of donating a
thousand cows (गोसहस्रफलम्) 3. 80. 75.

अलकनन्दा
Alakanandā f.: Name of a river.
Arjuna told the Gandharva Aṅgāraparṇa
that when the holy river Gaṅgā flows through
the sky the river has only one bank; there,
among the gods, it obtains the status of
Alakanandā (इयं भूत्वा चैकवप्रा शुचिर्
आकाशगा पुनः।देवेषु गङ्गा गन्धर्व
प्राप्नोत्य् अलकनन्दताम्) 1. 158. 18 (Nī.
on Bom. Ed. 1. 170 21: एकम् आकाशरूपं
वप्रं तटं यस्याः सा).

अलम्ब
Alamba nt.: Name of a तीर्थ।
Garuḍa, on his way to fetch अमृत
(सोम) from heaven, goes to Alambatīrtha
holding an elephant and a tortoise, one each in
his two claws; in the vicinity of this तीर्थ
there are divine trees (देववृक्षान् उपागमत्)
1. 25. 27.

अवतीर्ण
Avatīrṇa nt.: Name of a तीर्थ।
A. Location: Situated near the con-
fluence of the river Sarasvatī and the river
Aruṇā 3. 81. 133, (131).
B. Origin: It
was created in the bygone days by Darbhin
for he was compassionate to the Brāhmaṇas
(विप्राणाम् अनुकम्पार्थं दर्भिणा निर्-
मितं पुरा) 3. 81. 133; while creating it
Darbhin had brought together waters of the
four oceans (समुद्राश् चापि चत्वारः
समानीताश् च दर्भिणा) 3. 81. 136.
C.
Importance: Even if one has not performed
the sacred rites nor recited the मन्त्रस्, if
he bathes in this तीर्थ he is as good as one
who has observed the vows-this is declared
in an ancient text (?) (दृष्टम् एतत् पुरा-
तने) 3. 81. 135; one who bathes in the
तीर्थ does not meet with adversity (न
दुर्गतिम् अवाप्नुयात्) und he obtains the
fruit of donating four thousand cows 3. 81.
136.

अशोकतीर्थ
Aśokatīrtha nt.: Name of a तीर्थ।
Situated in the south (3. 86. 1) in the
land of the Martyas (? मर्त्येषु; v. 1. मत्-
स्येषु) 3. 86. 10; there were many आश्रमस्
around it (बहुलाश्रम) 3. 86. 10.

अश्वतर
Aśvatara nt.: Name of a तीर्थ।
Near Prayāga; together with Prayāga,
Pratiṣṭhāna, Kambala and Bhogavatī it is
considered to be the altar of Prajāpati (वेदी
प्रोक्ता प्रजापतेः) 3. 83. 72; there the Vedas
and the sacrifices in bodily form, as well as
the sages, wait upon Prajāpati, and the gods
and the Cakracaras offer sacrifices 3. 83. 73.

अश्वतीर्थ
Aśvatīrtha nt.: Name of a तीर्थ।
A. Location: The bank of the Ganges,
not far from the city Kanyakubja, “is even
now known as Aśvatīrtha” (अदूरे कन्य-
कुब्जस्य गङ्गायास् तीरम् उत्तमम्।अश्व-
तीर्थं तद् अद्यापि मानवाः परिचक्षते)
13. 4. 17; one of the तीर्थस् on Gomatī
3. 93. 2.
B. Description: Holy (पुण्य)
3. 93. 2.
C. Origin: Varuṇa gave to
Bhārgava Ṛcīka one thousand white (पाण्-
डुर), shining like the moon (चन्द्र-
वर्चस्), and swift (तरस्विन्) horses who
had a black ear on one side (एकतःश्याम-
कर्ण); the horses were meant to be given
by Ṛcika to Gādhi, king of Kanyakubja,
as a dowry for marrying his daughter 3.
115. 9, 12; 5. 117. 5; 13. 4. 14, 16; the
place where the horses emerged from the
water of Gaṅgā (13. 4. 16) came to be
known as Aśvatīrtha (तद् अश्वतीर्थं वि-
ख्यातम् उत्थिता यत्र ते हयाः) 3. 115.
16; 5. 117. 6.
D. Religious importance:
After bathing there, the Pāṇḍavas gave away
cows and riches 3. 93. 2; they repeatedly
offered there offerings to gods and manes
and satisfied the Brāhmaṇas (तत्र देवान्
पितॄन् विप्रांस् तर्पयित्वा पुनः पुनः) 3.
93. 3.

अश्वनदी
Aśvanadī f.: Name of a river.
Kuntī placed the newly born Karṇa in
a basket covered with wax (मञ्जूषायाम् …
मधूच्छिष्टस्थितायाम्) and released it
in the river Aśvanadī 3. 292. 7, 9, 22, 25
(from where it went to the river Carmaṇvatī,
Yamunā and finally to Gaṅgā).

अश्वरथा
Aśvarathā f.: Name of a river.
Draupadī pointed out to Bhīma on the
mountain Gandhamādana (Himavant) that
flowers of five colours which were blown
there by wind, produced by speed of Suparṇa,
were dropped in the river Aśvarathā-a sight
watched by all creatures (प्रत्यक्षं सर्व-
भूतानाम्) 3. 157. 19.

अस्वशिरस्
Asvaśiras nt.: Name of a तीर्थ।
A. Description: Holy (पुण्य) 7. 57.
28.
B. Epic events connected with this
तीर्थ: (1) The sage Bṛhadaśva taught
अक्षहृदय (the secret science of the game
of dice), which he knew thoroughly well
(3. 78. 15), to Yudhiṣṭhira (to dispel the
latter's fear of losing everything once again
in the game of dice), and then went to
Aśvaśiras to bathe (दत्त्वा चाश्वशिरो ऽगच्-
छद् उपस्प्रष्टुं महातपाः) 3. 78. 17
(Nī., however, on Bom. Ed. 3. 79. 21:
अश्वशिरो ऽस्वविद्याम् यया बृहदश्व इति
मुनेर् नाम।उपस्प्रष्टुं स्नानादिकं
कर्तुम्) (this Aśvaśiras apparently was in
the vicinity of the Kāmyaka forest where
Bṛhadaśva met the Pāṇḍavas 3. 49. 2, 29);
(2) Arjuna, on his way to the mountain
Himavant to receive the Pāśupata अस्त्र
from Śiva crossed many places near the
Himavant, one of them being Aśvaśiras 7.
57. 28 (this Aśvaśiras seems to be different
from the one referred to in the above event).

अश्विनोस्
Aśvinos tīrtham nt.: Name of a तीर्थ
sacred to the Aśvins.
By visiting this तीर्थ of the Aśvins one
becomes handsome (अश्विनोस् तीर्थम् आसाद्य
रूपवान् अभिजायते) 3. 81. 14.

अष्टावक्र
Aṣṭāvakra nt.: Name of a तीर्थ।
One who offers libation of water to
manes at Aṣṭāvakra and fasts for twelve
days obtains the fruit of performing a human
sacrifice (नरमेधफलं लभेत्) 13. 26.
39 (situated near Haridwar, see Editor's
note on the stanza, Cr. Ed. Vol. 17, part II,
p. 1067).

असिक्नी
Asiknī f.: Name of a river.
Listed by Saṃjaya among the rivers of
the Bhāratavarṣa 6. 10. 22, 5; its water is
used by people for drinking 6. 10. 13.

असित
Asita m.: Name of a mountain.
Situated in the west (3. 87. 1); des-
cribed as having many roots and fruit
(बहुमूलफल) 3. 87. 9.

असिपत्रवन
Asipatravana nt.: Name of a forest (?)
Yudhiṣṭhira while going in the company
of the Devadūta to see his brothers after
their death passed through Asipatravana (lit.
‘a forest having leaves as sharp as the blade
of a sword’) which was covered with sharp
razors (निषितक्षुरसंवृत) 18. 2. 23; a
wicked king, after death, before going to
hell is merged in the hot Vaitaraṇī river
and then gets his body pricked in the Asi-
patravana (असिपत्रवनभिन्नगात्रः) 12.
309. 31.

अस्त
Asta m.: Name of a mountain, also
called once Astaṃgiri (7. 31. 77).
A. Description: Holy (पुण्य) 15.
39. 24; the best among the mountains (गिरि-
श्रेष्ठ) 6. 51. 40; (पर्वतश्रेष्ठ) 10.
1. 24; (गिरिवर) 15. 39. 24; sages call it
the king of the mountains (अस्तं पर्व-
तराजानम् एतम् आहुर् मनीषिणः) 3. 160.
10, 11.
B. Relationship (1) with sun:
The sun approaches it at sunset 1. 43. 23;
1. 143. 17; 3. 280. 17; 5. 108. 6; 5. 180. 39;
5. 182. 16; 5. 183. 26; 6. 51. 40, 43; 6. 82.
41; 6. 90. 46 (सूर्यास्तमनवेला for सूर्-
यास्तमयनवेला ?); 7. 31. 77; 7. 48. 41;
7. 56. 22; 7. 121. 45; 7. 128. 10; 8. 21. 35;
9. 28. 62, 82; 10. 1. 24; 12. 58. 28; 12. 306.
12; 12. 318. 7; 15. 39. 24; the sun always sets
only at the proper time (भानुः … नाकालतो
ऽस्तं गिरिम् अभ्युपैति) 12. 26. 12; the sun
having reached the Asta mountain and going
beyond the dusk repairs to the north; then
going round the mountain Meru he moves
towards the east (अस्तं प्राप्य ततः सं-
ध्याम् अतिक्रम्य दिवाकरः।उदीचीं भ-
जते काष्ठां दिशम् एष विभावसुः॥स
मेरुम् अनुवृत्तः सन् पुनर् गच्छति
पाण्डव।प्राङ्मुखः सविता देवः) 3.
160. 25-26; the answer to the question:
“who leads the sun to the Asta ?”, the reply
is: “Dharma leads the sun to the Asta and
there it rests in truth” (कश् चैनम् अस्तं
नयति … धर्मश् चास्तं नयति सत्ये च
प्रतितिष्ठति) 3. 297. 26-27; (सत्येन प्रति-
तिष्ठति) 3. 160. 10; (2) with dusk: the
latter twilight (dusk) proceeds from it (अस्तो
नाम यतः संध्या पश्चिमा प्रतिसर्पति)
5. 108. 6; (3) with nights: they go to the
Asta mountain (अस्तं गच्छन्ति रात्रयः)
12. 318. 8; (4) with the luminaries: they
return to the Asta mountain at the end of
the night 7. 171. 4; (5) with clouds: Asta,
together with Udaya, receives a large number
of big clouds (प्रत्यगृह्णात् … महामेघान्
इव बहुञ् शैलाव् अस्तोदयाव् उभौ) 9. 15.
31.
C. Importance: King Varuṇa lives
on the Asta mountain and in the great ocean
and from there protects the beings (अस्तं
पर्वतराजानं समुद्रं च महोदधिं।
आवसन् वरुणो राजा भूतानि परिरक्षति)
3. 160. 11.
D. Similes: (1) Falling
down of the head of Daṇḍa, red-coloured,
when cut off by Arjuna, compared with the
falling down of the sun to the west from
the Asta mountain 8. 13. 19; (2) Falling
down of the excellent, bright diadem of
Arjuna, compared with the burning sun
falling down from the Asta mountain 8. 66.
16; (3) Karṇa, circled by the network of
the arrows shot from his bow, appeared like
the sun, having the circle of red rays, pro-
ceeding toward the Asta mountain 8. 66. 40;
(4) Duryodhana and Śalya received the
warriors rushing at them as do the Asta and
the Udaya mountains the clouds 9. 15. 31;
(5) the arrows shot at Bhīma by Aśvatthā-
man proceeded towards him like the luminaries
proceeding towards the Asta mountain at the
end of the night 7. 171. 4; (6) Bhīṣma's
downfall, after he had tormented the enemies
with the heat of his weapons, compared with
the setting of the sun (नरसूर्यो ऽस्तम्
अभ्येति सूर्यो ऽस्तम् इव केशव) 11. 23. 16;
(7) (i) Vicitravīrya's going to the abode of
Yama (his death) compared with the sun's
going to the Asta (जगामास्तम् इवादित्यः
कौरव्यो यमसादनम्) 1. 96. 58; (ii)
Vyuṣitāśva's death compared with the sun's
going to the Asta (जगामास्तम् इवांशुमान्)
1. 112. 17.
E. Use of the expression
अस्तम् इ or गम् to mean ‘die’: अस्तम् इते
भीष्मे 12. 46. 23; (व्युषिताश्वः) जगामा-
स्तम् 1. 112. 17.

अहुर्
Ahur nt.: Name of a तीर्थ।
Difficult to reach (सुदुर्लभ) 3. 81.
84; by bathing there one goes to the world
of the sun (सूर्यलोकम् अवाप्नुयात्) 3.
81. 84.

अहल्यायाः
Ahalyāyāḥ hradaḥ m.: Name of a
sacred lake.
Situated in the forest of Gautama 3. 82.
93; having bathed in the lake of Ahalyā
(अहल्यायाः ह्रदे स्नात्वा) one attains (after
death) the highest condition; acquiring
lustre, he attains the highest glory (व्रजेत्
परमां गतिम्।अभिगम्य श्रियं राजन्
विन्दते श्रियम् उत्तमाम्) 3. 82. 93; there
is also a well (उदपान) there which is
famous in the three worlds; by taking bath
in that well one obtains the fruit of perform-
ing a horse sacrifice (तत्राभिषेकं कृत्वा
तु वाजिमेधम् अवाप्नुयात्) 3. 82. 94.

आकाशगङ्गा
Ākāśagaṅgā f.: The river Gaṅgā flow-
ing in the sky, also called simply Gaṅgā
(18. 3. 37, 39).
A. Description: Holy (पुण्या) 18. 3.
26, 39; its waters described as holy (पुण्यं
 … तोयम्) 12. 315. 46; the river of the gods
(देवनदी) 18. 3. 26, 39; one that purifies
the three worlds (त्रैलोक्यपावनी) 18. 3. 26;
purifying (पावनी) 18. 3. 39; praised by
the sages (ऋषिसंस्तुता) 18. 3. 39; flowing
in the three worlds (त्रिलोकगा) 18. 3. 39.
B. Location in the sky: The sixth wind
known as Parivaha supports the holy waters
of the Ākāśagaṅgā (पुण्यं चाकाशगङ्-
गायास् तोयं विष्टभ्य तिष्ठति … षष्ठः
परिवहो नाम स वायुः) 12. 315. 46, 48
(Nī. on Bom. Ed. 12. 328. 46: तोयं
विष्टभ्य आकाशे एवावस्थाप्य).
C. Epic
event: Indra advised Yudhiṣṭhira to bathe in
the Ākāśagaṅgā before proceeding to heaven
18. 3. 26; accordingly he went to the Gaṅgā
and bathed there; having plunged in its
water he gave up his human body, assumed
a divine form and was free of the feelings of
enmity and sorrow 18. 3. 37-40.
D. My-
thological event: Formerly the sage Bhara-
dvāja, having gone to the Ākāśagaṅgā, was
performing religious ablution (उपास्पृशन्);
at that time he was touched by Viṣṇu who
was taking his three steps (त्रीन् क्रमान्
क्रमता विष्णुनाभ्यासादितः) 12. 329. 42.
E. Importance: When Yudhiṣṭhira bathes
in the Ākāśagaṅgā he will be free of his
human existence, he will be relived of grief
and fatigue and his feelings of enmity will
disappear (अत्र स्नातस्य तो भावो मानुषो
विगमिष्यति।गतशोको निरायासो मुक्तवैरो
भविष्यसि) 18. 3. 27.

आदित्यतीर्थ
Ādityatīrtha nt.: Name of a तीर्थ।
A. Location: On the river Sarasvatī
(तस्मिंस् तीर्थे सरस्वत्याः) 9. 48. 20;
near the hermitage of Āditya (आदितस्याश्रमो
यत्र; the तीर्थ not directly named) 3. 81.
160.
B. Description: auspicious (शिव)
9. 48. 20; holy (पुण्य) 9. 48. 20; excellent
among the तीर्थस् (तीर्थप्रवर) 9. 48. 21;
best (उत्तम) 9. 48. 21; famous in the three
worlds (त्रैलोक्यविश्रुत) 3. 81. 160 (the
तीर्थ not directly named).
C. Various
events, mythological and others, associated
with it: (1) God Sun, offered a sacrifice
there, and obtained sovereignty over luminous
bodies and prowess (ज्योतिषाम् आधिपत्यं
च प्रभावं चाभ्यपध्यत) 9. 48. 17;
(2) Formerly, Viṣṇu, after killing the demons
Madhu and Kaiṭabha, bathed in this excellent
तीर्थ (for purification ?) 9. 48. 21; (3)
Near that तीर्थ, on the bank of the river
Sarasvatī, are present all gods with Indra,
the Viśvedevas together with the Maruts, the
Gandharvas and the Apsarases, the Yakṣas,
the Rākṣasas and the Piśācas, (Kṛṣṇa)
Dvaipāyaṇa, Śukra, Kṛṣṇa and many others
by thousands who have acquired perfection
through योग 9. 48. 18-20; (4) (Kṛṣṇa)
Dvaipāyana acquired the highest योग and
the ultimate perfection by bathing in the
Ādityatīrtha (संप्राप्तः परमं योगं
सिद्धिं च परमां गतः) 9. 48. 22;
(5) The sage Asita Devala too, (having
bathed) in the same (तीर्थ,) and having
practised meditation of a high quality, obtain-
ed योग (असितो देवलश् चैव तस्मिन्न् एव
महातपाः।परमं योगम् आस्थाय ऋषिर्
योगम् अवाप्तवान्) 9. 48. 23.
D. Im-
portance: By bathing in the Ādityatīrtha
(not directly named) and by worshipping god
Sun (विभावसुम्) one goes to the world of
Āditya and saves his own family (आदित्य-
लोकं व्रजति कुलं चैव समुद्धरेत्) 3.
81. 161.

आपःप्रपतन
Āpaḥprapatana nt.: Name of a तीर्थ।
According to the Tīrthavaṃśa, narrated
by Aṇgiras to Gautama (13. 26. 3-4), one
who bathes in the तीर्थ is waited upon by
the Apsarases (सेव्यते सो ऽप्सरोगणिः) 13.
26. 26.

आपगा
Āpagā1 f.: Name of a river.
A. Location: Flowing to the east of
the Mānuṣatīrtha at a distance of one क्रोश
from it (मानुषस्य तु पूर्वेण क्रोश-
मात्रे) 3. 81. 55.
B. Description:
Famous (विख्यात) 3. 81. 55; frequented
by the Siddhas (सिद्धनिषेवित) 3. 81. 55.
C. Importance: One who offers food made
of श्यामाक grain to gods and manes obtains
high religious merit; if one Brāhmaṇa is fed
there, it is as good as feeding a crore of
them (श्यामाकभोजनं तत्र यः प्रयच्-
छति मानवः।देवान् पितॄंश् च उद्दिश्य
तस्य धर्मफलं महत्।एकस्मिन्
भोजिते विप्रे कोटिर् भवति भोजिता) 3. 81.
56; by bathing there, and by worshipping
gods and manes, and by spending there one
night one obtains the fruit of performing an
Agniṣṭoma sacrifice 3. 81. 57.

आपगा
Āpagā2 f.: Name of a river (could it
be Gaṅgā ? cf. गङ्गाह्रदश् च तत्रैव 3.
81. 153).
By bathing in Āpagā and by worshipping
Maheśvara one becomes the chief of the
Gaṇas of Śiva (? becomes a worshipper of
Gaṇeśa ?) and rescues his own family
(गाणपत्यम् अवाप्नोति कुलं चोद्धरते
स्वकम्) 3. 81. 154.

आपगा
Āpagā3 f.: Name of a river.
Near the city Śākala in the Bāhlīka
country (शाकलं नाम नगरम् आपगा
नाम निम्नगा।जर्तिका नाम बाह्लिकास्
तेषां वृत्तं सुनिन्दितम्) 8. 30. 14.

आर्चीकपर्वत
Ārcīkaparvata m.: Name of a moun-
tain.
A. Description: It has fruits in all the
seasons (सदाफल) and it has streams
flowing throughout the year (सदास्रोत)
3. 125. 13.
B. Inhabitants: It is the
abode of sages, and the highest station of
the Maruts (निवासो वै मनीषिणाम् … मरु-
तां स्थानम् उत्तमम्) 3. 125. 13.
C.
Structures: There were hundreds of struc-
tures sacred to gods on it (चैत्याश् चैतेबहु-
शतास् त्रिदशानां युधिष्ठिर) 3. 125. 13.
D. Other important features: (1) It had
three holy peaks and three waterfalls (शृङ्-
गाणि त्रीणी पुण्यानि त्रीणि प्रस्रवणानि च)
3. 125. 15; Lomaśa advised the Pāṇḍavas to
go around them in succession and bathe in
them 3. 125. 15; (2) Here flew Yamunā
whose current never dried up (यमुना
चाक्षयस्रोताः) 3. 125. 18; (3) There was
the तीर्थ of Candramas visited by sages, the
Vaikhānasas and the Vālakhilyas 3. 125. 14.
E. Place for practising austerities and for
offering religious rites: (1) Gods and manes,
together with great sages, always rested
(नित्यशयाः) there and practised austerities;
Yudhiṣṭhira was advised by Lomaśa to wor-
ship them 3. 125. 17; (2) These gods and
manes and the sages ate चरुस् (offered in
sacrifices) 3. 125. 18; (3) Kṛṣṇa practised
austerities on the mountain (कृष्णश् चेह त-
पोरतः) 3. 125. 18; (4) Śaṃtanu, Śunaka,
Nara and Nārāyaṇa acquired the eternal place
(by practising austerities) here (स्थानं
प्राप्ताः सनातनम्) 3. 125. 16; (5)
Lomaśa suggested to the Pāṇḍavas that he
and all of them should practise austerities and
become very thin (सर्वे चात्र गमिष्यामः
सुकृशाः सुतपस्विनः) 3. 125. 19.

इक्षुमती
Ikṣumatī f.: Name of a river.
Situated near the Kurukṣetra; along this
river lived the Nāga Takṣaka and his son
Aśvasena (कुरुक्षेत्रे निवसतां नदीम्
इक्षुमतीम् अनु) 1. 3. 145; finds place in
the Daivata-Ṛṣi-vaṃśa 13. 151. 20, 2.

इक्षुमालिनी
Ikṣumālinī f.: Name of a river.
One of the rivers of the Bhāratavarṣa
enumerated by Saṃjaya 6. 10. 16, 5; its
water used by people for drinking 6. 10. 13.

इक्षुवर्धनिका
Ikṣuvardhanikā f.: Name of a river.
One of the rivers of the Śākadvīpa
enumerated by Saṃjaya 6. 12. 30; all these
excellent rivers are holy (पुण्यास् ता हि सरिद्-
वराः) 6. 12. 32.

इन्द्रकील
Indrakīla m.: Name of a mountain.
Arjuna, after crossing the Himavant
and the Gandhamādana mountains, reached
Indrakīla where he saw Indra in the form
of an ascetic 3. 38. 30.

इन्द्रतीर्थ
Indratīrtha nt.: Name of a तीर्थ।
A. Location: Not far from the आश्रम
of Srucāvatī, daughter of Bharadvāja, near
the तीर्थ Badarapācana 9. 47. 17.
B.
Description: excellent (उत्तम) 9. 47. 17;
famous in the three worlds (त्रिषु लोकेषु
विश्रुते) 9. 47. 17; auspicious (शिव) 9. 48.
5; holy (पुण्य), most ancient (सनातन),
which frees one of all sins (सर्वपाप-
प्रमोचन) 9. 48. 5.
C. Name: Since
Indra performed there a hundred sacrifices,
the तीर्थ came to be known after him (तत्र
ह्य् अमरराजो ऽसाव् ईजे क्रतुशतेन ह …
तस्य नाम्ना च तत् तीर्थम् … इन्द्रतीर्थम्
इति ख्यातम्) 9. 48. 2, 5.
D. Events:
(i) Epic: Balarāma, in his तीर्थयात्रा,
went from the Badarapācanatīrtha to Indra-
tīrtha; he took bath according to the rites
and gave riches and jewels to Brāhmaṇas
9. 48. 1; Balarāma bathed there (उपस्पृश्य)
according to the rites and honoured Brāh-
maṇas by giving them drinks, clothes and food
(पानाच्छादनभोजनैः); from there he
went to the Rāmatīrtha 9. 48. 6; (ii) Mytho-
logical: Indra performed there, without any
hindrance, a hundred sacrifices according to
the prescribed rites, rich in meat, and giving
all kinds of दक्षिणास् (निरर्गलान् सजारू-
थ्यान् सर्वान् विविधदक्षिणान्; Nī. on Bom.
Ed. 9. 49. 1: जारूथ्यान् पुष्टान्) with the
help of priests versed in the Vedas; in those
sacrifices he gave ample wealth to Bṛhaspati
9. 48. 2-3; (iii) Indra, after his meeting
with Srucāvatī, went to the nearby Indra-
tīrtha and began to mutter मन्त्रस् (ततो
जप्यं जजाप सः) 9. 47. 17.

इन्द्रतोया
Indratoyā f.: Name of a river.
Near the Gandhamādana mountain; if
one who is controlled and pure bathes there
and fasts for three nights he gets the fruit of
a horse sacrifice 13. 26. 11.

इन्द्रद्युम्न
Indradyumna nt.: Name of a lake.
A. Location: Pāṇḍu, with his two
wives, after crossing the Himavant mountain
proceeded to the Gandhamādana, and after
reaching the Indradyumna lake and crossing
the Haṃsakūṭa, he lived as an ascetic on the
Śataśṛṅga mountain 1. 110. 45; the lake
was situated beyond the mountain Himavant
(mentioned in 3. 191. 4), the dwelling place
of the long-lived crane called Nādījaṅgha 3.
191. 9-10; a tortoise, Akūpāra by name and
older than Prākārakarṇa, also lived in this
lake 3. 191. 14, 18.
B. Origin: Akūpāra
told his visitors on the bank of this lake
(3. 191. 16) that the lake was created by
the treading of the cows given as gifts by
the king Indradyumna in the sacrifices per-
formed by him at that place (सरश् चेदम्
अस्य दक्षिणादत्ताभिर् गोभिर् अतिक्रम-
माणाभिः कृतम्) 3. 191. 18.

इन्द्रपर्वत
Indraparvata m.: Name of a mountain.
When Bhīma was in the country of the
Videhas, he conquered the seven chiefs of the
Kirātas in the neighbourhood of the Indra-
parvata mountain (इन्द्रपर्वतम् अन्तिकात्)
2. 27. 13.

इन्द्रमार्ग
Indramārga m.: Name of a तीर्थ।
Benefits of visiting this तीर्थ: (1) One
who is on a pilgrimage (तीर्थसेवी), if he
fasts for a day and night at the Indramārga
he is glorified in the Śakraloka (शक्रलोके
महीयते) 3. 81. 158; (2) By bathing at
Indramārga one is awakened in a विमान,
praised by the Apsarases (विबोध्यते विमान-
स्थः सो ऽप्सरोभिर् अभिष्टुतः) 13. 26. 9;
(3) If one gives offerings to manes at this
तीर्थ (इन्द्रमार्गे च तर्पयन्) he enjoys
सुधा in his next life (सुधां वै लभते
भोक्तुं यो नरो जायते पुनः) 13. 26. 15.

इन्द्रस्य
Indrasya prasravaṇam nt.: Name of a
cascade.
A. Location: Located on an excellent,
auspicious mountain which was visited by
persons of friendly and upright disposition
(मैत्राणाम् ऋजुबुद्धीनाम् अयं गिरिवरः
शुभः) 3. 125. 21.
B. Description:
Holy (पुण्य) 3. 125. 20.
C. Mytho-
logical event: Here Dhātṛ, Vidhātṛ and
Varuṇa became composed and lived a highly
virtuous life; from here they ascended to
heaven (?) (यत्र धाता विधाता च वरुणश्
चोर्ध्वम् आगताः।इह ते न्यवसन् राजन्
क्षान्ताः परमधर्मिणः) 3. 125. 20-21.

इरामा
Irāmā f.: Name of a river.
One of the rivers seen by Mārkaṇḍeya
in the belly of the child (Bāla 3. 186. 83
i. e. Nārāyaṇa 3. 187. 3) 3. 186. 95.

इरावती
Irāvatī f.: Name of a river.
A. Location: Enumerated among the
rivers of the Bhāratavarṣa whose water was
used by people for drinking 6. 10. 15, 5,
13; the country where the five rivers, among
which one is Irāvatī, with the Sindhu as the
sixth flow that is known as the Āraṭṭas
(आरट्टा नाम ते देशाः) 8. 30. 35-36; the
Bāhlīka country lies beyond the rivers
Śatadruka and the Irāvatī rivers 8. 30. 21.
B. Description: Excellent river (सरिद्-
वराः) 13. 134. 14; सरितां वराः) 13. 134.
19.
C. Characteristics: (1) There are
forests of Pīlu trees on this river (यत्र
पीलुवनान्य् अपि) 8. 30. 35-36; (2) Irāvatī
and other rivers contain water of all the
तीर्थस् (सर्वतीर्थोदकैर् युताः) 13. 134.
12; (3) Meeting the ocean (सागरगमाः)
13. 134. 14.
D. Importance: (1) One
of the rivers which wait upon Śiva for his
bath (उपस्परशनहेतोस् त्वा समीपस्था
उपासते) 13. 134. 12; (2) These rivers,
Sarasvatī, Irāvatī and others, were expert
in what constitutes the duties of women
(स्त्रीधर्मकुशलाः); therefore Umā wanted
to consult them on स्त्रीधर्म before ex-
pounding it to Śiva (तं (स्त्रीधर्मं)
तु संमन्त्र्य युष्माभिर् वक्तुम् इच्छामि
शङ्करे) 13. 134. 16, 19-20, 13; Umā
thus wants to honour them 13. 134. 12, 21;
(3) One of the rivers which wait upon
Varuṇa in his सभा 2. 9. 19.
E. Event:
Bhoja, Gopati and Tālaketu were killed by
Kṛṣṇa on the banks of Irāvatī 3. 13. 30.

इलास्पद
Ilāspada nt.: Name of a तीर्थ।
Situated near the Saraka तीर्थ; by
bathing there and by worshipping (अर्चयित्वा)
gods and manes, one does not meet with
calamity and wins the fruit of the Vājapeya
sacrifice 3. 81. 63-64.

ईशानाध्युषित
Īśānādhyuṣita nt.: Name of a तीर्थ।
Described as difficult to reach (सुदुर्-
लभ) 3. 82. 7; situated at a distance of six
throws of a sacrifical wooden peg from the
anthill near the river Sarasvatī (षट्सु शम्-
यानिपातेषु वल्मीकात्) 3. 82. 7; it has been
mentioned in an ancient text (?) (दृष्तम्
एतत् पुरातने; Nī. on Bom. Ed. 3. 84. 10:
पुरातने भविष्यपुराणादौ) that by
bathing there one obtains the fruit of giving
a thousand Kapilā cows and the fruit of a
horse sacrifice (कपिलानां सहस्रं च
वाजिमेधं च विन्दती) 3. 82. 8 (Nī. on
Bom. Ed. 3. 84. 9: शम्या मुद्गराकृतिर्
यज्ञोपकरणविशेषः स बलवता क्षिप्तो
यावद् दूरं पतेत् तावान् देशः शम्या-
निपातः).

उज्जयन्त
Ujjayanta m.: Name of a mountain.
A. Location: Situated in the Surāṣṭras
3. 86. 20, 16.
B. Description: Holy
(पुण्य) and inhabited by animals and birds
(मृगपक्षिणिषेवित) 3. 86. 20; great, having
summits, and one that brings success quickly
(उज्जयन्तश् च शिखरी क्षिप्रं सिद्धिकरो
महान्) 3. 86. 18.
C. Importance: Dhau-
mya informed Yudhiṣṭhira about an ancient
stanza (पुराणः श्लोकः) about this mountain
sung by Nārada (नारदेनानुकीर्तितः); ac-
cording to it one who practised austerities on
the mountain Ujjayanta was glorified in the
heaven (उज्जयन्ते स्म तप्ताङ्गो नाकपृष्ठे
महीयते) 3. 86. 20 (Nī. on Bom. Ed. 3.
88. 23: तप्ताङ्गः कृतततपस्कः).

उज्जानक
Ujjānaka1 m.: Name of a तीर्थ।
Situated near the आश्रमस् of Ārṣṭiṣena
and Piṅgā; by bathing (उपस्पृश्य) there one
became free of sins 13. 26. 52. [See Ujjā-
naka2]

उज्जानक
Ujjānaka2 m.: Name of a तीर्थ।
Seems to be different from Ujjānaka1;
situated not far from the Vātikaṣaṇḍa which
lay to the north of the Videha country (एष
वातिकषण्डो वै … विदेहान् उत्तरश् च यः।
एष उज्जानको नाम) 3. 130. 13-14; here
Yavakrī obtained peace and also the sage
Vasiṣṭha in the company of Arundhatī (एष
उज्जानको नाम यवक्रीर् यत्र शान्तवान्।
अरुन्धतीसहायश् च वसिष्ठो भगवान्
ऋषिः) 3. 130. 14. [See Ujjānaka1]

उज्जानक
Ujjānaka3 m.: Name of a desert.
A. Location: Situated on an even
waste land near the आश्रम of Uttaṅka
(ममाश्रमसमीपे (i. e. Uttaṅkasya) वै
समेषु मरुधन्वसु) 3. 193. 14.
B.
Description: A sea full of sand (समुद्रो
वालुकापुर्ण उज्जानक इति स्मृतः) 3. 193.
15; 3. 195. 7; it was many योजनस् long and
many योजनस् wide (बहुयोजनविस्तीर्णो
बहुयोजनम् आयतः) 3. 193. 15.
C.
Event: A Dānava named Dhundhu lived
there underground concealed in sand (अन्तर्
भूमिगतो राजन् वसति) 3. 193. 16-17;
(अन्तर् भूमिगतस् तत्र वालुकान्तर्हितस्
तदा) 3. 195. 8; Dhundhu caused disturbance
to the आश्रम of Uttaṅka 3. 195. 7.

उत्कोचक
Utkocaka nt.: Name of a तीर्थ।
Dhaumya, the younger brother of Devala,
had his आश्रम near this तीर्थ where he
practised austerities; Pāṇḍavas, as advised
by the Gandharva, went to this तीर्थ and
chose Dhaumya for their priest 1. 174. 2; 1.
174. 6 (तत उत्कोचकं तीर्थं गत्वा धौ-
म्याश्रमं तु ते।तं वव्रुः पाण्डवा
धौम्यं पौरोहित्याय भारत).

उत्तरमानस
Uttaramānasa nt.: Name of a lake.
Mentioned along with Puṣkara and Pra-
bhāsa 12. 148. 11; after visiting these lakes
one again obtains long life in this life (लब्-
धायुर्जीविते पुनः) 12. 148. 11.

उत्पलावत
Utpalāvata nt.: Name of a तीर्थ।
A. Location: Located near Kanya-
kubja in the Pāñcālas 3. 85. 12, 11.
B.
Past event: It was here that Viśvāmitra,
the Kauśika, offered sacrifice to Indra (विश्वा-
मित्रो ऽयजद् यत्र शक्रेण सह कौशिकः)
3. 85. 11; having seen Viśvāmitra's super-
human power (Rāma) Jāmadagnya sang
a family-related (stanza) (अनुवंश):
“Kauśika drank सोम with Indra at Kanya-
kubja; he then left his royal status and
declared: ‘I am a Brāhmaṇa’” (यत्रानु-
वंशं भगवाञ् जामदग्न्यस् तथा
जगौ॥विश्वामित्रस्य तां दृष्ट्वा विभूतिम्
अतिमानुषीम्।कन्यकुब्जे ऽपिबत् सोमम्
इन्द्रेण सह कौशिकः।ततः क्षत्राद्
अपाक्रामद् ब्राह्मणो ऽस्मीति चाब्रवीत्॥)
3. 85. 11-12.

उत्पलावती
Utpalāvatī f.: Name of a river.
Listed by Saṃjaya among the rivers of
the Bhāratavarṣa 6. 10. 33, 5; its water used
for drinking by the people 6. 10. 13; all these
rivers are described as mothers of the universe
(विश्वस्य मातरः) and very strong (महा-
बलाः) 6. 10. 35.

उत्पलावन
Utpalāvana nt.: Name of a तीर्थ।
If one bathes there (? offers libations to
the पितृस् ?) (कृतोदकः) for a month, he
obtains the fruit of performing an Aśvamedha
sacrifice 13. 26. 33.

उत्पलिनी
Utpalinī f.: Name of a river.
After coming down from the Himālayas
and while proceeding towards the east, Arjuna
first saw the beautiful (रम्या) river Utaplinī
near the Naimiṣa forest 1. 207. 6.

उदपान
Udapāna1 m.: Name (?) of a well
(कूप).
A. Location: Situated near Śālagrāma,
sacred to Viṣṇu 3. 82. 106.
B. Descrip-
tion: Capable of freeing of all sins (सर्व-
पापप्रमोचन) 3. 82. 108.
C. Im-
portance: All the four oceans are always
present in this well (समुद्रास् तत्र चत्-
वारः कूपे संनिहिताः सदा) 3. 82. 108;
if one bathed (उपस्पृश्य) there one did not
meet with calamities (न दुर्गतिम् अवाप्-
नुयात्) 3. 82. 108; by approaching (अभि-
गम्य) the great god Viṣṇu there one shines
like Soma being freed of all debts (विराजति
यथा सोम ऋणैर् मुक्तो युधिष्ठिर) 3.
82. 109. [See Kūpa1 and Kūpa2]

उदपान
Udapāna2 m.: Name (?) of a well.
Balarāma went there from the Cama-
sodbheda तीर्थ; since it is an excellent means
of acquiring well-being and great merit and
since the plants and the earth there look
glossy, the Siddhas know the river Sarasvatī,
although not visible, to be present there
(आद्यं स्वस्त्ययनं चैव तत्रावाप्य
महत् फलम्॥स्निग्धत्वाद् ओषढीनां
च भूमेश् च जनमेजय।जानन्ति सिद्धा
राजेन्द्र नष्टाम् अपि सरस्वतीम्॥) 9. 34.
80-81. [See Udapāna, Kūpa]

उदपान
Udapāna3 m.: The well of Trita.
A. Location: Situated on the bank of
the river Sarasvatī 9. 35. 24, hence called
नदीगत 9. 35. 1, 53.
B. Description:
Great (महत्) 9. 35. 24; very deep (अगाध)
and extremely terrible (सुमहाघोर) 3. 35.
25; without water (निर्जल), hence covered
with soil (पांसुस्ंवृत, पांसुग्रस्त) 9.
35. 28, 32; covered with plants and grass
(वीरुत्तृणावृत) 9. 35. 29; frightful to all
creatures (सर्वभूतभयङ्कर, प्रति-
भय) 9. 35. 25, 42.
C. Events: (1)
Epic: Balarāma bathed there and gave ample
wealth to Brāhmaṇas and worshipped them 9.
35. 2, 52; he praised the तीर्थ and left for
Vinaśanatīrtha 9. 35. 53; (2) Of the past
Yuga (9. 35. 7): Trita, afraid of a wolf,
fell into this well; his two brothers, Ekata
and Dvita (9. 35. 7), deserted him there
and went home (9. 35. 25, 27, 4-6); he, by
chance, saw a plant in the well (9. 35. 31);
using it as a Soma plant, Trita offered a
sacrifice in the well and drank Soma (9. 35.
32-35, 3); gods came to the well, where Trita
was consecrated for the sacrifice, to receive
their shares (9. 35. 40); Trita asked the
following boon from the gods: One who
bathes in this well shall obtain the same
condition after death as one who has (offered
a Soma sacrifice and) drunk Soma (यश्
चेहोपस्पृशेत् कूपे स सोमपगतिं लभेत्)
9. 35. 45; at that moment Sarasvatī sprang up
in the well and brought Trita out of the well
9. 35. 46.
D. Simile: Trita's falling
down in the well compared to a sinner's
falling in the Naraka 9. 35. 29.

उदय
Udaya m.: Name of the eastern moun-
tain from behind which the sun rises.
A. Mythological event: Indra, in con-
versation with Devasenā, saw the sun on
the Udaya mountain and the moon entering
the sun; at that point when the Raudra
मुहूर्त commenced on the new moon day
he saw the battle raging between gods and
demons on the Udaya mountain (अमावास्यां
संप्रवृत्तं मुहूर्तं रौद्रम् एव च।
देवासुरं च संग्रामं सो ऽपश्यद् उदये
गिरौ) 3. 213. 26-27.
B. Similes: (1)
Śālva mounted on his elephant appeared like
the sun on the Udaya mountain at the end
of the night 9. 19. 4; (2) Arjuna mounted
his excellent chariot as does the sun the
Udaya 7. 60. 16; (3) Karṇa, shining with
his white splendour (कर्णम् … श्वेतच्छ-
विविराजितम्), appeared like the sun beautify-
ing the Udaya mountain 8. 43. 38; (4) The
elephant, fierce and properly equipped, on
which Bhīma had mounted, looked like a man-
sion on the topmost part of the Udaya where
the sun had arisen (उदयाग्र्यभवनं
यथाभ्युदितभास्करम्) 8. 8. 22; (5)
Kṛṣṇa, with the Kaustubha jewel shining on
his chest, looked like the Udaya mountain
with the rising sun 12. 45. 15; (6) Duryo-
dhana and Śalya received the attacking
warriors like the Asta and the Udaya moun-
tains receiving the huge clouds 9. 15. 31;
(7) Just as an object on the Udaya moun-
tain shines due to the proximity of the sun
similarly a person of a lower order becomes
bright due to association with the people of
the higher order (यथोदयगिरौ द्रव्यं
संनिकर्षेण दीप्यते।तथा सत्संनिकर्-
षेण हीनवर्णो ऽपि दीप्यते॥) 12. 282. 4
(Nī. on Bom. Ed. 12. 293. 4: द्रव्यं
मणिकाञ्चनादि दीप्यते सूर्यसन्निकर्षेण
अत एव सन्ध्योः सूर्यरश्मयो द्रव्यप्र-
भाविच्छुरणाद् रक्ता दृश्यन्ते). [See
Udyant]

उद्यत्|उद्यन्त्
Udyant m.: Name of a mountain.
Described as resounding with songs
(गीतनादित) 3. 82. 81; on this mountain
are located Sāvitrapada (सावित्रं तु पदं
तत्र) and the famous Yonidvāra (योनि-
द्वारं च तत्रैव विश्रुतम्) 3. 82. 81, 83;
if a Brāhmaṇa, of strict vows, performed
संध्या on this mountain it was as good as
performing it for twelve years (उपास्ता च
भवेत् संध्या तेन द्वादशवार्षिकी) 3.
82. 82. [See Udaya]

उपजला
Upajalā f.: Name of a river.
Flowing near Yamunā (उपजलां चैव
यमुनाम् अभितो नदीम्); king Uśīnara,
having offered a sacrifice there, surpassed
Indra 3. 130. 17.

उपरिगिरि
Uparigiri m.: Name (?) of a mountain.
Situated in the north; Arjuna conquered
it 2. 24. 2, 1.

उपेन्द्रा
Upendrā f.: Name of a river.
Listed by Saṃjaya among the rivers of
the Bhāratavarṣa 6. 10. 26, 5; its water used
by people for drinking 6. 10. 13; all these
rivers are mothers of the universe (विश्वस्य
मातरः) and are very strong (महाबलाः)
6. 10. 35.

उर्वशी
Urvaśī f.: Name of a river (?)
If one, who is well composed, goes to
Urvaśī under the constellation Kṛttikā and
bathes there in the Lauhitya तीर्थ according
to the rites, he obtains the fruit of the Punḍa-
rīka sacrifice (उर्वशीकृत्तिकायोगे गत्वा यः
सुसमाहितः।लौहित्ये विधिवत् स्नात्वा
पुण्डरीकफलं लभेत्) 13. 26. 43; (for
Urvaśī as one of the names of Gaṅgā, see
12. 29. 61).

उर्वशीतीर्थ
Urvaśītīrtha nt.: Name of a तीर्थ।
Situated between Kālikāsaṅgama and
Somāśrama 3. 82. 136 (135).

उशीरबीज
Uśīrabīja m.: Name of a mountain.
Situated in the north (5. 109. 19-20)
near Maināka and Śveta mountains which the
Pāṇḍavas crossed in the company of Lomaśa
3. 140. 1; the mountain has a lake Jāmbū-
nada; it was here that the king Marutta
offered a sacrifice 5. 109. 20.

ऋक्षवत्|ऋक्षवन्त्
Ṛkṣavant m.: Name of a mountain
(lit. ‘where bears abound’).
A. Kulaparvata: Listed by Saṃjaya
among the seven Kulaparvatas (principal
ranges of mountains) of the Bhāratavarṣa
6. 10. 10.
B. Location: Nala told Dama-
yantī that many roads beyond the moun-
tain Ṛkṣavant lead to the Dakṣiṇāpatha (एते
गच्छन्ति बहवः पन्थानो दक्षिणा-
पथम्।अवन्तीम् ऋक्षवन्तं च समति-
क्रम्य पर्वतम्॥) 3. 58. 20.
C. Past
event: Son of Viḍūratha, a descendant
of the Pauravas (पौरवदायादः), was
one of the few Kṣatriyas saved during their
slaughter by Rāma Jāmadagnya; he was
reared by the bears on this mountain (ऋक्षैः
संवर्धितो विप्र ऋक्षवत्य् एव पर्वते)
12. 49. 67.
D. Simile: The army of the
Pāṇḍavas moving (in two divisions) in front
and at the back of the chariots of Kṛṣṇa and
the Pāṇḍavas resembled the river Narmadā
flowing (in two streams) in front and at the
back of the mountain after meeting it 12.
52. 32.

ऋश्यमूक
Ṛśyamūka m.: Name of a mountain
(once spelt Ṛṣyamūka 3. 26. 8).
A. Description: Having many roots
and fruit (बहुमूलफलं गिरिम्) 3. 264.
9.
B. Events from the Rāmāyaṇa:
Gandharva Viśvāvasu informed Rāma about
the mountain Ṛśyamūka: by its side lay
the lake Pampā; Sugrīva, with his four coun-
sellors, lived on that mountain 3. 263. 40-
41; Hanūmant also told Bhīma that he lived
for a long time on the Ṛśyamūka mountain
with Sugrīva after the latter was offended
by Vālin 3. 147. 27; Rāma and Lakṣmaṇa
saw the five monkey chiefs seated on the
summit of this mountain 3. 264. 9; 3. 147.
31; the sage Mārkaṇḍeya saw Rāma and
Lakṣmaṇa on the peak of the Ṛṣyamūka 3.
26. 8.

ऋषभ
Ṛṣabha1 m.: Name of a mountain.
A. Location: Situated in the Pāṇḍya
country (पाण्ड्येषु) 3. 83. 19, close to the
ocean (सागरोरसि) 5. 110. 22.
B. Des-
cription: Worshipped by gods (सुरपूजित)
3. 83. 19.
C. Importance: A visit to
the mountain Ṛṣabha secures for the visitor
the fruit of the Vājapeya sacrifice and he
(after death) rejoices in the heaven (नाक-
पृष्ठे च मोदते) 3. 83. 19.
D. My-
thological event: Suparṇa told Gālava
that after eating and resting on the Ṛṣabha
mountain they would go back from the
mountain 5. 110. 22; when the two of them
reached the summit of the mountain they
saw there the Brāhmaṇī Śāṇḍilī engaged in
austerities 5. 111. 1.

ऋषभ
Ṛṣabha2 m.: Name of a तीर्थ।
Situated in Kośalā; by visiting the तीर्थ
and by fasting there for three nights (त्रिरात्रो-
पोषितः) one gets the fruit of the Vājapeya
sacrifice 3. 83. 10.

ऋषभकूट
Ṛṣabhakūṭa m.: Name of a mountain.
An ascetic by name Ṛṣabha, hundreds of
years old, lived there (which probably explains
the name) 3. 109. 7. [See Hemakūṭa]

ऋषभद्वीप
Ṛṣabhadvīpa m.: Name of a holy
island (a तीर्थ).
A. Location: On the river Sarasvatī
3. 82. 139; Sarasvatī is known as Suveṇu
near Ṛṣabhadvīpa where Sarasvatī arrived
for king Kuru who was offering a sacrifice at
Kurukṣetra (सुवेणुर् ऋषभद्वीपे) 9. 37. 24.
B. Description: Holy (पुण्य) and visited
by royal sages (राजर्षिसेवित) 9. 37. 24; fit
to be resorted to (सेव्य) 3. 82. 139; the killer
of Krauñcas (?) (क्रौञ्चनिषूदन) 3. 82.
139.
C. Importance: If one bathes in
Sarasvatī at this island he shines in a विमान
(विमानस्थो विराजते) 3. 82. 139.

ऋषिकुल्या
Ṛṣikulyā1 f.: Name of a तीर्थ।
If one bathes in the Ṛṣikulyā and if one
lives there for a month subsisting only on
vegetables (शाकाहारः) he reaches the world
of the Ṛṣis (ऋषिलोकं प्रपद्यते) 3. 82.
44, 43.

ऋषिकुल्या
Ṛṣikulyā2 f.: Name of a river.
Listed by Saṃjaya among the rivers of
the Bhāratavarṣa; people use its water for
drinking purposes 6. 10. 34, 13; all the rivers
listed here are described as mothers of the
universe and very strong 6. 10. 35 (for cita-
tion see Atikṛṣṇā); finds mention in the
Daivata-Ṛṣi-Vaṃśa 13. 151. 21, 2; [ऋषिकुल्याः
(pl.) 2. 25. 4: probably not a proper name;
when Arjuna went beyond the Śveta moun-
tain and ran over the Hāṭaka country, he saw
the lake Mānasa and many small rivers of the
Ṛṣis (ऋषिकुल्याश् च ताः सर्वा ददर्श … )].

ऋषिगिरि
Ṛṣigiri m.: Name of a mountain.
One of the five mountains surrounding
the city Girivraja in the Magadha country;
the mountains came together as though for
protecting the city (रक्षन्तीवाभिसंहत्य
 … गिरिव्रजम्) 2. 19. 3; all the five moun-
tains are described as shining (शुभाः), hav-
ing high peaks (महाशृङ्गाः), shady trees
(शीतलद्रुमाः), and of solid body (सं-
हताङ्गाः) 2. 19. 2-3; they were as though
concealed by forests of fragrant and attractive
Lodhra trees whose branches were covered with
flowers 2. 19. 4.

ऋष्यमूक
Ṛṣyamūka m.: See Ṛśyamūka.

एकपर्वतक
Ekaparvataka m.: Name of a mountain.
Kṛṣṇa, Bhīma and Arjuna, while pro-
ceeding to Magadha, crossed the rivers
flowing near the mountain Ekaparvataka 2.
18. 27.

एकरात्र
Ekarātra nt.: Name of a तीर्थ।
One who is controlled (नियतः) and
speaks the truth, if he spends one night (एक-
रात्रोषितः) at this तीर्थ (which explains its
name), he is glorified in the world of Brahman
(ब्रह्मलोके महीयते) 3. 81. 159.

एकहंस
Ekahaṃsa nt.: Name of a तीर्थ।
By bathing at Ekahaṃsa one gets the
fruit of gifting a thousand cows (गोसहस्र-
फलं लभेत्) 3. 81. 16.

ओघवती
Oghavatī f.: Name of a river.
A. Origin: One half of the body of
Oghavatī, daughter of Oghavant and wife
of Sudarśana (13. 2. 37-38), became a river
of that name for purifying the world; she
could achieve this feat due to her austerities
and her mastery over योग (एषा हि तपसा
स्वेन संयुक्ता ब्रह्मवादिनी।पावनार्-
थं च लोकस्य सरिच्छ्रेष्ठा भविष्यति॥
अर्धेनौघवती नाम त्वाम् अर्धेनानु-
यास्यति।शरीरेण महाभागा योगो ह्य्
अस्या वशे स्थितः॥) 13. 2. 82-83.
B. One
of the forms of Sarasvatī: One of the seven
Sarasvatīs 9. 37. 4; when Sarasvatī of divine
water (दिव्यतोया), invited by Vasiṣṭha,
arrived at Kurukṣetra, she was known as
Oghavatī 9. 37. 25.
C. Location: Listed
by Saṃjaya among the rivers of the Bhārata-
varṣa; its water used by people for drinking
purposes 6. 10. 21, 13; flowing near the place
where Bhīṣma lay on his bed of arrows 12.
50. 6-7.
D. Description: Holy (पुण्या)
9. 61. 37; the best among the rivers (सरिच्-
छ्रेष्ठा) 13. 2. 82; all the rivers listed by
Saṃjaya are described as mothers of the
universe and very strong 6. 10. 35 (for cita-
tion see Atikṛṣṇā).
E. Epic connection:
(1) Bhīṣma lay on a cluster of arrows on
the bank of Oghavatī on a highly religious
spot (देशे परमधर्मिष्ठे) 12. 50. 7;
(2) After the war was over the Pāṇḍavas,
before proceeding to Hāstinapura, decided to
spend a night near the river Oghavatī 9.
61. 37.

औजस
Aujasa nt.: Name of a तीर्थ।
A. Location: On the river Sarasvatī
9. 45. 88; to the east of this तीर्थ was the
Kurutīrtha (औजसस्य तु पूर्वेण कुरु-
तीर्थम्) 3. 81. 144.
B. Description:
Excellent तीर्थ (तीर्थवर) 9. 45. 93, 94;
(तीर्थप्रवर) 9. 45. 89; holy (शृणु …
पुण्यताम्) 9. 45. 88; shines by its own lustre
(दीप्यते स्वेन तेजसा) 3. 81. 143; it was like
another heaven (त्रिविष्टपम् इवापरम्) 9.
45. 89.
C. Past events: (1) Formerly,
at this तीर्थ Varuṇa, was anointed as the
king of waters by the hosts of gods (औज-
सं नाम तत् तीर्थं यत्र पूर्वम् अपां
पतिः।अभिषिक्तः सुरगणैर् वरुणो भर-
तर्षभ) 9. 45. 92; hence sacred to Varuṇa
(औजसं वारुणं तीर्थम्) 3. 81. 143.
(2) At this तीर्थ, Brahman and the other
gods, and the sages anointed Guha (Kārtti-
keya) as the general of the gods 3. 81. 143;
9. 45. 91; hence sacred also to Skanda 9. 45.
93; Kārttikeya gave here powers individually
in the three worlds to the chiefs of the Nairṛtas
(ऐश्वर्याणि च तत्रस्थो ददाव् ईशः पृथक्
पृथक्।तदा नैरृतमुख्येभ्यस् त्रैलोक्ये
पावकात्मजः) 9. 45. 90.
D. Epic rela-
tionship: Balarāma bathed there and wor-
shipped Skanda; he gifted gold, garments and
ornaments to Brāhmaṇas; he stayed there for
a night, worshipped the excellent तीर्थ and
bathed there (स्पृष्ट्वा तोयं च लाङ्गली);
he became delighted and was happy 9. 45.
93-94.

औद्दालक
Auddālaka nt.: Name of a तीर्थ।
Resorted to by sages (मुनिनिषेवित);
by taking a ceremonial bath there (तत्राभि-
षेकम् कुर्वीत) one is freed of all sins 3.
82. 140.

औशनस
Auśanasa nt.: Name of a तीर्थ, also
called Kapālamocana (3. 81. 118; 9. 38. 4,
8, 20).
A. Location: On the river Sarasvatī
(सरस्वत्यास् तीर्थवरम्) 9. 38. 16.
B.
Description: Best (उत्तम) 9. 38. 7; (अनु-
त्तम) 9. 38. 16; excellent तीर्थ (तीर्थ-
वर) 9. 38. 16, (तीर्थप्रवर) 9. 38. 7;
famous (ख्यात) 9. 38. 16; famous in the three
worlds (त्रिषु लोकेषु विश्रुतम्) 3. 81. 116;
removing or destroying all sins (सर्वपाप-
प्रमोचन) 3. 81. 118; (सर्वपापप्रश-
मन) 9. 38. 16; inhabited by the Siddhas
(सिद्धक्षेत्र) 9. 38. 16.
C. Event: For-
merly Kāvya (Uśanas) practised austerities at
this तीर्थ (hence, perhaps, called Auśanasa);
the whole नीति flashed before him, and there
he pondered over the battle of the Daityas
and the Dānavas (तत्रस्थश् चिन्तयाम् आस
दैत्यदानवविग्रहम्) 9. 38. 6.
D. Its
name Kapālamocana explained by Vaiśaṃ-
pāyana: Rāma, of the Raghu family, while
in the Daṇḍakāraṇya, cut off the head of a
demon with a razor-sharp arrow; the flying
head, by chance, struck the flank (जङ्घा)
of an ascetic named Mahodara and got stuck
there; the ascetic could not get it out of the
जङ्घा although he visited and bathed in
many तीर्थस्; on the advice of some ascetics
he went to the Auśanasatīrtha and bathed
there; the head then came out of the जङ्घा
and fell into the water; when the incident
was reported to the ascetics they named
Auśanasa as Kapālamocana (ते श्रुत्वा वच-
नं तस्य ततस् तीर्थस्य मानद।कपाल-
मोचनम् इति नाम चक्रुः समागताः) 9.
38. 4-20.
E. Importance: Where Brah-
man and the other gods, great ascetics (तपो-
धनाः) and god Kārttikeya remain present
for all the three divisions of time to do good
to Bhārgava (त्रिसंध्यं किल भारत।
सांनिध्यम् अकरोत् तत्र भार्गवप्रिय-
काम्यया) 3. 81. 117; by bathing there one
was freed of all sins 3. 81. 118.
F. Epic
relationship: Balarāma arrived at this तीर्थ
and gave wealth according to the prescriptions
to the high-souled Brāhmaṇas; after giving
gifts and honouring the Brāhmaṇas, he pro-
ceeded to the आश्रम of Ruṣaṅgu 9. 38. 4,
7, 21.

कनकपर्वत
Kanakaparvata m.: Name of a moun-
tain (?)
Name of a mountain, or an epithet
(mountain of gold) of Meru (मेरौ कनक-
पर्वते) 12. 122. 3; (महामेरुः स्वयं
कनकपर्वतः) 12. 59. 122; this mountain
gave gold to king Vainya 12. 59. 122. [See
Meru]

कनखल
Kanakhala1 m. (pl.): Name of a moun-
tain range.
Loved by sages; the great river Gaṅgā
shines there (एते कनखला राजन् ऋषीणां
दयिता नगाः।एषा प्रकाशते गङ्गा युधि-
ष्ठिर महानदी) 3. 135. 5.

कनखल
Kanakhala2 nt.: Name of a तीर्थ।
Situated near Gaṅgādvāra 3. 88. 18; 13.
26. 12; described as holy (पुण्य) 3. 88. 19;
by bathing and fasting there for three nights
one gets the fruit of performing an Aśva-
medha sacrifice and, freed of sins, goes to
heaven 3. 82. 26; (धूतपाप्मा दिवं व्रजेत्)
13. 26. 12 (Acc. to Nī. the तीर्थस् listed in
13. 26. 12 are all on the river Gōdāvarī;
for his remark see Kuśāvarta below).

कन्या
Kanyā f.: See Kanyāsaṃvedya.

कन्याकूप
Kanyākūpa m.: Name of a तीर्थ।
One who bathes in this well becomes
famous among gods and shines with fame
(देवेषु कीर्तिं लभते यशसा च विराजते)
13. 26. 18.

कन्यातीर्थ
Kanyātīrtha1 nt.: Name of a तीर्थ।
Situated on the river Sarasvatī 3. 81. 93;
one who bathes there secures the fruit of an
Agniṣṭoma 3. 81. 94.

कन्यातीर्थ
Kanyātīrtha2 nt.: Name of a तीर्थ।
One of the तीर्थस् on the Gomatī 3. 93.
2; described as holy (पुण्य) 3. 93. 2; the
Pāṇḍavas after bathing there gave away
cows and riches; they repeatedly gave offer-
ings to gods and manes and satisfied the
Brāhmaṇas 3. 93. 3.

कन्यातीर्थ
Kanyātīrtha3 nt.: Name of a तीर्थ।
On the shore of the (southern ?) ocean
(तीरे समुद्रस्य); having bathed there, one
is freed of all sins 3. 83. 21.

कन्यासंवेद्य
Kanyāsaṃvedya nt.: Name of a तीर्थ,
also called Kanyā.
Restrained and subsisting on limited food
(नियतो नियताशनः), if one visits Kanyā-
saṃvedya तीर्थ one gets the worlds of Prajā-
pati Manu 3. 82. 117; (the merit of those)
who give food and drink at Kanyā तीर्थ
becomes inexhaustible—this is what the
sages of strict vows have declared (कन्यायां
ये प्रयच्छन्ति पानम् अन्नं च भारत।
तद् अक्षयम् इति प्राहुर् ऋषयः संशित-
व्रताः) 3. 82. 118.

कन्याह्रद
Kanyāhrada m.: Name of a तीर्थ।
Aṅgiras had told Gautama that one who
lived at Kanyāhrada never went (after death)
to the abode of Vaivasvata (Yama) but
went to the world of gods 13. 26. 50.

कपालमोचन
Kapālamocana nt.: See Auśanasa.

कपिञ्जला
Kapiñjalā f.: Name of a river.
Listed by Saṃjaya among the rivers of
the Bhāratavarṣa, its water used by people for
drinking 6. 10. 25, 13; all the rivers listed here
are called mothers of the universe (विश्वस्य
मातरः) and very strong (महाबलाः) 6.
10. 35.

कपिलस्य
Kapilasya tīrtham nt.: Name of a
तीर्थ; also called Nāgatīrtha.
Described as famous among all the
worlds (सर्वलोकेषु विश्रुतम्); it was sacred
to Kapila, the chief of the Nāgas (नाग-
राजस्य कपिलस्य) 3. 82. 28; hence also
known as Nāgatīrtha 3. 82. 29; by bathing
there one obtained the fruit of giving a
thousand tawny cows (कपिलानां सहस्रस्य
फलम्) 3. 82. 29 (this perhaps explains the
name of the तीर्थ). [See Kapilātīrtha]

कपिला
Kapilā f.: Name of a river.
Listed by Saṃjaya among the rivers of
the Bhāratavarṣa, its water used by people
for drinking 6. 10. 27, 13; all the rivers listed
here are called mothers of the universe (विश्व-
स्य मातरः) and very strong (महाबलाः)
6. 10. 35; listed by Mārkaṇḍeya among the
rivers which are proclaimed to be the mothers
of sacrificial hearths, i. e. on the banks of
which sacrifices were performed (एता नद्यस्
तु धिष्ण्यानां मातरो याः प्रकीर्तिताः) 3.
212. 24 (Nī. on Bom. Ed. 3. 222. 27: या-
वन्तः पावका धिष्ण्याः सन्ति तावन्तः
सोमाः सोमयागाः।एतच् च याज्ञिकेष्व् एव
प्रसिद्धम्); mentioned also in the Daivata-
Ṛṣi-Vaṃśa 13. 151. 15, 2.

कपिलातीर्थ
Kapilātīrtha nt.: Name of a तीर्थ।
One who has observed chastity and has a
concentrated mind (ब्रह्मचारी समाहितः),
if he bathes in this तीर्थ and worships gods
and manes he gets the fruit of giving a thou-
sand tawny cows (कपिलानां सहस्रस्य
फलम्) 3. 81. 38 (this perhaps explains
the name of the तीर्थ). [See Kapilasya
tīrtham]

कपिलाह्रद
Kapilāhrada m.: Name of a तीर्थ।
Situated in Vārāṇasī; by bathing there
and by worshipping Vṛṣadhvaja (Śiva) one
obtains the fruit of performing a Rājasūya
sacrifice 3. 82. 69.

कपिष्ठलस्य
Kapiṣṭhalasya kedāraḥ m.: Name of
a तीर्थ।
Sacred to the high-souled Kapiṣṭhala 3.
81. 59; described as very difficult of access
(सुदुर्लभ) 3. 81. 61; one who is pure
and has controlled his mind, if he bathes in the
Kedāra of the high-souled Kapiṣṭhala (के-
दारे … कपिष्ठलमहात्मनः), his soul is
cleansed of all sins, reaches Brahman and
goes to the world of Brahman (ब्रह्माणम्
अभिगम्याथ शुचिः प्रयतमानसः।सर्व-
पापविशुद्धात्मा ब्रह्मलोकं प्रपद्-
यते॥) 3. 81. 60; one who reaches this
sacred place burns his sins by practising
austerities and becomes invisible (कपिष्ठ-
लस्य केदारं समासाद्य … अन्तर्धानम्
अवाप्नति तपसा दग्धकिल्बिषः) 3. 81. 61.

कपोतक
Kapotaka nt.: Name of a तीर्थ।
By bathing in this तीर्थ and by fasting
there for twelve days one obtains the fruit of
performing a Naramedha 13. 26. 39 (नर-
मेधफलं लभेत्) (situated on the river
Sabarmati, Editor's note on the stanza Cr.
Ed. Vol. 17, part II, p. 1067).

कम्पना
Kampanā f.: Name of a river.
Listed by Saṃjaya among the rivers of
the Bhāratavarṣa; people use its water for
drinking 6. 10. 24, 13; all the rivers listed
here are said to be the mothers of the world
(विश्वस्य मातरः) and very strong (महा-
बलाः) 6. 10. 35; described as frequented
by the Siddhas (सिद्धनिषेविता); by visiting
it one obtains the fruit of offering a Puṇḍa-
rīka sacrifice and goes to the world of Sūrya
3. 82. 99.

कम्पुना
Kampunā f.: Name of a river.
One of the rivers seen by Mārkaṇḍeya in
the belly of the Bāla (3. 186. 83 = Nārāyaṇa
3. 187. 3) 3. 186. 95; finds mention in the
Daivata-Ṛṣi-Vaṃśa 13. 151. 15, 2.

कम्बल
Kambala nt.: Name of a तीर्थ।
The तीर्थस् Prayāga, Pratiṣṭhāna, Kam-
bala, Aśvatara and Bhogavatī form the Vedī
of Prajāpati; there the Vedas and the sacri-
fices, in bodily form (मूर्तिमन्तः), and the
sages wait upon Prajāpati; gods and Cakra-
caras offer sacrifices there 3. 83. 72-73.

करतोया
Karatoyā f.: Name of a river.
Flowing through the Kuraṅga country
(करतोयां कुरङ्गेषु) 13. 26. 11; listed by
Saṃjaya among the rivers of the Bhārata-
varṣa; its water used for drinking by the
people 6. 10. 34, 13; all the rivers listed here
are called the mothers of the world (विश्व-
स्य मातरः सर्वाः) and very strong (सर्वाश्
चैव महाबलाः) 6. 10. 35; finds mention
in the Daivata-Ṛṣi-Vaṃśa 13. 151. 15, 2; one
who is pure and self-controlled and bathes in
the river Karatoyā and fasts for three nights
obtains the fruit of an Aśvamedha by offering
worship to Pitāmaha (Brahmadeva) (कृते
पैतामहे विधौ) 3. 83. 3; 13. 26. 11.
[See Karatoyinī]

करतोयिनी
Karatoyinī f.: Name of a river (identi-
cal with Karatoyā ?).
Those who visit this river, become aus-
picious, and wearing heavenly garlands, and
rich in holy fragrance they reach there (i. e.
the Goloka ? गवां विमाने 13. 105. 44)
(तत्र ते दिव्यसंस्थाना दिव्यमाल्यधराः
शिवाः।प्रयान्ति पुण्यगन्धाढ्याः) 13. 105.
45, 48 (= Sadānīrā (?), Edititor's note on
the stanza, Cr. Ed. Vol. 17, part II, p. 1099).
[See Sadānīrā]

करीषिणी
Karīṣiṇī f.: Name of a river.
Listed by Saṃjaya among the rivers of
the Bhāratavarṣa; its water used for drinking
by people 6. 10. 16, 13; all the rivers listed
here are said to be mothers of the universe
and very strong (विश्वस्य मातरः सर्वाः
सर्वाश् चैव महाबलाः) 6. 10. 35.

कर्दमिल
Kardamila nt.: Name of a तीर्थ (?)
Situated on the river Madhuvilā Samaṅgā;
it was the bathing place of Bharata (? एतत्
कर्दमिलं नाम भरतस्याभिषेचनम्)
3. 135. 1.

कलशी
Kalaśī f.: Name of a river.
If a person who has controlled his sense
organs and has faith (श्रद्दधानो जितेन्-
द्रियः) bathes (उपस्पृश्य) in the river
Kalaśī he obtains the fruit of an Agniṣṭoma
3. 81. 66; by bathing (उपस्पृश्य) there a
person becomes one with Brahman (ब्रह्म-
भूतो विराजते) 13. 26. 41.

कल्माषी
Kalmāṣī f.: Name of a river (identical
with Yamunā ?).
Situated near the Gaṅgā; Drupada, in
search of priests who would agree to officiate at
his sacrifice to obtain a son, while wandering
near Kalmāṣī came across a holy settlement
of the Brāhmaṇas (अभितः सो ऽथ कल्माषीं
गङ्गाकूले परिभ्रमन्।ब्राह्मणावस-
थं पुण्यम् आससाद महीपतिः) 1. 155. 5
(Nī. on Bom. Ed. 1. 167. 5: कल्माषीं कृष्ण-
वर्णां यमुनाम् अभितः … ।कल्माषपाद्-
अस्य कल्माषीम् अभितः समीपे इत्य् अन्ये).

काञ्चनशैल
Kāñcanaśaila m.: Name of a mythical
mountain.
Situated in the west (5. 108. 1-2), near
the coast of the mythical ocean Kāñcanā-
mbuvaha; reaching its foot (?), Surabhi yields
milk 5. 108. 10 (for citation see Kāñcanā-
mbuvaha).

काञ्चनाक्षी
Kāñcanākṣī f.: One of the seven names
of Sarasvatī.
Described as the best of rivers (सरितां
श्रेष्ठा) 9. 37. 18; the sages once assembled
at the Naimiṣa forest to perform a सत्र;
when they thought of Sarasvatī, the river came
to the Naimiṣa forest for the sages and was
called Kāñcanākṣī; the river was revered by
them (नैमिषे काञ्चनाक्षी तु मुनीनां
सत्रयाजिनाम्।आगता सरीतां श्रेष्ठा तत्र
भारत पूजिता) 9. 37. 15-18; the seven
names of Sarasvatī are given in 9. 37. 4.

काञ्चनाम्बुवह
Kāñcanāmbuvaha m.: Name of a my-
thical ocean.
Situated in the west (5. 108. 1-2), near
the mountain Kāñcanaśaila; after reaching its
coast Surabhi pours out milk (अत्र काञ्चन-
शैलस्य काञ्चनाम्बुवहस्य च।उदधेस्
तीरम् आसाद्य सुरभिः क्षरते पयः) 5.
108. 10.

काम
Kāma nt.: Name of a तीर्थ।
Sacred to Rudra (कामाख्यं तत्र
रुद्रस्य तीर्थम्); it was visited by the
divine sages (देवर्षिसेवितम्); by bathing
there one obtained सिद्धि quickly (क्षिप्रम्)
3. 80. 113.

काम्यक
Kāmyaka1 nt.: Name of a lake.
The Vaṅgas, the Kaliṅga kings, the
Tāmraliptas and the Puṇḍrakas gave to Yudhi-
ṣṭhira as tribute elephants, having pole-long
tusks (ईषादन्तान्), who were gold-girdled
(हेमकक्षान्), lotus-coloured (पद्मवर्णान्),
covered with painted cloth (कुथावृतान्), huge
like mountains (शैलाभान्) and always in
rut (नित्यमत्तान्) to gain entry for the Rāja-
sūya sacrifice; these elephants hailed from the
Kāmyaka lake (अभितः काम्यकं सरः)
2. 48. 19-20, 17.

काम्यक
Kāmyaka2 nt.: Name of a forest, and
of the आश्रम of the Pāṇḍavas in this forest
(3. 146. 10-11; 3. 162. 12; 3. 244. 15).
A. Location: It was to the west, some
forests away, of the Yamunā, in the desert
plains on the bank of the Sarasvatī (यमु-
नां च निषेव्य ते।ययुर् वनेनैव वनं
सततं पश्चिमां दिशम्॥ततः सरस्वती-
कूले समेषु मरुधन्वसु।काम्यकं
नाम ददृशुर् वनम्) 3. 6. 2-3 (Nī. on
Bom. Ed. 3. 5. 3: मरुषु निर्जलदेशेषु।
धन्वसु जाङ्गलदेशेषु); ययौ सरस्वती-
तीरे काम्यकं नाम काननम्) 3. 37. 37; a
part of Kurujāṅgala (प्राप्तो ऽस्मि कुरुजाङ्-
गलम्।यद्दृच्छया धर्मराजं दृष्टवान्
काम्यके वने) 3. 11. 11; famed as the ‘head’
of the desert near the lake Tṛṇabindu (काम्-
यकं काननोत्तमम्।मरुभूमेः शिरः
ख्यातम् तृणबिन्दुसरः प्रति) 3. 244. 13;
it took Pāṇḍavas three days and nights to
reach the Kāmyaka forest from Hāstinapura
(इतः प्रयाताः … पाण्डवाः।जग्मुस् त्रिभिर्
अहोरात्रैः काम्यकं नाम तद् वनं)
3. 12. 3.
B. Description: Large forest
(महावन 3. 248. 3; 3. 13. 1 (not named);
3. 253. 2 (not named); (महत्य् अरण्ये)
3. 253. 9; best forest (काननोत्तम) 3. 244.
13; holy (पुण्यम् आश्रमम्) 3. 244. 15;
beautiful (रम्य) 3. 244. 13; prosperous
(ऋद्धिमन्त्) 3. 6. 5; with trees in blossom
(कुसुमितद्रुम) 3. 79. 13; having many
wonders (बह्वाश्चर्य) 3. 79. 13; liked by
ascetics (मुनिजनप्रिय) 3. 6. 3; (आश्र-
मम् तापसायुतम्) 3. 244. 15; resounding
with the sounds of birds (विहगोपघुष्ट)
3. 253. 2; full of many deer (बहुमृग)
3. 244. 13; 3. 248. 1; full of many deer and
birds (बहुमृगद्विज) 3. 6. 4; full of deer
and beasts of prey (मृगव्यालगणानुकीर्ण)
3. 253. 2; desolate (शून्य) 3. 12. 23.
C. Epic events: (1) The Pāṇḍavas lived
there intermittently during the term of exile:
when स्वस्ति was pronounced on the Pāṇḍavas,
they proceeded toward the Kāmyaka forest
for their वनवास 3. 4. 10; when Dhṛtarāṣṭra
blamed Vidura for siding with the Pāṇḍavas
and asked him to leave, if he so desired, he
went to the Kāmyaka anxious to meet the
Pāṇḍavas there 3. 6. 5; later, Saṃjaya went
to the Kāmyaka to bring Vidura back to
Hāstinapura 3. 7. 10; from the Kāmyaka
the Pāṇḍavas proceeded to the holy lake
Dvaitavana (ततस् ते प्रययुः सर्वे …
पुण्यं द्वैतवनं सरः) and entered the
forest of the same name (पुण्यं द्वैत-
वनं रम्यं विविशुर् भरतर्षभाः) 3.
25. 13, 16; 3. 26. 1; 3. 37. 31; from there
they returned to the Kāmyaka under instruc-
tions of Vyāsa; they were followed by learned
Brāmhaṇas; having reached Kāmyaka again
the Pāṇḍavas settled down there with their
counsellors and followers (ततः काम्यकम्
आसाद्य पुनस् ते भरतर्षभाः।न्यविशन्त
महात्मानः सामात्याः सपदानुगाः) 3.
37. 31, 37, 39; even after Arjuna left for the
Śakraloka to acquire divine weapons, the
rest of the Pāṇḍavas continued to live with
Draupadī in the Kāmyaka forest 3. 49. 2;
3. 80. 1; after Arjuna's departure from the
Kāmyaka to acquire divine weapons (3. 79.
1), the Pāṇḍavas felt dejected 3. 79. 4-7;
3. 161. 15; neither Draupadī (3. 79. 12-14),
nor Bhīma (3. 79. 22), nor Nakula (3. 79.
25), nor Sahadeva (3. 79. 29) found the
forest as beautiful as before; the divine sage
Nārada came there to meet them 3. 80. 2;
since the Pāṇḍavas and Draupadī were no
longer properly attentive (अवधानं न
गच्छामः काम्यके 3. 84. 16) and found
no delight in their continued stay in the Kām-
yaka in the absence of Arjuna, Yudhiṣṭhira
asked Dhaumya to suggest to him some other
forest rich in food and fruits 3. 84. 17, 20;
before the Pāṇḍavas left for their तीर्थयात्रा,
they lived in the Kāmyaka for three nights
with the sage Lomaśa 3. 90. 24; when Arjuna
had left the Pāṇḍavas to go to the Indraloka,
Ghaṭotkaca arrived at the Kāmyaka to help
the Pāṇḍavas to proceed to the Gandhamādana
mountain; he remained with them till Arjuna's
return 7. 158. 28 (a reference to 3. 144. 23-27);
Draupadī desired Bhīma to carry the heavenly
सौगन्धिक flower to the Kāmyaka आश्रम,
since she wanted to present it to Yudhiṣṭhira;
she would also take with her other flowers
which Bhīma might collect (हरेर् इदं मे
कामाय काम्यके पुनर् आश्रमे। … तान्य्-
अहं नेतुम् इच्छामि काम्यकं पुनर्
आश्रमम्) 3. 146. 10-11; when Arjuna came
back to the Pāṇḍavas on the Gandhamādana
mountain from the Indraloka in the company
of Indra, the latter advised Yudhiṣṭhira to
return to the hermitage Kāmyaka (स्वस्ति
प्राप्नुहि कौन्तेय काम्यकं पुनर् आश्र-
मम्) 3. 162. 12; on their way back, they
stayed at the Dvaitavana lake on the river
Sarasvatī (3. 174. 21) from where they
reached the holy Kāmyaka आश्रम full of
ascetics (ददृशुः काम्यकं पुण्यम् आश्र-
मं तापसायुतम् 3. 244. 15) and the Kām-
yaka forest where they settled down again
3. 179. 18; (काम्यकं प्राप्य कौन्तेयाः
 … निषेदुः सह कृष्णया) 3. 180. 1; a
certain Brāhmaṇa, friend of Arjuna, told the
Pāṇḍavas that Kṛṣṇa and the sage Mārkaṇ-
ḍeya would come there to visit them 3. 180.
3-6, 39; while the Pāṇḍavas were in the
Kāmyaka forest (not named) they completed
eleven years of their exile (वने निवसतां
तेषां … वर्षान्य् एकादशातीयुः) 3. 245. 1;
the Pāṇḍavas lived delightfully in the Kām-
yaka which was full of deer 3. 248. 1; Vār-
dhakṣatri (Jayadratha), the king of the
Sindhus, on his way to the Śālveyas, happened
to pass through the Kāmyaka 3. 248. 6-7;
when Draupadī was being forcibly carried
away by Jayadratha she was confident that
she would return to the Kāmyaka to meet her
husbands 3. 252. 21; the Pāṇḍavas conti-
nued to live in the Kāmyaka after the Jaya-
dratha episode 3. 256. 30; it was here that
the sage Mārkaṇḍeya narrated to the Pāṇḍa-
vas the story of Rāma and of Sāvitrī 3. 283.
16; at the end of the twelfth year (द्वादशे
ऽब्दे व्यतीते 3. 294. 41), the Pāṇḍavas, to-
gether with the Brāhmaṇas, once again went
to the Dvaitavana from the Kāmyaka forest
3. 294. 42-43; 3. 295. 2-3; (2) The Bhojas,
the Vṛṣṇis and the Andhakas, and many others,
under the leadership of Vāsudeva, had gone
to the Kāmyaka to meet the Pāṇḍavas 3. 13.
1-4; (3) A demon, Kirmīra by name and
brother of Baka, lived there 3. 12. 22; the
forest was always avoided from a distance by
ascetics and other forest-dwellers due to the
fear of man-eating demons (पुरुषादभयात्
किल) 3. 12. 4-5.
D. Similies: (1) When
Arjuna left, the (Kāmyaka) forest was to
the Pāṇḍavas like the Caitraratha वन in
the absence of Kubera 3. 79. 6; (2) The
Pāṇḍavas entered the Kāmyaka as do the
righteous the heaven 3. 244. 16; (3) When
Draupadī was abducted, Yudhiṣṭhira, noticing
certain omens, said that the Kāmyaka appear-
ed to him like a lake from where serpents had
been taken away, a kingdom without prospe-
rity in the absence of a king, or (an empty)
jar from which wine had been drunk by drun-
kards (सरः सुपर्णेन हृतोरगं यथा
राष्ट्रं यथाराजकम् आत्तलक्ष्मि।एवं-
विधं मे प्रतिभाति काम्यकं शौण्डैर्
यथा पीतरसश् च कुम्भः॥) 3. 253. 5.

कायशोधन
Kāyaśodhana nt.: Name of a तीर्थ।
By bathing there one's body was without
doubt purified (शरीरशुद्धिः स्नातस्य तस्-
मिंस् तीर्थे न संतयः) 3. 81. 35 (which
justifies the name of the तीर्थ).

कारंधम
Kāraṃdhama nt.: Name of a तीर्थ।
Described as serene (प्रसन्न) 1. 208.
3; one of the five तीर्थस् on the southern
ocean (समुद्रे तीर्थानि दक्षिणे) 1. 208.
1, 3; they were formerly thronged by ascetics
but later avoided by them due to the presence
of crocodiles there 1. 208. 2, 4-6; by bathing
there one obtained the fruit of an Aśvamedha
1. 208. 3. [See Nārītīrtha]

कारपचन
Kārapacana nt.: Name of a तीर्थ।
Described as best (उत्तम) and the most
excellent तीर्थ (तीर्थप्रवर) 9. 53. 11;
Balarāmā took bath in its cold water and
gave gifts 9. 53. 12; from there he went to
the आश्रम of Mitra and Varuṇa on the
Yamunā 9. 53. 12-13.

कारापतन
Kārāpatana nt.: Name of a तीर्थ।
Described as the best (उत्तम) 3. 82. 2;
(by bathing there) one got the fruit of an
Agniṣṭoma and went (after death) to the
world of the Munis (मुनिलोकं च गच्छति)
3. 82. 2.

कार्तिकेयस्य
Kārtikeyasya tīrtham nt.: See Pṛthū-
daka.

कालकूट
Kālakūṭa m.: Name of a mountain.
Kṛṣṇa, Arjuna and Bhīma, while pro-
ceeding to the Magadha country from the
Kuru country, crossed the Kālakūṭa 2. 18. 26;
the Kālakūṭa mountain is mentioned among the
places overrun by the army of the Kauravas
as there was not enough room for it in the
Hāstinapura 5. 19. 28, 30.

कालञ्जर|कालंजर
Kālaṃjara m.: Name of a mountain.
A. Description: Famous in the world
(लोकविश्रुत) 3. 83. 53;
B. तीर्थस् and
आश्रमस् on the mountain: (1) There was
the holy lake Devahrada on this mountain;
by bathing in it one got the fruit of giving
the gift of a thousand cows 3. 83. 53; there
was also the holy lake Ṣaṣṭihrada; the gift
given after bathing in this lake was equalled
by no other gift (दानं नान्यद् विशिष्यते)
13. 26. 34; (2) On this mountain there
was the excellent आश्रम of Agastya known
as Hiraṇyabindu (अगस्त्यस्य च राजेन्द्र
तत्राश्रमवरो महान्।हिरण्यबिन्दुः
कथितो गिरौ कालंजरे नृप) 3. 85. 15.
C. Importance: One who controls one's self
on this mountain is glorified in the heaven
(आत्मानं साधयेत् तत्र गिरौ कालं-
जरे नृप।स्वर्गलोके महीयेत नरो नास्त्य्
अत्र संशयः॥) 3. 83. 54.
D. Simile:
When one gave up all desires and fixed his
mind in the सत्त्व quality, one became (like)
the mountain Kālaṃjara 12. 238. 9 (Nī. on
Bom. Ed. 12. 246. 9: सत्त्वे सूक्ष्मायां
बुद्धौ चित्तं स्थूलबुद्धिं।कालञ्जर-
पर्वतवद् अप्रकम्प्यो भवेत्।कालं
क्षणमुहूर्तादिरूपम् जरयति नाशयति
तथा आत्मविद् एव कालं नाशयति न तु तं
काल इत्य् अर्थः).

कालतीर्थ
Kālatīrtha nt.: Name of a तीर्थ।
Situated near the city Kośalā; by bath-
ing there (उपस्पृश्य) one got without doubt
the fruit of letting loose eleven bulls (वृष-
भैकादशफलं लभते नात्र संशयः)
3. 83. 11.

कालपर्वत
Kālaparvata1 m.: Name of a mountain.
Situated in the Laṅkā; Rāvaṇa crossed
Trikūṭa and Kālaparvata before he reached
the ocean 3. 261. 53.

कालपर्वत
Kālaparvata2 m.: Name of a mountain,
also called Kālaśaila.
Situated in the north; described as having
the form of a heap of glistening collyrium
(स्निग्धाञ्जनचयाकार); Arjuna crossed it
before reaching the foot of the Himālayas
7. 57. 27, 23; Lomaśa pointed out to the
Pāṇḍavas that they had crossed Kālaśaila
and were about to reach the Śvetagiri 3.
140. 1, 4.

कालशैल
Kālaśaila m.: See Kālaparvata2.

कालाम्र
Kālāmra m.: Name of a tree.
Situated to the east of Meru 6. 8. 12;
described as tall (महाद्रुम) 6. 8. 13;
auspicious (शुभ) and having flowers and
fruit all the time (नित्यपुष्पफल) 6. 8.
14; by drinking the juice of the Kālāmra
fruit the people of that Dvīpa (Kālāmra ?)
stay ever young (कालाम्ररसपीतास् ते नित्यं
संस्थितयौवनाः) 6. 8. 17.

कालिकासङ्गम|कालिकासंगम
Kālikāsaṃgama m.: Name of a con-
fluence.
A self-controlled (यतः) wise man
(विद्वान्), having bathed at this confluence
of the rivers Kauśikī and Aruṇā (text has
Āruṇā म्। च्। ? कालिकासंगमे स्नात्वा कौ-
शिक्यारणयोः) and having fasted for three
nights, becomes freed of all sins 3. 82. 135.

कालिन्दी
Kālindī f.: Another name of the river
Yamunā.
The Pāṇḍavas, at the end of their वन-
वास, and before proceeding to the Virāṭa-
nagara, first went along the southern bank
of the river Kālindī (कालिन्दीम् अभितो ययुः।
ततस् ते दक्षिणं तीरम् अन्वगच्छन् पदा-
तयः) 4. 5. 1-2; Kālindī, in bodily form,
along with many other rivers wait upon god
Varuṇa in his सभा 2. 9. 18. [See Yamunā]

कालोद
Kāloda nt.: Name of a तीर्थ।
Śaunaka recommends it, among many
others, to king Janamejaya; by visiting the
तीर्थ one would again live long in this life
(? लब्धायुर्जीविते पुनः) 12. 148. 11.

कावेरका
Kāverakā f.: Name of a river.
One of the rivers in the Śākadvīpa 6. 12.
30, 26; its water is holy (नद्यः पुण्यजलास्
तत्र) 6. 12. 29.

कावेरी
Kāverī f.: Name of a river.
Listed by Saṃjaya among the rivers of
the Bhāratavarṣa; its water used by people
for drinking 6. 10. 19, 13; all the rivers
listed here are described as mothers of the
universe and very strong (विश्वस्य मातरः
सर्वाः सर्वाश् चैव महाबलाः) 6. 10. 35;
favourite river of the Apsarases (वृताम् अप्स-
रसां गणैः) 3. 83. 20; by bathing there
one obtained the fruit of gifting a thousand
cows 3. 83. 20; listed by Mārkaṇḍeya among
the rivers which are famous as the mothers of
the fire-hearths (i. e. sacrifices were performed
on the banks of these rivers; for Nī. on Bom.
Ed. 3. 222. 27 see Kapilā; एता नद्यस् तु
धिष्ण्यानां मातरो याः प्रकीर्तिताः) 3.
212. 24; finds place in the Daivata-Ṛṣi-Vaṃśa
13. 151. 17, 2.

काष्ठवत्|काष्ठवन्त्
Kāṣṭhavant m.: Name of a mountain.
One of the mountains described as kings
of mountains (एते पर्वतराजानः); listed
by Brahman for the information of the sages
Bṛhaspati and others (14. 35. 15-16) among
the principal mountains 14. 43. 4-5; (These
mountains also are to be looked upon as
having the मध्यम गुण (i. e. the quality
रजस्) ? 14. 43. 1 (Nī. on Bom. Ed. 14. 43.
1: मध्यमो गुणः रजोगुणप्रधानः).

किङ्कीणिकाश्रम
Kiṅkīṇikāśrama m.: Name of a तीर्थ।
By bathing there one is able to go any-
where at will and is glorified in the heavenly
abode of the Apsarases (निवासे ऽप्सरसां
दिव्ये कामचारी महीयते) 13. 26. 21.

किंजप्य
Kiṃjapya nt.: Name of a तीर्थ।
By bathing there (the merit of one's)
prayers becomes unlimited (अप्रमेयम् अवा-
प्नोति … जप्यं) 3. 81. 65 (this explains the
name of the तीर्थ). [See Kiṃdāna]

किंदत्त
Kiṃdatta m.: Name of a sacred well
(कूप).
Having visited the well and having offered
a प्रस्थ of sesame seeds, one is freed of
debts and attains the greatest perfection
(तिलप्रस्थं प्रदाय च।गच्छेत पर-
मां सिद्धिम् ऋणैर् मुक्तः) 3. 81. 83.

किंदान
Kiṃdāna nt.: Name of a तीर्थ।
Having bathed there one's gifts become
unlimited (अप्रमेयम् अवाप्नोति दानं) 3.
81. 65 (this explains the name of the तीर्थ).
[See Kiṃjapya]

कुक्षिमन्त्
Kukṣimant m.: Name of a mountain.
Situated near the country (?) Unnāṭa;
conquered by Bhīma in his expedition before
the Rājasūya (उन्नाटम् अभितो जिग्ये कुक्षि-
मन्तं च पर्वतम्) 2. 27. 5.

कुचरा
Kucarā f.: Name of a river.
Listed by Saṃjaya among the rivers of
the Bhāratavarṣa; its water used by people
for drinking 6. 10. 26, 13; all the rivers listed
here are said to be mothers of the universe
and very strong (for citation see Atikṛṣṇā)
6. 10. 35.

कुण्डला
Kuṇḍalā f.: Name of a river.
Described as holy (पवित्रा) 6. 10. 20;
listed by Saṃjaya among the rivers of the
Bhāratavarṣa; its water used by people for
drinking 6. 10. 20, 13; all the rivers listed
here are said to be mothers of the universe
and very strong (for citation see Atikṛṣṇā)
6. 10. 35.

कुण्डोद
Kuṇḍoda m.: Name of a mountain.
Pleasing (रम्य); having many roots,
fruits and water (बहुमूलफलोदक) 3.
85. 20; thirsty Nala got water and happiness
there (नैषधस् तृषितो यत्र जलं शर्म
च लब्धवान्) 3. 85. 20 (Nī. on Bom. Ed.
3. 87. 26 gives the following information:
नैषधो नलः तत्रैव लोलार्कदक्षिणे
नलग्रामस्य दर्शनात्).

कुबेरनलिनी
Kuberanalinī f.: Name (?) of Kubera's
pond.
Situated on the Gandhamādana mountain
3. 142. 22; pleasing (रम्या) and guarded
by demons (राक्षसैर् अभिरक्षिताम्); the
Pāṇḍavas desired to go there on foot (पद्-
भिर् एव गमिष्यामः) to meet Arjuna 3.
142. 24.

कुब्जाम्रक
Kubjāmraka nt.: Name of a तीर्थ।
A pilgrim (तीर्थसेवी), by visiting this
तीर्थ, obtains the fruit of giving a thousand
cows and goes to the heaven 3. 82. 36.

कुमारकोटि
Kumārakoṭi f.: Name of a तीर्थ।
One who is controlled (नियत) should
bathe in this तीर्थ and offer worship to manes
and gods (पितृदेवार्चने रतः); he thereby
obtains the fruit of performing a Gavāmayana
sacrifice and lifts up his family 3. 80. 123.

कुमारधारा
Kumāradhārā f.: Name of a river.
A. Source: Flows from the lake Pitā-
mahasaras situated on the Śailarāja (Hima-
vant) 3. 82. 128-129.
B. Description:
Purifying the worlds (लोकपावनी); famous
in the three worlds (त्रिषु लोकेषु विश्रुता)
3. 82. 129.
C. Importance: Bathing
there one feels to have achieved the purpose
of one's life (यत्र स्नात्वा कृतार्थो ऽस्मीत्य्
आत्मानम् अवगच्छति) 3. 82. 130; by eating
there only the sixth meal in three days one
is freed from the sin of killing a Brāhmaṇa
(षष्ठकालोपवासेन मुच्यते ब्रह्मह-
त्यया) 3. 82. 130.

कुमारिकाणां
Kumārikāṇāṃ tīrtham nt.: Name of
a तीर्थ।
One can reach there after visiting Bra-
hmatuṅga 3. 80. 97; sacred to Śakra (Indra)
(शक्रस्य), it is frequented by the Siddhas
(सिद्धनिसेवित); by bathing there one quickly
attains the world of Śakra 3. 80. 97; (Identical
with the next (?) which is situated in the
south). [See Kumārī1]

कुमारी
Kumārī1 f. (pl.): Name of a तीर्थ।
A. Location: Situated in the Pāṇḍya
country 3. 86. 11.
B. Description: They
are famous for their holiness (कुमार्यः
कथिताः पुण्याः) 3. 86. 11.
C. Import-
ance: One who bathes in Kokāmukha, visits
Caṇḍālikāśrama and observes other व्रतस्
gets the merit of having bathed in the Kumārī
तीर्थ ten times (?) (कुमारीर् विन्दते दश)
13. 26. 49. [See Kumārikāṇāṃ tīrtham]

कुमारी
Kumārī2 f.: Name of a river.
Listed by Saṃjaya among the rivers of
the Bhāratavarṣa; its water used by people
for drinking 6. 10. 34, 13; all these rivers are
said to be mothers of the universe and very
strong (for citation see Atikṛṣṇā) 6. 10. 35.

कुमारी
Kumārī3 f.: Name of a river.
One of the rivers of the Śākadvīpa;
water of these rivers is holy (नद्यः पुण्य-
जलास् तत्र) 6. 12, 30, 29, 26.

कुमुद
Kumuda m.: Name of a mountain.
One of the six mountains of the Kuśa-
dvīpa; the mountain is, indeed, lustrous
(? द्युतिमान् नाम; or is Dyutimant another
name of the mountain Kumuda ?) all the six
mountains are described as excellent moun-
tains (पर्वतोत्तमाः); the distance between
them doubles as one moves from the one to
the other (तेषाम् अन्तरविष्कम्भो द्विगुणः
प्रविभागशः) 6. 13. 10-11.

कुरुक्षेत्र
Kurukṣetra nt.: Name of a तीर्थ।
A. Description: Holy (पुण्यम् आहुः
कुरुक्षेत्रम्) 3. 81. 125; (पुण्य) 3. 81.
177; 12. 148. 10; very holy (महापुण्य)
3. 81. 4; full of holy तीर्थस् (पुण्यतीर्थैश्
च कलिलम्) 13. 151. 19; praised (अभिष्टुत)
3. 81. 1; resorted to by brahmanical sages
(ब्रह्मर्षिसेवित) 3. 81. 177; called ब्रह्-
मक्षेत्र 3. 81. 4; altar of Brahman (ब्र-
ह्मवेदी) 3. 81. 177.
B. Importance:
(1) Kurukṣetra is distinguished in all the
three worlds (त्रयाणाम् अपि लोकानां कुरु-
क्षेत्रं विशिष्यते) 3. 81. 173; (2) Brah-
man and other gods, the sages, the Siddhas,
the Cāraṇas, the Gandharvas and the Apsa-
rases, the Yakṣas and the mythical serpents
(Uragas) visit Kurukṣetra 3. 81. 3-4; (3)
Pulastya told Bhīṣma that one should live at
Kurukṣetra for a month 3. 81. 3; those who
live in Kurukṣetra are not reduced to a
lamentable condition in any way (न ते
शोच्याः कथंचन) 3. 81. 177; all crea-
tures who repair there are released from
their sins 3. 81. 1; one who always simply
says, ‘I shall visit Kurukṣetra, I shall live
in Kurukṣetra’ (कुरुक्षेत्रं गमिष्यामि
कुरुक्षेत्रे वसाम्य् अहम्), even he is freed
of all sins 3. 81. 2; one who says this
just once is freed of all sins (अप्य् एकां
वाचम् उत्सृज्य सर्वपापैः प्रमुच्यते) 3.
81. 176; one who mentally longs (मनसाप्य्
अभिकामस्य) for Kurukṣetra, his sins are
destroyed and he goes to the world of Brah-
man 3. 81. 5; one who visits Kurukṣetra
with faith (श्रद्धया) obtains the fruit
of an Aśvamedha and a Vājapeya 3. 81. 6;
if one bathes in Kurukṣetra or drinks its
water he will never (?) have an occasion to
repent a premature death (यत्रावगाह्य
पीत्वा वा नैवं श्वोमरणं तपेत्) 12.
148. 10; (4) There are many holy places
in the vicinity of Kurukṣetra 3. 81. 8-20; a
pilgrim (तीर्थसेवी) should make a round of
these holy places (प्रदक्षिणम् उपावृत्य)
3. 81. 20; the तीर्थ is mentioned in the
Daivata-Ṛṣi-Vaṃśa 13. 151. 19, 2. [See
Samantapañcaka and Kurukṣetra in 1. 5 A]

कुरुक्षेत्रस्य
Kurukṣetrasya dvāram nt.: Gate or
entrance of the Kurukṣetra.
Among the holy places near about Kuru-
kṣetra, the place where the world-famous
Yakṣī stands is known as the Gate of Kuru-
kṣetra (तत्रैव च महाराज यक्षी लोक-
परिश्रुता। … कुरुक्षेत्रस्य तद् द्वारं
विश्रुतं भरतर्षभ) 3. 81. 19-20.

कुरुतीर्थ
Kurutīrtha nt.: Name of a तीर्थ।
Situated to the east of the Aujasa तीर्थ;
by bathing there, one who observes chastity
and has controlled his senses (ब्रह्मचारी
जितेन्द्रियः) is cleansed of all sins and obtains
Kuruloka (the world obtained by the Kurus ?)
(कुरुलोकं प्रपद्यते; v. l. ब्रह्म-,
रुद्र-, देव- for कुरु-) 3. 81. 144.

कुलंपुन
Kulaṃpuna nt.: Name of a तीर्थ।
By bathing there one purifies one's family
(पुनाति स्वकुलं नरः) 3. 81. 88 (this
explains the name of the तीर्थ).

कुल्या
Kulyā f.: Name of a river.
By bathing there, by repeating the अघ-
मर्षण prayer (ṚV. 10. 190) and by fast-
ing for three nights a person becomes pure
(शुचिः) and gets the fruit of an Aśvamedha
13. 26. 53.

कुशधारा
Kuśadhārā f.: Name of a river.
Described as a great river (महानदी);
listed by Saṃjaya among the rivers of the
Bhāratavarṣa; its water used by people for
drinking 6, 10. 23, 13; all the rivers listed
here are called mothers of the universe and
very strong (for citation see Atikṛṣṇā).

कुशप्लवन
Kuśaplavana nt.: Name of a तीर्थ।
One who practises chastity and is com-
posed (ब्रह्मचारी समाहितः), if he bathes
in this तीर्थ and lives there for three nights,
he gets the reward of an Aśvamedha 3. 83. 33.

कुशवत्|कुशवन्त्
Kuśavant m.: Name (?) of a lake.
On the mountain Himavant there is the
lake Kuśavant (or a lake full of कुश grass ?)
(ह्रदश् च कुशवान् एषः) where are found
lotuses of the water-lily type (यत्र पद्मं
कुशेशयम्) 3. 130. 15.

कुशस्तम्ब
Kuśastamba m.: Name of a तीर्थ।
One who bathes there is waited upon by
a host of Apsarases 13. 26. 26.

कुशावर्त
Kuśāvarta m.: Name of a तीर्थ।
By bathing there one's sins are destroyed
and one goes to heaven 13. 26. 12 (Accord-
ing to Nī. on Bom. Ed. 13. 25. 13 the तीर्थस्
listed in the stanza are the ones on the river
Godāvarī on the Brahmagiri; for his remark
see Gaṅgādvāra).

कुशेशय
Kuśeśaya1 nt.: Name of a तीर्थ।
If a person, having controlled his mind,
does obeisance to Kuśeśaya and bathes there
his sin is cleansed and he (obtains ?) god-
hood (विक्षोभ्य प्रयतश् चाभिवाद्य तम्।
कुशेशयं च देवत्वं पूयते तस्य किल्-
बिषम्॥) 13. 26. 10.

कुशेशय
Kuśeśaya2 m.: Name of a mountain.
Name of the fifth among the six moun-
tains in the Kuśadvīpa 6. 13. 10, 6, 9; all
these mountains are said to be excellent
(पर्वतोत्तमाः); the distance between them
doubles as one moves from one to the other
(तेषाम् अन्तरविष्कम्भो द्विगुणः प्रवि-
भागशः) 6. 13. 11.

कूप
Kūpa1 m.: A sacred well, not named,
in the Gaṅgā.
Situated near the Gaṅgāhrada; there are
three crores of तीर्थस् in that well (तिस्रः
कोट्यस् तु तीर्थानां तस्मिन् कूपे); by
bathing there one goes to heaven 3. 81. 153.
[See Udapāna and Kūpa2]

कूप
Kūpa2 m.: A sacred well, not named.
It is near the sacred place called Jyeṣṭha-
sthāna 3. 83. 59-60; described as famous
(विश्रुत) 3. 83. 60; all the four oceans are
present in this Kūpa; by bathing there
(उपस्पृश्य) and by circumambulating it
(कृत्वा चापि प्रदक्षिणम्), a person who has
controlled his self (नियतात्मा) is purified
and acquires the highest state (after death)
(परमां गतिम्) 3. 83. 61. [See Udapāna
and Kūpa1]

कृतशौच
Kṛtaśauca nt.: Name of a तीर्थ।
A pilgrim (तीर्थसेवी), by reaching this
तीर्थ, will have purified himself (कृतशौचो
भवेन् नरः—which explains the name of
the तीर्थ); he will also obtain the fruit of
a Puṇḍarīka sacrifice 3. 81. 17.

कृत्तिकाङ्गारक
Kṛttikāṅgāraka nt.: Name of a तीर्थ
(? or of the conjunction of Kṛttikā and Aṅgā-
raka).
By bathing at this तीर्थ and by fasting
there for a fortnight one is purified and goes to
heaven (महागङ्गाम् उपस्पृश्य कृत्तिकाङ्-
गारके तथा) 13. 26. 20.

कृत्तिकामघयोस्
Kṛttikāmaghayos tīrtham nt.: Name
of a तीर्थ।
By visiting this तीर्थ, one gets the fruit
of an Agniṣṭoma and an Atirātra sacrifice
3. 82. 46.

कृत्या
Kṛtyā f.: Name of a river.
Listed by Saṃjaya among the rivers of
the Bhāratavarṣa; its water used for drinking
by people 6. 10. 17, 13; all the rivers listed
here are called mothers of the universe and
very strong 6. 10. 35 (for citation see Ati-
kṛṣṇā).

कृष्ण
Kṛṣṇa m.: Name of a mountain.
Situated in the west in the Madhyama
Dvīpa, it looks like Nārāyaṇa (पर्वतः
पश्चिमः कृष्णो नारायणनिभो नृप) 6.
13. 4; there Keśava himself stands guard to
all heavenly jewels; sitting near Prajāpati
he gave happiness to creatures (प्रजापतिम्
उपासीनः प्रजानां विदधे सुखम्) 6.
13. 5.

कृष्णवेण्णा
Kṛṣṇaveṇṇā, Kṛṣṇaveṇā f.: Name of a
river.
The holy lake Devahrada is formed in
the Kṛṣṇaveṇṇā (देवह्रदे रम्ये कृष्ण-
वेण्णाजलोद्भवे) 3. 83. 34; the sage Mār-
kaṇḍeya, while moving in the belly of the
Bāla (3. 186. 83 i. e. Nārāyaṇa 3. 187. 3),
saw, among other rivers, Kṛṣṇaveṇā 3. 186.
95; listed by Saṃjaya among the rivers of the
Bhāratavarṣa (twice, once as Kṛṣṇaveṇā and
again as Kṛṣṇaveṇṇā) 6. 10. 15 (निम्नगा),
27; its water used by people for drinking 6.
10. 13; all the rivers listed here are called
mothers of the universe and very strong 6.
10. 35 (for citation see Atikṛṣṇā); men-
tioned among the rivers who, along with
other watery places, in bodily form (देह-
वन्तः 2. 9. 21), wait upod god Varuṇa in
his Sabhā 2. 9. 17, 20; listed by Mārkaṇḍeya
among the rivers which are known as mothers
of the fire-hearths (एता नद्यस् तु धिष्ण्याणां
मातरो याः प्रकीर्तिताः) 3. 212. 24 (i. e.
Soma sacrifices were performed on their
banks; for Nī.'s remark on Bom. Ed. 3. 222.
27 see Kapilā above); finds mention in the
Daivata-Ṛṣi-Vaṃśa 13. 151. 17 (अद्रिजा), 2.

कृष्णा
Kṛṣṇā f.: Name of a river.
Listed by Mārkaṇḍeya among the rivers
which are famous as mothers of the sacrificial
hearths i. e. on the banks of which Soma
sacrifices were performed (धिष्ण्यानां मा-
तरो याः प्रकीर्तिताः) 3. 212. 24 (for Nī.
comm. on Bom. Ed. 3. 222. 27 see Kapilā
above).

केतुमाला
Ketumālā f.: Name of a river.
Mentioned by Dhaumya among the holy
and purifying places of the west 3. 87. 12, 1
(यानि तत्र पवित्राणि पुण्यान्य् आयतनानि
च); described as most holy (पुण्यतमा),
always frequented by ascetics (सततं ताप-
सायुता) 3. 87. 12.

केसर
Kesara, Kesarin m.: Name of a moun-
tain.
It is the seventh of the seven mountains
of the Śākadvīpa 6. 12. 21, 13; the distance
in योजनस् between these mountains doubles
as one moves from one to the other (तेषां
योजनविष्कम्भो द्विगुणः प्रविभागशः)
6. 12. 22; the wind blowing from it is laden
with filaments of flowers (केसरयुतो यतो
वातः प्रवायति) 6. 12. 21 (which explains
the name of the mountain); the Modākin
Varṣa belongs to the mountain Kesara (केस-
रस्य तु मोदाकी) 6. 12. 24.

कैरात
Kairāta adj.: Of the highest place on
the mountain Himavant (where Śiva lives).
The place Kairāta, described as the high-
est (कैरातम् स्थानम् उत्तमम्) on the
mountain Himavant (13. 20. 29), lies beyond
the mountains Kailāsa, Mandara and Haima
13. 20. 28-29; Aṣṭāvakra went north to reach
this mountain and after descending from it he
went round it thrice bowing down his head;
he then became a person of cleansed soul;
from there he again proceeded northwards
(प्रदक्षिणं ततश् चक्रे प्रयतः शिरसा
नमन्।धरणीम् अवतीर्याथ पूतात्मासौ
तदाभवत्॥स तं प्रदक्षिणं कृत्वा
त्रिः शैलम् चोत्तरामुखः। … ययौ) 13.
20. 28-30.

कैलास
Kailāsa m.: Name of a mountain, once
identified with Hemakūṭa (6. 7. 39).
A. Situation: Situated in the north 3.
145. 15; part of Himavant 13. 20. 2, 6; 5.
109. 1, 8; 2. 48. 6; beyond the Uttara Kurus
3. 145. 15; mountain Maināka lay to its
north 2. 3. 2, 8; 6. 7. 40.
B. Extent: It
is six hundred योजनस् in extent (कैलासः
पर्वतो राजन् षड् योजनशतान्य् उत) 3.
140. 10.
C. Description: Very big (सु-
महन्त्) 6. 7. 40; (महागिरि) 14. 76. 16;
(महाशैल) 13. 20. 29; excellent, best
mountain (पर्वतश्रेष्ठ) 3. 108. 15; (पर्-
वतोत्तम) 3. 145. 15; has splendid forests
(शुभकानन) 3. 151. 1; shining with clouds
(? वारिधरप्रकाश) 3. 174. 2; loved by
Kubera (कुबेरकान्त) 3. 174. 2; of unima-
ginable form (अचिन्त्यरूप) 3. 174. 6; having
various wonders (विविधाश्चर्य) 3. 145. 15;
having many caves (बहुकन्दर) 3. 141.
15; its peaks are lovely (रम्य) 3. 151. 1;
13. 82. 27; visited by gods and Gandharvas
(देवगन्धर्वसेवित) 13. 82. 27; most in
accessible (दुर्गतम) 3. 140. 15; (दुर्-
गम) 3. 140. 8, 10; (दुर्गेषु विषमेषु)
3. 141. 11; one cannot reach there driving in
chariots (अशक्यो रथैर् गन्तुम्) 3. 141.
15; there were invisible and strong Bhūtas
and Rākṣasas and hence one could reach there
with the help of fire (by worshipping fire ?)
and by practising austerities (अन्तर्हितानि
भूतानि रक्षांसि बलवन्ति च।अग्निना
तपसा चैव शक्यं गन्तुं वृकोदर)
3. 141. 1; house of powerful herbs 2.
48. 6 (see D (1) (ii) below); Kailāsa and
other mountains described 3. 140. 4-11; 3.
141. 11.
D. Events: (1) Epic: (i)
Since the mountain was not easy to reach,
Yudhiṣṭhira suggested that all, except him-
self, Lomaśa and Nakula, might return to
Gaṅgādvāra and wait there 3. 141. 1-7;
however, they all proceeded with the help
of Ghaṭotkaca and his Rākṣasas; the
Pāṇḍavas were delighted to see the Kailāsa
on their way to the Śveta and the Gandha-
mādana 3. 145. 15, and again on their return
3. 174. 2; they saw the Kailāsa along with the
Maināka, the Meru, and the slopes of the
Gandhamādana 3. 155. 14; while returning
from the Kailāsa the Pāṇḍavas went to the
आश्रम of Vṛṣaparvan 3. 174. 6; the Kro-
dhavaśa Rākṣasas who were guarding the
Pond of Kubera, when routed by Bhīma, fled
through the sky towards the peaks of Kailāsa
3. 152. 20; while on the Kailāsa, Bhīma had
challenged the friend of Maheśvara (i. e. Ku-
bera) with his mace 9. 10. 48; (ii) Power-
ful herbs from the Kailāsa in the north were
brought as tribute by the Pārvatīyas when
they came to attend the Rājasūya of Yudhi-
ṣṭhira (उत्तराद् अपि कैलासाद् ओषधीः सु-
महाबलाः) 2. 48. 6; (2) Past and My-
thological: (i) King Sagara, with his two
wives, resorted to the Kailāsa for practising
austerities since he desired to have a son 3.
104. 9; (ii) Bhagīratha went to the Kailāsa
and propitiated Śiva 3. 107. 24; (iii) Śiva
went to the Kailāsa after holding Gaṅgā on
his head 3. 108. 15; (iv) Vasiṣṭha brought
Gaṅgā, flowing towards the Kailāsa, to the
(Mānasa 13. 140. 16) lake; the banks of the
lake were shattered by Gaṅgā; 13. 140. 23;
Gaṅgā then became Sarayū (सरो भिन्नं
तया नद्या सरयूः सा ततो ऽभवत्) 13.
140. 24; (v) Divine Surabhi, the daughter
of Dakṣa, practised austerities on the peak
of the Kailāsa 13. 82. 27; (vi) Aṣṭāvakra
moved around the Kailāsa after reaching
the Himavant (कैलासम् अभितो ययौ) 13.
20. 2, 6; when Aṣṭāvakra left the residence
of Kubera he went further north and crossed
the mountains Kailāsa, Mandara and Haima
before reaching the Kairātasthāna 13. 20. 28-
29; (vii) Nahuṣa, as the king of gods
(देवराज 5. 11. 10), enjoyed the company
of the Apsarases and the Devakanyās on the
mountains Kailāsa, Himavatpṛṣṭha, Mandara,
Śveta and others 5. 11. 9; (viii) Bhara-
dvāja asked the great sage Bhṛgu seated on
the peak of the Kailāsa: “Who created the
world ?” 12. 175. 6; (ix) Rising from the
peak of the Kailāsa (कैलासपृष्ठाद् उत्-
पत्य) Śuka, the son of Vyāsa, soared to the
heaven moving through the mid-region (अन्त-
रिक्षचरः) 12. 319. 10.
E. Importance:
(1) Śiva lives on its peak (कैलासशिखरा-
वासिन् is one of the 1000 names of Śiva) 13.
17. 106; (2) Dhanada (Kubera) was conse-
crated on the Kailāsa as the chief of the Rā-
kṣasas, the Yakṣas and the Gandharvas (आधि-
पत्येन कैलासे धनदो ऽप्य् अभिषेचितः)
5. 109. 8; hence Kailāsa is known to be the
residence (स्थानम्) of Ailavila (Kubera)
5. 109. 18; 12. 44. 13; Vaiśravaṇa (Kubera)
is called कैलासनिलय 12. 274. 9; 3. 42. 31
(Dhanādhyakṣa = Kubera); 2. 6. 11 (Ku-
bera); King Vaiśravaṇa (Kubera) enjoys
himself on the Kailāsa in the company of the
Guhyakas 6. 7. 39; there are innumerable
Yakṣas, Rākṣasas, Kinnaras, Nāgas, Suparṇas
and Gandharvas in the residence of Kubera
(कुबेरसदनं प्रति) (on the Kailāsa) 3.
140. 11; there is the beautiful pond (नलिनी),
full of Saugandhika flowers, on the peak of
the Kailāsa near the abode of Kubera 3. 151.
1, 2; (3) Kailāsa visited by gods (यत्र
देवाः समायान्ति) 3. 140. 10; (4) There is
the Viśālā (Badarī) tree there 3. 140. 10 (Nī.
on Bom. Ed. 3. 139. 11: विशाला बदरी; also
cf. विशालां बदरीं प्रति 3. 145. 10, 18);
(5) The आश्रम of Nara and Nārāyaṇa
stands in its vicinity (तस्याभ्याशे) 3. 145.
16.
F. Figures in bad omens: (1)
Among the bad omens noticed by Vyāsa
before the start of the war, there was one
according to which hundreds of summits of
the mountains Kailāsa, Mandara and Hima-
vant fell down with great thunder 6. 3. 35;
(2) When the Sindhu heroes encircled Arjuna
there occurred bad omens one of which was
that the Kailāsa experienced trembling (वे-
पथुश् चाभवन् राजन् कैलासस्य) 14. 76.
16.
G. Similes: (1) Persons: (i) Bala-
rāma who was wearing a blue silk garment
(नीलकौशेयवसनः) is compared with the
summit of the Kailāsa 5. 154. 18; 1. 212. 20;
7. 10. 31; (ii) Bhīmasena with his raised
गदा looked like the Kailāsa with its (raised)
summit (कैलासम् इव शृङ्गिणम्) 6. 58.
30; 6. 90. 22; (iii) Duryodhana with his
raised गदा is similarly compared 9. 32. 36;
9. 55. 27; (iv) Śalya, with the सर्वायसी
गदा in his hand, looked like the Kailāsa with
its (raised) peak (सशृङ्गम् इव कैलासम्)
9. 11. 2; (v) Soma gave to Skanda his
two companions Maṇi and Sumaṇi who both
looked like the peaks of the Kailāsa 9. 44. 29;
(2) Elephant: The white elephant Airāvata
having four tusks looked like the Kailāsa with
its peaks 3. 43. 36; (3) Objects: (i) Chariot:
Kṛṣṇa's chariot compared with the peak of the
Kailāsa (कैलासशिखरोपमात्) 5. 92. 30;
(ii) Structures: (a) The सभा of Kubera,
a hundred योजनस् long and seventy योजनस्
wide, was comparable with the Kailāsaśikhara
2. 10. 2; (b) Sahadeva having received the
excellent residence (वेश्माग्र्यम् 12. 44. 12)
of Durmukha was delighted as was Dhanada
(Kubera) when he received the Kailāsa 12.
44. 13; (c) The arena of Draupadī's स्व-
यंवर was adorned with palatial buildings
which looked like the peaks of the Kailāsa
(कैलासशिखरप्रख्यैः) 1. 176. 19; (d)
The dwelling places (आवसथान्) created
for the kings who attended the Rājasūya
looked like the Kailāsa peaks 2. 31. 19-20;
(e) The Pāṇḍavas entered their residence at
the Vāraṇāvata as the Guhyakas the Kailāsa
1. 134. 12.

कोका
Kokā f.: Name of a river.
Listed by Saṃjaya among the rivers of
the Bhāratavarṣa; its water used by people for
drinking 6. 10. 33, 13; all the rivers listed
here are described as mothers of the universe
and very strong (for citation see Atikṛṣṇā).

कोकामुख
Kokāmukha nt.: Name of a तीर्थ।
Situated near the Caṇḍālikāśrama 13.
26. 49; described as holy (पुण्य) 3. 82.
137; if one who observes chastity and has
observed vows (ब्रह्मचारी यतव्रतः)
bathes there, he remembers his past lives—
this is known from an ancient text (?) (जाति-
स्मरत्वं प्राप्नोति दृष्टम् एतत् पुरातने)
3. 82. 137; if one who lives on vegetables
and puts on bark garments (शाकभक्षश्
चीरवासाः) bathes in the Kokāmukha he
obtains the merit of bathing ten times in the
Kumārītīrtha (?) (कुमारीर् विन्दते दश)
13. 26. 49 (Nī. on Bom. Ed. 13. 25. 52:
कुमारीः कुमारीसंज्ञकं तीर्थम्).

कोटितीर्थ
Koṭitīrtha1 nt.: Name of a तीर्थ।
Located near Mahākāla (in Ujjayinī ?);
one who is restrained and eats limited food
(नियतो नियताशनः) obtains by bathing
there (उपस्पृश्य) the fruit of a horse sacri-
fice 3. 80. 68. [See Tīrthakoṭi]

कोटितीर्थ
Koṭitīrtha2 nt.: Name of a तीर्थ।
Near the Pañcanada; one who is restrain-
ed and eats limited food obtains hy bathing
there (उपस्पृश्य) the fruit of a horse sacri-
fice 3. 81. 14. [See Tīrthakoṭi]

कोटितीर्थ
Koṭitīrtha3 nt.: Name of a तीर्थ।
Near the Gaṅgādvāra 3. 82. 23; one who
is composed gets by bathing there (तत्रा-
भिषेकं कुर्वीत) the fruit of a Puṇḍarīka
sacrifice and lifts up his family (कुलं चैव
समुद्धरेत्) 3. 82. 24. [See Tīrthakoṭi]

कोटितीर्थ
Koṭitīrtha4 nt.: Name of a तीर्थ।
Near the Bhartṛsthāna, a place sacred to
Mahāsena (Skanda) 3. 82. 68; 3. 83. 57;
by bathing there and by worshipping Guha
(Skanda) one gets the fruit of giving a
thousand cows and is full of splendour
(तेजस्वी) 3. 82. 68; 3. 83. 57. [See Tīrtha-
koṭi]

कोटिरूप
Koṭirūpa nt.: Name of a तीर्थ।
Situated in the vicinity of the Gaṅgā-
hrada (गङ्गाह्रदश् च तत्रैव) 3. 81.
172; by bathing there (उपस्पृश्य) one gets
much gold (लभेद् बहु सुवर्णकम्) 3.
81. 171.

कोलाहल
Kolāhala m.: Name of a mountain.
Described as having consciousness (चे-
तनायुक्त) 1. 57. 32; due to his love
(कामात्) for the river Śuktimatī, flowing by
his side, the mountain blocked her course; then
king Vasu struck the mountain with his foot;
the stroke produced a hole in the mountain
through which the blocked river began to
flow again; the mountain begot a pair - a
male and a female - on the river; the river,
happy to get past the mountain, informed
the king about the birth of two children 1.
57. 32-34.

कोल्लगिरि
Kollagiri m.: Name of a mountain.
Sahadeva in his expedition to the south
before the Rājasūya brought under control
the region of the entire Kollagiri (कृत्स्नं
कोल्लगिरिं चैव … वशे चक्रे महामतिः)
2. 28. 45-46.

कोशेश्वरस्य
Kośeśvarasya tīrthāni nt. (pl.): Name
of a number of तीर्थस् (sacred to Kubera ?)
Near the place Ambuvaśya; by bathing
there (कोशेश्वरस्य तीर्थेषु) one is freed
of all diseases and is glorified in the world
of Brahmadeva (सर्वव्याधिविनिर्मुक्तो ब्र-
ह्मलोके महीयते) 3. 81. 46. [See Kaubera1,
Kaubera2]

कौबेर
Kaubera1 nt.: Name of a तीर्थ sacred
to Kubera.
God Ailabila (Kubera) became the lord
of wealth (धनाधिपत्यं संप्राप्तः)
by practising austerities at this तीर्थ; while
Kubera was at this तीर्थ riches and trea-
sures waited on him (तत्रस्थम् एव तं
(i. e. ऐलबिलम्) राजन् धनानि निधयस्
तथा।उपतस्थुः) 9. 46. 22-23; Balarāma
visited this तीर्थ, bathed there according to
the rites, and gave wealth to Brāhmaṇas 9.
46. 23, 28. [See Kaubera2 and Kośeśva-
rasya tīrthāni]

कौबेर
Kaubera2 nt.: Name of a forest sacred
to Kubera.
Described as excellent (काननोत्तम)
9. 46. 24; Balarāma saw in this forest that
place where in ancient times Kubera practi-
sed severe austerities and received many
boons, as also lordship of wealth and friend-
ship with Rudra; Kubera became there a god
and a guardian of the world (सुरत्वं
लोकपालत्वम् … यत्र लेभे) and got a son
Nalakūbara 9. 46. 26; Kubera was conse-
crated there by the Marudgaṇas and was
given the Puṣpaka vimāna 9. 46. 24-27. [See
Kaubera1]

कौशन्त
Kauśanta nt.: Name of a तीर्थ।
According to the Tīrthavaṃśa (13. 26.
3) one who bathes in this तीर्थ is waited
upon by a number of Apsarases (सेव्यते सो
ऽप्सरोगणैः) 13. 26. 26.

कौशिकस्य
Kauśikasya hradaḥ m.: Name of a
holy lake.
Named after the sage Kauśika (Viśvā-
mitra); situated on the river Kauśikī (3.
82. 124); Viśvāmitra attained there the
highest perfection (यत्र सिद्धिं परां
प्राप्तो विश्वामित्रो ऽथ कौशिकः) 3. 82.
123.

कौशिकी
Kauśikī f.: Name of a river, also
called Pārā 1. 65. 32.
A. Location: Listed by Saṃjaya
twice among the rivers of the Bhāratavarṣa;
its water used by people for drinking 6.
10. 17, 28, 13; in the east 3. 85. 3; 1.
207. 5; near the आश्रम of Bharata 3. 82.
113.
B. Origin: The river, created by
Viśvāmitra for his purification, came to be
known as Kauśikī (शौचार्थं यो नदीं
चक्रे … तां पुण्यतमां लोके कौशिकीति
विदुर् जनाः) 1. 65. 30.
C. Description:
Auspicious (शिवा) 13. 3. 10; (शिवजला) 3.
109. 20; holy, most holy (पुण्या) 3. 109.
20; 3. 110. 1; 13. 3. 10; (पुण्यतीर्था) 13.
96. 6; (पुण्यतमा) 1. 65. 30; river of the
gods (देवनदी) 3. 110. 1; Kauśikī and
other rivers contain waters of all the तीर्थस्
(सर्वतीर्थोदकैर् युताः) 13. 134. 12; de-
stroyer of great sins (महापातकनाशिनी) 3.
82. 113; river of Viśvāmitra (विश्वामित्रस्य
 … नदी) 13. 3. 10; frequented by hosts of
Brahmanical and royal sages (ब्रह्मर्षि-
गणसेविता, राजर्षिसेविता) 13. 3. 10; broad
(विपुला) 13. 3. 10; difficult to cross due to
ample waters (दुर्गमां बहुभिर् जलैः)
1. 65. 30; charming (रम्या) 3. 109. 20;
famous (यशस्विनी) 1. 207. 7; full of roots
and fruit (बहुमूलफला) 3. 85. 9; Kauśikī
is among those described as excellent rivers
(सरिद्वराः) 13. 134. 14; (सरितां वराः)
13. 134. 19; these rivers were proficient in
their knowledge of the duties of women
(स्त्रीधर्मकुशलाः) 13. 134. 19; Kauśikī
(and other rivers) described as mothers of
the universe and very strong (for citation
see Atikṛṣṇā) 6. 10. 35.
D. Events: (1)
Epic: (i) Arjuna, during his exile, saw
Kauśikī while proceeding to the east 1. 207. 7;
(ii) Bhīma, in his eastern expedition (2. 26.
1) conquered the king who took resort on the
marshy land of Kauśikī (कौशिकीकच्छ-
निलयं राजानम् … निर्जित्य) 2. 27. 20-21;
(iii) Yudhiṣṭhira was advised by Lomaśa
to take bath in the river Nandā and then
proceed to Kauśikī which he did 3. 109. 19-
20; from Kauśikī he went to different sacred
places (in the east) 3. 114. 1; (2) Past
and mythological: (i) Viśvāmitra practised
austerities on the bank of Kauśikī 3. 109. 19;
here Viśvāmitra acquired the status of a
Brāhmaṇa (अभ्यगाद् यत्र ब्राह्मणत्वम्)
3. 85. 9; in ancient times, during a difficult
period, the royal sage Mataṅga supported
here the wife of Viśvāmitra; when the period
of famine was over, Viśvāmitra returned to
his आश्रम on this river and gave the river
the name Pārā (मुनिः पारेति नद्या वै
नाम चक्रे तदा प्रभुः); on this river
Viśvāmitra acted as priest in Mataṅga's
sacrifice 1. 65. 31-33; (ii) the sages
Śukra, Aṅgiras and others while visiting
different तीर्थस् reached the river Kauśikī on
the full moon day of the month of Māgha 13.
96. 6; (iii) Mṛtyu, conceived as a maiden,
while trying to avoid Brahmadeva's command
to deprive people of their lives, practised
severe austerities at different places, one
of them being the river Kauśikī 12. 250. 21
(Nī. on 12. 258. 21: कौशिकीं गण्डकीं
नदीम्). E Importance: (i) Umā
consulted Kauśikī and other rivers on the
duties of a women (स्त्रीधर्म) before ex-
pounding it to Śaṅkara 13. 134. 13, 18-20;
(ii) Kauśikī and other rivers wait upon
Maheśvara for his bath (उपस्पर्शनहेतोस्
त्वा समीपस्था उपासते) 13. 134. 12; (iii)
Mārkaṇḍeya saw Kauśiki, among other rivers,
in the belly of Bāla (3. 186. 83, i. e. Nārā-
yaṇa 3. 187. 3) 3. 186. 93; (iv) listed by
Mārkaṇḍeya among rivers famous as mothers
of fire-hearths, i. e. sacrifices were performed
on their banks (एता नद्यस् तु धिष्ण्यानां
मातरो याः प्रकीर्तिताः) 3. 212. 24 (For
Nī. see Kapilā); (v) on its banks there are
आश्रमस् of Viśvāmitra and Kāśyapa 3. 110,
1-2 and of Bharata 3. 82. 113; (vi) finds
mention in the Daivata-Ṛṣi-Vaṃśa 13. 151.
22, 2.
F. Holy: By waiting upon Kauśikī
(कौशिकीं तत्र सेवेत) one obtains the
fruit of a Rājasūya 3. 82. 113; by staying at
Kauśikī for a month one gets the merit of per-
forming an Aśvamedha (अश्वमेधस्य यत्
पुण्यम्) 3. 82. 124; by observing total fast
and by remaining uncovetous (वायुभक्षस्
त्व् अलोलुपः) at the gate of Kauśikī (कौशिकी-
द्वारम्) for twenty one nights one goes to
heaven 13. 26. 30; if one takes limited food
(नियताहारः) and bathes at the confluence
of the rivers Kauśikī and Dṛṣadvatī one is
freed of all sins 3. 81. 80; if one who is
controlled (यतः) and is learned (विद्वान्)
fasts for three nights and bathes at the con-
fluence of the Kauśikī and the Aruṇā he is
freed of all sins 3. 82. 135; Kauśikī is one of
those rivers by visiting which the high-souled
persons who have observed vows, go to the
Goloka (?) (ते तत्र मोदन्ति गवां विमाने
13. 105. 44) after assuming heavenly form,
wearing heavenly garlands, holy, and rich in
auspicious fragrance (दिव्यसंस्थाना दिव्य-
माल्यधराः शिवाः।प्रयान्ति पुण्यगन्-
धाढ्याः) 13. 105. 47-48.

क्रौञ्च
Krauñca1 m.: Name of a mountain.
A. Family: Son of Himavant (हिम-
वतः सुतम्) 3. 214. 31.
B. Location:
Part of the Śveta mountain 3. 214. 30-31;
34-35.
C. Description: Great mountain
(महाद्रि) 9. 16. 50; best among the moun-
tains (पर्वतश्रेष्ठ) 9. 45. 78; resounding
with sounds of Krauñca birds (क्रौञ्च-
नादनिनादित) 9. 45. 73; having Śāla and
Sarala (pine) trees (सशालस्कन्धसरल)
9. 45. 74; description of the mountain when
pierced by the शक्ति of Kārttikeya (the
mountain began to burn; the terrified ani-
mals, birds and serpents deserted it; the
Vidyādharas and the Kinnaras, living on the
peaks of the mountain, flew upwards; the
Daityas came out in the open in hundreds
and thousands and were killed by the follo-
wers of Kumāra Kārttikeya) 9. 45. 74-79;
the Krauñca mountain, though reduced to a
pitiable condition continued, to be resplendent
(शोच्याम् अपि दशां प्राप्तो रराजैव स पर्-
वतः) 9. 45. 76.
D. Mythological events:
(1) Kumāra (Kārttikeya) pierced the Krau-
ñca mountain with his arrows; through the
crevice created by the arrows swans and
vultures go to the mountain Meru (तेन
हंसाश् च गृध्राश् च मेरुं गच्छन्ति
पर्वतम्) 3. 214. 30-31; the mountain,
thus shattered, fell down issuing sounds of
excessive pain; seeing the Krauñca fall down,
other mountains howled excessively due to
fear 3. 214. 32; (2) When Kārttikeya
killed many Asuras, Bāṇa, the son of Bali,
resorted to Krauñca and started harassing
gods; when attacked by Kārttikeya, Bāṇa took
refuge with the Krauñca; then Kārttikeya
pierced Krauñca with the शक्ति given to him
by Agni 9. 45. 70, 73, 79, 81.
E. Similes:
(1) The arrows shot by Arjuna from his
Gāṇḍīva entered Karṇa as swans enter the
Krauñca (हंसाः क्रौञ्चम् इवाविशन्) 7.
114. 82; (2) The arrows shot by Karṇa
at Bhīma entered his left arm as the birds the
Krauñca (प्राविशन् … क्रौञ्चं पत्ररथा
इव) 7. 109. 29; (3) Śalya, with blood is-
suing out of his body when hit by the शक्ति
of Yudhiṣṭhira, was like the Krauñca hit by
Skanda 9. 16. 50; (4) Ghaṭotkaca said to
Aśvatthāman that he would strike at him as
did Agnisuta (Skanda) the Krauñca moun-
tain 7. 131. 56.

क्रौञ्च
Krauñca2 m.: Name of a mountain.
Located in the Krauñcadvīpa, it is des-
cribed as a great mountain (क्रौञ्चद्वीपे
महाराज क्रौञ्चो नाम महागिरिः) 6. 13.
17; beyond the Krauñca is the mountain
called Vāmanaka 6. 13. 17; the country relat-
ed to Krauñca is the Kuśala (क्रौञ्चस्य
कुशलो देशः) 6. 13. 20.

क्रौञ्चपादी
Krauñcapādī f.: Name of a तीर्थ।
By visiting (?) Krauñcapādī one is
freed of the sin of killing a Brāhmaṇa (मुञ्-
जपृष्ठं गयां चैव निरृतिं देवपर्व-
तम्।तृतीयां क्रौञ्चपादीं च ब्रह्महत्या
विशुध्यति) 13. 26. 40.

खाण्डव
Khāṇḍava m., nt.: Name of a forest.
A. Location: Situated in the Kurukṣetra
(यस्य (i. e. तक्षकस्य) वासः कुरु-
क्षेत्रे खाण्डवे चाभवत् सदा) 1. 3. 144;
near the river Yamunā 1. 214. 14; 1. 215. 1.
B. Description: Called दाव 1. 215. 6-7,
9-10, 12; 1. 216. 31, 34; 1. 218. 19 (?);
1. 219. 3 (?), 10, 22; 1. 220. 31; 1. 223. 22;
1. 225. 15; 4. 2. 9; 4. 34. 14; वन 1. 216. 33;
1. 217. 22; 1. 218. 2, 4; 1. 220. 1, 17, 20;
1. 224. 7; 1. 225. 5; महावन 1. 215. 18;
प्रस्थ 8. 29. 18; it had sanctuaries (?)
for manes and gods (which could not
offer shelter to animals when the forest was
on fire) (न चालभन्त ते शर्म … पितृ-
देवनिवासेषु) 1. 219. 27.
C. Inhabitants:
Demons (दानवाः), Rākṣasas, Nāgas, and
animals like hyenas (तरक्षु), bears, ele-
phants, tigers, lions, deer, buffalos and birds—
all lived in the Khāṇḍava (खाण्डवालोयाः)
1. 219. 1, 2; Takṣaka, friend of Indra, to-
gether with his followers (सगणः) and
his son Aśvasena lived there 1. 3. 144, 145;
1. 215. 7.
D. Agni's desire to burn the
forest: Agni approached Kṛṣṇa and Arjuna to
seek their help in fulfilling his desire to burn
the Khāṇḍava; since Indra's friend Takṣaka
lived in the forest, he foiled all Agni's ear-
lier attempts to burn it 1. 215. 1-12; 1. 223.
25; 3. 46. 40; 4. 34. 14;
E. Arjuna's
request for weapons: Hearing Agni's request
Arjuna asked for suitable weapons for him-
self and Kṛṣṇa so that both of them could
foil Indra's attempt to pour water on the
great forest 1. 215. 13-18; this was arranged
by Agni 1. 216. 1-27.
F. Burning of the
forest: The burning described 1. 216. 33-34;
1. 217-219; 1. 220. 32; the burning was so
frightful that it appeared as if the end of Aeon
had set in (ददाह खाण्डवं क्रुद्धो
युगान्तम् इव दर्शयन्) 1. 216. 32.
G.
Duration: The forest was burning for six
days (पावकश् चापि तं दावं दग्ध्वा
समृगपक्सिणम्।अहानि पञ्च चैकं च
विरराम सुतर्पितः) 1. 225. 15.
H. Who
were saved from the fire: (i) The Pannaga
Takṣaka, since he was not present at the
Khāṇḍava at the time of the burning 1. 218.
4; 1. 219. 13; (ii) His son Aśvasena was
present in the Khāṇḍava but was saved by
his mother, who swallowed him, and by
Indra who released gusts of wind 1. 218. 4-9;
(iii) Asura Maya who sought shelter with
Arjuna when Kṛṣṇa wanted to kill him
1. 219. 35-39; (iv) Four young sons
(Śārṅga birds) of Mandapāla were saved
by Agni at their father's request (प्रदहन्
खाण्डवं दावं मम पुत्रान् विसर्जय)
1. 220. 31-32; 20-21; 1. 223. 22; they were left
behind in the Khāṇḍava by their mother as they
did not listen to her advice to enter a mouse
hole to save themselves 1. 222. 16; actually,
at the time of the conflagration, only six were
not burnt by Agni, viz. Aśvasena, Maya, and
four Śārṅgaka birds 1. 219. 40; 1. 220. 2, 4.
I. Why was the forest burnt: Destruction
of the Khāṇḍava was ordained — this was told
to Indra by an invisible voice (वाग् उवाचा-
शरीरिणी … दिष्टं चानुपश्यैतत् खाण्डव-
स्य विनाशनम्) 1. 219. 12, 18; when Arjuna
was born an invisible voice had foretold that
Agni would burn the forest with the help of
Arjuna 1. 114. 28, 32; 8. 48. 7; but Agni is
said to have burnt the forest to make the world
free from fear (भगवान् अपि तिग्मांशुः
समिद्धं खाण्डवं वनम्।ददाह
सह कृष्णाभ्यां जनयञ् जगतो ऽभयम्)
1. 225. 5.
J. Allusions in the Ādi and the
other पर्वन्स् to the Khāṇḍavadāha: (i)
Agni desirous of burning the Khāṇḍava appro-
ached Arjuna and Kṛṣṇa 4. 2. 9; (ii) Agni
arranged to get two inexhaustible quivers
and the Gāṇḍīva bow for Arjuna and the
Cakra for Kṛṣṇa 1. 2. 93; 3. 40. 36; 3.
157. 20; 5. 155. 7; 7. 10. 21; 17. 1. 37-39;
(iii) Agni burnt the Khāṇḍava forest with
the help of Arjuna and Kṛṣṇa and was
satiated 1. 1. 104; 1. 55. 35; 3. 46. 14; 4.
18. 10; 4. 35. 10; 5. 51. 9; 5. 59. 8; 5. 61.
8; 6. 94. 5; 7. 10. 21; 8. 65. 15; 8. 66. 23;
13. 143. 23; 15. 46. 11; 17. 1. 36; (iv)
Arjuna (and Kṛṣṇa) fighting a war with Indra
and other gods and defeating them at the
Khāṇḍava forest: 1. 1. 104; 3. 157. 20; 5.
22. 13; 5. 51. 9; 5. 155. 26; 6. 94. 5; 7.
160. 15; 8. 29. 18; 8. 31. 9; 13. 143. 23;
(v) Aśvasena's escape from the Khāṇḍava
fire: 8. 66. 23.
K. Similes: (1) Bhīma
wanted to release his wrath on Duryodhana
as Arjuna released fire on the Khāṇḍava
(खाण्डवे ऽग्निम् इवार्जुनः) 9. 32. 30; (2)
Bhīma wanted to release his wrath on Duryo-
dhana as Fire released (his wrath) on the
Khāṇḍava (खाण्डवे पावको यथा) 9. 55.
16; (3) When the forest (Khāṇḍava, not
directly named) was on fire it looked like
the golden Meru mountain which is of great
lustre (दह्यतस् तस्य विबभौ रूपं
दावस्य भारत।मेरोर् इव नगेन्द्रस्य
काञ्चनस्य महाद्युतेः॥) 1. 216. 34.

गङ्गा
Gaṅgā1, (Mahāgaṅgā 3. 155. 85) f.:
Name of a river, also called Bhāgīrathī
(Bhagīrathasutā 5. 179. 5) and Jāhnavī
(Jahnusutā 1. 92. 49; Jahnukanyā 13. 14. 37)
at various places (see below); also referred
to as Tripathagā 1. 92. 39; 2. 39. 11; 3. 106.
27; 3. 108. 18; 6. 7. 44; 12. 38. 8; 13. 27.
76; 13. 44. 13; 14. 44. 13; 15. 41. 13; also
cf. 13. 27. 72; Tripathā 13. 27. 101; Trimārgā
13. 27. 87; Trivartmagā 13. 27. 83; Tripa-
thagāminī 1. 92. 39; Trilokagā 1. 91. 18;
18. 3. 37; Trilokapathagā 12. 29. 62; Triloka-
goptrī 13. 27. 83.
A. Location: Geographical references:
(1) The heavenly Tripathagā issuing from
the Brahmaloka first settled down at Bindu-
saras near the Hiraṇyaśṛṅga mountain and
then became sevenfold 6. 7. 44 (the seven
names are given in 6. 7. 45); this is how
the god had arranged (प्रभोर् एषैव
संविधिः) 6. 7. 46 (Nī. on Bom. Ed. 6. 6.
49: प्रभोर् ईश्वरस्यैष सप्तनद्यात्म-
कः संविधिः समीचीनं लोकोपकारार्थं
विधानम्); the seven divine rivers are
known as the seven Ganges 6. 7. 47; Gaṅgā
can be seen from the lake Bindusaras which
is on the slope of the mountain Hiraṇyaśṛṅga
6. 7. 41; (2) Gaṅgā Bhāgīrathī falls with
a terrific speed from the summit of the
mount Meru down into the lake Cāndra-
masa which was created by it 6. 7. 26-27;
(3) Lomaśa could hear the sound of dis-
tant Gaṅgā falling on top of Indra's golden
mountain 3. 140. 14; (4) Flowing near
the hermitage of Nara and Nārāyaṇa at
Badarī on mount Kailāsa 3. 145. 15-16; 3.
45. 20; at this आश्रम Gaṅgā has two curre-
nts, hot and cold, and has sand of gold (उष्ण-
तोयवहा गङ्गा शीततोयवहापरा।सुवर्ण-
सिकता राजन् विशालां बदरीम् अनु) 3. 88.
23; (5) Flows constantly by the hermitage
of Upamanyu on the Himavant mountain
13. 14. 27-28; (6) The river struck the
Himavant mountain (at its foot) at Gaṅgā-
dvāra 3. 88. 18; (7) Listed by Saṃjaya
twice as Gaṅgā and as all the Gaṅgās (सर्वा
गङ्गाः) among the rivers of the Bhārata-
varṣa; its water used by people for drinking 6.
10. 13, 35; (8) Vārāṇasī, established by
Divodāsa, is to the north of Gaṅgā and south
of Gomatī 13. 31. 16-18; (9) There are three
firepits at Prayāga through which Jāhnavī
flows out of Prayāga (तत्र त्रीण्य् अग्निकुण्-
डानि येषां मध्ये च जाह्नवी।प्रयागाद्
अभिनिष्क्रान्ता) 3. 83. 69; Gaṅgā and
Yamunā meet at Prayāga; the region bet-
ween the two rivers is known as the hip
(जघन) of the earth 3. 83. 70-71; (10)
The bank of the Gaṅgā, known as the Aśva-
tīrtha, is not far from Kanyakubja 13. 4. 17;
(11) Gaṅgā flows through the Pañcāla
country dividing it into northern and southern
Pañcāla 1. 128. 12; 1. 154. 24; the country
of Mākandī lay to its south with Kāmpilya
as its capital 1. 128. 15; (12) Pramāṇa-
koṭi was on the bank of the Gaṅgā 3. 13. 74;
(13) Arjuna in his journey towards the east
crossed many rivers one of them being
Gaṅgā 1. 207. 7; (14) Kṛṣṇa, Bhīma and
Arjuna, on their way to the Magadha in the
east crossed Gaṅgā after they crossed Mithilā
2. 18. 28-29; (15) The Bāhlīka country and
the Madra country were kept out by the river
Gaṅgā (बाह्लीकदेशं मद्रांश् च कुत्सयन्
वाक्यम् अब्रवीत्।बहिष्कृता हिमवता
गङ्गया च तिरस्कृताः) 8. 30. 9-10; (16)
The country between the Gaṅgā and the
Yamunā was the middle of the earth (मध्ये
पृथिव्याः) 1. 82. 5; (17) In the Madhya-
deśa, between the rivers Gaṅgā and Yamunā
and at the foot of the Yāmuna mountain
there was a large settlement of the Brāhmaṇas
known as Parṇaśālā 13. 67. 3-4; (18) On
the northern bank of the Gaṅgā there were
many routes of the Nāgas (बहूनि नाग-
वर्त्मानि गङ्गायास् तीर उत्तरे) 1. 3. 141;
B. Description: (1) Best among the
rivers: सरिच्छ्रेष्ठा 1. 91. 4; 1. 94. 22;
3. 108. 4; 7. 57. 24; 9. 36. 47; 13. 134. 22;
13. 154. 32; सरितां श्रेष्ठा 12. 274. 16; 12.
311. 12; 13. 27. 50; 13. 84. 66; सरिद्वरा
1. 91. 8; 13. 27. 25, 86; 13. 84. 64; 13.
134. 14; 13. 154. 33; सरिताम् वरा 1. 91.
10; 13. 134. 19; सरितां वरिष्ठा 13. 72.
40; सर्वसरिद्वरा 13. 134. 17; (2) pure,
auspicious, blessed, holy: शुचि 1. 158. 18;
11. 13. 4; (its water) 12. 221. 6; 13. 27. 30;
शिवा 3. 108. 2; 3. 145. 40; 11. 27. 1; 13. 27.
66, 85; 13. 134. 22; शुभा 1. 158. 20; 3. 155.
85; 6. 7. 27; 14. 82. 15; (its water) 13. 27.
33, 36; (its bank) 13. 53. 55; सुभगा 3.
140. 14; पुण्या 3. 85. 10, 17; 3. 97. 27; 3.
108. 2; 3. 155. 85; 6. 7. 27; 12. 335. 46;
15. 41. 13; (its water) 1. 158. 21; 3. 108.
14; 5. 40. 4; पुण्यजला 3. 108. 6; 13. 27. 66;
