C. Holy:
(1) The river confers holiness on the three
worlds (गङ्गा लोकानां पुण्यदा वै त्रया-
णाम्) 13. 27. 88; (2) Bathing on conflu-
ences: (i) one who bathes at the conflu-
ence of the river Saṅgamā and the Gaṅgā gets
the fruit of performing ten Aśvamedha sacri-
fices and lifts up his family 3. 82. 31; one
who bathes at the confluence of the river
Sarasvatī and the Gaṅgā gets the fruit of
performing an Aśvamedha and goes to heaven
8. 82. 34; (ii) one who bathes at the world-
famous confluence of the Gomatī and the
Gaṅgā gets the fruit of performing an Agni-
ṣṭoma and lifts up his family 3. 82. 70; (iii)
by bathing at the confluence of the Yamunā
and the Gaṅgā one gets the merit of studying
the four Vedas and of speaking the truth
3. 83. 80; the gift given after bathing (उप-
स्पृश्य) at this confluence is better than any
other gift (दानं नान्यद् विशिष्यते) 13. 26.
34; (iv) by bathing at the confluence of
the Gaṅgā and the ocean (गङ्गायास् … साग-
रस्य च संगमे) one gets tenfold the
fruit of an Aśvamedha (अशमेधं दश-
गुणम्) 3. 83. 4; (3) Bathing in the
Gaṅgā: By bathing (कृतोदकः) in the
Bhāgīrathī at Campā and by approaching
Daṇḍārka (दण्डार्कम् अभिगम्यैव ?) one
gets the fruit of donating a thousand cows
3. 82. 142; by bathing in the second island
of the Gaṅgā (? गङ्गायास् त्व् अपरं द्वी-
पम्) and by fasting for three nights one
achieves all desires 3. 83. 5; one who observes
chastity and is composed (ब्रह्मचारी समा-
हितः) and bathes in the Gaṅgā at Śṛṅgavera-
pura is cleansed of his sins and obtains the
fruit of a Vājapeya sacrifice 3. 83. 63; by
worshipping there Mahādeva and by making
a प्रदक्षिणा one gets the position of a
Gaṇapati (गाणपत्यम् अवाप्नुयात्) 3. 83.
64; by bathing ceremonially (यो नरस् त्व्
अभिषिच्यते) at a place where the Bhāgīrathī
Gaṅgā turns northwards near the abode (?)
of Maheśvara (महेश्वरस्य निष्ठने)
and by living there for a month, abstaining
from food, one sees the deities in person
(स्वयं पश्यति देवताः) 13. 26. 14; by
going to the तीर्थ Brahmaśiras, by bathing
(कृतोदकः) in the Bhāgīrathī and by
abstaining from food for a month one goes
to the Somaloka 13. 26. 38; for the benefits
of bathing in the Gaṅgā and of resorting to it
also cf. 13. 27. 26, 29-30 (Nī. on Bom. Ed.
13. 26. 31: व्युष्टिः पुण्यवृद्धिः), 32, 37-
49, 56, 59-63, 65-72, 77-86, 90, 92-95, 100;
(4) Meditating on the Gaṅgā: One who is
controlled and is respected by the learned
(प्रयतः शिष्टसंमतः) if, while leaving
his body, he thinks of the Gaṅgā he obtains
the best condition (after death) (स गतिं
परमां लभेत्) 13. 27. 69; (5) Fasting
on the Gaṅgā: One who fasts near the river
for thirteen days and eats a part of the obla-
tion in the evening of the fourteenth day, and
he does this for twelve months, he gets the
fruit of a great sacrifice and he lives in the
company of the Devakanyās for a full year
on the sandy banks of the river Jāhnavī
(चतुर्दशे तु दिवसे यः पूर्णे प्राशते
हविः।सदा द्वादशमासान् वै महामेध-
फलं लभेत्॥ … देवकन्यानिवासे च
तस्मिन् वसति मानवः।जाह्नवीवालुका-
कीर्णे पूर्णं संवत्सरं नरः) 13.
110. 60, 63; (6) Sand and earth on its
banks and the breeze coming from its waves
are holy 13. 27. 53-55. (7) Rites after
death performed at the Gaṅgā: Those
beings whose bones (गात्राणि; Nī. on
Bom. Ed. 13. 26. 28: गात्राणी अस्थीनि),
when thrown in the Gaṅgā come in con-
tact with its water are not thrown out of
heaven (न पुनस् तेषां त्यागः स्वर्गाद्
विधीयते) 13. 27. 27; those beings whose
obsequies (कृत्यानि) are performed with the
water of the Gaṅgā remain permanently in
the heaven (दिवि तिष्ठन्ति ते ऽचलाः) 13. 27.
28; also cf. 13. 27. 31, 36, 64; (8) The
country through which the Gaṅgā flows is as
good as a penance grove; a place along the
river Gaṅgā is to be looked upon as the place
of the Siddhas (यत्र गङ्गा महाराज स
देशस् तत् तपोवनम्।सिद्धक्षेत्रं तु
तज् ज्ञेयं गङ्गातीरसमाश्रितम्॥) 3. 83.
83; the countries (देशाः), the Janapadas, the
आश्रमस्, the mountains through which the
Bhāgīrathī Gaṅgā, the best among the rivers,
flows excel in holiness (प्रकृष्टाः पुण्यतः)
13. 27. 24-25 (Nī. on Bom. Ed. 13. 26. 18:
देशाः भूमिभागाः जनपदाः महाजन-
निवासस्थानानि आश्रमाः ऋषिस्थानानि); the
countries and the quarters which do not enjoy
the benefit of the auspicious water of the
Gaṅgā are like nights without the moon and
trees without flowers 13. 27. 33; also cf.
13. 27. 34-35; (9) Many तीर्थस् on the
river Gaṅgā: (i) Daśāśvamedhika 3. 83. 82;
(ii) Brahmaśiras 13. 26. 38; (iii) Mārka-
ṇḍeyatīrtha 3. 82. 70; (iv) Aśvatīrtha 13.
4. 17; (v) Prayāga 3. 83. 69, 71; (vi)
Daṇḍārka (?) 3. 82. 142; (also see the next
section: Importance).
D. Importance:
(i) Sages and gods pay homage to Nārāyaṇa
on the river Gaṅgā 3. 88. 18; (ii) Gaṅgā
is listed by Mārkaṇḍeya among rivers famous
as mothers of fire-hearths, i. e. sacrifices were
performed on their banks (गङ्गा च … ।एता
नद्यस् तु धिष्ण्यानां मातरो याः प्रकी-
र्तिताः॥) 3. 212. 24 (for Nī. see Kapilā);
(iii) Gaṅgā, and all the Gaṅgās, listed by
Saṃjaya among rivers which are called
mothers of the universe 6. 10. 13; (सर्वा
गङ्गाश् च मारिष।विश्वस्य मातरः सर्-
वाः) 6. 10. 35; (iv) Finds place twice in
the Daivata-Ṛṣi-Vaṃśa 13. 151. 7, 15, 2;
(v) Worlds which one gets by adoring with
faith and devotion the virtues of the Jāhnavī
were created by Gaṅgā herself (गङ्गाकृतान्
अचिरेणैव लोकान् यथेष्टम् इष्टान् विचरि-
ष्यसि त्वम्); such a person became famous
in the three worlds and achieved perfection
which was difficult to obtain 13. 27. 98-99;
(vi) The narration of the great importance
and virtues of the Gaṅgā is called a holy
Itihāsa containing the praise of the river; one
who recites it, or listens to it, is freed of all
sins (इतिहासम् इमं पुण्यं शृणुयाद् यः
पठेत वा।गङ्गायाः स्तवसंयुक्तं स
मुच्येत् सर्वकिल्बिषैः) 13. 27. 105; (vii)
Virtues of the river Gaṅgā are countless;
no one can fully describe or determine them
(वक्तुं शक्यं नेह गङ्गाजलानां गुणा-
ख्यानं परिमातुं तथैव) 13. 27. 97,
96; (viii) Gaṅgā offered shelter, protection,
support to those who are without it 13. 27. 44;
Lomaśa invoked the blessings of the Gaṅgā,
besides those of Varuṇa, Yama, and the
Yamunā, on Yudhiṣṭhira and requested her
to protect him from the mountains which he
was about to enter while on his way to the
Gandhamādana 3. 140. 13-14; (ix) Grief
due to separation from the Gaṅgā more
unbearable than from near relatives or wealth;
on the other hand, just the sight of the Gaṅgā
is more pleasing than that of the desired
objects or sons 13. 27. 74-76; (x) Gaṅgā
offers sustenance to those who depend on her
13. 27. 51-52; (11) Relationship with other
rivers: (i) Tripathagā Gaṅgā looked upon as
the first to be created among the rivers (तथा
त्रिपथगा गङ्गा नदीनाम् अग्रजा स्मृता)
14. 44. 13; (ii) among the Vibhūtis of the
Bhagavān, Jāhnavī is said to be the best
among the rivers (स्रोतसाम् अस्मि जाह्नवी)
6. 32. 31; also cf. 13. 27. 50; (iii) the Gaṅgā
has the same relationship to other rivers as
the sun has to other luminaries (?) in the sky,
the moon to the manes, and the king (?) to
men (दिवि ज्योतिर् यथादित्यः पितॄणां चैव
चन्द्रमाः।देवेशश् च यथा नॄणां
गङ्गेह सरितां तथा॥) 13. 27. 73 (Nī.
on Bom. Ed. 13. 26. 74: दिवि देवानाम् इति
शेषः।देवेशः राजेन्द्रः); (12) Service
to deities: Gaṅgā is mentioned among those
rivers who wait on Śiva for his ablutions
(उपस्पर्शनहेतोस् त्वा समीपस्था उपा-
सते) 13. 134. 12, 17; the Bhāgīrathī is one
of the rivers who wait upon Varuṇa in his
सभा 2. 9. 17; (13) Limitation: Bhagī-
ratha told Brahmadeva that his stay even for
a hundred years on the bank of the Jāhnavī,
practising austerities and giving as gift a
thousand mules and a host of maidens (अदां
च तत्राश्वतरीसहस्रं नारीपुरम्) was
not enough to take him to the Brahmaloka
which was beyond the world of the gods, the
cows and the sages 13. 106. 10, 5.
E. Epic
events related to the Gaṅgā: (1) Marriage
with Saṃtanu and birth of Bhīṣma: King
Pratīpa once went to the bank of the Gaṅgā
(गङ्गातीरगतः) and sat down for many years
muttering prayers (जपन्) 1. 92. 1; Gaṅgā,
in the form of a beautiful woman, rose from
the waters and sat on the right thigh of king
Pratīpa 1. 92. 2-3; when asked by the king
what he might do to please her she requested
him to make love with her (त्वाम् अहं
कामये राजन् कुरुश्रेष्ठ भजस्व माम्)
1. 92. 4-5; but, at the king's suggestion,
she agreed to be his daughter-in-law and
disappeared 1. 92. 9-12, 15-16; she laid
down the condition that the king's son (her
future husband) should not know her identity
and should never question the propriety of her
actions (स मे नाभिजनज्ञः स्याद् आचरे-
यं च यद् विभो।तत् सर्वम् एव पुत्रस्
ते न मीमांसेत कर्हिचित्) 1. 92. 13-14;
king Śāṃtanu, son of Pratīpa, once went for
hunting on the bank of the Gaṅgā; the river
appeared before him in the form of a beautiful
woman 1. 92. 25-26; when Śaṃtanu requested
her to be his wife she agreed on condition that
he did not prevent her from doing anything,
auspicious or otherwise (शुभं वा यदि
वाशुभम्); should the king question her,
she would abandon him 1. 92. 31-35; when
the king consented, she, full of lustre, attended
on him as his wife 1. 92. 39-40; Gaṅgā, as
the wife of Śaṃtanu, gave birth to eight sons
seven of whom, as soon as they were born,
she threw away in the waters of the river
Gaṅgā; the king did not object to her on the
first seven occasions, but on the eighth occa-
sion he asked her to spare him a son; he
also wanted to know who she really was
1. 92. 44-47; when thus questioned, she told
Śaṃtanu that she was the river Gaṅgā, the
daughter of Jahnu, and that she lived with
him to achieve some purpose of the gods
(देवकार्यार्थसिद्ध्यर्थम् 1. 92. 49); the
eight sons she bore him were the eight Vasus
who were born as human beings due to the
curse of Vasiṣtha; she had promised the
Vasus that she would release them from their
human birth as soon as they were born
(cf. 1. 93. 40); she blessed the king before
her departure (स्वस्ति ते ऽस्तु गमिष्यामि); she
told the king that she had lived with the Vasus
(while they were in her womb) in succession
(एष पर्यायवासो मे वसूनां संनिधौ
कृतः) and that the eighth son who was to be
given to him later by her was the one born of
her (Gaṅgā) (मत्प्रसूतं विजानीहि गङ्गा-
दत्तम् इमं सुतम्) 1. 92. 48-55; Śaṃtanu
asked Jāhnavī who was Āpava (Vasiṣṭha)
and what fault the Vasus had committed to
invite the curse of Vasiṣṭha; he also asked
why the eighth son (Gaṅgādatta) was requir-
ed to live long among human beings 1. 9. 1-3;
Gaṅgā Jāhnavī then told the king the whole
story 1. 93. 5-42; Gaṅgā then disappeared
taking the last-born son with her 1. 93. 43;
many years later, King Śaṃtanu, while once
hunting along the river Gaṅgā Bhāgīrathī,
noticed that the river had little water (अल्प-
जलाम् 1. 94. 21) and was not flowing as before
(स्यन्दते किं न्व् इयं नाद्य 1. 94. 22);
trying to find out the cause of it the king
saw a young boy who had covered waters of
the entire Gaṅgā with his arrows 1. 94. 24-25;
Śaṃtanu suspected the boy to be his son and
hence asked Gaṅgā to show herself to him;
Gaṅgā appeared before the king holding the
boy in her right hand, but the king did not
immediately recognize her; Gaṅgā handed
over the son to the king 1. 94. 28-31, 36;
Śaṃtanu's marriage with Gaṅgā Bhāgīrathī
and the birth of Devavrata by her mentioned
in 1. 57. 76; 1. 90. 50; 5. 179. 5; 12. 38. 8;
12. 46. 15; the birth of the Vasus from Bhāgī-
rathī in the house of Śaṃtanu mentioned
in 1. 2. 78; 1. 61. 68; (2) Her role in
Bhīṣma's fight with Rāma Jāmadagnya:
When the fight between Bhīṣma and Rāma
Jāmadagnya was imminent, the latter threa-
tened to kill Bhīṣma so that Jāhnavī might
see him lying on the bed of arrows and the
daughter of Bhagīratha (Gaṅgā), who
gave birth to him, might weep seeing him
dead 5. 179. 3-5; when Bhīṣma was ready
to fight with Rāma, his mother appeared be-
fore him in her original form (स्वरूपिणी)
to try to dissuade Bhīṣma from the fight, and
expressed her readiness to go to Jāmadagnya
to beg him not to engage Bhīṣma, who was
his pupil, in fight; Bhīṣma then told her the
incidents which had led to the fight; then the
river (Gaṅgā) went to Rāma to dissuade
him; when told that it was Bhīṣma who was
to be dissuaded, Gaṅgā returned to Bhīṣma
and again pleaded with him; but Bhīṣma,
angered, did not agree to her request 5. 179.
22-30; Bhāgīrathī again appeared later in
this event when she joined the sages, Nārada
and others, who stood between Bhīṣma and
Rāma to stop them fighting with each other
5. 186. 27; (3) Her pleading with Ambā:
Gaṅgā, the mother of Bhīṣma, rose from the
waters and asked Ambā the purpose she
wanted to achieve by performing the auste-
rities; when told by Ambā that her effort was
aimed at the destruction of Bhīṣma, Gaṅgā
(सागरगा) told her that her purpose was
crooked (जिह्मं चरसि भामिनि); if she
persisted in observing her vows and if she
died during the observance of the vows she
would become a crooked river having water
only during the rainy season and not in the
remaining eight months (नदी भविष्यसि
शुभे कुटिला वार्षिकोदका। … वार्षिकी नाष्ट-
मासिकी); Bhīsma's mother then returned from
the place where Ambā practised austerities
6. 187. 29-36; (4) Death of Bhīṣma: When
Bhīṣma, after his fall on the battle-field,
resolved to hold his life till the start of the
Uttarāyaṇa, Gaṅgā, knowing his resolve,
sent to him the great sages in the form of
swans 6. 114. 90; much later, after the
cremation of Bhīṣma, Dhṛtarāṣṭra and the
rest, including Vyāsa, Nārada, Asita and
Kṛṣṇa, went to the bank of the Bhāgīrathī
and all the Kṣatriya warriors and citizens
offered water offerings to him; then Bhāgīrathī
arose from water and, crying, lamented the
death of her son; she addressed her words to
the Kauravas praising and recounting the good
qualities of Bhīṣma 13. 154. 17-26; the
grieved Bhāgīrathī was consoled by Dāmo-
dara (Kṛṣṇa) assuring her that her son was
brought down from the chariot by Arjuna
and not by Śikhaṇḍin and that he had return-
ed to the Vasus in heaven 13. 154. 27-32;
Bhāgīrathī then gave up grief and entered
her own waters; Kṛṣṇa and others, after
honouring the river (सत्कृत्य ते तां सरितम्)
returned from that place (to Hāstinapura)
when permitted by her to do so (अनुज्ञातास्
तया) 13. 154. 33-34; when Dhṛtarāṣṭra had
offered water offerings to Bhīṣma, Yudhiṣṭhira
came out of water with Dhṛtarāṣṭra and,
grief-stricken, fell on the bank of the Gaṅgā
14. 1. 1-2; (5) Arjuna punished for his role
in the fall of Bhīṣma: Ulūpī told Arjuna
that his defeat at the hands of his son Babhru-
vāhana was an expiation (निष्कृतिः) he had
to undergo for the अधर्म committed by him
in bringing about the fall of Bhīṣma 14. 82. 8;
this expiation was prescribed by the Vasus
and the Gaṅgā (एषा तु विहिता शान्तिः पुत्राद्
यां प्राप्तवान् असि।वसुभिर् वसुधापाल
गङ्गया च महामते) 14. 82. 11; when
Bhīṣma died (हते शान्तनवे नृपे) the
Vasus emerged from waters and meeting the
great river, told her that they wanted to
curse Arjuna for his misdeed in the war, to
which Bhāgīrathī agreed (इदम् ऊचुर् वचो
घोरं भागीरथ्या मते तदा॥ … वयम्
अप्य् अर्जुनं … शापेन योजयामेति तथास्त्व्
इति चाब्रवीत्॥) 14. 82. 12-15; (6) The
Pāṇḍavas came across the Gaṅgā at various
places: (i) When Yudhiṣṭhira and his bro-
thers decided to go on a pilgrimage, the
Brāhmaṇas expressed their wish to visit with
them the Gaṅgā and other rivers 3. 91. 10;
when they arrived at Prayāga at the con-
fluence of the Gaṅgā and the Yamunā the
Pāṇḍavas bathed in their waters (आप्लुत्य
गात्राणि), practised the severest austerities
and gave gifts to the Brāhmaṇas 3. 93. 5-6;
(ii) They again arrived at the Bhāgīrathī
flowing by the side of the Agastyāśrama
where Lomaśa advised them to bathe at
will (यथेष्टम् अवगाह्यताम्) 3. 97. 27;
(iii) Going further from the river Kauśikī,
they arrived at the place where the Gaṅgā
met the ocean and bathed there in waters
of five hundred rivers (नदीशतानां पञ्चा-
नां मध्ये चक्रे समाप्लवम्) 3. 114. 2;
(iv) On reaching the vicinity of the Maināka
mountain, Lomaśa showed the river Gaṅgā
to Yudhiṣṭhira; he advised Yudhiṣṭhira to
bathe in the Gaṅgā to be freed of all sins;
he also advised him to bathe silently (तूष्णीं
गङ्गाम् … समुपस्पृश) 3. 135. 5-7; (v)
When the Pāṇḍavas had crossed the Uśīra-
bīja, the Maināka, the Śvetagiri and the
Kālaśaila mountains, Lomaśa showed them
the Gaṅgā flowing in seven currents (एषा
गङ्गा सप्तविधा) 3. 140. 1-2; Lomaśa
could hear the sound of the Gaṅgā on the
top on the mountain Jāmbūnada 3. 140. 14;
(vi) The Pāṇḍavas saw the Bhāgīrathī on
the Kailāsa mountain; they lived there giving
offerings to gods and manes again and again
3. 145. 37, 40, 42; (7) Some events after
the war and the funeral rites offered to the
dead: (i) When Yudhiṣṭhira went to meet
Dhṛtarāṣṭra who had left Hāstinapura, he
saw the Kaurava women lamenting on the
bank of the Gaṅgā 11. 11. 5; (ii) Vyāsa,
who knew that Gāndhārī would curse the
Pāṇḍavas in their first meeting with her after
the war, hastened to them after bathing (उप-
स्पृश्य) in the Gaṅgā 11. 13. 4; (iii) After
lifting the funeral pyre of Droṇa, his pupils,
keeping Kṛpī in the front, proceeded to the
Gaṅgā 11. 23. 42; (iv) After arranging
for the cremation of all the heroes who fell
in the war, Yudhiṣṭhira, accompanied by
Dhṛtarāṣṭra, went towards the Gaṅgā 11.
26. 44; on reaching the Gaṅgā, Yudhiṣṭhira
and the Kaurava women offered water offerings
to the departed (प्रचक्रुः सलिलक्रियाः);
at that moment the Gaṅgā became easily
fordable spreading herself out widely (सूप-
तीर्थाभवद् गङ्गा भूयो विप्रससार च);
the bank of the Gaṅgā then was without
joy and merriment (निरानन्दम् अनुत्सवम्
 … गङ्गातीरम् अशोभत) 11. 27. 1-5; (v)
Yudhisṭhira, after giving water offerings to
Karṇa (चकारास्योदकं प्रभुः 11. 27.
21) and after performing the funeral rites for
him with the wives of Karṇa, came out of
the river Gaṅgā (स ताभिः सह धर्मात्मा
प्रेतकृत्यम् अनन्तरम् कृत्व्ōत्ततार गङ्गा-
याः) 11. 27. 24; (vi) When the Pāṇḍavas,
who had given water offerings, were still
on the Bhāgīrathī, Dvaipāyana, Narada
and others and their pupils and hundreds
of thousands of other Brāhmaṇas gathered
there to console Yudhiṣṭhira 12. 1. 1-2,
4-5, 8; (8) Cremation of Pāṇḍu and
Mādrī: The cremation was performed on
an auspicious and even spot in the forest on
the river Gaṅgā (रमणीये वनोद्देशे
गङ्गातीरे समे शुभे); the bier (शिबिका)
in which their dead bodies were brought from
Hāstinapura were placed on this spot 1. 118.
16-17; (9) Certain other epic events in
which the Gaṅgā is referred to: (i) At
Pramāṇakoṭi, Duryodhana tied up Bhīma,
while he was asleep, and threw him in the
waters of the Gaṅgā 1. 55. 10; 3. 13. 74;
(ii) Droṇa with his pupils once went to the
Gaṅgā for bathing when a crocodile caught
him by his ankle (जङ्घान्ते) 1. 123. 69;
(iii) When Drupada was brought captive by
his pupils to Droṇa, the latter told Drupada
that in future he (Drupada) would rule over
the Pañcāla country which lay to the south
of the Bhāgīrathī while he (Droṇa) himself
would rule over the part of the country which
lay to its north; Drupada then established
himself in the capital city of Kampilya in the
countryside of Mākandī on the river Gaṅgā
ruling the southern Pāñcālas as far as the
river Carmaṇvatī 1. 128. 12, 15; 1. 154. 24;
(iv) Drupada while reaming along the bank
of the Gāṅgā, came across a settlement of the
Brāhmaṇas (ब्राह्मणावसथ) 1. 155. 5;
(v) The Aṅgāraparṇa episode: The Pāṇḍa-
vas on their way to the Pañcālas reached the
Somaśravāyaṇa तीर्थ on the river Gaṅgā;
Aṅgāraparṇa, king of the Gandharvas, had
already arrived there to sport with his wives
in the waters of the river Gaṅgā Bhāgīrathī;
he was angered when he heard the voice of
the Pāṇḍavas approaching the river; he told
the Pāṇḍavas to leave the place as the forest
along the rivers Gaṅgā and Vākā belonged
to him; Arjuna questioned the sole right of
the Gandharva over the river either at night,
or by day, or in twilight (नद्याम् अस्याम्
 … कस्य कॢप्तः परिग्रहः 1. 158. 15);
it was therefore not proper for the Gan-
dharva to withhold the river from others
since that was against the age old custom
(कथम् इच्छसि तां रोद्धुं नैष धर्-
मः सनातनः 1. 158. 20); why should the
Pāṇḍavas be restrained from touching the
waters of the Bhāgīrathī 1. 158. 2, 4, 5, 11,
13, 15, 20, 21; defeat of Aṅgāraparṇa in
this episode alluded to in 1. 2. 86; later the
Gandharva and the Pāṇḍavas took leave of
each other on the bank of the Bhāgīrathī
1. 174. 5; (vi) Arjuna, during the period
of his exile, entered the river Gaṅgā for
bathing; as he wanted to come out of the
water he was dragged by Ulūpī in the water
of that river 1. 206. 11-13; (vii) Arjuna,
during his exile, while going to the east,
crossed many rivers one of them being the
Gaṅgā 1. 207. 5-6; (viii) Kṛṣṇa, Bhīma
and Arjuna crossed the rivers Mālā, Carmaṇ-
vatī and Gaṅgā on their way to the Magadha
2. 18. 21; (ix) On account of the cries of
thousands of animals that were burnt at the
Khāṇḍava forest the fish in the waters (?)
of the Gaṅgā were terrified 1. 219. 28
(तेन शब्देन वित्रेसुर् गङ्गोदधिचरा
झषाः; Nī. on Bom. Ed. 1. 228. 32: गङ्गो-
दोधिचरा इति अतिदूरस्थोपलक्षणम्); (x)
The Pāṇḍavas spent their first night of forest
life under a banyan tree called Pramāṇa on
the river Jāhnavī; they bathed in it and had
only the water of the Jāhnavī to drink for
the night 3. 1. 39-40; from the bank of the
river Jāhnavī they started towards the Kuru-
kṣetra 3. 6. 1; (xi) On the mountain
Himavant Arjuna took bath in the Gaṅgā
before ascending Indra's chariot to go to the
Indraloka 3. 43. 20; (xii) Bhīṣma once
lived as a मुनि on the bank of the river
Bhāgīrathī practising the vow taken by his
father (पित्र्यं व्रतम्); there he heard
from Pulastya the fruit obtained by visiting
the तीर्थस् 3. 80. 11-12; there, on the bank
of the Gaṅgā, he also heard the narrative of
Vipula from Mārkaṇḍeya 13. 43. 17; (xiii)
When the Pāṇḍavas were near the Gandha-
mādana mountain (3. 155. 34) Yudhiṣṭhira
showed to Bhīma the river Mahāgaṅgā 3.
155. 69, 85; (xiv) The basket (मञ्जूषा)
containing the newly born Karṇa went down
from the river Aśvanadī to the Gaṅgā (via
the Carmaṇvatī and the Yamunā) and then
to the city of Campā 3. 292. 25-26; when
the Sūta Adhiratha went with his wife to the
Jāhnavī, she saw there by chance the floating
basket brought to the bank by the waves of
the Jāhnavī 3. 293. 1, 3; (xv) The army of
the Kauravas, collected for the war, spread
along the bank of the Gaṅgā 5. 19. 30;
(xvi) Kuntī, who wished to approach Karṇa
to tell him the truth about his birth, went
to the Bhāgīrathī to meet him; there on the
bank of the Gaṅgā she heard the sound of
the prayers recited by Karṇa 5. 142. 26-27;
(xvii) Arjuna wishing to propitiate Śiva
to seek his help in fulfilling the vow to kill
Jayadratha saw the Gaṅgā on his way 7. 57.
24; (xviii) Bhīma, in search of Aśva-
tthāman, reached the bank of the Bhāgīrathī
where he saw Vyāsa and the other sages seated
on the bank (उदकान्ते) 10. 13. 12-13;
(xix) After the great war, Kṛpa, Aśvatthā-
man and Kṛtavarman, after their meeting
with Dhṛtarāṣṭra, rode fast on horse-back to-
wards the Gaṅgā 11. 10. 19; (xx) Bhīṣma,
having narrated to Yudhiṣṭhira the Itihāsa
connected with the praise of the Gaṅgā
(इतिहासं … गङ्गायाः स्तवसंयुतम्), ad-
vised him to approach the Gaṅgā with great
devotion in order to obtain the highest per-
fection (सिद्धिम् उत्तमाम्); he and his
brothers were delighted to hear this Itihāsa
of the Gaṅgā from Bhīṣma 13. 27. 103-104;
(xxi) When Dhṛtarāṣṭra decided to retire to
the forest he, along with Gāndhārī, Kuntī,
Vidura and Saṃjaya, went in a day a long
distance from Hastinapura and camped on
the bank of the Bhāgīrathī; next morning
they started from there towards the north
15. 24. 16, 23; after going some distance they
again camped on the bank of the Bhāgīrathī;
in the evening he and Gāndhārī went to the
Gaṅgā and performed the prescribed puri-
ficatory rites (चकार विधिवच् छौचम्);
Vidura and other men performed individually
all the necessary rites (चक्रुः सर्वाः क्रियास्
तत्र पुरुषा विदुरादयः) after bathing in
the various तीर्थस् (तीर्थेष्व् आप्लुत्य); when
the purificatory rites were over Kuntī led
Dhṛtarāṣṭra and Gāndhārī to the bank of the
Gaṅgā; there the priests of the king laid a
Vedī (कृतो वेदीपरिस्तरः) on which Dhṛta-
rāṣṭra gave offerings in the fire; from the
bank of the Bhāgīrathī they all proceeded to
the Kurukṣetra 15. 25. 1, 4-8; (10) Meet-
ing with the dead: Vyāsa asked Dhṛtarāṣṭra
and all those staying with him to go to the
bank of the Bhāgīrathī to meet all those
who fell in the war; accordingly all of them
went to the Gaṅgā and resided there 15. 39.
18-22; then in the evening Vyāsa bathed in
the Bhāgīrathī and invoked all those who
fought on the side of the Pāṇḍavas and the
Kauravas; at his call, all the kings, Bhīṣma,
Droṇa, and the rest, together with their armies,
rose in thousands from the water (of the
Bhāgīrathī) 15. 40. 4, 7, 13; after some time,
at the instance of Vyāsa, they again dis-
appeared plunging into the river Tripathagā
(Gaṅgā) and repaired to their respective
places; then Vyāsa, standing in the water
(of the Tripathagā), told the Kaurava women
that those who wished to obtain the worlds
of their respective deceased husbands should
quickly enter the water of the Jāhnavī; the
women, fully believing the words of Vyāsa,
took permission of Dhṛtarāṣṭra and entered
the water of the Jāhnavī; freed of their bodies
they were united with their husbands and
acquired the worlds of their husbands 15.
41. 13, 17-21; (11) End of Dhṛtarāṣṭra,
Gāndhārī and Kuntī: When Nārada arrived
at Hāstinapura to meet Yudhiṣṭhira he paid
a visit to the Gaṅgā on his way; people
residing near the Gaṅgā had told Yudhi-
ṣṭhira that Dhṛtarāṣṭra was engaged in
severe austerities; Yudhiṣṭhira therefore
asked Nārada if he had met Dhṛtarāṣṭra
and the rest during his visit to the Gaṅgā
and how they fared; Nārada told him that
after their last meeting with Dhṛtarāṣṭra the
latter had repaired to the Gaṅgādvāra; once,
after his bath in the Gaṅgā, when Dhṛta-
rāṣṭra had started for his hermitage, wind
arose, fire engulfed the forest, and burnt it
(गङ्गायाम् आप्लुतो धीमान् आशृअमाभिमुखो
ऽभवत् 15. 45. 18); Dhṛtarāṣṭra, Gāndhārī
and Kuntī were burnt in the fire; only Saṃ-
jaya escaped from the forest fire and was
seen, surrounded by ascetics, by Nārada
on the bank of the Gaṅgā 15. 45. 5-6, 10,
29-32; Nārada further informed Yudhiṣṭhira
that Dhṛtarāṣṭra was burnt on the bank of
the Jāhnavī not by the ordinary fire but by
the sacred fire which Dhṛtarāṣṭra himself
and his priests had left after performing the
rites (i. e. the forest fire was caused by the
sacred fire left by Dhṛtarāṣṭra) (नासौ वृथा-
ग्निना दग्धो यथा तत्र श्रुतं मया);
this was reported to Nārada by the sages
whom he met on the bank of the Bhāgīrathī
15. 47. 1-6; when asked by Nārada to give
the water offerings to Dhṛtarāṣṭra, Gāndhārī
and Kuntī (कर्तुम् अर्हसि कौन्तेय तेषां
त्वम् उदकक्रियाम्), Yudhiṣṭhira went to the
Gaṅgā with his brothers and wife; there,
going into the water, they all offered water
(ददुस् तोयम्) and stayed outside the city
to undergo purification (शौचं निवर्तय-
न्तः) 15. 47. 9-13; (12) Ulūpī entered the
Gaṅgā when, at the end, the Pāṇḍavas and
Draupadī started for the forest 17. 1. 25;
F. Past and mythological events in which
the river Gaṅgā figures: (1) Past events:
(i) Bhagīratha brought her down from the
heaven: The sage Kapila had told Aṃśu-
mant, the grandson of Sagara, that his
grandson will bring down the Tripathagā
from the heaven by propitiating Maheśvara
for the purification of the burnt sons of
Sagara 3. 107. 27; however, the descent of
the Gaṅgā from the heaven was first attem-
pted by Dilīpa, father of Bhagīratha, with-
out success 3. 106. 38; Bhagīratha, desirous
of seeking the favour of the Gaṅgā, went
to the Himavant to practise austerities 3.
107. 4; after one thousand years the Gaṅgā
appeared before Bhagīratha in a bodily form
3. 107. 14; when requested by Bhagīratha to
wash the bones (शरीराणि) of the sons of
Sagara so that they might go to heaven,
she agreed, but first asked Bhagīratha to
propitiate Śiva by तपस् so that he might
agree to hold her on his head; no one else
could check her speed when she descended from
heaven; Bhagīratha succeeded in securing a
boon from Śaṅkara to hold the Gaṅgā 3.
107. 18-25; Śiva assured Bhagīratha to
hold the Devanadī (Gaṅgā) when she came
down from heaven; Śiva then went to the
Himavant and asked Bhagīratha to request
the daughter of the king of the mountains
(Gaṅgā not directly named) to come down
from the heaven; when Bhagīratha thought
of the Gaṅgā (गङ्गां समनुचिन्तयत्
3. 108. 5), the river descended from heaven
on Śiva's forehead; the river became triple
while flowing thence to the ocean (सा ब-
भूव विसर्पन्ती त्रिधा राजन् समुद्रगा
3. 108. 10); the river asked Bhagīratha to
show her the way; Bhagīratha led her to the
place where lay the bones (शरीऋआणि) of the
sons of Sagara; after holding the Gaṅgā on
his head Hara went to the Kailāsa; Bhagī-
ratha having reached the ocean with the
Gaṅgā filled it with the water of the river;
Bhagīratha made Gaṅgā his daughter (दुहि-
तृत्वे च नृपतिर् गङ्गां समनुकल्पयत्);
he offered water of the Gaṅgā to the manes
3. 108. 17; 12. 29. 62; Lomaśa thus told
Yudhiṣṭhira how the Gaṅgā came to be Tri-
pathagā (flowing in three regions-heaven,
mid-region, and the earth) and how she was
made to descend also to fill the ocean with
water (पूरणार्थं समुद्रस्य पृथिवीम्
अवतारिता) 3. 108. 2-18; the incident of the
descent of the Gaṅgā on the head of Śiva also
alluded to in 5. 109. 6; 6. 7. 28; 13. 27. 71, 87,
89, 95; 13. 106. 26; 13. 134. 17; (ii) Other
events related to Bhagīratha and the Gaṅgā:
(a) Gaṅgā Bhāgīrathī formerly sat on the
lap of Bhagīratha while he was seated on the
slope (near the river), hence she came to
be known as Urvaśī (उपह्वरे निवसतो
यस्याङ्के निषसाद ह।गङ्गा भागीऋअथी
तस्माद् उर्वशी ह्य् अभवत् पुरा 12. 29. 61
(Nī. on Bom. Ed. 12. 29. 68: उर्वशी ऊरौ
वासो यस्याः सा इति योगात्।ऊर्वसीत्य् अपेक्षिते
ह्रस्वत्वं वर्णविपर्यश् च पृषोदरादि-
त्वात् ज्ञेयः); (b) From the lake Bindu-
saras Bhagīratha watched Bhāgīrathī Gaṅgā
and lived there for many years 2. 3. 9; 6.
7. 41; (c) Bhagīratha gave on the Gaṅgā
a myriad of hundreds of cows (गवां
शतानाम् अयुतम्) 13. 106. 37; he gave
gifts (of cows ?) which would cover the
entire current of the Gaṅgā (स्रोतश् च
यावद् गङ्गायाश् छन्नम् आसीज् जगत्पते।
दक्षिणाभिः प्रवृत्ताभिः) 13. 106. 24;
(iii) Jahnu and the Gaṅgā: The Gaṅgā
became the daughter of Jahnu (दुहितृत्वम्
अनुप्राप्ता गङ्गा यस्य (i. e. जह्नोः))
13. 4. 3; Jahnu waited on her (जह्नुर्
जाह्नविसेविता) 13. 151. 44; (iv) King
Yayāti, desirous of arranging a Svayaṃvara
for his daughter Mādhavī, went to a hermitage
situated on the confluence of the Gaṅgā and
the Yamunā; his sons Pūru and Yadu put
their sister on a chariot and rushed to the
same hermitage 5. 118. 1-2; the entire region
between the Gaṅgā and the Yamunā in the
middle of the earth was given by Yayāti to
his son Pūru as his kingdom (गङ्गायमु-
नयोर् मध्ये कृत्स्नो ऽयं विषियस् तव।
मध्ये पृथिव्यास् त्वं राजा) 1. 82. 5;
(v) A battle was fought between Haryaśva
and the Haihayas, the kinsmen of Vītahavya,
in the region lying between the Gaṅgā and
the Yamunā; in this battle Haryaśva was
killed 13. 31. 11; Divodāsa, son of Sudeva,
established Vārāṇasī on the north bank of the
Gaṅgā and to the south of Gomatī (to avoid
the attack by the Haihayas) 13. 31. 18, 16;
when, later, Pratardana, the son of Divodāsa,
wanted to attack the Vaitahavyas (= Hai-
hayas) he crossed the river Gaṅgā 13. 31. 35;
(vi) On the river Gaṅgā, near Kanyakubja,
king Gādhi married his daughter Satyavatī to
Ṛcīka Bhārgava 3. 115. 17; (vii) The sage
Cyavana Bhārgava once took the vow of
staying in water for twelve years (उदवास-
कृतारम्भो बभूव सुमहाव्रतः … वर्-
षाणि द्वादश मुनिर् जलवासे धृतव्रतः)
13. 50. 3-4; he became stiff like a post
(स्थाणुभूतः) and after worshipping the
deities entered the waters of the Gaṅgā and
the Yamunā; he withstood with his head the
terrific current of the two rivers; the two
rivers, and those which followed them, made
a प्रदक्षिणा of the sage and did not cause
harm to him; the sage slept in the waters like
a log of wood and then stood erect (अन्तर्
जले स सुष्वाप काष्ठभूतो महामुनिः।
ततश् चोर्ध्वस्थितो धीमान् अभवद् भर-
तर्षभ) 13. 50. 6-9; (viii) Sage Cyavana
took his residence for some time on the bank of
the river Gaṅgā to observe a व्रत 13. 53. 55;
(ix) At a place not far from Kanyakubja
on the bank of the Gaṅgā is the Aśvatīrtha
where from the waters of the Gaṅgā arose
a thousand horses having one black ear;
Ṛcīka, the son of Cyavana, got them by
the favour of Varuṇa 13. 4. 16-17; (x)
A certain Brāhmaṇa once lived in the city
Mahāpadma on the southern bank of the
Gaṅgā 12. 341. 1; (xi) When Śuka was
born on the mountain Meru (मेरुपृष्ठे),
Gaṅgā in her original form (स्वरूपिणी)
arrived there to bathe him 12. 311. 12;
(xii) Once, Suvarṇaṣṭhīvin, the young son
of Sṛñjaya, accompanied by his nurse, ran
while playing on the bank of the Bhāgīrathī;
he was then attacked by Indra's वज्र in
the form of a tiger 12. 31. 31; (xiii) Gau-
tama and his brothers put their eldest brother
Dīrghatamas in a wooden box and put it on
the Gaṅgā; king Bali, who had gone to bathe
in the river Gaṅgā (not named), saw the box
brought to him by the current of the water
1. 98. 18, 21; (xiv) When the Kṣatriyas
were destroyed by Rāma Jāmadagnya, Aṅga,
the son of Diviratha, was protected by Gau-
tama on the bank of the Gaṅgā 12. 49. 72;
(xv) Bharata, the son of Duḥṣanta, offered
on different rivers a thousand horse-sacrifices
of which he bound fourteen horses on the river
Gaṅgā (यो बद्ध्वा … अश्वान् देवेभ्यो …
गङ्गाम् अनु चतुर्दश॥अश्वमेधसह-
स्रेण … इष्टवान् स महातेजा दौःषन्तिर्
भरतः पुरा॥) 12. 29. 41-42; (xvi)
Bharadvāja, when he went to the Gaṅgā for
bath, saw there the Apsaras Ghṛtācī who
had also come there to bathe 1. 154. 2;
(xvii) Vasiṣṭha turned the Gaṅgā, proceed-
ing towards the Kailāsa, to the Mānasa lake;
when that lake got mixed with the river,
the Gaṅgā became the Sarayū 13. 140. 23-24;
(xviii) Rājadharman, the son of Kaśyapa
and Dākṣāyaṇī, offered to Gautama, his guest,
large fishes (महामीनाः) obtained from the
regions through which the river Gaṅgā flew
12. 164. 4; (xix) A certain Brāhmaṇa,
Kauśika by name, told the truth to the robbers
about the whereabouts of the people who
were afraid of them; by this act he incurred
sin on the river Gaṅgā 12. 110. 8 (reference
to 8. 49. 41-46 where in st. 32 Gaṅgā is
not named); (xx) The following persons
attained perfection (सिद्धि) on the Gaṅgā:
(1) Śilavṛtti, when instructed by Siddha on
the virtues of the Tripathā, worshipped the
Gaṅgā according to the rites and attained
perfection which was very difficult to attain;
Siddha himself, after instructing Śilarati,
entered the sky 13. 27. 101-102; (2) Sage
Sanatkumāra attained great perfection on the
Gaṅgā 3. 135. 6; (xxi) Indra, in the form
of a very weak Brāhmaṇa, appeared before
Yavakrī and started doing an impossible
deed viz. constructing a dam in the Bhāgī-
rathī by filling the Gaṅgā with sand; he
poured constantly handfuls of sand in the
Bhāgīrathī; when asked by Yavakrī smilingly
why he was busy with this fruitless effort
Indra told him that he wanted to construct
a dam in the Gaṅgā so that the river can be
crossed easily 3. 135. 30-36; (2) Mytho-
logical: (i) Gaṅgā once went to pay a
visit to Pitāmaha (Brahmadeva) in his as-
sembly; there her garment was displaced by
the wind; King Mahābhiṣa, who happened to
be there, constantly looked at her in that
condition; he was therefore cursed to be born
again as a human being; Gaṅgā returned
from the assembly continuing to think about
Mahābhīṣa; she saw the Vasus, dejected,
going along the way; she asked them the
cause of their dejection; the Vasus told her
that they were cursed by Vasiṣṭha to be born
as humans; they requested Gaṅgā to assume
a human form so that she could give birth
to them as humans; Gaṅgā agreed and asked
them whom would they like to be their father;
they chose Śaṃtanu, the son of Pratīpa;
Gaṅgā also had thought of the same person,
hence she would do what was dear to the king
and to the Vasus; Vasus requested Gaṅgā to
throw them into water no sooner they were
born; Gaṅgā agreed to even that request,
but asked them to spare one of them so that
Śaṃtanu's union with her would not be totally
fruitless; Vasus consented to do that, each
one of them contributing one-eighth share for
Gaṅgā's son; and they also told her that the
son of the Gaṅgā would beget no son; having
come to this agreement with the Gaṅgā
the Vasus, delighted, went their way 1. 91.
4-22; (ii) The lustre (तेजः 13. 84. 11)
of Rudra fell in Agni; Agni was to beget
through that lustre a son on the Gaṅgā for
killing the enemy of the gods; Agni went
to the Gaṅgā Bhāgīrathī and became mixed
with her; as a result, Gaṅgā became pregnant;
Gaṅgā could not bear the embryo, was men-
tally distressed, and was in great agony;
when Agni laid the lustrous embryo in the
Gaṅgā, an Asura (not named) roared fiercely;
terrified, the Gaṅgā was unable to bear the
embryo; Jāhnavī, with her body covered with
lustre and trembling, told Agni that she could
not contain his lustre within her; she was
very much uneasy and was agitated; she
would like to cast away the embryo, as she
could hold it no longer, and not because of
her sweet will; she was no longer her usual
self; Agni, however, asked her to contain the
embryo within her: as she was capable of
bearing and containing the whole earth there
was nothing which Gaṅgā could not achieve
except (perhaps) containing the seed of Agni;
in spite of the entreaties of Vahni and the
other gods the Gaṅgā cast off the embryo on
mount Meru; Gaṅgā was capable of holding
an embryo, but she could not do it on this
occasion as she was overcome by the lustre
of Rudra; when she cast it off, she appeared
before Agni who asked her if the delivery
was happy (कच्चिद् गर्भः सुखोदयः);
he asked her to describe to him the colour,
the form and the lustre of the child; having
described to Agni the form of his son the god-
dess (देवी) Gaṅgā disappeared 13. 84. 8, 12,
52-72; 9. 43 8-9 (where the embryo is said
to have been cast off on the mountain Hima-
vant; when the embryo was cast off that part
of the mountain became of gold 9. 43. 14);
the son Kumāra was first Gāṅgeya (son of
Gaṅgā), then became Kārttikeya (the son of
the Kṛttikās); the Gaṅgā, the best among the
rivers, waited on him 9. 43. 20; when the
child approached Śiva, Pārvatī, Gaṅgā and
Pāvaka (Agni) each one of them wondered
whom he would show his honour by going to
him or her first (किं नु पूर्वम् अयं
बालो गौरवाद् अभ्युपैष्यति।अपि माम् इति
सर्वेषाम् तेषाम् आसीद् मनोगतम्) 9. 43.
34-35; knowing their mind the child assumed
four forms (ततो ऽभवच् चतुर्मूर्तिः), of
which the form Naigameṣa went to the Gaṅgā
9. 43. 37, 39; then all the four, Rudra, Devī,
Pāvaka and the Gaṅgā, bowed down to Pitā-
maha (Brahmadeva) and requested him to
grant Kumāra the overlordship of all beings
i. e. of the kings of all the classes of gods
(आधिपत्यम्; सेनापत्यम् ददौ तस्मै
सर्वभूतेषु भारत।सर्वदेवनिकायानां
ये राजानः परिश्रुताः।तान् सर्वान् व्यादि-
देशास्मै सर्वभूतपितामहः) 9. 43. 42,
44, 48, 49; when the gods gave different gifts
to Kumāra, Gaṅgā gave him a divine water
vessel which was the source of the nectar
(कमण्डलुं दिव्यम् अमृतोद्भवम् उत्त-
मम्) 9. 45. 45; people call Kumāra diffe-
rently the son of Pitamaha, or of Maheśvara,
or of Umā, or of the Kṛttikās, or of the
Gaṅgā 9. 45. 86; the incident is also allud-
ed to in 3. 207. 4; 13. 27. 87 (इयं गाङ्गा
 … गुहस्य रुक्मस्य च गर्भयोषा; Nī.
on Bom. Ed. 13. 26. 88: गर्भयोषा गर्भ-
धारिणी स्त्री); (iii) Once when the gods
performed a सत्र in the Naiṃiṣa forest (3.
189. 1), they saw a (golden) lotus coming
floating on the river Bhāgīrathī; to find out
its source, Indra went to the place of the
origin of the Gaṅgā (यत्र गङ्गा सततं
संप्रसूता); he saw there a woman weeping
while standing in the water of the river; the
tear which fell in the water became a golden
lotus 1. 189. 10-11; (iv) When, in former
times, Pitāmaha (Brahmadeva) once per-
formed a sacrifice on the Mahendra mountain,
Bhāgīrathī was present in the सदस् (यत्र
भागीरथी पुण्या सदस्यासीत्) 3. 85. 17;
(v) When the fish, reared by Manu, outgrew
the size of the large वापी, it requested Manu
to take it to the Gaṅgā, the chief wife of the
ocean (समुद्रमहीषीम् … गङ्गाम्); as
requested, Manu took the fish to the Gaṅgā
and put it in its water; when the fish further
so grew in size that it could not move in the
Gaṅgā (गङ्गायां हि न शक्नोमि बृहत्वाच्
देष्टितुं प्रभो), it requested Manu to take
it to the ocean; accordingly Manu pulled it
out of the Gaṅgā and took it to the ocean
3. 185. 18-19, 21-22; (vi) Nārada, once
early in the morning, descended into the water
of the Gaṅgā arising at the Dhruvadvāra to
take bath (पिस्पृक्षुः); Indra also happened
to go there; both of them bathed in its water
(आप्लुत्य) and, with controlled mind, per-
formed जप; then they sat down on the bank,
covered with thin golden sand, to tell each
other stories told by gods and sages narrat-
ing holy deeds (पुण्यकर्मभिर् आख्याता
देवर्षिकथिताः कथाः) 12. 221. 6-9; (vii)
The two rivers, the Gaṅgā and the Sarasvatī,
became the eyebrows of Nārāyaṇa when he
assumed a different form by his mighty device
(ऐश्वरेण प्रयोगेण द्वितीयां तनुम् आश्री-
तः) to get back the Vedas stolen by the two
Dānavas Madhu and Kaiṭabha 12. 335. 43,
46; (viii) Mṛtyu, conceived as a woman
(12. 249. 15-18), avoiding to kill men, went
to the river Gaṅgā on the mountain Meru
and stood there motionless like a piece of
wood 12. 250. 22; (ix) Mārkaṇḍeya saw the
Gaṅgā, among other rivers, in the belly of
the Bāla (3. 186. 83, i. e. Nārāyaṇa 3. 187.
3) 3. 186. 93; (x) When Śiva asked Umā
to instruct him in the duties of women (स्त्री-
धर्म 13. 134. 10), she first wanted to
consult the rivers, the Gaṅgā and others, who
were expert in that subject (स्त्रीधर्म-
कुशलाः); when Umā approached the rivers
they appointed the Gaṅgā to address Umā
on their behalf; the river told Umā that they
felt blessed since Umā held them in high
esteem, but it was indeed Umā who was the
right person to instruct them in the स्त्री-
धर्म; when the goddess (Umā) was thus
honoured by the Gaṅgā she discoursed on the
स्त्रीधर्मस् to them 13. 134. 17-30; (xi)
Once, when the ocean asked the rivers why
they carried away large trees but not the
small and weak cane growing on their banks,
the Gaṅgā told him the reason convincingly
giving the grounds 12. 114. 3-7; (xii)
Rāma crossed (the Gaṅgā) at Śṛṅgaverapura
3. 83. 4; (xiii) Once, while Śiva was
seated on the peak of the mountain Meru
and was being attended upon by gods and
others, the Gaṅgā in bodily form (रूपिणी)
waited on him 12. 274. 16.
G. Similes:
The Gaṅgā, in various aspects, figures as an
उपमान: (1) To compare an army with:
(i) The army of Duryodhana, returning to
the Hāstinapura, with its white parasols,
banners, and the very white chowries was an
image of the current of the Gaṅgā (गङ्-
गौघप्रतिमा चमूः) 3. 240. 42; (ii)
The army of Duryodhana, eleven अक्षौहिणीस्
strong, looked like the Gaṅgā while at some
distance from the Yamunā (गङ्गेव यमु-
नान्तरे) 6. 18. 18; (iii) The army of the
Pāṇḍavas proceeding to the battle-field looked
full and irresistible like the Gaṅgā (गङ्गेव
पूर्णा दुर्धर्षा) 5. 149. 49; (iv) The
army, led by Dhṛṣṭadyumna, with its formid-
able archers looked full, tranquil and flowing
like the Gaṅgā (भीमधन्वायनी सेना …
गङ्गेव पूर्णा स्तिमिता स्यन्दमाना व्यदृ-
श्यत) 5. 197. 10 (Nī. on Bom. Ed. 5. 196.
12: भीमधन्वानः अयन्ते प्रचरन्त्य्
अस्याम् इति भीमधन्वायनी); 6. 19. 17;
(v) Just as the sweet water of the Gaṅgā
becomes salty due to the property of the
ocean, similarly the valour of the heroes of
Duryodhana would be futile on meeting the
Pāṇḍavas 6. 79. 5-6; (vi) Duryodhana
desired to cross (the army of the Pāṇḍa-
vas) as one would want to cross in rainy
season the current of the Gaṅgā full of
sharks, alligators and crocodiles (सग्राहन-
क्रमकरं गङ्गावेगम् इवोष्णगे; Nī.
on Bom. Ed. 5. 139. 11: उष्णगे उष्णातिगमे
वर्षाकले) 5. 137. 11; (vii) Bhīma would
enter the army of the Kauravas as does the
current of the Gaṅgā the trees growing on
its banks 5. 50. 35; (viii) The Trigartas
(five brothers), in the war, would agitate
the army of the Pāṇḍavas as the crocodiles
agitate water of the Gaṅgā 5. 163. 10;
(ix) The army of the Kauravas, attacked
by Arjuna, was split into two (some going
to Droṇa, some to Duryodhana) as does the
Gaṅgā on meeting a mountain 7. 29. 29;
(x) The army of the Kauravas, at the sight
of Ghaṭotkaca, was struck with fear and was
agitated, as are the surging waves of the
Gaṅgā, whose eddies are agitated by wind
7. 131. 31; (xi) The Pāñcālas attacked the
army of Duryodhana on all sides as the
swans, returning from the Mānasa lake,
rush towards the Gaṅgā 8. 43. 64; (xii)
The army of the Pāṇḍavas was agitated by
the Madra warriors as is the Gaṅgā by the
hostile wind (पुरोवातेन गङ्गेव) 9. 17.
10; (xiii) When the Kaurava heroes (Droṇa
and others), who were ready (for attack)
at a distance of twenty steps attacked Abhi-
manyu, they appeared, for a while, like an
eddy of the Gaṅgā and the ocean (where the
former meets the latter) (ते विंशतिपदे
यत्ताः संप्रहारं प्रचक्रिरे।आसीद्
गाङ्ग इवावर्तो मुहूर्तम् उदधेर् इव)
7. 35. 13 (Nī., however, on Bom. Ed. 7. 36.
13: विंशतिर् इति व्यूहपर्यायः।तद् उक्तम्
‘विंशत्यङ्गतया व्यूहो विंशतिर् व्यपदिश्-
यते’ इति।विंशतेः पदे रक्षणे); (xiv)
The armies of Duryodhana and Yudhiṣṭhira
clashed speedily with each other as do the
swollen waters of the Gaṅgā and the Sarayū
in the rainy season 7. 16. 49; (xv) The
two large armies led by Droṇa and Dhṛsṭa-
dyumna, having clashed with each other,
sped along as do the swollen waters of the
Jāhnavī and the Yamunā in the rainy
season 7. 70. 8; (xvi) The armies led by
Karṇa and Arjuna clashed fiercely as do the
Gaṅgā and the Yamunā 8. 31. 68; (2) In
other contexts: (i) The river of smoke
which connected the heaven and the earth
looked like the river Gaṅgā (coming down
from the heaven to the earth) (भूमौ
स्वर्गे च संबद्धाम् नदीं धूम-
मयीम् नृपः (= ययातिः)।स गङ्गाम् इव
गच्छन्तीम् आलम्ब्य जगतीपतिः) 5. 119.
12; (ii) The sages (the Vālakhilyas and
others) sat near the Sarasvatī adorning it as
do the gods the river Gaṅgā 9. 36. 47; (iii)
Duḥṣanta entered the forest on the river
Mālinī which was like the hermitage of Nara
and Nārāyaṇa on the river Gaṅgā 1. 64. 24;
(iv) King Bṛhadratha between his two wives
looked like the ocean in the bodily form
between the Gaṅgā and the Yamunā (गङ्गा-
यमुनयोर् मध्ये मूर्तिमान् इव सागरः)
2. 16. 19; (v) King Divodāsa enjoyed
pleasures with Mādhavī as does the ocean
with the Jāhnavī 5. 115. 10; (vi) The eye-
brow with its three tips on the forehead of
the angered Bhīma looked like the Gaṅgā
flowing in three courses on the Trikūṭa (त्रि-
शिखां भ्रुकुटीम् चास्य ददृशुः सर्व-
पार्थिवाः।ललाटस्थां त्रिकूटस्थां गङ्-
गां त्रिपथगाम् इव) 2. 39. 11; (vii)
As the Gaṅgā is the best among the rivers,
so is the Kapilā among the cows (यथा
हि गङ्गा सरितां वरिष्ठा तथार्जुनीनाम्
कपिला वरिष्ठा) 13. 72. 40; (viii) A
certain Nāga named Padma was born in a
family which was (pure) like the water of
the Gaṅgā (गङ्गाह्रदाम्भो ऽभिजनोप-
पन्नः) 12. 343. 11; (ix) A man who
does not have anything desirable never gets
anything that is splendid; he goes into noth-
ing as does the Gaṅgā on reaching the ocean
(प्रियाभावाच् च पुरुषो नैव प्राप्नोति
शोभनम्।ध्रुवं चाभावम् अभ्येति
गत्वा गङ्गेव सागरम्) 5. 133. 16; (x)
Wealth causes hankering after it as does the
sweet water of the Gaṅgā (अनुतर्षुल एवार्-
थः स्वादु गाङ्गम् इवोदकम्) 12. 171.
28; (xi) Gaṅgā is comparable to the earth
in forbearance, protection and sustenance; to
the fire and the sun in brightness; and to
Guha in being always favourable to the
Brāhmaṇas (क्षान्त्या मह्या गोपने धारणे
च दीप्त्या कृशानोस् तपनस्य चैव।तुल्या
गङ्गा संमता ब्राह्मणानाम् गुहस्य
ब्रह्मण्यतया च नित्यम्॥) 13. 27. 91.
H. Measure: (1) King Amūrtarayasa Gaya
gave away in a horse sacrifice as many cows
as there is sand on the river Gaṅgā 12. 29.
111; (2) Śaibya, the son of Uśīnara, gave
in a sacrifice as दक्षिणा as many cows as
would, while drinking (the water of the
Gaṅgā), drink up the current of the Gaṅgā
(? पिबन्त्यो दक्षिणां यस्य गण्गास्रोतः
समपिबन्।तावतीर् गा ददौ वीर उशी-
नरसुतो ऽध्वरे॥) 7. 9. 62. [See Alaka-
nandā, Ākāśagaṅga, Āpaga2, Urvaśī, Gangā-
dvara, Gaṅgāhrada, Vaitaraṇī]

गङ्ग
Gaṅga2 f.: Name of one of the rivers
of the Śākadvīpa 6. 12. 29, (26).
All the rivers are described as having
holy water (पुण्यजलाः) 6. 12. 29, (पुण्यो-
दाः) 6. 12. 31; holy and excellent (पुण्यास्
ता हि सरिद्वराः) 6. 12. 32; Gaṅgā is
described as having many streams (बहुधा-
गतिः) 6. 12. 29.

गङ्गाद्वार
Gaṅgādvāra nt.: Name of the place
where the Gaṅgā enters the plains.
A. Location: On the river Bhāgīrathī
3. 80. 12-13; the place where the Gaṅgā cleft
with force the Himavant mountain is called
the Gaṅgādvāra (शैलं शिखरिणां वरम्
बिभेद तरसा गङ्गा गङ्गाद्वारे युधि-
ष्ठिर) 3. 88. 18; on the Himavant moun-
tain 9. 37. 26; the Koṭitīrtha is located at the
Gaṅgādvāra 3. 82. 23.
B. Description:
Holy (पुण्य) 3. 80. 13; (पुण्यं तत्
ख्यायते) 3. 88. 18; auspicious (शुभ) 3.
80. 13; visited by the Brahmanical sages
(ब्रह्मर्षिगणसेवित) 3. 88. 18, by the
divine sages (देवर्षिसेवित), and by the gods
and the Gandharvas (देवगन्धर्वसेवित)
3. 80. 13; comparable with the gate of the
heaven (स्वर्गद्वारेण यत् तुल्यम्) 3. 82.
23.
C. Holiness: (1) One who bathes
there is freed of sins and goes to heaven
13. 26. 12. (According to Nī. on Bom. Ed.
13. 25. 13 Gaṅgādvāra in this stanza refers
to the place on the river Godāvarī on the
Brahmagiri mountain: गङ्गाद्वारादयो ऽत्र
ब्रह्मगिरौ गोदावर्यनुगता एव ग्राह्याः
भागीरथीमाहात्म्यस्य अग्रे स्वातन्त्र्येण
वर्ण्यमानत्वात्).
D. Importance: Finds
mention in the Daivata-Ṛṣi-Vaṃśa 13. 151.
21, 2.
E. Events: (1) Epic events:
(i) Arjuna, during his exile, settled down
there for some time (निवेशम् अकरोत्);
during his stay the place looked very splendid
with the presence of the learned, self-
controlled and righteous Brāhmaṇas who
offered many अग्निहोत्रस् and flower offerings
between the banks (?) (कृतपुष्पोपहारेषु
तीरान्तरगतेषु च) 1. 206. 6, 8-10; (ii)
Since the path leading to the Śveta and the
Mandara mountains was difficult, Yudhiṣṭhira
suggested that Bhīma and the rest might
return and wait for him at the Gaṅgādvāra
3. 141. 7; (iii) Jayadratha, humiliated by
the Pāṇḍavas, went to the Gaṅgādvāra and
practised austerities to satisfy Śiva 3. 256. 24;
(iv) Bhīṣma once lived there and satisfied
the manes, the gods and the sages by per-
forming rites according to the prescription
(विधिदृष्टेन कर्मणा); and while he was
there he saw the great seer Pulastya 3. 80. 12-
15; Bhīṣma went to the Gaṅgādvāra to offer
श्राद्ध to Śaṃtanu 13. 83. 11; (v) From
the Kurukṣetra Dhṛtarāṣṭra, along with Gān-
dhārī, Kuntī and Saṃjaya, went to the Gaṅgā-
dvāra and practised austerities 15. 45. 10;
(vi) Yudhiṣṭhira sent many well-versed men
to the Gaṅgādvāra, where Dhṛtarāṣṭra and
others were burnt by fire, and asked them to
prepare there the receptacles for their bones
(तत्रैव तेषां कुल्यानि गङ्गाद्वारे ऽन्वशात्
तदा।कर्तव्यानीति पुरुषान् दत्तदेयान्
महीपतिः) 15. 47. 14-15 (Nī. however, on
Bom. Ed. 15. 39. 22: कुल्यानि अस्थीनि);
(vii) Bharadvāja lived there; when he there
once went to the Ganges for bath, he saw the
Apsaras Ghṛtācī bathing there 1. 154. 1-2;
(2) Past and mythological: (i) Newly
married Agastya went there with Lopāmudrā
and both practised severe austerities 3. 95. 11;
(ii) Once Dakṣa decided to offer a sacrifice;
all the gods proceeded to the Gaṅgādvāra to
take part in the sacrifice of Dakṣa 12. 274.
18, 20; the river Sarasvatī, when invited by
Brahman at the sacrifice of Dakṣa at the
Gaṅgādvāra, went to the Himavant mountain
9. 37. 26.

गङ्गारण्य
Gaṅgāraṇya nt.: Name of a forest.
Listed among the purifying and holy
spots (पवित्राणि पुण्यान्य् आयतनानि च) in
Avanti in the west 3. 87. 1, 12.

गङ्गाह्रद
Gaṅgāhrada m.: Name of various
तीर्थस् on the river Gaṅgā (referred to also
as Gāṅga hrada 5. 33. 26).
A. Holy places for bathing: (1)
Situated near the Mṛgadhūma तीर्थ; after
bathing there and worshipping Śūlapāṇi
Mahādeva one obtains the fruit of an Aśva-
medha 3. 81. 85; (2) Near the Svastipura
तीर्थ; a bath there secures heaven 3. 81. 152,
153; (3) Near the Koṭirūpa tīrtha; one who
observes chastity and has a controlled mind, if
he bathes there he obtains for ever the fruit
of a Rājasūya and an Aśvamedha (राजसूया-
श्वमेधाभ्यां फलं विन्दति शाश्वतम्)
3. 81. 171, 172; (4) Near the Utpalāvana
tīrtha; one who bathes (उपस्पृश्य) there
and offers water to manes for a month gets the
fruit of an Aśvamedha 13. 26. 33; (also see
the next Section).
B. Epic event: Duryo-
dhana entered the Gaṅgāhrada and lay con-
cealed; the Pāṇḍavas and Vāsudeva stood on
the Gaṅgāhrada and challenged Duryodhana
(for a fight) 1. 1. 151;
C. Simile: One
who is not delighted when honoured and
angered when insulted and remains unpur-
turbed is compared to the Gāṅga hrada (न
हृष्यत्य् आत्मसंमाने नावमानेन तप्यते।
गाङ्गो ह्रद इवाक्षोभ्यो यः स पण्डित
उच्यते) 5. 33. 26.

गङ्गोद्भेद
Gaṅgodbheda m.: Name of a तीर्थ।
If one visits this तीर्थ and fasts there
for three nights one obtains the fruit of a
Vājapeya sacrifice and becomes one with
Brahman (ब्रह्मभूतश् च जायते) 3. 82.
58.

गण्डकी
Gaṇḍakī f.: Name of a river, also called
Gaṇḍakīyā (2. 18. 27).
A. Location: A river in the east,
beyond the Pañcālas and near the Videhas;
Bhīma in his expedition to the east won the
country around Gaṇḍakī and the Videhas 2.
26. 4; the river Gaṇḍakīyā crossed by Kṛṣṇa,
Bhīma and Arjuna on their way to the
Magadha; situated beyond the Kālakūṭa
mountain; the three rivers Gaṇḍakīyā, Śoṇa
and Sadānīrā rise from the same mountain
(एकपर्वतके नद्यः) 2. 18. 26-27.
B.
Origin: The river was produced from the
waters of all the तीर्थस् (सर्वतीर्थजलोद्-
भवाम्)।
C. Holiness: By visiting
Gaṇḍakī one obtains the fruit of a Vājapeya
and goes to the world of Sun (सूर्यलोकं
च गच्छति) 3. 82. 97.
D. Importance:
Mentioned in the Daivata-Ṛṣi-Vaṃśa 13.
151. 16, 2. [See Gaṇḍasāhvayā].

गण्डकीया
Gaṇḍakīyā f.: See Gaṇḍakī.

गण्डसाह्वया
Gaṇḍasāhvayā f.: Name of a river,
identical with the Gaṇḍakī (?).
Mentioned among the rivers which are
called mothers of the fire-hearths i. e. on the
banks of which sacrifices were performed
(एता नद्यस् तु धिष्ण्यानां मातरो या प्र-
कीर्तिताः) 3. 212. 24 (for Nī. see Kapilā).
[See Gaṇḍakī]

गन्धतारिक
Gandhatārika nt.: Name of a तीर्थ।
By bathing there (उपस्पृश्य) and by
abstaining from food for a month (एकमासं
निराहारः) one obtains the power of becom-
ing invisible (? अन्तर्धानफलं लभेत्)
13. 26. 29 (Nī. on Bom. Ed. 13. 25. 30:
अन्तर्धानफलं गन्धर्वादिभोगम्).

गन्धमादन
Gandhamādana m.: Name of a moun-
tain.
A. Location: In the north (गच्छामो
गिरिम् उत्तरम्। … गन्धमादनम्) 5. 62.
21-22; beyond the Mālyavant mountain
(ततः परं माल्यवतः पर्वतो गन्ध-
मादनः) 6. 7. 8; an upper mountain range
of the Himavant (पर्वते गन्धमादने
 … हैमवते गिरौ) 3. 157. 1, 3; (पृष्ठे
हिमवतः) 3. 155. 16; (हिमवत्पृष्ठे) 3.
157. 8; (हिमवन्तम् अतिक्रम्य प्रययौ
गन्धमादनम्) 1. 110. 43; Arjuna crossed
the Himavant and the Gandhamādana before
reaching the Indrakīla 3. 38. 29; the river
Indratoyā flew by its side (इन्द्रतोयाम्
समासाद्य गन्धमादनसंनिधौ) 13.
26. 11; one could see from this mountain the
great river Gaṅgā (महागङ्गा) 3. 155. 85.
B. Description: Holy (puṇya) 1. 32. 4; its
peaks auspicious (शिव) 3. 157. 23; best of
the mountains (पर्वतश्रेष्थ) 1. 26. 5; 3.
156. 15; (पर्वतेन्द्र) 3. 155. 88; (नगेन्-
द्र) 3. 161. 1; (नगोत्तम) 3. 161. 3, 5, 8;
(शैलोत्तम) 3. 157. 16, 23; (गिरिम् उत्त-
मम्) 3. 142. 23; king of the mountains
(शैलराज) 3. 155. 87; 3. 157. 31; great
mountain (महाशैल) 3. 157. 15; its peak
was many palmlengths high (बहुतालोच्-
छ्रयं शृङ्गम्) 3. 157. 33; imperishable
(अव्यय) 1. 26. 5; its peak is marked
by colourful flowers (शैलोत्तमस्याग्रं
चित्रमाल्यधरं) 3. 157. 23; its peaks
are delightful in all seasons (सर्वर्तुरम-
णीयेषु गन्धमादनसानुषु) 3. 146. 19,
(रमणीयेषु) 33; rough and dreadful
(विषमं घोरं) 5. 49. 21; 5. 94.
17; it had rough as well as smooth spots
(उवास स तदा राजा समेषु विषमेषु च)
1. 110. 44; frequented by sages, Siddhas
and gods, liked by the Gandharvas and the
Apsarases, and frequented by the Kiṃnaras
(ऋषिसिद्धामरयुतं गन्धर्वाप्सरसां
प्रियम्। … किंनराचरितं गिरिम्) 3. 143.
5; 3. 146. 17; 5. 62. 22; 3. 146. 23 (which
also mentions Yakṣas and Brahmarṣis); 3.
142. 23; 3. 155. 34-35 (which also mentions
Cāraṇas, Vidhyādharas and Kiṃnarīs); 3.
155. 83, 86; also 1. 110. 44; 3. 259. 33;
where Druma, the lord of the Kiṃpuruṣas,
lived 5. 155. 3; a mountain which looked like
a bower all around (कुञ्जभूतं गिरिम्
सर्वम् अभितः) 5. 62. 22; it was like the
Nandanavana (नन्दनवनोपमा) 3. 155.
36; for the description of the mountain also
see 3. 143. 3-4; 3. 146. 17-29; 3. 155. 35-
84; 3. 156. 15-19, 25-29; 3. 157. 36; 3. 161.
3-10, 13; (also see the next section C).
C. Characteristics: (1) Kubera, along with
the Rākṣasas and in the company of the
Apsarases, enjoys himself on the peaks of the
Gandhamādana 6. 7. 32; its peak is the garden
of the gods, the Dānavas, the Siddhas and
of Vaiśravaṇa (Kubera) 3. 156. 27; 3. 259.
33; (2) Sages who lived on water and air
visited the mountain floating through the air
(प्लवमाना विहायसा) on the पर्वन् days
(पर्वसन्धिषु) 3. 156. 15; similarly Kiṃ-
puruṣas with their beloveds, the Gandharvas
and the Apsarases wearing silken garments
free from dust (अरजांसि च वासांसि वसा-
नाः कौशिकानि च), the Vidyādharas wear-
ing garlands, hosts of great Uragas and the
Suparṇas visit the mountain on the पर्वन्
days (पर्वसन्धिषु) 3. 156. 16-19; so also
on the पर्वन् days (पर्वसन्धिषु) one can
hear there the sound of kettle-drums (भेरी),
cymbals (पणव), conches (शङ्ख) and
tabors (मृदङ्ग) 3. 156. 19; (3) There
was a beautiful grove of कदली stretching
over many योजनस् on its peaks 3. 146. 42;
(4) On this mountain there is the Badarī
आश्रम of Nara and Nārāyaṇa 1. 32. 3; 3.
142. 23; 12. 321. 14; 12. 331. 22; also
the आश्रम of the royal sage Vṛṣaparvan
is close by (3. 155. 16-17) and the आश्रम
of the royal sage Ārṣṭiṣeṇa (3. 155. 90);
(5) There is also the lotus pond of Kubera
guarded by the Rākṣasas 3. 142. 24; (6)
It protects the Guhyakas (पाति … गुह्यकान्
गन्धमादनः) 8. 30. 77-78; (7) It has
many bright herbs (दीप्यमानौषधिगणम्)
5. 62. 22; (8) It has a rough abyss full
of serpents (विषमे तस्मिन् ससर्पे गिरि-
गह्वरे) 5. 62. 26; there are on this moun-
tain serpents of various forms and having
hundred heads (व्यालैश् च विविधाकारैः
शतशीर्षैः समन्ततः।उपेतम्) 3. 155.
87; (9) The region beyond the peak of the
Gandhamādana is accessible to the gods,
divine sages and the great Siddhas, but not
to ordinary mortals (अमानुषगतिः) 3. 156.
20-23; Lomaśa told the Pāṇḍavas that the
mountain could be reached by practising aus-
terities (तपसा शक्यते गन्तुम्) 3. 141. 22;
3. 142. 24-25; it cannot be reached by those
who are wicked, greedy and whose mind is
restless (न नृशंसेन लुब्धेन नाप्रशान्-
तेन) 3. 142. 25; (10) On the slopes of
the mountain there are other small hills and
the duration of life there is eleven thousand
years (गन्धमादनपादेषु परेष्व् अपर-
गण्डिकाः।एकादशसहस्राणि वर्षाणां
परमायुषः॥ 6. 7. 33; Nī. on Bom. Ed. 6.
6. 35: अपरगण्डिकाः अन्ये गन्धमादन-
स्यैवावयवभूता बुद्बुदोपमाः क्षुद्र-
शैलाः).
D. Importance: Finds mention
in the Daivata-Ṛṣi-Vaṃśa 13. 151. 27, 2.
E. Events related to the Gandhamādana:
(1) Epic: (i) Pāṇḍu, with his wives,
reached there after crossing the Himavant; he
lived there protected by the Mahābhūtas, the
Siddhas and the great sages 1. 110. 43-44;
(ii) Arjuna crossed the Himavant and the
Gandhamādana before reaching the Indrakīla
3. 38. 29-30; (iii) Yudhiṣṭhira and others,
with controlled minds (नियतात्मानः), start-
ed taking limited food (मिताहाराः) to prepare
themselves to reach the Gandhamādana moun-
tain to meet Arjuna there 3. 142. 22, 28;
the Pāṇḍavas proceed towards the mountain
aided by Ghaṭotkaca 3. 145. 2 (this event is
alluded to by Yudhiṣṭhira in 7. 158. 29);
the Pāṇḍavas and Pāñcālī reached the moun-
tain where they experienced strong wind and
heavy rain 3. 143. 2, 6, 16-17, 21; (iv)
Bhīma, in his search for the सौगन्धिक
lotus flowers roamed on the peaks of the
Gandhamādana; he went up and up the
mountain to its top (उपर्य् उपरि शैलाग्रम्)
3. 146. 33, 40; then, on the slopes of the
mountain, he saw a beautiful grove of कदली
extending over several योजनस् 3. 146. 42;
on his way he met Hanūmant and then he
roamed again on the mountain in search of the
सौगन्धिक flowers which he finally found
3. 150. 16, 18, 27 (the event on the Gandha-
mādana is referred to in the Parvasaṃgraha
where the name of the flower is मन्दार
1. 2. 112; the killing of the Krodhavaśa
demons on the Gandhamādana by Bhīma in
his effort to get the flowers is referred to by
Arjuna in 4. 66. 4, and by Saṃjaya in 5.
49. 21); (v) On their way further north to
the Śveta mountain Yudhiṣṭhira saw the
slopes of the Gandhamādana (गन्धमादन-
पादांश् च) and the forest on it 3. 155. 14,
34, 36; (vi) Arjuna met his brothers on
the Gandhamādana 3. 171. 10 (the meeting
of Arjuna and the Pāṇḍavas on the Gandha-
mādana referred to in the Parvasaṃgraha
1. 2. 122); (vii) Janamejaya asked Vaiśaṃ-
pāyana how many years did the Pāṇḍavas
live on the Gandhamādana mountain 3. 157.
1; Vaiśaṃpāyana told him that they were
there for four years and some more months;
at the end of the fourth year they arrived at
the आश्रम of Ārṣṭiṣeṇa where they passed
several months 3. 157. 9, 11; during the fifth
year wind brought to them from the top of the
(Gandhamādana) mountain divine, fragrant
flowers of five colours (पुष्पाणि … पञ्चवर्-
णानि) 3. 157. 16-17; (2) Past and mytho-
logical: (i) Nara and Nārāyaṇa practised
severe austerities on the Gandhamādana where
King Dambodbhava saw them 5. 94. 15, 17;
at that time Dakṣa performed there his sacri-
fice 12. 330. 41-42; (ii) Nārada once desc-
ended on the Gandhamādana from the summit
of the mount Meru 12. 321. 13-14; 12. 331.
22; (iii) To this mountain Aṣṭāvakra went
and to its north saw the great deity which
was the northern direction (तस्य चोत्तरतो
देशे दृष्टं तद् दैवतं महत्) 13. 22.
15, 4; (iv) Mārkaṇḍeya saw the Gandha-
mādana inside the belly of the Bāla (3. 186.
83 = Nārāyaṇa 3. 187. 4) 3. 186. 102;
(v) Rāvaṇa and his brothers lived on the
Gandhamādana mountain where they practised
severe austerities to satisfy Brahman 3. 259.
13-15; (vi) Kubera, when ousted from
the Laṅkā by Rāvaṇa, fled to the Gandha-
mādana with the Gandharvas, the Yakṣas,
 the Rakṣases and the Kiṃpuruṣas 3. 259. 33;
(vii) The Vānara named Gandhamādana,
who came to Rāma to help him, lived on this
mountain 3. 267. 5; (viii) Once, the gods
and the sages waited on Pitāmaha on the
Gandhamādana 6. 61. 37; (ix) Śeṣa went
there to practise austerities 1. 32. 3; (x)
Garuḍa, when he reached the mountain with
the huge branch in his beak, he saw there his
father Kaśyapa practising austerities 1. 26. 5;
(3) Other events: (i) Where Kṛṣṇa had
formerly observed the vow of an ascetic who
took up abode wherever he reached in the
evening (यत्रसायंगृह मुनि) for ten
thousand years 3. 13. 10 (Nī. on Bom. Ed.
3. 12. 11: यत्र सायंकालस् तत्रैव गृहं
यस्य स यत्रसायंगृह इत्य् एकं पदम्);
(ii) Rukmin learnt the entire Dhanurveda
from Druma who lived on the Gandhamādana
5. 155. 3.
F. Similes: (1) The नाराच
arrows shot by Duryodhana at Ghaṭotkaca
struck him as serpents do the Gandhamādana
6. 88. 3; (2) Bṛhatkṣatra showered arrows
on Droṇa as a big cloud showers rain on
the Gandhamādana 7. 101. 6; (3) Yudhi-
ṣṭhira's hope to defeat Bhīṣma was like a
fool's wish to ascend the Gandhamādana 5.
158. 12.

गन्धर्वतीर्थ
Gandharvatīrtha nt.: Name of a तीर्थ।
Balarāma went to the तीर्थ of the Gan-
dharvas (गन्धर्वाणां … तीर्थम्) from
Subhūmikā 9. 36. 10, (8); there the Gan-
dharvas, Viśvāvasu and others, practised aus-
terites and performed delightful dances, played
on musical instruments and sang (नृत्तवादि-
त्रगीतं च कुर्वन्ति सुमनोरमम्) 9. 36.
11; Haladhara (Balarāma) gave there wealth
of different kinds as also goats and sheep,
cows, donkeys, and camels, gold and silver
to the Brāhmaṇas; he also fed them and
satisfied them by giving large amounts of
wealth as desired; he went from the Gan-
dharvatīrtha (तस्माद् गन्धर्वतीर्थाच् च),
accompanied and praised by the Brāhmaṇas,
to the Gargasrotas 9. 36. 12-14.

गय
Gaya m.: Name of a mountain.
Situated in the east 3. 85. 3; described
as an excellent mountain (गिरिवर), holy
(पुण्य) and honoured by the royal sage
(Gaya) (राजर्षिसत्कृत) 3. 85. 6; it (the
mountain not directly named) was honoured
by the pious royal sage Gaya who knew
धर्म (ततो महीधरं जग्मुर् धर्म-
ज्ञेनाभिसत्कृतम्।राजर्षिणा पुण्यकृता ग-
येन) 3. 93. 9. [See Gayaśiras, Gayā]

गयशिरस्
Gayaśiras nt.: Name of a lake.
Situated in the east (3. 85. 3), near the
Gaya mountain and the river Mahānadī 3.
85. 8; 3. 93. 10; nearby stands the banyan
tree Akṣayyakaraṇa (i. e. Akṣayavaṭa) 3.
85. 8; mentioned among the holy places by
visiting which those that are high-souled
(महात्मानः) and have observed vows
(धृतव्रताः) become auspicious (शिवाः)
and, acquiring for themselves a divine form
(दिव्यसंस्थानाः) and wearing divine gar-
lands (दिव्यमाल्यधराः) and, endowed
with holy fragrance (पुण्यगन्धाढ्याः),
go to the Vimāna of the cows (ते तत्र
मोदन्ति गवां विमाने) 13. 105. 46, 48, 44.

गया
Gayā f.: Name of a sacred place.
A. Location: Arjuna, during the period
of his exile, came across Gayā while going
to the east 1. 207. 7, 5; the banyan tree
Akṣayavaṭa stands near it 13. 88. 14.
B.
Holy, important for offering श्राद्ध: (1)
By bathing (उपस्पृश्य) at Gayā one is
freed of the sin of ब्रह्महत्या 13. 26. 40;
(2) Just by visiting Gayā a Brahmacārī
who has controlled his sense organs gets the
fruit of an Aśvamedha; by living there in
the dark and bright fortnights one purifies,
without doubt, his lineage upto seven gene-
rations (पुनात्य् आसप्तमं राजन् कुलम्
नास्त्य् अत्र संशयः) 3. 82. 71, 84; (3)
Mentioned among the holy places by visiting
which those that are high-souled and have
observed vows go to the world of the cows
(गवां विमाने) 13. 105. 46 (for details
see Gayaśiras); (4) One of the Gāthās,
sung by the Pitṛs and recited in former
times by Sanatkumāra to Bhīṣma, said
that one should wish for many sons so that
at least one of them would go to Gayā to
offer श्राद्ध near the banyan tree Akṣayya-
karaṇa (गाथाश् चाप्य् अत्र गायन्ति पितृगीता
युधिष्ठिर।सनत्कुमारो भगवान् पुरा
मय्य् अभ्यभाषत॥ … एष्टव्या बहवः
पुत्रा यद्य् एको ऽपि गयां व्रजेत्) 13. 88.
11. 14; 3. 82. 85; 3. 85. 7; whatever is offered
for the manes there—water, roots, fruit,
meat, food or whatever is mixed with honey—
lasts for ever 13. 88. 15.
C. Past event:
Mataṅga practised austerities at Gayā by
standing on one toe for a hundred years in
order to get the status of a Brāhmaṇa (ब्राह्-
मण्यं कामयानो ऽहम्) 13. 28. 25; 13.
30. 1.
D. Importance: Finds mention in
the Daivata-Ṛṣi-Vaṃśa 13. 151. 23, 2.

गर्गस्रोतस्
Gargasrotas nt.: Name of a तीर्थ।
A. Name: Named after the old ascetic
Garga (तस्य नाम्ना च तत् तीर्थं गर्ग-
स्रोत इति स्मृतम्) 9. 36. 16;
B. Location:
On the river Sarasvatī (सरस्वत्याः शुभे
तीर्थे) 9. 36. 16.
C. Description: Great
तीर्थ (महातीर्थ) 9. 36. 14; auspicious
(शुभ) 9. 36. 16.
D. Past event: At
this तीर्थ, the aged and the high-souled
Garga, who had purified his soul by practis-
ing austerities, laid down the way to acquire
the knowledge of time, the deviations of the
luminous bodies and the portents, both
terrible and auspicious (यत्र गर्गेण वृद्-
धेन तपसा भावितात्मना।कालज्ञान-
गतिश् चैव ज्योतिषां च व्यतिक्रमः॥
उत्पाता दारुणाश् चैव शुभाश् च जन-
मेजय। … विहिता वै महात्मना) 9. 36.
15-16; there the sages, who had observed
vows, constantly waited upon Garga to obtain
knowledge of time (उपासां चक्रिरे नित्यं
कालज्ञानं प्रति) 9. 36. 17 (Nī. on Bom.
Ed. 9. 37. 17: कालज्ञानं प्रति काल-
ज्ञानार्थम्).
E. Epic event: Balarāma
reached this तीर्थ from the Gandharva-
tīrtha; there he distributed wealth to the
sages according to the prescriptions and gave
to Brāhmaṇas different kinds of food 9. 36.
18-19.

गवां
Gavāṃ tīrtham nt.: Name of a तीर्थ।
One of the holy तीर्थस् on the river
Gomatī 3. 93. 2; the Pāṇḍavas, having bathed
there, gave as gifts cows and wealth; they
satisfied gods, manes and the Brāhmaṇas at
this तीर्थ 3. 93. 2-3.

गवांभवन
Gavāṃbhavana nt.: Name of a तीर्थ।
By bathing at this तीर्थ a pilgrim
obtains the fruit of gifting a thousand cows
3. 81. 40.

गाङ्ग|गाङ्गः
Gāṅgaḥ hradaḥ: See Gaṅgāhrada.

गायत्र्याः
Gāyatryāḥ sthānam nt.: Name of a
sacred place.
Described as famous in the three worlds
(त्रैलोक्यविश्रुत); one who fasts (उपोषितः)
there for three nights gets the fruit of giving a
thousand cows 3. 83. 26; it is a direct testing
ground for the Brāhmaṇas: if a Brāhmaṇa
who is of mixed origin recites the Gāyatrī
stanza there it sounds like a गाथा (a non-
Vedic stanza) or a गीतिका (an ordinary song)
(निदर्शनं च प्रत्यक्षम् ब्राह्मणानां
नराधिप।गायत्रीं पठते यस् तु योनि-
संकरजस् तथा।गाथा वा गीतिका वापि
तस्य संपद्यते नृप॥) 3. 83. 27 (Nī.
on Bom. Ed. 3. 85. 29: निदर्शनम् उदा-
हरणम्; on 3. 85. 30: यो योनिसंकरजः
स चेत् तत्र गायत्रीम् पठति तस्य सम्यक्
पठतो ऽपि तीर्थम(? मा)हात्म्यात् सा
गायत्री गाथा स्वरनियमहीना मुखान्
निःसरति।गाथिका ग्राम्यगीतवत् स्वर-
वर्णविकृता।गीतिकेति पाठे ऽपि स एवार्-
थः।).

गायन्तिका
Gāyantikā f.: Name of a holy place
(a cave ?)
Situated in the north (on the mountain
Himavant) 5. 109. 3; the gate of this cave
is guarded by the excellent and the high-souled
sages, called Dhāmas, who speak truth (अत्र
गायन्तिकाद्वारं रक्षन्ति द्विजसत्तमाः।
धामा नाम महात्मानो मुनयः सत्य-
वादिनः॥) 5. 109. 14; as one enters it and
moves beyond this point, one gets dissolved
(यथा यथा प्रविशति तस्मात् परतरं
नरः।तथा तथा द्विजश्रेष्ठ प्रवि-
लीयति गातव॥) 5. 109. 16; no one has ever
gone beyond it except Nārāyaṇa and Nara
5. 109. 17; (Nī. who reads अत्र गङ्गां
महाद्वारं रक्षन्ति, on Bom. Ed. 5. 111.
16: गायन्तिकाद्वारम् इति पाठे गायन्तिका
बिलविशेषः).

गिरिमुञ्ज
Girimuñja m.: Name of a mountain.
Described as famous in the three worlds
(त्रिषु लोकेषु विश्रुतम्); after reaching there
and after paying reverence to Pitāmaha one
gets the fruit of gifting a thousand cows 3.
80. 102.

गृध्रकूट
Gṛdhrakūṭa m.: Name of a mountain.
When the Kṣatriyas were destroyed by
Rāma Jāmadagnya one of them, Bṛhadratha,
was protected on the Gṛdhrakūṭa by cow-
tailed monkeys (गोलाङ्गूलैः … अभिरक्षितः)
12. 49. 73.

गृध्रवट
Gṛdhravaṭa m.: Name of a sacred
place.
Sacred to the god given to meditation
(Śiva) (स्थानं देवस्य धीमतः); if a
Brāhmaṇa approaches there Vṛṣadhvaja (Śiva)
and bathes with ashes (स्नायीत भस्मना
तत्र) it is as good as his having observed a
vow for twelve years; and if other castes do
the same (इतरेषां तु वर्णानाम्) all their
sins are destroyed 3. 82. 79-80.

गोकर्ण
Gokarṇa nt., m.: Name of a sacred
place (स्थानम् 3. 261. 54) and a lake
(ह्रदः 3. 86. 13).
A. Location: In the south (दक्षिण-
स्याम्) 3. 86. 1; on the western coast (अपरा-
न्तेषु) 1. 210. 1; in the middle of the ocean
(very close to the ocean) (समुद्रमध्ये)
3. 83. 22.
B. Description: Holy (पुण्य)
1. 32. 4; 1. 210. 1; 3. 86. 1, 13; auspicious
(शिव) 3. 86. 13; famous in the three worlds
(त्रिषु लोकेषु विश्रुतम्) 3. 83. 22; (विख्या-
तं त्रिषु लोकेषु) 3. 86. 12; adored by all
people (सर्वलोकनमस्कृत) 3. 83. 22;
undisturbed (अव्यग्र) 3. 261. 54; a holy
and auspicious lake having cool and ample
water, difficult of access to those who have
not purified their souls (शीततोयो बहुजलः
पुण्यस् तात शिवश् च सः।ह्रदः परम-
दुष्प्रापो मानुषैर् अकृतात्मभिः) 3. 86.
13.
C. A place sacred to Śiva: Favourite
place of Śūlapāṇi (Śiva) (दयितम् स्थानम्
शूलपाणेः) 3. 261. 54; where Brahman and
other gods, sages, Bhūtas, Yakṣas, Piśācas,
Kiṃnaras, Mahoragas and many others, as
also rivers, oceans and mountains wait on
Umāpati (Śiva) 3. 83. 23-4; (also see
sections D and F below).
D. Holiness:
Characterized by the presence of ascetics
(गोकर्णे च तपोधनाः) 6. 7. 48; one who
worships there Īśāna (Śiva) and fasts for
three nights gets the fruit of performing
ten Aśvamedha sacrifices and the status of
a Gaṇapati (गाणपत्यं च विन्दति); by
staying there for twelve nights one has his
soul disciplined (कृतात्मा भवते नरः)
3. 83. 25 (also see section F below).
E.
Epic events: (1) During his exile Arjuna
went towards Gokarṇa from where, after
visiting the तीर्थस् on the western coast, he
went to Prabhāsa 1. 209. 24; 1. 210. 2;
(2) Arjuna, protecting the horse of the
Aśvamedha sacrifice, reached Gokarṇa from
where he went to Prabhāsa 14. 84. 12.
F.
Past and mythological events: (1) Gokarṇa
was one of the sacred places where Śeṣa,
abandoning his brothers and mother, practised
severe austerities 1. 32. 3; (2) Catuḥ-
śīrṣa Ālambāyana practised austerities at
Gokarṇa for hundred years as a result of
which he got a hundred sons from Śarva
(Śiva) 13. 18. 5-6; (3) Out of fear from
Rāma, Mārīca repaired to Gokarṇa to become
an ascetic (तापस्यं समुपाश्रितम्) 3. 261.
55; (4) Rāvaṇa went to Gokarṇa to meet
Mārīca 3. 261. 54; (5) Gokarṇa was one
of the holy places where Śeṣa practised auste-
rities.

गोदावरी
Godāvarī f.: Name of a river.
A. Location: Situated in the south
(दक्षिणस्याम्) 3. 86. 1-2; listed by Saṃ-
jaya among the rivers of the Bhāratavarṣa;
its water used by people for drinking 6. 10.
13.
B. Description: Holy, most holy
(पुण्या) 3. 86. 2, (पुण्यतमा) 3. 118. 2;
auspicious (शुभा) 3. 86. 2; (प्रशस्ता)
3. 118. 2; charming (रम्या) 3. 261. 40;
having ample water (बहुजला) 3. 86. 2;
having many groves on its banks (बह्वा-
रामा) 3. 86. 2; visited by ascetics (तापसा-
चरिता) 3. 86. 2; resorted to by Siddhas
(सिद्धनिषेविता) 3. 83. 30; going to the
ocean (समुद्रगा) 3. 118. 2, (सागरगा)
3. 118. 3; one of the rivers which are des-
cribed as mothers of the universe and very
strong (विश्वस्य मातरः सर्वाः सर्वाश्
चैव महाबलाः) 6. 10. 13, 35;
C. Epic
event: Yudhiṣṭhira, during his pilgrimage,
reached Godāvarī; he bathed there (आप्लुत्य)
and satisfied the manes and gods; he gave
wealth to the chiefs among the twice-born
3. 118. 2-3.
D. Past events: (1) One
of the rivers seen by Mārkaṇḍeya in the
belly of the Bāla (3. 186. 83 = Nārāyaṇa 3.
187. 3) 3. 186. 94; (2) Rāma lived on its
bank while in the Daṇḍaka forest 3. 261. 40.
E. Holiness: (1) By visiting Godāvarī one
secures for oneself the fruit of performing a
Gavāmaya and the world of Vāsuki 3. 83. 30;
(2) One of the rivers which are declared to
be mothers of the hearths i. e. on the banks
of which sacrifices were performed (एता
नद्यस् तु धिष्ण्यानां मातरो याः प्र-
कीर्तिताः) 3. 212. 23; (For Nī. see Kapilā).
F. Importance: (1) One of the rivers
present in bodily form in the Sabhā of Varuṇa
2. 9. 20-21; (2) Finds mention in the
Daivata-Ṛṣi-Vaṃśa 13. 151. 17, 2.

गोप्रतार
Gopratāra m.: Name of a तीर्थ।
Situated on the river Sarayū 3. 82. 63;
described as best (उत्तम) 3. 82. 63; at
this तीर्थ Rāma, together with his attendants,
army and draught-animals (सभृत्यबल-
वाहनः) abandoned his body and went to
heaven 3. 82. 63; due to the strength of the
तीर्थ, as also due to the favour and resolve
of Rāma (तस्य तीर्थस्य तेजसा।रामस्य
च प्रसादेन व्यवसायाच् च भारत), by
bathing at this तीर्थ one's soul is cleansed
of all sins and is glorified in heaven 3. 82.
64-65.

गोमती
Gomatī f.: Name of a river.
A. Location: Listed by Saṃjaya among
the rivers of the Bhāratavarṣa; its water used
by people for drinking 6. 10. 17, 13; situated
in the east, it flows near the Naimiṣa forest
3. 85. 1, 3-4; 3. 93. 1; (नैमिषे गोमतीतीरे)
12. 343. 2; on its bank there was the town
Nāgapura (नागाह्वयं पुरम्) 12. 343. 2;
Vārāṇasī is to the south of Gomatī 13. 31. 18.
B. Description: Holy (पुण्या) 3. 85. 5;
(पुण्यतमा) 13. 134. 22; auspicious (शिवा)
13. 134. 22; charming (रम्या) 3. 85. 5;
its sandy bank was splendid (पुलिने शुभे)
12. 345. 12; excellent river (सरिच्छ्रेष्ठा)
13. 134. 22; (सरिद्वरा) 13. 134. 14;
(सरितां वरा) 13. 134. 19; containing
waters of all तीर्थस् (सर्वतीर्थोदकैर्
युता) 13. 134. 12; resorted to by gods and
sages (देवर्षिसेविता) 3. 85. 5; flowing to the
ocean (सागरगमा) 13. 134. 21; one of the
rivers which are described as mothers of the
universe and very strong (विश्वस्य मातरः
सर्वाः सर्वाश् चैव महाबलाः) 6. 10. 35;
destroying sin (धूतपापा) 6. 10. 17 (or is it
the name of a different river ?).
C. Holi-
ness: There are holy तीर्थस् on it (3. 93.
2) like the Rāmatīrtha, the Śatasāhasrika-
tīrtha and the Mārkaṇḍeyatīrtha which is
on the confluence of the Gomatī and the
Gaṅgā 3. 82. 66, 67, 70; one of the rivers
which wait on Śiva for him to bathe in
(उपस्पर्शनहेतोः) 13. 134. 12; it was
the place of sacrifice for gods, and the place
for cooking the sacrificial flesh by Vivas-
vant (यज्ञभूमिश् च देवानां शामित्रं
च विवस्वतः) 3. 85. 5 (Nī., however, on
Bom. Ed. 3. 87. 7: शामित्रं शमितुः
कर्म यज्ञे पशुमारणं विवस्वतः
पुत्रस्य यमस्येति शेषः).
D. Epic
event: The Pāṇḍavas bathed in the holy
तीर्थस् on the Gomatī and gave cows and
wealth as gift; there they repeatedly satis-
fied gods, manes and Brāhmaṇas 3. 93. 2-3.
E. Past and mythological events: (1) The
Brāhmaṇa who went to see the Nāga Padma-
(nābha) decided to live on the sandy bank
of the Gomatī till the Nāga's return 12.
345. 12; 12. 347. 14; 12. 349. 4; (2)
Divodāsa founded the city Vārāṇasī to the
north of the Gaṅgā and to the south of the
Gomatī 13. 31. 18, 16; (3) Rāma, after
his coronation, performed, in the company
of gods and sages, ten जारूथ्य horse-
sacrifices without any hindrance (दशाश्व-
मेधान् आजह्रे जारूथ्यान् स निरर्गलान्)
3. 275. 69 (Nī. on Bom. Ed. 3. 291. 70:
जारूथ्यान् त्रिगुणदक्षिणान् इत्य् अर्जुन-
मिश्रः। … जरूथं मांसम् इति शाब्दिकाः।
तदा मांसमयान् मांसादिदानप्रधानान्
पुष्टान् इत्य् अर्थः। … जरूथं स्तोत्रम् इत्य्
उच्यत इति जारूथ्यान् स्तोत्रार्हान् इत्य् अर्थः);
(4) Gomatī was one of the rivers whom
Umā wanted to consult on the duties of
women as they were expert in it before
discoursing on it to Śiva 13. 134. 16, 13, 19-
20.
F. Occurs in a simile: Pāñcālī
embraced Bhīmasena as did a creeper a big
Śāla tree growing on the bank of the Gomatī
4. 16. 7.

गोमन्द
Gomanda m.: Name of a mountain.
Situated in the Krauñcadvīpa, one of
the Dvīpas in the north; described as big
(महन्त्), having all kinds of metals (सर्व-
धातुमन्त्); there dwells perpetually god
Nārāyaṇa Hari who is constantly praised by
the liberated ones (यत्र नित्यं निवसति … ।
मोक्षिभिः संस्तुतो नित्यं प्रभुर् नारा-
यणो हरिः) 6. 13. 8, 7, 1.

गोरथ
Goratha m.: Name of a mountain.
Situated on the outskirts of the Giri-
vraja, the capital town of the Magadha; it
was characterised by cattle, ample water, and
shining trees (गोधनाकीर्णम् अम्बुमन्तम्
शुभद्रुमम्) 2. 18. 30.

गोवर्धन
Govardhana1 m.: Name of a mountain.
It was held high by Kṛṣṇa to save the
cows (गवार्थे) 5. 128. 45; in the opinion
of Śiśupāla the mountain which was held up
by Kṛṣṇa for seven days was no bigger than
an ant-hill (वल्मीकमात्र) 2. 38. 9.

गोवर्धन
Govardhana2 m.: Name of a banyan
tree.
Karṇa told Śalya that he remembered
it being told to him since his childhood that
in the Bāhlīka country the gate to the king's
residence was marked by a banyan tree called
Govardhana (lit. where cows are skinned)
and by a cross-road called Subhāṇḍa (गोवर्-
धनो नाम वटः सुभाण्डं नाम
चत्वरम्।एतद् राजकुलद्वारम् आकुमारः
स्मराम्य् अहम्) 8. 30. 12 (Nī. on Bom.
Ed. 8. 44. 8: गोवर्धनः गवां छेदन-
स्थानम्).

गोविन्द
Govinda m.: Name of a mountain.
Situated in the Krauñcadvīpa, one of
the Dvīpas in the north, it lay beyond the
mountain Maināka, and beyond the Govinda
lay the mountain Nibiḍa; it is described as
the best (उत्तम) 6. 13. 18-19; the exten-
sion of these different mountains becomes
successively double (परस् तु द्विगुणस्
तेषां विष्कम्भः) 6. 13. 19.

गोशृङ्ग
Gośṛṅga m.: Name of a mountain.
Situated to the south of Indraprastha
2. 28. 1; described as the best among the
mountains (पर्वतप्रवर); conquered by
Sahadeva in his expedition to the south
2. 28. 5.

गौतमस्य
Gautamasya vanam nt.: Name of a
forest.
The forest of the Brahmarṣi Gautama
(ब्रह्मर्षेर् गौतमस्य वनम्); the lake
sacred to Ahalyā was in that forest 3. 82. 93.

गौतमी
Gautamī f.: Name of a river.
Listed among the sacred places by visit-
ing which those that are high-souled and who
have observed vows acquire divine form,
wear heavenly garlands, become auspicious
and endowed with holy fragrance they attain
the Vimāna of the cows (गवां विमाने)
13. 105. 47-48, 44 (for citation see Kara-
toyinī); listed in the Daivata-Ṛṣi-Vaṃśa
13. 151. 16.

गौर
Gaura m.: Name of a mountain.
One of the mountains which surround
the Dvīpas in the oceans to the north of the
Bhāratavarṣa (सर्वतश् च महाराज पर्व-
तैः परिवारिताः); Gaura was in the Madh-
yamadvīpa; described as great (महन्त्) and
full of red arsenic (मानःशिल) 6. 13.
3-4, 1.

गौरी
Gaurī f.: Name of a river.
One of the rivers of the Bhāratavarṣa;
its water used by people for drinking 6. 10.
24, 13; all the rivers listed here are said to
be mothers of the universe and very strong
6. 10. 35 (for citation see Atikṛṣṇā).

गौर्याः
Gauryāḥ śikharam nt.: Name of a
mountain peak.
Sacred to the great goddess (Pārvatī);
described as famous in the three worlds (त्रै-
लोक्यविश्रुत); the Stanakuṇḍas are on this
peak 3. 82. 131. [See Stanakuṇḍa]

घर्मसागर
Gharmasāgara m.: Name of an ocean.
One of the oceans, listed by Saṃjaya,
to the north of the Bhāratavarṣa 6. 13. 2.

घृतवती
Ghṛtavatī f.: Name of a river.
One of the rivers of the Bhāratavarṣa;
its water used by people for drinking 6. 10.
22, 13; all these rivers are said to be mothers
of the universe and very strong 6. 10. 35 (for
citation see Atikṛṣṇā).

घृतसमुद्र
*Ghṛtasamudra m.: Name of an ocean.
One of the oceans, listed by Saṃjaya,
to the north of the Bhāratavarṣa whose water
is घृत (घृततोयः समुद्रो ऽत्र) 6. 13. 2.

चन्दना
Candanā f.: Name of a river.
Listed by Saṃjaya among the rivers of
the Bhāratavarṣa; its water used by people
for drinking 6. 10. 28, 13; all the rivers
listed here are described as mothers of the
universe and very strong 6. 10. 35 (for
citation see Atikṛṣṇā).

चन्द्रभागा
Candrabhāgā f.: Name of a river.
A. Location: Listed by Saṃjaya among
the rivers of the Bhāratavarṣa; its water used
by people for drinking 6. 10. 14, 13; one of
the six rivers which flow outside the country
called the Āraṭṭa (पञ्च नद्यो वहन्त्य् एताः
 … आरट्टा नाम ते देशाः) 8. 30. 35-36.
B.
Description: Listed among the rivers which
are described as most holy (पुण्यतमाः)
and auspicious (शिवाः) 13. 134. 16, 22;
excellent rivers (सरिद्वराः) 13. 134. 14,
(सरिच्छ्रेष्ठाः) 13. 134. 22, containing
waters of all the तीर्थस् (सर्वतीर्थोदकैर्
युताः) 13. 134. 12, and flowing to the ocean
(सागरगमाः) 13. 134. 21; the rivers listed
by Saṃjaya are described as mothers of the
universe and very strong 6. 10. 35 (for cita-
tion see Atikṛṣṇā).
C. Importance:
(1) One of the rivers said to be expert in
the duties of women (स्त्रीधर्मकुशलाः)
13. 134. 19; Umā wanted to consult them
before expounding स्त्रीधर्म to Śiva 13.
134. 13, 18-21; (2) One of the rivers
which wait upon Śiva for him to take bath
(उपस्पर्शनहेतोः) 13. 134. 16, 12; (3)
One of the rivers which, in bodily form (2. 9.
21), wait upon Varuṇa in his Sabhā 2. 9.
19; (4) One of the rivers seen by the sage
Mārkaṇḍeya in the belly of the Bāla (3.
186. 83 = Nārāyaṇa 3. 187. 3) 3. 186. 93;
(5) Mentioned in the Daivata-Ṛṣi-Vaṃśa
13. 151. 14.
D. Holiness: He who,
being free from attachment (निर्ममः),
bathes in the Candrabhāgā for a week and
observes fast becomes like a मुनि (मुनिवद्
भवेत्) 13. 26. 7.

चन्द्रमसस्
Candramasas tīrtham nt.: Name of a
तीर्थ।
Situated on the Ārcīka mountain; it
was worshipped (पर्युपासते) by sages,
the Vaikhānasas and the Vālakhilyas 3. 125.
14.

चमस
Camasa, Camasodbheda (m.), Cama-
sonmajjana nt.: Name of a तीर्थ।
A. Location: Situated in the Surāṣṭras
(सुराष्ट्रेषु) 3. 86. 16-17.
B. Holy:
One of the three तीर्थस् where the river
Sarasvatī rises again after disappearing in
the desert near the Vinaśanatīrtha 3. 80. 118;
a तीर्थ where Sarasvatī can be seen; at
this तीर्थ many divine and holy (rivers),
flowing towards the ocean, turn towards the
Sarasvatī (यत्र दृश्या सरस्वती।यत्रैनाम्
अभ्यवर्तन्त दिव्याः पुण्याः समुद्रगाः)
3. 130. 5; by bathing at this तीर्थ one gets
the fruit of an Agniṣṭoma sacrifice 3. 80.
119.
C. Epic event: Halāyudha (Bala-
rāma) stayed there for a night, bathed in
the तीर्थ according to the prescriptions, and
gave many special gifts; from there he pro-
ceeded to the Udapāna 9. 34. 78-80.

चम्पकारण्य
Campakāraṇya nt.: Name of a sacred
forest.
Described as best (उत्तम); by staying
there for a night one gets the fruit of giving
a thousands cows 3. 82. 114. [See Jyeṣṭhila]

चरक्षा
Carakṣā f.: Name of a river.
Listed by Saṃjaya among the rivers of
the Bhāratavarṣa; its water used by people
for drinking 6. 10. 29, 13; all the rivers
listed here are described as mothers of the
universe and very strong 6. 10. 35 (for
citation see Atikṛṣṇā).

चर्मण्वती
Carmaṇvatī f.: Name of a river.
A. Location: Listed by Saṃjaya among
the rivers of the Bhāratavarṣa; its water
used by people for drinking 6. 10. 18, 13;
Droṇa gave to Drupada the kingship of the
Pāñcāla country to the south of the Bhāgī-
rathī and extending up to the Carmaṇvatī
(दक्षिणांश् चैव पाञ्चालान् यावच् चर्मण्-
वती नदी) 1. 128. 15, 12; Sahadeva, pro-
ceeding to the south of Indraprastha for his
expedition (2. 28. 1) encountered Bhoja, the
son of Jambhaka, on the bank of the Carmaṇ-
vatī; he defeated him and then proceeded to
the south (स तम् आजौ विनिर्जित्य दक्षिणा-
भिमुखो ययौ) 2. 28. 7-8; Kṛṣṇa and the
two Pāṇḍavas, while proceeding towards the
Magadha country, went beyond Mithilā and
reached the rivers Mālā and Carmaṇvatī
(अतीत्य जग्मुर् मिथिलां मालां चर्मण्-
वतीं नदीम्) 2. 18. 28.
B. Name ex-
plained: See section G below.
C. Descrip-
tion: Great river (महानदी) 12. 29. 116;
all the rivers listed by Saṃjaya are described
as mothers of the universe and very strong
6. 10. 35 (for citation see Atikṛṣṇā).
D.
Holiness: (1) He who is controlled and takes
limited food (नियतो नियताशनः), if he
visits the Carmaṇavatī, he gets, as permitted
by Rantideva, the fruit of an Agniṣṭoma
(रन्तिदेवाभ्यनुज्ञातो अग्निष्टोमफलं
लभेत्) 3. 80. 73; (2) Listed by Mārkaṇ-
ḍeya among the rivers which are proclaimed
to be mothers of sacrificial hearths, i. e. on
the banks of which sacrifices were performed
(एता नद्यस् तु धिष्ण्यानां मातरो याः
प्रकीर्तिताः 3. 212. 22, 24 (see Kapilā for
Nī.).
E. Importance: (1) Mentioned
in the Daivata-Ṛṣi-Vaṃśa 13. 151. 22, 2;
(2) One of the rivers seen by Mārkaṇḍeya
in the belly of the Bāla (3. 186. 83 = Nārā-
yaṇa 3. 187. 3) 3. 186. 93.
F. Epic
events: (1) The basket containing the
newly born Karṇa was put in the river Aśva-
nadī; from there it went to the Carmaṇvatī,
and further to Yamunā 3. 292. 25; (2-4);
for the other three epic events related to this
river see section A above.
G. Past events:
(1) The river flew from the dampness of the
heap of the skins of cows offered in the sacri-
fice of Rantideva; hence called Carmaṇvatī
(महानदी चर्मराशेर् उत्क्लेदात् सुस्रुवे
यतः।ततश् चर्मण्वतीत्य् एवं विख्याता
सा महानदी॥) 12. 29. 116; (रन्तिदेवस्य
यज्ञे ताः पशुत्वेनोपकल्पिताः।ततश् चर्-
मण्वती राजन् गोचर्मभ्यः प्रवर्तिता॥)
13. 65. 41.

चान्द्रमस
Cāndramasa hrada m.: Name of a lake.
From the summit of the mountain Meru
Gaṅgā Bhāgīrathī fell down with terrific
speed in the Cāndramasa lake; the lake was
created by the falling Gaṅgā 6. 7. 26-27;
described as auspicious (शुभ), holy
(पुण्य) and as large as the sea (सागरो-
पम) 6. 7. 27.

चित्रकूट
Citrakūṭa m.: Name of a mountain.
Described as a great mountain (महा-
गिरि) 3. 266. 67; best among excellent moun-
tains (गिरिवरश्रेष्ठ) 3. 83. 55; the river
Mandākinī flows on it 3. 83. 55; one who
observes fast and bathes in the river Mandā-
kinī gets the royal glory (राजलक्ष्मीं
निगच्छति) 13. 26. 27; Bharata, searching
Rāma to take him back to Ayodhyā, met
him on this mountain 3. 261. 37; Sītā told
Hanūmant that the incident when Rāma
threw a reed (इषीका) at a crow occurred on
the Citrakūṭa 3. 266. 67; mentioned in the
Daivata-Ṛṣi-Vaṃśa 13. 151. 27, 2.

चित्रपथा
Citrapathā f.: Name of a river.
Mentioned in the Daivata-Ṛṣi-Vaṃśa 13.
151. 21, 2.

चित्रबर्हा
Citrabarhā f.: Name of a river.
Listed by Saṃjaya among the rivers of
the Bhāratavarṣa; its water used by people
for drinking 6. 10. 32, 13; all the rivers
listed here are said to be mothers of the
universe and very strong 6. 10. 35 (for citation
see Atikṛṣṇā).

चित्रवती
Citravatī f.: Name of a river.
Listed by Saṃjaya among the rivers
of the Bhāratavarṣa; its water used by people
for drinking 6. 10. 25, 13; (for other details
see above Citrabarhā).

चित्रवहा
Citravahā f.: Name of a river.
Listed by Saṃjaya among the rivers
of the Bhāratavarṣa; its water used by people
for drinking 6. 10. 16, 13; (for other details
see above Citrabarhā).

चित्रसेना
Citrasenā f.: Name of a river.
Listed twice by Saṃjaya among the rivers
of the Bhāratavarṣa (on both occasions as
चित्रसेनां च निम्नगाम्); its water used
by people for drinking 6. 10. 16, 25, 13; (for
other details see above Citrabarhā).

चित्रोपला
Citropalā f.: Name of a river.
Listed by Saṃjaya among the rivers of
the Bhāratavarṣa; its water used by people
for drinking 6. 10. 32, 13 (for other details
see above Citrabarhā).

चीरवती
Cīravatī f.: Name of a river.
Described as holy (पुण्या) and chosen
by the most holy persons (पुण्यतमैर् वृता)
3. 82. 61; by visiting the river and by wor-
shipping gods and manes there (पितृदेवार्च-
नरतः) one gets the fruit of a Vājapeya
3. 82. 61.

चुलुका
Culukā f.: Name of a river.
Listed by Saṃjaya among the rivers of
the Bhāratavarṣa; its water used by people
for drinking 6. 10. 19, 13; (for other details
see above Citrabarhā).

चैत्यक
Caityaka m., nt.: Name of a mountain
and also of its peak (गिरेः शृङ्गम् 2. 19.
41).
One of the five mountains shown by
Kṛṣṇa to Bhīma and Arjuna which by coming
very close together were as though protecting
the city Girivraja in the Magadha (रक्षन्ती-
वाभिसंहत्य … गिरिव्रजम्) 2. 19. 2-3;
all the five mountains are described as shining
(शुभाः), having high peaks (महाशृङ्गाः)
and shady trees (शीतलद्रुमाः), and of
very solid forms (संहिताङ्गाः); they were
fully covered by the forests of Lodhra trees
which were fragrant, attractive, and whose
branches were covered with flowers 2. 19.
2-4; the peak of the mountain (शृङ्ग)
is described as very attractive (सुरुचिर),
firm (स्थिर), very large (सुविपुल), very
big (सुमहत्), old (पुरातन), always wor-
shipped with garlands (अर्चितं माल्यदामैश्
च सततम्), and firmly established (सु-
प्रतिष्ठित) 2. 19. 17-18; Kṛṣṇa and the
Pāṇḍavas ran up to the top of the mountain
(चैत्यकान्तम्) and struck it with their large
hands and broke it; then they saw from there
the city of Magadha (Girivraja) and entered
it 2. 19. 17, 19, 41.

चैत्ररथ
Caitraratha nt.: Name of the grove of
Kubera (named after Citraratha, the king of
the Gandharvas).
A. Location: In the north (अत्र (i. e.
अस्यां (उत्तरस्यां) दिशि 5. 109. 3) चैत्र-
रथं रम्यम् 5. 109. 9; on the Śveta
mountain 3. 214. 30, 34-35; 3. 215. 2.
B.
Epic events: (1) Pāṇḍu went to this
grove from the Nāgasabha mountain and
from there he proceeded further to the Hima-
vant 1. 110. 43; (2) Kṛṣṇa performed here
the Turāyaṇa and other sacrifices 3. 13. 21.
C. Mythological event: People living in the
Caitraratha were distressed when Skanda felled
down the peak of the Śveta (3. 214. 34) 3.
215. 2.
D. Similes: (1) Duḥṣanta saw a
large forest on the river Mālinī which looked
like the Caitraratha (महद् वनम् … चैत्र-
रथप्रख्यम्) 1. 64. 24-25; (2) The
large forest Viśākhayūpa on the Yāmuna
mountain looked like the Caitraratha (चैत्र-
रथप्रकाश 3. 174. 17, 20; (3) Indra
saw women sporting in a forest near the town
of Vṛṣaparvan which was comparable with
the Caitraratha 1. 73. 4; (4) In the third
inner enclosure (कक्ष्या) of the residence of
Janaka (12. 312. 32), Śuka saw a large forest
comparable with the Caitraratha 12. 312. 33;
(5) When Karṇa vowed the death of Arjuna,
Duryodhana, satisfied, entered the house as
does the master (Citraratha ? Kubera ?) the
Caitraratha (यथा चैत्ररथं प्रभुः)
3. 243. 17; (6) When Arjuna left the
Kāmyaka forest it became like the Caitra-
ratha devoid of Kubera 3. 79. 6; (7) The
terrified army of the Kauravas stood motion-
less like the Caitraratha grove covered with
flowers (ततः सा शुशुभे सेना निश्चेष्टा-
वस्थिता नृप।नानापुष्पसमाकीर्णम् यथा
चैत्ररथं वनम्) 8. 37. 10.

च्यवनस्य
*Cyavanasya saraḥ nt.: Name of a
sacred lake.
A. Description: Attractive (रम्य),
best (उत्तम) 3. 122. 5; resonant with sounds
of birds (द्विजसंघुष्ट) 3. 125. 11.
B.
Epic event: Lomaśa showed the lake to the
Pāṇḍavas (तस्य (i. e. च्यवनस्य) एतत्
सरः); he advised them to perform there rites
to satisfy manes and gods 3. 125. 11.
C.
Past events: Cyavana practised austerities
near this lake 3. 122. 1; (2) King Śaryāti
came to this lake with his wives and daughter
Sukanyā to sport 3. 122. 5-6; (3) Cyavana
entered this lake to be young again; Aśvinau
entered it too; they all emerged young, of
divine form and having the same appearance
3. 123. 15-17.

छावी
Chāvī f.: Name of a river.
Listed by Saṃjaya among the rivers of
the Bhāratavarṣa; its water used by people
for drinking 6. 10. 23, 13; all the rivers
listed here are described as mothers of the
universe and very strong 6. 10. 35 (for cita-
tion see Atikṛṣṇā).

जनकस्य
Janakasya kūpaḥ m.: Name (?) of a
sacred well.
Worshipped by gods (त्रिदशपूजित);
by bathing there one obtained the Viṣṇuloka
3. 82. 95.

जम्बू
Jambū f.: See Sudarśana.

जम्बूनदी
Jambūnadī1 f.: Name of a river.
The divine river Tripathagā (Gaṅgā),
when it flowed down from the Brahmaloka, it
was first established on the mountain Hiraṇya-
śṛṅga; there it assumed seven forms (तत्र
(i. e. on the Hiraṇyaśṛṅga 6. 7. 40) त्रिप-
थगा देवी प्रथमं तु प्रतिष्ठिता।
ब्रह्मलोकाद् अपक्रान्ता सप्तधा प्रति-
पद्यते॥) 6. 7. 44; Jambūnadī is one of
these seven forms 6. 7. 45; all these seven
Gaṅgās are described as heavenly (दिव्याः)
and famous in the three worlds (त्रिषु लोकेषु
विश्रुताः) 6. 7. 47.

जम्बूनदी
Jambūnadī2 f.: Name of a river.
Listed by Saṃjaya among the rivers of
the Bhāratavarṣa; its water used by people
for drinking 6. 10. 29, 13; all the rivers listed
here are described as mothers of the universe
and very strong 6. 10. 35 (for citation see
Atikṛṣṇā).

जम्बूनदी
*Jambūnadī3 f.: Name of a fabulous
river.
It has its origin in the silvery juice
(रजतसंनिभम् रसम्) of the ripe fruits
which fall down, from the great Jambū tree,
called Sudarśana, which is to the south of the
Nīla and to the north of the Niṣadha moun-
tain; the river flows around Meru keeping it to
the right, and then goes to the Uttara Kurus;
people drink that juice and then are not
affected by oldage (तस्या जम्ब्वाः फलरसो
नदी भूत्वा … । … तस्मिन् फलरसे पीते न
जरा बाधते च तान्) 6. 8. 18, 22-24.

जम्बूमार्ग
Jambūmārga nt.: Name of a sacred
place (प्रकीर्तितम् … जम्बूमार्गम् अथापि
च 13. 151. 19).
Described as frequented by gods, sages
and manes (देवर्षिपितृसेवित) 3. 80. 60; one
should go from Puṣkara to the Jambūmārga
and from there to the Taṇḍulikāśrama 3. 80.
59, 62; one who visits this place gets the fruit
of an Aśvamedha and secures for himself
the Viṣṇuloka 3. 80. 60; if one lives there
for five nights and eats only the sixth meal
(in the evening of the third day) (षष्ठका-
लक्षमी नरः) he will not meet with adver-
sities and will obtain the best perfection
(सिद्धिं प्राप्नोति चोत्तमाम्) 3. 80. 61; if
one leads there a well disciplined life with
a composed mind (संयतः सुसमाहितः)
he would achieve perfection in a day (अहो-
रात्रेण चैकेन सिद्धिं समधिगच्छति)
13. 26. 48; finds mention in the Daivata-
Ṛṣi-Vaṃśa 13. 151. 19, 2.

जम्बूषण्ड
Jambūṣaṇḍa m.: Name (?) of a thicket
of Jambū trees.
Located in the Ketumāla Varṣa which
is to the west of the mount Meru (मेरोस्
तु पश्चिमे पार्श्वे केतुमालो महीपते।
जम्बूषण्डश् च तत्रैव); described as very
large and comparable with the Nandanavana
(सुमहान् नन्दनोपमः) 6. 7. 29.

जयन्ती
Jayantī f.: Name of a river.
Somatīrtha is situated on it 3. 81. 16.

जलद
Jalada m.: See Malaya2.

जलधार
Jaladhāra m.: Name of a mountain
of the Śākadvīpa.
One of the seven mountains of the Śāka-
dvīpa 6. 12. 15, 13; described as big (महा-
गिरि) 6. 12. 15; all the seven mountains of this
Dvīpa are described as adorned with jewels
(मनिभूषिताः) and as mines of precious
stones (रत्नाकराः) 6. 12. 13; Vāsava
(Indra) always collects water in large quantity
on this mountain (which explains the name
of the mountain), and from that collection
it rains in the rainy season (यत्र नित्यम्
उपादत्ते वासवः परमं जलं।यतो
वर्षं प्रभवति वर्षाकाले) 6. 12. 15.

जला
Jalā f.: Name of a river.
Flowing near the river Yamunā (जलां
 … यमुनां अभितो नदीम्); King Uśīnara
offered a sacrifice there and surpassed Indra
3. 130. 17.

जह्नुकन्या
Jahnukanyā f.: 13. 14. 37. See Gaṅgā.

जह्नुसुता
Jahnusutā f.: 1. 92. 49. See Gaṅgā.

जातिमात्रह्रद
Jātimātrahrada m.: Name of a holy
lake.
Only by visiting (गमनाद् एव) this
place one gets the reward of performing a
hundred Agniṣṭoma sacrifices 3. 83. 34-35; and
by bathing there one remembers one's past
lives (जातिमात्रह्रदे स्नात्वा भवेज् जातिस्-
मरो नरः) 3. 83. 36. [See Jātismara]

जातिस्मर
Jātismara nt.: Name of a तीर्थ।
One who is pure and has a controlled
mind, if he bathes (उपस्पृश्य) at this
तीर्थ he is able to remember his past lives,
and there is no doubt about this (this explains
the name of the lake) (जातिस्मरत्वं प्रा-
प्नोति स्नात्वा तत्र न संशयः) 3. 82. 110.
[See Jātimātrahrada]

जाम्बूनद
Jāmbūnada nt.: Name of a lake.
Located on the Uśīrabīja mountain in
the north (यत्र जाम्बूनदं सरः); king
Marutta performed there his sacrifice 5. 109.
20, 19; described as holy (पुण्य), clean
(विमल), abounding in lotuses (कमला-
कर), and related to the mountain Himavant
(हैमवत) 5. 109. 21; the lake in person
(the lake not named) waited on the brahma-
nical sage Jīmūta (जीतूतस्यात्र विप्रर्षेर्
उपतस्थे महात्मनः।साक्षात् … कमला-
करः) 5. 109. 21.

जाम्बूनदपर्वत
Jāmbūnadaparvata m.: Name of a
mountain.
It belonged to Indra (इन्द्रस्य जाम्बू-
नदपर्वताग्रे); Lomaśa heard the sound
of the divine river Gaṅgā coming from the
summit of the Jāmbūnada mountain 3. 140.
14.

जाह्नवी
Jāhnavī f.: See Gaṅgā.

जैमूत
Jaimūta nt.: Name (?) of a forest.
The great sage Jīmūta chose to live in
this forest after donating all his large wealth
to the Brāhmaṇas (ब्राह्मणेषु च यत् कृत्-
स्नं स्वन्तं कृत्वा धनं महत्); hence
the forest was so called (वव्रे वनं
महर्षिः स (i. e. जीमूतः) जैमूतं तद्
वनं ततः) 5. 109. 22.

ज्येष्ठस्थान
Jyeṣṭhasthāna nt.: Name of a well.
Sacred to Mahādeva; after going round
the Koṭitīrtha (प्रदक्षिणम् उपावृत्य), one
should go to the Jyesṭhasthāna, and from
there proceed to Śṛṅgaverapura; by visiting
Mahādeva (अभिगम्य महादेवम्) at this
तीर्थ one shines like the moon; there is
a famous well at this तीर्थ where the four
oceans live (तत्र कूपो महाराज विश्रु-
तो … ।समुद्रास् तत्र चत्वारो निवसन्ति);
by bathing (उपस्पृश्य) in this well and by
making a प्रदक्षिणा round it a person who
has controlled himself (नियतात्मा) becomes
pure and attains the highest condition (पूतो
गच्छेत परमां गतिम्) 3. 83. 59-61.

ज्येष्ठिल
Jyeṣṭhila nt.: Name of a तीर्थ।
Perhaps located in the Campakāraṇya
(3. 82. 114); described as highly esteemed
(परमसंमत) 3. 82. 115; sacred to
Viśveśvara (Śiva); by fasting there for one
night one got the fruit of an Agniṣṭoma; by
taking there the दर्शन of Viśveśvara
(तत्र विश्वेश्वरं दृष्ट्वा) together with
the Devī (Umā) one attained the worlds of
Mitra and Varuṇa (मित्रावरुणयोर् लोकान्
आप्नोति) 3. 82. 115-116.

ज्योतिरथा
Jyotirathā f.: Name of a river.
Listed by Saṃjaya among the rivers of
the Bhāratavarṣa; its water used by people
for drinking 6. 10. 25, 13; all the rivers listed
here are described as mothers of the universe
and very strong 6. 10. 35 (for citation see
Atikṛṣṇā).

ज्योतिरथी
Jyotirathī f.: Name of a river.
One who is pure and while living at the
confluence of the Śoṇa and the Jyotirathī
satisfies manes and gods gets the fruit of an
Agniṣṭoma (शोणस्य ज्योतिरथ्याश् च सं-
गमे निवसञ् शुचिः।तर्पयित्वा पितॄन् देवान्)
3. 83. 8.

ज्योतिष्क
Jyotiṣka nt.: Name of a summit of
the mountain Meru.
Described as famous in the three worlds
(त्रैलोक्यविश्रुत); adorned with all kinds
of jewels (सर्वरत्नविभूषित); immeasur-
able and unassailable in all the worlds
(अप्रमेयम् अनाधृष्यं सर्वलोकेषु) 12.
274. 5; the wind which blew there was
auspicious, pleasing, carrying different fra-
grances and pure (ववौ शिवः सुखो वायुर्
नानागन्धवहः शुचिः), and the big trees
there blossomed with flowers of all seasons
(सर्वर्तुकुसुमोपेताः पुष्पवन्तो महा-
द्रुमाः) 12. 274. 11; it was sacred to Savitṛ
(सावित्र) 12. 274. 5; god (Śiva) once sat there
(गिरितटे) with his wife and was attended by
gods and other celestial beings 12. 274. 6-12.

तपोद
Tapoda nt. (pl.): Name of a तीर्थ।
Situated in the Rājagṛha; by bathing
there one enjoys like Kākṣīvant (उपस्पृश्य
तपोदेषु काक्षीवान् इव मोदते) 3. 82. 89;
by eating a part of the daily food offered to
the Yakṣiṇī there a pure person, by the grace
of the Yakṣiṇī, is freed of the sin of killing an
embryo (यक्षिण्या नैत्यकं तत्र प्राश्नीत
पुरुषः शुचिः।यक्षिण्यास् तु प्रसादेन
मुच्यते भ्रूणहत्यया) 3. 82. 90; (Nī. on
Bom. Ed. 3. 84. 105: नित्यकं नैवेद्यं
नैत्यकं च तद् एव).

तपोदान
Tapodāna nt.: Name of a तीर्थ।
Listed in the Daivata-Ṛṣi-Vaṃśa 13.
151. 19, 2.

तमसा
Tamasā f.: Name of a river.
Listed by Saṃjaya among the rivers of
the Bhāratavarṣa; its water used by people
for drinking 6. 10. 30, 13; all the rivers
listed by Saṃjaya are said to be mothers
of the universe and very strong 6. 10. 35
(for citation see Atikṛṣṇā); also listed by
Mārkaṇḍeya among the rivers which are
famous as mothers of sacrificial hearths, i. e.
on the banks of which sacrifices were per-
formed (एता नद्यस् तु धिष्ण्यानां मातरो
याः प्रकीर्तिताः) 3. 212. 23-24 (for Nī.
see Kapilā).

तरन्तुक
Tarantuka nt.: Perhaps also a तीर्थ
named after the gate-keeper Yakṣa of that
name.
Situated on the river Sarasvatī; sacred
to Arantuka, the chief of the Yakṣas 3. 81.
42; by living there for one night one gets
the fruit of giving a thousand cows (ततो
गच्छेत धर्मज्ञ द्वारपालं तरन्तु-
कं।तत्रोष्य रजनीम् एकाम् अग्निष्टोम-
फलं लभेत्॥) 3. 81. 13; by bathing
there one gets the fruit of an Agniṣṭoma
sacrifice 3. 81. 42; along with the Arantuka
तीर्थ and other तीर्थस् it forms the boun-
dary of the Kurukṣetra-Samantapañcaka
(तरन्तुकारन्तुकयोर् यद् अन्तरम् … एतत्
कुरुक्षेत्रसमन्तपञ्चकम्) 3. 81. 178 =
9. 52. 20.

ताम्रपर्णी
Tāmraparṇī f.: Name of a river.
Situated in the south 3. 86. 1; gods prac-
tised austerities there in an आश्रम wishing
something great for themselves (यत्र देवैस्
तपस् तप्तं महद् इच्छद्भिर् आश्रमे)
3. 86. 11-12.

ताम्रा
Tāmrā f.: Name of a river.
Listed by Saṃjaya among the rivers of
the Bhāratavarṣa; its water used by people
for drinking 6. 10. 27, 13; all the rivers
listed here are described as mothers of the
universe and very strong 6. 10. 35 (for
citation see Atikṛṣṇā); listed also by
Mārkaṇḍeya among the rivers seen by him
in the belly of the Bāla (3. 186. 83 =
Nārāyaṇa 3. 187. 3) 3. 186. 95; finds
place in the Daivata-Ṛṣi-Vaṃśa 13. 151. 16.

ताम्रारुण
Tāmrāruṇa nt.: Name of a तीर्थ।
One who has practised chastity and is
composed (ब्रह्मचारी समाहितः) he, by
visiting this तीर्थ, obtained the reward of a
horse sacrifice and went to the world of
Śakra (Indra) 3. 82. 133.

ताम्रावती
Tāmrāvatī f.: Name of a river.
Listed by Mārkaṇḍeya among the rivers
which are proclaimed as mothers of fire-
hearths i. e. on the banks of which sacrifices
were offered (एता नद्यस् तु धिष्ण्यानां
मातरो याः प्रकीर्तिताः) 3. 212. 22 (for Nī.
see Kapilā).

तीर्थकोटि
Tīrthakoṭi f.: Name of a तीर्थ।
Situated near the Maheśvarapada (तत्र
कोटिस् तु तीर्थानाम्) 3. 82. 103-104; described
as famous (विश्रुता) 3. 82. 104; they were
carried away by a wicked demon in the form
of a tortoise, but were brought back by
powerful Viṣṇu 3. 82. 104; by bathing there
(तत्राभिषेकं कुर्वाणस् तीर्थकोट्याम्)
one obtained the fruit of a Puṇḍarīka sacrifice
and went to the world of Viṣṇu 3. 82. 105.
[See Koṭitīrtha]

तुङ्गक
Tuṅgaka nt.: Name of a forest.
A. Past events: (1) The sage Sāras-
vata, the son of Aṅgiras, formerly taught
there the lost Vedas while he was sitting on
the upper garments of the great sages; when
his pupils pronounced properly the syllable
‘ओम्’ whatever each one of them had learnt
before came back to him (तुङ्गकारण्यम्
आसाद्य ब्रह्मचारि जितेन्द्रियः।वेदान्
अध्यापयत् तत्र ऋषिः सारस्वतः पुरा॥
तत्र वेदान् प्रनष्टांस् तु मुनेर् अङ्गि-
रसः सुतः।उपविष्टो महर्षीणाम् उत्तरी-
येषु भारत॥ॐकारेण यथान्यायं
सम्यगुच्चारितेन च।येन यत् पूर्वम्
अभ्यस्तं तत् तस्य समुपस्थितम्॥) 3.
83. 43-45; (2) many sages and gods like
Varuṇa, Agni, Prajāpati, Hari-Nārāyaṇa,
Mahādeva (had assembled there); Pitāmaha
(Brahmadeva) appointed Bhṛgu to perform a
sacrifice (भृगुं नियोजयाम् आस याजनार्-
थे); the blessed (Bhṛgu) then established
again fire for the sages according to the rites;
the gods and sages, satisfied by their shares of
the clarified butter, went happily to the three
worlds 3. 83. 46-49.
B. Holiness: The
sin of every one, whether man or woman,
who enters the Tuṅgaka forest is destroyed;
a wise person who is controlled and subsists
on limited food (धीरो नियतो नियताशनः),
if he lives there for a month he will go to-
the Brahmaloka and will purify his family
3. 83. 50-51.

तुङ्गवेणा
Tuṅgaveṇā f.: Name of a river.
Listed by Saṃjaya among the rivers of
the Bhāratvarṣa; its water used by people
for drinking 6. 10. 26, 13; all the rivers
listed here are said to be mothers of the uni-
verse and very strong 6. 10. 35 (for citation
see Atikṛṣṇā).

तुषारगिरि
Tuṣāragiri m.: See Himavant.

तूष्णींगङ्गा
Tūṣṇīṃgaṅgā f.: Name of a river.
The river is mentioned among those holy
places by visiting which the high-souled
persons, who have observed vows, go to the
Goloka (गवां विमाणे 13. 105. 44), after
they assume heavenly forms, wear heavenly
garlands, become auspicious and rich in holy
fragrance 13. 105. 46, 48 (for citation see
Karatoyinī).

तृणबिन्दुसरस्
Tṛṇabindusaras nt.: Name of a lake.
Situated near the Kāmyaka forest
(काम्यकं … तृणबिन्दुसरः प्रति) 3.
244. 13.

त्रसामन्या
Trasāmanyā f.: Name of a river.
Listed by Saṃjaya among the rivers of
the Bhāratavarṣa; its water used by people
for drinking 6. 10. 30, 13; all the rivers
listed here are said to be mothers of the
universe and very strong 6. 10. 35 (for
citation see Atikṛṣṇā).

त्रिकूट
Trikūṭa1 m.: Name of a mountain (?)
The eyebrow of Bhīma forming three
peaks on his forehead looked like the river
Gaṅgā flowing in three courses on the Trikūṭa
(or on the three peaks of a mountain ?)
(ट्रिशिखां भ्रुकुटीं चास्य ददृशुः सर्व-
पार्थिवाः।ललाटस्थां त्रिकूटस्थां
गङ्गां त्रिपथगाम् इव) 2. 39. 11. [See
Trikūṭavant and Triśṛṅga]

त्रिकूट
Trikūṭa2 m.: Name of a mountain in
the Laṅkā.
Rāvaṇa crossed it (and the Kāla-
parvata) before he reached the ocean while
he was on his way to Gokarṇa 3. 261. 53;
Laṅkā of Rāvaṇa was located in the valley
of the mountain Trikūṭa beyond the ocean
(लङ्का चास्य महापुरी।दृष्टा पारे समुद्-
रस्य त्रिकूटगिरिकन्दरे) 3. 266. 55.

त्रिकूटवत्|त्रिकूटवन्त्
Trikūṭavant m.: Name of a mountain.
Listed by Brahmadeva among the
mountains described as the kings of moun-
tains (एते पर्वतराजानः) 14. 43. 4. (Are
these mountains also to be looked upon as
having an excess of the मध्यम गुण i. e.
of the quality of रजस् ? cf. 14. 43. 1 and Nī.
on Bom. Ed. 14. 43. 1: मध्यमो गुणः
रजोगुणप्रधानः). [See Trikūṭa1 and
Triśṛṅga]

त्रिगङ्ग
Trigaṅga nt.: Name of a तीर्थ।
By giving offerings here to gods and
manes according to the rites one is glori-
fied in the world obtained by pious men
(पुण्यलोके महीयते) 3. 82. 25; if one
gives here offerings (to gods and manes)
he enjoys सुधा when he is born again (in
the world of the pious ?) (सुधां वै
लभते भोक्तुं यो नरो जायते पुनः)
13. 26. 15.

त्रिदिवा
Tridivā f.: Name of a river.
Listed by Saṃjaya twice among the
rivers of the Bhāratavarṣa; its water used by
people for drinking 6. 10. 16, 17, 13; all
the rivers listed here are said to the mothers
of the universe and very strong (for citation
See Atikṛṣṇā); finds mention in the Daivata-
Ṛṣi-Vaṃśa 13. 151. 22, 2.

त्रिविष्टप
Triviṣṭapa nt.: Name of a तीर्थ।
Described as famous in the three worlds
(त्रिषु लोकेषु विश्रुतम्) 3. 81. 70; situated
near the holy river Vaitaraṇī 3. 81. 70; by
bathing in this तीर्थ and by worshipping
god Śūlapāṇi Vṛṣadhvaja (Śiva), one's self
is cleansed of all evils and one attains the
highest state (after death) (सर्वपापविशुद्-
धात्मा गच्छेत परमां गतिम्) 3. 81. 71.

त्रिशूलखात
Triśūlakhāta nt.: Name of a तीर्थ।
Situated near the rivers (?) Sugandhā,
Śatakumbhā and Pañcayajñā; by bathing
there (तत्राभिषेकं कुर्वीत) and by being
devoted to the worship of gods and manes,
one obtains without doubt the status of a
Gaṇapati after death (पितृदेवार्चने रतः।
गाणप्त्यं स लभते देहं त्यक्त्वा न
संशयः) 3. 82. 9-10.

त्रिशूलपाणेः
Triśūlapāṇeḥ sthānam nt.: Name of a
sacred place.
Situated near the river Devikā; described
as famous in the three worlds (त्रिषु लोकेषु
विश्रुतम्) 3. 80. 111; by bathing in Devikā
and by worshipping Maheśvara (Śiva) there
and by offering a चरु according to one's
ability (यथाशक्ति चरुं तत्र निवेद्य),
one obtains the reward of a sacrifice that
grants all wishes (सर्वकामसमृद्धस्य
यज्ञस्य लभते फलम्) 3. 80. 112.

त्रिशृङ्ग
Triśṛṅga m.: Name of a mountain.
Described as an excellent mountain
(पर्वतोत्तम) 8. 11. 8; Aśvatthāman with
the three arrows shot at him by Bhīma and
stuck in the forehead looked like the Triśṛṅga
in the rainy season 8. 11. 7-8; (the three
holy peaks (शृङ्गाणि त्रीणि पुण्याणि) on the
Ārcīka mountain, pointed out by Lomaśa,
identical with the Triśṛṅga ? Yudhiṣṭhira was
advised by Lomaśa to go around them and
bathe in the three streams flowing there)
(सर्वाण्य् अनुपरिक्रम्य यथाकामन् उप-
स्पृश) 3. 125. 15; (Nī., however, on Bom.
Ed. 3. 125. 18: त्रीणि शृङ्गाणीति प्राग्व्या-
ख्यातरीत्या (cf. his comm. on 3. 82. 38) त्रि-
कोणं वाराणसीक्षेत्रम्।). [See Trikūṭa1,
Trikūṭavant]

दक्षिणसिन्धु
*Dakṣiṇasindhu m.: Name of a river,
the Sindhu of the south.
One should visit the Dakṣiṇasindhu after
visiting Narmadā, and from there proceed to
Carmaṇvatī 3. 80. 71-73; One who observes
chastity and has controlled his senses obtains,
by visiting the southern Sindhu, the fruit of an
Agniṣṭoma and rides in a विमान (दक्षिणं
सिन्धुम् आसाद्य … विमानं चाधिरोहति)
3. 80. 72.

दण्डक
Daṇḍaka (m. ?), Daṇḍakāraṇya nt.:
Name of a forest and a तीर्थ।
A. Location: The river Godāvarī flew
through it 3. 261. 40; the आश्रम of Śara-
bhaṅga was in this forest 3. 261. 39.
B.
Description: Large forest (महावन) 9. 38.
10; (महारण्य) 3. 261. 39; (वने महति)
3. 263. 24; holy forest (धर्मारण्य) 3.
261. 43.
C. Holy तीर्थ: One should
bathe there (उपस्पृशेत्); just by bathing
there (स्नातमात्रस्य) one gets the fruit of
gifting a thousand cows 3. 83. 38.
D.
Rāmāyaṇa events: (1) Rāma, during the
term of his exile, lived there with his wife and
brother on the river Godāvarī 3. 147. 29; 3.
261. 40; (2) Rāma and Lakṣmaṇa proceeded
towards its south in search of Sītā 3. 263. 23;
(3) There they encountered Kabandha 3. 263.
25; (4) Rāghava killed Khara, Dūṣaṇa and
other fourteen thousand demons and made the
holy forest safe again (चक्रे क्षेमं पुनर्
धीमान् धर्मारण्यं स राघवः) 3.
261. 43; 9. 38. 9.
E. Past events: (1)
“The fire of the anger of sages who blazed
with austerities is not extinguished even now
in the Daṇḍaka” said the wife of the Brāh-
maṇa to Kauśika (तथैव दीप्ततपसां
मुनीनां भावितात्मनाम्।येषां क्रोधाग्निर्
अद्यापि दण्डके नोपशाम्यति॥) 3. 197. 25
(Nī. on Bom. Ed. 3. 206. 27 has simply
दण्डके दण्डकारण्ये); 13. 136. 17; (2)
“A certain Brāhmaṇa destroyed the kingdom
of the Daṇḍakas.”—this is what Vāyu told
Sahasrārjuna (दण्डकानां महद् राज्यं
ब्राह्मणेन विनाशितम्) 13. 138. 11.

दण्डार्क
Daṇḍārka nt.: Name of a तीर्थ।
Situated in Campā, near the river
Bhāgīrathī; one who bathes in the Bhāgīrathī
(भागीरथ्यां कृतोदकः) and just visits
the Daṇḍārka (दण्डार्कम् अभिगम्यैव)
gets the fruit of giving a thousand cows 3.
82. 142.

दधिमण्डोदक
Dadhimaṇḍodaka m.: Name of an
ocean.
One of the four oceans around the
northern Dvīpas; apparently its water was
all whey (उत्तरेषु तु कौरव्य द्वीपेषु …
दधिमण्डोदको ऽपरः) 6. 13. 1-2.

दधीचस्य
Dadhīcasya tīrtham nt.: Name of a
तीर्थ।
Described as most holy (पुण्यतम),
purifying (पावन) and famous in the worlds
(लोकविश्रुत); Aṅgiras Sārasvata is present
there; one who bathes in this तीर्थ gets the
fruit of a Vājapeya and secures for himself,
without any doubt, the state which will be
reached by the sage Sārasvata (?) (सारस्-
वतीं गतिं चैव लभते नात्र संशयः)
3. 81. 163-164.

दर्दुर
Dardura m.: Name of a mountain.
Described as great mountain (महागिरि);
Hanūmant and others who accompanied him
saw Dardura (along with Sahya and Malaya)
near the (southern) ocean (लवणाम्भसः।
समीपे) when they came out of the cave
3. 266. 42; mentioned in the Daivata-Ṛṣi-
Vaṃśa 13. 151. 26, 2.

दर्वीसङ्क्रमण
Darvīsaṅkramaṇa nt.: Name of a
तीर्थ।
Described as famous in the three
worlds (त्रैलोक्यविश्रुत); by visiting it
(प्राप्य) one gets the fruit of an Aśvamedha
and goes to heaven 3. 82. 40.

दशगङ्गा
Daśagaṅgā f.: Name of a river.
The river is mentioned among those holy
places by visiting which the high souled
persons, who have observed vows, go to the
Goloka (? गवां विमाने 13. 105. 44), after
they assume heavenly form, wear heavenly
garlands, become auspicious and are rich in
holy fragrance 13. 105. 46, 48 (for citation
see Karatoyinī).

दशाश्वमेधिक
Daśāśvamedhika1 nt.: Name of a तीर्थ।
Situated near the Śālūkinī तीर्थ; by
bathing there a pilgrim (तीर्थसेवी) gets the
fruit of giving a thousand cows 3. 81. 11.

दशाश्वमेधिक
Daśāśvamedhika2 nt.: Name of a तीर्थ।
In Śītavana (?) 3. 81. 48; by bathing
there one acquires the highest condition (after
death) (गच्छेत परमां गतिम्) 3. 81. 52.

दशाश्वमेधिक
Daśāśvamedhika3 nt.: Name of a तीर्थ।
On the Gaṅgā (गङ्गायां), near the
Haṃsaprapatana तीर्थ 3. 83. 82; the places
on the bank of the Gaṅgā are meant for
practising austerities; they are the Siddha-
kṣetras (यत्र गङ्गा महाराज स देशस् तत्
तपोवनम्।सिद्धक्षेत्रं तु तज् ज्ञेयं
गङ्गातीरसमाश्रितम्॥) 3. 83. 83.

दासी
Dāsī f.: Name of a river.
Listed by Saṃjaya among the rivers of
the Bhāratavarṣa; its water used by people
for drinking 6. 10. 30, 13; all the rivers
listed here are said to be mothers of the
universe and very strong 6. 10. 35 (for
citation see Atikṛṣṇā).

दिवौकसां
Divaukasāṃ puṣkariṇī f.: Name of a
तीर्थ।
By visiting this तीर्थ a pure person
(शुचिः) does not experience bad condition
(after death) (न दुर्गतिम् अवाप्नोति) and
gets the reward of a Vājapeya sacrifice 3.
82. 102.

दिश्
Diś f.: Name of a river.
Listed by Saṃjaya among the rivers of
the Bhāratavarṣa; its water used by people
for drinking 6. 10. 18, 13; all the rivers
listed here are said to be mothers of the
universe and very strong 6. 10. 35 (for
citation see Atikṛṣṇā).

दीर्घसत्र
Dīrghasatra nt.: Name of a तीर्थ।
Brahman and other gods, as well as the
Siddhas and the great sages who have
observed vows perform there long sacrificial
sessions and give दक्षिणास् (दीर्घसत्रम्
उपासन्ते दक्षिणाभिर् यतव्रताः); just by
visiting the तीर्थ (गमनाद् एव) one
obtains the fruit of a Rājasūya and an
Aśvamedha sacrifice 3. 80. 116-117.

दुर्गशैल
Durgaśaila m.: Name of a mountain.
Listed by Saṃjaya as the sixth of the
seven mountains of the Śākadvīpa; described
as rising high (महोदय) 6. 12. 21, 12-
13; the extent in योजनस् of these mountains
doubles as one moves from one to the other
(तेषां योजनविष्कम्भो द्विगुणः प्रवि-
भागशः) 6. 12. 22.

दुर्गा
Durgā f.: Name of a river.
Listed by Saṃjaya त्wइचे among the rivers
of the Bhāratavarṣa; its water used by people
for drinking 6. 10. 29 (दुऋगाम् अन्तःशिलां
चैव) and 32 (दुर्गाम् अपि च भारत)
6. 10. 13; all the rivers listed here are said
to be mothers of the universe and very strong
6. 10. 35 (for citation see Atikṛṣṇā).

दृमि
Dṛmi(n) nt.: Name of a तीर्थ।
Described as famous in all the three
worlds (त्रिषु लोकेषु विश्रुतम्); famous
(दृमीति नाम्ना विख्यातम्) 3. 80. 88, and
one that relieves from all sins (सर्व-
पापप्रमोचनम्) 3. 80. 88; Brahman and
other gods wait there upon Maheśvara 3. 80.
89; by bathing there and by worshipping
Rudra, surrounded by hosts of gods, one drives
away sins committed since birth (जन्म-
प्रभृति पापानि कृतानि नुदते नरः) 3.
80. 89. [See Dṛmī]

दृमी
Dṛmī f.: Name of a तीर्थ।
Described as praised by all gods (दृमी
चात्र नरश्रेष्ठ सर्वदेवैर् अभिष्टुता) 3.
80. 90; by bathing there one obtains the fruit
of a horse sacrifice 3. 80. 90; Viṣṇu formerly
killed the demons and purified himself at this
तीर्थ (जित्वा … विष्णुना प्रभविष्णुना।
पुरा शौचं कृतं राजन् हत्वा दैवत-
कण्तकान्) 3. 80. 91 (identical with Dṛmi-
(n) ?).

दृषद्वती
Dṛṣadvatī f.: Name of a river.
A. Location: Listed by Saṃjaya among
the rivers of the Bhāratavarṣa; its water
used by people for drinking 6. 10. 14, 13;
situated in the north (उदीच्यां … दिशि) 3.
88. 1, 10; Kurukṣetra lay to the north of the
Dṛṣadvatī and to the south of the Sarasvatī
(दक्षिणेन सरस्वत्या उत्तरेण दृषद्वतीम्।
ये वसन्ति कुरुक्षेत्रे) 3. 81. 175.
B.
Description: Famous (ख्याता) and most
holy (पुण्यतमा) 3. 88. 10; all the rivers
listed by Saṃjaya are said to be mothers of
the universe and very strong 6. 10. 35 (for
citation see Atikṛṣṇā).
C. Holy: (1)
By bathing in the Dṛṣadvatī and by satis-
fying (तर्पयित्वा) gods one secures for
himself the fruit of an Agniṣṭoma and an
Atirātra 3. 81. 73; (2) One who bathes
in the confluence of the Dṛṣadvatī and the
Kauśikī and who lives on limited food
(नियताहारः) is freed of all sins 3. 81. 80;
(3) Those who visit, among other holy
places, Dṛṣadvatī obtain heavenly form, wear
heavenly garlands, become auspicious and,
rich in holy fragrance, they go to the Goloka
(? गवां विमाने) 13. 105. 47-48, 44 (for
citation see Karatoyinī); (4) One should
visit the Sarasvatī and the Dṛṣadvatī and,
moving along their banks (सरस्वतीदृषद्-
वत्यौ सेवमानो ऽनुसंचरेः) and reciting
regularly the Vedic text, should bathe at all
places (स्वाध्यायशीलः स्थानेषु सर्वेषु
समुपस्पृशेः) 12. 148. 12.
D. Events:
(1) Epic: (i) Śaṃbhu (Śiva) once instru-
cted Yudhiṣṭhira on this river (अनुशिष्टो ऽसि
 … दृषद्वत्यां च शंभुना) 2. 69. 13;
(ii) The Pāṇḍavas, at the start of their forest
life, lived on the Sarasvatī, the Dṛṣadvatī and
the Yamunā and then went westwards from
forest to forest (ययुर् वनेनैव वनं सत-
तं पश्चिमां दिशम्) 3. 6. 2; (iii) After
Yudhiṣṭhira had received his first instruction
in the राजधर्म (12. 56. 11), he and
others took bath in the Dṛṣadvatī and, after
duly performing the evening rites, entered
Hāstinapura 12. 58. 30; (2) Past: It was
at Dṛṣadvatī that Vaivarṇya and Varṇa
constantly offered holy sacrifices (यजन्तौ
क्रतुभिर् नित्यं पुण्यैः) 3. 88. 10-11.
E. Importance: Finds mention in the
Daivata-Ṛṣi-Vaṃśa 13. 151. 17, 2.

देवकूट
Devakūṭa m.: Name of a तीर्थ (?),
of a mountain (?).
Frequented by hosts of Brahmanical sages
(ब्रह्मर्षिगणसेवित); by visiting it one
gets the fruit of an Aśvamedha and rescues
one's family 3. 82. 122.

देवतीर्थ
Devatīrtha nt.: Name of a तीर्थ।
By bathing in the Devatīrtha one gets
the fruit of gifting a thousand cows 3. 81.
86; it is supposed to be present also at the
back of the little finger (कनिष्ठिकायाः
पश्चात् तु देवतीर्थम् इहोच्यते) 13. 107. 96.

देवदारुवन
Devadāruvana nt.: Name of a तीर्थ।
One who bathes at this तीर्थ, fasts for
seven nights, offers water libations to the dead
(कृतोदकः) washes off his sins, becomes
pure and goes to the world of the gods 13.
26. 25.

देवनद
Devanada m.: Name of a river ?
Perhaps not the name of an independent
river but the river Sindhu is so characterized
(सिन्धुर् देवनदस् तथा); present in bodily
form (देहवन्तः) in the Sabhā of Varuṇa
2. 9. 19, 21. [See Sindhu]

देवनदी
Devanadī1 f.: Name of a river.
Described as holy (पुण्या); finds men-
tion in the Daivata-Ṛṣi-Vaṃśa 13. 151. 24, 2.
[see Devanadī2]

देवनदी
Devanadī2 f.: Various rivers so called.
(1) Gaṅgā 1. 158. 20; 3. 108. 2; 3.
155. 85 (महागङ्गा); (2) Ākāśagaṅgā
18. 3. 26, 37, 39 (simply Gaṅgā); (3)
Narmadā 13. 2. 18; (4) Kauśikī 3. 110.
1. [See Devanadī1]

देवपथ
Devapatha m.: Name of a तीर्थ (?)
By visiting Devapatha one who is
restrained and lives on limited food (नियतो
नियताशनः) gets the merit (पुण्य) of
performing a long festival in honour of gods
(? देवसत्रस्य यत् पुण्यं तद् अवाप्नोति
मानवः) 3. 83. 42.

देवपर्वत
Devaparvata m.: Name of a mountain.
By visiting Devaparvata one is cleansed
of the sin of killing a Brāhmaṇa (ब्रह्म-
हत्या विशुध्यति) 13. 26. 40 (= Devagiri:
between Ujjain and Mandasor (Aravali
Hills ?); see note on the st., Cr. Ed. 17.
1067).

देववन
Devavana nt.: Name of a sacred forest.
Situated in the east 3. 85. 3; on the
mountain Kuṇḍoda (?) 3. 85. 20; described
as pleasing (रम्य) and adorned by ascetics
(तापसैर् उपशोभितम्) 3. 85. 21.

देवसभ
Devasabha m.: Name of a mountain.
Situated in the south (दक्षिणस्याम्) 3.
86. 1; near the sacred place Gokarṇa 3. 86.
12; on this mountain is located the hermi-
tage of Tṛṇasomāgni, the pupil of Agastya
3. 86. 14.

देवह्रद
Devahrada1 m.: Name of a तीर्थ।
Situated on the Śrīparvata 3. 83. 16;
by bathing there, one who is pure and has
controlled his mind (शुचिः प्रयतमानसः)
gets the fruit of an Aśvamedha and achieves
highest perfection (परां सिद्धिं च
गच्छति) 3. 83. 18.

देवह्रद
Devahrada2 m.: Name of a तीर्थ, also
called Sarvadevahrada (3. 83. 36).
Formed in the waters of the river
Kṛṣṇaveṇṇā (कृष्णवेण्णाजलोद्भवे); des-
cribed as pleasing (रम्य) 3. 83. 34; by
just visiting it (गमनाद् एव) one gets the
fruit of a hundred Agniṣṭoma sacrifices 3.
83. 35; by bathing at the Sarvadevahrada-
tīrtha one gets the fruit of gifting a thousand
cows 3. 83. 36.

देवह्रद
Devahrada3 m.: Name of a तीर्थ।
Situated on the mountain Kālaṃjara;
by bathing at the Devahrada one gets the
fruit of gifting a thousand cows 3. 83. 53.

देवह्रद
Devahrada4 m.: Name of a तीर्थ।
By bathing (उपस्पृश्य) there a pilgrim
becomes one with Brahman (ब्रह्मभूतो
विराजते) 13. 26. 41; (on the river Gaṇḍakī,
see note on the st., Cr. Ed. 17. 1067).

देवारण्य
Devāraṇya nt. (pl.): Certain forests,
some of them on the mountain Himavant, so
designated.
Described as holy (पुण्य) 1. 143. 25;
many epic and mythological events associated
with them: (1) Hiḍimbā sported with
Bhīma in many places, some of these being
the forests of gods (देवारण्येषु पुण्येषु)
1. 143, 25; (2) Some of the places visited
by Ambā for bathing while practising severe
austerities were the forests of gods (व्यचरत्
काशिकन्या … देवारण्येषु चैव ह … आप्ला-
वयत गात्राणि तीव्रम् आस्थाय वै तपः)
5. 187. 24, 26, 28; (3) In order to show
Indra to Indrāṇī, Upaśruti took her to a
lake after crossing the forests sacred to gods,
mountains and the Himavant (देवारण्यान्य्
अतिक्रम्य … हिमवन्तम् अतिक्रम्य उत्तरं
पार्श्वम् आगमत्) 5. 14. 5; (4) A croco-
dile, when delivered from her present condition,
told Arjuna that she was an Apsaras, Vargā
by name and a favourite of Kubera, who
sported in the forests of the gods (अप्सरास्मि
महाबाहो देवारण्यविचारिणी।इष्टा धन-
पतेर् नित्यं वर्गा नाम) 1. 208. 14.

देविका
Devikā f.: Name of a river.
A. Location: Listed by Saṃjaya
among the rivers of the Bhāratavarṣa; its
water used by people for drinking 6. 10. 15,
13.
B. Description: Holy (पुण्या) and
frequented by divine sages (देवर्षिसेविता) 3.
80. 115; famous in the worlds (लोकविश्रुता)
3. 80. 110; one of the rivers which are
described as best rivers (सरिच्छ्रेष्ठाः),
most holy (पुण्यतमाः) and auspicious
(शिवाः) 13. 134. 22; all rivers listed by
Saṃjaya are described as mothers of the
universe and very strong 6. 10. 35 (for
citation see Atikṛṣṇā).
C. Extent: Half
a योजन wide and five योजनस् long (अर्ध-
योजनविस्तारां पञ्चयोजनम् आयताम्।
एतावद् देविकाम् आहुः) 3. 80. 115.
D. Holy:
Sacred to Triśūlapāṇi (Śiva) 3. 80. 111;
by bathing in this river, by worshipping
Maheśvara, and by offering a चरु according
to one's mite one gets the fruit of a sacrifice
which fulfils all wishes (यथाशक्ति चरुं
तत्र निवेद्य भरतर्षभ।सर्वकाम-
समृद्धस्य यज्ञस्य लभते फलम्॥)
3. 80. 112; one who bathes in Devikā is
awakened in a Vimāna while being praised
by the Apsarases (विबोध्यते विमानस्थः
सो ऽप्सरोभिर् अभिष्टुतः) 13. 26. 9; one of
the rivers which are supposed to have waters
of all the तीर्थस् (सर्वतीर्थोदकैर् युताः)
13. 134. 12; also one of the rivers which are
called mothers of the fire-hearths, i. e. on the
banks of which sacrifices were performed (एता
नद्यस् तु धिष्ण्यानां मातरो याः प्र-
कीर्तिताः) 3. 212. 21, 24 (for Nī.'s remark
see Kapilā); there are many sacred places
on it like Kāma, Yajana, Yājana, Brahma-
vālukā and Puṣpanyāsa 3. 80. 113-114.
E. Importance: (1) Descendants in the
family of the Brāhmaṇas who hail from
the Devikā are famous (प्रसूतिर् यत्र वि-
प्राणां श्रूयते भरतर्षभ) 3. 80. 110;
(2) Devikā is one of the rivers who wait
on Śiva for his bath (उपस्पर्शनहेतोस्
त्वा समीपस्था उपासते) 13. 134. 12; these
rivers were conversant with the duties of
women (स्त्रीधर्मकुशलाः) and hence were
consulted and honoured by Umā before she
expounded स्त्रीधर्म to Śiva 13. 134.
19-20, 14, 25; (3) Finds place in the
Daivata-Ṛṣi-Vaṃśa 13. 151. 14 and in the
Tīrthavaṃśa 13. 26. 3, 9.

देव्यास्
Devyās tīrtham nt.: Name of a तीर्थ
(?)
Situated on the confluence of Sarasvatī
and Aruṇā; described as world famous (लोक-
विश्रुत) 3. 81. 131; a pilgrim should visit
it after visiting the Madhusravatīrtha 3. 81.
130-131; by fasting there for three nights
and by bathing, one is freed of the sin of
killing a Brāhmaṇa, obtains the fruit of an
Agniṣṭoma and an Atirātra, and purifies his
family up to seven generations (आसप्तमं
कुलं चैव पुनाति भरतर्षभ) 3. 81.
132.

द्युतिमत्|द्युतिमन्त्
Dyutimant m.: Name of a mountain.
Name of the second among the six
mountains of the Kuśadvīpa; it is made of
gold (द्वितीयो हेमपर्वतः।द्युतिमान्
नाम) 6. 13. 9-10; all the six mountains
are described as the best mountains (पर्व-
तोत्तमाः) 6. 13. 11; the distance between
them doubles as one moves from the one to
the other (तेषाम् अन्तरविष्कम्भो द्विगुणः
प्रविभागशः) 6. 13. 11.

द्रोण
Droṇa m.: Name of a mountain.
One of the three mountains used by
Indra for piling up the fire-altars of the
sacrifices of the ancestors of Sulabhā (द्रोणश्
च शतशृङ्गश् च वक्रद्वारश् च पर्वतः।
मम सत्रेषु पूर्वेषां चिता मघवता
सह॥) 12. 308. 183.

द्रोणशर्मपद
Droṇaśarmapada nt.: Name of a तीर्थ।
One who bathes there is waited upon by
the hosts of Apsarases (सेव्यते सो ऽप्सरो-
गनैः) 13. 26. 26.

द्वैतवन
Dvaitavana1 nt.: Name of a lake
(situated in the forest of the same name).
A. Location: Situated near the river
Sarasvatī (सरस्वतीम् एत्य निवासकामाः
सरस् ततो द्वैतवनं प्रतीयुः) 3. 174.
21.
B. Descriprion: Holy (पुण्य) 3.
25. 12, 13; 3. 27. 2; 3. 229. 13; suitable
for holy people (पुण्यजनोचित) 3. 25. 10;
famous (विख्यात) 3. 25. 12; beautiful
(रम्य) 3. 25. 10; having many fruits and
flowers (बहुपुष्पफल) 3. 25. 10; large
(महत्) 3. 25. 12; resorted to by different
kinds of birds (नानाद्विजनिषेवित) 3. 25.
10.
C. Epic events related to the lake:
(1) Arjuna recommended to Yudhiṣṭhira a
place near the Dvaitavana lake for their
residence during the period of their forest life;
Yudhiṣṭhira agreed to this suggestion and the
Pāṇḍavas proceeded towards the lake (इदं
द्वैतवनं नाम सरः … ।अत्रेमा
द्वादश समा विहरेमेति रोचये)।यदि
ते ऽनुमतं राजन् … ।ममाप्य् एतन्
मतं पार्थ त्वया यत् समुदाहृतम्) 3.
25. 10-13; (2) when the Pāṇḍavas
lived in the Dvaitavana forest, the lake
Dvaitavana, due to the sound of the recitation
of the Vedas heard all around, looked like the
world of Brahman (ब्रह्मलोकसमं
पुण्यम् आसीद् द्वैतवनं सरः) 3. 27. 2;
(3) While returning from the Gandhamādana
along with Arjuna, the Pāṇḍavas reached
Sarasvatī and then went to the Dvaitavana
lake with a view to settling down there
(सरस्वतीम् एत्य निवासकामाः सरस् ततो
द्वैतवनं प्रतीयुः) 3. 174. 21; (4)
Karṇa advised Duryodhana to show his pomp
to the Pāṇḍavas who were reported to be
residing near the Dvaitavana lake 3. 226.
12-13; (5) When permitted by Dhṛtarāṣṭra,
Duryodhana, Karṇa and others started for the
Dvaitavana lake and settled down at a
distance of just a गव्यूति (= 2 क्रोशस्) from
the lake (गव्यूतिमात्रे न्यवसद् राजा
दुर्योधनस् तदा) 3. 228. 25, 29; (6)
Duryodhana, once out for hunting, went near
the Dvaitavana lake; he asked his servants
to set up sporting tents (आक्रीडावसथाः
क्षिप्रं क्रियन्ताम्); so they started towards
the lake but the Gandharvas who had arrived
there before, obstructed Duryodhana's servants
who were approaching the lake; when this
was reported to Duryodhana he asked his
army to oust the Gandharvas; so they returned
to the lake 3. 229. 13, 16-19, 23; (7) The
return of the Pāṇḍavas to the Dvaitavana lake
after their encounter with the Gandharvas is
referred to in the list of the contents of the
Āraṇyakaparvan (घोषयात्रा च गन्धर्-
वैर् यत्र युद्धं किरीटिनः॥पुनर्
आगमनं चैव तेषां द्वैतवनं सरः)
1. 2. 122-123; (8) When Balarāma visited
the Dvaitavana forest he bathed in the
Dvaitavana lake (not named) and after
worshipping the Brāhmaṇas gave them many
articles of enjoyment (आप्लुत्य सलिले चापि
 … तथैव दत्त्वा विप्रेभ्यः परिभोगान्
सुपुष्कलान्) 9. 36. 27-28.

द्वैतवन
Dvaitavana2 nt.: Name of a forest.
A. Location: Situated along the river
Bhogavatī (= Sarasvatī) (मनोरमां
भोगवतीम् उपेत्य) 3. 25. 20; (तत्
काननं प्राप्य … विजह्रुः … सरस्वती-
शालवनेषु तेषु) 3. 26. 1; 3. 174. 23-24;
Balarāma arrived at the Dvaitavana and
then proceeded along the southern bank of
the Sarasvatī (ततः प्रायाद् बलो राजन्
दक्षिणेन सरस्वतीम्) 9. 36. 24, 28.
B.
Description: Holy (पुण्य) 3. 25. 16;
3. 27. 7; 3. 294. 43; 9. 36. 26; pleasing
(रम्य) 3. 25. 16; 3. 295. 3; large (महा-
वन) 3. 25. 17; 3. 26. 3; 3. 242. 7;
(महारण्य) 3. 27. 1; abode of religious
persons (वने धर्मभृतां निवासे) 3.
25. 20; full of many beasts of prey and
deer (बहुव्यालमृगाकीऋण) 3. 243. 21; the
forest is also described in 3. 25. 17-20
(having many kinds of trees and birds, which
are designated, elephants and hosts of perfected
sages).
C. Epic events: (1) After killing
the demon Kirmīra in the Kāmyaka forest,
the Pāṇḍavas proceeded towards the Dvaita-
vana 3. 12. 18; (2) The Pāṇḍavas wishing
to settle down for their forest life near the lake
Dvaitavana, entered the forest Dvaitavana
3. 25. 13, 16; (3) In the Dvaitavana (not
named) the Pāṇḍavas sported in the auspici-
ous woods of the Śāla trees along the river
Sarasvatī; there Yudhiṣṭhira satisfied the
twice-borns by offering them large-sized roots
and fruit; there Dhaumya officiated for their
religious rites to gods and manes; sage
Mārkaṇḍeya arrived there as a guest of the
Pāṇḍavas 3. 26. 1-4; (4) When the Pāṇḍa-
vas lived in the Dvaitavana, the forest
was full of Brāhmaṇas; the forest resounded
with the sound of Vedic recitations of the
Brāhmaṇas and the sound of the bow-strings
of the Pāṇḍavas; thus the Kṣatriya valour,
united with Brahmanic lustre, shone all the
more in the forest (संसृष्टं ब्रह्मणा
क्षत्रं भूय एव व्यरोचत); Baka Dāl-
bhya pointed out to Yudhiṣṭhira Bhṛgus and
others who, when protected by Yudhiṣṭhira,
gave offerings in fire (चरन्ति धर्मं
पुण्ये ऽस्मिंस् त्वया गुप्ता धृतव्रताः) 3.
27. 1-8; (5) Vyāsa advised Yudhiṣṭhira to
leave the Dvaitavana since staying long at
one place was not desirable; hence he went
from the Dvaita to the Kāmyaka forest 3.
37. 31-32, 37; (6) Later when the
Pāṇḍavas returned to the Dvaitavana from
the Gandhamādana, the ascetics in the forest
returned to them 3. 174. 22; (7) Karṇa
suggested to Duryodhana to visit the lake
Dvaitavana to show the pomp of the Kauravas
to the Pāṇḍavas 3. 226. 12-13; Duryodhana
approved of this idea; his only purpose was
to oust the Pāṇḍavas from the forest (न
हि द्वैतवने किंचिद् विद्यते ऽन्यत् प्रयो-
जनम्।उत्सादनम् ऋते तेषाम् वनस्थानां
मम द्विषः), and to show them, who
were in miserable condition, his pomp 3.
227. 5, 8-11; Karṇa suggested that their
pretext to visit the Dvaitavana should be to
meet the cowherds who awaited Duryodhana's
visit (घोषा द्वैतवने सर्वे त्वत्प्रतीक्षा
नराधिप।घोषयात्रापदेशेन गमिष्यामो
न संशयः) 3. 227. 19, 23; (8)
Yudhiṣṭhira reminded the Kauravas through
Saṃjaya of their defeat at the hands of the
Gandharvas in the Dvaitavana, where they
had arrived for the Ghoṣayātrā, and their
subsequent release from the captivity of
their adversaries by Bhīmasena and Arjuna
5. 23. 25; Śalya later alleged that in that
encounter with the Gandharvas Karṇa was
the first to run away from the battle
8. 28. 59; (9) After the Ghoṣayātrā
incident the Pāṇḍavas lived happily in the
Dvaitavana forest 3. 235. 25; (10)
Duḥśāsana sent a messenger to the Pāṇḍavas
and the Brāhmaṇas living in the Dvaitavana
to invite them to attend Duryodhana's
Vaiṣṇava Yajña 3. 242. 7; (11) Yudhi-
ṣṭhira, disturbed by Karṇa's vow to kill
Arjuna, thought of leaving the Dvaita-
vana 3. 243. 21; (12) While living in the
Dvaitavana, Yudhiṣṭhira once saw deer in a
dream who requested him to leave the forest
and go elsewhere as, on account of their pre-
sence, only a few deer were left in that forest
3. 244. 2, 5; (13) At the end of the
twelfth year of their forest life the Pāṇḍavas
went from the Kāmyaka to the Mārkaṇḍeyā-
śrama in the Dvaitavana 3. 294. 43; 3. 295.
3; (14) During their stay in the Dvaita-
vana the Pāṇḍavas, while once braving for the
sake of a Brāhmaṇa (ब्राह्मणार्थे परा-
क्रान्ताः), met with great difficulty which,
however, ended happily 17. 3. 18-19; 18. 3.
31 (a reference to the Yakṣapraśṇa episode;
Yudhiṣṭhira was tested by Dharma in that
episode which took place in the Dvaitavana
3. 295. 7-3. 298. 25); (15) Yudhiṣṭhira,
at the end of the twelfth year, while dismiss-
ing those who stayed with him in the forest,
asked them to tell people that they did not
know where the Pāṇḍavas went after they
(the Pāṇḍavas) left them in the Dvaitavana
4. 4. 5; (16) In the Dvaitavana Arjuna
used to praise the heroic qualities of Sātyaki
for Yudhiṣṭhira 7. 85. 61; (17) Yudhiṣṭhira,
humiliated by Karṇa, blamed Arjuna for not
killing Karṇa and told Arjuna that he should
have admitted to the Pāṇḍavas in the
Dvaitavana itself that he would not be able
to stand up to Karṇa in the war 8. 48. 2;
(18) Yudhiṣṭhira was dejected at the thought
of the destruction in the war and was think-
ing of retiring to forest; Draupadī then
reminded him of his resolve to kill
Duryodhana and rule the earth which he had
announced to his brothers in the Dvaitavana
12. 14. 8; (19) In the Dvaitavana,
Balarāma met the sages, bathed in Dvaitavana
lake (not named) and then proceeded along
the southern bank of the Sarasvatī 9. 36.
26-28.

द्वैपायन
Dvaipāyana m.: Name of a lake
(ह्रद, जलाशय).
A. Description: Famous (ख्यात) 9.
29. 53; pleasing (हृद्य), having cool and
dirt-free water (शीतामलजल), looking like
another ocean (द्वितीयम् इव सागरम्) 9. 29.
54.
B. Epic event: After the fall of Ulūka
and Śakuni, Duryodhana left the battlefield
and ran to the lake; he entered it controlling
its water with his special powers, and remain-
ed there concealed (lake not named) 9. 28.
23, 25, 49, 51-53, 57-58; (तं ह्रदं
प्राविशच् चापि विष्टभ्यापः स्वमायया) 9.
29. 7, 43, 54, 61, 64; 9. 30. 2-4 9. 31. 36;
Kṛpa, Aśvatthāman and Kṛtavarman, when
informed by Saṃjaya about the whereabouts
of Duryodhana, proceeded towards the lake
Dvaipāyana (not named) 9. 29. 4, 9-10;
Duryodhana's hiding himself in the lake was
accidentally known by the hunters of Bhīma
9. 29. 30; when they reported it to Bhīma, the
Pāṇḍavas, Kṛṣṇa, and all the Kṣatriyas rushed
to the lake Dvaipāyana 9. 29. 45, 47, 53, 57;
9. 30. 1-2; Yudhiṣṭhira challenged Duryodhana
who hid in the lake (not named) to save his
life to come out and fight with the Pāṇḍavas
9. 30. 17 (जलाशय), 24, 32 (जलाशय);
Duryodhana's entering the lake Dvaipāyana,
the Pāṇḍavas' forcing him out of the tamed
waters (स्तम्भिते सलिले), and Duryodhana's
getting out of the lake with his गदा reported
later by Nārada to Balarāma 9. 53. 27-29;
according to Vāsudeva's report of the war to
his father Vasudeva, Bhīmasena, who ran
after Duryodhana fleeing from the battlefield,
saw him in the water of the lake Dvaipā-
yana; the five Pāṇḍavas sat near the lake
and forced him out by using sharp words 14.
59. 27-29.

धर्मतीर्थ
Dharmatīrtha nt.: Name of a तीर्थ।
Described as ancient (पुरातन) 3. 82.
1, holy (पुण्य) and resorted to by Brahma-
nical sages (ब्रह्मर्षिसेवित) 3. 82. 141;
by bathing there one who is devoted to religion
and composed (धर्मशीलः समाहितः)
purifies, without doubt, his seven generations
(आसप्तमं कुलं राजन् पुनीते नात्र
संशयः) 3. 82. 1; by visiting Dharmatīrtha
one undoubtedly obtains the fruit of a
Vājapeya sacrifice 3. 82. 141.

धर्मपृष्ठ
Dharmapṛṣṭha nt.: Name of a sacred
place.
Dharma is always present there (यत्र
धर्मो महाराज नित्यम् आस्ते); by visiting
this place one who has a composed mind
(समाहितः) gets the fruit of a horse
sacrifice 3. 82. 87.

धर्मारण्य
Dharmāraṇya nt.: Name of a sacred
forest.
Described as a favourite of gods (सुरैर्
वृतम्) 13. 151. 23; lake Brahmasaras is
situated in it (ततो ब्रह्मसरो गच्छेद्
धर्मारण्योपशोभितम्) 3. 82. 74; 13. 26.
55; finds mention in the Daivata-Ṛṣi-Vaṃśa
13. 151. 23, 2; (also used as a general term
for holy groves 14. 96. 13 (दर्मारण्यानि);
qualifies Kaṇvāśrama 3. 80. 65 and Daṇḍa-
kāraṇya 3. 261. 43, 40).

धारा
Dhārā f.: Name of a तीर्थ।
Described as destroying all sin (सर्व-
पापप्रणाशिनी); by bathing there one does
not grieve (न शोचति) 3. 82. 22.

धूतपापा
Dhūtapāpā f.: Name of a river.
One of the rivers listed by Saṃjaya
among the rivers of the Bhāratavarṣa; its
water used by people for drinking 6. 10. 17,
13; all the rivers listed here are said to be the
mothers of the universe and very strong 6. 10.
35 (for citation see Atikṛṣṇā).

धूमत्या
Dhūmatyā f.: Name of a river.
One of the rivers listed by Saṃjaya
among the rivers of the Bhāratavarṣa; its
water used by people for drinking 6. 10. 23,
13; all the rivers listed here are said to be
mothers of the universe and very strong 6. 10.
35 (for citation see Atikṛṣṇā).

धूमावती
Dhūmāvatī f.: Name of a sacred place
(or of a goddess ?)
By fasting there for three nights one
undoubtedly gets the desired objects; to the
right side of the goddess there, there is a sacred
place called Rathāvarta (धूमावतीं ततो
गच्छेत् … ॥देव्यास् तु दक्षिणार्धेन
रथावर्तो नराधिप) 3. 82. 20-21.

धेनुक
Dhenuka nt., Denukā f.: Name of a
sacred place.
Described as famous in the world (लोक-
विश्रुता) 3. 82. 76; one should stay there
for a night and give as a gift a तिलधेनुका;
the gift cleanses the giver of all sins and he
goes to the world of Soma (एकरात्रोषितो राजन्
प्रयच्छेत् तिलधेनुकाम्) 3. 82. 76 (“In
imitation of the gift of the cow gifts of certain
articles were made and they are also described
as धेनुस्” P. V. Kane Hist. of Dharma.
II. II p. 880; cf. Mbh. 13. 70. 37-40);
Pulastya told Bhīṣma that a Kapilā cow with
her calf roamed near this place on the moun-
tain; the signs of their hoof-prints are seen
even now; if one touches the dust from those
prints (तेषूपस्पृश्य राजेन्द्र पदेषु नृप-
सत्तम), whatever unholy deed (अशुभं
कर्म) one may have committed that is
destroyed 3. 82. 77-78; Mṛtyu conceived as
a maiden, unwilling to carry out Brahman's
instruction to deprive the subjects of their
lives, repaired to Dhenuka without agreeing
to carry out the instruction, and practised
severe austerities 12. 250. 15-16 (Nī. on
Bom. Ed. 12. 258. 15: धेनुकं गोतीर्थं
मायान्तर्वर्ति).

ध्रुवद्वार
Dhruvadvāra nt.: Name of a place.
The place where Gaṅgā fell on the
earth (?); Nārada once went there to take
bath (ध्रुवद्वारभवां गङ्गां जगामा-
वततार च) 12. 221. 6.

नन्दन
Nandana nt.: Name of Indra's celestial
garden.
A. Relationship with deities: (1) Mostly
 related to Indra 3. 44. 3; 3. 78. 3; 3. 164.
41; 5. 11. 9-10; (2) Once with Aśvinau
14. 15. 4.
B. Description: Heavenly
(दिव्य) 3. 44. 3; garden of the gods (देवो-
द्यान) 3. 247. 8-9; holy (पुण्य) 3. 247.
9; offering sporting grounds for the righteous
(विहाराः पुण्यकर्मणाम्) 3. 247. 9; resort-
ed to by the hosts of Apsarases (अप्सरोगण-
सेवित) 3. 44. 3; for the relationship of the
Apsarases with the Nandanavana also cf. 1.
84. 17; 13. 26. 42; 13. 63. 17; house of
the Gandharvas and the Apsarases (गन्-
धर्वाणाम् अप्सरसां च सद्म) 13. 105.
23; liked by the king of the Kiṃnaras (किं-
नरराजजुष्ट) 13. 105. 23; liked by Nārada
(प्रियं वनं नन्दनं नारदस्य) 13.
105. 23; full of flowers (सुपुष्पित) 13.
105. 23; the trees in the Nandana have a holy
fragrance, are full of flowers and have pleas-
ing forms (पुण्यगन्धान् पश्यन्न् अगान्
पुष्पितांश् चारुरूपान्) 1. 84. 17; as though
inviting (the visitors) with trees having
heavenly flowers (दिव्यकुसुमैर् आह्वयद्-
भिर् इव द्रुमैः) 3. 44. 3; it is cherished by
those who are skilled in dancing and singing
and who offer unsolicited company (ये
नृत्तगीतकुशला जनाः सदा ह्य् अयाचमानाः
सहिताश् चरन्ति।तथाविधानाम् एष लोकः)
13. 105. 24; for the description of a forest
which is compared with Nandana cf. 12.
163. 6-10.
C. Epic events: (1) When
Arjuna reached the Amarāvatī of Indra
he saw there the Nandanavana 3. 44. 3;
(2) Mātali, on way to Indra's Amarā-
vatī, showed Nandana to Arjuna 3. 164.
41.
D. Past and mythological events:
(1) Aṣṭaka asked Yayāti why he fell down
on earth from the Nandana where he had lived
for an अयुत of centuries (संवत्सराणाम्
अयुतं शतानाम्) 1. 85. 1; Yayāti told
him that he lived in the Nandana for an
अयुत of centuries in the company of the
Apsarases, but when his merit was exhausted
(क्षीणपुण्यः) he fell down on earth from
the Nandana 1. 84. 17, 19; (2) When
Nahuṣa became the king of heaven he
sported in all the heavenly gardens and in
the groves of the Nandana (देवोद्यानेषु
सर्वेषु नन्दनोपवनेषु च) 5. 11. 9-10;
(3) The Devadūta while describing to
Mudgala the heavenly worlds reached by the
highly meritorious persons told him that there
were in those worlds heavenly gardens, the
Nandana and the rest; these offered sporting
grounds to the righteous (नन्दनादीनि
पुण्यानि विहाराः पुण्यकर्मणाम्) 3. 247.
9; (4) Gautama wanted king Dhṛtarāṣṭra
to give back to him his elephant for which he
was offered in return stay in the Nandana
(वनं नन्दनम्। … तत्र त्वाहम् हस्ति-
नं यातयिष्ये) 13. 105. 23 (Nī. on Bom.
Ed. 13. 102. 14: यातयिष्ये हस्तिनं स्वीयं
फलं त्वत्तो ग्रहीष्य इत्य् अर्थः); (5)
The mother of Viśvarūpa approached to
intercede on behalf of the Asuras her son
who was in the Nandana garden (Viśvarūpa
used to offer shares directly to gods but
indirectly to Asuras) 12. 329. 19.
E.
Mentioned as reward for meritorious acts:
(1) By resorting to the rivers Nandā and
Mahānandā one who is controlled and causes
no injury to others (दान्तः … अहिंसकः) is
waited upon by the Apsarases in the Nandana
13. 26. 42; (2) By giving as gift a bull
and fragrant substances under the coustella-
tion Citrā (चित्रायाम् ऋषभं दत्त्वा पुण्यान्
गन्धांश् च) one enjoys stay in the Nan-
dana 13. 63. 17; (3) One who recites the
आख्यान of women's duties towards their hus-
band (पतिधर्म), narrated by Śāṇḍilī to
Sumanā of the Kekayas, on every पर्वन्
day reaches the Devaloka (after death) and
lives happily in the Nandana 13. 124. 22.
F. Similes: (1) Forests and similar places
compared with the Nandana: (i) King
Duḥṣanta, when out for hunting, saw a
garden like the Nandana 1. 63. 12; also 1.
64. 28; (ii) Brāhmaṇa Gautama reached
a forest like the Nandana 12. 163. 7; (iii)
The forest on the Gandhamādana mountain
compared with the Nandana 3. 155. 36;
(iv) Rāvaṇa kept Sītā near the garden of
the Aśoka trees which was like the Nandana
(नन्दनोपमे।अशोकवनिकाभ्याशे) 3.
264. 41; (v) The Pāṇḍavas on seeing the
region of the lotus pond (Nalinī) of Kubera
were happy as are the Brahmanical seers
when they come to live in the Nandana 3.
174. 10; (2) Towns and similar places:
(i) Nala, with Damayantī, lived in his town
like Indra in his Nandana 3. 78. 3; (ii)
When the war was over Kṛṣṇa and Arjuna
enjoyed themselves in different places as do
the Aśvinau in the Nandana 14. 15. 4.

नन्दा
Nandā f.: Name of a river.
A. Location: In the east (1. 207. 5;
3. 85. 3; 3. 91. 28), on the top of the
mountain Kuṇḍoda (नन्दा च गिरिमूर्-
धनि) 3. 85. 20-21; on the Hemakūṭa 3.
109. 1-2, i. e. on the Ṛṣabhakūṭa 3. 109. 7.
B. Description: One that destroys the fear
of sin (पापभयापहा) 3. 109. 1.
C.
Epic events: (1) During the term of exile
Arjuna, while going to the east, saw the river
Nandā among many other rivers 1. 207.
7; (2) While in forest, Yudhiṣṭhira with
his followers visited it 3. 109. 1; Lomaśa
asked Yudhiṣṭhira to bathe with his brothers
in the river Nandā (अभिषेकं वै तस्मात्
कुरु सहानुजः।ततो नन्दाप्लुताङ्गस्
त्वम्) and then proceed to the river Kauśikī;
accordingly Yudhiṣṭhira and his followers
(सगणः) took bath in the Nandā 3. 109.
18-20.
D. Mythological event: Once
gods visited the Nandā and the people rushed
to see them; not wishing to be seen by the
people Indra and other gods made the region
inaccessible 3. 109. 11-12.
E. Reward:
(1) Bathing in the Nandā destroys sin
instantly (सद्यः पाप्मा निहन्यते) 3.
109. 18; (2) By visiting the Nandā even
once (सकृत् नन्दां समासाद्य) the soul
of a Brāhmaṇa is disciplined (कृतात्मा
भवति द्विजः) and, freed of sins, he goes
to the world of Śakra 3. 82. 138; (3) By
visiting the Nandā one who is controlled
(दान्तः) and who does not cause injury
to others (अहिंसकः) is waited upon by
the Apsarases in the Nandana 13. 26. 42.
F. Importance: Finds mention in the
Daivata-Ṛṣi-Vaṃśa 13. 151. 23, 2.

नन्दिनी
Nandinī f.: Name of a holy well
(कूप).
Described as frequented by gods
(त्रिदशसेवित); one who visits it gets the
merit of a Naramedha 3. 82. 134.

नर्मदा
Narmadā f.: Name of a river.
A. Location: Listed by Saṃjaya among
the rivers of the Bhāratavarṣa; its water
used by people for drinking 6. 10. 13; in
the south, to the south of the river
Carmaṇvatī 2. 28. 1, 7-8; in the west,
it flows westwards through the Avanti
country 3. 87. 1, 2.
B. Description: Holy
(पुण्या) 3. 87. 2; 13. 2. 18; auspicious
(शिवा) 13. 2. 18; river of the gods
(देवनदी) 13. 2. 18; excellent among the
rivers (सरितां वरा) 15. 26. 13; great
river (महानदी) 3. 121. 15; 12. 52. 32;
famous in the three worlds (त्रैलोक्यविश्रुता)
3. 80. 71; its water is cool (शीतजला) 13.
2. 18; flowing westwards (प्रत्यक्स्रोता) 3.
87. 2; it has on its banks Priyaṅgu and
mango trees (प्रियङ्ग्वाम्रवनोपेता) and
has garlands of abundant canes (वानीरवन-
मालिनी) 3. 87. 2.
C. Epic events: (1)
Sahadeva in his expedition to the south
(2. 28. 1) reached the Narmadā where he
defeated the two Avanti princes Vinda and
Anuvinda 2. 28. 9; (2) From the river
Payoṣṇī, Yudhiṣṭhira and his brothers went
to the mountain Vaiḍūrya and the river
Narmadā 3. 121. 15.
D. Past and Mytho-
logical events: (1) The river Narmadā fell
in love with Duryodhana, son of Durjaya
(13. 2. 12) and gave birth to a daughter
Sudarśanā 13. 2. 18-19; (2) The river
Narmadā became the wife of king Purukutsa
15. 26. 13; (3) Narmadā was one of the
rivers seen by the sage Mārkaṇḍeya in the
belly of the Bāla (3. 186. 83 = Nārāyaṇa 3.
187. 3) 3. 186. 94.
E. Importance: (1)
In the region of the river Narmadā and the
mountain Vaiḍūrya (3. 121. 15, 18) there is
the lake of Cyavana 3. 122. 1, 5; 3. 125. 11
(see *Cyavanasya saras); (2) The river
Narmadā is one of the rivers which are descri-
bed as mothers of the universe and very strong
6. 10. 13, 35 (for citation see Atikṛṣṇā);
(3) Listed by Mārkaṇḍeya among the rivers
known as mothers of the fire-hearths (i. e.
on the banks of which sacrifices were
performed; (for citation and Nī. see Kapilā)
3. 212. 23-24; (4) Narmadā is one of the
rivers which in bodily form (देहवन्तः)
wait upon Varuṇa in his Sabhā 2. 9. 18,
21; (5) The meeting point between the
river Narmadā and the mountain Vaiḍūrya is
looked upon as the joint between the Tretā
and the Dvāpara Yugas 3. 121. 18-19;
(6) Finds mention in the Daivata-Ṛṣi-Vaṃśa
13. 151. 15, 2.
F. Holiness: (1) By
giving offerings to manes and gods on the
river Narmadā one gets the fruit of an Agni-
ṣṭoma sacrifice 3. 80. 71; (2) By bathing
(उपस्पृश्य) at the source of the Narmadā
(नर्मदायाश् च प्रभवे) one gets the
fruit of performing a horse sacrifice 3. 83. 9;
(3) One who bathes (अवतीर्य) in the
Narmadā obtains the worlds of gods and
(meritorious) kings (देवानाम् एति कौन्तेय
तथा राज्ञां सलोकताम्) 3. 121. 18; (4)
By bathing (उपस्पृश्य) in the Narmadā
and by fasting there for a fortnight one
becomes a prince (in the next birth ?)
(एकपक्षं निराहारो राजपुत्रो विधीयते)
13. 26. 47;
G. Simile: The army of the
Pāṇḍavas moving in two parts compared
with the river Narmadā flowing in two
streams (see Ṛkṣavant) 12. 52. 32.

नलिनी
Nalinī1 f.: Name of a river.
One of the seven streams into which the
Gaṅgā was divided at the lake Bindusaras
where the river was first established after her
fall from the Brahmaloka (तत्र त्रिपथगा
देवी … सप्तधा प्रतिपद्यते 6. 7. 41, 44) is
called Nalinī 6. 7. 45; one of the rivers
seen by the sage Mārkaṇḍeya in the belly
of the Bāla (3. 186. 83 = Nārāyaṇa 6. 187.
3) 3. 186. 94.

नलिनी
Nalinī2 f.: Name (?) of the lotus pond
of Kubera.
A. Location: In the north (उदीच्यां
दिशि) 7. 57. 23; on the summit of the
Kailāsa, in an auspicious and beautiful
forest (कैलासशिखरे रम्ये ददर्श
शुभकानने) 3. 151. 1; near the residence
of Kubera (कुबेरभवनाभ्याशे) 3. 151.
2; in the sporting place of Kubera (कुबे-
रस्य विहारे) 7. 57. 23; it could be seen
from the Badarī, the place of residence of
Nārāyaṇa 3. 174. 8-9.
B. Description:
Auspicious (शुभा) and purifying the world
(पवित्रभूतां लोकस्य) 3. 151. 3; its water
was auspicious (शुभ) and holy (शिव)
3. 151. 4; heavenly (दिव्या) 3. 151. 3, 8;
(दिव्यं सरः) 3. 151. 9; pleasing, very
pleasing (रम्या) 3. 151. 1, 5; 3. 152. 10;
(सुरम्या) 3. 151. 2; (सुमनोहरा) 3.
153. 23; of wonderful appearance (अद्-
भुतदर्शना) 3. 151. 3; its ample water
was cool, light and clear (शीतं विमलं
तोयं … बहु) 3. 151. 4; its water was
like nectar (अमृतकल्पम् अम्भः) 3.
152. 22; or was nectar itself (अमृत-
रसम्) 3. 151. 4; covered with trees
and creepers of different kinds, hence offering
ample shade (विपुलच्छायां नानाद्रुमलता-
वृताम्) 3. 151. 2; covered with yellow and
golden lotuses (हरिताम्बुजसंच्छन्नां …
कनकपुष्कराम्) 3. 151. 3; full of golden
Saugandhika lotus flowers of excellent
fragrance which had variegated and charm-
ing stalks of excellent Vaiḍūrya (पद्म-
सौगन्धिकायुताम्।जातरूपमयैः पद्-
मैश् छन्नां परमगन्धिभिः॥वैडूर्-
यवरनालैश् च बहुचित्रैर् मनोहरैः) 3.
151. 5-6; full of lotuses, decorated by lotuses
(पद्मिनी) 13. 20. 8; (पुष्करिणी) 3. 152.
18, 21; (प्रफुल्लपङ्कजवती) 3. 153. 23;
(पद्मभूषिता) 7. 57. 23; sporting ground
of Kubera, the king of the Yakṣas (आक्रीडं
यक्षराजस्य कुबेरस्य) 3. 151. 7;
loved by Kubera (कुबेरकान्ता) 3. 174. 9;
highly honoured by the Gandharvas, the Apsa-
rases, and gods (गन्धर्वैर् अप्सरोभिश् च
देवैश् च परमार्चिताम्) 3. 151. 7; loved
by gods and the Siddhas (सुरसिद्धजुष्टा)
3. 174. 9; frequented by sages (सेविताम्
ऋषिभिः) 3. 151. 8; guarded by Rākṣasas
called the Krodhavaśas under instruction from
their king (Kubera) (राक्षसैर् अभिरक्षिताम्)
3. 151. 1; 13. 20. 8; (तच् च क्रोधवशा
नाम राक्षसा राजशासनात्।रक्षन्ति) 3.
151. 10; guarded by the Yakṣas, Kiṃpuruṣas,
Rākṣasas, Kiṃnaras and by Vaiśravaṇa
(Kubera) himself (यक्षैः किंपुरुषैस्
तथा।राक्षसैः किंनरैश् चैव गुप्तां
वैश्रवणेन च) 3. 151. 8.
C. Epic
events: (1) Bhīma, in search of the divine
Saugandhika flowers (3. 146. 6-14) saw the
Nalinī on the summit of the Kailāsa and
was very happy to see the lake 3. 151. 1,
9; he invaded the lake for the flowers
and, in the encounter that followed, killed
over a hundred Rākṣasas near the lotus
lake 3. 152. 18; he entered the lake and
plucked the Saugandhika flowers 3. 152.
21-22; when the Rākṣasas returned to the
lake, after reporting the incident to Kubera,
they saw Bhīma sporting in the Nalinī 3.
152. 25; Yudhiṣṭihra and others, helped by
Ghaṭotkaca and his Rākṣasas, proceeded
towards Kubera's Nalinī 3. 153. 21-22; after
meeting Bhīma, they all sported in the Nalinī
3. 153. 28; (reference to Bhīma's invading
Kubera's Nalinī for the Mandāra flowers is
found in 1. 2. 112); (2) When the Pāṇḍa-
vas, on their return journey, saw the Nalinī
they became free from grief (नलिनीं विशोकाः
संपश्यमानाः) 3. 174. 9; (तां चाथ दृष्ट्वा
नलिनीं विशोकाः 3. 174. 10; (3) Arjuna,
while proceeding at night to propitiate Śiva
to get from him his Pāśupata missile, saw on
his way the Nalinī in the sporting ground of
Kubera 7. 57. 23.
D. Past event: Aṣṭā-
vakra saw the Nalinī of Dhanada (Kubera)
near the Kailāsa summit of the mountain
Himālaya 13. 20. 7.
E. Simile: The
Pāṇḍavas sported near the Nalinī as do the
Brahmanical seers after reaching the Nandana
forest 3. 174. 10.

नागधन्वन्
Nāgadhanvan m.: Name of a तीर्थ।
Balarāma went along the south bank
of the Sarasvatī and reached the Nāga-
dhanvan तीर्थ which was not very far from
the Dvaitavana (ततः प्रायाद् बलो राजन्
दक्षिणेन सरस्वतीम्॥गत्वा चैव …
नातिदूरं … ।धर्मात्मा नागधन्वानं
तीर्थं आगमद् अच्युतः॥) 9. 36. 28-29;
Vāsuki, the king of the Pannagas, has his
abode there and he lives there with many
Pannagas (यत्र पन्नगराजस्य वासुकेः
संनिवेशनम्। … बहुभिः पन्नगैर्
वृतम्॥); gods once assembled there to
consecrate, according to the rites (यथा-
विधि), Vāsuki as the king of all Pannagas
9. 36. 30-31; one need have no fear from the
serpents there (पन्नगेभ्यो भयं तत्र
विद्यते न स्म कौरव) 9. 36. 31; there also
live perfected sages numbering fourteen thou-
sand 9. 36. 30 (ऋषयः सिद्धाः सहस्राणि
चतुर्दश); Balarāma gave there to the
Brāhmaṇas, according to the rites (विधिवत्),
heaps of gems (रत्नसंचयान्) and from
there he proceeded towards the east 9. 36. 32.

नागसभ
Nāgasabha m.: Name of a mountain.
Pāṇḍu, on his way to the Śataśṛṅga
mountain with his two wives, first reached
the mountain Nāgasabha 1. 110. 42.

नागोद्भेद
Nāgodbheda m.: Name of a तीर्थ।
One of the three तीर्थस् (the other two
being the Camasodbheda and the Śivodbheda)
where the river Sarasvatī reappears after
disappearing at the Vinaśana; by bathing at
the Nāgodbheda one goes to the world of
the Nāgas 3. 80. 118-119.

नारीतीर्थानि
Nārītīrthāni nt. (pl.): A collective
name for the five तीर्थस्।
Situated on the coast of the southern
ocean (समुद्रे तीर्थानि दक्षिणे) 1. 208.
1; in the marshy land of the southern ocean
(दक्षिणे सागरानूपे) 1. 209. 17; as
declared by the Brāhmaṇa the five तीर्थस्
would become famous as the Nārītīrthas
(नारीतीर्थानि नाम्नेह ख्यातिं यास्यन्ति
सर्वशः) 1. 209. 11; described as very holy
(सुपुण्यानि) 1. 208. 1, holy (पुण्यानि); puri-
fying for the thoughtful (पावनानि मनीषि-
णाम्) 1. 209. 11, 17; pleasing (रमणियानि)
1. 209. 17; these तीर्थस् are the Agastyatīrtha,
the Saubhadra, the Pauloma, the Kāraṃ-
dhama and the तीर्थ of Bhāradvāja (भार-
द्वाजस्य तीर्थम् 1. 208. 3); they were once
adorned by the sages (शोभितानि तपस्विभिः)
but were avoided by them due to the fear
of the five crocodiles which lived there 1.
208. 1-2, 4-6; Arjuna cleared the तीर्थस्
of the crocodiles which were really five
Apsarases (तीर्थानि शोधयित्वा) 1. 209. 23;
Yudhiṣṭhira, with Draupadī and brothers, later
visited these तीर्थस्; he heard there the heroic
deed of Arjuna and was pleased; they all
bathed in the तीर्थस् and gave thousands of
cows as gifts; Yudhiṣṭhira also praised the
gift of cows by Arjuna (this gift of Arjuna
is not reported earlier) 3. 118. 4-7. (See
also the five तीर्थस् named above).

निचीरा
Nicīrā f.: Name of a river.
Listed by Saṃjaya among the rivers of
the Bhāratavarṣa; people use its water for
drinking 6. 10. 20, 13; all the rivers listed
here are described as mothers of the universe
and very strong 6. 10. 35 (for citation see
Atikṛṣṇā).

निबिड
Nibiḍa m.: Name of a mountain.
Mountain of the Krauñcadvīpa; it lay
beyond the Govinda mountain 6. 13. 19, 17.

निरृति
Nirṛti m.: Name of a mountain (?).
Mentioned in the Tīrthavaṃśa narrated
by Aṅgiras 13. 26. 3; described as the
mountain of the gods; by visiting it (?)
one is freed of the sin of killing a Brāhmaṇa
(निरृतिं देवपर्वतम्। … ब्रह्महत्या
विशुध्यति) 13. 26. 40.

निश्चीरा
Niścīrā f.: Name of a river.
Famous in the three worlds (त्रिषु
लोकेषु विश्रुताम्) 3. 82. 119; by visiting
(समासाद्य) the river Niścīrā one gets the
fruit of a horse sacrifice and goes to the
world of Viṣṇu; those who give gift at the
confluence of the Niścīrā (निश्चीरासंगमे)
go without doubt to the world of Brahman;
on this river is situated the hermitage of
Vasiṣṭha 3. 82. 119-121.

निषध
Niṣadha m.: Name of a mountain.
A. Location: Listed among the six
mountains lying to the north of the Bhārata-
varṣa (6. 7. 6) and which extend from the west
to the east and are merged in the eastern and
the western oceans at the two ends (प्रागायता
महाराज षड् एते … ।अवगाढा ह्य् उभ-
यतः समुद्रौ पूर्वपश्चिमौ॥) 6. 7. 2;
these mountains lie at a distance of hundreds
of योजनस् from one another (तेषाम् अन्तर-
विष्कम्भो योजनानि सहस्रशः) 6. 7. 4; to
the south of the Nīla mountain and to the
north of the Niṣadha there is the big, eternal
Jambū tree named Sudarśana (दक्षिणेन तु
नीलस्य निषधस्योत्तरेण तु।सुदर्शनो
नाम महाञ् जम्बूवृक्षः सनातनः) 6. 8.
18; to the south of the Nīla mountain and to
the north of the Niṣadha also lies the mountain
Mālyavant 6. 7. 7.
B. Description:
Excellent (नगोत्तम) 6. 7. 3; all the six
mountains are frequented by the Siddhas and
the Cāraṇas (सिद्धचारणसेविताः) 6. 7. 4.
C. Characteristics: All the six mountains
are full of jewels (षड् एते रत्नपर्वताः)
6. 7. 2; the serpents and the Nāgas live on the
Niṣadha (सर्पा नागाश् च निषधे) 6. 7. 48;
also the Gandharvas live there (गन्धर्वा
निषधे शैले) 6. 7. 49.
D. Past event:
One of the mountains seen by Mārkaṇḍeya
in the belly of the Bāla (3. 186. 83 =
Nārāyaṇa 3. 187. 3) 3. 186. 102.
E. Impor-
tance: Finds place in the Daivata-Ṛṣi-Vaṃśa
13. 151. 26, 2.

निष्कुट
Niṣkuṭa m.: Name of a mountain (?)
A mountain range of the Himālayas
(?); Arjuna, in his expedition to the north,
conquered it along with the mountain
Himavant; from there he went to the Śveta
mountain (स विनिर्जित्य संग्रामे हिम-
वन्तं सनिष्कुटम्।श्वेतपर्वतम् आसाद्य
न्यवसत् पुरुषर्सभः॥) 2. 24. 27 (Nī. on
Bom. Ed. 2. 27. 29: निष्कुटं शैलविशेषम्).

नील
Nīla m.: Name of a mountain.
A. Location: Listed among the six
mountains lying to the north of the Bhārata-
varṣa (6. 7. 6) and which extend from the west
to the east and are submerged in the eastern
and the western oceans at the two ends 6. 7. 2
(for citation see Niṣadha); these six moun-
tains lie at a distance of hundreds of योजनस्
from one another 6. 7. 4; to the south of the
Nīla and to the north of the Niṣadha there
is the big, eternal Jambū tree named
Sudarśana 6. 8. 18; the Śvetavarṣa lies
beyond the Nīla mountain 6. 7. 35; the
Ramaṇakavarṣa lies to the south of the
Śvetavarṣa and to the north of the Nīla
6. 9. 2; to south of the Nīla and to the
north of the Meru lie the Uttarakurus 6.
8. 2; to the south of the Nīla and to the
north of the Niṣadha lies the mountain
Mālyavant 6. 7. 7.
B. Description: Big
(महागिरि) 3. 186. 103; reckoned by
Brahman among the kings of mountains
(एते पर्वतराजानः) 14. 43. 5; all the six
mountains are frequented by the Siddhas and
the Cāraṇas (सिद्धचारणसेविताः) 6. 7. 4.
C. Characteristics: All the six mountains
are full of jewels (षड् एते रत्नपर्वताः)
6. 7. 2; the Nīla is full of the cat's eye gems
(वैडूर्यमय) 6. 7. 3; the Brahmanical
seers live there (नीले ब्रह्मर्षयो नृप) 6. 7.
49; listed by Brahman among the mountains
which are characterized by the middle quality
i. e. the quality of रजस् (मध्यमो गुणः)
14. 43. 1; (Nī. on Bom. Ed. 14. 43. 1:
मध्यमो गुणः रजोगुणप्रधानः) 14.
43. 4.
D. Past event: One of the
mountains seen by Mārkaṇḍeya in the belly
of the Bāla (3. 186. 83 = Nārāyaṇa 3. 187.
3) 3. 186. 103;
E. Importance: Finds
place in the Daivata-Ṛṣi-Vaṃśa 13. 151.
26, 2.

नीलिका
Nīlikā f.: Name of a river.
Mentioned in the Daivata-Ṛṣi-Vaṃśa
13. 151. 22, 2.

नेमिपर्वत
Nemiparvata m.: Name of a mountain.
One who bathes on the Nemi mountain
washes off his sin and goes to heaven 13.
26. 12.

नैमिष
Naimiṣa1 nt., Naimiṣakuñja, Naimiṣeyaḥ
kuñjaḥ m.: Name of a तीर्थ।
A. Location: On the river Sarasvatī in
the Kurukṣetra (ततो नैमिषकुञ्जं च
समासाद्य … ।ऋषयः … कुरुक्षेत्रं गताः
पुरा॥ततः कुञ्जः सरस्वत्यां कृतो
भरतसत्तम) 3. 81. 92-93; 9. 36. 48,
50, 54.
B. Origin: The sages once went
to the Kurukṣetra to perform long sessions
of sacrifice but were disappointed as there
was no room for them; hence Sarasvatī
created many Kuñjas there and returned;
these Kuñjas together came to be known as the
Naimiṣeya Kuñja (एवं स कुञ्जो राजेन्द्र
नैमिषेय इति स्मृतः) 9. 36. 48-51, 54; (ततः
कुञ्जः सरस्वत्यां कृतो भरतसत्तम।
ऋषीणाम् अवकाशः स्याद् यथा … ॥) 3. 81.
93.
C. Description: Holy (पुण्य) 3.
82. 53; 13. 105. 45; 13. 151. 18; always
holy (नित्यं पुण्यम्) 3. 82. 57; ritually
pure (मेध्य) 3. 82. 57; resorted to by
the Siddhas (सिद्धनिषेवित) 3. 82. 53.
D.
Holy: (1) Naimiṣa looked upon as holy
on the whole earth (पृथिव्यां नैमिषं
पुण्यम्) 3. 81. 173 (Nī., who takes
नैमिष to mean the religious merit acquired
in the Naimiṣa forest (see the next entry),
on Bom. Ed. 3. 83. 202: नैमिषं
नैमिषारण्ये कृतम् पुण्यम् पृथिव्याम्
एव संततिसंपत्तिसार्वभौमादिपदप्रा-
प्तिहेतुर् इत्य् अर्थः); (2) By taking a
bath (अभिषेक) in this तीर्थ one who
is controlled and lives on limited food
secures the fruit of a Gavāmayana sacrifice
and purifies his lineage up to the seventh
generation 3. 82. 56; the bath (स्नात्वा) इन्
the तीर्थ secures for the person the fruit of
gifting a thousand cows 3. 81. 94; the bath
(उपस्पृश्य कृतोदकः) secures for one who
has controlled his sense organs the fruit of
a Puruṣamedha 13. 26. 32; one who bathes
(विगाह्य) in the ample waters of the Naimiṣa
wakes up in the Vimāna praised by the
Apsarases 9. 36. 35; (3) More than bathing
in waters one should bathe in (i. e. practise)
austerities at this तीर्थ (?) (अद्भ्यो
भूयः प्लाव्यं तपसा वै शरीरं) 12.
286. 37 (Nī., however, on Bom. Ed. 12.
297. 37: अद्भ्यः अद्भिः तपसा च शरीरं
प्लाव्यं शोधनो ऽयं (? शोधनीयम्)
तत्र आपः (? अपः) त्यक्त्वा); (4) The wise
declare that one who abandons life at the
Naimiṣa by fasting goes to heaven 3. 82. 57;
(5) Those that are high-souled, have observed
vows and who resort to this तीर्थ become
auspicious and reach the Goloka (? गवां
विमाने 13. 105. 44). 13. 105. 45 (for other
details see Gayaśiras).
E. Importance:
(1) Brahman always lives there together
with hosts of gods 3. 82. 53; (2) Finds
mention in the Daivata-Ṛṣi-Vaṃśa 13. 151.
18, 2.
F. Past event: The sages living in
the Naimiṣa forest once went to the Kuru-
kṣetra on a pilgrimage (ऋषयः … नैमिषेयास्
तपोधनाः।तीर्थयात्रां पुरस्कृत्य कुरु-
क्षेत्रं गताः पुरा) 3. 81. 92-93.
G.
Limitation: Bhagīratha told Brahmadeva that
he had not reached the Ṛṣiloka (13. 106. 5;
Brahmaloka according to 13. 106. 39) by
giving cows in large numbers as gifts at the
Naimiṣa (but due to तपस् 13. 106. 41)
13. 106. 37.

नैमिष
Naimiṣa2, Naimiṣāraṇya nt.: Name of
a forest.
A. Location: In the east 3. 85. 3;
1. 207. 5-6; the river Gomatī flows along
the Naimiṣa forest and the city Hāstinapura
is situated near it (नैमिषे गोमतीतीरे यत्र
नागाह्वयं पुरम्) 12. 343. 2; the river
Utpalinī flows close to it 1. 207. 6.
B.
Holiness: (1) There are many very holy
तीर्थस् sacred to gods in the Naimiṣa
forest 3. 85. 4, and on the river Gomatī
3. 93. 1-2; (2) One who desires to go
to the Naimiṣa forest destroys half of his
sin; as soon as he enters it he is freed
of all sins (नैमिषं प्रार्थयानस्य
पापस्यार्धं प्रणश्यति।प्रविष्टमात्रस्
तु नरः सर्वपापैः प्रमुच्यते॥) 3.
82. 54; (3) One who wants to visit
तीर्थस् (तीर्थतत्परः) should live in the
Naimiṣa for a month for all the तीर्थस् on
the earth are present there (पृथिव्यां यानि
तीर्थानी नैमिषे तानि भारत) 3. 82. 55.
C. Epic events: (1) Kulapati Śaunaka was
engaged in a twelve yearly sacrificial session
in this forest at which Sūta Ugraśravas
arrived 1. 1. 1; 1. 4. 1; the sages living in
the Naimiṣa forest surrounded Ugaśravas to
listen various narratives from him 1. 1. 3;
Ugraśravas narrated the eighteen पर्वन्स् of
the Mahābhārata to the sages in this forest
1. 2. 71; (2) Arjuna, during his exile,
passed by the river Utpalinī flowing along
the Naimiṣa forest after he descended from
the slopes of the Himavant and then
proceeded to the east 1. 207. 6; (3)
from the Kāmyaka forest the Pāṇḍavas
entered the Naimiṣa forest and bathed in the
तीर्थस् of the Gomatī 3. 93. 1; (4) Bala-
rāma went to the तीर्थ where the Sarasvatī
returned for the sake of the sages living in
the Naimiṣa forest (ऋषीणां नैमिषेयाणाम्)
9. 36. 35.
D. Past events: (1) King
Yayāti, while descending from the heaven,
saw four kings Pratardana, Vasumanas, Śibi
and Aṣṭaka, in the Naimiṣa forest performing
a Vājapeya sacrifice and he chose to fall
among them 5. 119. 9; (2) Baka Dālbhya
after receiving a large number of cattle saved
the kingdom of Dhṛtarāṣṭra from perishing
and returned to the Naimiṣa forest (मोक्ष-
यित्वा ततो राष्ट्रं प्रतिगृह्य पशून् बहून्।
हृष्टात्मा नैमिषारण्यं जगाम पुनर् एव
ह॥) 9. 40. 24; (3) The ascetics living
in the Naimiṣa forest (ऋषयः … नैमिषेयास्
तपोधनाः) left for Kurukṣetra when they
started for a तीर्थयात्रा 3. 81. 92; (4)
Sages coming together (from different places)
lived in the Naimiṣa forest; when once they
performed a सत्र there they thought of the
river Sarasvatī; when the river arrived it
was known there as Kāñcanākṣī 9. 37. 15,
18; (5) Formerly, once, when a twelve-
yearly सत्र of the ascetics living in the
Naimiṣa (नैमिषेयाणाम्) was over and they
had also performed the Viśvajit they left
for the Pāñcālas to ask Dakṣiṇā from the
king Kṛṣṇa 9. 40. 3; (6) The old men
living in the Naimiṣa forest (नैमिषारण्य-
वासिनः) used to characterize the narrative
of Āstīka, composed by Dvaipāyana, as an
old Itihāsa (इतिहासम् इमं वृद्धाः पुरा-
णं परिचक्षते) 1. 13. 6; (7) Formerly,
once, when gods offered a सत्र, Vaivasvata
(Yama) acted as a Śamitṛ (तत्र वैवस्वतो
राजञ् शामित्रम् अकरोत् तदा) 1. 189. 1
(Nī. on Bom. Ed. 1. 197. 1: शमिता यज्ञे
पशुवधकर्ता तस्य कर्म शामित्रम्);
(8) Formerly, in the Kṛtayuga, the ascetics
in the Naimiṣa forest (नैमिषेयास् तपस्-
विनः) were engaged in a twelve-yearly
sacrificial session for which many sages
arrived 9. 36. 39-40; (9) The wheel of
Dharma, in tune with the one in the former
creation, was set in motion in the Naimiṣa
forest (यत्र पूर्वाभिसर्गेण धर्म-
चक्रं प्रवर्तितम्।नैमिषे) 12. 343. 2.
E. Importance: People of the region of the
Naimiṣa (सनैमिषाः, आ नैमिषात्, नैमिषाः)
know the Dharma, follow the Dharma (धर्-
मं जानन्ति शाश्वतम्; धर्मं पुराणम्
उपजीवन्ति सन्तः; जानन्ति धर्मम्) 8.
30. 60-62, 75.

नैमिषकुञ्ज
Naimiṣakuñja m.: See Naimiṣa1.

नौबन्धन
Naubandhana nt.: Name of the highest
peak (शृङ्ग) of the Himavant.
The highest peak of the mountain
Himavant to which the ark of Manu was
tied by the seven sages was known as
Naubandhana even in the days of the narrator
of the Mahābhārata (तच् च नौबन्धनं
नाम शृङ्गं हिमवतः परम्।ख्यातम्
अद्यापि कौन्तेय) 3. 185. 45-47.

पञ्चनद
Pañcanada nt.: Name of a place
marked by five rivers ? (identical with Pañca-
srotas ?)
Described as famous in the world and
holy (लोके ख्यातं पञ्चनदं च पुण्यम्)
3. 134. 11 (Nī., however, on Bom. Ed. 3.
134. 12: लोके ऽपि पञ्चानां विषयस्रोतसां
समाहारः पञ्चनदम् उपेयम्). [See
Pañca nadyaḥ and Pañcasrotas below, and
Pañcanada in Section 1. 5 A]

पञ्च
Pañca nadyaḥ f. (pl.): Five rivers,
not specified.
Duryodhana assures Yudhiṣṭhira during
the game of dice that if the Pāṇḍavas
successfully passed the thirteenth year un-
known to the spies of the Kauravas, the latter
would get back the five rivers (तवैव ता
भारत पञ्चनद्यः) (i. e. the kingdom of
the region marked by the five rivers) 3. 35.
10 (Nī. on Bom. Ed. 3. 34. 11. वितस्तादि-
पञ्चनद्युपलक्षितो देशः); the five rivers,
excluding the Sindhu, are counted by Mārka-
ṇḍeya among those that are described as
mothers of the fire-hearths (i. e. sacrifices
were offered on their banks (for Nī. see
Kapilā) (सिन्धुवर्जं पञ्च नद्यो … एता
नद्यस् तु धिष्ण्यानां मातरो याः प्रकीर्-
तिताः) 3. 212. 21, 24. [See Pañcanada above
and Pañcanada in Section 1. 5 A]

पञ्चयज्ञा
Pañcayajñā f.: Name of a तीर्थ।
By visiting the तीर्थ (अभिगम्य) one
is glorified in the heaven 3. 82. 9.

पञ्चवट
Pañcavaṭa m.: Name of a sacred place.
One who has observed chastity and has
controlled his senses (ब्रह्मचारी जितेन्द्-
रियः), if he visits the Pañcavaṭa he secures
great merit and is glorified in the world of the
righteous (पुण्येन महता युक्तः सतां
लोके महीयते); God Sthāṇu (Śiva) himself
is present there; just by visiting the place and
by worshipping god Śiva one gets success
(तम् अर्चयित्वा देवेशं गमनाद् एव
सिध्यति) 3. 81. 141-142.

पञ्चस्रोतस्
Pañcasrotas nt.: Name of a place
marked by five streams ? (identical with
Pañcanada ?)
Pañcaśikha, the first pupil of Āsuri, was
once engaged in a long sacrificial session
lasting for a thousand years at Pañcasrotas
(पञ्चस्रोतसि यः सत्रम् आस्ते वर्षस-
हस्रिकम्) 12. 211. 10 (Nī., however, on
Bom. Ed. 12. 218. 10: पञ्च स्रोतांसि
विषयकेदारप्रणालिका यस्य तस्मिन् मनसि
मानसं सत्रम् इत्य् अर्थः). [See Pañca-
nada, Pañca nadyaḥ]

पद्मसरस्
Padmasaras nt.: Name of a lake.
Described as pleasing (रम्य); Kṛṣṇa,
Bhīma and Arjuna, starting for the Magadha
from the land of the Kurus and passing
through Kurujāṅgala, first reached Padma-
saras before crossing the Kālakūṭa mountain
2. 18. 26.

पम्पा
Pampā f.: Name of a large lake
(तटाकिनी 3. 263. 40).
A. Location: Located near the mountain
Ṛśyamūka 3. 263. 40.
B. Description:
Its water was auspicious (शिवजला) 3. 263.
40; frequented by swans and ducks (हंस-
कारण्डवायुता) 3. 263. 40; a lotus pond
having many day blooming and night-bloom-
ing lotuses in it (नलिनीं प्रभूतकमलोत्-
पलाम्) 3. 264. 1; a very cool and pleasing
breeze, having the fragrance of nectar, blows
in the forest near the Pampā (मारुतेन
सुशीतेन सुखेनामृतगन्धिना।सेव्यमानो
वने तस्मिन्) 3. 264. 2.
C. Rāmāyaṇa
events: Sugrīva and his four counsellors
lived near the Pampā 3. 263. 41; Rāma and
Lakṣmaṇa reached the lake in order to meet
Sugrīva 3. 264. 1; they drank its water and
gave offerings to manes before proceeding
towards Ṛśyamūka (तर्पयित्वा पितॄन् अपि)
3. 264. 8-9.

पयोष्णी
Payoṣṇī f.: Name of a river.
A. Location: Listed twice by Saṃjaya
among the rivers of the Bhāratavarṣa; its
water used by people for drinking 6. 10. 15,
19; in the south 3. 86. 1; near the Vindhya
mountain (एष विन्ध्यो महाशैलः पयोष्णी
च समुद्रगा) 3. 58. 21; one could
proceed from there to the mountain Vai-
ḍūrya and the Narmadā (स पयोष्ण्यां
 … स्नात्वा … वैडूर्यपर्वतं चैव नर्-
मदां च … समाजगाम) 3. 121. 15.
B. Description: Very holy (महापुण्या)
3. 83. 37; having excellent तीर्थस् on it
(सुतीर्था) 3. 120. 30; having pleasant तीर्थस्
on it (रम्यतीर्था), having ample water
(बहुजला), and visited by the Brāhmaṇas
(द्विजसेविता) 3. 86. 4; excellent river (सरि-
तां वरा) 3. 83. 37; flowing to the ocean
(समुद्रगा) 3. 58. 21; made prosperous
(?) by the king of Vidarbha (विदर्भ-
राजोपचिता) 3. 120. 30; river of king Nṛga
(सरिन् णृगस्य) 3. 86. 4; its water is
mixed with the Soma pressed (on its bank)
(सुतेन सोमेन विमिश्रितोदा) 3. 120. 30;
all the rivers listed by Saṃjaya are said to
be mothers of the universe and very strong
6. 10. 35 (for citation see Atikṛṣṇā).
C.
Epic event: Yudhiṣṭhira, while on pilgrimage,
reached the river Payoṣṇī and lived there 3.
120. 30; Dhaumya advised the Pāṇḍavas to
bathe in the river and be freed from sins 3.
121. 14; accordingly they bathed and proceed-
ed towards the Vaiḍūrya mountain and the
river Narmadā 3. 121. 15.
D. Past events:
(1) On the river Payoṣṇī gods with Indra,
and the Prajāpatis, offered many kinds of
sacrifices giving large दक्षिणास् 3. 121. 2;
(2) On its bank king Nṛga gave satisfaction
to Indra with Soma and gave ample दक्षिणास्
3. 121. 1; 3. 86. 6; here the great ascetic
Mārkaṇḍeya sang a गाथा in the presence
of king Nṛga, describing his genealogy,
at the time of his sacrifice (अनुवंश्यां
जगौ गाथां नृगस्य धरणीपतेः॥
नृगस्य यजमानस्य प्रत्यक्षम् इति नः
श्रुतम्।) 3. 86. 5-6 (Nī. on 3. 88. 5;
अनुवंश्यां वंशानुरूपां न तु मृग-
(? नृग) मात्रानुरूपाम्); (3) Here king
Gaya, the son of Amūrtarayas, satisfied Indra
with Soma in his seven horse sacrifices 3. 121.
3.
E. Holiness: (1) There were many
आश्रमस् of great sages on the river 3. 58.
21; (2) By worshipping manes and gods
on the Payoṣṇī one gets the fruit of gifting
a thousand cows 3. 83. 37; (3) One who
bathes (उपस्पृश्य) in the Payoṣṇī is freed
of sins (धूतपाप्मा भविष्यसि) 3. 121. 14;
(4) If one were to bathe (उपस्पृशेत्) in
the river Payoṣṇī he would obtain the world
obtained by Gaya (i. e. the world of Indra)
3. 121. 13.

परा
Parā f.: Name of a river.
Listed by Saṃjaya among the rivers of
the Bhāratavarṣa; its water used by people
for drinking 6. 10. 19, 13; all the rivers
listed here are said to be mothers of the uni-
verse and very strong 6. 10. 35 (for citation
see Atikṛṣṇā).

पर्णाशा
Parṇāśā f.: Name of a river.
(1) Described as a great river (माहा-
नदी) 7. 67. 44; excellent river (सरितां
वरा) 7. 67. 47; having cool water (शीततोया)
7. 67. 44; (2) She was the mother of
Śrutāyudha 7. 67. 44, 57; the river gave birth
to this son from Varuṇa; she wanted a
son who could not be killed by his enemies
(अवध्यो ऽयं भवेल् लोके शत्रूणां तनयो
मम) 7. 67. 44-45; Varuṇa, however,
gave the son a heavenly missile and made
him unassailable by enemies as he could not
make a mortal immortal (नास्ति चाप्य् अमर-
त्वं वै मनुष्यस्य कथंचन। …
दुर्धर्षस् त्व् एष शत्रूणां रणेषु भविता
सदा) 7. 67. 47-48; (3) Finds mention
in the Daivata-Ṛṣi-Vaṃśa 13. 151. 16, 2.
[See Pūrṇāśā]

पलाशक
Palāśaka m. pl.: Name of a holy place.
Situated in the north 3. 88. 1; described
as holy (पुण्येषु) and pleasing (रम्येषु)
3. 88. 13; Jamadagni offered a sacrifice at the
Palāśakas (जमदग्निर् महायशाः।पलाश-
केषु … अयजताभिभूः) 3. 88. 13; at this
sacrifice all the excellent rivers brought their
water and waited on Jamadagni; a श्लोक to
this effect was sung here by Viśvāvasu
himself 3. 88. 14-16.

पलाशिनी
Palāśinī f.: Name of a river.
Listed by Saṃjaya among the rivers of
the Bhāratavarṣa; its water used by people
for drinking 6. 10. 21, 13; all the rivers
listed here are described as mothers of the
universe and very strong 6. 10. 35 (for
citation see Atikṛṣṇā).

पवनस्य
Pavanasya hradaḥ m.: Name of a
lake sacred to the Maruts.
Described as an excellent तीर्थ of the
Maruts (मरुतां तीर्थम् उत्तमम्) 3. 81.
88; by bathing in this तीर्थ one is glorified
in the world of Vāyu (वायुलोके महीयते)
3. 81. 88.

पवित्रा
Pavitrā f.: Name of a river.
Listed by Saṃjaya among the rivers
of the Bhāratavarṣa; its water used by people
for drinking 6. 10. 20, 13 (for other details
see Palāśinī).

पाका
Pākā f.: Name of a river.
Mentioned among those rivers by visiting
which one becomes auspicious, assumes a
heavenly form and, wearing heavenly garlands
and full of holy fragrance, reaches the Goloka
(? गवां विमाने 13. 105. 44) 13. 105. 47-48
(for citation see Karatoyinī).

पाणिखात
Pāṇikhāta nt.: Name of a तीर्थ।
By bathing here and by giving offerings
to gods (तर्पयित्वा च देवताः) one gets
the fruit of a Rājasūya and goes to the world
of sages (ऋषिलोकं च गच्छति) 3. 81. 75.

पापहरा
Pāpaharā f.: Name of a river.
Listed by Saṃjaya among the rivers of
the Bhāratavarṣa; its water used by people
for drinking 6. 10. 21, 13 (for other details
see Palāśinī).

पारा
Pārā f.: Name of a river. [See
Kauśikī]

पारिप्लव
Pāriplava nt.: Name of a तीर्थ।
Described as famous in the three worlds
(त्रैलोक्यविश्रुत); by visiting this तीर्थ
one gets the fruit of an Agniṣṭoma and an
Atirātra 3. 81. 10.

पारियात्र
Pāriyātra m.: Name of a mountain.
A. Location: (1) Listed by Saṃjaya
among the seven chief mountain ranges of
the Bhāratavarṣa (सप्तैते कुलपर्वताः)
6. 10. 10.
B. Importance: Listed by
Brahman among the mountains who are
called kings of mountains (एते पर्वत-
राजानः) 14. 43. 4-5; (Are these mountains
also to be looked upon as possessing the
middle गुण, i. e. the quality of रजस् ? See
Kāṣṭhavant).
C. Past events: (1) Sage
Gautama having reached the Pāriyātra moun-
tain built his आश्रम there; he lived there
for sixty thousand years 12. 127. 3-4; (2)
A certain Dasyu, named Kāpavya, used to
roam always on the ranges of the Pāriyātra
(पारियात्रचरः सदा) 12. 133. 5; (3)
One of the mountains seen by Mārkaṇḍeya
in the belly of the Bāla (3. 186. 13 = Nārā-
yaṇa 3. 187. 3) 3. 186. 104.
D. Simile:
Yudhiṣṭhira compared his four brothers, felled
down by the Yakṣa, with the four moun-
tains Himavant, Pāriyātra, Vindhya and
Malaya 3. 297. 14.

पारिषेणा
Pāriṣeṇā f.: Name of a river.
Listed by Saṃjaya among the rivers
of the Bhāratavarṣa; its water used by
people for drinking 6. 10. 22, 13; (for other
details see Palāśinī).

पिङ्गा
Piṅgā f.: Name of a तीर्थ।
Situated on the Arbuda mountain (?) 3.
80. 74; one who has observed chastity and
has controlled his senses (ब्रह्मचारि
जितेन्द्रियः) if he bathes there (उपस्पृश्य)
he gets the reward of gifting a hundred
कपिला cows 3. 80. 76.

पिच्छिला
Picchilā f.: Name of a river.
Listed by Saṃjaya among the rivers of
the Bhāratavarṣa; its water used by people
for drinking 6. 10. 28, 13 (for other details
see Palāśinī).

पिञ्जला
Piñjalā f.: Name of a river.
Listed by Saṃjaya among the rivers of
the Bhāratavarṣa; people use its water for
drinking 6. 10. 26, 13 (for other details see
Palaśinī).

पिण्डारक
Piṇḍāraka nt.: Name of a तीर्थ।
A. Location: In the Surāṣṭras (सुरा-
ष्ट्रेषु) 3. 86. 16; in the Dvāravatī (ततो
द्वारवतीं गच्छेत् … पिण्डारके नरः
स्नात्वा) 3. 80. 82.
B. Description:
Auspicious (शुभ) and frequented by
ascetics (तापसाचरित) 3. 86. 18.
C.
Special feature: At Piṇḍāraka there were
seals (?) marked with lotuses which could
be seen even in the days of the narrator of
the Mahābhārata; this was its marvellous
feature (तस्मिंस् तीर्थे महाभाग पद्म-
लक्षणलक्षिताः।अद्यापि मुद्रा दृश्यन्ते
तद् अद्भुतम् अरिन्दम॥) 3. 80. 83; these
lotuses (on the seals, or lotus flowers ?)
bear the mark of trident (त्रिशूलाङ्कानि पद्-
मानि दृश्यन्ते कुरुनन्दन) 3. 80. 84.
D. Holiness: (1) Mahādeva is present
there 3. 80. 84; (2) By bathing there one
who is controlled and takes limited food
(नियतो नियताशनः) obtains much gold
(लभेद् बहु सुवर्णकम्) 3. 80. 82; (3)
By bathing there and by staying there over-
night (एकरात्रोषितो नरः) one gets the
fruit of an Agniṣṭoma and is pure the next
morning (प्रभातां शर्वरीं शुचिः) 13.
26. 54.

पितामहसरस्
Pitāmahasaras nt.: Name of a holy lake.
Situated on the Śailarāja (i. e. Hima-
vant ?) (शैलराजप्रतिष्ठितम्) 3. 82. 128;
from this lake rises the river Kumāradhārā
3. 82. 129, and also the river Sarasvatī 9.
41. 29; by bathing in this lake (तत्रा-
भिषेकं कुर्वाणः) one gets the fruit of
an Agniṣṭoma 3. 82. 128. [See Puṣkara]

पितामहस्य
Pitāmahasya uttaravedi f.: See Prajā-
pateḥ vedī2.

पिप्पलावती
Pippalāvatī f.: Name of a river.
Listed by Saṃjaya among the rivers of
the Bhāratavarṣa; its water used by people
for drinking 6. 10. 21, 13 (for other details
see Palāśinī).

पुण्डरीक
Puṇḍarīka nt.: Name of a तीर्थ।
By bathing at this तीर्थ on the tenth
day of the bright fortnight of a month (शुक्ल-
पक्षे दशम्यां तु) one gets the fruit of a
Puṇḍarīka sacrifice 3. 81. 69.

पुण्य
Puṇya nt.: Name of a sacred lake.
Situated near the river Pārā (i. e. the
river Kauśikī) and the mountains Maināka
and Asita 3. 87. 9, 7; Lomaśa advised Yudhi-
ṣṭhira to bathe silently in the lake (तूष्णीं …
समुपस्पृश) 3. 135. 7.

पुरमालिनी
Puramālinī f.: Name of a river.
Listed by Saṃjaya among the rivers of
the Bhāratavarṣa; people used its water for
drinking 6. 10. 20, 13 (for other details see
Palāśinī).

पुरापवर्तन
Purāpavartana nt.: Name of a sacred
place.
By repairing to (सेव्य) Purāpavartana,
one who is controlled (दान्तः) and causes
no injury to others (अहिंसकः) is served
in the Nandana forest by the Apsarases 13.
26. 42.

पुरु
Puru m.: Name of a mountain.
Where Purūravas was born (पर्वतश्
च पुरुर् नाम यत्र जातः पुरूरवाः) 3.
88. 19.

पुरुही
Puruhī f.: Name of a river.
Listed by Saṃjaya among the rivers
of the Bhāratavarṣa; its water used by people
for drinking 6. 10. 22, 13 (for other details
see Palāśinī).

पुष्कर
Puṣkara1 nt., sg. and pl. (Puṣkarāṇi,
Puṣkareṣu): Name of a तीर्थ; also called
once Pitāmahasaras (3. 87. 13).
A. Location: In the west 3. 87. 1.
B. Description: Holy (पुण्य) 3. 87. 13;
(पुण्यम् अन्तरिक्षे च पुष्करम्) 3. 81. 173;
the lake of Pitāmaha Brahmadeva (पितामह-
सरस्) 3. 87. 13; of the high-souled (Pitā-
maha ?) (तीर्थे महात्मनः) 3. 80. 51;
the तीर्थ of the god of gods (Brahmadeva)
(देवदेवस्य तीर्थम्) 3. 80. 41; famous,
famous in the three worlds (विख्यात, त्रै-
लोक्यविश्रुत) 3. 80. 41.
C. Epic events:
(1) Arjuna, after his marriage with Subhadrā,
spent with her at the Puṣkaras (पुष्करेषु)
the remaining period of his exile 1. 213. 13;
(2) Lomaśa advised Yudhiṣṭhira to bathe
(जलं स्पृश) in all the Puṣkaras (पुष्क-
रेषु … सर्वेषु) 3. 125. 12; (3) Pulastya
recommended it to Bhīṣma 3. 80. 41.
D.
Past events: (1) Arjuna, while recounting
the past austerities performed by Kṛṣṇa,
said that formerly he once lived at the
Puṣkaras (पुष्करेषु) for ten thousand and
ten hundred years living only on water 3.
13. 1; (2) When the Pitāmaha was once
engaged in a sacrifice at the Puṣkara
(पुष्करस्थे पितामहे), the sages said that
the sacrifice will not yield great fruit (नायं
यज्ञो महाफलः) as the Sarasvatī was
not to be seen there; hearing that, the
Pitāmaha thought of the river and invited
her to appear at the Puṣkaras (पुष्करेषु)
which she did as the river Suprabhā; thus the
Sarasvatī became manifest at the Puṣkaras
(पुष्करेषु) for the sake of the Pitāmaha
and for the satisfaction of the wise 9. 37. 11,
12, 14.
E. Holiness: (1) There are
आश्रमस् of the Vaikhānasas, the Siddhas,
and the sages at the Puṣkara 3. 87. 13; one
should settle down there (समाविशेत्) 3. 80.
41; gods and sages achieved there (पुष्क-
रेषु) great perfection and were endowed with
great merit (सिद्धिं समभिसंप्राप्ताः
पुण्येन महतान्विताः) 3. 80. 47; (2)
Prajāpati sang a गाथा at the Puṣkaras
(पुष्करेषु) in praise of the Puṣkaras: If
a spirited person (मनस्विन्) even mentally
longs for the Puṣkaras (पुष्कराणि) his sins
are destroyed and he is delighted in heaven
(नाकपृष्ठे च मोदते) 3. 87. 14-15; (3)
The wise say that one who is engaged in the
worship of the manes and gods (पितृदेवा-
र्चने रतः) and who takes bath (अभि-
षेक) in this तीर्थ gets the fruit of a horse
sacrifice ten times (अश्वमेधं दशगुणं
प्रवदन्ति मनीषिणः); if a person of any
one of the four classes bathes there these
high-souled persons are then not born in a
lower species (न वियोनिं व्रजन्त्य् एते स्नातास्
तीर्थे महात्मनः); if one visits the Puṣkara
especially on the full moon day of the month
of Kārtika his fruit increases without ever
being destroyed (फलं तत्राक्षयं तस्य
वर्धते) 3. 80. 48, 51-52; stay at the
Puṣkara on the full moon night of the
Kārtika (कार्तिकीं वा वसेद् एकाम्) is equal
to performing an Agnihotra for a full hundred
years (वर्षशतं पूर्णं अग्निहोत्रम्)
3. 80. 57; (4) One who remembers the
Puṣkara morning and evening with folded
hands will have bathed in all the तीर्थस् and
will get imperishable worlds in the abode of
Brahman (उपस्पृष्टं भवेत् तेन सर्वती-
र्थेषु भारत प्राप्नुयाच् च नरो लोकान्
ब्रह्मणः सदने ऽक्षयान्) 3. 80. 53
(Nī. on Bom. Ed. 3. 82. 33: उपस्पृष्टं
स्नातं भवेत्); whatever sin is com-
mitted by a man or a woman it gets
destroyed as soon as one bathes in the
Puṣkara (पुष्करे स्नातमात्रस्य) 3. 80.
54; if a wise person even mentally longs
for the Puṣkaras (मनसाप्य् अभिकामस्य
पुष्कराणि मनस्विनः) all his sins are
cleansed and he is worshipped in heaven
(नाकपृष्ठे च पूज्यते) 3. 80. 45; (5)
At the Puṣkara ten thousand crores of तीर्थस्
are present at all the three divisions of the
day (सांनिध्यं पुष्करे येषां त्रिसन्-
ध्यम्) 3. 83. 42; (6) At this तीर्थ the
Ādityas, the Vasus, the Rudras, the Sādhyas,
the Maruts, the Gandharvas, and the Apsa-
rases are present at all times; Pitāmaha lived
there happily for ever 3. 80. 43, 46; (7)
The gods, the Daityas, and the Brahmani-
cal sages practised austerities and, by the
great religious merit thus acquired, they at-
tained divine योग (दिव्ययोगाः), i. e., they
attained perfection (सिद्धिं समभिसं-
प्राप्ताः) 3. 80. 44, 47; (8) By living at
the Puṣkara for twelve years a person who
is controlled and pure (नियतः शुचिः)
obtains the fruit of all sacrifices and goes to
the world of Brahman 3. 80. 56; (9)
Puṣkara is one of those place by visiting
which one becomes auspicious, has a divine
form, puts on heavenly garlands and being
rich in heavenly fragrance delights in the
world of the cows (? मोदन्ति गवां
विमाने) 13. 105. 44, 48 (for citation see
Karatoyinī); (10) Aṅgiras told Gautama
that by bathing (विगाह्य) in the Puṣkara
one rides in the Vimāna (विमानस्थः)
and is awakened by the praises of the
Apsarases 13. 26. 9; (11) Śaunaka advised
Janamejaya to visit the Puṣkara; such
visit gave the person longevity again in this
life (लब्धायुर् जीविते पुनः) 12. 148. 11;
(12) Parāśara told Janaka that more than
bathing in the water of Puṣkara one should
practise (lit. bathe in) austerities at the
Puṣkaras (पुष्करेषु) and other holy places
(अद्भ्यो भूयः प्लाव्यं तपसा वै
शरीरम्) 12. 286. 37; (13) Puṣkara
considered as the holy place of the mid-region
(पृथिव्यां नैमिषम् पुण्यम् अन्तरिक्षे च
पुष्करम्) 3. 81. 173; (however, Nī. on
Bom. Ed. 3. 83. 202: अन्तरिक्षे सूर्य-
चन्द्रादिमार्गे नक्षत्रादिचक्रे पुष्करं
प्रापयतीत्य् अर्थः); (also see the section
G. Importance and
H. Simile below and
section
C. Epic events (2) and (3) above);
F. Limitations: (i) Giving gifts of horses
in very large numbers and of thousands of
cows to the Brāhmaṇas at the Puṣkara
(पुष्करेषु) was highly meritorious no
doubt; (दशायुतानि चाश्वानाम् अयुतानि च
विंशतिम्।पुष्करेषु द्विजातिभ्यः प्रादां
गाश् च सहस्रशः); but that was not
enough to enable one to reach the Brahma-
loka—this is what Bhagīratha told Brahman
13. 106. 11; (ii) Sprinkling one's body with
the water of the Puṣkara is not necessary for
one who listens to the Bhārata (यो भारतं
समधिगच्छति वाच्यमानं किं तस्य
पुष्करजलैर् अभिषेचनेन) 1. 2. 242 (Nī.
on Bom. Ed. 1. 2. 392: पुषकरं आदि-
तीर्थं शुण्डाग्रं वा तदुपाहृतजलैः);
G. Importance: (1) Puṣkara is the first
among the तीर्थस् as Madhusūdana is among
all gods (यथा सुराणाम् सर्वेषाम् आदिस् तु
मधुसूदनः।तथैव पुष्करं राजंस्
तीर्थानाम् आदिर् उच्यते) 3. 80. 55; (2) It
is not easy to go to the Puṣkara, not easy
to perform austerities there or to give gifts
there; to be able to live there is extremely
difficult (दुष्करं पुष्करं गन्तुं दुष्-
करं पुष्करे तपः।दुष्करं पुष्करे
दानं वस्तुं चैव सुदुष्करम्॥) 3. 80.
58; (3) Finds mention in the Daivata-
Ṛṣi-Vaṃśa 13. 151. 14, 2.
H. Simile:
The entrance of the Kurukṣetra is as holy as
the Puṣkaras (कुरुक्षेत्रस्य तद् द्वारम्
 … संमिते पुष्कराणां च) 3. 81. 20-21.
[See Pitāmahasaras]

पुष्कर
Puṣkara2 m.: Name of a mountain in
the Puṣkaradvīpa.
In the Puṣkaradvīpa 6. 13. 24; described
as full of precious stones and jewels (मणि-
रत्नमन्त्) 6. 13. 24; god Prajāpati himself
always lives there; all gods, along with the
great sages, always wait on him worshipping
it with agreeable words (तं पर्युपासते
नित्यं … वाग्भिर् मनोनुकूलाभिः पूज-
यन्तः) 6. 13. 24-25.

पुष्करारण्य
Puṣkarāraṇya nt.: Name of a forest
where there is the तीर्थ Puṣkara.
A. Location: In the west (2. 29. 2).
B. Epic events: (1) Nakula, in his ex-
pedition to the west before the Rājasūya, con-
quered the Gaṇas called the Utsavasaṃketas
who lived in the Puṣkarāraṇya 2. 29. 7-8;
(2) Takṣaka, when he came to know the curse
of Kadrū, started practising severe austerities
at various sacred places one of them being the
Puṣkarāraṇya 1. 32. 3.
C. Holy: If
one resorts to the Puṣkarāraṇya and feeds
only a single Brāhmaṇa he rejoices as a result
of that act in this and the next world (प्रेत्य
चेह च मोदते); and, if he gives there
to a Brāhmaṇa, faithfully and without malice
(श्रद्धावान् अनसूयकः), vegetables, roots
and fruits on which he himself subsists, then
by that act, he gets the fruit of a horse sacri-
fice 3. 80. 49-50.

पुष्पन्यास
Puṣpanyāsa m.: Name of a तीर्थ।
By bathing at the Puṣpanyāsa one does
not grieve over death (उपस्पृश्य न शोचेन्
मरणं ततः) 3. 80. 114.

पुष्पवती
Puṣpavatī f.: Name of a sacred bathing
place.
By bathing (उपस्पृश्य) at the Puṣpa-
vatī and by fasting there for three nights one
gets the fruit of gifting a thousand cows and
lifts up his family 3. 83. 12.

पुष्पवत्|पुष्पवन्त्
Puṣpavant m.: Name of a mountain
in the Kuśadvīpa.
The fourth of the six mountains in the
Kuśadvīpa 6. 13. 10; all these mountains are
described as the best among the mountains
(पर्वतोत्तमाः) 6. 13. 11; the distance
between these six mountains doubles as one
moves from the one to the other (तेषाम्
अन्तरविष्कम्भो द्विगुणः प्रविभागशः)
6. 13. 11.

पुष्पवेणी
Puṣpaveṇī f.: Name of a river.
Listed by Saṃjaya among the rivers of
the Bhāratavarṣa; people use its water for
drinking 6. 10. 33, 13; all the rivers listed
here are described as mothers of the universe
and very strong 6. 10. 35 (for citation see
Atikṛṣṇā).

पूर्णाशा
Pūrṇāśā f.: Name of a river.
Described as a great river (महानदी);
listed by Saṃjaya among the rivers of the
Bhāratavarṣa; its water used by people for
drinking 6. 10. 30, 13; (for other details see
Puṣpaveṇī). [Identical with Parṇāśā ?]

पूर्वान्तगण्डिका
Pūrvāntagaṇḍikā f.: Name of a range
of hills (?)
It lies on the eastern peak of the Mālya-
vant mountain (in the Uttara Kurus) (तथा
माल्यवतः शृङ्गे पूर्वे पूर्वान्तगण्डिका)
6. 8. 27 (Nī. on Bom. Ed. 6. 7. 28: गण्डिका
क्षुद्रपर्वतः).

पूर्वाभिरामा
Pūrvābhirāmā f.: Name of a river.
Listed by Saṃjaya among the rivers of
the Bhāratavarṣa; its water used by people
for drinking 6. 10. 21, 13; (for other details
see Puṣpaveṇī).

पृथिव्यास्
Pṛthivyās tīrtham nt.: Name of a
तीर्थ।
By visiting the Pṛthivītīrtha (पृथिव्यास्
तीर्थम् आसाद्य) one secures the fruit of
giving a thousand cows 3. 81. 11.

पृथूदक
Pṛthūdaka nt.: Name of a तीर्थ।
A. Location: On the northern bank of
the Sarasvatī (तीर्थम् … सरस्वत्याः; सर-
स्वत्युत्तरे तीरे) 9. 38. 25-27, 29; 12. 148.
10.
B. Description: Famous, famous in
the three worlds (ख्यात, त्रैलोक्यविश्रुत)
3. 81. 122; holy (पुण्य) 12. 148. 10;
ritually pure, clean and sanctifying (मेध्य,
पवित्र, पावन) 3. 81. 128; the best of all
the तीर्थस् (उत्तमे सर्वतीर्थानाम्) 3. 81.
126; the holiest of all (पृथूदकात् पुण्य-
तमं नान्यत् तीर्थम्) 3. 81. 128, 125.
C. Presiding deity: Sacred to Kārtikeya 3.
81. 122.
D. Holiness: (1) One should
bathe at the Pṛthūdaka (अभिषेकं कुर्वीत)
and be engaged in worship of manes and
gods; just a bath there (स्नातमात्रस्य)
destroys whatever inauspicious deed (अशुभं
कर्म) a man or a woman does, either
knowingly or unknowingly as a human being
(अज्ञानाज् ज्ञनतो वापि … कृतं मानुष-
बुद्धिना); it secures for him the fruit of
an Aśvamedha and leads him to heaven 3.
81. 122-124; the wise say that even sinners
go to heaven by bathing at the Pṛthūdaka
3. 81. 129; (2) One who gives up his body
at the Pṛthūdaka while muttering prayers is
not affected by the fear of imminent death
(यस् त्यजेद् आत्मनस् तनुम्॥पृथूदके
जप्यपरो नैनं श्वोमरणं तपेत्) 3.
81. 126; 9. 38. 29; in a Gāthā sung by
Yayāti it is said that one who bathes in
or drinks water of the Pṛthūdaka is not
affected by imminent death (यत्रावगाह्य
पीत्वा वा नैव श्वोमरणं तपेत्) 12. 148.
10; (3) Sanatkumāra and Vyāsa have
sung (a Gāthā ?) which says that a visit
to the Pṛthūdaka is prescribed in the Veda
(वेदे च नियतं) 3. 81. 127; (4) The
Pṛthūdaka is holier than even the Kurukṣetra,
the Sarasvatī, and all the other तीर्थस् 3.
81. 125.
E. Epic event: Balarāma visited
this place and after bathing there (आप्लुत्य
 … उपस्पृश्य) gave many gifts to the Brāh-
maṇas 9. 38. 23, 30.
F. Past event:
Ruṣaṅgu, a Brāhmaṇa ascetic, decided in
oldage to give up his body and told his sons
to take him to the Pṛthūdaka; his sons took
him there where he was given bath according
to the prescribed rites (विधिना … आप्लुतः);
Ruṣaṅgu gave up his body there 9. 38. 24-28,
23.

पौलोम
Pauloma nt.: Name of a तीर्थ।
A. Location: One of the five तीर्थस्
on the southern ocean (समुद्रे तीर्थानि
दक्षिणे) 1. 208. 1.
B. Description: Very
purifying (सुपावन) 1. 208. 3; all the five
तीर्थस् there are described as very holy (सु-
पुण्यानि) and adorned by ascetics (शोभितानि
तपस्विभिः) 1. 208. 1.
C. History:
All these five तीर्थस् were once thronged by
ascetics but later avoided by them as some
of the ascetics were dragged away by five
crocodiles who came to live there; then these
तीर्थस् became desolate 1. 208. 2, 4-6.
D.
Epic event: Arjuna visited the तीर्थस् and
freed them of the crocodiles 1. 208. 7-21; 1.
209. 1-23. [See Nārītīrthāni]

प्रजापतेर्
Prajāpater uttaravedi f.: See Prajā-
pateḥ vedī2.

प्रजापतेः
Prajāpateḥ vedī1 f.: Designation of a
sacred place.
A. Formation: Prayāga, Pratiṣṭhāna,
Kambala, Aśvatara and the Bhogavatī तीर्थ
constitute the Vedī of Prajāpati (वेदी प्रोक्ता
प्रजापतेः) 3. 83. 72; (3. 93. 7); described
as frequented by ascetics (तपस्विजनजुष्टा)
3. 93. 7.
B. Holiness: There the Vedas
and the sacrifices in bodily form, as well as
the sages observing important vows, wait
upon Prajāpati; gods and Cakracaras offer
sacrifices there 3. 83. 72-73 (Nī. on Bom.
Ed. 3. 85. 72: चक्रचराः सूर्यादयः).
C. Epic event: The Pāṇḍavas, in their
तीर्थयात्रा, visited it in the company of
Brāhmaṇas; living there they practised the
best austerities and constantly satisfied the
Brāhmaṇas by giving them offerings obtained
in the forest (वन्येन हविषा) 3. 93. 7-8.
[See Prajāpateḥ vedī2]

प्रजापतेः
Prajāpateḥ vedī2 f.: Designation of a
sacred place.
The land of the high-souled Kuru, i. e.
the Kurukṣetra, along the river Sarasvatī, is
known as the Vedī of Prajāpati; it is five
योजनस् in extent all around (वेदी प्रजा-
पतेर् एषा समन्तात् पञ्चयोजना) 3. 129.
22; listed among the places which form the
boundary of the Kurukṣetrasamantapañcaka
where the name occurs as Prajāpater uttara-
vedi 9. 52. 20; (Pitāmahasya uttaravedi) 3.
81. 178; here the divine sages, as also the
royal sages and sages offered sacrifices with
the help of Brāhmaṇas related to the river
Sarasvatī (इह सारस्वतैर् यज्ञैर् इष्ट-
वन्तः सुरर्षयः।ऋषयश् चैव कौन्तेय
तथा राजर्षयो ऽपि च॥) 3. 129. 20-21
(Nī. on Bom. Ed. 3. 129. 14: सारस्वतैः
ब्राह्मणैः). [See Prajāpateḥ vedī1, Pla-
kṣāvataraṇa]

प्रतिष्ठान
Pratiṣṭhāna nt.: Name of a तीर्थ।
One of the five तीर्थस् which together
form the Vedī of Prajāpati 3. 83. 72; there
the Vedas and the sacrifices, in bodily form,
and the sages observing great vows wait upon
Prajāpati; gods and Cakracaras offer sacri-
fies there 3. 83. 73. [See Prajāpateḥ vedī1]

प्रभास
Prabhāsa nt.: Name of a तीर्थ; its
original name Hiraṇyasaras (12. 329. 46(5)).
A. Location: In the Surāṣṭras (सु-
राष्ट्रेषु) 3. 86. 16; on the western ocean
(पश्चिमस्यां दिशि समुद्रे) 12. 329. 46;
(उदधौ) 3. 86. 17; (समुद्रे पश्चिमे)
1. 210. 2, 1; 13. 96. 3; (समुद्रान्ते) 16.
4. 10; (तीर्थं महोदधेः) 3. 119. 3; a
तीर्थ on the river Sarasvatī (सरस्वत्या
वरे तीर्थे) 9. 34. 67; (तीर्थं सरस्वत्याः)
9. 34. 69.
B. Etymology: Its original
name was Hiraṇyasaras; after the moon
(Soma) bathed there and was freed of sin, he
became bright; the तीर्थ then came to be
known as Prabhāsa (तत्र चावभासितस्
तीर्थे यदा सोमस् तदाप्रभृति तीर्थं तत्
प्रभासम् इति नाम्ना ख्यातं बभूव)
12. 329. 46 (10); (प्रभासनात् तस्य ततः
प्रभासः) 9. 34. 37; 9. 34. 76-77; (एतत्
प्रभासते तीर्थम्) 3. 130. 7.
C. Des-
cription: Holy (पुण्य) 3. 119. 1; 3. 130.
7; 9. 34. 36; (3. 86. 16); suitable for holy
people (पुण्यजनोचित) 3. 13. 14; purifying
(पवित्र) 3. 130. 7; destroying sins (पाप-
नाशन) 3. 130. 7; excellent (वर) 9. 34.
67; (तीर्थवर) 3. 80. 78; (तीर्थप्रवर)
9. 34. 37, 38; (तीर्थानां प्रवरम्) 9. 34.
75; great, best (परम) 9. 34. 69; (उत्तम)
9. 34. 76; famous on the earth, famous in
the worlds (पृथिव्यां प्रथितम्) 3. 118.
15; (लोकविश्रुत) 3. 80. 77; the तीर्थ of
the gods (त्रिदशानां तीर्थम्) 3. 86. 17;
dear to Indra (इन्द्रस्य दयितम्) 3. 130. 7.
D. Epic events: (1) During his exile
Arjuna, after visiting the other तीर्थस् on the
west coast, went to Prabhāsa; Kṛṣṇa, hav-
ing come to know that Arjuna had arrived
at the Prabhāsadeśa, went there to meet him;
the two met at Prabhāsa; they sported there
according to their wishes and from there they
went to the Raivataka mountain 1. 210. 2-4,
8; (2) The Brāhmaṇas wished to visit the
Prabhāsa and the other तीर्थस् along with
Yudhiṣṭhira 3. 91. 10; (3) After visiting
Śūrpāraka, Yudhiṣṭhira went to Prabhāsa;
he bathed there and, with his brothers and
Kṛṣṇā, gave offerings to gods and manes;
the Brāhmaṇas and Lomaśa too offered there
to gods and manes; Yudhiṣṭhira practised
there severe austerities 3. 118. 15-17; (4)
Balarāma and Janārdana, along with the
Vṛṣṇi heroes, went to Prabhāsa to meet the
Pāṇḍavas; the Pāṇḍavas and the Vṛṣṇis held
consultations together at Prabhāsa 3. 118.
18; 3. 119. 1-3; (5) Arjuna, in his wander-
ings with the sacrificial horse, came to
Prabhāsa from Gokarṇa 14. 84. 12; (6)
Balarāma, in his तीर्थयात्रा, first went to
Prabhāsa 9. 34. 36; (7) The Yādavas,
desirous of visiting a तीर्थ, went to
Prabhāsa and lived there; there they were
engaged in a drinking bout (प्रावर्तत
महापानं प्रभासे); in the mutual kill-
ing that followed the Vṛṣṇi heroes, the Bhojas
and the Andhakas were all destroyed at
Prabhāsa 16. 9. 8-9.
E. Past and my-
thological events: (1) At Prabhāsa Kṛṣṇa,
observing restraint (नियमे स्थितः) stood
on one foot for a thousand divine years
(दिव्यं वर्षसहस्रकम्) to practise aus-
terities 3. 13. 14; (2) The sages Śukra,
Aṅgiras and others who came together at
Prabhāsa thought of going on a तीर्थयात्रा
from there; (3) Soma was cursed by
Dakṣa; as a result he was emaciated and could
not shine; Dakṣa Prajāpati advised him to
go to the तीर्थ of Sarasvatī (i. e. Prabhāsa)
and emerge from there after taking a bath;
when Soma did this he could wax again; but
for one half of the month he would wane;
so Soma went to Prabhāsa and emerged
after bath on the new moon day; he could
illuminate the worlds; the gods then reached
Prabhāsa and, in the company of Soma,
met Dakṣa; this is why Prabhāsa became
the most excellent of all the तीर्थस् (प्र-
भासं च यथा तीर्थं तीर्थानां प्र-
वरं ह्य् अभूत्); on every new moon day
the moon bathes in Prabhāsa and waxes
again; that is why Prabhāsa is so called
9. 34. 67-77; 9. 34. 36-39; (the bath in
the Hiraṇyasaras तीर्थ, which later became
known as Prabhāsa, was prescribed for Soma
by the sages 12. 329. 46).
F. Holiness:
(1) If one who is pure and has a controll-
ed mind (शुचिः प्रयतमानसः) bathes at
Prabhāsa he secures for himself the fruit of
an Agniṣṭoma and an Atirātra sacrifice 3.
80. 78; (2) According to Aṅgiras one
who bathes in Prabhāsa is awakened in a
विमान by the praises of Apsarases 13.
26. 9; (3) According to Aṅgiras, again,
one who with concentrated mind (समाहितः)
spends one night of the new moon day
(अमावास्याम्) at Prabhāsa has (as though)
a second birth as a Siddha (सिद्ध्यते ऽत्र
महाबाहो यो नरो जायते पुनः) 13. 26.
51; (4) According to a Gāthā sung by
Yayāti one who visits Prabhāsa lives long
again in this life (लब्धायुर् जीविते पुनः)
12. 148. 11; (5) If the high-souled persons,
observing vows, visit Prabhāsa they become
auspicious, obtain divine forms, wear divine
garlands, and full of divine fragrance they
reach the world of cows (? गवां विमाने)
13. 105. 45, 48 (for citation see Karatoyinī).
G. Importance: (1) God Agni himself is
always present there (यत्र संनिहितो नित्यं
स्वयम् एव हुताशनः) 3. 80. 77; (2) Men-
tioned in the Daivata-Ṛṣi-Vaṃśa 13. 151.
18, 2.

प्रमाण
Pramāṇa m.: Name of a banyan tree.
The Pāṇḍavas left Hāstinapura for their
stay in the forest and started towards the
north (उदङ्मुखाः) 3. 1. 9; at the end
of the day they reached a big banyan tree
(महावट), called Pramāṇa, on the bank of
the Jāhnavī (Gaṅgā); they spent there that
night partaking only of water (उदकेनैव
तां रात्रिम् ऊषुस् ते) 3. 1. 39-40.

प्रयाग
Prayāga nt., m. (3. 83. 74): Name of
a तीर्थ।
A. Location: At the confluence of the
Gaṅgā and the Yamunā (गङ्गायमुनयोर्
वीर संगमम् … प्रयागम् इति विख्यातम्)
3. 85. 13-14; 3. 83. 70, 76, 80.
B. Name
explained: Prayāga (प्र-याग) so called
because Pitāmaha (Prajāpati) in the bygone
days offered a sacrifice there (यत्रायजत
भूतात्मा पूर्वम् एव पितामहः।प्रया-
गम् इति विख्यातं तस्माद् भरतसत्तम)
3. 85. 14.
C. Description: Holy, most
holy (पुण्य) 3. 85. 13 (Nī. on Bom. Ed.
3. 87. 18: पुण्यं धर्मवृद्धिहेतुः);
(पुण्यतम) 3. 83. 74; purifying (पवित्र)
3. 85. 13 (however, Nī. on Bom. Ed. 3. 87.
17: पविः वज्रं तत्तुल्यं जन्ममरणादि-
दुःखं तस्मात् त्रायत इति पवित्रम्);
best sanctifier (पावनं उत्तमम्) 3. 85.
13 (Nī. on Bom. Ed. 3. 87. 18: पावनं
पापनाशनम्); famous, famous in the
worlds (विख्यात) 3. 85. 14; (लोकविश्रुत)
3. 85. 13; liked by sages (ऋषिभिर् जुष्टम्)
3. 85. 13; praised by sages (ऋषिसंस्तुत)
3. 83. 65; place for sacrifices, honoured even
by gods (यजनभूमिर् हि देवानाम् अपि
सत्कृता) 3. 83. 77; place where gods offered
sacrifice (देवयजन) 3. 93. 5; 5. 187. 26.
D. Holiness: (1) No place is holier than
Prayāga in the three worlds; Prayāga sur-
passes by far all the other तीर्थस् (ततः
पुण्यतमं नास्ति त्रिषु लोकेषु भारत।
प्रयागः सर्वतीर्थेभ्यः प्रभवत्य् अधि-
कं विभो) 3. 83. 74 (Nī. on Bom. Ed. 3. 85.
76: तथा च पृथिव्या अपत्यभूतानि तीर्थानि
तत्फलभूताः स्वर्गाश् च तानि सर्वाणि
प्रयागाद् उत्पन्नानीति प्रयागस्य तीर्थ-
राजत्वम् उक्तम्); one is freed of sins either
by hearing the name of the तीर्थ (श्रवणात्),
or by reciting its name (नामसंकीर्तनाद्
अपि), or by touching the earth there (मृत्ति-
कालम्भनाद् वापि) 3. 83. 75; (2) If one
who is strict in his vows (संशितव्रतः)
and bathes at the confluence (of the Gaṅgā
and the Yamunā) at this तीर्थ, he gets the
religious merit of performing a Rājasūya
and an Aśvamedha 3. 83. 76; (3) If one
who is controlled and strict in his vows
(नियतः संशितव्रतः) bathes at Pra-
yāga in the month of Māgha he becomes
sinless (निर्मलः) and goes to heaven;
(4) By just bathing (स्नात एव) at the
confluence of the Gaṅgā and the Yamunā
(at Prayāga) one acquires the religious
merit that is obtained by one who has studied
the four Vedas and by those who speak truth
(चातुर्वेदे च यत् पुण्यं सत्यवादिषु
चैव यत्) 3. 83. 80; (5) If one gives
even a little there that assumes importance
(तत्र दत्तं सूक्ष्मम् अपि महद् भवति
भारत) 3. 83. 77; (6) Pulastya told
Bhīṣma that if he decided to die at Prayāga
he should not change his mind even at the
instance of the Vedas or due to the advice of
the people (न वेदवचनात् तात न लोकव-
चनाद् अपि।मतिर् उत्क्रमणीया ते प्रयाग-
मरणं प्रति) 3. 83. 78; (also see the
next section).
E. Importance: (1) At
Prayāga are present Brahman and other
gods, the quarters together with their rulers
(दिशश् च सदिगीश्वराः), the Lokapālas, the
Sādhyas, the Nairṛtas, manes, Sanatkumāra
and other great sages (सनत्कुमारप्रमु-
खास् तथैव परमर्षयः), Aṅgiras and
other Brahmanical sages (अङ्गिरःप्रमुखाश्
चैव तथा ब्रह्मर्षयः), the Nāgas,
the Suparṇas, Siddhas, Cakracaras, rivers,
oceans, the Gandharvas and the Apsa-
rases, and god Hari followed by Prajāpati
(हरिश् च भगवान् आस्ते प्रजाप्तिपुरस्-
कृतः) 3. 83. 65-68 (Nī. on Bom. Ed. 3.
85. 72: चक्रचराः सूर्यादयः); (2)
Prayāga, Pratiṣṭhāna, Kambala, Aśvatara,
and Bhogavatī together are known as the
Vedī of Prajāpati; there the Vedas and sacri-
fices in bodily form (मूर्तिमन्तः) as also
the sages worship (उपासते) Prajāpati;
there gods and Cakracaras offer sacrifices
(यजन्ते क्रतुभिः) 3. 83. 72-73; (3)
There are three Agnikuṇḍas at Prayāga
from where the Jāhnavī, followed by all the
other तीर्थस्, flows 3. 83. 69; (4) At
Prayāga, the daughter of Tapana (the sun),
i. e. the Yamunā, meets the Gaṅgā 3. 83.
70; (5) The land between the Gaṅgā and
the Yamunā is known as the जघन (part
below the navel) of the earth; Prayāga is
known to the sages as the उपस्थ, i. e.
the end of this जघन (गङ्गायमुनयोर्
मध्यं पृथिव्या जघनं स्मृतम्।
प्रयागं जघनस्यान्तम् उपस्थम् ऋषयो
विदुः॥) 3. 83. 71 (Nī. on Bom. Ed. 3.
85. 75: स्त्रीरूपायाः पृथिव्याः … जघ-
नं नाभेर् अधोभागः; on 3. 85. 76
where he reads जघमस्थानम्: जघ-
नस्य स्थानम् अवस्थानं समाप्तिर् अन्त
इति यावत् तद् एवोपस्थम्।); (6) At Pra-
yāga are present ten thousand and sixty
crores of तीर्थस् 3. 83. 79; according to
Aṅgiras ten thousand तीर्थस् and three crores
of them gather at Prayāga on the new
moon day of the month of Māgha (समा-
गच्छन्ति माघ्यां तु प्रयागे) 13. 26.
35; (7) Prayāga finds place in the Daivata-
Ṛṣi-Vaṃśa 13. 151. 18, 2.
F. Events:
(1) Epic: (i) The Pāṇḍavas bathed there;
they lived there and practised the severest
austerities (ऊषुर् आप्लुत्य गात्राणि तपश्
चातस्थुर् उत्तमम्); at the confluence of
the Gaṅgā and the Yamunā the sinless, high-
souled (विपाप्मानो महात्मानः) Pāṇḍa-
vas gave riches to Brāhmaṇas 3. 93. 5, 6;
(ii) Among other holy places Ambā visited
Prayāga; she bathed there and practised
severe austerities 5. 187. 28; (2) Mytho-
logical: Pitāmaha (Brahmadeva) formerly
offered there a sacrifice 3. 85. 14; 1. 50. 1.
 [See Prasravaṇāni trīṇi]

प्रवरा
Pravarā f.: Name of a river.
Listed by Saṃjaya among the rivers of
the Bhāratavarṣa; people use its water for
drinking 6. 10. 22, 13 (for other details see
Palāśinī).

प्रवेणी
Praveṇī f.: Name of a river.
Situated in the south (दक्षिणस्याम्)
3. 86. 1; to its north are forests of ascetics
(प्रवेण्युत्तरपार्श्वे तु … तापसानाम्
अरण्यानि) 3. 86. 8; listed by Mārkaṇḍeya
among the rivers which are known as mothers
of the fire-hearths, i. e. on whose banks
sacrifices were performed (धिष्ण्यानां
मातरो याः प्रकीर्तिताः) 3. 212. 24 (for
Nī. see Kapilā).

प्रशस्ता
Praśastā f.: Name of a river.
Located in the south (cf. 3. 117. 18);
described as most holy (पुण्यतमा) and
flowing to the ocean (समुद्रगा) 3. 118. 2;
Yudhiṣṭhira visited it along with his brothers
and, after bathing there (आप्लुत्य), he satis-
fied manes and gods (संतर्पयाम् आस
पितॄन् सुरांश् च) and gave riches to the
prominent among the Brāhmaṇas; from there
he went to the river Godāvarī 3. 118. 3.

प्रस्रवणानि
Prasravaṇāni trīṇi nt. (pl.): Three
streams, not named, on the mountain Ārcīka.
Described as holy (पुण्यानि); Yudhi-
ṣṭhira was advised to go round them and bathe
there as much as he desired (यथाकामम्
उपस्पृश) 3. 125. 15 (Nī., however, on
Bom. Ed. 3. 125. 18: त्रीणि प्रस्रवणानीति
च प्रयागम्। … यथाकामम् इत्य् अस्य
काशीप्रयागसेविनां चन्द्रतीर्थसेवङम्
ऐच्छिकम् इतरेषाम् अत्यावश्यकम् इति भा-
वः।).

प्लक्षप्रस्रवण
Plakṣaprasravaṇa nt.: Name of a
तीर्थ।
A. Location: On the Himavant moun-
tain 9. 53. 9, 11; (सो ऽवतीर्याचलश्रेष्ठात्
प्लक्षप्रस्रवणात्) 9. 53. 33; it is the source
of the river Sarasvatī (प्रभवं च सर-
स्वत्याः) 9. 53. 11; also cf. 3. 82. 5.
B.
Description: Holy (पुण्य) 9. 53. 10;
auspicious (शुभ) 9. 53. 33; an excellent
तीर्थ (तीर्थवर) 9. 53. 10.
C. Epic
event: Balarāma in his तीर्थयात्रा visited
it when he ascended the mountain Himavant
and was filled with wonder on seeing it;
from there he went to the Kārapacana तीर्थ
9. 53. 9-11; later he descended from the
mountain and the तीर्थ 9. 53. 33. [See
Plakṣarāja, Plakṣāvataraṇa]

प्लक्षराज
Plakṣarāja m.: The big Plakṣa tree,
not named.
Situated near the तीर्थ of Soma 9. 42.
38; God Kārtikeya always lived there in
person 9. 42. 41. [See Plakṣaprasravaṇa
and Plakṣāvataraṇa]

प्लक्षावतरण
Plakṣāvataraṇa nt.: Name of a तीर्थ,
also called Yamunātīrtha (3. 129. 13; 9. 48.
10).
A. Location: In the north (उदीच्याम्)
3. 88. 1, on the river Yamunā (यमुना-
तीर्थम् उच्यते) 3. 129. 13.
B. Descrip-
tion: Most holy (पुण्यतम) 3. 88. 3;
auspicious (शिव) 3. 88. 3; excellent तीर्थ
(तीर्थवर) 9. 48. 15; called the gate of the
heaven (नाकपृष्ठस्य द्वारम्) 3. 129. 13.
C. Holiness: (1) Brāhmaṇas go to this
तीर्थ for their अवभृथ bath at the end of
their sacrifices performed with the help of
the Brāhmaṇas hailing from the river Sara-
svatī (यत्र सारस्वतैर् इष्ट्वा गच्छन्त्य्
अवभृथं द्विजाः) 3. 88. 3 (Nī. on Bom.
Ed. 3. 90. 4: सारस्वतैः सरस्वत्यां
प्राप्तैः; अत्र सारस्वतैर् यज्ञैर् ईजानाः
परमर्षयः … ।गच्छन्त्य् अवभृथा-
प्लवम्॥) 3. 129. 14 (Nī. on Bom. Ed. 3.
129. 14: सारस्वतैर् ब्राह्मणैः ऋत्विग्भिर्
यज्ञैर् ईजानाः); (2) By bathing at this
तीर्थ one sees all the worlds (अत्रोपस्पृश्य
राजेन्द्र सर्वा̆ल् लोकान् प्रपश्यति) 3. 129.
17, 20; (3) By bathing at this तीर्थ one
is purified of bad deeds (पूयते दुष्कृताच्
चैव समुपस्पृश्य) 3. 129. 17.
D. Epic
events: (1) Yudhiṣṭhira bathed at this
तीर्थ with his brothers; by this act and due
to his austerities, he was able to see all the
worlds; he was also able to see Arjuna
(इहस्थः … पश्यामि श्वेतवाहनम्) 3. 129.
19 (Nī. on Bom. Ed. 3. 129. 19: इहस्थः
यमुनान्तर्गतप्लक्षावतरणस्थः); (2)
Balarāma visited the Yamunātīrtha; he bath-
ed there and gave wealth to the twice-born;
from there he went to the Ādityatīrtha 9. 48.
10, 15-16.
E. Mythological and Past
events: (1) Varuṇa, son of Aditi, performed
a Rājasūya at the Yamunātīrtha after con-
quering human and divine (opponents) 9. 48.
11-12; (2) King Marutta, helped by Saṃ-
varta, offered there an excellent सत्र 3. 129.
16; (3) Bharata, after conquering the earth
righteously (धर्मेणावाप्य मेदिनीम्),
often performed horse sacrifices using each
time a black and speckled horse (मेध्यम्
अश्वम् अवासृजत्।असकृत् कृष्णसारङ्गम्)
3. 129. 15. [See Yāmuna2, Plakṣaprasra-
vaṇa, Plakṣarāja]

फलकीवन
Phalakīvana nt.: Name of a forest.
Described as the best (उत्तम) 3. 81.
72; gods resort to it and practise austerities
for many thousand years 3. 81. 72; (perhaps
the river Dṛṣadvatī flows through it and the
Sarvadevānāṃ tīrtham is also in that forest
3. 81. 73-74).

फल्गु
Phalgu1 f.: Name of a river.
Described as a great river (महानदी)
and having holy water (पुण्यजला) 3. 85. 9;
flows near the mountain Gaya and along
Gayā 3. 85. 6, 7. [See Phalgu2]

फल्गु
Phalgu2, Phalgutīrtha nt.: Name of a
तीर्थ।
Situated near Gayā 3. 82. 84; by visiting
it one gets the fruit of an Aśvamedha and
acquires great perfection (सिद्धिं च महतीं
व्रजेत्) 3. 82. 86; mentioned in the Daivata-
Ṛṣi-Vaṃśa 13. 151. 23, 2. [See Phalgu1]

बदरपाचन
Badarapācana, Badarīpācana nt.:
Name of a तीर्थ।
A. Explanation of the name: The
तीर्थ so called because Indra asked Srucāvatī
to cook jujube berries there (पचस्वैतानि
सुभगे बदराणि) 9. 47. 16; Arundhatī
in the bygone days tasted and cooked jujube
fruits there for twelve years as told by
Mahādeva (ततो ऽब्रवीन् महादेवः पच-
स्वैतानि (i. e. बदराणि) सुव्रते) 9. 47. 34-
37. 42; Arundhatī expressed there her wish
that the तीर्थ be known as Badarapācana
(तीर्थं स्याद् इदं … नाम्ना बदरपाच-
नम्) 9. 47. 44.
B. Description: Auspicious
(शुभ) 9. 46. 29; 9. 47. 28; best (उत्तम)
9. 47. 44; excellent तीर्थ (तीर्थवर) 9.
47. 1, 27, 28; removing all sins (सर्वपापा-
पह) 9. 47. 27; famous in the three worlds
(विख्यातं त्रिषु लोकेषु) 9. 47. 27; perma-
nent in the world (स्थिरं लोके) 9. 47. 27;
inhabited by all kinds of beings (निषेवितं
सर्वसत्त्वैः) 9. 46. 29; dear to the Siddhas,
gods and sages (सिद्धदेवर्षिदयित) 9. 47.
44; frequented by ascetics and the Siddhas
(तपस्विसिद्धचरित) 9. 47. 1; thronged by
Brahmanical seers (ब्रह्मर्षिभिर् अभिप्लु-
तम्) 9. 47. 27; (having trees that are)
always flowering and bearing fruits (सदा-
पुष्पफल) 9. 46. 29; having forests bloom-
ing in different seasons (नानर्तुकवनोपेत)
9. 46. 29.
C. Holiness: (i) One who is
well composed (सुसमाहितः) if he lives
there for a night and bathes in the तीर्थ he
gets after death worlds that are difficult to
obtain (लोकान् … दुर्लभान्) 9. 47. 51;
(2) One who is pure (शुचिः) if he lives there
for three nights observing fast he obtains fruit
of fasting for twelve years 9. 47. 45; (3) One
should fast there for three nights and then eat
Badara berries; if one eats only Badara berries
for twelve years that is equal to fasting
for three nights 3. 81. 157.
D. Events:
(1) Epic: Balarāma visited the तीर्थ 9.
46. 28-29; 9. 47. 1; he bathed (उपस्पृश्य)
there and gave riches to great Brāhmaṇas
9. 47. 61; (2) Past: (i) Srucāvatī, the
beautiful daughter of Bharadvāja, practised
severe austerities to obtain the king of gods
(Indra) for her husband 9. 47. 2-3; (also
see section A above); (ii) The seven sages
left Arundhatī at this तीर्थ and went to the
Himavant 9. 47. 28. [See Badarikātīrtha]

बदरिकातीर्थ
Badarikātīrtha nt.: Name of a तीर्थ।
One who has subdued his mind (प्रयत-
मानसः), if he bathes there he gets long life
and goes to heaven 3. 83. 13. [See Badara-
pācana]

बलाका
Balākā f.: Name of a तीर्थ।
Mentioned in the Tīrthavaṃśa proclaim-
ed by Aṅgiras; one who bathes there (कृतोद-
कः) becomes famous among gods and shines
with his fame (देवेषु कीर्तिं लभते यशसा
च विराजते) 13. 26. 18.

बहिर्गिरि
Bahirgiri m.: Name of a mountain (?)
Situated in the north; it was conquered
by Arjuna in his expedition to the north
before the Rājasūya 2. 24. 2, 1.

बहुला
Bahulā f.: Name of a river.
Listed by Saṃjaya among the rivers of
the Bhāratavarṣa; people use its water for
drinking 6. 10. 26, 13; all the rivers listed
here are described as mothers of the universe
and very strong 6. 10. 35 (for citation see
Atikṛṣṇā).

बाहुदा
Bāhudā1 f.: Name of a river.
In the east 3. 85. 3, 22; flowing, along
with the river Nandā, from the mountain
Kuṇḍoda (बाहुदा च नदी यत्र नन्दा च
गिरिमूर्धनि) 3. 85. 20-21; listed by
Saṃjaya among the rivers of the Bhārata-
varṣa; people use its water for drinking
6. 10. 28, 13 (for other details see Bahulā);
the Pāṇḍavas in their तीर्थयात्रा bathed in
this river (चक्रुः सर्वे ऽभिषेचनम्) 3.
93. 4. [See Bāhudā2]

बाहुदा
Bāhudā2 f.: Name of a river.
A. Location: In the north, on the moun-
tain Himavant 13. 20. 3; listed by Saṃjaya
among the rivers of the Bhāratavarṣa; people
use its water for drinking 6. 10. 13.
B.
Description: Holy (पुण्या) 12. 24. 23;
13. 20. 3; great river (महानदी) 13. 151.
22; conferring the reward of performing one's
religious duties (धर्मदायिनी) 13. 20. 3;
all the rivers listed by Saṃjaya are described
as mothers of the universe and very strong
6. 10. 35 (for citation see Atikṛṣṇā).
C.
Name justified: Likhita, whose hands were
cut off as punishment for the sin of eating
without permission fruits in the आश्रम of
his brother Śaṅkha, received his hands back
when he bathed in the river Bāhudā (अव-
गाह्यापगां पुण्याम् … प्रादुरास्तां ततस्
तस्य करौ) 12. 24. 23-24.
D. Holi-
ness: (1) If one who observes chastity and
is composed (ब्रह्मचारी समाहितः) visits
the river he gets the fruit of performing a
Devasatra sacrifice (देवसत्रस्य यज्ञस्य
फलम् आप्नोति मानवः) 3. 82. 60; (2)
Those who visit the river Bāhudā become holy
and obtaining divine form and wearing heave-
nly garlands and rich in holy fragrance they
delight in the Goloka (? गवां विमाने) 13.
105. 45, 48, 44 (for citation see Karatoyinī).
E. Importance: Finds mention in the
Daivata-Ṛṣi-Vaṃśa 13. 151. 22, 2.
F.
Limitation: Giving cows in very large num-
bers on the river Bāhudā (गवां शतानाम्
अयुतम्) is highly meritorious no doubt; but
it is not enough to take one to Brahmaloka
13. 106. 37, 7.
G. Past events: (1) The
two brothers Śaṅkha and Likhita had esta-
blished their attractive आश्रमस् along the
river Bāhudā 12. 24. 3; Śaṅkha advised
Likhita, when the latter's hands were cut
off as punishment, to go to the river Bāhudā
and gratify according to the rites (यथा-
विधि) gods, manes and sages and never
again think of committing an अधर्म 12.
24. 22; (2) Aṣṭāvakra reached this river
when he, as advised by the sage Vadānya,
went to the north to see an old ascetic lady;
he bathed in the तीर्थ on this river and
gratified the deities and spent a night there
13. 20. 3-5; 13. 19. 24. [See Bāhudā1]

बिन्दुसरस्
Bindusaras nt.: Name of a lake.
A. Location: In the north-east (प्राग्-
उदीचीम् अगाद् दिशम्) 2. 3. 7; on the moun-
tain Hiraṇyaśṛṅga (or Hiraṇyaśikhara), near
the mountain Maināka, to the north of the
Kailāsa (उत्तरेण तु कैलासं मैनाकं
पर्वतं प्रति।हिरण्यशृङ्गः … गिरिः।
रम्यं बिन्दुसरो नाम) 2. 3. 8-9, 2;
(हिरण्यशिखरं चैव तच् च बिन्दुसरः)
3. 145. 39-41; near this lake the river Tri-
pathagā (Bhāgīrathī Gaṅgā), issuing from
Brahmaloka, got divided into seven streams
6. 7. 44.
B. Description: Pleasing
(रम्य) 2. 3. 2, 9; 6. 7. 41; auspicious
(शिव) 3. 145. 39; (शुभ) 6. 7. 41; hea-
venly (दिव्य) 6. 7. 41; large (महत्) 6. 7.
41; having golden sand (काञ्चनवालुक) 6.
7. 41.
C. Epic events: (1) Asura
Maya wanted to go to Bindusaras to bring
the pot of jewels to construct the Sabhā for
the Pāṇḍavas 2. 3. 2-4; he went there and
collected the गदा of Yauvanāśva which he
thought was suitable for Bhīma, the big
conch of Varuṇa, called Devadatta, for
Arjuna, and the crystals used for Vṛṣa-
parvan's Sabhā; he brought these to Indra-
prastha with the help of his Rakṣas servants
2. 3. 5-7, 16 (Nī., however, on Bom. Ed. 2.
3. 19: किंकरैः रक्षसां जातिविशेषैः);
(2) Maya built a lotus pond with jewels
brought from Bindusaras and covered it with
crystals (कृतां बिन्दुसरोरत्नैर् मयेन
स्फाटिकच्छदाम्। … नलिनीम्) 2. 46. 26.
D. Past and mythological events: (1) Vṛṣa-
parvan had a Sabhā made of crystals built
for him there 2. 3. 16; Asura Maya had
collected jewels in a pot in the Sabhā of
Vṛṣaparvan when all the Dānavas offered a
sacrifice near Bindusaras (यक्ष्यमानेषु
सर्वेषु दानवेषु तदा मया।कृतं मणि-
मयं भाण्डं रम्यं बिन्दुसरः
प्रति॥) 2. 3. 2-3 (Nī. on Bom. Ed. 2. 3.
3: भाण्डम् इव भाण्डं मूलधनं
विचित्ररङ्गोपादानद्रव्यं कृतं हिङ्गुला-
दिवन् निर्मितम् मणिमयं मणिप्रचु-
रम्); (2) Yauvanāśva, after killing his
enemies, left his गदा near Bindusaras 2. 3. 5;
(3) Varuṇa's big conch Devadatta was also
left there 2. 3. 7; (4) Bhagīratha lived
there for many years watching the river
Bhāgīrathī Gaṅgā 2. 3. 9; 6. 7. 41; (5) The
god of all beings (i. e. Prajāpati) performed a
hundred principal sacrifices there (यत्रेष्ट्वा
सर्वभूतानाम् ईश्वरेण महात्मना।
आहृताः क्रतवो मुख्याः शतं भरत-
सत्तम॥) 2. 3. 10 (Nī. on Bom. Ed. 2.
3. 11: ईश्वरेण प्रजापतिना); (6) Indra
obtained there perfection (सिद्धि) by per-
forming a sacrifice 2. 3. 12; 6. 7. 42; (7)
The eternal Bhūtapati (Mahādeva) created
there all the worlds and is waited upon by
thousands of Bhūtas 2. 3. 12; 6. 7. 43
(Nī. on Bom. Ed. 2. 3. 14: भूतपतिर्
महादेवः); (8) There Vāsudeva constantly
performed with faith सत्रस् lasting for a
thousand years in order to convince the learn-
ed (about the necessity of performing sacri-
fices) (यत्रेष्टं वासुदेवेन सत्रैर् वर्ष-
सहस्रकैः।श्रद्दधानेन सततम् शिष्ट-
संप्रतिपत्तये॥) 2. 3. 14 (Nī. on Bom.
Ed. 2. 3. 16: शिष्टसंप्रतिपत्तये … शिष्टान्
धर्मानुष्ठाने प्रवर्तयितुम्); at these
सत्रस् the sacrificial poles were decorated with
golden garlands and the altars were made of
bright gold; Keśava gave (दक्षिणा) by thou-
sands and millions (ददौ यत्र सहस्राणी
प्रयुतानि च केशवः) 2. 3. 15; 6. 7. 42;
(9) Nara, Nārāyaṇa, Brahman, Yama and
Sthāṇu (Śiva) perform there a सत्र at
the end of every thousand aeons (उपासते
यत्र सत्रं सहस्रयुगपर्यये) 2. 3. 13;
6. 7. 43, 46.

बिल्वक
Bilvaka nt.: Name of a तीर्थ।
One who bathes there washes off his sin
and goes to heaven (धूतपाप्मा दिवं
व्रजेत्) 13. 26. 12; (according to Nī. on
Bom. Ed. on 13. 25. 13 all the holy places
listed here are situated on the river Godāvarī;
for his remark see Gaṅgādvāra).

बृहद्वती
Bṛhadvatī f.: Name of a river.
Listed by Saṃjaya among the rivers of
the Bhāratavarṣa; people use its water for
drinking 6. 10. 29, 13; all the rivers listed
here are described as mothers of the universe
and very strong 6. 10. 35 (for citation
see Atikṛṣṇā).

ब्रह्मकुल्या
Brahmakulyā f.: Name of a river.
Listed by Saṃjaya among the rivers of
the Bhāratavarṣa; people use its water for
drinking 6. 10. 34, 13 (for other details
see Bṛhadvatī)

ब्रह्मगुहा
Brahmaguhā f.: Name of a place (?)
Kṛṣṇa entered the ancient (पौराणी)
Brahmaguhā and saw there before him the
merging of the earth (in the ocean) (मही-
सत्र); he, having thrown the Daityas, ser-
pents and the Dānavas into disorder, rescued
the earth (स पौराणीं ब्रह्मगुहां प्र-
विष्टो महीसत्रं भारताग्रे ददर्श।स
चैव गाम् उद्दधाराग्र्यकर्मा विक्षोभ्य
दैत्यान् उरगान् दानवांश् च॥) 13. 143. 16
(Nī. on Bom. Ed. 13. 158. 17: (महीसत्रं
पृथिव्याश् छादनं मज्जनम् इति यावत्;
Comm. Vādirāja, however, ब्रह्मगुहां
वेदहृदयम्).

ब्रह्मण|ब्रह्मणः
Brahmaṇaḥ sthānam1 nt.: Name of a
sacred place; also known as Brahmodumbara
(ब्रह्मोदुम्बरम् इत्य् एव प्रकाशं भुवि
भारत) 3. 81. 58.
A. Description: Described as best
(उत्तम) 3. 81. 58; holy (पुण्य) 5. 187.
24.
B. Holiness: At this place there are
the कुण्डस् of seven sages and the field
(केदार) of Kapiṣṭhala; one who bathes in
these two places and, being pure and having
a controlled mind (शुचिः प्रयतमानसः),
worships god Brahman he is cleansed of all
sins and reaches heaven 3. 81. 59-60.
C.
Epic event: One of the sacred places visited
by Ambā where she bathed and practised
severe austerities 5. 187. 24-25, 28. [See
Brahmaṇaḥ sthānam2, Brahmasthāna].

ब्रह्मण|ब्रह्मणः
Brahmaṇaḥ sthānam2 nt.: Name of a
तीर्थ।
If a person of a lower birth bathes there
he becomes a Brāhmaṇa; and if a Brāhmaṇa
bathes there he, with a pure soul, attains
(after death) the highest condition (तत्र
वर्णावरः स्नात्वा ब्राह्मण्यं लभते
नरः।ब्राह्मणश् च विशुद्धात्मा गच्-
छेत परमां गतिम्॥) 3. 81. 95. [See
Brahmaṇaḥ sthānam1 and Brahmasthāna]

ब्रह्मणस्
Brahmaṇas tīrtham nt.: Name of a
तीर्थ।
Sacred to Brahman; described as best
(उत्तम); by worshipping god Brahman there
one gets the fruit of a Rājasūya and an
Aśvamedha sacrifice 3. 82. 88.

ब्रह्मतुङ्ग
Brahmatuṅga1 nt.: Name of a तीर्थ।
By visiting it (समासाद्य) one who is
pure and has controlled his mind (शुचिः
प्रयतमानसः) and one who is virtuous
and is free of the quality of passion (सुकृती
विरजाः) wins the world of Brahman 3.
80. 96.

ब्रह्मतुङ्ग
Brahmatuṅga2 m.: Name of a mountain.
Situated in the north (उदीच्यां दिशि)
7. 57. 23; Arjuna saw it while he was on
his way to the place of Śiva to propitiate
him to get his Pāśupatāstra 7. 57. 27.

ब्रह्ममेध्या
Brahmamedhyā f.: Name of a river.
One of the rivers of the Bhāratavarṣa
listed by Saṃjaya; people use its water for
drinking 6. 10. 29, 13 (for other details see
Bṛhadvatī).

ब्रह्मयोनि
Brahmayoni f.: Name of a तीर्थ।
A. Holiness: Having reached this तीर्थ
and having bathed there one who is pure and
has controlled his mind (शुचिः प्रयतमा-
नसः) reaches the world of Brahman and
purifies his family up to seven generations;
there is no doubt about that (पुनात्य् आसप्त-
मं चैव कुलं नास्त्य् अत्र संशयः) 3.
81. 121.
B. Epic event: Balarāma went
there from the Agnitīrtha; he bathed there
and gave riches of various kinds; from there
he went to the Kauberatīrtha 9. 46. 20, 22.
C. Mythological event: Brahmadeva created
(the worlds) there; having bathed there with
all the gods Brahmadeva, formerly, created
according to the rites foods for gods (ससर्ज
भगवान् यत्र सर्वलोकपितामहः।तत्रा-
प्लुत्य ततो ब्रह्मा सह देवैः प्रभुः
पुरा।ससर्ज चान्नानि ततः देवतानां
यथाविधि) 9. 46. 21.

ब्रह्मवालुका
Brahmavālukā f.: Name of a तीर्थ।
Situated along the river Devikā; by
bathing there (उपस्पृश्य) one does not
grieve over death (न शोचेन् मरणं
ततः) 3. 80. 114.

ब्रह्मशाला
Brahmaśālā f.: Name of a river.
Situated in the east 3. 85. 3, near the
mountain Mahendra (?) 3. 85. 16; described
as holy (पुण्या), famous (ख्याता), and
crowded by those who have washed off their
sins (धूतपाप्मभिर् आकीर्णा); her very
sight is holy (पुण्यं तस्याश् च दर्शनम्)
3. 85. 18.

ब्रह्मशिरस्
Brahmaśiras nt.: Name of a तीर्थ।
On the river Bhāgīrathī; listed by Aṅgi-
ras in the Tīrthavaṃśa 13. 26. 3; one who
visits it, bathes in the Bhāgīrathī and fasts
for one month obtains the Somaloka 13.
26. 38.

ब्रह्मसरस्
Brahmasaras nt.: Name of a तीर्थ।
A. Location: In the east 3. 85. 3; in
the vicinity of the Gaya mountain, Gayā,
Mahānadī and Gayaśiras 3. 85. 7, 8.
B.
Origin: It was created by god Brahman
(सरश् च ब्रह्मनिर्मितम्) 13. 151. 24; 9.
50. 19.
C. Description: Holy, very holy
(पुण्य) 13. 151. 24, (सुपुण्य) 3. 93. 10;
13. 96. 7; auspicious (शिव) 3. 85. 6; 13. 151
24; removing all sins (सर्वपापहर)
13. 151. 24; best (उत्तम) 3. 93. 10;
famous in the three worlds (त्रिलोकविख्यात)
13. 151. 24; liked by sages (ऋषिजुष्ट) 3. 93.
10; resorted to by gods and sages (सेवितं
त्रिदशर्षिभिः) 3. 85. 6; a तीर्थ of gods
(देवस्य तीर्थे) 13. 96. 7; adorned by the
Dharmāraṇya (धर्मारण्योपशोभित) 3.
82. 74; 13. 26. 55.
D. Holiness: (1)
Mahādeva is always present there 3. 93. 12;
(2) Eternal Dharma himself lived there
(उवास च स्वयं यत्र धर्मो राजन्
सनातनः) 3. 93. 11; (3) If one stays
there overnight one becomes pure and gets the
fruit of a Puṇḍarīka sacrifice (पुण्डरीकम्
अवाप्नोति प्रभातां शर्वरीं शुचिः) 13.
26. 55; 3. 82. 74; (4) By circumambulating
the यूप raised there by Brahman one gets
the fruit of a Vājapeya 3. 82. 75.
E.
Importance: (1) It is the source of all rivers
(सर्वासां सरितां चैव समुद्भेदः) 3.
93. 12; (2) The river Sarasvatī, in the by-
gone days, arose in this lake; sages know this
(प्रसृतासि महाभागे सरसो ब्रह्मणः
पुरा।जानन्ति त्वां सरिच्छ्रेष्ठे मुन-
यः) 9. 50. 19; (3) Finds mention in the
Daivata-Ṛṣi-Vaṃśa 13. 151. 24, 2.
F.
Epic event: The Pāṇḍavas in their तीर्थ-
यात्रा lived there and offered four-monthly
sacrifices and a great Ṛṣiyajña (चातुर्मा-
स्यैस् तदेजिरे।ऋषियज्ञेन महता) near
the Akṣayavaṭa 3. 93. 13.
G. Past and
mythological events: (1) Brahmadeva
raised his यूप there (ब्रह्मणो यूप
उच्छ्रितः) 3. 82. 75; (2) Agastya went
from there to Vaivasvata (Yama) 3. 93. 11;
(3) Śukra, Aṅgiras and other sages reached
there in their तीर्थयात्रा; they bathed there
and ate lotus stalks and blossoms (विगाह्य
ते भुक्तबिसप्रसूनाः); some of them dug
out lotus stalks and roots (केचिद् बिसान्य्
अखनंस् तत्र राजन्न् अन्ये मृणालान्य्
अखनंस् तत्र विप्राः); when the पुष्कर
collected by Agastya from the lake disappear-
ed he doubted his companions; each one of
them then took oath to prove his innocence
13. 96. 8ff; (4) Many Brāhmaṇas used
to come there and perform the four-monthly
sacrifices according to the ancient rites
(चातुर्मास्येनायजन्त आर्षेण विधिना);
there the Brāhmaṇas, learned in the Vedas,
sitting in the सदस्, narrated holy stories
of the high-souled ones 3. 93. 13-15; (5)
Gaya, son of Amūrtarayas, performed his
famous sacrifice near this lake (अस्य सरसः
समीपे); in this sacrifice many दक्षिणास् and
large quantities of food were supplied; this and
other stories of Gaya Āmūrtarayasa were told
by Śamaṭha 3. 93. 16-27.

ब्रह्मस्थान
Brahmasthāna nt.: Name of a sacred
place.
By staying there for three nights one gets
the fruit of giving a thousand cows and goes
to heaven 3. 83. 32 [See Brahmaṇaḥ
sthānam1, 2]

ब्रह्माणी
Brahmāṇī f.: Name of a river.
One of the rivers of the Bhāratavarṣa
listed by Saṃjaya; its water used by people
for drinking 6. 10. 32, 13; all the rivers listed
here are described as mothers of the universe
and very strong 6. 10. 35 (for citation see
Atikṛṣṇā).

ब्रह्मावर्त
Brahmāvarta m.: Name of a तीर्थ।
By bathing there one goes to the world of
Brahman 3. 81. 43; one who observes chastity
and has a composed mind (ब्रह्मचारी समा-
हितः), if he visits Brahmāvarta he obtains
the fruit of an Aśvamedha and goes to heaven
3. 82. 38.

ब्रह्मोदुम्बर
Brahmodumbara: See Brahmaṇaḥ
sthānam1.

ब्राह्म
Brāhma nt.: Name of a तीर्थ।
It is supposed to exist in the middle space
of the thumb (अङ्गुष्ठस्यान्तराले च ब्राह्-
मं तीर्थम् उदाहृतम्) 13. 107. 96.

ब्राह्मणी
Brāhmaṇī f.: Name of a तीर्थ।
One who practises chastity and has con-
trolled his sense organs, if he visits this तीर्थ
he goes to the world of Brahman in a con-
veyance which has the colour of a lotus
(पद्मवर्णेन यानेन) 3. 82. 52.

भद्रकर्णेश्वर
Bhadrakarṇeśvara m.: Name of a
तीर्थ।
By visiting it and by worshipping the god
(Śiva) according to prescribed rites one does
not meet with misfortune (न दुर्गतिम्
अवाप्नोति) and reaches heaven 3. 82. 35.

भद्रवट
Bhadravaṭa m.: Name of a sacred place.
Described as a holy place (पुण्यस्थान)
and famous in the three worlds (त्रिषु लोकेषु
विश्रुतम्) 3. 80. 69; it was sacred to Śiva
3. 80. 69; by approaching there Īśāna
(Śiva) (तत्राभिगम्य चेशानम्) one gets
the fruit of giving a thousand cows and by
the favour of Mahādeva he obtains the
status of the chief of the Gaṇas (गाणपत्यम्
अवाप्नुयात्) 3. 80. 70; when Skanda was
made the chief of the army of the gods, Śiva,
with Umā, proceeded to the Bhadravaṭa in
a chariot to which a thousand lions were
yoked (सहस्रं तस्य सिंहानां तस्मिन्
युक्तं रथोत्तमे) 3. 221. 1-2.

भद्रसालवन
Bhadrasālavana nt.: Name of a forest.
Situated on the eastern side of mount
Meru 6. 8. 12-13; the great Kālāmra tree is
in that forest 6. 8. 13.

भर्तृस्थान
Bhartṛsthāna nt.: Name of a तीर्थ।
Described as best (अनुत्तम) 3. 82. 68;
3. 83. 57; god Mahāsena (Skanda) is always
present there 3. 83. 57; by bathing there in the
Koṭitīrtha and by worshipping Guha (Skanda)
one gets the fruit of gifting a thousand cows
and becomes lustrous (तेजस्वी) 3. 82. 68;
3. 83. 58; one obtains perfection by just
visiting it (गमनाद् एव सिध्यति) 3. 83. 58.

भागीरथी
Bhāgīrathī f.: See Gaṅgā.

भारद्वाजस्य
Bhāradvājasya tīrtham nt.: Name of a
तीर्थ।
One of the तीर्थस् on the southern coast
(समुद्रे तीर्थानि दक्षिणे) 1. 208. 1; 1.
209. 17; this तीर्थ, described as highly
effective in causing cessation of sins (पाप-
प्रशमनं महत् 1. 208. 3), was one of
the five तीर्थस् which were once frequented
by ascetics, but were later avoided by them
due to the fear of crocodiles 1. 208. 2-4, 6;
the crocodiles were in fact the Apsarases
1. 208. 14-21; Arjuna visited these तीर्थस्
1. 208. 7; he freed the तीर्थस् from the
crocodiles and gave them their original form
1. 209. 19-23; all the five तीर्थस् are describ-
ed as auspicious, very auspicious (पुण्यानि)
1. 209. 17, (सुपुण्यानि) 1. 208. 1; they were
sanctifying for the wise (पावनानि मनीषि-
णाम्) 1. 209. 11; attractive (रमणीयानि)
1. 209. 17; adorned by ascetics (शोभितानि
तपस्विभिः) 1. 208. 1; all the तीर्थस्, after
they would be freed from crocodiles, were
to be known as Nārītīrthas (नरीतीर्थानि
नाम्नेह ख्यातिं यास्यन्ति सर्वशः) 1.
209. 11. [See Nārītirthāni]

भारद्वाजी
Bhāradvājī f.: Name of a river.
Listed by Saṃjaya among the rivers of
the Bhāratavarṣa (भारद्वाजीम् च निम्न-
गाम्); its water used by people for drinking
6. 10. 28, 13; all the rivers listed here are
described as mothers of the universe and very
strong 6. 10. 35 (for citation see Atikṛṣṇā).

भारमर्दिनी
Bhāramardinī f.: Name of a river.
Listed by Saṃjaya among the rivers of
the Bhāratavarṣa; its water used by people
for drinking 6. 10. 22, 13 (for other details
see Bhāradvājī).

भास
Bhāsa m.: Name of a mountain.
One of the twelve mountains described
as kings of mountains (पर्वतराजानः) 14.
43. 4-5 (for other details see Kāṣṭhavant).

भीमरथी
Bhīmarathī f.: Name of a river.
Situated in the south (दक्षिणस्याम्)
3. 86. 1; described as remover of the fear of
sin (पापभयापहा), full of deer and birds
(मृगद्विजसमाकीर्णा), and adorned with
huts of ascetics (तापसालयभूषिता) 3. 86. 3;
finds mention in the Daivata-Ṛṣi-Vaṃśa
13. 151. 22, 2.

भीमा
Bhīmā f.: Name of a river.
Listed by Saṃjaya among the rivers of
the Bhāratavarṣa; its water used by people
for drinking 6. 10. 21, 13; the source of the
Bhīmā is described as the best (भीमायाः
स्थानम् उत्तमम्) 3. 80. 100; all the rivers
listed by Saṃjaya are said to be mothers of
the universe and very strong 6. 10. 35 (for
citation see Atikṛṣṇā); also listed by
Mārkaṇḍeya among the rivers which are
declared to be mothers of the fire-hearths
(i. e. on the banks of which sacrifices were
performed) 3. 212. 23 (for citation and Nī.
see Kapilā); having bathed there at the source
of the river (तत्र स्नात्वा तु योन्यां वै)
one becomes son of a goddess with radiant
gold ear-rings on his body (देव्याः पुत्रो
भवेद् राजंस् तप्तकुण्डलविग्रहः) and
gets the fruit of giving a hundred thousand
cows 3. 80. 100-101.

भृगुतुङ्ग
Bhṛgutuṅga m.: Name of a mountain.
A. Location: On the Himālayan range
(हिमवत्पार्श्वे) 1. 207. 1.
B. Descrip-
tion: Great mountain (महागिरि) 3. 88. 20;
3. 130. 16.
C. Relationship with Bhṛgu:
Bhṛgu, attended on by great sages, practised
austerities on this mountain; the mountain
then became famous as Bhṛgu's hermitage
(भृगुर् यत्र तपस् तेपे … स राजन्न् आश्र-
मः ख्यातो भृगुतुङ्गो महागिरिः) 3. 88.
20.
D. Epic events: (1) Yudhiṣṭhira
was once instructed by Rāma (Bhārgava) on
this mountain (अनुशिष्टो ऽसि … भृगुतुङ्गे च
रामेण) 2. 69. 12-13; (2) Arjuna, while
on exile, purified himself there (कृतवाञ्
शौचम् आत्मनः) 1. 207. 2 (Nī. on Bom.
Ed. 1. 215. 2: भृगुतुङ्गे तुङ्गनाथ इति
प्रसिद्धे); (3) Lomaśa told Yudhiṣṭhira
the aggregate (of holy places 3. 129. 20-3.
130. 15) after listening to which he would
soon be visiting the Bhṛgutuṅga (समाधी-
नां समासस् तु पाण्डवेय श्रुतस् त्वया।
तं द्रक्ष्यसि महाराज भृगुतुङ्गं
महागिरिम्) 3. 130. 16 (Nī., however, on
Bom. Ed. 3. 130. 19: समासः सङ्क्षेपः।
यस्मिन् दृष्टे समाधिफलं भवतीत्य्
अर्थः); later Lomaśa advised Yudhiṣṭhira
to bathe quietly on this mountain together
with those who lived in his house (तूष्णीम्
 … सामात्यः समुपस्पृश) 3. 135. 7; (4)
Departing from the Kāmyaka forest Arjuna
went to the Bhṛgutuṅga and practised aus-
terities; he stayed there for a night; next
day, he met on his way a Brāhmaṇa who
advised him to go up the mountain Himālaya
to practise austerities (गिरिम् आरुह्य शैशि-
रम्) 3. 163. 10, 13-14.
E. Past event.:
Bhṛgu practised austerities there (see section
C above).
F. Holiness: (1) By visit-
ing the mountain one gets the fruit of a
horse sacrifice 3. 82. 45; (2) It is mentioned
in the Tīrthavaṃśa (13. 26. 3); one who is
not covetous (अलोलुपः) if he bathes in the
great lake on this mountain (महाह्रद
उपस्पृश्य) and fasts for three nights he is
freed of the sin of killing a Brāhmaṇa 13.
26. 17.

भैमरथी
Bhaimarathī f.: Name of a river.
Listed by Saṃjaya among the rivers of
the Bhāratavarṣa; its water used by people
for drinking 6. 10. 19, 13; all the rivers listed
here are said to be mothers of the universe
and very strong 6. 10. 35 (for citation see
Atikṛṣṇā).

भोगवती
Bhogavatī1 f.: Name of a तीर्थ; also
called Vāsukes tīrtham.
Situated at the confluence of the Gaṅgā
and the Yamunā 3. 83. 80; described as best,
the तीर्थ is sacred to Vāsuki (तत्र भोग-
वती नाम वासुकेस् तीर्थम् उत्तमम्) 3.
83. 81; one who bathes there gets the fruit
of an Aśvamedha 3. 83. 81; one of the holy
places where Ambā practised severe austeri-
ties and bathed 5. 187. 26, 28; Bhogavatī,
together with Prayāga and other three holy
places, forms the altar of Prajāpati (प्रयागं
सप्रतिष्ठानं कम्बलाश्वतरौ तथा।
तीर्थं भोगवती चैव वेदी प्रोक्ता प्रजा-
पतेः॥) 3. 83. 72.

भोगवती
Bhogavatī2 f.: Name of the river
Sarasvatī (?)
Described as attractive (मनोरमा);
Pāṇḍavas visited it and in the adjoining
forest, which was the abode of ascetics, saw
many perfected sages (ददर्श सिद्धर्षि-
गणान् अनेकान्) 3. 25. 20 (Nī. on Bom. Ed.
3. 24. 20: भोगवतीम् सरस्वतीम् नदीम्).
[See Sarasvatī]

भोगवत्|भोगवन्त्
Bhogavant m.: Name of a mountain (?)
Situated in the east (ययौ प्राचीं
दिशं प्रति) 2. 26. 1; listed among the
regions conquered by Bhīma (भोगवन्तं
च पाण्डवः।तरसैवाजयद् भीमः) 2.
27. 11.

मकरवाहिनी
Makaravāhinī f.: Name of a river.
Listed by Saṃjaya among the rivers of
the Bhāratavarṣa; its water used by people for
drinking 6. 10. 32, 13; all the rivers listed
here are said to be mothers of the universe and
very strong 6. 10. 35 (for citation see
Atikṛṣṇā).

मञ्जु
Mañju f.: Name of a river.
One of the rivers listed by Saṃjaya
among the rivers of the Bhāratavarṣa; its
water used by people for drinking 6. 10.
32, 13 (for other details see Makaravāhinī
above).

मणिजला
Maṇijalā f.: Name of a river.
A river of the Śākadvīpa 6. 12. 30; all
the rivers of this Dvīpa contain holy water
(पुण्यजलाः) 6. 12. 29, (पुण्योदाः) 6. 12.
31, are holy (पुण्याः) and excellent rivers
(सरिद्वराः) 6. 12. 32.

मणिनाग
Maṇināga m.: Name of a holy place.
Sacred to a serpent called Maṇināga (?);
by visiting the place one obtains the fruit
of giving a thousand cows 3. 82. 91; by
living there for a night one is freed of
all sins 3. 82. 92; one who eats the food
offered to Maṇināga is not affected by the
poison even when bitten by a venomous snake
(नैत्यकं भुञ्जते यस् तु मणिनागस्य
मानवः।दष्टस्याशीविषेणापि न तस्य
क्रमते विषम्॥) 3. 82. 91-92 (Nī. on
Bom. Ed. 3. 84. 105: नित्यकं नैवेद्यं
नैत्यकं च तद् एव).

मणिमत्|मणिमन्त्
Maṇimant1 m.: Name of a mountain.
One of the mountains in the north
crossed by Arjuna when he went to propitiate
Śiva to get from him his Pāśupatāstra 7.
57. 27.

मणिमत्|मणिमन्त्
Maṇimant2 m.: Name of a sacred place.
One who observes chastity and has
concentrated his mind (ब्रह्मचारी समा-
हितः), if he visits this place and stays there
for a night (एकरात्रोषितः) he will get the
fruit of an Agniṣṭoma 3. 80. 109.

मतङ्गवापी
Mataṅgavāpī f.: Name of a sacred
tank.
Sacred to the sage Mataṅga; one who
bathes there obtains perfection (सिद्धि) in one
night, and can dive, even without support, in
the eternal Andhaka world (? मतङ्गवाप्यां
यः स्नायाद् एकरात्रेण सिध्यति।विगाहति
ह्य् अनालम्बम् अन्धकं वै सनातनम्॥)
13. 26. 31 (Comm. unknown, however, अन्ध-
कं तीर्थम् अनालम्बं शववद् यो विगाहति
स सनातनं नित्यस्थानं लभेत इति
शेषः। He also explains some other readings
Cr. Ed. Vol. 17, p. 1067, note on 13. 26. 31).

मतङ्गस्य
Mataṅgasya kedāraḥ m.: Name of a
sacred place.
Sacred to the sage Mataṅga, it was locat-
ed on the mountain Mahendra 3. 83. 14-15; 3.
85. 16; also known as Mataṅgasya Āśramaḥ
3. 85. 19; described as sanctifying (पवित्र),
auspicious (मङ्गलीय), famous in the world
(ख्यातो लोके) and eternal (सनातन) 3. 85.
19; by bathing there one obtains the fruit of
giving a thousand cows 3. 83. 15.

मदर्वीक
Madarvīka m.: Name of a mountain.
The mountain, along with the lands
bordering on it, was conquered by Bhīma in
his expedition before the Rājasūya; from
there he went northwards (मदर्वीकं
महीधरं।सोपदेशं विनिर्जित्य प्रय-
याव् उत्तारामुखः) 2. 27. 9.

मधुवटी
Madhuvaṭī f.: Name of a तीर्थ।
It was sacred to Devī (देव्यास् तीर्थम्);
one who has a controlled mind and is pure
(प्रयतः शुचिः) if he bathes there and wor-
ships gods and manes (अर्चयेद् देवान् पितॄंश्
च) he gets, with the consent of the Devī
(देव्या समनुज्ञातः) the fruit of giving
a thousand cows 3. 81. 79.

मधुवन
Madhuvana nt.: Name of a forest.
Described as dense (स्फीत) and large
(महत्); it was first protected by Vālin and
then by Sugrīva; Hanūmant, Aṅgada and
others who went to the south in search of
Sītā, rested there for a while on their return
journey 3. 266. 26-27.

मधुविला
Madhuvilā f.: Name of a river, also
called Samaṃgā.
Situated near Kardamila, the bathing
place of Bharata; it was pointed out to
Yudhiṣṭhira by Lomaśa (एषा मधुविला राजन्
समंगा संप्रकाशते) 3. 135. 1 (Nī. on
Bom. Ed. 3. 135. 1: मधुविलेति अष्टावक्रा-
ङ्गसमीकरणात् पूर्वं समङ्गाया एवं
नाम); Indra lost his lustre after killing
Vṛtra (अलक्ष्म्या किल संयुक्तो वृत्रं
हत्वा शचीपतिः); he was freed from all sins
when he bathed in the river Samaṃgā
3. 135. 2.

मधुस्रव
Madhusrava nt.: Name of a तीर्थ।
Situated near the Pṛthūdaka तीर्थ; by
bathing there one gets the fruit of giving a
thousand cows 3. 81. 130.

मनोजव
Manojava nt.: Name of a तीर्थ।
Situated in the Vyāsavana; one who has
a controlled mind and takes limited food
(नियतो नियताशनः) if he bathes there he
gets the fruit of giving a thousand cows
3. 81. 78.

मनोह्रदा
Manohradā f.: Name of one of the
seven forms of Sarasvatī (सप्त सरस्व-
त्यः); also called Mānasahradā (9. 37. 4).
Described as the best of the rivers
(सरिच्छ्रेष्ठा) 9. 37. 23; when Auddālaka
performed a sacrifice in the Uttara Kosala
country he thought of Sarasvatī; the river
came to that region for the sake of the sage
and was worshipped by the sages; the river
was there known as Manohradā; the river was
so called because it was brought there by the
mind of the sages (मनोह्रदेति विख्याता
सा हि तैर् मनसा हृता) 9. 37. 21-23.

मन्दगा
Mandagā f.: Name of a river.
One of the rivers of the Bhāratavarṣa
listed by Saṃjaya; its water used by people
for drinking 6. 10. 31, 13; all the rivers listed
here are described as mothers of the universe
and very strong 6. 10. 35 (for citation see
Atikṛṣṇā).

मन्दर
Mandara m.: Name of a mountain;
also referred to as Mahāmandara (7. 57.
29).
A. Location: (1) In the north (अस्यां
दिशि … उत्तरायां 5. 109. 3.) 5. 109. 9; 13.
20. 28; beyond the Uśīrabīja, the Maināka
and the Śveta mountains 3. 140. 1;
close to the Śvetagiri (श्वेतं गिरिं
प्रवेक्ष्यामो मन्दरं चैव पर्वतम्)
3. 140. 4; the river Śailodā flows between the
Meru and the Mandara 2. 48. 2; (2)
Mandara covers the entire earth up to the
ocean in the east (प्राचीं दिशम् … असौ
सागरपर्यन्तां भूमिं आवृत्य तिष्ठति)
3. 160. 3-4; (3) The root of the Himavant
reaches in the west (cf. 5. 108. 1-2) eternally
up to the Mandara mountain so deep that one
cannot reach its end even after a thousand
years (अत्र मूलं हिमवतो मन्दरं याति
शाश्वतम्।अपि वर्षसहस्रेण न चास्यान्तो
ऽधिगम्यते) 5. 108. 9 (Nī. on Bom. Ed.
5. 110. 9: मन्दरं समुद्रे मग्नं
एतेन हिमवन्मूलस्य समुद्रजलस्य
चाप्रमेयत्वम् उक्तम्).
B. Descrip-
tion: (1) Excellent mountain (पर्वत-
वर) 1. 16. 1; (शैलवर) 3. 99. 14; (2)
big mountain (महाद्रि) 1. 16. 19; (महा-
शैल) 3. 43. 24; 13. 20. 29; (महामन्दर)
7. 57. 29; eleven thousand योजनस् high
(above the earth), and established the same
number of योजनस् deep below the earth
1. 16. 3; all the gods together could not lift it
1. 16. 4; but king Duḥṣanta was capable of
lifting it with its forest and carry it on his arms
(उद्यम्य मन्दरं दोर्भ्यां हरेत् स-
वनकाननम्) 1. 62. 11; (3) King of
mountains (पर्वतराजन्) 1. 16. 7; (शैल-
राज) 3. 43. 21; 3. 160. 4; (अद्रिराज) 3. 43.
24; (4) Adorned with summits which were
like towering clouds (अभ्रशिखराकारैर्
गिरिः शृङ्गैर् अलंकृतम्) 1. 16. 1; its peaks
were formed of gold and silver (हेमरूप्य-
मयैः शृङ्गैः) 7. 57. 26; (5) Its caves
were attractive (चारुकन्दर) 3. 220. 22;
(6) Full of तीर्थस् (तीर्थवन्त्) 3. 43. 24;
(7) Covered with the network of creepers
(लताजालसमावृत) 1. 16. 1; (8) Resound-
ing with sounds of many birds (नानाविहग-
संघुष्ट) 1. 16. 2; (9) Beset with many
tusked animals (नानादंष्ट्रिसमाकुल)
1. 16. 2 (10) Resorted to by the Kiṃnaras,
the Apsarases, and even by gods 1. 16. 2;
7. 57. 29; (11) Resort of sages (मुनि-
संश्रय) 3. 43. 24; (also see the next
section C).
C. Characteristics: (1) The
Meru and the Mandara mountains adorn the
earth (मेरुमन्दरभूषणां … वसुन्ध-
राम्) 3. 187. 10; the sun circles untiringly
round the Meru and returns to the Mandara
(in the east to start his course the next day)
(एवम् एव परिक्रम्य महामेरुम् अतन्द्रि-
तः। … पुनर् गच्छति मन्दरम्) 3. 160.
28; (2) Mandara is the place of Śaṅkara
(शङ्करस्थानम्); Śaṅkara lives there; un-
less one goes to the Mandara one cannot
see Śiva 7. 69. 55-56; (3) Yakṣa Māṇicara
and Kubera, the king of the Yakṣas, live there;
thousands of Gandharvas, Kiṃpuruṣas and
Yakṣas, having varied forms and equipped
with different weapons, wait upon Māṇibhadra,
the lord of the Yakṣas (यक्षेन्द्रं … माणि-
भद्रम् उपासते) 3. 140. 4-6; in the bowers
of Mandara the Gandharvas sing गाथास्
which enchant one's mind and intelligence
(अत्र मन्दरकुञ्जेषु … ।गन्धर्वा गान्ति
गाथा वै चित्तबुद्धिहराः) 5. 107. 9; the
regions of the Mandara resound with songs
of the Kiṃnaras 7. 57. 26; (4) The regions
of the Mandara were illuminated by the
different kinds of herbs and by its gold and
silver peaks (हेमरूप्यमयैः शृङ्गैर्
नानौषधिविदीपितान्); they were also adorn-
ed by blossoming Mandāra trees 7. 57. 26;
(5) The mountain is one of those which
are looked upon as difficult of access (दुर्-
गमाः पर्वताः) 3. 140. 8; (6) Mandara
was the place of resort of the pious sages who
longed for heaven; by the grace of the
Mandara, the Brāhmaṇas, the Kṣatriyas, and
the Vaiśyas reach heaven and live there with
gods, free from distress 3. 43. 22, 23; (7)
The mountain had many peaks, bowers, rivers
streams and many holy तीर्थस् on it (तव
सानूनि कुञ्जांश् च नद्यः प्रस्रवणानि
च।तीर्थानि च सुपुण्यानि) 3. 43. 25;
(8) Various tribes like the Khaśas, the
Ekāśanājyohas (? एकाशना ज्योहाः ?), the
Pradaras, the Dīrghaveṇus, the Paśupas, the
Kuṇindas, the Taṅgaṇas and the Parataṅgaṇas
lived there 2. 48. 3.
D. Epic events: (1)
At the time of the burning of the Khāṇḍava
forest a huge peak of the Mandara mountain
was uprooted by Indra and hurled, along
with trees on it, at Arjuna 1. 218. 47; (2)
The tribes living along the Śailodā river
flowing between Meru and Mandara brought
tributes of various kinds to Yudhiṣṭhira for
his Rājasūya 2. 48. 2-5; (3) Arjuna, in
the company of Mātali, started from this
mountain for his journey to Indraloka; while
taking leave of the mountain, Arjuna said
that he had lived there happily and had seen
there many peaks, bowers, rivers and holy
तीर्थस् 3. 43. 21, 24, 25; (4) Lomaśa
pointed out Mandara to Yudhiṣṭhira as they
were about to enter it after crossing the
Uśīrabīja, the Maināka, the Śveta and the
Kālaśaila 3. 140. 1, 4; (5) Arjuna and
Kṛṣṇa saw the mountain Mandara on their
way while they were going to the Kailāsa
7. 57. 26, 29.
E. Mythological and past
events: (1) When gods were advised by the
god Nārāyaṇa to churn the great Kalaśodadhi
(1. 15. 11-12), they went to the Mandara
but could not lift it (for using it as a
churning rod) 1. 16. 1, 4; then, at the bidding
of Brahman, the serpent Ananta lifted it for
them 1. 16. 5-7; when gods took it to the
ocean and told it that they wanted to churn the
ocean for अमृत, the ocean asked for a share
in it as it would bear the pounding by the
Mandara 1. 16. 8-9; gods then requested
Akūpāra, the king of tortoises, to offer
support to the mountain; it agreed and then
Indra fixed the top of the mountain on the
tortoise with some mechanism (तस्य शैलस्य
चाग्रं वै यन्त्रेणेद्रो ऽभ्यपीडयत्); gods
then started churning the ocean using Man-
dara as the churning rod 1. 16. 10-12; from
the top of the mountain showers of flowers
fell on gods and demons and there arose
a loud noise as the ocean was being churned;
the great mountain crushed many acquatic
creatures and they perished by hundreds; the
mountain destroyed many creatures belonging
to Varuṇa who lived in Pātāla; huge trees, as
they rubbed against each, other, fell down,
together with the birds on them, from the top
of the mountain when the ocean was being
churned; fire which arose due to the rubbing
of the trees engulfed the Mandara mountain;
the fire burnt elephants, lions and other
creatures (on the mountain) 1. 16. 17-23;
when gods were tired, Viṣṇu gave them
strength and exhorted them to agitate the
Kalaśa ocean by rotating Mandara 1. 16. 31;
when at the end gods got victory over demons
they honoured the mountain and replaced it
on its original site 1. 17. 29; the water of
the ocean which was churned by gods and
demons using Mandara as a churning rod
was mixed with the milk of four cows, the
daughters of Surabhi, who guarded the four
directions (आसां तु पयसा मिश्रं पयो
निर्मथ्य सागरे) 5. 100. 11, (1, 7);
(2) When gods, led by Indra, were defeated
by Vṛtra they sat down on the top of the
mountain Mandara and prayed to Viṣṇu;
thereupon Viṣṇu showed them the way
5. 9. 52, (5. 10. 6-13); (3) In another
version, Viṣṇu advised gods, Indra and the
rest, to go to Mandara to see Śiva; only
then they would be able to kill their enemy
(Vṛtra); then gods, together with Brahman,
went to Mandara and saw Śiva there 7. 69.
56; (4) When Śiva's chariot was assembled
for his fight with the three sons of Tāraka,
riding the त्रिपुरस्, Mandara was made
the axle of the chariot (मन्दरं पर्वतं
चाक्षम्) 8. 24. 69; (5) Viṣṇu once hurled
Mandara (against his enemy) 3. 99. 14;
(6) As directed by Vadānya, Aṣṭāvakra,
in his journey towards the north to meet the
old female ascetic, came across mountains
Kailāsa, Mandara, and Haima, and he went
beyond them (सर्वान् अनुचचार ह॥तान्
अतीत्य महाशैलान्) 13. 20. 28-29; (7)
Nahuṣa, after he became the king of heaven,
sported with the Apsarases and the Deva-
kanyās on mountain Kailāsa, Himavant,
Mandara and Śveta 5. 11. 9; (8) Mārka-
ṇḍeya saw, among other mountains, Mandara
in the belly of the Bāla (3. 186. 83 = Nārā-
yaṇa 3. 187. 4) 3. 186. 103.
F. Impor-
tance: Finds place in the Daivata-Ṛṣi-
Vaṃśa 13. 151. 26, 2.
G. Bad omen
related to it: Among the bad omens noticed
by Vyāsa before the war mention is made
of the falling down of the summits of the
mountains Kailāsa, Mandara and Himavant
6. 3. 35.
H. Similes: (1) Hanūmant
assumed a form as huge as Vindhya and
Mandara 3. 149. 10; (2) The golden moun-
tain with Skanda on it shone like Mandara
with the sun having a circle of rays around it
3. 220. 22; (3) Karṇa with his arrows in
his chariot appeared like Mandara with the
sun full of rays 8. 26. 15; (4) The towers
on the gates of Indraprastha were (huge) like
Mandara (गोपुरैर् मन्दरोपमैः) 1.
199. 31; (5) The वज्र was hurled by Indra
at Vṛtra as Mandara was hurled by Viṣṇu 3.
99. 14.

मन्दवाहिनी
Mandavāhinī f.: Name of a river.
Listed by Saṃjaya among the rivers of
the Bhāratavarṣa; its water used by people
for drinking 6. 10. 31, 13; all the rivers
listed by Saṃjaya are described as mothers
of the universe and very strong 6. 10. 35
(for citation see Atikṛṣṇā).

मन्दाकिनी
Mandākinī1 f.: Name of a river.
A. Location: Listed by Saṃjaya among
the rivers of the Bhāratavarṣa; people use
its water for drinking 6. 10. 33, 13; on the
Citrakūṭa mountain in the Janasthāna 13.
26. 27; 3. 83. 55.
B. Description: Des-
cribed as a river that frees one from sins
(पापप्रमोचनी) 3. 83. 55; all the rivers
listed by Saṃjaya are described as mothers of
the universe and very strong 6. 10. 35 (for
citation see Atikṛṣṇā).
C. Holiness:
(1) By bathing there and by being engaged
in worshipping gods and manes (तत्राभिषेकः
कुर्वाणः पितृदेवार्चने रतः) one gets the
fruit of an Aśvamedha and the highest state
(after death) (गतिं च परमां व्रजेत्)
3. 83. 56; (2) One who fasts and bathes
there obtains royal glory (विगाह्य वै निरा-
हारो राजलक्ष्मीं निगच्छति) 13. 26. 27.
D. Importance: Finds place in the Daivata-
Ṛṣi-Vaṃśa 13. 151. 17, 2.

मन्दाकिनी
Mandākinī2 f.: Name of a river.
A. Location: In the north 13. 20. 2, 36;
5. 109. 3, 9; (13. 19. 14); on the mountain
Himavant, near Kailāsa 13. 20. 2, 6-7, and
near the mountain Mandara 5. 109. 9; near
the residence of the old female ascetic (who
was really the northern direction 13. 22. 4)
13. 20. 36 [See also E (1) below].
B.
Relationship: It belongs to Vaiśravaṇa
(Kubera) 13. 105. 18; 13. 20. 7.
C. Des-
cription: (1) Full of Mandāra flowers
(मन्दारपुष्पैः संकीर्णा) 13. 20. 36;
(2) It has great enjoyments (महाभोगा),
and as such is fit to be entered by those who
are devoted to enjoyments (भोगिजनप्र-
वेश्या), and is liked by the Gandharvas, the
Yakṣas and the Apsarases (गन्धर्वयक्-
षैर् अप्सरोभिश् च जुष्टा) 13. 105. 18.
D. Holiness: Those who consider hospita-
lity as a vow, who observe (other) vows,
who give shelter to Brāhmaṇas, and who eat
the remainder (of the food) after serving it
to the dependents—such people adorn the
Mandākinī (अतिथिव्रता सुव्रता ये जना वै
प्रतिश्रयं ददति ब्राह्मणेभ्यः।शिष्टा-
शिनः संविभज्याश्रितांश् च मन्दाकिनीं
ते ऽपि विभूषयन्ति) 13. 105. 19.
E. Past
events: (1) Aṣṭāvakra, in his journey to
the north to meet the old female ascetic
(13. 19. 24), came across the river Mandā-
kinī 13. 20. 7; Aṣṭāvakra saw Mandākinī in
a beautiful forest spot further to the north
(13. 20. 28) of the residence of Kubera,
and arrived at it when he crossed the Kailāsa,
the Mandara, the Haima and the Kairāta-
sthāna 13. 20. 28-29, 31, 36; (2) The Brāh-
maṇa Gautama offered to take the crocodile
named Dhṛtarāṣṭra (who was really Indra)
to the river Mandākinī in lieu of his elephant
that was snatched by the crocodile 13. 105. 6,
18. [See Vasor dhārā2]

मन्दाकिनी
Mandākinī3 f.: Name of a river.
A. Location: Flowing high up in the
mid-region (ततो मन्दाकिनीम् … उपरिष्टाद् …
ददर्श) 12. 320. 16.
B. Description:
Charming (रम्या); having forests of flower-
ing trees (on its banks) (पुष्पितद्रुम-
कानना) 12. 320. 16.
C. Characteristic:
Apsarases sport and bathe there (तस्यां
क्रीडन्त्य् अभिरताः स्नान्ति चैवाप्सरोगणाः)
12. 320. 17, 28.
D. Past event: In his
upward journey through the space Śuka saw
Mandākinī when he went through the two
peaks of the mountains Himavant and Meru
which were torn asunder; the mountain could
no longer check his gait 12. 320. 16, 8-11;
when Vyāsa followed his son Śuka flying
up (उत्तमां गतिम् आस्थाय) and reached
the mountain peaks rent asunder by Śuka he
sat down on the slope of the mountain think-
ing about his son (निषसाद गिरिप्रस्थे);
he saw there Apsarases sporting on the bank
of Mandākinī; they were all confused and
lost their senses when they saw the sage
(आसाद्य तम् ऋषिं सर्वाः संभ्रान्ता गत-
चेतसः) 12. 320. 18, 27-28. [See Vasor
dhārā2]

मरुतां
Marutāṃ Tīrtham nt.: Name of a
तीर्थ। [See Pavanasya hradaḥ]

मरुद्गण
Marudgaṇa m., nt. (?): Name of a
तीर्थ।
A person by bathing at this तीर्थ is
purified and himself becomes a तीर्थ (मरु-
द्गण उपस्पृश्य … शुचिः … तीर्थभूतो
भवेन् नरः॥) 13. 26. 37.

मलदा
Maladā f.: Name of a river.
One should proceed to this river from the
Vimalatīrtha 3. 80. 103, 105; described as
famous in the three worlds (त्रिषु लोकेषु
विश्रुताम्) 3. 80. 105; one should bathe in it
in the evening twilight according to the pre-
scribed rites and offer a चरु according to
one's mite in the fire having seven flames;
such an offering to manes is considered to be
inexhaustible (पश्चिमायां तु संध्यायाम्
उपस्पृश्य यथाविधि॥चरुं नरेन्द्र
सप्तार्चेर् यथाशक्ति निवेदयेत्।पितॄणाम्
अक्षयं दानं प्रवदन्ति मनीषिणः॥)
3. 80. 105-106; offering such a चरु is more
meritorious than gifting a hundred thousand
cows, than a hundred Rājasūya sacrifices, and
a thousand Aśvamedha sacrifices 3. 80. 107.

मलय
Malaya1 m.: Name of a mountain.
A. Location: Listed by Saṃjaya among
the seven principal mountains of Bhārata-
varṣa (सप्तैते कुलपर्वताः) 6. 10. 10; on
the southern ocean, near the mountain Sahya
and Dardura 3. 266. 42.
B. Description:
Glorious (श्रीमन्त्) 3. 264. 34; 6. 7. 53;
great mountain (महाशैल) 3. 264. 34; red
in colour (ताम्रवर्ण) 6. 7. 53.
C.
Characteristics: (1) The two Apsarases,
Urvaśī and Pūrvacitti, visit the mountain
constantly (यं नित्यम् उपसेवते) 12. 319.
20; (2) Sandalwood is known as growing
on the mountain Malaya (मलयज) 1. 23.
4 (the forest to which the Nāgas were carried
by Suparṇa was marked by sky-high (sandal-
wood) trees which grow on mountain Malaya
उपजिघ्रद्भिर् आकाशं वृक्षैर् मलयजैर्
अपि 1. 23. 4; (3) Malaya mountain formed
the head of the Jambudvīpa which had the
form of a hare having two Dvīpas, the
Nāgadvīpa and the Kaśyapadvīpa, for its
two ears 6. 7. 52-53.
D. Past events:
(1) Malaya was the first mountain beyond
which Śuka sojourned in his journey upwards
through the space (ततः समतिचक्राम
मलयं नाम पर्वतम्) 12. 319. 20;
(2) Nahuṣa, when he became the king of
heaven, enjoyed in the company of the Apsa-
rases and Devakanyās on Malaya and other
mountains 5. 11. 9; (3) Mārkaṇḍeya saw
Malaya in the belly of the Bāla (3. 186.
83 = Nārāyaṇa 3. 187. 3) 3. 186. 104;
(4) Hanūmant and others when they came
out of a cave in the south they saw the
mountains Malaya, Sahya and Dardura near
the ocean; when they went up the moun-
tain Malaya they realized the expanse of the
ocean and were dejected.
E. Importance:
Mentioned in the Daivata-Ṛṣi-Vaṃśa 13. 151.
26, 2.
F. Similes: (1) Sugrīva with
a garland around his neck looked like the
great mountain Malaya, circled by a garland
of clouds 3. 264. 34; (2) Malaya, is one
of the four mountains with which Yudhiṣṭhira
compared his four brothers 3. 297. 14; (3)
The banner (केतु) on the chariot of the king
of the Pāṇḍyas, adorned with चन्दन and
अगुरु, is compared with Malaya 8. 15. 32;
(4) The narrative of Nārāyaṇa was collected
(समुद्धृतम्) by Vaiśaṃpāyana from the
Mahābhārata as one collects the sandalwood
from Malaya 12. 331. 3.

मलय
Malaya2 m.: Name of a mountain of
the Śākadvīpa; also called Jalada.
One of the seven mountains of the Śāka-
dvīpa 6. 12. 12, 14; described as extending to-
wards the east (प्रागायत); clouds originate
there and appear everywhere (यतो मेघाः
प्रवर्तन्ते प्रभवन्ति च सर्वशः) 6.
12. 14; hence referred to also as Jalada 6. 12.
23; all the seven mountains of Śākadvīpa
are said to be decked with gems (मणि-
भूषिताः) and are mines of jewels (रत्ना-
कराः) 6. 12. 13; the extent of all the seven
mountains of the Śākadvīpa is double that of
the one preceding it in the order of their enu-
meration (तेषां योजनविष्कम्भो द्विगुणः
प्रविभागशः) 6. 12. 22; the Varṣa related
to this mountain is Kumudottara 6. 12. 23.

मलवासस्
Malavāsas f.: Name of a river.
Mentioned in the Daivata-Ṛṣi-Vaṃśa
(मलवासाश् च नद्य् अपि) 13. 151. 20, 2.

महत्सरस्
Mahatsaras, Mahāsaras nt.: Name of
a holy lake.
Those high-souled ones who visit this
lake (प्रभासं मानसं पुण्यं पुष्क-
राणि महत्सरः। … ये प्रयान्ति 13. 105.
45, 47) become auspicious, assume heavenly
form, wear heavenly garlands, and full of holy
fragrance they reach the Goloka (? मोदन्ति
गवां विमाने 13. 105. 44) 13. 105. 45, 48
(for citation see Karatoyinī); one who visits
Mahāsaras shall again get life in this life (?)
(महासरः … गन्तासि लब्धायुर्जीविते पु-
नः) 12. 148. 11.

महद्द्युमन्
Mahaddyuman nt.: Name of a sacred
place.
According to one of the stanzas in praise
of the Nāgas, recited by Uttaṅka, the youngest
brother of Takṣaka, known as Śrutasena,
lived at Mahaddyuman praying to become the
chief of the Nāgas (जघन्यजस् तक्षकस्य
श्रुतसेनेति यः श्रुतः।अवसद् यो महद्-
द्युम्नि प्रार्थयन् नागमुख्यताम्॥) 1.
3. 146 (Nī., however, on Bom. Ed. 1. 3. 142:
महद्युम्नि तीर्थविशेष इति प्राञ्चः।म-
हद्युम्नि सूर्ये तत्समीपे नागमुख्यतां
प्रार्थयन् कुरुक्षेत्र ऽवसद् इति पूर्वेण
संबन्धः कुरुक्षेत्रवासमात्राद् एव
महत् स्थानं प्राप्यत इत्य् आशयः।).

महाकाल
Mahākāla m.: Name of a holy place
sacred to Śiva.
One should reach there from Yayāti-
patana; the Koṭitīrtha is situated there 3.
80. 68.

महाक्रौञ्च
Mahākrauñca m.: Name of a mountain
of the Krauñcadvīpa.
Located in the Krauñcadvīpa; it is a
mine of heaps of jewels (रत्नचयाकरः);
it is always worshipped by people of the
four castes (संपूज्यते महाराज चातुर्-
वर्ण्येन नित्यदा) 6. 13. 7.

महागङ्गा
Mahāgaṅgā f.: Name of a river.
According to the Tīrthavaṃśa narrated
by Aṅgiras to Gautama (13. 26. 3-4) one
who bathes in the Mahāgaṅgā at the junction
of the Kṛttikās with the Mars and observes
fast for a fortnight becomes pure and goes
to heaven (महागङ्गाम् उपस्पृश्य कृत्तिका-
ङ्गारके तथा।पक्षम् एकम् निराहारः
स्वर्गम् आप्नोति निर्मलः॥) 13. 26. 20.

महागिरि
Mahāgiri m.: Name of a mountain.
After visiting Dhārā and after paying
homage to Mahāgiri (महागिरिं नमस्-
कृत्य) one should go to Gaṅgādvāra 3. 82.
23.

महागौरी
Mahāgaurī f.: Name of a river.
Listed by Saṃjaya among the rivers of
the Bhāratavarṣa; people use its water for
drinking 6. 10. 32, 13; all the rivers listed
here are described as mothers of the universe
and very strong 6. 10. 35 (for citation see
Atikṛṣṇa).

महानद
Mahānada m.: Name of a river (or an
epithet of Lohitya ?).
Finds mention in the Daivata-Ṛṣi-Vaṃśa
(लोहित्यश् च महानदः) 13. 151. 16, 2.

महानदि
Mahānadi1 f.: Name of a river.
A. Location: Listed by Saṃjaya among
the rivers of the Bhāratavarṣa; its water
used by people for drinking 6. 10. 26, 13;
in the east (प्राचीं दिशम् अभिप्रेप्सुः 1.
207. 5) 1. 207. 7; 3. 85. 3; near Gayā,
Gayāśiras and Brahmaśiras (महानदी च
तत्रैव) 3. 85. 8; (पुण्या चैव महानदी)
3. 93. 10.
B. Description: Described as
holy (पुण्या) 3. 93. 10; all the rivers listed
by Saṃjaya are said to be mothers of the
universe and very strong 6. 10. 35 (for citation
see Atikṛṣṇā).
C. Epic event: Arjuna,
during his exile, came across the Mahānadī
while he was proceeding towards the east
1. 207. 7, 5.
D. Past event: One of the
rivers seen by Mārkaṇḍeya in the belly of
the Bāla (3. 186. 83 = Nārāyaṇa 3. 187. 3)
3. 186. 95.
E. Holiness: By bathing
(उपस्पृश्य) in this river and by satisfying
manes and gods (by giving offerings to them)
one gets imperishable worlds and rescues his
family (अक्षयान् प्राप्नुयाल् लोकान् कुलं
चैव समुद्धरेत्) 3. 82. 73.
F. Impor-
tance: Finds mention in the Daivata-Ṛṣi-
Vaṃśa 13. 151. 15, 2.

महानदी
Mahānadī2 f.: Name of a river of the
Śākadvīpa.
Listed by Saṃjaya among the rivers of
the Śākadvīpa 6. 12. 30; all the rivers of the
Śākadvīpa contain holy water (पुण्यजलाः)
6. 12. 29, (पुण्योदाः) 6. 12. 31; all of them
are holy and excellent rivers (पुण्यास् ता हि
सरिद्वराः) 6. 12. 32; Vāsava (Indra) gives
rain after collecting water from these rivers
(यतो वर्षति वासवः) 6. 12. 31.

महानदी
Mahānadī3 f. (sg., pl.): Epithet of
certain rivers.
(1) When Śiva's chariot was made
ready for his fight with demons who fought
from the Tripuras, the Mahānadī's were made
its hind parts (जङ्घास् तस्य महानदीः)
8. 24. 69 (by Mahānadīs (pl.) are probably
meant rivers like Kuśadhārā, Gaṅgā, Car-
maṇvatī, Pūrṇāśā, Bāhudā2, Yamunā, Vadhū-
sarā, Vandanā, which are described as ‘great
rivers’); (2) When Pāṇḍu with his two
wives went to the north beyond the Śataśṛṅga
mountain, he saw the regions of the king of
mountains and banks of big rivers (महा-
नदीनितम्बान्) 1. 111. 5-7; (3) Just as
a person who knows the other bank is not
afflicted while crossing a big river so are
those who know the highest knowledge
(महानदीं हि पारज्ञस् तप्यते न तरन्
यथा।एवं ये विदुः … ज्ञानम् उत्तमम्)
12. 187. 53.

महानन्दा
Mahānandā f.: Name of a river.
One who is controlled (दान्तः) and who
does not cause injury to others (अहिंसकः)
if he visits the Mahānandā (महानन्दां च
सेव्य वै) he is served by the Apsarases
in the Nandana forest 13. 26. 42.

महापगा
Mahāpagā f.: Name of a river.
Listed by Saṃjaya among the rivers of
the Bhāratavarṣa; people used its water for
drinking 6. 10. 27, 13 (for other details see
Mahānadī1, section B).

महापुर
Mahāpura nt.: Name of a तीर्थ।
One who bathes (उपस्पृश्य) in this
तिर्थ and fasts for three nights has no fear
from living (lit. moving) beings and non-
moving objects and from bipeds (त्रसानां
स्थावराणां च द्विपदानां भयं त्यजेत्)
13. 26. 24 (Nī. on Bom. Ed. 13. 25. 26:
त्रसानां जङ्गमानाम्).

महामन्दर
Mahāmandara m.: See Mandara.

महामेरु
Mahāmeru m.: See Meru1.

महालय
Mahālaya m.: Name of a sacred place.
By staying at Mahālaya for a month
and by taking food only in the evening of
every third day (षष्ठकालोपवासेन) one is
freed of all sins and gets much gold (विन्द्याद्
बहु सुवर्णकम्) 3. 82. 49.

महावैतरणी
Mahāvaitaraṇī f.: See Vaitaraṇī.

महाशङ्ख
Mahāśaṅkha m.: Name of a tree.
A. Location: On the bank of the river
Sarasvatī (महाशङ्खम् … सरस्वत्यास् तटे
जातं नगम्) 9. 36. 20 (Nī. on Bom. Ed.
9. 37. 21: नगं वृक्षम्); near the Śaṅkha-
tīrtha 9. 36. 19-20.
B. Description:
Lordly tree (वनस्पतिः) 9. 36. 22, 24; as
high as the mountain Mahāmeru (महा-
मेरुम् इवोच्छ्रितम्) 9. 36. 20; looking like
the Śveta mountain (श्वेतपर्वतसंकाशम्)
9. 36. 20; resorted to by sages (ऋषिसंघैर्
निषेवितम्) 9. 36. 20.
C. Characteristic:
Yakṣas, Vidyādharas, Rākṣasas, Piśācas and
Siddhas give up taking food there and eat
only the fruit of that tree at proper intervals
observing certain vows and rules; they then
move about separately observing these regu-
lations and are unseen by men; the tree was
renowned for this (ते सर्वे ह्य् अशनं
त्यक्त्वा फलं तस्य वनस्पतेः।व्रतैश्
च नियमैश् चैव काले काले स्म भूञ्जते॥
प्राप्तैश् च नियमैस् तैस् तैर् विचरन्तः
पृथक् पृथक्।अदृश्यमाना मनुजैर् व्य-
चरन् पुरुषर्षभ॥एवं ख्यातो नर-
पते लोके ऽस्मिन् स वनस्पतिः) 9. 36. 21-24.

महासरस्
Mahāsaras nt.: See Mahatsaras.

महाह्रद
Mahāhrada nt.: Name of a तीर्थ (13.
151. 23).
A. Location: On the Bhṛgutuṅga moun-
tain 13. 26. 17.
B. Description: Ex-
cellent among all तीर्थस् (सर्वतीर्थवर)
3. 82. 125.
C. Holiness: (1) By stay-
ing at this तीर्थ one does not meet with
bad condition and gets much gold (यो वसेत
महाह्रदे।न दुर्गतिम् अवाप्नोति विन्देद्
बहु सुवर्णकम्) 3. 82. 125; (2) By
bathing in the lake one has done one's duty
and becomes pure (अत्र स्नातः कृतकृत्यो
विशुद्धः) 3. 113. 25; (3) According
to the Tīrthavaṃśa proclaimed by Aṅgiras
(13. 26. 3), one who is free from desire
(अलोलुपः) if he bathes (उपस्पृश्य) in
the lake and fasts for three nights he is
freed from the sin of killing a Brāhmaṇa
(मुच्यते ब्रह्महत्यया) 13. 26. 17; (4)
According to the same authority one who has
a pure mind, if he bathes (उपस्पृश्य) there
and fasts for a month he gets the condition
obtained by Jamadagni (जमदग्निगतिं
लभेत्) 13. 26. 45; (5) The high-souled
ones who visit the Mahāhrada become auspi-
cious and assuming a heavenly form, wear-
ing heavenly garlands and becoming rich in
fragrance, they reach the world of the cows
(? मोदन्ति गवां विमाने 13. 105. 44) 13.
105. 46, 48 (for citation see Karatoyinī).
D. Importance: Finds mention in the
Daivata-Ṛṣi-Vaṃśa (तीर्थं महाह्रदम्)
13. 151. 23, 2.
E. Epic event: Lomaśa
advised Yudhiṣṭhira to bathe in this lake and
then proceed to other तीर्थस् 3. 113. 25.
F. Past event: Sage Kāśyapa practised
austerities at this lake; once while he was
bathing in the lake (अप्सूपस्पृशतः) he
happened to see Apsaras Urvaśī; his semen
spilled in water which was drunk by a female
deer; Ṛṣyaśṛṅga was born at this lake from
this female deer 3. 110. 12-16; the holy her-
mitage of Ṛṣyaśṛṅga adorned the Mahāhrada
(तस्याश्रमः पुण्य एषो विभाति महाह्र-
दं शोभयन्) 3. 113. 25.

महिता
Mahitā f.: Name of a river.
Listed by Saṃjaya among the rivers of
the Bhāratavarṣa; its water used by people
for drinking 6. 10. 20, 13; all the rivers listed
by Saṃjaya are described as mothers of the
universe and very strong 6. 10. 35 (for citation
see Atikṛṣṇā).

महिरोही
Mahirohī f.: Name of a river.
Listed by Saṃjaya among the rivers of
the Bhāratavarṣa 6. 10. 29, 13; (for other
details see Mahitā).

मही
Mahī f.: Name of a river.
One of the rivers listed by Mārkaṇḍeya;
all these rivers are famous as mothers of fire-
hearths i. e. on the banks of which sacrifices
were performed 3. 212. 22 (for citation and
Nī. see Kapilā).

महीधर
Mahīdhara m.: Name of a sacred moun-
tain.
Situated near Gayaśiras and the holy
river Mahānadī 3. 93. 10; it was honoured
by the virtuous royal sage Gaya who knew
the धर्म (धर्मज्ञेनाभिसत्कृतम्।
राजर्षिणा पुण्यकृता गयेन) 3. 93. 9; the
Pāṇḍavas visited it 3. 93. 9.

महेन्द्र
Mahendra m.: Name of a mountain.
A. Location: In the east, beyond the
Kaliṅgas, near the sea coast 1. 207. 5, 12-
13 (समुद्रतीरेण); 3. 85. 3; 12. 2. 17,
(समुद्रान्ते) 19.
B. Description: Holy
(पुण्य) and auspicious (शिव) 3. 85. 16;
excellent mountain, surpassing other moun-
tains (गिरिवर, अत्य् अन्यान् पर्वतान्) 3. 85.
16, (पर्वतोत्तम) 1. 58. 4; 12. 2. 17;
(गिरिश्रेष्ठ) 5. 175. 2; (शैलेन्द्र) 3. 117.
14; one of the mountains called ‘king of
mountains’ (पर्वतराजानः) 14. 43. 5;
adorned by ascetics (तापसैर् उपशोभितम्)
1. 207. 13; having shining Karṇikāra trees
on it (शुभकर्णिकारवन्त्) 8. 66. 39.
C.
Characteristics: (1) Bhārgava Rāma Jāma-
dagnya lived on the Mahendra (गिरिवरः … ।
महेन्द्रो नाम … भार्गवस्य महात्म-
नः) 3. 85. 16; (जामदग्न्यनिषेवितम्)
3. 83. 14; he was there waited upon by seers
who knew the Vedas, the Gandharvas and
the Apsarases (महेन्द्रे … रामं नित्यम्
उपासते।ऋषयो वेदविदुषो गन्धर्वाप्स-
रसस् तथा) 5. 175. 2; 5. 187. 11; (अस्मिन्
महेन्द्रे शैलेन्द्रे वसत्य् अमितविक्रमः
जामदग्न्यः) 3. 117. 14, 11; he made it a
rule to show himself to the Brāhmaṇas on
this mountain on every fourteenth day of the
month 3. 117. 16; (2) Mahendra listed by
Brahman among mountains which are also to
be looked upon as possessing the मध्यम
गुण, i. e. they were characterised by the
quality of रजस् ? 14. 43. 5, 1 (Nī. on Bom.
Ed. 14. 43. 1: मध्यमो गुणः रजोगुण-
प्रधानः); (3) Holy Rāmatīrtha and the
Mataṅgakedāra located on it 3. 83. 14; so also
the holy Brahmaśālā river flows on it 3. 85.
18.
D. Epic events: (1) Arjuna, during
his exile, saw it when he went beyond the
Kaliṅgas and while going further along the
seashore 1. 207. 13; (2) The Brāhmaṇas
expressed their wish to visit Mahendra and
other mountains in the company of the Pāṇḍa-
vas 3. 91. 10; (3) After visiting the river
Vaitaraṇī, Yudhiṣṭhira went to Mahendra and
lived there for a night; he honoured there the
ascetics, Bhṛgus, Aṅgirases and others, and
expressed his wish to see Rāma Jāmadagnya
3. 114. 26; 3. 115. 1-4; he also honoured the
Brāhmaṇas 3. 117. 18; Jāmadagnya appeared
before the Pāṇḍavas and was honoured by
them (स तम् आनर्च राजेन्द्रः); Yudhi-
ṣṭhira too was honoured by him (पूजितस्
तेन) 3. 117. 16-18; (4) Hotravāhana
advised Ambā to go to Mahendra to see
Jāmadagnya 5. 175. 1-2; (5) Jāmadagnya
admitted to Ambā his inability to defeat
Bhīṣma and returned to Mahendra 5. 187. 11;
(6) When Droṇa refused to impart Brahmā-
stra to Karṇa, the latter went to Mahendra to
acquire it from Jāmadagnya 12. 2. 14; there
Karṇa met many Gandharvas, Rākṣasas,
Yakṣas and gods 12. 2. 17.
E. Mythologi-
cal and past events: (1) Pitāmaha (Brah-
man), in bygone days, offered a sacrifice on
the mountain Mahendra; the river Bhāgīrathī
was in his सदस् (यत्र भागीरथी पुण्या
सदस्यासीत्) 3. 85. 17; (2) After extirpat-
ing the Kṣatriyas from this earth twenty one
times Rāma Jāmadagnya practised austerities
on mount Mahendra 1. 58. 4; after perform-
ing a sacrifice and giving away the earth to
Kaśyapa, Jāmadagnya took his residence on
Mahendra 3. 117. 14; (3) Mārkaṇḍeya saw
Mahendra, among other mountains, in the
belly of the Bāla (3. 186. 83 = Nārāyaṇa
3. 187. 3) 3. 186. 104; (4) King Nahuṣa,
after he became the king of heaven, enjoyed
himself on Mahendra and at other places in
the company of the Apsarases and the Deva-
kanyās 5. 11. 9.
F. Importance: Mahendra
heads the list of the seven principal mountains
(सप्तैते कुलपर्वताः) listed by Saṃjaya
6. 10. 10; finds mention in the Daivata Ṛṣi-
Vaṃśa 13. 151. 26, 2.
G. Simile: Karṇa
with arrows pierced in his body looked like
the Mahendra with trees covering its peaks
and valleys (महीरुहैर् आचितसानुकन्दरो
यथा महेन्द्रः) 8. 66. 39.

महेन्द्रवाणी
Mahendravāṇī f.: Name of a river.
Mentioned in the Daivata-Ṛṣi-Vaṃśa 13.
151. 22, 2.

महेन्द्रा
Mahendrā f.: Name of a river.
Listed by Saṃjaya among the rivers of
the Bhāratavarṣa; people use its water for
drinking 6. 10. 21, 13; all the rivers listed
by Saṃjaya are described as mothers of the
universe and very strong 6. 10. 21 (for cita-
tion see Atikṛṣṇā).

महेश्वरपद
Maheśvarapada nt.: Name of a तीर्थ।
One who practises chastity and is com-
posed (ब्रह्मचारी समाहितः) if he visits
this तीर्थ and bathes there he will get the
fruit of a horse sacrifice (वाजिमेधफलं
लभेत्) 3. 82. 103.

महोदय
Mahodaya m.: Name (?) or epithet of
Durgaśaila. [See Durgaśaila]

माठरस्य
Māṭharasya vanam nt.: Name of a
forest.
Situated on the Varuṇasrotas mountain
in the south (3. 86. 1); described as holy,
auspicious and having many roots and fruits
(पुण्यं बहुमूलफलं शिवम्) 3. 86. 7.

मातृतीर्थ
Mātṛtīrtha nt.: Name of a तीर्थ।
Situated near the तीर्थस् of Kośeśvara;
the progeny of one who bathes there increases
and he gets endless prosperity (प्रजा विवर्-
धते राजन्न् अनन्तां चाश्नुते श्रियम्) 3.
81. 47.

माधवीतीर्थ
Mādhavītīrtha nt.: Name of a तीर्थ।
Situated in the Kuśasthalī in the west
(2. 13. 49); the Yādavas were delighted to
see it when they decided to settle down in
Kuśasthalī (माधवाः … परां मुदम्
अवाप्नुवन्) 2. 13. 52.

मानवी
Mānavī f.: Name of a river.
Listed by Saṃjaya among the rivers of
the Bhāratavarṣa; people use its water for
drinking 6. 10. 31, 13; all the rivers listed
here are described as mothers of the universe
and very strong 6. 10. 35 (for citation see
Atikṛṣṇā).

मानस
Mānasa1 nt. (sg., pl.): Name of a
lake.
A. Location: In the north (प्रययाव्
उत्तरां तस्माद् दिशम्) 2. 24. 1; situated
beyond the Himavant and the Śveta moun-
tains 2. 24. 27; 2. 25. 1; beyond the country
of the Kiṃpuruṣas; near the Hāṭaka country
(हाटकान् अभितः) of the Guhyakas and the
Gandharva country 2. 25. 1-3, 5.
B. Des-
cription: Holy (पुण्य) 13. 105. 45; heavenly
(दिव्य) 13. 140. 23 (not named); best
(उत्तम) 2. 25. 4; having fruits and flowers
of all seasons (सर्वर्तुफलपुष्पेषु मान-
सेषु सरःसु च) 1. 143. 26.
C. Chara-
cteristics: (1) Dwelling place of swans,
hence they are called मानसौकसः 6. 114.
91; 8. 28. 20; 8. 43. 64; (2) Owing to the
boon given by Brahman to the lake (ब्रह्म-
दत्तवरं सरः), the Khalin demons, when
killed in war, repeatedly bathed there and
came out alive (हता हता वै ते तत्र
जीवन्त्य् आप्लुत्य दानवाः) 13. 140. 18.
D. Holiness: The high-souled persons and
those who observe vows if they visit the
Mānasa lake they assume heavenly form,
become auspicious, and putting on heavenly
garlands and rich in holy fragrance they enjoy
in the Goloka (? मोदन्ति गवां विमाने)
13. 105. 45, 44, 48 (for citation see Kara-
toyinī).
E. Epic events: (1) Hiḍimbā,
after she was allowed to take Bhīma as her
husband, delighted him at many places
(रमयाम् आस पाण्डवम्), some of those
being the Mānasa lakes (माणसेषु सरःसु
च) 1. 143. 26; (2) Arjuna saw it in his
expedition to the north and then conquered
Hāṭaka, the country of the Guhyakas, along
with the country of the Gandharvas 2. 25.
4-5; (3) Lomaśa showed to Yudhiṣṭhira
the gate of the Mānasa (एतद् द्वारं महा-
राज मानसस्य प्रकाशते) 3. 130. 12;
(4) When Bhīṣma decided to extend his life
till the advent of the Uttarāyaṇa, Gaṅgā sent
great sages to him in the form of swans living
in the Mānasa lake 6. 114. 91.
F. Past
and mythological events: (1) The illustri-
ous Rāma (Jāmadagnya) established a place
for him to reside on the mountain (Hima-
vant) and near the gate of the Mānasa (एतद्
द्वारं महाराज मानसस्य प्रकाशते।
वर्षम् अस्य गिरेर् मध्ये रामेण श्रीमता
कृतम्॥) 3. 130. 12 (Nī. on Bom. Ed. 3.
130. 12: वर्षं वसतिस्थानम्); (2)
The Ādityas once performed a सत्र near the
Mānasa lake; sage Vasiṣṭha also lived near
it; the demons, called Khalins, disturbed the
sacrifice of the Ādityas; Śakra (Indra) sought
help from Vasiṣṭha and the latter burnt the
demons by his lustre 13. 140. 16-22; (3)
Vasiṣṭha brought the river Gaṅgā, flowing
towards Kailāsa. to the lake Mānasa; the
river broke the lake and hence the river came
to be known as Sarayū (सरो भिन्नं तया
नद्या सरयूः सा ततो ऽभवत्) 13. 140.
23-24; (4) Indra, afraid of the sin of killing
a Brāhmaṇa, divided it into two (तस्यां
द्वैधीभूतायां ब्रह्मवध्यायाम्) and
went to a lotus flower (नलिनीम्) in the
Mānasa lake; there he became of the size of
an atom and entered a knot on the lotus
stalk (अणुमात्रो भूत्वा बिसग्रन्थिं प्र-
विवेश) 12. 329. 28 (1); goddess Upaśruti
took Indra's wife, Śacī, to the lotus in the
Mānasa lake and showed her Indra who had
entered the knot on the stalk 12. 329. 34 (6).
G. Fable: A certain crow, who thought
much of himself, once dared to challenge one
of the swans living in the Mānasa lake 8.
28. 20. [See Uttaramānasa]

मानस
Mānasa2 m.: Name of a mountain.
Indra went to the Mānasa mountain in
search of a leader for the army of the gods
(देवसेना) which was overpowered by the
demons; there he heard the cry of a woman
(who was Devasenā); the two sisters Deva-
senā and Daityasenā, daughters of Prajāpati,
used to come there with their friends for
pleasure; from this mountain the demon
Keśin took away Daityasenā, who longed for
him, but Devasenā was rescued by Indra
3. 213. 17.

मानस
Mānasa3 nt.: A metaphorical तीर्थ।
One should bathe in the mental lake
which is unfathomable, dirt-free, pure, has
truth for water and forbearance for lake
(अगाधे विमले शुद्धे सत्यतोये धृतिह्रदे।
स्नातव्यं मानसे तीर्थे … ) 13. 111. 3.

मानसह्रदा
Mānasahradā f.: See Manohradā.

मानुष
Mānuṣa nt.: Name of a तीर्थ।
Situated at a distance of one क्रोश to
the west of the river Āpagā 3. 81. 55; one
should proceed to the Mānuṣatīrtha from the
Daśāśvamedhika 3. 81. 52-53; described as
famous in the world (लोकविश्रुत) 3. 81.
53; black antelopes, when afflicted by a
hunter, jumped into this तीर्थ and became
human beings (which explains the name of
the तीर्थ) (यत्र कृष्णमृगा राजन् व्या-
धेन परिपीडिताः।अवगाह्य तस्मिन् सरसि
मानुषत्वम् उपागताः) 3. 81. 53; one who
observes chastity and has controlled his
sense organs (ब्रह्मचारी जितेन्द्रियः), if
he bathes there he is cleansed of all sins and
is glorified in heaven 3. 81. 54.

मार्कण्डेयस्य
Mārkaṇḍeyasya tīrtham nt.: Name of
a तीर्थ।
Situated at the confluence of Gomatī and
Gaṅgā; described as world famous (लोकवि-
श्रुत), and difficult to reach (दुर्लभ);
by visiting it one gets the fruit of an Agni-
ṣṭoma and rescues one's family (मार्कण्डेय-
स्य राजेन्द्र तीर्थम् आसाद्य … अग्निष्टोमम्
अवाप्नोति कुलं चैव समुद्धरेत्॥) 3.
82. 70.

माला
Mālā f.: Name of a river.
Kṛṣṇa, Bhīma and Arjuna went beyond
Mithilā and reached the river Mālā (and Car-
maṇvatī) (अतीत्य जग्मुर् मिथिलां मालां
चर्मण्वतीम् नदीम्) 2. 18. 28.

मालिनी
Mālinī1 f.: Name of a river.
A. Location: On the lovely table-land
of the Himavant (प्रस्थे हिमवतो रम्ये)
1. 66. 8; flowing through the forest in which
there was an excellent hermitage of Kaṇva
(1. 64. 25) (प्रेक्षमाणो वनं तत् तु …
आश्रमप्रवरं रम्यं ददर्श … मालि-
नीम् अभितो राजन् नदीम्) 1. 64. 15, 18;
(नदीम् आश्रमसंश्लिष्टाम्) 1. 64. 20; (नदीम्
आश्रमसंबद्धाम्) 1. 64. 23; (अलंकृतं
 … मालिन्या … महद् वनम्) 1. 64. 24.
B. Description: Holy, whose water is holy
(पुण्या) 1. 64. 18; (पुण्यतोया) 1. 64. 20;
whose water caused happiness (सुखोदका)
1. 64. 18; whose banks were pleasing (रम्य-
तीरा) 1. 64. 24; delightful to the mind in
the forest meant for austerities (तपोवन-
मनोरमा) 1. 64. 18; bringing in her current
flowers and foam (पुष्पफेनप्रवाहिनी)
1. 64. 21; full of islets (द्वीपवती) 1. 64. 24;
Cakravāka birds resting on her sandy banks
(सचक्रवाकपुलिना) 1. 64. 21; adorned
with sandy banks (पुलिनैर् उपशोभिताम्)
1. 64. 22; thronged by many birds (नैक-
पक्षिगणाकीर्णा) 1. 64. 18; resorted to by
monkeys and bears (वानरर्क्षनिषेविता)
1. 64. 21; resorted to by elephants in rut,
tigers and lordly serpents (मत्तवारणशार्-
दूलभुजगेन्द्रनिषेविता) 1. 64. 22; provid-
ing residence to the Kiṃnaras (सकिंनर-
गणावासा) 1. 64. 21; humming with the
sound of the recitations of holy Vedic studies
(पुण्यस्वाध्यायसंघुष्टा) 1. 64. 22;
stationed (in the forest) like the mother of
all beings (सर्वप्राणिभृतां तत्र जननीम्
इव विष्ठिताम्) 1. 64. 20.
C. Past event:
(1) Viśvāmitra begot Śakuntalā on Menakā
near the river Mālinī; Menakā left Śakuntalā,
no sooner born, on the river Mālinī and return-
ed to the assembly of Śakra (Indra) 1. 66.
8-9; (2) Duḥṣanta, while out for hunting,
saw the river Mālinī near a hermitage in the
forest 1. 64. 18.
D. Simile: The hermi-
tage of Kaṇva adorned by Mālinī compared
with the place of Nara-Nārāyaṇa adorned
by Gaṅgā (आश्रमपदम् … अलंकृतम् …
मालिन्या … नरनारायणस्थानं गङ्ग-
येवोपशोभितम्) 1. 64. 23, 24.

माल्यवत्|माल्यवन्त्
Mālyavant1 m.: Name of a mountain.
A. Location: In the north, beyond the
Śveta mountain and near Gandhamādana 3.
155. 33-34, 27; situated to the south of the
Nīla and to the north of the Niṣadha moun-
tain, spread towards the east (प्रागाय-
तः) 6. 7. 7 (Nī. on Bom. Ed. 6. 6. 9:
माल्यवान् पूर्वसमुद्रावधिः); beyond
Mālyavant is Gandhamādana and between
the two is the circular, golden mountain
Meru (परिमण्डलस् तयोर् मध्ये मेरुः
कनकपर्वतः) 6. 7. 8.
B. Extent:
It extends over fifty thousand योजनस्
(योजनानां सहस्राणि पञ्चाशन् माल्यवान्
स्थितः) 6. 8. 27.
C. Description: Holy
(पुण्य) 3. 155. 33; very attractive (सु-
मनोहर) 3. 155. 32; big (महागिरि) 3.
155, 33; having lotus ponds, pools and big
forests (पद्मसरोपेतं सपल्वलमहा-
वनम्) 3. 155. 33; noisy with sounds of
beasts and birds, crowded with many kinds
of birds and resorted to by troops of monkeys
(मृगद्विजसंघुष्टं नानाद्विजसमाकु-
लम्।शाखामृगगणैश् चैव सेवितम्) 3.
155. 32; listed by Brahman among ‘kings
of mountains’ (एते पर्वतराजानः) 14.
43. 5.
D. Characteristics: (1) On the
peak of the Mālyavant blazes the fire called
Saṃvartaka, the fire that destroys the world
(तथा माल्यवतः शृङ्गे दीप्यते तत्र हव्-
यवाट्।नाम्ना संवर्तको नाम कालाग्निः)
6. 8. 26; (2) On the eastern peak there
is a hill which marks the end of the east
(तथा माल्यवतः शृङ्गे पूर्वे पूर्वान्त-
गण्डिका) 6. 8. 27 (Nī. on Bom. Ed. 6. 7.
28: गण्डिका क्षुद्रपर्वतः); (3) Men
who fall down from the world of Brahman
are born there with the colour of gold (महा-
रजतसंकाशा जायन्ते तत्र मानवाः।
ब्रह्मलोकाच् च्युताः सर्वे) 6. 8. 28 (Nī.
on Bom. Ed. 6. 7. 29: महारजतं काञ्च-
नम्); all of them are expounders of the
Veda; they practise austerities and observe
chastity and for the protection of beings they
enter the sun (सर्वे च ब्रह्मवादिनः।
तपस् तु तप्यमानास् ते भवन्ति ह्य् ऊर्ध्व-
रेतसः।रक्षणार्थं तु भूतानां प्र-
विशन्ति दिवाकरम्॥) 6. 8. 28-29; sixty six
thousand of them surround the sun and march
ahead of Aruṇa (the sun's charioteer); they
are heated by the sun's heat for sixty six
thousand years and then they enter the moon
6. 8. 30-31; are all the mountains listed by
Brahman to be looked upon as characterised
by the middle quality (मध्यम गुण,
i. e. रजस्) ? 14. 43. 1.
E. Epic events:
(1) The Pāṇḍavas reached it on their way
from the Śveta to the Gandhamādana; from
there they saw the Gandhamādana 3. 155.
33-34; (2) Dhṛtarāṣṭra asked Saṃjaya to
describe to him the Mālyavant mountain 6.
8. 1.

माल्यवत्|माल्यवन्त्
Mālyavant2 m.: Name of a mountain.
A. Location: Near Kiṣkindhā in the
south 3. 264. 15-16, 26.
B. Description:
Its top described as auspicious (पृष्ठे माल्य-
वतः शुभे) 3. 264. 40.
C. Rāmāyaṇa
events: (1) Vālin, when he came out of
his cave, saw Sugrīva standing near the
Mālyavant and challenging him with roars
(स्थितं माल्यवतो ऽभ्याशे) 3. 264. 26, 16;
(2) After killing Vālln, Rāma lived on its top
for four months and was served by Sugrīva
3. 264. 40; during his stay Rāma, as well as
Lakṣmaṇa, was protected by Sugrīva 3. 266.
1; (3) Lakṣmaṇa and Sugrīva went to
Rāma on the Mālyavant and reported to him
the arrangements made for the search of Sītā
3. 266. 21.

माहेश्वरी
Māheśvarī dhārā f.: Name of a sac-
red place.
By reaching it (समासाद्य) a pilgrim
obtains the fruit of an Aśvamedha and rescues
his family 3. 82. 101.

मिश्रक
Miśraka nt.: Name of a तीर्थ।
Described as the best (उत्तम) 3. 81.
76; according to a tradition Vyāsa mixed
together all the तीर्थस् in this तीर्थ for the
benefit of the twice-born (तत्र तीर्थानि
राजेन्द्र मिश्रितानि महात्मना॥व्यासेन
नृपशार्दूल द्विजार्थम् इति नः श्रुतम्।)
3. 81. 76-77 (this explains the name of the
तीर्थ); one who bathes in this तीर्थ has the
benefit of bathing in all the तीर्थस् 3. 81. 77.

मुञ्जपृष्ठ
Muñjapṛṣṭha1 m.: Name of a तीर्थ।
Near Gayā; by visiting it (?) one is freed
of the sin of killing a Brāhmaṇa 13. 26. 40.

मुञ्जपृष्ठ
Muñjapṛṣṭha2 m.: Name of a holy
summit.
A. Location: Situated on the summit
of the Himavant, on the golden mountain
Meru 12. 122. 3.
B. Description: Wor-
shipped by the divine sages (देवर्षिगण-
पूजित) 12. 122. 2.
C. Holiness: The
place was resorted to by Rudra (स देशो
रुद्रसेवितः) 12. 122. 4.
D. Past event:
Vasuhoma, the righteous king of the Aṅgas,
repaired to it together with his wife 12. 122.
2; the region was named as Muñjapṛṣṭha by
the sages after Rāma ordered cutting off the
locks of his hair (?) at Muñjavaṭa (because
Rāma's matted hair were like thickets of
Muñja ?) (यत्र मुञ्जवटे रामो जटाहर-
णम् आदिशत्॥तदाप्रभृति राजेन्द्र ऋषिभिः
संशितव्रतैः।मुञ्जपृष्ठ इति प्रोक्तः
स देशः) 12. 122. 3-4. [See Muñjavaṭa2,
Muñjavant]

मुञ्जवट
Muñjavaṭa1 m.: Name of a तीर्थ।
Sacred to Mahādeva 3. 81. 18; by stay-
ing there for a night one gets the status of a
Gaṇapati (तत्रोष्य रजनीम् एकां गाण-
पत्यम् अवाप्नुयात्) 3. 81. 18; there is also a
Yakṣī there, famous in the world (तत्रैव
च … यक्षी लोकपरिश्रुता); by approaching
her one the gets holy worlds (पुण्याल्̃ लोकान्)
3. 81. 19; the area is known as the Gate of
the Kurukṣetra (कुरुक्षेत्रस्य तद् द्वारम्)
3. 81. 20.

मुञ्जवट
Muñjavaṭa2 m.: Name of a tree (?).
Situated on the Muñjapṛṣṭha, on the
summit of the Himavant, on the golden
Meru; at Muñjavaṭa, Rāma (Jāmadagnya ?)
ordered cutting off the locks of his hair (?)
(तत्र शृङ्गे हिमवतो मेरौ कनकपर्-
वते।यत्र मुञ्जवटे रामो जटाहरणम्
आदिशत्) 12. 122. 3. [See Muñjapṛṣṭha2]

मुञ्जवत्|मुञ्जवन्त्
Muñjavant m.: Name of a mountain.
A. Location: On the top of the moun-
tain Himavant (गिरेर् हिमवतः पृष्ठे
मुञ्जवान् नाम पर्वतः) 14. 8. 1.
B.
Description: King of mountains (शैलराज)
14. 8. 2.
C. Characteristics: (1) The
mountain blazes with lustre like that of the
morning sun; neither its outward appearance
nor shape can be seen in any form, nor can it
be described by men with their normal fleshy
eyes (न रूपं दृश्यते तस्य संस्थानं
वा कथंचन।निर्देष्टुम् प्राणिभिः कैश्चित्
प्राकृतैर् मांसलोचनैः) 14. 8. 8; (2)
There is neither heat nor cold there, neither
wind nor sun; there is neither old age, nor
hunger, nor thirst; and neither death nor
fear 14. 8. 9; (3) On all the slopes of the
mountain there is gold which is guarded by
helpers of Kubera armed with weapons (तस्य
शैलस्य पार्श्वेषु सर्वेषु … ।धातवो जात-
रूपस्य … रक्ष्यन्ते ते कुबेरस्य सहायैर्
उद्यतायुधैः।) 14. 8. 10-11.
D. My-
thological and past events: (1) Enraged
and dejected at the sight of the creatures
created by another creator (10. 17. 15),
Bhava (Śiva) went away to the foot of the
mountain Muñjavant (गिरेर् मुञ्जवतः
पादम्) to practise austerities 10. 17. 26;
he practised austerities according to his desire
and convenience at the roots of big trees,
on the edges, summits, and caves of the
mountain (वनस्पतीनाम् मूलेषु टङ्केषु
शिखरेषु च।गुहासु शैलराजस्य यथा-
कामं यथासुखम्) 14. 8. 1-2; Mahe-
śvara always lives there with Umā and is
surrounded by hosts of different Bhūtas; there
Rudras, Sādhyas, all the Vasus and various
other gods, as well as the Gandharvas and
the Apsarases, and Yātudhānas wait on him
14. 8. 3-6; god Śiva enjoys himself there in
the company of the followers of Kubera
(रमते भगवांस् तत्र कुबेरानुचरैः
सह) 14. 8. 7; (2) Saṃvarta asked king
Marutta to send his men to the Muñjavant
to get gold from there for his sacrifice after
paying homage to Mahādeva 14. 8. 31. [See
Muñjapṛṣṭha2]

मुर्मुरा
Murmurā f.: Name of a river.
One of the rivers listed by Mārkaṇḍeya
which are declared to be mothers of the fire-
hearths, i. e. on the banks of which sacrifices
were performed (एता नद्यस् तु धिष्ण्यानां
मातरो याः प्रकीर्तिताः) 3. 212. 24 (for Nī.
see Kapilā).

मृगधूम
Mṛgadhūma m., n. (?): Name of a
तीर्थ।
One should proceed to it from the तीर्थस्
Ahan and Sudina; situated on Gaṅgā; des-
cribed as famous in the three worlds (त्रिषु
लोकेषु विश्रुतम्); by bathing there in the
lake of Gaṅgā and by worshipping Mahādeva,
wielding Śūla in his hand, one gets the fruit
of an Aśvamedha 3. 81. 85.

मेद्रथा
Medrathā f.: Name of a river.
One of the rivers listed by Mārkaṇḍeya
which are declared to be mothers of the fire-
hearths 3. 212. 23 (for other details see Mur-
murā).

मेधातिथि
Medhātithi f.: Name of a river.
One of the rivers listed by Mārkaṇḍeya
which are declared to be mothers of the fire-
 hearths 3. 212. 22 (for other details see
Murmurā).

मेधाविक
Medhāvika nt.: Name of a तीर्थ।
Having reached Medhāvika one should
satisfy manes and gods; he thereby wins the
fruit of an Agniṣṭoma and gets remembrance
and intellect (स्मृतिं मेधां च विन्दति)
3. 83. 52.

मेध्या
Medhyā f.: Name of a river.
Situated in the west (प्रतीच्यां … दिशि।
यानि तत्र पवित्राणि पुण्यान्य् आयतनानि
च) 3. 87. 1; described as most holy (पुण्य-
तमा) and always frequented by ascetics
(सततं तापसायुता) 3. 87. 12; listed by
Mārkaṇḍeya among rivers which are declared
to be mothers of the fire-hearths 3. 212. 22
(for other details see Murmurā); finds place
in the Daivata-Ṛṣi-Vaṃśa 13. 151. 21, 2.

मेध्यारण्य
Medhyāraṇya nt.: Name (?) of a forest.
Where the blind and dethroned king
Dyumatsena lived with his wife and son
Satyavant 3, 278. 7-9; described as big
forest (महारण्य) 3. 278. 9; (महावन)
3. 280. 23; king Aśvapati went to Medhyā-
raṇya forest with his daughter Sāvitrī 3.
279. 3.

मेना
Menā f.: Name of a river.
One of the rivers of the Bhāratavarṣa
listed by Saṃjaya; its water used by people
for drinking 6. 10. 22, 13; all the rivers
listed here are said to be mothers of the
universe and very strong 6. 10. 35 (for cita-
tion see Atikṛṣṇā).

मेरु
Meru1 m.: Name of a mountain, also
referred to as Mahāmeru (1. 65. 36; 3. 160.
12, 14, 28; 9. 36. 20; 12. 14. 22-24; 12. 59.
122; 12. 321. 13; 13. 14. 156; 14. 44. 12).
A. Location: In the Svarloka (उप-
रिष्टाद् असौ लोको यो ऽयं स्वर् इति संज्ञि-
तः। … मेरुः पर्वतराड् यत्र) 3. 247. 2,
8; in the north (उदीचीं दीपयन्न् एष दिशं
तिष्ठति कीर्तिंआन्।महामेरुः) 3. 160. 12; 3.
155. 13-14; 12. 320. 9; 17. 2. 2; on the summit
of the mountain Himavant (शृङ्गे हिमवतो
मेरौ) 12. 122. 3; on the northern side of
the Himavant (हिमवत्पार्श्व उत्तरे) 14. 4.
25; beyond the Himavant 17. 2. 2; between
the Mālyavant lying to its east and the Gan-
dhamādana lying to its west lies the circular
mountain Meru 6. 7. 8 (Nī. on Bom. Ed. 6. 6.
9: नीलनिषधयोर् मध्ये मेरुस् तस्य प्राक्
माल्यवान् पूर्वसमुद्रावधिः पश्चिम-
समुद्रावधिर् गन्धमादन इत्य् अर्थः);
Śuka after crossing the Varṣas of Meru and
Hari (i. e. the Ilāvṛta and the Harivarṣa
Varṣas) and that of Himavant (called Kiṃ-
puruṣa) reached the Bhāratavarṣa (मेरोर्
हरेश् च द्वे वर्षे वर्षं हैमवतं
तथा।क्रमेणैव व्यतिक्रम्य भारतं
वर्षम् आसदत्) 12. 312. 14 (Nī. on Bom.
Ed. 12. 325. 14: मेरोर् वर्षं इलावृतम्।
हरेर् वर्षं हरिवर्षाख्यम्।हैमवतं
वर्षं किंपुरुषाख्यम्); to the north of
Meru is the Kṣīroda (milky ocean) (मेरोर्
उत्तरभागे तु क्षीरोदस्यानुकूलतः) 12.
323. 21; from the summit of the Meru one
can see in the north-west Śvetadvīpa to the
north of the Kṣīrodadhi (आलोकयन्न् उत्तर-
पश्चिमेन ददर्श … क्षीरोदधेर् उत्तरतो
हि द्वीपः श्वेतः स नाम्ना प्रथितः) 12.
322. 7-8; the Śvetadvīpa was at a distance
of 32000 योजनस् in the north from the foot
of the mount Meru (मेरोः सहस्रैः स
हि योजनानां द्वात्रिंशतोर्ध्वं कविभिर्
निरुक्तः) 12. 322. 8 (Nī. on Bom. Ed. 12.
335. 9: मेरुमूलात् द्वात्रिंशत्सहस्रयोज-
नाद् ऊर्ध्वम्); on its four sides (तस्य पार्-
श्वे) are the four Dvīpas, viz. the Bhadrāśva,
the Ketumāla, the Jambūdvīpa and the Uttara
Kurus 6. 7. 11; to the north of the Mahāmeru
is the Bhadrāśva 12. 14. 24; to the east of
the Mahāmeru is the Śākadvīpa 12. 14. 23;
to the west of the Mahāmeru is the Krauñca-
dvīpa 12. 14. 22; on the western side of the
Meru is the Ketumāla, to the south of the
Nīla and to the north of the Meru are the
Uttara Kurus, and to the east of the Meru is
the Bhadrāśva 6. 7. 29; 6. 8. 2, 13; the river
Śailodā flows between the Meru and the
Mandara 2. 48. 2.
B. Extent: Its extent
is thirty three thousand योजनस् (त्रयस्त्रिं-
शत् सहस्राणि योजनानाम् … मेरुः) 3. 247.
8; it is sixteen thousand योजनस् deep and
eighty four (thousand) योजनस् high; it covers
the worlds above, within and crosswise (योज-
नानां सहस्राणि षोडशाधः किल स्मृतः॥
उच्चैश् च चतुराशीतिर् योजनानां महीपते।
ऊर्ध्वम् अन्तश् च तिर्यक् च लोकान् आवृत्य
तिष्ठति॥) 6. 7. 9-10 (Nī. on Bom. Ed. 6. 6.
11: अधस्तात् भूमेर् गर्भे); its peak was
a hundred योजनस् high crosswise and above
(शतयोजनविस्तारे तिर्यग् ऊर्ध्वम् च …
संददर्श ह) 12. 320. 9.
C. Descrip-
tion: Auspicious (शिव) 3. 160. 12, 14; big
(महागिरि) 1. 15. 7; 8. 27, 59; (महाशैल)
3. 102. 2; 17. 2. 2; rising up to the sky
(गगनम् उच्छ्रितः) 12. 175. 37; नाकम्
आवृत्य तिष्ठन्तम् उच्छ्रयेण) 1. 15. 7;
having many peaks (अनेकशृङ्गवन्त्) 9. 44.
13; king of mountains (पर्वतराट्) 3. 247.
8; (अद्रिराज) 3. 102. 2; (नगेन्द्र) 1. 93.
6; 1. 216. 34; excellent among the mountains
(शिखरिणाम् वरम्) 17. 2. 2; (श्रेष्ठं
शिखरिणां) 5. 63. 5; (गिरिवर) 12. 327.
18; 13. 84. 64; (पर्वतोत्तम) 12. 320. 11
(said of Meru or Himavant ?); its peak
(उत्तम) 3. 160. 16; no other mountain is
as excellent as Meru (अनुत्तम) 1. 15. 5; its
top (पृष्ठ) is elevated for many कल्पस् (?)
(अनेककल्पम् उद्विद्धम्) 1. 15. 9 (Nī.
on Bom. Ed. 1. 17. 9: अनन्तकल्पं अनन्तो
विष्णुर् आकाशो वा तत ईषन् न्यूनम्।बहु-
गुणत्वाद् अतिप्रमाणत्वाच् च।ईषद् असमा-
प्तौ कल्पप्।उद्विद्धम् उच्चम्।); its
summits rise high (शिखरैः … उच्छ्रितैः)
6. 78. 26; very high (शृङ्गैर् अत्यर्थम् उच्-
छ्रितैः) 6. 106. 33; circular (परिमण्डल)
6. 7. 8; steady, unshakable (अचल) 1. 15. 5;
6. 59. 8; 6. 74. 24; 7. 33. 18; (7. 149. 17);
8. 31. 62; firm (स्थैर्येण मेरोः) 8. 48. 9;
its peak (शृङ्ग) unequalled (अप्रतिम) 12.
320. 8; immeasurable, immeasurable in all the
worlds (अप्रमेय) 1. 15. 6; (अप्रमेयं …
सर्वलोकेषु) 12. 274. 5; unassailable in all
the worlds (अनाधृष्यं सर्वलोकेषु) 12.
274. 5; unassailable by impious persons (अना-
धृष्यम् अधर्मबहुलैर् जनैः) 1. 15. 6;
inaccessible to ordinary people even in thought
(अगम्यं मनसाप्य् अन्यैः) 1. 15. 8 (Nī.
on Bom. Ed. 1. 17. 8: अगम्यं अप्राप्यम्
अन्यैः प्राकृतैः); its region (देश) free
from dust (विरजस्) 3. 160. 16; free from
diseases (अनामय) 3. 160. 14; famous
(कीर्तिमन्त्) 3. 160. 12; has many peaks
(अङेकशृङ्गवन्त्) 9. 44. 13; golden moun-
tain (कनकपर्वत) 3. 102. 2; 3. 186.
103; 6. 7. 8; 12. 59. 122; 12. 122. 3; (काञ्-
चनपर्वत) 13. 101. 6; (हिरण्मय) 3.
247. 8; (काञ्चन) 1. 216. 34; (7. 60. 17);
it has gold as its ornament (काञ्चनाभरण)
1. 15. 6; its peak (शृङ्ग) is golden (रुक्-
ममय) 12. 320. 8; it excels with its peaks,
shining with gold, the lustre of the sun (आक्षि-
पन्तं प्रभां भानोः स्वशृङ्गैः काञ्च-
नोज्ज्वलैः) 1. 15. 5; (शिखरैः काञ्चन-
मयैः) 6. 78. 26; (7. 96. 4); its foot (पाद)
is golden (काञ्चन) 14. 4. 25; its slopes
(गिरितट) are ornamented with gold (हेम-
धातुविभूषित) 12. 274. 6; it is covered all
over with splendid, golden houses (भवनैर्
आवृतः सर्वैर् जाम्बूनदमयैः शुभैः)
6. 7. 15; its surface (पृष्ठ) is full of many
jewels (बहुरत्नाचित) 1. 15. 9; its peak
(शृङ्ग) is adorned with all kinds of jewels
(सर्वरत्नविभूषित) 12. 274. 5; very large
number of jewels on Meru alluded to in 13.
27. 97; it is a mass of lustre (तेजोराशि) 1.
15. 5; burning (ज्वलन्त्) 1. 15. 5; lustrous
(श्रीमन्त्) 7. 33. 18; of great lustre (महा-
द्युति) 1. 216. 34; it is illuminated with
heavenly herbs (दिव्यौषधिविदीपित) 1. 15.
7; it is yellow (पीत) 12. 320. 8; its peaks
(शृङ्ग) and tops (पृष्ठ) are shining (शुभ)
12. 320. 8-9; 1. 15. 9; its peak (शृङ्ग) is
heavenly (दिव्य) and splendid (रुचिर) 12.
320. 8; highly lustrous (महाद्युति) 1. 216.
34; it is very lustrous all around like the sun
and like smokeless fire (आदित्यतरुणाभासो
विधूम इव पावकः) 6. 7. 9; it brightens
the north (उदीचीं दीपयन्न् एष दिशं तिष्-
ठति) 3. 160. 12; lustrous (चित्र) 1. 15. 6;
Meru looked upon as an excellent crest of the
earth (पृथिवीम् … मेरुवरोत्तंसाम्) 1.
159. 20; Meru and Mandara are the two
ornaments of the earth (मेरुमन्दरभूष-
णाम् … वसुंधराम्) 3. 187. 10; pleasing
(रम्य) 12. 327. 18; the forest on it is
pleasing (रम्य), full of flowers (सुपुष्पित)
and agreeable due to the singing of the Kin-
naras (किन्नरगीतजुष्ट) 13. 105. 20; its
peak (शृङ्ग) has forests of Karṇikāra trees
(कर्णिकारवनायुत) 12. 310. 11; on the
northern side of the mountain is a forest of
the Karṇikāra trees which is heavenly, aus-
picious, pleasing, flowering in all seasons and
which has grown out of the crevices in its slabs
(पार्श्वे तस्योत्तरे दिव्यं सर्वर्तुकुसुमं
शिवम्।कर्णिकारवनं रम्यं शिलाजाल-
समुद्गतम्॥) 6. 7. 22; the mountain has
many rivers and forests (नदीवृक्षसमन्-
वित) 1. 15. 8; full of heavenly flowers and
fruits (दिव्यपुष्पफलान्वित) 6. 7. 15; re-
sounding with the sounds of various, attrac-
tive birds (नानापतगसंघैश् च नादितं
सुमनोहरैः) 1. 15. 8; resorted to by gods
and the Gandharvas (देवगन्धर्वसेवित)
1. 15. 6; also by the Siddhas and the Cāraṇas
(सिद्धचारणसेवित) 12. 327. 18; haunted
by fierce beasts of prey (व्यालैर् आचरितं
घोरैः) 1. 15. 7; also see the next section
C.
Characteristics and the entry Jyotiṣka: the
peak on mountain Meru.
C. Characteri-
stics: (1) Lustre is the chief characteristic
of Meru (प्रभां मेरोः) 13. 98. 10; (2)
Aśvatthāman had the गौरव (respectability,
respy. heaviness) of Meru (मेरुगौरवम्)
9. 5. 8; (3) Kaṇiṅka (Bharadvāja) told
king Śatruṃtapa that one should adopt
what is best in Meru, i. e. its best characte-
ristics (मेरोः … यच् छ्रेष्ठं तत् समा-
चरेत्) 12. 138. 21 (according to Nī. on Bom.
Ed. 12. 140. 21 these are अचञ्चलत्वम् अनु-
ल्लङ्घनीयत्वं; according to Arjunamiśra
सर्वोच्चप्रकृतित्वं; according to Vimala-
bodha कोषबहुलत्वं सर्वोच्चप्रकृतित्वं
च; see Editor's notes, Cr. Ed. Vol. 14, p. 936);
(4) Prajāpati dwells in his residence (ब्रह्-
मसदस्) on the Mahāmeru while creating
the worlds; he dwells there with gods 3. 160.
13, 16; on the summit of Meru there is the
abode (सदन) of Svayaṃbhū (Brahmadeva)
13. 92. 7; Meru forms the pericarp of the
lotus (i. e. the earth) (कर्णिका तस्य पद्-
मस्य मेरुः); sitting on it Brahman creates
the world 12. 175. 37; (5) The seven mind-
born sons of Brahman, Dakṣa and others,
also live on the Mahāmeru 3. 160. 14; (6)
beyond the residence (सदन) of Brahman
on the Meru shines the highest place (परं
स्थानम्) of Nārāyaṇa 3. 160. 17-18; (7)
There god Paśupati (Śiva) himself sports
with Umā and other divine beings (दिव्यैर्
भूतैः समावृतः) wearing a garland of
Karṇikāra flowers reaching down up to his
feet and illuminating the surroundings on
the mountain with his three eyes; the
Siddhas there can see him 6. 7. 23-24; (8)
The seven high-souled sages and Kaśyapa
Prajāpati visit the mountain on every पर्-
वन् day 6. 7. 19; (9) On the top of
Meru, Uśanas Kāvya sports with the Daityas
(तस्यैव मूर्धन्य् उशनाः काव्यो दै-
त्यैः … ) 6. 7. 20 (Nī. on Bom. Ed. 6.
6. 22: रमत इति शेषः); (10) The gods
have their gardens there (यत्र देवोद्यानानि)
3. 247. 8; there the hosts of gods, the Gan-
dharvas, the Asuras and the Rākṣasas always
sport in the company of the Apsarases 6. 7.
16; (11) There Brahman, Rudra and Śakra,
the king of gods, come together and offer
various sacrifices giving many दक्षिणास् (स-
मेत्य विविधैर् यज्ञैर् यजन्ते ऽनेकदक्-
षिणैः) 6. 7. 17; (12) All the jewels and
the six jewelled mountains (षड् एते रत्न-
पर्वताः 6. 7. 2) belong to Meru (तस्य
हीमानि रत्नानि तस्येमे रत्नपर्वताः) 6. 7.
20 (Nī., however, on Bom. Ed. 6. 6. 22: तस्य
काव्यस्य); from it Kubera gets one fourth
share and from what he has obtained he gives
to men a portion of its sixteenth part (तस्-
मात् कुबेरो भगवांश् चतुर्थं भागम्
अश्नुते।ततः कलांशं वित्तस्य मनुष्ये-
भ्यः प्रयच्छति॥) 6. 7. 21 (Nī. on Bom.
Ed. 6. 6. 23: कलांशं षोडशभागस्यापि
लेशम्); (13) Tumburu, Nārada, Viśvāvasu,
Hahā, Huhū and the foremost among gods
gather together and praise (mount Meru)
with praises 6. 7. 18; (14) The sun (आदित्य)
drags behind him all the luminaries and going
round Meru, keeping it to the right, he dispels
darkness (एतं ज्योतींषि सर्वाणि प्रकर्षन्
भगवान् अपि।कुरुते वितमस्कर्मा आदि-
त्यो ऽभिप्रदक्षिणम्) 3. 160. 24; the sun
goes to the Asta mountain and, passing the
twilight there (संध्याम् अतिक्रम्य) he goes
to the north; again continuing his journey
along Meru (स मेरुम् अनुवृत्तः सन्) the
sun goes eastwards 3. 160. 25-26; 3. 102.
2-3; this path of the sun is unhindered (मार्-
गम् एतद् असम्बाधम् आदित्यः परिवर्तते)
3. 160. 29; this route of the sun round Meru
was ordained by the Creator of the world
(एष मार्गः प्रदिष्टो मे येनेदं निर्मितं
जगत्) 3. 102. 4; similarly the moon, along
with the नक्षत्रस्, moves round Meru
dividing the duration of the month into पर्-
वन्स् and returns to Mandara (स मासं
विभजन् कालं बहुधा पर्वसंधिषु।
तथैव भगवान् सोमो नक्षत्रैः सह
गच्छति॥) 3. 160. 27-28; besides the sun,
the moon and the नक्षत्रस्, Vāyu also moves
round Meru keeping it to the right (अनु-
पर्येति … वायुश् चैव प्रदक्षिणम्) 6. 7.
14; (15) The seven divine sages (देव-
र्षयः), chief among whom is Vasiṣṭha, also
set on this mountain and again rise there
(अत्रैव प्रतितिष्ठन्ति पुनर् अत्रोदयन्ति
च) 3. 160. 15; (16) All birds on mount
Meru are golden (सौवर्णान् प्रेक्ष्य वाय-
सान्) 6. 7. 12; seeing them the bird Sumukha,
son of Suparṇa, thought of leaving mount
Meru since it made no distinction between the
best, the intermediate, and the lowest (मेरुर्
उत्तममध्यानाम् अधमानां च पक्षि-
णाम्।अविशेषकरो यस्मात् तस्माद् एनं
त्यजाम्य् अहम्॥) 6. 7. 13; (17) There is
a large, good-looking (सुदर्शन 13. 105. 20)
Jambū tree called Sudarśana (सुदर्शनो नाम)
on mount Meru 6. 8. 18; the river formed by
the juice of the fruit of this tree flows round
Meru and goes to the Uttara Kurus (मेरुं
प्रदक्षिणं कृत्वा संप्रयात्य् उत्तरान्
कुरून्) 6. 8. 23; (18) From the summit
of mount Meru the river Gaṅgā Bhāgīrathī
falls down with terrific speed in the Cāndra-
masa lake 6. 7. 26-27; (19) Various tribes
like the Khaśas, the Ekāśanājyohas (?), the
Pradaras, the Dīrghaveṇus, the Paśupas, the
Kuṇindas, the Taṅgaṇas, and the Parataṅ-
gaṇas live in the valley of the mountains
Meru and Mandara (मेरुमन्दरयोर् मद्-
ह्ये) 2. 48. 2-3; (20) Swans and vultures
go to Meru by passing through a hole in the
Krauñca mountain made by Skanda 3. 214.
31.
D. Holiness: One who falls down
along the precipice of Meru is freed of all
blemishes (मेरुप्रपातं प्रपतन् … मुच्-
यते सर्वकिल्बिशैः) 12. 36. 14; Brāhmaṇas
who are truthful, learned, kind to all beings,
who study the Itihāsa and the Purāṇa, who
offer honey offerings to Brāhmaṇas (मध्-
वाहुत्या जुह्वति च द्विजेभ्यः) go to the
regions of Meru 13. 105. 21-22.
E. Im-
portance: (1) While narrating his विभूतिस्
Bhagavān told Arjuna that he was Meru
among the mountains (मेरुः शिखरिणाम्
अहम्) 6. 32. 23; (2) Meru is the ultimate
place where the knowers of Brahman go
(ब्रह्मविदां गतिः) 3. 160. 12; (3) Śiva
is the Mahāmeru among mountains (पर्वता-
नां महामेरुः) 13. 14. 156; (4) Mahā-
meru was the first to be created among all
the mountains (पर्वतानां महामेरुः
सर्वेषाम् अग्रजः स्मृतः) 14. 44. 12; (5)
When Śiva appointed some one in each class
as its head he made Meru the chief of the
mountains (पर्वताणां पतिम्) 12. 122. 28;
(6) Finds mention in the Daivata-Ṛṣi-
Vaṃśa 13. 151. 26, 2.
F. Epic events:
(1) Kṛṣṇa Dvaipāyana (Vyāsa) taught the
four Vedas, and the Mahābhārata as the
fifth, to his five pupils Sumantu, Jaimini,
Paila, Vaiśaṃpāyana, and Śuka (his son)
on Meru 12. 327. 16-18; (2) Dhṛtarāṣṭra
asked Saṃjaya to describe to him the nor-
thern and the eastern side of Meru (मेरोर्
अथोत्तरं पार्श्वं पूर्वं चाचक्ष्व सं-
जय) 6. 8. 1; (3) On his way northwards
to the Śveta mountain, Yudhiṣṭhira saw
Meru and other mountains 3. 155. 14; (4)
Draupadī, while comforting Yudhiṣṭhira who
was dejected, reminded him that he once ran
over the Krauñcadvīpa with his दण्ड
(दण्डेन मृदितस् त्वया) which lay to the
west of Mahāmeru, so also the Śākadvīpa
to the east of Mahāmeru, and Bhadrāśva to
the north of Mahāmeru 12. 14. 22-24; (5)
Vyāsa, while practising austerities in order
to obtain a son, recited Śivastava on Meru
13. 18. 2; (6) The Pāṇḍavas, on their
great journey (महाप्रस्थान), saw Meru
when they went beyond the Himavant 17.
2. 2.
G. Mythological and past events:
(1) God (Śiva) once sat on the summit of
Meru (गिरितटे) in a पर्यङ्क posture
(पर्यङ्क इव विभ्राजन्न् उपविष्टो बभूव
ह) 12. 274. 6; (2) Formerly Mahādeva
sported on the peak of Meru in the company
of the Bhūtas (भूतगणैर् वृतः) 12. 310.
11; (3) Formerly Nārāyaṇa became the
great sage Vaḍavāmukha; while practising
austerities on Meru he invited the ocean, but
it did not come 12. 329. 48 (2); (4) When
gods were afflicted by the food offered to them
which was proper for manes (निवापान्न)
they went to Pitāmaha on Meru 13. 92. 7;
(5) Bharadvāja asked Bhṛgu how Brahman
created the creatures while sitting in the middle
of Meru (मेरुमध्ये स्थितो ब्रह्मा) 12.
176. 1; (6) Gods mounted the top of Meru
and sat down to think of the way to obtain
अमृत; there Nārāyaṇa told Brahman that gods
and Asuras together should churn the Kala-
śodadhi to get अमृत 1. 15. 9-13; (7) Sixty-
six thousand ऋषिस् who follow Sūrya (सूर्या-
नुगामिभिस् तात ऋषिभिः) narrated the Pañca-
rātra doctrine (12. 326. 100) to gods who
had assembled on Meru 12. 326. 109; (8)
Vindhya told the sun to go round it as it
went round Meru 3. 102. 2; (9) Dānava
Hiraṇyakaśipu was able to shake Meru
(हिरण्यकशिपुर् यो ऽभूद् दानवो मेरु-
कम्पनः) 13. 14. 52; (10) Mṛtyu, con-
ceived as a woman, was reluctant to carry
out the instruction of Brahman to destroy
creatures; she went to Meru and stood
there motionless like a log of wood for doing
good to creatures (भूतानां हितकाम्यया)
12. 250. 22; (11) Gaṅgā, unable to bear
the embryo planted in her by Agni, cast it
off on Meru 13. 84. 64; (12) Meru was
present at the consecration of Kumāra (Ska-
nda) as the chief of the army of gods 9.
44. 13, 16; after the consecration, Meru gave
his two followers (अनुचरौ) Kāñcana and
Hemamālin to Skanda; he also gave him
Sthira and Atisthira 9. 44. 43-44; (13) An
ascetic named Suvarṇa and Manu sat together
on a stoneslab on Meru and told each other
stories of Brahmarṣis, gods and Daityas
from the Purāṇas 13. 101. 6-7; (13) A
Brāhmaṇa Gautama offered to take king
Dhṛtarāṣṭra (really Indra) to Meru, if he
returned to the Brāhmaṇa his elephant; but
the latter did not wish to go there 13. 105. 20-
21; (14) Mahāmeru gave gold to (Pṛthu)
Vainya when he was anointed king by Viṣṇu
and others 12. 59. 122; (15) King Marutta
went to Meru and performed a sacrifice
at the foot of the mountain; his sacrificial
enclosure was close to the mountain (तस्यैव
च समीपे स यज्ञवाटो बभूव ह); for
this sacrifice Marutta used utensils made of
gold obtained from Meru 14. 4. 25-27; (16)
Ekata, Dvita and Trita told Bṛhaspati that
the country where they practised austerities
in order to see Nārāyaṇa lay to the north of
Meru and on the shores of the ocean of milk
12. 323. 21; (17) Rāma (Jāmadagnya ?)
ordered the removal of his matted locks (?)
at a place called Muñjavaṭa on Muñja-
pṛṣṭha on Meru (यत्र मुञ्जवटे रामो
जटाहरणम् आदिशत्) 12. 122. 3; (18) On
the slope (पार्श्व) of Meru was the her-
mitage of Vasiṣṭha where he practised auste-
rities 1. 93, 6-7; Vasiṣṭha, grieved over the
death of his sons, jumped down from the
summit of Meru to end his life (but he did
not die) 1. 166. 41; (19) The great sage
Sthūlaśiras practised austerities on the north-
eastern side of Meru (प्रागुत्तरे दिग्भागे)
12. 329. 47 (1); (20) When Śuka was
born, Gaṅgā came in her original form (स्व-
रूपिणी) on the summit of Meru to bathe
Śuka with her water 12. 311. 12; (21) Śuka
reached the Bhāratavarṣa after crossing the
two Varṣas of Meru and Hari 12. 312. 14
(Nī. on Bom. Ed. 12. 325. 14: मेरोर् वर्षं
इलावृतम्।हरेर् वर्षं हरिवर्षाख्यम्);
when Śuka moved through the sky he saw
before him the two summits of Meru and
Himavant closely connected with each other;
undeterred Śuka went on flying and suddenly
the two peaks split into two; that was a
marvel; Śuka passed beyond the two peaks
and the mountain (Meru or Himavant ?)
could not stop his movement; the mountain
was split into two 12. 320. 8, 10-11, 13;
(22) In order to go to the Śvetadvīpa Nārada
flew up in the sky and reached the top of
Meru 12. 322. 6; after seeing Hari on
the Śvetadvīpa, Nārada returned to Meru;
from Meru Nārada proceeded to Gandha-
mādana and reached the Viśālā Badarī to see
Nara and Nārāyaṇa 12. 331. 22; 12. 321.
13; (23) Mārkaṇḍeya saw, among other
mountains, Meru in the belly of the Bāla
(3. 186. 83 = Nārāyaṇa 3. 187. 3) 3. 186.
103; (24) When Gaṅgā fell down from
heaven Śiva held the river on his head on
Meru (or Himavant ?) and from there the
river reached the earth (दिवश् च्युता शिरसात्ता
भवेन गङ्गावनीध्रात्) 13. 27. 89 (Nī.
on Bom. Ed. 13. 26. 89: अवनीध्रस्य
मेरोः हिमवतो वा पर्वतस्य; on 13. 26.
90: अवनीध्रात् पृथिवीं प्राप्नोतीति शेषः).
H. Similes: (1) Various warriors taking
part in the battle compared with Meru:
(a) Epic war: (i) Aśvatthāman showered
(अभ्यवर्षत्) arrows on Śaineya (Sātyaki)
as a cloud showers rain on Meru 7. 141. 13;
(ii) Aśvatthāman, showered with arrows by
Añjanaparvan, grandson of Bhīma, was affli-
cted as is Meru by the showers of rain sent
by the cloud 7. 131. 45; (iii) Eight sons
of Dhṛtarāṣṭra showered arrows on Abhi-
manyu as do clouds on Meru 6. 75. 25;
(iv) Ghaṭotkaca showered arrows on Karṇa
and others as a cloud showers rain on Meru
7. 149. 17; (v) Ghaṭotkaca covered (प्र-
च्छादयाम् आस) Bhagadatta with arrows as
a cloud covers Meru 6. 79. 31; (vi) Aśva-
tthāman with Śikhaṇḍin's three arrows stuck
on his forehead compared with Meru with its
three high, golden summits 6. 78. 26; (vii)
Arjuna with arrows, shot at him by Duḥśā-
sana, stuck on his forehead looked like Meru
with its very high peaks 6. 106. 33; (viii)
Arjuna was equal to Meru in steadiness
(स्थैर्येण) 8. 48. 9; (ix) Bhīma was
unshakable (अचल) like Meru 6. 59. 8; 8.
31. 62; (x) Abhimanyu did not shake and
remained steady like Meru when struck by
five arrows of Durjaya and Vikarṇa 6. 74.
24; (xi) Jayadratha stood steadfast at the
entrance of the Cakravyūha like Meru (श्री-
मान् मेरुर् इवाचलः) 7. 33. 18; (xii)
Arjuna, covered with gold on his golden cha-
riot, shone like the blazing sun on Meru (स
रथे … काञ्चने काञ्चनावृतः) 7. 60. 17;
(xiii) Sātyaki with his golden bracelet
(अङ्गद), helmet (शिरस्त्राण) and armour
(वर्मन्) and golden shaft shone like the
peak of Meru 7. 96. 4; (xiv) Bhīṣma
with his raised silvery staff with five stars on
it (केतुना पञ्चतारेण … राजतेन) looked
like Meru with moon on it (चन्द्रमा इव
मेरुणा) 6. 44. 48 (Nī. on Bom. Ed. 6. 46.
50: अत्र चन्द्रकेत्वोर् मेरुसरथभीष्म-
योश् चोपमो (? उपमानो) पमेयभावः।
भीष्मस्य रुक्मरथत्वात्); (xv) Arjuna
was best among warriors as Meru is among
the mountains 5. 63. 5; (b) Outside the epic
war: (i) Rāma (Jāmadagnya) with blood
issuing from the wounds all over his body
appeared like Meru throwing out the red mine-
rals (मेरुर् धातून् इवोत्सृजन्) 5. 180. 30;
(c) Other contexts: (i) Śiva's body, when
he was dressed like a Kirāta which made him
look like a golden tree, appeared like another
Meru (कैरातं वेषम् आस्थाय काञ्चन-
द्रुमसंनिभम्।विभ्राजमानो वपुषा
गिरिर् मेरुर् इवापरः॥) 3. 40. 2; (ii)
(Gāndhārī, Kuntī, and other) Kaurava women
mounted the seats (in the arena) as the women
of gods mount mountain Meru (आरुरुहुर्
मञ्चान् मेरुं देवस्त्रियो यथा) 1. 124.
14; (iii) Yājñasenī did not leave the
Pāṇḍavas as the lustre of the sun does not
leave Meru (मेरुं अर्कप्रभा यथा)
3. 80. 4; (iv) The Raivataka mountain,
richly decorated for the festival and the
Yādavas moving on it, looked like Meru
with the hosts of sages on it 14. 58. 8; (v)
Kṛṣṇa's chariot appeared like the summit of
Meru (मेरुशिखरप्रख्यम्) 5. 81. 21;
(vi) Nārada told the huge Śālmali tree on
the Himavant that since many birds, ele-
phants, and other kinds of beasts resorted to
it and since it offered shelter to travellers
(सार्थाधिवासैश् च) it shone like Meru
12. 150. 17; (vii) A tree called Mahāśaṅkha
at the Śaṅkhatīrtha was as tall as Mahāmeru
9. 36. 20 (Nī. on Bom. Ed. 9. 37. 31: नगं
वृक्षम्); (viii) The burning Khāṇḍava
forest looked like the highly lustrous, golden
Meru 1. 216. 34 (also see the next section
Idioms).
I. Idioms: (1) For describing
unexpected or impossible events: (i) Fall of
Bhāradvāja (Droṇa) was like displacing Meru
(विपर्यासं यथा मेरोः) 7. 165. 73;
(ii) Dhṛtarāṣṭra could not bear the felling of
Droṇa as he could not bear the shifting of
Meru 7. 33. 18 (मेरोर् इव विसर्पणम्) 7. 8.
12; (iii) Karṇa's death was as unbelievable
and unexpected (अश्रद्धेयम् इवाद्भुतम्)
as is the tossing about (पर्यसनम्) of
Meru 8. 5. 3; (iv) In the opinion of Dhṛta-
rāṣṭra, wishing to conquer Droṇa in battle
was as unheard of as wind uprooting Meru
(न हि शुश्रुम वातेन मेरुम् उन्मथितं
गिरिम्) 5. 158. 15; (v) also in his opinion if
the Pāṇḍavas were to win the war it would be
like wind blowing away Meru (अनिलो वा
वहेन् मेरुम्) 5. 158. 16; (vi) in the
opinion of Saṃjaya one may carry off Meru
(अपि मेरुं वहेत् कश्चित्) but it would not
be possible for any one to overpower the Vṛṣṇi
heroes 7. 119. 27; (iii) Kṛṣṇa's out of place
great delight (अतिहर्षो ऽयम् अस्थाने 7. 155.
6) and the lightness of his heart (तथैतल्
लाघवम्) over the death of Ghaṭotkaca was
(as unbelievable) as the shifting of Meru
(मेरोर् इव विसर्पणम्) 7. 155. 10; (iv)
Menakā told Indra that Viśvāmitra by his
तपस् could abbreviate Mahāmeru and quickly
turn it around (संक्षिपेच् च महामेरुं
तूर्णम् आवर्तयेत् तथा) 1. 65. 36 (Nī.,
who reads तूर्णम् आवर्तयेद् दिशः, on Bom.
Ed. 1. 71. 36: आवर्तयेद् एकीकुर्यात्); (v)
Karṇa could split asunder even Meru (निर्-
भिन्द्याम् … अपि मेरुम्) with his special
arrow which he had reserved for Kṛṣṇa or
Arjuna 8. 27. 59; (vi) Only a person who
could transgress the lustre of Meru would
(do such an unthinkable act as) killing one
who had taken resort with him ( … प्र-
भां मेरोः … एतन्य् अतिक्रमेद् यो वै स
हन्याच् छरणागतम्) 13. 98. 10; (2) To
express great difference: (i) According to
Śakuntalā the difference between her and king
Duḥṣanta was as great as between Meru and
the mustard seed (आवयोर् अन्तरं पश्य
मेरुसर्षपयोर् इव) 1. 69. 3; (ii) It may
be possible to tell the number of all the
jewels on Meru (मेरोः … सर्वरत्नैः
संख्या … वक्तुम् शक्यम्) but it was not
possible to describe or measure the virtues of
the Gaṅgā waters 13. 27. 97. [See Kanaka-
parvata]

मेरु
Meru2 m.: Name of a mountain in the
Śākadvīpa, also referred to as Mahāmeru (6.
12. 23).
One of the seven mountains of the Śāka-
dvīpa 6. 12. 13; described as great (परम)
and resorted to by gods, sages and Gandharvas
(देवर्षिगन्धर्वयुतः) 6. 12. 14; all the
seven mountains of the Śākadvīpa are adorned
with gems (मणिभूषिताः) and are mines of
jewels (रत्नाकराः) 6. 12. 13; the Varṣa
of Mahāmeru is called Mahākāṣa 6. 12. 23;
the extent of these seven mountains doubles
as one proceeds from one to the other (तेषां
योजनविष्कम्भो द्विगुणः प्रविभागशः)
6. 12. 22.

मैनाक
Maināka1 m.: Name of a mountain.
A. Location: To the north-east of Indra-
prastha (प्रागुदीचीम् अगाद् दिशम्) 2. 3. 7;
to the north of Kailāsa, and close to the
Hiraṇyaśṛṅga mountain (उत्तरेण तु कैला-
सं मैनाकं पर्वतं प्रति।हिरण्य-
शृङ्गो … गिरिः) 2. 3. 8, 2; 6. 7. 40; 3. 145.
39; near the Kailāsa, the Gandhamādana and
the Meru mountains (अवेक्षमाणः कैलासं
मैनाकं चैव पर्वतम्।गन्धमादन-
पादांश् च मेरुं चापि शिलोच्चयम्॥) 3.
155. 14; near the Uśīrabīja and the Kāla-
śaila mountains in the north; from there one
could reach the Śveta and the Mandara moun-
tains (उशीरबीजं मैनाकं गिरिं श्वेतं
च भारत।समतीतो ऽसि कौन्तेय काल-
शैलं च पार्थिव॥ … श्वेतं गिरिं प्र-
वेक्ष्यामो मन्दरं चैव पर्वतम्।) 3.
140. 1, 4; Maināka could be seen from the
Naranārāyaṇāśrama at the Visālā Badarī on
the Himālaya 3. 145. 10, 16, 39.
B. Des-
cription: Immeasurable and unassailable
(अप्रमेय, अनाधृष्य) 3. 149. 13; full of
many kinds of birds (नानाद्विजगणायुत)
3. 145. 39; called the king of mountains
(पर्वतराजन्) 3. 135. 4; (also see the next
section C).
C. Characteristics: As re-
vealed in comparisons: (i) not shakable
(नाकम्पयद् … मैनाकम् इव पर्वतम्)
6. 45. 19; 7. 46. 15; 7. 74. 28; 7. 99. 2; 6.
43. 64; 6. 88. 23; immovable (न चचाल …
मईनाक इव पर्वतः) 9. 18. 43; (ii)
huge (महाकायः … व्यदृश्यत मैनाक
इव पर्वतः) 7. 150. 58-59; (iii) Great
and irresistible (महान्तम् इव मैनाकम्
असह्यम्) 7. 3. 4; (also see the section G).
D. Holiness: (1) A place in the cave of
the Maināka was known as Vinaśana; by
ascending the mountain and by reaching this
place it was possible to destroy evil fortune
that is disgraceful and unspeakable (this ex-
plains the name Vinaśana) (एतद् विनशनं
कुक्षौ मैनाकस्ग … एनं पर्वतराजानम्
आरुह्य … अयशस्याम् असंशब्द्याम् अलक्ष्मीं
व्यपनोत्स्य् अथ॥) 3. 135. 3-4; (2) One
who has observed chastity for a month if he
performs the संध्या ceremony after bathing
on Maināka he gets the fruit of a Sarva-
medha (मैनाके पर्वते स्नात्वा तथा सं-
ध्याम् उपास्य च कामं जित्वा च वै मा-
सम् सर्वमेधफलं लभेत्) 13. 26. 56.
E. Epic events: (1) Asura Maya went to
Maināka to reach the lake Bindusaras on the
Hiraṇyaśṛṅga mountain 2. 3. 2, 8; (2)
Lomaśa referred to the holy place Vinaśana on
Maināka and advised the Pāṇḍavas to ascend
the mountain 3. 135. 3-4; (3) The Pāṇḍa-
vas had crossed Maināka before entering the
Śveta and the Mandara mountains 3. 140. 1,
4; (4) The Pāṇḍavas could see Maināka
from the hermitage of Nara and Nārāyaṇa at
Badarī 3. 145. 39; Yudhiṣṭhira could see it
while on his way northwards to the Śveta
mountain from the Nārāyaṇāśrama 3. 155.
14.
F. Past events: (1) Nārāyaṇa practis-
ed severe austerities on Maināka 7. 172. 52;
(2) At the Vinaśana in the cave on Mai-
nāka, Aditi, in bygone days, cooked food (for
gods) to get a son (अदितिर् यत्र पुत्रार्थं
तद् अन्नम् अपचत् पुरा) 3. 135. 3 (Nī. on
Bom. Ed. 3. 135. 3: अन्नं ब्रह्मौद-
नम्।अदितिः पुत्रकामा साध्येभ्यो देवे-
भ्यो ब्रह्मौदनम् अपचद् इत् श्रुतेः).
G. Similes: Various heroes compared with
Maināka. (1) For its unshakableness: (i)
Śrutakarman, son of Sahadeva, could not he
shaken by the arrows of Sudakṣiṇa like
Maināka 6. 43. 64; similarly (ii) Abhi-
manyu 6. 45. 19; 7. 46. 15; (iii) Sātyaki
7. 99. 2; (iv) Kṛṣṇa (by the hit of a गदा)
7. 74. 28; (v) Ghaṭotkaca, seeing the Kau-
rava army led by their heroes advance against
him, did not shake like Maināka 6. 88. 23;
(vi) Similarly Bhīma did not move from his
chariot seat when attacked by the Kaurava
army (न चचाल रथोपस्थे मैनाक इव
पर्वतः) 9. 18. 43; (2) For its huge-
ness: Ghaṭotkaca rising up, assuming a
huge form having hundred heads and hundred
stomachs (महाकायः शतशीर्षः शतोद-
रः), looked like Maināka 7. 150. 58-59;
(3) For its hugeness and irresistibility:
Bhīṣma lying on his bed of arrows was like
the huge and irresistible Maināka felled down
(महान्तम् इव मैनाकम् असह्यं भुवि
पातितम्) 7. 3. 4; (4) Hanūmant was im-
measurable and unassailable like Maināka
(अप्रमेयम् अनाधृष्यम्) 3. 149. 13;
(5) Arjuna avoided Droṇa who stood like
Maināka 7. 67. 17; (6) Kirmīra, obstruct-
ing the entrance of the Kāmyaka forest stood
there like Maināka 3. 12. 15; (7) All
(kings) were inferior to king Maithila
(Janaka) as are other mountains to Maināka
(सर्वे राज्ञो मैथिलस्य मैनाकस्येव पर्-
वताः) 3. 134. 5.

मैनाक
Maināka2 m.: Name of a mountain in
the west.
Located in the west (प्रतीच्याम्) 3. 87.
1; it has holy lakes on it (पुण्यह्रद)
3. 87. 9.

मैनाक
Maināka3 m.: Name of a mountain in
the Krauñcadvīpa.
A. Location: One of the six mountains
of the Krauñcadvīpa; it lies beyond the moun-
tain Andhakāra and beyond Maināka lies the
mountain Govinda 6. 13. 17-18; the name of
the region (देशांस् तत्र प्रवक्ष्यामि 6.
13. 20) related to Maināka is Prāvaraka (?)
6. 13. 21.
B. Extent: The extent of the
mountains of the Krauñcadvīpa doubles as one
proceeds from the one to the other (परस्
तु द्विगुणस् तेषं विष्कम्भः) 6. 13. 19.
C. Description: Excellent mountain (पर्-
वतोत्तम) 6. 13. 18.

मोघा
Moghā f.: Name of a river.
One of the rivers listed by Saṃjaya
among the rivers of the Bhāratavarṣa; people
used its water for drinking 6. 10. 22, 13; (for
other details see Atikṛṣṇā).

यजन
Yajana nt.: Name of a तीर्थ।
Situated in the wide region Devikā along
the river of the same name; if one bathes at
Yajana one does not grieve over death (उप-
स्पृश्य न शोचेन् मरणं ततः) 3. 80.
114-115. [See Devikā]

यमुना
Yamunā f.: Name of a river.
A. Location: Listed by Saṃjaya among
the rivers of the Bhāratavarṣa; its water used
by people for drinking 6. 10. 14, 13; in the
north (उदीच्यां … यमुना) 3. 88. 1-2; near
the mountain Ārcīka 3. 125. 13, 17-18;
Gaṅgā flows at some distance from Yāmunā
(गङ्गेव यमुनान्तरे) 6. 18. 18; flowing
through the mid-country along with Gaṅgā;
a big village of Brāhmaṇas, called Parṇaśālā,
situated between Gaṅgā and Yamunā and at
the foot of the Yāmunagiri (मध्यदेशे …
गङ्गायमुनयोर् मध्ये यामुनस्य गिरेर्
अधः) 13. 67. 3; flowing near the Kuru-
kṣetra 15. 30. 16; the rivers Jalā and Upa-
jalā flow by the side of Yamunā 3. 130. 17;
at Prayāga, Yamunā meets Gaṅgā 3. 83. 70;
the Bāhlīka country is outsides the rivers
Gaṅgā, Sarasvatī and Yamunā (गङ्गया
च तिरस्कृताः।सरस्वत्या यमुनया) 8.
30. 10-11; the place Vanaprastha situated
on Yamunā (स चागम्य वनप्रस्थं
यमुनायाम्) 13. 139. 13.
B. Descri-
ption: Big river (महानदी) 6. 10. 14;
purifying the worlds (लोकपावनी) 3. 83.
70; highly purifying (परमपावनी) 15. 30.
16; holy (पुण्या), removing the fear of sin
(पापभयापहा), on the banks of which
different sacrifices were offered (नानायज्ञ-
चिता) and resorted to by royal sages (राजर्षि-
गणसेविता) 3. 125. 22; flowing with undecay-
ing stream (अक्षयस्रोतस्) 3. 125. 18; flowing
with great speed (महावेगा) 3. 88. 2; the
current of Gaṅgā and Yamunā after they
meet each other is very terrific and produces
fearful sound (गङ्गायमुनयोर् वेगं सु-
भीमं भीमनिःस्वनम्) 13. 50. 7; flowing
to the ocean (समुद्रगा) 3. 88. 2; all the
rivers listed by Saṃjaya are said to be mothers
of the universe and very strong 6. 10. 35 (for
citation see Atikṛṣṇā).
C. Characteristic:
The region between Gaṅgā and Yamunā is
known as the जघन of earth (गङ्गायमु-
नयोर् मध्यं पृथिव्या जघनं स्मृतम्)
3. 83. 71 (Nī. on Bom. Ed. 3. 85. 75: जघ-
नं नाभेर् अधोभागः).
D. Holiness:
(1) No sooner one bathes at the confluence
of Gaṅgā and Yamunā he gets the religious
merit that is obtained by studying the four
Vedas and by speaking truth (चातुर्वेदे च
यत् पुण्यं सत्यवादिषु चैव यत्।स्नात
एव तद् आप्नोति) 3. 83. 80; no gift is superior
to a bath at the तीर्थ on Gaṅgā and Yamunā
(गङ्गायमुनयोस् तीर्थे … उपस्पृश्य दानं
नान्यद् विशिस्यते) 13. 26. 34; (2) The
river Yamunā is mentioned among those holy
places by visiting which the high-souled ones
assume heavenly form, put on heavenly gar-
lands and, becoming auspicious and rich in
holy fragrance, obtain the Goloka (? गवां
विंआने 13. 105. 44) 13. 105. 47-48 (for
citation see Karatoyinī); (3) Lomaśa in-
vokes Yamunā, besides Varuṇa, Yama and
Gaṅgā, in the benediction (स्वस्ति) he pro-
nounces on Yudhiṣṭhira 3. 140. 13; (4) There
are many तीर्थस् on Yamunā like Plakṣāva-
taraṇa and Agniśiras 3. 88. 2-3; Prayāga is
at the confluence of Gaṅgā and Yamunā 3.
83. 70-71; 3. 85. 13-14.
E. Importance:
Finds mention in the Daivata-Ṛṣi-Vaṃśa 13.
151. 22, 2.
F. Epic events: (1) The
sage Parāśara wanted to cross Yamunā;
while he was being ferried over by Satyavatī
the sage made advances to her 1. 99. 7-8;
Kṛṣṇa Dvaipāyana was born to Kālī (Satya-
vatī) from Parāśara on an island in Yamunā
(यमुनाद्वीपे) 1. 54. 2; 1. 57. 69; (2)
Śaṃtanu offered seven great sacrifices (सप्त
मुख्यान् महामेधान्) on the river Ya-
munā 3. 159. 23; when he once went to a
forest along the river Yamunā he saw a fisher-
man's girl who plied a ferry on the river 1.
94. 41, 44; (3) After the Rājasūya, Kṛṣṇa
stayed back at Indraprastha and, in the com-
pany of Arjuna, used to roam on the banks
of Yamunā 1. 213. 57; once, as the days
were hot, Arjuna suggested to Kṛṣṇa to spend
a day on the bank of Yamunā 1. 214. 14;
(4) After leaving Gaṅgā and the Kurukṣetra
the Pāṇḍavas, in their westward march, went
to Yamunā 3. 6. 2; (5) At the confluence
of Gaṅgā and Yamunā the Pāṇḍavas bathed
and gave gifts to Brāhmaṇas 3. 93. 6; shown
by Lomaśa to the Pāṇḍavas 3. 125. 18, 22;
(6) The basket containing the newly-born
Karṇa went from the river Carmaṇvatī to
Yamunā and from there to Gaṅgā 3. 292. 25;
(7) Ambā practised extraordinary austerities
(तपस् तेपे ऽतिमानुषम्) on the bank of
Yamunā for a year 5. 187. 18, 20; at the end
she entered fire near Yamunā saying ‘for the
death of Bhīṣma’ (उक्त्वा भीष्मवधायेति
प्रविवेश हुताशनम्। … यमुनाम् अभितो
नदीम्) 5. 188. 18; (8) The army of the
Kauravas, gathered for the war, spread out
from Hāstinapura to the land adjacent to
Yamunā (यमुनान्तरे) 6. 18. 18; (9)
Duryodhana, dejected at the death of Jaya-
dratha, told Droṇa that he wanted to offer
water oblations near Yamunā to those from
his side who were killed in the war (तर्पयि-
ष्यामि तान् एव जलेन यमुनाम् अनु) 7. 125.
23; (10) Yudhiṣṭhira, wanting to see Dhṛta-
rāṣṭra and others, reached Kurukṣetra and
crossed the river Yamunā 15. 30. 16; the as-
cetics there told Yudhiṣṭhira that Dhṛtarāṣṭra
had gone to Yamunā to get flowers and water
(पुष्पाणाम् उदकुम्भस्य चार्थे गत इति
प्रभो) 15. 31. 6; (11) Balarāma proceeded
from the Kārapacanatīrtha to the hermitage
of Mitra and Varuṇa on Yamunā 9. 53. 13;
(12) Kṛṣṇa practised austerities on Yamunā
3. 125. 18; (13) Kṛṣṇa killed a lordly
horse (the demon Keśin) who lived in the
forest on Yamunā (हयराजं … यमुना-
वनवासिनम्) 7. 10. 3 (Nī. on Bom. Ed.
7. 11. 3: हयराजं केशिनम्); (14)
Haṃsa and Ḍimbhaka were two excellent
warriors of Jarāsandha; when Dimbhaka heard
that Haṃsa (really his namesake) was killed,
he drowned himself in Yamunā; when Haṃsa
knew this he did the same 2. 13. 40, 42.
G. Past events: (1) The semen of King
Vasu, being carried by a falcon, fell in the
water of Yamunā when another falcon attack-
ed it 1. 57. 46; (2) Bharata; son of Duḥ-
ṣanta, performed many horse sacrifices; he
bound thirty horses for gods (according to 3.
88. 7 thirty-five horse sacrifices) on the river
Yamunā 12. 29. 41-42; (3) Yayātī wish-
ing to perform the स्वयंवर of his daughter
went to a hermitage on the confluence of
Gaṅgā and Yamunā 5. 118. 1; he offered
sacrifices on Yamunā 3. 129. 2; when Yayāti
gave his kingdom to Puru he told him
(Puru) that he would be the king of the
land in the middle of the earth and he
would rule over the entire region between
Gaṅgā and Yamunā (गङ्गायमुनयोर् म-
ध्ये कृत्स्नो ऽयं विषयस् तव।मध्ये
पृथिव्यास् त्वं राजा) 1. 82. 5; (4) King
Sahadeva offered sacrifices on the bank of
Yamunā 3. 125. 23; there is a गाथा sung
by Indra, and which was later sung by the
twice-born, which said that Sahadeva offered
on Yamunā a hundred thousand sacrifices at
which he gave a hundred thousand दक्षिणास्
3. 88. 5-6; (5) King Māndhātṛ and king
Somaka offered sacrifices on the bank of the
river Yamunā 3. 125. 22-23; (6) Ambarīṣa
Nābhāga and Prajāpati himself offered sacri-
fices on Yamunā 3. 129. 2; (7) In the region
between Gaṅgā and Yamunā Haryaśva was
killed by the sons of Hehaya in a battle 13.
31. 11; (9) Sage Cyavana entered the
waters of the rivers Gaṅgā and Yamunā at
their confluence in order to observe a vow of
staying in water for twelve years; he checked
the current of the two rivers with his head; the
two rivers and the rivers which followed them
did not cause any pain to the sage but made
a प्रदक्षिणा around him (गङ्गा च यमुना
चैव सरितश् चानुगास् तयोः।प्रदक्षिणम्
ऋषिं चक्रुर् न चैणं पर्यपीडयन्॥);
Cyavana slept in waters like a log of wood;
when once some fishermen cast their net to
catch fish they dragged out Cyavana, along
with fish, from the water of the two rivers
13. 50. 6-9, 11-20; (a) Agastya practised
austerities on the bank of Yamunā 3. 158.
52; (10) Varuṇa abducted Bhadrā (Uta-
thya's wife) from Vanaprastha on Yamunā
and took her to his city 13. 139. 13-14;
(11) Mārkaṇḍeya saw Yamunā, among other
rivers, in the belly of the Bāla (3. 186. 83,
i. e. Nārāyaṇa 3. 187. 3) 3. 186. 93.
H.
Similes: (1) Bhīṣma, when he fell down
from the chariot, was covered with arrows as
with the stream of Yamunā (स्रोतसा यामु-
नेनेव शरौघेण परिप्लुतम्) 7. 3. 3;
(2) The two armies of the Kauravas and
the Pāñcālas in their confrontation made
terrific dash as the two rivers Jāhnavī and
Yamunā do in the rainy season when they
are full of water 7. 70. 8; 8. 31. 68; (3)
King Bṛhadratha appeared between his two
wives as the ocean, in bodily form, appears
between the rivers Gaṅgā and Yamunā
(गङ्गायमुनयोर् मध्ये मूर्तिमान् इव
सागरः) 2. 16. 19.

यमुनातीर्थ
Yamunātīrtha: See Plakṣāvataraṇa.

यमुनाद्वीप
Yamunādvīpa: See Yamunā, F. Epic
events (1. 54. 2; 1. 57. 69).

ययातिपतन
Yayātipatana nt.: Name of a sacred
place.
One can reach it from the Kaṇvāśrama;
by visiting it one gets the fruit of a horse
sacrifice (हयमेध) 3. 80. 67.

यवक्रीतस्य
Yavakrītasya tīrtham nt.: Designation
of a तीर्थ।
The तीर्थ on the river Bhāgīrathī where
Yavakrīta used to go for his purificatory cere-
monies is so designated; Indra started to
build a bridge there with sand (यवक्रीतस्य
यत् तीर्थम् उचितं शौचकर्मणि।भागी-
रथ्यां तत्र सेतुं वालुकाभिश् चकार सः)
3. 135. 31.

याजन
Yājana nt.: Name of a तीर्थ।
Situated in the wide region designated
as Devikā along the river of the same name;
by visiting it and by bathing (उपस्पृश्य)
at this तीर्थ one does not grieve over death
(न शोचेन् मरणं ततः) 3. 80. 114-115.
[See Devikā]

यामुन
Yāmuna1 (giri, adrī, parvata) m.: Name
of a mountain related to the river Yamunā.
A. Location: In the Madhyadeśa; a big
settlement of Brāhmaṇas, known as Parṇa-
śālā, was situated at the foot of the Yāmuna
mountain and between the rivers Gaṅgā and
Yamunā (मध्यदेशे महान् ग्रामो ब्राह्-
मणानाम् … ।गङ्गायमुनयोर् मध्ये या-
मुनस्य गिरेर् अधः॥पर्णशालेति विख्या-
तः) 13. 67. 3-4; located at some distance
from Hāstinapura (यामुनश् चैव पर्व-
तः) 5. 19. 28, 30; a place called Viśākhayūpa
was on this mountain (तस्मिन् गिरौ) 3. 174.
16.
B. Description: King of mountains
(अद्रिराज), full of streams (प्रस्रवणोप-
पन्न), its pale red peaks covered with snow
(हिमोत्तरीयारुणपाण्डुसानु) 3. 174. 16.
C. Characteristics: Characterized by a big
forest full of boats, various animals and birds
and which looked like the forest of Citra-
ratha (वराहनानामृगपक्षिजुष्टं महद्
वनं चैत्ररथप्रकाशम्) 3. 174. 17;
(तस्माद् वनात् चैत्ररथप्रकाशात्) 3. 174.
20.
D. Epic events: (1) The Pāṇḍavas,
after they met Arjuna, descended from the
Himavant and stayed at Viśhākhayūpa on the
Yāmuna mountain for a year (the twelfth
year) 3. 174. 15-16, 20; (2) The army of
the Kauravas, gathered for the war, spread
on a wide region extending up to the Yāmuna
mountain as it did not have enough space in
Hāstinapura (यामुनश् चैव पर्वतः।
एष देशः सुविस्तीर्णः … ।बभूव कौरवे-
याणां बलेन सुसमाकुलः॥) 5. 19. 28,
30-31.

यामुन
yāmuna2 nt.: Name of a तीर्थ।
Located at the source of the river
Yamunā; by bathing there one gets the fruit
of a horse sacrifice and is glorified in heaven
(यमुनाप्रभवं गत्वा उपस्पृश्य च
यामुने।अश्वमेधफलं लब्ध्वा स्व-
र्गलोके महीयते॥) 3. 82. 39. [See Pla-
kṣāvataraṇa]

यायात
Yāyāta nt.: Name of a तीर्थ (related
to Yayāti).
From the तीर्थ on the river Sarasvatī
near the आश्रम of Baka Dālbhya, Balarāma
went to the Yāyāta तीर्थ; Yayāti, son of
Nahuṣa, offered a sacrifice there for which
the river Sarasvatī yielded clarified butter
and milk and also fulfilled the desires of the
Brāhmaṇas (यत्र यज्ञे ययातेस् तु महा-
राज सरस्वती।सर्पिः पयश् च सुस्राव
 … ॥ … सरस्वती।प्रसृता प्रददौ कामान्
ब्राह्मणानां महात्मनाम्॥) 9. 40. 29-
30, 32-33.

योनि
Yoni f.: Name of a तीर्थ।
On the river Bhīmā; described as the
best place on that river (भीमायाः स्थानम्
उत्तमम्) 3. 80. 100; if one bathes there one
becomes the son of a goddess (?) and puts on
shining कुण्डलस् (देव्याः पुत्रो भवेद्
राजंस् तप्तकुण्डलविग्रहः); he also gets
the great fruit (फलं … महत्) of gifting
a hundred thousand cows 3. 80. 101.

योनिद्वार
Yonidvāra nt.: Name of a तीर्थ।
Situated on the mountain Udyant 3. 82.
81; described as famous (विश्रुत); if one
visits it one is freed of the sin of misalliance
(तत्राभिगम्य मुच्येत पुरुषो योनिसं-
करात्) 3. 82. 83.

रथचित्रा
Rathacitrā f.: Name of a river.
Listed by Saṃjaya among the rivers of
the Bhāratavarṣa; people used its water for
drinking 6. 10. 25, 13 (for other details see
Puṣpaveṇī).

रथस्था
Rathasthā f.: Name of a river.
Listed by Saṃjaya among the rivers of
the Bhāratavarṣa; people used its water for
drinking 6. 10. 18, 13 (for other details see
Puṣpaveṇī).

रथावर्त
Rathāvarta m.: Name of a sacred place.
Situated to the right of the goddess at
Dhūmāvatī (देव्यास् तु दक्षिणार्धेन र-
थावर्तो नराधिप); if one mounts on the
Rathāvarta with faith and with controlled
senses he gets the highest condition by the
favour of Mahādeva (तत्रारोहेत … श्रद्द-
धानो जितेन्द्रियः।महादेवप्रसादाद् धि
गच्छेत परमां गतिम्॥) 3. 82. 21;
circumambulating it one should proceed to
the तीर्थ called Dhārā 3. 82. 22,

रमणी
Ramaṇī f.: Name of a तीर्थ।
Listed in the Tīrthavaṃśa narrated by
Aṅgiras 13. 26. 3; by bathing at Ramaṇī,
while observing fast for a month, one gets
the power of becoming invisible (?) (रम-
ण्यां च उपस्पृश्य … एकमासं निराहारस्
त्व् अन्तर्धानफलं लभेत्) 13. 26. 29
(Nī., however, on Bom. Ed. 13. 25. 30:
अन्तर्धानफलं गन्धर्वादिभोगम्).

राजगृह
Rājagṛha nt.: Name of a तीर्थ।
One who is on a pilgrimage should visit
Rājagṛha; by bathing in the hot springs (?)
there one rejoices like Kākṣīvant; a pure
person, by partaking of the food offered to
the Yakṣiṇī there, is released by the favour
of the Yakṣiṇī from the sin of killing an
embryo (ततो राजगृहं गच्छेत् तीर्थसेवी
 … ।उपस्पृश्य तपोदेषु काक्षीवान् इव मो-
दते॥यक्षिण्या नैत्यकं तत्र प्राश्नीत
पुरुषः शुचीः।यक्षिण्यास् तु प्रसादेन
मुच्यते भ्रूणहत्यया॥) 3. 82. 89-90
(Nī. on Bom. Ed. 3. 84. 105: नित्यकं
नैवेद्यं नैत्यकं च तद् एव).

रामक
Rāmaka m.: Name of a mountain.
Situated near the island Tāmra (?) on
the west coast not far from Śūrpāraka; Saha-
deva conquered it in the expedition he under-
took before the Rājasūya (द्वीपं ताम्रा-
ह्वयं चैव पर्वतं रामकं तथा)
2. 28. 43, 46.

रामतीर्थ
Rāmatīrtha nt.: Name of different
तीर्थस्, most of which are related to Rāma
Jāmadagnya.
(1) On the mountain Mahendra, re-
sorted to by Jāmadagnya (hence so called);
by bathing there one gets the fruit of a horse
sacrifice (Vājimedha) 3. 83. 14; (2) Situ-
ated at Śūrpāraka, resorted to by Jāma-
dagnya (hence so called); by bathing there
one gets much gold (विन्द्याद् बहु सुवर्ण-
कम्) 3. 83. 40; (3) One described as
auspicious (शुभ) and excellent तीर्थ
(तीर्थवर) 9. 48. 6; Balarāma went to it
from Indratīrtha 9. 48. 6; Rāma Bhārgava,
after destroying the Kṣatriyas several times,
offered at this तीर्थ a Vājapeya and a
hundred horse sacrifices, and gave the whole
earth as दक्षिणा 9. 48. 7-8; (4) Situated
on the river Gomatī; by bathing there one
gets the fruit of a horse sacrifice (Aśva-
medha) and purifies his lineage (पुनाति च
कुलं नरः) 3. 82. 66.

रामह्रद
Rāmahrada m. pl., (sg.): Name of a
तीर्थ।
A. Location: Listed among the four
places which form the boundaries of the
Kurukṣetrasamantapañcaka (रामह्रदानाम्)
3. 81. 178; 9. 52. 20.
B. Description:
Holy (पुण्याः) 3. 81. 33; famous (विश्रु-
ताः) 3. 81. 27.
C. Holiness: (1) A
pilgrim should visit them (रामह्रदान्) 3.
81. 22; by bathing at these lakes and by
worshipping Rāma (Jāmadagnya) one who
has observed chastity and practised auspicious
vows obtains much gold (स्नात्वा ह्रदेषु
रामस्य ब्रह्मचारी शुभव्रतः।रामम्
अभ्यर्च्य राजेन्द्र लभेद् बहु सुवर्ण-
कम्॥) 3. 81. 33; (2) One should bathe in
these lakes and satisfy manes; the manes, thus
pleased, will grant him whatever unobtainable
is desired by him and heaven for all times
(ह्रदेष्व् एतेषु यः स्नात्वा पितॄन् संतर्-
पयिष्यति।पितरस् तस्य वै प्रीता दास्यन्ति
भुवि दुर्लभम्।ईप्सितं मनसः कामं
स्वर्गलोकं च शाश्वतम्॥) 3. 81. 31;
(3) By bathing in this lake and by abstain-
ing from food for twelve days one is freed
of sin (रामह्रद उपस्पृश्य … ।द्वादशा-
हं निराहारः कल्मषाद् विप्रमुच्यते॥)
13. 26. 44.
D. History: Rāma (Bhār-
gava), after extirpating the Kṣatriyas, founded
five lakes and filled them with blood; he
satisfied there his ancestors and grand-fathers
(क्षत्रम् उत्साद्य वीर्येण ह्रदाः पञ्च
निवेषिताः॥पूरयित्वा नरव्याघ्र रुधि-
रेणेति नः श्रुतम्।पितरस् तर्पिताः सर्वे
तथैव च पितामहाः) 3. 81. 22-23; Rāma
requested the satisfied ancestors to turn the
lakes of blood into तीर्थस्; this request
was granted (ह्रदांश् च तीर्थभूता मे
भवेयुः। … ह्रदाश् च तव तीर्थत्वं
गमिष्यन्ति न संशयः) 3. 81. 27, 30.
E. Epic event: (1) While visiting the
तीर्थस् on the river Yamunā, Lomaśa pointed
out these lakes to Yudhiṣṭhira (रामह्रदान्)
3. 129. 6; (2) Rāmahrada (रामह्रदे)
was one of the places where Ambā bathed
(आप्लावयत गात्राणि) and practised severe
austerities to achieve her objective of killing
Bhīṣma 5. 187. 27-28; (3) While proceed-
ing to Kurukṣetra to meet Bhīṣma, Kṛṣṇa
showed to Yudhiṣṭhira at some distance the
five lakes of Rāma (अमी रामह्रदाः पञ्च
दृश्यन्ते पार्थ दूरतः) 12. 48. 8.
F.
Past event: Rāma satisfied his ancestors
with the blood of Kṣatriyas who were killed
by him (येषु संतर्पयाम् आस पूर्वान्
क्षत्रियशोणितैः); after rendering the earth
devoid of Kṣatriyas twentyone times Rāma
Jāmadagnya gave up this activity here (इहे-
दानीं ततो राम कर्मणो विरराम ह)
12. 48. 8-9.

रुद्रकोटि
Rudrakoṭi1 f.: Name of a तीर्थ।
A. History: Formerly a crore of devout
sages sat down in order to see god (Śiva);
they started for this place vying with one
another to see god Śiva first; god Śiva with
his divine power (योगम् आस्थाय) created
a crore of Rudras in front of every one of
them so that every one felt that he saw Rudra
first (सृष्टा कोटिस् तु रुद्राणाम् ऋषीणाम्
अग्रतः स्थिता।मया पूर्वतरं दृष्ट
इति ते मेनिरे पृथक्) and did not entertain
anger (with the thought that he was behind
others in seeing Rudra) (तेषां मन्यु-
प्रणाशार्थम् ऋषीणाम्); pleased Mahādeva
granted them a boon so that their religious
merit would increase (अद्यप्रभृति युष्मा-
कं धर्मवृद्धिर् भविष्यति) 3. 80. 124-
128.
B. Holiness: A devout pilgrim
should visit it; by bathing there, a pure person
(नरः शुचिः) gets the fruit of an Aśvamedha
and lifts up his family (कुलं चैव समुद्-
धरेत्) 3. 80. 124, 129.

रुद्रकोटि
Rudrakoṭi2 f.: Name of a तीर्थ।
Located at the holy place Saraka in a
well and in lakes (सरके कुरुनन्दन।
रुद्रकोटिस् तथा कूपे ह्रदेषु च मही-
पते॥) 3. 81. 63.

रुद्रावर्त
Rudrāvarta m.: Name of a तीर्थ।
Situated at the confluence of the rivers
Gaṅgā and Sarasvatī; a pilgrim (तीर्थसेवी)
should visit it; by bathing there one gets
the fruit of an Aśvamedha and when he goes
to heaven he is glorified there (स्वर्गलोके
महीयते) 3. 82. 33-34.

रेणुकातीर्थ
Reṇukātīrtha nt.: Name of a तीर्थ।
Situated near the holy place called
Kumārikāṇāṃ tīrtham (रेणुकायाश् च तत्-
रैव तीर्थम्) 3. 80. 97-98; described as
best (उत्तम) 3. 81. 139 and resorted to by
gods (देवनिषेवित) 3. 80. 98; by bathing
there a Brāhmaṇa becomes clean like the
moon (विमलश् चन्द्रमा यथा) 3. 80. 98;
by bathing there and by being engaged in
the worship of manes and gods (पितृदेवार्-
चने रतः) a man's soul is cleansed of all
sins and he gets the fruit of an Agniṣṭoma
3. 81. 139.

रैवत
Raivata1, Raivataka1 m.: Name of a
mountain.
A. Location: In the west (प्रतीच्याम्);
Raivata adorns the town Kuśasthalī (Dvā-
rakā) 2. 13. 49.
B. Description: Great
mountain (महाशैल) 14. 58. 6; (महा-
गिरि) 14. 58. 12; chief among mountains
(गिरिमुख्य) 2. 13. 52; king of mountains
(शैलराज्) 14. 58, 14; (शैलेन्द्र) 1. 212.
6; (पर्वतेन्द्र) 14. 58. 9; described at
some length at the time of the festival of
the mountain (वर्तमाने महाराज महे
रैवतकस्य च): it was adorned with many
variegated forms and it shone all around by
the golden Kāśa grass (अलंकृतस् तु स
गिरिर् नानारूपविचित्रितैः।बभौ रुक्म-
मयैः काशैः सर्वतः); it was adorned
with excellent golden garlands, flowers, cloth-
pieces (वासोभिः) and by Kalpavṛkṣas (कल्प-
वृक्षैश् च सर्वशः); it was adorned with
golden trees with lighted lamps on them
(दीपवृक्षैश् च सौवर्णैः); with different
kinds of flags with bells hanging on them;
it resounded with songs of men and women;
the mountain became attractive to look at
like Meru with hosts of sages on it (अतीव
प्रेक्षनीयो ऽभून् मेरुर् मुनिगणैर् इव);
many shops were set up for the festival which
offered diverse kinds of food and wines; these
were also freely given to poor, blind and
miserable (सुरामैरेयमिश्रेण भक्ष्य-
भोज्येन चैव ह।दीनान्धकृपणादिभ्यो
दीयमानेन चानिशम्); there were holy
lodgings set up for the meritorious people
(पुण्यावसथवान् वीर पुण्यकृद्भिर् निषे-
वितः); the mountain, full of houses meant
for Vṛṣṇi heroes, appeared like the place of
gods (स नगो वेश्मसंकीर्णो देवलोक
इवाबभौ); due to the presence of Kṛṣṇa the
mountain gave the appearance of the residence
of Śakra (Indra) (शक्रसद्मप्रतीकाशो
बभूव स हि शैलराट्) 14. 58. 4-14; the
decorating of the mountain for its festival
also described at another place: the Vṛṣṇis
and the Andhakas gave gifts by thousands
to Brāhmaṇas; the countryside around the
mountain was decorated by palatial buildings
shining with jewels and by trees holding the
lamps; the players on musical instruments
played on instruments, the dancers danced,
and the singers sang; Vṛṣṇi princes, adorned,
moved everywhere in their golden conveyances;
the citizens also moved in thousands, with
wives and retinue (सदाराः सानुयात्राश् च),
either on foot or in vehicles 1. 211. 1-6.
C.
Epic events: (1) Kṛṣṇa went to Prabhāsa to
meet Arjuna during the term of the latter's
exile 1. 210. 4; from Prabhāsa the two went
to Raivataka where they spent a night before
going to Dvārakā; the mountain was deco-
rated at the instance of Kṛṣṇa; Arjuna took
food there and, in the company of Kṛṣṇa,
saw the performances of actors and dancers
(दृष्टवान् नटनर्तकान्) 1. 210. 8-10;
Arjuna rested there on a decorated bed and,
next morning, left Raivataka for Dvārakā
1. 210. 11-15; (2) After some days a
great festival of the mountain was held by
the Vṛṣṇis and the Andhakas for which the
mountain Raivataka was decorated 1. 211.
1-2; all the important Yādavas like Ugrasena,
Balarāma, Akrūra, Sātyaki, Kṛtavarman,
Pradyumna, Sāmba, also Kṛṣṇa and Arjuna,
participated in it; there Arjuna saw Subhadrā
and fell in love with her 1. 211. 7-15; (3)
On another occasion when Arjuna came to
know that Subhadrā had gone to worship
Raivataka he, with the consent of Kṛṣṇa,
started for it 1. 212. 1-2; Subhadrā worshipp-
ed the mountain Raivata and all the deities
there and received blessings of the Brāhmaṇas;
after making a प्रदक्षिणा of the mountain
(ब्राह्मणान् स्वस्ति वाच्य च।प्रदक्षिणं
गिरिं कृत्वा) she started to return to Dvārakā
1. 212. 6-7.
D. Other events: (1) When
the Mādhavas (Yādavas) left Mathurā to
settle down at Kuśasthalī (Dvārakā) they
were delighted to see the (Raivata) mountain
2. 13. 52; (2) When the Bhoja princes
were sporting on the mountain Raivataka,
Śiśupāla attacked them; he slew and captured
them all (हत्वा बद्ध्वा च तान् सर्वान्)
and returned to his town 2. 42. 8.

रैवत
Raivata2, Raivataka2 m.: Name of a
mountain of the Śākadvīpa.
One of the seven mountains of the Śāka-
dvīpa; described as very high (उच्चैर्गिरि) 6.
12. 16; all the seven mountains of this Dvīpa
are said to be adorned with jewels (मणि-
भूषिताः) and are mines of precious stones
(रत्नाकराः) 6. 12. 13; the extent in योजनस्
of these mountains is double the preceding
one (तेषां योजनविष्कम्भो द्विगुणः प्र-
विभागशः) 6. 12. 22; it is characterized
by the the नक्षत्र Revatī in the sky (this
explains the name of the mountain); that was
the permanently established ordainment of
Pitāmaha (Brahmadeva) (उच्चैर्गिरी रैव-
तको यत्र नित्यं प्रतिष्ठितः।रेवती दिवि
नक्षत्रम् पितामहकृतो विधिः) 6. 12. 16
(Nī. on Bom. Ed. 6. 11. 18: रेवती ज्योतिर्-
मण्डलरूपेण दिवि विभ्रम्यमाणापि दिव्-
येन रूपेणात्रापि वर्तते एवं विधिर्
मर्यादा पितामहेन कृता); the Varṣa rela-
ted to the mountain Raivata is Kaumāra 6.
12. 24.

रोहितकारण्य
Rohitakāraṇya nt.: Name of a forest.
Mentioned among the places to which the
army of the Kauravas spread out as it could
not to be accommodated in Hāstinapura (न
हास्तिनपुरे राजन्न् अवकाशो ऽभवत् तदा
 … एष देशः सुवीस्तीर्णः … बभूव कौर-
वेयाणां बलेन सुसमाकुलः 5. 19. 28, 31)
5. 19. 29.

रौप्या
Raupyā f.: Name of a river (?).
Pointed out by Lomaśa to Yudhiṣṭhira;
the highly illustrious son of Ārcīka who
roamed on the earth with his Yogic powers
withdrew (?) in the river Raupyā (एतद्
आर्चीकपुत्रष्य योगैर् विचरतो महीम्।
अपसर्पणं महीपाल रौप्यायाम् अमित-
उजसः॥) 3. 129. 7 (Nī. on Bom. Ed. 3.
129. 7: रूप्यवत् श्वेतवर्णायां स्थल्यां
नद्यां वा).

ललितिका
Lalitikā f.: Name of a तीर्थ।
The तीर्थ of Śaṃtanu (शन्तनोस् तीर्-
थम्) on the river Gaṅgā (?); described as
the best तीर्थ (तीर्थम् उत्तमम्); by bath-
ing there one does not meet with adversity
(न दुर्गतिम् अवाप्नुयात्) 3. 82. 30.

लवेडिका
Laveḍikā f.: Name of a तीर्थ।
Described as holy (पुण्या), resorted to
by the holy (पुण्योपसेविता); by visiting
it one gets the fruit of a Vājapeya; he rides
in a विमान and is worshipped (विमानस्थश्
च पूज्यते) 3. 82. 143.

लोकोद्धार
Lokoddhāra nt.: Name of a तीर्थ।
Described as an excellent तीर्थ (तीर्थ-
वर) 3. 81. 37; famous in the three worlds
(त्रैलोक्यविश्रुत) 3. 81. 36, 37; it was at
this तीर्थ that Viṣṇu in the bygone days
lifted the worlds (this explains the name
of the तीर्थ) (लोका यत्रोद्धृताः पूर्वं
विष्णुना) 3. 81. 36; by bathing there one lifts
up his own kinsmen (लोकान् उद्धरते
स्वकान्) 3. 81. 37.

लोलोद्धृतकरा
Loloddhṛtakarā f.: Name of a river.
Listed by Saṃjaya among the rivers of
the Bhāratavarṣa; its water used by people
for drinking 6. 10. 30, 13 (for other details
see Puṣpaveṇī).

लोहतारिणी
Lohatāriṇī f.: Name of a river.
Listed by Saṃjaya among the rivers of
the Bhāratavarṣa; people used its water for
drinking 6. 10. 17, 13 (for other details see
Puṣpaveṇī).

लोहित
Lohita, Lohitoda, Lauhitya1 m.: Name
of an ocean.
A. Location: In the east (see My-
thological event below) (Nī. on Bom. Ed.
17. 1. 33: लौहित्यम् उदयाचलप्रान्तस्थं
समुद्रम्).
B. Description: The abode
of Varuṇa (वरुणालय) 3. 213. 28.
C.
Epic Event: When the Pāṇḍavas started on
their great journey they first went to the Lau-
hitya ocean (लौहित्यं सलिलार्णवम्) 17.
1. 31; there they saw god Agni and at his
instance Arjuna returned his Gāṇḍīva bow
and the two inexhaustible quivers to Varuṇa
by throwing them into the water of the
ocean 17. 1. 33-40.
D. Mythological
event: Before the birth of Skanda, Indra
saw the Lohitoda ocean when he looked at
the sun on the rising mountain 3. 213. 28,
26; the daughter of the Lohita ocean (लोह्त्-
तस्योदधेः कन्या), cruel and drinking
blood (क्रूरा लोहितभोजना), embraced the
newly born Mahāsena (Skanda) and protected
him like her son 3. 215. 22; the daughter of
the Lohita ocean acted as the nurse of Skanda
(धात्री स्कन्दस्य सा स्मृता); she is wor-
shipped as Lohitāyani on the Kadamba tree
(लोहितायनिर् इत्य् एवं कदम्बे सा हि पूज्-
यते) 3. 219. 39; the seed of Rudra was
poured in the womb of Umā; from there it fell
out in five ways (तद् एवं पञ्चधापतत्):
first (a part of) it fell on a mountain; the
remaining in the Lohitoda ocean (लोहितोदे
तु शुक्रशेषम् अवापतत्); a part fell in the
rays of the sun, another part on earth, and
the rest got stuck on trees 3. 220. 10-11.

लोहित्य
Lohitya1, Lauhitya2 m.: Name of the
river Brahmaputra.
A. Location: In the east (ययौ प्रा-
चीं दिशं प्रति) 2. 26. 1; at the other end
of the mountain Himavant, rising on the
mountain of sunrise, flowing to the Vāriṣena (?)
ocean (परार्धे हिमवतः सूर्योदय-
गिरौ … ।वारिषेणसमुद्रान्ते लोहित्यम्
अभितश् च) 2. 48. 8.
B. Description:
Called a big river (महानदः) 13. 151. 16.
C. Epic event: (1) Bhīmasena reached it
in his expedition to the east before the Rāja-
sūya (लौहित्यम् अगमद् बली); he collected
there tributes of all sorts from all the Mleccha
kings who lived in the islands of the ocean
(Vāriṣeṇa ?) (लौहित्यम् अगमद् बली।स
सर्वान् म्लेच्छनृपतीन् सागरद्वीपवासिनः।
करम् आहारयाम् आस) 2. 27. 24-26; (2)
The Kirāta kings who lived near the Lohitya
river brought tribute to Yudhiṣṭhira at the
time of his Rājasūya sacrifice; the tribute
consisted of sandal-wood and other fragrant
substances and heaps of skins, jewels and
gold 2. 48. 9-10.
D. Importance: Finds
mention in the Daivata-Ṛṣi-Vaṃśa 13. 151.
16, 2.

लोहित्य
Lohitya2, Lauhitya3 nt.: Name of a
तीर्थ।
The तीर्थ was established in the by-
gone days by the grace of Rāma (Bhārgava);
by visiting it one gets much gold (रामस्य
च प्रसादेन तीर्थं राजन् कृतं पुरा।
तल् लोहित्यं समासाद्य विन्द्याद् बहु सु-
वर्णकम्॥) 3. 83. 2; by visiting the Lau-
hitya तीर्थ and by bathing there, according
to the rites, at the conjunction of Urvaśī (?)
and Kṛttikā a person who is well composed
gets the fruit of a Puṇḍarīka sacrifice (उर्वशी-
कृत्तिकायोगे गत्वा यः सुसमाहितः।लौहित्ये
विधिवत् स्नात्वा पुण्डरीकफलं लभेत्)
13. 26. 43 (For Nī. see p. 244. 2 under
Kṛttikā).

लोहित्या
Lohityā f.: Name of a river.
Listed by Saṃjaya among the rivers of
the Bhāratavarṣa; people used its water for
drinking 6. 10. 34, 13 (for other details see
Puṣpaveṇī).

लौहित्य
Lauhitya1 m.: See Lohita.

लौहित्य
Lauhitya2 m.: See Lohitya1.

लौहित्य
Lauhitya3 m.: See Lohitya2.

वंशगुल्म
Vaṃśagulma m.: Name of a तीर्थ।
It is the source of the rivers Śoṇa and
Narmadā (शोणस्य नर्मदायाश् च प्र-
भवे … ।वंशगुल्मे); by bathing there
(उपस्पृश्य) one gets the fruit of a horse
sacrifice (Vājimedha) 3. 83. 9.

वंशमूलक
Vaṃśamūlaka nt.: Name of a तीर्थ।
By reaching it (आसाद्य) and by bathing
there a pilgrim (तीर्थसेवी) lifts up his
family 3. 81. 34.

वक्रद्वार
Vakradvāra m.: Name of a mountain.
One of the three mountains, the other
two being Droṇa and Śataśṛṅga, piled up
together by Indra for the सत्रस् of the ance-
stors of Sulabhā (द्रोणश् च शतशृङ्गश् च
वक्रद्वारश् च पर्वतः।मम सत्रेषु
पूर्वेषाम् चिता मघवता सह॥) 12. 308.
183 (Nī. on Bom. Ed. 12. 320. 182: द्रोणा-
दयः पर्वताः मम पूर्वेषां सत्रेषु
मघवता सह चिताः चयने इष्टकास्थाने
निवेशिता इत्य् अर्थः).

वङ्क्षु
Vaṅkṣu f.: Name of a river.
Listed by Bhīṣma in the Daivata-Ṛṣi-
Vaṃśa 13. 151. 17, 2.

वटेश्वरपुर
Vaṭeśvarapura nt.: Name of a तीर्थ।
Sacred to Keśava (Kṛṣṇa); by reaching
(गत्वा) Vaṭeśvarapura, by worshipping Keśava
there, and by observing fast (उपवासात्) one
undoubtedly gets the desired objects (ईप्सितान्
 … कामान्) 3. 82. 111.

वधूसरा
Vadhūsarā f.: Name of a river.
Flowing by the आश्रम of Cyavana
(च्यवनस्याश्रमं प्रति) 1. 6. 7; described
as a great river (महानदी) 1. 6. 6; a
river arose from the tears flowing from the
eyes of Pulomā, wife of Bhṛgu; the river
followed the step of Pulomā; seeing that,
Pitāmaha (Brahman) named the river Vadhū-
sarā (अश्रुबिन्दूद्भवा तस्याः प्रावर्तत
महानदी। … तस्या मार्गं सृतवतीं
दृष्ट्वा तु सरितं तदा।नाम तस्यास् तदा
नद्याश् चक्रे लोकपितामहः वधूसरेति)
1. 6. 6-7.

वन्दना
Vandanā f.: Name of a river.
Described as a great river (महानदी):
listed by Saṃjaya among the rivers of the
Bhāratavarṣa; people used its water for drink-
ing 6. 10. 17, 13 (for other details see Puṣpa-
veṇī).

वरदा
Varadā f.: Name of a river.
If one bathes at the confluence of Varadā
(वरदासंगमे) one gets the fruit of gift-
ing a thousand cows 3. 83. 31.

वरदान
Varadāna nt.: Name of a तीर्थ।
One can reach this तीर्थ from the place
where Sarasvatī meets the ocean 3. 80. 79;
by bathing at this तीर्थ one gets the fruit
of gifting a thousand cows 3. 80. 81; sage
Durvāsas gave here a boon to Viṣṇu (विष्णोर्
दुर्वाससा यत्र वरो दत्तः) 3. 80. 81.

वराणसी
Varāṇasī f.: Name of a river.
Listed by Saṃjaya among the rivers of
the Bhāratavarṣa; people used its water for
drinking 6. 10. 30, 13 (for other details see
Puṣpaveṇī).

वराह
Varāha1 m.: Name of a mountain.
Described as having big summits (महा-
शृङ्ग) 2. 19. 2; one of the five mountains
—the other four being Vaihāra, Vṛṣabha,
Ṛṣigiri and Caityaka—surrounding the city
Girivraja in the Magadha country; the five
mountains came together as though for pro-
tecting the city (एते पञ्चमहाशृङ्गाः पर्-
वताः … ।रक्षन्तीवाभिसंहत्य संह-
ताङ्गा गिरिव्रजम्॥) 2. 19. 2-3 (for other
details see Ṛṣigīri). [See Varāha2]

वराह
Varāha2 m.: Name of a mountain.
So called because Vṛṣākapi (Nārāyaṇa),
after assuming the form of a boar and after
lifting up the lost earth (इमां हि धरणीं
पूर्वं नष्टाम् … गोविन्द उज्जहाराशु
वाराहं रूपम् आश्रितः 12. 333. 11) offered
पिण्डस् on the Varāha mountain with all
detailed rites to his father, grandfather and
great-grandfather and worshipped himself; he
then disappeared instantly 12. 333. 22.

वरुणस्रोतस
Varuṇasrotasa m.: Name of a moun-
tain.
In the south (दक्षिणस्याम्) 3. 86. 1;
on this mountain (वरुणस्रोतसे गिरौ)
there is the forest of Māṭhara and his sacri-
ficial post (यूप) 3. 86. 7.

वरुणह्रद
Varuṇahrada m.: Name of a lake.
The lake of Varuṇa in the Nāgaloka
below the earth (5. 96. 6, 8); fire in big
flames is wide awake there (अग्निर् एष महा-
र्चिष्मान् जागर्ति वरुणह्रदे) 5. 96. 18.

वसिष्ठस्य
Vasiṣṭhasya parvataḥ m.: Designation
of a mountain.
On the lower range of the Himavant
(हिमवत्पार्श्वम् 1. 207. 1); Arjuna visited
it during his exile 1. 207. 2.

वसिष्ठापवाह
Vasiṣṭhāpavāha m.: Name of a तीर्थ,
described as a ह्रद 9. 42. 9.
A. Location: On the river Sarasvatī,
near Sthāṇutīrtha 9. 41. 6-7.
B. Descrip-
tion: Famous in the world (लोके ख्यातः) 9.
41. 39; excellent (तीर्थवर), bright (शुभ्र)
9. 42. 1; having fearful, very fearful current
(भीमवेग) 9. 41. 1; (महाभीमवेग)
9. 40. 35.
C. Name explained: As asked
by Viśvāmitra, Sarasvatī, in order to carry off
Vasiṣṭha to Viśvāmitra, removed a part of her
bank on the eastern side near the आश्रम of
Vasiṣṭha so that he was carried away by the
water of the river Sarasvatī to the oppo-
site bank near the आश्रम of Viśvāmitra;
the river then carried Vasiṣṭha back (अप-
वह्-) to his eastern bank; hence the तीर्थ
was so called (अपोवाह वसिष्ठं तु प्राचीं
दिशम् अतन्द्रिता 9. 41. 34) 9. 41. 1-39.
D. Epic event: Balarāma visited it in his
तीर्थयात्रा 9. 40. 35; he bathed there (उप-
स्पृश्य) and gave many kinds of gifts; he
thereby got religious merit (अवाप्य धर्-
मम्); from there he went to Somatīrtha
9. 42. 38.
E. Past event: Due to the
curse of Viśvāmitra, Sarasvatī flew with blood
at this तीर्थ which was drunk by the
Rākṣasas; the river was later freed by as-
cetics from the curse and the water near the
lake became normal (प्रकृतिष्था सरस्वती।
प्रसन्नसलिला जज्ञे) 9. 42. 1-13.

वसूनां
Vasūnāṃ tīrtham nt.: Name of a
तीर्थ, sacred to the Vasus.
Situated near the Vasordhārā तीर्थ;
described as excellent (पर) and holy
(पुण्य); if one bathes there and drinks
its water one is liked by the Vasus (तत्र
स्नात्वा च पीत्वा च वसूनां संमतो भवेत्)
3. 80. 94.

वसोर्
Vasor dhārā1 f.: Name of a तीर्थ।
One reaches there from the Dṛmī तीर्थ
(3. 80. 90-91); described as praised (by
pilgrims) (अभिष्टुता) 3. 80. 92; just by
visiting it one gets the fruit of a horse sacri-
fice (गमनाद् एव तस्यां हि हयमेधम्
अवाप्नुयात्) 3. 80. 92; a pious minded person
(प्रयतात्मा), if he bathes there and gives
offerings to gods and manes he is glorified in
the Viṣṇuloka (विष्णुलोके महीयते) 3. 80.
93.

वसोर्
Vasor dhārā2 f.: Name of a heavenly
river.
It flows from a place where the Gan-
dharvas and the Apsarases live and where
there are golden palaces (प्रासादा यत्र
सौवर्णाः … गन्धर्वाप्सरसो यत्र);
those who give a thousand cows as a gift
go to the place where Vasor dhārā flows 13.
79. 5 (Nī. on Bom. Ed. 13. 80. 5; वसोर्
धारा मन्दाकिनी). [See Mandākinī2,
Mandākinī3]

वस्वोकसारा
Vasvokasārā f.: Name of one of the
seven streams of Gaṅgā.
The divine Tripathagā (Gaṅgā) river,
after it was first established on the mountain
Hiraṇyaśṛṅga, got divided into seven streams;
one of them was Vasvokasārā (तत्र (i. e.
हिरण्यशृङ्गे) त्रिपथगा देवी प्रथमं
तु प्रतिष्ठिता।ब्राह्मलोकाद् अपक्रान्ता
सप्तधा प्रतिपद्यते॥वस्वोकसारा … )
6. 7. 44-45, 40; one of the rivers seen by
Mārkaṇḍeya in the belly of the Bāla (3. 186.
83, i. e. Nārāyaṇa 3. 187. 3) 3. 186. 94.

वस्त्रापद
Vastrāpada nt.: Name of a sacred
place.
One can reach it from the river Maladā;
by visiting Vastrāpada and by visiting Mahā-
deva (अभिगम्य महादेवम्) one gets the
fruit of an Aśvamedha 3. 80. 108.

वाका
Vākā f.: Name of a river.
The forest Aṅgāraparṇa, belonging to
Aṅgāraparṇa Gandharva, was situated on the
banks of Gaṅgā and Vākā (अङ्गारपर्णम्
इति च ख्यातं वनम् इदं मम।अनु
गङ्गां च वाकां च) 1. 158. 13.

वाजिनी
Vājinī f.: Name of a river.
Listed by Saṃjaya among the rivers of
the Bhāratavarṣa; people used its water for
drinking 6. 10. 20, 13; all the rivers listed
here are described as mothers of the universe
and very strong 6. 10. 35 (for citation see
Atikṛṣṇā).

वापी
Vāpī f.: Name of a river.
Listed by Saṃjaya among the rivers of
the Bhāratavarṣa; people used its water for
drinking 6. 10. 19, 13; all the rivers listed
here are described as mothers of the universe
and very strong 6. 10. 35 (for citation see
Atikṛṣṇā).

वामन
Vāmana1 nt.: Name of a sacred place.
Sacred to god Hari; one can reach it
from Vaṭeśvarapura; described as one that
frees the visitor from all sins (सर्वपाप-
प्रमोचन); by worshipping god Hari there
(अभिवाद्य हरिं देवम्) one does not
meet with miserable condition (न दुर्गतिम्
अवाप्नुयात्) 3. 82. 112.

वामन
Vāmana2, Vāmanaka1 m.: Name of a
mountain.
One of the six mountains of the Krauñca-
dvīpa; Vāmanaka lies beyond the Krauñca
mountain and beyond Vāmana is Andha-
kāraka (क्रौञ्चात् परो वामनको वामनाद्
अन्धकारकः) 6. 13. 17; the extent of each
succeeding mountain is double that of the
preceding one (परस् तु द्विगुणो तेषां
विष्कम्भः) 6. 13. 19; the country related
to Vāmana is Manonuga (वामनस्य मनो-
नुगः) 6. 13. 20.

वामनक
Vāmanaka1 m.: see Vāmana.

वामनक
Vāmanaka2 nt.: Name of a तीर्थ।
Sacred to Vāmana; one can reach it
from Devatīrtha; described as famous in
the three worlds (त्रिषु लोकेषु विश्रुतम्);
by bathing at the Viṣṇupada there and by
worshipping Vāmana (अर्चयित्वा च वाम-
नम्) the worshipper's soul is cleansed of all
sins (सर्वपापविशुद्धात्मा) and he goes
to the world of Viṣṇu (विष्णुलोकम् अवाप्-
नुयात्) 3. 81. 86-87.

वाराह
Vārāha nt.: Name of a तीर्थ।
Described as best (उत्तम); one can
reach it from Aśvinos tīrtham; so called be-
cause Viṣṇu formerly stood there in the form
of a boar (विष्णुर् वाराहरूपेण पूर्वं
यत्र स्थितो ऽभवत्); by bathing there one
gets the fruit of an Agniṣṭoma 3. 81. 14-15.

वारिषेण
Vāriṣeṇa1 m.: Name of a mountain.
Pāṇḍu crossed it after he reached the
Caitraratha; after crossing Vāriṣeṇa, he cross-
ed the Himavant to reach Gandhamādana 1.
110. 43.

वारिषेण
Vāriṣeṇa2 m.: Name of an ocean.
The kings who lived on the other (eas-
tern) side of the Himavant, on the mountain
of the sun-rise, at the shore of the Vāriṣeṇa
ocean and around Lohitya and the Kirātas
brought tribute, consisting of fragrant sub-
stances, exotic deer and birds, and gold
collected from mountains to Yudhiṣṭhira for
his Rājasūya (ये परार्धे हिमवतः सूर्-
योदयगिरौ नृपाः।वारिषेणसमुद्रान्ते
लोहित्यम् अभितश् च ये … ये च किराताः … ॥
 … गन्धानां चैव राशयः। … दूरजान्
मृगपक्षिणः।विचितं पर्वतेभ्यश् च
हिरण्यम्॥) 2. 48. 8-11.

वारुण
Vāruṇa nt.: Name of a तीर्थ।
Sacred to Varuṇa, in the Pāṇḍya country
in the south 3. 86. 10, 1. [See Aujasa]

वालकोटि
Vālakoṭi f.: Name of a place.
On the mountain Vṛṣaprastha and near
the river Bāhudā 3. 93. 4.

वासिष्ठ
Vāsiṣṭha nt.: Name of a तीर्थ।
By wading through Vāsiṣṭha all the
वर्णस् become Brāhmaṇas (वासिष्ठं सम-
तिक्रम्य सर्वे वर्णा द्विजातयः) 3. 82. 43.

वासुकेस्
Vāsukes tīrtham nt.: See Bhogavatī1.

वास्तु
Vāstu f.: Name of a river.
Listed by Saṃjaya among the rivers of
the Bhāratavarṣa; people used its water for
drinking 6. 10. 24, 13; all the rivers listed
here by Saṃjaya are described as mothers of
the universe and very strong 6. 10. 35 (for
citation see Atikṛṣṇā).

विचित्रा
Vicitrā f.: Name of a river.
Listed by Saṃjaya among the rivers of
the Bhāratavarṣa; people used its water for
drinking 6. 10. 17, 13; all the rivers listed
here are described as mothers of the universe
and very strong 6. 10. 35 (for citation see
Atikṛṣṇā).

वितस्ता
Vitastā f.: Name of a river.
A. Location: Listed by Saṃjaya among
the rivers of tha Bhāratavarṣa; people used
its water for drinking 6. 10. 15, 13; A Brāh-
maṇa had told in the assembly of the Kurus
that the river Vitastā and other four rivers
along with Sindhu as the sixth flow outside
the country called the Āraṭṭas (चन्द्र-
भागा वितस्ता च सिन्धुषष्ठा बहिर्गताः॥
आरट्टा नाम ते देशाः) 8. 30. 34-36.
B.
Description: Described as having a garland
in the form of waves (ऊर्मिमालिनी) 13. 26. 7;
Vitastā and the other rivers listed by Umā
are described as most holy (पुण्यतमाः) and
auspicious (शिवाः) 13. 134. 22; containing
waters of all the तीर्थस् (सर्वतीर्थोदकैर्
युताः) 13. 134. 12; excellent and best among
the rivers (सरिद्वराः) 13. 134. 14; (सरि-
तां वराः) 13. 134. 19; (सरिच्छ्रेष्ठाः) 13.
134. 22; expert in the knowledge of duties of
women (स्त्रीधर्मकुशलाः) 13. 134. 18;
all the rivers listed by Saṃjaya are described
as mothers of the universe and very strong
6. 10. 35 (for citation see Atikṛṣṇā).
C.
Holiness: It is said in the Tīrthavaṃśa
declared by Aṅgiras to Gautama that one
who observes fast and is without attachment
(निराहारो निर्ममः) if he bathes for a
week in Vitastā he becomes like a मुनि
(सप्ताहम् … वितस्ताम् … विगाह्य वै …
मुनिवद् भवेत्) 13. 26. 7;
D. Impor-
tance: (1) One of the rivers who wait
upon Śiva for his bath (उपस्पर्शनहेतोस्
त्वा समीपस्था उपासते) 13. 134. 12; Umā
honoured these rivers by requesting them to
instruct her in the duties of women (स्त्री-
धर्म), before she could expound them to
Śiva 13. 134. 14, 21, 25, 19-20; (2) Vitastā
is one of the rivers who, in bodily form (2.
9. 21), wait on Varuṇa in his Sabhā 2. 9. 19,
22; (3) Finds mention in the Daivata-Ṛṣi-
Vaṃśa 13. 151. 20, 2.
E. Past event:
Four hundred moon-white horses having one
black ear each (एकतःश्यामकर्णानाम् हया-
नाम् चन्द्रवर्चसाम् 5. 117. 5) were swept
away by the river Vitastā at the crossing on
it (चत्वारि शतानि … ।नीयमानानि संतारे
हृतान्य् आसन् वितस्तया) 5. 117. 8; (these
horses were originally obtained by Ṛcīka at the
abode of Varuṇa and given to Gādhi as bride-
price in order to marry the latter's daughter
Satyavatī 5. 117. 4-6).

विदिशा
Vidiśā f.: Name of a river.
One of the rivers who, in bodily form
(2. 9. 21), wait on Varuṇa in his Sabhā 2.
9. 18, 22; listed by Saṃjaya among the rivers
of the Bhāratavarṣa; people used its water
for drinking 6. 10. 27, 13; all the rivers listed
here are described as mothers of the universe
and very strong 6. 10. 35 (for citation see
Atikṛṣṇā).

विद्यातीर्थ
Vidyātīrtha nt.: Name of a तीर्थ।
Described as best (अनुत्तम); if one
reaches it in the evening and bathes there he
becomes versed in all fields of knowledge
(विद्यास्) (ततः संध्यां समासाद्य
विद्यातीर्थम् … ।उपस्पृश्य च विद्यानां
सर्वासां पारगो भवेत्॥) 3. 82. 47; (this
explains the name of the तीर्थ).

विनशन
Vinaśana1 nt.: Name of a तीर्थ।
A. Location: A तीर्थ on the river
Sarasvatī; a place where Sarasvatī disappear-
ed in a desert land (गच्छत्य् अन्तर्हिता यत्र
मरुपृष्ठे सरस्वती) 3. 80. 118; Sarasvatī
entered the earth as she did not want to be
known to the Niṣādas due to her dislike for
them; this then is the gate of the Niṣādarāṣṭra
(एतद् विनशनं नाम सरस्वत्या विशां
पते॥द्वारं निषादराष्ट्रस्य येषां द्वेषात्
सरस्वती।प्रविष्टा पृथिवीं वीर मा निषादा
हि मां विदुः॥) 3. 130. 3-4; she disappeared
also due to her dislike for the Śūdras and the
Ābhīras (शूद्राभीरान् प्रति द्वेषाद् यत्र
नष्टा सरस्वती) 9. 36. 1.
B. Name
explained: Because Sarasvatī disappeared
(नष्टा) at the place of this तीर्थ, sages
named it Vinaśana (यस्मात् सा भरतश्रेष्ठ
द्वेषान् नष्टा सरस्वती।तस्माद् ऋषयो
नित्यं प्राहुर् विनशनेति ह) 9. 36. 2.
C. Holiness: A pilgrim while visiting the
तीर्थ should be controlled and take restricted
food (ततो विनशनं गच्छेन् नियतो नियता-
शनः) 3. 80. 118.
D. Epic event: Bala-
rāma proceeded to Vinaśana from Udapāna
9. 35. 53; he bathed (उपस्पृश्य) there in
the river Sarasvatī and went from there to
Subhūmika which was also on the bank of
Sarasvatī 9. 36. 3.

विनशण
Vinaśaṇa2 nt.: Name of a तीर्थ।
Situated in the east; from there one
reaches the river Gaṇḍakī 3. 82. 97; described
as one that relieves from all sins (सर्वपाप-
प्रमोचन); by visiting this तीर्थ one gets
the fruit of a Vājapeya and goes to the
world of Soma (सोमलोकं च गच्छति) 3.
82. 96.

विनशन
Vinaśana3 nt.: Name of a sacred
place (?)
Situated in the cave (?) of the mountain
Maināka where Aditi formerly cooked food
(for gods and Brāhmaṇas) to get a son
(एतद् विनशनं कुक्षौ मैनाकस्य नर-
र्षभ।अदितिर् यत्र पुत्रार्थं तदन्नम्
अपचत् पुरा॥) 3. 135. 3 (Nī. on Bom. Ed.
3. 135. 3: अन्नं ब्रह्मौदनम्।अदितिः
पुत्रकामा साध्येभ्यो देवेभ्यो ब्रह्मौ-
दनम् अपचद् इति श्रुतेः).

विन्ध्य
Vindhya m.: Name of a mountain.
A. Location: Listed by Saṃjaya among
the seven principal mountains of the Bhārata-
varṣa (सप्तैते कुलपर्वताः) 6. 10. 10;
described as a great mountain; the river
Payoṣṇī flows by it on which there are the
आश्रमस् of great sages (एष विन्ध्यो महा-
शैलः पयोष्णी च समुद्रगा।आश्रमाश् च
महर्षीणाम्) 3. 58. 21; it is on the way to
the Dakṣiṇāpatha 3. 58. 20-21.
B. Des-
cription: Big mountain (महाशैल) 3. 58.
21; excellent mountain (पर्वतोत्तम) 3.
102. 11, (नगोत्तम) 3. 101. 15; king of
mountains, king of big mountains (शैलराज)
3. 102. 8; (एते पर्वतराजानः) 14. 43. 4-5;
(शैलेन्द्र) 3. 102. 4, 12; (महाद्रिराज)
3. 102. 6; it has many minerals, is rich in
herbs (used in medicine) and has many
तीर्थस् (विन्ध्यो धातुविचित्राङ्गस् तीर्थवान्
औषधान्वितः) 13. 151. 25; has Śāla trees
with flowering tops on it (पुष्पिताग्रेषु
शालेषु) 1. 204. 6; the Karṇikāra trees grow
on the banks of the rivers on this mountain
(नदीतीरेषु जातान् सा कर्णिकारान् विचिन्वती)
1. 204. 10.
C. Characteristic: The Mle-
cchas in hundreds and thousands who arose
from a person (churned out from the right
thigh of Vena) live on the Vindhya (ये
चान्ये विन्ध्यनिलया म्लेच्छाः शतसहस्र-
शः) 12. 59. 101-103.
D. Importance:
(1) Listed by Brahman among the mountains
which are described as kings of mountains
14. 43. 4; (are these mountains also supposed
to have the quality of रजस् (मध्यमो
गुणः) ? 14. 43. 1; for Nī. see Kāṣṭha-
vant); (2) Finds mention in the Daivata-
Ṛṣi-Vaṃśa 13. 151. 25, 2.
E. Holiness:
One who is truthful and causes no injury to
others, if he lives on Vindhya for six
months (?) and practises austerities, he is
then cleansed (of sins) in a month (विन्ध्ये
संताप्य चात्मानं सत्यसंधस् त्व् अहिं-
सकः।षण्मासं पदम् आस्थाय मासे-
नैकेन शुध्यति) 13. 26. 46.
F. Past
and mythological events: (1) Nala points
to Vindhya while showing to Damayantī the
paths leading to the Dakṣiṇāpatha and to
the Vidarbhas (एते गच्छन्ति बहवः पन्-
थानो दक्षिणापथम्। … एष विन्ध्यो महा-
शैलः) 3. 58. 20-22; (एष पन्था विदर्-
भाणाम्) 3. 58. 22; (2) Mārkaṇḍeya saw
Vindhya, among other mountains, in the belly
 of the Bāla (3. 186. 83 = Nārāyaṇa 3. 187.
3) 3. 186. 104; (3) The demons Sunda
and Upasunda took दीक्षा and went to
Vindhya to practise austerities; the mountain
was heated for a long time by their तपस्,
so it started issuing smoke; that was a
miracle (तयोस् तपःप्रभावेण दीर्घकालं
प्रतापितः धूमं प्रमुमुचे विन्ध्यस्
तद् अद्भुतम् इवाभवत्) 1. 201. 5-9; the
two demons once went to the top of Vindhya
where there was level land (विन्ध्यस्य
पृष्ठे समशिलातले; Nī., Bom. Ed. 1. 212. 6,
reads प्रस्थे which he explains as शिखरे);
Tilottamā approached the two demons there;
in the duel that followed between the two
over Tilottamā, both were killed on the moun-
tain 1. 204. 6, 10, 19; (4) The mountain
Vindhya, angry with the sun, began to grow
upwards, but, at the instance of the sage Aga-
stya, stopped growing (वचस् तवानतिक्रा-
मन् विन्ध्यः शैलो न वर्धते) 3. 101.
15; Yudhiṣṭhira asked Lomaśa why Vindhya
suddenly started to grow 3. 102. 1; Vindhya
asked the sun to make a प्रदक्षिणा round
him as it did round Meru; the sun told the
mountain that he did not do it at his own
will, but that was the course laid down by the
Creator; when the sun did not oblige, Vindhya,
angered, began to grow and obstructed the
path of the sun and the moon; the gods tried to
stop him from growing but Vindhya did not
stop; the gods then approached Agastya and
told him that Vindhya, under the influence of
anger, was covering the path of the luminaries;
they added that no one else except the sage was
able to dissuade the mountain; hearing that
Agastya, in the company of his wife, appro-
ached Vindhya and told him that he wanted
to go to the south on some purpose; he asked
the mountain to wait for his return and grow
again as desired after he returned; Agastya
made this contract with Vindhya but never re-
turned from the south; Vindhya was thus made
to stop growing due to the power of Agastya
(एवं स समयं कृत्वा विन्ध्येनामित्र-
कर्शन।अद्यापि दक्षिणाद् देशाद् वारुणिर् न
निवर्तते॥एतत् ते सर्वम् आख्यातं यथा
विन्ध्यो न वर्धते।अगस्त्यस्य प्रभा-
वेन (सिच्)) 3. 102. 3-14; (5) Vindhya, along
with other mountains, arrived for the अभिषेक
of Kumāra (Skanda) 9. 44. 13, 16; Vindhya
presented his two companions Ucchrita and
Atiśṛṅga, who fought with big rocks, to
Skanda (महापाषाणयोधिनौ।प्रददाव्
अग्निपुत्राय विन्ध्यः पारिषदाव् उभौ) 9.
44. 45.
G. Similes: (1) Yudhiṣṭhira
compared his four fallen brothers with the
mountains Himavant, Pāriyātra, Vindhya and
Malaya (चत्वारः पर्वताः केन पातिताः)
3. 297. 14; (2) The गदा hurled by Śrutā-
yudha at Kṛṣṇa did not shake him as wind
does not shake Vindhya (विन्ध्यं गिर्त्म्
इवानिलः) 7. 67. 52; (3) Hanūmant as-
sumed a form wonderful and very frightful,
like that of Vindhya or Mandara (तद् अद्-
भुतं महारौद्रं विन्ध्यमन्दरसं-
निभम्) 3. 149. 10; (4) Ghaṭotkaca,
afraid of Karṇa's शक्ति, ran away after as-
suming a form like that of the foot of Vindhya
(कृत्वात्मानं विन्ध्यपादप्रमाणम्) 7.
154. 55; (5) Yudhiṣṭhira, accompanied by
the Devadūta, went along the path that was
covered with corpses which were comparable
to the Vindhya mountain (प्रेतैर् विन्ध्य-
शैलोपमैर् वृतम्) 18. 2. 20; (6) Prati-
vindhya, Yudhiṣṭhira's son, was to be another
Vindhya in not taking cognisance of the
hittings by opponents (परप्रहरणज्ञाने
प्रतिविन्ध्यो भवत्व् अयम्) 1. 213. 74
(Nī. on Bom. Ed. 1. 221. 81: परप्रह-
रणज्ञाने शत्रुकृतप्रहारवेदनायां विन्-
ध्य इव निर्विज्ञान इति प्रतिविन्ध्यः).

विपापा
Vipāpā f.: Name of a river.
Listed by Saṃjaya among the rivers of
the Bhāratavarṣa; people used its water for
drinking 6. 10. 14, 13; all the rivers listed
here are described as mothers of the universe
and very strong 6. 10. 35 (for citation see
Atikṛṣṇā).

विपाशा
Vipāśā f.: Name of a river.
A. Location: Listed by Saṃjaya among
the rivers of the Bhāratavarṣa; people used
its water for drinking 6. 10. 14, 13; according
to a Brāhmaṇa living in the court of Dhṛta-
rāṣṭra, the rivers Śatadru, Vipāśā, Irāvatī,
Candrabhāgā and Vitastā, with Sindhu as
the sixth, flow outside the Āraṭṭa country
(पञ्च नद्यो वहन्त्य् एताः … शतद्रुश् च
विपाशा च … सिन्धुषष्ठा बहिर्गताः॥आरट्टा
नाम ते देशाः) 8. 30. 35-36; the Bāhlīka
country lies between these rivers (पञ्चानां
सिन्धुषष्ठानां नदीनां ये ऽन्तराश्रिताः।
तान् … बाह्लीकान् परिवर्जयेत्) 8. 30. 11 (Nī.
on Bom. Ed. 8. 44. 7: पञ्चानाम् वक्ष्य-
माणानां सिन्धुः षष्ठी यासाम् अन्तरम्
अवकाशम् आश्रिताः); (पञ्च नद्यो वहन्त्य्
एताः … आरट्टा नाम बाह्लीकाः) 8. 30. 43;
the Kālikāśrama was on this river 13. 26. 22.
B. Name explained: Vasiṣṭha, grieved over
the death of his sons, bound himself with
fetters and threw himself in a river; the river
cut off his fetters and made him as before;
the sage came out of waters free of the
fetters (विपाश) and named the river Vipāśā
(समस्थं तम् ऋषिं कृत्वा विपाशं सम-
वासृजत्॥उत्ततार ततः पाशैर् विमुक्तः
स महान् ऋषिः।विपाशेति च नामास्या
नद्याश् चक्रे महान् ऋषिः॥) 1. 167.
5-6; Vasiṣṭha drowned himself due to fear of
Viśvāmitra (तथैवास्य (i. e. विश्वामित्रस्य)
भयाद् बद्ध्वा वसिष्ठः सलिले पुरा।
आत्मानं मज्जयाम् आस विपाशः पुनर्
उत्थितः॥तदाप्रभृति पुण्या हि विपाशा-
भून् महानदी।विख्याता कर्मणा तेन
वसिष्ठस्य महात्मनः॥) 13. 3. 12-13.
C. Description: Holy (पुण्या) 13. 3. 13;
highly purifying (परमपावनी) 3. 130. 8;
pleasing (रम्या) 3. 130. 8; famous (वि-
ख्याता) 13. 3. 13; big river (महानदी) 1.
167. 4; 13. 3. 13; full of fresh water in rainy
season and washing away many trees of
various kinds growing on its banks (सरितं
पूर्णां प्रावृत्काले नवाम्भसा।वृक्षान्
बहुविधान् पार्थ वहन्ती तीरजान् बहून्)
1. 167. 2; all the rivers listed by Saṃjaya
are described as mothers of the universe and
very strong 6. 10. 35 (for citation see
Atikṛṣṇā); all the rivers (Vipāśā among
them) whom Umā wanted to consult on
स्त्रीधर्म, are described as auspicious
(शिवाः), very holy (पुण्यतमाः) 13. 134.
22; excellent rivers (सरिद्वराः) 13. 134.
14, (सरितां वराः) 13. 134. 19; best among
rivers (सरिच्छ्रेष्ठाः) 13. 134. 22; contain-
ing waters of all तीर्थस् (सर्वतीर्थोदकैर्
युताः) 13. 134. 12; conversant with the
duties of women (स्त्रीधर्मकुशलाः) 13.
134. 19.
D. Characteristic: Two Piśācas
named Bahi and Hlīka lived near Vipāśā; the
Bāhlīkas are their progeny and not the crea-
tion of Prajāpati (बहिश् च नाम ह्लीकश्
च विपाशायां पिशाचकौ।तयोर् अपत्यं
बाह्लीका नैषा सृष्टिः प्रजापतेः) 8. 30. 44.
E. Holiness: (1) One who observes chastity
and who has conquered anger if he visits
Kālikāśrama, bathes in Vipāśā and stays there
for three nights he is not required to return
to this world again (विपाशायां कृतोदकः।
ब्रह्मचारी जितक्रोधस् त्रिरात्रान् मुच्यते
भवात्) 13. 26. 22; (2) Vipāśā is men-
tioned among those holy places by visiting
which the high-souled ones assume heavenly
form and becoming auspicious and wearing
heavenly garlands, rich in holy fragrance,
they reach the Goloka (? ते तत्र मोदन्ति
गवां विमाने 13. 105. 44) 13. 105. 46.
F. Importance: (1) Vipāśā is one of
the rivers who wait upon Śiva for his bath
13. 134. 12; Umā consulted them on the
स्त्रीधर्म and thereby honoured them 13.
134. 14, 19-21; but Gaṅgā on behalf of all
the rivers requested Umā to teach स्त्रीधर्म
to them 13. 134. 29; (2) Finds mention in
the Daivata-Ṛṣi-Vaṃśa narrated by Bhīṣma
to Yudhiṣṭhira 13. 151. 14, 2.
G. Epic
event: It was shown by Lomaśa to Yudhi-
ṣṭhira 3. 130. 8.
H. Past events: (1)
Vasiṣṭha, out of grief for the death of his
sons, threw himself in Vipāśā 1. 166. 39; 1.
167. 1-4; 3. 130. 9; 13. 3. 12 (see above
B.
Name explained); (2) Vipāśā was one of
the rivers seen by Mārkaṇḍeya in the belly
of the Bāla (3. 186. 83 = Nārāyaṇa 3. 187.
3) 3. 186. 94.

विमल
Vimala1 nt.: Name of a तीर्थ।
One can reach it after visiting the Giri-
muñja mountain; described as the best तीर्थ
(विमलं तीर्थम् उत्तमम्); it is chara-
cterized by gold-coloured and silver-coloured
fishes (अद्यापि यत्र दृश्यन्ते मत्स्याः सौ-
वर्णराजताः); by bathing there one gets the
fruit of a Vājapeya and, with his soul cleans-
ed of all sins, he attains the highest state
(गच्छेच् च परमां गतिम्) 3. 80. 102-
104. [Identical with Vimala2 ?]

विमल
Vimala2 nt.: Name of a lake,
Situated near the place which is sacred
to Viśveśvara (Śiva) (तच् च विश्वेश्वर-
स्थानं यत्र तद् विमलं सरः); men-
tioned in the Daivata Ṛṣi-Vaṃśa narrated by
Bhīṣma to Yudhiṣṭhira 13. 151. 18, 2. [Identi-
cal with Vimala1 ?]

विमलाशोक
Vimalāśoka nt.: Name of a तीर्थ।
By visiting this तीर्थ one shines like
the moon (विराजति यथा शशी); by staying
there for a night one is glorified in heaven
(स्वर्गलोके महीयते) 3. 82. 62.

विमलोदका
Vimalodakā, Vimalodā f.: Name of
one of the seven forms of Sarasvatī.
Described as blessed (विमलोदा भग-
वती) 9. 37. 26; when Sarasvatī was invited
to appear for the sacrifices at various places
by powerful persons, it appeared at those
places under seven different names, one of
them being Vimalodakā (आहुता बलवद्भिर्
हि तत्र तत्र सरस्वती। … सुवेणुर् विमलो-
दका) 9. 37. 3-4; one of the persons to invite
Sarasvatī was Dakṣa; when he performed a
sacrifice at the Gaṅgādvāra, Sarasvatī appear-
ed there under the name Vimalodā 9. 37. 26.

विमोचन
Vimocana nt.: Name of a तीर्थ।
By bathing (उपस्पृश्य) at this तीर्थ,
one who has subdued anger and has controlled
senses (जितमन्युर् जितेन्द्रियः) is freed of
all faults committed in receiving gifts (प्रति-
ग्रहकृतैर् दोषैः सर्वैः स परिमुच्यते)
3. 81. 140; (this explains the name).

विरज
Viraja nt.: Name of a तीर्थ।
Situated on the river Vaitaraṇī; by
visiting it (विरजं तीर्थम् आसाद्य) one
shines like the moon (विराजति यथा शशी),
destroys all sin and is born in a holy family
(प्रभवेच् च कुले पुण्ये सर्वपापं व्य-
पोहति); he also gets the fruit of gifting a
thousand cows and purifies his family 3. 83.
6-7.

विशल्या
Viśalyā f.: Name of a river.
One of the rivers seen by Mārkaṇḍeya
in the belly of the Bāla (3. 186. 83 = Nārā-
yaṇa 3. 187. 3) 3. 186. 95; finds mention in
the Daivata-Ṛṣi-Vaṃśa narrated by Bhīṣma
to Yudhiṣṭhira 13. 151. 15.

विशाखयूप
Viśākhayūpa m.: Name of a sacred
place.
A. Location: In the north (उदीच्याम्)
3. 88. 1; on the Yāmuna mountain 3. 174. 15.
B. Description: Most holy (पुण्यतम)
3. 88. 12.
C. Epic event: The Pāṇḍavas
lived in a big forest near the Viśākhayūpa
for a year 3. 174. 16-17.
D. Mythological
event: Formerly, gods led by Indra and
Varuṇa practised austerities there; hence it is
holy (देवाः … अतप्यन्त तस्मात् पुण्यतमोः
स वै) 3. 88. 12; all the gods had piled their
sacrificial altars at Viśākhayūpa (विशाख-
यूपे देवानां सर्वेषाम् अग्नयश् चिताः)
12. 12. 3 (Nī. on Bom. Ed. 12. 12. 3: वि-
शाखयूपे क्षेत्रविशेषे।देवानां देवैः
अग्नयो ऽग्निस्थापनार्थानि स्थंडिलानि।चिता
इष्टकाभी राचिता अद्यापि दृश्यन्ते।).

विशाला
Viśālā f.: Name of a river (or two
rivers ?).
A. Location: The river has its origin
on the slope of the Himavant (सरित् सा हिम-
वत्पार्श्वात् प्रसूता) 9. 37. 20.
B. Des-
cription: Famous in the three worlds (त्रै-
लोक्यविश्रुता) 3. 82. 100; flowing swiftly
(शीघ्रगामिनी) 9. 37. 20.
C. Origin:
One of the seven forms of the river Sarasvatī
which pervade the whole world (राजन् सप्त
सरस्वत्यो याभिर् व्याप्तम् इदं जगत्) 9.
37. 3; (seven forms of Sarasvatī are listed in
9. 37. 4); when Gaya performed a great
sacrifice at Gayā (गयेषु), Sarasvatī was
invited to appear there by sages; when the
river appeared the sages called it Viśālā 9.
37. 19-20.
D. Holiness: (1) By visiting
Viśālā one gets the fruit of an Agniṣṭoma and
goes to heaven 3. 82. 100; (2) According
to the Tīrthavaṃśa narrated by Aṅgiras to
Gautama one who bathes in Viśālā is absorbed
in Brahman (विशालायां कृतोदकः … ब्रह्म-
भूतो विराजते) 13. 26. 41; (3) According
to Angiras again one who bathes in Viśālā
and observes fast for twelve days is freed of
all blemish (विशालायां कृतोदकः।द्वाद-
शाहं निराहारः कल्मषाद् विप्रमुच्यते)
13. 26. 44; (this Viśālā may be different from
the one mentioned by Aṅgiras before).

विश्वामित्रनदी
Viśvāmitranadī f.: The river Pārā so
called.
See Kauśikī and Pārā2 in Additions.

विश्वामित्रस्य
Viśvāmitrasya tīrtham nt.: Name of a
तीर्थ।
Situated near the Agnitīrtha (अग्नितीर्थं
ततो गच्छेत् … विश्वामित्रस्य तत्रैव तीर्थम्)
3. 81. 119-120; one who bathes there is born
as a Brāhmaṇa (तत्र स्नात्वा महाराज
ब्राह्मण्यम् अभिजायते) 3. 81. 120.

विश्वामित्रा
Viśvāmitrā f.: Name of a river.
Listed by Saṃjaya among the rivers of
the Bhāratavarṣa; people used its water for
drinking 6. 10. 25, 13; all rivers listed by
Saṃjaya are called mothers of the universe
and very strong 6. 10. 35 (for citation see
Atikṛṣṇā).

विश्वेश्वरस्थान
Viśveśvarasthāna nt.: Name of a holy
place.
A dirt-free lake near the place sacred to
Viśveśvara (Śiva) (तच् च विश्वेश्वरस्था-
नं यत्र तद् विमलं सरः) 13. 151. 18;
finds mention in the Daivata-Ṛṣi-Vaṃśa 13.
151. 2.

विष्णुपद
Viṣṇupada1 nt.: Name of a तीर्थ।
A. Location: In the north (उत्तरां
दिशम् आश्रितम्) 5. 109. 19; (अस्यां दिशि …
उत्तरायाम्) 5. 109. 3; situated near the
Vāmanaka तीर्थ 3. 81. 86-87.
B. Origin:
Viṣṇu, while traversing the three worlds esta-
blished it in the north (अत्र विष्णुपदं
नाम क्रमता विष्णुना कृतम्।त्रिलोकवि-
क्रमे) 5. 109. 19.
C. Description: Ex-
cellent (तीर्थम् उत्तमम्) 3. 130. 8.
D.
Holiness: By bathing at Viṣṇupada and by
worshipping Vāmana there one is freed of sins
and goes to the world of Viṣṇu 3. 81. 87.

विष्णुपद
Viṣṇupada2 m.: Name of a mountain.
When King Aṅga performed a sacrifice on
the Viṣṇupada mountain (विष्णुपदे गिरौ),
Indra was gladdened by Soma and Brāhmaṇas
by the दक्षिणास् they received (अमाद्यद्
इन्द्रः सोमेन दक्षिणाभिर् द्विजातयः) 12.
29. 31.

विष्णोः
Viṣṇoḥ sthānam nt.: Name of a sacred
place.
Descrihed as best (अनुत्तम) 3. 81. 8;
god Hari is always present there; by bathing
there and by worshipping Hari one gets the
fruit of a horse sacrifice and goes to the world
of Viṣṇu 3. 81. 8-9.

वीरप्रमोक्ष
Vīrapramokṣa nt.: Name of a तीर्थ।
By visiting this तीर्थ one is freed of all
sins 3. 82. 45.

वीरवती
Vīravatī f.: Name of a river.
Listed by Saṃjaya among the rivers of
the Bhāratavarṣa; people used its water for
drinking 6. 10. 24, 13; all the rivers listed
by Saṃjaya are said to be mothers of the
universe and very strong 6. 10. 35 (for cita-
tion see Atikṛṣṇā).

वीरा
Vīrā f.: Name of a river.
Listed by Saṃjaya among the rivers of
the Bhāratavarṣa; people used its water for
drinking 6. 10. 21, 13 (for other details see
Vīravatī).

वीरिणी
Vīriṇī f.: Name of a river.
A certain fish approached the bank of the
river Vīriṇī and requested Manu, who was
practising austerities, to save it from stronger
fish; Manu took it out of the river water and
put it in a small water-jar 3. 185. 6-7, 10-11.

वृद्धकन्यायास्
*Vṛddhakanyāyās tīrtham nt.: Name
of a तीर्थ।
A. Description: Famous (ख्यातं),
large (महत्) 9. 50. 51.
B. Holiness:
According to a blessing given by Vṛddha-
kanyā one who is composed (समाहितः)
if he passes one night near the तीर्थ and
satisfies gods with oblations (तर्पयित्वा दिव्-
औकसः) he will get the fruit of one who has
observed properly chastity for sixty-four years
(चत्वारिंशतम् अष्टौ च द्वे चाष्टौ सम्-
यग् आचरेत्।यो ब्रह्मचर्यं वर्षाणि
फलं तस्य लभेत सः) 9. 51. 20-21.
C. Past event: Kuṇī Gārgya mentally created
a daughter (मानसीम् स सुतां सुभ्रूं
समुत्पादितवान् विभुः); as no one was ready
to marry her she started practising austerities;
ultimately Śṛṅgavant Gālava married her
agreeing to stay with her only for a night;
next morning she reminded her husband of
his agreement and, before leaving him, she
blessed the place where she spent the night
with him and made it a तीर्थ 9. 51. 3-20.

वृषदंश
Vṛṣadaṃśa m.: Name of a mountain.
Described as chief among the mountains
(शैलेन्द्र) 7. 57. 29; one of the mountains
seen by Arjuna when he journeyed through
space towards the north (7. 57. 23) on his
way to propitiate Śiva for his Pāśupata missile
7. 57. 16-17, 29.

वृषप्रस्थ
Vṛṣaprastha m.: Name of a mountain.
Situated in Vālakoṭī; the Pāṇḍavas lived
there before they took bath in the river Bāhuda
(वालकोट्यां वृषप्रस्थे गिराव् उष्य च
पाण्डवाः) 3. 93. 4.

वृषभ
Vṛṣabha m.: Name of a mountain.
One of the five mountains surrounding
Girivraja in the Magadha; by coming close
to one another they as if protected Girivraja
(रक्षन्तीवाभिसंहत्य संहताङ्गा गिरि-
व्रजम्) 2. 19. 2-3; all the five mountains
are described as having high peaks (महा-
शृङ्गाः), cool trees (शीतलद्रुमाः) 2. 19. 3;
the mountains were covered by forests of
Lodhra trees which were fragrant, attractive,
and their branches full of flowers; they were
liked by lovers 2. 19. 4.

वृषभङ्गिनी
Vṛṣabhaṅginī f.: Name of a river.
Listed by Saṃjaya among the rivers of
the Bhāratavarṣa; people used its water for
drinking 6. 10. 34, 13 (for other details see
Atikṛṣṇā).

वृषभा
Vṛṣabhā f.: Name of a river.
Listed by Saṃjaya among the rivers of
the Bhāratavarṣa; people used its water for
drinking 6. 10. 31, 13 (for other details see
Atikṛṣṇā).

वेण्णा
Veṇṇā f.: Name of a river.
A. Location: In the south (दक्षिण-
स्याम्) 3. 86. 1; listed by Saṃjaya among the
rivers of the Bhāratavarṣa; people used its
water for drinking 6. 10. 26, 13.
B. Des-
cription: Having holy water (पुण्यतोया);
bringing what is auspicious to the visitor
(शुभावहा) 3. 186. 95; removing fear of
sin (पापभयापहा) 3. 86. 3; thronged by
deer and birds (मृगद्विजसमाकीर्णा) and
adorned by the hermitages of ascetics (ताप-
सालयभूषिता) 3. 86. 3; all the rivers listed
by Saṃjaya are said to be mothers of the
universe and very strong 6. 10. 35 (for cita-
tion see Atikṛṣṇā).
C. Holiness: (1) By
satisfying manes and gods at Veṇṇā one
rides in a Vimāna that is drawn by peacocks
and swans (तर्पयेत् पितृदेवताः।मयूर-
हंससंयुक्तं विमानं लभते नरः)
3. 83. 29; (2) By bathing at the confluence
of Veṇṇā (वेण्णायाः संगमे स्नात्वा) one
gets the fruit of a Vājapeya 3. 83. 31.
D.
Past event: One of the rivers seen by
Mārkaṇḍeya in the belly of the Bāla (3.
186. 83 = Nārāyaṇa 3. 187. 3) 3. 186. 95.
E. Importance: (1) Listed by Mārkaṇḍeya
among the rivers which are declared to be
mothers of fire-hearths (i. e. on the banks of
which sacrifices were performed) 3. 212. 23-
24 (for citation and Nī. see Kapilā); (2)
finds mention in the Daivata-Ṛṣi-Vaṃśa 13.
151. 17, 2.

वेतसिका
Vetasikā f.: Name of a river.
Inhabited by Pitāmaha (Brahman)
(पितामहनिषेविता); one who visits it (गत्वा)
gets the fruit of an Aśvamedha and the world
of Uśanas (गच्छेच् चौशनसीं गतिम्) 3.
82. 50 (Nī., however, on Bom. Ed. 3. 84. 56:
औशनसीं गतिं शुक्रत्वम्).

वेतसिनी
Vetasinī f.: Name of a river.
Listed by Saṃjaya among the rivers of
the Bhāratavarṣa; people used its water for
drinking 6. 10. 16, 13 (for other details see
Atikṛṣṇā).

वेत्रवती
Vetravatī f.: Name of a river.
A. Location: Listed by Saṃjaya twice
among the rivers of the Bhāratavarṣa; people
used its water for drinking 6. 10. 15, 18, 13
(or in 6. 10. 18 वेत्रवती is Carmaṇvatī's
epithet ‘full of reeds’).
B. Description:
All the rivers listed by Saṃjaya are described
as mothers of the universe and very strong
(विश्वस्य मातरः सर्वाः सर्वाश् चैव
महाबलाः) 6. 10. 35.
C. Past event:
One of the rivers seen by Mārkaṇḍeya in the
belly of the Bāla (3. 186. 83 = Nārāyaṇa
3. 187. 3) 3. 186. 93.
D. Importance:
(1) Listed by Mārkaṇḍeya among rivers
which are proclaimed to be mothers of fire-
hearths, i. e. on the banks of which sacrifices
were performed 3. 212. 22 (for citation and
Nī. see Kapilā); (2) Finds mention in
the Daivata-Ṛṣi-Vaṃśa 13. 151. 16, 2.

वेदस्मृति
Vedasmṛti f.: Name of a river.
Listed by Saṃjaya among the rivers of
the Bhāratavarṣa; people used its water for
drinking 6. 10. 16, 13 (for other details see
Atikṛṣṇā); finds mention in the Daivata-
Ṛṣi-Vaṃśa 13. 151. 20, 2.

वेदाश्वा
Vedāśvā f.: Name of a river.
Listed by Saṃjaya among the rivers of
the Bhāratavarṣa; people used its water for
drinking 6. 10. 27, 13 (for other details see
Atikṛṣṇā).

वेदी
Vedī1 f.: Name of a sacred place.
Described as highly inaccessible (परम-
दुर्गमा) 3. 82. 42; by visiting it one gets
the fruit of an Aśvamedha and obtains the
condition of Uśanas (गच्छेच् चौशनसीं
गतिम्) 3. 82. 42 (Nī., however, on Bom.
Ed. 3. 84. 56: औशनसीं गतिं शुक्रत्वम्)

वेदी
Vedī2 f.: Name of a sacred place having
the form of an altar.
A. Origin: Viśvakarman offered a
sacrifice in the forest of Svayaṃbhū (Brah-
man); at this sacrifice Svayaṃbhū gave the
entire earth as दक्षिणा to Kaśyapa; angered
at being gifted to a mortal, the earth entered
Rasātala; when propitiated by Kaśyapa, the
earth emerged from water and appeared in the
form of an altar (पुनर् उन्मज्ज्य सलिताद्
वेदीरूपा स्थिता बभौ॥सैषा प्रकाशते
राजन् वेदीसंस्थानलक्षणा) 3. 114. 17-23.
B. Characteristic: If touched by a mortal
the Vedī would enter the ocean (स्पृष्टा हि
मर्त्येन ततः समुद्रम् एषा वेदी प्रविशति
 … ) 3. 114. 24; hence described as ‘going
to the ocean’ (सागरगा) 3. 114. 26.
C.
Holiness: By ascending it one is endowed
with virility (आरुह्यात्र महाराज वीर्यवान्
वै भविष्यसि) 3. 114. 23.
D. Epic event:
As advised by Lomaśa, Yudhiṣṭhira ascended
the Vedī; before he did it, Lomaśa pronounced
on him benediction (स्वस्त्ययन); Yudhi-
ṣṭhira was also to utter the following truth
(सत्यवाक्य) while ascending the altar;
अग्निर् मित्रो योनिर् आपो ऽथ देव्यो विष्णो रेतस्
त्वम् अमृतस्य नाभिः 3. 114. 24-26.

वेद्या
Vedyā f.: Name of a river.
Described as having water for most part
of the year (? बहुशोजला) 13. 26. 41; by
bathing there (उपस्पृश्य) a person becomes
one with Brahman (ब्रह्मभूतो विराजते)
13. 26. 41.

वैजयन्त
Vaijayanta m.: Name of a mountain.
A. Location: In the midst of the ocean
of milk (क्षीरोदस्य समुद्रस्य मध्ये)
12. 338. 9.
B. Description: Well known
(ख्यात) 12. 333. 9; excellent mountain
(पर्वतप्रवर) 12. 338. 9, (गिरिवर)
12. 338. 21; having lustre like that of gold
(हाटकसमप्रभ) 12. 338. 9; where god
Brahman walks (त्वत् (i. e. Brahman) पाद-
सेवित) 12. 338. 17.
C. Characteristic:
God Brahman abandons his own residence
(12. 338. 19-20) and takes his resort on this
mountain to meditate with great concentration
on Virāj Puruṣa (वैजयन्तो गिरिवरः सत-
तं सेव्यते मया।अत्रैकाग्रेण मनसा
पुरुषश् चिन्त्यते विराट्) 12. 338. 21.
D.
Mythological event: On this mountain god
Brahman, sitting all alone in his residence,
meditates constantly on the nature of the
Supreme Soul (तत्राध्यात्मगतिं देवः
एकाकी प्रविचिन्तयन्।वैराजसदने नित्यं
वैजयन्तं निषेवते॥) 12. 338. 10; once,
while he was sitting on the mountain, Śiva,
his son born to him from his forehead,
happened to go there travelling through space;
a dialogue between the two took place on
this mountain on the nature of the great,
eternal Puruṣa 12. 338. 11-25; 12. 339. 1-21.

वैडूर्यपर्वत
Vaiḍūryaparvata, Vaiḍūryaśikhara m.:
Name of a mountain.
A. Location: In the south (दक्षिण-
स्याम् 3. 86. 1) 3. 86. 15, and in the west, in
the Avanti, country (अवन्तिषु प्रतीच्यां
वै … दिशि) 3. 87. 1; the river Narmadā flows
by it 3. 121. 15; the mountain can be reached
from the river Payoṣṇī 3. 121. 15.
B. Des-
cription: Holy (पुण्य) 3. 87. 4, 6; auspi-
cious (शिव) 3. 86. 15; 3. 87. 4; excellent
mountain (गिरिवर) 3. 87. 4; illustrious
(श्रीमन्त्) 3. 86. 15; full of jewels (मणि-
मय) 3. 86. 15; heavenly (दिव्य), com-
parable with heaven (स्वर्गोपम) 3. 87. 6;
always resorted to by gods and sages (नित्यं
देवर्षिसेवितः) 3. 87. 6; meeting place of the
river Narmadā and the Vaiḍūrya mountain is
described as the meeting place of the Tretā
and the Dvāpara Yugas (सन्धिर् एष नर-
श्रेष्ठ त्रेताया द्वापरस्य च) 3. 121. 18-
19.
C. Characteristic: (1) On the peak
of this mountain is a lake of Dhīmant (?)
(तस्य शैलस्य शिखरे सरस् तत्र च धी-
मतः) which has full blown lotuses and
which is visited by gods and Gandharvas 3.
87. 5; (2) Trees on this mountain have hea-
venly flowers and fruits and they are always
green (दिव्यपुष्पफलास् तत्र पादपा हरि-
तच्छदाः) 3. 87. 4; (3) There are many
wonderful things on this mountain (बह्व्-
आश्चर्यं महाराज दृश्यते तत्र पर्वते)
3. 87. 6.
D. Holiness: By seeing (दृष्ट्वा)
the Vaiḍūrya mountain one goes to the world
of gods and (righteous) kings (देवानाम् एति
कौन्तेय तथा राज्ञां सलोकताम्) 3. 121.
18; by visiting the meeting place of Vaiḍūrya
and Narmadā one is freed of all sins 3. 121.
19.
E. Epic event: Yudhiṣṭhira and his
brothers reached the mountain after bathing
in Payoṣṇī 3. 121. 15.

वैतरणी
Vaitaraṇī1 f.: Name of a river.
A. Location: Listed by Saṃjaya among
the rivers of the Bhāratavarṣa; people used
its water for drinking 6. 10. 33, 13; in the
Kaliṅga country (एते कलिङ्गाः कौन्तेय यत्र
वैतरणी नदी) 3. 114. 4; flowing near the
तीर्थ Triviṣṭapa 3. 81. 70 and the तीर्थ Viraja
3. 83. 6.
B. Description: Holy (पुण्या) 3.
81. 70; releasing from sins (पापप्रमोचनी)
3. 81. 70; 3. 83. 6; the northern bank of
Vaitaraṇī is described as adorned by a moun-
tain; this bank is fit for performing sacrifices,
is thronged by sages and is always visited by
Brāhmaṇas (ऋषिभिः समुपायुक्तं यज्ञियं
गिरिशोभितम्।उत्तरं तीरम् एतद् धि सत-
तं द्विजसेवितम्॥) 3. 114. 5; all the rivers
listed by Saṃjaya are described as mothers
of the universe and very strong 6. 10. 35
(for citation see Atikṛṣṇā).
C. Holiness:
(1) By bathing in Vaitaraṇī and by wor-
shipping there god Vṛṣadhvaja (Śiva) one
is cleansed of all sins and he obtains the
highest condition (गच्छेत परमां गतिम्)
3. 81. 71; (2) By visiting Vaitaraṇī (and
also the तीर्थ Viraja) one shines like moon
(विराजति यथा शशी); he destroys all sins and,
(after death), is born in a meritorious family
(प्रभवेच् च कुले पुण्ये); he gets the
fruit of gifting a thousand cows and purifies
his family 3. 83. 6-7; (3) Its northern bank
specially suitable for performing sacrifices
(यज्ञियं … उत्तरं तीरम्) 3. 114. 5
(see the section on Past and mythological
events); (4) One who touches the water of
this river and recites the following गाथा
(called Anuvaṃśa of Rudra): अयातयामं
सर्वेभ्यो भागेभ्यो भागम् उत्तमम्।
देवाः संकल्पयाम् आसुर् भयाद् रुद्रस्य
शाश्वतम् (3. 114. 11) goes (to heaven)
by the देवयान and his eye shines (इमां
गाथाम् अत्र गायन्न् अपः स्पृशति यो नरः।
देवयानस् तस्य पन्थाश् चक्षुश् चैव
प्रकाशते) 3. 114. 12.
D. Epic events:
Pointed out by Lomaśa to Yudhiṣṭhira 3. 114.
4; the Pāṇḍavas and Draupadī descended into
the river Vaitaraṇī and gave offerings to manes
(अवतीर्य महाभागा (? महाभागां)
तर्पयां चक्रिरे पितॄन्) 3. 114. 13; Yudhi-
ṣṭhira told Lomaśa that by bathing (उप-
स्पृश्य) in the river he went above the realm
of human beings and saw all the worlds
and (heard) the sound of the Vaikhānasas
who were offering prayers (मानुषाद् अस्मि
विषयाद् अपेतः पश्य लोमश।सर्वाल्̃ लोकान्
प्रपश्यामि … वैखानसानाम् जपताम् एष
शब्दो महात्मनाम्) 3. 114. 14-15; Lomaśa
then told him that the sound he was hearing
was coming from a distance of three hundred
thousand योजनस् and that he should keep
quiet (तूष्णीम् आस्स्व विशां पते) 3. 114.
16.
E. Past and mythological events:
(1) Sages formerly offered sacrifices on the
bank of Vaitaraṇī and went to heaven by a
path similar to the देवयान (समेन देव-
यानेन पथा स्वर्गम् उपेयुषः।अत्र वै
ऋषयो ऽन्ये ऽपि पुरा क्रतुभिर् ईजिरे) 3. 114.
6; (2) Here Dharma himself took refuge
with gods and offered a sacrifice (यत्रायजत
धर्मो ऽपि देवाञ् शरणम् एत्य वै) 3.
114. 4; (3) Here Rudra once took away
the sacrificial animal (पशु) in a sacrifice
saying ‘this is (my) share’; gods then
requested him not to take away what belonged
to some one else and destroy the धर्मस्;
they praised Rudra and satisfied him with
a sacrifice and honoured him; Rudra then
let go the sacrificial animal and went away by
the Devayāna 3. 114. 7-10; (4) Near the
river Vaitaraṇī was the wood of Svayaṃbhū
where Viśvakarman offered a sacrifice 3. 114.
17 (for details see Vedī2).

वैतरणी
Vaitaraṇī2 f.: Name of a river.
Situated in the south 5. 107. 1; it was
sought by those who wished to go beyond
(the cycle of life and death) (अत्र वैतरणी
नाम नदी वितरणैर् वृता) (this explains
the name of the river); by reaching it one
puts an end both to happiness and misery
(अत्र गत्वा सुखस्यान्तं दुःखस्यान्तं
प्रपद्यते) 5. 107. 14 (Nī., however, on
Bom. Ed. 5. 109. 14-15: वितरणैः वैत-
रणीनदीसज्ञकनरकगामिभिः।सुख-
स्यान्तं नरकं दुःखस्यान्तं स्वर्ग-
सुखम्).

वैतरणी
Vaitaraṇī3 f.: Name of a mythological
river; also called Mahāvaitaraṇī (6. 55. 125;
8. 58. 7; 8. 68. 18)
A. Location: In the realm of Yama
(वैतरण्यां … यमक्षये) 12. 290. 31;
flows towards the kingdom of Yama (यथा
वैतरणी राजन् यमराष्ट्रपुरं प्रति) 7.
146. 47; 6. 99. 38.
B. Description: Big
river (महानदी) 12. 309. 31; hot (उष्णा)
12. 309. 31; cruel (क्रूरा) 6. 55. 125; fierce
(उग्रा) 8. 55. 42; frightful (घोरा) 16. 6.
10; very frightful (सुघोरा) 6. 55. 121;
(सुभीमा) 6. 55. 125; (महाभया) 7. 48.
50; painful to look at (दुर्दृशा) 8. 68. 18;
river of blood (असृग्जला) 7. 48. 49; (शोणि-
तौघतरङ्गिणी) 7. 146. 47; difficult to cross
(दुस्तरा) 7. 48. 50; difficult to cross by
evildoers (दुस्तरा पापकर्मभिः) 1. 158.
19; difficult to cross by those who have not
realized the Soul (वैतरणीम् … दुस्तराम्
अकृतात्मभिः) 8. 55. 42 (also see section F.
Similes below).
C. Characteristic: A
person who does evil deeds (दुष्कृतकर्मा
12. 309. 30) plunges into Vaitaraṇī; his
limbs are cut by a forest of sword-sharp
leaves and, lying on the bed of axes, he lives
in hell, severely afflicted 12. 309. 31; those
who fall in Vaitaraṇī experience grief (वैत-
रण्यां च यद् दुःखं पतितानाम्) 12.
290. 31; (knowing it the followers of the
Sāṃkhya doctrine seek knowledge and go
beyond the phenomenon of birth 12. 290. 69).
D. Form of Gaṅgā: Dvaipāyana (Vyāsa)
had declared that the river Gaṅgā became
Vaitaraṇī after reaching the world of Pitṛs
and was difficult to cross by evildoers (तथा
पितॄन् वैतरणी दुस्तरा पापकर्मभिः।
गङ्गा भवति गन्धर्व यथा द्वैपायनो
ऽब्रवीत्॥) 1. 158. 19.
E. Epic event:
When Indra and other gods and Dharma in
bodily form came to meet Yudhiṣṭhira, the
river Vaitaraṇī with its thorny Śālmali trees
disappeared (नदी वैतरणी चैव कूट-
शाल्मलिना सह (नादृश्यत)) 18. 3. 1-2,
4-5.
F. Similes: (1) The river of blood
of the warriors killed by Arjuna (6. 55. 121)
compared with Mahāvaitaraṇī (महावैत-
रणीप्रकाशाम्) 6. 55. 125; (2) The river
of blood and entrails (लोहितान्त्रतरङ्गिणी)
flowing on the field of battle and carrying
away the timid ones compared with Vaitaraṇī
which carries corpses to the city of Yama
(यथा वैतरणी प्रेतान् प्रेतराजपुरं
प्रति) 6. 99. 38; (3) The river made to flow
on the field of battle by prominent warriors
(योधवरैः प्रवर्तिता रणनदी) com-
pared to Vaitaraṇī 7. 48. 50; (4) The river
of blood with mud (शोणितकर्दमाम्॥शोणि-
तोदाम्) made to flow by Bhīma compared
with Vaitaraṇī 8. 55. 38-39, 42; (5) The
battle-field appeared like Mahāvaitaraṇī
(रणभूमिर् अभूद् राजन् महावैतरणी
यथा) 8. 58. 7; (6) Dvārakā, bereft of
Balarāma, Kṛṣṇa and other Yādava heroes,
appeared as frightful to Arjuna as Vaitaraṇī
(घोरां नदीं वैतरणीम् इव) 16. 6. 10.

वैतसिका
Vaitasikā f.: Name of a river.
Described as one that is resorted to by
Pitāmaha (Brahman); by reaching it one
gets the fruit of a horse sacrifice and obtains
the condition of Uśanas (Śukra) (पितामह-
निषेविताम्।अश्वमेधम् अवाप्नोति गच्छेच्
चौशनासीं गतिम्) 3. 82. 50 (Nī. on Bom.
Ed. 3. 84. 56: औशनसीम् गतिं शुक्रत्वम्).

वैदसिनी
Vaidasinī f.: Name of a river.
Mentioned in the Daivata-Ṛṣi-Vaṃśa 13.
151. 20, 2.

वैनन्दी
Vainandī f.: Name of a river.
Listed by Saṃjaya among the rivers of
the Bhāratavarṣa; people used its water for
drinking 6. 10. 26, 13; all the rivers listed
by Saṃjaya are described as mothers of the
universe and very strong 6. 10. 35 (for cita-
tion see Atikṛṣṇā).

वैमानिक
Vaimānika nt.: Name of a तीर्थ।
Situated near the Kiṅkiṇīkāśrama;
according to the Tīrthavaṃśa narrated by
Aṅgiras to Gautama (13. 26. 3-4) one who
bathes (उपस्पृश्य) there is able to move at
will and is glorified in the heavenly abode
of the Apsarases (निवासे ऽप्सरसां दिव्ये
कामचारी महीयते) 13. 26. 21.

वैवस्वतस्य
Vaivasvatasya tīrtham nt.: Name of a
तीर्थ।
According to the Tīrthavaṃśa narrated
by Aṅgiras to Gautama (13. 26. 3-4) one
who bathes (उपस्पृश्य) in this तीर्थ him-
self becomes a तीर्थ (तीर्थभूतो भवेन्
नरः) 13. 26. 37.

वैहायस
Vaihāyasa m.: Name of a lake (called
ह्रद, also सरस्).
Situated near the आश्रम of Naranārā-
yaṇa (समासादितवान् दिव्यं नरनारायणा-
श्रमम्।यत्र … ह्रदो वैहायसस् तथा)
12. 126. 2-3; sage Ṛṣabha (12. 126. 1) satis-
fied gods and manes at this lake by giving
offerings according to the rites and then
visited the आश्रम (तस्मिन् सरसि कृत्वाहं
विधिवत् तर्पणं पुरा।पितॄणाम् देवता-
नां च ततोऽश्रमम् इयां तदा॥) 12.
126. 2-4.

वैहार
Vaihāra m.: Name of a mountain.
One of the five mountains surrounding
Girivraja, the capital of the Magadha country;
described as having wide extent (वैहारो
विपुलः शैलः) 2. 19. 2; these five mounta-
ins, coming close to one another, as if guard-
ed the Girivraja (रक्षन्तीवाभिसंहत्य
संहताङ्गा गिरिव्रजम्) 2. 19. 3 (for the
description of the five mountains see Ṛṣigiri.

व्यासवन
Vyāsavana nt.: Name of a forest.
The lake Manojava is located in this
forest 3. 81. 78.

व्यासस्थली
Vyāsasthalī f.: Name of a sacred
place.
It was here that Vyāsa, afflicted by grief
over the disappearance of his son (Śuka)
(cf. 12. 320. 26, 32), decided to give up his
body; but his spirits were again raised by gods
(यत्र व्यासेन धीमता।पुत्रशोकाभितप्-
तेन देहत्यागार्थनिश्चयः॥कृतो देवैश्
च राजेन्द्र पुनर् उत्थापितस् तदा।); by
visiting the place one gets the fruit of gifting
a thousand cows 3. 81. 81-82.

व्योमगङ्गा
Vyomagaṅgā f.: Name of the heavenly
Gaṅgā.
After explaining to Śuka the nature
of the seven winds, who are the sons of Aditi
(एवम् एते ऽदितेः पुत्रा मारुताः परमा-
द्भुताः) 12. 315. 36-53), and after asking
him to continue his Vedic study Vyāsa left
for Vyomagaṅgā (उक्त्वा पुत्रम् अधीष्वेति
व्योमगङ्गाम् अयात् तदा) 12. 315. 57. [See
Ākāśagaṅgā]

शक्रस्य
Śakrasya tīrtham nt.: See Kumārikā-
ṇāṃ tīrtham.

शक्रावर्त
Śakrāvarta m.: Name of a तीर्थ।
One who satisfies according to the rites
gods and manes (by giving offerings) is glori-
fied in the world of the meritorious (शक्रा-
वर्ते च तर्पयन्।देवान् पितॄंश् च विधिवत्
पुण्यलोके महीयते॥) 3. 82. 25.

शङ्खतीर्थ
Śaṅkhatīrtha nt.: Name of a तीर्थ।
A. Location: On the river Sarasvatī
(तत्र तीर्थं सरस्वत्याः) 9. 36. 24;
Balarāma reached it from Gargasrotas 9.
36. 16, 19.
B. Description: Purifying
(पावन), famous in the worlds (लोक-
विश्रुत) 9. 36. 24; a तीर्थ of those who
get success (तीर्थे यशस्विनाम्) 9. 36. 25.
C. Characteristic: The famous Mahāśaṅkha
tree on the river Sarasvatī situated near it
9. 36. 20 (see Mahāśaṅkha).
D. Epic
event: Balarāma gave there vessels of copper-
iron and various kinds of garments to Brāh-
maṇas and worshipped them; he was honoured
there by ascetics (दत्त्वा … ताम्रायसानि
भाण्डानि वस्त्राणि विविधानि च); from there
he went to Dvaitavana 9. 36. 25-26.

शङ्खिनी
Śaṅkhinī f.: Name of a तीर्थ।
Sacred to Devī (देव्यास् तीर्थे); a
pilgrim, by bathing there, gets excellent form
(लभते रूपम् उत्तमम्) 3. 81. 41.

शतकुम्भा
Śatakumbhā f.: Name of a river.
Listed by Saṃjaya among the rivers of
the Bhāratavarṣa; its water used by people
for drinking 6. 10. 18, 13; all the rivers listed
by Saṃjaya are described as mothers of the
universe and very strong 6. 10. 35 (for cita-
tion see Atikṛṣṇā); also listed by Mārka-
ṇḍeya among rivers which are famous as
mothers of the sacrificial hearths (धिष्ण्या-
नां मातरो याः प्रकीर्तिताः) i. e. on the
banks of which sacrifices were performed 3.
212. 21 (for Nī. see Kapilā); by visiting it
one is glorified in heaven (अभिगम्य नर-
श्रेष्ठ स्वर्गलोके महीयते) 3. 82. 9.

शतद्रु
Śatadru f.: Name of a river; once
referred to as Śatadrukanadī (8. 30. 21).
A. Location: Listed by Saṃjaya among
the rivers of the Bhāratavarṣa; people used
its water for drinking 6. 10. 14, 13; flowing
from the Himavant (हैमवती) 1. 167. 8;
the Bāhlīka (or the Āraṭṭa) country lies
between the five rivers and Sindhu 8. 30. 11;
the five rivers are Śatadru, Vipāśā, Irāvatī,
Candrabhāgā and Vitastā 8. 30. 35-36; one
has to cross the rivers Śatadru and Irāvatī
to reach the Bāhlīka country (सा नूनम् …
माम् अनुस्मरती शेते बाह्लिकम् … ॥शतद्रु-
कनदीं तीर्त्वा तां च रम्याम् इरावतीम्।
गत्वा स्वदेशम् द्रक्ष्यामि) 8. 30. 20-21.
B. Description: Flowing from the Himavant
(हैमवती) 1. 167. 8; having ferocious
crocodiles (चण्डग्राहवती) 1. 167. 8; ex-
cellent river (सरिद्वरा) 1. 167. 9; all the
rivers listed by Umā are described as auspici-
ous (शिवाः), most holy (पुण्यतमाः) 13.
134. 22; having waters of all the तीर्थस्
(सर्वतीर्थोदकैर् युताः) 13. 134. 12; ex-
cellent rivers (सरिद्वराः), (सरितां वराः),
(सरिच्छ्रेष्ठाः) 13. 134. 14, 19, 22; flow-
ing to the ocean (सागरगमाः) 13. 134.
21; expert in the knowledge of the duties of
women (स्त्रीधर्मकुशलाः) 12. 134. 19;
all the rivers listed by Saṃjaya are described
as mothers of the universe and very strong
6. 10. 35 (for citation see Atikṛṣṇā).
C.
Name explained: When Vasiṣṭha jumped
into a river to end his life, the river, feeling
him like fire, ran into hundred streams; hence
the river came to be known as Śatadru (सा
तम् अग्निसमं विप्रम् अनुचिन्त्य सरिद्-
वरा।शतधा विद्रुता यस्माच् छतद्रुर्
इति स्मृता) 1. 167. 9.
D. Past events:
(1) Vasiṣṭha, grieved over the death of his
sons, made attempts to end his life; once he
threw himself in a river which later came to
be known as Śatadru 1. 166. 39; 1. 167. 8;
(2) One of the rivers seen by Mārkaṇḍeya
in the belly of the Bāla (3. 186. 83 = Nārā-
yaṇa 3. 187. 3) 3. 186. 93.
E. Impor-
tance: (1) One of the rivers who wait up-
on Śiva for his bath (उपस्पर्शनहेतोस् त्वा
समीपस्था उपासते) 13. 134. 12; (2)
Umā wanted to consult rivers, one of them
being Śatadru, on स्त्रीधर्म before expound-
ing it to Śiva 13. 134. 13, 20; Umā thus
wanted to honour them 13. 134. 14, 25;
(3) One of the rivers who, in bodily form
(2. 9. 21), wait on Varuṇa in his Sabhā
2. 9. 19; (4) Finds mention in the Daivata-
Ṛṣi-Vaṃśa 13. 151. 14, 2.

शतबला
Śatabalā f.: Name of a river.
Listed by Saṃjaya among the rivers of
the Bhāratavarṣa; people used its water for
drinking 6. 10. 19, 13; all the rivers listed
by Saṃjaya are said to be mothers of the
universe and very strong 6. 10. 35 (for
citation see Atikṛṣṇā).

शतशृङ्ग
Śataśṛṅga m.: Name of a mountain.
A. Location: Beyond the Gandha-
mādana and Haṃsakūṭa mountains (प्रय-
यौ गन्धमादनम् … हंसकूटम् अतीत्य
च) 1. 110. 43, 45.
B. Description: King
of mountains (शैलराज) 1. 111. 5, 10.
C. Characteristic: Siddhas and Cāraṇas
lived there 1. 111. 1; so also Brāhmaṇas
(विप्राः) 1. 115. 21, sages (ऋषयः) 1. 113.
3, and ascetics (तापसाः) 1. 111. 5, (तप-
स्विनां … शतशृङ्गनिवासिनाम्) 1. 114.
37; 8. 48. 11; 1. 110. 45;
D. Epic
events: (1) Forsaking all enjoyments
Pāṇḍu repaired to this mountain 1. 117. 20;
when he, with his two wives, reached Śata-
śṛṅga he became an ascetic (शतशृङ्गे …
तापसः समपद्यत) 1. 110. 45; there he
practised austerities of a high order (तत्रापि
तपसि श्रेष्ठे वर्तमानः) 1. 111. 1; when
Pāṇḍu, with his wives, wanted to go further
northwards from this mountain he was dis-
suaded by the ascetics who lived there 1. 111.
5, 10; (2) When the Pāṇḍavas were born,
the Brāhmaṇas who lived on Śataśṛṅga gave
them names (नामानि चक्रिरे तेषां शत-
शृङ्गनिवासिनः) 1. 115. 19; (3) A week after
Arjuna's birth an invisible voice from sky on
top of Śataśṛṅga told Kuntī the future heroic
deeds of Arjuna (इत्य् अन्तरिक्षे शतशृङ्ग-
मूर्ध्नि तपस्विनां शृण्वतां वाग् उवाच)
8. 48. 6-11 (a reference to 1. 114. 28-36);
the ascetics living on Śataśṛṅga were delighted
to hear the incorporeal voice which were the
words spoken by Vāyu in sky (वाग् उवाचा-
शरीरिणी। … उक्तवान् वायुर् आकाशे … ।वाचम्
उच्चारिताम् … निशम्य तपस्विनाम्।बभूव
परमो हर्षः शतशृङ्गनिवासिनाम्॥) 1.
114. 28, 37; (4) Kuntī told the Pāṇḍavas
when they started for the forest that if she had
known what was in their store she, after the
death of Pāṇḍu, would not have returned
from Śataśṛṅga to Hāstinapura 2. 70. 17;
(5) One of the mountains seen by Arjuna
when he, with Kṛṣṇa, went at night to Śiva's
abode to obtain his Pāśupata 7. 57. 16-17,
28.
E. Past event: In the sacrifices of
the ancestors of Sulabhā, for the चयन,
the mountains Droṇa, Śataśṛṅga and Vakra-
dvāra were used as bricks with the help of
Maghavant (मम सत्रेषु पूर्वेषां चिता
मघवता सह) 12. 308. 183 (Nī. on Bom.
Ed. 12. 320. 82: द्रोणादयः पर्वताः मम
पूर्वेषां सत्रेषु मघवता सह चिताः
चयने इष्टकास्थाने निवेशिता इत्य् अर्थः).

शतसहस्रक
Śatasahasraka nt.: Name of a तीर्थ।
Situated near the Sāhasraka तीर्थ; both
the तीर्थस् were famous in the world (द्वे-
तीर्थे लोकविश्रुते) 3. 81. 137; by bathing
there one got the fruit of giving a thousand
cows, and his gifts and fasts would give him
a thousandfold benefit (दानं वाप्य् उपवासो
वा सहस्रगुणितं भवेत्) 3. 81. 138.

शतसाहस्रिक
Śatasāhasrika nt.: Name of a तीर्थ।
Situated on the river Gomatī, near
Rāmatīrtha 3. 82. 66-67; by bathing in it
(उपस्पर्शनम्) and by controlling oneself
and taking limited food (नियतो नियताशनः)
one gets the fruit of gifting a thousand cows
3. 82. 67.

शतावरी
Śatāvarī f.: Name of a river.
Listed by Saṃjaya among the rivers of
the Bhāratavarṣa; people used its water for
drinking 6. 10. 19, 13 (for other details see
Atikṛṣṇā).

शन्तनोस्
Śantanos tīrtham nt.: See Lalitikā.

शरयू
Śarayū f.: See Sarayū.

शर्यातिवन
Śaryātivana nt.: Name of a forest.
One of the regions over which Arjuna
flew when he, with Kṛṣṇa, went during the
night to see Śiva to get his Pāśupata 7. 57.
16-17, 28.

शलु
Śalu f.: Name of a river.
Listed by Saṃjaya among the rivers of
the Bhāratavarṣa; people used its water for
drinking 6. 10. 27, 13 (for other details see
Atikṛṣṇā).

शशयान
Śaśayāna nt.: Name of a तीर्थ।
A. Location: Located on the river Sara-
svatī (सरस्वत्याम् … स्नायन्ते) 3. 80. 121.
B. Description: Described as difficult to
reach (दुर्लभ) 3. 80. 120.
C. Chara-
cteristic: Lotuses in this तीर्थ are concealed
since they appear in the form of rabbits
(शशरूपप्रतिच्छन्नाः पुष्करा यत्र
भारत) 3. 80. 120 (this explains the name
of the तीर्थ ?).
D. Holiness: People
bathe (in this तीर्थ) on Sarasvatī all the
year round (सरस्वत्यां महाराज अनु
संवत्सरं हि ते।स्नायन्ते); if one bathes
there on the full moon day of the Kārtika
month one shines always like the moon and in
addition gets the fruit of gifting a thousand
cows (वृत्तां वै कार्तिकीं सदा॥तत्र
स्नात्वा नरव्याघ्र द्योतते शशिवत् सदा।
गोसहस्रफलं चैव प्राप्नुयात्) 3. 80.
121-122.

शशिकान्ता
Śaśikāntā f.: Name of a river.
Listed by Saṃjaya among the rivers of
the Bhāratavarṣa; people used its water for
drinking 6. 10. 24, 13 (for other details see
Atikṛṣṇā).

शाक
Śāka m.: Name of a tree of the Śāka-
dvīpa.
Described as famous (विख्यात) and
a big tree (महाद्रुम); it is situated in
the middle of that Dvīpa (तस्य मध्ये
महाद्रुमः॥शाको नाम महाराज तस्य
द्वीपस्य मध्यगः।) 6. 12. 25-26.

शाकम्भरी
Śākambharī f.: Name of a place
(स्थानम्) sacred to goddess Śākambharī.
A. Description: Place of the famous
goddess, known in the three worlds as Śākam-
bharī; very difficult of access (देव्याः स्था-
नं सुदुर्लभम्।शाकम्भरीति विख्याता
त्रिषु लोकेषु विश्रुता) 3. 82. 11.
B. Holi-
ness: One who practises austerities and is
composed (ब्रह्मचारी समाहितः) should
visit Śākambharī and stay there for three
nights; pure and controlled (नियतः शुचिः)
he should eat only vegetables; he thereby
obtains the fruit of living only on vegetables
for twelve years; this happens by the will of
the goddess (शाकाहारस्य यत् सम्यग् वर्-
षैर् द्वादशभिः फलम्।तत् फलं तस्य
भवात् देव्याश् छन्देन) 3. 82. 14-15 (Nī.
on Bom. Ed. 3. 84. 18: छन्देन इच्छया).

शालिशूर्प
Śāliśūrpa nt.: Name of a तीर्थ।
A तीर्थ of Śālihotra (शालिहोत्रस्य शालि-
शूर्पे); by bathing there according to the
prescribed rites one gets the fruit of giving
a thousand cows 3. 81. 90.

शालूकिनी
Śālūkinī f.: Name of a river (?).
Daśāśvamedhika तीर्थ is situated there
3. 81. 11.

शिवा
Śivā f.: Name of a river.
Listed by Saṃjaya among the rivers of
the Bhāratavarṣa; people used its water for
drinking 6. 10. 24, 13 (for other details see
Atikṛṣṇā).

शिवोद्भेद
Śivodbheda m.: Name of a तीर्थ।
One of the three places—the other two
being Camasa and Nāgodbheda—where the
river Sarasvatī reappears after disappearing
at Vinaśana on a desert place (गच्छत्य्
अन्तर्हिता यत्र (i. e. विनशने) मरुपृष्ठे
सरस्वती।चमसे च शिवोद्भेदे नागोद्भेदे
च दृश्यते॥) 3. 80. 118; by bathing there
one gets the fruit of giving a thousand cows
3. 80. 119.

शीघ्रा
Śīghrā f.: Name of a river.
Listed by Saṃjaya among the rivers of
the Bhāratavarṣa; people used its water for
drinking 6. 10. 28, 13 (for other details see
Atikṛṣṇā).

शीतवन
Śītavana nt.: Name of a forest.
There is a तीर्थ in this forest; it is
great and one similar to it is difficult to find
elsewhere (तीर्थं तत्र महाराज महद्
अन्यत्र दुर्लभम्); one who is controlled
and takes limited food (नियतो नियताशनः)
should go there; it purifies some people by its
mere sight, others by prostration (?) (पुनाति
दर्शनाद् एव दण्डेनैकं नराधिप);
(however Arjunamiśra: एकम् इति तृतीयार्थे
द्वितीया; cf. Cr. Edn. fn. to st. 49), and still
others by sprinkling water on their hair (केशान्
अभ्युक्ष्य वै तस्मिन् पूतो भवति भारत)
3. 81. 48-49.

शुक्तिमती
Śuktimatī f.: Name of a river.
A. Location: It flows by the city of
king Vasu Uparicara (पुरोपवाहिनीं तस्य
नदीं शुक्तिमतीम्) 1. 57. 32; listed by
Saṃjaya among the rivers of the Bhārata-
varṣa; people used its water for drinking 6.
10. 33, 13.
B. Description: All the rivers
listed by Saṃjaya are said to be mothers of
the universe and very strong 6. 10. 35 (for
citation see Atikṛṣṇā).
C. Past event:
The mountain Kolāhala, who had gained con-
sciousness, obstructed the course of the
river Śuktīmatī as he was enamoured of her
(अरौत्सीच् चेतनायुक्तः कामात् कोलाहलः
किल); Vasu struck the mountain with his
foot and the river gushed forth from the
hole produced by the stroke of the foot; the
mountain begot on the river two children—a
male and a female; this was reported to the
king by the river; the king, delighted by her
release, made the male chief his child of army
and married the female 1. 57. 32-35.

शुक्तिमत्|शुक्तिमन्त्
Śuktimant m.: Name of a mountain.
Listed by Saṃjaya among the seven
principal mountain ranges (कुलपर्वताः)
of the Bhāratavarṣa, there are many other
thousands of mountains near them (तेषां
सहस्रशो राजन् पर्वतास् तु समीपतः)
6. 10. 10-11.

शुभस्कन्ध
Śubhaskandha m.: Name of a moun-
tain.
One of the mountains described by
Brahman to the sages as kings of mountains
(एते पर्वतराजानः) 14. 43. 5.

शूर्पारक
Śūrpāraka m., nt.: Name of a place
and a तीर्थ; also called once Sūrpāraka
(13. 26. 47).
A. Location: In the south (दक्षिण-
स्याम्) 3. 86. 1; (दक्षिणां दिशम्) 2. 28.
1; in the south, along the seacoast (पारं
समुद्रस्य दक्षिणे) 12. 49. 58; (शूर्पा-
रकं देशं सागरस्य) 12. 49. 59; on
the western border of the earth (सो ऽपरान्तं
महीतलम्) 12. 49. 59; one of the तीर्थस्
along the seacoast (तानि तीर्थानि च साग-
रस्य) 3. 118. 8; (तेन तीर्थेन तु साग-
रस्य) 3. 118. 15; Rāmatīrtha located near
it (?) 3. 83. 40.
B. Description: Most
holy (पुण्यतम) 3. 118. 8.
C. Chara-
cteristic: Frequented by Jāmadagnya 3. 83.
40; there are two altars (वेदी) of Jāmadag-
nya called Pāṣāṇatīrthā and Puraścandrā at
Śūrpāraka 3. 86. 9.
D. Holiness: By
bathing in waters of Sūrpāraka and by
observing fast for a fortnight one becomes a
prince (उपस्पृश्य तथा सूर्पारकोदके।
एकपक्षनिराहारो राजपुत्रो विधीयते) 13.
26. 47.
E. Epic events: (1) Śūrpāraka
was conquered by Sahadeva in his expedition
to the south before the Rājasūya 2. 28. 43;
(2) Visited by the Pāṇḍavas in their तीर्थ-
यात्रा 3. 118. 8; after visiting some more
places, they returned to Śūrpāraka 3. 118.
14.
F. Past event: When Kaśyapa asked
Rāma Jāmadagnya to go to the southern sea-
coast, the ocean, due to fear of Rāma, (re-
ceded and) vacated space for him; that space
emptied by the ocean, which was on the
western border of the earth, came to be known
as Śūrpāraka (ततः शूर्पारकं देशं
सागरस् तस्य निर्ममे।संत्रासाज् जाम-
दग्न्यस्य सो ऽपरान्तं महीतलम्) 12.
49. 59.

शृङ्ग
Śṛṅga, Śṛṅgavant, Śṛṅgin m.: Name
of a mountain.
A. Location: To the south of Śṛṅgin
and to the north of Śveta lies the Varṣa
called Hairaṇvata 6. 9. 5 (according to 6.
7. 35 Hairaṇyaka); beyond Śṛṅga and to its
north and up to the coast of the ocean
lies the Varṣa called Airāvata (उत्तरेण तु
शृङ्गस्य समुद्रान्ते जनाधिप।वर्षम्
ऐरावतं नाम तस्माच् छृङ्गवतः परम्)
6. 9. 10; 6. 7. 35.
B. Description: Beset
with all kinds of minerals (सर्वधातु-
विनद्ध) 6. 7. 3; Śṛṅgavant is one of the
six mountains listed by Saṃjaya which are
called mountains of precious stones (षड्
एते रत्नपर्वताः); all of them stretch to-
ward the east and are merged at both ends
in the eastern and western oceans (प्रागा-
यताः … अवगाढा ह्य् उभयतः समु-
द्रौ पूर्वपश्चिमौ) 6. 7. 2; all of them
are visited by the Siddhas and Cāraṇas
(सिद्धचारणसेविताः) 6. 7. 4; the distance
between these mountains extends to thousands
of योजनस् (तेषाम् अन्तरविष्कम्भो योज-
नानि सहस्रशः) 6. 7. 4; (see also the next
section).
C. Characteristics: (1) There
are only three peaks on this mountain; one
of them is full of jewels, the other is golden
and wonderful, and the third is full of all
kinds of precious stones and is adorned with
palatial mansions (शृङ्गाणि वै शृङ्गवतस्
त्रीण्य् एव मनुजाधिप।एकं मणिमयं
तत्र तथैकं रौक्मम् अद्भुतम्॥सर्व-
रत्नमयं चैकं भवनैर् उपशोभि-
तम्) 6. 9. 8-9; (2) The goddess Śāṇḍilī,
who is self-luminous, always lives there
(तत्र स्वयंप्रभा देवी नित्यं वसति
शाण्डिली) 6. 9. 9; (3) Manes haunt Śṛṅga-
vant (शृङ्गवांस् तु महाराज पितॄणां
प्रतिसंचरः) 6. 7. 49.
D. Importance:
Finds mention in the Daivata-Ṛṣi-Vaṃśa 13.
151. 26, 2.

शैलोदा
Śailodā f.: Name of a river.
Flows between the mountains Meru and
Mandara; there is a lovely shade of different
kinds of bamboos on its banks (कीचकवेणू-
नां छायां रम्याम् उपासते) 2. 48. 2.

शैशिर
Śaiśira m.: Name of a mountain (one
of the ranges of Himavant).
A. Location: In the north (प्रायाद्
उदङ्मुखः।शैशिरं गिरिम् उद्दिश्य)
12. 314. 2 (Nī. on Bom. Ed. 12. 327. 2:
शैशिरं गिरिं हिमालयम्); near the Bhṛgu-
tuṅga range 3. 163. 10.
B. Characteristic:
Considered extremely unshakable; hence
Bhīma boasted that his arms were capable
of toppling down even the Śaiśira mountain
(समर्थौ पर्वतस्यापि शैशिरस्य निपा-
तने) 7. 170. 48.
C. Epic event: As
advised by a Brāhmaṇa living at Bhṛgutuṅga,
Arjuna went up the Śaiśira mountain to
practise austerities (गिरिम् आरुह्य शैशिरम्।
तपो ऽतप्यं महाराज); he met there a
boar chased by a Kirāta (Śiva) 3. 163.
14, 17, 19 (Nī. on Bom. Ed. 3. 167. 15:
शैशिरं हिममयम्); on the day following
Arjuna's encounter with the Kirāta, there
blew holy wind and heavenly, fresh, fragrant
flowers appeared at the foot of Śaiśira (शै-
शिरस्य गिरेः पादे प्रादुरासन् समन्ततः)
3. 164. 8; he saw there Indra and other gods;
he received missiles from Kubera and other
gods and a promise from Indra to give him
all heavenly missiles at his residence; when
the heavenly chariot of Indra was brought to
Arjuna by Mātali, he bade farewell to Śaiśira
and mounted the chariot after making a
प्रदक्षिणा (of the chariot) (गिरिम् आमन्-
त्र्य शैशिरम्।प्रदक्षिणम् उपावृत्य
समारोहं रथोत्तमम्॥) 1. 164. 9-34.
D. Past event: When instructed by Janaka,
Śuka flew like wind towards the north to the
Śaiśira mountain to meet Vyāsa 12. 314. 2.
[See Himavant]

शोण
Śoṇa m., Soṇā f.: Name of a river.
A. Source and location: Listed by
Saṃjaya (Śoṇā) among the rivers of the
Bhāratavarṣa; people used its water for drink-
ing 6. 10. 28, 13; in the east; Kṛṣṇa, Bhīma
and Arjuna crossed the rivers Gaṅgā and
Śoṇa while proceeding towards the east to the
Magadha country (उत्तीर्य गङ्गां शोणं
च सर्वे ते प्राङ्मुखास् त्रयः … जग्मुर्
मागधं क्षेत्रम्) 2. 18. 29; the river
flew between Gaṇḍakīyā and Sadānīrā rivers
(गण्डकीयां तथा शोणं सदानीरां त-
थैव च … क्रमेणैत्य व्रजन्ति ते) 2. 18.
27; the three rivers rise on the same moun-
tain (एकपर्वतके नद्यः) 2. 18. 27; its
source is known as Vaṃśagulma which is
also the source of Narmadā (शोणस्य नर्-
मदायाश् च प्रभवे कुरुनन्दन।वंश-
गुल्मे) 3. 83. 9.
B. Description: All
the rivers listed by Saṃjaya are said to be
mothers of the universe and very strong 6.
10. 35 (for citation see Atikṛṣṇā).
C.
Holiness: (1) A pure person (शुचिः) who
lives (निवसन्) at the confluence of Jyoti-
rathyā and Śoṇa and satisfies manes and
gods gets the fruit of an Agniṣṭoma 3. 83.
8; (2) By bathing (उप्स्पृश्य) at Vaṃśa-
gulma, the source of Śoṇa and Narmadā,
one gets the fruit of a horse sacrifice 3. 83.
9; (3) Listed by Mārkaṇḍeya among rivers
which are declared to be mothers of fire-
hearths, i. e. on the banks of which sacrifices
were performed 3. 212. 24 (for citation and
Nī. see Kapilā).
D. Epic event: Śoṇa
was one of the rivers crossed by Kṛṣṇa, Bhīma
and Arjuna when they left Indraprastha to go
to the Magadha country 2. 18. 27, 29.
E.
Past event: Śoṇa is one of the rivers seen
by Mārkaṇḍeya in the belly of the Bāla (3.
186. 83 = Nārāyaṇa 3. 187. 3) 3. 186. 95.

श्याम
Śyāma m.: Name of a mountain.
A. Location: One of the seven moun-
tains of the Śākadvīpa, located in its north
(उत्तरेण तु राजेन्द्र श्यामो नाम महा-
गिरिः) 6. 12. 17; the distance in योजनस्
between the seven mountains doubles as one
progresses from the one to the other (तेषां
योजनविष्कम्भो द्विगुणः प्रविभागशः)
6. 12. 22; the name of the Varṣa of Śyāma
mountain is Maṇīcaka 6. 12. 24.
B. Des-
cription: Big mountain (महागिरि) 6. 12.
17; all the seven mountains of the Śākadvīpa
are described as adorned with jewels and
mines of precious stones (तथैव पर्वता
राजन् सप्तात्र मणिभूषिताः।रत्नाकराः)
6. 12. 13.
C. Characteristic: Owing to
the existence of Śyāma (black) mountain
in Śākadvīpa the people there are black in
colour; the reason for the black colour of the
mountain as told by Saṃjaya to Dhṛtarāṣṭra,
is that god Kṛṣṇa lives on that mountain and
the colour of the mountain has turned black
due to Kṛṣṇa's colour (श्यामो नाम महा-
गिरिः।यतः श्यामत्वम् आपन्नाः प्रजा
जनपदेश्वर॥ … श्यामो यस्मात् प्रवृत्तो
वै तत् ते वक्ष्यामि भारत।आस्ते ऽत्र भग-
वान् कृष्णस् तत्कान्त्या श्यामतां गतः॥)
6. 12. 17, 20.

श्रीकुञ्ज
Śrīkuñja nt.: Name of a तीर्थ।
On the river Sarasvatī (सरस्वत्यां
तीर्थम्); one who bathes there gets the fruit
of an Agniṣṭoma sacrifice 3. 81. 91.

श्रीतीर्थ
Śrītīrtha nt.: Name of a तीर्थ।
One who reaches there (समासाद्य)
gets the best prosperity (विन्दते श्रियम्
उत्तमाम्) 3. 81. 37.

श्रीपर्वत
Śrīparvata m.: Name of a mountain.
Mahādeva with the goddess (Umā) lived
on this mountain; god Brahman, surrounded
by other gods, also lived there 3. 83. 17; a
river flows along the mountain Śrīparvata;
by bathing on its bank (नदीतीर उपस्पृशेत्)
one gets the fruit of an Aśvamedha and
goes to heaven 3. 83. 16; one who is pure
and has controlled his mind he, by bathing
in the तीर्थ Devahrada there, gets the fruit
of an Aśvamedha and attains highest success
(शुचिः प्रयतमानसः।अश्वमेधम् अवा-
प्नोति परां सिद्धिं च गच्छति) 3. 83. 18.

श्वानलोमापनयन
Śvānalomāpanayana, Śvānalomāpaha
nt.: Name of a तीर्थ।
Situated in the Śītavana (तीर्थं तत्र
महाराज श्वानलोमापहं स्मृतम्) 3. 81.
48, 50; at this तीर्थ pilgrims who are ex-
cellent Brāhmaṇas remove the hair of dogs
by doing breath exercises (?); by purifying
thus their souls they reach the highest condi-
tion (यत्र विप्राः … तीर्थतत्पराः॥श्वा-
नलोमापनयने तीर्थे भरतसत्तम।
प्राणायामैर् निर्हरन्ति श्वलोमानि द्विजो-
त्तमाः।पूतात्मानश् च राजेन्द्र प्रयान्ति
परमां गतिम्) 3. 81. 50-51.

श्वेत
Śveta m.: Name of a mountain.
A. Origin: The seed secreted by Rudra
became the Śveta mountāin (रुद्रेण शुक्रम्
उत्सृष्टं तच् छ्वेतः पर्वतो ऽभवत्) 3.
218. 27.
B. Location: In the north
(उदीच्याम्) 7. 57. 23; in the north, beyond
the Himavant and Niṣkuṭa mountains 2. 24.
27; beyond the Śveta is the land of the Kiṃ-
puruṣas (श्वेतपर्वतं … समतिक्रम्य …
देशं किंपुरुषावासम्) 2. 25. 1; in the
vicinity of the Uṣīrabīja, Malnāka and Kāla-
śaila mountains 3. 140. 1, and of Mandara
3. 140. 4; the Ramaṇaka varṣa is to the south
of Śveta and to the north of Nīla 6. 9. 2; to
the south of Śṛṅgin and to the north of Śveta
is the Hairaṇvata varṣa 6. 9. 5; one of the six
mountains listed by Saṃjaya which extend
to the east (प्रागायताः) and merge at both
ends in the eastern and the western ocean
(अवगाढा ह्य् उभयतः समुद्रौ पूर्व-
पश्चिमौ) 6. 7. 2; the distance between these
mountains is thousands of योजनस् (तेषाम्
अन्तरविष्कम्भो योजनानि सहस्रशः) 6.
7. 4.
C. Description: Shining (शुभ)
3. 155. 28; big mountain (महागिरि) 3. 214.
30; 9. 59. 8; huge (अतिप्रमाण) 5. 47. 66;
king of mountains (पर्वतराजन्) 3. 155.
4; excellent among mountains (शिखरिणां
वरम्) 3. 155. 4; heap of rocks (शिलोच्चय)
5. 47. 66; having many summits (नाना-
समुच्छ्रय) 3. 155. 28; its top (शैल-
पृष्ठ) not easy to reach (सुदुर्गम) 3.
214. 12; having bright forests (शुभकानन)
3. 220. 22; covered with thickets of reeds
(शरस्तम्बैः सुसंवृतम्) 3. 214. 10;
golden (काञ्चन) 3. 220. 21; delightful due
to gold and jewels (मङीकाञ्चनरम्य) 3.
155. 28; inlaid with silver (रजताचित) 3.
186. 102; 13. 151. 26, and bright like silver
(रजतप्रभ) 6. 7. 3 (does रजत here stand
for महारजत ‘gold’ ?); variegated due to
many kinds of minerals (बहुधातुविचित्र)
9. 59. 8; looking like a big dense cloud (महा-
भ्रघनसंकाशं), and full of water
(सलिलोपहितम्) 3. 155. 28; full of Rakṣases,
Piśācas, frightful Bhūtas, Rākṣasīs, and many
animals and birds (रक्षोभिश् च पिशाचैश्
च रौद्रैर् भूतगणैस् तथा।राक्षसी-
भिश् च सम्पूर्णम् अनेकैश् च मृगद्वि-
जैः) 3. 214. 11; all the six mountains listed
by Saṃjaya are described as stretching to-
wards the east (प्रागायताः), jewelled moun-
tains (रत्नपर्वताः), and frequented by
the Siddhas and the Cāraṇas (सिद्धचारण-
सेविताः) 6. 7. 2, 4 (also see the next section).
D. Characteristics: (1) On the Śvetagiri
(and Mandara) live the Yakṣa Māṇicara
and Kubera, the king of the Yakṣas; eighty-
eight thousand quick moving (शीघ्रचारिणः)
Gandharvas, Kiṃpuruṣas and their four times
Yakṣas, having many forms and weapons
serve there Māṇibhadra, the chief of the
Yakṣas 3. 140. 4-6; (2) The mountain is
protected by strange snakes having seven
heads and poisonous eyes (दृष्टिविषैः सप्त-
शीर्षैर् गुप्तं भोगिभिर् अद्भुतैः) 3.
214. 11; (3) Śveta mountain shone with the
flowering Saṃtānaka forests, forests of Kara-
vīra, Pārijāta, Japā and Aśoka trees, clusters
of Kadamba trees and hosts of heavenly
animals and birds (दिव्यैर् मृगगणैर् अपि।
दिव्यैः पक्षिगणैश् चैव शुशुभे श्वेत-
पर्वतः) 3. 220. 23-24; (4) Are the
Śveta and the other mountains listed by
Brahman to be looked upon as characterized
by the middle quality (मध्यम गुण),
i. e. by the quality रजस् ? 14. 43. 4, 1 (Nī.
on Bom. Ed. 14. 43. 1: मध्यमो गुणः
रजोगुणप्रधानः).
E. Importance:
(1) Listed by Brahman among mountains
called ‘kings of mountains’ (पर्वतराजा-
नः) 14. 43. 4; (2) Finds mention in the
Daivata-Ṛṣi-Vaṃśa 13. 151. 26, 2.
F. Epic
events: (1) Arjuna, in his expedition to the
north before the Rājasūya, reached the Śveta
mountain after conquering the peoples on the
Himavant and the Niṣkūṭa mountains and
lived there 2. 24. 2; he then crossed Śveta and
conquered the country of the Kiṃpuruṣas 2.
25. 1-2; (2) The Pāṇḍavas in their journey
northwards in the company of Lomaśa were to
enter it and proceed to inaccessible mountains
3. 140. 1, 4, 8; it was agreed that the Pāṇḍa-
vas were to meet Arjuna, who had left for
heavenly missiles, on the Śveta mountain at
the end of the fifth year of Arjuna's student-
ship 3. 155. 3-5; after killing Jaṭāsura, the
Pāṇḍavas entered Śveta from Nārāyaṇā-
śrama (3. 155. 1) on the fourth day (पर्-
वतं विविशुः श्वेतं चतुर्थे ऽहनि पाण्ड-
वाः) 3. 155. 27; (3) Seen by Arjuna
during the night on his way to the north to
propitiate Śiva for his Pāśupata 7. 57. 23.
G. Past and mythological events: (1)
When Nahuṣa became the king of heaven he
enjoyed at many places, one of them being
the Śveta mountain 5. 11. 9; (2) The sage
Mārkaṇḍeya saw Śveta among other moun-
tains in the belly of the Bāla (3. 186. 83 =
Nārāyaṇa 3. 187. 3) 3. 186. 102; (3) When
Dakṣa's daughter Svāhā in the form of Śivā,
the wife of Aṅgiras, held the seed of Agni
she took the form of a Suparṇī Garuḍī and
flew away; when she saw Śveta she poured
the seed in a golden pot on the top of the
mountain; this she did six times on each
प्रतिपद् day; Kumāra (Skanda) with six
heads was born; the child played on the top
of the mountain 3. 213. 52; 3. 214. 1, 7,
9-10, 15, 17, 26; the Kṛttikās gathered (?)
the seed of Pāvaka (Agni) on the mountain
Śveta (पावकस्येन्द्रियं श्वेते कृत्तिकाभिः
कृतं नगे) 3. 218. 27; the child Kumāra
sitting on the top of the mountain saw all
directions by his different heads; he drew his
bow and shot arrows at Śveta and pierced the
Krauñca mountain, the son of Himavant;
he then hurled a शक्ति which by its impact
broke the summit of Śveta; the mountain,
afraid, deserted the earth and flew up in the
sky with other mountains; later Śveta return-
ed to the earth 3. 214. 27, 30-31, 34-35, 37;
Skanda, surrounded by hosts of Piśācas and
gods, shone on the golden mountain Śveta;
the whole world, including Indra, looked at the
delighted Skanda and was not tired of looking
at him; there were also the rest of gods and
all great sages to look at Skanda; there one
heard the sounds of musical instruments, of the
dancing heavenly Gandharvas and Apsarases
and of the delighted beings 3. 220. 21, 25-27;
(4) Rāmāyaṇa events: (i) Avindhya, an old
learned Rākṣasa, saw in a dream that while
Kumbhakarṇa and other demons, wearing red
garlands, were being dragged to the south,
Vibhīṣaṇa and his four counsellors alone, with
white parasole and head-gear, all wearing
white garlands, mounted on top of the Śveta
mountain 3. 264. 65-67; (ii) a Guhyaka, with
marvellous water sent by Kubera, arrived
from Śveta mountain to Rāma and Lakṣmaṇa
3. 273. 9.
H. Similes: (1) Duḥsaha,
who had put on a lustrous armour and a
golden garland looked like the Śveta moun-
tain engulfed by fire (अग्निनेव गिरिः श्वेतः)
11. 19. 21; (2) Balarāma holding the plough
in his raised hand looked like the big Śveta
mountain (ततो लाङ्गलम् उद्यम्य … तस्-
योर्ध्वबाहोः सदृशं रूपम् आसीत् महात्-
मनः … श्वेतस्येव महागिरेः॥) 9. 59.
7-8; (3) The serpent Śeṣa with different
ornaments on his person had the appearance
of Śveta mountain (श्वेतोच्चयनिभाकारः)
5. 101. 3; (4) Gāndhārī and other Kaurava
women came out of houses which looked like
the Śveta mountain (श्वेतपर्वतरूपेभ्यो
गृहेभ्यः) 11. 9. 11; (5) The tree called
Mahāśaṅkha at the Śaṅkhatīrtha was like
Śveta mountain (महाशङ्खम् … श्वेत-
पर्वतसंकाशम्) 9. 36. 20.
I. Use in
an illustration: According to Arjuna one who
wants to win victory in a battle over Vāsu-
deva wants to split the huge Śveta mountain
with his palm; in such an effort his palm,
along with nails, will be shattered and he
will do no harm to the mountain (गिरिं य
इच्छेत तलेन भेत्तुं शिलोच्चयं श्वेतम्
अतिप्रमाणम्।तस्यैव पाणिः सनखो
विशीर्येन् न चापि किंचित् स गिरेस् तु कुर्यात्)
5. 47. 66.

षष्टिह्रद
Ṣaṣṭihrada m.: Name of a तीर्थ।
There is no gift superior to taking bath
in Ṣaṣṭihrada (षष्टिह्रद उपस्पृश्य दानं
नान्यद् विशिष्यते) 13. 26. 34.

संवर्तस्य
Saṃvartasya vāpī f.: Name of a sacred
tank.
Sacred to the brahmanical sage Saṃ-
varta; described as not easily accessible (दुर्-
लभा); one who visits it becomes handsome
and fortunate (रूपस्य भागी भवति सु-
भगश् चैव जायते) 3. 83. 28.

संवेद्य
Saṃvedya nt.: Name of a तीर्थ।
Described as best (उत्तम); by reach-
ing there in the evening (संध्यां समा-
साद्य) and by bathing there one undoubtedly
becomes learned (उपस्पृश्य नरो विद्वान्
भवेन् नास्त्य् अत्र संशयः) 3. 83. 1.

सङ्गम|संगम
Saṃgama m., nt. (3. 85. 13): Con-
fluence of two rivers, or of a river and the
ocean, considered as holy.
Various confluences are mentioned:
(1) Confluence of the river Gaṅgā: (i)
with Yamunā, famous as Prayāga (गङ्गा-
यमुनयोर् वीर संगमम् … प्रयागम्
इति विख्यातम्) 3. 85. 13-14;
A. Descrip-
tion: Holy (पुण्य); purifying (पवित्र),
best purifier (पावनम् उत्तमम्); liked
by sages (ऋषिभिर् जुष्टं); famous in the
world (लोकविश्रुत) 3. 85. 13.
B. Holi-
ness: One who has strictly observed the
vows (शंशितव्रतः) if he bathes at this
confluence he gets as fruit the religious merit
of performing a Rājasūya and an Aśva-
medha (पुण्यं स फलं आप्नोति राज-
सूयाश्वमेधयोः) 3. 83. 76.
C. Epic
event: The Pāṇḍavas lived at this confluence;
after bathing there they practised best auste-
rities (आप्लुत्य गात्राणि तपश् चातस्थुर्
उत्तमम्) and gave wealth to Brāhmaṇas
3. 93. 5-6.
D. Past event: Formerly
Pitāmaha offered a sacrifice there (hence
called Prayāga) 3. 85. 14; (ii) with
Sarasvatī: One who bathes at the confluence
of Gaṅgā and Sarasvatī gets the fruit of an
Aśvamedha and goes to heaven 3. 82. 34;
(iii) with Saṃgamā: One who bathes at
the confluence of Gaṅgā and Saṃgamā gets
the fruit of ten horse sacrifices and lifts up
his family (कुलं चैव समुद्धरेत्) 3.
82. 31; (iv) with the ocean: Wise say
that one who performs a rite related to
Pitāmaha at this Saṃgama gets tenfold
fruit of a horse sacrifice (कृते पैतामहे
विधौ॥गङ्गायास् त्व् अथ राजेन्द्र साग-
रस्य च संगमे।अश्वमेधं दशगुणं
प्रवदन्ति मनीषिणः॥) 3. 83. 3-4; (2)
Confluence of the river Sarasvatī, the other
river not mentioned (संगमं … सरस्व-
त्याः 3. 80. 130):
A. Description: Des-
cribed as very holy (महापुण्य) and famous
in the world (लोकविश्रुत) 3. 80. 130;
B.
Holiness: (i) Brahmadeva, gods, sages,
Siddhas, and Cāraṇas go to this संगम on
bright fortnight of the month of Caitra and
worship Janārdana (उपासन्ते जनार्दनम्)
3. 80. 130-131; (ii) By bathing there one
gets much gold (विन्देद् बहुसुवर्णकम्)
and, by purifying himself of all sins, goes
to the world of Brahman 3. 80. 132, (iii)
By visiting the place there where the sages
completed their सत्रस् (सत्रावसानम् आसाद्य)
one gets the fruit of giving a thousand cows
3. 80. 133.
C. Past events: Sages (in the
past) completed their sacrificial session on this
confluence of Sarasvatī (ऋषीणां यत्र सत्राणि
समाप्तानि) 3. 80. 133; (3) Confluence of
rivers Śoṇa and Jyotirathyā: One who is pure
(शुचिः) if he lives at the confluence of Śoṇa
and Jyotirathyā and satisfies (तर्पयित्वा)
manes and gods gets the reward of an Agni-
ṣṭoma 3. 83. 8; (4) Confluence of Veṇṇā
(and Godāvarī) rivers: One who bathes at this
confluence (Godāvarī not directly mentioned)
gets the fruit of a Vājapeya 3. 83. 31; (5)
Confluence of Varadā (and Godāvarī ?):
One who bathes at the confluence of Varadā
(and Godāvarī) gets the fruit of gifting a
thousand cows 3. 83. 31.

संगमा
Saṃgamā f.: Name of a river.
One who bathes at the confluence of the
rivers Gaṅgā and Saṃgamā (गङ्गासंग-
मयोश् चैव स्नाति यः संगमे नरः) gets
the fruit of ten Aśvamedha sacrifices and lifts
up his family 3. 82. 31.

सत्रावसान
Satrāvasāna nt.: Name of an indepen-
dent तीर्थ ? (3. 80. 133); see Saṃgama:
2 (iii) Confluence of Sarasvatī.

सदानिरामया
Sadānirāmayā f.: Name of a river.
Listed by Saṃjaya among the rivers of
the Bhāratavarṣa; people used its water for
drinking 6. 10. 31, 13; all the rivers listed
by Saṃjaya are described as mothers of the
universe and very strong 6. 10. 35 (for cita-
tion see Atikṛṣṇā).

सदानीरा
Sadānīrā f.: Name of a river.
Listed by Saṃjaya among the rivers of
the Bhāratavarṣa; people used its water for
drinking 6. 10. 23, 13; all the rivers listed
by Saṃjaya are described as mothers of the
universe and very strong 6. 10. 35 (for citation
see Atikṛṣṇā); Sadānīrā, Gaṇḍakīyā and
Śoṇa rise from the same mountain (एकपर्-
वतके नद्यः) 2. 18. 27; Bhīma, Arjuna,
and Kṛṣṇa had to cross these rivers on their
way to the Magadha country 2. 18. 27;
(identical with Karatoyinī ?). [See Kara-
toyinī]

सन्ध्या|संध्या
Saṃdhyā f.: Name of a river.
By reaching this river and by bathing in
it one undoubtedly becomes learned (अथ
संध्यां समासाद्य … उपस्पृश्य नरो
विद्वान् भवेन् नास्त्य् अत्र संशयः) 3.
83. 1.

संनिहिती
Saṃnihitī f.: Name of a तीर्थ।
Brahmadeva, other gods and ascetics
visit the तीर्थ every month and are endowed
with great religious merit (मासि मासि समा-
यान्ति पुण्येन महतान्विताः) 3. 81. 166;
whatever तीर्थस् that exist on this earth or
in the mid-region, as well as rivers, male
and female, ponds, all kinds of streams,
wells, river banks and other holy places,
they all undoubtedly visit Saṃnihitī every
month (this explains the name of the तीर्थ)
(पृथिव्यां यानि तीर्थानि अन्तरिक्षचराणि
च।नद्यो नदास् तडागाश् च सर्वप्रस्र-
वणानि च॥उदपानाश् च वप्राश् च पुण्यान्य्
आयतनानि च।मासि मासि समायान्ति संनि-
हित्यां न संशयः॥) 3. 81. 168-169;
by bathing in Saṃnihitī on the day of solar
eclipse one gets for ever the fruit of perform-
ing a hundred horse sacrifices (संनिहित्याम्
उपस्पृश्य राहुग्रस्ते दिवाकरे।अश्वमेध-
शतं तेन इष्टं भवति शाश्वतम्) 3.
81. 167; whatever evil act a man or a woman
commits is undoubtedly destroyed by bathing
at this तीर्थ and he goes to the world of
Brahman riding in a lotus-coloured conveyance
(पद्मवर्णेन यानेन ब्रह्मलोकं स
गच्छति) 3. 81. 170; Yakṣa Arantuka acts
there as a gate-keeper (द्वारपाल); the
sacred places Koṭirūpa and Gaṅgāhrada are
also there 3. 81. 171-172.

सप्तगङ्ग
Saptagaṅga nt.: Name of a तीर्थ।
If one satisfies according to the rites gods
and manes at this तीर्थ he is glorified in the
world of the holy (पुण्यलोके महीयते) 3.
82. 25; he also gets सुधा to drink if he is
born again (सुधां वै लभते भोक्तुं
यो नरो जायते पुनः) 13. 26. 15.

सप्तगोदावर
Saptagodāvara nt.: Name of a तीर्थ।
One who is controlled and takes limited
food if he bathes at this तीर्थ he will get
great religious merit and will go to the world
of gods (सप्तगोदावरे स्नात्वा नियतो नियता-
शनः।महत् पुण्यम् अवाप्नोति देवलोकं
च गच्छति॥) 3. 83. 41.

सप्तर्षिकुण्ड
Saptarṣikuṇḍa nt. (pl.): Name of a
तीर्थ।
Situated at the place known as Brahma-
ṇaḥ sthānam or Brahmodumbara 3. 81. 58;
one who is pure and has restrained his mind
(शुचिः प्रयतमानसः) he, by bathing at
this तीर्थ (सप्तर्षिकुण्डेषु स्नातस्य) and
by approaching Brahman, is cleansed of all
sins and goes to the world of Brahman 3. 81.
59-60. [See Brahmaṇaḥ sthānam1]

सप्तसारस्वत
Saptasārasvata nt.: Name of a तीर्थ।
A. Location: Related to the river Sara-
svatī (सरस्वतीतीर्थवरम्) 9. 36. 57; on
the Himavant (हैमवते गिरौ) 9. 37. 26.
B. Name explained: When Sarasvatī was
invited again by Brahman for his sacrifice all
the seven forms of the river were once more
united in a तीर्थ on the Himavant; that तीर्थ
became known as the Saptasārasvata tīrtha
(ब्रह्मणा यजता पुनः।समाहूता ययौ
तत्र पुण्ये हैमवते गिरौ॥एकीभूतास्
ततस् तास् तु तस्मिंस् तीर्थे समागताः।
सप्तसारस्वतं तीर्थं ततस् तत् प्रथितं
भुवि॥) 9. 37. 26-27.
C. Description:
Holy (पुण्य) 9. 37. 28; excellent (तीर्थ-
वर) 9. 36. 57; famous on the earth (प्र-
थितं भुवि) 9. 37. 27; full of many kinds
of birds (नानाद्विजगणायुत) 9. 36. 57;
crowded with hundreds of herds of animals
(मृगयूथशताकुल) 9. 36. 62; filled with
the sound of Vedic studies (स्वाध्यायघोष-
संघुष्ट) 9. 36. 62; resorted to often by
peaceful and righteous men (अहिंस्रैर्
धर्मपरमैर् नृभिर् अत्यन्तसेवितम्) 9.
36. 62; trees growing near the तीर्थ and
different ascetics living there mentioned in
9. 36. 58-61.
D. Holiness: Mahādeva
lives there in the आश्रम of Maṅkaṇaka
3. 81. 114; 9. 37. 48; those who bathe in the
Saptasārasvata tīrtha and worship Mahādeva
nothing will be unobtainable to them, here
in this world or in the next, and they will un-
doubtedly go to the world of Sarasvatī (न
तेषां दुर्लभं किंचिद् इह लोके परत्र
च।सारस्वतं च ते लोकं गमिष्यन्ति
न संशयः) 3. 81. 114-115; 9. 37. 49.
E. Epic events: (1) Janamejaya asked
Vaiśaṃpāyana to tell him why Saptasārasvata
was so called (सप्तसारस्वतं कस्मात्)
9. 37. 1; (2) Halāyudha (Balarāma)
arrived at this तीर्थ from the Naimiṣeya
kuñja of Kurukṣetra (9. 36. 54) 9. 36. 63.
F. Past event: At this तीर्थ the great
sage Maṅkaṇaka, who was a Siddha, prac-
tised austerities 9. 36. 63; once Maṅkaṇaka
cut his hand with the tip of a Kuśa blade;
from his injured hand flowed the juice of
vegetables (पुरा मङ्कणको राजन् कुशा-
ग्रेणेति नः श्रुतम्।क्षतः किल करे
राजंस् तस्य शाकरसो ऽस्रवत्॥) 3. 81. 98.

समङ्गा
Samaṅgā f.: Name of a river. [See
Madhuvilā]

सरक
Saraka nt.: Name of a तीर्थ।
Described as famous in the world (लोक-
विश्रुत) 3. 81. 62; by visiting (अभिगम्य)
Vṛṣadhvaja (Śiva) there on the fourteenth
day of the dark fortnight one gets all desires
and goes to heaven; there are three crores of
तीर्थस् at Saraka and a crore of Rudras in a
well and in lakes (तिस्रः कोट्यस् तु तीर्था-
नाम् सरके कुरुनन्दन।रुद्रकोटिस् तथा
कूपे ह्रदेषु च महीपते); the तीर्थ called
Ilāspada is also there 3. 81. 62-63.

सरयू
Sarayū f.: Name of a river; also called
Śarayū (3. 212. 21).
A. Location: Listed by Saṃjaya twice
among the rivers of the Bhāratavarṣa; people
used its water for drinking 6. 10. 18, 13;
in the east; Bhīma, Arjuna and Kṛṣṇa crossed
it to enter the eastern Kosala country (सं-
तीर्य सरयूं रम्यां दृष्ट्वा पूर्वांश् च
कोसलान्) 2. 18. 28.
B. Origin (name
explained): Vasiṣṭha brought the river Gaṅgā,
flowing towards Kailāsa, to the lake which
had received a boon from Brahman (ब्रह्म-
दत्तवरं सरः 13. 140. 18); Gaṅgā broke
that lake (सरस्) and then became the river
Sarayū (कैलासं प्रस्थितां चापि नदीं
गङ्गां महातपाः।आनयत् तत् सरो दिव्यं
तया भिन्नं च तत् सरः॥सरो भिन्नं
तया नद्या सरयूः सा ततोऽभवत्) 13. 140.
23-24.
C. Description: Pleasing (रम्या)
2. 18. 28; all the rivers listed by Saṃjaya
are said to be mothers of the universe and
very strong 6. 10. 35 (for citation see Ati-
kṛṣṇā).
D. Holiness and its limitation:
(1) All the rivers listed by Mārkaṇḍeya—
Śarayū one of them—are declared to be
mothers of the sacrificial hearths, i. e. on
the banks of which sacrifices were performed
3. 212. 21 (एता नद्यस् तु धिष्ण्यानां
मातरो याः प्रकीर्तिताः 3. 212. 24; for Nī.
see Kapilā); (2) The excellent तीर्थ
called Gopratāra is on the river Sarayū
(सरय्वास् तीर्थम् उत्तमम्) 3. 82. 63;
limitation: Gifting cows in very large
numbers on the bank of Sarayū is highly
meritorious, but not enough to take the donor
to Brahmaloka 13. 106. 37.
E. Impor-
tance: Finds mention in the Daivata-Ṛṣi-
Vaṃśa 13. 151. 16, 2.
F. Epic event:
Bhīma, Arjuna and Kṛṣṇa crossed the river
Sarayū on their way to the Magadha country
2. 18. 28.
G. Past event: (1) Vīra, one
of the fires, begot Siddhi on the river Sarayū
(वीरः सरय्वां जनयत् सिद्धिम्) 3. 209.
9-11 (Nī. on Bom. Ed. 3. 219. 11: शरय्वां
भार्यायां सिद्धिं नाम पुत्रं जनयत्)
(2) Asamañjas, the son of Sagara, used to
drown the children of citizens in the river
Sarayū; he was therefore rebuked by his
father and was banished by him 12. 57. 9.
H. Simile: The armies of the Kauravas and
the Pāṇḍavas clashed with each other with
the speed of flooded Gaṅgā and Sarayū in
the rainy season (गङ्गासरय्वोर् वेगेन
प्रावृषीवोल्बणोदके) 7. 16. 49.

सरला
Saralā f.: Name of a river.
Listed by Saṃjaya among the rivers of
the Bhāratavarṣa; people used its water for
drinking 6. 10. 22, 13 (for other details see
Atikṛṣṇā).

सरस्वती
Sarasvatī f.: sg, (pl. 6. 10. 35; 9. 37.
3; 9. 44. 18; 12. 255. 39; 13. 75. 12): Name
of a river (in some events conceived as a
woman); also called Bhogavatī (3. 25. 20).
A. Location: (1) Listed by Saṃjaya
among the rivers of the Bhāratavarṣa; people
used its water for drinking 6. 10. 13; (2)
In the north (उदीच्याम्) 3. 88. 1; on the top
of Himavant (प्रस्थे हिमवतः शुभे)
9. 4. 49; Balarāma saw on the Himavant
mountain (9. 53. 9), the source of Sarasvatī
at Plakṣaprasravaṇa (प्रभवं च सरस्-
वत्याः प्लक्षप्रस्रवणं बलः (दृष्ट्वा))
9. 53. 11; Sarasvatī's origin in an ant-hill near
a Plakṣa tree (प्लक्षाद् देवी सृता राजन्
महापुण्या सरस्वती॥तत्राभिषेकं कुर्-
वीत वल्मीकान् निःसृते जले) 3. 82. 5-6;
flowing from Himavant (हैमवती) 9. 43.
51; (3) Rises in the lake of Brahman
(प्रसृतासि महाभागे सरसो ब्रह्मणः
पुरा) 9. 50. 19; 9. 41. 29; (4) The Bāh-
līka country was disregarded by Gaṅgā,
Yamunā and Sarasvatī (गङ्गया च तिरस्-
कृताः।सरस्वत्या यमुनया) 8. 30. 10;
(5) Nakula in his march towards the west
of Khāṇḍavaprastha (खाण्डवप्रस्थात्
प्रतीचीम् अभितो दिशम् 2. 29. 2) conquered
people who lived along Sarasvatī (ये चाश्रित्य
सरस्वतीम्।वर्तयन्ति) 2. 29. 9; one of
the rivers visited by the Pāṇḍavas in their
westward march (ययुः … पश्चिमां दिशम्);
on its bank is the Kāmyaka forest (सरस्-
वतीकूले) 3. 6. 2-3; (6) Flowing through
Kurukṣetra (तत्र (i. e. कुरुक्षेत्रे)  …
सरस्वत्याम्) 3. 81. 3, 92-93; 3. 129. 21-22;
3. 130. 3; flowing through Samantapañcaka 9.
43. 51; Kurukṣetra to the south of Sarasvatī
and to the north of Dṛṣadvatī 3. 81. 175; lake
Dvaitavana near Sarasvatī 3. 174. 21.
B.
Description: Auspicious (शिवा) 3. 179. 15;
13. 134. 22; holy (पुण्या) 3. 129. 20; 3. 130.
3; 9. 37. 17; 9. 38. 27; 9. 43. 51; 13. 134.
15; very holy (सुपुण्या) 6. 10. 35; (महा-
पुण्या) 3. 82. 5; most holy (पुण्यतमा)
13. 134. 22; brings holiness (to visitors)
(पुण्यवहा) 3. 88. 2; holy among all rivers
(सर्वनदीषु पुण्या) 9. 53. 35; has holy
तीर्थस् on it (पुण्यतीर्था) 3. 179. 14;
having hundreds of तीर्थस् on it (तीर्थ-
शतोपेता) 9. 38. 27; having waters of all
तीर्थस् (सर्वतीर्थोदकैर् युता) 13. 134.
12; purifying (पावना) 6. 7. 45; sinless
(अनघा) 9. 42. 11; highly fortunate (महा-
भागा) 9. 37. 24; 9. 50. 19, 22, 23; (भगवती)
9. 37. 26; as though the sacrificial ground of
gods (आयागभूताम् इव देवतानाम्) 3. 174.
24; divine (देवी) 9. 43. 51; (दिव्या) 3. 130. 3;
having heavenly water (दिव्यतोया) 9. 37. 25;
9. 44. 18; excellent river, best or first among
rivers (सरिच्छ्रेष्ठा) 3. 82. 5; 9. 36. 36, 38,
44, 47; 9. 37. 11, 14, 23, 24; 9. 40. 33; 9.
41. 19, 23; 9. 42. 12, 13; 9. 43. 51; 9. 50. 19;
13. 134. 22; (सरितां श्रेष्ठा) 9. 37. 18,
19; 9. 41. 12, 20; 9. 42. 8; (सरिद्वरा) 9.
36. 51; 13. 134. 14; (सरितां वरा) 9.
36. 52; 9. 41. 27, 39; 9. 50. 11; 13. 134.
19; (नदीनाम् उत्तमा) 3. 82. 5; 13. 134.
15; (प्रथमा सर्वसरिताम्) 13. 134. 15;
shining (शुभा) 9. 50. 23; 13. 139. 26;
भामिनी 9. 41. 13; beautiful (वरवर्णिनी)
9. 50. 20; pleasing to look at (प्रियदर्शना)
9. 50. 20; red (अरुणा) 9. 4. 49; always
bringing happiness to people (लोकसुखावहा
सदा) 9. 53. 35; great river (महानदी)
9. 36. 53; 9. 39. 7 (not named); 9. 42. 20;
9. 50. 10, 18, 24; 12. 335. 46; full of lakes
(ह्रदिनी) 3. 88. 2; has placid water (प्र-
सन्नसलिला) 3. 179. 15; (as a woman)
whose eyes were like a lotus (पुण्डरीक-
निभेक्षणा) 9. 41. 17; its banks wide like
sky (आकाशनीकाशतटा) 3. 179. 14; having
a garland of forests (वनमालिनी) 3. 88. 2;
full of नीप and नीवार (on its banks)
(नीपनीवारसंकुला) 3. 179. 14; flowing
rapidly (शीघ्रगामिनी) 9. 37. 20; 9. 41. 23;
(वेगयुक्ता) 9. 37. 13; (ओघवती) 3. 130.
3; flowing to the sea (सागरगामिनी) 13.
134. 15; (सागरगमा) 13. 134. 21; liked
by Yakṣas, Gandharvas and great sages
(यक्षगन्धर्वमहर्षिकान्ता) 3. 174. 24;
resorted to by hosts of Brāhmaṇas (विप्र-
संघैर् निषेविता) 9. 38. 27; worshipped by
the sages (पूज्यमाना मुनिगणैः) 9. 37.
23; worshipped by good people at all times
(सरस्वती नदी सद्भिः सततं पार्थ
पूजिता) 3. 88. 9; thronged by people to
whom she is the sole resort (एकशरणावृता)
3. 129. 20; famous in the three worlds (त्रिषु
लोकेषु विश्रुता) 9. 43. 51; 6. 7. 47; versed in
the knowledge of the duties of women (स्त्री-
धर्मकुशला) 13. 134. 19; all the rivers
listed by Saṃjaya are described as mothers
of the universe and very strong (विश्वस्य
मातरः सर्वाः सर्वाश् चैव महाबलाः)
6. 10. 35 (also see the next section C).
C. Characteristics: (1) Sarasvatī appears
and disappears again at various places (दृश्या-
दृश्या च भवति तत्र तत्र सरस्वती)
6. 7. 47; the trees growing on the banks of
Sarasvatī are (सरस्वतीतीररुहैः … शोभि-
तम्): Badara, Iṅguda, Kāśmarya, Plakṣa,
Aśvattha, Vibhītaka, Panasa, Palāśa, Karīra,
Pīlu, Bandhana, Syandana, Bilva, Āmrātaka,
and Pārijāta; there are also on its bank
forests of Parūṣaka (परूषकवनैश् चैव)
and groves of Atimuktaka (अतिमुक्तक-
षण्डैश् च) 9. 36. 58-60; auspicious Śāla
forests grow on its banks (शिवेषु।सरस्वती-
शालवनेषु तेषु) 3. 26. 1; the big Mahā-
śaṅkha tree is on its bank 9. 36. 20; the forests
on its bank are inhabited by the righteous who
have controlled their self and who wear bark
garments and have matted hair and also
by hosts of perfected sages (भोगवतीम्
उपेत्य धृतात्मनां चीरजटाधराणाम्
तस्मिन् वने धर्मभृतां निवासे।ददर्श
सिद्धर्षिगणान् अनेकान्) 3. 25. 20; cf. 3. 26.
1; (Nī. on Bom. Ed. 3. 24. 20: भोगवतीं
सरस्वतीं नदीम्); always pleasing to
Dadhīca (मम प्रीयकरी चापि सततं)
9. 50. 20; Śūdras and hosts of Ābhīras took
resort on Sarasvatī and lived on fish (शूद्रा-
भीरगणाश् चैव ये चाश्रित्य सरस्वतीम्।
वर्तयन्ति च ये मत्स्यैः) 2. 29. 9; there is
no pleasure, there are no virtues which are
equal to the residence on Sarasvatī (सरस्वती-
वास समा कुतो रतिः सरस्वतीवाससमाः
कुतो गुणाः) 9. 53. 34; Sarasvatī disappears in
the desert at Vinaśana, but appears again at
Camasa, Śivodbheda and Nāgodbheda 3. 80.
118; (13. 139. 26); the Siddhas know, due to
the wetness of plants and earth, the presence
of Sarasvatī there though not seen (स्निग्ध-
त्वाद् ओषधीनां च भूमेश् च जनमेजय।
जानन्ति सिद्धा राजेन्द्र नष्टाम् अपि सर-
स्वतीम्॥) 9. 34. 81; at Camasodbheda all
ocean going rivers turn to her (यत्रैनाम्
अभ्यवर्तन्त दिव्याः पुण्याः समुद्रगाः)
3. 130. 5.
D. Holiness: (1) Vaiśaṃ-
pāyana told Janamejaya the holiness of the
Tīrthavaṃśa of Sarasvatī (here in particular
of the Aujasatīrtha 9. 45. 92) 9. 45. 88; Sara-
svatī and the तीर्थस् on Sarasvatī are holier
than Kurukṣetra (पुण्यम् आहुः कुरु-
क्षेत्रं कुरुक्षेत्रात् सरस्वतीम्।सर-
स्वत्याश् च तीर्थानि) 3. 81. 125; by the
favour of sage Dadhīca, Sarasvatī was to
be at all times holiest among the other holy
rivers (पुण्याभ्यश् च सरिद्भ्यस् त्वं सदा
पुण्यतमा शुभे।भविष्यसि महाभागे
मत्प्रसादात् सरस्वति) 9. 50. 23; (9. 53.
35); (2) By bathing in the river Sarasvatī
one washes off one's sins (धूतपाप्मा
भविष्यसि) 3. 129. 20; by bathing in Sara-
svatī one rides in a विमान (सरस्वत्याम्
उपस्पृश्य विमानस्थो विराजते) 3. 82. 139;
by visiting Sarasvatī people have gone to
heaven; those who have done evil acts if
they visit Sarasvatī they never grieve in this
or the other world (सरस्वतीं प्राप्य जनाः
सुदुष्कृताः।सदा न शोचन्ति परत्र चेह
च॥) 9. 53. 34-35; according to the Gāthās
sung by Yayāti (12. 148. 8) if one bathes
and drinks water at Pṛthūdaka on Sarasvatī
one does not have to worry about death in
near future (नैव श्वोमरणं तपेत्) 12.
148. 10; this was also told by Ruṣaṅgu to
his sons 9. 38. 29; by visiting Sarasvatī and
by satisfying there gods and manes one re-
joices undoubtedly in the worlds of Sarasvatī
(सारस्वतेषु लोकेषु मोदते नात्र सं-
शयः) 3. 82. 59; by bathing at the तीर्थ
on Sarasvatī gods, Gandharvas, Apsarases,
Dvaipāyana, Śuka, Kṛṣṇa, Yakṣas and many
others became perfected in Yoga (योग-
सिद्धाः) 9. 48. 18-20; one should live on
Sarasvatī for a month 3. 81. 3; (3) By
bathing at the confluence of Gaṅgā and Sara-
svatī one gets the fruit of an Aśvamedha and
goes to heaven 3. 82. 34; by visiting the place
where Sarasvatī meets the ocean (सरस्वत्याः
सागरस्य च संगमे) one gets the fruit
of gifting a thousand cows and shining always
with lustre like that of fire he is glorified in
heaven (स्वर्गलोके महीयते।दीप्यमानो
ऽग्निवन् नित्यं प्रभया); living there for
three nights one should satisfy manes and
gods; he thereby shines like the moon (प्र-
भासते यथा सोमः … ) and gets the reward
of an Aśvamedha 3. 80. 79-80; at the con-
fluence of Sarasvatī (the other river is not
named) people worship Janārdana; Brahmā
and other gods, as well as sages and Siddhas
and Cāraṇas, visit it on the fourteenth day
of the bright half of Caitra 3. 80, 130; it is
recommended that one should live at Kuru-
kṣetra on Sarasvatī for a month (तत्र (कुरु-
क्षेत्रे) सरस्वत्यां मासं वसेत्) 3. 81.
3; (4) There are many तीर्थस् on Sara-
svatī 5. 154. 33; 9. 34. 33; all these तीर्थस्
are holy 3. 81. 125; their holiness described
in the Śalyaparvan (शल्यपर्वणि … सर-
स्वत्याश् च तीर्थानां पुण्यता परिकीर्तिता)
1. 2. 174-175; these तीर्थस् are: Śaśayāna
3. 80. 120-121; a तीर्थ sacred to Aran-
tuka, chief of Yakṣas 3. 81. 42; Śrīkuñja
3. 81. 91; Naimiṣakuñja 3. 81. 92; Devī-
tīrtha at the confluence of Sarasvatī and Aruṇā
3. 81. 131; Vinaśana 3. 130. 3; Camasodbheda
3. 130. 5; Janamejaya asked Vaiśaṃpāyana
to tell him the origin, the merits, the reward
of visiting them, and how one achieves suc-
cessful completion of visiting the तीर्थस् on
Sarasvatī (सारस्वतानां तीर्थानां गुणोत्-
पत्तिं वदस्व मे।फलं च द्विपदां
श्रेष्ठ कर्मनिर्वृत्तिम् एव च॥ 9. 34. 33:
Nī. on Bom. Ed. 9. 35. 38: कर्मनिर्वृत्तिं
तीर्थयात्राविधिसिद्धिम्); Vaiśaṃpāyana's
account includes Prabhāsa 9. 34. 36; Cama-
sodbheda 9. 34. 78; Subhūmika 9. 36. 3;
Gargasrotas 9. 36. 14, 16; Śaṅkhatīrtha 9.
36. 24; Auśanasa 9. 38. 16, also called
Kapālamocana 9. 38. 20; Pṛthūdaka 9.
38. 25-26; a तीर्थ not named 9. 38. 33;
9. 39. 6, 10, 23, 30; (5) The region
deserted by Sarasvatī would be bereft of
holiness (अपुण्य एष भवतु देशश् त्यक्तस्
त्वया शुभे) 13. 139. 26; cows act like
Sarasvatīs (pl.) in delivering persons from
the remainder of their actions (?), in free-
ing them from the body and in the obtain-
ment of bliss (शेषोत्सर्गे कर्मभिर् देह-
मोक्षे सरस्वत्यः श्रेयसि संप्रवृत्ताः)
13. 75. 12 (But Nī. on Bom. Ed. 13. 76. 12:
(गावः) क्षयरोगादिनिवृत्तौ देहमोक्षे च
कर्मभिः पञ्चगव्यादिभिः सेविताः सत्यः
सरस्वत्यो नद्य इव श्रेयसे संप्रवृत्ताः);
one should live on the rivers Sarasvatī and
Dṛṣadvatī worshipping them, doing one's
studies and bathing in all places (सरस्वती-
दृषद्वत्यौ सेवमानो ऽनुसंचरेः।स्वा-
ध्यायशीलः स्थानेषु सर्वेषु समुपस्पृ-
शेः) 12. 148. 12; but sage Parāśara told to
king Janaka that, more than with waters of
the rivers, one should bathe one's body with
austerities (i. e. one should practise austeri-
ties) at all holy places like Sarasvatī, Nai-
miṣa, Puṣkara and the rest (अद्भ्यो भूयः
प्लाव्यं तपसा वै शरीरम्।सरस्वती-
नैमिषपुष्करेषु ये चाप्य् अन्ये पुण्यदेशाः
पृथिव्याम्) 12. 286. 37; (6) Sarasvatī suited
for sacrifices: (i) The fire-altar of Prajāpati
was on holy Sarasvatī (सरस्वतीम् इमां
पुण्यां पश्य … वेदी प्रजापतेर् एषा) 3.
129. 20, 22; (ii) Many sages, divine sages,
and royal sages had offered sacrifices on
Sarasvatī (इह सारस्वतैर् यज्ञैर् इष्टवन्-
तः सुरर्षयः।ऋषयश् चैव कौन्तेय
तथा राजर्षयो ऽपि च) 3. 129. 21; (iii)
Formerly Vālakhilya sages offered sacrifices
on Ṣarasvatī 3. 88. 9; (iv) Sarasvatī is
listed by Mārkaṇḍeya among the rivers which
are called mothers of the sacrificial hearths
(i. e. on the banks of which sacrifices were
performed) 3. 212. 21 (for citation and Nī.
see Kapilā); (7) Sarasvatī also mentioned
among the holy places by visiting which the
high-souled ones who have observed vows
(महात्मानो धृतव्रताः) assume heavenly
form and, becoming auspicious, wearing
heavenly garlands and rich in holy perfume,
they go to the world of cows (? ते तत्र
मोदन्ति गवां विमाने 13. 105. 44) 13.
105. 48 (for citation see Karatoyinī); (8)
According to Tulādhāra, however, all rivers
are equal in point of holiness to Sarasvatī
(सर्वा नद्यः सरस्वत्यः) 12. 255. 39.
E. Epic events: (1) The Pāṇḍavas, at the
beginning of their forest life, lived on the
banks of Sarasvatī, Yamunā and Gaṅgā;
they next saw the Kāmyaka forest on the
bank of Sarasvatī and lived there 3. 6. 3-4;
(2) The Pāṇḍavas saw in Dvaitavana the
river Bhogavatī (= Sarasvatī) (मनोरमां
भोगवतीम् उपेत्य … तस्मिन् वने (i. e. in
Dvaitavana)) 3. 25. 20; they sported in the
Śāla forests on the bank of Sarasvatī 3. 26.
1; the Pāṇḍavas left Dvaitavana and went to
Kāmyaka on the bank of Sarasvatī (ययौ
सरस्वतीतीरे काम्यकं नाम काननम्)
3. 37. 37; (3) Shown by Lomaśa to the
Pāṇḍavas 3. 130. 3; after crossing the desert
they reached Sarasvatī in order to live in
Dvaitavana 3. 174. 21; seeing them settled in
Dvaitavana ascetics came to them 3. 174. 22;
the Pāṇḍavas were happy roaming along the
river Sarasvatī 3. 174. 24; they spent the most
holy autumnal Kārtika full moon night while
living on the bank of Sarasvatī (तेषाम् पुण्य-
तमा रात्रिः पर्वसंधौ स्म शारदी।
तत्रैव वसताम् आसीत् कार्तिकी जनमे-
जय॥) 3. 179. 16; (4) Rāma Jāmadagnya,
along with Ambā and other ascetics, went to
Kurukṣetra to meet Bhīṣma and stayed near
Sarasvatī (न्यविशन्त ततः सर्वे परिगृह्य
सरस्वतीम्) 5. 177. 24; (5) After the fall
of Karṇa, the Kṣatriyas fighting on the side
of the Kauravas went to Sarasvatī flowing
near Himavant, and bathed, and drank her
water; they felt refreshed and returned
for the battle (अरुणां सरस्वतीं प्राप्य
पपुः सस्नुश् च तोज्जलम्) 9. 4. 49; (6)
Balarāma decided to go on a pilgrimage to
visit the तीर्थस् on Sarasvatī as he was not
prepared to watch the destruction of those
born in the Kuru family (तस्माद् यास्यामि
तीर्थानि सरस्वत्या निषेवितुम् । न हि शक्-
ष्यामि कौरव्यान् नश्यमानान् उपेक्षितुम्)
5. 154. 33; ha set out on the Maitra नक्षत्र;
from the ocean he started his pilgrimage up-
stream on the river (प्रतिस्रोतः सरस्वत्याः;
सरस्वतीं प्रतिस्रोतः समुद्राद् अभिज-
ग्मिवान्) 9. 34. 12, 17-18; Balarāma gave to
Brāhmaṇas large दक्षिणास् at the excellent
तीर्थस् on Sarasvatī 9. 34. 29-32; the तीर्थस्
and other places visited by Balarāma were
Prabhāsa 9. 34. 36; Camasodbheda 9. 34.
78-79; Udapāna 9. 34. 80; 9. 35. 1-2;
52-53; Vinaśana where Sarasvatī dis-
appeared 9. 36. 1-3; Subhūmika 9. 36. 3-9;
Gandharvatīrtha 9. 36. 10-14; Gragasrotas
9. 36. 14-19; Śaṅkhatīrtha where he saw
the big tree Mahāśaṅkha 9. 36. 19-26;
Dvaitavana, from where he went along
the southern bank of Sarasvatī (ततः प्रा-
याद् बलो राजन् दक्षिणेन सरस्वतीम्)
9. 36. 26-28; Nāgadhanavan, from where
he went towards the east (प्रायात् प्राचीं
दिशम्) 9. 36. 29-32; Naimiṣeya kuñja
from where hte eastward flowing Sarasvatī
again returned to the west (यत्र भूयो
निववृते प्राङ्मुखा वै सरस्वती) 9. 36. 35;
भूयः प्रतीच्यभिमुखी सुस्राव सरितां
वरा) 9. 36. 52; 9. 36. 34-56; Saptasāra-
svata 9. 36. 57-63; 9. 38. 1-3; Auśanasa
(Kapālamocana) 9. 38. 4, 7, 21; Āśrama of
Ruṣaṅgu 9. 38. 21; Pṛthūdaka 9. 38. 23, 30;
a तीर्थ (not named) 9. 38. 33; 9. 39. 6, 10,
23, 30-31; Balarāma gave there many kinds
of gifts to Brāhmaṇas nad honoured them 9.
39. 30-31; Āśrama of Baka 9. 39. 32; 9. 40.
28-29; Yāyāta 9. 40. 29; Vasiṣṭhāpavāha 9.
40. 35; Blarāma bathed there (उपस्पृश्य)
and gave various gifts and from there went
to Somasya tīrtham 9. 42. 38; Aujasa, where
Balarāma bathed (स्नात्वा, स्पृष्ट्वा), wor-
shipped Skanda, gave gold, garments and
ornaments to Brāhmaṇas and was happy
and pleased 9. 45. 92-94; Kaubera forest 9.
46. 22-24, 28; Badarapācana 9. 46. 29; 9.
47. 1, 61; Indratīrtha 9. 47. 61;/ 9. 48. 1,
5-6; Rāmatīrtha 9. 48. 6, 9-10; Yamunā-
tīrtha 9. 48. 10, 15; Ādityatīrtha 9. 48. 16,
20; 9. 49. 65; Somasya tīrtham 9. 49. 65;
9. 50. 2; तीर्थ of sage Sārasvata 9. 50. 2,
51; तीर्थ of Vṛddhakanyā 9. 50. 51; 9. 51.
24; Balarāma mounted Himavant and saw
Plakṣaprasravaṇa tīrtha at the source of
Sarasvatī (प्रभवं च सरस्वत्याः प्ल-
क्षप्रस्रवणं बलः) 9. 53. 9-11; from
there he went to Kārapacana 9. 53. 11-12; at
Plakṣaprasravaṇa he heard about the destruc-
tion in the battle; so he descended from the
mountain Himavant and went to hte place
where the duel between Bhīma and Duryo-
dhana was to take place; he was delighted to
look at Sarasvatī again and again 9. 53. 33,
36-37; before leaving the place Balarāma sang
two stanzas praising the qualities of Sarasvatī
and describing her holiness 9. 53. 34-35; (7)
The prowess (प्रभाव) of Sarasvatī was
narrated by Vaiśaṃpāyana to Janamejaya 9.
43. 1 (reference to Adhyāyas 9. 39-42);
(8) The Pāṇḍavas and Duryodhana selected
a place which had no ditches near a तीर्थ
called Svayana to the south of Sarasvatī
(दक्षिणेन सरस्वत्याः स्वयनं तीर्थम्
उत्तमम् । तस्मिन् देशे त्व् अनिरिणे तत्र
युद्धम् अरोचयन् ॥) 9. 54. 13 (Nī.,
however, on Bom. Ed. 9. 55. 18: अनिरिणे
अणूषरे); (9) After the mutual destruc-
tion of the Yādavas, Arjuna established
Yauyudhāni, son of Sātyaki(n), in the region
of Sarasvatī (यौयुधानीम् सरस्वत्यां
पुत्रं सात्यकिनः प्रियम्।न्यवेशयत)
16. 8. 69; (10) Sixteen thousand wives of
Vāsudeva (Kṛṣṇa) enterd the river Sarasvatī
(न्यमज्जन्त सरस्वत्याम्); they then
became the Apsarases and returned to Vāsu-
deva 18. 5. 21.
F. Past and Mythological
events: (1) King Matināra performed a
sacrificial session lasting for twelve years on
the bank of Sarasvatī; after the सत्र was
over, Sarasvatī chose Matināra for her hus-
band; a son was born to Sarasvatī, Taṃsu
by name; this is recorded in a stanza describ-
ing lineage (अत्रानुवंशो भवति।तंसुं
सरस्वती पुत्रं मतिनाराद् अजीजनत्) 1.
90. 25-28); (2) Describing past events in
Kṛṣṇa's life Arjuna said that in a सत्र
lasting for twelve years on Sarasvatī Kṛṣṇa
discarded his upper garment, became thin,
having stretched veins (अपकृष्टोत्तरासङ्गः
कृशो धमनिसंततः।आसीः कृष्ण सरस्व-
त्यां सत्रे द्वादशवार्षिके॥) 3. 13, 13 (Nī.
on 3. 12. 14; अपकृष्टोत्तरासङ्गः त्यक्तोत्त-
रीयवस्त्रः); (3) Sarasvatī is one of the
seven forms assumed by Gaṅgā on the moun-
tain Hiraṇyaśṛṅga (6. 7. 40); these forms
became famous as seven Gaṅgās in the three
worlds 6. 7. 44-45, 47; (4) Trita fell down
at night in a well which was not far away from
Sarasvatī 9. 35. 24-25; when Trita requested
gods to rescue him from the well, Sarasvatī,
full of waves, leapt up and threw Trita out of
the well (तत्र चोर्मिमती राजन्न् उत्पपात
सरस्वती।तयोत्क्षिप्तस् त्रितस् तस्थौ) 9. 35,
46; (5) Sarasvatī, in bygone days, dis-
appeared due to her hatred for Śūdras and
Ābhīras; the place where she disappear-
ed was named by sages Vinaśana tīrtha
(शूद्राभीरान् प्रति द्वेषाद् यत्र नष्टा
सरस्वती … तस्मात् तद् ऋषयो नित्यं प्राहुर्
विनशनेति ह॥) 9. 36. 1-2; (6) Sarasvatī,
flowing towards the east, returned from a
certain तीर्थ to the west out of her regard
for the sages living in the Naimiṣa forest;
formerly, in the Kṛta age, many sages from
the Naimiṣa forest, after completing सत्र
of twelve years, flocked to Sarasvatī for
pilgrimage (तीर्थकारणात्); on account of
their large numbers the तीर्थस् on the south
bank of Sarasvatī appeared like cities
(ऋषीणां बहुलत्वात् तु सरस्वत्या विशां
पते।तीर्थानि नगरायन्ते कूले वै दक्षिणे
तदा॥); these sages resorted to the bank
of Sarasvatī as far as the Samantapañcaka
on account of their love for तीर्थस् (तीर्थ-
लोभात्); due to the fires of their अग्नीहोत्रस्
the river shone (अशोभत सरिच्छ्रेष्ठा);
the sages, dwelling near Sarasvatī, beautified
the river as do gods the Ganges (शोभयन्-
तः सरिच्छ्रेष्ठाम् गङ्गाम् इव दिवौकसः);
when other sages arrived there to perform a
सत्र they found no place in Kurukṣetra;
then Sarasvatī showed herself to the despon-
dent sages (ततस् तम् ऋषिसंघातं निरा-
शं चिन्तयान्वितम्।दर्शयाम् आस राजेन्द्र
तेषाम् अर्थे सरस्वती); the river created
for them many bowers, returned (ततः
कुञ्जान् बहून् कृत्वा संनिवृत्ता सरिद्वरा),
and again flowed towards the west thinking
“I shall not render the arrival of the sages
futile; now I shall go my way”; this
is a great wonder that the river perfor-
med (भूयः प्रतीच्यभिमुखी सुस्राव
सरितां वरा॥अमोघा गमनं (अमोघा-
गमनम् ?) कृत्वा तेषां भूयो व्रजाम्य्
अहम्।इत्य् अद्भुतं महच् चक्रे ततो
राजन् महानदी) 9. 36. 35-53; (7) When
Maṅkaṇaka, who was observing chastity
(कौमारब्रह्मचारिणः) saw by chance
a woman taking bath in Sarasvatī his seed
fell into water; when it was collected in a
jar by the sage, the seed got divided into
seven parts; from it were born seven seers,
from whom sprang the Maruts (तत्रर्षयः
सप्त जाता जज्ञिरे मरुतां गणाः। … एवम्
एते समुत्पन्ना मरुतां जनयिष्णवः)
9. 37. 29-32 (Nī. on Bom. Ed. 9. 38. 37
(एतेषां तपसा मरुतो ऽदित्याम् उत्पन्ना इति
कल्पान्तरविषयो ऽयम् अर्थः); (8) The
Brāhmaṇa Ruṣaṅgu, when he decided to
give up his body in old age, asked his sons
to carry him to Pṛthūdaka, a तीर्थ on
Sarasvatī; when he was carried to the river
by his sons, he took bath there (आप्लुतः)
and, knowing the qualities of the तीर्थ,
told his sons: “one who gives up his body
on the northern bank of Sarasvatī will not
have to worry about iminent death” (नैनं
श्वोमरणं तपेत्) 9. 38. 24-29, (9) Baka
Dālbhya, when insulted by Dhṛtarāṣṭra, son
of Vicitravīrya (9. 40. 1; probably different
from the son of Ambikā and the father of the
Kauravas), kindled fire at a desolate तीर्थ on
Sarasvatī (अवकीर्णे सरस्वत्यास् तीर्थे प्र-
ज्वाल्य पावकम् 9. 40. 12; Nī., however, who
reads अवाकीर्णम् takes it as the name of a
तीर्थ: अवाकीर्णं नाम दाल्भ्यसेवितं तीर्-
थं जगाम Bom. Ed. 9. 41. 1) and started
giving offerings of flesh of dead animals;
as a result the kingdom of Dhṛtarāṣṭra began
to waste away; he was therefore advised to
propitiate Baka in a bower in the water of
Sarasvatī (अपां कुञ्जे सरस्वत्यास् तं
प्रसादय पार्थिव) and request Baka to
forgive him for his fault 9. 40. 10-21; (also
see No. 27 below); (10) For the sacrifice
of Yayāti, son of Nahuṣa, Sarasvatī brought
in her currents clarified butter and milk
(घृतं पयश् च सुस्राव); in that sacri-
fice, Sarasvatī fulfilled the wishes of Brāh-
maṇas by producing many juices (?) in
accordance with their wishes (यत्र यत्र
हि यो विप्रो यान् यान् कामान् अभीप्सति।
तत्र तत्र सरिच्छ्रेष्ठा ससर्ज सुबहून्
रसान्) 9. 40. 30, 33; (11) Viśvāmitra
practised severe austerities on an excellent
तीर्थ (not named) of Sarasvatī and became
a Brāhmaṇa 9. 39. 23, 28-29; the आश्रम
of Vasiṣṭha was at Sthāṇutīrtha on the
eastern bank of Sarasvatī and that of
Viśvāmitra on the western bank; at the
तीर्थ Vasiṣṭhāpavāha, Viśvāmitra was able
to displace Vasiṣṭha with the help of severe
austerities (वसिष्ठं चालयाम् आस तप-
सोग्रेण) 9. 41. 4, 8; Viśvāmitra wanted
Sarasvatī to bring Vasiṣṭha to him swiftly
so that he could kill him (Vasiṣṭha); Viśvā-
mitra therefore thought of Sarasvatī; she
appeared before him, trembling with fear, and
asked him what she might do for him; Viśvā-
mitra told the river what he wanted her to do;
hearing that Sarasvatī was pained; she just
stood there all the while shaking with fear;
Viśvāmitra asked her again to bring Vasiṣṭha
quickly to him; she was worried what
to do as she was afraid of the curses
of both the sages; she went to Vasiṣṭha
and informed him what Viśvāmitra's desire
was; Vasiṣṭha saw her pale and lean and
told her to carry him to Viśvāmitra and save
herself from the latter's curse; hearing that
Sarasvatī reflected on what she might
do which would turn out beneficial to
Vasiṣṭha as he had been merciful to her;
when she saw on the other bank Viśvāmitra
engaged in giving offerings she thought that
to be the right moment to act swiftly (सरस्-
वत्य् अभ्यचिन्तयत्।इदम् अन्तरम् इत्य् एव
9. 41. 26-27); she washed away a part of
her bank on the side of Vasiṣṭha so that he
was carried on her current to the आश्रम of
Viśvāmitra; while he was being thus carried
Vasiṣṭha praised Sarasvatī (Sarasvatī's praise
9. 41. 29-31); Sarasvatī informed Viśvāmitra
that she had brought Vasiṣṭha; Viśvāmitra
began to look for a weapon to kill Vasiṣṭha;
being afraid of the sin of killing a Brāhmaṇa
Sarasvatī carried Vasiṣṭha back to the eastern
bank (ब्रह्महत्याभयान् नदी।अपोवाह
वसिष्ठं तु प्राचीं दिशम् अतन्द्रिता 9. 41.
34); she thus did what both the sages asked
her to do, but Viśvāmitra was deceived;
enraged, he cursed the river to flow with
blood; as a result Sarasvatī flew with water
mixed with blood for a year; the sages, gods,
Gandharvas and Apsarases were excessively
pained to see Sarasvatī in that condition; this
is how the तीर्थ Vasiṣṭhāpavāha came into
existance 9. 41. 11-39; when Sarasvatī
carried blood with water in her current,
Rākṣasas came there and were happy to drink
blood from the river water; once, some sages,
while visiting the तीर्थस्, came to Vasiṣṭhā-
pavāha they saw the Rākṣasas drinking
blood from the river; they decided to do
something to save the river; they invited
Sarasvatī and found out from her the cause
of the disturbed condition of the तीर्थ
(कारणं ब्रूहि कल्याणि किमर्थं ते
ह्रदो ह्य् अयम्।एवम् आकुलतां यातः
9. 42. 9); on hearing the cause, they decided
to free the river from the curse; by their
mere word Sarasvatī returned to her normal
condition and her water was as placid as
before (तेषां तु वचनाद् एव प्रकृतिस्था
सरस्वती।प्रसन्नसलिला जज्ञे यथा पूर्-
वम् तथैव हि 9. 42. 13); the excellent river
shone as before; since the river water was
normal again the Rākṣasas were afflicted by
hunger and they requested the sages to relieve
them from that condition; the sages praised
the river and urged her to relieve the Rākṣasas
from their condition; knowing what the sages
wanted Sarasvatī brought to her current the
river Aruṇā (अरुणाम् आनयाम् आस स्वां
तनुम्); bathing in that river the Rākṣasas
abandoned their bodies and went to heaven
9. 42. 1-25; (12) While Dadhīca was
giving offerings to gods on the bank of Saras-
vatī (तस्य तर्पयतो देवान् सरस्वत्याम्
9. 50. 8), the Apsaras Alambusā, sent by
Indra to disturb the austerities of Dadhīca,
approached him; seeing her divine form the
seed of Dadhīca spilled into water of Sara-
svatī; the river held it in her womb as she
desired to have a son and also because the seed
might not be wasted (कुक्षौ चाप्य् अदधत् …
तद् रेतः … पुत्रहेतोर् महानदी 9. 50. 10;
न विनाशम् इदं गच्छेत् त्वत्तेज इति निश्च-
यात् 9. 50. 14); when Sarasvatī delivered the
child at proper time she took him to Dadhīca;
seeing Dadhīca seated in the assembly of
sages she handed over the child to him saying
it was his son whom she bore out of her
devotion to the sage (ब्रह्मर्षे तव पुत्रो
ऽयं त्वद्भक्त्या धारितो मया 9. 50. 12);
Dadhīca accepted the child and was very much
delighted; he then gave the following boon
to Sarasvatī: “all gods, manes, Gandharvas
and Apsarases will be satisfied when they
receive offerings of your water (तृप्तिं या-
स्यन्ति सुभगे तर्प्यमाणास् तवाम्भसा 9.
50. 17); the sage then praised the great river
(9. 50. 19-20); he declared that this her
son will be known as Sārasvata after the
mother's name (तवैव नाम्ना प्रथितः
पुत्रस् ते लोकभावनः 9. 50. 21); he also
declared that by his grace Sarasvatī would
be the holiest of all holy rivers (पुण्याभ्यश्
च सरिद्भ्यस् त्वं सदा पुण्यतमा शुभे।
भविष्यसि महाभागे मत्प्रसादात् सरस्-
वति 9. 50. 23); when praised by the sage and
having received a boon from him Sarasvatī
went away taking her son with her 9. 50.
5-24; (13) Once there was drought lasting
for twelve years; when Sārasvata, like other
people, wanted to leave the place and go else-
where in search of food, Sarasvatī told him
not to leave the place; she assured him to
provide food to him in the form of excellent
fish; Sārasvata therefore lived there; he ate
the food offered by the river and preserved the
Vedas 9. 50. 36-38; (14) Bharata, son of
Duḥṣyanta and Śakuntalā, bound twenty
horses for sacrifice on the bank of Sarasvatī
(सरस्वतीं विंशतिं च) 12. 29. 41; (15)
Gārgya satisfied Śiva by offering a mental
sacrifice on the bank of Sarasvatī (सर्स्वत्यास्
तटे तुष्टो मनोयज्ञेन पाण्डव); Śiva
then gave him wonderful knowledge of time
(कालज्ञानं ममाद्भुतम्), a thousand
sons, equal to Gārgya, versed in the exposition
of Brahman (तुल्यं मम सहस्रं तु
सुतानां ब्रह्मवादिनाम्), and very long
life to him and to his sons 13. 18. 25-26;
(16) Nahuṣa invited Agastya, who was
then on the bank of Sarasvatī, to come to
him and draw his carriage (वाहनायाजुहाव
सः।द्रुतं सरस्वतीकूलात्) 13. 103. 12;
(17) Utathya, angered at the abduction
of his wife by Varuṇa, began to drink up
water everywhere, compelled the ocean to
recede and asked Sarasvatī: “Be invisible
in a desert land; when deserted by you let
the land be unholy” (अदृश्या गच्छ भीरु
त्वं सरस्वति मरुं प्रति।अपुण्य एष
भवतु देशस् त्यक्तस् त्वया शुभे) 13. 139.
25-26; (18) Sarasvatī was one of the rivers
seen by Mārkaṇḍeya in the belly of the Bāla
(3. 186. 83 = Nārāyaṇa 3. 187. 3) 3. 186.
96; (19) Janamejaya asked Vaiśaṃpāyana
the origin of the Saptasārasvata tīrtha;
Vaiśaṃpāyana then began the narration of
a past event in which Sarasvatī, when invited
for a sacrifice at different places, appeared
there under different names 9. 37. 1, 3-4; (i)
When Pitāmaha (Brahmadeva) thought of
Sarasvatī she first appeared as Suprabhā at
Puṣkara to make the sacrifice of Pitāmaha
on this earth highly fruitful (महाफलः);
Sarasvatī thus showed her respect for Pitāmaha
(पितामहं मानयन्तीम्) 9. 37. 11-14;
(ii) When Sarasvatī was thought of by the
sages performing a सत्र at Naimiṣa forest
she appeared there as Kāñcanākṣī to help the
sages (सहायार्थं महात्मनाम्); she was
honoured by the sages (पूजिता) 9. 37. 15-18;
(iii) When she appeared for the sacrifice of
Gaya among the people of Gayā (गयेषु),
sages called her Viśālā 9. 37. 20; (iv) In
the sacrifice of Auddālaki in the northern Ko-
salas when she was thought of by Auddālaka
the river appeared there for him (आजगाम
सरिच्छ्रेठा तं देशम् ऋषिकारणात्) under
the name Manohradā (Mānasahradā in 9. 37.
4) since she was carried there by the sages
through the agency of their mind (सा हि
तैर् मनसा हृता); the river was honoured
there by the sages (पूज्यमाना मुनिगणैः)
9. 37. 21-23; (v) In the Ṛṣabhadvīpa the
river appeared with the name Suveṇu 9. 37.
24; (vi) In the sacrifice of Kuru at
Kurukṣetra. when invoked by Vasiṣṭha, the
river Sarasvatī appeared with the name Ogha-
vatī 9. 37. 24-25; (vii) In the sacrifice
of Dakṣa at Gaṅgādvāra the river appear-
ed as Vimalodā 9. 37. 26 (Vimalodakā
9. 37. 4); when Brahman offered a sacri-
fice again he called the river back on the
Himavant mountain; the तीर्थ where all
the seven forms of the river got united
became famous as Saptasārasvata 9. 37. 26-
28; (20) When the chariot of Śiva was
got ready for his fight with Asuras fighting
from the Tripuras the Mahānadīs became
its hind parts (जङ्घास् तस्य महानदीः)
8. 24. 69 (Sarasvatī could be one of these
‘big rivers’; but cf. the next); (21) Saras-
vatī was the परिरथ्य (?) of Śiva's
chariot 8. 24. 75 (however, according to Nī.
on Bom. Ed. 8. 34. 34, सरस्वती here
means speech: परिरथ्या प्रचारमार्गः।
सरस्वती वाग्देवीकल्पितः शब्दमात्रशरीर
इत्य् अर्थः); (22) When Hari resorted to
another body with the head of a horse for
the rescue of the Vedas, Gaṅgā and Sarasvatī
became his two eyebrows (गङ्गा सरस्वती
पुण्या भ्रुवाव् आस्तां महानदी) 12. 335.
46; (23) The gods, led by Brahman, took
with them Skanda and went to Himavant
and the river Sarasvatī for his consecration
as the general of their army 9. 43. 50-52;
they consecrated Skanda at Sthāṇutīrtha on
Sarasvatī 9. 41. 6-7; gods consecrated Skanda
as their general with the holy waters of Saras-
vatī having heavenly waters (सरस्वतीभिः
पुण्याभिर् दिव्यतोयाभिर् एव तु।अभ्यषिञ्चन्
कुमारं वै) 9. 44. 18-19; (24) Dakṣa
told gods that the emaciated Soma (moon)
would grow again after bathing in the exce-
llent तीर्थ on Sarasvatī (सरस्वत्या वरे
तीर्थे उन्मज्जन् शशलक्षणः।पुनर्
वर्धिष्यते देवाः); Soma then proceeded
to the great तीर्थ Prabāsa on Sarasvatī
9. 34. 67, 69; (25) Sthāṇu (Śiva) offered
a sacrifice and honoured Sarasvatī and then
established Sthāṇutīrtha on the river 9. 41. 8;
(26) When Indra was pursued by the head
of Namuci, Pitāmaha (Brahman) asked Indra
to offer a sacrifice and to bathe in Aruṇā;
Indra then offered a sacrifice in the Kuñja of
Sarasvatī and bathed in Aruṇā (सरस्वत्याः
कुञ्जे … इष्ट्वा … अरुणायाम् उपास्पृशत्)
9. 42. 34-35; (27) At the तीर्थ (not
named) situated near the आश्रम of Baka
Dālbhya on the river Sarasvatī (9. 39. 32;
9. 40. 1) Bṛhaspati gave offerings of flesh
for the prosperity of gods and the decline of
Asuras (असुराणाम् अभावाय भावाय च
दिवौकसाम्) 9. 40. 26-27; (28) Sarasvatī
was one of the rivers whom Umā wanted to
consult on स्त्रीधर्म before expounding
it to Śiva as these rivers were well-versed
in it; Umā thereby wanted to honour the
rivers; the rivers appointed Gaṅgā to speak
on their behalf to Umā 13. 134. 13, 19-22,
25.
G. Importance: (1) One of the rivers
who wait upon Varuṇa in his Sabhā (उपा-
सते महात्मानम्) 2. 9. 19, 22; (2) Men-
tioned twice in the Daivata-Ṛṣi-Vaṃśa reci-
ted by Bhīṣma 13. 151. 14, 22, (2).
H.
Simile: Draupadī having five Pāṇḍavas as
her husbands was very happy with them and
they with Draupadī as is Sarasvatī with the
Nāgas (बभूव परमप्रीता नागैर् इव
सरस्वती) 1. 205. 3 (Nī. on 1. 213. 3:
नागैर् गजैः; he, however, adds: सरस्वती
बहुसरोयुक्ता वनस्थली।सा हि गजैर्
युक्तान्यैश् छेत्तुम् अशक्या।तया च गजा
बलिनः।एवं ते मिथो वृद्धिहेतवः).
[See Bhogavatī2]

सरस्वतितीर्थ
Sarasvatitīrtha nt.: See Sthāṇutīrtha.

सर्पदर्वी
Sarpadarvī f.: Name of a तीर्थ।
Sacred to Nāgas; described as best (तीर्-
थम् उत्तमम्); by visiting it (समासाद्य)
one gets the fruit of an Agniṣṭoma and wins
for himself the world of the Nāgas (नाग-
लोक) 3. 81. 12. [See Kapilasya tīrtham]

सर्वदेवह्रद
Sarvadevahrada nt.: Name of a तीर्थ।
By bathing there one gets the fruit of
gifting a thousand cows 3. 83. 36.

सर्वदेवानां
Sarvadevānāṃ tīrtham nt.: Name of
a तीर्थ।
Perhaps in the Phalakīvana 3. 81. 72;
by bathing there one gets the fruit of gifting
a thousand cows 3. 81. 74.

सलिलराजस्य
Salilarājasya tīrtham nt.: Name of a
तीर्थ।
Situated at the place where the river
Sindhu meets the ocean (सागरस्य च सिन्धोश्
च संगमं प्राप्य); if one who has con-
trolled his mind (प्रयतमानसः) bathes in
this तीर्थ and gives offerings to manes,
gods and sages (तर्पयित्वा पितॄन् देवान्
ऋषींश् च) he shines with his own lustre
and goes to the world of Varuṇa (प्राप्नोति
वारुणं लोकं दीप्यमानः स्वतेजसा); the
wise say (प्रवदन्ति मनीषिणः) that if one
worships the god Śaṅkukarṇeśvara there one
gets the reward of an Aśvamedha ten times
(अश्वमेधं दशगुणम्) 3. 80. 85-87.

सह्य
Sahya m.: Name of a mountain.
A. Location: Near the (southern)
ocean (लवणाम्भसः।समीपे) 3. 266.
42.
B. Importance: (1) One of the eleven
mountains listed by Brahman as kings of
mountains (एते पर्वतराजानः); (are these
mountains also supposed to be characterized
by the मध्यम गुण, i. e. by the quality of
रजस् ? 14. 43. 1; Nī on Bom. Ed. 14. 43. 1:
मध्यमो गुणः रजोगुणप्रधानः; (2)
Listed by Saṃjaya among the seven princi-
pal mountains (सप्तैते कुलपर्वताः) 6.
10. 10.
C. Past event: (1) When Nahuṣa
was made the king of the heaven he used
to sport with Apsarases and Devakanyās on
the Sahya and other mountains 5. 11. 8-10;
(2) When Hanūmant and others, in search
of Sītā, came out of the residence of Maya
in a big cave they saw the Sahya and the
Malaya mountains (लवणाम्भसः।समीपे
सह्यमलयौ) 3. 266. 42.

सागरसिन्धुसंगम
*Sāgarasindhusaṃgama m.: See Salila-
rājasya tīrtham.

सागरोदक
Sāgarodaka nt.: Name of a तीर्थ।
Listed in the Tīrthavaṃśa narrated by
Aṅgiras to Gautama 13. 26. 9, 3-4; by bath-
ing in it (विगाह्य) one rides in a विमान
and is awakened (in the morning) by the
praises sung by the Apsarases (विबोध्यते
विमानस्थः सो ऽप्सरोभिर् अभिष्टुतः) 13.
26. 9.

सामुद्रक
Sāmudraka nt.: Name of a तीर्थ।
Near Arundhatīvaṭa; by bathing in this
तीर्थ (उपस्पृश्य) and by fasting there for
three nights one gets the fruit of giving a
thousand cows and lifts up his family (कुलं
चैव समुद्धरेत्) 3. 82. 37.

सारस्वतमुनेस्
Sārasvatamunes tīrtham nt.: Name of
a तीर्थ।
At this तीर्थ, formerly when there was
drought lasting for twelve years, the sage Sāra-
svata taught Vedas to the Brāhmaṇas 9. 50.
2, 22; Balarāma gave there gifts consisting
of wealth (तत्रापि दत्त्वा वसु) 9. 50. 51.

सावित्र
Sāvitra nt.: A peak of Meru, sacred
to Savitṛ. [See Jyotiṣka]

साहस्रक
Sāhasraka nt.: Name of a तीर्थ।
Near the तीर्थ called Śatasahasraka;
described as famous in the world (लोक-
विश्रुत); by bathing in both these तीर्थस्
one gets the fruit of giving a thousand
cows, and his gifts and fasts give him thou-
sandfold rewards (दानं वाप्य् उपवासो वा
सहस्रगुणितं भवेत्) 3. 81. 137-138.

सिकताक्ष
Sikatākṣa nt.: Name of a lake ?
The Pāṇḍavas were to visit Sikatākṣa
after performing the rites near the lake of
Cyavana and then reach the Saindhavāraṇya
3. 125. 11-12.

सिन्धु
Sindhu m., f.: Name of a river.
A. Location: In the west (2. 29. 2,
8); listed twice by Saṃjaya among the
rivers of the Bhāratavarṣa; people used its
water for drinking 6. 10. 13, 20; the river
Gaṅgā, after descending from Brahmaloka,
was first established on the Hiraṇyaśṛṅga
mountain; from there it began to flow in
seven streams, of which Sindhu was the
seventh (तत्र त्रिपथगा देवी … सप्तधा
प्रतिपद्यते। … सिन्धुश् च सप्तमी) 6.
7. 44-45; the Bāhlīka (Āraṭṭa) country
lies within the region of the five rivers with
Sindhu as the sixth flowing through it (पञ्चा-
नां सिन्धुषष्ठानां नदीनां ये ऽन्तरा-
श्रिताः।तान् … बाह्लीकान् परिवर्जयेत्) 8. 30.
11; (सिन्धुषष्ठा बहिर्गताः॥आरट्टा
नाम ते देशाः) 8. 30. 35-36; (पञ्च नद्यो
वहन्त्य् एता यत्र निःसृत्य पर्वतात्।आरट्टा
नाम बाह्लीकाः) 8. 30. 43; the rivers which
flow through the Kāśmīramaṇḍala reach
Sindhu (काश्मीरमण्डले नद्यो याः पतन्ति
महानदम्।ता नदीः सिन्धुम् आसाद्य)
13. 26. 8.
B. Description: Characterized
as a great Nada (महानद) 13. 26. 8 (Nī.
on Bom. Ed. 13. 25. 8: नदं सिन्धुम्);
(नदस्य महतः) 1. 89. 35; all the rivers,
including Sindhu, who wait upon god Śiva
are described as auspicious (शिवाः) 13. 134.
22; very holy (पुण्यतमाः) 13. 134. 22;
excellent rivers (सरिद्वराः) 13. 134. 14;
(सरितां वराः) 13. 134. 19; (सरिच्छ्रे-
ष्ठाः) 13. 134. 22; having the waters of all
तीर्थस् (सर्वतीर्थोदकैर् युताः) 13. 134.
12; and expert in the knowledge of duties of
women (स्त्रीधर्मकुशलाः) 13. 134. 19;
the source (प्रभव) of the river Sindhu
is frequented by the Siddhas and Gandhar-
vas (सिद्धगन्धर्वसेवित) 3. 82. 41; all
the rivers listed by Saṃjaya are described as
mothers of the universe and very strong 6.
10. 35 (for citation see Atikṛṣṇā).
C.
Holiness: (1) By staying for five nights
at the source of Sindhu one gets much gold
(सिन्धोश् च प्रभवं गत्वा … ।तत्रोष्य
रजनीः पञ्च विन्द्याद् बहु सुवर्ण-
कम्) 3. 82. 41; (2) In the Tīrthavaṃśa
proclaimed by Aṅgiras to Gautama it is said
that one who has a good character if he
reaches the rivers which meet Sindhu and also
Sindhu he goes to heaven (ता नदीः सिन्धुम्
आसाद्य शीलवान् स्वर्गम् आप्नुयात्) 13. 26.
8; (3) There is the तीर्थ of Salilarāja
(Varuṇa) at the place where Sindhu meets
the ocean (सागरस्य च सिन्धोश् च संग-
मं प्राप्य) 3. 80. 85.
D. Epic events:
(1) Nakula, in his expedition to the west
before the Rājasūya, subjugated the powerful
Grāmaṇeyas (?) who lived along the banks
of Sindhu (सिन्धुकूलाश्रिता ये च ग्राम-
णेया महाबलाः) 2. 29. 8; (2) Those who
lived along the river Sindhu brought various
kinds of tribute to Yudhiṣṭhira for Rājasūya
(परिसिन्धु च मानवाः। … विविधं बलिम्
आदाय … द्वारि तिष्ठन्ति वारिताः) 2. 47. 9-
11; (3) Yudhiṣṭhira staked whatever wealth
that belonged to different castes (?), in their
order, and who lived to the east of Sindhu
(यत् किंचिद् अनुवर्णानाम् प्राक् सिन्धोर्
अपि सौबल।एतन् मम धनं राजन्)
2. 58. 5.
E. Past events: (1) King Saṃ-
varaṇa, when attacked and defeated by
Pāñcālya, fled with his family members,
ministers and friends and took shelter in a
thicket (निकुञ्ज) of the Sindhunada, in the
region of the river near the mountain; the
Bhāratas lived there for a long time taking
resort to the inaccessible land (सिन्धोर्
नदस्य महतो निकुञ्जे न्यवसत् तदा।
नदीविषयपर्यन्ते पर्वतस्य समीपतः।
तत्रावसन् बहून् कालान् भारता दुर्गम्
आश्रिताः॥) 1. 89. 33-35; (2) Mārkaṇḍeya
saw Sindhu, among other rivers, in the belly
of the Bāla (3. 186. 83 = Nārāyaṇa 3. 187.
3) 3. 186. 94.
F. Importance: (1) Sindhu
is one of the rivers which wait upon Varuṇa
in his Sabhā 2. 9. 19; (2) Finds mention in
the Daivata-Ṛṣi-Vaṃśa 13. 151. 14, 2.
G.
Limitation: Sindhu is not included among
the rivers which are declared as mothers of
fire-hearths, i. e. on the banks of which
sacrifices were performed (सिन्धुवर्जं
पञ्चनद्यः … एता नद्यस् तु धिष्ण्यानां
मातरो याः प्रकीर्तिताः) 3. 212. 21, 24 (for
Nī. See Kapilā).
H. Simile: (1) Suc-
cessful emerging of Kṛṣṇa and Arjuna out
of the army led by Droṇa (7. 76. 23) com-
pared to crossing Sindhu and other five rivers
swollen with water at the end of summer
(बाहुभ्याम् इव संतीर्णौ सिन्धुषष्ठाः
समुद्रगाः।तपान्ते सरितः पूर्णाः) 7.
76. 28 (Nī. on Bom. Ed. 7. 101. 28: सिन्धुः
षष्ठो यासां ताश् च शतद्रुविपाशेरावती-
चन्द्रभागावितस्ताः); (2) The army of
the Pāṇḍavas encountering Śalya was check-
ed like the current of Sindhu encountering a
mountain (सिन्धोर् वेग इवाचलम्) 9. 9. 6.
I. Bad omens: Among the bad omens which
occurred when Kṛṣṇa left for Hāstinapura
is mentioned one according to which great
rivers among whom Sindhu was the fore-
most, flowing eastwards, began to flow in the
opposite direction (प्रत्यग् ऊहुर् महानद्यः
प्राङ्मुखाः सिन्धुसत्तमाः) 5. 82. 6 (Nī.
on Bom. Ed. 5. 84. 6: प्रत्यक् प्रतीपम्
ऊहुः प्रवाहं कृतवत्यः; or does सिन्धु
here mean ‘river’ ?). [See Sindhūttama,
Salilarājasya tīrtham]

सिन्धूत्तम
Sindhūttama nt.: Name of a तीर्थ।
Situated near the Vasordhārā tīrtha 3.
80. 92; described as famous (ख्यात) and
destroying all sins (सर्वपापप्रणाशन);
by bathing there one gets much gold (लभेद्
बहु सुवर्णकम्) 3. 80. 95; finds mention
in the Daivata-Ṛṣi-Vaṃśa 13. 151. 19, 2.

सिन्धोस्
Sindhos tīrtham nt.: Name of a तीर्थ।
Described as great (महन्त्); Lopāmudrā
met Agastya there and chose him for her
husband 3. 130. 6.

सीता
Sītā1 f.: Name of a river.
A. Location: One of the seven streams
of the divine river Tripathagā into which
it was divided after it was established on
Hiraṇyaśṛṅga mountain (ब्रह्मलोकाद् अप-
क्रान्ता सप्तधा प्रतिपद्यते) 6. 7. 44-45.
B. Past event: Sītā was one of the rivers
seen by Mārkaṇḍeya in the belly of the Bāla
(3. 186. 83 = Nārāyaṇa 3. 187. 3) 3. 186.
93.
C. Importance: Finds mention in the
Daivata-Ṛṣi-Vaṃśa 13. 151. 22, 2.

सीता
Sītā2 f.: Name of a river.
A certain river apparently famous for
its whirlpools in which boats sink (सीता नाम
नदी राजन् प्लवो यस्यां निमज्जति) 12. 83.
44 (Nī. on Bom. Ed. 12. 82. 44: यथा
बह्वावर्तायां सीतायां प्लवस् तारणोपायः
निमज्जति … )

सीता
Sītā3 f.: Name of a river.
One of the rivers of the Śākadvīpa 6. 12.
30; all the rivers of the Śākadvīpa are said
to be holy (पुण्याः) 6. 12. 32, having holy
water (नद्यः पुण्यजलास् तत्र) 6. 12. 29,
(पुण्योदाः) 6. 12. 31, and excellent (सरिद्-
वराः) 6. 12. 32; Indra takes water from
these rivers to give it as rain (यतो वर्षति
वासवः) 6. 12. 31.

सुकुमारी
Sukumārī f.: Name of a river.
One of the rivers of the Śākadvīpa 6. 12.
30 (for other details see Sītā3).

सुगन्धा
Sugandhā f.: Name of a river.
Described as famous in the world (लोक-
विश्रुता) 3. 82. 32; by visiting it one is glori-
fied in heaven (अभिगम्य … स्वर्गलोके
महीयते) 3. 82. 9; he is also freed of all sins
and is glorified in the world of Brahman (ततो
गच्छेत राजेन्द्र सुगन्धाम् … ।सर्व-
पापविशुद्धात्मा ब्रह्मलोके महीयते)
3. 82. 32.

सुतीर्थक
Sutīrthaka nt.: Name of a तीर्थ।
Described as unsurpassed (अनुत्तम)
3. 81. 44; gods and manes are always present
there; by bathing there and by worshipping
gods and manes (पितृदेवार्चने रतः) one
gets the fruit of a horse sacrifice and goes to
the world of manes (पितृलोकं च गच्छति)
3. 81. 44-45.

सुदर्शन
Sudarśana m., Sudarśanā f.: Name of
a big Jambū tree.
A. Location: In the beautiful forest on
mount Meru (मेरोर् अग्रे यद् वनं भाति
रम्यम् … सुदर्शना यत्र जम्बूर् विशाला)
13. 105. 20; to the south of mount Nīla and
to the north of Niṣadha (दक्षिणेन तु नीलस्य
निषधस्योत्तरेण तु।सुदर्शनो नाम
महाञ् जम्बूवृक्षः) 6. 8. 18.
B. Extent:
The tree is one thousand one hundred योज-
नस् high (योजनानां सहस्रं च शतं च
भरतर्षभ।उत्सेद्धो वृक्षराजस्य) 6.
8. 20; its circumference is one thousand and
fifteen hundred अरत्निस् (अरत्नीनां सह-
स्रं च शतानि दश पञ्च च।परिणाहस् तु
वृक्षस्य) 6. 8. 21.
C. Description: Eternal
(सनातन) 6. 8. 18; holy (पुण्य) 6. 8. 19;
big (महन्त्) 6. 8. 18; extensive (विशाला)
13. 105. 20; touching the sky (दिवस्पृश्) 6.
8. 20; king of trees (वृक्षराज) 6. 8. 20; ful-
filling all desires (सर्वकामफल) 6. 8. 19;
beautiful (सुदर्शना) 13. 105. 20; resorted
to by Siddhas and Cāraṇas (सिद्धचारण-
सेवित) 6. 8. 19.
D. Characteristic: When
the fruit of Sudarśana, bursting with juice,
fall on the ground they make much noise;
juice, shining like silver, issues from the split
fruit; that juice of the fruit of Jambū tree
turns into a river, flows around Meru and
goes to the Uttara Kurus; delighted men
drink that juice and they do not grow old;
gold of the type of Jāmbūnada, from which
ornaments for gods are fashioned, is avail-
able there; men who live on this river
produced from the fruit of the Jambū tree
have the complexion of morning sun (तत्र
जाम्बूनदं नाम कनकं देवभूष-
णम्।तरुणादित्यवर्णाश्च जायन्ते तत्र
मानवाः) 6. 8. 25.
E. Importance: (1)
The eternal Jambūdvīpa is named after this
Jambū tree (तस्य नाम्ना समाख्यातो
जम्बूद्वीपः सनातनः) 6. 8. 19; (2)
Gautama offered to take king Dhṛtarāṣṭra
(really Indra) to the beautiful forest on
mount Meru where there was the beautiful
Jambū tree in lieu of his elephant that was
being carried away by the king, (but the king
did not wish to go there) 13. 105. 20.

सुदिन
Sudina nt.: Name of a तीर्थ।
Mentioned along with the तीर्थ Ahar;
described as one of difficult access (सुदुर्-
लभ); by bathing there one goes to the world
of the sun (सूर्यलोकम् अवाप्नुयात्) 3. 81.
84.

सुधामन्
Sudhāman m.: Name of a mountain.
One of the six mountains of the Kuśa-
dvīpa; described as full of corals and difficult
to be assaulted (पर्वतो विद्रुमैश् चितः।
सुधामा नाम दुर्धर्षः) 6. 13. 9; all
the six mountains of Kuśadvīpa are said to be
the best mountains (षड् एते पर्वतोत्तमाः)
6. 13. 11; the distance between the six moun-
tains doubles as one goes from one to the other
(तेषाम् अन्तरविष्कम्भो द्विगुणः प्रविभा-
गशः) 6. 13. 11.

सुनसा
Sunasā f.: Name of a river.
Listed by Saṃjaya among the rivers of
the Bhāratavarṣa; people used its water for
drinking 6. 10. 30, 13; all the rivers listed
by Saṃjaya are said to be mothers of the
universe and very strong 6. 10. 35 (for cita-
tion see Atikṛṣṇā).

सुन्दरिकातीर्थ
Sundarikātīrtha nt., Sundarikāhrada
m.: Name of a तीर्थ, a sacred lake.
Described as visited by Siddhas (सिद्-
धनिषेवित) 3. 82. 51; by reaching it
(सुन्दरिकातीर्थं प्राप्य) one gets a good
form; this has been told in the old (text)
(रूपस्य भागी भवति दृष्टम् एतत् पुरा-
तने) 3. 82. 51; by bathing in the Sundarikā-
hrada at proper time and place (?) one receives
from the Aśvins good form and lustre in
the next birth (देशकाल उपस्पृश्य तथा
सुन्दरिकाह्रदे।अश्विभ्यां रूपवर्चस्यं
प्रेत्य वै लभते नरः) 13. 26. 19 (Nī.,
who reads रूपवर्चस्कम्, on Bom. Ed. 13.
25. 21: रूपवर्चसोः समाहारः रूपवर्-
चस्कं वर्चस् तेजः।; on 13. 25. 6 प्रेत्य-
भावे जन्मान्तरे).

सुप्रभा
Suprabhā f.: Name of a river.
A. Location: Flowing through the
Puṣkaras (पुष्करेषु वै।सुप्रभा नाम)
9. 37. 12, 14.
B. Description: Flowing
with speed (वेगयुक्ता) 9. 37. 13; best
among rivers (सरिच्छ्रेष्ठा) 9. 37. 14.
C. Past events: One of the seven forms
of Sarasvatī which cover the whole world
(सप्त सरस्वत्यो याभिर् व्याप्तम् इदं
जगत्) 9. 37. 3; when Pitāmaha (Brahman)
was offering a sacrifice on this earth (पिता-
महस्य महतो वर्तमाने महीतले।
वितते यज्ञवाटे 9. 37. 5) the sages said
that the sacrifice will not bear great fruit
as Sarasvatī was not present; then god Pitā-
maha thought of Sarasvatī and invited her
to appear at the Puṣkaras; the river appeared
there under the name Suprabhā (सुप्रभा
नाम राजेन्द्र नाम्ना तत्र सरस्वती; एवम्
एषा सरिच्छ्रेष्ठा पुष्करेषु सरस्वती);
Sarasvatī appeared there for the sake of
Pitāmaha and for the satisfaction of the sages
9. 37. 5-14.

सुप्रयोगा
Suprayogā f.: Name of a river.
Listed by Saṃjaya among the rivers of
the Bhāratavarṣa; people used its water for
drinking 6. 10. 20, 13; all the rivers listed
by Saṃjaya are said to be mothers of the uni-
verse and very strong 6. 10. 35 (for citation
see Atikṛṣṇā); listed by Mārkaṇḍeya among
rivers which are famous as mothers of the fire-
hearths i. e. on the banks of which sacrifices
were performed (एता नद्यस् तु धिष्ण्यानां
मातरो याः प्रकीर्तिताः) 3. 212. 24 (for Nī.
see Kapīlā).

सुभूमिक
Subhūmika nt., Subhūmikā f.: Name
of a तीर्थ।
A. Location: Situated on the bank of
Sarasvatī (सुभूमिकं … सरस्वत्यास् तटे
वरे) 9. 36. 3; (सुभूमिकेति विख्याता सर-
स्वत्यास् तटे वरे) 9. 36. 8.
B. Descrip-
tion: Holy (पुण्य) 9. 36. 5; resorted to
by Brāhmaṇas (ब्राह्मणसेवित) 9. 36. 5;
auspicious sporting ground of the Apsarases
(आक्रीडभूमिः … अप्सरसां शुभा) 9. 36.
8.
C. Characteristics: (1) There the
shining Apsarases sport at all times without
lassitude (तत्र चाप्सरसः शुभ्रा नित्य-
कालम् अतन्द्रिताः।क्रीडाभिर् विमलाभिश् च
क्रीदन्ति) 9. 36. 4; (2) Hosts of Gandharvas
and Apsarases are seen there together as they
meet and as long as they wish (समेत्य सहिता
राजन् यथाप्राप्तं यथासुखं) 9. 36. 6.
D. Holiness: (1) The holy तीर्थ is visited
by gods and Gandharvas every month 9. 36.
5; (2) There gods and manes, showered
again and again at all times with holy and
divine flowers along with plants (?) (सवी-
रुधः।पुण्यैः पुष्पैः सदा दिव्यैः
कीर्यमानाः पुनः पुनः॥), take delight
9. 36. 7.
E. Epic event: Balarāma went
to it from Vinaśana; he bathed there and
offered wealth to Brāhmaṇas; he heard there
heavenly music (of the Apsarases) and sound
of musical instruments; he also saw there
many shadows of gods, Gandharvas and
Rakṣases (छायाश् च विपुला दृष्ट्वा देव-
गन्धर्वरक्षसाम्) 9. 36. 3, 9-10.

सुरोद
Suroda m.: Name of an ocean.
One of the oceans surrounding the Dvīpas
in the north 6. 13. 1-2.

सुवर्णाक्ष
Suvarṇākṣa nt. Name of a तीर्थ।
A. Description: Described as famous
in the three worlds (त्रिषु लोकेषु विश्रुतम्)
3. 82. 16.
B. Holiness: By visiting this
तीर्थ (अभिगम्य) and by worshipping
there Vṛṣadhvaja (Śiva) one gets the fruit
of a horse sacrifice and the status of a Gaṇa-
pati (गाणपत्यं च विन्दति) 3. 82. 19.
C. Past event: Formerly Viṣṇu propiti-
ated Rudra to win his favour; as a result
he obtained many boons from Rudra; Rudra,
who was satisfied, said that Kṛṣṇa would be
more dear (to people) than Śiva and that
he would be the foremost in the whole world
(अपि चास्मत् प्रियतरो लोके कृष्ण भविष्यसि।
त्वन्मुखं च जगत् कृत्स्नं भविष्यति
न संशयः॥) 3. 82. 16-18 (Nī. on Bom.
Ed. 3. 84. 21: त्वन्मुखं त्वत्प्रधा-
नम्).

सुवामा
Suvāmā f.: Name of a river.
Listed by Saṃjaya among the rivers of
the Bhāratavarṣa; people used its water for
drinking 6. 10. 27, 13; all the rivers listed by
Saṃjaya are said to be mothers of the uni-
verse and very strong 6. 10. 35 (for citation
see Atikṛṣṇā).

सुवास्तु
Suvāstu f.: Name of a river.
Listed by Saṃjaya among the rivers of
the Bhāratavarṣa; people used its water for
drinking 6. 10. 24, 13; all the rivers listed
by Saṃjaya are said to be mothers of the
universe and very strong 6. 10. 35 (for cita-
tion see Atikṛṣṇā).

सुवेणा
Suveṇā f.: Name of a river.
One of the rivers seen by Mārkaṇḍeya
in the belly of the Bāla (3. 186. 83 = Nārā-
yaṇa 3. 187. 3) 3. 186. 95.

सवेणु
Saveṇu f.: Name of a river.
One of the seven forms of the river
Sarasvatī which pervade the whole world
(याभिर् व्याप्तम् इदम् जगत्) 9. 37. 3-4;
when Sarasvatī was invited by sages perform-
ing the sacrifice at the holy Ṛṣabhadvīpa the
river Sarasvatī appeared there as Suveṇu
9. 37. 24; when Sarasvatī was invited again
by Brahman at his sacrifice on the Hima-
vant all the seven streams gathered there
together in the form of the Saptasārasvata
tīrtha 9. 37. 26-27.

सुशृङ्ग
Suśṛṅga m.: Name of a mountain.
One of the mountains seen by Arjuna
when he, along with Kṛṣṇa, went at night
through the sky to propitiate Śiva in order to
get his Pāśupata 7. 57. 28, 16-17.

सूची
Sūcī f.: Name of a river.
Listed by Saṃjaya among the rivers of
the Bhāratavarṣa; people used its water for
drinking 6. 10. 23, 13; all the rivers listed by
Saṃjaya are said to be mothers of the universe
and very strong 6. 10. 35 (for citation see
Atikṛṣṇā).

सूर्पारक
Sūrpāraka nt.: See Śūrpāraka.

सूर्यतीर्थ
Sūryatīrtha nt.: Name of a तीर्थ।
One who has controlled his mind (नियत-
मानसः) if he visits this तीर्थ, bathes there,
and worships manes and gods while observ-
ing fast (उपवासपरायणः) he gets the
fruit of an Agniṣṭoma and goes to the world
of the sun (सूर्यलोकं च गच्छति) 3.
81. 39.

सूर्योदयगिरि
Sūryodayagiri m.: Designation of the
eastern mountain.
The mountain from behind which the
sun rises; it is situated at the other end
of the Himavant, near the Vāriṣeṇa ocean
and the river Lohitya (Brahmaputra) (ये
परार्धे हिमवतः सूर्योदयगिरौ नृपाः।
वारिषेणसमुद्रान्ते लोहित्यम् अभितश् च
ये) 2. 48. 8; the kings who lived there and
the Kirātas brought various kinds of tributes
for the Rājasūya sacrifice of Yudhiṣṭhira 2.
48. 8-11. [See Udaya and Udyant]

सैन्धवारण्य
Saindhavāraṇya nt.: Name of a forest.
A. Location: In the west (प्रतीच्याम्)
3. 87. 1.
B. Description: Holy (पुण्य),
famous (ख्यात), and visited by Brāhmaṇas
(द्विजनिषेवित) 3. 87. 12.
C. Characteri-
stic: There were many canals there; Lomaśa
advised Yudhiṣṭhira to visit them (सैन्ध-
वारण्यं आसाद्य कुल्यानां कुरु दर्श-
नम्) 3. 125. 12.

सोमगिरि
Somagiri m.: Name of a mountain.
Described as holy (पुण्य); listed by
Bhīṣma in the Daivata-Ṛṣi-Vaṃśa 13. 151.
27, 2.

सोमतीर्थ
Somatīrtha1 nt.: Name of a तीर्थ।
On the river Jayantī (in Kurukṣetra 3.
81. 2); by bathing in it one gets the fruit of
a Rājasūya 3. 81. 16.

सोमतीर्थ
Somatīrtha2 nt.: Name of a तीर्थ।
Situated on the river Sarasvatī 3. 81. 93;
described as unsurpassed (अनुत्तम); by
bathing in it one goes to the world of Soma
(सोमलोकम् अवाप्नुयात्) 3. 81. 96, 162
(identical with Somasya tīrtham ?).

सोमश्रवायण
Somaśravāyaṇa nt.: Name of a तीर्थ।
The Pāṇḍavas, along with Kuntī, on
their way to the Pāñcāla country reached
the Somaśravāyaṇa tīrtha on the river Gan-
ges; Aṅgāraparṇa, the king of the Gandhar-
vas, had come there with his women to sport
in the waters of Gaṅgā 1. 158. 2, 4.

सोमस्य
Somasya tīrtham nt.: Name of a तीर्थ।
A. Description: Great (महन्त्) 9. 42.
38; 9. 49. 65.
B. Epic event: Balarāma
reached there from the तीर्थ Vasiṣṭhāpavāha
9. 42. 38; (9. 41. 39); he reached there
also from Ādityatīrtha 9. 48. 16; 9. 49. 65;
from there he went to the तीर्थ of the
sage Sārasvata 9. 50. 2; Balarāma bathed
there (उपस्पृश्य) and gave gifts 9. 50. 2.
C. Past event: Soma formerly performed
Rājasūya sacrifice at this तीर्थ in which
Atri acted as the Hotṛ priest; at the end of the
sacrifice a fierce battle was fought between
the gods and the Dānavas, Daiteyas and
Rākṣasas in which Skanda killed Tāraka 9.
42. 39-41; 9. 50. 1; (identical with Soma-
tīrtha2 ?).

सौगन्धिकवन
Saugandhikavana nt.: Name of a forest.
A. Location: In the north (अस्यां
दिशि वरिष्ठायाम् उत्तरस्याम्) 5. 109. 3; in
the north-west; the wind blowing from the
north-west (पूर्वोत्तरो वायुः) carried with
it a lotus flower having heavenly fragrance to
Draupadī 3. 146. 6-7; on the Gandhamādana
mountain 3. 150. 16; it was on a river, full
of golden lotuses and Kāraṇḍaka and Cakra-
vāka birds, on this mountain 3. 150. 27.
B.
Description: Great (महन्त्), causing de-
light (प्रीतिजनन), and having the lustre
of the morning sun (बालार्कसदृशद्युति)
3. 150. 27.
C. Characteristics: (1) Brah-
man and other gods, sages practising austeri-
ties, Siddhas, Cāraṇas and Gandharvas, Kiṃ-
naras, along with big serpents (समहोर-
गाः) lived there 3. 82. 3-4; (2) The garden
of Kubera, having heavenly lotus flowers, was
in Saugandhikavana 3. 149. 22; (3) Suparṇa
told Gālava that it was protected by the
Nairṛta demons 5. 109. 10.
D. Holiness:
Just by entering this forest (तद् वनं प्र-
विशन्न् एव) one is freed of all sins 3. 82. 4.
E. Epic events: (1) Hanūmant showed
Bhīma the way to Saugandhikavana 3. 149.
22; (2) Bhīma roamed through the forests
and gardens on the Gandhamādana mountain
to find out the Saugandhika forest 3. 150. 18;
(3) Bhīma saw the forest on a river 3.
150. 27.

सौभद्र
Saubhadra nt.: Name of a तीर्थ।
A. Location: One of the five तीर्थस्
on the southern ocean (समुद्रे तीर्थानि
दक्षिणे) 1. 208. 1; on watery land along the
southern ocean (दक्षिणे सागरानूपे) 1. 209.
17.
B. Description: Described as an exce-
llent तीर्थ of the great sage (Subhadra ?)
(सौभद्रम् … महर्षेस् तीर्थम् उत्तमम्)
1. 208. 8; all the five तीर्थस् are said to be
holy, very holy (पुण्यानि) 1. 209. 11, 17;
(सुपुण्यानि) 1. 208. 1; purifying the wise
(पावनानि मनीषिणाम्) 1. 209. 11; pleasing
(रमणीयानि) 1. 209. 17; (once) adorned
by the ascetics (शोभितानि तपस्विभिः) 1.
208. 1, but later avoided by them and hence
desolate (विविक्तानि … वर्ज्यमानानि मुनि-
भिः) 1. 208. 2, 4; all the five तीर्थस् became
famous as Nārītīrthas 1. 209. 11
C. Epic
event: Arjuna asked the ascetics why the
तीर्थस् were avoided by sages who discoursed
on Brahman (तीर्थानीमानि वर्ज्यन्ते किमर्-
थं ब्रह्मवादिभिः) 1. 208. 5; the ascetics
told him that they were avoided because of the
fear of five crocodiles residing in the तीर्थस्
1. 208. 6; when Arjuna entered the Saubhadra
तीर्थ for a bath a crocodile caught hold of
him; the crocodile was really an Apsaras,
Vargā by name 1. 208. 8, 14; (Arjuna releas-
ed the five Apsarases from curse 1. 209. 21)
[See Nāritirthāni.]

स्तनकुण्ड
Stanakuṇḍa nt. (pl.): Name of a sacred
bathing place.
One can reach it by ascending the famous
Gaurīśikhara (शिखरं वै महादेव्या
गौर्यास् त्रैलोक्यविश्रुतम्।(समारुह्य …
स्तनकुण्डेषु संविशेत्); while visiting the
place one should be a believer (श्राद्धः); by
bathing there (अभिषेकं कुर्वाणः) and by
worshipping manes and gods (पितृदेवार्चने
रतः) one gets the fruit of a horse sacrifice
and goes to the world of Śakra (Indra) 3. 82.
131-132. [See Gauryāḥ śikharaṃ]

स्थाणुतीर्थ
Sthāṇutīrtha nt.: Name of a तीर्थ।
A तीर्थ on the river Sarasvatī (तस्मिन्
सरस्वतीतीर्थे) 9. 41. 8; at Sthāṇutīrtha,
on the eastern bank of the river, was the big
आश्रम of Vasiṣṭha; Sthāṇu (Śiva) practised
severe austerities there; Sthāṇu offered a
sacrifice there, worshipped Sarasvatī and
established the तीर्थ, known after him, as
Sthāṇutīrtha; at this तीर्थ gods consecrated
Skanda as the chief of their army; at this
तीर्थ Viśvāmitra moved Vasiṣṭha from the
eastern to the western bank 9. 41. 4-8. [See
Vasiṣṭhāpavāha]

स्थाणुवट
Sthāṇuvaṭa m.: Name of a तीर्थ।
Described as famous in the three worlds
(त्रिषु लोकेषु विश्रुतम्); by bathing there and
by passing one night there (तत्र स्नात्वा
स्थितो रात्रिं) one gets the world of Rudra
3. 81. 155.

स्थूलवालुका
Sthūlavālukā f.: Name of a river.
Listed by Saṃjaya among the rivers of
the Bhāratavarṣa; people used its water for
drinking 6. 10. 14, 13; all the rivers listed by
Saṃjaya are said to be mothers of the uni-
verse and very strong 6. 10. 35 (for citation
see Atikṛṣṇā); Sthūlavālukā is listed among
the rivers by visiting which the high-souled
ones who have observed vows (महात्मानो
धृतव्रताः) obtain heavenly form, become
auspicious, and wearing heavenly garlands and
rich in holy fragrance they reach the world
of cows (गवां लोके 13. 105. 42; मोदन्ति
गवां विमाने 13. 105. 44) 13. 105. 46, 48
(for citation see Karatoyinī).

स्वयन
Svayana nt.: Name of a तीर्थ।
A. Location: On the southern bank of
Sarasvatī (दक्षिणेन सरस्वत्याः स्वयनं
तीर्थम्) 9. 54. 13; near Samantapañcaka 9.
54. 5, 7; towards the west of the main battle-
field (प्रतीच्यभिमुखं देशम्) 9. 54. 12.
B. Description: Best (उत्तम) 9. 54. 13;
level land having no holes in the earth (तस्मिन्
देशे त्व् अनिरिणे) 9. 54. 13 (Nī., however,
on Bom. Ed. 9. 55. 18: अनिरिणे अनूषरे)
C. Epic event: A place near this तीर्थ was
selected by the warriors for the final duel
between Bhīma and Duryodhana (तत्र युद्-
धम् अरोचयन्) 9. 54. 13.

स्वयंभुवो
Svayaṃbhuvo vanam nt.: Name of a
forest.
Shown by Lomaśa to Yudhiṣṭhira; Viśva-
karman Svayaṃbhū offered a sacrifice in this
forest in which he gave the entire earth as
दक्षिणा to Kaśyapa (यस्मिन् यज्ञे हि भूर्
दत्ता कश्यपाय महात्मने।सपर्वत-
वनोद्देशा दक्षिणा वै स्वयंभुवा) 3. 114.
17-18.

स्वर्गतीर्थ
Svargatīrtha nt.: Name of a तीर्थ।
According to the Tīrthavaṃśa proclaimed
by Aṅgiras, by bathing in this तीर्थ for a
month (उपस्पृश्य, मासं कृतोदकः) one
who has controlled his sense organs (जितेन्-
द्रियः) gets the fruit of a Puruṣamedha
(फलं पुरुषमेधस्य लभेत्) 13. 26.
32, 3.

स्वर्गद्वार
Svargadvāra nt.: Name of a तीर्थ।
One who is controlled and takes limited
food (नियतो नियताशनः) if he visits this
तीर्थ he goes to heaven and reaches the world
of Brahman (स्वर्गलोकम् अवाप्नोति ब्रह्म-
लोकं च गच्छति) 3. 81. 145.

स्वर्णबिन्दु
Svarṇabindu m.: Name of a तीर्थ।
According to the Tīrthavaṃśa proclaimed
by Aṅgiras, one who bathes (विगाह्य) in
this तीर्थ is awakened in a Vimāna by the
praises of Apsarases 13. 26. 9.

स्वस्तिपुर
Svastipura nt. Name of a तीर्थ।
Situated at a place where there is
Gaṅgāhrada and a Kūpa containing three
crores of तीर्थस् 3. 81. 153; described as
purifying (पावनं तीर्थम्) 3. 81. 152;
a pilgrim (तीर्थसेवी) by visiting this तीर्थ
(आसाद्य) and by satisfying manes and gods
gets the fruit of an Agniṣṭoma 3. 81. 152.

हंसकूट
Haṃsakūṭa m.: Name of a mountain.
When Pāṇḍu, with his two wives, left for
forest (1. 110. 37, 42), he reached Gandha-
mādana, from where he crossed Haṃsakūṭa to
reach Śataśṛṅga where he became an ascetic
1. 110. 43. 45.

हंसप्रपतन
Haṃsaprapatana nt.: Name of a तीर्थ।
On the river Gaṅgā (गङ्गायाम्); famous
in the three worlds (त्रैलोक्यविश्रुत) 3.
83. 82.

हरिगिरि
Harigiri m.: Name of a mountain.
One of the six mountains of the Kuśa-
dvīpa; all the six mountains are said to be
best among the mountains (पर्वतोत्तमाः);
the distance between them doubles as one
proceeds from the one to the other (तेषाम्
अन्तरविष्कम्भो द्विगुणः प्रविभागशः)
6. 13. 11.

हरिस्रावा
Harisrāvā f.: Name of a river.
Listed by Saṃjaya among the rivers of
the Bhāratavarṣa; people used its water for
drinking 6. 10. 27, 13; described as a big
river (महापगा) 6. 10. 27 (or Mahāpagā
name of an independent river ?); all the rivers
listed by Saṃjaya are said to be mothers
of the universe and very strong 6. 10. 35
(for citation see Atikṛṣṇā).

हस्तिसोमा
Hastisomā f.: Name of a river.
Listed by Saṃjaya among the rivers of
the Bhāratavarṣa; people used its water for
drinking 6. 10. 18, 13 (for other details see
Harisrāvā).

हिडिम्बवन
Hiḍimbavana nt.: Name of a forest.
Described as a large forest (महारण्य)
3. 13. 85; Pāṇḍavas approached it and slept
there; there they met Hiḍimbā and Hiḍimba
and Bhīma killed the latter in an encounter
3. 13. 86-97.

हिमवत्|हिमवन्त्
Himavant m.: Name of a mountain;
also referred to as Haimavata 1. 116. 27;
Haimavata giri 9. 37. 26; Haima 13. 20. 28;
Himadri 8. 13. 16, 20; Himālaya 6. 32. 25;
Tuṣāragiri 13. 14. 109; Śvetanaga 8. 13. 20.
A. Location: In the north (अत्र (i. e.
उत्तरस्यां दिशि) वै हिमवत्पृष्ठे 5. 109. 5;
ततो ऽगच्छत् स भगवान् उत्तराम् उत्त-
मां दिशम्।हिमवन्तं गिरिश्रेष्ठम्)
13. 20. 2; 13. 19. 14, 16; 13. 20. 28; 1. 189.
22; 5. 14. 5; ततस् ते नियतात्मान उदीचीं
दिशम् आश्रिताः।ददृशुर् … हिमवन्तम्) 17.
2. 1; Arjuna went to the north to reach the
top of Himavant (जगाम … दिशं ह्य् उदीचीं
कौरव्यो हिमवच्छिखरं प्रति) 3. 39.
11; प्रायाद् उदङ्मुखः।शैशिरं गिरिम्
उद्दिश्य) 12. 314. 2 (Nī. on Bom. Ed. 12.
327. 2: शैशिरं गिरिं हिमालयम्); the
world to the north of Himavant is called
Vara (उत्तरे हिम्वत्पार्श्वे … स वरो लोक
उच्यते) 12. 185. 8; Meru is to the north
of Himavant (मेरुं पर्वतम् … हिमवत्-
पार्श्व उत्तरे) 14. 4. 25; lies at a long dis-
tance (प्रकृष्टे चाध्वनि हिमवान्) 3. 191.
4; 2. 23. 4, 9; 2. 24. 1; the mountain of sun-
rise lies at the extreme end of Himavant (ये
परार्धे हिमवतः सूर्यदयगिरौ नृपाः)
2. 48. 8; in the west, the root of Himavant
reaches up to Mandara and its end cannot
be reached even after a thousand years (अत्र
(i. e. in the west 5. 108. 2) मूलं हिमवतो
मन्दरं याति शाश्वतम्।अपि वर्षसह-
स्रेण न चास्यान्तो ऽधिगम्यते) 5. 108. 9;
the slope of Himavant is to the north of the
Kosalas 2. 27. 4; counted by Saṃjaya
among the six mountains which stretch
towards the east and merge at both ends
in the eastern and the western ocean; the dis-
tance between these mountains is thousands
of योजनस् (प्रागायता महाराज षड् एते … ।
अवगाढा ह्य् उभयतः समुद्रौ पूर्व-
पश्चिमौ। … तेषाम् अन्तरविष्कम्भो योज-
नानि सहस्रशः) 6. 7. 2, 4; the gate leading
to the lake Mānasa is on the Himavant (not
