(हंसा हिमवतः प्रस्थे पिबन्त इव मेदि-
नीम्) 9. 8. 12. (iv) A Bhūliṅga bird: A
female Bhūliṅga bird, living on the other side
of Himavant, utters warnings to others: ‘Do
not act rashly’, not realizing that she was
doing the same thing herself (भूलिङ्ग-
शकुनिर् नाम पार्श्वे हिमवतः परे।
भीष्म तस्याः सदा वाचः श्रूयन्ते ऽर्थ-
विगर्हिताः॥मा साहसम् इतीदं सा सततं
वाशते किल।साहसं चात्मनातीव चरन्ती
नावबुध्यते॥) 2. 41. 19-20; (v) Kiṃśuka
trees: Flowering Kiṃśukas of Himavant
(हिमवति पुष्पितौ … किंशुकौ) 9. 57. 31;
(vi) A very big Śālmali tree grew on the
summit of Himavant for a number of years;
it had large roots and branches (हिमवत्-
पृष्ठजः कश्चिच् छाल्मलिः … बृहन्मूलो
बृहच्छाखः॥) 12. 151. 2; वनस्पतिः।
वऋसपूगाभिसंवृद्धः शाखास्कन्ध-
पलाशवान्॥) 12. 150. 2; 7. (i) Certain
regions of Himavant are always covered
with snow; there are no trees, animals or
birds there; others get heavy rains, and still
others are inaccessible and difficult to reach
(सन्ति नित्यहिमा देशा निर्वृक्षमृगपक्षि-
णः।सन्ति केचिन् महावर्षा दुर्गाः केचिद्
दुरासदाः॥) 1. 111. 8; (ii) Even birds
cannot cross the inaccessible regions of
Himavant, let alone other animals; only
wind and great sages who have attained per-
fection can go beyond them (अतिक्रामेन् न
पक्षी यान् कुत एवेतरे मृगाः।वायुर् एको
ऽतिगाद् यत्र सिद्धाश् च परमर्षयः॥)
1. 111. 9; 8. Rivers originating on it:
(i) Sarasvatī 9. 37. 19-20; (प्रभवं च
सरस्वत्याः) 9. 53. 9-11; (3. 82. 5); there-
fore called Haimavatī 9. 43. 51; (ii) Gaṅgā
1. 158. 17; (iii) Śatadru is called Haimavatī
1. 167. 8; 9. Special qualities: (i) Steadi-
ness, steadfastness (स्थिर) 5. 154. 2; 11.
21. 8; 12. 126. 51; (सुस्थिर) 3. 270. 2; 14.
4. 20; (स्थैर्य) 6. 14. 8; (स्थावर) 6. 32.
25 (Nī. on Bom. Ed. 6. 34. 25: स्थावरा-
णां स्थितिमताम्); not moving, immovable
(अचल) 12. 219. 15; 14. 77. 1; (निश्चल)
13. 17. 13; (अचाल्य) 13. 35. 20; also
cf. 2. 68. 35; 5. 80. 48; cannot be easily
torn asunder (गदाप्रहाराभिहतो हिम-
वान् अपि पर्वतः। … विशीर्येत) 5. 54. 38;
firmness (धैर्य) 1. 179. 9; unchanging
(स्थितः प्रकृत्या) 12. 219. 15; strong (हिम-
वांश् च … मयाभिपन्नं त्रायेरन् बलम्
आस्थाय न त्रयः॥) 5. 74. 10; trustworthy
(विश्वास्य) 12. 57. 29; 10. No one has
monopoly of it, is accessible to all at all
times ( … हिमवत्पार्श्वे … ।रात्राव् अहनि
संधौ च कस्य कॢप्तः परिग्रहः॥) 1.
158. 15; 11. Sweet honey collected from
flowers on Himavant (हिमवत्पुष्पजं
चैव स्वादु क्षौद्रं तथा बहु) 2. 48.
5; different kinds of honey on Himavant
(मधूनि विविधानि) 3. 157. 8; 12. Is Hima-
vant also characterized by the middle quality,
i. e. by रजस् (मध्यमो गुणः) ? 14.
43. 1, 4.
D. Holiness: (i) One who
duly gives up his body on Himavant by
observing fast to death he, after worshipping
the deities there and bowing down to the sages,
obtains perfection and goes to the eternal
world of Brahman in heaven (शरीरम् उत्सृजेत्
तत्र विधिपूर्वम् अनाशके। … अभ्यर्च्य
देवतास् तत्र नमस्कृत्य मुनींस् तथा।
ततः सिद्धो दिवं गच्छेद् ब्रह्मलोकं
सनातनम्) 13. 26. 58-59 (Nī. on Bom.
Ed. 13. 25. 63: विधिपूर्वकम् आत्मश्राद्धा-
दिकं कृत्वा अनाशके अनशनव्रते कृते
सति); (ii) The region of Himavant in the
north is holy, giving peace, desirable and
excellent (पुण्यः क्षेम्यश् च काम्यश् च स
वरोलोक उच्यते) 12. 185. 8; (for the descrip-
tion of the people there see 12. 185. 9-13);
(iii) Gods had offered a sacrifice on top of
Himavant (हिमवतो मूर्ध्नि यत्र देवाः
समीजिरे) 12. 250. 23; they made a sixth part
of the merit of that sacrifice equal to giving
the gift of land (षष्ठम् अंशं क्रतोस्
तस्य भूमिदानं प्रचक्रिरे) 13. 65. 24
(Nī., however, on Bom. Ed. 13. 66. 25: हिम-
वति हिमवत्समीपे).
E. Importance: (i)
For Upamanyu, Śiva was like Himavant
among mountains (शैलानां हिमवान् गिरिः)
13. 14. 161; (ii) Bhagavān is the Himālaya
among those that do not move (स्थावराणां
हिमालयः) 6. 32. 25; (iii) Finds mentions
in the Daivata-Ṛṣi Vaṃśa 13. 151. 25, 2.
F. Epic events: (1) Pāṇḍu left Hāstinapura
and lived with his two wives in the forest
on the southern side of Himavant giving
himself to hunting (अरण्यनित्यः सततं
बभूव मृगयापरः॥स चरन् दक्षिणं
पार्श्वं रम्यं हिमवतो गिरेः) 1. 106.
7-8; (ii) Pāṇḍu crossed Himavant to go
to Gandhamādana from where he went to
Śataśṛṅga 1. 110. 43; when Pāṇḍu with his
two wives wished to go from Śataśṛṅga
further north, the ascetics dissuaded him des-
cribing to him the higher inaccessible regions of
Himavant; they said that the two princesses
(Kuntī and Mādrī) would be pained walking
on that mountain (गिरेर् अस्य दुर्गान् देशान्
बहून्। … गच्छन्त्यौ शैलराजे ऽस्मिन् राज-
पुत्र्यौ कथं त्व् इमे।न सीदेतां) 1.
111. 5-10; (3) Vyāsa retired to Hima-
vant (हिमवन्तं शिलोच्चयम्) to practise
austerities after advising Gāndhārī what she
should do about the piece of flesh (मांस-
पेशी) born to her 1. 107. 23; (4) Pāṇḍavas
grew on Himavant causing wonder to the
great sages (हैमवते गिरौ) 1. 115. 27;
(5) Arjuna told Aṅgāraparṇa Gandharva
that no one had an exclusive claim on Hima-
vant (हिमवत्पार्श्वे) (nor on ocean and
Gaṅgā) 1. 158. 15; (6) Arjuna, during his
exile, went from Gaṅgādvāra to Himavant
(हिमवत्पार्श्वम्) 1. 207. 1; (7) Arjuna
conquered Himavant, along with Niṣkuṭa, in
his expedition to the north before the Rāja-
sūya (हिमवन्तं सनिष्कुटम्) 2. 24. 27;
(8) Bhīma, in his expedition to the east
(2. 26. 1, 7), defeated Jaradgava who ruled
over the region near Himavant (हिमवतः
पार्श्वे समभ्येत्य जरद्गवम्) 2. 27. 4;
(9) Yudhiṣṭhira in his childhood was instru-
cted by Merusāvarṇīn on Himavant (हिम-
वत्य् अनुशिष्टो ऽसि मेरुसावर्णिना पुरा) 2.
69. 12; (10) Lomaśa showed the gate of
the Mānasa lake to Yudhiṣṭhira (एतद् द्वारं
महाराज मानसस्य प्रकाशते।वर्षम्
अस्य गिरेर् मध्ये) 3. 130. 12; (11)
Arjuna went to the summit of Himavant to
practise austerities in order to meet Indra
and Śiva (हिमवच्छिखरं प्रति। …
शुशुभे हिमवत्पृष्ठे। … हिमवत्पृष्ठम्
आश्रितः।) 3. 39. 10-12, 16, 26; (12) From
Subāhu's realm the Pāṇḍavas proceeded to
Himavant to meet Arjuna (हिमवन्तम्
गिरिं प्रति) 3. 141. 27; (13) Yudhiṣṭhira
started from the आश्रम of Nārāyaṇa (3.
155. 1) and reached the tableland of Hima-
vant on the seventeenth day (प्रस्थं हिम-
वतः पुण्यं ययौ सप्तदशे ऽहनि) 3. 155.
15; from there Gandhamādana could be seen
at close quarters (ददृशुः पाण्डवा राजन्
गन्धमादनम् अन्तिकात्।पृष्ठे हिमवतः
पुण्ये) 3. 155. 16; (14) The Pāṇḍavas lived
on the tableland of Himavant (हिमवत्पृष्ठे)
eating foods partaken by sages (भुञ्जाना
मुनिभोज्यानि), juicy fruits, as also meat of
deer killed with purified arrows (शुद्धबाण-
हतानां च मृगाणां पिशितान्य् अपि), and
different kinds of honey (मधूनि विविधानि
च); here they completed the fifth year of their
forest life 3. 157. 7-9; (15) On their return
journey the Pāṇḍavas crossed the inaccessible
regions of Himavant (दुर्गं हिमवत्-
प्रदेशम्) to reach once again the realm of
Subāhu 3. 174. 12; (16) When the Pāṇḍa-
vas lived in Dvaitavana on the bank of
Sarasvatī (सरस्वतीम् एत्य निवासकामाः)
3. 174. 21, Bhīma noticed the regions of
Himavant (देशान् गिरेर् हिमवतः) 3. 175.
6; (17) Arjuna told Uttarā that he was
born on the plateau of Himavant (जातो
हिमवत्पृष्ठे) 4. 39. 14; (18) Arjuna had
fought with Maheśvara on Himavant 7. 53.
21; (19) Arjuna, while journeying through
the air on his way to propitiate Śiva for
his Pāśupata, saw the foot of Himavant
(हिमवतः पादम्) 7. 57. 27; (20) Vṛka
pierced with arrows Kuṇinda prince who
lived on the king of mountains (Himavant ?)
(वृको … गिरिराजवासिनम् … पराभिनत्) 8.
62. 48; (21) The Kauravas, after the fall
of Karṇa, went to Sarasvatī flowing near the
Himavant and after drinking its water and
bathing in it returned refreshed (कौरवाः। …
प्रस्थे हिमवतः शुभे।अरुणां सर-
स्वतीं प्राप्य पपुः सस्नुश् च तज्जलम्॥
तव पुत्राः कृतोत्साहाः पर्यावर्तन्त ते
ततः॥) 9. 4. 48, 50; (हैमवते प्रस्थे) 9.
5. 1; they lived there for a night (ते रात्रिम्
उषिताः); at the fall of Karṇa the Kauravas
found no peace except near Himavant
(नालभञ् शर्म ते पुत्रा हिमवन्तम् ऋते
गिरिम्) 9. 5. 2-4; (22) Balarāma, in his तीर्थ-
यात्रा, visited the holy आश्रम near Himavant
(पार्श्वे हिमवतः); he worshipped the sages
there and ascended the mountain (आरुरुहे
ऽचलम्); he saw at a short distance the
तीर्थ called Plakṣaprasravaṇa (नातिदूरं
ततो गत्वा नगम्) 9. 53. 9-10; (23)
Kṛṣṇa begot Pradyumna on Rukmiṇī after
practising austerities on Himavant (हिमवत्-
पार्श्वम् अभ्येत्य) and observing chastity
for twelve years 10. 12. 29; (24) Vyāsa
advised Yudhiṣṭhira to get for his Aśvamedha
wealth left on Himavant by the Brāhmaṇas
officiating at the sacrifice of Marutta (विद्यते
द्रविणं पार्थ गिरौ हिमवति स्थितम्)
14. 3. 20; (25) Yudhiṣṭhira with his brothers,
protected by Vyāsa, desired to repair to
Himavant (हिमवन्तं त्वया गुप्ता गमि-
ष्यामः पितामह) 14. 14. 9; (26) After
Dhṛtarāṣṭra, Gāndhārī and Kuntī were burnt
by the forest fire near Gaṅgādvāra, Saṃjaya
went to Himavant (हिमवन्तं मही-
धरम्) 15. 45. 33; (27) The Pāṇḍavas
in their final journey saw Himavant in
the north; after crossing it they saw the
big desert and the mount Meru (तं चाप्य्
अतिक्रमन्तस् ते ददृशुर् वालुकार्णवम्।
अवैक्षन्त महाशैलं मेरुम्) 17. 2. 1-2;
(28) Vyāsa lived at the foot of Hima-
vant (गुरोर् मे … हिमवत्पाद आसतः);
there he composed the Bhārata and felt
tired; he was served there by his pupils and
his son Śuka 12. 337. 9-10, 12.
G. Past
and mythological events: (1) The fish
dragged the ship of Manu to the highest
peak (शृङ्गं यत् परम्) of Himavant; it
advised the seven sages to quickly tie the
are to that peak of Himavant; the sages
acted accordingly; that highest peak of Hima-
vant is famous as Naubandhana even today
(तच् च नौबन्धनं नाम शृङ्गं हिम-
वतः परम्।ख्यातम् अद्यापि) 3. 185. 44-
47; (2) Rāma (Jāmadagnya) established
his residence on mountain (Himavant) (वर्-
षम् अस्य गिरेर् मध्ये रामेण श्रीमता
कृतम् 3. 130. 12; Nī. on Bom. Ed. 3. 130.
12: वर्षं वसतिस्थानम्); (3) Hima-
vant waited on king Vainya and offered
jewels to him 12. 59. 121; (4) After Nahuṣa
was made king of the heaven he sported at
various places, one of them being the summit
of Himavant (हिमवत्पृष्ठे) 5. 11. 9; (5)
Viśvāmitra begot Śakuntalā on Menakā on the
lovely summit of Himavant (प्रस्थे हिम-
वतो रम्ये) 1. 66. 8; (हिमवतः पृष्ठे)
1. 68. 69; Menakā abandoned Śakuntalā on
Himavant (हिमवतः पृष्ठे) 1. 68. 69,
73; (6) Bhagīratha went to the slope of
the Himavant (हिमवत्पार्श्वम्) to practise
austerities 3. 107. 3-4; Gaṅgā split the
mountain Himavant at Gaṅgādvāra 3. 88.
18; (7) Pulastya and Vasiṣṭha requested
Parāśara to end his sacrifice of the Rākṣasas
(राक्षससत्र); he stopped it; the fire
that was collected by him for the sacrifice
was thrown by him in the great forest on
the northern side of Himavant (उत्तरे
हिमवत्पार्श्वे उत्ससर्ज महावने); the
fire is seen there even today consuming the
Rakṣases, forests and rocks on every पर्-
वन् day (स तत्राद्यापि रक्षांसि वृक्षान्
अश्मान (?) एव च।भक्षयन् दृश्यते वह्निः
सदा पर्वणि पर्वणि॥) 1. 172. 15-17;
(8) Leaving behind his daughter Srucāvatī
in the आश्रम, Bhāradvāja repaired to the
forest on Himavant (जगाम हिमवद्-
वनम्) 9. 47. 60; (9) The great sage
Bhṛgu approached Himavant and asked for
his daughter; Himavant told Bhṛgu that the
desired bridegroom was Rudra (तम् अब्रवीद्
धिमवान् अभिलषितो वरो रुद्र इति); since
Bhṛgu's request was rejected by Himavant
the former uttered a curse that the mountain
would not be a source of jewels; that word
of the sage is true even today (न रत्ना-
नां भवान् भाजनं भविष्यतीति।अद्य-
प्रभृत्य् एतद् अवस्थितम् ऋषिवचनम्) 12.
329. 49 (2-5); (10) Vadānya told Aṣṭā-
vakra to cross the place of Kubera, the moun-
tain Himavant, and the place of Rudra to
see the direction Uttarā; accordingly Aṣṭā-
vakra went to Himavant and visited the holy
river Bāhudā; he then roamed on mountains
Kailāsa, Mandara and Haima (कैलासं
मन्दरं हैमम् सर्वान् अनुचचार ह);
he crossed them and went to the Kairāta-
sthāna 13. 19. 16; 13. 20. 2-3, 28-29;
(11) Sage Mārkaṇḍeya saw Himavant in
the belly of the Bāla (13. 186. 83 = Nārā-
yaṇa 13. 187. 3) 3. 186. 101; (12) The
Vālakhilyas, when appeased by Kaśyapa, left
the branch of the Rohiṇa tree (1. 25. 31) on
which they were hanging and went to Hima-
vant to practise austerities 1. 26. 14; (13)
When the descendants of Kṛtavīrya destroyed
the Bhṛgus, even those who were still in the
womb, the women of the Bhṛgu family fled
and took resort on Himavant (हिमवन्तं
प्रपेदिरे) 1. 169. 19; (14) Leaving Arun-
dhatī behind at the Badarapācana tīrtha the
seven sages went to Himavant; while they
obtained their livelihood in a forest on Hima-
vant, there occurred a severe drought lasting
for twelve years; Mahādeva told the seven
sages that the merit which they had acquired
by their austerities on Himavant (हिमवत्-
पृष्ठे) was not equal to the merit of Arun-
dhatī's austerities 9. 47. 28, 30, 41; (15)
Vyāsa resorted to the east of Himavant and
there, in a solitary place, taught Vedas to
his pupils Sumantu, Vaiśaṃpāyana, Jaimini,
and Paila (ऐन्द्रीं तु दिशम् आस्थाय
शैलराजस्य धीमतः।विविक्ते पर्वत-
तटे … वेदान् अध्यापयाम् आस व्यासः)
12. 314. 23-24; Vyāsa lived on Hima-
vant (हिमवत्पृष्ठे) teaching (Vedas) to
his pupils and his son 12. 314. 30; once his
pupils expressed their wish to leave the
mountain and go to the plains to propagate
the Vedas at different places, if that pleased
Vyāsa (शैलाद् अस्मान् महीं गन्तुं काङ्क्षि-
तं नो महामुने।वेदान् अनेकधा कर्तुम्
यदि ते रुचितं विभो) 12. 315. 4; (16)
Nārada once visited Himavant 12. 314. 3;
he saw Vyāsa all alone and silent in his
आश्रम on Himavant; the sage told Vyāsa
that the mountain, without the sound of the
Vedas, was not delightful as before (ब्रह्म-
घोषैर् विरहितः पर्वतो ऽयं न शोभते।
 … न भ्राजते यथापूर्वम् … वेदध्वनि-
निराकृतः) 12. 315. 11-14; (17) Śuka,
son of Vyāsa, after he was instructed by
Janaka in Mithilā, journeyed to the north
through air to reach Himavant (प्रायाद्
उदङ्मुखः।शैशिरं गिरिम् उद्दिश्य स-
धर्मा मातरिश्वनः) 12. 314. 2; Śuka
saw his father surrounded by pupils in his
आश्रम; Vyāsa saw his son arriving, lustrous
like the sun; Śuka told his father all about
his conversation with Janaka 12. 314. 25-29;
when Śuka got the consent of Nārada to leave
this world he went to meet his father; after
a प्रदक्षिणा of him, Śuka, intent on achie-
ving liberation (मोक्ष), took leave of his
father 12. 318. 60-61, 63; Śuka went up
to the summit of Himavant and sat there
on a desolate table-land (गिरिपृष्ठं समा-
रुह्य … समे देशे विविक्ते च … उपाविशत्);
taking recourse to Yoga he went beyond the
sky to reach the path of liberation (स पुनर्
योगम् आस्थाय मोक्षमार्गोपलब्धये।
महायोगीश्वरो भूत्वा सो ऽत्यक्रामद् विहा-
यसम्॥) 12. 319. 1, 6; when Śuka attained
perfection (सिद्धि) and was established in
ब्रह्मन् (ब्रह्मणि प्रत्यतिष्ठत् सः)
some unexpected things happened; one of
them was that it appeared due to loud
thunders that Himavant was being torn
asunder (निर्घातशब्दैश् च गिरिर् हिम्-
अवान् दीर्यतीव ह) 12. 320. 5; he then
saw before him towards the north two hea-
venly summits closely attached to each other,
one of Himavant, white and silvery, and the
other of Meru, yellow and golden; the two
peaks were a hundred योजनस् in height and
width (शृङ्गे … हिमवन्मेरुसंभवे।सं-
श्लिष्टे श्वेतपीते द्वे रुक्मरूप्यमये शुभे॥
शतयोजनविस्तारे तिर्यग् ऊर्ध्वं च भा-
रत।उदीचीं दिशम् आश्रित्य) 12. 320. 8-9;
undeterred Śuka continued to fly upwards:
then a wonderful thing happened—the two
peaks suddenly got separated and Śuka swiftly
passed through them; the excellent mountain
(Himavant ? Meru ?) could not check Śuka's
gait; those who lived in heaven and on the
mountain uttered a loud cry (ततः पर्वत-
शृङ्गे द्वे सहसैव द्विधाकृते।अदृश्य-
तां महाराज तद् अद्भुतम् इवाभवत्॥
ततः पर्वतशृण्गाभ्यां सहसैव विनिः-
सृतः।न च प्रतिजघानास्य स गतिं
पर्वतोत्तमः॥) 12. 320. 10-12; Vyāsa who
followed Śuka saw his son pass through the
mountain peak rent into two (द्विधा कृत्वा
पर्वताग्रम्) 12. 320. 21; Vyāsa then sat
down on the summit of the mountain (गिरि-
प्रस्थे) thinking continuously of his son
(पुत्रम् एवानुचिन्तयन्) 12. 320. 27; (18)
A certain Brāhmaṇa, son of Pippalāda and
of Kuśika gotra, lived at the foot of Hima-
vant engaged in Vedic studies (ब्राह्मणो
जापकः कश्चित् … पैप्पलादिः स कौशिकः।
 … हिमवत्पादसंश्रयः) 12. 192. 4-5
(Nī. on Bom. Ed. 12. 199. 4: जापकः
मन्त्राध्ययनपरः); (19) A certain
Śūdra approached the head of an आश्रम of
the Brāhmaṇas on Himavant (ब्रह्माश्र-
मपदे वृत्तं पार्श्वे हिमवतः शुभे) 13.
10. 5, 10 (the आश्रम described 13. 10. 6-9);
(20) An owl named Prākārakarṇa lived on
Himavant; Indradyumna became a horse and
carried Mārkaṇḍeya to the owl on the distant
Himavant (प्रकृष्टे चाध्वनि हिमवान्) 3.
191. 4-5; (21) A lotus pond on Himavant
(हिमवतः … कमलाकरः) waited in per-
son (साक्षात्) on the brahmanical sage Jīmūta
5. 109. 21; (22) Gaṅgā, unable to bear
the seed (emitted lustre of Maheśvara तेजो
माहेश्वरं स्कन्नम् 9. 43. 6) placed in her
by Agni, released it on Himavant (उत्ससर्ज
गिरौ रम्ये हिमवति); there it grew and
was seen by the Kṛṭṭikās in a cluster of reeds
9. 43. 9-11; Nārada went to see Himavant
where Kumāra (Skanda) in his childhood
threw his शक्ति on earth; he challenged any
one to uproot or shake the शक्ति (हिमवन्तम्
इयाद् द्रष्टुम् … ।यत्रैव च कुमारेण …
शक्तिर् न्यस्ता क्षितितले) 12. 314. 3, 7-10;
Prahlāda in his effort to draw out the शक्ति
fainted on the summit of the mountain
(मूर्च्छितो गिरिमूर्धनि) 12. 314. 16-17;
gods, led by Brahman, took Kumāra
to the best mountain (Himavant), to
Sarasvatī of Himavant for his coronation
(अभिषेकार्थम् आजग्मुः शैलेन्द्रम् … ।
हैमवतीम् … सरस्वतीम्) 9. 43. 50-51;
Himavant present at the time of the corona-
tion 9. 44. 13; he gave for coronation an
excellent, divine seat decorated with excellent
gems and heavenly jewels (हिमवता दत्ते
 … निषण्णः परमासने) 9. 44. 2; after
the coronation, Himavant gave to Kumāra
as his attendants (अनुचरौ) Suvarcas and
Ativarcas 9. 44. 42; Skanda, while shoot-
ing arrows at Śveta mountain, pierced
Krauñca mountain, the son of Himavant
(बिभेद स शरैः शैलं क्रौञ्चं हिम-
वतः सुतम्); through the hole created by
him swans and vultures go to Meru 3. 214. 31;
(23) Śiva went from Kailāsa to Himavant
(हिमवन्तम् उपागमत्) to hold Gaṅgā on
his head when the river descended from the
sky (महादेवः शिरसा यां अधारयत्)
3. 108. 3; (हिमवति गङ्गायाः … ।मूर्ध्ना
धारां महादेवः शिरसा याम् अधारयत्)
13. 106. 26; (24) Rudra desired Umā,
daughter of Himavant (हिमवतो गिरेर्
दुहितरम् उमां रुद्रश् चकमे) 12. 329.
49(1); Umā practised on a spot on Hima-
vant severe austerities for Śiva and hence it
is said that the spot was liked by both of
them (तत्र (i. e. इष्टं किल गिरौ स्थानम्)
देव्या तपस् तप्तं शंकरार्थम् … ।अतस्
तद् इष्टं देवस्य तथोमाया इति श्रुतिः)
13. 19. 20; (25) Śiva always went to the
northern side of Himavant (यत्रोत्तरां दिशं
गत्वा शैलराजस्य पार्श्वतः) to practise
austerities 12. 314. 18; when Śiva practised
austerities on Himavant (गिरितटे 13. 127.
17), the mountain shone due to Śiva's auste-
rites (स गिरिस् तपसा तस्य भूतेशस्य
व्यरोचत) 13. 127. 2, 10; Umā also resorted
to that place on Himavant (सेवन्ती हिम-
वत्पार्श्वम्) and approached Śiva 13. 127.
25; when she closed the eyes of Śiva with her
hands a big flame issued from his forehead;
the mountain was afflicted by Śiva's third
eye which looked like the sun (येनासौ
मथितो गिरिः) 13. 127. 29-30, 45, (मथितं
शैलम्) 36; the flame burnt the whole forest
on Himavant; hence the animals came to
Śiva's abode for shelter; the entire mountain
Himavant, with its peaks full of minerals and
herbs in its forests, was burnt in a moment
(क्षणेन तेन दग्धः स हिमवान् अभवन्
नगः।सधातुशिखराभोगो दीनदग्ध-
वनौषधिः॥); when Śiva noticed that Umā
was unhappy due to the wretched condition
of her father, he looked with affection at the
mountain and it returned to its former origi-
nal condition, beautiful to look at (शर्वः
 … प्रीत्यापश्यत् ततो गिरिम्।ततो ऽभवत्
पुनः सर्वः प्रकृतिस्थः सुदर्शनः)
13. 127. 32-39, 42, 45; (26) The marriage
of Rudra with Rudrāṇī took place on Hima-
vant (गिरौ हिमवति श्रेष्ठे) 13. 83. 40;
(27) Viṣṇu practised austerities on Hima-
vant to get a son (विष्णुना यत्र पुत्रार्थे
तपस् तप्तं महात्मना) 12. 314. 7;
Kṛṣṇa went to Himavant to practise auste-
rities to beget a son on Jāmbavatī; Tārkṣya
took Kṛṣṇa to Himavant (अहं तार्क्ष्यम्
अचिन्तयम्।सो ऽवहद् धिमवन्तं माम्)
13. 14. 12-13, 26; Kṛṣṇa saw on Himavant
miraculous occurrences (तत्राहम् अद्भुतान्
भावान् अपश्यं गिरिसत्तमे) 13. 14. 27;
Kṛṣṇa observed a व्रत, lasting for twelve
years on Himavant (व्रतं चर्तुम् इहायातस्
त्व् अहं गिरिम् इमं शुभम्) 13. 126. 10, 33;
the unthinkable miracle of fire issuing from
the mouth of Kṛṣṇa (13. 126. 16) witnessed
by Nārada and other sages on Himavant
(यद् आश्चर्यं अचिन्त्यं च गिरौ हिम-
वति प्रभो।अनुभूतं मुनिगणैः) 13.
126. 48-49; the fire burnt the mountain with
its trees, creepers and bushes, as well as
all kinds of animals; the summit of the
mountain was afflicted (शिखरं तस्य शै-
लस्य मथितम्) 13. 126. 17-18; (एतद्
तद् वैष्णवं तेजो मम वक्त्राद् विनिः-
सृतम्। … येनायं मथितो गिरिः) 13. 126.
30; Viṣṇu by looking at the forest with gentle
eyes brought it back to its original condition
(सौम्यैर् दृष्टिनिपातैस् तत् पुनः प्रकृतिम्
आनयत् 13. 126. 20-21, 36; (28) When
Rudra and Nārāyaṇa fought with each other
the ocean went dry and Himavant was
shattered (हिमवांश् च व्यशीर्यत) 12.
330. 54; (29) Once, god Brahman waited
upon by brahmanical sages stayed on Hima-
vant (तदा हिमवतः पृष्ठे … तस्थौ)
12. 160. 31-32; (30) Indra saw a young
man (really god Śiva 1. 189. 21) playing
dice with a young woman on the summit of
the king of mountains (क्रीडन्तम् अक्षैर्
गिरिराजमूर्ध्नि); Śiva asked Indra to turn
(the summit of) the mountain and enter
it (विवर्तयैनं च महाद्रिराजम् … ।स
तद् विवृत्य शिखरं महागिरेः); when
Indra did what he was asked to do he saw
four former Indras, equal to him in lustre,
held captive there 1. 189. 14, 19-20; Śiva
asked Indra to enter the cave of the moun-
tain and stay there (दरीम् एतां प्रविश
त्वम् शतक्रतो … एतां दरिम् आविश्य शेध्-
वम्) 1. 189. 14, 19-24, 32; (31) Upaśruti
crossed Himavant and went with Indrāṇī
to a big island in the ocean to the north of
the mountain (हिमवन्तम् अतिक्रम्य उत्त-
रं पार्श्वम् आगमत्।समुद्रं च समा-
साद्य … आससाद महाद्विपम्) 5. 14. 5-6;
(32) Mṛtyu, conceived as a woman, reluc-
tant to carry out the instruction of Pitāmaha
to deprive people of their lives, went to the
top of Himavant (हिमवतो मूर्ध्नि) and
stood there for an extremely long period
(निखर्वम् अपरं ततः।तस्थौ) on her
toe to satisfy Pitāmaha 12. 250. 23; (33)
Śeṣa, disgusted with the behaviour of his
stupid brothers, left his mother Kadrū and
went to different places to practise austerities,
one of them being the slope of Himavant
(हिमवतस् तटे) 1. 32. 2-3; (34) Nārada
told to Vāyu that a certain large Śālmali tree
grown on the summit of Himavant (हिम-
वत्पृष्ठजः) disrespected him 12. 151. 2.
H. Similes: (1) Various persons compared
with Himavant for different qualities: (a)
Steadiness: (i) Bhīṣma (हिमवन्तम् इव
स्थिरम्) 5. 154. 2; (स्थैर्ये च हिमवान्
इव) 6. 14. 8; (ii) Karṇa (हिमवान् इव च
स्थिरः) 11. 21. 8; (iii) King Avikṣit and (iv)
Vibhīṣaṇa (हिमवान् इव सुस्थिरः) 14. 4.
20; 3. 270. 2; (v) Hanūmant (हिमवन्तम्
इव स्थितम्) 3. 264. 10; (vi) Yudhiṣṭhira
advised to be steady like Himavant (स्थिरो
भव यथा राजन् हिमवान्) 12. 126. 51;
(b) Immovability: (i) Kṣemavṛddhi under
the attack of arrows (तद्बाणवर्षं …
विषेहे … हिमवान् इव निश्चलः) 3. 17. 13;
(ii) Duryodhana (नाचलद् गिरिराड् इव) 6.
74. 7; (c) Firmness: Arjuna (धैर्येण
हिमवान् इव) 1. 179. 9; (d) Undisturbed
nature: A learned man (पण्डितः … स्थितः
प्रकृत्या हिमवान् इवाचलः) 12. 219. 15;
(e) Unconquerable: Arjuna (दुर्धर्षो
हिमवान् इवाचलः) 14. 77. 1; (f) Trust-
worthy: A king (विश्वास्यो हिमवान् इव) 12.
57. 29; (g) Store of jewels: The Bhārata text
(यथा समुद्रः … यथा च हिमवान् गिरिः।
ख्याताव् उभौ रत्ननिधी तथा भारतम्
उच्यते) 18. 5. 52; (h) Vastness, extensive-
ness: King Sumitra (हिमवान् वा महाशैलः
समुद्रो वा महोदधिः।महत्वान् नान्व-
पद्येताम् रोदस्योर् अन्तरं यथा) 12.
125. 29; (i) Greatness, largeness: Dadhīca
(अतिकायः स तेजस्वी … जज्ञे शैलगुरुः
प्रांशुः) 9. 50. 32; (j) Superiority: Arjuna
(हिमवान् इव शैलानाम् … वरः) 4. 2. 19-
20; Bhīṣma to Arjuna (unexpressed simile)
(गिरीणां हिमवान् वरः … श्रेष्ठस् त्वम्
असि धन्विनाम्) 6. 116. 33; (k) Not to be
toppled down: Himavant, one of the four
mountains with which the four Pāṇḍavas are
compared (हिमवान् पारियात्रश् च विन्ध्यो
मलय एव च।चत्वारः पर्वताः केन
पातिता भुवि तेजसा) 3. 297. 14; (2) Com-
parison with Himavant under certain situa-
tions: (a) Arjuna with the great monkey
on his banner shone like Himavant with
fire (हिमवान् इव वह्निना) 7. 80. 29;
(b) (i) Karṇa said he would withstand
Arjuna in battle as does Himavant the
fierce, stormy wind (प्रभञ्जनं मातरि-
श्वानम् उग्रम्। … हिमवान् इवाचलः) 8.
29. 15; (ii) Similarly Alambusa checked
the attack of Arjuna (प्रभञ्जनम् इवाद्रि-
राट्) 7. 142. 37; (iii) Ghaṭotkaca's son
(Añjanaparvan) withstood the attack of
Aśvatthāman (प्रभञ्जनम् इवाद्रिराट्) 7.
131. 44; (c) (i) The Saṃśaptakas showered
weapons on Arjuna from all sides as the
clouds, hurled by winds, rush at Himavant
in the rainy season (मरुद्भिः प्रेषिता
हिमवन्तम् इवोष्णगे) 8. 14. 8 (Nī. on
Bom. Ed. 8. 19. 8; उष्णगे ग्रीष्मे गते सति
प्रावृषीत्य् अर्थः।उष्णो ग्रीष्मो गतो ऽतीतो
यत्र स उष्णगः कालविशेष इति विग्रहः);
(ii) Similarly Vaitahavyas attacked Pratar-
dana (हिमवन्तम् इवाम्बुदाः) 13. 31. 38;
(d) Duryodhana who had put on a head-
gear and wore a golden armour shone like the
golden king of mountains (काञ्चनः शैलराड्
इव) 9. 54. 15; (e) When blood began to
flow down from the body of Vajradatta's
elephant, hit by the arrows of Arjuna, he was
compared with Himavant with many streams
(हिमवान् इव शैलेन्द्रो बहुप्रस्रवणस्
तदा) 14. 74. 20; (f) (i) Bāhlīka, with his
head cut off, fell down like Himavant when
hit by वज्र (वज्राहत इवाद्रिराट्) 7. 132. 15;
(ii) Daṇḍa's elephant in similar condition
(हिमाद्रिकूटः कुलिसाहतो यथा) 8. 13. 20;
(3) Summit of Himavant as an उपमान:
(a) Daṇḍa's elephant, white like snow and
wearing golden garlands, was the image of
the summit of Himavant (हिमावदातेन
सुवर्णमालिना हिमाद्रिकूटप्रतिमेन दन्-
तिना) 8. 13. 16; (द्विपं श्वेतनगाग्रसं-
निभम्) 8. 13. 20; (b) Hump on Śiva's
bull compared with the summit of the snowy
mountain (तुषारगिरिकूटाभम्) 13. 14. 109;
(c) The residences, tall and studded with
minerals, looked like summit of Himavant
(बहुधातुपिनद्धाङ्गान् हिमवच्छिखरान्
इव) 2. 31. 23; 1. 176. 22; (d) Duryodhana's
गदा had the form of the summit of Hima-
vant (हिमवच्छिखराकाराम्) 9. 32. 47;
(4) Earth has Himavant as her crest (शैल-
राजावतंशकाम्) 1. 69. 27; (5) Certain
animals, birds and other objects from Hima-
vant serve as उपमानस्: (a) Elephants (i)
Arjuna and Karṇa fought as do two elephants
in rut from Himavant (यथा गजौ हैम-
वतौ प्रभिन्नौ) 8. 65. 2; (ii) kings
assembled for Draupadī's स्वयंवर (यथा
हैमवता गजेन्द्राः) 1. 178. 2; (iii) Heroes
defeated by Arjuna slept like grown up
elephants from Himavant (नागा यथा हैम-
वताः प्रवृद्धाः) 4. 49. 15; (iv) (a)
Elephants from Himavant as उपमेय: The
elephants from Himavant with golden nets
hanging from their bodies looked like clouds
with lightnings (सुकल्पिता हैमवताः …
सुवर्णजालावतता बभुर् गजा तथा यथा
वै जलदाः सविद्युतः) 8. 62. 36; (b)
Lions: (i) Kuntī blessed Karṇa saying
that when he became a young man he would
be like a lion with a mane from the forest of
Himavant (हिमवद्वनसंभूतं सिंहं
केसरिणं यथा) 3. 292. 21; (ii) Bhīma
rushed at Duḥśāsana as a lion from Hima-
vant rushes at a jackal (सिंहो यथा हैम-
वतः शृगालम्) 2. 68. 15; (iii) Bhīma,
Arjuna and Kṛṣṇa went to Jarāsandha's
residence as do the Himavant lions to a
cow-pen (गोवासम् इव … सिंहा हैमवता
यथा) 2. 19. 25; (c) Swans: (i) Horses
adorned with चामरस्, running on the battle-
field looked like swans from the summit of
Himavant touching the earth (हंसा हिम-
वतः प्रस्थे पिबन्त इव मेदिनीम्) 9. 8. 12;
(ii) Thousands of horses hit by Arjuna's
arrows fell down like swans falling down on
the slopes of Himavant when struck by
water (हंसा हिमवतः पृष्ठे वारिविप्र-
हता इव) 7. 66. 19; (d) Kiṃśuka tree:
Bhīma and Duryodhana, wounded and smear-
ed with blood, looked like two Kiṃśuka trees
in blossom on Himavant (हिमवति पुष्पिताव्
इव किंशुकौ) 9. 57. 31; (e) A leaf: Indra,
humiliated, trembled as does a leaf of a fig
tree, stirred by wind, on the Himavant
summit (अनिलेनेव नुन्नम् अश्वत्थपत्रं
गिरिराजमूर्ध्नि) 1. 189. 22; (f) A cave:
A king is said to be like a cavern on Hima-
vant, inaccessible and difficult to enter (दुरा-
सदां दुष्प्रवेशां गुहां हैमवतीम्
इव) 12. 83. 39. (6) Vyāsa surrounded by
his pupils and his son at the foot of Himavant
looked like the lord of the Bhūtas (Śiva) sur-
rounded by Bhūtas (शुशुभे हिमवत्पादे
भूतैर् भूतपतिर् यथा) 12. 337. 12; (7)
Himavant an उपमेय: Himavant without
the sound of the recitation of the Vedas did
not shine like moon when covered with dust
and darkness at the time of the eclipse or
like a habitation of the Niṣādas (ब्रह्मघो-
षैर् विरहितः पर्वतो ऽयं न शोभते।
रजसा तमसा चैव सोमः सोपप्लवो
यथा॥न भ्राजते यथापूर्वं निषादा-
नाम् इवालयः) 12. 315. 13-14.
I. Modes
of expression: These are based on various
characteristics of the mountain: (a) Stead-
iness: (i) Himavant might start moving
about, but Duḥśāsana would not rule
the earth without Duryodhana (हिमवांश्
च परिव्रजेत्। … न चाहं त्वद् ऋते राजन्
प्रशासेयं वसुन्धराम्) 3. 238. 31; (ii)
If Arjuna's words were to prove false
then, indeed, Himavant may move from its
place (चलेद् धि हिमवान् स्थानात् … मत्-
सत्यं विचलेद् यदि) 2. 68. 35; the same
said by Kṛṣṇa (चलेद् धि हिमवाञ् शैलो
 … न मे मोघं वचो भवेत्) 5. 80. 48;
(b) Solid form: (i) Kṛṣṇa to Draupadī:
Himavant may be shattered, but his words
would not be false (हिमवाञ् शीर्येत् … न मे
मोघं वचो भवेत्) 3. 13. 117; (ii)
Duryodhana to Dhṛtarāṣṭra: Even Himavant
would be shattered in a hundred thousand
ways if hit just once by Duryodhana with his
गदा (गदाप्रहाराभिहतो हिमवान् अपि
पर्वतः। … विशीर्येत गिरिः शतसहस्रधा)
5. 54. 38; (iii) Hearing Bhīma's loud roar
after the death of Jarāsaṃdha people wondered
if Himavant had split (किं नु स्विद् धिम-
वान् भिन्नः) 2. 22. 9; (c) Not subject
to reduction in size: Even Himavant would
decay under certain conditions (भक्ष्य-
माणो ह्य् अनावापः क्षीयते हिमवान् अपि) 3.
33. 9; (d) Not to be easily toppled down:
Himavant is one of the four mountains which
cannot be easily toppled down (हिमवान् …
चत्वारः पर्वताः केन पातिता भुवि तेजसा)
3. 297. 14; (e) Very large size: Bhīma
to Yudhiṣṭhira—Yudhiṣṭhira's wish to hide
Pāṇḍavas for a year was like trying to hide
Himavant with a handful of grass (तृणानां
मुष्टिनैकेन हिमवन्तं तु पर्वतम्।
छन्नम् इच्छसि कौन्तेय यो ऽस्मान् सं-
वर्तुम् इच्छसि) 3. 36. 22; (f) Strength:
Bhīma to Kṛṣṇa—even Himavant, ocean and
Indra together cannot rescue a person attack-
ed by Bhīma (हिमवांश् च समुद्रश् च
वज्री च … ।मयाभिपन्नं त्रायेरन् बलम्
आस्थाय न त्रयः) 5. 74. 10; (g) Impass-
ableness: One cannot say that the back side of
Himavant does not exist simply because men
have not seen it (यथा हिमवतः पृष्ठं
 … न दृष्टपूर्वं मनुजैर् न च तन् नास्ति
तावता) 12. 196. 6; (h) Mighty elephants
at its foot: Wishing to defeat Yudhiṣṭhira
was like driving away with a stick a huge ele-
phant in rut roaming at the foot of Himavant
with its herd (नागम् … उपत्यकां हैम-
वतीं चरन्तम्।दण्डीव यूथाद् अपसे-
धसे त्वं यो जेतुम् आशंससि धर्म-
राजम्॥) 3. 252. 5.
J. Relationships with
Himavant: (a) Daughters of Himavant:
(i) Umā (हिमवतो गिरेर् दुहितरम् उमाम्)
12. 329. 49(1); (उमां … पितुर् दैन्यम्
अनिच्छन्तीम्) 13. 127. 37; (ii) River
Gaṅgā: (हिमवतः सुता) 3. 108. 8; 6. 114.
90; (शैलराजसुतां नदीम्) 3. 108. 4;
(सुतावनीध्रस्य हरस्य भार्या) 13. 27.
88 (Nī. on Bom. Ed. 13. 26. 89: अवनीध्र-
स्य मेरोः हिमवतो वा पर्वतस्य); (b)
Sons of Himavant: (i) Mountain Krauñca
(क्रौञ्चं हिमवतः सुतम्) 3. 214. 31;
(ii) Mountain Arbuda (हिमवत्सुतम् अर्-
बुदम्) 3. 80. 74; (c) Father-in-law of
Śaṃkara (हिमवान् पुण्यः शंकरश्वशुरो
गिरिः) 13. 26. 57; (d) General association:
Gandhamādana mountain called हैमवत
mountain 3. 157. 3.
K. Bad omen: The
falling down with great roar of thousands of
summits of Kailāsa, Mandara and Himavant
is mentioned among the bad omens noticed by
Vyāsa before the war (तथा हिमवतो गिरेः
सहस्रशो महाशब्दं शिखराणि पतन्ति
च) 6. 3. 35. [See Śaiśira]

हिरण्यबिन्दु
Hiraṇyabindu m.: Name of a तीर्थ।
A. Location: On the slope of the
Himavant mountain (हिमवत्पार्श्वम्) 1.
207. 1.
B. Holiness: According to the
Tīrthavaṃśa narrated by Aṅgiras (13. 26. 3),
if one who is controlled bathes in this तीर्थ
(विक्षोभ्य) and bows down to the god-
head lying in the Kuśa grass his sins are
cleansed (हिरण्यबिन्दुं विक्षोभ्य प्रय-
तश् चाभिवाद्य तम्।कुशेशयं च देव-
त्वं पूयते तस्य किल्बिषम्) 13. 26. 10.
C. Epic event: Arjuna, during the term
of his exile, visited this तीर्थ; he bathed
there and saw the best among the mountains
(Himavant) and the sacred places (दृष्टवान्
पर्वतश्रेष्ठं पुण्यान्य् आयतनानि च);
he descended from there and went to the east
1. 207. 4-5; [For Hiraṇyabindu, as name
of Agastyāśrama, see Section 1. 5A]

हिरण्यशिखर
Hiraṇyaśikhara m.: See Hiraṇyaśṛṅga.

हिरण्यशृङ्ग
Hiraṇyaśṛṅga, Hiraṇyaśikhara, Hema-
śṛṅga (1. 158. 17) m.: Name of a mountain.
A. Location: Belongs to Himavant
(हिमवतः … हेमशृङ्गात्) 1. 158. 17; to
the north of Kailāsa, near the mountain
Maināka (उत्तरेण तु कैलासं मैनाकं
पर्वतं प्रति।हिरण्यशृङ्गः) 2. 3. 8;
6. 7. 40; on its slope is the lake Bindusaras
(तस्य (i. e. हिरण्यशृङ्गस्य) पार्श्वे …
बिन्दुसरो नाम) 6. 7. 41; 2. 3. 9.
B.
Description: Auspicious (भगवन्त्) 2. 3.
8; very big (सुमहन्त्) 6. 7. 40; heavenly
(दिव्य) 6. 7. 40; full of jewels, full of large
jewels (मणिमय) 6. 7. 40; (महामणि-
मय) 2. 3. 8.
C. Epic event: The Pāṇḍa-
vas and Draupadī, when carried by Ghaṭo-
tkaca to the place of Nara and Nārāyaṇa
near the river Bhāgīrathī, saw from there
Maināka, Hiraṇyaśikhara and Bindusaras
3. 145. 39.
D. Past event: The divine
Tripathagā (Gāṅgā), issuing from the world
of Brahman, settled down at Hirṇyaśṛṅga and
then was divided into seven streams (तत्र
त्रिपथगा देवी प्रथमं तु प्रतिष्ठिता।
ब्रह्मलोकाद् अपक्रान्ता सप्तधा प्रतिप-
द्यते॥) 6. 7. 44; formerly, Gaṅgā issued
from Hemaśṛṅga of Himavant and on reach-
ing the ocean got divided into seven streams
(पुरा हिमवतश् चैषा हेमशृङ्गाद् विनिः-
सृता।गङ्गा गत्वा समुद्राम्भः सप्त-
धा प्रतिपद्यते) 1. 158. 17.

हिरण्यसरस्
Hiraṇyasaras nt.: Name of a तीर्थ।
Located on the ocean in the west (पश्चि-
मस्यां दिशि समुद्रे हिरण्यसरस् तीर्थम्)
12. 329. 46(5); since Soma was afflicted with
consumption (यक्ष्मन्) he was advised by
the sages to bathe in Hiraṇyasaras (आत्मा-
नम् अभिषेचयस्व); Soma did accordingly
and freed himself of the sin (गत्वा चात्मनः
स्नपनम् अकरोत्।स्नात्वा चात्मानं
पाप्मनो मोक्षयाम् आस) 12. 329. 46 (5-9);
since Śoma got back his lustre there, the
तीर्थ thereafter came to be known as Pra-
bhāsa (तत्र चावभासितस् तीर्थे यदा सोमस्
तदाप्रभृति तीर्थं तत् प्रभासम् इति
नाम्ना ख्यातं बभूव) 12. 329. 46(10).
[See Prabhāsa]

हिरण्वती
Hiraṇvatī f.: Name of a river.
A. Location: Listed by Saṃjaya among
the rivers of the Bhāratavarṣa; people used
its water for drinking 6. 10. 24, 13; in
Kurukṣetra (कुरुक्षेत्रे … नद्यास् तीरे
हिरण्वत्याः) 1. 95. 8; (सरितं … कुरु-
क्षेत्रे हिरण्वतीम्) 5. 149. 73;
B. Descrip-
tion: Holy (पुण्या), having bright water
(शुचिजला); free from pebbles and mud (शर्-
करापङ्कवर्जिता), having easy fords (सूप-
तीर्था) (Nī., however, on Bom. Ed. 5. 152. 7:
सूपतीर्थां शोभनोपकण्ठाम्) 5. 149.
73; all the rivers listed by Saṃjaya are
said to be mothers of the universe and very
strong 6. 10. 35 (for citation see Atikṛṣṇā).
C. Epic events: (1) Citrāṅgada, son of
Śaṃtanu, and his namesake, the king of the
Gandharvas (गन्धर्वराजो बलवांस् तुल्य-
नामा 1. 95. 7), fought a battle lasting for
three years (समास् तिस्रो ऽभवद् रणः)
on the bank of Hiraṇvatī; in this battle the
former was killed 1. 95. 8-10; (2) The
camp of the Pāṇḍavas was laid by Dhṛṣṭa-
dyumna near the river Hiraṇvatī (शिबिरं
मापयाम् आस धृष्टद्युम्नः … आसाद्य
सरितं … हिरण्वतीम्) 5. 149. 72-73; when
the Pāṇḍavas were encamped there Duryo-
dhana sent Ulūka as his messenger to them
(हिरण्वत्यां णिविष्टेषु पाण्डवेषु) 5. 157.
1.
D. Importance: Finds mention in the
Daivata-Ṛṣi-Vaṃśa 13. 151. 20.

हेमकूट
Hemakūṭa m.: Name of a mountain.
(also called Ṛṣabhakūṭa 3. 109. 7; once
identified with Kailāsa 6. 7. 39).
A. Location: Listed by Saṃjaya among
the six mountains which stretch towards the
east and merge at both ends in the eastern
and the western oceans (प्रागायता महाराज
षद् एते रत्नपर्वताः।अवगाढा ह्य् उभ-
यतः समुद्रौ पूर्वपश्चिमौ) 6. 7. 2;
the distance between them is thousands of
योजनस् (तेषाम् अन्तरविष्कम्भो योजनानि
सहस्रशः) 6. 7. 4; it lies between Haima-
vatavarṣa and Harivarṣa; the Varṣa beyond
Hemakūṭa is Harivarṣa (इदं तु भारतं
वर्षं ततो हैमवतं परम्।हेमकूटात्
परं चैव हरिवर्षं प्रचक्षते) 6. 7.
6; identified with Kailāsa (हेमकूटस् तु
सुमहान् कैलासो नाम पर्वतः) 6. 7. 39;
to the north of Kailāsa and towards Maināka
is the Hiraṇyaśṛṅga mountain 6. 7. 40;
near the rivers Nandā and Aparanandā
(ततः प्रयातः … नन्दाम् अपरनन्दां
च नद्यौ … ।स पर्वतं समासाद्य
हेमकूटम्) 3. 109. 1-2; 3. 109. 18-19.
B. Description: Free from disease (अना-
मय) 3. 109. 2; big (महागिरि) 3. 109. 14;
(सुमहन्त्) 6. 7. 39; all the six mountains
listed by Saṃjaya are full of jewels (रत्न-
पर्वताः) 6. 7. 2 and resorted to by Siddhas
and Cāraṇas (सिद्धचारणसेविताः) 6. 7. 4.
C. Characteristics: (1) Many unthinkable
wonders happen on the mountain (अचिन्त्यान्
अद्भुतान् भावान् ददर्श सुबहून् नृपः);
spoken words turn into clouds and rocks by
thousands and hence people cannot climb it
(वाचो यत्राभवन् मेघा उपलाश् च सहस्र-
शः।नाशक्नुवंस् तम् आरोढुम् …
जनाः॥) 3. 109. 3; wind always blows there
and it rains continuously; the oblation bearing
god (Fire) can be seen there morning and
evening (वायुर् नित्यं ववौ यत्र नित्यं
देवश् च वर्षति।सायं प्रातश् च भग-
वान् दृश्यते हव्यवाहनः॥) 3. 109. 4; (2)
One cannot even look at this mountain, let
alone climb it; one who has not practised
austerities cannot look at it or climb it
(नाशक्नुवन्न् अभिद्रष्टुं कुत एवाधिरो-
हितुम्॥नातप्ततपसा शक्यो द्रष्टुम् एष
महागिरिः।आरोढुं वापि कौन्तेय) 3. 109.
13-14; (3) Guhyakas live there (हेम-
कूटे तु गुह्यकाः) 6. 7. 48; King Vaiśra-
vaṇa, along with the Guhyakas, enjoys him-
self there (यत्र वैश्रवणो राजा गुह्य-
कैः सह मोदते) 6. 7. 39.
D. Epic
event: Yudhiṣṭhira having reached Hemakūṭa
saw many wonders there 3. 109. 5; Lomaśa
gave to him the explanation of these
wonders 3. 109. 6-17 (see the next section);
he advised Yudhiṣṭhira to bathe in the
river Nandā flowing along the mountain
since a bath destroyed the sin instantly
3. 109. 18; he also asked him to restrain his
speech (नियतवाग् भव) 3. 109. 14.
E. Past
events: (1) An ascetic named Ṛṣabha
once lived on this mountain (hence called
Ṛṣabhakūṭa ?) and was practising austerities
for many hundred years (अनेकशतवर्षायुस्
तपस्वी); he got angry when he was drawn
into conversation by others; so he told the
mountain to release rocks if any one uttered
a word there; he summoned wind and bade
him not to make noise; hence if any one tried
to speak there he was restrained by a cloud
(स वै संभाष्यमाणो ऽन्यैः कोपाद् गिरिम्
उवाच ह।य इह व्याहरेत् कश्चिद् उपलान्
उत्सृजेस् तदा॥वातं चाहूय मा शब्दम्
इत्य् उवाच स तापसः।व्याहरंश् चैव
पुरुषो मेघेन विनिवार्यते॥) 3. 109.
7-9; (2) When gods formerly came to the
river Nandā (flowing near Hemakūṭa) men
followed there to see the gods; since the
gods, Indra and the rest, did not wish to be
seen by men they made the land inaccessible
making this mountain an obstacle (दुर्गं
चक्रुर् इमं देशं गिरिप्रत्यूहरूपकम्);
hence men cannot even look at the mountain,
let alone climb it; the gods then always per-
formed best sacrifices there; the signs of
those sacrifices could even now be seen in
the form of the sprawling दूर्वा grass having
the form of sacrificial grass (कुश) and many
trees having the shape of sacrificial posts
(यूप) (तेषाम् एतानि लिङ्गानि दृश्यन्ते ऽद्यापि
भारत॥कुशाकारेव दुर्वेयं … यूप-
प्रकारा बहवो वृक्षाश् चेमे॥) 3. 109.
11-16; (3) Hamakūṭa was one of the
mountains seen by Mārkaṇḍeya in the belly
of the Bāla (3. 186. 83 = Nārāyaṇa 3. 187.
3) 3. 186. 101. [See Rṣabhakūṭa]

हेमशृङ्ग
Hemaśṛṅga m.: See Hiraṇyaśṛṅga.

हैम
Haima m.: See Himavant.

हैरण्वती
Hairaṇvatī f.: Name of a river.
The river flows in the Hairaṇvatavarṣa
6. 9. 5.

अगस्त्यशिष्यस्य
Agastyaśiṣyasya āśramaḥ m.: See
Tṛṇasomāgner āśramaḥ.

अगस्त्यस्य
Agastyasya āśramaḥ m.: Name of an
आश्रम।
An आश्रम established by Agastya
in the south (दक्षिणस्यां … शृणु तीर्थानि
 … कीर्त्यमानानि) 3. 86. 1; located near the
Vaiḍūrya mountain (वैडूर्यपर्वतस् तत्र
 … अगस्त्यस्याश्रमश् चैव) 3. 86. 15; des-
cribed as having many roots and fruits and
ample water (बहुमूलफलोदक) 3. 86.
15.

अगस्त्याश्रम
Agastyāśrama m.: Name of an आश्रम
of Agastya, also called Hiraṇyabindu (3.
85. 15).
A. Location: In the east (प्राचीम् दि-
शं … कीर्तयिष्यामि) 3. 85. 3; in the vicinity
of the confluence of Gaṅgā and Yamunā
at Prayāga (प्रयागम् इति विख्यातम् …
अगस्त्यस्य … तत्राश्रमवरः) 3. 85. 13-
15; on the Kālañjara mountain, known
there as Hiraṇyabindu (हिरण्यबिन्दुः
कथितो गिरौ कालञ्जरे नृप) 3. 8. 15;
near the place called Durjayā (अगस्त्याश्र-
मम् आसाद्य दुर्जयायाम् उवास ह) 3. 94. 1.
B. Description: Excellent (आश्रमवर) 3.
85. 15; extensive (महन्त्) 3. 85. 15; well
known (ख्यात) 3. 97. 26; pleasing (रम-
णीय) 3. 97. 27; having (all) qualities
(गुनैर् युतः) 3. 97. 27; having flowers of
all seasons (सर्वर्तुकुसुमान्वित) 3. 97. 26.
C. Epic event: The Pāṇḍavas, in their
तीर्थयात्रा, reached this आश्रम and lived
there for some time 3. 94. 1.
D. Past
events: (1) Vātāpi was made quiet there
(put out of action) by Agastya (अगस्त्ये-
नेह वातापिः … उपशामितः) 3. 94. 2;
(वातापिर् अगस्त्येन विनाशितः) 3. 97. 26;
(2) Wealth given by Ilvala to Agastya,
after the destruction of Vātāpi, was loaded
on a chariot and carried to Agastyāśrama
3. 97. 15; (3) Gods, as directed by Viṣṇu,
went to Agastyāśrama (to request him to
drink up the ocean) and saw him in his
आश्रम 3. 101. 11-13.

अच्युतस्थल
Acyutasthala nt.: Name of a town.
A place in the Āraṭṭa (Bāhlīka) coun-
try; one who stays there (long) cannot go
to heaven; hence one should not stay there
for more than a day—this is what a Brāh-
maṇa told in the assembly of the Kurus
(यद् अन्यो ऽप्य् उक्तवान् सभ्यो ब्राह्मणः
कुरुसं सदि॥ … प्रोष्य चाप्य् अच्युतस्थले।
 … कथं स्वर्गं गमिष्यति॥ … आरट्टा
नाम बाह्लीका न तेष्व् आर्यो द्व्यहं वसेत्
॥) 8. 30. 41-43; the place also mentioned
in what a Piśācī said to a Brāhmaṇī (?)
who came to stay at Raupyā with her sons;
this was told by Lomaśa to Yudhiṣṭhira
when he wanted to recite the अनुवंश
stanzas about Raupyā; according to the
Piśācī no one who had stayed at Acyuta-
sthala was supposed to stay near Raupyā
for more than one night (अत्रानुवंशं
पठतः शृणु मे कुरुनन्दन। … पिशाची
यद् अभाषत। … उषित्वा चाच्युतस्थले। …
एकरात्रम् उषित्वेह द्वितीयां यदि वत्स्यसि।
एतद् वै ते दिवा वृत्तं रात्रौ वृत्तम् अतो
ऽन्यथा॥) 3. 129. 8-10; (according to the
प्राञ्चः, whose view is cited by Nī. on Bom.
Ed. 3. 129. 9, one could stay at Raupyā even
after staying at Acyutasthala if he had
performed the prescribed प्रायश्चित्त viz.
the प्राजापत्य व्रत; according to these
प्राञ्चः, Acyutasthala was the village where
people born of mixed marriages lived
(अच्युतस्थलाख्ये संकरजानां ग्रामे);
according to others, however, who under-
stood the word in good light, Acyutasthala
meant the subtle body (लिङ्गशरीर) and
उषित्वा meant by being near the सूत्रात्मन्
(सूत्रात्मानम् उपास्य)).

अन्ताखी
Antākhī (?) f.: Name of a city.
A city outside the Bhāratavarṣa; Saha-
deva brought it under control just by send-
ing messengers and made its people pay
tribute for the Rājasūya of Yudhiṣṭhira
(अन्ताखीं चैव रोमां च … दूतैर् एव
वशे चक्रे करं चैनान् अदापयत्) 2. 28
49. [See F. Edgerton JAOS 58. 264-265,
1938]

अपरपर्यट
Aparaparyaṭa nt.: Name of a city.
In the west; one of the cities brought
under control (वशे चक्रे) by Nakula in
his expedition before the Rājasūya 2. 29.
10.

अभिसारी
Abhisārī f.: Name of a city.
Situated in the north-west near the
Trigartas; described as attractive (रम्या);
Arjuna conquered it in his expedition to
the north-west and north before the Rāja-
sūya 2. 24. 18, 17.

अमरावती
Amarāvatī, Amarāvati (म्। च्। 3. 170.
25) f.: Name of Indra's city.
A. City of Indra (शक्रस्य पुरीम्
 … अमरावतीम्) 3. 43. 38; (शक्रस्य दयि-
तां पुरीम्) 3. 44. 7; 1. 168. 20; 13. 31.
18; (देवराजस्य … अमरावती) 5. 101. 1;
(शक्रस्य भवनम् … अमरावतीम्) 3. 164.
42; (महेन्द्रभवन) 7. 10. 22; (पुरन्-
दरपुर) 3. 169. 27.
B. Description:
Pleasing (रम्या) 3. 44. 1; (पुरीं रम्-
याम्) 3. 164. 51; excellent city (पुरी वर्या)
5. 101. 1; adorned with jewels (रत्नैश् च
समलंकृताम्) 3. 164. 42; beautified with
holy trees blossoming in all seasons (सर्व-
र्तुकुसुमैः पुण्यैः पादपैर् उपशोभि-
ताम्) 3. 44. 1; adorned with celestial trees
giving the desired fruits (दिव्यैः काम-
फलवृक्षैः … समलंकृताम्) 3. 164. 42;
cold and holy winds carrying the fragrance
of flowers blew there (पाण्डवः।पुष्प-
गन्धवहैः पुण्यैर् वायुभिश् चानुवीजितः)
3. 44. 9; (शीतस् तत्र ववौ वायुः सुगन्धो
जीवनः शुचिः) 3. 164. 47; resorted to by
Siddhas and Cāraṇas (सिद्धचारणसेविता)
3. 44. 1; Gandharvas and Apsarases pre-
sent there 3. 44. 9; for the description of
Śakra's residence (शक्रस्य भवनम् अम-
रावतीम्, सुरवेश्मन्) see also 3. 164. 43-48.
C. Characteristics: (1) विमानस् of gods,
moving at will, in very large numbers,
standing and going around (तत्र देव-
विमानानि कामगानि सहस्रशः।संस्थितान्य्
अभियातानि ददर्शायुतशस् तदा) 3. 44. 8;
(2) Not easy to obtain: Maheśvara told
Umā that a Dīkṣita who, while living in
the company of deer, lives only on grass
that falls down from the mouth of deer,
will go to Amarāvatī (शष्पं मृगमु-
खोत्सृष्टं यो मृगैः सह सेवते।दीक्षितो
वै मुदा युक्तः स गच्छत्य् अमरा-
वतीम्॥) 13. 130. 40; also see section
G below.
D. Epic events: (1)
Arjuna saw Amarāvatī in the Devaloka 3.
43. 14; 3. 164. 42. (2) Arjuna, when
he saw the town of the Nivātakavacas,
found it to be superior to the city of the
gods and also to the city of Indra (विशिष्टं
देवनगरात्) 3. 169. 26; (पुरन्दरपुराद्
धीदं विशिष्टम् इति लक्षये) 3. 169. 27;
he asked Mātali why the gods did not live
in that city 3. 169. 26-27.
E. Past event:
Kṛṣṇa, mounted on Vainateya (Garuḍa),
frightened (the denizens of) Amarāvatī
(त्रासयित्वामरावतीम्) and brought Pārijāta
from Indra's residence (महेन्द्रभवनात्)
7. 10. 22.
F. Similes: (1) When king
Saudāsa returned to the city of Ayodhyā it
shone like Amarāvatī with Indra (शक्रेणे-
वामरावती) 1. 168. 20; (2) Divodāsa
built Vārāṇasī like Amarāvatī of Śakra 13.
31. 18; (3) Hiraṇyapura of the Kālakeya
demons, which could move at will, was
like Amarāvatī (अमरावतिसंकाशं पुरं
कामगमं तु तत्) 3. 170. 25; (4) The
town Bhogavatī of Vāsuki was like Amarā-
vatī of Indra (यादृशी देवराजस्य पुरी
यर्यामरावती) 5. 101. 1.
G. Mode of
expression: (1) To express great wonder:
King Kuśika, seeing many wonderful things
in the forest, wondered whether he had
reached Uttara Kurus or Amarāvatī 13. 54.
16; (2) To express unattainability: Kṛṣṇa
told Subhadrā that Jayadratha, even if he
entered Amarāvatī, would not get away
from Arjuna 7. 54. 19.

अयोध्या
Ayodhyā f.: Name of a city, also called
Kosalā (3. 75. 3; 3. 263. 29).
A. Location: In the east (ययौ
प्राचीं दिशं प्रति) 2. 26. 1.
B. Des-
cription: Pleasing (रम्या) 3. 63. 19; 3.
275. 36; excellent, best town (पुरवर) 1.
168. 14; (पुरम् उत्तमम्) 1. 168. 19;
famous (ख्यात) 1. 168. 14; city of the
righteous (नगरीं पुण्यकर्मणाम्) 1.
168. 16; full of people who were contend-
ed and well fed (तुष्टपुष्टजनाकीर्णा) 1.
168. 20.
C. Epic event: Bhīma defeated
king Dīrghaprajña of Ayodhyā in his ex-
pedition to the east before the Rājasūya
2. 27. 2.
D. Past events: (1) Events
related to Rāmāyaṇa: (i) When Lakṣmaṇa
was held and dragged towards his mouth
by Kabandha, he lost hope of meeting Rāma
again when he, with Sītā, would return
to Kosalā (नाहं त्वाम् … कोसलागतं।
द्रक्ष्यामि) 3. 263. 29; (ii) Rāma won-
dered whether he would rule over Ayodhyā
again after killing the enemies in battle and
after getting Sītā back 3. 266. 34; (iii)
After the सत्यक्रिया of Sītā, Rāma told
Daśaratha that he would return to Ayodhyā
at his bidding; Daśaratha asked him to go
to Ayodhyā and rule over it 3. 275. 36-37;
(iv) On reaching Ayodhyā, Rāma sent Ha-
nūmant to Bharata 3. 275. 59; (2) Events
related to the story of Nala: (i) Vārṣṇeya,
the charioteer of Nala, left Nala's children
with king Bhīma of Kuṇḍinapura and
went to Ayodhyā to seek service with king
Ṛtuparṇa 3. 57. 22; (ii) Karkoṭaka nāga
advised Nala to assume the name Bāhuka
and go to king Ṛtuparṇa of Ayodhā 3. 63.
19; Nala, accordingly, reached the town of
Ṛtuparṇa (ऋतुपर्णस्य नगरम्) 3. 64. 1;
(iii) The Brāhmaṇa Parṇāda told Dama-
yantī that he had reached Ayodhyā in
search of Nala; Damayantī wanted Sudeva
to be sent back to Ayodhyā to get Nala;
Damayantī sent Sudeva to Ṛtuparṇa resid-
ing at Ayodhyā (hence called Ayodhyāpati
in 3. 69. 22) to announce to him that she de-
sired another husband and for this she was
arranging another Svayaṃvara (ऋतुपर्णं
वचो ब्रूहि पतिम् अन्यंचिकीर्षति।आस्थास्यति
पुनर् भैमी दमयन्ती स्वयंवरम्॥)
3. 68. 2, 16, 21; 3. 72. 17; (iv) Damayantī
later told Nala that the Brāhmaṇa Parṇāda,
while searching Nala, had reached the resi-
dence of king Ṛtuparṇa in Kosalā (अभ्य-
गच्छत् कोसलायाम् ऋतुपर्णनिवेशने) 3.
75. 3; (3) Other events: (i) Śaśāda
ruled over Ayodhyā after Ikṣvāku 3. 193.
1; (ii) Parīkṣit, of Ikṣvāku family, once
ruled over Ayodhyā 3. 190. 3; (iii) Gālava
took Mādhavī with him and went to king
Haryaśva of Ikṣvāku family who ruled at
Ayodhyā 5. 113. 18; (iv) King Kalmāṣa-
pāda, when freed from Rakṣas by Vasiṣṭha,
returned to Ayodhyā; his subjects greeted
him; Kalmāṣapāda entered the city with
Vasiṣṭha; the citizens of Ayodhyā saw their
king with Vasiṣṭha as the sun rising in
conjunction with Puṣya; the city, with its
streets cleansed and sprinkled with water
and decorated with raised flags, pleased
Kalmāṣapāda; when the king entered the
city Ayodhyā with Vasiṣṭha, the queen, at
the king's command, approached Vasiṣṭha
for a son 1. 168. 14-19, 21.
E. Similes:
(1) Ayodhyā made prosperous by Kalmāṣa-
pāda compared with the sky made to shine
at the rise of the autumnal moon (स हि तां
पूरयाम् आस लक्ष्म्या … ।अयोध्यां व्योम
शीतांशुः शरत्काल इवोदितः॥) 1. 168. 18;
(2) Ayodhyā, with its citizens contended
and well nourished shone in the reign of
Kalmāṣapāda as Amarāvatī due to Śakra
(अशोभत तदा तेन शक्रेणेवामरावती) 1.
168. 20.

अलका
Alakā1 f.: Name of a lotus pond near
the Sabhā of Kubera.
Wind, carrying the fragrance from the
lotus pond Alakā and giving delight to
mind and heart, waits on Kubera in his
Sabhā (आदाय गन्धान् … नलिन्याश् चालका-
ख्यायाः … मनोहृदयसंह्लादी वायुस् तम्
उपसेवते) 2. 10. 7-8.

अलका
Alakā2 f.: Name of the city of
Kubera.
Kubera is called the ‘lord of Alakā’
(अलकाधिप) 9. 10. 48; 12. 75. 4, 15.

अवन्ती
Avantī f.: Name of a city.
Nala showed Damayantī the paths
which, after crossing Avantī and Ṛkṣavant
mountain, led to the Dakṣiṇāpatha (एते
गच्छन्ति बहवः पन्थानो दक्षिणापथम्।
अवन्तीम् ऋक्षवन्तं च समतिक्रम्य पर्-
वतम्॥) 3. 58. 20. [Avanti, name of a
Janapada, Section I. 6]

अश्वमेध
Aśvamedha m.: Name of a town (?).
In the east (प्राचीम् दिशम्) 2. 26. 1,
7; Bhīma, in his expedition before the
Rājasūya, conquered Rocamāna, king of
Aśvamedha (सो ऽश्वमेधेश्वरं राजन्
रोचमानम् … ।जिगाय समरे वीरः … ॥)
2. 26. 8.

अहिच्छत्रा
Ahicchatrā f.: Name of a city.
Situated in the territory called Ahic-
chatra; described as having many commu-
nities (जनपदायुता); it was conquered by
Arjuna for Droṇa (अहिच्छत्रं च विषयं
द्रोणः समभिपद्यत।एवं राजन्न् अहि-
च्छत्रा पुरी जनपदायुता।युधि निर्जित्य
पार्थेन द्रोणाय प्रतिपादिता॥) 1. 128. 18.

आथर्वणस्य
Ātharvaṇasya sthānam nt.: Name of
a place.
One of the places seen by Arjuna when
he and Kṛṣṇa journeyed at night to Hima-
vant to propitiate Śiva for his Pāśupata
(स्थानम् आथर्वणस्य च) 7. 57. 28.

आदित्यबन्धन
Ādityabandhana nt.: Name of the
आश्रम of Vṛṣadhvaja (Śiva).
A. Location: Situated to the north
of Himavant (उत्तरां दिशं गत्वा शैल-
राजस्य पार्श्वतः) 12. 314. 18.
B. Ex-
tent: Its extent was ten योजनस् (दशयो-
जनविस्तारम्) 12. 314. 20.
C. Chara-
cteristics: (1) Vṛṣadhvaja constantly
practised austerities in this आश्रम (तपो
ऽतप्यत दुर्धर्षस् तात नित्यं व्र्षध्व-
जः) 12. 314. 18, 22; (2) It is encircled
by blazing fire and hence inaccessible to
those who have not controlled their self
(पावकेन परिक्षिप्तो दीप्यता तस्य चाश्र-
मः।आदित्यबन्धनं नाम दुर्धर्षम्
अकृतात्मभिः) 12. 314. 19; (अग्निज्वाला-
समावृतम्) 12. 314. 20; God Fire himself
is present there to destroy all obstacles
to the austerities of Mahādeva (भगवान्
पावकस् तत्र स्वयं तिष्ठति वीर्यवान्।
सर्वविघ्नान् प्रशमयन् महादेवस्य धी-
मतः॥) 12. 314. 21; (3) Yakṣas, Rākṣa-
sas, and Dānavas cannot go there 12. 314.
20.

आदित्यस्य
Ādityasya āśramaḥ m.: Name of an
आश्रम।
The आश्रम of the high-souled Āditya
(sun), the store of lustre, situated near the
Ādityatīrtha (आदित्यस्याश्रमो यत्र तेजो-
राशेर् महात्मनः) 3. 81. 160. [See Aditya-
tīriha Vol. I. 293-294]

आनर्तनगर
Ānartanagara (nt.), Ānartanagarī,
Ānartapurī (f.): See Dvārakā.

आश्रम|आश्रमः
Āśramaḥ m.: An आश्रम, name of
which is not mentioned; it once belonged
to Viṣṇu and then to the daughter of
Śāṇḍilya.
A. Location: To the north of Kuru-
kṣetra, near the Himavant mountain (पार्श्वे
हिमवतः) 9. 53. 9, 1.
B. Description:
Holy, having holy characteristics (पुण्य)
9. 53. 2, 9, (पुण्यलक्षण) 9. 53. 3; hea-
venly (दिव्य) 9. 53. 1; excellent, excellent
आश्रम (प्रवर) 9. 53. 3, (आश्रमवर)
9. 53. 3; extensive (सुमहन्त्) 9. 53. 1;
having Madhūka, Āmra, Plakṣa, Nyagro-
dha, Ciribilva, Panasa and Arjuna trees in
very large number (मधूकाम्रवनोपेतं
प्लक्षन्यग्रोधसंकुलम्।चिरिबिल्वयुतं
पुण्यं पनसार्जुनसंकुलम्॥) 9. 53. 2.
C. Epic event: Balarāma visited it after
seeing Kurukṣetra and asked the sages
whose आश्रम it was; Balarāma, after
listening to their account, bowed down to
them and went up the Himavant mountain
9. 53. 1, 3, 9.
D. Past event: The sages
when asked by Balarāma whose आश्रम it
was told him to whom the आश्रम formerly
belonged (यस्यायं पूर्वम् आश्रमः) 9.
53. 4: (1) Formerly Viṣṇu practised in the
आश्रम the best austerities and performed
according to rites all the ancient sacrifices
(अत्र विष्णुः पुरा देवस् तप्तवांस् तप
उत्तमम्।अत्रास्य विधिवद् यज्ञाः सर्वे
वृत्ताः सनातनाः) 9. 53. 5; (2) The dau-
ghter of Śāṇḍilya who observed chastity
since her maidenhood (कौमारब्रह्म-
चारिणी) practised austerities there; she
enjoyed in the आश्रम the fruit of the Aśva-
medha sacrifice (भुक्त्वाश्रमे ऽश्वमेध-
स्य फलम्) and then taking recourse to
योग went to heaven (योगयुक्ता दिवं
याता; सा तु प्राप्य परं योगं गता
स्वर्गम्) 9. 53. 6-8.

आश्रमपद
Āśramapada nt.: The precincts of an
आश्रम (not named).
A. Location: On the confluence of
Gaṅgā and Yamunā (आश्रमपदं गङ्गा-
यमुनसंगमे) 5. 118. 1.
B. Descrip-
tion: Nāgas, Yakṣas and men gathered
there, as also birds (पतत्रिन् and पक्षिन्, big
and small birds ?), deer, and forest-dwellers
who lived on mountain trees; the forest
near the आश्रम was thronged by kings of
different peoples and countries and by sages
who resembled Brahman (नागयक्षम-
नुष्याणां पतत्रिमृगपक्षिणाम्।शैलद्रु-
मवनौकानाम् आसीत् तत्र समागमः॥
नानापुरुषदेशानाम् ईश्वरैश् च समाकुलम्।
ऋषिभिर् ब्रह्मकल्पैश् च समन्ताद् आवृतं
वनम्॥) 5. 118. 3-4.
C. Past event:
King Yayāti, wishing to arrange, the स्व-
यंवर of his daughter Mādhavī a second
time, went to this Āśramapada (उपगम्या-
श्रमपदम्); Puru and Yadu, his two
sons, took their sister there in a chariot
(रथम् आरोप्य माधवीम् पुरुर् यदुश् च
भगिनीम् आश्रमे पर्यधावताम्) 5. 118. 2.

आश्रममण्डल
Āśramamaṇḍala nt.: A group of
आश्रमस् (not named).
A. Location; Situated on the bank
of Yamunā (प्रविश्याश्रममण्डलम्।य-
मुनातीरम् आश्रित्य) 5. 187. 18; (यमुना-
तीरम् आसाद्य) 5. 187. 20.
B. Epic event:
Ambā entered the Āśramamaṇḍala to pra-
ctise severe austerities in order to be able
to kill Bhīṣma 5. 187. 18.

आसन्दी
Āsandī f.: Name of a village (ग्राम).
One of the five villages for five Pāṇḍa-
vas in return of which Yudhiṣṭhira was
prepared to have peace with the Kauravas;
four of these five villages—Kuśasthala,
Vṛkasthala, Āsandī and Vāraṇāvata—were
actually named by Yudhiṣṭhira; he left to
Duryodhana to name the fifth (किंचिद् एव
तु पञ्चमम्) 5. 31. 19; (भ्रातॄणाम् देहि
पञ्चानां ग्रामान् पञ्च सुयोधन।शान्तिर्
नो ऽस्तु) 5. 31. 20; (पञ्च ग्रामा वृता
मया) 5. 70. 14-15; (पञ्च नस् तात दीय-
न्तां ग्रामा वा नगराणि वा) 5. 70. 16; 5.
80. 7.

इन्द्रप्रस्थ
Indraprastha nt.: Name of a city, the
capital of the Pāṇḍavas; earlier called Khāṇ-
ḍavaprastha; occasionally referred to also
as Śakraprastha (1. 213. 57; 2. 25. 20; 16.
8. 10, 11, 68; 17. 1. 9), Śatakratuprastha
(3. 24. 11), Śakrapura (5. 30. 47); desig-
nated variously as पुर (1. 199. 27; 3. 24.
11, also पुरोत्तम and पुरश्रेष्ठ see
below Description), नगर (1. 55. 25; 1.
199. 28, 39; 1. 213. 57), राष्ट्र 1. 199. 47
(besides प्रस्थ as in its name).
A. Location: Near the river Yamunā
(व्यचरद् यमुनाकूले पार्थेन सह) 1.
213. 57; (गच्छामो यमुनां प्रति) 1. 214.
14.
B. Description: Delightful (रम्य)
1. 213. 57; best city (पुरोत्तम) 1. 199. 33;
1. 213. 22; 2. 25. 20; 2. 65. 17; (पुरश्रेष्ठ)
1. 199. 30, 49; unrivalled (अप्रतिम) 3. 24.
11; large (महन्त्) 1. 199. 47; 3. 24. 11;
looking like the city of gods (देवपुरप्र-
काश) 3. 24. 11; city of the righteous people
(पुण्यजनोपेत) 1. 199. 47; it had well
distributed large roads (सुविभक्तमहा-
पथ) 1. 55. 24; full of clean people and
adorned by merchants (सुसंमृष्टजना-
कीर्णं वणिग्भिर् उपशोभितम्) 1. 213. 33,
full of communities (जनपदोपेत) 1. 55.
24; (also see the next section).
C. Found-
ing of the city: Dhṛtarāṣṭra gave half of
the Kuru kingdom to the Pāṇḍavas and
asked them to settle down at Khāṇḍava-
prastha (अर्धं राज्यस्य संप्राप्य खा-
ण्डवप्रस्थम् आविश); the Pāṇḍavas had
to pass through a dense forest to reach
Khāṇḍavaprastha from Hāstinapura (प्र-
तस्थिरे ततो घोरं वनं तत् … खाण्डव-
प्रस्थम् आविशन्) 1. 199. 25-26; led by
Kṛṣṇa, the Pāṇḍavas renovated the city so
that it looked like heaven (कृष्णपुरो-
गमाः।मण्डयां चक्रिरे तद् वै पुरं
स्वर्गवत्) 1. 199. 27; they performed शान्ति
on a holy and auspicious spot and then
measured out the town under the guidance
of Vyāsa (ततः पुण्ये शिवे देशे शान्तिं
कृत्वा महारथाः।नगरं मापयाम्
आसुर् द्वैपायनपुरोगमाः) 1. 199. 28; 3.
24. 11; its protective deep and tall walls,
wide gates, tall गोपुरस्, different weapons
stored in it, and its palatial buildings des-
cribed in 1. 199. 29-36; it had gardens all
around filled with trees of different kinds
and birds (विविधैर् द्रुमैः। … नानाद्विज-
गणायुतम्; the trees are listed); the gar-
dens were filled with the notes of excited
peacocks and cuckoos (मत्तबर्हिणसं-
घुष्टं कोकिलैश् च सदामदैः) 1. 199.
39-43; it had clean, residential houses,
creeper houses (लतागृह), houses display-
ing pictures on their walls (चित्रगृह) and
artificial mountains for the sport of kings
(जगतिपर्वत; Nī. who reads अजगतिपर्-
वतैः (Bom. Ed. 1. 207. 46) says: नृप-
लीलायात्रार्थैः कृत्रिमैः पर्वतैः) 1. 199.
44; it had ponds (वापी) filled with water,
lakes (सरस्), fragrant with lotuses and
adorned with swans, कारण्डव and चक्र-
वाक birds, varied and delightful lotus
ponds covered with clusters of lotus plants
(रम्याश् च विविधास् तत्र पुष्करिण्यो वना-
वृताः), and other beautiful ponds, large and
wide (तडागानि च रम्याणि बृहन्ति च म-
हान्ति च) 1. 199. 44-46; Brāhmaṇas learned
in all the Vedas came to settle down there,
as also men who knew different languages
(सर्वभाषाविदस् तथा), merchants from
all directions seeking to make money
(वणिजश् चाभ्ययुस् तत्र देशे दिग्भ्यो ध-
नार्थिनः), and artisans who were skilled
in different crafts (सर्वशिल्पविदश् चैव
वासायाभ्यगमंस् तदा) 1. 199. 37-38;
Indraprastha, shining with its various white,
excellent palatial buildings, shone like heaven
(विरोचमानं विविधैः पाण्डुरैर् भवनो-
त्तमैः॥तत् त्रिविष्टपसंकाशम् इन्द्र-
प्रस्थं व्यरोचत।) 1. 199. 34-35; there
Yudhiṣṭhira had his residence on a beauti-
ful, auspicious spot; filled with wealth it
shone like the residence of Kubera (तत्र
रम्ये शुभे देशे कौरव्यस्य निवेशनम्।
शुशुभे धनसंपूर्णं धनाध्यक्ष-
क्षयोपमम्) 1. 199. 36; the Pāṇḍavas, as
they settled down there, developed a liking
for the town (तेषां … राष्ट्रम् आवसतां …
पाण्डवानां … शश्वत् प्रीतिर् अवर्धत) 1.
199. 47; the excellent town, with those five
Indra-like archers, shone like Bhogavatī with
the Nāgas (शुशुभे तत् पुरश्रेष्ठं नागैर्
भोगवती यथा) 1. 199. 49; the Pāṇḍavas
thus became the inhabitants of Khāṇḍava-
prastha (समपद्यन्त खाण्डवप्रस्थवा-
सिनः) 1. 199. 48; they thus got the kingdom
of Indraprastha (एवं संप्राप्य राज्यं
तद् इन्द्रप्रस्थे) 1. 200. 1; Pāṇḍavas' settl-
ing down at Khāṇḍavaprastha and ruling
from there half of the (Kuru) kingdom is
referred to in the Parvasaṃgrahaparvan
(खाण्डवप्रस्थवासश् च तथा राज्यार्ध-
शासनम्) 1. 2. 89; also mentioned briefly
in the summary of the Mahābhārata (अस्मा-
भिः खाण्डवप्रस्थे युष्मद्वासो ऽनुचिन्ति-
तः) 1. 55. 23-27; while describing the
Pāṇḍavas' rule at Indraprastha Draupadī
told Satyabhāmā that a hundred thousand
horses and ten अयुतस् of elephants were in
regular attendance of Yudhiṣṭhira (शतम्
अश्वसहस्राणि दशनागायुतानि च।युधि-
ष्ठिरस्यानुयात्रम् इन्द्रप्रस्थनिवासिनः)
3. 222. 48 (Nī. on Bom. Ed. 3. 233. 50;
अनुयात्रं स्वैरयात्रायाम् अपि परिवार-
भूतम्); Pāṇḍavas' going to Khāṇḍava-
prastha alluded to by Draupadī when she
introduced herself to Koṭikāśya 3. 250. 5;
Draupadī, while lamenting over the condi-
tion of the Pāṇḍavas during their stay in
the Virāṭanagara remembered Yudhiṣṭhira's
glory while living in Indraprastha 4. 17. 15-
21, 23-26, 28.
D. Epic events: (1)
When the cows of a Brāhmaṇa were stolen
by thieves he came to Khāṇḍavaprastha
and blamed the Pāṇḍavas 1. 205. 6; (2)
While ruling from Indraprastha the Pāṇḍa-
vas subjugated other kings at the instance
of Dhṛtarāṣṭra and Bhīṣma (apparently
even before the Rājasūya) (इन्द्रप्रस्थे
वसन्तस् ते जघ्नुर् अन्यान् नराधिपान्।
शासनाद् धृतराष्ट्रस्य राज्ञः शान्तनवस्य
च॥) 1. 214. 1; (3) Dharmarāja, who was
at Indpraprastha, was informed of Arjuna's
plan to abduct Subhadrā and his permi-
ssion was obtained 1. 211. 25; (4) Arjuna,
along with Subhadrā, returned to Khāṇḍava-
prastha when he completed his period of
exile of twelve years 1. 213. 13, 22; (5) The
Yādavas went to Khāṇḍavaprastha to offer
marriage gifts to Arjuna 1. 213. 29; (this
is referred to in the Anukramaṇīparvan 1.
1. 103); when Kṛṣṇa, Balarāma and other
Yādavas arrived, the city of Khāṇḍava-
prastha was gaily decorated with flags and
banners, its roads were swept and sprink-
led with water, flowers scattered all around,
cool and fragrant sandalwood juice was
abundantly used, and fragrant अगुरु burnt
at every place (विवेश खाण्डवप्रस्थं
पताकाध्वजशोभितम्।सिक्तसंमृष्टपन्-
थानं पुष्पप्रकरशोभितम्।चन्दनस्य
रसैः शीतैः पुण्यगन्धैर् निषेवितम्॥
दह्यतागुरुणा चैव देशे देशे सुगन्धिना)
1. 213. 31-33; (6) When the Yādavas
left, after giving gifts to Arjuna, Kṛṣṇa
stayed behind at Śakraprastha (उवास
नगरे रम्ये श्रक्रप्रस्थे महामनाः)
1. 213. 57; (7) Sairandhrī told Uttara
that Bṛhannaḍā was the charioteer of
Arjuna when he defeated all kinds of beings
at Khāṇḍavaprastha (अजयत् खाण्डव-
प्रस्थे) 4. 34. 15 (here Khāṇḍavaprastha
stands for Khāṇḍava forest); this feat of
Arjuna at Khāṇḍavaprastha (= Khāṇḍava
forest) also referred to by Kṛṣṇa in his
address to Duryodhana (अजयत् खाण्डव-
प्रस्थे) 5. 122. 52, and by Karṇa when
he spoke to Śalya (प्रस्थे ऽजयत् खाण्डवे
सव्यसाची) 8. 29. 18; (8) After a com-
fortable stay (सुखवास) at Khāṇḍava-
prastha Kṛṣṇa wished to leave for Dvārakā
2. 2. 1; (9) Kṛṣṇa went again to Indra-
prastha when invited by Yudhiṣṭhira for
consultation regarding his wish to perform
a Rājasūya 2. 12. 30-31; (10) After the
death of Jarāsandha, Kṛṣṇa returned to
Indraprastha with Bhīma and Arjuna 2.
22. 44; (11) When the four younger
Pāṇḍavas went for the conquest of the
four directions before the Rājasūya, Yudhi-
ṣṭhira stayed back at Khāṇḍavaprastha 2.
30. 10; (12) After completing successfully
his expedition to the north Arjuna return-
ed to Śakraprastha with all kinds of
tributes (शक्रप्रस्थं पुरोत्तमम्) 2.
25. 20; (13) When Bhīma returned to
Indraprastha after his expedition to the
east he reported to Yudhiṣṭhira the great
wealth brought by him 2. 27. 28; (14)
Nakula went to the west from Khāṇḍava-
prastha 2. 29. 2; when he came back to
Yudhiṣṭhira at Indraprastha he too report-
ed to him the wealth brought by him 2. 29.
18; (15) After the Rājasūya, when Dur-
yodhana visited the Mayasabhā in Indra-
prastha, the Pāṇḍavas laughed at Duryo-
dhana (Bhīṣma told this to Yudhiṣṭhira)
12. 124. 5 (reference to 2. 43. 7, 9); (16)
Dhṛtarāṣṭra asked Vidura to go to Khāṇ-
ḍavaprastha to invite Yudhiṣṭhira for a
game of dice 2. 45. 56; (17) At the end
of the first game of dice, Dhṛtarāṣṭra per-
mitted Yudhiṣṭhira to return to Khāṇḍva-
prastha 2. 65. 15; accordingly Yudhiṣṭhira,
with his brothers and Draupadī, left for
Indraprastha 2. 65. 17; (18) The bright
prosperity (at the time of Rājasūya) of
Yudhiṣṭhira while he was ruling at Indrapra-
stha (इन्द्रप्रस्थगते … युधिष्ठिरे) was
snatched away from him by Duryodhana in
the game of dice (Karṇa told Duryodhana)
3. 226. 5-6; (19) People lamented when
Yudhiṣṭhira had to leave for the forest
leaving behind the great city Śatakratu-
prastha founded by himself (स्वयं निवेश्य
 … पुरं महत् … शतक्रतुप्रस्थम् …
हित्वा प्रयातः क्व नु धर्मराजः) 3. 24.
11; (20) Kṛṣṇa had assured Yudhiṣṭhira
when he met him in the forest that he
(Kṛṣṇa) could kill the Kauravas and get
back for him his prosperity which he had
seen at Indraprastha at the time of Rāja-
sūya (and of which he was now deprived)
3. 48. 17, 23; (21) Duryodhana re-
minded Dhṛtarāṣṭra that when Kṛṣṇa and
the other kings met the Pāṇḍavas in the
forest, at a place not far from Indraprastha
(वनं प्रव्राजितान् पार्थान् … इन्द्रप्रस्थ-
स्य चादूरात् समाजग्मुः), they blamed
Dhṛtarāṣṭra and the other Kauravas 5. 54.
2, 4; (22) Aśvatthāman asked Karṇa in
derision in which battle did he (Karṇa)
win Indraprastha from the Pāṇḍavas; now
Karṇa should fight with Arjuna (at the time
of the cow raid at Virāṭanagara) since he
was responsible for the game of dice and for
winning Indraprastha 4. 45. 10, 21; (23)
Yudhiṣṭhira told Saṃjaya “Let Suyodhana
recognize my kingship at Indraprastha and
I shall be at peace with the Kauravas”
(शान्तिं गमिष्यामि यथा त्वम् आत्थ।इन्द्र-
प्रस्थे भवतु ममैव राज्यं सुयोधनो
यच्छतु भारताग्र्यः॥) 5. 26. 28; he
again asked Saṃjaya to tell Duryodhana:
“Hand over Śakrapura to me or get
ready for battle” (ददस्व वा शक्रपुरं
ममैव युध्यस्व वा भारतमुख्य
वीर॥) 5. 30. 47; Bhīṣma, after he fell on
the battlefield, also advised to hand over
half of the kingdom to the Pāṇḍavas and
let Yudhiṣṭhira rule at Indraprastha (रा-
ज्यस्यार्धं दीयतां पाण्डवानाम् इन्द्र-
प्रस्थं धर्मराजो ऽनुशास्तु) 6. 116; 48.
(24) Kṛṣṇa reminded Dhṛtarāṣṭra that he
himself and his sons had sent away Yudhi-
ṣṭhira to Indraprastha (इन्द्रप्रस्थं त्व-
यैवासौ सपुत्रेण विवासितः), where he
(Yudhiṣṭhira) brought under control other
kings and made them subservient to Dhṛta-
rāṣṭra 5. 93. 55-56 (reference to 1. 199.
24-25; 1. 214. 1); (25) After the Pāṇḍa-
vas won the war, Kṛṣṇa and Arjuna rejoic-
ed at Indraprastha 14. 15. 5; (26) Arjuna
told Vasudeva that he would take with
him women folk, as also the young and
the old, of the Vṛṣṇis, to Indraprastha
16. 8. 5; He told the Brāhmaṇas and
the merchants of Dvārakā (नैगमाः),
who had gathered around him, that he
would take with him the Vṛṣṇis and the
Andhakas to Śakraprastha since Dvārakā
would be merged in the ocean (शक्र-
प्रस्थम् अहं नेष्ये वृष्ण्यन्धकजनं
स्वयम्।इदं तु नगरं सर्वं समुद्रः
प्लावयिष्यति) 16. 8. 10; he also told them
that Vajra would be their king at Śakra-
prastha (वज्रो ऽयं भवतां राजा शक्र-
प्रस्थे भवीष्यति) 16. 8. 11; Arjuna reha-
bilitated the old, the young and the women
of the Vṛṣṇis and the Andhakas at Śakra-
prastha (शक्रप्रस्थे न्यवेशयत्) 16. 8.
68; Arjuna gave the kingdom of Indra-
prastha to Vajra 16. 8. 70; (27) Yudhi-
ṣṭhira told Subhadrā, when he decided to
abandon the kingdom, that Parikṣit would
be the king of Hāstinapura and Vajra, the
Yādava, of Śakraprastha (परिक्षिद् धास्तिन-
पुरे शक्रप्रस्थे तु यादवः।वज्रो राजा)
17. 1. 9.
E. Similes: (1) Khāṇḍavaprastha
compared with Bhogavatī, the city of the
Nāgas (सुशुभे तत् पुरश्रेष्ठं नागैर्
भोगवती यथा) 1. 1. 9. 30; 1. 199. 49; (2)
Compared with heaven (तत् त्रिविष्टपसं-
काशं इन्द्रप्रस्थं व्यरोचत) 1. 199. 35;
(देवपुरप्रकाशम्) 3. 24. 11. [See Uda-
yendu]

उत्तङ्काश्रम
Uttaṅkāśrama m.: Name of the hermi-
tage of the great seer Uttaṅka.
Situated near the delightful sandy
desert, the sea full of sand, called Ujjānaka
(महर्षिर् विश्रुतस् तात उत्तङ्क ईति भारत।
मरुधन्वसु रम्येषु आश्रमस् तस्य
कौरव॥) 3. 192. 8; (ममाश्रमसमीपे
वै समेषु मरुधन्वसु) 3. 193. 14;
(समुद्रो वालुकापूऋण उज्जानक इति स्मृतः)
3. 195. 7; the demon Dhundhu lived under-
ground, concealed by sand, and oppressed
from there the hermitage of Uttaṅka by
breathing out flames of fire (स दुष्टात्मा …
बाधते स्म परं शक्त्या तम् उत्तङ्का-
श्रमं प्रभो। … धुन्धुर् भीमपराक्र-
मः॥शेते … उत्तङ्कस्याश्रमाभ्याशे निः-
श्वसन् पावकार्चिषः॥) 3. 195. 7-9; 3. 193.
14-17.

उत्तरज्योतिक
Uttarajyotika nt.: Name of a town (?)
Nakula in his expedition to the west
before the Rājasūya brought Uttarajyotika,
along with the town Vṛndāṭaka, under his
control (उत्तरज्योतिकं चैव तथा वृन्दा-
टकम् पुरम्। … वशे चक्रे) 2. 29. 10.

उदयेन्दु
Udayendu nt.: Name of a city.
A city of the Kurus (Pāṇḍavas); Suta-
soma, son of Bhīma from Draupadī, was
born there while there arose the sound of the
pounding of Soma plants (?); hence called
Sutasoma (पुरे कुरूणाम् उदयेन्दुनाम्नि।
तस्मिञ् जातः सोमसंक्रन्दमध्ये यस्मात्
तस्मात् सुतसोमो ऽभवत् सः॥) 7. 22. 22
(Nī. on Bom. Ed. 7. 23. 29 identifies Uda-
yendu with Śakraprastha: तस्मिन् उदयेदु-
नाम्नि उदयेन्दुपर्याये पुरे शक्रप्रस्थ
एव।सोमसंक्रन्दः सोमाभिषवणं
तस्य मध्ये तम् अधिकृत्य तत्फेनेनेत्य्
अर्थः।). [See Indraprastha]

उपप्लव्य
Upaplavya nt.: Name of the town near
the capital of Virāṭa; called नगर 4. 67.
38; ग्राम 5. 22. 1.
Epic events: (1) At the end of the
thirteenth year, the Pāṇḍavas gathered to-
gether at Upaplavya of Virāṭa and settled
down there (ततस् त्रयोदशे वर्षे निवृत्ते
पञ्च पाण्डवाः।उपप्लव्ये विराटस्य सम-
पद्यन्त सर्वशः॥) 4. 67. 14; (उपप्लव्ये
निविष्टः … युधिष्ठिरः) 5. 142. 4; (2)
While living there, Arjuna brought to Upa-
plavya, Janārdana, Abhimanyu and the
Dāśārhas from the Ānarta country; many
other kings also assembled there; Abhi-
manyu's marriage with Uttarā took place at
Upaplavya 4. 67. 15-19, 25, 34; the city at
that time shone as in a great festival and
became full of people who were delighted
and well nourished (तन् महोत्सवसंकाशं
हृष्टपुष्तजनावृतम्।नगरं मत्स्यरा-
जस्य शुशुभे भरतर्षभ॥) 4. 67. 38;
(3) When the Pāṇḍavas were settled in
Upaplavya (उपप्लव्ये निविष्टेषु पाण्डवेषु),
Duryodhana from Hāstinapura and Arjuna
from Upaplavya went independently to see
Vāsudeva to seek his help in the battle
as they wished to win victory 1. 2. 136 (this
is mentioned in the contents of the Udyoga-
parvan which is a reference to 5. 7. 2-20);
(4) After Duryodhana succeeded in trick-
ing Śalya and in extracting a promise from
him to fight from his side, the latter went to
Upaplavya to report to the Pāṇḍavas what
had happened 5. 8. 15; (5) When Dhṛta-
rāṣṭra was informed that the Pāṇḍavas had
resorted to Upaplavya, he sent Saṃjaya
to greet them and to seek peace with them
(प्राप्तान् आहुः संजय पाण्डुपुत्रान् उप-
प्लव्ये) 5. 22. 1; 5. 22. 36; Saṃjaya, ac-
cordingly, went to Upaplavya to meet the
Pāṇḍavas (उपप्लव्यं ययौ द्रष्टुम्) 5.
23. 1; (6) Janārdana went from Upaplavya
to Hāstinapura to negotiate peace with
the Kauravas: on way he had encamped
at Vṛkasthala (उपप्लव्याद् इह … उपयातो
जनार्दनः।वृकस्थले निवसति) 5. 84. 1;
(उपप्लव्याच् छान्तिम् इच्छञ् जनार्दनः।
आगतः) 7. 61. 21; on Kṛṣṇa's way from
Upaplavya to Hāstinapura people gathered
in different towns to see him 5. 82. 18;
Kṛṣṇa, without achieving his purpose,
returned to Upaplavya when the sun
arose (उच्चैःसूर्यम्) and reported to the
Pāṇḍavas what happened at Hāstinapura
5. 135. 30; 5. 145. 1; (यदैवाकृतकार्यस्
त्वम् उपप्लव्यं गतः पुनः) 11. 25. 31;
(स गत्वा हास्तिनपुरं धृतराष्ट्रम् सम्-
एत्य च … ।अनवाप्य शमं तत्र कृष्णः … ।
आगच्छत महाबाहुर् उपप्लव्यम् … ॥) 9.
34. 5-7; (7) When Kṛṣṇa arrived at Upa-
plavya, Yudhiṣṭhira offered him मधुपर्क
and requested him to protect Arjuna in the
battle (उपयातम् उपप्लव्यम् … एष भ्राता
सखा चैव तव कृष्ण धनंजयः।
रक्षितव्यो महाबाहो सर्वास्व् आपत्स्व् इति
प्रभो॥) 9. 61. 23-24 (No such specific
request is reported earlier in the Udyoga-
parvan; a general request by Yudhiṣṭhira to
protect all the Pāṇḍavas is, however, repor-
ted at 5. 70. 4); (8) While at Upaplavya,
Kṛṣṇa Dvaipāyana had assured Yudhi-
ṣṭhira that victory would be on that side
which was helped by Kṛṣṇa (यतः कृष्णस्
ततो जयः) 9. 61. 30; (such a statement
by Vyāsa is not found earlier in the Ud-
yogaparvan; however, such statement was
made by Saṃjaya to Dhṛtaraṣṭra in Hāstina-
pura 5. 66. 9 and by Nārada to Arjuna
6. 21. 12, 14; what Vyāsa told Dhṛtarāṣṭra
was यतो धर्मस् ततो जयः 6. 2. 14;
(9) Kṛṣṇa, along with the Pāṇḍavas, left
Upaplavya for Kurukṣetra 9. 34. 14; when
the Pāṇḍavas with their army started for the
battlefield, Draupadī returned to Upapla-
vya; before leaving, the Pāṇḍavas made
arrangements for the defence of their base at
Upaplavya by erecting forts and stationing
troops all around (उपप्लव्ये तु पाञ्चाली
 … निववृते) 5. 149. 55; (कृत्वा मूलप्रती-
कारान् गुल्मैः स्थावरजङ्गमैः) 5. 149.
56 (Nī. on Bom. Ed. 5. 151. 61: मूलप्रती-
कारं धनदाररक्षां गुल्मैः स्थावरैः
प्राकाररूपैः जङ्गमैः परितः स्थाने
स्थाने शूरसङ्घैः); (10) Balarāma did
not agree to Kṛṣṇa's request to him to
help the Pāṇḍavas in the battle and left
from Upaplavya for a pilgrimage 9. 34. 10-
12; (11) During the battle Kṛṣṇa, at one
stage, in order to encourage Yudhiṣṭhira
reminded him that Arjuna had taken the
vow at Upaplavya to bring about the down-
fall of Bhīṣma (प्रतिज्ञातम् उपप्लव्ये यत्
तत् पार्थेन … घातयिष्यामि गाङ्गेयम्) 6.
103. 35 (a reference to 5. 160. 8, 12, 13; 5,
162. 1); (12) At the end of the war Nakula
went to fetch Draupadī who was at Upa-
plavya; she was afflicted when she heard the
extremely sad news about the destruction of
all her sons (उपप्लव्यगता सा तु श्रुत्वा
सुमहद् अप्रियम्) 10. 11. 4-5; she taunt-
ingly said to Arjuna that while living with
her at Upaplavya he would happily forget
his sons who were slain rightfully (in battle)
(आत्मजांस् तेन धर्मेण श्रुत्वा शूरान्
निपातितान्।उपप्लव्ये मया सार्धं दिष्ट्या
त्वं न स्मरिष्यसि) 10. 11. 12; (13) A cer-
tain Brāhmaṇa, observing vows, after seeing
Uttarā at Upaplavya had foretold that when
the Kurus were destroyed (परिक्षीण) a
son would be born to her; the child thus
would have the nature परिक्षित् while he
was still in the womb (विराटस्य सुताम् … ।
उपप्लव्यगतां दृष्ट्वा व्रतवान् ब्राह्मणो
ऽब्रवीत्॥परिक्षिणेषु कुरुषु पुत्रस् तव
जनिष्यति।एतद् अस्य परिक्षित्त्वम् गर्भस्-
थस्य भविष्यति॥) 10. 16. 2-3.

उपमन्योर्
Upamanyor āśramaḥ m.: The आश्रम
of Upamanyu.
A. Location: The आश्रम of Upamanyu
Vaiyāghrapadya (son of Vyāghrapāda 13.
14. 75) on Himavant (तत्र … गिरिसत्तमे
आश्रअमम् … वैयाघ्रपद्यस्य उपमन्योः)
13. 14. 27-28.
B. Description: Best
(श्रेष्ठ) 13. 14. 43, (उत्तम) 13. 14. 27;
delightful to all beings (सर्वभूतमनो-
रम) 13. 14. 43; heavenly (दिव्य) 13. 14.
28; everything in the hermitage was end-
owed with heavenly aspect (सर्वम् एतन् …
दिव्यभावसमन्वितम्) 13. 14. 199; the like
of the आश्रम cannot even be imagined by
others (अचिन्त्यं मनसाप्य् अन्यैः) 13. 14.
36; covered by sacred splendour (ब्राह्म्या
लक्ष्म्या समन्वितम्) 13. 14. 28; the best
place for practising austerities (क्षेत्रं च
तपसां श्रेष्ठम्) 13. 14. 27; adorned by
great sages who were like fire (महर्षिभिर्
भूषितम् अग्निकल्पैः) 13. 14. 37; 13. 14. 198;
excellent Brāhmaṇas observing in the आश्र-
मस् different kinds of very difficult vows;
their vows are detailed in 13. 14. 38-40; very
learned Brāhmaṇas versed in the Vedas and
the Vedāṅgas took resort to it (सेविते द्विज-
शार्दूलैर् वेदवेदाङ्गपारगैः) 13. 14. 43;
resorted to by high-souled sages famous
for observing various restrictions (नानानिय-
मविख्यातैर् ऋषिभिश् च महात्मभिः) 13.
14. 44; adorned with large places of sacri-
ficial fire (विशालैश् चाग्निशरणैर् भूषितम्)
13. 14. 36; covered with कुश grass (कुश-
संवृतम्) 13. 14. 36; honoured by hosts
of high-souled gods, Śiva and others, the
surroundings of the hermitage shone at
all times like the orb of the sun in the
sky (सुपूजितं देवगणैर् महात्मभिः
शिवादिभिर् … रराज तच् चाश्रममण्डलं
सदा दिवीव राजन् रविमण्डलं यथा)
13. 14. 41; honoured by gods and Gan-
dharvas (पूजितं देवगन्धर्वैः) 13. 14.
28; Siddhas, Vidyādharas, Yakṣas and
Apsarases also present there 13. 14. 198;
adorned and always liked by the river
Gaṅgā (विभूषितं … सदा च जुष्टं नृप
जह्नुकन्यया) 13. 14. 37; adorned on all
sides by lakes (सरोभिः समलंकृतम्)
13. 14. 36; full of all kinds of forest trees
yielding flowers and fruits (वन्यैर् बहु-
विधैर् वृक्षैः फलपुष्पप्रदैर् युतम्)
13. 14. 31 (the trees like धव, ककुभ
कदम्ब etc. are listed in 13. 14. 29-30);
adorned by trees and fruits to be enjoyed
by birds (नानाशकुनीसंभोज्यैः फलैर्
वृक्षैर् अलंकृतम्) 13. 14. 32; having
attractive trees, always full of flowers and
fruits, covered with flowers of all seasons,
having glossy leaves and large branches
(पश्य वृक्षान् मनोरम्यान् सदा पुष्प-
फलान्वितान्।सर्वर्तुकुसुमैर् युक्तान् स्नि-
ग्धपत्रान् सुशाखिनः) 13. 14. 199; thick
with flowering thickets and creepers and
adorned with clusters of कदली trees (पुष्प-
गुल्मलताकीर्णं कदलीषण्दशोभितम्) 13.
14. 31; adorned with rows of trees placed
in their proper order (यथास्थानविनिक्षि-
प्तैर् भूषितं वनराजिभिः) 13. 14. 32; it
was full of different kinds of animals like
Ruru antelopes, elephants, lions, tigers,
leopards, peacocks, cats, serpents, buffaloes
and bears 13. 14. 33; one special feature
of the आश्रम was that due to the prowess
of the austerities (of its ascetics) ichneu-
mons played with serpents, and tigers with
deer, like friends (क्रीडन्ति सर्पैर् नकुला
मृगैर् व्याघ्राश् च मित्रवत्।प्रभावाद्
दीप्ततपसः) 13. 14. 42; wind, mixed with
the pollen of various flowers and carrying
with it the scent of the rut of the elephants
and thick with songs of heavenly women
blew there (नानापुष्परजोमिश्रो गजदाना-
धिवासितः।दिव्यस्त्रीगीतबहुलो मारुतो ऽत्र
सुखं ववौ॥) 13. 14. 34; one could also
hear other sounds as those of waterfalls,
of birds, of trumpetings, of elephants, of
songs of Kiṃnaras and of Sāman-singers 13.
14. 35.
C. Presence of Śiva: As a boon
Upamanyu asked Śiva to be always near
him in his आश्रम; that boon was granted
by Śiva (आश्रमे च सदा मह्यं सांनि-
ध्यं परम् अस्तु ते। … सांनिध्यम्
आश्रमे नित्यं करिष्यामि द्विजोत्तम) 13.
14. 189, 194.

उरशा
Uraśā f.: Name of a city.
Arjuna in his expedition to the north
defeated Rocamāna living at Uraśā in the
north-west (उरशावासिनं चैव रोचमानं
रणे ऽजयत्) 2. 24. 18.

उलूकाश्रम
Ulūkāśrama m.: Name of an आश्रम।
Established by the sage Ulūka; des-
cribed as auspicious (शुभ) 5. 187. 25; the
Kāśī princess Ambā, while practising aus-
terities for the death of Bhīṣma, visited
many holy places, one of them being Ulūkā-
śrama; she bathed at these holy places day
and night and practised austerities (तत्र
पुण्येषु देशेषु साप्लुताङ्गी दिवानिशम्।व्य-
वचरत् काशिकन्या सा … ॥ … ततोलूकाश्रमे
शुभे) 5. 187. 24-25; (एतेषु तीर्थेषु तदा
काशिकन्या … आप्लावयत गात्राणि तीव्रम्
आस्थाय वै तपः) 5. 187. 28.

ऋश्यशृङ्गस्य
Ṛśyaśṛṅgasya āśramaḥ m.: Name of
the hermitage of Ṛśyaśṛṅga.
Situated near the lake Mahāhrada;
described as holy (पुण्य) and beautifying
the lake (महाह्रदं शोभयन्) 3. 113.
25. [See Kāśyapāśrama]

एकचक्रा
Ekacakrā f.: Name of a town.
A. Description: Delightful (रम्य)
1. 156. 3; (रमणीय) 1. 144. 11; whole-
some (निरामय) 1. 144. 11; many pleas-
ing forests and gardens around Ekacakrā
(यानीह रमणीयानि वनान्य् उपवनानि च)
1. 156. 4.
B. Epic events: (1) Vyāsa
advised the Pāṇḍavas to live in the town
Ekacakrā concealing their identity (वस-
तेह प्रतिच्छन्नाः); Vyāsa then went with
them to Ekacakrā and put Kunti and
her sons in the house of a Brāhmaṇa 1.
144. 12, 18; he asked them to live there
until he returned to the town (इह मां
संप्रतीक्षध्वम् आगमिष्याम्य् अहं पु-
नः) 1. 144. 19; (ममागमनकांक्षिणः)
1. 144. 11; (2) The Pāṇḍavas went to
Ekacakrā and lived for some time in the
house of a Brāhmaṇa (एकचक्रां गतास् ते
तु) 1. 145. 1-2; (3) When some people
heard about the death of Baka, they went
out of the town next morning and saw the
Rākṣasa dead on the ground; then they re-
turned to Ekacakrā and reported the news
to others 1. 152. 8-9; the people of the
entire country flocked to Ekacakrā (not
named) to see the most wonderful event
(ततो जानपदाः सर्वे आजग्मुर् नगरं
प्रति।तम् अद्भुतं द्रष्टुम्) 1. 152.
19; (4) The Pāṇḍavas continued to live
in Ekacakrā after the death of Baka (पा-
र्थास् तत्रैव चावसन्) 1. 152. 19; Kuntī
once told her sons that they had lived
too long in the house of the Brāhmaṇa in
Ekacakrā (not named) (चिररात्रोषिताः
स्मेह ब्राह्मणस्य निवेशने) 1. 156. 2; as
promised, Vyāsa arrived to meet the Pāṇḍa-
vas living in disguise at Ekacakrā; he
advised them to go to the Pāñcāla country
1. 157. 1, 16; (5) The Pāṇḍavas took leave
of the Brāhmaṇa and left Ekacakrā for
the town of Drupada in the Pāñcāla coun-
try (ततो आमन्त्र्य तं विप्रम् … प्रतस्थे
नगरिम् रम्याम् द्रुपदस्य महात्मनः)
1. 156. 6-11; (7) On way to the Pāñcāla
country Yudhiṣṭhira told the Brāhmaṇas
that they had come from Ekacakrā (आगतान्
एकचक्रायाः) 1. 175. 4; (7) The event
of the Pāṇḍavas' stay, along with Kuntī,
in the house of a Brāhmaṇa in Ekacakrā,
the killing of Baka, and their proceeding
to the Pāñcāla country, is referred to by
different persons on different occasions:
(a) By Vaiśaṃpāyana in his summary of
the epic events told to king Janamejaya
(ते वीरा एकचक्रां व्रजंस् तदा। … बकं
हत्वा महाबलम्। … जग्मुः पाञ्चालानां
पुरं ततः) 1. 55. 20-21; 1. 90. 79-80;
(b) By Draupadī to Kṛṣṇa while recount-
ing past events in the life of the Pāṇḍavas
(ततश् च प्राद्रवन् सर्वे … एकचक्राम्
अभिमुखाः) 3. 13. 98-99; (c) By Kṛṣṇa
while addressing Duryodhana (ऊषुश् च
सुचिरं कालं प्रच्छन्नाः पाण्डवास् तदा।
 … एकचक्रायाम्) 5. 126. 14.

कक्षसेनस्य
Kakṣasenasya āśramaḥ m.: Name of
an आश्रम established by Kakṣasena.
Listed among the holy places in the
west 3. 87. 1; on the mountain Asita (असितो
नाम पर्वतः।आश्रमः कक्षसेनस्य …
तत्र) 3. 87. 9-10; described as holy
(पुण्य) 3. 87. 10; men obtain perfection
there by practising austerities even for a
short period (तत्राल्पेनैव सिध्यन्ति मा-
नवास् तपसा विभो) 3. 87. 10.

कण्वाश्रम
Kaṇvāśrama1 m.: Name of an आश्रम
where Kaṇva (Kāśyapa) lived (काश्यप-
स्यायतनम् 1. 64. 42.
A. Location: Along the river Mālinī
(मालिनीम् अभितो … नदीम्) 1. 64. 18; (अलं-
कृतं मालिन्या) 1. 64. 24.
B. Descrip-
tion: Isolated (विविक्त) 1. 64. 42; holy
(शिव) 1. 64. 42; auspicious (शुभ) 1.
64. 41; excellent आश्रम (आश्रमप्रवर)
1. 64. 15, 41; best (उत्तम) 1. 64. 29;
pleasing (रम्य) 1. 64. 15; attractive, very
attractive (मनोरम) 1. 64. 15; (सुमनो-
हर) 1. 64. 19; (अत्यर्थमनोहर) 1. 64.
42; protected by the austerities of Kāśyapa
(काश्यपतपोगुप्त) 1. 64. 41; full of asce-
tics who observed rigid vows (महाव्रतैर्
वृतं समन्ताद् ऋषिभिस् तपोधनैः) 1. 64.
42; (तपोधनगणैर् युतम्) 1. 64. 41;
resembling the world of gods (देवलोक-
प्रतीकाश) 1. 64. 19; resembling the world
of Brahman (ब्रह्मलोकप्रतीकाश) 1. 64.
30; (ब्रह्मलोक इव) 1. 64. 34, 40; for
other details regarding trees, birds, animals,
and ascetics engaged in their ritual practices
and Vedic recitations see 1. 64. 16-18; 30-
39; 41-42.
C. Past events: (1) Duḥ-
ṣanta did not find Kāśyapa in the आश्रम
when he visited it since the sage had gone
to collect fruits (नापश्यद् आश्रमे तस्मिन्
ऋषिम्) 1. 65. 1-2; (फलाहारो गतो राजन्
पिता मे इत आश्रमात्) 1. 67. 5; Kāśyapa's
daughter (Śakuntalā) came out of the
आश्रम to receive the king and offered him
guest worship (कन्या … निश्चक्रामाश्रमात्
तस्मात्) 1. 65. 3-6; later Śakuntalā reminded
the king about their meeting in the आश्रम
of her father (अहम् आसादिता राजन् कुमारी
पितुर् आश्रमे) 1. 68. 66; Duḥṣanta, while he
was in the आश्रम, asked the girl who she
was (कासि कस्यासि सुश्रोणि … एवम् उक्ता तदा
कन्या तेन राज्ञा तदाश्रमे) 1. 65. 12-14;
Kaṇva returned to his आश्रम from the
forest (कण्वो ऽप्याश्रमम् आगमत्) 1. 67.
23; when Śakuntalā's son was six years
old he bound tigers, lions, boars, elephants
and buffaloes to trees all around in the
surroundings of the आश्रम; he mounted
them, tamed them and ran hither and
thither playing with them in the precincts
of the आश्रम (षड्वर्ष एव बालः स
कण्वाश्रमपदं प्रति।व्याघ्रान् सिंहान्
वराहांश् च गजांश् च महिषांस् तथा॥
बद्ध्वा वृक्षेषु बलवान् आश्रमस्य समन्-
ततः।आरोहन् दमयंश् चैव क्रीडंश् च
परिधावति॥) 1. 68. 5-6; the residents of
the Kaṇvāśrama (कण्वाश्रमनिवासिनः)
named the child Sarvadamana since he
tamed all (अस्त्व् अयं सर्वदमनः सर्-
वं हि दमयत्य् अयम्) 1. 68. 7; Kaṇva
asked his pupils to take Śakuntalā and her
son from the आश्रम to her husband's place
(इतो ”श्रमात्।भर्त्रे प्रापयत) 1. 68.
10; when disowned by the king, Śakuntalā
decided to return to the आश्रम (गमि-
ष्याम्य् अहम् आश्रमम्) 1. 68. 71. [See
Kāśyapāśrama]

कण्वाश्रम
Kaṇvāśrama2 m.: Name of an आश्रम
established by Kaṇva.
A. Location: On the west coast (?)
(mentioned after Jambūmārga and Agastya-
saras and before one reached Narmadā) 3.
80. 60, 63, 71.
B. Description: Adorn-
ed with glory (श्रीजुष्ट) and honoured by
people (लोकपूजित) 3. 80. 64.
C. Holi-
ness: Called an excellent holy forest for
observing religious practices (धर्मारण्-
यं हि तत् पुण्यम् आद्यं च) 3. 80. 65;
by just entering it one was freed of all sins
(यत्र प्रविष्टमात्रो वै पापेभ्यो विप्र-
मुच्यते) 3. 80. 65; by satisfying manes
and gods there, one who is controlled and
takes limited food gets the fruit of a sacri-
fice performing which all desires are ful-
filled (अर्चयित्वा पितॄन् देवान् नियतो नियता-
शनः।सर्वकामसमृद्धस्य यज्ञस्य
फलम् अश्नुते) 3. 80. 66.

कण्वाश्रम
Kaṇvāśrama3 m.: Name of an आश्रम
of Kaṇva.
Listed among the holy places of the
south 3. 86. 1; near the river Praveṇī (?)
(प्रवेण्युत्तरपार्श्वे तु पुण्ये कण्वाश्रमे
तथा) 3. 86. 8; described as holy (पुण्य)
3. 86. 8; Dhaumya told Yudhiṣṭhira that
he had heard that there were many forests
of ascetics near the आश्रम (तापसानाम्
अरण्यानि कीर्तितानि यथाश्रुति) 3. 86. 8.

कन्यकुब्ज
Kanyakubja nt.: Name of a city.
A. Location: Near Gaṅgā, where on
its bank there is a तीर्थ known to men
as Aśvatīrtha (अदूरे कन्यकुब्जस्य गङ्गा-
याष् तीरम् उत्तमम्।अश्वतीर्थं तद् अद्यापि
मानवाः परिचक्षते) 13. 4. 17; 3. 115. 17.
B. Past events: (1) There was once a
king called Gādhi(n) who ruled at Kanya-
kubja (कन्यकुब्जे महान् आसीत् पार्थिवो
भरतर्षभ।गाधीति विश्रुतो लोके) 1.
165. 3; 3. 115. 9; formerly at Kanyukubja
Ṛcīka Bhārgava, chose Satyavatī, daughter
of Gādhi, for his wife (पुरा हि कन्यकुब्जे
वै गाधेः सत्यवतीं सुताम्।भार्यार्थे
ऽवरयत् कन्याम् ऋचीकः) 5. 117. 4; at
Kanyakubja, near the river Gaṅgā, Gādhi
gave his daughter Satyavatī to Ṛcīka, son
of Bhṛgu; in this marriage gods acted as
companions of the bridegroom (गङ्गायां
कन्यकुब्जे वै ददौ सत्यवतीं तदा।
ततो गाधिः सुतां तस्मै जन्याश् चासन्
सुरास् तदा) 3. 115. 17; (2) Jāmadagnya
sang in an अनुवंश stanza that Kau-
śika (Viśvāmitra) drank Soma with Indra
at Kanyakubja (यत्रानुवंशं भगवाञ्
जामदग्न्यस् तदा जगौ। … कन्यकुब्जे ऽपि-
बत् सोमम् इन्द्रेण सह कौशिकः) 3. 85.
11-12.

कन्याश्रम
Kanyāśrama1 m.: Name of an आश्रम।
One reaches Kanyāśrama from Soma-
tīrtha and Dadhīcatīrtha 3. 81. 162-163,
165; one should visit it with a controlled
mind and observe chastity; intent on
fasting, if he fasts there for three nights
he gets a hundred heavenly maidens and
goes to the world of Brahman (ततः कन्-
याश्रमं गच्छेन् नियतो ब्रह्मचर्यवान्।
त्रिरात्रोपोषितो राजन्न् उपवासपरायणः।
लभेत् कन्याशतं दिव्यं ब्रह्मलोकं च
गच्छति॥) 3. 81. 165.

कन्याश्रम
Kanyāśrama2 m.: Name of an आश्रम।
A. Location: Situated near Devahrada
on the confluence of Kṛṣṇā and Veṇṇā
3. 83. 34.
B. Holiness: By living there
for three nights and by bathing there one
gets the fruit of an Aśvamedha (त्रिरात्रम्
उषितः स्नात्वा अश्वमेधफलं लभेत् …
तथा कन्याश्रमे नृप) 3. 83. 33-34; just
by visiting the place (गमनाद् एव) one
gets the fruit of performing a hundred Agni-
ṣṭoma sacrifices 3. 83. 35.
C. Past event:
By offering there a hundred sacrifices the
king of gods (Indra) went to heaven
(कन्याश्रमे नृप।यत्र क्रतुशतैर् इष्ट्वा
देवराजो दिवं गतः) 3. 83. 34-35.

कपिलावट
Kapilāvaṭa m.: Name of a holy place.
A pilgrim should visit Kapilāvaṭa; by
staying there for a night he gets the fruit
of gifting a thousand cows (कपिलावटं
च गच्छेत तीर्थसेवी नराधिप।उष्यैकां
रजनीं तत्र गोसहस्रफलं लभेत्॥)
3. 82. 27.

करहाटक
Karahāṭaka nt.: Name of a city (?
country ?).
Sahadeva, in his expedition to the south
before the Rājasūya, subjugated Karahā-
ṭaka just by sending messengers and he
made the people pay tribute (करहाटकं
दूतैर् एव वशे चक्रे करं चैनान् अदा-
पयत्) 2. 28. 47.

कवाट
Kavāṭa nt.: Name of a city.
Kṛṣṇa killed the Pāṇḍya king at Ka-
vāṭa (अयं कवाटे निजघान पाण्ड्यम्)
5. 47. 70.

कान्तिपुर
Kāntipura nt.: Name of a city.
It was near this city that the earth
received the child conceived by the six
Kṛttikās and which (after delivery) was
united into one (ततस् तं षडधिष्ठानं
गर्भम् एकत्वम् आगतम्।पृथिवी प्रति-
जग्राह कान्तीपुरसमीपतः॥) 13. 86. 11.

काम्पिल्य
Kāmpilya nt.: Name of a city; also
referred to as Drupadasya nagarī or pura
1. 156. 11; 3. 13. 101.
A. Location: Capital of Mākandī
(southern Pāñcāla country) on the south
bank of Gaṅgā (राजासि दक्षिणे कूले भागी-
रथ्या(ः) 1. 128. 12; (माकन्दीम् अथ गङ्-
गायास् तीरे … ।दक्षिणांश् चैव पाञ्चालान्)
1. 128. 15.
B. Description: Excellent
town (पुरोत्तम) 1. 128. 15.
C. Epic
events: (1) When Droṇa gave half of the
Pāñcāla country to Drupada, the latter
went to Kāmpilya and settled down there
(सो ऽध्यावसद् … काम्पिल्यम्) 1. 128. 15;
hence referred to as द्रुपदस्य नगरी 1.
56. 11; द्रुपदस्य पुर 3. 13. 101; (2)
Kuntī and the Pāṇḍavas took leave of the
Brāhmaṇa at Ekacakrā and went to the
town of Drupada 1. 156. 11; 3. 13. 101;
(3) Śikhaṇḍin, after his marriage with the
daughter of the king of Daśārṇas, re-
turned to Kāmpilya 5. 190. 13; the king of
Daśārṇas arrived at Kāmpilya to find out
whether Śikhaṇḍin was a man or a woman
and sent his messenger to Drupada 5. 193.
13.
D. Past event: When Brahmadatta
ruled at Kāmpilya there lived with him
for a long time a female bird, Pūjanī by
name, in his inner apartment (अन्तःपुर-
निवासिनी) 12. 137. 5. [See Pāñcālanagara]

कालिकाश्रम
Kālikāśrama m.: Name of an आश्रम।
On the bank of the river Vipāśā;
by reaching Kālikāśrama and by bathing
in Vipāśā, one who observes chastity and
one who has mastered his wrath is freed
of rebirth after three nights (काइइकाश्र-
मम् आसाद्य विपाशायां कृतोदकः।ब्र-
ह्मचारी जितक्रोधस् त्रिरात्रान् मुच्यते
भवात्॥) 13. 26. 22.

काशिनगरी
Kāśinagarī, Kāśipurī f.: See Vārāṇasī.

कश्यपाश्रम
Kaśyapāśrama m. An आश्रम where
Kāśyapa and his son Ṛṣyaśṛṅga lived.
A. Location: Near the river Kauśikī
and near Viśvāmitrāśrama; the Pāṇḍavas,
with Lomaśa, were to reach it from the river
Nandā (ततो नन्दाप्लुताङ्गस् त्वं कौशि-
कीम् अभियास्यसि। … ततस् तत्र समाप्लुत्य
गात्राणि सगणो नृपः।जगाम कौशिकीम्)
3. 109. 19-20; (एषा देवनदी पुण्या कौशिकि
 … विश्वामित्राश्रमः … अत्र प्रकाशते।
आश्रमश् चैव … काश्यपस्य) 3. 110. 1-2.
B. Description: Holy (पुण्य) 3. 113. 25;
known to be holy (प्न्ण्याख्य) 3. 110.
2; Sarja, Aśoka and Tilaka trees, in full
blossom, in its precincts (सर्जान् अशोकांस्
तिलकांश् च वृक्षान् प्रपुष्पितान् अवनाम्याव-
भज्य) 3. 111. 16; beautifies the great lake
near it (महाह्रदं शोभयन्) 3. 113.
25.
C. Holiness: By bathing there one
becomes pure and has done all his duties
(अत्र स्नातः कृतकृत्यो विशुद्धः) 3. 113. 25.
D. Epic event: Lomaśa asked Yudhiṣṭhira
to bathe in the lake near the आश्रम and then
proceed to other तीर्थस् 3. 113. 25.
E. Past
event (related to the Rāmāyaṇa): Ṛśya-
śṛṅga, son of Kāśyapa by a female deer, born
here 3. 110. 2, 4; the old courtesan who,
with her daughter, went to seduce Ṛśyaśṛṅga
tied her boat not far from the Kāśyapā-
śrama (अदूरे काश्यपाश्रमात्) 3. 111. 4;
her daughter reached the आश्रम (आश्रमं
समासाद्य) and saw there the son of
Kāśyapa 3. 111. 6: Kāśyapa returned to his
आश्रम after collecting fruits and roots from
the forest (अथोपायात् … स्वम् आश्रमं फल-
मूलानि गृह्य) 3. 113. 14; after Ṛśyaśṛṅga's
wife Śāntā gave birth to a child, he, having
done all what the king desired, was expected
to return with his wife to the forest and
the place of his father (i. e. to the आश्रम)
(जाते पुत्रे वनम् एवाव्रजेथाः … ययौ
च यत्रास्य पिता बभूव) 3. 113. 21-22.
[See Ṛśyaśṛṅgasya āśramaḥ]

किङ्किणीकाश्रम
Kiṅkiṇīkāśrama m.: Name of an
आश्रम।
One who bathes at this आश्रम can
move at will and is glorified in the heavenly
abode of the Apsarases (निवासे ऽप्सरसां
दिव्ये कामचारी महीयते) 13. 26. 21.

किष्किन्धा
Kiṣkindhā f.: Name of the city where
first Vālin, and next Sugrīva ruled.
Rāmāyaṇa events: (1) After Rāma
and Sugrīva entered into a covenant they
all proceeded to Kiṣkindhā (अभ्येत्य सर्वे
किष्किन्धाम्) looking forward to the fight
between Vālin and Sugrīva; Sugrīva having
reached the city (सुग्रीवः प्राप्य किष्किन्-
धाम्) roared (challenging Vālin for a
duel) 3. 264. 15-16; (2) Rāma asked
Lakṣmaṇa to go to Kiṣkindhā and find
out what Sugrīva's plans were (regarding
the search of Sītā); Rāma doubted Sugrī-
va's sincerity about carrying out the terms
of the covenant after the death of Vālin
by Rāma in the forest bordering on
Kiṣkindhā (किष्किन्धोपवने); Lakṣmaṇa
started for Kiṣkindhā and having rea-
ched its gate (किष्किन्धाद्वारम् आसाद्य)
enterd the city without any opposition 3.
266. 5, 7, 12; (3) After honouring the
monkey chiefs, the Gopucchas and the bears
and after allowing them to leave, Rāma,
along with Sugrīva, reached Kiṣkindhā
(किष्किन्धां पुनर् आगमत्); at Kiṣkindhā
(किष्किन्धाम् तु समासाद्य) Rāma conse-
crated Aṅgada as crown prince 3. 275. 55, 57.

कुण्डिन
Kuṇḍina nt.: Name of a city.
A. Epic event: Rukmin, after he suffer-
ed the defeat at the hands of Kṛṣṇa, did
not return to Kuṇḍina but established
another town Bhojakaṭa 5. 155. 14-15.
B. Past events (from Nala story): Dama-
yantī sent away her two sons with Nala's
charioteer to her kinsmen at Kuṇḍina
3. 57. 17; When Damayantī announced
her second स्वयंवर, Ṛtuparṇa reached
Vidarbha and entered Kuṇḍina after his
arrival was reported to king Bhīma 3. 71. 2;
After Nala's meeting with Damayantī and
after the departure of Ṛtuparṇa, he did
not stay very long in the city of Kuṇḍina 3.
76. 19.

कुम्भकर्णाश्रम
Kumbhakarṇāśrama m.: Name of an
आश्रम।
Near Urvaśītīrtha and Somāśrama; by
bathing there one is honoured in the world
(पूज्यते भुवि मानवः) 3. 82. 136.

कुरुक्षेत्राश्रम
Kurukṣetrāśrama m.: See Dhṛtarāṣṭra-
sya āśramaḥ1.

कुशवति
Kuśavati f.: Name of a town.
When gods once held counsel at Kuśa-
vatī it was attended by Kubera with his
Yakṣas in very large numbers (देवतानाम्
अभून् मन्त्रः कुशवत्याम् नरेश्वर।
वृतस् तत्राहम् अगमं महापद्मशतैस्
त्रिभिः।यक्षाणाम्) 3. 158. 51 (Nī. on
Bom. Ed. 3. 161. 54: कुशवत्यां कुश-
स्थली संज्ञे देशविशेषे).

कुशस्थल
Kuśasthala nt.: Name of a village
(ग्राम).
One of the five villages (ग्रामाः) for
which Yudhiṣṭhira was willing to come to
terms with the Kauravas; he named four
of these five villages and left the fifth to
be named by Duryodhana 5. 31. 19-20;
5. 70. 15; 5. 80. 7 (for the names of the
other three villages see Āsandī).

कुशस्थली
Kuśasthalī f.: See Dvārakā.

कृत्तिकानाम्
Kṛttikānām āśramaḥ m.: Name of an
आश्रम।
By bathing there, by offering libations
to manes and by satisfying god Mahādeva
one becomes clean and goes to heaven
(आश्रमे कृत्तिकानां तु स्नात्वा यस् तर्प-
येत् पितॄन्।तोषयित्वा महादेवं निर्मलः
स्वर्गम् आप्नुयात्॥) 13. 26. 23.

कोशला
Kośalā f.: Name of a city (or river ?)
Two तीर्थस् Ṛṣabhatīrtha and Kāla-
tīrtha located near Kośalā 3. 83. 10-11.

कोसला
Kosalā f.: See Ayodhyā.

कौशिकस्य
Kauśikasya āśramaḥ m.: A hermitage
founded by Kauśika (Viśvāmitra).
(1) Epic event: One of the आश्रमस्
visited by Ambā for bathing and for practi-
sing austerities in order to be able to kill
Bhīṣma (कौशिकस्याश्रमे तथा … एतेषु
तीर्थेषु तदा काशिकन्या … आप्लावयत गा-
त्राणि तीव्रम् आस्थाय वै तपः) 5. 187. 26,
28. (2) Past event: When Indra asked
Menakā to cause disturbance to the austeri-
ties of Viśvāmitra (1. 65. 25), she went to
the आश्रम of Kauśika; she saw Viśvāmitra
practising तपस् in his आश्रम (ययौ साश्र-
मं कौशिकस्य) 1. 65. 42; 1. 66. 2.

खाण्डवप्रस्थ
Khāṇḍavaprastha nt.: See Indra-
prastha.

गजपुर
Gajapura, Gajasāhvaya, Gajāhvaya,
nt.: See Hāstinapura.

गिरिव्रज
Girivraja m.: Name of a city, also
referred to as Bārhadrathapura (2. 22. 42).
A. Location: The Capital of the
Magadha country (मागधं पुरम्)
2. 18. 30; 2. 19. 2, 19; निवेशो मागधः
2. 19. 1 (Nī. on Bom. Ed. 2. 21. 1:
मागधः मगधदेशसंबन्धी निवेशः
विन्यासः).
B. Description: Large (म-
हन्त्) 2. 19. 1; shining (शुभ) 2. 19. 1;
charming (स्वादु) 2. 19. 1; free from
diseases (निरामय) 2. 19. 1; unassailable
(अनाधृष्य) 2. 19. 13; full of cattle (पशु-
मन्त्) 2. 19. 1; no dearth of water there
(नित्यम् अम्बुमान्) 2. 19. 1; full of good
dwellings (सुवेश्माढ्य) 2. 19. 1; thronged
by people of the four classes (चातुर्वर्ण्य-
जनाकुल) 2. 19. 13; full of people who
were satisfied and well nourished (तुष्ट-
पुष्टजनाकुल) 2. 19. 13; marked by lavish
festivals (स्फीतोत्सव) 2. 19. 13; the splen-
dour of its markets of eatables and garlands
was excellent (भक्ष्यमाल्यापणानां …
श्रियम् उत्तमाम्) 2. 19. 22; the prosperity,
marked by all qualities and full of all
desired objects, was thriving on its streets
(स्फीतां सर्वगुणोपेतां सर्वकाम-
समृद्धिनीम्॥ … समृद्धिम् … वीथ्यां
तस्याम्) 2. 19. 22-23; delightful forests
of Priyāla trees, shining forests of Lodhra
trees stood near the dwelling of Gau-
tama in the city (see Past events) (वन-
राजीस् तु पश्येमाः प्रियालानाम् मनोरमाः।
लोध्राणां च शुभाः पार्थ गौतमौ-
कःसमीपजाः) 2. 19. 8; the city was mar-
ked by the dwelling of the snakes Arbuda,
Śakravāpin, Svastika and the best dwelling
of Maṇināga (अर्बुदः शक्रवापी च पन्-
नगौ शत्रुतापनौ।स्वस्तिकस्यालयश् चात्र
मणिनागस्य चोत्तमः) 2. 19. 9; five high-
peaked, bright and solid mountains Vai-
hāra, Varāha, Vṛṣabha, Ṛṣigiri, and Cai-
tyaka, closed on each other as if to protect
Girivraja on all sides (एते पञ्च महाशृङ्-
गाः पर्वताः शीतलद्रुमाः।रक्षन्तीवाभि-
संहत्य संहताङ्गा गिरिव्रजम्) 2. 19.
2-3; the tall mountain (Caityaka) was
honoured by the descendants of Bṛhadratha
and the people of Girivraja 2. 19. 14; in
the city were placed three भेरीस् which
were made out of the hide of Ṛṣabha killed
by Bṛhadratha; the भेरीस्, covered with
the powders of heavenly flowers, produced
sounds (तं हत्वा माषनालाश् (?) च तिस्रो
भेरीर् अकारयत्॥आनह्य चर्मणा तेन
स्थापयाम् आस स्वे पुरे।यत्र ताः प्राण-
दन् भेर्यो दिव्यपुष्पावचूर्णिताः) 2. 19. 15-
16.
C. Epic events: (1) Jarāsandha held
captive kings, whom he had conquered, in
the cave of a mountain in Girivraja (गिरि-
व्रजे।कन्दरायां गिरीन्द्रस्य) 2. 13. 62;
(2) Kṛṣṇa, Bhīma and Arjuna saw the
मागध town (Girivraja) from the moun-
tain Goratha (गोरथं गिरिम् आसाद्य
ददृशुर् मागधं पुरम्) 2. 18. 30; when
they proceeded towards the मागध
town (प्रतस्थुर् मागधं पुरम्), they
did not enter it through the main gate
but rushed towards the summit of the lofty
mountain Caityaka (Nī., however, on Bom.
Ed. 2. 21. 15: चैत्यकं नगरसूचकम्)
and broke its old huge peak, honoured
(by the people) with garlands, as if thereby
striking on the head of Jarāsandha whom
they wanted to kill (ते ऽथ द्वारम् अना-
साद्य पुरस्य गिरिम् उच्छ्रितम्। … चैत्य-
कान्तं समाद्रवन्।शिरसीव जिघांसन्तो
जरासन्धजिघांसवः॥ … शृङ्गं सुम-
हान्तं पुरातनम्।अर्चितं माल्यदामैश् च
 … ते ऽभिहत्याभ्यपातयन्) 2. 19. 14, 17-
19; then they entered the मागध town
(Girivraja) 2. 19. 19; after killing Jarāsan-
dha, Kṛṣṇa, with Bhīma and Arjuna,
mounted the chariot of Jarāsandha and
went out of Girivraja; they alighted there
on even ground (समे देशे) where they
were honoured by the people of Girivraja
and by the kings released from their capti-
vity 2. 22. 13, 26, 28-30; Sahadeva, Jarā-
sandha's son, after he was consecrated by
Kṛṣṇa as king of the Magadha country, en-
tered again the town of Bṛhadratha (Giri-
vraja) (विवेश राजा … पुनर् बार्हद्रथं
पुरम्) 2. 22. 42; the release by Kṛṣṇa of
kings held captive in Girivraja mentioned
in the summary of the Sabhāparvan (गिरि-
व्रजे निरुद्धानां राज्ञां कृष्णेन मोक्ष-
णम्) 1. 2. 99; mighty Jarāsandha's death-
in Girivraja due to flash of Kṛṣṇa's intelli-
gence predicted by Nārāyaṇa to Nārada
(जरासन्धश् च बलवान् … गिरिव्रजे।मम
बुद्धिपरिस्पन्दाद् वधस् तस्य भविष्यति)
12. 326. 89; (3) Bhīma, in his expedition
to the east (2. 26. 1) before the Rājasūya,
marched on Girivraja and made Jarāsan-
dha's son pay tribute 2. 27. 15-16; (4)
while recounting Karṇa's exploits, Bhīṣma
referred to his overthrowing the kings,
Nagnajit and others, who came together at
Girivraja 7. 4. 5.
D. Past events: (1) Sage
Gautama begot Kākṣīva and other sons on
Śūdrā Auśīnarī (शूद्रायां गौतमो यत्र
 … औशीनर्याम् अजनयत् काक्षीवादीन् सुतान्
ऋषिः) 2. 19. 5; formerly kings of Aṅga,
Vaṅga and other countries used to delight
themselves reaching the abode of Gautama
(in Girivraja) 2. 19. 7; (2) Bṛhadratha
killed a bull who ate beans, and then made
out of his hide three माषनाल (?) drums
and installed them in his town (यत्र माषा-
दम् ऋषभम् आससाद बृहद्रथः।तं
हत्वा माषनालाश् च तिस्रो भेरीर् अकारयत्॥
आनह्य चर्मणा तेन स्थापयाम् आस स्वे
पुरे) 2. 19. 15-16; (3) The royal sage
Dhundhumāra, instead of enjoying the boon
given to him by gods, slept at Girivraja
(धुन्धुमारश् च राजर्षिः … प्रीतिदायं
परित्यज्य सुष्वाप स गिरिव्रजे) 13. 6. 39
(Nī. on Bom. Ed. 13. 6. 39: प्रीतिदायं
देवैर् दत्तं वरम्). [See Rājagṛha]

गोकुल
Gokula nt.: Name of a settlement.
A number of people following the
same trade (cowherds ?), skilled in warfare,
who were brought up in Gokula were done
to death by Arjuna when they attacked
him—this is what Saṃjaya reported to
Dhṛtarāṣṭra (गोकुले नित्यसंवृद्धा युद्धे
परमकोविदाः।श्रेणयो बहुसाहस्राः …
ते सर्वे पार्थम् आसाद्य गता वैवस्वत-
क्षयम्॥) 8. 4. 38.

गौतमस्य
Gautamasya āśramaḥ1 m.: An आश्रम
established by Gautama.
A. Location: Situated on the moun-
tain Pāriyātra (पारियात्रगिरीं प्राप्य गौ-
तमस्याश्रमो महान्) 12. 127. 3.
B. Des-
cription: Large (महन्त्) 12. 127. 3.
C.
Past event: (1) Gautama practised auste-
rities there for sixty thousand years (उवास
गौतमो यत्र कालं तद् अपि मे शृणु॥
षष्टिं वर्षसहराणि सो ऽतप्यद् गौतमस्
तपः) 12. 127. 3-4; (2) A dialogue took
place between Yama and Gautama at this
place (गौतमस्य च संवादं यमस्य
च) 12. 127. 2, 8-10.

गौतमस्य
Gautamasya āśramaḥ2 m.: An आश्रम
founded by Gautama.
After receiving the two कुण्डलस् from
Madayantī, the wife of Saudāsa, Uttaṅka
started for the आश्रम of Gautama to give
them to Ahalyā (जवेन महता प्रायाद्
गौतम्स्याश्रमं प्रति) 14. 57. 17; the
horse (really Jātavedas) asked Uttaṅka to
blow in his anus; when he hesitated, the
horse told him that he (Uttaṅka) had
formerly often done it in the आश्रम of
Gautama (मा जुगुप्सां कृथाः पुत्र त्वम्
अत्रार्थे कथंचन।त्वयैतद् धि समा-
चीर्णं गौतमस्याश्रमे तदा॥) 14. 57.
40; also referred to as गौतमस्य निवेश-
नम् 14. 57. 54, गुरुसद्मन् 14. 57. 53.

गौतमस्य
Gautamasya āśramaḥ3 m., āśramapadam
nt.: An आश्रम of Gautama Śaradvant.
Described as beautiful (रमणीय) 1.
120. 7; Devakanyā (Apsaras) Jālapadī,
sent by Indra, went to the आश्रम of
Gautama Śaradvant to cause obstacle in
his austerities (साभिगम्याश्रम्पदम् …
शरद्वतः।लोभयाम् आस गौतमम्)
1. 120. 6-7; Gautama left the आश्रम and
also the Apsaras after his semen, with-
out his knowledge, spilled on a cluster of
शर grass (स विहायाश्रमं तं च तां
चैवाप्सरसं मुनिः।जगाम) 1. 120. 12.

चण्डालिकाश्रम
Caṇḍālikāśrama: Name of an आश्रम।
Situated near the Kokāmukha तीर्थ;
one who visits this आश्रम and bathes in
the Kokāmukha tīrtha and if he subsists
on vegetables and wears bark garments
or rags he gets the reward of visiting the
Kumārī tīrtha ten times (शाकभक्षश् चीर-
वासाः कुमारीर् विन्दते दश) 13. 26. 49
(Nī. on Bom. Ed. 13. 25. 52: कुमारीः
कुमारीसंज्ञकतीर्थम्). [See Kumārī1,
Vol. 1, p. 312]

चम्पा
Campā f.: Name of a city, also called
Mālinī (12. 5. 7).
A. Location: In the Aṅgaviṣaya (here
called Mālinī) (प्रीत्या ददौ स कर्णाय
मालिनीं नगरीम् अथ।अङ्गेषु … ॥पालयाम्
आस चम्पां तु कर्णः) 12. 5. 6-7; (जगाम
चम्पाम् … तम् अङ्गराजं विषयं च तस्य)
3. 113. 15; 13. 42. 7-8, 33; river Bhāgīrathī
(Gaṅgā) flew by Campā (तथा चम्पां
समासाद्य भागीरथ्यां कृतोदकः) 3. 82.
142; 3. 292. 26.
B. Description: Having
the rows of Campaka trees as garland
(चम्पकमालिनी) 13. 42. 16.
C. Charac-
teristic: Characterized as a town (पुरी)
having the settlement of Sūtas (सूतविषयं
चम्पाम् अभ्याययौ पुरीम्।स मञ्जूषागतो
गर्भः) 3. 292. 26; also called नगरी
(12. 5. 6).
D. Epic events: (1) The
basket in which the newly born child
(Karṇa) was placed went from Aśvanadī
to Carmaṇvatī and then flew to Yamunā
and then along Gaṅgā to Campā 3. 292.
26; (2) Jarāsandha, defeated by Karṇa
in a duel, gave him the town Mālinī in the
Aṅga country; Karṇa, with the consent of
Duryodhana, protected Campā (प्रीत्या
ददौ स कर्णाय मालिनीं नगरीम् अथ।
अङ्गेषु … ॥पालयाम् आस चम्पां तु कर्णः
 … ।दुर्योधनस्यानुमते) 12. 5. 6-7.
E.
Past events: (1) Sage Vibhāṇḍaka, enraged
at not finding Ṛśyaśṛṅga in his आश्रम,
started for Campā to burn the king of Aṅgas
and his country 3. 113. 15; (2) Vipula
picked up the flowers having heavenly fra-
grance from the place where they had fallen
from the body of a divine woman (13. 42.
5-6) and went to Campā 13. 42. 16; having
reached Campā he gave the flowers to his
teacher Devaśarman 13. 42. 33.

चेदिपुर
Cedipura, Cedipurī, Cedirājapurī, Cedī-
nāṃ purī: See Śuktimatī.

च्यवनस्य
Cyavanasya āśramaḥ m.: An आश्रम
of Cyavana.
A. Location: In the west (प्रतीच्याम्)
3. 87. 1; the river Vadhūsarā which arose
from the tears of Pulomā, wife of Bhṛgu,
flew along the आश्रम (नाम तस्यास् तदा
नद्याश् चक्रे लोकपितामहः।वधूसरेति
भगवांश् च्यवनस्याश्रमं प्रति) 1. 6. 7.
B. Description: Holy (पुण्य) 3. 100. 4;
known (ख्यात) 3. 87. 10; resorted to by
the twiceborn (द्विजनिषेवित) 3. 100. 4.
C. History: Apparently Bhṛgu, father of
Cyavana, also lived in the same आश्रम
with his wife Pulomā; in that case the आश्रम
could have been established by Bhṛgu 1.
5. 13.
D. Holiness: Men obtain perfec-
tion there by practising austerities even
for a short period (तत्राल्पेनैव सिध्यन्ति
मानवास् तपसा विभो) 3. 87. 10.
E.
Epic event: One of the places where Ambā
bathed and practised austerities to be able
to kill Bhīṣma (च्यवनस्याश्रमे चैव …
आप्लावयत गात्राणि तीव्रम् आस्थाय वै तपः)
5. 187. 25, 28.
F. Past events: (1) A cer-
tain demon (रक्षस्) entered the आश्रम,
when Bhṛgu was away; he became infatua-
ted at the sight of Pulomā 1. 5. 14; the
demon desired to kidnap Pulomā from the
आश्रम after finding out from the fire
whether she was Bhṛgu's wife 1. 5. 20, 25;
(2) The Kāleya demons devoured a hun-
dred ascetics living in Cyavana's आश्रम
who subsisted on fruit and root (फलमूला-
शनानां हि मुनीनां भक्षीतं शतम्)
3. 100. 4. [See Bhṛgor āśramaḥ]

छत्रवती
Chatravatī f.: Name of a city.
Droṇa told the Pāṇḍavas to deprive
Drupada, who ruled at Chatravatī, of his
kingdom and present it to him 1. 154. 21.

जनस्थान
Janasthāna nt.: Name of a region.
A. Location: Situated in the Daṇḍa-
kāraṇya 3. 147. 29; 3. 261. 40.
B. Rāmā-
yaṇa event: While Rāma lived in the
Daṇḍakāraṇya he became the enemy of
Khara who lived in Janasthāna (खरेण
 … जनस्थाननिवासिना) 3. 261. 41; Rāvaṇa
abducted Sītā from Janasthāna 3. 147.
30; in Janasthāna Rāma cut off the
head of the demon (Khara or Dūṣaṇa ?) 9.
38. 10 (reference to 3. 261. 43).
C. Holi-
ness: According to the Tīrthavaṃśa narra-
ted by Aṅgiras to Gautama, one who obser-
ves fast and bathes in Janasthāna obtains
royal glory (जनस्थाने … विगाह्य वै निरा-
हारो राजलक्ष्मीं निगच्छति) 13. 26. 27.

जमदग्नेर्
*Jamadagner āśramaḥ m.: An आश्रम
of Jamadagni.
Jamadagni, after marrying Reṇukā,
lived in his आश्रम and practised austerities
with his wife 3. 116. 3; Reṇukā, when she
went for bathing, saw king Citraratha and
entertained longing for him; she then return-
ed to the आश्रम 3. 116. 8; when Rāma
returned to the आश्रम after collecting fruit
(3. 116. 5), Jamadagni asked him to kill his
mother 3. 116. 13-14; once Kārtavīrya, the
king of Anūpa, arrived at the आश्रम (तम्
आश्रमपदप्राप्तम्) and was received by
Reṇukā; disregarding the respect shown to
him, the king forcibly took away the calf
of the cow whose milk was used for giving
offerings (होमधेनु) and broke many big
trees in the आश्रम 3. 116. 20-21; the sons
of (Kārtavīrya) Arjuna attacked Jamadagni
in the absence of Rāma from the आश्रम
and killed him 3. 116. 25-26; Rāma returned
to the आश्रम after collecting fuel (समित्-
पाणिर् उपागच्छद् आश्रमं भृगुनन्दनः)
3. 116. 28; according to another account, as
directed by the sea, Kārtavīrya went to the
आश्रम of Jamadagni to find his match for
a duel; he did things in the आश्रम which
would not be liked by Rāma 14. 29. 8.

जम्बूमार्ग
Jambūmārga m.: Name of an आश्रम।
Situated in the west 3. 87. 1; near the
river Ketumālā 3. 87. 12; described as full
of deer and birds (मृगद्विजगणायुत) 3.
87. 11; it was the आश्रम of ascetics whose
souls were purified (जम्बूमार्गो महाराज
ऋषीणाम् भावितात्मनाम्।आश्रमः) 3. 87. 11
[For Jambūmārga, name of a sacred place,
see Vol. 1. 355].

जारूथी
Jārūthī f. Name of a city.
Kṛṣṇa defeated Āhuti, Krātha, Śiśu-
pāla and his people, Bhīmasena, Śaibya,
and Śatadhanvan at Jārūthī 3. 13. 27 (Nī.
on Bom. Ed. 3. 12. 30: जारूथ्यां नगर्-
याम्).

तक्षशिला
Takṣaśilā f.: Name of a city.
Janamejaya, after instructing his bro-
thers to act as told by his chosen Purohita
Somaśravas, marched on Takṣaśilā and
brought it under his control 1. 3. 18; when
Uttaṅka went to Hāstinapura to incite
Janamejaya to take revenge on Takṣaka,
the latter had already returned victorious
from Takṣaśilā 1. 3. 179; Janamejaya, after
completing the सर्पसत्र, returned from
Takṣaśilā to Hāstinapura (ततः समाप-
याम् आसुः कर्म तत् तस्य याजकाः। … ततः
तक्षशिलायाः स पुनर् आयाद् गजाह्वयम्)
18. 5. 27, 29.

तण्डूलिकाश्रम
Taṇḍūlikāśrama m.: Name of an
आश्रम।
After visiting the तीर्थ called Jambū-
mārga one should visit Taṇḍūlikāśrama;
he is thereby not affected by distress and
is honoured in heaven (न दुर्गतिम् अवा-
प्नोति स्वर्गलोके च पूज्यते) 3. 80. 62.

तण्डेर्
*Taṇḍer āśramaḥ m.: The आश्रम
of Taṇḍi.
After receiving a boon from god Śiva,
Taṇḍi returned to his आश्रम and narrated
one thousand and eight names of Śarva
(Śiva) to Upamanyu 13. 16. 12, 71-72; 13.
17. 29.

तृणसोमाग्नेर्
Tṛṇasomāgner āśramaḥ m.: An आश्रम
established by Tṛṇasomāgni.
Tṛṇasomāgni was the pupil of Agastya
(आश्रमो ऽगस्त्यशिष्यस्य) 3. 86. 14; situa-
ted in the south (3. 86. 1); on the moun-
tain Devasabha: it was near the Vaiḍūrya
mountain and the आश्रम of Agastya 3. 86.
14-15; described as holy (पुण्य) and full
of fruits and roots (संपन्नफलमूलवन्त्)
3. 86. 14.

त्रिपुर
Tripura nt.: Name of the three cities
of the three Asuras.
A. Creation: Created by Asura Maya
for the three sons of Tāraka, viz. Tārākṣa (or
Tārakākṣa), Kamalākṣa and Vidyunmālin;
the cities were obtained by them as a boon
from Pitāmaha; one of the three cities was
made of gold, the other of silver, and the
third of iron; they moved in them respectively
in heaven, in mid region, and with the third,
stationed on wheels, on the earth; (काञ्चनं
दिवि तत्रासीद् अन्तरिक्षे च राजतम्।आय-
सं चाभवद् भूमौ चक्रस्थं पृथिवी-
पते॥) 8. 24. 4, 10, 13-15 (Nī. on Bom. Ed.
8. 33. 18, however, चक्रस्थं आज्ञावशं
यथेष्टसंचारीत्य् अर्थः); (according to
13. 145. 24, however, all the three cities were
in heaven (असुराणां पुराण्य् आसंस् त्रीणि
वीर्यवतां दिवि।आयसं राजतं चैव
सौवर्णम् अपरं तथा॥).
B. Des-
cription: Inaccessible (दुर्ग) 8. 24. 20;
guarded by Daityas and Dānavas (दैत्य-
दानवरक्षित) 8. 24. 114.
C. Charac-
teristics: (1) The three cities were
supposed to come together and be united
at the end of one thousand years; if some
prominent god were then to strike the cities
with a single arrow, the god would be death
for them (समागतानि चैतानि यो हन्याद्
भगवंस् तदा।एकेषुणा देववरः स
नो मृत्युर् भविष्यति॥) 8. 24. 11-12; (2)
Whatever was desired by a person who had
taken shelter in the Tripuras (त्रिपुरसं-
श्रयः) was procured for him by Maya with
the help of his माया (तस्मै कामं मयस्
तं तं विदधे मायया तदा) 8. 24. 22;
(3) Hari, the son of Tārakākṣa, obtained
as a boon from Pitāmaha, a well in their
पुर (वापी भवतु नः पुरे); if any
demon, wounded by weapons, was thrown
into this well, he arose from it stronger;
if a dead demon was thrown into it, he
came back alive (मृतानां जीवनीम्); forti-
fied with this well the denizens of the
Tripuras oppressed all the three worlds
8. 24. 23-27.
D. Mythological event:
Since Indra was unable to shatter the Tri-
puras, although he used all his weapons
against them, gods approached Rudra and
requested him to destroy the demons and
their cities; Śiva then burnt the three पुरस्
together with the demons, using gods as
chariot (देवान् रथवरम् कृत्वा), god
Viṣṇu as arrow, Agni as tip of the arrow
(शल्य), Yama as hind part of the arrow
(पुङ्ख); Śiva's arrow had three joints
and three heads (to correspond to the
three पुरस् ?) (त्रिपर्वणा त्रिशल्येन …
शरेण) 13. 145. 24-29; Śiva's chariot
was driven in the direction of the Tripuras
by Pitāmaha; Śiva employed his Pāśupata
missile on his bow and thought of the
Tripuras (त्रिपुरं समचिन्तयत्) 8. 24.
115; at the appointed time the three पुरस्
came together and were united; when they
came in his view, Śiva shot his arrow which
burnt the Tripuras and the demons in them
and threw them in the western ocean; thus
Maheśvara, wishing well for the three
worlds, burnt the Tripuras and the demons
8. 24. 114-121; this report in the Karṇa-
parvan of the downfall of the Tripuras
which was according to the account in the
Purāṇas is referred to in the Anukramaṇī-
parvan (आख्यातं यत्र पौराणं त्रिपु-
रस्य निपातनम्) 1. 2. 169.
E. Similies:
(1) The town Saubha, when cut into two
by the Sudarśanacakra of Kṛṣṇa, fell down
as did the Tripura when tossed up by the
arrow of Maheśvara (महेश्वरशरो-
द्धूतं पपात त्रिपुरं यथा) 3. 23. 34;
(2) Aśvatthāman, after burning an अक्षौ-
हिणी army of the demons (of Ghaṭotkaca),
shone as Maheśvara formerly did in heaven
after burning the Tripura (पुरेव तृइपुरं
दग्ध्वा दिवि देवो महेश्वरः) 7. 131. 98;
(3) The same simile is found when Karṇa
killed the demons (of Ghaṭotkaca) 7.
150. 83.

दधीचाश्रम
Dadhīcāśrama m.: An आश्रम of
Dadhīca.
A. Location: On the other bank of
Sarasvatī (सरस्वत्याः परे पारे) 3. 98. 13.
B. Description: Very attractive (सुमनो-
रम) 3. 98. 17; beautified at various places
(तेषु तेष्व् अवकाशेषु शोभितम्) 3. 98. 17;
having splendour like that of heaven (त्रि-
विष्टपसमप्रख्य) 3. 98. 17; covered with
different kinds of trees and creepers (नाना-
द्रुमलतावृत) 3. 98. 13; humming with
the sounds produced by the bees, mixed
with the notes of the male cuckoo, and alive
with the sounds of Jīvakas (जीवं जीवक-
नादितम्) 3. 98. 13; buffalos, boars, Sṛma-
ras and Camara deer moved everywhere
freely without fear of tigers (तत्र तत्रानु-
चरितं शार्दूलभयवर्जितैः) 3. 98. 14;
resounding all around with the trumpets
of elephants in rut sporting with female
elephants in lakes (करेणुभिर् वारणैश् च
प्रभिन्नकरटामुखैः।सरोवगाढैः
क्रीडद्भिः समन्ताद् अनुनादितम्॥) 3. 98.
15; resounding with the loud roars of lions
and tigers and of other animals lying con-
cealed in caves (अपरैश् चापि संलीनैर्
गुहाकन्दरवासिभिः) 3. 98. 16.
C. Past
event: Gods, led by Nārāyaṇa, went to
the आश्रम of Dadhīca to ask for his
bones (दधीचस्याश्रमं ययुः) 3. 98.
12; (दधीचाश्रमम् आगमन्) 3. 98. 17;
there they saw Dadhīca shining like the sun
3. 98. 18.

दन्तकूर
Dantakūra nt.: Name of a city.
(1) Sahadeva defeated the assembled
kings of the southern countries at Danta-
kūra (यो दन्तकूरे व्यजयन् नृदेवान् समा-
गतान् दाक्षिणात्यान् महीपान्) 3. 119. 18;
(2) Sahadeva defeated the assembled
Kaliṅgas at Dantakūra (सहदेवः कलिङ्-
गान् समागतान् अजयद् दन्तकूरे) 5. 23. 23
(Nī., however, on Bom. Ed. 5. 23. 24;
दन्तकूरः सङ्ग्रामः तस्मिन्); (3) Kṛṣṇa
crushed the Kaliṅgas at Dantakūra 5. 47.
70 (Nī. on Bom. Ed. 5. 48. 76; दन्तकूरे
सङ्ग्रामे; but he also mentions the view
of other commentators according to whom
Dantakūra was the name of a city (नगर).

दिलीपस्य
Dilīpasya āśramaḥ m.: An आश्रम
established by Dilīpa.
Ambā, while practising austerities in
order to be able to kill Bhīṣma, visited
many holy places, one of them being the
आश्रम of Dilīpa (दिलीपस्याश्रमे तथा) 5.
187. 27; she bathed at these holy places and
practised severe austerities (एतेषु तीर्थेषु
तदा काशिकन्या … आप्लावयत गात्राणि
तीव्रम् आस्थाय वै तपः) 5. 187. 28.

दिवःप्रस्थ
Divaḥprastha nt.: Name of a town.
It was a big town of Senābindu (सेना-
बिन्दोः पुरं महत्) 2. 24. 12; Arjuna, in
his expedition to the north (प्रययाव्
उत्तरां तस्माद् दिशम् 2. 24. 1) before the
Rājasūya, encamped there with his army
and from there he attacked the Paurava
king Viṣvagaśva 2. 24. 12-13.

दर्जया
Darjayā f.: Name of a city.
The आश्रम of Agastya was located
near it; Yudhiṣṭhira, having reached the
आश्रम, lived there; he asked Lomaśa why
Vātāpi was put out of action there (अगस्-
त्याश्रमम् आसाद्य दुर्जयायाम् उवास ह। …
अगस्त्येनेह वातापिः किमर्थम् उपशामि-
तः) 3. 94. 1-2 (Nī. on 3. 96. 1 takes दुर्-
जया as an epithet ‘invincible’ of the city
of Vātāpi, called Maṇimatī: दुर्जयायां
वातापिपुर्यां मणिमती संज्ञायां).

द्वारका
Dvārakā, Dvāravatī f.: Name of a
city, also called Kuśasthalī (2. 13. 49; 12.
326. 83, 85), Ānartanagarī (5. 7. 4; 14. 51.
41), Ānartanagara (3. 21. 1), Ānartapurī
(14. 51. 56), Vṛṣṇipura (3. 21. 4; 3. 180.
25).
A. Location: In the west (प्रतीचीं
दिशम् आश्रिताः) 2. 13. 49; (समावृत्ताः पश्चि-
मां दिशम् एव ते।ददृशुर् द्वारकां चापि)
17. 1. 43; in the Anarta country (आनर्तम्
एवाभिमुखाः … वृष्णिपुरं प्रविश्य) 3.
180. 25; in the Surāṣṭra country (सुराष्ट्रेषु
 … पुण्या द्वारवती तत्र) 3. 86. 20-21; near
the Raivataka mountain (रईवतेनोपशोभि-
ताम्) 2. 13. 49; 2. 13. 52; 14. 58. 3-4.
B. Description: Holy (पुण्या) 3. 13. 31;
pleasing (रम्या) 2. 13. 49; 5. 7. 4; 14. 58.
3; 14. 84. 13; liked by the sages (ऋषिकान्ता)
3. 13, 41; offering different kinds of enjoy-
ments (भोगवती) 3. 13. 31; full of jewels
(रत्नसंपूर्णा) 16. 8. 40; adorned by
Raivataka mountain (रैवतेनोपशोभिताम्)
2. 13. 49; guarded by Vṛṣṇi heroes (वृष्णि-
वीराभिरक्षिता) 14. 84. 13; the place of
residence of the Vṛṣṇis (वृष्णिनिलय) 16.
6. 4; having ramparts and watch towers
(प्राकाराट्टालकोपेता) 16. 7. 17; referred
to chiefly as पूरी 1. 212. 9; 1. 213. 55;
2. 13. 49, 65; 2. 42. 49, 55; 3. 16. 2, 4;
3. 21. 9; 5. 7. 3; 12. 326. 83, 84; 14. 15. 21,
26; 14. 51. 42; 14. 58. 3; 14. 84. 15; 16. 5.
7; 16. 7. 13; but also as नगर 3. 16. 12;
3. 21. 8; 16. 2. 17, 18; 16. 8. 10; नगरी
16. 7. 17; and पुर 3. 16. 18.
C. Forti-
fication: The Yādavas fortified Dvārakā
in such a way that even gods could not
reach it and women could defend it
(तथैव दुर्गसंस्कारं देवैर् अपि दुरा-
सदम्॥स्त्रियो ऽपि यस्यां युध्येयुः
किं पुनर् वृष्णिपुंगवाः) 2. 13. 50-51.
D. Epic events: (1) The Yādavas fled to
the west from Mathurā due to fear of
Jarāsandha and repaired to Kuśasthalī;
they settled down there and fortified the
town; they lived in Kuśasthalī without fear
from any quarter (अकुतोभयाः); seeing
the mountain (Raivataka) nearby and the
Mādhavītīrtha, the Yādavas were highly
delighted 2. 13. 49-52, 65; hence the city is
referred to as the residence of the Yāda-
vas (यदुसदन) 8. 26. 63; (2) Hearing
that Śiśupāla was killed by Kṛṣṇa, Śālva,
during the absence of Kṛṣṇa from Dvā-
rakā, attacked the city riding in his Saubha
town; he killed young Vṛṣṇi heroes who
defended the city and destroyed all gardens
(पुरोद्यानानि सर्वाणि भेदयाम् आस दुर्म-
तिः) 3. 15. 5-7; hearing that Śrautaśrava
(Śiśupāla) was killed, Śālva besieged Dvāra-
vatī from all sides; he mounted his Saubha,
flying in the sky, and from there attacked
the city; the fortification and the defence
arrangements of the city were looked after
by Gada, Sāmba, Uddhava and others
according to the rules laid down in the
Śāstras (शास्त्रदृष्टेन विधिना संयूक्ता);
drinking liquor was forbidden in the town
to avoid negligence on the part of citizens
(आघोषितं च नगरे न पातव्या सुरेति ह।
प्रमादं परिरक्षद्भिः) 3. 16. 2-18;
Dvārakā was well guarded by king Āhuka by
giving largesses (द्वारका भूरिदक्षिणैः।
आहुकेन सुगुप्ता च राज्ञा) 3. 16. 23; Śālva
attacked Dvārakā with the speed of the king
of birds (अभिसारयाम् आस तदा वेगेन पत-
गेन्द्रवत्) 3. 17. 7; all the people in Dvārakā
were bewildered when Śālva descended on
the earth with his Saubha (सौभस्थं
पृथिवीगतम्) 3. 17. 28; when Śālva was
defeated by the Vṛṣṇis led by Pradyumna
he left Dvārakā mounting his Saubha 3.
20. 27; (3) At the end of the Rājasūya
Kṛṣṇa wished to return to Dvārakā 2. 42.
46, 52; Yudhiṣṭhira approved of Kṛṣṇa's
return to Dvāravatī 2. 42. 49; when Kṛṣṇa
returned to Ānartanagara after the Rāja-
sūya of Yudhiṣṭhira at Indraprastha he saw
Dvārakā lack-lustre; it was bereft of the
sound of Vedic studies and Vedic sacrifices
(आनर्तनगरं मुक्तं ततो ऽहम् अगमं
तदा।महाक्रतौ राजसूये निवृत्ते … ॥
अपश्यं द्वारकां चाहं महाराज हत-
त्विषम्।निःस्वाध्यायवषट्कारम्); noble
women of the town did not put on orna-
ments; the gardens of Dvārakā were chang-
ed beyond recognition (अनभिज्ञेयरूपाणी
द्वारकोपवनानी च); Kṛṣṇa found Vṛṣṇi-
pura with its men and women very much
ill at ease (अस्वस्थनरनारीकम् इदं वृष्णि-
पुरं भृशम्); the siege of Dvārakā by
Śālva and lifting of the siege later by him
was reported to Kṛṣṇa; enraged, he asked
the Yādava heroes to be watchful in the
city (अप्रमादः सदा कार्यो नगरे याद-
वर्षभाः) and left for the destruction of
Śālva; he vowed not to return to Dvāravatī
without killing Śālva (नाहत्वा तं निवर्-
तिष्ये पुरीं द्वारवतीं प्रति) 3. 21. 1-9;
he asked Sātyaki, Baladeva, and Pradyumna
to protect Dvārakā and his father Vasudeva
3. 22. 16-17; during the fight with Śālva,
a certain resident of Dvārakā (पुरुषः
कश्चिद् द्वारकानिलयः), a servant (परि-
चारकः) of Āhuka, met Kṛṣṇa and gave
him a false message from Āhuka; accord-
ing to the message Śālva had attacked
Dvārakā and killed the son of Śūrasena
(Vasudeva); hence Kṛṣṇa was advised to
leave the battle, return to Dvārakā and
protect it; that should be Kṛṣṇa's prime
concern (द्वारकाम् एव रक्षस्व कार्यम्
एतन् महत् तव) 3. 22. 12-14; Kṛṣṇa then
mentally blamed Sātyaki and others who
were entrusted with the protection of Dvā-
rakā and of Vasudeva 3. 22. 16-17; (Kṛṣṇa,
however, soon realized that he was tricked
by Śālva by his माया and started to fight
with him again); he was incited to action
by his charioteer who reminded him that
Dvārakā was ransacked by Śālva (द्वारका
चावमर्दिता) 3. 23. 25; (4) Kṛṣṇa told
Yudhiṣṭhira that he was not in Dvārakā
when the game of dice was played in Hās-
tinapura 3. 14. 1; he heard of the द्यूत
only when he returned to Dvārakā after
vanquishing Śālva 3. 14. 15; (5) After
informing Yudhiṣṭhira in the forest about
Śālva's attacking Dvārakā and Kṛṣṇa's sub-
sequent battle with him, he comforted Yudhi-
ṣṭhira and returned to Dvārakā 3. 23. 42-45;
(6) Dvārakā was once burnt by Śiśupāla
when Kṛṣṇa and others had gone to Prāg-
jyotiṣapura 2. 42. 7; (7) Prophecies regard-
ing Dvārakā: (i) Nārāyaṇa told Nārada
that at the conjunction of Dvāpara and
Kali (द्वापरस्य कलेश् चैव संधौ 12.
326. 82) he would be born at Mathurā
but would make Kuśasthalī (i. e. Dvārakā)
his residence (कुशस्थलीं करिष्यामि
निवासं द्वारकां पुरीम्) 12. 326. 83-85;
while residing in that city he would kill
Naraka, Mura and Pīṭha 12. 326. 84; he
would also kill the demons and take the
wealth of Prāgjyotiṣapura to Kuśasthalī
(प्राग्ज्योतिषपुरं रम्यं नानाधन-
समन्वितम्।कुशस्थलीं नयिष्यामि) 12.
326. 85; having lessened the burden of the
earth he would bring about the destruction
of the Sātvata heroes, his kinsmen and of
Dvārakā (कृत्वा भारावतरणं वसु-
धाया यथेप्सितम्।सर्वसात्वतमुख्या-
नां द्वारकायाश् च सत्तम।करिष्ये प्र-
लयं घोरम् आत्मज्ञातिविनाशनम्॥) 12.
326. 92; (ii) prophesied also by Arjuna
that Dvārakā, which was made his home
by Kṛṣṇa, would be drowned in the sea by
him (द्वारकाम् आत्मसात् कृत्वा समुद्रं
गमयिष्यसि) 3. 13. 31; (iii) Kṛṣṇa too
had foretold that when Arjuna would leave
Dvārakā taking with him the citizens, the
city, together with its ramparts and watch-
towers, would be instantly inundated by the
sea (इमां च नगरीं सद्यः प्रतियाते ध-
नंजये।प्राकाराट्टालकोपेतां समुद्रः
प्लावयिष्यति) 16. 7. 17; 16. 8. 10; (8) Des-
truction of Dvārakā: Arjuna advised all
people to leave the town at the end of a
week and stay outside 16. 8. 12; before
leaving Dvārakā, the citizens (द्वारकावासि-
नः) attended the funeral of Vasudeva 16.
8. 19-23; when all people had left, the city
was overrun by the sea (सागरः … ।द्वार-
कां रत्नसंपूऋणां जलेनाप्लावयत् तदा॥)
16. 8. 40; the people of Dvārakā witnessed
the event the like of which had not happened
before (अद्भुतम्) 16. 8. 41; the people of
Dvārakā who followed Arjuna to Indra-
prastha were handed over to Vajra 16. 8.
73: the Pāṇḍavas when they started on
their great final journey (महाप्रस्थान)
went, on their way, to the west and saw
Dvārakā inundated by the sea (ददृशुर्
द्वारकां चापि सागरेण परिप्लुताम्) 17. 1.
43; Arjuna's going to Dvāravatī, bereft of
the Vṛṣṇi heroes, and his taking with him
the people of Dvāravatī listed in the con-
tents of the Mausalaparvan 1. 2. 223, 226;
(9) After the Pāṇḍavas were established at
Indraprastha Kṛṣṇa and Balarāma left for
Dvāravatī with the consent of the Pāṇḍavas
1. 199. 50. (10) During the period of his
exile Arjuna went from Raivataka mountain
to Dvārakā; the city, even up to the modest
houses (?), was decorated to welcome
him (अलंकृता द्वारका … अपि निष्कुटकेष्व्
अपि) 1. 210. 15-16 (Nī. on Bom. Ed. 2.
218. 16: निष्कुटेषु गृहारामेष्व् अपि अलंकृता
किम् उत राजमार्गादिषु); the people of
Dvārakā rushed to the main roads to see
Arjuna; women in large numbers rushed
to the windows (?) (अवलोकेषु नारीणाम्
सहस्राणि शतानि च); there was a great
gathering (समवायो महान् अभूत्) of the
Bhojas, the Vṛṣṇis and the Andhakas;
Arjuna lived (in Dvārakā) in the house
of Kṛṣṇa for many nights 1. 210. 17-21;
once, while Subhadrā was returning to Dvā-
rakā after worshipping Raivataka mountain
she was kidnapped by Arjuna; the helpless
soldiers cried aloud and ran towards Dvā-
rakā 1. 212. 7, 9; the incident is referred to
in 8. 26. 63; (11) The Yādavas, returned to
Dvāravatī after visiting Indraprastha where
they had gone to give gifts to the Pāṇḍa-
vas in connection with the marriage of
Subhadrā 1. 213. 55; Subhadrā's abduction
by Arjuna from Dvārakā referred to (i) in
the Anukramaṇīparvan 1. 1. 103; also listed
in the contents of the Ādiparvan narrated
in the Parvasaṃgrahaparvan 1. 2. 92, (ii)
in Vaiśaṃpāyana's summary of the Mahā-
bhārata events 1. 55. 32-34, and (iii) in the
Saṃbhavaparvan of the Ādiparvan 1. 90.
85; (12) After asking Maya to build a
सभा for the Pāṇḍavas, Kṛṣṇa left for
Dvārakā 2. 2. 23; (13) Yudhiṣṭhira sent
a messenger to Dvārakā to invite Kṛṣṇa,
living in Dvārakā, for consultations regard-
ing the Rājasūya 2. 12. 29; at the end of the
Rājasūya, Yudhiṣṭhira consented to Kṛṣṇa's
return to Dvāravatī; accordingly Kṛṣṇa
reached Dvāravatī 2. 42. 49, 55, 60; (14)
The sons of Draupadī, during the period of
exile of the Pāṇḍavas, went to Vṛṣṇipura
situated in the Ānarta country 3. 180. 25;
later, Satyabhāmā informed Draupadī that
her sons were all well and happy at Dvāra-
vatī 3. 224. 11; (15) Before going to the
Virāṭanagara for the अज्ञातवास, Yudhi-
ṣṭhira sent away Indrasena and others, with
their chariots, to Dvāravatī 4. 4. 3; the
spies, who were sent by Duryodhana in
search of the Pāṇḍavas, told him that the
charioteers of the Pāṇḍavas had reached
Dvāravatī but neither the Pāṇḍavas nor
Kṛṣṇā was to be found in Dvāravatī 4. 24.
15-16; (11) After the marriage of Abhi-
manyu, Kṛṣṇa, Balarāma and others, per-
mitted by Virāṭa, went to Dvārakā; after
Kṛṣṇa's departure to Dvārakā, Yudhiṣṭhira
started making all kinds of preparations
for the war (चक्रुः साङ्ग्रामिकं सर्वम्)
5. 5. 11-12; 5. 7. 1 (Dvāravatī); (12)
When Duryodhana knew through his messe-
ngers and spies that Kṛṣṇa had returned
to Dvārakā, he started to go there to seek
Kṛṣṇa's help in war; that very day Arjuna
too arrived in Ānartanagarī; both of them,
after reaching Dvārakā, saw Kṛṣṇa sleep-
ing 5. 7. 3 (आनर्तनगरीं रम्यां जगा-
माशु धनंजयः) 5. 7. 4, 5; (13) When
Balarāma started for his pilgrimage he, on
his way, asked his servants to bring from
Dvārakā all the materials and utensils
required for the pilgrimage, as also the
sacred fires and priests (संभारांस् तीर्थ-
यात्रायां सर्वोपकरणानि च।आनयध्वं
द्वारकाया अग्नीन् वै याजकांस् तथा) 9. 34.
15; when Balarāma chose to go to the
battlefield to watch the duel between
Bhīma and Duryodhana, he sent away his
co-pilgrims and attendants to Dvārakā 9.
53. 32; at the end of the duel, Balarāma,
expressing his disapproval of the way
Bhīma brought about the downfall of
Duryodhana, left for Dvārakā 9. 59. 26;
when he left for Dvāravatī, the Pāñcālas
and the Pāṇḍavas, did not feel very happy
9. 59. 27; (14) When the sacrificial horse
for the Aśvamedha of Yudhiṣṭhira reached
Dvāravatī, king Ugrasena came out of the
town to honour Arjuna who accompanied
the horse 14. 84. 13-15; when Yudhiṣṭhira
asked Kṛṣṇa to give some news about
Arjuna (who was accompanying the horse),
Kṛṣṇa told him that a confidential attendant
who lived in Dvārakā (द्वारकावासी ममा-
प्तः पुरुषः) had seen him (Arjuna) who,
fighting many battles, was emaciated (बहु-
संग्रामकर्शितम्) 14. 88. 9; (15) After the
war, Kṛṣṇa informed Arjuna his intention
to return to Dvāravatī to meet his father,
Baladeva and others, if permitted by Yudhi-
ṣṭhira, but not otherwise; hence he wanted
Yudhiṣṭhira to be informed by Arjuna
about his wish to go to Dvārakā 14. 15.
20-21, 26, 31; before Kṛṣṇa's return to
Dvārakā, Arjuna wanted Kṛṣṇa to tell him
once again what he taught him before in the
Gītā 14. 16. 6-7; Arjuna approved Kṛṣṇa's
wish to return to Dvārakā; so he suggest-
ed that they should go to Hāstinapura to
seek Yudhiṣṭhira's permission for Kṛṣṇa's
return to Dvārakā 14. 50. 51; 14. 51. 23;
Arjuna sought Yudhiṣṭhira's permission
for Kṛṣṇa's return to Ānartanagarī 14. 51.
40-41; Yudhiṣṭhira gave Kṛṣṇa his permi-
ssion to return to Dvāravatī to see his
father 14. 51. 42; Arjuna and others emb-
raced Kṛṣṇa when he left Hāstinapura to
go to Dvārakā 14. 52. 1; (16) Yudhiṣṭhira
was grieved to think of what Subhadrā, who
was then in Dvārakā (द्वारकावासिनी), would
say to Kṛṣṇa when he returned to Dvārakā
(since her son was killed in war) 12. 1. 16;
(17) Aśvatthāman once went to Dvārakā
where he stayed for some time honoured
by the Vṛṣṇis; he wanted to exchange his
Brahmaśiras missile for the Sudarśana of
Kṛṣṇa; while he was in Dvāravatī (वसन्
द्वारवतीम् अनु), one day he approached
Kṛṣṇa who was sitting alone on seashore;
Kṛṣṇa informed Aśvatthāman that none of
the Vṛṣṇi and the Andhaka heroes who lived
in Dvārakā had ever asked him to part with
his Sudarśana 10. 12. 11-12, 15, 31-33;
(18) The Yādavas, headed by Sāraṇa,
once saw Viśvāmitra, Kaṇva, Nārada and
other sages who were on a visit to Dvārakā
16. 2. 4; by the proclamation of a royal
decree Āhuka prohibited fermentation of
spirituous liquor in all the houses of Vṛṣṇis
and Andhakas living in the town (Dvārakā)
(अद्यप्रभृति सर्वेषु वृष्ण्यन्धकगृहेष्व्-
इह।सुरासवो न कर्तव्यः सर्वैर् नगर-
वासिभिः) 16. 2. 17-18; one of the bad
omens that occurred for the citizens of
Dvārakā was that a laughing black woman
with white teeth entered the houses at
night, stole the marriage threads of women
while they were asleep, and ran through
the streets of Dvārakā (काली स्त्री पाण्डुरैर्
दन्तैः प्रविश्य हसती निशि।स्त्रियः स्व-
प्नेषु मुष्णन्ती द्वारकां परिधावति)
16. 4. 1 (Nī. on Bom. Ed. 16. 3. 1: मुष्णन्ती
स्त्रीणाम् मङ्गलसूत्रादिकं चोरयन्ती);
when the Yādavas were destroyed, Kṛṣṇa
entered Dvāravatī and told Vasudeva to
guard the women folk and wait for the
arrival of Arjuna in Dvāravatī 16. 5. 7;
16. 7. 13; when Arjuna reached Dvārakā
with Dāruka the city appeared to him like
a woman who had lost her husband (मृत-
नाथाम् इव स्त्रियम्) 16. 6. 4; Arjuna, after
he witnessed the plight of Dvārakā and
the women of Kṛṣṇa he wept loudly and
fell down on the ground 16. 6. 12.
E. Past
events or events not related to the epic
narrative: (1) Kṛṣṇa told Uttaṅka whom
he met on his way to Dvārakā that he
(Uttaṅka) should think of him (Kṛṣṇa)
if he desired something 14. 54. 13; Govinda
(Kṛṣṇa) gave boon to Uttaṅka and went
to Dvārakā in the company of Sātyaki
14. 58. 2, 3 (Dvāravatī); (2) Pious king
Nṛga, due to a sin unknowingly committed
by him (13. 69. 22; 13. 71. 2), had to live
as a lizard in a deep well at Dvāravatī 13.
69. 1-4; Kṛṣṇa liberated him when the
Yādavas were settling down at Dvāravatī
13. 71. 2-3; 13. 69. 25-29; (3) Śiva, in
the form of Durvāsas, lived for a long time
with Kṛṣṇa in his residence at Dvāravatī
13. 145. 35; (4) Yudhiṣṭhira asked Bhīṣ-
ma the kind of gifts which one should
give under different नक्षत्रस् (नक्षत्र-
योगस्येदानीं दानकल्पं ब्रवीहि मे);
Bhīṣma then told him what formerly Nārada,
who had arrived at Dvārakā, told Devaki
in reply to her question 13. 63. 1-4.
F.
Dvārakā as a holy place: Described as
holy (पुण्या) 3. 86. 21; Yudhiṣṭhira, while
on a pilgrimage, visited Dvārakā (यच् चापि
तीर्थानि चरन्न् अगच्छं द्वारकां प्रति)
7. 85. 63; a holy place Piṇḍāraka located
in Dvāravatī 3. 80. 82.
G. Similes:
(1) The city Dvārakā was well protected
and well camouflaged and was furnished
with all kinds of weapons as is done for
the residence of Indra (सुरक्षितं सुगुप्-
तं च सर्वायुधसमन्वितम्।तत् पुरं
भरतश्रेष्ठ यथेन्द्रभवनं तथा॥)
3. 16. 18; (2) As Indra left for heaven
after killing his enemies so did Kṛṣṇa leave
for Ānartapurī (when all the Kauravas
were killed) 14. 51. 56; (3) Dvārakā,
bereft of Vṛṣṇi heroes, compared with a
woman who had lost her husband (द्वार-
कां … मृतनाथां इव स्त्रियम्) 16. 6. 4;
(4) In a long drawn metaphor Dvārakā
compared to a river: the Vṛṣṇis and the
Andhakas were its water, horses its fishes,
chariots its boats, the sound of musical
instruments and the one produced by
chariots its current, residences and holy
bathing places its big crocodiles, jewels
its thick layer of moss, ramparts made of
वज्र its garlands, streets its whirlpools,
cross-roads its steady, deep pieces of water,
Rāma and Kṛṣṇa its big sharks; this
river in the form of Dvārakā looked like
the terrible Vaitaraṇī river having the noose
of Kāla as its shark (ताम् स वृष्ण्यन्-
धकजलां हयमीनां रथोडुपाम्।
वादित्ररथघोषौघां वेश्मतीर्थमहा-
ग्रहाम्॥रत्नशैवलसंघाटां वज्रप्रा-
कारमालिनीम्।रथ्यास्रोतोजलावर्तां चत्व-
रस्तिमितह्रदाम्॥रामकृष्णमहाग्राहां
द्वारकासरितम् तदा।कालपाशग्रहां घो-
रां नदीं वैतरणीम् इव॥) 16. 6. 8-10;
(5) Arjuna saw Dvārakā bereft of Vṛṣṇi
heroes like a lotus pond in winter which
is without its glory and gives no delight
(गतश्रियं निरानन्दां पद्मिनीं शिशिरे
यथा) 16. 6. 11.

द्वारपाल
Dvārapāla nt.: Name of a city (पुर) ?
Nakula subjugated the city in his
expedition to the west (प्रतीचीम् अभितो
दिशम् 2. 29. 2) before the Rājasūya (तथा
वृन्दाटकं पुरम्।द्वारपालं च तरसा
वशे चक्रे महाद्युतिः) 2. 29. 10.

धृतराष्ट्रस्य
Dhṛtarāṣṭrasya āśramaḥ1 m.: An
आश्रम established by Dhṛtarāṣṭra at Kuru-
kṣetra; also called Kurukṣetrāśrama (15.
29. 21).
A. Location: At Kurukṣetra, on the
other bank of Yamunā at some distance
from the river; when Dhṛtarāṣṭra, with
Gāndhārī and Kuntī, left Hāstinapura he
reached Kurukṣetra (कुरुक्षेत्रं जगाम
सः) 15. 25. 8; when Yudhiṣṭhira, with his
brothers and wife, went to meet Dhṛtarāṣṭra
in his आश्रम he had to cross the river
Yamunā (ततो युधिष्ठिरो राजा कुरुक्षे-
त्रम् अवातरत्। … उत्तीर्य यमुनां … स
ददर्शाश्रमं दूरात् … धृतराष्ट्रस्य)
15. 30. 16-17; 15. 31. 6; it was situated near
the आश्रम of Śatayūpa 15. 25. 9, 12; 15. 30.
17; also not far from Bhāgīrathī 15. 25. 8;
15. 39. 18, 21; 15. 40. 4.
B. Description:
Solitary (शून्य) 15. 31. 3; resorted to by
Siddhas and Cāraṇas (सिद्धचारणसेवीत)
15. 31. 20; in the precincts of the आश्रम
there were fire altars with burning sacrifi-
cial fires attended to by sages who had
taken bath and who gave offerings in the fire
(ददर्श तत्र वेदीश् च संप्रज्वलितपाव-
काः।कृताभिषेकैर् मुनिभिर् आहुताग्निभिर्
उपस्थिताः।) 15. 34. 7; the fire altars were
scattered with forest flowers, were full of
smoke issuing from clarified butter, were
endowed with Brahmanical lustre, and were
surrounded by hosts of sages (वानेय-
पुष्पनिकरैर् आज्यधूमोद्गमैर् अपि।ब्रा-
ह्मेण वपुषा युक्ता युक्ता मुनिगणैश् च
ताः) 15. 34. 8; the hermitage was full of deer
(मृगगणाकीर्ण) 15. 31. 3; herds of deer
moved about undistractedly near the आश्रम
and singing birds flew over it fearlessly;
notes of peacocks, Dātyūhas, sweet sounds
of cuckoos and sounds of Vedic recitations
of Brāhmaṇas could be heard at different
places (मृगयूथैर् अनुद्विग्नैस् तत्र तत्र
समाश्रितैः।अशङ्कितैः पक्षिगणैः प्रगी-
तैर् इव च प्रभो॥केकाभिर् नीलकण्ठा-
नां दात्यूहानां च कूजितैः।कोकिलानां
च कुहरैः शुभैः श्रुतिमनोहरैः॥)
15. 34. 9-10; beautified by large number of
banana trees (कदलीवनशोभित) 15. 31. 3;
there were large baskets for collecting fruits
and roots (फलमूलसमुद्वाहैर् महद्-
भिश् चोपशोभितम्) 15. 34. 11.
C. Epic
events: (1) In Kurukṣetra, Dhṛtarāṣṭra
first reached the आश्रम of the royal sage
Śatayūpa; he lived in this आश्रम and after
he was initiated by Vyāsa in his own
आश्रम and was instructed by Śatayūpa in
the way of the life of a forest-dweller,
Dhṛtarāṣṭra established another आश्रम for
himself, Gāndhārī and Kuntī for the pra-
ctice of austerities (ययौ व्यासाश्रमं
तदा। … स दिक्षां तत्र संप्राप्य राजा …
शतयूपाश्रमे तस्मिन् निवासम् अकरोत्
तदा॥तस्मै सर्वं विधिं राजन् राजा-
चख्यौ महामतिः।आरण्यकम् … एवं
स तपसा राजा धृतराष्ट्रो महामनाः।
योजयाम् आस चात्मानम्) 15. 25. 11-14;
(2) Yudhiṣṭhira, desirous of meeting
Dhṛtarāṣṭra and others, ordered his
carriages and the rest to move to Kuru-
kṣetrāśrama (निर्यान्तु … कुरुक्षेत्राश्रमं
प्रति) 15. 29. 19-21; (3) When Yudhiṣṭhira,
with his brothers and Draupadī, reached
Kurukṣetra and crossed the river Yamunā
he saw from a distance the आश्रमस् of
Śatayūpa and Dhṛtarāṣṭra (स ददर्शाश्र-
मं दूराद् राजर्षेस् तस्य धीमतः।शत-
यूपस्य कौरव्य धृतराष्ट्रस्य चैव ह॥)
15. 30. 16-17; the Pāṇḍavas got down from
their chariots and went on foot (पदातयः)
to the आश्रम of Dhṛtarāṣṭra (पाण्डवाः …
अभिजग्मुर् नरपतेर् आश्रमम्) 15. 31. 1;
आश्रमं ते ततो जग्मुर् धृतराष्ट्रस्य
पाण्डवाः 15. 31. 3; when Dhṛtarāṣṭra, who
had gone to bathe in Yamunā and to fetch
flowers, returned to the आश्रम along with
the Pāṇḍavas who had rushed there to
meet him, he sat down in the आश्रम
with the Pāṇḍavas and the ascetics who had
gathered to see the Pāṇḍavas 15. 31. 6-8,
20; 15. 32. 1-2; when the ascetics and
others had left the आश्रम (आश्रम-
मण्डलम्) Dhṛtarāṣṭra asked Yudhiṣṭhira
his कुशल 15. 32. 18; when Vidura saw
from a distance some people seated in the
आश्रम he wanted to go away from it 15.
33. 18; the Pāṇḍavas lived in the आश्रम
for that night 15. 33. 35-37; 15. 34. 1, 4;
next morning Yudhiṣṭhira and the rest went
around to see the precincts of the आश्रम
(ददर्शाश्रममण्डलम्) 15. 34. 5-6;
after finishing their round (परीत्याश्रम-
मण्डलम्) Yudhiṣṭhira gave many kinds
of gifts to the ascetics 15. 34. 12-15; the
Pāṇḍavas lived in the forest near the आश्रम
for a month 15. 36. 6-7; (4) While the
Pāṇḍavas were still In the आश्रम, Vyāsa,
by the strength of his austerities, showed
them the miracle, promised before, on
the river Bhāgīrathī which was not done
by any great sage before (न कृतं
यत् पुरा कैश्चित् कर्म लोके महर्षिभिः।
आश्चर्यभूतं तपसः फलं संदर्श-
यामि वः) 15. 35. 24; (वसत्सु पण्डु-
पुत्रेषु सर्वेष्व् आश्रममण्डले।यत् तद्
आश्चर्यम् इति वै करिष्यामीत्य् उवाच ह।
व्यासः) 15. 36. 2-3; (the miracle is describ-
ed in 15. 40-41); (5) After witnessing
the miracle, Dhṛtarāṣṭra returned to the
आश्रम; Vyāsa instructed him there and
asked him to give permission to the Pāṇḍa-
vas to return to Hāstinapura 15. 44. 2, 5-11,
21, 52.
D. Simile: The आश्रम filled with
people curious to see it compared with the
sky full of stars (आश्रमम् … दिदृक्षुभिः
समाकीर्णं नभस् तारागणैर् इव) 15.
31. 20.

धृतराष्ट्रस्य
Dhṛtarāṣṭrasya āśramaḥ2 m.: आश्रम
of Dhṛtarāṣṭra.
When Dhṛtarāṣṭra went from Kuru-
kṣetra to Gaṅgādvāra he established there
another आश्रम on the river Gaṅgā 15.
45. 10; once, when Dhṛtarāṣṭra had bathed
in Gaṅgā and was facing his आश्रम strong
wind blew and a great forest fire suddenly
arose in which Dhṛtarāṣṭra, Gāndhārī and
Kuntī were burnt to ashes (ततः कदा-
चिद् गङ्गायाः कच्छे स नृपसत्तमः।
गङ्गायाम् आप्लुतो धिमान् आश्रमाभिमुखो
ऽभवत्।अथ वायुः समुद्भूतो दावाग्निर्
अभवन् महान्) 15. 45. 18-19, 31.

धौम्याश्रम
Dhaumyāśrama m.: Hermitage of
Dhaumya.
Situated near the तीर्थ Utkocaka
(तत उत्कोचकं तीर्थं गत्वा धौम्या-
श्रमं तु ते); as advised by the Gan-
dharva Citraratha, the Pāṇḍavas reached
the आश्रम of Dhaumya and chose Dhau-
mya as their Purohita; Dhaumya received
the Pāṇḍavas in his आश्रम by offering
them water to wash feet and fruits and
roots and by agreeing to be their Purohita
(तान् धौम्यः प्रतिजग्राह … ।पाद्येन
फलमूलेन पौरोहित्येन चैव ह॥) 1.
174. 6-7.

नन्दाश्रम
Nandāśrama m.: Name of an आश्रम।
One of the holy places and आश्रमस्
(पुण्येषु देशेषु 5. 187. 24) where the prin-
cess of Kāśi (Ambā) stayed to practise
austerities for the death of Bhīṣma 5. 187.
25; all the आश्रमस् were of high-souled as-
cetics who were extremely pious (आश्रमं
पुण्यशीलानां तापसानां महात्मनाम्)
5. 187. 23; at these holy places the princess
bathed day and night and practised auste-
rities (तत्र पुण्येषु देशेषु साप्लुताङ्गी
दिवानिशम्।व्यचरत् काशिकन्या सा) 5. 187.
24; (एतेषु तीर्थेषु … आप्लावयत गात्राणि
तीव्रम् आस्थाय वै तपः) 5. 187. 28.

नन्दिग्राम
Nandigrāma m.: Name of a village.
During Rāma's term of exile, Bharata,
stayed at Nandigrāma and ruled from there
keeping before him Rāma's sandals (नन्दि-
ग्रामे ऽकरोद् राज्यं पुरस्कृत्यास्य पादु-
के) 3. 261. 38; when Rāma returned to
Ayodhyā, he first sent Hanūmant as his
messenger to Bharata; Hanūmant met
Bharata at Nandigrāma and told him the
good news (of Rāma's return); when
Hanūmant returned after meeting Bharata,
Rāma went to Nandigrāma 3. 275. 60.

नरनारायणाश्रम
Naranārāyaṇāśrama, Nārāyaṇāśrama1
m.: Name of a very holy hermitage, also
called Naranārāyaṇasthāna (1. 64. 24; 3.
145. 37), Nārāyaṇasthāna (3. 174. 9).
A. Location: Listed by Lomaśa among
the holy places in the north (उदीच्यां …
दिशि) 3. 88. 1; situated on the Gandha-
mādana mountain (पर्वतं गन्धमाद-
नम्। … यत्र नरनाराय्व्णाश्रमः) 3. 142.
22-23; on a place near the large Badarī tree
(नारायणः … ।तस्य … पुण्यां विशालां
बदरीम् अनु।आश्रमः ख्यायते) 3. 88. 21-
22; 3. 142. 23; 3. 145. 17, 23; 3. 174. 8-9;
12. 126. 2-3; the river Bhāgīrathī flew near
it (नरनारायणस्थानं भागीरथ्योप-
शोभितम्) 3. 145. 37; (नरनारायण-
स्थानं गङ्गयेवोपशोभितम्) 1. 64. 24;
near the Kailāsa mountain (कईलासम् … ।
तस्याभ्याशे तु ददृशुर् नरनारायणा-
श्रमम्) 3. 145. 15-16.
B. Descrip-
tion: Resorted to by the sages Nara
and Nārāyaṇa (नरनारायणाश्रित) 3.
145. 23; (आश्रमम् … ।रेमाते यत्र तौ
नित्यं नरनारायणाव् ऋषी) 12. 126. 4-5;
holy (पुण्य) 3. 88. 22; 3. 145. 23, 24, 35;
heavenly (दिव्य) 3. 145. 26, 28; 12. 126. 2;
pleasing (मनोरम) 3. 145. 35; indescriba-
ble (अनिर्देश्य) 3. 145. 28; full of splend-
our (शोभया युक्तम्) 3. 145. 36; endowed
with lustre (श्रिया युतम्) 3. 145. 28; shin-
ing with brahmanical lustre (ब्राह्म्या
लक्ष्म्या समन्वितम्) 3. 145. 25; looking
like the residence of Śakra (शक्रसदन-
प्रख्य) 3. 145. 35; comparable to heaven
(स्वर्गोपम) 3. 145. 35; famous in the
three worlds (त्रिषु लोकेषु विश्रुतः) 3. 88.
22; fit to be resorted to (आश्रयणीय) 3.
145. 28; removing fatigue (श्रमनाशन)
3. 145. 28; destroying sorrow (शोकनाशन)
3. 145. 24; free from the afflictions caused
by hunger, thirst, cold and heat (क्षुत्तृट्-
शीतोष्णदोषैश् च वर्जितम्) 3. 145. 24; free
from wrath and greed (अपेतक्रोधलोभो
ऽयं आश्रमः) 5. 94. 21; free from dark-
ness (तमसा रहितम्) 3. 145. 24; not
penetrated by the rays of the sun (अनादृ-
ष्टं रवेह् करैः) 3. 145. 24; honoured by
gods and divine sages (देवदेवर्षिपूजित)
3. 145. 37; full of hosts of great sages
(महर्षिगणसंबाध) 3. 145. 25; resor-
ted to by great sages and ascetics (महर्-
षिभिः … यतिभिः … उपेतम्) 3. 145. 29-30;
offering shelter to all beings (शरण्यं
सर्वभूतानां) 3. 145. 27; beautified by
the service to gods (देवचर्योपशोभित) 3.
145. 28 (Nī. on Bom. Ed. 3. 145. 32: देव-
चर्या सत्यसंकल्पत्वादिका); resounding
with the sound of Vedic recitations (ब्रह्-
मघोषनिनादित) 3. 145. 27; honoured by
the बलि and fire offerings (बलिहोमार्चित)
3. 145. 26; having many large fire-halls
(विशालैर् अग्निशरणैः … आचितम्) 3. 145. 27;
full of heavenly trees always laden with
flowers and fruits (उपेतं पादपैर् दिव्यैः
सदापुष्पफलोपगैः) 3. 145. 16; well
swept and well smeared (सुसंमृष्टानु-
लेपन) 3. 145. 26 (Nī. on Bom. Ed. 3. 145.
29: सुष्ठु संमृष्टं संमार्जनम् अनु-
लेपनं च यत्र); shining on all sides with
the offerings of heavenly flowers (दिव्य-
पुष्पोपहारैश् च सर्वतो ऽभिविराजितम्)
3. 145. 26; adorned with big and sturdy
water vessels (महद्भिस् तोयकलशैः
कठिनैश् चोपशोभितम्) 3. 145. 27 (but
Nī. on Bom. Ed. 3. 145. 30: कठिनैः
शिक्यैः करण्डैर् वा); filled with shining
ladles and vessels (स्रुग्भाण्डैर् आचितं
शुभैः) 3. 145. 27; difficult of access to men
who were placed outside the pale of religion
(दुष्प्रवेशं … नरैर् धर्मबहिष्कृतैः)
3. 145. 25.
C. Characteristic: Aśvaśiras
(Nārāyaṇa) recites the eternal Vedas in
this आश्रम (यत्राश्वशिरा राजन् वेदान्
पठति शाश्वतान्) 12. 126. 3.
D. Epic
events: (1) The Pāṇḍavas saw the आश्रम
at Badarī: they enjoyed themselves there
looking at different sights; they lived there
for six nights anxious to meet Arjuna 3.
145. 23, 37, 39-43; 3. 146. 1; (2) After
killing Jaṭāsura, the Pāṇḍavas returned to
Nārāyaṇāśrama 3. 155. 1; (3) After meet-
ing Arjuna, the Pāṇḍavas on their return
journey, again stayed at the Nārāyaṇa-
sthāna (ऊषुस् ततस् तत्र … नारायणस्थान-
गता नराग्र्याः) 3. 174. 9.
E. Past events:
(1) Ṛṣabha, a brahmanical sage (विप्रर्षि),
told king Sumitra that once, while he was
on a pilgrimage, he happened to reach
Naranārāyaṇāśrama; he bathed in the lake
Vaihāyasa which was nearby, satisfied
manes and gods according to the rites,
and returned to the आश्रम; he stayed at a
place not far from the आश्रम 12. 126. 2.
4-5; while living there he met a sage called
Tanu and, later, king Vīradyumna who
was searching his lost son Bhūridyumna;
the sages in the आश्रम asked the king the
purpose of his visiting the आश्रम 12. 126.
6, 14, 26-27; (2) Nara and Nārāyaṇa
told king Dambhodbhava who sought a
duel with them that the आश्रम was not
the right place for a duel, nor for the use
of weapons, nor for the practice of false-
hood (न ह्य् अस्मिन्न् आश्रमे युद्धं कुतः
शस्त्रं कुतो ऽनृजुः) 5. 94. 21.
F. Simile:
The आश्रम of Kaṇva along the river
Mālinī looked like the Naranārāyaṇasthāna
along the river Gaṅgā (अलंकृतं … मालि-
न्या … नरनारायणस्थानं गङ्गयेवोप-
शोभितम्) 1. 64. 24. [See Badarī, Badaryā-
śrama]

नागपुर
Nāgapura, Nāgasāhvaya, Nāgāhvaya1:
See Hāstinapura.

नागाह्वय
Nāgāhvaya2 nt.: Name of the city of
the Nāga Padmanābha (Padma).
A. Location: Situated in the Naimiṣa
forest on the bank of the river Gomatī (नै-
मिषे गोमतीतीरे तत्र नागाह्वयं पुरम्)
12. 343. 2; 12. 345. 12; 12. 349. 4; Nāga
Padmanābha, also called Padma, resided
there 12. 343. 4; hence called the resort
of the lord of the नागास् (भुजगेन्द्र-
संश्रय) 12. 344. 10.
B. Past events:
(1) All the gods once performed a sacri-
fice at Nāgāhvaya (समग्रैस् त्रिदशैस्
तत्र इष्टम् आसीत्) 12. 343. 3; (2) Here
king Māndhātṛ offended Indra (यत्रेन्द्राति-
क्रमं चक्रे मान्धाता) 12. 343. 3; (3)
Atithi proceeded to Nāgāhvaya to meet
Padmanābha 12. 344. 10.

नारायणाश्रम
Nārāyaṇāśrama2 m.: Name of a her-
mitage.
Located near the lakes of Rāma near
Kurukṣetra (कुरुक्षेत्रस्य मध्यतः) 3.
126. 42; shown by Lomaśa to Yudhiṣṭhira
(पश्य रामह्रदान् एतान् पश्य नारायणा-
श्रमम्) 3. 129. 6.

निर्मोचन
Nirmocana nt.: Name of a city.
Six thousand great Asuras tried to
bind Kṛṣṇa with snares at Nirmocana, but
they did not succeed; Kṛṣṇa cut off those
sharp snares, killed the six thousand Asuras
and Mura, and then proceeded to Nirmo-
cana (निर्मोचने षट्सहस्राः पाशैर्
बद्ध्वा महासुराः।ग्रहीतुं नाशकंश्
चैनम्) 5. 128. 43 (Nī. on Bom. Ed. 5.
130. 45: निर्मोचने नगरविशेषे); (निर्मो-
चने षट्सहस्राणि हत्वा संछिद्य पाशान्
सहसा क्षुरान्तान्।मुरं हत्वा … निर्मो-
चनं चापि जगाम वीरः) 5. 47. 77 (Nī.
on Bom. Ed. 5. 48. 83: निर्मोचने नगरे).

पञ्चस्रोतस्
Pañcasrotas nt.: Name of a place (?)
The great sage Pañcaśikha, who was
looked upon as Kapila incarnate (12. 211.
9), the first pupil of Āsuri, had performed
a सत्र, lastīng for a thousand years, at
Pañcasrotas (पञ्चस्रोतसि यः सत्रम् आस्ते
वर्षसहस्रिकम्) 12. 211. 10 (Nī., however,
on Bom. Ed. 12. 218. 10: पञ्च स्रोतांसि
विषयकेदारप्रणालिका यस्य तस्मिन् मनसि
मानसं सत्रम् इत्य् अर्थः).

पत्तन
Pattana nt.: Name of a city (?)
One of the kings who came for Drau-
padī's स्वयंवर is called Pattanādhipati
(ruler of Pattana) (पत्तनाधिपतिस् तथा)
1. 177. 12.

पर्णशाला
Parṇaśālā f.: Name of a village
(ग्राम).
A. Location: Located in Madhya-
deśa, between the rivers Gaṅgā and Ya-
munā, and at the foot of the mountain
Yāmuna (मध्यदेशे … ।गङ्गायमुनयोर्
मध्ये यामुनस्य गिरेर् अधः) 13. 67. 3.
B. Description: Big (महन्त्) 13. 67. 3;
famous (विख्यात) 13. 67. 4; pleasing (र-
मणीय) 13. 67. 4;
C. Characteristic: It
was a settlement of the Brāhmaṇas, most
of them known for their learning (ग्रामो
ब्राह्मणानां बभूव ह) 13. 67. 3;
(विद्वांसस् तत्र भूयिष्ठा ब्राह्मणाश्
चावसंस् तदा) 13. 67. 4; hence also refe-
rred to as Brāhmaṇagrāma 13. 67. 6.
D.
Past event: Yama once told one of his
men to go to the Brāhmaṇagrāma and br-
ing from there a Brāhmaṇa named Śarmin
belonging to the Agastya गोत्र (अगस्त्यं
गोत्रतश् चापि नामतश् चापि शर्मिणम्) 13.
67. 5-6.

पाञ्चालनगर
Pāñcālanagara nt.: The capital town
Kāmpilya of the southern Pāñcāla country
where Drupada ruled.
The Pāṇḍavas, after the death of Baka
in Ekacakrā, proceeded to Pāñcālanagara
(पाञ्चालनगरम् अभिगताः) 1. 90. 80;
Vyāsa advised the Pāṇḍavas to go to
Pāñcālnagara where they would get Kṛṣṇā
(Draupadī) for their wife (पाञ्चालनगरं
तस्मात् प्रविशध्वं महाबलाः) 1. 157.
15. [See Kāmpilya, Śiśumārapura]

पिङ्गाया
Piṅgāyā āśramaḥ m.: A hermitage so
called.
By bathing at the आश्रम of Piṅgā
one was freed of all sins (पिङ्गायाश् चाश्रमे
स्नात्वा सर्वपापैः प्रमुच्यते) 13. 26. 52.

पिच्छण्ड
Picchaṇḍa nt.: Name of a town.
Sahadeva, in his expedition to the
south (प्रययौ दक्षिणां दिशम् 2. 28. 1)
before the Rājasūya, subjugated Picchaṇḍa
just by sending envoys and made the citi-
zens pay tribute (पिच्छण्डं … ।दूतैर्
एव वशे चक्रे करं चैनान् अदापयत्) 2.
28. 47.

पितॄणाम्
Pitṝṇām āśramaḥ m.: A hermitage so
called.
The तीर्थस् known as Marudgaṇa and
Vaivasvata were probably located near this
आश्रम; if one who is pure bathes in those
तीर्थस् himself becomes as holy as a तीर्थ
(तीर्थभूतो भवेन् नरः) 13. 26. 37.

पुण्य
Puṇya m.: Name (?) of an आश्रम।
The आश्रम of the high-souled Kāśyapa
on the river Kauśikī was called Puṇya
(आश्रमश् चैव पुण्याख्यः काश्यपस्य
महात्मनः) 3. 110. 2 [See Kāśyapāśrama;
for Puṇya, name of a तीर्थ, see Vol. 1.
383].

पुरिका
Purikā f.: Name of a town.
Described as glorious (श्रीमती); a very
cruel king called Paurika once lived in the
city Purikā (पुरिकायां पुरि पुरा श्रीम-
त्यां पौरिको नृपः।परहिंसारुचिः क्रूरो
बभूव पुरुषाधमः॥) 12. 112. 3.

पुलिन्दनगर
Pulindanagara nt.: Name of a town.
Bhīma, in his expedition to the east
(ययौ प्राचीं दिशं प्रति 2. 26. 1) before
the Rājasūya, subjugated Sukumāra and
Sumitra at Pulindanagara; described as a
big town (महन्त्) 2. 26. 10.

पैलगार्ग्यस्य
Pailagārgyasya āśramaḥ m.: Name
of an आश्रम।
One of the holy places where the Kāśī
princess Ambā lived to practise austerities
in order to be able to kill Bhīṣma 5. 187.
27; she bathed at these holy places day and
night and practised severe austerities (आश्र-
मं पुण्यशीलानां तापसानां महात्म-
नाम्॥तत्र पुण्येषु देशेषु साप्लुताङ्गी
दिवानिशम्।व्यचरत् काशिकन्या सा) 5. 187.
24; (एतेषु तीर्थेषु … आप्लावयत गात्राणि
तीव्रम् आस्थाय वै तपः) 5. 187. 28.

पोतन
Potana nt.: Name of a town.
Established by the royal sage Aśmaka,
son of the wife of Kalmāṣapāda begotten
by sage Vasiṣṭha (अश्मको नाम राजर्षिः
पोतनं यो न्यवेशयत्) 1. 168. 25.

प्रतिष्ठान
Pratiṣṭhāna nt.: Name of a city.
Suparṇa took Gālava to king Yayāti
in Pratiṣṭhāna to ask him if he could pro-
vide Gālava with eight hundred white
horses with one black ear each 5. 112. 9.
[For Pratiṣṭhāna, a तीर्थ, see Vol. 1. 388]

प्रमाणकोटि
Pramāṇakoṭi f.: Name of a place on
the river Gaṅgā.
A place on the river Gaṅgā where at
a suitable place Duryodhana once got
ready rest houses made of garments and
कम्बलस् for water sports; there Duryo-
dhana bound Bhīma, who fell asleep due
to fatigue, by fetters made of creepers
and threw him in water (ततो जलविहारा-
र्थं कारयाम् आस भारत।चेलकम्बल-
वेश्मानि … ।प्रमाणकोट्याम् उद्देशं
स्थलं किंचिद् उपेत्य च॥ … प्रमाण-
कोट्यां वाषार्थी सुष्वापारुह्य तत् स्थ-
लम्॥); he also tried to kill Bhīma there
by serpent bites and by mixing poison in
his food 1. 119. 29-30, 32, 34, 36-41 (Nī.
on Bom. Ed. 1. 128. 33; प्रमाणकोट्यां
गङ्गायां प्रदेशविशेषे।स्थलं किंचिद्
अर्धं जले ऽर्धं स्थले च क्रीडागारम्);
these incidents are referred to on various
occasions: (1) by Vaiśaṃpāyana in his
summary of the epic narrative (प्रमाण-
कोट्यां संसुप्तं पुनर् बद्ध्वा वृकोद-
रम्।तोयेषु भीमं गङ्गायाः प्रक्षिप्य
पुरम् आव्रजत्) 1. 55. 9-12 (Nī. on Bom.
Ed. 1. 61. 11: प्रमाणकोट्यां गङ्गायास्
तीर्थविशेषे); (ii) by Draupadī while re-
counting to Kṛṣṇa Duryodhana's misdeeds
(प्रमाणकोट्यां विश्वस्तं तथा सुप्तं
 … ।गङ्गायां प्रक्षिप्य पुनर् आव्रजत्॥)
3. 13. 71-77 (Nī. on Bom. Ed. 3. 12. 82:
प्रमाणकोट्यां प्रमाणाख्यो गङ्गातीर-
स्थो वटविशेषस् तत्प्रदेशे); (iii) By
Bhīma while proclaiming the misdeeds of
the Kauravas at the time of Duḥśāsana's
death (प्रमाणकोट्यां शयनम्) 8. 61. 12;
(iv) By Bhīma while enumerating to
Yudhiṣṭhira the misdeeds of Duryodhana
(सर्पोत्सर्गस्य शयने विषदानस्य भोजने
प्रमाणकोट्यां पातस्य) 9. 55. 20.

प्राग्ज्योतिष
Prāgjyotiṣa m.: Name of a famous city
(called पुर 2. 42. 7; 3. 13. 26; 5. 47. 74;
नगर 14. 74. 3, 6).
A. Location: Situated in the east;
it was encircled by the Kirātas, Cīnas and
other warrior tribes living near the sea coast
(स किरातैश् च चीनैश् च वृतः प्राग्ज्योतिषो
ऽभवत्।अन्यैश् च बहुभिर् योधैः साग-
रानूपवासिभिः॥) 2. 23. 19 (Nī. on Bom.
Ed. 2. 22. 9; प्राग्ज्योतिषं पूर्वसमुद्र-
तीरस्थं नगरविशेषम्); from there
Arjuna proceeded to the north (प्रयास्यामि
दिशं धनदरक्षिताम्) 2. 23. 4; 2. 24. 1.
B. Description: Beautiful (रम्य) 12. 326.
85; difficult of access (दुर्ग) 5. 47. 74;
fierce (घोर) 5. 47. 74; insuperable (असह्य)
5. 47. 74; full of wealth of different kinds
(नानाधनसमन्वित) 12. 326. 85; the city
of Asuras (असुराणां पुरम्) 5. 47. 74.
C. Its rulers: Governed by Bhagadatta
(2. 23. 18) and then by his son Vajradatta
(14. 74. 1); hence they are called Prāgjyoti-
ṣādhipa (Bhagadatta) 2. 47. 12; 5. 164. 35;
(Vajradatta) 14. 75. 16.
D. Epic events:
(1) Arjuna attacked Prāgjyotiṣa during
his expedition before the Rājasūya and
then proceeded to the north 2. 23. 17; 2.
24. 1; Arjuna's battle with Bhagadatta
alluded to in 5. 164. 35-37; (2) King
Bhagadatta of Prāgjyotiṣa brought fine-bred
horses as tribute to Yudhiṣṭhira 2. 47. 12;
(3) Once, during his battle with Kṛṣṇa,
Śālva, riding his Saubha which could move
at will (सौभं कामगमम्), suddenly
went as far as Prāgjyotiṣa 3. 23. 9; (4) The
excellent horse of the Aśvamedha sacri-
fice, while roaming, went to Prāgjyotiṣa
14. 74. 1.
E. Past events: (1) Powerful
Naraka, son of Bhūmi, carried away the
jewelled earrings of Aditi to Prāgjyotiṣa
(महाबलो नरकस् तत्र भौमो जहारा-
दित्या मणिकुण्डले शुभे) 5. 47. 74; (2)
Nārāyaṇa prophesied to Nārada that at
the close of the junction of Dvāpara and
Kali (12. 326. 82) he would be born at
Mathurā; he would then kill Naraka, Mura
and Pīṭha and carry away the wealth of
Prāgjyotiṣa to Kuśasthalī (प्राग्ज्योतिषपुरं
रम्यं नानाधनसमन्वितम्।कुशस्थलीं
नयिष्यामि) 12. 326. 85; Naraka, and his
Dānavas, could not arrest Kṛṣṇa who had
gone to Prāgjyotiṣa 5. 128. 44; (3) When
Kṛṣṇa and the other Sātvata heroes had
gone to Prāgjyotiṣa, Śiśupāla burnt Dvā-
rakā 2. 42. 7; (4) By killing Nisunda and
Naraka, Kṛṣṇa once again made the way
to Prāgjyotiṣa safe (कृतः क्षेमः पुनः
पन्थाः पुरं प्राग्ज्योतिषं प्रति) 3. 13. 26.

बदरी
Badarī f., Badaryāśrama m.: Name
of a tree and also of an आश्रम situated
near it (तम् आश्रमपदं … बदरी नाम
विश्रुतम् 3. 45. 19); once referred to as
Badarāśrama (12. 326. 99).
A. Location: In the north (अस्यां
दीशि … उत्तरायाम्) 5. 109. 3; on the Gandha-
mādana mountain (गन्धमादनम् आसाद्य
बदर्यां च) 1. 32. 3; प्रवेक्षामो …
पर्वतं गन्धमादनम्॥विशाला बदरी
यत्र) 3. 142. 22-23; 3. 145. 2, 10; 12. 321.
13; 12. 330. 41; 12. 331. 22.
B. Descrip-
tion: Holy (आश्रमपदं पुण्य्म्) 3. 45.
19; (पुण्या) 3. 88. 22; auspicious (शुभा)
3. 145. 18; heavenly (दिव्या) 3. 145. 19;
pleasing (रम्या) 12. 126. 3; (मनोरमा)
3. 145. 17; resplendent (स्निग्धा) 3. 145. 17;
very glorious (श्रिया परमया युताम्) 3.
145. 17; very lustrous (अतिद्युतिसमन्विता)
3. 145. 18; extensive (विस्तीर्णा) 3. 145. 18
(see विशाला as its characteristic in the next
section); resorted to by great sages (मह-
र्षिगणसेविता) 3. 145. 19; having a round
trunk (वृत्तस्कन्धा) 3. 145. 17; having
extensive branches (विशालशाखा) 3. 145.
18; offering dense shade (अविरलच्छाया)
3. 145. 17; full of shining, and densely
grown soft leaves (पत्रैः स्निग्धैर् अविर-
लैर् उपेताम् मृदुभिः) 3. 145. 18; always
full of heavenly and densely growing fruit
which are tasty and have sweet juice
(फलैर् उपचितैर् दिव्यैर् आचितां स्वादुभिर्
भृशम्।मधुस्रवैः सदा) 3. 145. 19;
resorted to always by hosts of different
kinds of birds delighted due to excitement
(मदप्रमुदितैर् नित्यं नानाद्विजगणैर्
युताम्) 3. 145. 19; it grew on a region
which was free from biting insects, which
was rich in roots, fruits and water, covered
with green grass, visited by gods and
Gandharvas, on the ground which was
naturally level, auspicious, soft to touch
due to snow, and free from thorns (अदं-
शमशके देशे बहुमूलफलोदके।नील-
शाद्वलसंछन्ने देवगन्धर्वसेविते॥
सुसमीकृतभूभागे स्वभावविहिते शुभे।
जातां हिममृदुस्पर्शे देशेऽपहतकण्टके)
3. 145. 20-21.
C. Characteristics: (1)
Extensive, wide growing, hence often referr-
ed to as विशाला Badarī 3. 13. 12.; 3. 88. 22-
23; 3. 142. 23; 3. 145. 10; 3. 152. 1; 3. 174.
8; 3. 185. 4; 12. 331. 22 (also cf. विस्तीर्णा
in section B above); (2) Characterized by
the आश्रम of the sages Nara and Nārāyaṇa
3. 45. 18-20; 3. 88. 22; 3. 142. 23; 3. 145.
16; (Nārāyaṇasthāna) 3. 174. 9; 5. 109. 4:
13. 153. 42; (3) Gaṅgā originated at
Badarī (यतः प्रववृते गङ्गा) 3. 45. 20;
Gaṅgā flew near it (गङ्गा … विशालां
बदरीम् अनु) 3. 88. 23; (4) Sages and
gods always visit it to bow down to god
Nārāyaṇa (ऋषयो यत्र देवाश् च … प्राप्य
नित्यं नमस्यन्ति देवं नारायोणं वि-
भुम्) 3. 88. 24; (5) It cannot be seen by
gods or by high-souled sages (यन् न शक्यं
सुरैर् द्रष्टुं ऋषिभिर् वा महात्मभिः।
तद् आश्रमपदं पुण्यं बदरी नाम वि-
श्रुतम्॥) 3. 45. 19; (6) One could see the
lotus pond loved by Kubera from Badarī
(कुबेरकान्तां नलिनीम्) 3. 174. 9-10.
D. Epic events: (1) Ghaṭotkaca and his
Rākṣasas carried the Pāṇḍavas, Draupadī
and the Brāhmaṇas to Badarī 3. 145. 10,
22; (2) Bhīma told the Rākṣasas, guard-
ing the lotus lake of Kubera, that he with
his brothers had reached Badarī from
where he went out in search of the lotus
having heavenly fragrance 3. 152. 1; (3)
On their return journey from Gandha-
mādana, the Pāṇḍavas reached Badari and
lived there for a month 3. 174. 8, 11; (4)
Dhṛtarāṣṭra while praising Kṛṣṇa said that
he knew him as the greatest sage who had
lived with Nara at Badarī for a very long
time (नरेण सहितं देवं बदर्यां सुचि-
रोषितम्) 13. 153. 42.
E. Past events: (1)
As advised by the supreme god Hari Nārā-
yaṇa, Nārada once hastened to Badarāśrama
from Śvetadvīpa to see there Nara and Nārā-
yaṇa (नारदः।नरनारायणौ द्रष्टुं
प्राद्रवत् बदराश्रमम्) 12. 326. 99; he
hastened to Badarī hermitage (बदरीम्
आश्रमं यत् तु नारदः प्राद्रवत् पुनः।
नरनारायणौ द्रष्टुम्) 12. 331. 15-16;
Nārada dropped down to Gandhamādana
from the peak of the great mountain Meru
in order to reach Badaryāśrama (महा-
मेरोर् गिरेः शृङ्गात् प्रच्युतो गन्धमाद-
नम्।नारदः … तं देशम् अगमद् राजन्
बदर्याश्रमम्) 12. 321. 13-14; (निपपात
च खात् तूर्णम् विशालां बदरीम् अनु) 12.
331. 22-23; (2) A brahmanical sage
(विप्रर्षि) told king Sumitra that in the
bygone days, while he was once on a pil-
grimage (तीर्थान्य् अनुचरन्), he reached
Naranārāyaṇāśrama near Badarī 12. 126.
2-3; (3) At Badarī, Manu, with raised
hands, standing on one foot, head bent
downwards and with unblinking eyes, pra-
ctised severe austerities for ten thousand
years (ऊर्ध्वबाहुर् विशालायां बदर्याम्
स … ।एकपादस्थितस् तीव्रं चचार सुम-
हत् तपः॥अवाक्शिरास् तथा चापि नेत्रैर्
अनिमिषैर् दृढम्) 3. 185. 4-5; (4) Ser-
pent Śeṣa was disgusted with the behavi-
our of his brother-serpents; hence, among
other holy places, he repaired to Badarī
to practise austerities 1. 32. 3; (5) In
the Kṛta age a Rākṣasa named Cārvāka
practised austerities for many years at
Badarī 12. 39. 39; (6) In the Kṛta age
Nara and Nārāyaṇa went to Badaryāśrama
in a golden cart to practise austerities
(बदर्याश्रमम् आसाद्य शकटे कनका-
मये) 12. 321. 10; there they practised
austerities for several myriad years (वर्षा-
युतान् बहून्) 3. 41. 1; 12. 330. 41; (7)
Kṛṣṇa practised austerities with raised
hands and standing on one foot, living only
on wind, at Viśālā Badarī for hundred
years 3. 13. 12; (8) After destroying the
sacrifice of Dakṣa, the शूल of Rudra rushed
with great force to Badaryāśrama (सहसा-
गच्छद् बदर्याश्रमम् अन्तिकात्) and fell
with great vehemence on the chest of Nārā-
yaṇa 12. 330. 44. [See Naranārāyaṇāśrama;
for Badarikā tīrtha see Vol. 1. 393]

ब्रह्माश्रमपद
Brahmāśramapada nt.: The place where
the Brahmāśrama stood.
A. Location: On the slope of Hima-
vant (हिमवतः पार्श्वे) 13. 10. 5.
B. Des-
cription: Holy (पुण्य) 13. 10. 6; pleasing
(रम्य) 13. 10. 7; surrounded by flowering
forests (पुष्पितकानन) 13. 10. 7; full of
many clusters of different kinds of trees
(नानावृक्षगणायुत) 13. 10. 6; full of
many shrubs and creepers (बहुगुल्मलता-
कीर्ण) 13. 10. 6; resorted to by deer and
birds (मृगद्विजनिषेवित) 13. 10. 6; full of
sounds of Siddhas and Cāraṇas (सिद्ध-
चारणसंघुष्ट) 13. 10. 7: full of many
ascetics observing vows, adorned by ascetics,
thronged by brahmanical ascetics observ-
ing regulations and vows, full of those who
were initiated, who took limited food, and
who had disciplined themselves, resorted
to by Vālakhilyas and many mendicants
(व्रतिभिर् बहुभिः कीऋणं तापसैर् उपशो-
भितम्॥ब्राह्मणैश् च … नियमव्रतसं-
पन्नैः समाकीर्णं तपस्विभिः।दीक्षितैर्
 … यताहारैः कृतात्मभिः॥ … वालखिल्यैश्
च बहुभिर् यतिभिश् च निषेवितम्) 13. 10.
7-9; resounding with the sounds of Vedic
recitations (वेदाध्ययनघोषैश् च नादि-
तम्) 13. 10. 9.
C. Organisation: A कुल-
पति presided over it and decided whether
a newcomer was to be permitted in the
आश्रम 13. 10. 12-15 (see the next section).
D. Past events: A certain Śūdra once
arrived at Brahmāśrama and was honour-
ed by the ascetics; he desired to practise
धर्म (इच्छामि धर्मं चर्तुम्) 13. 10.
13, and hence requested the head of the
आश्रम (कुलपति) to teach him and initiate
him into the ascetic practices (तन् मां त्वं
भगवन् वक्तुं प्रव्राजयितुम् अर्हसि) 13.
10. 13 (Nī. on Bom. Ed. 13. 10. 14: प्रव्राज-
यितुम् विधिवत् स्वोचितं कर्म त्याजयितुम्);
the head of the आश्रम told him that it was
not possible for him to be an ascetic (प्र-
व्राजक) and live in the आश्रम (न शक्यम्
इह शूद्रेण लिङ्गम् आश्रित्य वर्तितुम्) 13.
10. 15 (Nī. on Bom. Ed. 13. 10. 16: लिङ्गं
संन्यासचिह्नम्); so the Śūdra went some
distance from the आश्रमपद and constru-
cted a cottage for himself; he put up an
altar, levelled the ground, and raised abodes
for gods (गत्वाश्रमपदाद् दूरम् उटजं
कृतवांस् तु सः।तत्र वेदिं च भूमिं
च देवतायतनानि च।निवेश्य।) 13. 10. 17
(Nī., however, on Bom. Ed. 13. 10. 20:
वेदीं पूजार्थं, भूमिं शयनाद्यर्थम्);
a certain ascetic (मुनि, ऋषि, तापस) who
acted as a priest for the rites of manes
(पितृकार्य) of this Śūdra became in his
next birth the Purohita of the king (viz.
the Śūdra who was born as a king); when
the Purohita was told by the king about his
past life he went to the same Brahmāśrama
to practise austerities; he obtained great
perfection (सिद्धिं परां प्राप्तः) and
was respected by the residents of the
आश्रम 13. 10. 10-59.

ब्राह्मणग्राम
Brāhmaṇagrāma m.: See Parṇaśālā.

भगस्य
Bhagasya āyatanam nt.: Nāme of a
holy resort (temple ?) of Bhaga.
A. Location: In a forest, not very
far from the sea and the तीर्थ called
Śūrpāraka (शूर्पारकं ददर्श॥तत्रो-
दधेः कंचिद् अतीत्य देशम् … वनम् आस-
साद) 3. 118. 8-9; (स तत्र … भगस्य …
आयतनानि तेषां ददर्श) 3. 118. 10. 12-13.
B. Description: Holy (पुण्य) and very
attractive (सुमनोहर) 3. 118. 13.
C. Epic
event: Yudhiṣṭhira visited it and many
other आयतनस् in that forest; he bathed in
all the तीर्थस् at the आयतनस् and observed
different fasts; after giving as gifts precious
gems he returned to Śūrpāraka 3. 118. 13-
14.

भरतस्य
Bharatasya āśramaḥ m.: Name of the
आश्रम of Bharata.
On the river Kauśikī (कौशिकीं तत्र
सेवेत); described as one which frees the
visitor from all sins (सर्वपापप्रमोचन);
by visiting it one gets the fruit of performing
a Rājasūya sacrifice 3. 82. 113.

भरद्वाजाश्रम
Bharadvājāśrama m.: Name of the
आश्रम of Bharadvāja.
A. Description: The आश्रम had a
shed for sacred fire (अग्निहोत्र 3. 137.
17; Nī. on Bom. Ed. 3. 136. 17; अग्नि-
होत्रे अग्निहोत्रशालायां; अग्न्यागार 3. 138.
7) where Bharadvāja gave offerings in
fire (अग्निहोत्र) 3. 137. 17; the अग्न्या-
गार was guarded by a blind शूद्र
(शूद्रेणान्धेन रक्षिणा 3. 137. 18; 3.
138. 3.
B. Past events: (1) When
Bharadvāja, after doing the daily Vedic
recitation returned to his आश्रम, the fires,
as usual, did not stand up to greet him
(भरद्वाजस् तु कौन्तेय कृत्वा स्वाध्या-
यम् आह्निकम् … प्रविवेश स्वम् आश्रमम्।
 … पावकाः।न त्वेनम् उपतिष्ठन्ति) 3.
138. 1-2 (Nī. on Bom. Ed. 3. 137. 1:
आह्निकं स्वाध्यायं प्रत्यहं कर्तव्यं
ब्रह्मयज्ञम्); on enquiry, Bharadvāja was
told by the blind Śūdra that as his son was
trying to enter the अग्न्यागार he was stopped
by him (the Śūdra) and the son was killed
by a Rākṣasa 3. 137. 17-19; 3. 138. 7-8);
(2) The Kāleya demons used to hide
themselves in the ocean during the day; at
night they used to come out and eat the
sages living in holy places and आश्रमस्;
once they killed twenty sages from the
आश्रम of Bharadvāja who were self-contro-
lled, observed celibacy, and lived on air
and water (भरद्वाजाश्रमे चैव नियता
ब्रह्मचारिणः।वाय्वाहाराम्बुभक्षाश् च
विंशतिः संनिपातिताः) 3. 100. 1-2, 5; (3)
When the Hehayas defeated king Divodāsa,
he fled from his town and took shelter with
Bharadvāja in his आश्रम (स त्व् आश्रमम्
उपागम्य भरद्वाजस्य धीमतः।जगाम
शरणं राजा) 13. 31. 23.

भरुकच्छ
Bharukaccha m.: Name of a town.
Sahadeva in his expedition to the south
before the Rājasūya (प्रययौ दक्षिणां
दिशम् 2. 28. 1) reached it and from there
he sent envoys to Paulastya Vibhīṣaṇa
2. 28. 50; the Śūdras from Bharukaccha
(शूद्राः … भरुकच्छनिवासिनः) brought
as tribute to Yudhiṣṭhira for his Rājasūya
a hundred thousand Dāsīs, skins of Raṅku
deer and horses from Gandhāra country
(राङ्कवान्य् अजिनानि च। … हयान् गान्धार-
देशजान्) 2. 47. 7-8.

भूतिलय
Bhūtilaya m.: Name of a village.
Situated in the Bāhlīka (Āraṭṭa)
country 8. 30. 40; a certain Brāhmaṇa sitting
in the Sabhā of the Kauravas had said that
one who bathed at Bhūtilaya could not
hope to go to heaven (भूतिलये स्नात्वा
कथं स्वर्गं गमिष्यति) 8. 30. 42 (accor-
ding to Nī. on Bom. Ed. 8. 44. 41 there was
a pond which was used commonly by both
Caṇḍālas and Brāhmaṇas (hence it was
unholy): भूतिलये हि चन्डालब्राह्मण
साधारण एको जलाशयस् तत्र च स्नातः
कथं स्वर्गं गच्छेन् न कथंचिद् इत्य्
अर्थः); Bhūtilaya is also mentioned in
an अनुवंश stanza which reports what a
Piśācī told a Brāhmaṇī who, with her
son(s), had come to stay on the river
Raupyā; she told the Brāhmaṇī that after
bathing at Bhūtilaya she could not stay near
Raupyā for more than one night; and if
she did stay, some calamity would over-
take her at night (तद्वत् भूतिलये स्ना-
त्वा सपुत्रा वस्तुम् इच्छसि॥एकरात्रम्
उषित्वेह द्वितीयं यदि वत्स्यसि।एतद् वै
ते दिवा वृत्तं रात्रौ वृत्तं अतो ऽन्यथा)
3. 129. 9-10; (according to Nī. on Bom.
Ed. 3. 129. 9 in the opinion of the eastern
critics (प्राञ्चः) Bhūlilaya was a village
of the Dasyus where burnt corpses were
thrown in the river (hence it was unholy),
cf. भूतिलये दस्युग्रामे अग्निदग्धानां
मृतानां क्षेपणं यस्यां नद्यां क्रियते
तस्यां स्नातासि; according to a Dharmaśāstra
stanza cited by Nī. a Brāhmaṇa who had
lived in Bhūtilaya was to observe Prājāpatya
vrata as an expiation: एतत्करणे प्रायश्-
चित्तं धर्मशास्त्रे प्रसिद्धम्। … प्रोष्य
भूलिलये विप्रः प्राजापत्यं व्रतं चरेत्;
in the opinion of the critics nearer to Nī.
(अर्वाञ्चः) भूलिलय meant pure ब्रह्मन्
(भूतिर् ऐश्वर्यम्।तस्यापि च लयो ऽस्मिन्न्
इति शुद्धं ब्रह्म) and स्नात्वा meant
मलं त्यक्त्वा).

भृगोर्
Bhṛgor āśramaḥ1 m.: The आश्रम
established by Bhṛgu.
Past events: (1) King Yuvanāśva,
who lived in forest, entered the आश्रम of
Bhṛgu and drank from a jar filled with
water that was sanctified with the मन्त्रस्
and consecrated with austerities (संभृतो
मन्त्रपूतेन वारिणा कलशो महान् 3. 126.
10; आपस् तपसा चैव संभृताः 3. 126. 18);
(the waters were meant for the queen and
were to cause birth of a son) 3. 126. 8,
12, 14; (2) When Bhṛgu had gone to
bathe, a certain Rakṣas approached his
आश्रम; entering it, he saw there Pulomā,
the wife of Bhṛgu; the Rakṣas was re-
ceived by Pulomā (in the आश्रम) with
fruits and roots 1. 5. 13-15; the Rakṣas
wanted to abduct Pulomā from the आश्रम
after ascertaining from Agni that Pulomā
was really the wife of Bhṛgu 1. 5. 20, 25;
(3) When Vītahavya's sons were killed
by Pratardana, he (Vītahavya) abandoned
his city and fled to the आश्रम of Bhṛgu
(प्राद्रवन् नगरं हित्वा भृगोर् आश्रमम्
अप्य् उत) 13. 31. 41; Pratardana followed
Vītahavya to Bhṛgu's आश्रम; he told Bhṛgu
that he wanted to see his pupils living in the
आश्रम; knowing this, Bhṛgu came out of
the आश्रम, honoured Pratardana, and was
told that there was no Kṣatriya living in
the आश्रम; all the inmates of the आश्रम
were twice-born; as a result, Vītahavya
became a Brāhmaṇa; Pratardana was happy
that he was instrumental in bringing about
the change in the जाति of Vītahavya (change
from क्षत्रिय to द्विज) 13. 31. 43-51. [See
Cyavanasya āśramaḥ above p. 528 and
Bhṛgutuṅga Vol. 1. 5, p. 400]

भृगोर्
Bhṛgor āśramaḥ2: The आश्रम of
Bhṛgu (i. e. of Bhṛguśārdūla (12. 3. 1),
viz. Paraśurāma).
A. Location: Near the Mahendra
mountain (जगाम सहसा रामं महे-
न्द्रं पर्वतं प्रति) 12. 2. 14; (महेन्द्रे
पर्वतोत्तमे) 12. 2. 17; not far from the
ocean (समुद्रान्ते … आश्रमान्तिके) 12. 2.
19.
B. Epic event: Karṇa, who had
approached Rāma for ब्रह्मास्त्र, lived in
this आश्रम; once, while he was wandering
on the seashore near the आश्रम he in-
advertently killed the cow of a Brāhmaṇa
(स कदाचित् समुद्रान्ते विचरन्न् आश्रमा-
न्तिके) 12. 2. 19; Karṇa, after he received
the ब्रह्मास्त्र, lived happily in the आश्रम
of Bhṛgu (i. e. Rāma) (विदितास्त्रस् ततः
कर्णो रममाणो ”श्रमे भृगोः) 12. 3. 3;
once, while Rāma was wandering near his
आश्रम with Karṇa, he slept placing his
head on the lap of Karṇa (ततः कदाचित्
रामस् तु चरन्न् आश्रमम् अन्तिकात्।कर्णेन
सहितो … सुष्वाप … कर्णस्योत्सङ्ग आधाय
शिरः) 12. 3. 4-5.

भोगवती
Bhogavatī f.: Name of the city of the
Nāgas.
A. Location: Towards the south
(दक्षिणेत्य् उच्यते ऽथ दिक् 5. 107. 1; अत्र
भोगवती नाम पुरी) 5. 107. 19; below the
earth, from where Śeṣa, the Nāga, holds the
earth on his head (एष शेषः स्थितो नागो
येनेयं धार्यते सदा … मही) 5. 101. 2.
B. City of the Nāgas: It enjoyed the
protection of Vāsuki (इयं भोगवती
नाम पुरी वासुकिपालिता) 5. 101. 1; along
with Vāsuki, it was also protected by
Takṣaka and Airāvata (भोगवती नाम
पुरी वासुकिपालिता।तक्षकेण च नागेन
तथैवैरावतेन च॥) 5. 107. 19; here the
Nāgas, the sons of Surasā and Kaśyapa,
lived without fear (सुरसायाः सुता नागा
निवसन्ति गतव्यथाः) 5. 101. 4; (एते चान्ये
च बहवः कश्यपस्यात्मजाः स्मृताः) 5.
101. 17; they were of different shapes, very
large in number, strong and of fierce nature;
very large in size and having large hoods,
having three or more heads, even a
thousand; marked with gems, स्वस्तिकस्,
wheels and the shapes of कमण्डलु
(मणिस्वस्तिकचक्राङ्काः कमण्डलुक-
लक्षणाः) 5. 101. 5-8; some of the Nāgas
living in Bhogavatī are named 5. 101.
9-16.
C. Similes: (1) The city Bhoga-
vatī was like the excellent city Amarā-
vatī of Indra (यादृषी देवराजस्य पुरी-
वर्यामरावती) 5. 101. 1; (2) (as उप-
मान) (i) The excellent city of Khāṇḍava-
prastha, with its white rampart, shone like
Bhogavatī with its Nāgas (प्राकारेण …
पाण्डुराभ्रप्रकाशेन हिमराशिनिभेन च।
शुशुभे तत् पुरश्रेष्ठं नागैर् भोगवती
यथा॥) 1. 199. 30; (ii) Khāṇḍavaprastha
with the five Pāṇḍavas shone like Bhoga-
vatī with the Nāgas (पञ्चभिस् तैः …
समन्वितम्।शुशुभे तत् पुरश्रेष्ठम्
नागैर् भोगवती यथा॥) 1. 199. 49 (four
of the five implied Nāgas could be Vāsuki,
Takṣaka, Śeṣa and Airāvata); (iii) The
assembly of the kings gathered for the स्व-
यंवर of Damayanti looked like Bhoga-
vatī with the Nāgas (तां राजसमितिं
पूर्णां नागैर् भोगवतीम् इव) 3. 54. 5.

भोजकट
Bhojakaṭa nt.: Name of a city.
A. Location: To the south of Hās-
tinapura (प्रययौ दक्षिणां दिशम्) 2.
28. 1: (दक्षिणाभिमुखो ययौ) 2. 28. 8;
(प्रायाद् विजयी दक्षिणां दिशम्) 2. 28. 37;
not far from Surāṣṭra country (सुराष्ट्र-
विषयस्थश् च प्रेषयाम् आस रुक्मिणे) 2.
28. 40.
B. Description: Excellent (उत्तम)
5. 155. 15; famous on the earth on account
of its large army consisting of many elephants
and horses (सैन्येन महता तेन प्रभू-
तगजवाजिना।पुरं तद् भुवि विख्यातं
नाम्ना भोजकटं नृप) 5. 155. 16.
C.
Epic event: Rukmin did not return to
his former town Kuṇḍina from the place
where he was defeated by Kṛṣṇa; he raised
another town for himself at the place where
he was defeated which came to be known
as Bhojakaṭa (तत्र भोजकटं नाम
चक्रे नगरम् उत्तमम्) 5. 155. 14, 15;
(2) Sahadeva, while he was in Surāṣṭra,
sent for Rukmin, who ruled at Bhojakaṭa;
Rukmin brought jewels as tribute for the
Rājasūya 2. 28. 40, 42.

भोजनगर
Bhojanagara nt.: Name of a town.
Gālava, along with Mādhavī, went to
Bhojanagara to see king Auśīnara (or
Uśīnara 5. 116. 9, 16-17) and to get from
him four hundred white horses having one
black ear on one side 5. 116. 2, 5.

मचक्रुक
Macakruka m., nt. (?): Place name,
(or name of a तीर्थ, short for Macakruka-
tīrtha ?).
It is mentioned along with Tarantuka,
Arantuka, and the lakes of Rāma as form-
ing the boundary of Kurukṣetrasamanta-
pañcaka which is called as the Uttaravedi
of Pitāmaha (Brahmadeva) (तरन्तुका-
रन्तुकयोर् यद् अन्तरं रामह्रदानां च
मचक्रुकस्य।एतत् कुरुक्षेत्रसमन्त-
पञ्चकं पितामहस्योत्तरवेदिर् उच्यते॥)
3. 81. 178 = 9. 52. 20.

मणलूर
Maṇalūra, Maṇipūra nt.: Name of a
city.
A. Location: On the (eastern) seacoast
(समुद्रतीरेण शनैर् मणलूरं जगाम
ह) 1. 207. 13.
B. Epic events: Arjuna,
during his exile, visited it from the Mahen-
dra mountain; he met there king Citra-
vāhana; while he was in that city he
happened to see Citravāhana's daughter
Citrāṅgadā (तां ददर्श पुरे तस्मिन्) 1.
207. 13-15; Arjuna lived in this town for
three years (उवास नगरे तस्मिन् कौन्तेयस्
त्रिहिमाः समाः) 1. 207. 23; (2) Having
freed the five तीर्थास् of the crocodiles,
Arjuna returned to Maṇalūra to meet
Citrāṅgadā; he begot on her a son Babhru-
vāhana 1. 209. 23-24; (3) The horse of
Yudhiṣṭhira's Aśvamedha reached the coun-
try of the king of Maṇipūra (मणिपूर-
पतेर् देशम् उपायात्) 14. 77. 46. (4) When
the Pāṇḍavas and Draupadī set out for
their great journey (महाप्रस्थान),
Citrāṅgadā left Hāstinapura for Maṇipūra
(चित्राङ्गदा ययौ चापि मणिपूरपुरं
प्रति) 17. 1. 26.
C. Mention in titles:
(1) Citravāhana, father of Citrāṅgadā,
called Maṇalūreśvara 1. 207. 14; (2) Ba-
bhruvāhana, who ruled after Citravāhana,
called Maṇipūrapati 14. 77. 46; 14. 78. 39;
14. 81. 21; 14. 82. 1; 14. 88. 19; Maṇipūre-
śvara 14. 78. 2; 14. 81. 1; 14. 82. 18, 23.

मणिपूर
Maṇipūra nt.: See Maṇalūra.

मणिमती
Maṇimatī f.: Name of a city.
Formerly a Daitya named Ilvala and
his younger brother Vātāpi lived in the
town Maṇimatī (इल्वलो नाम दैतेय आसीत् … ।
मणिमत्यां पुरि पुरा वातापिस् तस्य चानु-
जः॥) 3. 94. 4 (Nī. on Bom. Ed. 3. 96. 1
seems to take दुर्जया as an epithet ‘invin-
cible’ of Maṇimatī: दुर्जयायां वातापि-
पुर्यां मणिमतीसंज्ञायां; Durjayā is
mentioned in 3. 94. 1). [See Agastyāśrama,
Durjayā]

मतङ्गस्य
Mataṅgasya āśramaḥ m.: An आश्रम
of Mataṅga.
A. Location: In the east (पूर्वं
प्राचीं दिशं … कीर्तयिष्यामि) 3. 85. 3.
B. Description: Sanctifying (पवित्र),
auspicious (मङ्गलीय), known in the
world (ख्यातो लोके), ancient (सनातन),
great (महन्त्), best (उत्तम) 3. 85. 19.
C. Special feature: Mataṅga had his field
there (केदारश् च मतङ्गस्य) 3. 85. 19.

मत्स्यनगर
Matsyanagara nt.: See Virāṭanagara.

मथुरा
Mathurā f.: Name of a city.
A. Famous for: (1) Milch cows of
holy complexion; Kṛṣṇa gave to the Pāṇḍa-
vas, as a part of dowry, large number of
such milch cows from the place around
Mathurā (माथुरदेश्यानां दोग्ध्रीणां
पुण्यवर्चसाम्। … ददौ जनार्दनः प्री-
त्या) 1. 213. 42-43; (2) Men around
Mathurā known for their skill in wrestling
(मथुराम् अभितश् च ये।एते नियुद्ध-
कुशलाः) 12. 102. 5 (Nī. on Bom. Ed. 12.
101. 5: नियुद्धं बाहुयुद्धम्).
B. Epic
events: (1) Krṣṇa and the other Yādavas
lived happily at Mathurā when Jarāsandha,
after the death of Haṃsa and Dibhaka,
left fighting and returned to his city 2. 13.
44; (2) Kṛṣṇa and the Yādavas fled from
Mathurā out of fear of Jarāsandha and
went to Dvārakā 2. 13. 65.
C. Past event:
Nārāyaṇa had prophesied to Nārada that
at the close of the conjunction of Dvāpara
and Kali he would be born in Mathurā
for the death of Kaṃsa (द्वापरस्य कलेश्
चैव संधौ पर्यवसानिके।प्रादुर्भावः
कंसहेतोर् मथुरायां भविष्यति) 12.
326. 82.

मरुद्गणानाम्
Marudgaṇānām āyatanam: nt. Name
of a holy resort (temple ?) of the Marud-
gaṇas.
A. Location: In a holy forest, not very
far from the sea and the तीर्थ called Śūr-
pāraka (शूर्पारकं ददर्श॥तत्रोदधेः
कंचिद् अतीत्य देशम् … वनम् आससाद)
3. 118. 8-9; (स तत्र … मरुद्गणानाम् …
आयतनानि तेषां ददर्श) 3. 118. 10-11, 13.
For
B. Description and
C. Epic event: see
Bhagasya āyatanam.

महापद्म
Mahāpadma nt.: Name of a city.
Situated on the southern bank of Gaṅgā
(गङ्गाया दक्षिणे तीरे); described as ex-
cellent city (पुरोत्तम); a certain pious
Brāhmaṇa, deliberating on the nature of
Dharma, lived there 12. 341. 1, 6-7.

महाश्रम
Mahāśrama m.: Name of an आश्रम।
A. Description: One that frees from all
sins (सर्वपापप्रमोचन) 3. 82. 48;
B.
Holiness: (1) By staying there for a night
and by abstaining from food for one time in
a day one lives in auspicious worlds (महा-
श्रमे वसेद् रात्रिम्। … एककालं नीराहारो
लोकान् आवसते शुभान्) 3. 82. 48; (2) By
bathing there, by regularly offering Agni-
hotra, and by fasting for a month, one who
is pure, obtains perfection at the end of a
month (महाश्रम उपस्पृश्य यो ऽग्निहोत्र-
परः शुचिः।एकमासं निराहारः सिद्धिं
मासेन सो व्रजेत्) 13. 26. 16.

महेच्छ
Maheccha nt.: Name of a city.
To the west of Khāṇḍavaprastha
(निर्याय खाण्डवप्रस्थात् प्रतीचीम् अभितो
दिशम्) 2. 29. 2; described as having
abundant grain (बहुधान्याक); Nakula
brought it under his control (वशे चक्रे)
in his expedition to the west before the
Rājasūya 2. 29. 6.

महेन्द्रस्य
Mahendrasya Vaiśravaṇasya ca sadman
nt.: The house of Mahendra (Indra) and
Vaiśravaṇa (Kubera).
The eastern direction is so called; it is
guarded by Indra and Vaiśravaṇa; it was
pointed out by Dhaumya to Yudhiṣṭhira
holding him by his right hand (प्राचीं
दिशम् अभिप्रेक्ष्य महर्षिर् इदम् अब्रवीत्॥
 … इन्द्रवैश्रवणाव् एतां दिशं पाण्डव
रक्षतः। … एतद् आहुर् महेन्द्रस्य राज्ञो
वैस्रवणस्य च … सद्म) 3. 160. 3, 5-6;
it is adorned by mountains, forest regions
and woods (पर्वतैश् च वनान्तैश् च कान-
नैश् चोपशोभिताम्) 3. 160. 5; people, sages,
Siddhas, Sādhyas and gods worship sun
rising from there 3. 160. 7.

माण्डव्यस्य
Māṇḍavyasya āśramaḥ m.: Name of
the आश्रम of the sage Māṇḍavya.
A. Epic event: One of the holy places
where Ambā lived to practise austerities
to be able to kill Bhīṣma; these आश्रमस्
were of high-souled ascetics who were holy
(आश्रमं पुण्यशीलानां तापसानां महा-
त्मनाम्) 5. 187. 23; she bathed there day
and night and practised austerities (तत्र
पुण्येषु देशेषु साप्लुताङ्गी दिवानिशम्।
व्यचरत् … ॥ … माण्डव्यस्याश्रमे … एतेषु
तीर्थेषु तदा काशिकन्या … आप्लावयत गात्-
राणि तीव्रम् आस्थाय वै तपः॥) 5. 187. 24,
27-28.
B. Past event: Māṇḍavya once
observed the vow of silence and stood,
with raised hands, under a tree at the
entrance of his आश्रम (माण्डव्यः … स
आश्रमपदद्वारि वृक्षमूले महातपाः।
ऊर्ध्वबाहुर् महायोगी तस्थौ मौनव्रता-
न्वितः॥) 1. 101. 2-3; once, some Dasyus,
who stole wealth and were chased by guar-
dians, reached the hermitage of Māṇḍavya;
they left the stolen property in the residence
of Māṇḍavya and hid themselves (ते
तस्यावसथे लोप्त्रं निदधुः) 1. 101. 4-5.

मार्कण्डेयाश्रम
Mārkaṇḍeyāśrama m.: The आश्रम
of Mārkaṇḍeya.
A. Location: In the Dvaitavana (पुनर्
द्वैतवनं … आजगाम युधिष्ठिरः …
मार्कण्डेयाश्रमं प्रति) 3. 295. 3.
B.
Description: Delightful (रम्य) and having
sweet roots and fruits (स्वादुमूलफल)
3. 295. 3.
C. Epic event: (1) The Pāṇḍa-
vas and Draupadī lived in this आश्रम
after they left the Kāmyaka forest (न्य-
वसन् पाण्डवास् तत्र कृष्णया सह) 3. 295.
4; (2) Formerly, when Bhīṣma went
out for hunting he reached the आश्रम of
Mārkaṇḍeya where he saw many sages
assembled together; Bhīṣma heard there
the narrative (कथैषा कथिता) of Viṣṇu
in which he (Viṣṇu) appeared in the form
of a boar (पुराहं मृगयां यातो मार्क-
ण्डेयाश्रमे स्थितः।तत्रापश्यं मुनि-
गणान् … ॥कथैषा कथिता तत्र कश्यपेन
महऋषिणा) 12. 202. 4-6.

मालिनी
Mālinī f.: See Campā.

माहिष्मती
Māhiṣmatī f.: Name of a city.
A. Location: In the south, near the
river Narmadā (प्रययौ दक्षिणां दिशम्)
2. 28. 1; (दक्षिणाभिमुखो ययौ) 2. 28. 8;
(नर्मदाम् अभितो ययौ) 2. 28. 9; (तथा
माहिष्मतीवासी नीलः … दक्षिणापथवासि-
भिः) 5. 19. 23.
B. Characterized generally
as पुरी 2. 28. 11, 22-23, 34; once as
राष्ट्रम् 2. 28. 25.
C. Special features:
(1) Agni always lived in the city of Māhiṣ-
matī (ततः सांनिध्यम् अद्यापि माहिष्म-
त्यां विभावसोः) 13. 2. 32; (तत्र माहिष्-
मतीवासी भगवान् हव्यवाहनः।श्रूयते)
2. 28. 17. (2) Under the rule of Duryo-
dhana (not Kaurava) his town and king-
dom (नगरं विषयश् चास्य) were full of
jewels, riches, cattle and different kinds of
corn (सस्यैश् चापि प्र्थग्विधैः) 13. 2. 14;
nobody in his kingdom (विषये) was wret-
ched, distressed, afflicted by disease, or
emaciated 13. 2. 15; (3) King Nīla asked
as a boon from Agni freedom from fear
(विभावसुः॥वरेण छन्दयाम् आस तं
नृपम् … अभयं स च जग्राह स्वसैन्ये
वै महीपतिः॥) 2. 28. 20-21; hence who-
ever wished to subjugate the city Māhi-
ṣmatī was burnt down by fire 2. 28. 22;
(4) Also as a result of the boon of Agni,
women of the city Māhiṣmatī, under the
rule of Nīla, could not be withheld from
their desire (?); so women of the town
were unrestrained and they behaved ac-
cording to their desire (तस्यां पुर्यां
तदा चैव माहिष्मत्याम् … ।बभूवुर्
अनभिग्राह्या योषितश् छन्दतः किल॥एवम्
अग्निर् वरं प्रादात् स्त्रीणाम् अप्रतिवारणे।
स्वैरिण्यस् तत्र नार्यो हि यथेष्टं
प्रचरन्त्य् उत॥) 2. 28. 23-24; (5)
Due to the fear of Agni kings avoided
that city (वर्जयन्ति च राजानस् तद् रा-
ष्ट्रं … ।भयाद् अग्नेर्) 2. 28. 25; Agni
told Sahadeva that he would continue to
protect the city as long as the descendents
of Nīla ruled it 2. 28. 54.
D. Epic events:
(1) Sahadeva in his expedition to the
south before the Rājasūya marched on
Māhiṣmatī from Avantī; Māhiṣmatī was
then ruled by king Nīla (पुरीं माहिष्म-
तीम् ययौ) 2. 28. 11; Sahadeva could not
subjugate it as it was protected by Agni
(2. 28. 26; 13. 2. 32); but when he pleased
Agni, the latter withdrew and Nīla recei-
ved Sahadeva (पावके विनिवृत्ते तु नीलो
राजाभ्ययात् तदा।सत्कारेण … सहदेवम्)
2. 28. 36; (2) King Nīla of Māhiṣmatī
went with his southern warriors, using
dark weapons (swords ?) to Duryodhana
to help him in war with the Pāṇḍavas
(ततो माहिष्मतीवासी नीलो नीलायुधैः सह।
महीपालो महावीर्यैर् दक्षिणापथवासि-
भिः) 5. 19. 23; (3) King Nīla of Māhi
ṣmatī, wearing dark armour and, fighting
with a host of chariot fighters, will des-
troy Duryodhana's enemies for he (Nīla)
has formerly formed enmity with Sahadeva
(नीतो माहिष्मतीवासी नीलवर्मधरस् तव।
रथवंशेन शतृऊणां कदनं वै करि-
ष्यति॥) 5. 163. 4-5 (Nī. on Bom. Ed. 5.
166. 4: रथवंशेन रथसंघेन);
(कृतवैरः पुरा चैव सहदेवेन) 5. 163.
5 (a reference to 2. 28. 11-15).
E. Past
events: (1) Daśāśva, the tenth son of
Ikṣvāku, once ruled Māhiṣmatī 13. 2. 6;
(2) In Daśāśva's lineage was born Duryo-
dhana; when Agni asked for Sudarśanā,
daughter of Duryodhana, the latter in
return asked as dowry (शुल्क) Agni's
continuous presence in Māhiṣmatī; hence
Agni was always present in Māhiṣmatī (13.
2. 31-32); Agni's presence in Māhiṣmatī
was witnessed by Sahadeva in his expedi-
tion before the Rājasūya (दृष्टं हि सह-
देवेन दिशो विजयता तदा) 13. 2. 32 (a
reference to 2. 28. 13-15). (3) When
Arjuna Kārtavīrya ruled at Mahīṣmatī, he
ruled the entire earth (कार्तवीर्यो ऽभवत्
प्रभुः। … माहिष्मत्यां महाबलः॥ …
शशास सर्वां पृथिवीं हैहयः) 13. 137.
3-4.

मित्रस्य
Mitrasya Varuṇasya ca āśramaḥ m.:
The आश्रम of Mitra and Varuṇa.
On the river Yamunā (यमुनायां
जगाम ह) 9. 53. 13; Balarāma went to
the आश्रम of Mitra and Varuṇa from the
Kārapacanatīrtha (संप्राप्तः कारपच-
नं तीर्थप्रवरम्। … तस्माच् चापि जगा-
म ह।आश्रमं परमप्रीतो मित्रस्य
वरुणस्य च॥) 9. 53. 11-13; formerly
Indra, Agni and Aryaman were very pleased
to be in this आश्रम (इन्द्रो ऽग्निर् अर्यमा
चैव यत्र प्राक् प्रीतिम् आप्नुवन्) 9. 53. 13;
Balarāma bathed there in Yamunā and
heard stories from the sages and the Siddhas;
when Nārada arrived there, Balarāma heard
from him about the duel that was going to
be fought between Bhīma and Duryodhana;
hearing it, Balarāma went from the आश्रम
to Kurukṣetra 9. 53. 14-15; 29-31, 37.

मिथिला
Mithilā f.: Name of a city.
A. Location: In the eastern Kosala
country, beyond Sarayū river and near
Mālā and Carmaṇvatī rivers (संतीर्य
सरयूं रम्यां दृष्ट्वा पूर्वांश् च कोस-
लान्।अतीत्य जग्मुर् मिथिलां मालां चर्-
मण्वतीम् नदीम्॥) 2. 18. 28; the (capi-
tal) town of the Videhas (विदेहानां
पुरीम्) 12. 308. 11; 1. 105. 11.
B. Descrip-
tion: Pleasing (रम्या) 3. 198. 7; 12. 308.
12; its grove (मिथिलोपवन) was pleasing
(रम्य) and of luxurious growth (महर्-
धिमन्त्) 12. 312. 22; auspicious (शुभा)
3. 198. 6; full of fords for religious practices
(धर्मसेतुसमाकीर्णा) 3. 198. 6; in which
festivals of sacrifices were held (यज्ञो-
त्सववती 3. 198. 6; busy with constant festi-
vals (नित्योत्सवसमाकुला) 3. 198. 8; full of
prosperous people (समृद्धजनसंकुला)
12. 308. 12; full of happy and well nourish-
ed people (हृष्टपुष्टजनाकीर्णा) 3. 198. 8;
thronged by men and women (नरनारी-
समाकुला) 12. 312. 22; it had gates and
watchtowers (गोपुराट्टालकवती) 3. 198.
7; adorned by houses and protective walls
(गृहप्राकारशोभिता) 3. 198. 6; surrounded
by many tall houses (विमानैर् बहुभिर्
वृताम्) 3. 198. 7; full of market goods
(पण्यैश् च बहुभिर् युक्ताम्) 3. 198. 7;
its main roads were well distributed (सुवि-
भक्तमहापथा) 3. 198. 7; having many
horses, chariots, elephants and carriages
(अश्वै रथैस् तथा नागैर् यानैश् च बहु-
भिर् वृताम्) 3. 198. 8; crowded with ele-
phants, horses and chariots (हस्त्यश्वरथ-
संकीर्ण) 12. 312. 22-23; full of activities
(बहुवृत्तान्ता) 3. 198. 9.
C. Its ruler: The
city was ruled and protected by king Janaka
(मिथिलां जनकेन सुरक्षिताम्) 3. 198. 5;
hence Janaka called Mithilādhipa 12. 211.
1, 3; Mithileśvara 12. 308. 8, 12; 12. 312. 6;
Maithila 12. 308. 4; 12. 312. 7; also Vide-
harāja 12. 268. 3.
D. Epic events: (1)
Pāṇḍu reached Mithilā and defeated the
Videhas in a battle 1. 105. 11; (2) Kṛṣṇa,
with Bhīma and Arjuna, while on their
way to the Magadha country, reached Mi-
thilā after crossing the river Sarayū 2. 18. 28.
E. Past events: (1) A certain Brāhmaṇī
once advised the Brāhmaṇa Kauśika to go
to Mithilā where lived a hunter who would
teach him the nature of धर्म (मिथिलायां
वसन् व्याधः स ते धर्मान् प्रवक्ष्यति)
3. 197. 41; 3. 205. 2-3; the Brāhmaṇa deci-
ded to go to Mithilā to meet the hunter and
question him on the nature of धर्म 3.
198. 2-5; the Brāhmaṇa reached the town
and enquired about the Vyādha who knew
धर्म (धर्मव्याध) 3. 198. 7-9; the
Vyādha already knew that the Brāh-
maṇa was directed to go Mithilā by the
Brāhmaṇī 3. 198. 13; (2) King Janaka,
engaged in meditating on the धर्मस् rela-
ted to the condition after death, lived in
Mithilā (जनकः … मिथिलायां जनाधिपः।
और्ध्वदेहिकधर्माणाम् आसीद् युक्तो विचिन्-
तने॥) 12. 211. 3 (But Nī. on Bom. Ed.
12. 218. 3: ऊर्ध्वं देहाद् इत्य् ऊर्ध्व-
देहम् अशरीरं ब्रह्म तत्प्राप्तिकराणाम्
और्ध्वदेहिकानां विचिन्तने युक्तः); (3)
A certain sage by name Pañcaśikha, son of
Kapilā, while wandering on earth reached
Mithilā 12. 211. 6; (4) Sulabhā reached
Mithilā to meet Janaka and to know from
him the nature of मोक्ष 12. 308. 12; (5)
Śuka proceeded to Mithilā on foot to know
the nature of धर्म and मोक्ष 12. 312.
6-7, 12; Śuka reached the grove on the out-
skirts of Mithilā (मिथिलोपवन) before
entering Mithilā 12. 312. 22; (6) Janaka
told a certain Brāhmaṇa that when he got
the ancestral kingdom he was not certain
about his own territory; he sought it on
earth, and when he did not find it there, he
sought it in Mithilā; when he did not find
it even there, he sought it in his subjects
(पितृपैतामहे राज्ये वश्ये जनपदे सति।
विषयं नाधिगच्छामि विचिन्वन् पृथिवीम्
इमाम्॥नाध्यगच्छं यदा पृथ्व्यां मि-
थिला मार्गिता मया।नाध्यगच्छं यदा
तस्यां स्वप्रजा मार्गिता मया) 14. 32. 8-
9 (Nī., however, on Bom. Ed. 14. 32. 8:
विषयं विशेषेण सिनोति बध्नातीति तं
बन्धकं ममतास्पदं नाधिगच्छामि
विचिन्वन् अन्वेषमाणो ऽपि); concerning his
own indifference to the opposīte pairs of
feelings, his disattached condition, and while
visualizing his liberation, Janaka is reported
to have sung a गाथा in which he said that
even if the whole Mithilā was ablaze, nothing
belonging to Janaka was burnt (अपि गाथाम्
इमां गीतां जनकेन वदन्त्य् उत।निर्द्वन्-
द्वेन विमुक्तेन मोक्षं समनुपश्यता॥
अनन्तं बत मे वित्तं यस्य मे नास्ति
किंचन।मिथिलायां प्रदीप्तायां न मे
दह्यति किंचन॥) 12. 17. 17-18; 12. 171.
55-56; with a change in the first quarter
the गाथा also appears as: गीतं विदेह-
राजेन … सुसुखं बत जीवामि यस्य मे
नास्ति किंचन।मिथिलायां प्रदीप्तायां …
12. 268. 3-4.

मुरचीपत्तन
Muracīpattana nt.: Name of a city.
One of the places subjugated by
Sahadeva in his expedition to the south
(प्रययौ दक्षिणां दिशम् 2. 28. 1; दक्षि-
णाभिमुखो ययौ 2. 28. 8) before the
Rājasūya (मुरचीपत्तनं तथा। … वशे
चक्रे) 2. 28. 45-46.

मेरुव्रज
Meruvraja nt.: Name of a city.
A. Events: (1) As advised by Rāja-
dharman, the king of the cranes, the Brāh-
maṇa Gautama, went to Meruvraja, the
city of the Rākṣasa king Virūpākṣa (इत्य्
उक्तः प्रययौ राजन् गौतमः … । … मेरु-
व्रजं नाम नगरम्) 12. 164. 17, 19, 15;
(2) The Rākṣasas returned to Meruvraja
with Gautama and the dead body of Rāja-
dharman 12. 166. 14.
B. Description: Hav-
ing arched doorways made of stone (शै-
लतोरण); having rampart walls built with
stones (शैलप्राकारवप्र); having mecha-
nical bolts made of stone (शैलयन्त्रार्गल)
12. 164. 19.

मोदापुर
Modāpura nt.: Name of a city.
One of the places subjugated by Arjuna
in his expedition to the north (प्रययाव्
उत्तरां तस्माद् दिशम् 2. 24. 1) before the
Rājasūya 2. 24. 10.

यवक्रीतस्य
Yavakrītasya āśramaḥ m.: The her-
mitage of Yavakrī(ta).
A. Location: It was probably establi-
shed by his father Bharadvāja (3. 135. 12-
13, 42) near the आश्रम of Raibhya 3. 137.
1.
B. Description: Described as holy
(पुण्य) and having trees with flowers
and fruits at all times (सदापुष्पफल-
द्रुम) 3. 139. 24.
C. Holiness: One who
stayed there could be free of all sins (अत्रोष्य
राजशार्दूल सर्वपापैः प्रमोक्ष्यसे) 3.
139. 24. [See Bharadvajāśrama]

यवनानां
Yavanānāṃ puram nt.: The city of
the Yavanas.
Located outside the Bhāratavarṣa;
Sahadeva in his expedition to the south of
Hāstinapura प्रययौ दक्षिणां दिशम् 2.
28. 1; दक्षिणाभिमुखो ययौ 2. 28. 8) and
along the seacoast before the Rājasūya sub-
jugated it by just sending his messengers and
made the people of the town pay tribute
(यवनानां पुरं तथा।दूतैर् एव वशे
चक्रे करं चैनान् अदापयत्॥) 2. 28. 49
(The city referred to is possibly Alexandria,
See Edgerton's note on the stanza, Cr.
Edn. Vol. II. p. 502 and his article in JAOS
58. 262-265).

युगन्धर
Yugandhara nt.: Name of a town.
A. Location: In the Āraṭṭa (Bāhlīka)
country (आरट्टा नाम बाह्लीका वर्जनीया
विपश्चिता) 8. 30. 40, 9, 36.
B. Unholy:
If one drank milk at Yugandhara one could
not go to heaven-this is what a Brāhmaṇa
told in the assembly of the Kurus (यद्
अन्यो ऽप्य् उक्तवान् सभ्यो ब्राह्मणः कुरु-
संसदि।युगन्धरे पयः पीत्वा … कथं
स्वर्गं गमिष्यति) 8. 30. 41-42 (Nī. on
Bom. Ed. 8. 44. 39: युगन्धरे नगरे
औष्ट्रादिकम् अपि क्षीरं पीयते, भक्ष्या-
भक्ष्यविवेकाभावात् तत्रावश्यम् अभक्ष्य-
भक्षणम् आपतत्य् एव (cf. 8. 30. 39)); the
town is also mentioned in what a Piśācī
told a woman who, with her son(s), came
to stay near the river Raupyā; according
to the Piśācī one who has eaten curds at
Yugandhara was not supposed to stay near
Raupyā for more than one night; otherwise
some calamity would overtake the person
at night (पिशाची यद् अभाषत।युगन्धरे
दधि प्राश्य … एकरात्रम् उषित्वेह द्वितीयं
यदि वत्स्यसि।एतद् वै ते दिवा वृत्तं
रात्रौ वृत्तं अतो ऽन्यथा) 3. 129. 8-10
(according to the प्राञ्चः whose view is
cited by Nī. on 3. 129. 9 one was required
to undergo a प्रायश्चित्त called प्राजा-
पत्य व्रत, prescribed in the Dharma-
śāstra, if one ate curds at Yugandhara:
अत्र प्राञ्चः। … पिशाची वदति।त्वया युगन्-
धरे पर्वते देशे वा दधिप्राशनं कृतम्।
तत्र उष्ट्रीक्षीरं गर्दभ्यादिक्षीरं च
दधीक्रियते। … एतत्करणे हि प्रायश्चित्तं
धर्मशास्त्रे प्रसिद्धम्।‘औष्ट्रम् ऐक-
शफं क्षीरं सुरातुल्यम्’ इति।‘संसृज्य
संकरैः सार्धं प्राजापत्यं व्रतं
चरेत्’ इति; according to अर्वाञ्चः, however,
eating curds etc. entitled the person to stay
near Raupyā for one night, but not a
second; according to these interpreters of
the stanza युगन्धर meant जीव and
दधिप्राशन meant leading a married life
for paying back the threefold debt: युगन्-
धरः स्थूलशरीराभिमानि जीवः। … दधि-
प्राशनशब्देन धर्मप्रजासंपत्त्यर्थो
दारसंयोग उच्यते। … दधिप्राशन-
शब्देन लक्षितलक्षणया आनृण्यं ग्राह्यम्।
तेन स्वधर्मनिष्ठः प्रजावान् एतत् तीर्थं
सेवितुम् अर्हतीति पूर्वपादार्थः।).

राजगृह
Rājagṛha nt.: Name of a town.
A. Location: The capital town of the
Magadha country (गोप्ता मगधराष्ट्र-
स्य दार्वो राजगृहे हतः) 1. 105. 10; (आसीद्
राजगृहे राजा मागधानाम्) 1. 196. 17.
B. Epic event: (1) Pāṇḍu killed Dārva
the protector of the Magadha country, at
Rājagṛha 1. 105. 10; he collected treasure,
chariots and forces from the city before
marching from there on Mithilā of the
Videha country (ततः कोशं समादाय
वाहनानि बलानि च।पाण्डुना मिथिलां
गत्वा विदेहाः समरे जिताः) 1. 105. 11;
(2) The sacrificial horse of the Pāṇḍavas
reached Rājagṛha town while wandering at
its own will (यदृच्छया समापेदे पुरं
राजगृहं तदा) 14. 83. 2; Meghasaṃdhi
marched out of the town (Rājagṛha) in
a chariot, equipped with bows, arrows,
and arm guards, to attack Arjuna (ततः
पुरात् स निष्क्रम्य रथी धन्वी शरी तली)
14. 83. 2, 4.
C. Past event: Formerly
Ambuvīca was the king of the Magadha
chieftains at Rājagṛha (श्रूयते हि पुरा
कश्चिद् अम्बुवीच इति श्रुतः।आसीद् राजगृहे
राजा मागधानां महीक्षिताम्) 1. 196. 17.
[See Givīvraja; for Rājagṛha tīrtha see Vol. 1.
431-432]

राजपुर
Rājapura1 nt.: Name of a town.
A. Location: In the Kaliṅga country
(कलिङ्गविषये … राजपुरं नाम नग-
रम्) 12. 4. 2-3.
B. Description: Wealthy
(श्रीमन्त्) 12. 4. 3.
C. Epic event: Citrāṅ-
gada ruled this country; when the स्वयं-
वर of the daughter of Citrāṅgada was
held it was attended by Duryodhana,
Karṇa and many other kings 12. 4. 3-4.

राजपुर
Rājapura2 nt. Name of a town.
Located in the Kamboja country; while
referring to the exploits of Karṇa, Bhīṣma
said that he went to Rājapura and killed the
Kāmboja warriors (कर्ण राजपुरं गत्वा
काम्बोजा निहतास् त्वया) 7. 4. 4.

राजाश्रम
Rājāśrama m.: Name (?) of the her-
mitage of a king.
The hermitage was specially created
by king Lomapāda of the Aṅgas (3. 110.
19) on the bank of the river to receive
Ṛśyaśṛṅga when he was brought to Campā;
the आश्रम was indeed a charming forest
(तीराद् उपादाय तथैव चक्रे राजाश्रमं
नाम वनं विचित्रम्) 3. 113. 9 (or, this
to be read as राजा आश्रमं चक्रे and
नाम to be treated as ind.).

रामस्य
Rāmasya āśramaḥ m.: The आश्रम
established by Rāma.
A. Location: On the river Godāvarī
in the Daṇḍakāraṇya (दण्डकारण्यम् आश्रि-
तः।नदीं गोदावरीं रम्याम् आश्रित्य न्य-
वशत् तदा) 3. 261. 40.
B. Rāmāyaṇa
events: (1) Rāvaṇa abducted Sītā from
(Rāma's) आश्रम (जानकी … हृता … आश्र-
माद् राक्षसेन्द्रेण) 3. 258. 1-2; (2) Mārīca
followed Rāvaṇa to the आश्रम of Rāma
(ततस् तस्याश्रमं गत्वा रामस्य) 3. 262.
14; (3) Sītā refused to go with Rāvaṇa and
again entered the आश्रम (इति सा तं समा-
भाष्य प्रविवेशाश्रमं पुनः) 3. 262. 39;
(4) After killing Mārīca, Rāma, anxious
about Sītā who was left alone in the forest,
hastened to his आश्रम (रामो ऽभ्यपतद्
आश्रमम्) 3. 263. 15; (5) When Rāma
reached the आश्रम he found that the
grass-seats and pots there were broken,
the jars were destroyed, the precincts of
the आश्रम were empty, and a herd of
jackals had occupied it (ततो दृष्ट्वाश्र-
मपदम् व्यपविद्धबृसीघटम्।विध्व-
स्तकलशं शून्यं गोमायुबलसेवितम्॥)
3. 263. 22; (6) When Rāma and Lakṣ-
maṇa knew about the abduction of Sītā,
they left the आश्रम in search of her and
went to the south of Daṇḍakāraṇya (वै-
देहीहरणार्दितौ।जग्मतुर् दण्डकार-
ण्यं दक्षिणेन परंतपौ) 3. 263. 23.

रुक्मिण्या
Rukmiṇyā āśramaḥ m.: Name of an
आश्रम।
The आश्रम was near the lake where
कुश grass grew and where there were lotuses
of the type of कुशेशय; Rukmiṇī found
peace there (ह्रदश् च कुशवान् एष यत्र
पद्मं कुशेशयम्।आशृअमश् चैव रुक्-
मिण्या यत्राशाम्यद् अकोपना॥) 3. 130. 15.

रुद्रस्य
Rudrasya āyatanam nt.: Name of the
holy resort (temple ?) of Rudra along
with his गण (रुद्रस्य सगणस्य)) 3. 118.
12.
A. Location: In a forest, not very far
from the sea and the तीर्थ called Śūrpāraka
(शूर्पारकं ददर्श॥तत्रोदधेः कं-
चिद् अतीत्य देशम् … वनम् आससाद) 3. 118.
8-9; (स तत्र … रुद्रस्य राजन् सगणस्य
चैव … आयतनानि तेषां ददर्श) 3. 118.
10, 12, 13. For
B. Description and
C.
Epic event see Bhagasya āyatanam.

रैभ्याश्रम
Raibhyāśrama m.: Name of the
आश्रम of Raibhya.
A. Description: Holy (पुण्य) 3. 137.
2; 3. 139. 24; splendid (श्रीमन्त्) 3. 135. 9;
adorned by flowering trees (पुष्पितद्रुम-
भूषित) 3. 137. 2; having trees with flowers
and fruits at all times (सदापुष्पफलद्रुम)
3. 139. 24.
B. Holiness: One who lives in
Raibhyāśrama is freed of all sins (सर्वपा-
पैः प्रमोक्ष्यसे) 3. 139. 24.
C. Epic
event: The आश्रम was shown by Lomaśa
to Yudhiṣṭhira; the incidents related with
the आश्रम were told by Lomaśa to him
3. 135. 9-3. 139. 23.
D. Past event:
Yavakrī(ta), son of Bharadvāja, once
while wandering reached the precincts
of the आश्रम of Raibhya (जगाम …
रैभ्याश्रमपदं प्रति) 3. 137. 1; Yava-
krī saw in the आश्रम the daughter-in-law
of Raibhya 3. 137. 2; when Raibhya re-
turned to his आश्रम, she told him what
Yavakrī had asked of her 3. 137. 5, 7; the
Rākṣasa after killing Yavakrīta returned
to Raibhya (in his आश्रम) 3. 137. 20; the
sage Yavakrīta perished at the आश्रम of
Raibhya (एष रैभ्याश्रमः … भारद्वाजो
यत्र कविर् यवक्रीतो व्यनश्यत) 3. 135. 9;
when Arvāvasu and Parāvasu, the two sons
of Raibhya, went with king Bṛhaddyumna
to officiate at his sacrifice, Raibhya and the
wife of Parāvasu remained behind in the
आश्रम 3. 139. 3.

रोमा
Romā f.: Name of a city.
It lay outside the Bhāratavarṣa; Saha-
deva, in his expedition to the south of Indra-
prastha (प्रययौ दक्षिणां दिशम् 2. 28. 1;
दक्षिणाभिमुखो युयौ 2. 28. 8; प्रायाद् …
दक्षिणां दिशम् 2. 28. 37) before the
Rājasūya subjugated it just by sending
messengers and made the people pay tribute
(दूतैर् एव वशे चक्रे करं चैनान् अदा-
पयत्) 2. 28. 49 (identified with Rome; cf.
Edgerton JAOS 58. 262 ff. and his note on
2. 28. 49, Vol. 2, p. 502).

रोहीतक
Rohītaka nt.: Name of a city.
A. Identification: According to Nī.,
however, a mountain (Bom. Ed. 2. 32. 5
रोहीतकं गिरिम्).
B. Location: Situated
to the west of Khāṇḍavaprastha (निर्याय
खाण्डवप्रस्थात् प्रतीचीम् अभितो दिशम् 2.
29. 2).
C. Description: Delightful (रम्य),
wealthy (बहुधन), full of cows, horses,
wealth and grain (गवाश्वधनधान्यवन्त्),
dear to Kārtikeya (कार्तिकेयस्य दयितम्)
2. 29. 4.
D. Epic event: Nakula in his
expendition to the west before the Rājasūya
invaded it and there was a great battle with
heroic Mattamayūrakas (तत्र युद्धं
महद् वृत्तं शूरैर् मत्तमयूरकैः)
2. 29. 5 (Nī. on Bom. Ed. 2. 32. 5: मत्त-
मयूरसंज्ञैः क्षत्रियैः).

लङ्का
Laṅkā f.: Name of the city of Rāvaṇa.
A. Location: On the other side of the
ocean (पारे महोदधेः) 3. 262. 33; in the
valley of the Trikūṭa mountain on the
other side of the ocean (पारे समुद्रस्य
त्रिकूटगिरिकन्दरे) 3. 266. 55.
B. History:
Pitāmaha assigned Laṅkā, together with
the Rākṣasas, to Vaiśravaṇa (Kubera) as
the seat of his capital (पितामहस् तु …
ददौ वैश्रवणस्य ह। … राजधानीनिवे-
शं च लङ्कां रक्षगणान्विताम्) 3. 258.
15-16; Kubera, while living in Laṅkā gave
three Rākṣasīs as servants to appease Viśra-
vas, his father 3. 259. 3; Daśagrīva
(Rāvaṇa), son of Viśravas, defeated Kubera
in battle and drove him out of Laṅkā 3.
259. 32; Kubera left Laṅkā and entered
Gandhamādana (हित्वा स भगवाई लङ्काम्
आविशद् गन्धमादनम्) 3. 259. 33; Laṅkā
then belonged to Rāvaṇa and he was its
king (मम लङ्का पुरी नाम्ना) 3. 262.
33; 3. 266. 54; Rāvaṇa called king and
resident of Laṅkā (राज्ञा लङ्कानिवासिना)
3. 263. 39; (लङ्कां भ्रातुर् निवेशनम्) 3.
261. 44.
C. Description: Pleasing (रम्या)
3. 262. 33; naturally unassailable (प्रकृत्य-
इव दुराधर्षा) 3. 268. 2; having strong
ramparts with arched doorways (दृढ-
प्राकारतोरणा) 3. 268. 2; its southern gate
was unapprochable (दक्षिणं नगरद्वा-
रं … दुरासदम्) 3. 268. 24; when besieged
by Rāma, Rāvaṇa made arrangements (for
the fortification) of the town as prescribed
in the शास्त्र (रावणश् च विधिं चक्रे
लङ्कायां शास्त्रनिर्मितम्) 3. 268. 2; the
seven deep trenches around Laṅkā are des-
cribed in 3. 268. 3-5; troops, both stationary
and moving, consisting of many foot-sol-
diers, elephants and horses, were stationed
near all gates of the town (पुरद्वारेषु
सर्वेषु गुल्माः स्थावरजङ्गमाः।बभू-
वुः पत्तिबहुलाः प्रभूतगजवाजिनः) 3.
268. 6; called पूरी 3. 262. 33; 3. 264. 41;
3. 266. 68; 3. 268. 21; महापुरी 3. 266.
54; पुर 3. 268. 6; 3. 270. 29; 3. 271.
1; नगर 3. 268. 24.
D. Rāmāyaṇa
events: (1) Śūrpaṇakhā, when her nose
and lips were cut off, went to Laṅkā the
residence of her brother (ययौ … लङ्कां
भ्रातुर् निवेशनम्) 3. 261. 44; (2) Rāvaṇa
told Sītā that his town Laṅkā lay beyond
the ocean (लङ्का पुरी … पारे महोदधेः)
3. 262. 33; (3) Gandharva Viśvāvasu
told Rāma that Rāvaṇa had carried off
Sītā to Laṅkā 3. 263. 39; (4) Rāvaṇa on
reaching Laṅkā with Sītā placed her in
an आश्रम-like dwelling near the Aśoka
grove which was like Nandana (भवने
नन्दनोपमे।अशोकवनिकाभ्याशे तापसा-
श्रमसंनिभे) 3. 264. 41; (5) Sampāti
told Hanūmant that Rāvaṇa to whom the
big town Laṅkā belonged was known to him
(रावणो विदितो मह्यं लङ्का चास्य महा-
पुरी) 3. 266. 54; (6) Hanūmant burnt
the town (Laṅkā) (ततो दग्ध्वा च तां
पुरीम्) before returning to Rāma 3. 266.
68; Bhīma told Hanūmant that he (Hanū-
mant) alone could destroy Laṅkā with its
warriors and chariots (लङ्कां सयोधां
सहवाहनाम्) 3. 149. 15; (7) When Rāma
with his army crossed the ocean to reach
Laṅkā, he asked the monkeys to destroy
many large gardens there (लङ्कोद्यानान्य्
अनेकशः।कपिभिर् भेदयाम् आस म-
हान्ति च बहूनि च॥) 3. 267. 51; Rāma
is also reported to have burnt Laṅkā with
his sharp arrows (दग्ध्वा लङ्कां शितैः
शरैः) 3. 258. 3; (8) Aṅgada, as messen-
ger of Rāma, reached the gate of Laṅkā
(लङ्कायाः द्वारदेशम्) and entered it 3.
268. 7, 9; Aṅgada leapt over Laṅkā to
return to Rāma (लङ्घयित्वा पुरीं लङ्काम्)
3. 268. 21; (9) Rāma shattered the ram-
part of Laṅkā with the help of his fast
monkey forces (भेदयाम् आस लङ्कायाः
प्राकारं रघुनन्दनः) 3. 268. 23; (10)
Lakṣmaṇa, with Vibhīṣaṇa and Jāmbavant,
broke the unapproachable southern gate of
the town (Laṅkā) (दक्षिणं नगरद्वा-
रम्) 3. 268. 24; Laksmaṇa attacked Laṅkā
with crores of monkeys 3. 268. 25; the
ramparts of Laṅkā appeared tawny with
monkeys moving on it (वानरैः … समन्तात्
कपिलीकृतम्) 3. 268. 28; the monkeys broke
the jewelled pillars and summits of watch-
towers and threw on the town machines
whose speed was checked and destroyed
(by the summits of the towers) (बिभिदुस्
ते मणिस्तम्भान् कर्णाट्टशिखराणि च।
भग्नोन्मथितवेगानि यन्त्राणि च विचिक्षि-
पुः) 3. 268. 29 (Nī. on Bom. Ed. 3. 284.
30: कर्णस् तिर्यग्यानं तेन प्रकारेण यत्
पाषाणादिविस्तरेण क्रियते तत् तद् गृहविशे-
षं कर्णाट्टम् इति वदन्ति); the monkeys
threw the ‘hundred killer’ missiles together
with wheels and stones (hurled) by हुडस् (?)
inside Laṅkā (परिगृह्य शतघ्नीश् च सच-
क्राः सहुडोपलाः।चिक्षिपुर् भुजवेगेन
लङ्कामध्ये) 3. 268. 30; the monkeys
chased the Rākṣasas who stood on the
protective walls (of Laṅkā) (प्राकारस्थाश्
च ये केचिन् निशाचरगणाः) 3. 268. 31; then
the Rākṣasas attacked the monkeys and
cleared the walls (कृतो निर्वानरो भूयः
प्राकारो भीमदर्शनैः) 3. 268. 34; the
arrows of Rāma reached as far as Laṅkā
and killed the Rākṣasas in it (शरजालानि
ववर्ष … ।तानि लङ्कां समासाद्य जघ्नुस्
तान् रजनीचरान्); Lakṣmaṇa too felled
down the Rākṣasas standing at the fort-
ress (of Laṅkā) (दुर्गस्थान् पातयाम् आस
राक्षसान्) 3. 268. 38-39; there was much
fighting in Laṅkā in which the targets
were struck and victory was in view;
then Rāma asked his armies to stop
fighting (कृते विमर्दे लङ्कायाम् ल-
ब्धलक्षो जयोत्तरः॥) 3. 268. 40 (Nī.
on Bom. Ed. 3. 284. 41: लब्धाः आयुधैः
प्राप्ता लक्ष्या वध्या यस्मिन्।अवन्ध्य-
प्रहार इति यावत्।जयोत्तरो जयोत्कर्ष-
वान्); (11) At the fall of Dhūmrākṣa, the
Rākṣasas, attacked by the monkeys, fled
back to Laṅkā in fear 3. 270. 16; (12)
Vajravega and Pramāthin, led by Kumbha-
karṇa, came out of the town (Laṅkā) to
fight with Rāma (तूर्णं निर्ययतुः पुरात्)
3. 270. 29; (ततो विनिर्याय पुरात् कुम्भ-
कर्णः) 3. 271. 1; (13) The empty chariot
of Indrajit, when he and his charioteer
were killed by Lakṣmaṇa, was taken in-
side Laṅkā by the horses (लङ्कां प्रवे-
शयाम् आसुर् वाजिनस् तं रथं तदा) 3.
273. 25; (14) Rāvaṇa came out (of the
city) in his chariot for his fight with
Rāma (निर्ययौ रथम् आस्थाय) 3. 274.
1; (15) After killing Rāvaṇa, Rāma gave
Laṅkā to Vibhīṣaṇa 3. 275. 5; (16) After
making arrangements for the protection of
Laṅkā Rāma, followed by Vibhīṣaṇa,
crossed the ocean, along the same
bridge, riding his Puṣpaka (रामः …
विधाय रक्षां लङ्कायां विभीषणपुरस्-
कृतः।संततार पुनस् तेन सेतुना मकरा-
लयम्॥पुष्पकेण विमानेन) 3. 275. 50-52.

वरुणस्य
Varuṇasya āśramaḥ m.: See Mitrasya
 … āśramaḥ.

वर्धमानद्वार
Vardhamānadvāra, Vardhamānapuradvāra
 nt.: Name of the gate of Hāstina-
pura facing the town Vardhamāna.
Epic events: (1) Kuntī, after the
death of Pāṇḍu, came in the company of the
ascetics and her sons to Kurujāṅgala and
from there she reached the Vardhamāna-
puradvāra before entering Hāstinapura
(सा … संप्राप्ता कुरुजाङ्गलम्।वर्ध-
मानपुरद्वारं आससाद यशस्विनी॥) 1.
117. 8 (Nī. on Bom. Ed. 3. 1. 10: वर्ध-
मानपुरं नाम ग्रामविशेषः।तदभि-
मुखं द्वारम्; however, on 1. 126. 9
he simply says: वर्धमानपुरद्वारं
मुख्यद्वारम्); (2) The Pāṇḍavas when
they left Hāstinapura for their exile, came
out of the Vardhamānapura gate and
went to the north (निर्ययुर् गजसाह्वयात्।
वर्धमानपुरद्वारेणाभिनिष्क्रम्य ते त-
दा।उदङ्मुखाः … प्रययुः॥) 3. 1. 8-9;
(3) When Dhṛtarāṣṭra decided to repair
to the forest he left Hāstinapura coming
out of the Vardhamānadvāra (स वर्ध-
मानद्वारेण निर्ययौ गजसाह्वयात्) 15. 22.
3; (Vardhamānadvāra, according to S. K.
Belvalkar, means ‘an entrance or exit other
than the southern’, cf. दक्षिणाद्वारहीनं
तु वर्धमानम् उदाहृतम् from the Bṛhat-
saṃhitā of Varāhamihira 53. 33. 36 cited by
him. Dr. Belvalkar further observes: “It is
also the name of a specific gate of Hastinā-
pura”, his note on the stanza in the Cr. Ed.
Vol. 19, p. 153. The Bṛhatsaṃhitā passage,
however, seems to mean that a house which
does not have a gate to the south is called
Vardhamāna. The editions of the Bṛhat-
saṃhitā consulted by me read in 53. 33 as
तद्वच् च (or तस्मिंश् च) वर्धमाने
द्वारं तु न दक्षिणं कार्यम्).

वर्धमानपुर
Vardhamānapura nt.: Name of a town.
Suburb of Hāstinapura; one of the
gates of Hāstinapura faced this town; see
Vardhamānadvāra.

वसिष्ठस्य
Vasiṣṭhasya āśramaḥ1 m.: The आश्रम
of Vasiṣṭha.
A. Description: Holy (पुण्य) 1. 165.
1.
B. Past event: Viśvāmitra, when out
for hunting and thirsty, happened to reach
the आश्रम of Vasiṣṭha (मृगलिप्सुः पिपा-
सितः।आजगाम … वसिष्ठस्याश्रमं प्रति)
1. 165. 6; when Viśvāmitra tried to take
away Vasiṣṭha's cow Nandinī by force, she
did not leave the आश्रम of Vasiṣṭha 1.
165. 23; enmity arose between Vasiṣṭha and
Viśvāmitra when the latter stayed in the
आश्रम of Vasiṣṭha (वैरं विश्वामित्र-
वसिष्ठयोः।वसतोर् आश्रमे) 1. 165. 1.

वसिष्ठस्य
Vasiṣṭhasya āśramaḥ3 m.: The आश्रम
of Vasiṣṭha (identical with the above ?)
A. Location: On the confluence of
Niścīrā (निश्चीरासंगमे … तत्राश्रमो वसि-
ष्ठस्य) 3. 82. 120-121.
B. Description:
Famous in the three worlds (त्रिषु लोकेषु
विश्रुतः) 3. 82. 121.
C. Holiness: By
bathing there one got the fruit of perform-
ing a Vājapeya sacrifice (तत्राभिषेकं
कुर्वाणो वाजपेयम् अवाप्नुयात्) 3. 82. 121.

वसिष्ठस्य
Vasiṣṭhasya āśramaḥ3 m.: The आश्रम
of Vasiṣṭha.
A. Location: At Sthāṇutīrtha (also
called Sarasvatītīrtha) on the eastern bank
of the river Sarasvatī (आश्रमो वै वसिष्ठ-
स्य स्थाणुतीर्थे ऽभवन् महान्।पूर्वतः)
9. 41. 4; (अपोवाह वसिष्ठं तु प्राचीं
दिशम्) 9. 41. 34.
B. Description: Great
(महन्त्) 9. 41. 4.
C. Past event: Sara-
svatī carried away Vasiṣṭha from his आश्रम
by withdrawing her bank near it (तेन
कूलापहारेण मैत्रावरुणिर् औह्यत) to
the other side (west) 9. 41. 27-28; later she
carried him back to his side 9. 41. 34. [See
Vasiṣṭhāpavāha Vol. 1. 438 and Sarasvatī
(Past events 11) Vol. 1. 473-474]

वसिष्ठस्य
Vasiṣṭhasya āśramaḥ4 m.: The आश्रम
of Vasiṣṭha.
A. Location: Near the western ocean
(समुद्रं ते समाश्रित्य वारुणम् … काले-
याः संप्रवर्तन्त) 3. 100. 1.
B. Past
event: (1) The Kāleya demons ate at
night the ascetics living in the आश्रम of
Vasiṣṭha (वसिष्ठस्याश्रमे विप्रा भक्षितास्
तैर् दुरात्मभिः) 3. 100. 3; (2) Vasiṣṭha
wanted to end his life when his sons, Śakti
and the rest, were killed; when he failed to
drown himself in the ocean, dejected, he
returned to his आश्रम 1. 166. 45.

वसिष्ठस्य
Vasiṣṭhasya āśramaḥ5 m.: The आश्रम
of Vasiṣṭha.
A. Location: On the mountain Arbuda,
the son of Himavant (हिमवत्सुतम् अर्बु-
दम्। … तत्राश्रमो वसिष्ठस्य) 3. 80. 74-
75.
B. Holiness: By living there for one
night one got the reward of gifting a
thousand cows (तत्रोष्य रजनीम् एकां
गोसहस्रफलं लभेत्) 3. 80. 75.

वसिष्ठस्य
Vasiṣṭhasya āśramāḥ6 m.: The आश्रम
of Vasiṣṭha.
Situated near the Badarīpācana tīrtha
(बदरीपाचनं गच्छेद् वसिष्ठस्याश्रमं
प्रति) 3. 81. 156. [See Badarapācana Vol. 1.
393]

वसूनाम्
Vasūnām āyatanam nt.: Name of a
holy resort (temple ?) of Vasus.
A. Location: In a holy forest, not
very far from the sea and the तीर्थ known
as Śūrpāraka (शूर्पारकं ददर्श॥तत्रो-
दधेः कंचिद् अतीत्य देशम् … वनम् आस-
साद) 3. 118. 8-9; (स तत्र … वसूनाम् …
आयतनानि तेषां ददर्श) 3. 118. 8-13.
For
B. Description and
C. Epic event see
Bhagasya āyatanam.

वातिकषण्ड
Vātikaṣaṇḍa m.: Name of a place.
To the north of the Videhas (विदेहान्
उत्तरं च यः): described as famous and
truely powerful; nobody approached its
gate (एष वातिकषण्डो वै प्रख्यातः सत्य-
विक्रमः।नाभ्यवर्तत यद्द्वारं विदे-
हान् उत्तरं च यः॥) 3. 130. 13 (However,
Nī. on Bom. Ed. 3. 130. 13 takes वातिकषण्ड
to mean ‘a collection of lotuses etc. brought
by wind’: यद् वर्षस्य द्वारं एषो ऽनुभू-
यमानो वातिकषण्डो वातानीतः पद्मादिस-
मूहो नात्यवर्तत … ।अनेन वायोर् अप्य्
अस्मिन् वर्षे प्रवेशो नास्ति किमुतेतरस्येति।
Nī. construes the stanza quite differently.
He connects it with the वर्षम् of the
preceding stanza (12) and according to
him the stanza is intended to reveal the
prowess of (Paraśu) Rāma.

वारणा
Vāraṇā f.: Short for Vāraṇāvata ?
One of the places to which the army
of the Kauravas, gathered for the war,
spread out since it could not be contained
in Hāstinapura (न हास्तिनपुरे राजन्न्
अवकाशो ऽभवत् तदा 5. 19. 28; वारणा
वाटधानं च। … एष देशः सुविस्तीर्णः
 … बभूव कौरवेयाणां बलेन सुसमा-
कुलः) 5. 19. 30-31.

वारणावत
Vāraṇāvata nt.: Name of a city.
A. Description: Pleasing (रम्य) 1.
131. 2, 5; (रमणीय) 1. 131. 14; more
pleasing than any other town (रमणीय-
तरं लोके) 1. 131. 7; attractive place for
men (पुंसाम् देशे मनोरमे) 1. 131. 4;
full of all kinds of jewels (सर्वरत्नसमा-
कीर्ण) 1. 131. 4; full of people (जनाकीर्ण)
1. 131. 14; usually referred to as नगर
1. 131. 2, 3, 5, 7, 14; 1. 132. 15, 18;
1. 134. 1; 1. 137. 12, 17; 2. 69. 12; 10.
11. 23; the people of the town called
नागर (नागरं जनम्) 1. 133. 30;
(नागरो जनः) 1. 137. 1; (नागराः) 1. 137.
9; (नराः नगरवासिनः) 1. 135. 21; on a
few occasions referred to as पुर 1. 134. 6;
people of the town called पौर 1. 134. 5,
8; पुरनिवासिन् 1. 134. 10; called ग्राम
when listed among the places for which the
Pāṇḍavas were ready to settle with the
Kauravas 5. 31. 20; 5. 70. 14; 5. 80. 7.
B.
Place of festival: A famous festival in
honour of god Paśupati (Śiva) used to be
held at Vāraṇāvata which attracted visi-
tors; it used to be the talk of the nearby
towns like Hāstinapura (केचित् कुशलमन्-
त्रिणः।कथयां चक्रिरे … अयं समाजः
सुमहान् रमाणीयतरो भुवि।उपस्थितः
पशुपतेर् नगरे वारणावते) 1. 131. 2-3,
8 (Nī. on Bom. Ed. 1. 143. 3: समाजः
पशुपतेः पूजार्थं मेलकः).
C. Epic
events: (1) Duryodhana suggested to
Dhṛtarāṣṭra to persuade the Pāṇḍavas to
visit Vāraṇāvata and stay there for some
time; they would return from there to
Hāstinapura when Duryodhana felt esta-
blished in the kingdom (विवासयितुम् अर्हति
मृदुनैवाभ्युपायेन नगरं वारणाव-
तम्) 1. 130. 10-11; there would be no
fault in removing the Pāṇḍavas and their
mother to Vāraṇāvata (नात्र दोषो भवि-
ष्यति) 1. 130. 19; at the instance of Dhṛta-
rāṣṭra his clever ministers began to praise
Vāraṇāvata 1. 131. 2-5; hearing the descrip-
tion of Vāraṇāvata, the Pāṇḍavas desired to
go there; Dhṛtarāṣṭra permitted the Pāṇḍa-
vas to go to Vāraṇāvata to see the festival
and enjoy themselves there; they might give
gifts to Brāhmaṇas and singers as desired
and then return to Hāstinapura 1. 131. 7-
10; Yudhiṣṭhira told Bhīṣma and others his
wish to live in Vāraṇāvata for some days
and prayed for their blessings so that no
harm would come to them (आशीर्भिर् वर्-
धितान् अस्मान् न पापं प्रषहिष्यति) 1.
131. 14-15; after receiving the blessings
the Pāṇḍavas left for Vāraṇāvata 1. 131.
18; (2) Duryodhana told Purocana that
the Pāṇḍavas were sent away to Vāraṇā-
vata by Dhṛtarāṣṭra for the festival there;
he asked Purocana to rush to Vāraṇāvata
the same day in a chariot drawn by don-
keys 1. 132. 6-7; Purocana was to build
at Vāraṇāvata for the Pāṇḍavas a house
of four halls, well concealed, and in the
construction of which all sorts of infla-
mable materials were to be used (चतुःशा-
लं गृहं परमसंवृतम्। … यानि द्र-
व्याणि कानिचित्। … आग्नेयान्य् उत सन्तीह तानि
सर्वाणि दापय) 1. 132. 8-9 (Nī. on Bom.
Ed. 1. 144. 9: आग्नेयानि अग्निसंदीपकानि);
Purocana was to ask the Pāṇḍavas and
Kuntī to live in that house; he was to
see that the Pāṇḍavas lived at Vāraṇāvata
with comfort and without fear; he was
later to set the house on fire 1. 132. 13, 15-
16; accordingly Purocana left for Vāraṇā-
vata in a chariot drawn by donkeys 1. 132.
18; (3) The Pāṇḍavas left for Vāraṇā-
vata (प्रययुर् वारणावतं 1. 133. 4) on
the eighth day of the month of Phalguna
and under the Rohiṇī constellation; on
reaching it they met the citizens of the
town (अष्टमे ऽहनि रोहिण्यां प्रयाताः
फल्गुनस्य ते।वारणावतम् आसाद्य ददृशुर्
नागरं जनम्॥) 1. 133. 30; the people of
Vāraṇāvata, delighted, came out to receive
the Pāṇḍavas with all auspicious things;
they pronounced blessings for their victory
and waited on them (वारणावतका जनाः।
कृत्वा जयाशिषः सर्वे परिवार्योपतस्थिरे)
1. 134. 1-3; 5-6; The Pāṇḍavas entered the
town and visited the houses of all the four
classes and were led to their residence by
Purocana 1. 134. 5-8; (4) The citizens of
Vāraṇāvata believed that the Pāṇḍavas were
burnt by fire and lamented their death
1. 136. 13-15; the Pāṇḍavas, however, had
escaped with their mother from the house
at Vāraṇāvata through a tunnel and went
to the south 1. 136. 15. (प्रययुः … दक्षी-
णां दिशम् आश्रिताः) 1. 137. 17; (दक्षिणा-
मुखाः) 1. 137. 18; (5) Dhṛtarāṣṭra sent
his men to Vāraṇāvata to perform the fune-
ral rites of the Pāṇḍavas and Kuntī 1. 137.
12; (6) Bhīma lamented that the Pāṇḍavas
could not sleep even on the best beds at
Vāraṇāvata (शयनेषु परार्ध्येषु ये पुरा
वारणावटे।नाधिजग्मुस् तदा निद्राम् … )
1. 138. 15; (7) Attempt on the life of the
Pāṇḍavas at Vāraṇāvata and their escape
from the house of lac with the help of
Bhīma referred to (i) by Kuntī while talking
to Yudhiṣṭhira 1. 150. 15; (ii) by Drau-
padī while talking to Kṛṣṇa 3. 13. 78; (iii)
by Saṃjaya while talking to Dhṛtarāṣṭra
5. 49. 18, 20; (iv) by Kṛṣṇa while talking
to Duryodhana 5. 126. 13; (v) by Bhīma
while addressing Duryodhana 9. 32. 37 = 9.
55. 28; (vi) by Draupadī while talking to
Bhīma 10. 11. 23; (vii) the burning of the
lac house (at Vāraṇāvata) is listed in the
Parvasaṃgrahaparvan (दाहो जतुगृहस्य)
1. 2. 35, and the going of the Pāṇḍavas to
Vāraṇāvata is referred to in the detailed con-
tents of the Ādiparvan (वारणावतयात्रा च)
1. 2. 83; (8) Vidura reminded Yudhiṣṭhira
that he was formerly instructed by Kṛṣṇa
Dvaipāyana at Vāraṇāvata (अनुशिष्टो ऽसि … ।
द्वैपायन कृष्णेन नगरे वाराणावते॥)
2. 69. 12 (this incident is not reported in the
epic account of Pāṇḍavas' stay at Vāraṇā-
vata 1. 134-136); (9) The kings fighting
with Yuyutsu for six months at Vāraṇāvata
were not able to defeat him (यं (i. e. युयुत्-
सुम्) योधयन्तो राजानो नाजयन् वारणा-
वते।षण्मासान्) 7. 9. 54 (the incident is not
reported in the epic); (10) Vāraṇāvata
figures among the four of the five villages
specifically named by Yudhiṣṭhira for which
he was ready to settle with the Kauravas
(कुशस्थलं वृकस्थलम् आसन्दी वारणाव-
तम्॥भ्रातॄणाम् देहि पञ्चानाम् ग्रामान्
पञ्च सुयोधन) 5. 31. 19-20; 5. 70. 15-16;
5. 80. 7.

वाराणसी
Vārāṇasī f.: Name of a town, capi-
tal of Kāśi, hence referred to also as Kaśi-
purī (5. 175. 17; 6. 14. 6; 13. 154. 23);
Kāśinagarī (5. 174. 11).
A. History: It was founded by Divo-
dāsa, son of Sudeva, at the instance of
Indra (दिवोदासस् तु … वाराणसीं महातेजा
निर्ममे शक्रशासनात्) 13. 31. 16.
B. Loca-
tion: On the northern bank of Gaṅgā,
behind a protective wall, and to the south
of the river Gomatī (गङ्गाया उत्तरे कूले
वप्रान्ते … ।गोमत्या दक्षिणे चैव) 13. 31.
18 (Nī. on Bom. Ed. 13. 30. 18: वप्रान्ते
तटसमीपे).
C. Capital town: Place of
residence of the king of Kāśi (काशिपती
राजा वाराणस्याम्) 5. 49. 38.
D. (1) Des-
cription: Crowded with all the four classes
(विप्रक्षत्रियसंबाधां वैश्यशूद्रसमा-
कुलाम्) 13. 31. 17; having heaps of many
kinds of goods (नैकद्रव्योच्चयवती) 13.
31. 17; having markets of prosperous shops
(समृद्धविपणापणा) 13. 31. 17. (2)
Called पुरी 1. 96. 4; 12. 253. 45; 13. 31. 22;
14. 6. 27, 28, 29; (काशि) पुरी 5. 175. 17; 6.
14. 6; 13. 154. 23; नगरी 5. 47. 40; 14. 6.
22; (काशि) नगरी 5. 174. 11.
E. Holy place:
One who worships Vṛṣadhvaja (Śiva) at
Vārāṇasī gets the fruits of a राजसूय sacri-
fice 3. 82. 69.
F. Epic events: (1) Hearing
that the three Kāśi princesses were holding
a स्वयंवर, Bhīṣma, in a single chariot,
went to the town Vārāṇasī (रथेनैकेन
 … ।जगाम … पुरीं वाराणसीं प्रति) 1.
96. 3-4; all the Kṣatriyas had then assem-
bled at Kāśipurī for the स्वयंवर 5. 175.
17; Bhīṣma's victory over the Kṣatriyas,
single-handed, at Kāśīpurī referred to by
Saṃjaya while reporting Bhīṣma's fall in the
war (जिगायैकरथेनैव काशिपुर्यां महा-
रथः) 6. 14. 6; this incident that occurred
in Vārāṇasī is referred to by Yudhiṣṭhira
while lamenting over the death of Bhīṣma
12. 27. 9; also by Gaṅgā (समेतं पार्थिवं
क्षत्रं काशिपुर्यां स्वयंवरे।विजित्यै-
करथेनाजौ कन्यास् ता यो जहार ह॥) 13.
154. 23; (2) Ambā told the ascetics that
it was impossible for her to go back to
her father's house in Kāśinagarī since she
would be disrespected by her relatives (न
शक्यं काशिनगरीं पुनर् गन्तुम् पितुर्
गृहान्) 5. 174. 11; (3) Dhṛṣṭadyumna in a
battle at Vārāṇasī felled down with a भल्ल
arrow the son of Kāśirāja, who was greedy
for women, from his chariot (this event is
not reported in the epic) (यः (i. e. Dhṛṣṭa-
dyumna) पुत्रं काशिराजस्य वाराणस्यां
महारथम्।समरे स्त्रीषु गृध्यन्तं
भल्लेनापहरद् रथात्) 7. 9. 56; (4)
Kṛṣṇa had burnt the town Vārāṇasī which
remained without a protector for a number
of years (this incident is not reported in the
epic (अनेन (i. e. by Kṛṣṇa) दग्धा वर्-
षपूगान् विनाथा वाराणसी नगरी संब-
भूव) 5. 47. 70.
G. Past events: (1) The
Hehayas attacked king Divodāsa who lived
in Vārāṇasī, the city founded by him;
Divodāsa came out of the town to fight
with them 13. 31. 19-20; the battle lasted
for a thousand days (दिनानां दशतीर्
दश) (Nī. on Bom. Ed. 13. 30. 21: दश-
तिशब्दो ऽपि दशगुनितान् दश ब्रूते); with his
army killed and his treasury empty, Divo-
dāsa fled from the town (हतयोधस् ततो
राजन् क्षीणकोशश् च भूमिपः।दिवोदासः
पुरीम् हित्वा पलायनपरो ऽभवत्॥) 13. 31.
21-22; (2) A merchant of great fame,
Tulādhāra by name, lived in Vārāṇasī; the
Piśācas told Jājali that even Tulādhāra did
not boast of himself as did Jājali 12. 253.
8; Jājali then decided to meet Tulādhāra,
went to him at Vārāṇasī, and spoke to him
(वाराणस्यां तुलाधारं समासाद्याब्रवीद्
वचः) 12. 253. 11; when Jājali boasted
again (that he knew धर्म: धर्मः
प्राप्तो मयेति वै 12. 253. 41), an invisible
voice from the sky told him that even Tulā-
dhāra of Vārāṇasī did not deserve to speak
in terms in which Jājali did (वाराणस्यां
 … तुलाधारः प्रतिष्ठितः।सो ऽप्य् एवं
नार्हते वक्तुम् यथा त्वं भाषसे द्विज॥)
12. 253. 42-43; when Jājali went to Vārā-
ṇasī he saw Tulādhāra selling goods (कालेन
महतागच्छत् स तु वाराणसीं पुरीम्)
12. 253. 45; (3) Nārada told king Marutta
that Saṃvarta, son of Aṅgiras and younger
brother of Bṛhaspati, often visited Vārāṇasī
(वाराणसीं तु नगरीम् अभीक्ष्णम् उपसे-
वते); Marutta then went to Vārāṇasī and,
as suggested by Nārada (14. 6. 23), placed
a corpse at the gate of the town (पुर्या
द्वारे); when Saṃvarta came to the gate
(पुरीद्वारम् आविशत्) he saw the corpse and
turned back (that is how Marutta recogni-
zed Saṃvarta) 14. 6. 22, 27-29; (4) Kṛṣṇa
Dvaipāyana once approached Maitreya in
the family of an unchaste woman at Vārā-
ṇasī; a conversation between the two on the
virtues of gift (दान), austerities (तपस्)
and learning (श्रुत, विद्या) took place there
वाराणस्याम् उपातिष्ठन् मैत्रेयं स्वैरिणी-
कुले) 13. 121. 3, 1-2 (Nī., however, on
Bom. Ed. 13. 120. 3: स्वम् ईरयति धर्माय
प्रेरयति स्वैरिणी मुनिश्रेणी तस्याः कुले
गृहे); (5) At Vārāṇasī the sage Jaigīṣavya
once got with very little effort eight quali-
ties of superhuman power from Śiva (म-
माष्टगुणम् ऐश्वर्यं दत्तं भगवता
पुरा।यत्नेनाल्पेन … वाराणस्याम्) 13. 18.
24.
H. Simile: Vārāṇasī, founded by
Divodāsa, was like Amarāvatī of Indra
(शक्रस्येवामरावतीम्) 13. 31. 18.

विभोर्
Vibhor āyatanam nt.: Name of the
holy resort (temple ?) of Viṣṇu.
A. Location: In a holy forest, not
very far from the sea and the तीर्थ known
as Śūrpāraka (शूर्पारकं ददर्श॥तत्रो-
दधेः कंचिद् अतीत्य देशम् … वनम्
आससाद) 3. 118. 8-9; (स तत्र … विष्णोः …
आयतनानि तेषां ददर्श) 3. 118. 10-11, 13.
For
B. Description and
C. Epic event see
Bhagasya āyatanam.

विराटनगर
Virāṭanagara nt.: Name of a city,
the seat of the Matsya kingdom of Virāṭa;
once the name occurs as Virāṭa, short for
Virāṭanagara (?) 4. 1. 23; also Virāṭarāṣṭra
appears for Vlrāṭanagara 1. 1. 114, (4.
1. 16).
A. Description: (1) When the victory
of Uttara was announced Virāṭa ordered
that the main roads (of the town) be deco-
rated with banners (राजमार्गाः क्रियन्तां
मे पताकाभिर् अलंकृताः) 4. 63. 23; (2)
The town of Matsyarāja shone as in a great
festival and was filled with delighted and
well nourished people (तन् महोत्सवसं-
काशं हृष्टपुष्टजनावृतम्।नगरं मत्-
स्यराजस्य शुशुभे॥) 4. 67. 38; (3) The
city is referred to as (i) नगर (besides in
the name Virāṭanagara) 1. 2. 13; 4. 67. 38; 5.
63. 15: as (ii) पुर 4. 29. 10; 4. 32. 48,
49, 50 (विराटस्य पुराभ्याशे); 4. 66. 21; as
(iii) राष्ट्र (धनंजयेन … विराटराष्ट्रे
वसता) 1. 1. 114; (राष्ट्रे … विराटनृपतेः)
4. 1. 16.
B. Epic event: (1) Dharma
comforted Yudhiṣṭhira by telling him that
the Pāṇḍavas, by his grace, would be able
to live concealed, unknown to others, in
the Virāṭanagara during the thirteenth year
of their exile (विराटनगरे गूढा अविज्ञाताश्
चरिष्यथ) 3. 298. 15, 18; (2) Jana-
mejaya asked Vaiśaṃpāyana how his great-
grandfathers lived during their अज्ञातवास
in Virāṭanagara (कथं विराटनगरे …
अज्ञातवासम् उषिताः) 4. 1. 1; (3) Yudhi-
ṣṭhira suggested to the Pāṇḍavas to live in
Virāṭanagara serving Virāṭa (विराटनगरे
 … कुर्वन्तस् तस्य कर्माणि) 4. 1. 14; (4)
Arjuna asked Yudhiṣṭhira what kind of
work he would do for Virāṭa while living
in his राष्ट्र (कठं कर्म राष्ट्रे तस्य,
करिष्यसि।विराटनृपतेः) 4. 1. 16; (राष्ट्रे,
however, may mean here ‘kingdom’); (5)
Bhīma was asked how he would amuse him-
self in Virāṭa (nagara) (वृकोदर विराटे
त्वं रंस्यसे केन कर्मणा) 4. 1. 23;
(6) Nakula told his brothers that he
would tell the people of Virāṭanagara that
his name was Granthika and that he was
expert in horse-training (ये माम् आमन्त्र-
यिष्यन्ति विराटनगरे जनाः।तेभ्य एवं
प्रवक्ष्यामि) 4. 3. 2-4; (7) After reaching
Virāṭanagara, where the Pāṇḍavas lived in
disguise, they hid their arms on a large Śamī
tree in the cremation ground (विराटनग-
रं गत्वा श्मशाने विपुलां शमीम्।दृष्ट्वा
संनिदधुस् तत्र पाण्डवा आयुधान्य् उत॥
यत्र प्रविश्य नगरं छद्मभिर् न्यव-
सन्त ते) 1. 2. 130-131; (8) Suśarman of
the Trigartas proposed to the Kauravas to
oppress the town (of Virāṭa) and carry
away his thousands of cows (प्रतिपीड्य
पुरं बलात्) 4. 29. 10; Duryodhana sugge-
sted that first Suśarsman should rush on
Virāṭanagara and capture the cows (ते यात्वा
विराटनगरं प्रति) 4. 29. 25; (9) When
Suśarman carried away the cows of Virāṭa,
the chief cowherd went to the town and
reported the raid to Virāṭa (गोपाः पुरम्
अथाव्रजत्) 4. 30. 4; the Matsya army, led
by Virāṭa, came out of the town to fight
with the Trigartas (निर्याय नगरात्) 4. 31.
1; when Virāṭa, with the help of the Pāṇḍa-
vas, defeated Suśarman and his army he
ordered his messengers to go to the town
and declare his victory (आचक्षध्वं
पुरं गत्वा संग्रामे विजयं मम); he
wanted the princes, the courtesans and the
players on musical instruments to come out
of his town to meet him (पर्यागच्छन्तु मे
पुरात्) 4. 32. 48-49; accordingly the messen-
gers went at sunrise to the town of Virāṭa
and declared the king's victory (विराटस्य
पुराभ्याशे) 4. 32. 50; after defeating the
Trigartas, Virāṭa entered the town with the
Pāṇḍavas (विराटः … प्राविशन् नगरम्)
4. 63. 1; (10) After the defeat of the Kau-
ravas, Arjuna told Uttara that they both
would return to Virāṭanagara in the after-
noon (ततो ऽपराण्हे यास्यामो विराटनग-
रं प्रति) 4. 62. 9; (11) The messengers
sent by Uttara reached Virāṭanagara and
announced his victory 4. 63. 17; (12)
Virāṭa, delighted to know the identity of
the Pāṇḍavas, offered to Yudhiṣṭhira his
whole kingdom, with the army, treasury,
and the town (राज्यं च सर्वं विससर्ज
तस्मै सदण्डकोशं सपुरं महात्मा)
4. 66. 21; (13) The town of the Matsya
king, full of delighted and nourished people,
shone as in a great festival (तन् महोत्स-
वसंकाशं हृष्टपुष्टजनावृतम्।नगरं
मत्स्यराजस्य शुशुभे) 4. 67. 38; (14) The
Pāṇḍavas' stay in Virāṭanagara was like
their entering another womb (विराटनगरे
योन्यन्तरगतैर् इव) 5. 20. 11; 9. 55. 30;
(cf. 4. 66. 10); (15) Arjuna's defeating
the Kauravas single-handed when he lived
in Virāṭanagara is referred to on various
occasions: (i) by Dhṛtarāṣṭra (धनं-
जयेनैकरथेन भग्नान्।विराटराष्ट्रे
वसता) 1. 1. 114 (विराटराष्ट्र however,
may mean here kingdom of विराट); (ii)
by Vāsudeva in his message to Dhṛta-
rāṣṭra through Saṃjaya 5. 58. 26-27; (iii)
by Dhṛtarāṣṭra while speaking to Duryo-
dhana 5. 63. 14, 15 (तस्मिन् नगरे); (iv)
by Kṛṣṇa while speaking to Duryodhana
5. 122. 53; (v) by Bhīṣma and Droṇa
while reminding Duryodhana of the past
incident 5. 136. 6; (vi) by Bhīṣma once
again while replying to Duryodhana (the
stanzas also refer to the depriving of the
Kaurava heroes of their upper garments)
6. 94. 8-9; (vii) by Kṛpa while remind-
ing Karṇa 7. 133. 17; (viii) by Śalya
when he asked Karṇa why he did not kill
Arjuna at Virāṭanagara although he then
enjoyed the protection of Bhīṣma, Droṇa
and others 8. 28. 56; (16) Arjuna's stay
at Virāṭanagara as Bṛhannaḍā wearing a
braid mentioned by Ulūka while delivering
Duryodhana's message to the Pāṇḍavas
(धृता हि वेणी पार्थेन विराटनगरे तदा)
5. 158. 31; (17) The enmity formed by
the five Trigarta brothers with Arjuna at
Virāṭanagara (based on the incident of the
cow-raid) referred to by Bhīṣma while
giving his estimate of the heroes (त्रिगर्ता
भ्रातरः पञ्च … ।कृतवैराश् च पार्थेन
विराटनगरे तदा) 5. 163. 9; (18) When
Bhīṣma routed the army of the Pāṇḍavas,
Kṛṣṇa reminded Arjuna of his declaration
at Virāṭanagara that he would kill Bhīṣma,
Droṇa and others in the battle (यत् पुरा
कथितं वीर त्वया … विराटनगरे) 6. 102.
32; (19) Facing Karṇa in the battle,
Bhīma remembered the grief they had
suffered at Virāṭanagara (विराटनगरे …
प्राप्तं दुःखम्) 7. 107. 9; he remember-
ed the same when he faced Duryodhana
(दुःखं च यत् प्राप्तम् … विराटनगरे
चैव) 9. 55. 30; (20) Karṇa admitted
Bhīma's strength of arms exhibited by him
in killing Kīcaka and his followers at Virāṭa-
nagara (विराटनगरे तदा। … केवलं बाहु-
संश्रयत् … कीचकः सगणो हतः) 8. 34.
19; the same incident referred to by Drau-
padī when she exhorted Bhīma to kill
Aśvatthāman 10. 11. 24.

विश्रवसः
Viśravasaḥ niketaḥ m.: The residence
of the sage Viśravas.
Situated on the holy river Narmadā
(प्रत्यक्स्रोता नदी पुण्या नर्मदा तत्र … ।
निकेतः ख्यायते पुण्यो यत्र विश्रवसो
मुनेः) 3. 87. 2-3; described as holy
(पुण्य) 3. 87. 3; Kubera, the lord of
riches, was born in this निकेत (जज्ञे ध-
नपतिर् यत्र कुबेरः) 3. 87. 3.

विश्वामित्राश्रम
Viśvāmitrāśrama m.: The hermitage
of Viśvāmitra.
A. Location: On the western bank
of Sarasvatī (आश्रमः … पश्चिमश् चासीद्
विश्वामित्रस्य धीमतः … यत्र पूजयित्वा
सरस्वतीम्) 9. 41. 4, 6.
B. Events: (1)
Viśvāmitra asked Sarasvatī to bring to him
Vasiṣṭha whose आश्रम was on the opposite
bank for the wanted to kill Vasiṣṭha 9. 41.
16, 18; Sarasvatī did accordingly by with-
drawing a portion of her opposite bank
(कूलापहारम् अकरोत् 9. 41. 27) and took
Vasiṣṭha to the आश्रम of Viśvāmitra
(वेगेनोवाह तं विप्रं विश्वामित्राश्रमं
प्रति) 9. 41. 32; Sarasvatī then carried
back Vasiṣṭha from Viśvāmitra's आश्रम to
his own आश्रम to the east 9. 41. 34; (2)
Formerly, at the junction of Tretā and Dvā-
para, during a period of severe drought
which lasted for twelve years, Viśvāmitra and
other sages left their hermitages and, home-
less, they ran about here and there 12. 139.
13, 26; (आश्रमान् संपरित्यज्य पर्यधा-
वन्न् इतस् ततः।विश्वामित्रो ऽथ … अनिके-
तनः।क्षुधापरिगतो धीमान् समन्तात्
पर्यधावत॥) 12. 139. 25-26.

विष्णोः
Viṣṇoḥ sthānam: See Śālagrāma.

विष्णोर्
Viṣṇor āyatanam nt.: Name of a holy
resort (temple ?) of Viṣṇu.
A. Location: In a holy forest, not very
far from the sea and the तीर्थ known as
Śūrpāraka (शूर्पारकं ददर्श॥तत्रोद-
धेः कंचिद् अतीत्य देशं … वनम् आस-
साद) 3. 118. 8-9; (स तत्र … विष्णोः …
आयतनानि तेषां ददर्श) 3. 118. 10-11, 13.
For
B. Description and
C. Epic event see
Bhagasya āyatanam.

विष्णोर्
Viṣṇor āśramaḥ m.: The आश्रम of
Viṣṇu.
A. Location: From Kurukṣetra, Bala-
rāma went to the आश्रम of Viṣṇu (कुरु-
क्षेत्रं ततो दृष्ट्वा … आश्रमं (विष्णोः) …
अगमत्) 9. 53. 1; by the side of Himavant
(पार्श्वे हिमवतः) 9. 53. 9.
B. Descrip-
tion: Holy (पुण्य) 9. 53. 2, 9, having holy
marks (पुण्यलक्षण) 9. 53. 3; heavenly
(दिव्य) 9. 53. 1; very large (सुमहन्त्) 9.
53. 1; excellent (प्रवर), (आश्रमवर)
9. 53. 3; it was full of trees such as
Madhūka, mango, Plakṣa, banyan, Ciri,
Bilva, Panasa, and Arjuna 9. 53. 2;
C.
History: On enquiry, the sages told Bala-
rāma that the आश्रम formerly belonged to
Viṣṇu; god Viṣṇu, in bygone days, practised
excellent austerities in that आश्रम; all
ancient sacrifices were performed according
to the rites by Viṣṇu in the आश्रम (शृणु
विस्तरशो राम यस्यायं पूर्वम् आश्रमः॥
अत्र विष्णुः पुरा देवस् तप्तवांस् तप
उत्तमम्।अत्रास्य विधिवद् यज्ञाः सर्वे
वृत्ताः सनातनाः॥) 9. 53. 4-5.
D. Past
event: In this आश्रम the daughter of
Śāṇḍilya who observed chastity obtained
perfection by practising austerities; after
enjoying in the आश्रम the fruit of an
अश्वमेध sacrifice, she was absorbed in
meditation and went to heaven (अत्रैव
ब्राह्मणी सिद्धा कौमारब्रह्मचारिणी।
योगयुक्ता दिवं याता तपःसिद्धा … ॥ब-
भूव … शाण्डिल्यस्य … सुता॥सा तु प्राप्य
परं योगं गता स्वर्गम् अनुत्तमम्।
भुक्त्वाश्रमे ऽश्वमेधस्य फलं … ।गता
स्वर्गं महाभागा॥) 9. 53. 6-8.
E.
Epic event: Balarāma paid respects to the
sages and from that आश्रम he mounted the
mountain (आरुरुहे ऽचलम्) 9. 53. 9.

वीराश्रम
Vīrāśrama m.: Name of an आश्रम।
One who visits Kumāra living in the
Vīrāśrama gets without doubt the fruit of
an Aśvamedha sacrifice (कुमारम् अभि-
गत्वा च वीराश्रमनिवासिनम्।अश्वमेधम्
अवाप्नोति नरो नास्त्य् अत्र संशयः॥) 3.
82. 126.

वृकस्थल
Vṛkasthala nt.: Name of a village.
A. Location: On way from Upapla-
vya to Hāstinapura (उपप्लव्याद् अथायान्-
तम् (केशवम्) 5. 82. 18; (उपप्लव्याद् इह
क्षत्तर् उपयातो जनार्दनः।वृकस्थले
निवसति स च प्रातर् इहेष्यति॥) 5. 84. 1.
B. Characterized as ग्राम: (ग्रामान्
पञ्च) 5. 70. 16; (पञ्च ग्रामा वृता मया)
5. 70. 14; (पञ्च नस् तात दीयन्तां ग्रामा
इति) 5. 80. 7; (तस्मिन् ग्रामे) 5. 82. 25;
(ग्रामे वृकस्थले) 5. 83. 16.
C. Epic
events: (1) Vṛkasthala was one of the
five villages in lieu of which Yudhiṣṭhira
was prepared to come to terms with the
Kauravas (the other three villages actu-
ally named being Kuśasthala. Āsandī and
Vāraṇāvata)—this was mentioned by
Yudhiṣṭhira first to Saṃjaya 5. 31. 19, and
then again in his message to the Kauravas
through Kṛṣṇa 5. 70. 15; also referred to
by Draupadī in her address to Kṛṣṇa 5. 80.
7; (2) Kṛṣṇa, on his way to Hāstinapura,
from Upaplavya, reached Vṛkasthala in the
evening and performed there evening rites;
he decided to stay there for the night (वृक-
स्थलं समासाद्य … प्रकीर्णरश्माव् आदित्ये
विमले लोहितायति॥अवतीर्य रथात् तूर्णं
 … संध्याम् उपविवेश ह) 5. 82. 20-21;
(इह वत्स्यामहे क्षपाम्) 5. 82. 23; the
people of the village Vṛkasthala arranged for
Kṛṣṇa's stay (चक्रुर् आवसथं नराः);
the principal Brāhmaṇas of the village went
to Kṛṣṇa and worshipped him according
to the rules and gave him blessings (तस्मिन्
ग्रामे प्रधानास् तु य आसन् ब्राह्मणा
नृप।अभिगम्य … हृषीकेशं … पूजां
चक्रुर् यथान्यायम् आशीर्मङ्गलसं-
युताम्॥); as requested by the Brāhmaṇas,
Kṛṣṇa visited their houses and returned; he
fed them and dined with them and spent
the night happily there (अवसत् तां क्षपां
सुखम्) 5. 82. 24-29; Duryodhana had
constructed a hall in the village Vṛkasthala
for Kṛṣṇa's stay; but Kṛṣṇa ignored this
सभा (as well as others in other villages)
and proceeded to the house of the Kurus
(विशेषतश् च वासार्थं सभां ग्रामे
वृकस्थले।विदधे कौरवो राजा। … ताः
सभाः … असमीक्ष्यैव दाशार्ह उपायात्
कुरुसद्म तत्) 5. 83. 16, 18; when Kṛṣṇa
started for the town (Hāstinapura), people
of Vṛkasthala took his leave and returned
to their village 5. 87. 2.

वृन्दाटक
Vṛndāṭaka nt.: Name of a town.
Located to the west of Hāstinapura;
it was one of the towns subjugated by
Nakula in his expedition to the west (निर्-
याय खाण्डवप्रस्थात् प्रतीचीम् अभितो
दिशम् 2. 29. 2) before the Rājasūya (तथा
वृन्दाटकं पुरम्। … वशे चक्रे) 2. 29. 10.

वृषध्वजस्य
Vṛṣadhvajasya āśramaḥ: See Āditya-
bandhana.

वृष्णिपुर
Vṛṣṇipura: See Dvārakā.

वृष्ण्यन्धकपुर
Vṛṣṇyandhakapura nt.: Another name
of Dvārakā.
When Śālva beseiged Dvārakā no one
could go out or enter Vṛṣṇyandhakapura
without stamped permission (न चामुद्रो
ऽभिनिर्याति न चामुद्रः प्रवेश्यते।
वृष्ण्यन्धकपुरे राजंस् तदा सौभसमा-
गमे) 3. 16. 19; army having many ele-
phants and horses was stationed along all
the roads and squares of the town (अनु रथ्-
यासु सर्वासु चत्वरेषु च कौरव।बलं
बभूव राजेन्द्र प्रभूतगजवाजिमत्) 3.
16. 20. [See Dvārakā]

वेत्रकीयगृह
Vetrakīyagṛha nt.: Name of a place,
another name of Ekacakrā (?)
The wife of the Brāhmaṇa told Kuntī
that the king who had agreed to give to
the demon Baka as वेतन a cart-full of
rice, two buffaloes and the man who took
the cart to him lived in Vetrakīyagṛha; the
king had not acted justly towards his subjects
(वेत्रकीयगृहे राजा नायं नयम् इहास्थि-
तः) 1. 148. 9 (Nī. on Bom. Ed. 1. 160. 9:
वेत्रकीयगृहे स्थानविशेषे); Kirmīra told
Yudhiṣṭhira that he had for long sought
to kill Bhīma since the latter had killed his
(Kirmīra's) brother Baka in Vetrakīyagṛha
(अनेन हि मम भ्राता बको विनिहतः
प्रियः।वेत्रकीयगृहे) 3. 12. 30 (Nī. in
Bom. Ed. 3. 11. 31 reads वैत्रकीयवने and
identifies it with Ekacakrā: वैत्रकीयवने
एकचक्रायाम्). [See Ekacakrā]

वैखानसाश्रम
Vaikhānasāśrama, Vaikhānasānāmāśramaḥ
 m.: The आश्रम where the Vai-
khānasas lived.
A. Location: Situated in the north
(अस्यां दिशि वरिष्ठायाम् उत्तरायाम्) 5. 109.
3.
B. Holiness: One of the holy and
sanctified places in the west mentioned by
Dhaumya (प्रतीच्याम् … दिशि।यानि तत्र
पवित्राणि पुण्यान्य् आयतनानि च) 3. 87. 1;
the आश्रम was dear to the Vaikhānasa
sages who had obtained perfection (वैखा-
नसानां सिद्धानां ऋषीणाम् आश्रमः प्रि-
यः) 3. 87. 13.
C. Past event: It was poin-
ted out by Suparṇa to Gālava (अत्र वैखा-
नसाश्रमः) 5. 109. 9.

वैदिश
Vaidiśa nt.: Name of a town (=
Vidiśā ?)
In ancient times a dialogue took place
between a vulture and a jackal which was
narrated by Bhīṣma to Yudhiṣṭhira (शृणु
पार्थ यथावृत्तम् इतिहासं पुरातनम्।
गृध्रजम्बूकसंवादं यो वृत्तो वैदिशे
पुरा) 12. 149. 1.

वैवस्वतस्य
Vaivasvatasya āyatanam nt.: Name of
a holy resort (temple ?) of Vaivasvata.
A. Location: In a holy forest, not
very far from the sea and the तीर्थ known
as Śūrpāraka (शूर्पारकम् ददर्श॥तत्रो-
दधेः कंचिद् अतीत्य देशम् … वनम्
आससाद) 3. 118. 8-9; (स तत्र … वैवस्व-
तस्य … आयतनानि तेषाम् ददर्श) 3. 118.
10-11, 13. For
B. Description and
C. Epic
event see Bhagasya āyatanam.

वैवस्वती
Vaivasvatī f.: See Saṃyamanī.

वैश्रवणस्य
Vaiśravaṇasya sadman nt.: See Mahen-
drasya sadman.

व्यासवन
Vyāsavana nt.: A forest named after
Vyāsa.
One proceeds to Vyāsavana from the
तीर्थ called Miśraka 3. 81. 76; while visits
ing this आश्रम, one should be controlled
and should take limited food (ततो व्यासव-
नं गच्छेन् नियतो नियताशनः) 3. 81. 78;
the तीर्थ called Manojava was in Vyāsa-
vana (ततो व्यासवनं गच्छेन् … ) 3. 81. 78.
[See also the next]

व्यासस्थली
Vyāsasthalī f.: Name of a place.
Located in Vyāsavana (ततो व्यासवनं
गच्छेन् … ) 3. 81. 78; Vyāsa, grieved over the
departure of his son, decided to end his life
at this place; he was however, comforted
by gods (ततो व्यासस्थली नाम यत्र व्या-
सेन धीमता।पुत्रशोकाभितप्तेन देह-
त्यागार्थनिश्चयः॥कृतो देवैश् च राजेन्द्र
पुनर् उत्थापितस् तदा) 3. 81. 81-82 (in the
Śāntiparvan it is reported that Vyāsa, griev-
ed over his separation from Śuka, sat down,
dejected, on the slope of HImavant; he was
there comforted by Śiva who arrived with
gods and Gandharvas 12. 320. 27-38); one
who visits Vyāsasthalī gets the fruits of gift-
ing a thousand cows (अभिगम्य स्थलीं
तस्य गोसहस्रफलं लभेत्) 3. 81. 82.

व्यासाश्रम
Vyāsāśrama1 m.: Hermitage of Vyāsa.
A. Location: On the slope of the
mountain Himavant (हिमवत्पृष्ठे) 12.
314. 30; to the east, on a lonely spot on
the slope of the mountain (ऐन्द्रीं तु दिशम्
आस्थाय शैलराजस्य धीमतः।विविक्ते
पर्वततटे … ।तत्राश्रमपदं … पितुः)
12. 314. 23, 25.
B. Description: Holy (पुण्य)
and best (उत्तम) 12. 314. 25.
C. Epic
events: (1) Vyāsa was surrounded by his
pupils Sumantu, Vaiśaṃpāyana, Jaimini and
Paila in the आश्रम; he taught them the
Vedas 12. 314. 23, 25; (2) Śuka, after his
dialogue with Janaka, went to see his
father in the आश्रम to the east of Himavant
12. 314. 23, 25; Vyāsa saw his son arriving
through air; Śuka reported to Vyāsa about
his dialogue with Janaka 12. 314. 26-27, 29;
Vyāsa taught the Vedas also to his son 12.
314. 30; (3) Once Vyāsa's pupils requested
him that he should not accept any one,
other than his four pupils and his son
Śuka, as his pupil (षष्ठः शिष्यो न ते
ख्यातिं गच्छेद् अत्र प्रसीद नः॥चत्वा-
रस् ते वयं शिष्या गुरुपुत्रश् च पञ्च-
मः) 12. 314. 37-38; Vyāsa then told his
pupils, living with him in the आश्रम, to go
down on the earth and propagate the Vedas
(वेदो विस्तार्यताम् अयम्); the Vedas should
be taught to all the four Varṇas (श्रावयेच्
चतुरो वर्णान्); he explained to them the
procedure of Vedic teaching (एतद् वः
सर्वम् आख्यातम् स्वाध्यायस्य विधिं
प्रति) 12. 314. 39-49; accordingly the pupils
expressed their wish to leave (the आश्रम
on) the mountain and go down on the
earth to propagate the Vedas (शैलाद् अस्मान्
महीं गन्तुं काङ्क्षितं नो महामुने।
वेदान् अनेकधा कर्तुम्) 12. 315. 4; when
permitted by Vyāsa they (left the आश्रम)
and descended from the mountain to
the earth (जग्मुः प्रदक्षिणं कृत्वा व्या-
सं … ।अवतीर्य महीम्) 12. 315. 7-10;
(4) Nārada, who arrived at the आश्रम,
saw Vyāsa, sitting alone, and engaged in
meditation and not reciting the Vedas (तं
ददर्शाश्रमपदे) 12. 315. 11-12; as
suggested by Nārada, Vyāsa and his son
Śuka recited the Vedas loudly 12. 315. 22-
23; Vyāsa explained to Śuka why he stopp-
ed Vedic recitation when there was a strong
gust of wind (वातो ऽतिमात्रं प्रववौ) 12.
315. 24; later he asked Śuka to continue
the recitation and himself went (from the
आश्रम) to Vyomagaṅgā (उक्त्वा पुत्रम्
अधीष्वेति व्योमगङ्गाम् अयात् तदा) 12. 315.
57; (5) When instructed by Nārada,
Śuka took leave of Vyāsa and left him (in
the आश्रम) to ascend to the mountain top
(पितरं संपरित्यज्य जगाम … ॥गिरि-
पृष्ठं समारुह्य) 12. 318. 60-63; 12.
319. 1; Vyāsa (then left the आश्रम and)
followed his son (तं प्रक्रमन्तम्
आज्ञाय पिता … पृष्ठतो ऽनुससार ह) 12.
320. 18.

व्यासाश्रम
Vyāsāśrama2 m.: Another आश्रम of
Vyāsa.
A. Location: On way from Indra-
prastha to Hāstinapura (?) 16. 8. 74 (see
the next section).
B. Epic events: (1)
After establishing Vajra at Indraprastha,
Arjuna, on his way to Hāstinapura, saw
Kṛṣṇa-Dvaipāyana in his आश्रम (कृष्णद्वै-
पायनं राजन् ददर्शासीनम् आश्रमे) 16. 8.
74: Arjuna entered the आश्रम of Vyāsa
and saw the holy sage sitting in a solitary
place; when consoled by Vyāsa over the
destruction of the Yādavas, he left for
Hāstinapura (प्रविशन्न् अर्जुनो राजन्न् आश्र-
मं सत्यवादिनः।ददर्शासीनम् एकान्ते
मुनिं सत्यवतीसुतम्) 16. 9. 1; (अनुज्ञातो
ययौ पार्थो नगरं नागसाह्वयम्) 16.
9. 37; (2) After meeting Dhṛtarāṣṭra and
others, Aśvatthāman went to Vyāsāśrama
(द्रौणिर् व्यासाश्रमं ययौ) 11. 10. 21.

शक्रपुर
Śakrapura nt.: See Indraprastha.

शक्रप्रस्थ
Śakraprastha nt.: See Indraprastha.

शङ्कुकर्णेश्वर
Śaṅkukarṇeśvara m.: Name of a holy
place.
Close to the famous तीर्थ called Dṛmi
3. 80. 87; wise men say that by worshipp-
ing god Śaṅkukarṇeśvara (Śiva) at this
place one got tenfold fruit of performing
an Aśvamedha sacrifice (अश्वमेधं दश-
गुणं प्रवदन्ति मनीषिणः) 3. 80. 87.

शतक्रतुप्रस्थ
Śatakratuprastha nt.: See Indrapra-
stha.

शतयूपाश्रम
Śatayūpāśrama m.: The आश्रम of
the royal sage Śatayūpa.
A. Location: In Kurukṣetra (कुरु-
क्षेत्रं जगाम सः।तत्राश्रमपदं …
अभिगम्य … आससाद … शतयूपम्) 15. 25.
8-9; (ततो युधिष्ठिरो राजा कुरुक्षेत्रम्
अवातरत्) 15. 30. 16; beyond the river
Yamunā, at some distance from it (क्रमेणो-
त्तीर्य यमुनां नदीम् … ॥स ददर्शाश्र-
मं दूरात् … शतयूपस्य) 15. 30. 16-17.
B. Epic events: (1) When Dhṛtarāṣṭra
decided to leave Hāstinapura and live in
an आश्रम, he went to Kurukṣetra; there
he reached the hermitage of Śatayūpa,
the great king of the Kekayas (तत्राश्रम-
पदं … अभिगम्य … आससाद … शतयू-
पम्); with him Dhṛtarāṣṭra went to Vyāsā-
śrama 15. 25. 9-11; after he was initiated
by Vyāsa (स दीक्षां तत्र संप्राप्य),
Dhṛtarāṣṭra returned to the आश्रम of
Śatayūpa and lived there; as suggested by
Vyāsa, Śatayūpa gave complete instructions
to Dhṛtarāṣṭra regarding the mode of life
of a forest-dweller (शतयूपाश्रमे तस्मिन्
निवासम् अकरोत् तदा॥तस्मै सर्वं
विधिं … राजाचख्यौ … ।आरण्यकम् …
व्यासस्यानुमते तदा) 15. 25. 12-13; (2)
When Yudhiṣṭhira went to meet Dhṛta-
rāṣṭra he crossed the river Yamunā and
saw from a distance the आश्रम of the
royal sage Śatayūpa (and that of Dhṛta-
rāṣṭra) (स ददर्शाश्रमं दूराद् राजर्षेः
 … शतयूपस्य) 15. 30. 17.

शरभङ्गाश्रम
Śarabhaṅgāśrama m.: Name of an
आश्रम।
A. Location: In the great forest Daṇḍa-
kāraṇya 3. 261. 40.
B. Holiness: One who
visited the आश्रम did not experience misery
and purified his family (शरभङ्गाश्र-
मं गत्वा … न दुर्गतिम् अवाप्नोति पुनाति
च कुलं नरः) 3. 83. 39.
C. Rāmāyaṇa
event: Fearing the return of the citizens,
Rāma entered the great forest and went
to the hermitage of Śarabhaṅga; he honour-
ed there Śarabhaṅga and took his residence
in Daṇḍakāraṇya (प्रविवेश महार-
ण्यं शरभङ्गाश्रमं प्रति।सत्कृत्य
शरभङ्गं स दण्डकारण्यम् आश्रितः)
3. 261. 39-40.

शाकल
Śākala nt.: Name of a city.
A. Location: To the west of Indra-
prastha (निर्याय खाण्डवप्रस्थात् प्रती-
चीम् अभितो दिशम्) 2. 29. 2; the principal
town of the Madra country (मद्राणां
पुटभेदनम्) 2. 29. 13 (Nī. on Bom. Ed.
2. 32. 14 cites Amara (2. 2. 1) पत्तनं
पुटभेदनम्); in the Bāhlīka country
(बाह्लीकेषूषितं मया। … शाकलं नाम
नगरम्) 8. 30. 13-14.
B. Description: Pro-
sperous (स्फीत) 8. 30. 29; people living
there called शाकलावतः 8. 30. 33.
C.
Characteristic: In the Śākala town a
Rākṣasī beat the drum on every four-
teenth day of the dark fortnight of the
month and sang songs in which it was
said: when would the loud singers (? घोषि-
काः) sing again गाथास् in Śākala after
eating beef and drinking wine of गुड ?
(तत्र स्म राक्षसी गाति सदा कृष्णचतुर्-
दशीम्।नगरे शाकले स्फीते आहत्य निशि
दुन्दुभिम्॥कदा वा घोषिका गाथाः पुनर्
गास्यन्ति शाकले।गव्यस्य तृप्ता मांसस्य
पीत्वा गौडं महासवम्॥) 8. 30. 29-30.
D. Epic event: Nakula went to Śākala in
his expedition before the Rājasūya and
won over Śalya, his maternal uncle, by
taking recourse to affection (and not battle)
(ततः शाकलम् अभ्येत्य … मातुलं प्रीति-
पूर्वेण शल्यं चक्रे वशे बली॥) 2.
29. 13.

शालग्राम
Śālagrāma m.: Name of a village.
A village sacred to Viṣṇu Nārāyaṇa;
Hari is always present there; by approach-
ing Viṣṇu there one got the fruit of Aśva-
medha sacrifice and went to the world of
Viṣṇu (स्थानं नारायणस्य तु।सदा
संनिहितो यत्र हरिर् वसति भारत।शाल-
ग्राम इति ख्यातो विष्णोर् अद्भुतकर्मणः।
अभिगम्य … विष्णुम् … ।अश्वमेधम् अवा-
प्नोति विष्णुलोकं च गच्छति॥) 3. 82. 106-
107; there is a well there which freed the
visitor of all sins; four oceans are present
in it; by bathing in the well one did not
meet with calamity (तत्रोदपानो धर्मज्ञ
सर्वपापप्रमोचनः।समुद्रास् तत्र
चत्वारः कूपे संनिहिताः सदा।ततोप-
स्पृश्य राजेन्द्र न दुर्गतिम् अवाप्नुयात्॥)
3. 82. 108.

शिव
Śiva nt.: Name of a house in Vāraṇā-
vata meant for the Pāṇḍavas.
A. Location: In the town Vāraṇāvata
(वारणावतम् अद्यैव यथा यासि तथा
कुरु॥तत्र गत्वा … गृहं … कारयेथाः॥)
1. 132. 7-8 (गृहं शिवाख्यम्) 1. 134. 11;
the house was constructed near the store
of arms (आयुधागारम् आश्रित्य) 1. 132. 8.
B. Description: Inauspicious (अशिव) 1.
134. 11 (Nī. on Bom. Ed. 1. 146. 11: शिवम्
इत्य् आख्यामात्रम् अर्थतस् त्व् अशिवं मरणा-
र्थं कृतत्वात्); expensive (महाधन) 1.
132. 8 (Nī. on Bom. Ed. 1. 144. 8: महा-
धनं बहुधनसाध्यम्); it had four
halls and was well enclosed (चतुःशालं
गृहं परमसंवृतम्) 1. 132. 8.
C.
Furniture: Essential seats and beds as well
as conveyances for the use of the Pāṇḍavas
were provided in the house (तत्रासनानि
मुख्यानि यानानि शयनानि च।विधातव्यानि
पाण्डवानाम्) 1. 132. 14.
D. Materials
used in the construction of the house:
Hemp, resin, मुञ्ज, बल्वज, bamboo;
these and other materials used in its constru-
ction were sprinkled with घृत; (शणसर्-
जरसं व्यक्तम् आनीतं गृहकर्मणि।
मुञ्जबल्वजवंशादि द्रव्यं सर्वं घृ-
तोक्षितम्॥) 1. 134. 14; Duryodhana had
asked Purocana to use in the construction
of the house hemp, resin and all such in-
flammable material; the clay meant to be
used as plaster of the walls was to be mixed
with butter, oil, and lac in ample quantity;
hemp, bamboo, घृत, and wood and other
contrivances (? यन्त्राणि) of different kinds
were to be used in all parts of the house; it
was to be inflammable (शणसर्जरसादीनि
यानि द्रव्याणि कानिचित्।आग्नेयान्य् उत सन्तीह
तानि सर्वाणि दापय॥सर्पिषा च सतैलेन
लाक्षया चाप्यनल्पया।मृत्तिकां मिश्रयि-
त्वा त्वं लेपं कुड्येषु दापयेः॥शणान्
वंशं घृतं दारु यन्त्राणि विविधानि च।
तस्मिन् वेश्मनि सर्वाणि निक्षिपेथाः समन्-
ततः॥ … आग्नेयम् इति तत् कार्यम्) 1. 132.
9-12 (Nī. on Bom. Ed. 1. 144. 9: आग्ने-
यानि अग्निसंदीपकानि).
E. Epic events:
(1) Purocana led the Pāṇḍavas to this
house called Śiva (पुरोचनः।निवेदयाम्
आस गृहं शिवाख्यम् अशिवं तदा) 1. 134.
11; (2) When the Pāṇḍavas entered it,
Yudhiṣṭhira, on smelling the odour of fat
mixed with clarified butter and lac, realized
that the house was highly inflammable
(उवाचाग्नेयम् इत्य् एवं भीमसेनं युधि-
ष्ठिरः।जिघ्रन् सोम्य वसागन्धं सर्पिर्-
जतुविमिश्रितम्॥कृतं हि व्यक्तम् आग्नेयम्
इदं वेश्म) 1. 134. 13-14, 18; (इदं
शरणम् आग्नेयम्) 1. 135. 10; Purocana
was always present at the entrance of the
house (स तत्र च गृहद्वारि वसत्य् अशुभ-
धीः सदा) 1. 135. 18; (3) A digger, sent
by Vidura, dug a big tunnel in the middle
of the house; its opening was not very
wide; it was covered with a wooden plank,
unknown to others and level with the
ground; its opening was concealed lest
Purocana noticed it; the Pāṇḍavas were
to escape through this tunnel (खनको
यत्नम् आस्थितः।परिखाम् उत्किरन् नाम
चकार सुमहद् बिलम्॥चक्रे च वेश्म-
नस् तस्य मध्ये नातिमहन् मुखम्।
कपाटयुक्तम् अज्नातम् समं भूम्या च
भारत॥पुरोचनभयाच् चैव व्यदधात्
संवृतं मुखम्) 1. 135. 16-18; (4) A
Niṣādī who came to the lac-house for food
with her five sons, drank wine and slept
in the same house 1. 136. 7-8; (5) The
burning of the house was blamed on Puro-
cana by the people (दुर्योधनप्रयुक्तेन
पापेनाकृतबुद्धिना।गृहम् आत्मविनाशाय
कारितं दाहितं च तत्॥) 1. 136. 11; 1.
137. 2.

शिशुमारपुर
Śiśumārapura nt.: Name of a town.
The kings, Duryodhana and others all
gathered at Śiśumārapura for the स्वयं-
वर of Draupadī; the sages, desirous to see
the स्वयंवर, and the Brāhmaṇas from
different countries reached there; then all
the subjects of the king also reached there
and they and the kings settled down at
Śiśumārapura (ततः पौरजनाः सर्वे …
 … शिशुमारपुरं प्राप्य न्यविशंस् ते च
पार्थिवाः॥) 1. 176. 12-15; the enclosure
for the gathering was erected to the north-
east of the town on an even and auspicious
spot (प्रागुत्तरेण नगराद् भूमिभागे
समे शुभे।समाजवाटः शुशुभे) 1. 176.
16. [See Kāmpilya, Pāñcālanagara]

शुकस्य
Śukasya āśramaḥ m.: Name of the
आश्रम of the high-souled Śuka.
Situated near the आश्रम of Śarabhaṅga;
by visiting it one did not meet with misery
and he purified his family (न दुर्गतिम्
अवाप्नोति पुनाति च कुलं नरः) 3. 83. 39.

शुक्तिमती
Śuktimatī, Śuktisāhvayā f.: Name of
a town, the capital of the Chedi country,
hence referred to as Cedipura (2. 40. 14),
Cedipurī (3. 65. 6), Cedirājapurī (3. 62. 20).
A. Description: Delightful (रम्या) 3.
23. 47; 3. 65. 6; 14. 84. 2.
B. Epic events:
(1) Dhṛṣṭaketu, king of the Chedi country,
after meeting the Pāṇḍavas, took his sister
(Kareṇumatī, wife of Nakula) with him
and left for the town Śuktimatī (धृष्टकेतुः
स्वसारं च समादायाथ चेदिराट्।जगाम
 … रम्यां शुक्तिमतीम् पुरीम्) 3. 23. 47
(Nī. on 3. 22. 50: स्वसारं करेणुमतीं
नकुलभार्याम्); (2) The sacrificial horse
for the Aśvemedha of Yudhiṣṭhira reached
Śuktisāhvayā, the town of the Cedis (आस-
साद पुरीं रम्यां चेदीनां शुक्तिसाह्व-
याम्) 14. 84. 2; (3) Balarāma and Kṛṣṇa
once went to Cedipura to meet the sister of
their father (ततश् चेदिपुरं प्राप्तौ सं-
कर्षणजनार्दनौ) 2. 40. 14.
C. Events
from Nala story: (1) The people of Cedi-
rājapurī saw Damayantī entering their town
after she was deserted by Nala (ददृशुः
पुरवासिनः॥प्रविशन्तीं … चेदिराजपुरीं
तदा) 3. 62. 19-20; (2) A Brāhmaṇa,
called Sudeva, reached Cedipurī in search
of Damayantī (ततश् चेदिपुरीं रम्यां
सुदेवो नाम वै द्विजः।विचिन्वानो ऽथ वै-
दर्भीम्) 3. 65. 6. [For river Śuktimatī, see
Vol. I. 457]

शृङ्गवेरपुर
Śṛṅgaverapura nt.: Name of a town.
Near Gaṅgā 3. 83. 63; described as
big (महन्त्) 3. 83. 62; it was at Śṛigavera-
pura that Rāma crossed the river (Gaṅgā)
(यत्र तीर्णो महाराज रामो दाश्रथिः
पुरा) 3. 83. 62.

शैरीषक
Śairīṣaka nt.: Name of a town ?
To the west of Indraprastha (निर्याय
प्रतीचीम् अभितो दिशम्) 2. 29. 2; described
as fertile (बहुधान्यक) 2. 29. 5; Nakula
in his expedition to the west before the
Rājasūya subjugated it (शैरिषकं … वशे
चक्रे) 2. 29. 6.

श्यामाया
Śyāmāyā āśramaḥ m.: Name of an
आश्रम।
Mentioned in the Tīrthavaṃśa narrated
by Aṅgiras to Gautama 13. 26. 3; by visit-
ing the आश्रम of Śyāmā and by living and
bathing there for nine nights at a stretch one
would live in the Gandharvanagara (उष्य
चैवाभिषिच्य च।त्रींस् त्रिरात्रान् स सं-
धाय गन्धर्वनगरे वसेत्॥) 13. 26. 28.

श्रावस्ती
Śrāvastī f.: Name of a city.
It was founded by king, Śrāvasta(ka)
of the Ikṣvāku family (जज्ञे श्रावस्तको
राजा श्रावस्ती येन निर्मिता) 3. 193. 4.

श्वेतकेतोर्
*Śvetaketor āśramaḥ m.: The आश्रम
where Śvetaketu lived.
Described as holy (पुण्य) and where
the trees always gave fruit (सदाफलैर्
उपपन्नं महीजैः) 3. 132. 1; Śvetaketu
lived there with his father Uddālaka,
his sister Sujātā who was married to
Kahoḍa, and Kahoḍa's son Aṣṭāvakra 3.
132. 3 ff; in the आश्रम Śvetaketu saw
Sarasvatī in human form; he said to her,
who had appeared there, that he would like
to know from her the (nature of) ‘speech’.
(साक्षाद् अत्र श्वेतकेतुर् ददर्श सरस्वतीं
मानुषरूपदेहाम्।वेत्स्यामि वाणीम् इति
संप्रवृत्तां सरस्वतीं श्वेतकेतुर् ब-
भाषे) 3. 132. 2.

संयमन
Saṃyamana (nt.), Saṃyamanī f.:
The residence of Yama Vaivasvata, also
referred to as Vaivasvatī (13. 105. 16),
Pretarajasya bhavanam (3. 160. 9.)
A. Location: In the southern direc-
tion (यमस् तु राजा धर्मात्मा … दक्षि-
णाम् आश्रितो दिशम्॥एतत् संयमनं
 … प्रेतराजस्य भवनम्) 3. 160. 8-9.
B. Relationship with Yama Vaivasvata:
Yama lived there, hence called प्रेत-
राजस्य भवनम् 3. 160. 9; वैवस्वती 13.
105. 16.
C. Description: Holy (पुण्य)
3. 160. 9; pleasing (रम्या) 7. 50. 42; of
extremely wonderful sight (अतीवाद्भुतदर्-
शन) 3. 160. 9; endowed with great perfec-
tion (ऋद्ध्या परमया युतम्) 3. 160. 9; vir-
tuous people always went there (सदा सुकृति-
नां गतिः) 7. 50. 42.
D. Characteristics:
(1) Controller of people (जनानां संय-
मनी) 13. 105. 16 (this explains the name
of the residence); (2) Where untruth is
not spoken but only the truth (यत्रानृतं
नोच्यते यत्र सत्यम्) 13. 105. 16; (3)
Where the weak are able to make the
strong ones make amends (यत्राबला बलि-
नं यातयन्ति) 13. 105. 16.
E. Epic events:
(1) Lomaśa showed it to Yudhiṣṭhira
holding him by his right hand (युधिष्ठि-
रं धौम्यो गृहीत्वा दक्षिणे करे) 3. 160.
3, 9; (2) Arjuna said that when Abhi-
manyu would reach Saṃyamanī it would
be illumined by his lustre and would
shine more brightly 7. 50. 42; there Yama
(Vaivasvata), Varuṇa, Śatakratu (Indra)
and Dhaneśa (Kubera) will praise Abhi-
manyu 7. 50. 43.
F. Past event: Gautama
told king Dhṛtarāṣṭra (really Indra), who
was forcibly taking away his elephant,
that he would make Indra compensate
for his elephant in the abode of Vaivasvata
(वैवस्वती संयमनी जनानाम् … तत्र
त्वाहं हस्तिनं यातयिष्ये) 13. 105. 16.
G. Mode of expression: संयमनीं गम्-
or या- ‘to go to the abode of Yama’ used
to express the meaning ‘to die’: (1)
The charioteer of Sātyaki wondered who,
by opposing him in battle, desired to go to
the abode of Yama (केषां संयमनीम्
अद्य गन्तुम् उत्सहते मनः) 7. 95. 18;
(2) Bhūriśravas told Sātyaki that he (Sā.)
would reach the abode of Yama when
struck by him (Bhūri.) (अद्य संयमनीं
याता मया त्वं निहतो रणे) 7. 117. 10.

संजयन्ती
Saṃjayantī f.: Name of a town.
Situated to the south of Indraprastha
(प्रययौ दक्षिणां दिशम्) 2. 28. 1;
(दक्षिणाभिमुखो ययौ) 2. 28. 8; (प्रायाद्
 … दक्षिणाम् दिशम्) 2. 28. 37; Sahadeva in
his expedition to the south before the
Rājasūya subjugated Saṃjayantī by just
sending his messengers and made the
people pay tribute (नगरीं संजयन्तीं
च … दूतैर् एव वशे चक्रे करं चैनान्
अदापयत्) 2. 28. 47.

समन्तपञ्चक
Samantapañcaka nt.: Name of a holy
place, also called Kurukṣetrasamantapañca-
ka and Pitāmahasya uttaravediḥ or Prajā-
pater uttaravediḥ (or uttaravedī) 3. 81.
178 = 9. 52. 20, 1; 9. 54. 5.
A. Location: Along the southern bank
of the river Sarasvatī (सरस्वत्याः … ।तीर्-
थानि … कूले वै दक्षिणे तदा।समन्त-
पञ्चकं यावत् तावत् ते द्विजसत्तमाः।
तीर्थलोभान् … नद्यास् तीरं समाश्रिताः॥)
9. 36. 41-42; a part of Kurukṣetra (9. 52.
1-2), hence called Kurukṣetrasamanta-
pañcaka; the land between Tarantuka
and Arantuka and between the (five) lakes
of Rāma and Macakruka—that is the
extent of Kurukṣetrasamantapañcaka
(तरन्तुकारुन्तकयोर् यद् अन्तरं राम-
ह्रदानां च मचक्रुकस्य।एतत् कुरु-
क्षेत्रसमन्तपञ्चकम्) 3. 81. 178 = 9.
52. 20.
B. Description: Holy (पुण्य) 1.
1. 11; 1. 2. 7, 11; 9. 63. 39; most holy in
the three worlds (महापुण्यतमे त्रैलो-
क्यस्य) 9. 54. 6; very ancient (सनातन)
9. 54. 6; pleasing (रमणीय) 1. 2. 11;
resorted to by twice-born (द्विजनिषेवित) 1.
1. 11; very pious (परमधर्मिष्ठ) 1. 2.
10; free from the defects of the earth (भू-
दोषवर्जित) 1. 2. 10; famous in the three
worlds (त्रिषु लोकेषु विश्रुते) 9. 63. 39.
C.
Characteristic: Rāma created at this place
five ponds filled with the blood of the Kṣa-
triyas killed by him; the place near these five
ponds came to be called Samantapañcaka,
since the wise say that a place should be
called after the characteristic by which it is
distinguished (तेषां समीपे यो देशो ह्रदा-
नां रुधिराम्भसाम्।समन्तपञ्चकम्
इति पुण्यं तत् परिकीर्तितम्॥येन लिङ्गेन
यो देशो युक्तः समुपलक्ष्यते।तेनैव
नाम्ना तं देशम् वाच्यम् आहुर् मनीषिणः॥)
1. 2. 7-8.
D. Holiness: (1) The holy
तीर्थस् on the southern bank of Sarasvatī
became towns and extended as far as Sama-
ntapañcaka (सरस्वत्याः … ।तीर्थानि नग-
रायन्ते कूले वै दक्षिणे तदा॥समन्त-
पञ्चकं यावत्) 9. 36. 42; (2) It was
called the most ancient उत्तरवेदि of Pra-
jāpati (or Pitāmaha) (प्रजापतेर् उत्तरवेदिर्
उच्यते सनातना राम समन्तपञ्चकम्। 9.
52. 1, 20; 9. 54. 5 (उत्तरवेदी); (पितामह-
स्योत्तरवेदिर् उच्यते) 3. 81. 178; a place in
heaven was assured for one who died while
fighting at Samantapañcaka (तस्मिन् … सं-
ग्रामे निधनं प्राप्य ध्रुवं स्वर्गो भ-
विष्यति) 9. 54. 6; 9. 63. 39.
E. Epic events:
(1) Sūta Ugraśravas visited Samantapañ-
caka before he arrived at the सत्र of
Śaunaka in the Naimiṣa forest (समन्तपञ्-
चकं नाम … ।गतवान् अस्मि तं देशम्) 1.
1. 11; the sages expressed their wish to
know more about the place Samantapañ-
caka 1. 2. 1; (2) Yudhiṣṭhira asked his
men to raise tents in thousands outside
Samantapañcaka (समन्तपञ्चकाद् बा-
ह्यम्) 6. 1. 6; (3) The battle between the
Pāṇḍavas and the Kauravas and between
all the kings was fought at Samantapañcaka
(युद्धं यत्राभवत् पुरा पाण्डवानां
कुरूणां च सर्वेषां च महीक्षिताम्) 1.
1. 11; the battle at Samantapañcaka took
place at the junction of the Kali and Dvā-
para and where the armies, eighteen अक्षौ-
हिणीस् in number had gathered for fighting
the battle (अन्तरे चैव सम्प्राप्ते कलिद्वा-
परयोर् अभूत्।समन्तपञ्चके युद्धं
कुरुपाण्डवसेनयोः॥ … अष्टादश समाज-
ग्मुर् अक्षौहिण्यो युयुत्सया) 1. 2. 9-10;
(4) While consoling Subhadrā over the
death of Abhimanyu, Kṛṣṇa told her that
on the following day she would hear that
the head of Jayadratha was severed from
his body and carried outside Samantapañ-
caka (श्वः शिरः श्रोष्यसे तस्य सैन्धव-
स्य रणे हृतम्।समन्तपञ्चकाद् बाह्यं)
7. 54. 20; Kṛṣṇa advised Arjuna to remove
the head of Jayadratha and let it fall on
the lap of Vṛddhakṣatra (father of Jaya-
dratha) who was practising austerities in
a forest outside Samantapañcaka (वृद्ध-
क्षत्रो वनं यातः … तप्यति … तपो
घोरं … ।समन्तपञ्चकाद् अस्माद् बहिः)
7. 121. 24-26; Arjuna, after he cut the head
of Jayadratha, took it outside Samantapañ-
caka with arrows which formed a close clu-
ster (शरैः कदम्बकीकृत्य काले तस्मिंश्
च पाण्डवः।समन्तपञ्चकाद् बाह्यं
शिरस् तद् व्याहरत् ततः॥) 7. 121. 34; (5)
Duryodhana suggested to go to Samanta-
pañcaka for his duel with Bhīma (समन्त-
पञ्चकं क्षिप्रम् इतो याम विशां पते)
9. 54. 5; Yudhiṣṭhira, followed by Duryo-
dhana, then went to Samantapañcaka 9.
54. 7; (6) From the तीर्थ of Vṛddha-
kanyā, Mādhava (Balarāma) came out of
Samantapañcaka (समन्तपञ्चकाद् द्वारात्
ततो निष्क्रम्य माधवः) 9. 51. 25.
F. Past events: (1) At Samantapañcaka,
which was known as the Uttaravedi
of Prajāpati, gods formerly offered an
excellent सत्र (प्रजापतेर् उत्तरवेदिर्
उच्यते … समन्तपञ्चकम्।समीजिरे यत्र
पुरा दिवौकसो वरेण सत्रेण) 9. 52. 1;
(2) Once many sages arrived at the तीर्थस्
on Sarasvatī which extended as far as Sa-
mantapañcaka with a view to visiting them;
they offered there sacrifices and filled the
regions with the sound of their vedic reci-
tations (समन्तपञ्चकं यावत् तावत् ते
द्विजसत्तमाः।तीर्थलोभान् नरव्याघ्र
नद्यास् तीरं समाश्रीताः॥) 9. 36. 42-43;
(3) Rāma deprived the earth of the Kṣa-
triyas twentyone times and filled at Samanta-
pañcaka five ponds with blood (त्रिःसप्त-
कृत्वः पृथिवीं कृत्वा निःक्षत्रियां प्र-
भुः।समन्तपञ्चके पञ्च चकार रुधि-
रह्रदान्॥) 3. 117. 9; 1. 2. 3-4. [see
Prajāpateḥ vedi2 Vol. 1. 387-88]

सम्भलग्राम
Sambhalagrāma m.: Name of a village.
A. Description: Auspicious (शुभ)
3. 188. 90.
B. Future event: Mārkaṇḍeya
told the Pāṇḍavas that in future (कालान्-
तरे ऽन्यस्मिन् 3. 188. 86) Kalki Viṣṇuśarman
a Brāhmaṇa will be born in the habitation of
the Brāhmaṇas at Sambhalagrāma; he will
be a sovereign monarch (कल्किर् विष्णुयशा
नाम द्विजः … ।उत्पत्स्यते … ॥संभूतः
सम्भलग्रामे ब्राह्मणावसथे शुभे। …
स धर्मविजयी राजा चक्रवर्ती भविष्यति)
3. 188. 89-91.

सरकस्य
*Sarakasya (? Sarakastasya) āśramaḥ
m.: Name of an आश्रम of Saraka (?
Sarakasta).
In the north, on the river Sarasvatī
(उदीच्यां … दिशि पुण्यानि … आयतनानि) 3.
88. 1; (सरस्वती पुण्यवहा ह्रदिनी … यत्र)
3. 88. 2; (सरस्वती नदी सद्भिः … पूजिता)
3. 88. 9; described as extremely holy and
famous (अत्यन्तम् आश्रमः पुण्यः सरकस्
तस्य (? सरकस्तस्य) विश्रुतः) 3. 88. 8.
[For Saraka, a तीर्थ see Vol. I. 466]

सरस्वत्या
Sarasvatyā āyatanam nt.: A holy
resort (temple ?) sacred to Sarasvatī.
A. Location: Located in the famous
forest near Śūrpāraka, not very far from the
sea (शूर्पारकं पुण्यतमं ददर्श।
तत्रोदधेः कंचिद् अतीत्य देशं ख्यातं
पृथिव्यां वनम् आससाद। … सरस्व-
त्याः। … आयतनानि तेषां ददर्श) 3. 118.
8-9, 13). For
B. Description and
C. Epic
event See Bhagasya āyatanam.

सवितुर्
Savitur āyatanam nt.: A holy resort
(temple ?) sacred to Savitṛ.
A. Location: Located in a holy forest,
famous on the earth, near Śūrpāraka and
not very far from the sea (शूर्पारकं
पुण्यतमं ददर्श॥तत्रोदधेः कंचिद्
अतीत्य देशं ख्यातं पृथिव्यां वनम् आस-
साद। … सवितुः … आयतनानि तेषां ददर्श)
3. 118. 8-9, 11, 13. For
B. Description and
C. Epic event see Bhagasya āyatanam.

साध्यगणस्य
Sādhyagaṇasya āyatanam nt.: A holy
resort (temple ?) sacred to the Sādhyas.
A. Location: Located in a holy forest,
famous on the earth, near Śūrpāraka and
not very far from the sea (शूर्पारकं
ददर्श॥तत्रोदधेः कंचिद् अतीत्य देशं
ख्यातं पृथिव्यां वनम् आससाद॥ …
साध्यगणस्य चैव … आयतनानि तेषाम्
ददर्श) 3. 118. 8-9, 12-13. For
B. Des-
cription and
C. Epic event see Bhagasya
āyatanam.

सिंहपुर
Siṃhapura nt.: Name of a city.

अ
A Location: In the north (प्रययाव्
उत्तरां तस्माद् दिशम्) 2. 24. 1.
B. Des-
cription: Delightful (रम्य) 2. 24. 19.
C. Epic event: It was ruled by Cirāyudha:
Arjuna defeated him in battle in his expedi-
tion to the north of Indraprastha before
the Rājasūya (ततः सिंहपुरं रम्यं
चित्रायुधसुरक्षितम्।प्रामथद् … पाक-
शासनिर् आहवे॥) 2. 24. 19.

सिद्धगणस्य
Siddhagaṇasya āyatanam nt.: A holy
resort (temple ?) sacred to the Siddhas.
A. Location: Situated in the forest,
well known on the earth, near Śūrpāraka,
not very far from the sea (शूर्पारकं …
ददर्श॥तत्रोदधेः कंचिद् अतीत्य देशं
ख्यातं पृथिव्यां वनम् आससाद। …
सिद्धगणस्य चैव … आयतनानि तेषां
ददर्श) 3. 118. 8-9, 13. For
B. Description
and
C. Epic event see Bhagasya āyatanam.

सुधर्मा
Sudharmā f.: Name of the Sabhā of
the Yādavas in Dvārakā.
A. Designation: Yādavī 16. 8. 7;
Dāśārhī 2. 3. 24.
B. Equipment: (1)
Furnished with hundreds of royal seats
(सिंहासनानि); parts of them were made of
gold, they were variegated due to gems and
corals set in them, were lustrous like burning
fire and were spread with precious covers,
(जाम्बूनदाङ्गानि स्पर्ध्यास्तरणवन्ति च।
मणिविद्रुमचित्राणि ज्वलीताग्निप्रभाणि च॥
भेजिरे पुरुषव्याघ्रा … सिंहासनानि शत-
शः) 1. 212. 13-14; (2) A war-drum was
placed in it; it was adorned with gold and,
when struck, it produced loud sound (भेरीं
सांनाहिकीं। … महाघोषां जाम्बूनद-
परिष्कृताम्) 1. 212. 11.
C. Management:
The Sabhā was supervised by a Sabhāpāla
whose duty was to beat the drum and alert
the citizens in the event of an emergency
(see the next).
D. Purpose: Whenever
an emergency arose the Sabhāpāla beat
the भेरी to produce loud sound; hearing
it, the agitated Bhojas, Vṛṣṇis and Andha-
kas would leave aside their food and drink
and rush to the Sabhā to know the nature
of the emergency 1. 212. 11-12.
E. Epic
events: (1) When Subhadrā was forcibly
abducted by Arjuna, the soldiers accom-
panying her rushed to the Sudharmā Sabhā
and acquainted the Sabhāpāla with what
had happened; when the Vṛṣṇi heroes who
gathered in the Sabhā sat down on the
royal seats, the Sabhāpāla told them about
the abduction of Subhadrā by Arjuna 1.
212. 9-10, 15; (2) After the mutual kill-
ings by the Yādavas, when Arjuna reached
Dvārakā he entered the Sudharmā to meet
the ministers of the Vṛṣṇi heroes; when he
occupied a seat in the Sabhā the citizens
gathered around him 16. 8. 7-8.
F. Compa-
rison: Sudharmā was not equal to the
unrivalled Sabhā constructed by Maya for
the Pāṇḍavas (सभा तु सा महाराज …
न दाशार्ही सुधर्मा वा … तादृशी … यां
चक्रे ऽप्रतिमां मयः) 2. 3. 19, 24.

सुभाण्ड
Subhāṇḍa nt.: Name of a square (?)
Along with the Sudarśana वट, it
marked the entrance of the royal residence
of the Bāhlīka counry; it was referred to
by an old Brāhmaṇa while speaking to
Dhṛtarāṣṭṛa deriding the Bāhlīkas (तत्र
वृद्धः … द्विजोत्तमः।बाह्लीकदेशं …
कुत्सयन् वाक्यम् अब्रवीत्॥ … सुभाण्डं
नाम चत्वरम्।एतद् राजकुलद्वारम्
आकुमारं स्मराम्य् अहम्॥) 8. 30. 9, 12
(Nī., who reads सुभद्रं नाम चत्वरं
in 8. 44. 8, observes: सुभद्रं चत्वरं
सुराभाण्डाश्रयभूलम्।एतद् उभयं
राजकुलस्य राजगृहद्वारोपलक्षणम्).

सोमकस्य
*Somakasya āśramaḥ m.: आश्रम of
king Somaka.
A. Location: On the river Yamunā,
in the middle of Kurukṣetra (एषा सा यमु-
ना) 3. 125. 22, (कुरुक्षेत्रस्य मध्यतः)
3. 126. 42.
B. Description: Holy (पुण्य)
3. 128. 18.
C. Holiness: If one who has
suppressed his anger lives for six nights at
Somaka's आश्रम he will be in a happy con-
dition (एष तस्याश्रमः (i. e. of Somaka)
पुण्यो य एषो ऽग्रे विराजते।क्षान्त उष्यात्र
षड्रात्रं प्राप्नोति सुगतिं नरः) 3. 128.
18.
D. Epic event: Lomaśa showed it to
Yudhiṣṭhira and suggested to him that
they all should stay there for six nights
controlling themselves; so he asked Yudhi-
ṣṭhira to be ready for it (एतस्मिन्न् अपि
राजेद्र वत्स्यामो … ।षड्रात्रं नियतात्-
मानः सज्जीभव कुरूद्वह॥) 3. 128. 19.

सोमपुरप्रभ
Somapuraprabha nt.: Name of a
town (?)
Aṣṭaka, son of Viśvāmitra from Mā-
dhavī, went to the town Somapuraprabha
(or to the town shining like Somapura ?)
(अथाष्टकः पुरं प्रायात् तदा सोमपुर-
प्रभम्) 5. 117. 19.

सोमाश्रम
Somāśrama m.: An आश्रम of Soma.
Situated between Urvaśītīrtha and
Kumbhakarṇāśrama; one who bathes there
is honoured on this earth (स्नात्वा पूज्यते
भुवि मानवः) 3. 82. 136.

सौभ
Saubha1 nt.: Name of the city of
Śālva, the demon.
A. Location: Located in the sky
(खस्थ) 5. 47. 73; 7. 10. 14; (खे विषक्-
तं हि तत् सौभम्) 3. 21. 25; (वैहायसं
 … पुरम्) 3. 16. 3; (दिवम् आस्थितः …
सौभेन) 3. 15. 15; 3. 20. 27; (वियद् अभ्या-
गमत् पुनः) 3. 22. 1, 3; (सौभस्थं
पृथिवीगतम्) 3. 17. 28; (Nī. on Bom. Ed.
3. 12. 32: सौभं खेचरं पुरम्: on 3.
16. 15: सौभेन खेचरेण पुरेण).
B. Its
ruler and subjects: It was Śālva's town, ruled
over by him and protected by him (शाल्वस्य
नगरं सौभम्) 3. 15. 2; (शाल्वगुप्त)
7. 10. 14; hence Śālva was called Saubha-
pati 3. 13. 29; 3. 17. 1, 31; 3. 18. 19; 3. 21.
31; 3. 23. 20; Saubharāj 3. 15. 11; 3. 17.
32; 3. 18. 15; 3. 20. 12, 14, 16; Saubhā-
dhipati 3. 180. 33; Daiteyas and Dānavas
were its inhabitants, hence called Daityapura
7. 10. 14; (दैतेयान् … सौभनिवासिनः) 3. 18.
4; (युद्धं … दानवैः सह) 3. 15. 21;
(दानवानां) 3. 21. 27; (सौभात् … विबुध-
द्विषाम्) 3. 23. 1.
C. Description: Moving
at will (कामग) 3. 15. 6, 15; (कामगम)
3. 23. 9; difficult to be attacked (दुरासद)
7. 10. 14; having the form of a peak of
Meru mountain (मेरुशिखराकार) 3. 23.
39; it lost its lustre (when struck by the
चक्र of Kṛṣṇa) and its watch-towers and
gateways were shattered (व्यपगतत्विष्) 3.
23. 33 (Nī. on Bom. Ed. 3. 14. 6 explains
सौभ as: सौभं सुष्ठु भान्ति ते सुभाः
काञ्चनादयो धातवस् तज्जम्); (विध्वस्ता-
ट्टालगोपुर) 3. 23. 39; called पुर 3. 16. 3; 3.
21. 18; 7. 10. 14; नगर 3. 15. 2; 3. 21. 9; 3.
23. 33.
D. Epic events: Kṛṣṇa told Yudhi-
ṣṭhira that at the time of the game of dice
he had gone to Saubha, the town of Śālva,
to kill him (शाल्वस्य नगरं सौभं गतो
ऽहम्) 3. 15. 2; in the absence of Kṛṣṇa,
Śālva, enraged at the killing of Śiśupāla, rode
his Saubha, moving at will, and attacked
Dvārakā (आगतः कामगं सौभम् आरु-
ह्य) 3. 15. 5-7; when Śālva did not find
Kṛṣṇa in Dvārakā, he reviled Kṛṣṇa, rode
his Saubha, and flew up in the sky (दिवम्
आस्थितः।कामगेन च सौभेन क्षिप्त्वा
माम्) 3. 15. 15; therefore Kṛṣṇa, when he
returned to Dvārakā from Indraprastha, left
for the destruction of Saubha (ततः सौ-
भवधायाहं प्रतस्थे) 3. 15. 19; Yudhi-
ṣṭhira then requested Kṛṣṇa to tell him the
downfall of Saubha in detail (विस्तरेण …
सौभस्य वधम् आचक्ष्व) 3. 16. 1; when
Śālva reached Dvārakā, he besieged it on
all sides, arranging his sky-moving town (all
around) in battle positions (अरुन्धत् तां
(द्वारवतीं पुरीम्) … सर्वतः … ।शाल्वो
वैहायसं चापि तत्पुरं व्यूह्य विष्ठि-
तः॥) 3. 16. 3 (Nī. on Bom. Ed. 3. 15. 3:
व्यूह्य स्वरक्षापरोपमर्दयोग्यरचना-
विशेषेण स्थापयित्वा); Dvārakā was well
protected when Śālva attacked it (तदा
सौभसमागमे) 3. 16. 19; when Śālva's
heroes were killed in battle, he (went
back; but) came again in his Saubha,
moving at will, to attack Dvārakā (काम-
गेन स सौभेन शाल्वः पुनर् उपागमत्)
3. 17. 27; the army in Dvārakā was dis-
tressed seeing Śālva descending from sky
on the earth (दृष्ट्वा शाल्वं … सौभस्थं
पृथिवीगतम्) 3. 17. 28; Pradyumna assu-
red his army that he would defeat in battle
the Saubha with its king (Śālva) (न भीः
कार्या।सौभराड् अद्य नश्यति। … ससौ-
भो विनशिष्यति) 3. 17. 30-32; Pradyumna
confounded all demons of the Saubha
with quickly shifting the bow from palm
to palm (स … चापं विहरन् वै तलात्
तलम्।मोहयाम् आस दैतेयान् सर्वान् सौ-
भनिवासिनः) 3. 18. 4; when defeated by
Pradyumna, Śālva abandoned Dvārakā,
rode his Saubha and flew up in the sky
(सौभम् आस्थाय … दिवम् आचक्रमे) 3.
20. 27; when Kṛṣṇa, on his return to Dvā-
rakā, learnt about the attack on Dvārakā
by Śālva, he vowed to destroy the town
Saubha along with Śālva (सशाल्वं सौभ-
नगरं हन्ता) 3. 21. 9; when he learnt that
Sālva, in his Saubha, had gone back, he
pursued him (प्रयातं सौभम् आस्थाय)
3. 21. 15; Kṛṣṇa left for the destruction of
Saubha after asking Sātyaki and others to
protect Dvārakā (तेषु रक्षां समाधाय
प्रयातः सौभपातने) 3. 22. 17; Śālva
then in his Saubha, had taken refuge in
the bay of the ocean and remained hidden
in its navel (ततः सागरम् आसाद्य कुक्षौ
तस्य महोर्मिणः।समुद्रनाभ्यां शाल्वो
ऽभूत् सौभम् आस्थाय) 3. 21. 16 (Nī. on
Bom. Ed. 3. 20. 17: नाभ्यां गर्भे गुप्त
इत्य् अर्थः); Kṛṣṇa's arrows could not reach
the town (Saubha) (पुरं नासाद्यत
शरैः) 3. 21. 18; the Saubha though close
to the sky appeared as if it was at a dis-
tance of only a क्रोश from Kṛṣṇa (खे
विषक्तं हि तत् सौभं क्रोशमात्र इवा-
भवत्) 3. 21. 25; when Kṛṣṇa's arrows
pierced the bodies of the Dānavas, there
was a loud din in the Saubha (ततो हल-
हलाशब्दः सौभमध्ये व्यवर्धत) 3.
21. 28; Kṛṣṇa saw Vasudeva falling down
from Saubha: but after some time, Saubha,
Śālva and Vasudeva disappeared; all this
was माया of Śālva (अपश्यं … प्रपतन्-
तम् अहं तदा।सौभाच् छूरसुतं) 3.
22. 22; न तत्र सौभं न रिपुं न
शाल्वम् पश्यामि वृद्धं पितरं न चापि॥
ततो ममासीन् मनसि मायेयम्) 3. 22. 29-
30; Kṛṣṇa then felled down the heads of
the demons from the Saubha (सौभाच्
छिरांसि विबुधद्विषाम्) 3. 23. 1; the
Saubha then disappeared due to माया of
Śālva (ततो नादृश्यत तदा सौभं … ।
अन्तर्हितं माययाभूत्) 3. 23. 3; Saubha,
moving at will, went to Prāgjyotiṣa and, (on
its return), was seen again (ततः प्राग्ज्योति-
षं गत्वा पुनर् एव व्यदृश्यत।सौभं
कामगमम्) 3. 23. 9 (Nī. on Bom. Ed. 3.
22. 9: प्राग्ज्योतिषं पूर्वसमुद्रतीरस्थं
नगरविशेषं); Kṛṣṇa's charioteer drew his
attention to Śālva, the ruler of Saubha (पश्य
 … शाल्वं सौभपतिं स्थितम्) 3. 23. 20;
Kṛṣṇa then decided to kill Śālva and bring
down Saubha (युद्धे मतिम् अधारयम्।
वधाय शाल्वराजस्य सौभस्य च निपात-
ने॥) 3. 23. 27; he then employed the आग्नेय
अस्त्र on his चक्र and commanded “kill
Saubha and my enemies” (आग्नेयम् अस्त्रम्
 … चक्रम् … अभिमन्त्र्य … जहि सौभं
स्ववीर्येण ये चात्र रिपवो मम।इत्य्
उक्त्वा … तस्मै प्राहिणवम्) 3. 23. 28. 31;
the चक्र struck the town Saubha and cut
it into two in the middle; when the Saubha
fell down the चक्र came back to Kṛṣṇa's
hand (तत् समासाद्य नगरं सौभम् …
मध्येन पाटयाम् आस … ।द्विधा कृतं
ततः सौभम् … तस्मिन् निपतिते सौभे
चक्रम् आगात् करं मम) 3. 23. 33-35; see-
ing the Saubha on fire, the women (of the
Dānavas) fled 3. 23. 39; Kṛṣṇa steadied his
chariot near the Saubha and blew his conch
(ततो ऽहं समवस्थाप्य रथं सौभ-
समीपतः शङ्खं प्रध्माप्य) 3. 23. 38;
after killing Śālva and bringing down the
Saubha, Kṛṣṇa returned to the Ānarta
country (एवं निहत्य समरे शाल्वं सौ-
भं निपात्य च।आनर्तान् पुनर् आगम्य)
3. 23. 40; the downfall of Saubha and the
killing of Śālva by Kṛṣṇa is referred to
at various places: (1) By Arjuna when
he recounted the exploits of Kṛṣṇa (त्वया
सौभं च पातितम्) 3. 13. 29; (2) By
Arjuna again in his message to Dhṛtarāṣṭra
through Saṃjaya (अयं सौभं योधयाम्
आस खस्थं … सौभद्वारि प्रत्यगृह्णाच्
छतघ्नीम्) 5. 47. 73 (reference to 3. 22.
2-3 where attack on Kṛṣṇa with शतघ्नीस्
and other missiles is mentioned ?); (3) By
Kṛṣṇa when he suggested to Yudhiṣṭhira
to send Suyodhana and his allies the way
Śālva and Saubha had gone (प्रस्थाप्य-
तां पाण्डव धार्तराष्ट्रः सुयोधनः …
सौभस्य सौभाधिपतेश् च मार्गम्॥)
3. 180. 33; (4) By Vidura when he remind-
ed Duryodhana that a monkey-chief, Dvi-
vida by name, covered Kṛṣṇa with rocks
at the gate of Saubha in order to arrest him
but he did not succeed (सौभद्वारे वानरे-
न्द्रो द्विविदो नाम नामतः।शिलावर्षेण
महता छादयाम् आस केशवम्॥ग्रहीतु-
कमो … ग्रहीतुं नाशकत् तत्र) 5. 128. 41-
42 (reference to 3. 23. 10-19 where the
showering of rocks is attributed to a Dānava
who had assumed the form of a monkey
दानवो वानराकृतिः); (5) By Dhṛtarāṣṭra
when he recounted Kṛṣṇa's wonderful
exploits (दिव्यानि कर्माणि 7. 10. 1); he re-
ferred to his bringing down Saubha which
had taken refuge in the bay of the ocean
(सौभं … समुद्रकुक्षौ विक्रम्य पात-
याम् आस माधवः) 7. 10. 14 (reference
to 3. 21. 16-38); (6) By Bhagavān when
he told Nārada that at the conjunction
of Dvāpara and Kali he would destroy all
those residing in the Saubha (सर्वान् सौ-
भनिवासिनः) 12. 326. 87.
E. Simile: The
falling down of the Saubha, when struck
by Sudarśana, compared with the falling
down of Tripura tossed up by the arrow
of Maheśvara (सौभं सुदऽशनबलाद्
धतम्।महेश्वरशरोद्धूतं पपात
त्रिपुरं यथा) 3. 23. 34.

सौभ
Saubha2 nt.: Name of the city of
king Śālva.
A. Its king: Śālva is referred to as
Saubhapati 1. 96. 48; 5. 175. 24; 5. 176. 2;
as Saubharāj 5. 176. 36; sometimes the
name of the king is identified with the
name of the city and hence the king of
the city Saubha is referred to as Śālvapati
instead of Saubhapati in 5. 171. 6; 5. 172.
2, 10, 14, 18; 5. 174. 3; 5. 175. 22 (मया
शाल्वपतिर् वीर मनसाभिवृतः पतिः
where पति is repeated; cf. with this 1. 96.
48 where सौभपतिः occurs and not शाल्व-
पतिः); 5. 176. 34.
B. Epic event:
When Śālva was defeated by Bhīṣma, he
returned to his town (Saubha) (ततः
शाल्वः स्वनगरं प्रययौ) 1. 96. 39;
Ambā told Bhīṣma that she had already
chosen the king of Saubha as her husband
(मया सौभपतिः पूर्वं मनसाभिवृतः
पतिः) 1. 96. 48; permitted by Bhīṣma, she
went to the town Saubha (गता सौभ-
पुरं प्रति) 5. 178. 10; Ambā returned to
Śālva, the ruler of Saubha, and told him
that she was allowed by Bhīṣma to go to
him (शाल्वं सौभपतिं ततः।कन्ये-
यं … वचनम् अब्रवीत्॥विसर्जितास्मि
भीष्मेण) 5. 175. 24-25; Ambā approached
the king of Saubha, but he did not accept
her (सौभराजम् उपेत्याहम् अब्रुवं दुर्-
वचं वचः।न च मां प्रत्यगृह्णात् सः)
5. 176. 36; when rejected by Śālva, Ambā
went out of the town (Saubha) and took
resort in the आश्रम of the ascetics outside
the town (निश्चक्राम पुराद् दीना) 5. 172.
23; 5. 173. 1; (जगाम नगराद् बहिः।
आश्रमं … तापसानाम्) 5. 173. 9; Akṛta-
vraṇa, the follower of Rāma, told Ambā
that if she desired Rāma to enjoin the
ruler of Saubha (to accept her), he (Rāma)
would do so (यदि सौभपतिर् भद्रे नियो-
क्तव्यो मते तव।नियोक्ष्यति … तं रामः)
5. 176. 2 (Nī. on Bom. Ed. 5. 177. 2: नियो-
क्तव्यस् तव पाणिग्रहणार्थम् इति शेषः).

स्थूलकेशाश्रम
Sthūlakeśāśrama m.: Name of an
आश्रम।
The आश्रम of the great sage Sthūla-
keśa (ऋषिरासीन् महान् … स्थूलकेश इति
ख्यातः॥) 1. 8. 4; Menakā abandoned her
child, a daughter, begotten on her by the
Gandharva king Viśvāvasu, on the bank
of a river near the आश्रम of Sthūlakeśa
(मेनका … तं गर्भं … ।उत्ससर्ज
यथाकालं स्थूलकेशाश्रमं प्रति॥उत्सृ-
ज्य चैव तं गर्भं नद्यास् तीरे जगाम
ह) 1. 8. 6-7; Sthūlakeśa saw the new-born
child alone on the bank of the river; he
brought her to his आश्रम and reared her
(तां ददर्श समुत्सृष्टां नदीतीरे महान्
ऋषिः। … स तां दृष्ट्वा तदा कन्यां स्थूल-
केशो … ।जग्राहाथ मुनिश्रेष्ठः … पुपोष
च।ववृधे सा … आश्रमपदे) 1. 8. 8-9;
she was named Pramadvarā; Ruru, son of
Pramati, saw her in the आश्रम and fell in
love with her; when Ruru asked for her
through his friends, Sthūlakeśa gave his
daughter to him (ताम् आश्रमपदे तस्य
रुरुर् दृष्ट्वा प्रमद्वराम्।बभूव …
मदनानुगतात्मवान्॥) 1. 8. 11-13.

स्थूलशिरास
Sthūlaśirāsa āśramaḥ m.: The आश्रम
of Sthūlaśiras.
Described as delightful (रमणीय);
Yudhiṣṭhira was advised by Lomaśa to give
up pride and anger while in that आश्रम
(आश्रमः स्थूलशिरसो रमणीयः प्रकाश-
ते।अत्र मानं च कौन्तेय क्रोधं चैव
विवर्जय॥) 3. 135. 8.

हास्तिनपुर
Hāstinapura nt.: Name of a city, also
referred to as Nāgapura 1. 105. 18, 21,
23; 1. 110. 37, 40; 1. 117. 9; 3. 90. 22; 3.
180. 34, 35; 4. 24. 6; 5. 145. 5, 6; 8. 1. 25;
9. 26. 22; 14. 51. 52, Gajapura 13. 153.
6; also once Dhārtarāṣṭrapura 3. 242. 17;
Nāgasāhvaya 1. 2. 145; 1. 39. 20; 1.
117. 4; 1. 122. 11; 1. 154. 16; 1. 199.
11; 2. 43. 2; 3. 1. 33; 5. 6. 18; 5. 147. 9;
9. 61. 38; 9. 62. 32; 12. 4. 21; 12. 38. 43;
13. 152. 11; 14. 61. 7; 14. 69. 13; 14. 70. 10;
16. 9. 37; (Nī. on Bom. Ed. 1. 2. 231:
नागो हस्ती।तेन समानसंज्ञं हस्तिना-
पुरम् इत्य् अर्थः), Gajasāhvaya 1. 68. 12;
1. 102. 22; 1. 105. 19, 27; 1. 122. 12; 2. 43.
12; 2. 71. 25; 3. 1. 8; 3. 34. 81; 5. 176. 10;
5. 179. 15; 11. 11. 1; 14. 14. 16; 14. 50. 50;
14. 51. 2; 15. 22. 3; 15. 31. 18; 15. 44. 15;
17. 1. 23, Vāraṇasāhvaya 1. 119. 3; 3.
150. 8; 3. 293. 15; 5. 173. 2; 9. 55. 19; 13.
152. 13; 14. 51. 24; 14. 65. 1; 14. 70. 2,
Nāgāhvaya 7. 1. 7; 8. 1. 17, 25; 14. 64.
18; 14. 83. 1; 14. 86. 1), Gajāhvaya 1. 37.
9; 2. 71. 20; 3. 7. 17; 5. 175. 19; 12. 58.
30; 15. 21. 12; 18. 5. 29, Vāraṇāhvaya 3.
238. 13; 15. 47. 21; when referred to as
Nāgasāhvaya etc., generally accompanied
by the word नगर or पुर।
A. Founding and explanation of the
name: The city was founded by king
Hastin, the son of Suhotra and Suvarṇā;
that is why the city is called Hāstinapura
(तस्याम् (i. e. सुवर्णायाम्) अस्य (i. e.
सुहोत्रस्य) जज्ञे हस्ती।य इदं हास्तिन-
पुरं मापयाम् आस।एतद् अस्य हास्तिन-
पुरत्वम्) 1. 90. 36;
B. Description:
Delightful (रम्य) 1. 94. 10; the best
city (नगरोत्तम) 13. 153. 5; praised
as the best among towns (ततो निर्वचनं
लोके सर्वराष्ट्रेष्व् अवर्तत॥ … पुराणां
गजसाह्वयम्॥) 1. 102. 21-22 (Nī. on
Bom. Ed. 1. 109. 23: निर्वचनं प्रशंसा);
comparable with the city of Indra (पुरन्-
दरपुरोपम) 1. 94. 38; the houses in
Hāstinapura looked like white mountains
(श्वेतपर्वतरूपेभ्यो गृहेभ्यः) 11. 9. 9;
the capital town of the Kurus (कुरूणाम्
पुटभेदने) 1. 94. 10 (Nī. on Bom. Ed.
1. 100. 12: पुटभेदने पत्तने).
C. Des-
cription of the town on specific occasions:
(1) On the arrival of Kṛṣṇa and Arjuna:
full of delighted people (संप्रहृष्टनरा-
कुल) 14. 51. 24; (2) When the still-born
child, Parīkṣit, was brought back to life:
people decorated the town with heaps of
garlands; citizens beautified their houses
with small and big flags; the highways
were decorated with flowers; the city looked
bright and produced sound similar to the
tide of the ocean; owing to the sound of
dancing and singing of dancers the town
appeared like the residence of Vaiśravaṇa
(Kubera); the city's empty places were
filled with bards in thousands, accom-
panied by women; flags moving in the blow-
ing wind as if pointed out to the Kurus
the northern and the southern direction;
the high-placed king's officer then announc-
ed to the people enjoyment, all through the
night, in which ornaments of jewels were
to be displayed (अलंचक्रुश् च माल्यौ-
घैः पुरुषा नागसाह्वयम्॥पताकाभिर्
विचित्राभिर् ध्वजैश् च विविधैर् अपि।वेश्मानि
समलंचक्रुः पौराश् चापि जनाधिप॥
राजमार्गाश् च तत्रासन् सुमनोभिर् अलं-
कृताः।शुशुभे तत् पुरं चापि समुद्रौ-
घनिभस्वनम्॥नर्तकैश् चापि नृत्यद्-
भिर् गायकानां च निस्वनैः।आसीद्
वैश्रवणस्येव निवासस् तत् पुरं तदा॥
बन्दिभिश् च नरै राजन् स्त्री सहायैः सह-
स्रशः।तत्र तत्र विविक्तेषु समन्ताद्
उपशोभितम्॥पताका धूयमानाश् च श्व-
सता मातरिश्वना।अदर्शयन्न् इव तदा
कुरून् वै दक्षिणोत्तरान्॥अघोषयत् तदा
चापि पुरुषो राजधूर्गतः।सर्वरात्रिविहारो
ऽद्य रत्नाभरणलक्षणः॥) 14. 69. 13-20;
(3) After the departure of Dhṛtarāṣṭra,
Gāndhārī, Kuntī and Vidura, the whole
town with its old men, women and child-
ren became cheerless, the town was as if
without any sound as at the end of a festival
(तद् अहृष्टम् इवाकूजं गतोत्सवम् इवाभ-
वत्।नगरं हास्तिनपुरं सस्त्रीवृद्ध-
कुमारकं॥) 15. 24. 14.
D. Epic events:
The name of the city occurs in connection
with many important events; on various
occasions, however, Hāstinapura is referred
to simply by words such as नगर or पुर
(in the following listing references of this
type where the city is not directly named
are likely to be incomplete) (1) Jana-
mejaya, son of Parikṣit, after the comple-
tion of his सत्र at Kurukṣetra, returned
to Hāstinapura and searched for a suita-
ble Purohita who could pacify the evil
act done by him (स तस्मिन् सत्रे समाप्ते
हास्तिनपुरं प्रत्येत्य पुरोहितम् अनुरू-
पम् अन्विच्छमानः परं यत्नम् अकरोद्
यो मे पापकृत्यां शमयेद् इति) 1. 3. 10 (Nī.
on Bom. Ed. 1. 3. 11: पापकृत्यां शापरू-
पां बलायुःप्राणनिकृन्तनीं देवताम्);
(2) Uttaṅka, wanting to take revenge on
Takṣaka for his misdeed, started for Hāsti-
napura; (उत्तङ्कः … हास्तिनपुरं प्रतस्-
थे।स हास्तिनपुरं प्राप्य) 1. 3. 177-
178; (3) Parikṣit, after placing the body
of a dead snake on the shoulder of Śṛṅgin's
father returned to his town Gajāhvaya
(स्वनगरं प्रतियातो गजाह्वयम्) 1. 37.
9; (4) When Kāśyapa ceased from pro-
ceeding to Hāstinapura, Takṣaka himself
went speedily to the town Nāgasāhvaya
(निवृत्ते काश्यपे … ।जगाम तक्षकस् तूर्-
णं नगरं नागसाह्वयम्॥) 1. 39. 20;
(5) Śaṃtanu ruled the earth from Hāsti-
napura, the capital town of the Kurus (स
हास्तिनपुरे रम्ये कुरूणां पुटभेदने।
वसन् … अन्वशाद् वै वसुंधराम्) 1. 94.
10; (6) Śaṃtanu, unwilling to agree to
the condition laid down by the Dāśa, re-
turned to Hāstinapura (प्रत्ययाद् धास्तिन-
पुरम्) 1. 94. 53; (7) Bhīṣma took Satya-
vatī on a chariot to Hāstinapura and repor-
ted to Śaṃtanu (आगम्य हास्तिनपुरम्
शंतनोः संन्यवेदयत्) 1. 94. 92; (8)
Bhīṣma having won the Kāśi princesses,
brought them to Hāstinapura (प्रययौ
हास्तिनपुरम्) 1. 96. 41; (9) Kings who
formerly collected wealth from Kuru kings
(wealth described in 1. 105. 16-18) were
made to pay it back as tribute by Pāṇḍu,
king of Nāgapura and the lion of Nāgapura
(तत् सर्वं प्रतिजग्राह राजा नागपुरा-
धिपः) 1. 105. 18; (ते नागपुरसिंहेन
पाण्डुना करदाः कृताः) 1. 105. 21; he then
returned to Gajasāhvaya (ययौ पाण्डुः …
पुरं च गजसाह्वयम्) 1. 105. 19; Bhīṣma
and others who lived in Nāgapura (नाग-
पुरालयाः) went out (of the town) a little
distance to receive Pāṇḍu 1. 105. 23;
Bhīṣma, delighted, entered the town Gaja-
sāhvaya with Pāṇḍu (विवेश गजसाह्वयम्)
1. 105. 27; (10) Pāṇḍu sent messengers to
Nāgapura to inform Bhīṣma and others
that he had resolved to repair to the forest
to lead the life of an ascetic; accordingly,
the messengers quickly went to Nāgapura
(गत्वा नागपुरं वाच्यं पाण्डुः प्रव्र-
जितो वनम्॥ … ययुर् नागपुरं तूर्णम्)
1. 110. 37, 40; (11) After the death of
Pāṇḍu, Kuntī and the Pāṇḍavas were
brought by the ascetics to Hāstinapura and
reported to Bhīṣma and Vidura (हास्तिन-
पुरम् आनीय … भीष्मस्य विदुरस्य च
निवेदिताः) 1. 90. 77; (नगरं नागसाह्व-
यम्॥ … गमने चक्रिरे मनः) 1. 117.
4-5; when the citizens of Hāstinapura
heard about the arrival of the ascetics they
were astonished; the people of Nāgapura
went out to receive them (श्रुत्वा नागपुरे
नॄणां विस्मयः समजायत॥ … निर्ययुः
पुरवासिनः) 1. 117. 9-10; (12) When
Pāṇḍu's श्राद्ध ceremony was performed
on the Ganges by Bhīṣma and others, the
citizens took the Pāṇḍavas, who had per-
formed purification, and entered the town
Vāraṇasāhvaya (कृतशौचान् … पाण्डवान् … ।
आदाय विविशुः पौराः पुरं वारणसाह्व-
यम्॥) 1. 119. 3; (13) Droṇa, insulted
by Drupada, decided to do something to
the Pāñcālas and went to Hāstinapura, the
city of the Kuru chiefs (जगाम कुरुमु-
ख्यानां नगरं नागसाह्वयम्॥) 1. 122.
11 = 1. 154. 16; the Kuru princes had come
out of Gajasāhvaya and were playing with
a wooden piece (tip cat) (निष्क्रम्य …
गजसाह्वयात्।क्रीडन्तो वीटया) 1. 122. 12
(Nī. on Bom. Ed. 1. 131. 17: वीटया यवा-
कारेण प्रादेशमात्रकाष्ठेन।यत् हस्त-
मात्रदण्डेन उपर्य् उपरि कुमाराः प्र-
क्षिपन्ति।लोहगुलिकयेत्य् अन्ये); (14)
Adhiratha sent Karṇa to Vāraṇasāhvaya
(to learn the science of missiles from Droṇa
(प्रस्थापयाम् आस पुरं वारणसाह्वयम्)
3. 293. 15; (15) After the battle that
ensued at the time of the स्वयंवर of the
Kaliṅga princess, Duryodhana, protected
by Karṇa, went from Rājapura to Nāga-
sāhvaya taking with him the princess (नग-
रं नागसाह्वयम्) 12. 4. 21; (16) Dhṛta-
rāṣṭra told the Pāṇḍavas that after enjoy-
ing themselves at Vāraṇāvata for some
time, they would return to Hāstinapura
(हास्थिनपुरं सुखिनः पुनर् एष्यथ)
1. 131. 10; (17) When Duryodhana and
others realized that the Pāṇḍavas were
really not dead, they blamed Virocana and
entered Hāstinapura (विविशुर् हास्तिनपुरम्)
1. 192. 13; (18) Vidura told Drupada
that the Pāṇḍavas and Kuntī would be
anxious to return to the town (Hāstina-
pura); that all the Kuru ladies, the
city and the country, anxious to see them,
were awaiting their arrival (इमे चापि नरर्-
षब्ःआः।उत्सुका नगरं द्रष्टुं भविष्य-
न्ति पृथा तथा॥ … कुरुवरस्त्रियः।द्रष्टु-
कामाः प्रतीक्षन्ते पुरं च विषयं च
नः॥) 1. 198. 22-23; the Pāṇḍavas, to-
gether with Draupadī and Kuntī, went
happily to the town Nāgasāhvaya (नग-
रं नागसाह्वयम्) 1. 199. 11; they slowly
entered the town Hāstinapura (नगरं
हास्तिनपुरम्) 1. 199. 14; when the Pāṇḍa-
vas arrived, the town as though burst with
curiosity (कौतूहलेन नगरं दीर्यमा-
णं इवाभवत्) 1. 199. 15; at the bidding
of Dhṛtarāṣṭra, the Pāṇḍavas, with the
whole town (following them), entered their
houses (सर्वेण नगरेण ते।समाविशन्त
वेश्मानि) 1. 199. 22; this event is included
in Vaiśaṃpāyana's summary of the epic (ते
तत्र द्रौपदीं लब्ध्वा … हास्तिनपुरं
प्रत्याजग्मुर् अरिंदमाः॥) 1. 55. 22; (19)
Yudhiṣṭhira sent Nakula to Hāstinapura
to invite Bhīṣma and others for the Rāja-
sūya; accordingly Nakula went to Hāstina-
pura and invited Bhīṣma and Dhṛtarāṣṭra
(प्रेषयाम् आस पाण्डवम्।नकुलं हास्तिन-
पुरम् … ॥; स गत्वा हासिइनपुरं नकुलः)
2. 30. 53; 2. 31. 1; (20) Duryodhana saw
in the Sabhā of the Pāṇḍavas heavenly
(architectural) designs which he had never
seen in the town Nāgasāhvaya (तस्यां
दिव्यान् अभिप्रायान् ददर्श कुरुनन्दनः।
न दृष्टपूर्वा ये तेन नगरे नागसाह्वये)
2. 43. 2 (Nī, however, on Bom. Ed. 2. 47.
2: अभिप्रायान् देवादीनां क्रीडातत्स्थानाद्।
यभिनयप्रदर्शकचित्रादिगतान् आशयविशे-
षान्); (21) Duryodhana returned to Gaja-
sāhvaya sad after seeing the prosperity of
the Pāṇḍavas at Rājasūya (जगाम गज-
साह्वयम्) 2. 43. 12; (22) On reaching
Hāstinapura, Yudhiṣṭhira went straight to
the residence of Dhṛtarāṣṭra 2. 52. 22; (23)
While going to the forest Draupadī said
that fourteen years later the Kuru women,
with their hair loose, will enter Gajāhvaya
after offering water libations to their dead
husbands (मुक्तकेश्यो … एवं कृतोदका
नार्यः प्रवेक्ष्यन्ति गजाह्वयम्) 2. 71. 20;
(24) While the Pāṇḍavas were going out
of Gajasāhvaya, bad omens like lightning
flashes in the absence of clouds, shaking
of the earth occurred (निर्यत्सु गजसाह्व-
यात्) 2. 71. 25; (25) The Pāṇḍavas came
out of Gajasāhvaya to go to the forest
through a gate at Vardhamānapura (निर्य-
युर् गजसाह्वयात्॥वर्धमानपुरद्वारेणा-
भिनिष्क्रम्य) 3. 1. 8-9; (26) Yudhiṣṭhira,
while requesting the citizens to return, told
them that Bhīṣma, the king (Dhṛtarāṣṭra),
Vidura, Kuntī, and friends would still be
in the town Nāgasāhvaya (नगरे नागसाह्-
वये) 3. 1. 33; (27) Enraged, Dhṛtarāṣṭra
told Vidura that he would no more want
him (for consultations) to protect the
earth or the city (Hāstinapura) (महीम्
इमां पालयितुं पुरं वा) 3. 6. 17; (28)
When requested by Dhṛtarāṣṭra to come
back, Vidura returned to Gajāhvaya (पुनर्
आयाद् गजाह्वयम्) 3. 7. 17; (29) Kṛṣṇa
told Yudhiṣṭhira that since he was involved
in battle with Śālva he could not go to Hās-
tinapura even though he had heard about
the dice game (येनाहं नागमं तदा।
श्रुत्वैव हास्तिनपुरम् द्यूतम्) 3. 15. 22
(here Kṛṣṇa says that he had heard about
the game; but earlier he said that he knew
nothing about it 3. 14. 2, 14-16); (30)
Bhīma urged Yudhiṣṭhira to attack Gaja-
sāhvya with his brothers (त्वरमाणो ऽभि-
निर्यातु … अद्यैव गजसाह्वयम्) 3. 34. 80-
81; (31) Kṛṣṇa assured Yudhiṣṭhira that
he could get him his kingdom back (3. 48.
23) so that he could rule the earth from
Hāstinapura (ततस् त्वं हास्तिनपुरे … वसन्
। … प्रशाधि पृथिवीम् इमाम्॥) 3. 48. 26;
(32) The citizens (पौराः) who followed
Yudhiṣṭhira to the forest returned to Nāga-
pura when he decided to go on a pilgrimage
with Lomaśa (जग्मुर् नागपुरं प्रति) 3.
90. 22; (33) Hanūmant asked Bhīma if he
should go to Vāraṇasāhvaya and kill the
Kauravas (गत्वा वारणसाह्वयम्) 3. 150. 8;
(34) Kṛṣṇa told Yudhiṣṭhira that after the
fulfilment of the contract (समय), let
Nāgapura await his arrival, for he was
sure to get back Nāgapura and the whole
kingdom (प्रतीक्षतां नागपुरं भवन्-
तं॥ … प्रपत्स्यसे नागपुरं सराष्ट्रम्॥)
3. 180. 34-35; (35) When released by
the Pāṇḍavas from the captivity of the
Gandharvas, Duryodhana left for the town
(Hāstinapura) (जगाम नगरं प्रति) 3.
235. 23; (स्वपुरं प्रययौ राजा) 3. 236. 6;
Janamejaya felt that Duryodhana, proud
as he was, must have found it difficult to
enter Hāstinapura (नित्याहंकारवादिनः।
प्रवेशो हास्तिनपुरे दुष्करः प्रतिभाति
मे॥) 3. 236. 3; (36) Duryodhana, humi-
liated by his adversaries, decided to fast
unto death (इह प्रायम् उपासिष्ये) and not
return to the town; he asked his brothers,
led by Duḥśāsana, to return to the town
(प्रयान्त्व् अद्य पुरं प्रति) 3. 238. 10-11;
(न ह्य् अहं प्रतियास्यामि पुरं शत्रुनिरा-
कृतः) 3. 238. 12; he wondered what he could
tell Dhṛtarāṣṭra after reaching Vāraṇāhvaya
(वारणाह्वयम् आसाद्य किं वक्ष्यामि जना-
धिपम्) 3. 238. 13; (37) When asked by
Janamejaya, Vaiśaṃpāyana told him what
happened after Duryodhana's return to
