राजन् येन नागाह्वयं पुरम्) 14. 83. 1;
(73) The horse, after Arjuna's battle with
Śakuni's son in the Gāndhāra country,
returned to the direction of the town Nāgā-
hvaya (न्यवर्तत ततो वाजी येन नागाह्व-
यं पुरम्) 14. 86. 1; (7) Dhṛtarāṣṭra,
before leaving for forest life, advised Yudhi-
ṣṭhira to look after the safety of the town
(Hāstinapura); he asked him to see that
it was well protected by strong ramparts
and arched doorways; it should have on all
sides high watchtowers, close to each other
with enough space for six persons to walk;
it should have sufficient entrances, large
in size; they should be well distributed and
protected by mechanical devices (पुरं
च ते सुगुप्तं स्याद् दृढप्राकारतोरणम्।
अट्टाट्टालकसंबाधं षट्पथं सर्वतो-
दिशम्॥तस्य द्वाराणि कार्याणि पर्याप्तानि
बृहन्ति च।सर्वतः सुविभक्तानि यन्त्रैर्
आरक्षितानि च॥) 15. 9. 16-17) (Nī. on Bom.
Ed. 15. 5. 16: अट्टाः दुर्गोपरिभागे सञ्चार-
स्थानानि, षट्पदं (this is Nī.'s reading)
षड्भिः पदैः पदनीयैः स्थानैर् युक्तं
तेन सप्तप्राकारम् इति गम्यते।तत्र
सप्तमस्यान्तःपुरत्वात् षड् एवान्येषां
पदनीयानि स्थानानि); (75) At the time
of Dhṛtarāṣṭra's departure, the citizens of
Gajāhvaya were very much grieved (दुः-
खितः पौरवर्गो गजाह्वये ऽतीव बभूव)
15. 21. 12; he went out of Gajasāhvaya
through the gate called Vardhamāna (स
वर्धमानद्वारेण निर्ययौ गजसाह्वयात्)
15. 22. 3; (76) Yudhiṣṭhira requested
Kuntī not to follow Dhṛtarāṣṭra to the
forest but to return to the town and be
with her daughters-in-law (वधूपरिवृता
राज्ञि नगरं गन्तुम् अर्हसि) 15. 22. 8;
(77) After the departure of Dhṛtarāṣṭra,
the Pāṇḍavas, along with women, returned
to the town (पाण्डवाः … स्त्रीसहिताः सर्वे
पुरं प्रविविशुस् तदा); the whole town
Hāstinapura, with its women, old men and
children, then became cheerless, noiseless,
as after a festival (नगरं हास्तिन्पुरं
तद् अहृष्टम् इवाकूजं गतोत्सवम् इवाभवत्
सस्त्रीवृद्धकुमारकम्।) 15. 24. 13-14;
(78) When Dhṛtarāṣṭra in the forest was
surrounded by Yudhiṣṭhira and others, as
well as by citizens, he felt he was as though
in Gajasāhvaya as before (मेने … पुरेव
गजसाह्वये) 15. 31. 18; (रमे चाहं
 … पुरेव गजसाह्वये) 15. 44. 15; (79)
When permitted by Dhṛtarāṣṭra, Gāndhārī
and Kuntī, Yudhiṣṭhira returned to the
town Hāstinapura (नगरं हास्तिनपुरं
पुनर् आयात्) 15. 44. 52; (80) When Yudhi-
ṣṭhira heard about the death of Dhṛta-
rāṣṭra, Gāndhārī and Kuntī, he went out
(of the town) to the river Gaṅgā (निर्ययौ
सह सोदर्यैः सदारः … गङ्गां प्रजग्-
मुः) 15. 47. 10-11; after offering water
libations to the dead (15. 47. 12), Yudhi-
ṣṭhira and others returned to town but
stayed outside it until they were freed from
impurity (शौचं निवर्तयन्तस् ते तत्रोषुर्
नगराद् बहिः) 15. 47. 13; on the twelfth
day he performed the श्राद्ध and gave
gifts (15. 47. 16) and then entered the town
Vāraṇāhvaya (प्रविवेषा … नगरं वारणा-
ह्वयम्) 15. 47. 21; Dhṛtarāṣṭra had lived
a total of fifteen years in the town (Hāstina-
pura) after the death of his sons in the
battle, and three years in the forest (एवं
वर्षाण्य् अतीतानि धृतराष्ट्रस्य धीमतः।
वनवासे तदा त्रीणि नगरे दश पञ्च च॥
हतपुत्रस्य संग्रामे) 15. 47. 25-26;
(81) Consoled by Vyāsa over the death
of Kṛṣṇa and others, Arjuna returned to
the town Nāgasāhvaya (ययौ पार्थो नग-
रं नागसाह्वयम्) 16. 9. 37; (82) When
Yudhiṣṭhira decided to start on the great
journey (महाप्रस्थान) he gave the king-
dom of Hāstinapura to Parikṣit and of
Śakraprastha to Vajra (परिक्षिद् धास्तिन-
पुरे शक्रप्रस्थे तु यादवः) 17. 1. 9; he,
along with his brothers, Draupadī and a
dog, left Gajasāhvaya on their great journey;
he was followed by the citizens and the
women of the inner apartments; all the
citizens then returned to (the town) (निर्य-
यौ गजसाह्वयात् … न्यवर्तन्त ततः सर्वे
नरा नगरवासिनः) 17. 1. 23-24; (83)
After completing his सर्पसत्र, king Jana-
mejaya took leave of the officiating priests
and came back from Takṣaśilā to Gajāhvaya
(ततः तक्षशिलायाः स पुनर् आयाद् गजाह्-
वयम्) 18. 5. 29.
E. Past event: When
Kaṇva asked his pupils to take Śakuntalā
and her son to her husband Duḥṣanta,
(1. 68. 10), they all left for Gajasāhvaya
(ते सर्वे … प्रातिष्ठन्त … गजसाह्वयम्) 1.
68. 12.
F. Simile: (1) With the dances
of the dancers and sounds of the songs, the
town (Hāstinapura) became like the resi-
dence of Kubera (नर्तकैश् चापि नृत्यद्-
भिर् गायनानां च निस्वनैः।आसीद् वैश्र-
वणस्येव निवासस् तत् पुरं तदा॥) 14. 69.
17. [See Vardhamānapura, Nāgāhvaya2]

हिरण्यपुर
Hiraṇyapura1 nt.: The city of the
Nivātakavaca demons.
A. Location: In the bay of the ocean
(निवातकवचा नाम दानवा … ।समुद्र-
कुक्षिम् आश्रित्य दुर्गे प्रतिवसन्त्य् उत) 3.
165. 10: at the end of the ocean (पारे
समुद्रस्य) 4. 56. 11; 5. 48. 16; one had
to cross the ocean to reach it (अपश्यम्
उदधिम्) 3. 166. 1; (तम् अतीत्य … सर्वाम्-
भोनिधिं … अपश्यं … तद् दैत्यपुरम्
अन्तिकात्) 3. 166. 6; also said to be located
in the Pātāla (पातालतलम् आश्रितम्) 5. 98.
2.
B. Creation: Conceived mentally and
created with great effort by the architect
Maya in Pātāla (हिरण्यपुरम् एतत् … अनल्-
पेन प्रयत्नेन निर्मितं विश्वकर्मणा।
मयेन मनसा सृष्टम् पातालतलम् आश्रि-
तम्) 5. 98. 1-2.
C. Description: City of
Daityas (दैत्यपुर) 3. 166. 6); full of
Dānavas (दानवाकीर्ण) 3. 166. 6; residence
of Dānavas (दानवालय) 3. 165. 23; city of
Daityas and Dānavas (दैत्यानां दानवा-
नां च) 5. 98. 1; city of the Asuras (पुरम्
आसुरम्) 3. 166. 11; famous (ख्यात) 5. 98.
1; best (उत्तम) 3. 169. 26; excellent town
(पुरवर) 5. 98. 1; having a wonderful
shape (अद्भुताकार) 3. 169. 26; big (म-
हन्त्) 5. 98. 1; inaccessible (दुर्ग) 3. 165.
10; very formidable (अत्युग्र) 3. 165. 23;
excelling the city of gods (विशिष्तं देव-
नगरात्) 3. 169. 26; excelling the city of Pura-
ndara (Indra) (पुरन्दरपुरात् … विशिष्तम्)
3. 169. 27; the houses of the Nivātakavacas
were made of gold, beset with gems (वेश्मा-
नि … बहुरत्नविचित्राणि शातकुम्भमयानि
च) 3. 169. 25; the golden and silvery houses
of Hiraṇyapura, the houses shining like the
sun (वेश्मानि रौक्माणि … राजतानि च …
सूर्यरूपाणि चाभान्ति) described in some
details 5. 98. 9-12; it was impossible to
describe their appearance and the materials
used for their construction; they were
perfected in qualities; (hence) they had
proper form and qualities (नैतानि शक्यं
निर्देष्टुं रूपतो द्रव्यतस् तथा।गुणतश्
चैव सिद्धानि प्रमाणगुणवन्ति च॥) 5. 98.
13; there were places of amusement and the
houses were provided with jewelled beds and
precious vessels and seats (आक्रीडान् पश्य
दैत्यानां तथैव शयनान्य् उत।रत्न-
वन्ति महार्हाणि भाजनान्य् आसनानि च॥)
5. 98. 14 (Nī. on Bom. Ed. 5. 100. 14: आक्री-
डान् क्रीडास्थानानि); there were mountains,
looking like clouds and full of streams,
and trees giving flowers and fruits accord-
ing to one's desire and moving at will (जल-
दाभांस् तथा शैलांस् तोयप्रस्रवणान्वि-
तान्।कामपुष्पफलांश् चैव पादपान्
कामचारिणः॥) 5. 98. 15; it was called पुर
3. 166. 6, 7, 10, 11; 3. 169. 3, 22, 28; 5. 98.
1; नगर 3. 169. 21, 26, 35.
D. History:
As told by Mātali to Arjuna: The city
once belonged to the king of gods (Indra);
the Nivātakavaca demons practised severe
austerities, satisfied Pitāmaha (Brahma-
deva) and obtained as a boon this city for
their residence and for freedom from fear
of gods in battles (इदं वृतं निवासाय
देवेभ्यश् चाभयं युधि॥); Indra, out
of self-interest, agreed to what the demons
had asked for (विधत्तां भगवान् अत्रेत्य्
आत्मनो हितकाम्यया); the Nivātakavacas
then drove out gods from this place and
made the city their residence (ततो निवात-
कवचैर् इतः प्रच्याविताः सुराः) 3. 169. 28-
30); (निवातकवचा नाम दानवाः … प्रती-
वसन्त्य् उत) 3. 165. 10; 1. 2. 121; 5. 166.
34 (?).
E. Epic event: Arjuna, at the
instance of Indra, attacked the residence
of Dānavas riding the chariot driven by
Mātali (तांस् तत्र जहि कौन्तेय … ततो
मातलिसं युक्तंप्रादान् मे रथम्) 3.
165. 10-12; (दानवालयम् अत्युग्रं प्रयातो
ऽस्मि) 3. 165. 23; battle described in 3. 166.
7-23; 3. 167-3-169. 20; when the Nivātaka-
vacas were killed, their wives cried aloud in
the city (दारास् तेषां तु सर्वशः।प्राक्रो-
शन् नगरे तस्मिन्) 3. 168. 21; Arjuna
entered the town along with Mātali frighten-
ing the women by the loud sound of the
chariot; after killing Nivātakavacas, Arjuna
returned to the residence of the gods (ततो
मातलिना सार्धम् अहं तत् पुरम् अभ्य-
याम्) 3. 169. 22; (पुनर् मातलिना सार्धम्
अगच्छं देवसद्म तत्) 3. 169. 35;
(निहत्य … निवातकवचांश् चैव ततो ऽहं
शक्रम् आगमम्) 3. 170. 61; Mātali told
Indra the killing of Nivātakavacas 3. 170.
63; according to Indra, Arjuna's feat excell-
ed that of gods and Asuras (अतिदेवासुरं
कर्म कृतम् एतद् त्वया रणे) 3. 170. 66;
the incident is referred to on several occa-
sions: (1) In the list of the contents of the
Āraṇyakaparvan in the Parvasaṃgrahapar-
van (निवातकवचैर् युद्धं हिरण्यपुर-
वासिभिः) 1. 2. 121; (2) By Arjuna while
describing his feats to Uttara (अहं पारे
समुद्रस्य हिरण्यपुरम् आरुजम्) 4. 56.
11; (3) By Bhīṣma while addressīng
Duryodhana (एष पारे समुद्रस्य हिरण्य-
पुरम् आरुजत्।हत्वा षष्टिसहस्राणि निवात-
कवचान् रणे) 5. 48. 16; (4) By Bhīṣma
again while giving his estimate to Duryodha-
na about the heroes assembled on the side
of the Pāṇḍavas (दानवानां सहस्राणि हिर-
ण्यपुरवासिनाम्।हतान्य् एकरथेनाजौ) 5.
166. 34 (but this could also refer to the killing
of Paulomas and Kālakeyas of Hiraṇya-
pura2); (5) By Yudhiṣṭhira when he,
while lamenting over the death of Abhi-
manyu, referred to Arjuna's exploits (निवा-
तकवचाञ् जघ्ने कालकेयांश् च … ।हिरण्य-
पुरवासिनः) 7. 49. 16-17 (Kālakeyas seem
here to be identified with Kālakhañjas who,
with Nivātakavacas, lived in Hiraṇyapura1
5. 98. 5, 7); (6) By Jayadratha, frightened
by the vow of Arjuna (दानवानां सह-
स्राणि हिरण्यपुरवासिनाम्।जघान … देव-
राजप्रचोदितः) 7. 53. 22; (7) By Droṇa,
while reminding Duryodhana of Arjuna's
past exploits (निवातकवचाश् चापि … तेन
वीरेण निर्जिताः) 7. 160. 18; दानवानां सह-
स्राणि हिरण्यपुर्वासिनाम्।विजिग्ये पुरुष-
व्याघ्रः) 7. 160. 19 (but this could also
refer to the killing of Paulomas and Kāla-
keyas in addition to the Nivātakavacas of
st. 18).
F. Past event: While telling
Mātali about Hiraṇypura, Nārada mentions
the defeat of Indra several times at the
hands of the Nivātakavacas of Hiraṇya-
pura 5. 98. 7-8.

हिरण्यपुर
Hiraṇyapura2 nt.: Name of the town
of the demons called Kālakeyas (or Kāla-
khañjas) and Paulomas.
A. History: As told by Mātali to
Arjuna: A Daiteyī named Pulomā and a
Mahāsurī named Kālakā practised severe
austerities for one thousand divine years
of gods; at the end of their austerities they
received a boon by which they secured
less misery for their sons and impossibility
of being killed by gods, demons and ser-
pents: they also received the city Hiraṇya-
pura, made for the Kālakeyas by Brah-
man and occupied by the demons, the
sons of Pulomā and Kālakā (अगृह्णीतां
वरं ते तु सुतानाम् अल्पदुःखताम्।अव-
ध्यतां च … राजेन्द्र पन्नगासुरराक्ष-
सैः … ॥ … पुरं चेदं … ब्रह्मणा …
कालकेयकृते कृतम् … पौलोमाध्युषितं …
कालकेयैश् च दानवैः॥हिरण्यपुरम् इत्य्
एतत् ख्यायते नगरम्) 3. 170. 6-11; पौ-
लोमैः कालकेयैश् च … अधिष्ठितम्) 3.
170. 2; (रक्षितं कालकेयैश् च पौलोमैश्
च महासुरैः) 3. 170. 11; (त एते … अव-
ध्याः सर्वदैवतैः।निवसन्त्य् अत्र 3. 170.
12; hence called city of demons (दानव-
पुर) 3. 170. 58: (दैत्यानां पुरम्) 3.
170. 5; city where demons lived happily
due to a boon (दैतेयैर् वरदानेन धार्-
यते स्म यथासुखम्) 3. 170. 23; full of
Asuras everywhere (असुरैः … सर्वतो
वृतम्) 3. 170. 4.
B. Description: Heavenly
(दिव्य) 3. 170. 1, 3. 10. 23; of heavenly
lustre (दिव्यवर्चस्) 3. 170. 23; having the
lustre of fire and sun (पावकार्कसमप्र-
भ) 3. 170. 1; beset with jewels all around
(सर्वरत्नमय) 3. 170. 3; (सर्वरत्नैः
समुदितम्) 3. 170. 8; of well-executed
lustre (सुकृतप्रभ) 3. 170. 8; like Amarā-
vatī (अमरावतिसंकाश) 3. 170. 25; of the
form of the city of Gandharvas (गन्धर्-
वनगराकार) 3. 170. 59; of wonderful
sight (अद्भुतदर्शन) 3. 170. 5; (अद्भु-
तोपमदर्शन) 3. 170. 3; big (महन्त्)
3. 170. 11, 54; moving in the sky
(खग) 3. 170. 54; (खचर) 3. 170. 8.
10, 23; moving as desired (कामग) 3. 170.
23; (कामगम) 3. 170. 25; (कामचर)
3. 170. 1; endowed with all desires and
qualities (सर्वकामगुणोपेत) 3. 170. 9;
healthy (अनामय) 3. 170. 9; free from
sorrow (वीतशोक) 3. 170. 9; having
gates and watchtowers (गोपुराट्टालकोपेत)
and four gates (चतुर्द्वार) 3. 170. 3;
full of trees which were beset with jewels,
were bright and full of flowers and
fruits (द्रुमै रत्नमयैश् चित्रैः … अधि-
ष्ठितम्) 3. 170. 2; (द्रुमैः पुष्पफलोपे-
तैर् दिव्यरत्नमयैर् वृतम्) 3. 170. 3; full
of bright, heavenly and very attractive
birds (भास्वरैश् च पतत्रिभिः … अधिष्ठि-
तम्) 3. 170. 2; (पतत्रिभिर् दिव्यैर् उपेतं
सुमनोहरैः) 3. 170. 4; inaccessible (दुरा-
सद) 3. 170. 3; difficult to be attacked
even by gods together with Yakṣas and
Gandharvas (दुर्धर्षम् अमरैर् अपि।स-
यक्षगन्धर्वगणैः) 3. 170. 8; as also by
serpents, Asuras and Rākṣasas (पन्नगा-
सुरराक्षसैः) 3. 170. 8; hence avoided by
gods (अमरवर्जित) 3. 170. 10; but after
the demons were killed by Arjuna, the city,
whose rulers were killed, lacked all lustre,
became devoid of glory, was full of grief,
and was struck by sorrow and miserable
condition; it then did not shine as before
(तच् छोकयुक्तम् अश्रीकं दुःखदैन्य-
समाहतम्।न बभौ दानवपुरं हत-
त्विट्कं हतेश्वरम्॥) 3. 170. 58; usually
referred to as पुर (cf. the name Hiraṇya-
pura) 3. 170. 1, 5, 8, 13, 21, 23, 25,
26, 54, 55, 58, 59, but also as नगर
3. 170. 11, 21, 55.
C. Characteristic:
As the city could move at will (see above
B. Description: (कामग, कामगम); it
could go underground and again rise high
above, and then again moving quickly and
obliquely submerge in waters (अन्तर् भू-
मौ निपतितं पुनर् ऊर्ध्वं प्रतिष्ठते।
पुनस् तिर्यक् प्रयात्य् आशु पुनर् अप्सु निम-
ज्जति॥) 3. 170. 24.
D. Epic event: Arjuna,
while returning to the residence of gods
after killing the Nivātakavaca demons,
saw on way the town Hiraṇyapura 3. 170.
1; on hearing from Mātali about the de-
mons occupying the town (3. 170. 8-10),
Arjuna asked Mātali to take him to
Hiraṇyapura so that he might kill the
demons; accordingly Mātali drove him
there quickly in the heavenly chariot 3.
170. 13-15; the battle between Arjuna and
the demons in the town described (3. 170.
16-50); when the demons were being
killed they employed माया of the demons
and flew up in the sky together with the
town (ते वध्यमाना दैतेयाः पुरम्
आस्थाय तत् पुनः।खम् उत्पेतुः सनगरा
मायाम् आस्थाय दानवीम्॥) 3. 170. 21;
Arjuna steadied the town along with the
demons and when broken by his iron
arrows it fell down on the ground 3. 170.
26-27; Mātali praised Arjuna for his feat
of destroying Hiraṇyapura,—a feat which
could not be accomplished even by gods
and Asuras 3. 170. 51-54; when the town
was destroyed and the demons were killed
(विध्वस्ते ऽथ पुरे तस्मिन् दानवेषु
हतेषु च) the women of the demons
came out of the town weeping aloud
in grief 3. 170. 55-57; Arjuna, after
destroying Hiraṇyapura and killing the
Asuras (हिरण्यपुरम् आरुज्य निहत्य च
महासुरान्), returned to Indra with Mātali
3. 170. 60-61; hearing from Mātali in
details the exploits of Arjuna, (हिरण्य-
पुरघातं च मायानां च निवारणम्),
Indra exclaimed ‘well done’ 3. 170. 63-64;
this exploit of Arjuna is referred to: (i)
by Bhīṣma, when he referred to the boon
granted by Nara and Nārāyaṇa to Indra,
while addressing Duryodhana (ताभ्यां च
सहितः शक्रो विजिग्ये दैत्यदानवान्॥नर
इन्द्रस्य संग्रामे हत्वा शत्रून् … ।पौ-
लोमान् कालखञ्जांश् च) 5. 48. 13-14 (in
the earlier account in 3. 170 Indra is not
mentioned as taking part in the battle);
(ii) again by Bhīṣma while reminding
Duryodhana about the exploits of Arjuna
(दानवानां सहस्राणि हिरण्यपुरवासिनाम्।
हतान्य् एकरथेनाजौ) 5. 166. 34 (this
could also be a reference to Nivātakavacas
of Hiraṇyapura1); (iii) by Arjuna while
telling Uttara his earlier exploits (अहम्
इन्द्रस्य वचनात् संग्रामे ऽभ्यहनं
पुरा।पौलोमान् कालखञ्जांश् च) 4. 56.
9 (actually, according to the account in
3. 170, Indra had not asked Arjuna to kill
Paulomas and Kālakhañjas (there called
Kālakeyas); Arjuna did this on his own;
Indra had asked him to destroy the Nivāta-
kavacas of Hiraṇyapura1 (3. 165. 10-11)
which is mentioned by Arjuna in 4. 56. 11);
(iv) by Yudhiṣṭhira when, while lamenting
over the death of Abhimanyu, he referred
to the feats of Arjuna (हिरण्यपुरवासिनः
 … पौलोमाः सगणा हताः) 7. 49. 17; (v)
possibly by Duryodhana while reminding
Droṇa of Arjuna's exploits (दानवानां
सहस्राणि हिरण्यपुरवासिनाम्।विजिग्ये
पुरुषव्याघ्रः) 7. 160. 19.
E. Simile:
When the demons were killed the town
Hiraṇyapura became unfit to be seen like a
pond with its elephants killed or like a forest
the trees of which had gone dry (हतनागम्
इव ह्रदम्।शुष्कवृक्षम् इवारण्यम् अदृ-
श्यम् अभवत् पुरम्॥) 3. 170. 59.

हिरण्यबिन्दु
Hiraṇyabindu m.: See Agastyāśrama.

अकृष्ट
Akṛṣṭa m. (pl.): A class of sages.
Mentioned among those sages who
observed the eternal Vedic धर्म pre-
scribed by Brahman after creating the
world (सर्वलोकपितामहः।शाश्वतं
वेदपठितं धर्मं च युयुजे पुनः॥
॥।अकृष्टाश् चैव हंसाश् च ऋषयो … स्थिता
ब्रह्मानुशासने॥) 12. 160. 21. 25.

अग्नियोनिज
Agniyonija m. (pl.): A class of sages.
Mentioned among those who after the
creation of the world followed the instruc-
tion of Brahman and observed the eternal
Vedic धर्म (ऋषयो ऽथाग्नियोनिजाः। …
स्थिता ब्रह्मानुशासने॥) 12. 160. 21, 25.

अग्निवेश्य
Agniveśya m. (pl.): Name of a
people.
The Agniveśya warriors were stationed
on the left side of the Krauñcāruṇa Vyūha
of the army of the Pāṇḍavas on the second
day of the battle (अग्निवेश्या जगत्तुण्डाः
 … वामं पार्श्वं समाश्रिताः) 6. 46. 51
(39, 50).

अङ्ग
Aṅga, Aṅgaka m. (pl., also sg.),
Aṅgaviṣaya m. (sg.): Name of a country
and its people; often mentioned along with
Vaṅga and Kaliṅga.
A. Location: Listed by Saṃjaya
among the Janapadas of the Bhārata-
varṣa (अङ्गा वङ्गाः कलिङ्गाश् च) 6. 10.
44, 5, 37; mentioned among the eastern
countries, holy places in which were
visited by Arjuna (प्राचीम् दिशम् अभि-
प्रेप्सुर् जगाम) 1. 207. 5; (अङ्गवङ्ग-
कलिङ्गेषु यानि पुण्यानि कानिचित्।जगाम
तानि सर्वाणि) 1. 207. 9; the army prote-
cted by the king of the Aṅga country
(Karṇa) said to be of the easterners (तद्
अङ्गपतिना गुप्तं … प्राच्यानाम् अभवद्
बलम्) 6. 17. 28.
B. Capital town: The
capital of the Aṅga country was Campā
(जगाम चम्पां प्रदिधक्षमाणस् तम्
अङ्गराजं विषयं च तस्य) 3. 113. 15;
also called Mālinī (मालिनीं नगरीम् … ।
अङ्गेषु) 12. 5. 6.
C. Characteristics of
the people: The people of the Aṅga and
Kalinga country were mentioned by Karṇa
among those peoples who knew eternal
धर्म (कोसलाः काशयोऽङ्गाश् च कलिङ्गा
 … । धर्मं जानन्ति शाश्वतम्) 8. 30. 60-
61; according to Karṇa the old men of the
Aṅgaka, Kaliṅgaka and some other cou-
ntries lived according to the धर्म taught
to them (कालिङ्गकाश् चाङ्गका … शिष्टान्
धर्मान् उपजीवन्ति वृद्धाः) 8. 30. 75;
(Nī., however, on Bom. Ed. 8. 45. 30; स्व-
यं धर्मस्वरूपम् अजानन्तो ऽपि शिष्टानु-
गामिन इत्य् अर्थः); according to Śalya,
however, people of the Aṅga country for-
sook the sick people and sold their wives
and children (आतुराणाम् परित्यागः स्व-
दारसुतविक्रयः।अङ्गेषु वर्तते कर्ण)
8. 30. 83;
D. Aṅga warriors: Specially
skilled in fighting while riding elephants
(गजयोधिनः, गजयुद्धेषु कुशलाः) 8. 17.
1-3; (शिक्षिता हस्तिसादिनः) 7. 68. 31; also
cf. 8. 12. 59; (आचार्यपुत्रे … हस्तिशिक्षावि-
शारदे 8. 17. 15-18; 8. 49. 79.
E. Epic
events: (1) Child Karṇa, who was picked
up by Adhiratha and Rādhā, grew up in
the Aṅga country (स ज्येष्ठपुत्रः सूतस्य
ववृधेऽङ्गेषु) 3. 293. 14; (2) Duryo-
dhana said that if Arjuna was unwilling
to fight with one who was not a king, he
would make Karṇa the king of the Aṅga
country; immediately afterwards the cere-
mony of consecration of Karṇa as the
ruler of the Aṅga country was duly per-
formed by those who knew the मन्त्रस्
(यद्य् अयं फल्गुनो युद्धे नाराज्ञा
योद्धुम् इच्छति।तस्माद् एषो ऽङ्गविषये
मया राज्ये ऽभिषिच्यते॥ … ततस् तस्मिन्
क्षणे कर्णः … अभिषिक्तो ऽङ्गराज्ये सः … ॥)
1. 126. 35-36; Karṇa whose head was
moist due to water of consecration as a
king of the Aṅga country was embraced
by Adhiratha (परिष्वज्य च तस्याथ
मूर्धानम् … अङ्गराज्याभिषेकार्द्रम्) 1.
127. 4; when Bhīma said that Karṇa did
not deserve to be a king of the Aṅgas,
Duryodhana retorted that Karṇa deserved
not only to be the king of the Aṅgas but of
the whole earth (अङ्गराज्यं च नार्हस्
त्वम् उपभोक्तुम्) 1. 127. 7; (पृथिवीराज्यम्
अर्हो ऽयं नाङ्गराज्यं नरेश्वरः) 1.
127 16; Karṇa is called the king of
the Aṅgas in various contexts: (i)
Śiśupāla calls Karṇa the chief of the
Vaṅga and Aṅga countries (वङ्गाङ्ग-
विषयाध्यक्ष) 2. 41. 9; (ii) Śalya refers
to the rulership of Karṇa of the Aṅgas
(अङ्गेषु … कर्ण येषाम् अधिपतिर् भवान्)
8. 30. 83; (3) While recounting the ex-
ploits of Karṇa, Dhṛtarāṣṭra mentions
Aṅgas (!) among the countries conquered
by Karṇa and made to pay tribute (सुह्मान्
अङ्गांश् च पुण्ड्रांश् च … यो जित्वा समरे
वीरश् चक्रे बलिभृतः पुरा) 8. 5. 19-20;
(4) When Jayadratha was subdued by
Karṇa in a wrestling bout, he (J.), pleased
with Karṇa, gave him the city of Mālinī in
the Aṅga country (प्रीत्या ददौ स कर्णाय
मालिनीम् नगरीम् अथ।अङ्गेषु) 12. 5. 6;
(5) Arjuna, during the period of exile,
visited all the holy places in the Aṅga,
Vaṅga and Kaliṅga countries (अङ्गवङ्ग-
कलिङ्गेषु … जगाम तानि सर्वाणि तीर्थान्य्
आयतनानि च) 1. 207. 9; (6) Aṅga country
mentioned among those which were con-
quered by Sahadeva before the Rājasūya
(यः काशीन् अङ्गमगधान् … युधाजयत्)
5. 49. 28 (however, according to 2. 27. 16-
18 it was Bhīma who subjugated Karṇa;
in 2. 28 where Sahadeva's expedition is
described there is no reference to the Aṅga
country); (7) The Kṣatriyas of the Aṅga
and Vaṅga countries mentioned among
those who brought riches by hundreds for
the Rājasūya of Yudhiṣṭhira (अङ्गा वङ्गाश् च
पुण्ड्राश् च … आहार्षुः क्षत्रिया वित्तं शत-
शः) 2. 48. 15-16; (8) Aṅgas and Vaṅgas
mentioned among those people who along
with their kings were present at the Rāja-
sūya of Yudhiṣṭhira and served meals (यत्र
सर्वान् महीपालान् … सवङ्गाङ्गान् … आगतान्
अहम् अद्राक्षं यज्ञे ते परिवेषकान्) 3.
48. 18, 22; (9) The army of the easterners
protected by the ruler of the Aṅga country
and by Kṛpa marched out for the battle
(तद् अङ्गपतिना गुप्तं कृपेण च॥।प्रा-
च्यानाम् अभवद् बलम्) 6. 17. 28; (10)
When Ayutāyus and Dīrghāyus, the sons
of Śrutāyus and Acyutāyus, were killed by
Arjuna, the Aṅga warriors, riding elephants,
attacked Arjuna (अङ्गास् तु गजवारेण
पाण्डवं पर्यवारयन्। … हस्तिसादिनः)
7. 68. 31; (11) When Arjuna attacked
the army of the Saṃśaptakas (8. 12. 54),
the Aṅga warriors, riding elephants, along
with Kaliṅga, Vaṅga, and Niṣāda warriors
attacked him (कलिङ्गवङ्गाङ्गनिषादवीरा
जिघांसवः पाण्डवम् अभ्यधावन्) 8.
12. 59; (12) The Aṅga warriors, along
with Vaṅgas and others, riding elephants
and skilled in fighting with elephants,
attacked Dhṛṣṭadyumna (हस्तिभिस् तु महा-
मात्राः … धृष्टद्युम्नं जिघांसन्तः
क्रुद्धाः पार्षतम् अभ्ययुः॥ … गजयो-
धिनः।अङ्गा वङ्गाश् च … गजयुद्धेषु
कुशलाः) 8. 17. 1-3; (13) Sahadeva, after
killing the elephant of a Punḍra warrior,
attacked the elephant of an Aṅga warrior;
Nakula took on himself the fight with the
Aṅga warrior and his elephant; the Aṅga
warrior threw तोमरस् on Nakula; the
warrior (here called म्लेच्छ and Ācārya-
पुत्र) fell down along with his elephant;
at the death of this Aṅga warrior, other
warriors from the Aṅga country with their
elephants attacked Nakula (विवर्मध्वज-
जीवितम्।तं कृत्वा द्विरदं भूयः सह-
देवो ऽङ्गम् अभ्यगात्॥सहदेवं तु नकुलो
वारयित्वाङ्गम् आर्दयत्। … अङ्गश् चिक्षेप
तोमरान्।स पपात हतो म्लेच्छस् तेनैव
सह दन्तिना॥आचार्यपुत्रे निहते … अङ्गाः
क्रुद्धा महामात्रा नागैर् नकुलम् अभ्य-
युः) 8. 17. 13-18; (14) Elephants from
Kaliṅga, Vaṅga, Aṅga, Niṣāda and Ma-
gadha countries along with their warriors
mentioned among those who were killed
by Bhīma (कलिङ्गवङ्गाङ्गनिषादमागधान्
सदामदान् … निहन्ति यः शत्रुगणान् अने-
कशः) 8. 49. 79; (15) Dhṛtarāṣṭra while
recounting Kṛṣṇa's exploits mentioned
Aṅgas, Vaṅgas and Kaliṅgas among the
countries which were conquered by him
in battle (अङ्गान् वङ्गान् कलिङ्गांश् च
 … अजयद् रणे) 7. 10. 15 (this incident
is not mentioned in the epic).
F. Past
events: (1) Lomapāda, a friend of Daśa-
ratha, was the king of the Aṅgas (लोम-
पाद इति ख्यातो अङ्गानाम् ईश्वरो ऽभवत्) 3.
110. 19; he, the king of the Aṅga country,
called his ministers and consulted with
them about the means to bring Ṛśyaśṛṅga
to the Aṅga country; he asked the courte-
zans to get Ṛśyaśṛṅga from his आश्रम
to his country by some means (ततो ऽङ्ग-
पतिर् आहूय सचिवान् … ।यत्नम् अकरोन्
मन्त्रणिश्चये॥।ऋश्यशृङ्गम् … आनयध्वम्
विषयं मम शोभनाः॥) 3. 110. 28, 31;
the courtezans deluded Ṛśyaśṛṅga by
various means and brought him to the
ruler of the Aṅgas (प्रलोभयन्त्यो विवि-
धैर् उपायैर् आजग्मुर् अङ्गाधिपतेः समी-
पम्) 3. 113. 8; enraged, Vibhāṇḍaka, father
of Ṛśyaśṛṅga, started towards Campā to
burn it along with the king and his (Aṅga)
country (जगाम चम्पां प्रदिधक्ष-
माणस् तम् अङ्गराजं विषयं च तस्य)
3. 113. 15; being honoured at various places
on his way to Campā, Vibhāṇḍaka calmed
down and, delighted, he approached the
king of the Aṅgas in his town (समास-
सादाङ्गपतिं पुरस्थम्) 3. 113. 18; (2)
Once, Vasuhoma was the king of the Aṅgas
(अङ्गेषु राजा … वसुहोम इति श्रुतः) 12.
122. 1; (3) (Ruci, the wife of Devaśar-
man, once gathered flowers of heavenly
fragrance that fell down near her आश्रम
13. 40. 16; 13. 42. 7); just then she received
an invitation from the Aṅga country where
Prabhāvatī, the eldest sister of Ruci, was
the wife of Citraratha, the king of the
Aṅgas; Ruci put the heavenly flowers in her
hair and went to the residence of the king of
the Aṅgas; seeing those flowers Prabhāvatī,
the wife of the chief of the Aṅgas, asked
her sister for the flowers (तदा निमन्त्रकस्
तस्या अङ्गेभ्यः क्षिप्रम् आगमत्॥तस्या
हि भगिनी तात ज्येष्ठा नाम्ना प्रभावती।
भार्या चित्ररथस्याथ बभूवाङ्गेश्वर-
स्य वै॥ … आमन्त्रिता ततो ऽगच्छद् रुचिर्
अङ्गपतेर् गृहान्॥पुष्पाणि तानि दृष्ट्वाथ
तदाङ्गेन्द्रवराङ्गना।भगिनीं चोदयाम्
आस पुष्पार्थे) 13. 42. 7-10; (4) Once,
the earth in rivalry with the king of the
Aṅgas (not named) gave up her nature
as earth and got lost; then the Brāhmaṇa
Kaśyapa steadied her—this was told by
Vāyu to Sahasrārjuna Kārtavīrya (त्यक्त्वा
महीत्वं भूमिस् तु स्पर्धयाङ्गनृपस्य
ह।नाशं जगाम तां विप्रो व्यष्टम्भ-
यत कश्यपः॥) 13. 138. 2.

अङ्गद
Aṅgada m. (pl.): Name of a Jana-
pada in the south.
Listed by Saṃjaya among the southern
Janapadas of the Bhāratavarṣa (जनपदान्
निबोध गदतो मम) 6. 10. 37, 5; (अथा-
परे जनपदा दक्षिणा … ) 6. 10. 56; (कुकु-
राङ्गदमारिषाः) 6. 10. 59.

अङ्गमलद
Aṅgamalada m. (pl.): Name of a
Janapada.
Listed by Saṃjaya among the (nor-
thern) Janapadas of the Bhāratavarṣa (अत
ऊर्ध्वं जनपदान् निबोध गदतो मम)
6. 10. 37, 5; (बहिर्गिर्याङ्गमलदाः) 6.
10. 48.

अङ्गिरस्
Aṅgiras m. (pl.): The descendents of
the sage Aṅgiras; the family was also
known as Āṅgirasa; often mentioned along
with Bhṛgus.
A. Their connection with Agni:
Because Agni adopted Aṅgiras, all those
born in the line of Aṅgiras were to be known
as Angirases (जग्राहाङ्गिरसं देवः शिखी
 … ।तस्मादङ्गिरसो ज्ञेयाः सर्व एव
तदन्वयाः) 13. 85. 45.
B. Extensive
lineage: Bhārgava and Āṅgirasa families
are characterized by extensive lineage
(भार्गवाङ्गिरसौ लोके लोकसंतानल-
क्षणौ) 13. 85. 34.
C. Persons born in
the family of Aṅgiras: (1) Bṛhaspati
referred to as the best among the Aṅgi-
rases (अङ्गिरसां वरिष्ठे बृहस्पतौ) 5.
16. 27; (अङ्गिरसां वर) 12. 323. 43;
(बृहस्पतिं … अङ्गिरसां वरम्) 18. 5.
10; (उत्पन्नेऽङ्गिरसे … बृहस्पतौ) 12.
322. 51. (2) Droṇa referred to as the
best among the Aṅgirases (अङ्गिरसां
वरः) 1. 123. 49, 68; (द्रोणम् अङ्गिरसां
वरम्) 5. 194. 15; (अङ्गिरसां … श्रेष्ठे …
गुरौ) 12. 2. 5; (3) Aśvatthāman (द्रोण-
पुत्रः … जातम् आङ्गिरसे कुले) 10. 7. 52-
54; (4) Utathya (उतथ्यस्य जातस्य्-
आङ्गिरसे कुले) 13. 139. 9; (5) Cirakāri
(चिरकारेस् तु यत् पूर्वं वृत्तम् आङ्गिरसे
कुले) 12. 258. 2.
D. Gods related
to Aṅgirases (?): While describing the
fourfold classification of gods, those rela-
ted to the Aṅgirases are said to be the
Brāhmaṇas among the gods (स्मृतास् त्व् अङ्गि-
रसो देवा ब्राह्मणा इति निश्चयः) 12. 201.
23.
E. Epic events: (1) Baka Dālbhya
pointed out to Yudhiṣṭhira, sages of diffe-
rent families, among whom were mentioned
Bhṛgus and Aṅgirases, who, observing vows,
practised धर्म in Dvaitavana under the
protection of Yudhiṣṭhira (पश्य द्वैतवने
पार्थ … चरन्ति धर्मम् … त्वया गुप्ता
धृतव्रताः।भृगवो ऽङ्गिरसश् चैव) 3.
27. 6-7; (2) When the Pāṇḍavas were
on the Mahendra mountain, Yudhiṣṭhira,
along with his brothers, honoured many as-
cetics, introduced by Lomaśa, among whom
there were, Bhṛgus and Aṅgirases (महेन्-
द्रम् आसाद्य … स तत्र … तापसानां परं
चक्रे सत्कारं भ्रातृभिः सह॥लोम-
शश् चास्य तान् सर्वान् आचख्यौ तत्र
तापसान्।भृगून् अङिगिरसश् चैव) 3. 114.
26; 3. 115. 1-2; (3) When Droṇa releas-
ed Brāhma astra to kill the Pāñcālas (7.
164. 79), great sages, led by Agni, came
to him; among these sages were Bhṛgus and
Aṅgirases; they told Droṇa that he had not
acted according to Dharma and that it was
time for his death (हव्यवाहपुरोगमाः …
भृगवो ऽङ्गिरसश् चैव … त एनम् अब्रुवन्
सर्वे द्रोणम् … अधर्मतः कृतं युद्धं
समयो निधनस्य ते) 7. 164. 86, 88-89.
F. Past events: (1) As an example of the
Kṣatriya lustre and power pacified by the
Brāhmaṇas, it was pointed out that the
Aṅgirases had defeated the Nīpas (क्षत्रिया-
णां प्रतपतां … ब्रामणेष्व् एव शाम्यन्ति
तेजांसि च बलानि च॥नीपान् अङ्गिरसो
ऽजयन्) 13. 34. 15-16; (2) Bhṛgus and
Aṅgirases, along with Daṇḍa, are mentioned
among those who followed Hara (Śiva) and
Pārvatī when they started for Bhadravaṭa
when Skanda was anointed as the leader of
gods; they were on the right side of Hara
(तस्य दक्षिणतो भाति दण्डो गच्छञ् श्रिया
वृतः।भृग्वङ्गिरोभिः सहितो … ) 3. 221. 14;
Aṅgirases, along with Bhṛgus, mentioned
among those who were present at the
time of anointing of Skanda (भृगुभिश्
चाङ्गिरोभिश् च … तथा वृतः) 9. 44. 8; (3)
Indra saw in the east at the Raudra muhūrta
on an Amāvāsyā day (3. 213. 26-27) Agni
entering the sun after receiving oblations
offered with various मन्त्रस् by Bhṛgus and
Aṅgirases (भृगुभिश् चाङ्गिरोभिश् च हुतं
मन्त्रैः पृथग्विधैः।हव्यं गृहीत्वा
वह्निं च प्रविशन्तं दिवाकरम्॥) 3.
213. 29.

अज
Aja m. (pl.): A class of ऋषिस्।
Ajas mentioned among the Ṛṣis who
waited on Pitāmaha (Brahman) in his
Bhavana (अजाश् चैवाविमूढाश् च … ।ऋषयः
सर्व एवैते पितामहम् उपासते) 1. 203. 5.

अटविक
Aṭavika m. (pl.): Forest tribes.
Dhṛtarāṣṭra mentions them along with
the Mlecchas who live on this earth (इयं
च पृथिवी सर्वा सम्लेच्छाटविका) 9. 31. 3.

अटवीशबर
Aṭavīśabara m. (pl.): Forest tribes
(Śabaras living in forests ?)
Mentioned by Saṃjaya while listing the
(northern) Janapadas of the Bhāratavarṣa
(जनपदान् निबोध गदतो मम) 6. 10.
37, 5; (अटवीशबराश् चैव) 6. 10. 46.

अनुपावृश्च
Anupāvṛśca m. (pl.): Name of a
Janapada.
Listed by Saṃjaya among the (nor-
thern) Janapadas of the Bhāratavarṣa
(जनपदान् निबोध गदतो मम) 6. 10.
37, 5; (उपावृश्चानुपावृश्च°) 6. 10. 47.

अनूप
Anūpa m.: Name of a country (near
water).
The unassailable king of the Anūpa
country (the king not named) mentioned
among those who came to Indraprastha to
learn the science of archery from Arjuna
(अनूपराजो दुर्धर्षः) 2. 4. 25; (अर्जुनं
चापि संश्रित्य राजपुत्राः … अशिक्षन्त
धनुर्वेदम्) 2. 4. 28; Kārtavīrya was
called the king of the Anūpa country (अनू-
पपतिर् वीरः कार्तवीर्यः) 3. 116. 19. [See
the next]

अनूपवासिक
Anūpavāsika m. (pl.): People who
lived in the Anūpa Janapada.
Listed by Saṃjaya among the (nor-
thern) Janapadas of Bhāratavarṣa (जन-
पदान् निबोध गदतो मम) 6. 10. 37, 5;
(विदर्भानूपवासिकाः) 6. 10. 42. [See Anūpa]

अन्तर्गिर्य
Antargirya m. (pl.): Name of a
Janapada.
One of the (northern) Janapadas of
the Bhāratavarṣa listed by Saṃjaya (अत
ऊर्ध्वं जनपदान् निबोध गदतो मम)
6. 10. 37, 5; (अन्तर्गिर्यास् तथैव च) 6.
10. 48.

अन्त्यज
Antyaja m. (pl.): Characterization of
a war-like class of people.
In battle they never turned back; they
therefore deserved always to be placed in
the front of the army; they either got killed
or killed others; they did not much care for
the rules of war, they broke away from
the proper way of conduct; their defeat
was beneficial (to their opponent); they
often got angry with the king (अन्त्यजा
ह्य् अनिवर्तिनः।पुरस्कार्याः सदा सैन्ये
हन्यन्ते घ्नन्ति चापि ते॥अधार्मिका
भिन्नव्ट्त्ताः साध्व् एवैषां पराभवः।
एवम् एव प्रकुप्यन्ति राज्ञो ऽप्य् एते ह्य्
अभीक्ष्णशः॥) 12. 102. 19-20 (Nī. on
Bom. Ed. 12. 101. 19: प्रान्तदेशोद्भवाः
कैवर्तभिल्लादयः; S. K. Belvalkar:
“belonging to borderlands or outlying dis-
tricts”, critical note on the stanza Vol. 13,
p. 672).

अन्धक
Andhaka, Andha m. (pl.): Name of
a people, mentioned in most cases along
with Vṛṣṇis, and sometimes also with
Bhojas and Kukuras.
A. Place: Residents of Dvārakā where
they lived after they fled from Mathurā
(see Epic events below Section D) (द्वा-
रकावासिभिश् … वृष्ण्यन्धकमहारथैः)
10. 12. 33; (also cf. द्वारकावासिनो जनाः 1.
210. 17).
B. Heroes referred to as chiefs
of Andhakas and Vṛṣṇis: (1) Kṛṣṇa:
(मुख्यम् अन्धकवृष्णीनाम् … कृष्णम्) 5.
56. 2; (अन्धकवृष्णिनाथ) 6. 55. 95; (वृ-
ष्ण्यन्धककुरूत्तम) 7. 79. 1; (वृष्ण्यन्-
धकपति) 14. 88. 13; (2) Sātyaki; (वृष्ण्य-
न्धकव्याघ्र) 7. 117. 47; (वृष्ण्यन्धक-
महारथ) 9. 20. 12; (सात्यकिश् … संमतो
ऽन्धकवृष्णिषु) 5. 63. 7; (3) Kṛtavarman:
(वृष्ण्यन्धकमहारथ) 9. 20. 12; (4)
Ugrasena: (वृष्ण्यन्धकपति) 14. 84. 15;
(5) Kaṃsa shone among the Vṛṣṇis and
Andhakas (तथोग्रसेनस्य सुतं …
वृष्ण्यन्धकानां मध्यगतं तपन्तम्)
5. 47. 72.
C. Characteristics: (1) Their
close relationship with the Pāṇḍavas: The
Pāṇḍavas had no friends other than the
Andhakas and the Vṛṣṇis and vice versa
(अस्माकं … मित्रम् अन्यन् न विद्यते।
परम् अन्धकवृष्णिभ्यः … ॥तथैवा-
न्धकवृष्णीनां॥।अस्मत्तो मित्रम् अन्यन् न
विद्यते॥) 7. 169. 48-49; it was on account
of their friendship with the Pāṇḍavas that
the Andhakas and Vṛṣṇis did not pay them
tribute at the time of the Rājasūya (द्वौ
करं न प्रयच्छेतां … सख्येनान्धक-
वृष्णयः) 2. 48. 42; (2) Fortunate, strong,
and difficult to be assailed, the Andhakas
and the Vṛṣṇis had become prosperous by
being ever industrious ( … सुमहाभागा
बलवन्तो दुरासदाः।नित्योत्थानेन सं-
पन्ना नारदान्धकवृष्णयः॥) 12. 82. 8;
(3) The Andhakas and the Vṛṣṇis were
not subjugated by Jarāsandha due to either
their policy or due to good luck (नयेना-
न्धकवृष्णयः।ते न तस्य वशं जग्मुः
केवलं दैवम् एव वा॥) 5. 50. 39; (4) All
the Andhakas and the Vṛṣṇis were attached
to Kṛṣṇa (सर्वे चान्धकवृष्णय्ः।त्वय्य्-
आसक्ता … ) 12. 82. 29; they relied on the
wisdom of Kṛṣṇa (वृष्ण्यन्धकाः … यस्य
प्रज्ञाम् उपासते) 5. 84. 4; Andhakas, Vṛ-
ṣṇis, and Bhojas were led by Kṛṣṇa; relying
on the counsel of Vāsudeva (Kṛṣṇa) they
subjugated the enemies and gave delight to
their friends (अन्धकाश् च वार्ष्णेयभोजाः
कौकुराः … ।उपासीना वासुदेवस्य बुद्धिं
विगृह्य शत्रून् सुहृदो नन्दयन्ति॥वृष्ण्य-
न्धका … कृष्णप्रणीताः) 5. 28. 11-12;
(5) According to Yudhiṣṭhira, Vṛṣṇis, An-
dhakas and all the Yādavas were like Indra,
spirited, who proved their valour, very
strong and who enjoyed pleasures (वृष्ण्यन्-
धका … सर्व एवेन्द्रकल्पाः।मनस्विनः
सत्यपराक्रमाश् च महाबला यादवा भोग-
वन्तः) 5. 28. 12; (6) Arjuna described
them as brave, high-souled, proud like lion,
very strong, capable of bearing the strokes
of गदा, परिघ and शक्ति, having arms
like परिघ, having strong arms (ये ते
शूरा महात्मानः सिंहदर्पा महाबलाः।
भोजवृष्ण्यन्धका … ॥गदापरिघशक्ती-
नां सहाः परीघबाहवः) 16. 9. 9-10;
(7) Vyāsa too called them high-souled
(दिष्तम् एतन् महात्मनाम्) 16. 9. 26;
(8) (According to Bhūriśravas, however,
the Vṛṣṇis and Andhakas could be trea-
cherous); he, therefore, while blaming
Arjuna for his misdeed asked him why
he regarded them as authority (वृष्ण्यन्-
धकाः कथं पार्थ प्रमाणं भवता
कृताः) 7. 118. 15.
D. Epic events: (1)
Viṣṇu was born among the Andhakas and
Vṛṣṇis for the advancement of धर्म
(धर्मसंवर्धनार्थाय प्रजज्ञे ऽन्ध-
कवृष्णिषु) 1. 57. 87; there in the lineage of
Vṛṣṇis and Andhakas he shone like the moon
among the stars (क्षिताव् अन्धकवृष्णीनां
वंशे … ।परया शुशुभे लक्ष्म्या नक्ष-
त्राणाम् इवोडुराट्) 2. 33. 17; (2) Vṛṣṇis and
Andhakas mentioned among those who ap-
proached Droṇa to learn the अस्त्रस् (अभि-
जग्मुस् ततो द्रोणम् अस्त्रार्थे … वृष्णयश्
चान्धकाश् चैव) 1. 122. 46; (3) They came
to witness the स्वयंवर of Draupadī
(वृष्ण्यन्धाश् चैव … प्रेक्षां स्म चक्रुः)
1. 178. 8; (4) When Arjuna, during the
period of his exile, visited Dvārakā, the
Bhojas, Vṛṣṇis and Andhakas gathered in a
crowd on the main road to see him; he
was honoured by their sons and was greet-
ed by them (दिदृक्षवश् च कौन्तेयं …
नरेन्द्रमार्गम् आजग्मुस् … भोजवृष्ण्यन्-
धकानां च समवायो महान् अभूत्।स
तथा सत्कृतः सर्वैर् भोजवृष्ण्यन्धकात्-
मजैः। … सर्वैश् च प्रतिनन्दितः॥) 1. 210.
17-19; (5) A great festival of the Raivataka
mountain was observed by the Vṛṣṇis and
Andhakas; they, along with the Bhojas, gave
gifts to thousands of Brāhmaṇas in that
festival (तस्मिन् रैवतके गिरौ।वृष्ण्यन्-
धकानाम् अभवत् सुमहान् उत्सवो नृप॥
तत्र दानं ददुर् वीरा … भोजवृष्ण्यन्ध-
काश् चैव) 1. 211. 1-2; (6) When Bhojas,
Vṛṣṇis and Andhakas heard the sound of
the भेरी sounded by the Sabhāpāla, they
were agitated; they left their food and
drink and rushed to the Hall; there the
great heroes among the Vṛṣṇis and Andha-
kas took their royal seats (क्षुब्धास् तेना-
थ शब्देन भोजवृष्ण्यन्धकास् तदा।अन्न-
पानम् अपास्याथ समापेतुः सभां ततः॥
 … भेजिरे … वृष्ण्यन्धकमहारथाः।
सिंहासनानि शतशः) 1. 212. 12, 14; (7)
When Balarāma declared his intention to
fight with Arjuna, Bhojas, Vṛṣṇis and
Andhakas followed him (अन्वपद्यन्त ते
सर्वे भोजवृष्ण्यन्धकास् तदा) 1. 212. 32;
(8) Rāma and Keśava, along with the
chiefs among Vṛṣṇis and Andhakas, and
Bhojas went to Khāṇḍavaprastha to give
nuptial gifts after the marriage of Su-
bhadrā (आजगाम … सह रामेण केशवः।
वृष्ण्यन्धकमहामात्रैः; एते चान्ये च
बहवो वृष्णिभोजान्धकास् तथा; सह
रामेण केशवः।वृष्ण्यन्धकमहाभो-
जैः संवृतः) 1. 213. 23, 29, 34; they were
received and honoured by Yudhiṣṭhira and
their gifts were accepted by him (तांश् च
वृष्ण्यन्धकश्रेष्ठान्; पूजयाम् आस तांश्
चैव वृष्ण्यन्धकमहारथान्) 1. 213. 38,
52; they enjoyed their stay at Khāṇḍava-
prastha and returned to Dvārakā after a
few days (°वृष्ण्यन्धकोत्तमाः।विजह्रुर्
 … ॥ … ययुर् वृष्ण्यन्धकमहारथाः) 1.
213. 53, 56; (9) Jarāsandha was neglect-
ed by Andhakas, Kukuras and Vṛṣṇis on
considerations of policy (कुकुरान्धकैः।
वृष्णिभिश् च … नीतिहेतोर् उपेक्षितः॥) 2.
17. 27; (10) Andhakas, Yādavas and
Bhojas had deserted Kaṃsa; similarly
Vidura wanted Dhṛtarāṣṭra to desert Dur-
yodhana (अन्धका यादवा भोजाः समेताः
कंसम् अत्यजन्) 2. 55. 6; later Kṛṣṇa
told the same thing (here Vṛṣṇis are men-
tioned along with Andhakas) to Bhīṣma
and others (कंसम् एकं परित्यज्य कुला-
र्थे … संभूय सुखम् एधन्ते … अन्ध-
कवृष्णयः) 5. 126. 39; (11) Having
heard about the Pāṇḍavas' exile, the Bhojas
went with Vṛṣṇis and Andhakas to meet
them in the Dvaitavana (भोजाः॥।वृष्णयश्
चान्धकैः सह … समाजग्मुर् महावने)
3. 13. 1; (12) When Pradyumna was afli-
cated by the arrows of Śālva, the army of
Vṛṣṇis and Andhakas wailed loudly (हाहा-
कृतम् अभूत् सर्वं वृष्ण्यन्धकबलं
तदा) 3. 19. 2; (13) Pradyumna asked his
charioteer how he should face Andhakas
and Vṛṣṇis who always vied with him
(अन्धकवृष्णयः।मया स्पर्धन्ति सत-
तम्) 3. 19. 28; (14) Sātyaki wanted
Vṛṣṇi, Bhoja and Andhaka heroes to kill
the sons of Dhṛtarāṣṭra and earn fame
(सवृष्णिभोजान्धकयोधमुख्याः) 3. 120.
19; (15) Kṛṣṇa assured Yudhiṣṭhira that
Kukura and Andhaka heroes would carry
out his orders and they would be wherever
he wanted them to be (कुकुरान्धकाश् च।
एते निदेशं तव पालयन्ती तिष्ठन्ति यत्रे-
