J. References to Kuru
women of Hāstinapura (mostly of the royal
family): Bhīṣma, Vidura, Dhṛtarāṣṭra, and
all Kuru women offered water libations to
Pāṇḍu (उदकं चक्रिरे तस्य सर्वाश् च
कुरुयोषिताः) 1. 118. 27; all high-ranking
women of the Kurus (सर्वाः कुरुवरस्त्रि-
यः) were anxious to meet newly-married
Draupadī 1. 198. 23; the desires of Kuru
women would remain unfulfilled after the
death of the sons of Dhṛtarāṣṭra (हत-
संकल्पाः … कुरुस्त्रियः) 3. 224. 8; ser-
vants of Kauravas requested help from
Pāṇḍavas lest the wives of the Kurus were
molested (परामर्शो मा भविष्यत् कुरु-
दारेषु) 3. 237. 7; Gāndhārī and all Kuru
women became unconscious hearing Saṃ-
jaya say that all except ten perished in
battle (सर्वाश् च कुरुयोषितः) 9. 1. 39;
Dhṛtarāṣṭra, Pāṇḍavas and Kṛṣṇa met
Kuru women (कुरुस्त्रियः समासाद्य)
and they all went to Kurukṣetra; there,
those women whose husbands were killed
(ताः स्त्रियो निहतेश्वराः) saw their dead
sons, brothers, fathers, husbands; seeing
the sight they, lamenting, fell down
from their vehicles (स्त्रियः … यानेभ्यो
विक्रोशन्त्यो निपेतिरे); that was a very piti-
able condition of Pāñcāla and Kuru women
(पाञ्चालकुरुयोषाणां कृपणं तद् अभून्
महत्); Gāndhārī showed to Kṛṣṇa
daughters-in-law who were lamenting like
कुररीस् (स्नुषा मे … प्रकीर्णकेशाः
क्रोशन्तीः कुररीर् इव माधव); they
remembered their near ones and ran to
them separately; those women from
noble families (परमाङ्गनाः), afflicted
by sorrow and grief, lamented; their faces
had dried up (मुखानि परमस्त्रीणाम्;
वक्त्राणि कुरुयोषिताम्); grieving Kuru
women described by Gāndhārī 11. 16. 10-
11, 13, 15, 18-19, 42-58; Kuru women,
took away their ornaments, upper garments,
girdles and, weeping due to excessive grief,
knowing their धर्म, gave water libations
to their relatives and friends; when they were
performing these rites, the river became
fordable and then again spread out widely
(भूषणान्य् उत्तरीयाणि वेष्टनान्य् अवमुच्य
च। … कुरुस्त्रियः।उदकं चक्रिरे सर्वा
रुदन्त्यो भृशदुःखिताः। … धर्मज्ञाः प्र-
चक्रुः सलिलक्रियाः॥) 11. 27. 2-4; all Kuru
women, Kuntī and Draupadī, mounted
different vehicles and went to Hāstinapura
led by Vidura 12. 38. 41; Kuru women
(कुरुयोषितः) held Subhadrā, grieving over
Abhimanyu's death, in their arms and
lamented 14. 60. 26; Citrāṅgadā and Ulupī
approached Draupadī, Subhadrā and other
Kuru women (याश् चान्याः कुरुयोषितः)
with modesty 14. 90. 2; knowing Kuntī's
firm resolve to retire to forest and seeing the
Pāṇḍavas return without her, Kuru women
wept loudly (कुरुस्त्रियः। … प्ररुरुदुस्
तदा॥) 15. 24. 11; wives of Kuru chiefs
followed Pāṇḍavas on foot when they too
on foot started towards the आश्रम of
Dhṛtarāṣṭra (स्त्रियश् च कुरुमुख्यानां
पद्भिर् एवान्वयुस् तदा) 15. 31. 2; Saṃ-
jaya introduced by name Draupadī and
all other Kuru women to the ascetics
in the आश्रम (सर्वान् नामाभिनामतः।
 … सर्वाश् चान्याः कुरुस्त्रियः) 15. 32. 4.
