कुरुक्षेत्र
Kurukṣetra (nt.): The country of the
Kurus; also part of it where the great
battle was fought; also called Kurukṣetra-
samantapañcaka.
A. Location: Close to the river
Sarasvatī (अभ्यगच्छत् ततो रामः …
कुरुक्षेत्रं … न्यविशन्त ततः सर्वे परि-
गृह्य सरस्वतीम्) 5. 177. 23-24; (ततो
गच्छेत … कुरुक्षेत्रम् … तत्र मासं
वसेद् वीर सरस्वत्याम्) 3. 81. 1, 3; not far
from Gaṅgā—Rāma wanted the river
Gaṅgā to see Bhīṣma killed by him at
Kurukṣetra (अयं गच्छामि कौरव्य
कुरुक्षेत्रं त्वया सह। … तत्र त्वां
निहतं माता … जाह्नवी पश्यतां भीष्म)
5. 179. 2-3; along the river Ikṣumatī
(कुरुक्षेत्रे निवसतां नदीम् इक्षुमतीम्
अनु) 1. 3. 145; near the river Hiraṇvatī
(आसाद्य सरितं पुण्यां कुरुक्षेत्रे हिरण्-
वतीम्) 5. 149. 73; (युद्धं कुरुक्षेत्रे
बभूव ह। … नद्यास् तीरे हिरण्वत्याः) 1.
95. 7-8; the boundaries of Kurukṣetra
were marked by Tarantuka, Arantuka, the
(five) lakes of Rāma and Macakruka—
this whole area was called Kurukṣetra-
samantapañcaka (also called Brahmavedi,
Uttaravedi of Pitāmaha, Uttaravedi of
Prajāpati) (ब्रह्मवेदी कुरुक्षेत्रं …
तरन्तुकारुन्तकयोर् यद् अन्तरं राम-
ह्रदानां च मचक्रुकस्य।एतत् कुरु-
क्षेत्रसमन्तपञ्चकं पितामहस्योत्तर-
वेदिर् उच्यते) 3. 81. 177-178; 9. 52. 20
(प्रजापतेर् उत्तरवेदिर् उच्यते); the five
lakes of Rāma could be seen from a dis-
tance while reaching Kurukṣetra from
Hāstinapura (कुरुक्षेत्रं … गच्छन्न् एव
 … अमी रामह्रदाः पञ्च दृश्यन्ते पार्थ
दूरतः) 12. 48. 6-8; Muñjavaṭa तीर्थ,
sacred to Mahādeva, was the famous gate
of Kurukṣetra (मुञ्जवटम् … कुरुक्षेत्र-
स्य तद् द्वारं विश्रुतम्) 3. 81. 18, 20; the
Plakṣāvataraṇa तीर्थ on Yamunā river was
also called the gate of Kurukṣetra (द्वारम्
एतद् धि कौन्तेय कुरुक्षेत्रस्य … ।एतत्
प्लक्षावतरणं यमुनातीर्थम् उच्यते)
3. 129. 11, 13; Naimiṣeya कुञ्ज was located
in Kurukṣetra (एवं स कुञ्जो राजेन्द्र
नैमिषेय इति स्मृतः।कुरुक्षेत्रे) 9. 36.
54; the Bāhlīka country lay outside Kuru-
kṣetra (बहिष्कृता … कुरुक्षेत्रेण चापि ये।
 … तान् … बाह्लीकान्) 8. 30. 10-11.
B. Name
and history: The great royal sage Kuru
ploughed the Kuru land for many years,
hence called Kurukṣetra (पुरा च राजर्षि-
वरेण … बहूनि वर्षाण्य् … ।प्रकृष्टम्
एतत् कुरुणा … ।ततः कुरुक्षेत्रम् इतीह
पप्रथे॥) 9. 52. 2 (Rāma asked the sages
why Kuru ploughed the land; the sages
told him the reason 9. 52. 3 ff.); the place
known after the pious Kuru, son of
Saṃvaraṇa and Tapatī (ततः संवरणात्
सौरी सुषुवे तपती कुरुम्। … तस्य नाम्ना-
भिविख्यातं पृथिव्यां कुरुजाङ्गलम्।
कुरुक्षेत्रम्) 1. 89. 42-43.
C. Descrip-
tion: very famous (अभिविख्यात) 1. 89. 43;
pleasing (रमणीय) 9. 22. 23; holy
(पुण्य) 9. 22. 23; very holy (महत्पुण्य)
9. 52. 21; most holy in the three worlds
(पुण्यतमे त्रैलोक्यस्यापि) 5. 139. 53 (also
see the next section D); auspicious (शिव)
9. 52. 21; place suitable for austerities
(तपःक्षेत्र) 6. 1. 2; honoured by gods
(दिवौकसां सुसंमतम्) 9. 52. 21;
place where people practise धर्म
(धर्मक्षेत्र) 6. 23. 1; 14. 93. 2; chosen
by many who were conversant with धर्म
(धर्मज्ञैर् भहुभिर् वृते) 14. 93. 2;
place of the whole धर्म (क्षेत्रम्
धर्मस्य कृत्स्नस्य) 12. 53. 23; having
heavenly qualities (स्वर्गगुणैः समन्-
वितम्) 9. 52. 21; battlefield (रणक्षेत्र)
5. 179. 15; (after the war) full of hair,
marrow, and bones (केशमज्जास्थिसं-
कुल) 12. 48. 3 (also stanzas 4-6).
D.
Holy: King, Kuru made the place holy
by his austerities (कुरुक्षेत्रं स तपसा
पुण्यं चक्रे) 1. 89. 43; it was desirable
for the Kṣatriyas to get killed by weapons
on Kurukṣetra (शस्त्रेण निधनं गच्छेत्
समृद्धं क्षत्रमण्डलम्।कुरुक्षेत्रे
पुण्यतमे) 5. 139. 53; all kings killed here
would obtain the condition of the high-
souled ones 9. 52. 21; fruit obtained by
people by visiting Kurukṣetra (कुरुक्षेत्र-
स्य यत् फलम्) 9. 51. 25-26; Śakra him-
self sang a गाथा in praise of the holi-
ness of Kurukṣetra: even the dust parti-
cles carried by wind were capable of
leading a sinner to the highest condition
(पांसवो ऽपि कुरुक्षेत्राद् वायुना समुद्-
ईरिताः।अपि दुष्कृतकर्माणं नयन्ति पर-
मां गतिम्) 9. 52. 18; chief gods (सुर-
र्षभाः) and excellent Brāhmaṇas, simi-
larly great kings like Nṛga and others
obtained good condition after death by
offering costly sacrifices at Kurukṣetra 9.
52. 19.
E. Epic events: (1) Takṣaka
and his son Aśvasena used to live in
Kurukṣetra 1. 3. 144-145; 1. 218. 4; 1. 219.
13; (2) Citrāṅgada and the Gandharva
king of the same name fought a battle at
Kurukṣetra on the river Hiraṇvatī for
three years 1. 95. 7; (3) When Dhṛta-
rāṣṭra, Pāṇḍu and Vidura were born, the
Kurus, Kurukṣetra and Kurujāṅgala pros-
pered 1. 102. 1 (the way they prospered
described in stanzas 2-14); (4) The
Pāṇḍavas, at the start of their life in the
forest, proceeded towards Kurukṣetra from
the bank of Gaṅgā (प्रययुर् जाह्नवीकूलात्
कुरुक्षेत्रम्) 3. 6. 1; (5) Before going
to Virāṭa, Yudhiṣṭhira unstrung his
bow with which he formerly protected
Kurukṣetra 4. 5. 18; (6) Duryodhana
asked the kings to proceed towards Kuru-
kṣetra under the Puṣya nakṣatra (प्रया-
ध्वं वै कुरुक्षेत्रं पुष्यो ऽद्येति);
accordingly the kings started for Kuru-
kṣetra 5. 148. 3, 18; he also asked them
to establish camps at Kurukṣetra 5,
150. 14; Duryodhana himself with his
brothers, led by Bhīṣma, went to Kuru-
kṣetra with his large army; he made a
round of Kurukṣetra with Karṇa and
measured on level ground the land required
for his camp (कुरुक्षेत्रं जगाम ह। …
परिक्रम्य कुरुक्षेत्रं कर्णेन सह … ।
शिबिरं मापयाम् आस समे देशे) 5. 153. 33-
34; he and his allies got ready for the war
on the western half of Kurukṣetra (कुरु-
क्षेत्रस्य पश्चार्धे) 5. 196. 11 (should
this be कुरुक्षेत्रस्य पूर्वार्धे ? see 6. 1. 5*
and the editor's note on 6. 1. 5 (p. 755));
(7) The Pāṇḍavas too reached Kurukṣetra;
reaching there, they blew their conches;
there, Dhṛṣṭadyumna and Sātyaki measured
the land for raising the camp of the
Pāṇḍavas (शिबिरं मापयाम् आस धृष्ट-
द्युम्नश् च … ।सात्यकिश् च); Kṛṣṇa ordered
the digging of a ditch at Kurukṣetra for
the protection of the camp (खानयाम्
आस परिखां केशवस् तत्र … ।गुप्त्यर्-
थम्) 5. 149. 63-64; 72-74; the place of
the camp of Pāṇḍavas described in 5. 149.
67-69; (the camp of Pāṇḍavas was
outside the Samantapañcaka 6. 1. 6);
Pāṇḍavas were encamped on the western
side (of the Kurukṣetra) and faced east
(प्राङ्मुखाः पश्चिमे भागे) 6. 1. 5; (8)
The two armies were arrayed against each
other at Kurukṣetra (तथा व्यूढेष्व् अनी-
केषु कुरुक्षेत्रे) 5. 156. 1; (9) Duryo-
dhana informed Yudhiṣṭhira through Ulūka
that Kurukṣetra was free from mud and
that the road to it was even (कुरुक्षेत्रम्
अकर्दमम्।समः पन्था … ) 5. 157.
18; 5. 158. 11 (Nī. on Bom. Ed. 5. 160. 93:
अकर्दमम् इति युद्धयोग्यत्वं भूमेर्
उक्तम्); (10) Rāma (Bhārgava) took
Ambā to Kurukṣetra (to meet Bhīṣma)
5. 177. 23; (11) Bhīṣma agreed to fight
with Rāma at Kurukṣetra and asked him
to return there (कुरुक्षेत्रे योत्स्ये) 5. 178.
31; (विनिवर्तस्व कुरुक्षेत्रम्) 5. 178. 33;
Rāma agreed to return to Kurukṣetra and
he went there (अयं गच्छामि कौरव्य
कुरुक्षेत्रम्) 5. 179. 2; (ययौ रमः
कुरुक्षेत्रम्) 5. 179. 8; later, Bhīṣma
too reached Kurukṣetra from Hāstinapura
(निष्क्रम्य गजसाह्वयात्।कुरुक्षेत्रम्
उपायाम्) 5. 179. 15, 17; (apparently the
earlier meeting between Rāma and Bhīṣma
did not take place at Kurukṣetra but on
the outskirts of Hāstinapura); the fight
between Bhīṣma and Rāma at Kurukṣetra
referred to in 12. 27. 8; 13. 154. 25; (12)
Kauravas and Pāṇḍavas were encamped
at Kurukṣetra and were eager to fight 6.
1. 2-3, 23; (13) Vaiśaṃpāyana began the
narration of what the Kauravas and the
Pāṇḍavas did at Kurukṣetra as was done
earlier by Saṃjaya 6. 1. 2; 6. 23. 1; (14)
After the death of Śalya, the Kṣatriyas,
in spite of bad omens, were ready to fight at
Kurukṣetra desirous of reaching the heaven
(if killed in war) (कुरुक्षेत्रे … स्वर्-
गं यियांसवः) 9. 22. 23; (15) Bala-
rāma in his तीर्थयात्रा went to Kuru-
kṣetra 9. 34. 32; (16) From Kurukṣetra he
went to the आश्रम where formerly Viṣṇu
practised austerities 9. 53. 1, 5; (17) On
reaching Kurukṣetra, the Kuru women saw
their near relatives lying dead 11. 16. 11;
(18) Kṛṣṇa, along with the Pāṇḍavas, went
to Kurukṣetra to meet Bhīṣma lying on the
bed of arrows 12. 48. 2-3, 6; 12. 53. 23;
12. 57. 2; (19) When Uttarāyaṇa set in,
Yudhiṣṭhira, with Dhṛtarāṣṭra, Gāndhārī
and others, went from Hāstinapura to
Bhīṣma lying at Kurukṣetra 13. 153. 12;
(20) Dhṛtarāṣṭra first went to Kurukṣetra
from the river Bhāgīrathī where there was
the आश्रम of Śatayūpa 15. 25. 8-9; (21)
Yudhiṣṭhira and others started for the
आश्रम of Dhṛtarāṣṭra which was at Kuru-
kṣetra (कुरुक्षेत्राश्रमं प्रति) 15. 29.
21; he reached Kurukṣetra after crossing
the river Yamunā (कुरुक्षेत्रम् अवातरत्।
क्रमेणोत्तीर्य यमुनाम्) 15. 30. 16; (22)
The great sages, Śatayūpa and others,
living at Kurukṣetra arrived to meet Dhṛta-
rāṣṭra and the Pāṇḍavas (शतयूपप्रभृ-
तयः कुरुक्षेत्रनिवासिनः) 15. 34. 21;
(23) Vyāsa told Gāndhārī that Gandhar-
vas, Apsarases, and the rest, born as
human beings, met their death at Kuru-
kṣetra (गन्धर्वाप्ररसश् चैव त …
एते निधनं प्राप्ताः कुरुक्षेत्रे) 15. 39.
6-7; (24) Dhṛtarāṣṭra went from Kuru-
kṣetra to Gaṅgādvāra (where he was
reduced to ashes by forest fire) (कुरु-
क्षेत्रात् पिता तुभ्यं गङ्गाद्वारं ययौ)
15. 45. 10; (25) Arjuna arrived at Kuru-
kṣetra from Dvārakā after he was attacked
by Dasyus on his way 16. 8. 85.
F. Past
events: (1) Viṣṇu once told Pṛthivī that
the kings who would gather at Kurukṣetra
would kill each other (कुरुक्षेत्रे समा-
गताः।अन्योन्यं घातयिष्यन्ति) 11. 8. 25;
(2) Janamejaya, son of Parikṣit, with his
brothers performed a long sacrificial
session at Kurukṣetra (जनमेजयः पारि-
क्षितः सह भ्रातृभिः कुरुक्षेत्रे दीर्घ-
सत्रम् उपास्ते) 1. 3. 1; (3) The place
where king Māndhātṛ offered sacrifices
was situated in the middle of Kurukṣetra
(तस्यैतद् देवयजनं … कुरुक्षेत्रस्य
मध्यतः) 3. 126. 42; (4) Sudarśana, with
his wife Oghavatī, decided to lead the life
of a householder at Kurukṣetra 13. 2. 39;
(5) When king Kuru offered a sacrifice at
Kurukṣetra, Sarasvatī appeared at Ṛṣabha-
dvīpa as Suveṇu (सुवेणुर् ऋषभद्वीपे …
कुरोश् च यजमानस्य कुरुक्षेत्रे … आज-
गाम … सरस्वती) 9. 37. 24; (6) When
Vasiṣṭha invited her at Kurukṣetra, Sara-
svatī appeared there as Oghavatī (ओघवत्य्
अपि … वसिष्ठेन … ।समाहूता कुरुक्षेत्रे …
सरस्वती) 9. 37. 25; (7) When the sages
of the Nimiṣa forest decided to go on a
pilgrimage, they went to Kurukṣetra 3. 81.
92; (8) In the Kṛtayuga (9. 36. 39),
when the ascetics from the Nimiṣa forest
went to Kurukṣetra, they found no place
there as it was already full of sages (ते
ऽवकाशं न ददृशुः कुरुक्षेत्रे) 9. 36. 48;
(9) Pious Mudgala, who lived only by
gleaning ears of corn, lived at Kurukṣetra
(शिलोञ्छवृत्तिर् धर्मात्मा मुद्गलः … ।
आसीद् … कुरुक्षेत्रे) 3. 246. 3; (10) A cer-
tain noble Brāhmaṇa (name not mention-
ed), who lived the life of a pigeon by
gleaning ears of corn, lived at Kuru-
kṣetra (उञ्छवृत्तेर् वदान्यस्य कुरुक्षेत्र-
निवासिनः) 14. 92. 9, 19, 21; (कुरुक्षेत्रे … ।
उञ्छवृत्तिर् द्विजः कश्चित् कापोतिर् अभवत्
पुरा) 14. 93. 2; (11) Sunda and Upa-
sunda, after conquering the whole earth,
settled down at Kurukṣetra (निःसपत्नौ
कुरुक्षेत्रे निवेशम् अभिचक्रतुः) 1. 202.
27 [See Kurukṣetra (holy place) Vol. 1. 5.
pp. 312-313 and Kurujāṅgala (below)].

कुरुजाङ्गल
Kurujāṅgala nt. (sg.), m. (pl.): Name
of the country with Hāstinapura as capital
and people living there (while referring to
people used in m. pl.); occasionally the
term refers to the battlefield at Kurukṣetra
(5. 150. 4; 6. 5. 6; 8. 1. 17).
A. Description: Called देश 1. 102.
22; राष्ट्र 1. 191. 9; 12. 38. 23; after the
birth of Dhṛtarāṣṭra, Pāṇḍu and Vidura,
Kurujāṅgala was looked upon as the most
distinguished among all countries (देशा-
नां कुरुजाङ्गलम्) 1. 102. 22.
B. Epic
events: (1) To Dhṛtarāṣṭra belonged as
ancestral share the rulership of the
Kurujāṅgala country and its people
(पित्र्यं राज्यं महाराज कुरवस् ते
सजाङ्गलाः) 5. 53. 7; (2) Kuntī and the
Pāṇḍavas, with the hermits from the Himā-
laya, reached the Kurujāṅgala 1. 117. 8;
(3) Kuntī blessed Draupadī that she will
be the anointed queen of the countries
and cities among which the Kurujāṅgala
was the principal one (कुरुजाङ्गल-
मुख्येषु राष्ट्रेषु नगरेषु च) 1. 191.
9; (4) To reach the Magadha country,
Kṛṣṇa, Bhīma and Arjuna started from
the Kurus and passed through the Kuru-
jāṅgala (कुरुभ्यः प्रस्थितास् ते तु म-
ध्येन कुरुजाङ्गलम्) 2. 18. 26; (5)
People of the Kurujāṅgala country saw
Draupaḍī helpless in the Sabhā (यदा जनौ-
घः कुरुजाङ्गलानां कृष्णां सभायाम्
अवशाम् अपश्यत्) 3. 180. 20; (6) Dhṛta-
rāṣṭra asked sage Maitreya if he reached
Kurujāṅgala comfortably 3. 11. 9; (7)
The Kurujāṅgala people and their chiefs
grieved while taking leave of the Pāṇḍavas
(मुख्याश् च सर्वे कुरुजाङ्गलानाम्। …
जनौघं कुरुजाङ्गलानाम् 3. 24. 5-6;
(8) The entire Kurujāṅgala country and
the country around it became disturbed
when the Kaurava army came together
(कृत्स्नं च कुरुजाङ्गलम्) 5. 19. 29;
(9) Janamejaya wanted Vaiśaṃpāyana to
tell him what transpired at Kurujāṅgala (=
Kurukṣetra) (संभ्रमे तुमुले तस्मिन्
यद् आसीत् कुरुजाङ्गले) 5. 150. 4; (10)
According to Dhṛtarāṣṭra, crores of heroic
men had gathered at Kurujāṅgala (=
Kurukṣetra) (कोट्यश् च लोकवीराणां समे-
ताः कुरुजाङ्गले) 6. 5. 6; (11) After the
fall of Karṇa, Saṃjaya went to Hāstina-
pura to report what had happened at
Kurujāṅgala (= Kurukṣetra) (आचख्यौ
धृटराष्ट्राय यद् वृत्तं कुरुजाङ्गले) 8.
1. 17; (12) Yudhiṣṭhira went to Bhīṣma
with the kings who survived the battle
and all Kurujāṅgala people (सर्वे च कुरु-
जाङ्गलाः) 13. 153. 22; (13) Dhṛtarāṣṭra
requested the Brāhmaṇas, Kṣatriyas, Vaiśyas
and Śūdras of the Kurujāṅgala country to
give him permission to go to the forest; he
said they had lived for a long time happily
with the Kurus (ब्राह्मणाः कुरुजाङ्गलाः।
क्षत्रियाश् चैव वैश्याश् च शूद्राश् चैव … ॥
भवन्तः कुरवश् चैव बहुकालं सहोषि-
ताः। … परस्परस्य सुहृदः परस्परहिते
रताः॥) 15. 13. 13-14; hearing those
words the people of Kurujāṅgala (कुरु-
जाङ्गलाः) wept with their voices chocked
due to tears 15. 13. 21; 15. 14. 17; 15.
15. 6; they consulted among themselves
and appointed one Brāhmaṇa to speak on
their behalf 15. 15. 7-10.
F. Past events:
(1) A certain Bāhlīka chief while once
living away in Kurujāṅgala remembered
his beloved and sang a गाथा 8. 30. 19-20;
(2) The large quantity of gold accumulat-
ed at Kurujāṅgala was given away by king
Suhotra in a sacrifice (तद् धिरण्यम्
अपर्यन्तम् आवृत्तं कुरुजाङ्गले।ईजानो
वितते यज्ञे) 12. 29. 26. [See Jāṅgala].

कुलक
Kulaka m. (pl.): Name of a Janapada.
Listed by Saṃjaya among the southern
Janapadas (also called Deśas 6. 10. 68)
of the Bhāratavarṣa (अथापरे जनपदा
दक्षिणा भरतर्षभ) 6. 10. 56, 5;
(कुलिन्दाः कुलकाश् चैव) 6. 10. 61.

कुलिन्द
Kulinda m. (pl.): Name of a Janapada.
Listed by Saṃjaya among the southern
Janapadas (also called Deśas 6. 10. 68)
of the Bhāratavarṣa (अथापरे जनपदा
दक्षिणा … ) 6. 10. 56, 5; (कुलिन्दाः कुलकाश्
चैव) 6. 10. 61.

कुलिन्दोपत्यका
Kulindopatyakā f. (pl.): Name of a
Janapada (low-land of Kulinda).
Listed by Saṃjaya among the nor-
thern Janapadas (also called Deśas 6. 10.
68) of the Bhāratavarṣa (अत ऊर्ध्वं
जनपदान् निबोध गदतो मम) 6. 10. 37,
5; कुलिन्दोपत्यकास् तथा) 6. 10. 54.

कुलूत
Kulūta m. (pl.): Name of a Janapada
and its people.
Listed by Saṃjaya among the northern
Janapadas (also called Deśas 6. 10. 68) of
the Bhāratavarṣa (अत ऊर्ध्वं जनपदान्
निबोध) 6. 10. 37, 5; (अभीसाराः कुलूताश्
च) 6. 10. 52; Kṣemadhūrti, their king
(कुलूताधिपतिः 8. 8. 35), was killed by
Bhīma (निहतं नृपतिं दृष्ट्वा कुलूता-
नाम्) 8. 8. 45.

कुशद्वीप
Kuśadvīpa m.: Name of one of the
seven Dvīpas of the terrestrial world.
A. Location: They lie to the north
(apparently of the Jambudvīpa) (उत्तरेषु
तु कौरव्य द्वीपेषु) 6. 13. 1.
B. Disti-
nctive features as described by Saṃjaya
to Dhṛtarāṣṭra 6. 12. 2: (1) It has a bunch
of Kuśa grass in the middle of the country
(कुशद्वीपे कुशस्तम्बो मध्ये जनपद-
स्य ह) 6. 13. 6; (2) There are six exce-
llent mountains (पर्वतोत्तमाः) in the
Kuśadvīpa viz.: (1) Sudhāman, full of
corals and unassailable (विद्रुमैश् चितः
 … दुर्धर्षः), (2) Dyutimant, golden
(हेमपर्वतः), (3) Kumuda, (4) Puṣpa-
vant, (5) Kuśeśaya, and (6) Hari; the
distance between these mountains doubles
as one goes from one mountain to the other
(तेषाम् अन्तरविष्कम्भो द्विगुणः प्रविभा-
गशः) 6. 13. 9-11.
C. Characteristics
common to all the seven Dvīpas: (1) All
Dvīpas are progressively double the size
of the Dvīpa preceding it (as one proceeds
towards the north ?) and they are all sur-
rounded by mountains on all sides (पर-
स्परेण द्विगुणाः सर्वे द्वीपा नराधिप।
सर्वतश् च महाराज पर्वतैः परिवारि-
ताः॥) 6. 13. 3; (2) All Dvīpas receive
different kinds of jewels from Jambudvīpa
(जम्बुद्वीपात् प्रवर्तन्ते रत्नानि विविधान्य्
उत।द्वीपेषु तेषु सर्वेषु) 6. 13. 26; (3)
The state of health and the duration of life
progressively doubles in these Dvīpas owing
to ब्रह्मचर्य, truth, and self-control of
the Brāhmaṇas (विप्राणां ब्रह्मचर्येण
सत्येन च दमेन च।आरोग्यायुःप्रमा-
णाभ्यां द्विगुणं द्विगुणं ततः) 6.
13. 27; (4) In these islands there is
only one Janapada and even if in some
there are many Janapadas there is only
one धर्म in all of them (एको जनपदो
राजन् द्वीपेष्व् एतेषु भारत।उक्ता जनपदा
येषु धर्मश् चैकः प्रदृश्यते॥) 6. 13.
28; (5) Prajāpati himself, raising his
दण्ड, protects the people of these Dvīpas,
both dull and learned; he is their king,
is kind to them, their father, and their
grand-father (ईश्वरो दण्डम् उद्यम्य
स्वयम् एव प्रजापतिः।द्वीपान् एतान् महा-
राज रक्षंस् तिष्ठति नित्यदा॥स राजा
स शिवो … स पिता स पितामहः।गोपायति
नरश्रेष्ठ प्रजाः सजदपण्डिताः॥) 6.
13. 29-30; (3) People eat food received
ready for use (भोजनं चात्र कौरव्य
प्रजाः स्वयम् उपस्थितम्।सिद्धम् एव
महाराज भुञ्जते तत्र नित्यदा॥) 6. 13.
31.
D. Epic event: Dhṛtarāṣṭra asked
Saṃjaya to describe to him the different
Dvīpas including the Kuśadvīpa 6. 12. 2.
E. Past event: Upamanyu told Kṛṣṇa
that the rulership of Kuśadvīpa was given
to Vidyutprabha (Dānava) by the Un-
born god (Śiva) (कुशद्वीपं च स ददौ
राज्येन भगवान् अजः) 13. 14. 57.

कुशबिन्दु
Kuśabindu m. (pl.): Name of a Jana-
pada.
Listed by Saṃjaya among the northern
Janapadas (also called Deśas 6. 10. 68) of
the Bhāratavarṣa (अत ऊर्ध्वं जनपदान्
निबोध) 6. 10. 37, 5; (रोमाणः कुश-
बिन्दवः) 6. 10. 54.

कुशल
Kuśala1 m. (pl.): Name of a Jana-
pada.
Listed by Saṃjaya among the northern
Janapadas (also called Deśas 6. 10. 68) of
the Bhāratavarṣa (अत ऊर्ध्वं जनपदान्
निबोध गदतो मम) 6. 10. 37; (कुशलाः
कुनटास् तथा) 6. 10. 50.

कुशल
Kuśala2 m.: Name of a Deśa related
to the Krauñca mountain on the Krauñca
Dvīpa.
Each of the six mountains on this
Dvīpa is related to some Deśa (देशांस्
तत्र प्रवक्ष्यामि … क्रौञ्चस्य कुशलो
देशो … ) 6. 13. 20; these Deśas are resorted
to by gods and Gandharvas (देवगन्ध-
र्वसेविताः) 6. 13. 23.

कुशिक
Kuśika, Kauśika m. (pl.): Designa-
tion of the descendants of king Kuśika;
also referred to as Kuśikavaṃśa 13. 3. 5,
Kauśika vaṃśa (13. 52. 4).
A. History: (1) Kuśikas were those
born in the lineage of Jahnu of boundless
spirit (अन्वयाः कुशिका राजन् जह्नोर् अमित-
तेजसः) 1. 89. 29; (2) They were made
firm in this world by Viśvāmitra (तेन
(i. e. by Viśvāmitra) … कुशिकवंशश् च …
स्थापितो नरलोके ऽस्मिन्) 13. 3. 3, 5; (3)
Yudhiṣṭhira once asked Bhīṣma how one
born in the Kṣatriya lineage of Kauśikas
became a Brāhmaṇa (कौशिकाच् च कथं
वंशात् क्षत्राद् वै ब्राह्मणो ऽभवत्) 13.
52. 4; Bhīṣma then told him how the rela-
tionship between Kuśikas and Bhṛgus was
formed (भृगूणां कुशिकानां च प्रति सं-
बन्धकारणम्) 13. 56. 19.
B. Descrip-
tion: Great (महन्त्), learned (विद्वंस्),
full of many Brahmarṣis (ब्रह्मर्षिशत-
संकुल), and praised by Brāhmaṇas (ब्राह्-
मणसंस्तुत) 13. 3. 5.
C. Past events:
(1) Cyavana wanted to burn all the descen-
dants of Kuśika and destroy them (चिकी-
र्षन् कुशिकोच्छेदं संदिधक्षुः कुलं
तव) 13. 55. 12; 13. 52. 9; (2) Vasiṣṭha,
controlling his anger, did not wish to des-
troy the descendants of Kuśika on account
of the fault of Viśvāmitra (यस् तु नोच्छे-
दनं चक्रे कुशिकानाम् उदारधीः।विश्वा-
मित्रापराधेन धारयन् मन्युम् उत्त-
मम्॥) 1. 164. 6.

कृमि
Kṛmi m. (pl.): Name of a people.
Mentioned by Bhīma among the six-
teen peoples whose kings were defilers of
their families (कुलपांसनाः), most wicked
men in their families (कुलेषु पुरुषाध-
माः), and who extirpated their kinsmen
and friends together with their relatives
(ये समुच्चिच्छिदुर् ज्ञातीन् सुहृदश् च स-
बान्धवान्); one of them was the rude
Vasu of the Kṛmis (कृमीणाम् उद्धतो
वसुः) 5. 72. 11, 13.

कृष्ण
Kṛṣṇa m. (pl.): Name (?) of a people.
Mentioned by Duryodhana among
those who had brought tributes of different
kinds for the Rājasūya of Yudhiṣṭhira but
were stopped at the gate (कृष्णान् … द्वारि
वारितान्।बल्यर्थं ददतस् तस्य नाना-
रूपान् अनेकशाः) 2. 47. 19-20.

केकय
Kekaya, Kaikaya, Kaikeya m. (pl.):
Name of a Janapada and the warriors of
this country; they are often mentioned
along with Pāñcālas (or Sṛñjayas) and
Matsyas in the war.
A. Use of the terms: The term Kekaya
is specifically used to refer to the five
brothers fighting on the side of the Pāṇḍa-
vas (one of them was named Bṛhatkṣatra
7. 81. 7); the warriors and the five brothers
also referred to as Kaikaya or Kaikeya
(6. 52. 4); a warrior once referred to as
केकयज (8. 4. 69); a Kekaya princess (Su-
kumārī) referred to as Kaikeyī (1. 90. 45).
B. Location: Listed by Saṃjaya among
the northern Janapadas (also called Deśas
6. 10. 68) of Bhāratavarṣa (अत ऊर्ध्वं
जनपदान् निबोध गदतो मम) 6. 10.
37. 5; (सुराषृराः केकयास् तथा) 6. 10.
47.
C. Relationship with Pāṇḍavas: The
five brothers were the sons of the sister of
Pāṇḍavas' mother (भ्रातरः पञ्च कैकेया
 … मातृष्वसुः सुता वीराः) 7. 9. 53 (how-
ever, see below Nī.'s remark under
F. Epic
events No. 4).
D. Description (often
only of the five brothers, occasionally of all
warriors): High-souled (महात्मन्) 1.
61. 11; having the colour of a fire-fly
(इन्द्रगोपकवर्ण) 5. 139. 26; 7. 9. 52
(Nī. on Bom. Ed. 5. 141. 26: इन्द्रगोपकः
वर्षासु प्रचलन् रक्तजन्तुस् तद्वर्णास्
ताम्रा इत्य् अर्थः); religious (धार्मिक)
7. 9. 52; heroic (वीर) 7. 9. 52-53; brave
(शूर) 5. 47. 23; 5. 49. 35; 6. 18. 14; 8. 8.
19; 11. 25. 13; of great prowess (महा-
वीर्य) 3. 13. 2; 7. 34. 5; 8. 31. 21; strong
(बलिन्) 5. 22. 19; (बलवन्त्) 6. 112. 107;
always on their guard (संयत्त) 6. 112.
107; of true valour (सत्यविक्रम) 7. 9. 52;
eminent Kṣatriyas (क्षत्रियर्षभ) 3. 13.
4; tigers among men (नरव्याघ्र) 5. 19.
25; best and prominent among the kings
(पार्थिवर्षभसत्तम) 1. 61. 11; famous
among the world (लोकविश्रुत) 3. 13. 2;
great chariot-fighters (महारथ) 6. 112.
107; 7. 135. 16; bowmen (धन्विन्) 6. 112.
7; having large bows (महेष्वास) 2. 4.
27; 3. 252. 16; 5. 22. 19; 5. 49. 35; 6. 45. 29;
6. 73. 56, 58, 59; 11. 26. 36; versed in the
science of archery (धनुर्वेदविशारद)
6. 70. 33; (धनुर्वेदविद्) 6. 57. 13; who
had learnt the use of missiles (कृतास्त्र)
7. 34. 6; wearing shining bracelets (रुचिरा-
ङ्गद) 11. 25. 13; having gold banners
(सुवर्णविकृतध्वज) 6. 73. 58; having
copper-coloured standards, and chariot-
garlands (ताम्रध्वजरथस्रजः) 11. 25.
14; having red banners (लोहितकध्वज)
7. 22. 11; 7. 24. 40; wearing well-polished
armours (सुमृष्टकवच) 5. 49. 35; wearing
armours shining like heated gold (तप्त-
काञ्चनवर्माणः) 11. 25. 14; having red
armours, weapons and banners (रक्तवर्-
मायुधध्वज) 7. 9. 52; in war, invincible
by enemies (अजेयाः शत्रुभिर् युधि) 6. 57.
13; arrogant in war (युद्धदुर्मद) 7.
34. 6; ready to die (in war) (तनुत्यज्) 6. 18.
14.
E. History: The five great and strong
Asuras Ayaḥśiras, Aśvaśiras, Ayaḥśaṅku,
Gaganamūrdhan, and Vegavant were born
as the five great, prominent kings among
the Kekayas (पञ्चैते जज्ञिरे … केक-
येषु … पार्थिवर्षभसत्तमाः) 1. 61.
10-11.
F. Epic events: (1) At the birth
of Arjuna a non-corporal voice prophesied
that he would defeat Kekayas and other
peoples 1. 114. 31; 8. 48. 7 (here the pro-
phecy is said to have been heard a week
after Arjuna's birth (सप्ताहजाते त्वयि) 8.
48. 6; (2) Kekayas mentioned among
those who waited on Yudhiṣṭhira in his
Sabhā 2. 4. 27; (3) The Kekaya Kṣatriyas
(क्षत्रियाः 2. 48. 16; राजन्याः 2. 48. 13)
brought tribute in hundreds for Yudhi-
ṣṭhira's Rājasūya 2. 48. 13, 16; (4) The
five Kekaya brothers, along with others,
came to meet the Pāṇḍavas during their
वनवास (केकयाश् च … भ्रातरो लोक-
विश्रुताः) 3. 13. 2; they took leave of
Pāṇḍāvas and left the forest 3. 23. 48
(Nī. on Bom. Ed. 3. 22. 51: केकयाश्
सहदेवश्यालाः); (5) Bhīma assured
Yudhiṣṭhira that with the support of
Sṛñjayas and Kekayas they were sure to
get back the lost kingdom 3. 34. 85; (6)
Kṛṣṇa mentioned Kekayas among those
who would help them in the war 3. 120.
25; (7) Draupadī warned Jayadratha that
if he tried to abduct her, Kekayas and
Vṛṣṇi warriors would chase him to rescue
her (केकयाश् चापी सर्वे। … मम … पदवीं
चरेयुः) 3. 252. 16; but according to 11.
22. 12 Kekayas were Jayadratha's compa-
nions (यदा कृष्णाम् उपादाय प्राद्रवत्
केकयैः सह): (8) Drupada asked
Yudhiṣṭhira to send messengers to Keka-
yas to seek their support 5. 4. 8; (9) The
five Kekaya brothers joined Duryodhana
with the army of one अक्षौहिणी (केकयाश्
च … सोदर्याः पञ्च … । … कौरव्यम्
अक्षौहिण्या समाद्रवन्) 5. 19. 25; Keka-
yas were among those who were brought
together by Duryodhana to fight with the
Pāṇḍavas (ये राजानः पाण्डवायोधनाय
समानीता धार्तराष्ट्रेण … केकयाश् च) 5.
30. 23; Dhṛtarāṣṭra was able to win over
half of the Kekayas (अर्धं मे केकया
लब्धाः) 7. 23. 7 (also see the next);
(10) The five Kekaya brothers, driven
out from the Kekaya country, joined the
Pāṇḍavas anxious to get back the king-
dom of the Kekayas (अवरुद्धा बलिनो
केकयेभ्यो महेष्वासो भ्रातरः सन्ति
पञ्च।केकयेभ्यो राज्यम् आकाङ्क्षमाणा
युद्धार्थिनस् चानुवसन्ति पार्थान्) 5.
22. 19 (Nī. on 5. 22. 20: केकयेभ्यो
देशेभ्यः।अवरुद्धाः बहिर् निःसा-
रिताः। … पूर्वम् अस्मदीया अपि संप्रति
पाण्डवान् अनुवसन्ति अनुसरन्ति); 5. 49. 7,
35; 5. 52. 2; they do not respect Dhṛta-
rāṣṭra 5. 53. 17; 5. 54. 3; 5. 139. 26; 5. 142.
3; Dhṛtarāṣṭra considered the presence of
the Kekayas on the side of the Pāṇḍavas
a great asset to them (केकयाश् चैव
 … क एताञ् जातु युध्येत) 7. 61. 39, 41;
since Kekayas were divided, one Kekaya
brother was killed by his own brother
fighting from the opposite side (केकयेनैव
विक्रम्य भ्रात्रा भ्राता निपातितः) 8. 4.
69; (11) When Duryodhana would see
the Kekayas rushing against him, he would
repent the war 5. 47. 23; but Duryodhana
assured Dhṛtarāṣṭra that he would defect
them 5. 60. 25; (12) Kekayas were among
those who followed Kṛṣṇa some distance
when he started for Hāstinapura 5. 81. 32;
(13) When Yudhiṣṭhira started for Kuru-
kṣetra, Kekayas followed him 5. 149. 58;
5. 150. 2; (14) Kekayas (on the side of
the Kauravas), led by Droṇa, ready to
march against Pāṇḍavas (केकया … ।प्रय-
युः सर्व एवैते भारद्वाजपुरोगमाः) 5.
196. 5; (15) Mentioned among the twelve
Janapadas who protected Bhīṣma with
their force of chariot-riders (केकयास्
तथा। … द्वादशैते जनपदाः … ।महता
रथवंशेन तेऽभ्यरक्षन् पितामहम्॥)
6. 18. 13-14; (16) Arjuna expected
Kekayas to act only as spectators when
Bhīma would fight with his गदा (केकया
 … एते तिष्ठन्ति … प्रेक्षकास् … ) 6. 19. 14;
(17) On the first day of the war, the five
Kekaya brothers with their armies fought
with five Gāndhāras and their armies 6.
43. 73; they rushed to protect Abhimanyu
6. 45. 30; Bhīṣma felled them with his
arrows (केकयांश् च … ।भीष्मः … पात-
याम् आस मार्गणैः) 6. 45. 54; (18)
On the second day of the war, Virāṭa,
supported by Kekayas, guarded the rear of
the Krauñcavyūha of Pāṇḍavas 6. 46
54; Bhīṣma, protected by Kekayas (those
on the side of the Kauravas) and other
warriors, opposed Arjuna (गुप्तः प्राच्य-
सौवी रकेकयैः) 6. 48. 21; (19) On the
third day of the war, Kaikeyas (Kauravas'
side) stood at the head of the Garuḍavyūha
of the Kauravas (शीर्षम् आस्तां … । …
मत्स्यकैकेयैर् … ) 6. 52. 4; (20) On the
same day Kekayas stood behind Yudhi-
ṣṭhira in the middle of the Ardhacandra-
vyūha of the Pāṇḍavas 6. 52. 16; (21)
The chief Kekayas (मुख्याः) (Kaura-
vas' side), Trigartas and Madras, totalling
thirty-five thousand, surrounded Arjuna
and Abhimanyu as ordered by Duryo-
dhana (सह केकयैः पञ्चत्रिंशतिसाह-
स्रास् तव पुत्रेण चोदिताः) 6. 57. 12-13;
Dhṛṣṭadyumna, with his army, marched
against them 6. 57. 16; (22) Sātyaki,
Cekitāna and Abhimanyu engaged Śālvas
and Kekayas 6. 68. 8; (23) Matsyas and
Kekayas encircled Arjuna 6. 70. 33; (24)
On the sixth day of the war, the five
Kekaya brothers stood on the left side of
the Makaravyūha of the Pāṇḍavas (वामं
पार्श्वं समाश्रिताः); when Droṇa and
Bhīṣma started killing Sṛñjayas and Keka-
yas they began to flee 6. 71. 19, 32; at mid-
day, Kekayas, Draupadī's sons, and Dhṛṣṭa-
ketu, led by Abhimanyu, formed the Sūci-
mukhavyūha and broke the chariot-army
of the Kauravas (रथानीकं बिभिदुह्) 6.
73. 54-55; they fought with Dhṛtarāṣṭra's
eight sons 6. 75. 21; Duḥśāsana fought a
wonderful battle with the five Kekaya
brothers (तद् अद्भुतम् इवाभवत्) 6. 74.
25; the five Kekaya brothers rushed to help
Śatānīka; five Dhṛtarāṣṭra's sons, Dur-
mukha and others, attacked the advancing
Kekaya brothers 6. 75. 50, 52; (25) On
the same day, Bhagadatta, along with
Madras, Sauvīras and Kekayas stood at
the chest (उरस्य् अभून् … ) of the Krauñcas
vyūha of the Kauravas 6. 71. 18; (26) On
the eighth day of the war, Kekayas, Abhi-
manyu and others surrounded the Supra-
tīka elephant of Bhagadatta 6. 91. 39-40;
Bhagadatta pierced the (five) Kekayas
with five नाराच arrows; that was a fierce
battle (तुमुलं युद्धम्) of Bhagadatta
with Pāñcālas, Sṛñjayas, and Kekayas 6.
91. 67, 80; (27) On the tenth day of the
war, Ambaṣṭhas, Kekayas and others,
instigated by Duryodhana, attacked Arjuna;
he burnt them with his missiles; then they
did not return 6. 112. 110, 112, 114; Keka-
yas (Kauravas' side) mentioned among
the twelve Janapadas who, although affli-
cted with arrows and pained by wounds,
did not abandon Bhīṣma fighting with
Arjuna ( … केकयैः सह।द्वादशैते
जनपदाः शरार्ता व्रणपीदिताः।संग्रामे
न जहुर् भीष्मम्) 6. 114. 77; (28)
Eleventh day: Kekayas mentioned among
those who did many valorous acts and
checked the army of Droṇa 7. 7. 4, 6-7;
Droṇa bruised the five principal warriors
(brothers) of Kekayas with arrows (स
केकयानां प्रवरांश् च पञ्च … शरैः
प्रमृद्य) 7. 7. 24; (द्रोणेन निहताः
शूराः शेरते … । … सर्वे भ्रातरः पञ्च
केकयाः॥) 11. 25. 13; (29) Dhṛtarāṣṭra
felt that Droṇa must have been encircled
and confused by Kekayas and others when
Dhṛṣṭadyumna killed him 7. 8. 27-28; he
wanted Saṃjaya to tell him who checked
the five Kekaya brothers when they advanc-
ed towards Droṇa 7. 9. 52; (30) Kekayas
mentioned among those who rushed to
rescue the sons of Draupadī when they
were attacked by Aśvatthāman 7. 15. 11;
Kekayas among those who checked Droṇa
advancing towards Yudhiṣṭhira 7. 15. 32;
(31) On the 12th day, Kekayas (on
Kauravas' side) stood at the neck of
the Suparṇavyūha (ग्रीवायां … मद्र-
केकयाः) 7. 19. 8; (32) Kekayas (on
Pāṇḍavas' side) attacked Droṇa when they
saw Yudhiṣṭhira running away from him;
Droṇa scattered them away and defeated
them again and again 7. 20. 18-19, 23;
when a Pāñcāla prince was killed by Droṇa
(7. 20. 48), angered Pāñcālas, Kekayas
and others rushed at him shouting ‘kill
Droṇa, kill Droṇa’; Droṇa agitated them
all (व्यक्षोभयत्); when they were getting
killed by Droṇa they trembled (समकम्-
पन्त) 7. 20. 49, 53; Duryodhana delighted
to see Pāñcālas, Kekayas and others put
to flight by Droṇa's arrows (द्रोणसाय-
कैह् प्रणुन्नान्) 7. 21. 7; (33) Karṇa
told Duryodhana that Kekayas and other
warriors would rally round Bhīma espe-
cially when instigated by him (विशेषतश्
च भीमेन … अभिचोदिताः) 7. 21. 23-24;
in the battle that followed, Kekayas follow-
ed Virāṭa; the five Kekaya brothers rode
in chariots drawn by firefly-coloured
horses and carrying red-coloured banners 7.
22. 8, 11; (34) There was extremely
tumultuous fighting (उत्पिञ्जलकं यु-
द्धम्) between Matsyas and Kekayas
(Kauravas' side) in which the horse-
riders, chariot-fighters and elephant-riders
were not afraid (अभीताश्वरथद्विपम्)
7. 24. 21 (Nī. on Bom. Ed. 7. 25. 31:
उत्पिञ्जजलकम् अत्यन्ताकुलम्); (35)
Karṇa tried to halt the march of five
Kekaya brothers towards Droṇa; angered,
they showered arrows on him; Karṇa
repeatedly covered them with arrows;
neither Karṇa nor they could be seen as
they were covered with arrows 7. 24. 40-
42; (36) On the thirteenth day, Kekayas
and others attacked Droṇa 7. 34. 5; Bhīma
assured Abhimanyu that he, along with
Kekayas and others, would follow him in
his attempt to make an opening in the
Cakravyūha 7. 34. 22; Kekayas mentioned
among those who raised a loud roar (केक-
याश् चैव सिंहनादम् अथानदन्) seeing
Abhimanyu compelling Duḥśāsana to sit
down in his chariot; they advanced to-
wards Droṇa's army to get through it
7. 39. 13, 17; (37) The day Abhimanyu
was killed, great sound which used to be
heard in the evenings issuing from the
houses of Kekayas (on Kauravas' side)
could not be heard by Dhṛtarāṣṭra (शिबिरे
यो महाध्वनिः।श्रूयते सो ऽद्य न
तथा केकयानां च वेश्मसु) 7. 61. 16;
(38) On the fourteenth day, Droṇa repul-
sed the attack on him by Pāñcālas and
Kekayas 7. 70. 13; Duryodhana pierced
Kekayas with sharp arrows 7. 128. 23;
(39) During the night war, Kekayas men-
tioned among those who fought with
Droṇa 7. 129. 7; Droṇa killed Kekaya
warriors with swift arrows 7. 130. 12; when
Bhīma killed Durmada and Duṣkarṇa
(Dhṛtarāṣṭra's sons), Kekayas and others
applauded him 7. 130. 38; Duryodhana
pointed out to Karṇa that the Kaurava army
was surrounded by Pāñcālas, Matsyas and
Kekayas 7. 133. 3; Karṇa assured him that
he would kill all of them including Keka-
yas (केकयान् … शकलीकृत्य) 7. 133. 11;
Duryodhana wanted Aśvatthāman to check
Kekayas before they, protected by Arjuna,
destroyed his army 7. 134. 8; Aśvatthāman
assured him that he would fight with the
Kekayas and the rest 7. 135. 10; he challeng-
ed Kaikeyas and others and asked them to
remain steady and show their skill in the
use of the missiles (ततो ऽब्रवीत् स कैकेयान्
पाञ्चालान् गौतमीसुतः। … स्थिरीभूताश् च
युध्यध्वं दर्शयन्तो ऽस्त्रलाघवम्) 7.
135. 16; thus challenged, they showered
arrows on Aśvatthāman, but were killed
by him 7. 135. 17-18; Kekayas and others
rushed towards Droṇa and made all attem-
pts to kill him (सर्वोद्योगेन) 7. 141. 60;
Yudhiṣṭhira wanted Sātyaki and Kekayas
to attack Droṇa with great speed (अभि-
द्रवन्तु वेगेन) 7. 159. 6; Droṇa defeat-
ed Kekayas and killed them 7. 161. 32,
35; (40) On the fifteenth day, Droṇa
killed many Kekayas and others with his
ब्रह्मास्त्र 7. 165. 100-101; after the fall of
Droṇa, Aśvatthāman assured Duryodhana
that he would put to flight (विद्रावयिष्यामि)
Kekayas and others with his नारायणास्त्र
7. 166. 52; (41) After the death of Droṇa,
Karṇa fought bravely to kill Kekayas 8. 2.
18; (42) Kekayas (Kauravas' side) listed
by Saṃjaya among those killed by Arjuna 8.
4. 45; (43) On the sixteenth day, Kekayas
helping Bhīma riding on an elephant rush-
ed against the army of the Kauravas 8. 8.
19; (44) When Anuvinda was killed, (the
hearts of) Kekayas (on Kauravas' side)
were dried up (शोषयन् केकयान् सर्वान्)
8. 9. 21; Sātyaki dissipated the large
army of Kekayas 8. 9. 34; (45) Kekayas
mentioned among those who showered
various weapons on Karṇa (नानाशस्त्रैर्
अवाकिरन्) 8. 21. 26-27; (46) On the
seventeenth day, Duryodhana, protected
by Kekayas and Madras, stood at the rear
of the Vyūha of the Kauravas 8. 31. 21;
Kṛpa, Kṛtavarman and Śakuni fought with
Kekayas 8. 32. 16-17; (47) Kekayas were
among those who attacked Karṇa to kill
him 8. 32. 43; they checked the advance of
Karṇa towards Yudhiṣṭhira 8. 33. 9; they
checked Vasuṣeṇa 8. 33. 22; Karṇa check-
ed the onward march of Bhīmasena, Keka-
yas and Sṛñjayas towards Kṛpa 8. 38. 16;
8. 40. 1; when Bhīma left, Karṇa killed
Kekayas by thousands 8. 40. 4; (48)
Bhīmasena fought with Kurus, Madras and
Kekayas (Kauravas' side) 8. 40. 69; (49)
Kekayas and others, protected by Arjuna,
destroyed Kauravas' army 8. 51. 6; (50)
Bhīṣma reported to have killed Kekayas and
others warriors along with their kings 8.
51. 27; (पृथिवी पालांश् चेदिपान्चालकेक-
यान्) 8. 51. 32; (51) On the eighteenth
day, Duryodhana checked the advance of
Kekayas and others 9. 20. 34; (52) Keka-
yas accompanied Jayadratha when he tried
to abduct Draupadī (यदा कृष्णाम् उपादाय
प्राद्रवत् केकयैः सह) 11. 22. 12; (53)
At the instance of Yudhiṣṭhira, Sudhar-
man (Duryodhana's Purohita), Dhaumya
and others cremated the dead bodies of
Kekayas and other fallen heroes (केक-
यांश् च … । … पावकैः समदाहयन्) 11.
26. 36, 38 (Nī. on Bom. Ed. 11. 26. 24:
सुधर्माणम् दुर्योधनपुरोहितम्).
D.
Other events: (1) A certain king of Keka-
yas doing स्वाध्याय and observing rigid
vows in a forest was possessed by a dread-
ful Rakṣas (केकयानाम् अधिपतिं रक्षो
जग्राह दारुणम्) 12. 78. 7; (2) Śatayūpa
was once a great king of the Kekayas (स
हि राजा महान् आसीत् केकयेषु परंतपः)
15. 25. 10.
E. Use in a title: Certain
princes (probably the well known five
Kekaya brothers) referred to as ‘princes
of the Kekayas’ (केकयराजपुत्राः) 3.
48. 38.

केकरक
Kekaraka m. (pl.): Name of a Jana-
pada.
Listed by Saṃjaya among the southern
Janapadas (also called Deśas 6. 10. 68) of
the Bhāratavarṣa (अथापरे जनपदा
दक्षिणा भरतर्षभ) 6. 10. 56, 5; (त्र्यङ्-
गाः केकरकाः) 6. 10. 60.

केतुमाल
Ketumāla m.: Name of Dvīpa.
A. Location: One of the four Dvīpas
on the four sides of mountain Meru (तस्य
पार्श्वे त्व् इमे द्वीपाश् चत्वारः … । भद्रा-
श्वः केतुमालश् च) 6. 7. 11; to the west
of Meru (मेरोस् तु पश्चिमे पार्श्वे केतु-
मालो महीपते) 6. 7. 29.
B. Characteri-
stics: (1) A large Jambūṣaṇḍa, beautiful
like Nandana, is located there 6. 7. 29;
see Vol. I. p. 356); (2) People live there
for ten thousand years; men have golden
complexion, women are like Apsaras; they
are free from sickness and grief, and are
always of delightful disposition; all have
lustre like that of heated gold (अनामया
वीतशोका नित्यं मुदितमानसाः।जायन्ते
मानवास् तत्र निष्टप्तकनकप्रभाः) 6.
7. 30-31.

केरल
Kerala m. (pl.): Name of a Janapada
and its people.
A. Location: Included by Saṃjaya
among the southern Janapadas (also call-
ed Deśas 6. 10. 68) of the Bhāratavarṣa
(अथापरे जनपदा दक्षिणा भरतर्षभ)
6. 10. 56, 5; (द्रविडाः केरलाः) 6. 10. 57;
Sahadeva subjugated them in his expedi-
tion to the south (प्रययौ दक्षिणां
दिशम्) 2. 28. 1; (दक्षिणाभिमुखो ययौ)
2. 28. 8; (दक्षिणां दिशम्) 2. 28. 37; lay
along the coast (ततः समुद्रतीरेण …
पुण्ड्रान् सकेरलान्) 14. 83. 29.
B.
Description of the people: Of pleasing
appearance (प्रियदर्शन), having long-
arms (दीर्घभुज), broad-chest (व्यूढो-
रस्क), red teeth (रक्तदन्त), tall (प्रा-
ंशु) 8. 8. 15; they had long hair (दीर्घ-
केश), wore chaplets (आपीडिन्), they put
on garments of different colours (नाना-
विरागवसन), and smeared their bodies
with fragrant powder (गन्धचूर्णावचूर्-
णित) 8. 8. 16 (Nī. on Bom. Ed. 8. 12.
16: आपीडिनः भूषावन्तः नाना पृथक्
विविधरागाणि वसनानि येषां ते); equipped
with swords (बद्धासि), holding nooses
in hand (पाशहस्त), they were capable
of forcing back the (enemy's) elephants
(वारणप्रतिवारण) 8. 8. 17; they liked
battles (प्रियाहव), carried bows and
quivers filled with arrows (चापहस्त,
कलापिन्), fought on foot (पत्ति) 8. 8. 18;
their valour was like that of elephants in
rut (मत्तमातङ्गविक्रम) 8. 8. 16 and
fierce (घोररूपपराक्रम) 8. 8. 18; they
were ready to die with their comrades-in-
arms (समानमृत्यवो राजन्न् अनीकस्थाः
परस्परम्) 8. 8. 17.
C. Epic events:
(1) Sahadeva, in his expedition to the
south before the Rājasūya, subjugated
them just by sending envoys and made
them pay tribute 2. 28. 47-48; (2) They
were hired for war by Pāṇḍavas by paying
them large sums (भृता वित्तेन महता
 … ओड्राः सकेरलाः) 8. 8. 15; (3) After
defeating Meghasaṃdhi in Magadha,
Arjuna, with the Aśvamedha horse, went
along the coast to the Vaṅga, Puṇḍra and
Kerala countries (ततः समुद्रतीरेण
वङ्गान् पुण्ड्रान् सकेरलान्) 14. 83. 29.

कैकय
Kaikaya, Kaikeya: See Kekaya.

कैशिक
Kaiśika m. (pl.): Name of a people.
Caturyu (Jarāsandha ? cf. 2. 13. 8)
conquered them along with Pāṇḍyas and
Krathakas by the power of his knowledge
(in the use of missiles ?) (चतुर्युः स
महाराज … विद्याबलाद् यो व्यजयत् पाण्ड्य-
क्रथककैशिकान्) 2. 13. 20.

कोकनद
Kokanada m. (pl.): Name of a people.
They probably lived in Punjab; chara-
cterized as क्षत्रियस्; mentioned along
with the Trigartas; Arjuna defeated them
in his expedition to the north (प्रययाव्
उत्तरां दिशम् 2. 24. 1; 2. 23. 9) before
the Rājasūya (ततस् त्रिगर्तान् कौन्तेयो
दार्वान् कोकनदाश् च ये।क्षत्रिया बहवो
राजन्) 2. 24. 17.

कोङ्कण
Koṅkaṇa m. (pl.): Name of a Jana-
pada.
Listed by Saṃjaya among the southern
Janapadas (also called Deśas 6. 10. 68)
of the Bhāratavarṣa (अथापरे जनपदा
दक्षिणा … ) 6. 10. 56, 5; (कोङ्कणा माल-
वाणकाः) 6. 10. 58, 5.

कोपन
Kopana m. (pl.): Name of a Janapada.
Listed by Saṃjaya among the southern
Janapadas (also called Deśas 6. 10. 68)
of the Bhāratavarṣa (अथापरे जनपदा
दक्षिणा … ) 6. 10. 56, 5; (समङ्गाः कोप-
नाश् चैव) 6. 10. 59.

कोल्लगिर
Kollagira m. (pl.): Name of a degra-
ded Kṣatriya tribe.
Mentioned among those Kṣatriyas who
lost their upper caste and became low
owing to their not respecting Brāhmaṇas
(कोल्लगिरास् तथा। … तास् ताः क्षत्रियजात-
यः।वृषलत्वम् अनुप्राप्ता ब्राह्मणानाम्
अदर्शनात्) 13. 35. 17-18 [see the next].

कोल्लगिरेय
Kollagireya m. (pl.): Tribes living on
Kollagiri in the south.
Living near the southern ocean (प्र-
ययौ … दक्षिणं सलिलार्णवम्) 14. 84.
10; Arjuna fought with them while he
accompanied the horse of the Aśvamedha
14. 84. 11 [Identical with the preceding ?
See Kollagirī Vol. I, p. 319].

कोशल
Kośala: See Kosala.

कोसल
Kosala m. (pl.): Name of a country
and its people; the name is found twice
as Kośala (2. 13. 26; 8. 17. 3) and once
as Kosalā (f.) (9. 37. 22 कोसलाभागे).
A. Location: Distinguished as eastern
and southern Kosalas; the eastern Kośalas
formed part of the Kuntī country (पूर्वाः
कुन्तिषु कोशलाः) 2. 13. 26; in the east,
beyond the river Sarayū; beyond Kosala
lay Mithilā and the rivers Mālā and Car-
maṇvatī 2. 18. 28 (see Epic events no. 3
below); in the south, beyond the Kosalas
lay the region called Dakṣiṇāpatha (अतः
परं च देशो ऽयं दक्षिणे दक्षिणापथः)
3. 58. 22 (see Past events no. 1 below); its
capital town Ayodhyā (see
B. 2 below).
B.
Designation of certain kings after Kosala:
(1) Bṛhadbala called कोसलाधिपति 2. 27.
1; 8. 4. 21; 11. 25. 10; कोसलानाम् अधिपः
7. 46. 20; कोसलराज 7. 46. 21; कोसला-
नाम् भर्ता 7. 46. 22; Sukṣatra's father
(Bṛhadbala ?) called कोसलाधिपति 7. 22. 47;
(2) Ṛtuparṇa, king of Ayodhyā, called
कोसलाधिप 3. 71. 23; (3) Kṣemadarśin
called कोसलानाम् अधिपतिः (कोसलानाम्
आधिपत्यं संप्राप्ते क्षेमदर्शिनि) 12.
83. 6.
C. Description: (1) Holy (उत्तरे
कोसलभागे पुण्ये) 9. 37. 22; (2) Their
warriors: Brave (शूर) 8. 8. 19 and heroic
(वीर) 8. 33. 22; (शूरवीर) 8. 32. 17;
skilled in battles while riding elephants
(कोशला … गजयुद्धेषु कुशलाः) 8. 17. 3.
D. Characterization: Kosalas were counted
among those who knew the eternal धर्म
(कोसला … धर्मं जानन्ति शाश्वतम्) 8.
30. 60-61; they comprehended a thing
as soon as they saw it (प्रेक्षितज्ञाश्
च कोसलाः) 8. 30. 79.
E. Epic events:
(1) Bhīṣma defeated all Māgadhas, Kāśis
and Kosalas and brought two maidens for
Vicitravīrya 13. 44. 37; (2) Kośalas, along
with many other peoples, resorted to the
west as they were afraid of Jarāsandha 2.
13. 26-28; (3) Bhīma, Arjuna and Kṛṣṇa,
while going to the Magadha country, had
to cross the river Sarayū before they could
reach the eastern Kosala (संतीर्य सर-
यूं रम्यां दृष्ट्वा पूर्वांश् च कोसलान्।
अतीत्य जग्मुर् मिथिलां मालां चर्मण्व-
तीम् नदीम्॥) 2. 18. 28; (4) Kṛṣṇa once
defeated them 7. 10. 15; (5) Karṇa also
had once defeated them 8. 5. 19; (6) Some
of the Kosalas sided with the Kauravas
(and others with the Pāṇḍavas) (अर्धं
मे केकया लब्धाः काशिकाः कोसलाश् च ये)
7. 23. 7; (7) On the second day of war,
Kosalas and others, led by Duryodhana,
guarded the army of Śakuni 6. 47. 15-16;
(8) On the twelfth day of war, Kosalas, on
the side of the Pāṇḍavas, attacked Droṇa
when they saw Yudhiṣṭhira retreating from
Droṇa; he scattered their army 7. 20. 18-19;
(9) On the sixteenth day of war, they rush-
ed at the Kaurava army; their chariot-
fighters, elephant-riders, and excellent foot
soldiers, who were delighted, danced mak-
ing various sounds and laughed (नाना-
विधरवैर् हृष्ता नृत्यन्ति च हसन्ति च)
8. 8. 19-20; Bhīma, seated on an elephant
was in the midst of their army 8. 8. 21;
(10) On the same day, Kośalas (on the
side of the Kauravas), skilled in elephant
battles, attacked Dhṛṣṭadyumna to kill
him; they showered arrows, तोमरस् and
नाराचस् (कोशला … गजयुद्धेषु कुशलाः)
8. 17. 3-4; (11) On the seventeenth day
of war, Kṛpa, Kṛtavarman and Śakuni
fought with Kosalas (on the side of the
Pāṇḍavas) and killed many of them 8. 32.
17-18; (12) On the same day, Kosalas,
along with other warriors, checked the
advance of Vasuṣeṇa 8. 33. 22; (13) On
the same day, Arjuna killed many Kosalas
(on the side of the Kauravas) 8. 37. 2;
(14) Kosala country mentioned among
those reached by the Aśvamedha horse 14.
84. 4.
F. Past events: (1) Nala showed
to Damayantī the roads leading to Dakṣiṇā-
patha; one of them led to Kosala country
(एते गच्छन्ति बहवः पन्थानो दक्षिना-
पथम् … एष पन्था विदर्भाणाम् अयं
गच्छति कोसलान्।अतः परं च देशो ऽयं
दक्षिणे दक्षिणापथः॥) 3. 58. 20, 22;
(2) For the sacrifice of Auddālaka, per-
formed in the northern Kosalā, Sarasvatī
appeared as Manohradā (उत्तरे कोसला-
भागे … औद्दालकेन यजता … सरस्वती॥
आजगाम … मनोह्रदेति विख्याता) 9. 37.
22-23.

कोसला
Kosalā: See Kosala.

कौकुट्टक
Kaukuṭṭaka m. (pl.): Name of a
Janapada.
Listed by Saṃjaya among the southern
Janapadas (also called Deśas 6. 10. 68) of
the Bhāratavarṣa (अथापरे जनपदा
दक्षिणा … कौकुट्टकास् तथा चोलाः) 6. 10.
56, 58.

कौकुर
Kaukura m. (pl.); Name of a people.
(1) Characteristics: They are mention-
ed among those who acted on Kṛṣṇa's
advice and subdued their enemies to gladden
their friends (कौकुराः सृञ्जयाश् च।उपा-
सीना वासुदेवस्य बुद्धिं निगृह्य शत्रून्
सुहृदो नन्दयन्ति) 5. 28. 11; (2) Epic
events: At the time of Rājasūya, they lived
in Yudhiṣṭhira's house like docile slaves
(आवर्जिता इवाभान्ति निघ्नाश् चैत्रकिकौ-
कुराः) 2. 46. 21 (Nī. on Bom. Ed. 2. 50. 20;
आवर्जिताः दासवद् वशगाः); the Kṣatriyas
among them brought wealth in hundreds
for Yudhiṣṭhira's Rājasūya (कौकुरास् …
आहार्षुः क्षत्रिया वित्तं शतशो ऽजातश-
त्रवे) 2. 48. 14-16.

कौमार
Kaumāra m. (pl.): Name of a Varṣa.
It is related to the mountain Raivata-
(ka) (6. 12. 16) in the Śākadvīpa (वर्षाणि
तेषु कौरव्य … रैवतस्य तु कौमारः)
6. 12. 22, 24.

कौरव
Kaurava, Kauraveya, Kauravya (pl.):
Name of a people; like the word Kuru,
these words also have various significances
(the choice of the word depending on
metrical requirements).
A. People of the Kuru country:
Duryodhana, the king of the Kauravas
(कौरवाणाम् अधिपः) 6. 55. 106; Yudhi-
ṣṭhira, the king of the Kauravas (स राजा
 … कौरवाणाम्) 5. 32. 9; he was the pro-
tector and the ruler of Kaurava people 5.
147. 31; Karṇa, while praising the people of
certain countries as opposed to the Bāhlī-
kas, said that Kauraveyas were the reli-
gion incarnate (i. e. they practised धर्म
scrupulously) (कौरवेयाः स्वधर्मः)
8. 30. 73 (Nī. on Bom. Ed. 8. 45. 28
reads कौरवेयास् तु धर्म्यम् which he
explains as धर्म्यं धर्माद् अनपेतं
कर्म मानयन्तीति शेषः).
B. Those
born in the lineage of Kuru and living at
Hāstinapura; the term may occasionally
include also those like Droṇa, Kṛpa and
others not born in Kuru's line but who
sided with Dhārtarāṣṭras; the term may also
refer not only to the sons of Dhṛtarāṣṭra
but also the sons of Pāṇḍu; occasionally
the word कौरववंश or कौरव वंश
is used instead of simple कौरव: All
Kauravyas sat near the sages who brought
with them Kuntī and the five Pāṇḍavas 1.
117. 16; Kauravas and others delighted to
hear the arrival of the Pāṇḍavas 1. 1. 73;
the sage (Vyāsa) composed in the ninth
पर्वन् three thousand two hundred and
twenty stanzas to describe the events of
the famous Kauravas (कौरवाणां यशोभृ-
ताम्) 1. 2. 177; Parikṣit was born in the
lineage of the Kauravas (कौरववंश-
भृत्) 1. 36. 8; Śakuni took his sister to
the Kauravas 1. 103. 14; Pāṇḍu described
as the bearer of the fame of the Kaura-
vas; he procured for them fame and
kingdom (कौरवाणां यशोभृता) 1. 105.
8; (पाण्डुनावर्जितं राज्यं कौरवाणां
यशस् तथा) 7. 62. 15; Bhīṣma and other
Kauravas did not see the end of the
riches brought by Pāṇḍu 1. 105. 24;
Bhīṣma, Vidura and other Kauravas
grieved at the funeral of Pāṇḍu and Mādrī
1. 118. 26; Droṇa accepted Kauravas (i. e.
also the Pāṇḍavas) as his pupils 1. 122.
40; Dhṛtarāṣṭra told Duryodhana that they
(i. e. Dhṛtarāṣṭra himself and his sons) and
the Pāṇḍavas were the same to Kauraveyas
(i. e. to Bhīṣma and other Kauraveyas); if
they acted contrary to the wishes of the
Kauraveyas they may be killed by them
(समा हि कौरवेयाणां वयम् एते च … ।
 … ते वयं कौरवेयाणां … कथं न
वध्यतां तात गच्छेम) 1. 130. 14, 15;
Vidura gave to Drupada and others gifts
given to them by Kauravas (यथा दत्तानि
कौरवैः) 1. 198. 13; Bhīṣma and all other
Kauravas enquired through Vidura about
the well-being of Drupada in all respects
1. 198. 17; Dhṛtarāṣṭra asked Kauravas to
receive the sons of Pāṇḍu 1. 199. 12; Arjuna
was one who brought fame to Kauravas (in-
cludes the Pāṇḍavas) (कौरवाणां यशस्-
करम्) 1. 206. 1; Balarāma willing to
kill all Kauravas (includes the Pāṇḍavas)
(अद्य निष्कौरवाम् एकः करिष्यामि वसुन्-
धराम्) 1. 212. 31; Bhīṣma was the leader
of the Kauravas (includes Pāṇḍavas) 2.
38. 3; Kauravas delighted to see Pāṇḍavas
in Hāstinapura 2. 52. 30; asking Draupadī
to come to the Sabhā meant that the
doom of the Kauravas was imminent
(मन्ये प्राप्तः संक्षयः कौरवाणाम्)
2. 60. 12; forcing virtuous women to
appear in the Sabhā meant that the Kaura-
veyas were acting against their ancient,
eternal धर्म (स नष्टः कौरवेयेषु
पूर्वो धर्मः सनातनः) 2. 62. 9;
Duḥśāsana defiled the good name of
Kauravas (कौरवाणां यशोहरः) 2. 62.
12; Vidura was impartial, hence was respe-
cted by the Kauravas (includes Pāṇḍavas)
(समश् च त्वं संमतः कौरवाणां)
3. 5. 2; Vidura spoke what was proper for
Kauravas (यत् क्षमं कौरवाणाम्) 3. 6.
13; destruction of Kauravas was certain
3. 6. 16; Vyāsa wanted to tell what was
beneficial to the Kauravas 3. 9. 1; if
Kauravyas wished to remain alive (कौर-
व्याञ् जीवमानान्) conciliation with the
Pāṇḍavas was necessary 3. 10. 23; Kṛṣṇa
would have come to Hāstinapura at the
time of the game of dice even if not in-
vited by the Kauravas 3. 14. 2; Dhṛta-
rāṣṭra surrounded by all Kauravas 3.
242. 19; Duryodhana expressed his desire
to the Kauravas to perform Rājasūya
3. 243. 14; Dhṛtarāṣṭra was the central
figure among Kauravas (including Pāṇḍa-
vas) (मेढीभूतः कौरवाणाम्) 5. 36.
71; Kṛṣṇa to approach the Kauravas for
peace 5. 70. 89; Kṛṣṇa to find out the view
of the Kauravas towards war 5. 71. 33; 9.
62. 2; Kṛṣṇa did not deserve to be arrest-
ed by the Kauraveyas 5. 86. 18; Kṛṣṇa
dismissed Kauravas 5. 89. 37; Kṛṣṇa advis-
ed Duryodhana to see that the Kauravas
were not destroyed without any one to
survive and that the (Kaurava) family
did not perish (अस्तु शेषं कौरवाणां
मा पराभूद् इदं कुलम्) 5. 122. 58;
bad omens for Kauravas 5. 141. 18; Kaura-
vas destined to be destroyed 5. 144. 24;
Bhīṣma carried forward the line of the
Kauravas (कौरवं वंशम् उद्वहन्) 5.
145. 32; Bhīṣma had saved the race of the
Kauravas which had (almost) perished
(प्रनष्टः कौरवो वंशस् त्वयायं पुनर्
उद्धृतः) 5. 146. 18; Arjuna born in the
