कौशिक
Kauśika: See Kuśika.

कौशिज
Kauśija m. (pl.): Name of Janapada.
Listed by Saṃjaya among the northern
Janapadas (also called Deśas 6. 10. 68)
of the Bhāratavarṣa (पाञ्चालाः कौशिजाश्
चैव) 6. 10. 40, 37, 5.

क्रथक
Krathaka m.: Name of a people.
Caturyu (Jarāsandha ?) conquered
Pāṇḍyas, Krathakas and Kaiśikas on the
strength of his knowledge (in the use of
missiles ?) (चतुर्युः स महाराज भोज
इन्द्रसखो बली।विद्याबलाद् यो व्यजयत्
पाण्ड्यक्रथककैशिकान्) 2. 13. 20.

क्रौञ्चद्वीप
Krauñcadvīpa m.: Name of a द्वीप।
A. Location: It lay to the west of
the great mountain Meru (क्रौञ्चद्वीपो
 … अपरेण महामेरोर् … ) 12. 14. 22; the
great mountain Krauñca, full of jewels,
was in Krauñcadvīpa (क्रौञ्चद्वीपे महा-
क्रौञ्चो गिरी रत्नचयाकरः) 6. 13. 7, 17;
the Deśa of the Krauñcadvīpa was known
as Kuśala (क्रौञ्चस्य कुशलो देशो … ) 6.
13. 20.
B. Description: It resembled
Jambūdvīpa; and the Śākadvīpa which lay
to the east of Meru resembled Krauñcadvīpa
(जम्बूद्वीपेन सदृशः क्रौञ्चद्वीपो … ।
क्रौञ्चद्वीपेन सदृशः शाकद्वीपो … ) 12.
14. 22-23; the Deśas of all Dvīpas were
frequented by gods and Gandharvas (देव-
गन्धर्वसेविताः) 6. 13. 23; the people of
these Dvīpas got jewels of all sorts from
the Jambudvīpa; due to chastity, truthful-
ness and self-control of the twice-born,
health and longevity was doubled in each
next Dvīpa; all Dvīpas had only one
Janapada and one धर्म; god Prajāpati
himself protected the Dvīpas with his
raised दण्ड; he was their king, source of
their welfare, their father and grand-
father; he protected dull and learned alike;
people there always got their food cooked
by itself and ready to serve (विप्राणां
ब्रह्मचर्येण सत्येन च दमेन च।
आरोग्यायुःप्रमाणाभ्यां द्वीगुणं द्विगु-
णं ततः॥ … ईश्वरो दण्डम् उद्यम्य
स्वयम् एव प्रजापतिः।द्वीपान् एतान् महा-
राज रक्षंस् तिष्ठति नित्यदा॥स राजा स
शिवो राजन् स पिता स पितामहः। … भोजनं
चात्र कौरव्य प्रजाः स्वयम् उपस्थितम्।
सिद्धम् एव महाराज भुञ्जते तत्र
नित्यदा॥) 6. 13. 26-31.
C. Epic events:
(1) Dhṛtarāṣṭra asked Saṃjaya to des-
cribe to him the Krauñcadvīpa along with
the other द्वीपस् 6. 12. 3; (2) Draupadī
reminded Yudhiṣṭhira that he had once
caused Krauñcadvīpa to tremble (as also
theor the द्वीपस्) (दण्डेन मृदितस् त्वया)
12. 14. 22.

क्षुद्रक
Kṣudraka m. (pl.): Name of a people,
often mentioned along with Mālavas.
A. Description: Described as Kṣatri-
yas 2. 48. 16.
B. Epic events: (1) They
and Mālavas brought wealth in hundreds
for the Rājasūya of Yudhiṣṭhira 2. 48. 14;
(2) On the first day of war, Duryodhana,
along with Kṣudraka, Mālava and other
warriors, took position to protect the army
of Śakuni (क्षुद्रकमालवैः अभ्यरक्षत
 … सौबलेयस्य वाहिनीम्) 6. 47. 16; (3)
On the third day, they and Mālavas
attacked Arjuna at the instance of Bhīṣma
6. 55. 74; towards the end of the day, they
were killed by Arjuna which was looked
upon as a great feat not possible for any
other warrior (महत् कृतं कर्म ध-
नंजयेन कर्तुं यथा नार्हति कश्चिद्
अन्यः) 6. 55. 130; (4) On the eighth
day, they and Mālavas accompanied Droṇa
who followed Bhīṣma 6. 83. 7; (5) On
the fifteenth day, after the fall of Droṇa,
Aśvatthāman, along with twenty Kṣudra-
kas, rushed towards Dhṛṣṭadyumna 7. 171.
35; (6) Mentioned by Saṃjaya among
those on the side of the Kauravas who
were killed during the first fifteen days of
war 8. 4. 46.

खश
Khaśa m. (pl.): Name of a people
(identical with Khaśikas ?)
A. Location: They lived between
mountains Meru and Mandara under the
pleasant shade of bamboos and reeds along
the river Śailodā 2. 48. 2-3 (for citations see
Ekāśanājyoha).
B. Description: Describ-
ed as goat-faced (बस्तमुख) 7. 97. 39;
fierce and cruel (उग्राश् च क्रूरकर्मा-
णः) 8. 51. 18; wrathful, fond of battles,
strong and of firm fists (?) (संरम्भिणो
युद्धशौण्डा बलिनो दृब्धपाणयः) 8. 51.
19; they could not be conquered by any
one except by Arjuna (न शक्या युधिनिर्-
जेतुं त्वदन्येन परंतप) 8. 51. 20.
C.
Weapons: They fought with axes, spears
and stones (अयोहस्त, शूलहस्त, अश्म-
वृष्टिं समन्ततः … क्सिप्तां क्सिप्तां) 7.
97. 39; also with शक्तिस्, प्रासस्, and quivers
(i. e. arrows stored in तूणीरस्) 8. 15. 9.
D. Epic events: (1) Kings of Khaśas
brought as tribute for the Rājasūya heaps
of पिपीलिक gold, to be measured by
द्रोणस् (ते वै पिपीलिकं नाम … जात-
रूपं द्रोणमेयम् अहार्षुः) 2. 48. 3-4;
(2) Ulūka mentioned Khaśas among those
who had joined the army of Duryo-
dhana (राजचमूं समेताम्) 5. 158.
19-20; (3) On the fourteenth day of
war, Sātyaki repulsed with नाराच arrows
stones showered on him again and again
by Khaśas 7. 97. 39; (4) On the sixteenth
day, Pāṇḍya killed Khaśas and others
fighting on horse-backs, along with their
horses (अश्वारोहान् हयान् अपि) 8. 15. 9 [see
Khaśika].

खशिक
Khaśika m. (pl.): Name of a people
(identical with Khaśas ?)
Mentioned by Saṃjaya among the
northern Mlecchas of Bhāratavarṣa (उत्त-
राश् चापरे म्लेच्छा जना … खशिकाश् च
तुखाराश् च) 6. 10. 63, 66, 5 [See Khaśa].

गय
Gaya m. (pl.): Name of a country
and its people.
A. Location: To the east of Hāstina-
pura, beyond Matsya and Malaya coun-
tries (ययौ प्राचीं दिशं प्रति; ततः
प्राचीं दिशं भीमो ययौ) 2. 26. 1, 7;
(ततो मत्स्यान् … मलयांश् च … गयांश्
चैव) 2. 27. 8.
B. Description: The
country was rich in cattle (पशुभूमि)
and the people there were blameless
(अनवद्य) 2. 27. 8.
C. Epic events:
(1) Bhīma in his expedition to the east
before the Rājasūya conquered them 2.
27. 8; (2) Distinguished Kṣatriyas of
noble birth, who came for the Rājasūya
with their followers and with weapons
in hand, brought wealth by hundreds
(गयास् तथा।सुजातयः श्रेणिमन्तः
श्रेयांसः शस्त्रपाणयः।आहार्षुः क्ष-
त्रिया वित्तं शतशो ऽजातशत्रवे॥) 2. 48.
15-16.
D. Past event: Sarasvatī, when
invited at the time of the great sacrifice
of Gaya, appeared in the land of Gayas
and was known there as Viśālā (गयेष्व्
एव … आहूता सरस्वती॥विशालां तु गयेष्व्
आहुर् ऋषयः) 9. 37. 19-20.

गर्ग
Garga1 m. (pl.): Name of a people.
Mentioned by Dhṛtarāṣṭra among the
exploits of Kṛṣṇa who defeated them in
battle along with Vatsas and Karūṣas
(वत्सगर्गकरूषांश् च … अजयद् रणे) 7.
10. 15.

गर्ग
Garga2 m. (pl.): A class of sages
(born in the line of Garga).
Mentioned along with the great sages
Viśvāmitra and others (महर्षयः) who
appeared to Droṇa when he started fight-
ing fiercely after hearing the news of Aśva-
tthāman's death; they all told him that
it was time for him to lay down the weapon
since the hour of his death had arrived;
it did not behove Droṇa to do anything
which would be more cruel than what he
had already done (त एनम् अब्रुवन् सर्वे
द्रोणम् … समयो निधनस्य ते॥न्यस्या-
युधं रणे द्रोण … नातः क्रूरतरं
कर्म पुनः कर्तुं त्वम् अर्हसि॥) 7.
164. 88-90.

गान्धार
Gāndhāra, Gāndhāraka m. (pl.):
Name of a country and its people or its
warriors; warriors occasionally referred to
as Gāndhāraka (7. 6. 3, 7. 70. 42, 8. 27.
80); horses of the Gāndhāra country once
referred to as Gāndhāraka (9. 27. 43); the
country once referred to as Gāndhāradeśa
(2. 47. 8) and twice as Gāndhāraviṣaya
(14. 84. 18; 14. 86. 3).
A. Location: Listed by Saṃjaya
among the northern Janapadas (also called
Deśas 6. 10. 68) of the Bhāratavarṣa (अत
ऊर्ध्वं जनपदान् निबोध गदतो मम)
6. 10. 37, 5; (गान्धारा दर्शकास् तथा)
6. 10. 52; (उत्तरापथजन्मानः कीर्तयि-
ष्यामि तान् अपि।यौनकाम्बोजगान्धाराः)
12. 200. 40; the Aśvamedha horse went
to the Gāndhāraviṣaya from Pañcanada
(ततः पञ्चनदं ययौ॥तस्माद् अपि
स कौरव्य गान्धारविषयं हयः।
विचचार) 14. 84. 17-18.
B. Famous for
horses: Gāndhāra horses were offered as
tribute for the Rājasūya (हयान् गान्धर-
देशजान्) 2. 47. 8.
C. Characteristics
of the people and their warriors: (1)
People: Living on mountains (पार्वती-
यैः … गान्धारैः) 6. 20. 8; according
to Karṇa, there was no purity among
Gāndhārakas (नास्ति … शौचं गान्धार-
केषु च) 8. 27. 80; a Brāhmaṇa once
told the Kuru assembly that among the
Gāndhāras a family had only one Brāh-
maṇa, the rest were imprudent who
behaved as they liked (भवत्य् एकः कुले
विप्रः शिष्टान्ये कामचारिणः।गान्धारा
 … के ऽप्य् अचेतसः॥) 8. 30. 55; accor-
ding to Bhīṣma, Gāndhāras did not
believe in Bhūtapati as the अध्यक्ष of
the world; they were sinful; they wan-
dered over the earth and lived like dogs,
crows, बलस् (?) and vultures; they did
not exist in the कृतयुग, but were met
with since the त्रेतायुग; (निरध्यक्षांस्
तु … °गान्धाराः॥एते पापकृतस् तात
चरन्ति पृथिवीम् इमाम्।श्वकाकबल-
गृध्राणां सधर्माणो नराधिप॥न्लिते
कृतयुगे तात चरन्ति पृथिवीम् इमाम्।त्रेता-
प्रभृति वर्तन्ते ते जना भरतर्षभ॥)
12. 200. 38, 40-42; (2) Warriors: Great
chariot-fighters (महारथ), horseriders
(सादिन्), controlled (यत्त), using armours
(वर्मिन्) and fighting with lances which
were shaped like a claw and were polish-
ed (प्रासपाणि) 7. 63. 16, (नखरप्रास-
योधिन्) 12. 102. 3, (विमलप्रासयोधिन्)
7. 6. 3; they also used bows and arrows,
शक्तिस् and swords (चापशक्तिशरासि) 7.
70. 42; arrogant while fighting (युद्ध-
दुर्मद) 6. 86. 26; very strong (अतिबल)
8. 5. 18; very difficult to be conquered
(सुदुर्जय) 8. 57. 31; (दुर्जय) 8. 5. 18.
D. Epic events: (1) Kṛṣṇa once quickly
overpowered Gāndhāras and released the
captive king Sudarśanīya 5. 47. 69 (Nī. on
Bom. Ed. 5. 48. 75: सुदर्शनं नाम
राजानम्); (2) Bhīṣma reminded Karṇa
that he had formerly defeated Gāndhāras
and made them subservient to Duryo-
dhana (गान्धाराश् च जितास् त्वया … दुर्यो-
धनस्य वशगाः कृताः कर्ण त्वया
पुरा) 7. 4. 5-6; Karṇa had defeated
Gāndhāras, very strong and difficult to
win, and made them pay tribute (यो जित्वा
समरे वीरश् चक्रे बलिभृतः पुरा) 8. 5.
18, 20; 8. 57. 31 (a reference to Karṇa's
conquest of earth before the Vaiṣṇava
sacrifice of Duryodhana ? See 3. 241. 32
and Appendix I, No. 24, pp. 1078-1080);
(3) In the Sabhā of Kauravas, Śakuni
and his son were protected by Gāndhāras
5. 92. 49; (4) On the first day of war,
in the Kaurava व्यूह, Śakuni with his
Gāndhāra warriors, living on mountains,
offered protection to Duryodhana (पार्व-
तीयैः सार्धं गान्धारैः पाति) 6. 20. 8;
the same day, five Kekaya brothers fought
with five Gāndhāra warriors with their
respective armies (ससैन्यास् ते ससैन्यांश्
च) 6. 43. 73; (5) On the second day,
Gāndhāras and others protected Droṇa in
the Mahāvyūha (6. 47. 10) of Kauravas
6. 47. 14; (6) On the third day, the large
army of Gāndhāras, led by Śakuni, en-
gaged Sātyaki and Abhimanyu in a battle
6. 54. 6; (7) On the fifth day, the king
of Kaliṅgas (Śrutāyus) was surrounded by
Gāndhāras and others 6. 67. 13; (8) On
the eighth day, war-arrogant Gāndhāras
desirous of heaven or victory, broke the
front line of the army of Irāvant and
entered it (तदनीकं भित्त्वा … बलेन
महता युक्ताः स्वर्गाय विजयैषिणः।
विविशुस् ते तदा हृष्टा गान्धारा युद्धदुर्-
मदाः॥) 6. 86. 26; (9) On the eleventh
day, Śakuni with his excellent Gāndhā-
raka warriors riding on horsebacks, occu-
pied the extreme end (प्रपक्ष) of the
right side (दक्षिन पार्श्व 7. 6. 2) of the
Śakaṭavyūha (7. 6. 15) of Kauravas 7. 6.
3; (10) On the twelfth day, Gāndhāras,
led by Śakuni, stood at the rear (पृष्ठ)
of the Suparṇavyūha (7. 19. 4) of Kaura-
vas 7. 19. 11; Arjuna bewildered (व्याकु-
लांश् चक्रे) with his arrows Gāndhāra
warriors led by Śakuni's sons Vṛṣaka and
Acala and killed five hundred of them
7. 29. 5-6; (11) On the thirteenth day,
Abhimanyu killed seventyseven Gāndhāra
warriors who followed Kālakeya (Subala's
son) 7. 48. 7; (12) On the fourteenth day,
Jayadratha, along with Gāndhāras riding
on horsebacks and holding lances in hand,
left to occupy the place (fixed for him)
in the Vyūha 7. 63. 16; Śakuni, with his
army of seven hundred Gāndhāra warriors
fighting with arrows, शक्तिस् and swords
(चापशक्तिशरासिभिः), checked the ad-
vance of the son of Mādrī (माद्रीपुत्रम्
अवारयत्) 7. 70. 42; (13) On the eighteenth
day, Pāñcāla and Pāṇḍava warriors (9.
18. 13) felt that seeing Gāndhāras (and
others) killed all around (गान्धारेषु च
सर्वशः), Duryodhana would realize the
prowess of Pāṇḍavas and other heroes on
their side 9. 18. 22-25; Sahadeva attacked
Śakuni who was covered from behind
by Gāndhāraka warriors riding horses
(गान्धारकैर् गुप्तम् प्र्ष्ठैर् अश्वैः …
सौबलम्) 9. 27. 43; Kṛṣṇa reminded
Bhīma that Gāndhāras who had attacked
him were killed by him (गान्धाराः … ।
त्वाम् आसाद्य महायुद्धे निहताः पाण्डु-
नन्दन) 9. 32. 22; (14) Gāndhrī pointed
out to Kṛṣṇa that Gāndhāra women
(गान्धार° °स्त्रियः) and other women
kept watch on the body of fallen Jaya-
dratha 11. 22. 11; (15) The horse of the
horse-sacrifice went to the Gāndhāra
country (गान्धारविषय) when Arjuna
had to fight a fierce battle with the
then king of Gāndhāra (गान्धारराजेन),
the son of Śakuni, the great chariot-
warrior of the Gāndhāras (गान्धाराणां
महारथः); Gāndhāra warriors (यो-
धाः), not forgiving Śakuni's death in
the war, opposed Arjuna; Arjuna tried to
dissuade them from fighting, but when
they did not listen to him he fought with
them; the Gāndhāra warriors struck
Arjuna, but he felled down their heads;
when Gāndhāras were being killed all
around, Śakuni's son opposed Arjuna; all
Gāndhāra warriors were wonderstruck
when Arjuna removed the headgear of
Śakuni's son; they knew that Arjuna did
not wish to kill Śakuni's son 14. 84. 18-19;
14. 85. 1-3, 7-8, 12; war with Gāndhāra
warriors described in 14. 85. 14-17; Yudhi-
ṣṭhira was delighted to hear Arjuna's
victory in the Gāndhāra country (गान्धार-
विषये) 14. 86. 3; (16) Kṛṣṇa had once
defeated Gāndhāras 16. 7. 10 (same event
as no. 1 ?).
E. Past event: Māndhātṛ
asked Indra what was the धर्म of
Gāndhāras and others who lived like
Dasyus and how they could be controlled
by kings like him (कथं धर्मं चरेयुस्
ते … मद्विधैश् च कथं स्थाप्याः सर्वे
ते दस्युजीविनः) 12. 65. 13, 15; Indra there-
upon told him what the duties of Dasyus
were 12. 65. 17-21.
F. Certain persons
designated as king, prince, or chief of
Gāndhāras: (1) गान्धारपति: Śakuni 8.
62. 50, (2) गान्धारमुख्य: Acala and
Vṛṣala (both sons of Subala) 5. 165. 1-2;
(3) गान्धारराज्: Śakuni 7. 36. 24; (4)
गान्धारराज: Śakuni 1. 1. 100; 3. 227. 21;
3. 297. 5; 5. 2. 5; 5. 29. 39; 5. 30. 27; 5. 92.
49; 5. 196. 7; 6. 20. 8; 7. 29. 2; 7. 33. 20;
7. 165. 75; 8. 4. 96; 8. 53. 6; 9. 22. 28, 29;
11. 24. 21; Śakuni's father (not named)
1. 103. 14; 5. 2. 9; 7. 10. 10; 9. 17. 18; 9.
22. 24; Śakuni's son (not named 14. 84.
19; 14. 85. 18; Subala 1. 103. 10; 7. 10. 10;
7. 29. 2; (5) गान्धारराजपुत्र: Śakuni
1. 57. 94; Śakuni's son (not named) 14. 85.
13; (6) गान्धारराजस्य पुत्रः: Śakuni
1. 103. 14; 9. 17. 18; 9. 22. 24; (7)
गान्धारराजस्य जननी (not named) 14. 85.
18; (8) गान्धारराजस्य सुतः: Śakuni
5. 2. 9; गान्धारराजस्य सुतौ: Vṛṣaka
and Acala 7. 29. 2; (9) गान्धारराजस्य
सुता: Gāndhārī (one of Kṛṣṇa's wives) 7.
10. 10; (10) गान्धाराणां महारथः:
Śakuni's son (not named) 14. 85. 1; (11)
गान्धाराणां यशोहर (voc.): Śakuni 2.
68. 39; (12) गान्धाराधिपति: A certain
king (not named), born in the lineage of
Soma (सोमकुलोत्पन्न) 3. 126. 40.

गिरिगह्वर
Girigahvara m. (pl.): Name of a
people.
Listed by Saṃjaya among the northern
Mleccha people of Bhāratavarṣa (उत्तराश्
चापरे म्लेच्छा जना … ) 6. 10. 63, 5;
(पल्लवा गिरिगह्वराः) 6. 10. 66.

गोपराष्ट्र
Goparāṣṭra m. (pl.): Name of a
Janapada.
Listed by Saṃjaya among the northern
Janapadas (also called Deśas 6. 10. 68)
of Bhāratavarṣa (अत ऊर्ध्वं जनपदान्
निबोध गदतो मम) 6. 10. 37, 5; (गोप-
राष्ट्राः पनीतकाः) 6. 10. 42.

गोपाल
Gopāla m. (pl.): Name of a group
of warriors.
A. Occurrence: They are mentioned
mostly along with Nārāyaṇas; they formed
part of the army of the Saṃśaptakas.
(7. 66. 38; 8. 37. 33; 9. 2. 36).
B. Des-
cription: Respected by the brave (शूर-
संमत) 7. 66. 39. arrogant in battles
(युद्धदुर्मद) 9. 2. 36.
C. Epic
Events: (1) On the twelfth day of war,
encouraged by Suśarman after the fall of
Sudhanvan (7. 17. 27), they, along with
Nārāyaṇas, returned to the battlefield
determined to fight till death (ततस् ते
संन्यवर्तन्त … नारायणाश् च गोपालाः
कृत्वा मृत्युं निवर्तनम्) 7. 17. 31; (2)
On the fourteenth day, they were among
those who tried to check the advance of
Arjuna towards Jayadratha 7. 66. 38, 41;
(3) On the sixteenth day, they, led by
Kṛtavarman, were stationed at the left
foot of the Makaravyūha of the Kauravas
8. 7. 14, 17; (4) On the seventeenth day,
Gopālas and Saṃśaptakas were struck with
fear when Arjuna released Aindrāstra (8.
37. 31); no one of them was then able to
oppose Arjuna 8. 37. 33; (5) They were
counted by Dhṛtarāṣṭra among those all
of whom were killed in the war of eigh-
teen days 9. 2. 36; (6) They are said to
have been once defeated by Karṇa in
battle (कर्णेन विजिताः पूर्वं संग्रामे)
7. 66. 39.

गोपालकच्छ
Gopālakaccha m. (sg., pl.): Name of
a Janapada.
Listed by Saṃjaya among the northern
Janapadas (also called Deśas 6. 10. 68) of
Bhāratavarṣa (अत ऊर्ध्वं जनपदान्
निबोध गदतो मम) 6. 10. 37, 5;
(कच्छा गोपालकच्छाश् च) 6. 10. 55;
Bhīmasena in his expedition to the east
before the Rājasūya (2. 23. 9; 2. 26. 1)
conquered Gopālakaccha (ततो गोपाल-
कच्छं च … व्यजयत् प्रभुः) 2. 27. 3.

गोवास
Govāsa, Govāsana: m. (pl.): Name
of a Brāhmaṇa settlement (?) and its
warriors.
During the war, mentioned by Kṛṣṇa
along with the Dāsamīya Kṣatriyas; the
Brāhmaṇa warriors from Govāsa along
with the Dāsamīya Kṣatriyas, lost their
lives while fighting with Arjuna during
the first seventeen days of war (गोवासदा-
समीयानां … उदीर्णाश् च महासेना
ब्रह्मक्षत्रस्य … ।त्वां समासाद्य
निधनं गताः साश्वरथद्विपाः॥) 8. 51.
16-17; at the time of Rājasūya, the
Govāsana Brāhmaṇas brought a tribute
of three billions to please Yudhiṣṭhira
but were stopped at gate; when they
brought in addition shining कमण्डलुस्
of gold they were permitted to enter
(गोवासना ब्राह्मणाश् च दासमीयाश् च
सर्वशः॥ … त्रिखर्वं बलिम् आदाय द्वारि
तिष्ठन्ति वारिताः॥कमण्डलून् उपादाय
जातरूपमयाञ् शुभान्।एवं बलिं
प्रदायाथ प्रवेशं लेभिरे ततः॥) 2.
47. 5-6.

गोविन्द
Govinda m. (pl.): Name of a Jana-
pada.
Listed by Saṃjaya among the nor-
thern Janapadas (also called Deśas 6. 10.
68) of Bhāratavarṣa (अत ऊर्ध्वं जन-
पदान् निबोध गदतो मम) 6. 10. 37, 5;
(गोविन्दा मन्दकाः) 6. 10. 42.

ग्रामणीय
Grāmaṇīya, Grāmaṇeya: Name of a
people.
A. Location: They lived to the west
of Khāṇḍavaprastha along the river Sindhu
(निर्याय खाण्डवप्रस्थात् प्रतीचीम् अभितो
दिशम्) 2. 29. 2; (सिन्धुकूलाश्रिता ये च
ग्रामणेया … ) 2. 29. 8.
B. Characteri-
stics: Very strong (महाबल) 2. 29. 8;
they were expert elephant-riders (ग्रामणी-
यैः समारूधा कुशलैर् हस्तिसादिभिः)
4. 31. 3 (Nī. on Bom. Ed. 4. 32. 3: ग्राम-
णीयै राजकीयैः).
C. Epic events: (1)
Nakula defeated them in his expedition to
the west before Rājasūya 2. 29. 8, 2; (2)
They were in the armies of both the
Trigartas and Matsyas who fought with
each other 4. 31. 2.

चर्मखण्डिक
Carmakhaṇḍika m. (pl.): Name of a
Janapada.
Listed by Saṃjaya among the nor-
thern Janapadas (also called Deśas 6. 10.
68) of Bhāratavarṣa (पह्लवाश् चर्म-
खण्डिकाः) 6. 10. 46 (for other citation
see above Govinda).

चिच्छिल
Cicchila m. (pl.): Name of a people.
On the eighth day of war, the Cicchila
warriors formed part of the army which,
led by Bṛhadbala, stood behind Bhagadatta
in the Mahāvyūha (6. 83. 5, 15) of Kaura-
vas (कौसल्यो ऽथ बृहद्बलः। … चिच्छि-
लैश् च समन्वितः) 6. 83. 9.

चीन
Cīna m. (pl.): Name of a people;
Cīnadeśa (m. sg.) Name of the country
(5. 84. 10; 12. 312. 15).
A. Location: Listed by Saṃjaya among
the northern म्लेच्छस् of the Bhārata-
varṣa (उत्तराश् चापरे म्लेच्छा जना … )
6. 10. 63; (तथैव मरधाश् चीनास् … )
6. 10. 65; they lived between Badarī and
Subāhu's country; Pāṇḍavas crossed their
land to reach Subāhu's country (चीनांस्
तुखारान् … अतीत्य दुर्गम् हिमवत्प्रदे-
शम् पुरं सुबाहोर् ददृशुर् नृवीराः)
3. 174. 12; the country lay between
the peak of Meru and Āryāvarta 12.
312. 15.
B. The country famous for:
Antelope-skins; Dhṛtarāṣṭra wanted to
give Kṛṣṇa antelope-skins as gift (अजिना-
नां सहस्राणि चीनदेशोद्भवानि च) 5. 84.
10; other materials: among the tributes
brought for the Rājasūya of Yudhiṣṭhira
are mentioned woolens, blankets made
from the hair of Raṅku deer (राङ्कवम्),
silk, पत्तज kind of cloth, all in bundles
(?कुट्टीकृतम्; Nī. on Bom. Ed. 2. 51. 27:
कुटीकृतम् चित्रगुच्छाकारं कृतम्), all
in large sizes, rich in colour, very soft to
touch (प्रमाणरागस्पर्शाढ्यं बाह्ली-
चीनसमुद्भवम्), as also other materials,
soft and having the colour of lotus
(कमलाभं … श्लक्ष्णम्), not made
of cotton, viz. sheep-skins and soft
antelope skins (वस्त्रम् अकार्पासम् आवि-
कम् मृदु चाजिनम्) 2. 47. 22-23.
C. Epic
events: (1) When Arjuna fought with
Bhagadatta in his expedition to the north
before the Rājasūya, the latter was assis-
ted by Kirātas and Cīnas 2. 23. 19; (2)
They brought tribute for the Rājasūya,
but were stopped at the gate 2. 47. 19-20;
(for their tribute see above section B);
at the Rājasūya they acted as servers
(यज्ञे ते परिवेषकान्) 3. 48. 21-22; (3)
Pāṇḍavas proceeded to Subāhu's country
from Badarī; on way, they had to cross the
country of Cīnas 3. 174. 12; (4) Bhaga-
datta's unassailable army consisted of Cīnas
and Kirātas equipped with gold coloured
outfit (चीनैः किरातैश् च काञ्चनैर् इव
संवृतम्।बभौ बलम् अनाधृष्यम्) 5.
19. 15.
D. Past events: (1) Bhīma men-
tioned Dhautamūlaka, king of Cīnas, who
was among the eighteen kings who extirpa-
ted their kinsmen, friends and relations
5. 72. 11, 14; (2) When Śuka left the
peak of mountain Meru (12. 310. 11) to
go to Mithilā, he crossed countries inhabi-
ted by Cīnas and Hūṇas before he arrived
at Āryāvarta (स देशान् विविधान् पश्यन्
चीनहूणनिषेवितान्।आर्यावर्तम् ईमं
देशम् आजगाम महामुनिः) 12. 312. 15;
(3) Māndhātṛ asked Indra how kings like
him should govern people like Cīnas who,
although they lived in country side, led
the life of Dasyus; he also asked Indra
the nature of their धर्म (कथं धर्-
मं चरेयुस् ते सर्वे विषयवासिनः।मद्-
विधैश् च कथं स्थाप्याः सर्वे ते दस्यु-
जीविनः॥) 12. 65. 13, 15; thereupon Indra
told him their धर्म 12. 65. 17-22.

चूचुप
Cūcupa m. (pl.): Name of a people.
A. Location: They belonged to the
south (दक्षिणापथजन्मानः) 12. 200.
39.
B. Characterization: They did not
believe in Dhātṛ being the अध्यक्ष of all
beings (अध्यक्षं सर्वभूतानां धाता-
रम् अकरोत् प्रभुः॥ … निरध्यक्षांस्
तु कौन्तेय कीर्तयिष्यामि तान् अपि॥ …
चूचुपाः मण्डपैः सह) 12. 200. 33,
38-39; sinful, they roamed about over the
earth living like dogs, crows, बलस् (?)
and vultures; they did not exist in the Kṛta-
yuga, but were found since the Tretā 12.
200. 41-42.
C. Epic events: (1) Kṛṣṇa
told Karṇa before the war that if he were
to join the Pāṇḍavas, Cūcupas and many
other people would lead his procession
(पुरोगमाश् च ते सन्तु) 5. 138. 25; (2)
On the second day of the war, Duryodhana,
helped by Cūcupas and other warriors,
protected the army of Śakuni 6. 47. 16:
(3) On the sixth day, they were posted at
the right wing of the Krauñcavyūha of
the Kauravas 6. 71. 14, 20.

चेदि
Cedi(ka) m. (pl.): Name of a
country and its people, often mentioned
along with Kāśis, Karūṣas, Pāñcālas, and
Matsyas; the people once referred to as
चैद्य (5. 4. 14); the country is referred to
as Janapada (4. 1. 9; 6. 10. 39), Deśa (1.
57. 7, 9), or Viṣaya (1. 57. 2); its warriors
once designated as Cedika (8. 32. 34).
A. Location: Mentioned by Saṃjaya
among the northern Janapadas (also called
Deśas 6. 10. 68) of Bhāratavarṣa (चेदि-
वत्साः करूषाश् च) 6. 10. 39, 37, 5; one of
the Janapadas lying around Kuru country
(परितः कुरून्।पाञ्चालास् चेदिमत्स्याश्
च) 4. 1. 9.
B. Capital: Śukti (पुरीं
रम्यां चेदीनां शुक्तिसाह्वयाम्) 14. 84.
2; it is referred to as Cedirājapurī 3.
62. 20, or as Cedipura 2. 40. 14, or as
Cedipurī 3. 65. 6.
C. Description: (1)
Country: holy (पुण्य) 1. 57. 8; gentle
(सौम्य) 1. 57. 8; delightful (रम्य) 1.
57. 2; 4. 1. 9; worth accepting (ग्रहणीय)
1. 57. 2; firmly established (सुस्थिर) 1.
57. 8; called the udder of the land (ऊधः
पृथिव्या यो देशः) 1. 57. 7; hence rich in
food (बह्वन्न) 4. 1. 9; having ample
corn, wealth, jewels (धनधान्यवन्त्) 1.
57. 8; (धनरत्नादिभिर् युतः) 1. 57. 9;
the land was full of wealth (वसुपूर्णा
च वसुधा) 1. 57. 9; thus having all
enjoyable qualities of (good piece of)
land (भोग्यैर् भूमिगुणैर् वृतः) 1. 57.
8; suitable for cattle (पशव्य) 1. 57. 8;
excelled other countries (अत्यन्यान् एष
देशो हि) 1. 57. 9; to be well protected
(स्वारक्ष्य) 1. 57. 8; (2) People: They
were virtuous, followed their धर्म, were
quite satisfied; they did not utter a lie even
in joke, were obedient to fathers, intent on
doing good to teachers; cows were never
put to yoke, the lean ones were nourished;
all वर्णस् lived within the limits of their
धर्म (धर्मशीला जनपदाः सुसंतोषाश्
च साधवः।न च मिथ्याप्रलापो ऽत्र
स्वैरेष्व् अपि कुतो ऽन्यथा॥न च पित्रा
विभज्यन्ते नरा गुरुहिते रताः।युञ्जते
धुरि नो गाश् च कृशाः संधुक्षयन्ति च)
1. 57. 10-11 (Nī. on Bom. Ed. 1. 63. 11
takes गाः as mas. pl. and explains संधु-
क्षयन्ति as पुष्टान् कुर्वन्ति); the most
excellent among them knew eternal
धर्म; virtuous and, distinguished they
lived according to the ancient धर्म
(चेदयश् च महाभागा धर्मं जानन्ति
शाश्वतम्; चेदयो ये विशिष्टाः।धर्मं
पुराणम् उपजीवन्ति सन्तो … ) 8. 30. 61-62;
(3) Warriors: brave (शूर) 7. 8. 27; 7.
101. 68; 8. 8. 19; honoured by the brave
(शूरसंमत) 8. 40. 62; distinguished
chariot-fighters (महारथ) 6. 102. 17; 8.
40. 2, 51; 8. 56. 23; born in noble families
(कुलपुत्र) 6. 102. 17; they were willing
to die but not turn away from the battle-
field (तनुत्यजः।अपरावर्तिनः सर्वे)
6. 102. 17; (चेदीनाम् अनिवर्तिनाम्) 8. 32.
80; their banners made of gold (सुवर्ण-
विकृतध्वज) 6. 102. 17.
D. Epic
events: (1) At the birth of Arjuna, a
noncorporeal voice declared that Arjuna
would bring under his control Cedis,
Kāśis and Karūṣas 1. 114. 31; (2) King
Pauṇḍraka was known as पुरुषोत्तम
among the Cedi people (पुरुषोत्तम-
विज्ञातो यो ऽसौ चेदिषु दुर्मतिः) 2. 13. 17;
(3) Yudhiṣṭhira installed the son of
Śiśupāla as the ruler of the Cedi country
(चेदीनाम् आधिपत्ये) 2. 42. 31; (4) Dru-
pada suggested to Pāṇḍavas to send messen-
gers (5. 4. 25) to different kings to seek
their help, one of them being Dhṛṣṭaketu,
the king of the Cedis (चैद्याधिपतिर् एव
च) 5. 4. 14; (5) Dhṛṣṭaketu joined the
Pāṇḍavas with an अक्षौहिणी army of Cedi
warriors 5. 19. 7; 5. 22. 24; 5. 56. 33;
5. 70. 14; 5. 142. 3; 5. 197. 2; Dhṛṣṭa-
ketu was the lone principal warrior from
the Cedis who joined the Pāṇḍavas (एको
ऽपसृत्य चेदिभ्यः पाण्डवान् यः समाश्रि-
तः।ध्र्ष्टकेतुम् तम् … ) 7. 9. 39; (6)
Others joined the Kauravas (चेदयश्
चापरे वङ्गा माम् एव समुपाश्रिताः) 7.
23. 7; (7) Cedis mentioned among those
who would consecrate Karṇa as the king
if he were to join the Pāṇḍavas 5. 138. 17;
(8) Kuntī grieved at the prospect of Cedis
fighting against Bhāratas (चेदिपाञ्चालाः …
भारतैर् यदि योत्स्यन्ति किं नु दुःखम्
अतः परम्) 5. 142. 12; (9) Before the
war Duryodhana boasted that, helped by
his army, he would fight against Cedis and
all those on the side of Pāṇḍavas 9. 2. 23;
(10) On the first day of the war, Bhīṣma's
banner was seen moving in the army of
the Pāṇḍavas consisting of warriors from
Cedi, Kāśi and Karūṣa countries 6. 45.
3-4; (11) On the second day, Bhīṣma
showered them with arrows 6. 48. 9;
(12) On the same day Bhīma faced the
attack of Ketumant helped by the Cedis
(on the side of the Kauravas) (भीम-
सेनः … आर्छद् … केतुमन्तं च … आया-
तं सह चेदिभिः) 6. 50. 5; Śrutāyu and
Ketumant attacked Bhīma surrounded by
Cedis (on the Pāṇḍavas' side) 6. 50. 6, 8;
Cedis were outnumbered by Kaliṅgas
and Niṣādas; they fought bravely but,
finally, they returned abandoning Bhīma;
even though Cedis deserted Bhīma (संणि-
वृत्तेषु चेदिषु) he continued to fight
with Kaliṅgas 6. 50. 13-16; (13) On the
third day, Cedis, led by Dhṛṣṭaketu, stood
on the right side of the Ardhacandravyūha
of Pāṇḍavas 6. 52. 10, 13; towards the end
of the same day, Cedis and others raised
a loud roar with delīght due to the great
havoc caused by Arjuna 6. 55. 126; (14)
On the fourth day, Cedis occupied the same
place in the Vyūha as on the previous
day 6. 56. 11; (15) On the ninth and
tenth day, Bhīṣma killed fourteen thousand
Cedi, Kāśi and Karūṣa warriors along with
their horses, chariots and elephants (सवाजि-
रथकुञ्जराः) 6. 102. 17-18; 6. 112. 73;
(16) On the tenth day, Śikhaṇḍin, along
with Cedis and Pāñcālas, attacked Bhīṣma
6. 111. 26; they rushed at Bhīṣma, produc-
ing noise, riding chariots and horses
and elephants; some of them were foot-
soldiers (ततः हिलहिलाशब्द्áः क्षणेन
समपद्यत।मत्स्यपाञ्चालचेदीनाम् …
ते वराश्वरथव्रातैर् वारणैः सपदाति-
भिः) 6. 113. 47-48; on the seventeenth
day of war, Kṛṣṇa, while recounting the
past incidents, reminded Arjuna that Cedis
and others, protected by him, had reduced
the army of the enemies; but Bhīṣma
succeeded in putting many of them to
death 8. 51. 6, 27, 32; (17) On the ele-
venth day, Dhṛtarāṣṭra feared that Dhṛṣṭa-
dyumna, helped by Cedis and others,
had killed Droṇa 7. 8. 27; (18) On
the twelfth day, seeing Yudhiṣṭhira runn-
ing away from Droṇa, Cedis, Kārūṣas and
others attacked Droṇa; Droṇa defeated
them repeatedly 7. 20. 18, 23; Droṇa's
arrows put Cedis, Kekayas into utter dis-
order; they were carried away like small
boats by the strong current of the river
(सिन्धोर् इव महौघेन ह्रियमाणान् यथा
प्लवान्) 7. 21. 7-8; Droṇa killed many
Cedis 7. 31. 39; (19) The king of
Cedis showering arrows, kept Ambaṣṭha
away from Droṇa 7. 24. 47; (20) Subhadrā
blamed Cedis and others neglecting Abhi-
manyu's fall in battle 7. 55. 13; (21)
On the fourteenth day, Alambusa Rākṣasa
made a river of blood flow carrying away
many Cedis and others 7. 83. 30; Kṛtavar-
man defeated Cedis and others 7. 90. 47;
Cedis and others, delighted, attacked
Droṇa crying ‘kill Droṇa, kill Droṇa’;
they made effort with all their might to
kill Droṇa; Droṇa killed them, specially
their chiefs, with arrows; seeing them
diminished Pāñcālas trembled 7. 101. 50-
53; Duryodhana struck Cedis with many
sharp arrows 7. 128. 23; (22) During
the night war (fourteenth-fifteenth day),
distinguished archers among Cedis (चेद-
यश् च महेष्वासा … ) attacked Droṇa;
he defeated them and killed them 7. 161,
30, 32, 35; (23) On the fifteenth day,
the crown prince of Cedis (युवराजश् च
चेदीनाम्) struck Aśvatthāman with five
arrows; he killed the prince, who was dear
to Cedis (चेदिप्रियम्), along with his
horses and the chariot-driver 7. 171. 56, 65;
(24) On the sixteenth day, Cedis and
others rushed at the Kaurava army 8. 8.
19; they also attacked Karṇa 8. 21. 26;
(25) On the seventeenth day, Cedis and
others fought fiercely with the Kaurava
army; Duryodhana offered protection
to Karṇa while he was fighting with
Cedis and others; in their renewed battle
with Karṇa, three hundred Cedi chariot-
fighters, who did not turn back, lost
their life (स रथांस् त्रिशतान् हत्वा
चेदीनाम् अनिवर्तिनाम्) 8. 32. 15, 20, 43,
80; in the meantime Karṇa had also
killed hundreds and thousands of ordi-
nary Cedi fighters (चेदिकान् अवधीद् वीरः
शतशोऽथ सहस्रश्हः) 8. 32. 34; when
Yudhiṣṭhira, defeated and humiliated
by Karṇa in a duel, retreated from the
battlefield, Cedis and other warriors
followed him 8. 33. 41; when Cedi and
Pāñcāla armies were engaged with Karṇa,
he destroyed them; then they began to
flee 8. 43. 24, 26-28; in his fight with
Karṇa, Bhīma was accompanied by Cedis;
Karṇa killed great Cedi chariot-fighters
(महारथान्) and many others, respected
by brave (शूरसंमताः) 8. 40. 1, 2, 51,
62, 68; 8. 45. 41; Śalya drove Karṇa's
chariot towards Cedis, Pāñcālas and Karū-
ṣas; Karṇa killed Pāñcalas and the great
chariot-fighters (महारथान्) of the Cedis;
Cedis and others, although being killed
by Karṇa, continued to shoot arrows at
Karṇa; Karṇa killed more than a hundred
Cedi horse-riders (सादयः क्रोधाच् चेद-
यश् च परःशताः) 8. 56. 9. 23-24, 49;
(26) On the last day of the war, Śalya
wanted to show his valour to Pāñcālas,
Cedis and the rest 9. 6. 13; he killed twenty
five Cedi warriors 9. 11. 53; during the
war of eighteen days, all Cedis were killed
(चेदयश् च निषूदिताः) 9. 1. 30; 15. 44.
34; (27) The Aśvamedha horse, wander-
ing at will, reached the beautiful town
of the Cedis called Śukti (आससाद पुरीं
रम्यां चेदीनां शुक्तिसाह्वयाम्) 14. 84. 2.
E. Past events: (1) King Vasu Upari-
cara, a Paurava, accepted the rulership
of the Cedi country as directed by Indra
(स चेदिविषयं रम्यं वसुः पौरव-
नन्दनः।इन्द्रोपदेशाज् जग्राह ग्रहणी-
यं महीपतिः॥) 1. 57. 2, (वस चेदिषु
चेदिप) 1. 57. 9; while living in Cedi
country, he protected the earth according
to धर्म 1. 57. 27; (2) Bhīma mentioned
king Sahaja of Cedis and Matsyas among
the eighteen kings who were responsible
for the destruction of their kinsmen, friends
and relatives (अष्टादशेमे राजानः … ।
ये समुच्चिच्छिदुर् ज्ञातीन् सुहृदश् च स-
बान्धवान्॥ … सहजश् चेदिमत्स्यानाम्)
5. 72. 11, 16.
F. Certain persons
referred to as the king of the Cedis
or as the foremost among the Cedis:
चेदिप: (1) Dhṛṣṭaketu 3. 13. 2; 5. 78.
14; 5. 81. 31; 6. 91. 23, 39; 7. 34. 3;
(2) Vasu Uparicara 1. 57. 9; चेदिपति: (1)
Dhṛṣṭaketu 3. 120. 25; 5. 49. 43; 5. 168. 9;
11. 25. 20; (2) Vasu Uparicara 1. 57. 23,
27; 13. 116. 54; (3) Śiśupāla 2. 35. 5;
2. 37. 13, 15; 2. 39. 20; 2. 41. 1, 24; 2. 42.
22; 2. 49. 6; 5. 22. 24, 27; (4) Subāhu
3. 65. 33; चेदिपुंगव: (1) Dhṛṣṭaketu
11. 25. 18; (2) Śiśupāla 2. 36. 15; 2. 37.
9; चेदिराज्: (1) Dhṛṣṭaketu 3. 23. 47; 5.
56. 8; 6. 43. 75; (2) Śiśupāla 2. 35. 27;
2. 41. 4; 2. 42. 1; चेदिराज: (1) Dhṛṣṭa-
ketu 5. 168. 8; 6. 43. 37; 6. 112. 23; 7. 24.
47; 7. 82. 15; 7. 101. 38; 11. 25. 21, 22;
(2) Śiśupāla 2. 26. 12, 14; 2. 33. 32; 2. 35.
14; 2. 37. 12; 2. 39. 18; 2. 41. 24; 2. 42.
16, 22; 7. 10. 13; 7. 155. 29; 7. 156. 2, 5,
21; (3) Subāhu 3. 61. 125; 3. 62. 18;
चेदिवृष: Śiśupāla 2. 26. 13; चेदीनाम्
अधिपतिः: Dhṛṣṭaketu (चेदीनाम् आधिपत्ये)
5. 42. 31; चैद्याधिपति: Dhṛṣṭaketu 5. 4.
14; चेदीनाम् ईश्वरः प्रभुः: Vasu 14. 94.
22; चेदीनाम् ऋषभः: Dhṛṣṭaketu 5. 19.
7; 7. 22. 16; 7. 81. 9; 7. 101. 25; चेदीनां
प्रवरो रथः: Dhṛṣṭaketu 8. 4. 80.

चेदिवत्स
Cedivatsa m. (pl.): Name of a Janapada.
Listed by Saṃjaya among the northern
Janapadas (also called Deśas 6. 10. 68)
of the Bhāratavarṣa (अत ऊर्ध्वं जन-
पदान् निबोध) 6. 10. 37, 5; (चेदिवत्साः
करूषाश् च) 6. 10. 39.

चैत्रक
Caitraka, Caitraki m. (pl.): Name
of a people.
(1) Duryodhana saw Caitrakis and
others acting very submissively towards
Yudhiṣṭhira as if they were his slaves
(अवार्जिता इवाभान्ति निघ्नाश् चैत्रकिकौकु-
राः … युधिष्ठिरनिवेशने) 2. 46. 21; (2)
They followed Kṛṣṇa's advice and hence
could control their enemies and give
delight to their friends (चैत्रकाश् चान्ध-
काश् च … उपासीना वासुदेवस्य बुद्धिं
निगृह्य शत्रून् सुहृदो नन्दयन्ति) 5. 28. 11.

चोल
Cola m. (pl.): Name of a Janapada
and its people.
A. Location: (1) South of Bhārata-
varṣa: Listed by Saṃjaya among by the
southern Janapadas (also called Deśas 6. 10.
66) of the Bhāratavarṣa (अथापरे जनपदा
दक्षिणा भरतर्षभ) 6. 10. 58, 5;
(कौकुट्टकास् तथा चोलाः) 6. 10. 58;
called Janapadas also in चोलाः पाण्ड्याश् च
भारत।एते जनपदा राजन् 6. 46. 50;
mentioned along with Draviḍas 3. 48. 22;
(2) However, Arjuna is said to have con-
quered them in his expedition to the north
before Rājasūya (धनंजयः।प्रययाव्
उत्तरां दिशम्) 2. 24. 1; (ततः सुह्माश्
च चोलांस् च … प्रामथत् कुरुनन्दनः)
2. 24. 20.
B. Epic events: (1)
Arjuna defeated them before Rājasūya 2.
24. 20; (2) They and their kings acted
as servers in the Rājasūya of Yudhiṣṭhira
(यत्र सर्वान् महीपालाञ् … सचोलद्रविडा-
न्ध्रकान् … यज्ञे ते परिवेषकान्) 3. 48.
18; (3) On the second day of war, they
were stationed at the right wing of the
Krauñcāruṇavyūha of the Pāṇḍavas (चोलाः
 … दक्षिणं पक्षम् आश्रिताः) 6. 46. 50, 39;
(4) While recounting the past victories of
Kṛṣṇa, Dhṛtarāṣṭra mentioned his victory
over the Colas 7. 10. 17.

जगत्तुण्ड
Jagattuṇḍa m. (pl.): Name of a
Janapada and its people.
Characterized as Janapada (एते जन-
पदा … जगत्तुण्डाः) 6. 46. 50-51; on the
second day of war, they were among those
who were stationed at the left wing of the
Krauñcāruṇavyūha (6. 46. 39) of the
Pāṇḍavas 6. 46. 51.

जठर
Jaṭhara m. (pl.): Name of a Jana-
pada.
Listed by Saṃjaya among the northern
Janapadas (also called Deśas 6. 10. 68)
of the Bhāratavarṣa (अत ऊर्ध्वं जन-
पदान् निबोध) 6. 10. 37, 5; जठराः कुक्कु-
शाश् चैव 6. 10. 41.

जनक
Janaka m. (pl.): Designation of the
family of Janaka.
Aṣṭāvakra addressed king Janaka as
the best in the family of Janakas (भो भो
राजन् जनकानां वरिष्ठ) 3. 133. 16.

जम्बूद्वीप
Jambū̆dvīpa, Jambuparvata, Jambūkhaṇḍa
 (m.): Name of a द्वीप (called
Jambūkhaṇḍa 6. 12. 1, Jambuparvata 6.
12. 5).
A. Location: One of the four द्वीपस्
which lie on the four sides of mount
Meru, the other three being Bhadrāśva,
Ketumāla, and Uttara Kurus (मेरुः
कनकपर्वतः। … तस्य पार्श्वे त्व् इमे
द्वीपाश् चत्वारः संस्थिताः प्रभो। …
जम्बूद्वीपश् च) 6. 7. 8, 11; Jambūdvīpa
to the south of Meru 6. 12. 21-25; a great
(Jambū) tree, which had become famous
on account of Jambūdvīpa, stands in its
middle (जम्पूद्वीपेन विख्यातस् तस्य
मध्ये महाद्रुमः) 6. 12. 25.
B. Name
explained: The Dvīpa is named after the
great, ancient Jambū tree, called Sudarśana,
which stands on it (सुदर्शनो नाम महाञ्
जम्बूवृक्षः सनातनः। … तस्य नाम्ना
समाख्यातो जम्बूद्वीपः सनातनः) 6. 8.
18-19.
C. Extent: Described by Saṃjaya
for Dhṛtarāṣṭra 6. 12. 1; in extent it was
a full eighteen thousand and six hundred
योजनस् (अष्टादशसहस्राणि योजनानां
विशां पते।षट्शतानि च पूर्णानि विष्कम्-
भो जम्बुपर्वतः)॥ 6. 12. 5 (Nī. on
Bom. Ed. 6. 11. 5: विष्कम्भश् चतुर्दल-
कमलाकारस्य जम्बूद्वीपस्य पत्रान्त-
परिधिः तादृशविस्तार एव पिण्डप्रमाणम्
अन्तर्भाव्य पर्वताकृतित्वाज् जम्बूपर्वत
इत्य् उच्यते); its circular extent spread over
many योजनस् (मण्डलं बहुयोजनम्) 6.
1. 9; the Śākadvīpa is double the size of
Jambūdvīpa 6. 12. 9; its extent sometimes
identified with Bhāratavarṣa (यावत् … जम्बू-
द्वीपस्य मण्डलम्।तावद् एव समावृत्तं
बलं … ) 6. 1. 8.
D. Description: An-
cient (सनातन) 6. 8. 18; the salty ocean
which encircles it (सागरः परिम्ण्डलः)
is double the extent of the Jambūdvīpa;
the Jambūdvīpa is full of many Janapadas
(नानाजनपदाकीर्ण) and is adorned with
jewels and corals and by mountains which
shine with many minerals (मणिविद्रुम-
चित्रितः।नैकधातुविचित्रैश् च पर्वतैर्
उपशोभितः); it is resorted to by Siddhas
and Cāraṇas 6. 12. 6-7; (नानाजनपदा-
युत) 12. 14. 21; 14. 87. 13; Krauñcadvīpa
is similar to Jambūdvīpa 12. 14. 22.
E.
Characteristics: (1) Used as a measure
of time: as much as it rains in the Jambū-
dvīpa (i. e. the total number of drops of
rain) for a thousand years, so long a
person who fasts for a month eating only
once on the last day lives in the Brahma-
loka 13. 110. 121, 128; (2) Many kinds
of jewels go from Jambūdvīpa to the
other Dvīpas for the people living there
(जम्बूद्वीपात् प्रवर्तन्ते रत्नानि विविधान्य्
उत।द्वीपेषु तेषु सर्वेषु प्रजानां … ॥
6. 13. 26.
F. Epic events: (1) The
army for the great war was drawn from
the entire Jambūdvīpa (यावत् तपति सूर्यो
हि जम्बूद्वीपस्य मण्डलम्।तावद् एव
समावृत्तं बलम्) 6. 1. 8; (2) Drau-
padī reminded Yudhiṣṭhira that he had
formerly overpowered the entire Jambū-
dvīpa 12. 14. 21; (3) In the Aśvamedha
sacrifice of Yudhiṣṭhira, the entire Jambū-
dvīpa had gathered (जम्बूद्वीपो हि सकलो
 … अदृश्यतैकस्थो … ) 14. 87. 13.
G. Past
event: Nala became famous throughout
Jambūdvīpa when he again became the
king of Niṣadhas (प्रकाशतां यातो जम्बु-
द्वीप) 3. 78. 4.

जर्तिक
Jartika: See Āraṭṭa,

जागुड
Jāguḍa m. (pl.): Name of a people.
Mentioned by Kṛṣṇa among those
whom he saw at the Rājasūya of Yudhi-
ṣṭhira and who acted as servers at meals
(जागुडान् … आगतान् अहम् अद्राक्षं यज्ञे
ते परिवेषकान्) 3. 48. 21-22.

जाङ्गल
Jāṅgala m. (pl.): Name of a Jana-
pada (forest area as part of the Kuru
country ?) and its residents.
A. Location: Mentioned by Saṃjaya
among the northern Janapadas of the
Bhāratavarṣa (अत ऊर्धवं जनपदान्
निबोध गदतो मम) 6. 10. 37, 5; (शाल्व-
माद्रेयजाङ्गलाः) 6. 10. 37.
B. Epic
events: (1) Kṛṣṇa saw the inhabitants
of Jāṅgala (here as opposed to पत्तन-
वासिनः ?) attending the Rājasūya and act-
ing as servers at meals (ये ते जाङ्गलवासि-
नः … आगातान् अहम् अद्राक्षं यज्ञे ते
परिवेषकान्) 3. 48. 19, 22; (2) Saṃjaya
told Dhṛtarāṣṭra that the entire Kuru
country along with the Jāṅgala had be-
longed to him (कृत्सं राज्यं … कुरवस्
ते सजाङ्गलाः) 5. 53. 6-7; [See Kuru-
jāṅgala].

ज्योह
Jyoha: See Ekāśanājyoha.

तङ्गण
Taṅgaṇa m. (pl.): Name of a Jana-
pada and its people.
A. Location: There seem to be two
Taṅgaṇas: northern and southern: (1)
They are said to have lived in the large
kingdom of Subāhu on Himālaya (सुबाहोर्
विषयं महत् … किराततङ्गणाकीर्णम् …
हिमवत्य् अमरैर् जुष्टम्) 3. 141. 24-25;
they lived in the region between the
mountains Meru and Mandara and along
the river Śailodā (मेरुमन्दरयोर् मध्ये
शैलोदाम् अभितो नदीम्) 2. 48. 2; (2)
Listed by Saṃjaya among the southern
Janapadas (also called Deśas 6. 10. 68)
of the Bhāratavarṣa (अथापरे दक्षिणा
जनपदा … ) 6. 10. 56, 5; (तङ्गणाः
परतङ्गणाः) 6. 10. 63; designated as
जनपद also in 6. 46. 50.
B. Characte-
ristic: They enjoyed the pleasing shadow
of कीचक and वेणु types of bamboos (ये ते
कीचकवेणूनां छायां रम्याम् उपासते)
2. 48. 2.
C. Description: Strong, very
strong (बलिन्) 8. 51. 19; (अतिबल) 8. 5.
18; fierce (उग्र) and of cruel deeds
(क्रूरकर्मन्) 8. 51. 18; furious, expert
in battles, firm-fisted (संरंभिणो युद्ध-
शौण्डा … दृब्धपाणयः) 8. 51. 19; diffi-
cult to be won (दुर्जय) 8. 5. 18; no one
except Arjuna could conquer them (न
शक्या युधि निर्जेतुं त्वद् अन्येन परं-
तप) 8. 51. 20.
D. Epic events: (1) King
of Taṅgaṇas brought lumps of gold of the
पिपीलिक variety, given as boon by ants (?),
to be measured by द्रोणस्, as tribute for
the Rājasūya; they were stopped at the
gate (ते वै पिपीलिकं नाम वरदत्तं
पिपीलिकैः।जातरूपं द्रोणमेयम् अहार्षुः
पुञ्जशो नृपाः … द्वारि तिष्ठन्ति वारिताः)
2. 48. 3-4, 7; (2) Subdued by the fear
of the sharp edge of the weapons of
Pāṇḍavas, they attended the Rājasūya and
acted as servers at meals (शस्त्रतेजो-
भयार्दितान् … तङ्गणान् … यज्ञे ते पऋइ-
वेषकान्) 3. 48. 18, 21-22; (3) Karṇa had
once defeated them and were made to pay
tribute (चक्रे बलिभृतः पुरा) 8. 5. 18;
(4) Mentioned among those who joined
the Kauravas for the sake of Duryodhana
8. 51. 18, 20; (5) On the second day of
war, the Taṅgaṇas on the side of the
Pāṇḍavas were stationed at the right wing
(दक्षिणं पक्षम्) of the Krauñcāruṇa
vyūha 6. 46. 39) of the Pāṇḍavas 6. 46.
49; (6) On the fourteenth day of
war, Taṅgaṇas on the side of the Kauravas,
led by Duryodhana, attacked Sātyaki;
Sātyaki repulsed with ञाराच arrows the
attack of Taṅgaṇas who fought with iron
weapons and शूलस् (अयोहस्तैः शूल-
हस्तैः) 7. 97. 14, 39; (7) On the
sixteenth day of war, Pāṇḍya killed many
of them who rode on horsebacks and
fought with शक्ति, प्रास and bows and
arrows (सशक्तिप्रासतूणीरान् अश्वारोहान्)
8. 15. 9; (8) One of the countries visited
by the Aśvamedha horse was Taṅgaṇa
(किरातान् अथ तङ्गणान्) 14. 84. 4.

तरतोय
Taratoya m. (pl.): Name of a Jana-
pada.
Listed by Saṃjaya among the northern
Janapadas (also called Deśas 6. 10. 68)
of the Bhāratavarṣa (अत ऊर्ध्वं जन-
पदान् निबोध गदतो मम) 6. 10. 37, 5;
(तीरग्राहास् तरतोया … ) 6. 10. 51.

तरल
Tarala m. (pl.): Name of a people.
Karṇa had once defeated Tarala
warriors in battle and made them pay
tribute (तरलान् … यो जित्वा समरे वीरश्
चक्रे बलिभृतः पुरा) 8. 5. 20.

तलवन
Talavana m. (pl.): Name of a people.
Sahadeva in his expedition to the
south (2. 28. 1, 8, 37) subjugated them just
by sending messengers and made them pay
tribute for the Rājasūya (अन्ध्रांस् तल-
वनांश् चैव … दूतैर् एव वशे चक्रे
करं चैनान् अदापयत्) 2. 28. 48-49.

तामर
Tāmara m. (pl.): Name of a Jana-
pada.
Listed by Saṃjaya among the southern
Janapadas (also called Deśas 6. 10. 68)
of the Bhāratavarṣa (अथापरे जनपदा
दक्षिणा … ) 6. 10. 56; (तामरा हंस-
मार्गाश् च) 6. 10. 68.

ताम्र
Tāmra nt.: Name of a द्वीप।
Sahadeva in his expedition to the
south (2. 28. 1, 8, 37) subjugated it just
by sending messengers and made the people
pay tribute for the Rājasūya (द्वीपं
ताम्राह्वयं चैव) 2. 28. 46-47.

ताम्रलिङ्गक
Tāmraliṅgaka m. (pl.): Name of a
Janapada.
Listed by Saṃjaya among the northern
Janapadas (also called Deśas 6. 10. 68)
of the Bhāratavarṣa 6. 10. 37, 5; (विदेहास्
ताम्रलीङ्गकाः) 6. 10. 55.

ताम्रलिप्त
Tāmralipta(ka) m. (pl.): Name of
a people.
A. Characteristic: Skilled in fighting
while riding elephants (गजयोधिनः। …
ताम्रलिप्तकाः॥ … गजयुद्धेषु कुशलाः)
8. 17. 2-3.
B. Epic events: (1) Their
kings brought fine cloth, silk material,
thin cotton cloth and mantles as tribute
for Yudhiṣṭhira's Rājasūya, but they
were not allowed to enter the sacrificial
enclosure by the gate-keepers; on being
asked to give more, each one of them gave
a thousand well-bred elephants of the
Kāmyaka lake, huge like mountains, having
long tusks, gold girdles, lotus-coloured,
covered with painted cloth and protected
by armours, always in rut yet patient;
then they were allowed to enter the gate
(ताम्रलिप्ताः … दुकूलं कौशिकं चैव
पत्रोर्णं प्रावरान् अपि) 2. 48. 17; (ईषा-
दन्तान् हेमकक्षान् पद्मवर्णान् कुथा-
वृतान्।शैलाभान् नित्यमत्तांश् च अभितः
काम्यकं सरः॥दत्त्वैकैको दशशतान्
कुञ्जरान् कवचावृतान्।क्षमावतः कुली-
नांश् च) 2. 48. 19-20; (2) On the four-
teenth day of war, Sātyaki, while advanc-
ing to meet Arjuna had to fight with them
who were armed with various weapons
(ताम्रलिप्तकाः … विविधायुधपाणयः)
7. 95. 13; (3) On the sixteenth day of
war, their elephant-riders (गजयोधिनः)
attacked Dhṛṣṭadyumna and showered on
him arrows of the नाराच type and तोम-
रस् 8. 17. 2, 4; on the same day they also
attacked Nakula with arrows and तोमरस्
(ताम्रलिप्तकाः।शरतोमरवर्षाणि विमुञ्-
चन्तो जिघांसवः) 8. 17. 20, 21.

तार्क्ष्य
Tārkṣya m. (pl.): Name of a people.
Mentioned among those who brought
tribute in thousands to Yudhiṣṭhira for his
Rājasūya 2. 48. 14.

तालजङ्घ
Tālajaṅgha m. (pl.): Name of some
Kṣatriyas.
Past events: (1) King Sagara extir-
pated them along with Haihayas 3. 104. 7;
(2) King Bakula of the Tālajaṅghas was
one of the sixteen kings who completely
annihilated their kinsmen, friends and
relatives (ये समुच्चिच्छिदुर् ज्ञातीन् सुहृदश्
च सबान्धवान्) 5. 72. 13, 11; (3) To
illustrate that the lustre and strength of
the Kṣatriyas was pacified when they
faced Brāhmaṇas, Bhīṣma mentioned that
the Bhṛgus had conquered Tālajaṅghas 13.
34. 15-16; Aurva (a Bhārgava) alone
destroyed a large number of Tālajaṅgha
Kṣatriyas (तालजङ्घं महत् क्षत्रम्
और्वेणैकेन नाशितम्) 13. 138. 11.

तालचर
Tālacara m. (pl.): Name of a people.
Kṛṣṇa told Karṇa that if the were to
join the Pāṇḍavas, Tālacaras would be in
the forefront of his march (पुरोगमाश्
च ते सन्तु … तालचराश् चैव) 5. 138. 25.

तित्तिर
Tittira m. (pl.): Name of a Jana-
pada and its people.
A. Special feature: Famous for its
horses (see
B. Epic events, No. 2);
B.
Epic events: (1) On the second day of
war, the Tittira warriors, along with many
others, were stationed at the right wing of
the Krauñcāruṇavyūha (6. 46. 39; Krauñca
6. 47. 1) of the Pāṇḍavas (तित्तिराश् चैव …
एते जनपदा राजन् दक्षिणं पक्षम्
आश्रिताः) 6. 46. 50; (2) On the eighth day
of war, Irāvān confronted the cavalry of
Śakuni and Hārdikya (Kṛtavarman) with
his Tittira-bred horses which were swift,
having the speed of wind, decorated with
gold, provided with armour and well-
equipped (ये चापरे तित्तिरजा जवना वातर-
ंहसः) 6. 86. 4-5; for further description
of horses see 6. 86. 15-16.

तिलक
Tilaka m. (pl.): Name of a Janapada.
Listed by Saṃjaya among the northern
Janapadas (also called Deśas 6. 10. 68)
of the Bhāratavarṣa 6. 10. 37, 5; (तिलकाः
पारसीकाश् च) 6. 10. 51.

तीरग्राह
Tīragrāha m. (pl.): Name of a Jana-
pada.
Listed by Saṃjaya among the northern
Janapadas (also called Deśas 6. 10. 68) of
the Bhāratavarṣa 6. 10. 37, 5; (तीरग्राहास्
तरतोया … ) 6. 10. 51.

तुखार
Tukhāra, Tuṣāra m. (pl.): Name of
a people; name Tuṣāra occurs at 6. 71.
20; 12. 65. 13.
A. Location: Mentioned by Saṃjaya
along with the northern मेल्च्छस् of the
Bhāratavarṣa (उत्ताराश् चापरे म्लेच्छा
जना … ) 6. 10. 63, 5; (खशीकाश् च तुखा-
राश् च) 6. 10. 66; Pāṇḍavas on their
return journey from Badarī crossed the
country of Tukhāras before reaching
Subāhu's realm 3. 174. 12.
B. Descrip-
tion: Fierce and doing cruel deeds (उग्राश्
च क्रूरकर्माणः) 8. 51. 18; wrathful,
fond of battles, strong and of firm fists
(?) (संरम्भिणो युद्धशौण्डा बलिनो
दृब्धपाणयः) 8. 51. 19; nobody except
Arjuna could defeat them 8. 51. 20.
C.
Characteristic: Tuṣāras lived in countries
but behaved like दस्युस्; Māndhātṛ asked
Indra how they could be made to follow
धर्म and how they were to be controll-
ed by kings like him 12. 65. 13, 15-16 (for
citation see Kahva); Indra then told him
their धर्म 12. 65. 17-22; their country
was rich in gold and famous for horses (see
below Epic events
D. No. 1).
D. Epic
events: (1) They brought to Yudhiṣṭhira
as tribute one अर्बुद horses of noble
breed and going long distances (महा-
गमान् दूरगमान् गणितान् अर्बुदं हयान्)
and gold by crores amounting to one
पद्म (कोटिशश् चैव बहुशः सुवर्णं
पद्मसंमितम्) 2. 47. 26-27; (2) Their
kings, afraid of the lustre of weapons
(शस्त्रतेजोभयार्दितान्), acted as servers at
the Rājasūya sacrifice 3. 48. 18; 21-22;
(3) Tukhāras had allied themselves with
Duryodhana (एते सुयोधनस्यार्थे सं-
रब्धाः कुरुभिः सह) 8. 51. 20; (4)
On the sixth day of war, Tuṣāras stood
at the right wing of the Krauñcavyūha
of the Kauravas 6. 71. 14, 20; (5) On
the seventeenth day of war, Tukhāras and
others, riding horses, attacked Arjuna;
Arjuna cut off with क्षुर arrows their
heads and hands holding excellent weapons
(तुखारा … सादिनः … वरायुधान् पाणि-
गतान् करैः सह … शिरांसि च) 8. 64.
16-17.

तुण्डिकेर
Tuṇḍikera m. (pl.): Name of a people.
At the end of the eleventh day of
war, Tuṇḍikeras and Mālavas, along with
Sudhanvan, took oath to kill Arjuna 7. 16.
18-19; they are mentioned by Saṃjaya
among those who were killed during the
first seventeen days of war 8. 4. 47.

तुम्बुप
Tumbupa m. (pl.): Name of a people.
On the second day of the war, they
along with others and led by Nakula and
Sahadeva, stood on the left side of the
Krauñcāruṇavyūha (Krauñca 6. 47. 1) of
the Pāṇḍavas (6. 46. 39, 51).

त्रिगर्त
Trigarta m. (pl.): Name of a Jana-
pada and its people; people occasionally
referred to also as Traigarta (7. 17. 6-7,
25) or Traigartaka (7. 17. 5; 7. 136. 3;
14. 73. 27, 31).
A. Location: To the north of Indra-
prastha: Trigartas mentioned among those
Kṣatriyas who gathered together to oppose
Arjuna in his expedition to the north before
the Rājasūya (प्रययाव् उत्तरां तस्मात्
दिशम्) 2. 24. 1; (ततस् त्रिगर्तान् कौन्तेयो
 … क्षत्रिया बहवो राजन्न् उपावर्तन्त
सर्वशः) 2. 24. 17; the horse of the
Aśvamedha went to the north where
Arjuna had to fight with the Trigartas
(स हयः … ससारोत्तरतः) 14. 72. 21;
(त्रिगर्तैर् अभवद् युद्धम् … किरीटिनः)
14. 73. 1; mentioned also among those
whom Nakula conquered in his expedition
to the west (प्रतीचीं नकुलो … दिशम्
व्यजयत्) 2. 23. 10; (निर्याय खाण्डव-
प्रस्थात् प्रातीचीम् अभितो दिशम्) 2. 29.
2; (वशे चक्रे … त्रिगर्तान्) 2. 29. 6;
but they are listed by Saṃjaya among the
Janapadas (also called Deśas 6. 10. 68) of
the south (अथापरे जनपदा दक्षिणा) 6.
10. 56; त्रिगर्ताः सर्वसेनयः) 6. 10. 59;
called Janapada also in 6. 18. 14; 6. 114.
77.
B. Description: Brave (शूर) 4.
31. 10; 4. 32. 25; 6. 18. 14; 6. 20. 15; 9.
13. 1; heroic (वीर) 7. 16. 23; very strong
(महाबल) 4. 31. 2; (अतिबल) 8. 5. 18;
difficult to be defeated (दुर्जय) 8. 5. 18;
high-souled (महात्मन्) 6. 78. 13; skilled
in archery (कृतास्त्र) 6. 20. 15; arrogant in
battles (युद्धदुर्मद) 4. 31. 2; doing
cruel acts (क्रूरकारिन्) 7. 99. 5; holding
iron clubs in hands (परिघबाहु) 4. 31.
10; proficient in warfare (युद्धविशारद)
7. 99. 5; high-ranking chariot-fighters
(महारथ) 4. 24. 8; 9. 13. 1; 11. 26. 36;
14. 73. 31; (महारथसमाज्ञात) 14.
73. 1; (Nī. on Bom. Ed. 14. 74. 1:
महारथत्वेन सम्यग् आज्ञातैः); exce-
llent chariot-fighters (रथोदार) 5. 163.
9; leaders of Kṣatriyas (क्षत्रियाणाम्
धुरंधराः) 5. 163. 13; great archers
(महेष्वास) 8. 7. 18; their standards
made of gold (सुवर्णविकृतध्वज)
7. 91. 14; 7. 116. 2; their arrows
decked with gold (शरा … कार्तस्वरवि-
भूषिताः) 9. 13. 5; readiness to die in battle
considered as doing one's duty (कृत-
कृत्यास् तनुत्यजः) 7. 16. 24; (तनुत्यजः)
6. 18. 14;
C. Epic events: (1) After
killing Hiḍimba, Pāṇḍavas and Kuntī
crossed Matsya, Trigarta, Pāñcāla and
Kīcaka countries before they reached
Ekacakrā 1. 144. 2; (2) Arjuna conquer-
ed Trigartas in his expedition to the
north 2. 24. 1 (व्यजयत् … त्रिगर्तान्)
2. 24. 16-17; (3) Mentioned among
those who were brought under control
by Nakula in his expedition to the west
2. 29. 2, 6; (4) The princely Trigartas
(राजन्याः) brought tribute in hundreds
for the राजसूय of Yudhiṣṭhira 2. 48. 13,
16; (5) The spies of Duryodhana saw
the Trigarta brothers, who were formerly
defeated by Kīcaka, seated with Duryo-
dhana in his Sabhā 4. 24. 8, 19; (6) Suśar-
man suggested to Duryodhana a joint ex-
pedition by Kauravas and Trigartas against
Matsyas to capture their cattle; Duryodhana
suggested that Suśarman, with Trigartas,
should first attack the country of Matsyas
4. 29. 11, 23; the cowherds (गोपाः)
reported to Virāṭa the capture of cows by
hundreds and thousands by Trigartas 4.
30. 7; (7) Matsyas attacked Trigartas at
sunset; Matsyas and Trigartas, both long-
ing for the cows, fought with one another;
they battled with swords, परिघस्, lances,
शक्तिस् and तोमरस्; Śatānīka and Viśālā-
kṣa entered the large army of the chariot-
fighters of Trigartas; Virāṭa attacked
Suśarman of Trigartas 4. 31. 1-2, 9, 15-16,
18; when Virāṭa was captured, Matsyas,
afflicted by Trigartas, fled in fear; Bhīma,
Nakula and Sahadeva marched against
Trigartas; they broke the army of Trigartas;
Yudhiṣṭhira killed a thousand Trigartas,
Bhīma and Nakula seven hundred each,
and Sahadeva three hundred warriors of
Trigartas; Suśarman, the king of Trigartas,
was captured by Bhīma; then, the army
of Trigartas was scattered (अभज्यत बलं
सर्वं त्रैगर्तम्) 4. 32. 10, 22, 24-25,
32-33; (8) Uttara complained to Arjuna
that his father had taken the entire army
with him to fight with the Trigartas 4. 36.
15; (9) Duryodhana reminded Bhīṣma
that they had gone out to fight with
Matsyas for the sake of Trigartas (त्रिगर्-
तानां … हेतोः) 4. 42. 9; (10) Virāṭa,
after defeating Trigartas, entered his town;
he knew that Kurus, after the defeat
of Trigartas, would not sit idle; he there-
fore ordered the warriors, who were not
wounded by Trigartas, to go to help
Uttara (ये त्रिगर्तैर् अविक्षताः) 4. 63. 2.
10-11; (11) Principal Trigarta warriors
were among those who sided with
Duryodhana to fight against Pāṇḍavas
(त्रिगर्ताश् च मुख्याः) 5. 30. 23; (12)
The five Kekaya brothers on the side of
the Pāṇḍavas were to fight, among others,
with two chief Trigarta brothers who
were among the Saṃśaptakas (त्रिगर्तानां
च द्वौ मुख्यौ यौ तौ संशप्तकाव् इति)
5. 56. 18; the sons of Draupadī were to fight
with the five Trigarta (brothers) 5. 161. 8;
(13) Before the start of war, Trigartas
mentioned among the twelve Janapadas
who with their large armies of chariot-
fighters (महता रथवंशेन) were to
protect Bhīṣma 6. 18. 13-14; (14) On the
first day of war, brave Trigartas were ready
to take on Arjuna (येनार्जुनस् तेन …
प्रयाता … ) 6. 20. 15; (15) On the second
day, Duryodhana wanted to protect Bhīṣma
with the help of Trigartas and others
6. 47. 7; (16) On the third day, Trigar-
tas stood at the head of the Garuḍavyūha
of the Kauravas 6. 52. 2, 4; (17) On
the fourth day, Trigartas were among
those who attacked Arjuna and Abhi-
manyu 6. 57. 12; (18) On the fifth day,
when Arjuna attacked Bhīṣma, Trigartas
and others, afraid, took shelter with the
king of Kaliṅga 6. 67. 13; the same day
Nakula fought with the high-ranking
chariot-fighters of Trigartas (त्रिगर्तानां
रथोदारैः) 6. 68. 7; (19) On the seventh
day, Bhīṣma was surrounded on all
sides by Trigartas when he marched ahead
to attack Arjuna 6. 78. 13; (20) On
the ninth day, Duryodhana, with Trigartas
standing on all sides, took position in the
middle of the Sarvatobhadravyūha 6. 95.
31, 26; even though Trigartas were getting
killed by Arjuna they, risking their life,
attacked Arjuna and showered him with
arrows; Arjuna then released Vāyavyāstra
on them 6. 98. 14-15, 18; (21) On the
tenth day, Bhīma and Arjuna harassed the
large army of Trigartas (अपीडयेतां
समरे त्रिगर्तानां महद् बलम्) 6. 110.
8; incited by Duryodhana (6. 112. 102-
107), Trigartas attacked Arjuna as do
moths the flame of fire (पतङ्गा इव पाव-
कम्) 6. 112. 110; Trigartas were among
the twelve Janapadas who did not abandon
Bhīṣma although they were pierced by
arrows and afflicted by wounds (शरार्ता
व्रणपी दिताः) 6. 114. 77; (22) On the ele-
venth day, Karṇa led Trigartas and other
warriors who formed the Śakaṭavyūha
7. 6. 6, 15; (23) Kṛṣṇa's defeating the
Trigartas mentioned by Dhṛtarāṣṭra to
Saṃjaya 7. 10. 17; (24) On the twelfth
day, Satyaratha vowed that by the end of
that day the earth would be either with-
out Arjuna or without the Trigartas
(specifically the five Trigarta brothers:
Satyaratha, Satyadharman, Satyavarman,
Satyeṣu and Satyakarman) (अद्यास्त्व् अनर्-
जुना भूमिर् अत्रिगर्ताथ वा पुनः) 7. 16.
16-18; that day, Arjuna left to fight with
Trigartas 7. 16. 47; Suśarman with his five
brothers and an अयुत chariot-fighters took
an oath in the presence of fire to kill
Arjuna; the mode of taking oath descri-
bed 7. 16. 19-36; Arjuna was first surprised
to see Traigartaka brothers delighted when
they should have wept, but then felt that
Traigartas were delighted because they
would attain best worlds (after death);
he then assailed the army of Traigartas
which was ready in a formation (भ्रा-
तॄंस् त्रैगर्तकान् … अथ वा हर्षकालो ऽयं
त्रैगर्तानाम् असंशयम् … आससाद रणे
व्यूढां त्रैगर्तानाम् अनीकिनीम्) 7. 17.
5-7; Traigartas afraid when Sudhanvan
was killed by Arjuna (त्रैगर्तान् भयम्
आविशत्) 7. 17. 25; they were confused when
they were being killed by Arjuna; Suśar-
man exhorted them to take courage and
fight in accordance with the oath taken
by them; they then returned to fight till
death 7. 17. 26-31; Arjuna harassed Trigr-
tas and others with his arrows and killed
them; they in return showered arrows so
that neither he, his chariot, not Kṛṣṇa
could be seen; Trigartas, feeling that Kṛṣṇa
and Arjuna were killed, shook with delight
their upper garments (वासांस्य् आदुधुवुस्
तदा) and blew by thousands भेरिस्,
मृदङ्गस् and conches 7. 18. 16-20;
of the fourteen thousand Saṃśaptaka
warriors (who had taken oath) who
attacked Arjuna, ten thousand were Tri-
gartas (and four thousand Gopālas) 7.
26. 10-11; (25) On the fourteenth day,
Duryodhana, accompanied by a striking
force of a thousand chariot-fighters of
Trigartas, went to attack Arjuna (रथा-
नां च सहस्रेण त्रिगर्तानां प्रहारिणां)
7. 69. 72; when Niramitra (son of Suśar-
man) was killed a great roar of grief
went up from the Trigartas 7. 82. 27-29;
Sātyaki saw that the excellent Trigarta
chariot-fighters (त्रिगरतानां रथोदाराः)
stood in readiness to fight with him; so
he asked his charioteer to drive his chariot
to them so that he could engage them in a
battle in the presence of Droṇa (त्रिगर्तैः
सह योत्स्यामि भारद्वाजस्य पश्यतः)
7. 91. 14-15; when Duḥśāsana was covered
with arrows, Duryodhana asked Trigartas
to attack Sātyaki; three thousand Trigar-
tas, skilled in warfare, then surrounded
Sātyaki; Sātyaki killed five hundred of
them; afraid, they took shelter with
Droṇa 7. 99. 4-13; when Duḥśāsana lost
his chariot, the general of the Trigarta
army took him away in his chariot
7. 99. 25; a host of Trigarta archers, fight-
ing from chariots, surrounded Sātyaki;
Sātyaki, alone, defeated fifty (Trigarta)
princes; Trigartas, afflicted, returned to
their own people (त्रिगर्ताः संन्यवर्-
तन्त संतप्ताः स्वजनं प्रति) 7. 116. 2;
(26) During the night war, Yudhiṣṭhira
killed a number of Trigartas 7. 132. 23;
(त्रैगर्तकान्) 7. 136. 3; Duryodhana
asked the surviving great warriors among
Trigartas to stay in front of Droṇa (त्रि-
गर्तानां च ये शूरा हतशिष्टा महा-
रथाः) 7. 139. 19; (27) Dhṛtarāṣṭra
remembered that Karṇa had formerly
defeated Trigartas 8. 5. 18; (28) On the
sixteenth day, Kṛpa, along with Trigartas,
stood at the place of the right foot of
the Makaravyūha of the Kauravas 8. 7.
18, 14; Trigartas and others, along with
Kauravas marched against Arjuna; they did
not abandon fighting with Arjuna though
they got killed by him (ते वध्यमानाः
समरे नाजहुः पाण्डवं तदा) 8. 19. 2, 7;
in the afternoon of that day (अपराह्णे)
Arjuna killed Trigartas 8. 19. 74-75; (29)
On the seventeenth day, when Ulūka lost
his horse and charioteer, he jumped down
from his chariot and took shelter with the
large army of Trigartas (त्रिगर्तानां बलं
पूर्णं जगाम) 8. 44. 41; (30) On the
eighteenth day, Kṛtavarman, with Trigartas
all around him, stood on the left side of
the Sarvatobhadravyūha of the Kauravas
9. 7. 24, 19; Arjuna was pierced with many
arrows by Aśvatthāman and by the great
Trigarta chariot-fighters (त्रिगतानां महा-
रथैः); they did not leave fighting with
Arjuna though they were getting killed with
sharp arrows 9. 13. 1, 3; Arjuna attacked
Trigartas and killed their horses and
broke their chariots; then the great
chariot-fighters of Trigartas gathered to-
gether and showered arrows on Kṛṣṇa and
Arjuna 9. 26. 34-35; (31) Vidura and
others cremated the dead bodies of the
great Trigarta chariot-fighters (त्रिगर्तांश्
च महारथान्) 11. 26. 36; (32) Arjuna,
while following the Aśvamedha horse, had
to fight with the sons and grand-sons of
Trigartas, famous as महारथस्, with
whom he had formed enmity during the
great war; at one stage the Traigartaka
warriors encircled Arjuna; (the battle des-
cribed in 14. 73. 3-33) (जिष्नुं त्रैगर्तका
योधास् त्वरिताः पर्यवारयन्) 14. 73. 1,
27; afflicted by Arjuna's arrows, dejected,
they fled in all directions (त्रैगर्तक-
महारथाः।दिशो विदुद्रुवुः सर्वा … )
14. 73. 31; ultimately they all surrendered
(तव स्म किंकराः सर्वे सर्वे च वशगास्
तव) 14. 73. 32-33.
D. Various persons,
especially Suśarman (who is not always
directly mentioned), referred to as the
king of Trigartas or chief warrior of Tri-
gartas, or simply as belonging to Trigartas;
त्रिगर्तराज्: Suśarman 7. 17. 27; 6. 81. 10;
6. 98. 10; त्रिगर्तराज: (1) Kṣemaṃkara
3. 249. 6; (2) Suratha 3. 255. 18; (3)
Suśarman 3. 249. 6; 3. 255. 18; 4. 32. 32;
6. 77. 3, 34; 6. 81. 4, 8; 6. 98. 13; 6. 104.
57; 7. 82. 27; 8. 19. 4; त्रिगर्तराजन्: Suśar-
man (त्रिगर्तानां राजा) 4. 29. 1; Sūrya-
varman 14. 73. 9; त्रिगर्ताधिपति: (1)
Satyaratha 7. 16. 11 (17); (2) Suśarman
4. 32. 7; 6. 100. 10; 7. 27. 6, 8; 9. 2.
18; 9. 26. 16; त्रिगर्तानां महारथः:
(1) Vīradhanvan 7. 82. 18; (2) Suśar-
man 4. 32. 33; त्रिगर्त: Suśarman 6.
83. 10, 11; 6. 109. 47; 7. 16. 19; 9. 2.
34 (त्रिगर्तश् च जनाधिपः); त्रैगर्त:
Suśarman 4. 32. 4, 30; 6. 100. 8; त्रैगर्ती
(f.) Yaśodharā, princess of Trigarta 1.
90. 37 [See Prasthala, Saṃśaptaka].

त्रैपुर
Traipura m. (pl.): Designation of
the warriors of Tripura.
On the eighth day of war, Traipuras
accompanied Bṛhadbala, king of Kosala,
who stood behind Bhagadatta in the
Mahāvyūha (6. 83. 5) of the Kauravas
(कौसल्यो थ बृहद्बलः।त्रैपुरैश्
चैव … समन्वितः) 6. 83. 9.

त्र्यक्ष
Tryakṣa m. (pl.): Name of a people
(having three eyes ?).
Mentioned among those who brought
tribute in the form of gold and silver in
large quantities for the Rājasūya, but
were stopped at the gate (बल्यर्थं
ददतस् तस्मै हिरण्यं रजतं बहु)
2. 47. 15-16 (Nī. on Bom. Ed. 2. 51. 17:
द्व्यक्षादयः प्राच्यदेशभेदाः).

त्र्यङ्ग
Tryaṅga m. (pl.): Name of a Jana-
pada.
Mentioned by Saṃjaya among the
southern Janapadas (also called Deśas 6.
10. 68) of the Bhāratavarṣa (अथापरे
जनपदा दक्षिणा …  6. 10. 56, 5); (त्र्यङ्गाः
केकरकाः प्रोष्ठाः) 6. 10. 60.

दक्षिणमल्ल
Dakṣiṇamalla m. (pl.): Name of a
people.
A. Location: In the east: Bhīma
encountered them in his expedition to the
east of Indraprastha before the Rājasūya
(2. 23. 9; 2. 26. 1, 7); the southern Mallas
are distinguished from the northern and
the most northern Mallas (सोत्तमान् अपि
चोत्तरान् मल्लानाम् अधिपम्) 2. 27. 3.
B.
Epic event: Bhīma, in his expedition to
the east, expeditiously defeated them
without having to use much force (ततो
दक्षिणमल्लांश् च … तरसैवाजयद् भी मो
नातितीव्रेण कर्मणा) 2. 27. 11 [See Malla,
Mallarāṣṭra; and Uttamamalla and Uttara-
malla in Addenda].

दक्षिनापथ
Dakṣināpatha m. (pl.): Name of the
southern region; its people referred to as
दक्षिणापथवासिन् (5. 19. 23).
A. Characteristics: The people of
Dakṣiṇāpatha are described as very heroic
(महावीर्य) 5. 19. 23; Talavaras, Andhra-
kas and others born in Dakṣiṇāpatha
(दक्षिणापथजन्मानः) did not believe
in Dhātṛ or Bhūtapati as being the
अध्यक्ष of all the beings (12. 200. 33, 38);
they are sinful; they roam over the earth;
they lead the life of dogs, crows, बलस् (?),
and vultures; they did not exist in the
Kṛta age but are to be met with since
the Tretāyuga 12. 200. 39-42 (for citation
see Andhraka).
B. Epic event: King
Nīla of Māhiṣmatī, along with the heroic
warriors of Dakṣiṇāpatha, joined the army
of Duryodhana (दक्षिणापथवासिभिः) 5.
19. 23.
C. Past event: Nala showed to
Damayanti many paths which led to
Dakṣiṇāpatha (एते गच्छन्ति बहवः पन्-
थानो दक्षिणापथम्) 3. 58. 20 [See
Dākṣiṇātya].

दण्डक
Daṇḍaka m. (pl.): Name of a people.
A. Location: South: they were en-
countered by Sahadeva in the south
(प्रययौ दक्षिणां दिशम्) 2. 28. 1, 8, 37;
B. Epic event: They were subjugated
by Sahadeva in his expedition before the
Rājasūya (वशे चक्रे … दण्डकांश् च
महाबलः) 2. 28. 43;
C. Past event:
Their large kingdom was destroyed by a
Brāhmaṇa 13. 138. 11.

दरद
Darada m. (pl.): Name of a people.
A. Location: North: Arjuna defeated
them along with Kāmbojas in his conquest
of the north (2. 23. 9; 2. 24. 1) 2. 24. 22;
listed by Saṃjaya among the northern
म्लेच्छ peoples (उत्तराश् चापरे म्लेच्छा
जना … शूद्राभीराथ दरदाः) 6. 10. 63,
66; also see
E. Epic Events No. 3. below.
B. Origin: They arose from the foam of
the cow of Vasiṣṭha (तथैव दरदान् म्ले-
च्छान् फेनतः सा ससर्ज ह) 1. 165. 36;
Daradas mentioned among those Kṣatriyas
who became वृषलस् due to not respect-
ing Brāhmaṇas 13. 35. 17-18.
C. Characte-
risation: म्लेच्छस् 1. 165. 36; 6. 10. 63, 66;
7. 95. 13.
D. Description: (1) Having
faces like those of goats (बस्तमुख) 7.
97. 39; holding iron weapons and spears
in hands (अयोहस्त, शूलहस्त) 7. 97. 39;
very difficult to be conquered (सुदुर्जय)
7. 10. 17.
E. Epic events: (1) Arjuna
defeated them in his expedition before the
Rājasūya 2. 24. 22; (2) Mentioned among
those Kṣatriyas (क्षत्रियाः 2. 48. 16;
राजन्याः 2. 48. 13) who brought riches by
hundreds as tribute for Yudhiṣṭhira's
Rājasūya (आहार्षुः क्षत्रिया वित्तं शतशो
जातशत्रवे) 2. 48. 12, 16; they were
among those who acted as servers at the
Rājasūya (यज्ञे ते परिवेषकान्) 3. 48. 20,
22; (3) Pāṇḍavas had to cross their
country before they could reach Subāhu's
realm from Badarī 3. 174. 12; (4) Dru-
pada suggested to Pāṇḍavas to send messen-
gers to the kings of Daradas to seek their
help in war 5. 4. 15; (5) On the second
day of war, Daradas (on the side of the
Pāṇḍavas) stood at the right side of the
Krauñcāruṇavyūha (6. 46. 39; Krauñca
6. 47. 1) of the Pāṇḍavas (दरदाश् चैव
 … दुक्षिणं पक्षम् आश्रिताः) 6. 46. 49-50;
(6) On the same day, Duryodhana with
Daradas (on the side of the Kauravas)
and others protected the army of Śakuni
(दरदैश् … अभ्यरक्षत सौबलेयस्य
वाहिनीम्) 6. 47. 16; (7) On the tenth
day, Daradas, instigated by Duryodhana,
attacked Arjuna to protect Bhīṣma 6. 112.
109; (8) On the twelfth day, Daradas
were posted at the neck of the Suparṇa-
vyūha (7. 19. 4) of Kauravas 7. 19. 8;
(9) On the fourteenth day, Daradas were
among those who were killed in large
numbers by Arjuna 7. 68. 42-43; (10) On
the same day, Sātyaki asked his charioteer
to take him where Daradas, fighting with
varied weapons (विविधायुधपाणयः)
were posted to face him 7. 95. 13; Sātyaki
repulsed with his नाराच arrows the stones
hurled at him (अश्मवृष्टिम्) repeatedly by
Daradas 7. 97. 35; (11) On the seventeenth
day, Daradas were among those who
survived to fight for Duryodhana; according
to Kṛṣṇa they could not be conquered by
any one except Arjuna (न शक्या युधी
निर्जेतुं त्वदन्येन परंतप) 8. 51. 18,
20; (12) Kṛṣṇa had once defeated
Daradas (दरदांश् च … जितवान् पुण्डरी-
काक्षो … ) 7. 10. 17-18.

दर्व
Darva m. (pl.): Name of a Janapada
and its people.
Listed by Saṃjaya among the northern
Janapadas (also called Deśas 6. 10. 68)
of Bhāratavarṣa 6. 10. 37, 5; (दर्वीकाः
सकचा दर्वा … ) 6. 10. 53 (is सकचाः
name of a Janapada or description of
Darvīkas and Darvas ?); mentioned among
those Kṣatriyas who were degraded to the
status of वृषल due to their not res-
pecting Brāhmaṇas (वृषलत्वम् अनुप्राप्ता
ब्राह्मणानाम् अदर्शनात्) 13. 35. 17-18.
[See Darvīka and Dārva].

दर्वीक
Darvīka m. (pl.): Name of a Jana-
pada.
Listed by Saṃjaya among the northern
Janapadas (also called Deśas 6. 10. 68) of
Bhāratavarṣa 6. 10. 37, 5; (दर्वीकाः सकचा
दर्वा … ) 6. 10. 53 (for सकचाः see above
Darva).

दर्शक
Darśaka m. (pl.): Name of a Jana-
pada.
Listed by Saṃjaya among the northern
Janapadas (also called Deśas 6. 10. 68) of
Bhāratavarṣa 6. 10. 37, 5; (गान्धारा दर्श-
कास् तथा) 6. 10. 52.

दशमालिक
Daśamālika m. (pl.): Name of one
of the म्लेच्छ tribes.
Listed by Saṃjaya among the nor-
thern म्लेच्छस् of Bhāratavarṣa 6. 10. 5;
(उत्तराश् चापरे म्लेच्छा जना भरत-
सत्तम) 6. 10. 63; (तथैव दशमालिकाः)
6. 10. 65; described as fierce (दारुणा
म्लेच्छजातयः) 6. 10. 64.

दशापार्श्व
Daśāpārśva m. (pl.): Name of a
Janapada.
Listed by Saṃjaya among the northern
Janapadas (also called Deśas 6. 10. 68) of
Bhāratavarṣa 6. 10. 37, 5; (वानायवो दशा-
पार्श्वा … ) 6. 10. 54.

दशार्ण
Daśārṇa m. (pl.): Name of a Jana-
pada and its people; the people or warriors
of Daśārṇa also referred to as Dāśārṇa
or Dāśārṇaka (f. -ikā).
A. Location: Listed by Saṃjaya
among the northern Janapadas (also called
Deśas 6. 10. 68) of Bhāratavarṣa (अत
ऊर्ध्वं जनपदान् निबोध) 6. 10. 37, 5;
उत्तमौजा दशार्णाश् च 6. 10. 39; mention-
ed as Janapada also in 4. 1. 9; were there
two Daśārṇas: (1) one to the east
of Hāstinapura, and (2) another to its
south ?: (1) Bhīmasena in his conquest
of the east (2. 26. 1, 7) reached Daśārṇa
country after crossing Gaṇḍakī river and
conquering the Videhas (ततः स गण्ड-
कीं शूरो विदेहांश् च … ।विजित्य … दशा-
र्णान् अगमत् प्रभुः) 2. 26. 4; the name
of their king was Sudharman (तत्र
दाशार्णको राजा सुधर्मा) 2. 26. 5; (2)
Daśārṇa also mentioned as surrounding
the Kurus (परितः कुरून्) 4. 1. 9; before
reaching the Matsya country Pāṇḍavas
had to go along the north of Daśārṇa
and the south of Pāñcāla (उत्तरेण
दशार्णांस् ते पाञ्चालान् दक्षिणेन तु) 4.
5, 3; the name of their king was Hiraṇya-
varman (स राजा दशार्णेषु … हिरण्य-
वर्मा) 5. 190. 11.
B. Description:
Pleasing (रम्य) and rich in harvest
(बह्वन्न) 4. 1. 9; sinful (आगस्कृत्) 1. 105.
8 (Nī. on Bom. Ed. 1. 113. 25: आगस्कृतः
चोरप्रायाः पर्वताद्याश्रयित्वात्); skilled
in fighting while riding elephants (गज-
योधिनः, गजयुद्धेषु कुशलाः) 8. 17.
2-3; their name contains the word
दश (?) (दशेरका दश दाशा दशार्णाः)
3. 134. 16.
C. Epic events: (1) Pāṇḍu
in his expedition after his marriage with
Kuntī conquered first the Daśārṇas 1. 105.
8; (2) Kṛṣṇa told Karṇa that if he were
to join Pāṇḍavas, Dāśārṇas would form
part of his retinue (परिवारास् ते दाशार्णाश्
च) 5. 138. 23; (3) On the second day
of war, Dāśārṇakas (on the side of
Pāṇḍavas) were stationed at the neck
(दाशार्णकाः … ग्रीवायाम्) of the Krauñcā-
ruṇavyūha of Pāṇḍavas 6. 46. 33, 46; (4)
On that day the Daśārṇas (on the side
of the Kauravas), led by Droṇa, followed
Bhīṣma who was at the head of their
Mahāvyūha 6. 47. 10, 12; (5) On the
sixteenth day, instigated by Duryodhana,
Daśārṇas riding elephants attacked Dhṛṣṭa-
dyumna 8. 17. 3; (6) The Aśvamedha
horse visited the Daśārṇas 14. 84. 5.
D. Past event: Damayantī born in the
Daśārṇa country (त्वं तु जाता … दशा-
र्णेषु) 3. 66. 13.
E. Different person(s)
referred to variously: (i) King of
Daśārṇas: दशार्ण Hiraṇyavarman 6. 91.
44; दशार्णराज Hiraṇyavarman 5. 190. 21;
(also called Kāñcanavarman 5. 190. 20);
5. 193. 26; राजा दशार्णानाम् 7. 25. 28;
राजा दशार्णेषु 5. 190. 11; दशार्णपति
Hiraṇyavarman 5. 192. 8; 5. 193. 20;
दशार्णाधिपति (1) Hiraṇyavarman 5. 190.
8, 16; 5. 192. 3; 5. 193. 11, 13; 6. 91. 23,
39, 42; 7. 25. 30; (2) Sudāman 3. 66.
12; दाशार्ण Hemavarman 5. 192. 12;
5. 193. 6; दाशार्णक (1) Hiraṇyavarman
5. 190. 9, 10, 19; (2) Sudharman 2. 26.
5; दाशार्णनृप Hiraṇyavarman 5. 193. 15;
(ii) Messenger of Daśārṇa country: दूतं
दाशार्णम् 5. 191. 11; (iii) Nurses of
Daśārṇa country: धात्र्यो दाशार्णिकास् …
5. 190. 15.

दशार्ह
Daśārha, Dāśārha m. (pl.): Name of
a country and its people.
A. Description: Strong and large in
number (बलवन्तश् च दाशार्हा बहवश्
च) 1. 197. 25.
B. Characteristic: Dāśā-
rhas did not try to save their life in war
(न हि … दाशार्हा रणे रक्षन्ति जीवितम्);
they did not go the way the cowards and
the unrighteous do, i. e. they did not
avoid war; during the war they remained
steadfast and did not run away from the
battlefield (अयुद्धम् अनवस्थानं सं-
ग्रामे च पलायनम्।भीरूणाम् असतां
मार्गो नैष दाशार्हसेवितः॥ 7. 85. 95-96;
Nī. on Bom. Ed. 7. 110. 98: अनवस्थानम्
अस्थैर्यम्).
C. Epic events: (1) Vidura
told Dhṛtarāṣṭra that if Kṛṣṇa sided with
Pāṇḍavas, the Dāśārha people (दाशार्हाः)
would join him 1. 197. 25; (2) Nārada
took leave of Yudhiṣṭhira to go to the
town of the Dāśārha people (दाशार्ह-
नगरीं प्रति) 2. 11. 71; (3) When Pra-
dyumna was about to put his excellent
arrow to the bow for discharging it against
Śālva, all the Dāśārha warriors honoured
it with blessings (तम् अर्चितं सर्वदा-
शार्हपूगैः आशीर्भिर् … शरं ज्याम् अभि-
नीयमानम्) 3. 20. 20; (4) When the
Dāśārha people (दशार्हाः) saw the condi-
tion of the Pāṇḍavas in forest, they
shed tears due to grief 3. 118. 23; (5)
Sātyaki desired the army of Daśārha
warriors (दशार्हसेना) to attack Kaura-
vas 3. 120. 5; but Yudhiṣṭhira desired the
Daśārha heroes (दशार्हवीराः) to return
to their country (and not march against
Kauravas) 3. 120. 28; (6) Kṛṣṇa assured
Yudhiṣṭhira that the Daśārha fighters
would carry out the latter's orders (दशा-
र्हयोधाः … निदेशं तव पालयन्ति) 3.
180. 21; he suggested that Hāstinapura with
Dāśārha army consisting of horse-riders
and foot-soldiers might wait for his return
to Hāstinapura (दाशार्हयोधैस् तु ससादि-
योधं प्रतीक्षताम् नागपुरं भवन्-
तम्) 3. 180. 34; (7) Arjuna brought
with him to Upaplavya the Dāśārha people
from Ānarta (आनर्तेभ्यो ऽपि दाशार्हान्) 4.
67. 15; (8) Arjuna returned to Yudhiṣṭhira
along with Kṛṣṇa and excellent Dāśārha
persons (दाशार्हप्रवरैः) 5. 7. 36; (9)
Bhīṣma and Droṇa wanted Duryodhana
to make peace with Pāṇḍavas so that all
kings headed by Dāśārha (= Kṛṣṇa ?)
might shed tears of joy (दाशार्हप्रमुखा
नृपाः) 5. 136. 17; (10) If Karṇa were
to join the Pāṇḍavas, Dāśārha people
would form part of his retinue (दाशार्हाः
परिवारास् ते) 5. 138. 23; (11) The people
of Daśārha country (दाशार्हाः) were angry
when they saw Durvāsas yoking Rukmiṇī
to a chariot and driving it in the city 13.
144. 27.
D. Kṛṣṇa variously called as
one belonging to the Daśārha country, the
delighter, or protector, or king etc. of
Daśārha people: (1) दशार्हनाथ 8. 12.
67; (2) दशार्हभर्ता 3. 180. 23; (3)
दशार्हसिंह 3. 180. 22; (4) दशार्हाधि-
पति 3. 24. 1; (5) दाशार्ह 3. 23. 46; 5. 90.
25; 5. 136. 17 (?); 8. 22. 47, 54; 8. 42. 57;
(6) दाशार्हकुलनन्दन 12. 52. 9; दाशार्ह-
नन्दन 1. 214. 26; (7) सर्वदाशार्ह-
मुख्य 8. 45. 67.
E. Princesses of the
Daśārha country: दाशार्ही: (1) Jayā 1.
90. 35 (2) Śubhāṅgī 1. 90. 41; (3)
Sudevā 1. 90. 38; (4) Śiśupāla's mother,
(not named) 11. 25. 22;
F. The Sabhā
of the Daśārha people; दाशार्ही 2. 3. 24.
[See Yādava, Vṛṣṇi].

दशेरक
Daśeraka, Dāśeraka m. (pl. sg.):
Name of a country, and its people.
A. Name explained: The name con-
tains the word ‘ten’ (दश) (दशेरका
दश दाशा दशार्णाः) 3. 134. 16.
B. Epic
events: (1) On the second day of war,
hosts of Dāṣerakas stood at the ‘neck’
(ग्रीवायाम्) of the Krauñcāruṇavyūha 6.
46. 39 (Krauñca 6. 47. 1) of the Pāṇḍavas
(दाशेरकगणैः सह) 6. 46. 46; (2)
On the third day, equipped (दंशिताः),
they stood at the right wing (दक्षिणं
पक्षम् आसाद्य) of the Garuḍavyūha (6.
52. 2) of Kauravas (दाशेरकगणैः सह)
6. 52. 8; (3) On the tenth day, instigated
by Duryodhana, they attacked Arjuna to
protect Bhīṣma (दाशेरकगणैः सह) 6.
112. 108; (4) On the twelfth day, Daśe-
rakas (दशेरकाः) occupied the ‘neck’
of the Suparṇavyūha (7. 19. 8-9) of the
Kauravas 7. 19. 7; (5) Dhṛtarāṣṭra men-
tioned among Kṛṣṇa's exploits, his victory
over Daśerakas (दशेरकान् … जितवान् पुण्ड-
रीकाक्षः) 7. 10. 16, 18.

दस्यु
Dasyu m. (pl.): Designation of a
class of people following a mode of life not
approved by the law-makers; sometimes
(especially in the Śāntiparvan) the term
designates robbers; they moved in groups,
hence sometimes referred to as दस्युगण।
A. Location: Lived in the north-east
(प्रागुत्तरां दिशं ये च वसन्त्य् आश्रित्य
दस्यवः) 2. 24. 23; lived on mountains
(दस्यून् पर्वतवासिनः) 2. 24. 15; lived
in forests (अप्य् अरण्यं समाश्रित्य चरेद्
दस्युगणैः सह) 12. 131. 10.
B. Des-
cription: Their heads shaven (लूनमूर्-
धज) 7. 95. 40; sinful (पापकर्मन्), their
minds obsessed by avarice (लोभोपहतचे-
तस्), and their sight inauspicious (अशुभ-
दर्शन) 16. 8. 45; cruel (क्रूर) 8. 49.
43; used sticks as weapons (यष्टिप्रह-
रण) 16. 8. 47.
C. Relations with other
tribes: Ocassionally referred to as Śabara
(तत्रावसत् … शबरालये) 12. 162. 34; (वासो
मे शबरालये) 12. 162. 5; Yavanas,
Kirātas, Gāndhāras, and many other tribes
led the life of Dasyus (सर्वे ते दस्युजी-
विनः) 12. 65. 13-15.
D. Their degraded
status in society revealed in many ways:
(1) By comparing men who behaved
improperly or unlawfully with Dasyus: (i)
A poor man's begging is like an attack;
he thereby annoys others like a Dasyu
(याञ्चाम् आहुर् अनीशस्य अभिहारं च
भारत।उद्वेजयति याचन् हि सदा भूतानि
दस्युवत्॥) 13. 59. 4 (Nī. on Bom.
Ed. 13. 60. 4: अनीशस्य दरिद्रस्य। but
अभिहारं तिरस्कारम्); (ii) A man of
evil conduct considered mean like a Dasyu
(दुराचारस् तु दुर्बुद्धिर् … दस्युर् इवा-
धमः) 12. 166. 9; (iii) Ignorant men
carry on their heads the burden of सं-
सार by considering the wrong direction
(as the right one) just as the Dasyus
carry on their heads the load of flesh
while following the wrong way (प्रकीर्ण-
मेषभारो हि यद्वत् धार्येत दस्युभिः।
प्रतिलोमां दिशं बुद्ध्वा संसारम्
अबुधास् तथा॥) 12. 208. 13 (Nī. Bom. Ed.
12. 215. 14 reads प्रकीर्णमेषभारं हि
and explains: आमिषभारं वहन्तश् चोराः
गम्यां दिशं राजकीयाद्यवरोधात् प्रति-
कूलां बुध्वा (?) आमिषं त्यक्त्वान्यां
दिशम् गच्छन्तो यथा न बध्यन्ते …
प्रकीर्णमेषः विशस्तमेषः आमिषम् इत्य्
अर्थः क्लीबत्वम् आर्षम् see Editors note
on Vol. 16. p. 2169 where Arjunamiśra's
reading मोष, meaning लोप्त्र ‘stolen pro-
perty’, in place of मेष is preferred); but
just as one should abandon the company of
the Dasyus going the wrong way and follow
the wholesome way, similarly one should
give up doing actions dominated by रजस्
and तमस् and gain happiness (तान् एव च
यथा दस्यून् क्षिप्त्वा गच्छेच् छिवां
दिशम्।तथा रजस्तमःकर्माण्य् उत्सृज्य
प्राप्नुयात् सुखम्) 12. 208. 14; (iv)
According to Maitreya what happened in
the सभा of the Kauravas was like imi-
tating the behaviour of Dasyus (दस्यूनाम्
इव यद् वृत्तं सभायाम्) 3. 11. 17; (v)
Draupadī told Virāṭa that his following
the धर्म of Dasyus (since he did
nothing to check Kīcaka) brought no
credit to his Sabhā (दस्यूनाम् इव
धर्मस् ते न हि संसदि शोभते) 4.
15. 24; (vi) Sātyaki's killing Bhūriśravas
in the unlawful way was choosing the
धर्म of Dasyus 7. 131. 2; (2) By referr-
ing to the unlawful and dangerous acts of
Dasyus: (i) Yavanas, Kirātas and others,
though they lived in towns, followed the
way of Dasyus (सर्वे ते दस्युजीविनः) 12.
65. 15; (ii) Māndhātṛ told Indra that
there were Dasyus living in disguise among
all Varṇas and all the Āśramas (दृश्यन्ते
मानवा लोके सर्ववर्णेषु दस्यवः।
लिङ्गान्तरे वर्तमाना आश्रमेषु चतुर्ष्व्
अपि॥) 12. 65. 23; (iii) Yudhiṣṭhira
asked Bhīṣma how should a Brāhmaṇa,
who did not want to give up his sons and
grandsons, live when the धर्म was at
its lowest ebb, when all means of sub-
sistence were under the control of Dasyus
(सर्वस्मिन् दस्युसाद्भूते पृथिव्याम् उप-
जीवने) 12. 130. 1 (दस्यु is equated with
असाधु in 12. 130. 2-3); 12. 138. 1; 12.
139. 6; (iv) Dasyus have been killing
men since old times thinking ‘they have
wealth’; they torture men inflicting on
them various punishments and always
distress them (धनम् अस्येति पुरुषं
पुरा निघ्नन्ति दस्यवः) 12. 171. 36; (v)
As good men do not take what belongs
to others, so do Dasyus not practise
non-violence; people are pleased with
Dasyus if they observe restraint (यथा
सद्भिः परादानम् अहिंसा दस्युभिस् तथा।
अनुरज्यन्ति भूतानि समर्यादेषु दस्युषु॥
12. 131. 14 (Nī., however, who reads
दस्युभिः कृता on 12. 133. 15: सद्भिर्
दस्युभिः परादानं परस्वहरणम् अपि
कृतम् अहिंसा भवति तथा वक्ष्ये इति
शेषः); (vi) Killing some one when he
is not fighting, violation of wives of others,
ungratefulness, robbing a Brāhmaṇa of
his wealth, leaving him without any posse-
ssions (निःशेषकरणं तथा), robbing
women, coersion (परिस्थानम् cf. Critical
Notes Vol. 14. p. 932), all this is practised
by Dasyus and is censurable; and even
if a Dasyu does not practise such acts,
he is all the same a Dasyu (दस्युष्व् एतद्
विगर्हितम्॥स एष एव भवति दस्युऋ
एतानि वर्जयन्) 12. 131. 15-16 (Nī. on
Bom. Ed. 12. 133. 16: निःशेषकरणम्
सर्वहरणम्); (vii) Death at the hands
of a Dasyu is considered wretched (प्राकृतो
वध उच्यते) and is equated with death
due to poison, hanging, or burns, or
due to getting killed by animals having
jaws 12. 286. 25 (Nī. on Bom. Ed. 12. 297.
25 seems to explain प्राकृत as दुर्म-
रण cf. योगी अत्यन्तव्याधिपीडाग्रस्तो ऽपि
दुर्मरणं नेच्छेद् इत्य् अर्थः); (viii)
Dasyus are the limit; (1) even Dasyus
do not trust in those who act merci-
lessly (दस्यवो ऽप्य् उपशङ्कन्ते निरनु-
क्रोशकारिणः) 12. 131. 11; (2) even
Dasyus trust ascetics (तापसेषु हि विश्वा-
सम् अपि कुर्वन्ति दस्यवः) 12. 87. 28;
(3) The Rākṣasas refused to eat the flesh
of the mean Gautama, and suggested that
it might be distributed among the Dasyus;
but even Dasyus did not wish to eat
the flesh of the sinful and unfaithful
Gautama, nor the beasts of prey 12. 166.
18-19, 22-23; (ix) Dasyus are equated
with impious men; when Dhṛtarāṣṭra,
Pāṇḍu and Vidura were born, there were
no Dasyus in the Kuru land, nor other
impious men (नाभवन् दस्यवः केचिन्
नाधर्मरुचयो जनाः) 1. 102. 5; (x) If
Brāhmaṇas parted company with Kṣatri-
yas, the latter became degraded and were
as good as Dasyus (अपध्वस्ता दस्यु-
भूता भवन्ति ये ब्राह्मणाः क्षत्रियान्
संत्यजन्ति) 12. 74. 10.
E. The Duties
of Dasyus: On being questioned by
Māndhātṛ about the धर्म of Dasyus
(कथं धर्मं चरेयुस् ते 12. 65. 15),
Indra told him in details the duties of
Dasyus which included service (शुष्रूषा)
to parents, teachers, elders, ascetics and
kings, gifts to twice-born, observance of
non-violence, truth, purity, faithfulness
and other virtues 12. 65. 17-22; a Dasyu
who lived within limits did not perish
after his death; this is illustrated by
the narrative of Kāpavya; those Dasyus
who observed their धर्म achieved
perfections (अपि ते दस्यवो भूत्वा क्षि-
प्रं सिद्धिम् अवाप्नुयुः) 12. 133. 1-22.
F. Limitations of Dasyus: They are not
able to overpower a person who has no
desires and one who is free from (the fear
of) loss of wealth (न च दस्यवः।
प्रभवन्ति धनज्यानिनिर्मुक्तस्य निरा-
शिषः) 12. 170. 12.
G. King's relationship
with Dasyus: Indra created for a king
his duty and armour, weapon and bow, for
killing Dasyus (इन्द्रेणेदं दस्युवधाय
कर्म उत्पादितं वर्म शस्त्रं धनुश्
च) 5. 29. 27 (But Nī. on Bom. Ed. 5. 29.
30: कर्म युद्धं); Brahman created
Kṣatriyas for killing Dasyus who obstruct-
ed those that were engaged in agriculture,
cattle-care, trade, and also those who
performed the duties of Hotṛ, Adhvaryu
and Udgātṛ priests (ऊर्ध्वं चैव त्रयी
विद्या) 12. 90. 7-8 (Nī., however, on Bom.
Ed. 12. 89. 7: ऊर्ध्वं स्वर्गम्); a
Kṣatriya should always be ready to kill
Dasyus in battles 12. 60. 14; for a king,
there is no higher duty than destroying
Dasyus 12. 60. 17; their absence, (as
also of beggars), in a kingdom considered
desirable 12. 89. 20; a king should take
his subjects into confidence by drawing
their attention to the danger posed by
his enemies who collaborated with Dasyus
12. 88. 26; a king must protect all the
वर्णस् if the Dasyus tried to plunder
their wives and possessions 13. 47. 44; a
king who saved the beings from Dasyus
and gave them wealth and happiness
was a great king (दस्युभ्यः प्राणदानात्
स धनदः सुखदो विराट्) 12. 98. 8; if
a king did not protect his subjects, they
could be at the mercy of Dasyus (लोको
ऽयं दस्युसाद् भवेत्) 12. 68. 20 (Nī. on
Bom. Ed. 12. 68. 20: दस्युसात् चोराधी-
नाः); if due to a king's negligence his
subjects were being robbed, such a king
was Kali 12. 12. 27; Yudhiṣṭhira wanted
to know if there were boundaries beyond
which he should not allow Dasyus to
step (अस्ति स्विद् दस्युमर्यादा याम् अहं
परिवर्जये) 12. 140. 1 (Nī. on Bom. Ed.
12. 142. 1: दस्यूनाम् अकार्यकारिणाम् अपि
मर्यादा काचिद् अस्ति इतो ऽधिकं दस्यूनां न
कर्तव्यम् इति); when a king behaved dis-
regarding all restraints and in such a state
Dasyus brought about total confusion, then
if all वर्णस् took up weapons (to protect
themselves) no blemish attached to them
(उन्मर्यादे प्रवृत्ते तु दस्युभिः संकरे
कृते।सर्वे वर्णा न दुष्येयुः शस्त्र-
वन्तो … ) 12. 79. 18; if the power of Dasyus
increased (अभ्युत्थिते दस्युबले), then
even a Brāhmaṇa, Vaiśya or Śūdra should
hold the rod of punishment in hand and
protect the subjects from Dasyus; any
one, Śūdra or some one else, whom the
subjects, when tortured by Dasyus, turned
for protection should be honoured (12.
79. 34-35, 38); a king in whose dominion
hordes of Dasyus freely plundered the posse-
ssions of others, as do crows the fishes
in water, was contemptible among the
Kṣatriyas (स वै क्षत्रियपांसनः) 12.
140. 28; Dasyus overpower a kingdom
which has no ruler and which is weak (अनि-
न्द्रम् अबलं राष्ट्रं दस्यवो ऽभिभवन्ति
च) 12. 67. 2 (Nī. on Bom. Ed. 12. 67. 2:
अनिन्द्रं अराजकं अत एवाबलम्); kings
in whose dominion Brāhmaṇas were with-
out proper means of subsistence, their oxen
and draught-animals did not prosper, the
churning pot (i. e. the curds in it) was not
churned (because the pot was empty)
when it was gifted, they became degraded
like Dasyus (नैषाम् उक्षा वर्धते नोत
वाहा न गर्गरो मथ्यते संप्रदाने।अप-
ध्वस्ता दस्युभूता भवन्ति येषां राष्ट्रे
ब्राह्मणा वृत्तिहीनाः) 12. 329. 12 (Nī.
on Bom. Ed. 12. 342. 19: गर्गरः दधी-
क्षुतैलादिनिपीडनयन्त्रम्।येषां राज्ञां
कृष्यादिहीनत्वात् तादृशा राजानो नष्टाश् चोराश्
च भवन्तीत्य् अर्थः; Nī. on Bom. Ed.
12. 68. 23: गर्गरा मन्थन्यः on the
authority of Medinī); if a king and his
Brāhmaṇa Purohita were opposed to each
other, Dasyus took the side of him who was
stronger of the two (अन्वग्बलं दस्यवस्
तद् भजन्ते) 12. 74. 8 (Nī., however, on
Bom. Ed. 12. 73. 7: अनु पश्चात् प्रकाशमा-
नं बलम् अन्वग्बलं यथा स्यात् तथा);
a king might take away the wealth of Dasyus
(and of those who did not perform sacri-
fices) 12. 134. 2; a king should always
kill Dasyus and should not pardon any
one on any account (निहन्यात् सर्वतो
दस्यून् न कामात् कस्यचित् क्षमेत्) 12. 76.
5; Dyumatsena told Satyavant that if
Dasyus were not awarded capital punish-
ment, there would be chaos everywhere;
in the Kali age, one would say: ‘this was
mine, not his’ and normal life would be
impossible (लोकयात्रा न चैव स्यात्) 12.
259. 6 (Nī., however, on Bom. Ed. 12.
267. 6: लोकयात्रा तीर्थगमनवाणिज्या-
दिव्यवहारः कलौ युगे अधर्मप्र-
धाने काले); however, a king should be
careful while giving capital punishment to
Dasyus, because when a Dasyu died, many
other innocents dependent on him, like
his wife, mother, father, son, also got
killed for no fault of theirs (राजा तस्माट्
सम्यक् प्रधारयेत्) 12. 259. 10; but, a
Dasyu, in fact, did not belong to men,
nor to gods, nor to Gandharvas, nor to
Pitṛs; for no one belonged to any one (कः
कस्येह न कश्चन) 12. 259. 21 (Nī. on
Bom. Ed. 12. 267. 21: दस्युवधे तद्-
भार्यादीनां वधो नास्तीत्य् अर्थः।सम्-
बन्धाभावात्); entering into an agreement
(with Dasyus) who were ignorant and of
confused mind was like trying to find a
lotus in a cemetery or godliness in a Piśāca
(i. e. trying to do what was impossible)
(पद्मं श्मशानाद् आदत्ते पिशाचाच् चापि
दैवतम्।तेषु यः समयं कुर्याद् अज्ञेषु
हतबुद्धिषु॥) 12. 259. 22 (Nī., however,
on Bom. Ed. 12. 267. 22: पद्मं शवालङ्-
कार(? °रम्) आदत्ते पिशाचात् पिशाचोपह-
तात्।आदत्ते चैलादिकम् इति शेषः।कीदृशं
समयं दैवतं देवताशपथादिरूपम्।;
also cf. Critical Notes to Vol. 16 (p. 2193)
on 12. 259. 22: “Lotus does not grow in
cemetery, and if it does, it is not consi-
dered as holy. Similarly one does not
expect good conduct or divine grace from
persons possessed by ghosts. Cp. (i. e. the
commentary of Paramānanda Bhaṭṭācārya)
remarks at the end as follows: तद् यथा
पद्मं स्वगुणैर् उत्कृष्टं श्मशानाद्
उपादाय कश्चिच् छिरसि कुर्याद् देवाय वा
दद्यात्, तत्राश्वसीत कः।भाविपिशाचाद्यु
पद्रवाशङ्किचेताः स्यात्-इत्य् अर्थः); a king
who, following the Śāstra, teaches Dasyus
to pay attention to place and time is
not touched by sin (देशकालप्रतीक्षे यो
दस्योर् दर्शयते नृपः।शास्त्रजां बुद्धिम्
आस्थाय नैनसा स हि युज्यते॥) 12. 25. 11
(Nī., however, who reads मर्षयते in
Bom. Ed. 12. 24. 11: मर्षयते दस्यून्
अपि न हन्ति एनसा तज्जेन पापेन); in bad
times, if a king had to take resort to a
forest and live with Dasyus he should
not associate with Dasyus who threw
all norms of behaviour to the winds;
it was easy to raise an army of Dasyus
(of good behaviour) for performing fear-
ful acts (अप्य् अरण्यं समाश्रित्य चरेद्
दस्युगणैः सह।न त्व् एवोद्धृतमर्या-
दैर् दस्युभिः सहितश् चरेत्।दस्यूनां
सुलभा सेना रौद्रकर्मसु भारत) 12.
131. 10 (but Nī. on Bom. Ed. 12. 133. 11:
दस्युभिः दस्युप्रायैर् अमात्यैः); when
a king considered himself more prosperous
than his (Dasyu) adversaries, he should
turn on them and strike the (horde
of) Dasyus without hesitation (यदा बहु-
विधां वृद्धिम् मन्यते प्रतिलोमतः।
तदा विवृत्य प्रहरेद् दस्यूनाम् अविचार-
यन्॥) 12. 104. 38 (Nī. on Bom. Ed. 12.
103. 39: प्रतिलोमतः शत्रोर् अपेक्षया
विवृत्य प्रकटीभूय दस्यूनां दस्यून्);
Dasyus should not thoroughly annihilate
even those who happened to be under their
control; they should not act in a cruel
manner thinking that they were very strong
(तस्मात् सशेषं कर्तव्यं स्वाधीनम्
अपि दस्युभिः।न बलस्थो ऽहम् अस्मीति
नृशंसानि समाचरेत्) 12. 131. 17; Dasyus,
if not forced to remain within certain
limits of behaviour, acted as robbers
(निर्मर्यादा दस्यवस् तु भवन्ति परि-
पन्थिनः) 12. 101. 3 (Nī. on Bom. Ed.
12. 100. 3: ये ऽर्थधर्मयोर् निर्मर्-
यादास् ते परिपन्थीनो नाशका भवन्ति).
H. Epic events: (1) Arjuna, in his
conquest of the north before the Rāja-
sūya, conquered Dasyus who lived on
mountains (दस्यून् पर्वतवासिनः) 2. 24.
15; he also conquered the Dasyus living
in the forest in the northeast (प्रागुत्तरां
दिशम् ये च वसन्त्य् आश्रित्य दस्यवः।
निवसन्ति वने ये च) 2. 24. 23; (2)
Yudhiṣṭhira asked Saṃjaya whether the
Kauravas, if they encountered the bands
of Dasyus, remembered Arjuna 5. 23. 19;
(3) Arjuna told Saṃjaya that when he
would scatter the hordes of Dasyus gather-
ed for the battle, Dhṛtarāṣṭra and his
sons would repent 5. 47. 59; (4) On the
fourteenth day of war, Sātyaki covered
the earth with the shaven heads of Dasyus
together with their headgears 7. 95. 40; he
killed many Dasyus 7. 97. 20; (5) Kṛṣṇa
told Babhru to protect the Yādava women
so that they were not attacked by Dasyus
due to their greed for wealth (नैता हिं-
स्युर् दस्यवो वित्तलोभात्) 16. 5. 4; (6)
When Arjuna stopped at Pañcanada on his
way to Hāstinapura with Vṛṣṇi women,
Dasyus became greedy and took counsel
among themselves; then, thousands of
them, using sticks as weapons, attacked
Vṛṣṇis desirous of looting property; they
disregarded Arjuna's warning and continued
their attack; Arjuna could not check them
as he forgot his अस्त्रस्; the Vṛṣṇi warriors
could not stop Dasyus running away with
Vṛṣṇi women; Arjuna and the Vṛṣṇi
warriors killed some of the plundering
Dasyus with arrows; when Arjuna's arrows
were exhausted, he killed Dasyus with the
tip of his bow; but that was of no avail;
before his very eyes, Dasyus (म्लेच्छस्)
took away Vṛṣṇi and Andhaka women 16.
8. 44-61.
I. Past events: (1) Nahuṣa,
during his rule, had killed hordes of
Dasyus 1. 70. 26; (2) Yayāti pleased the
Dasyus by completely controlling them
(अतर्पयद् … दस्यून् संनिग्रहेण च) 1.
80. 3-4; (3) Dasyus who had stolen wealth,
when pursued by royal guards, reached the
hermitage of Māṇḍavya; they kept the loot
in the आश्रम and hid themselves due
to fear; the guards asked Māṇḍavya
which way the Dasyus had fled; when
Māṇḍavya did not reply they searched
the आश्रम and found the hidden thieves
(चोरान्); the guards reported them and
Māṇḍavya to the king; the king asked to
kill the thieves (Dasyus) and Māṇḍavya
(तं राजा सह तैश् चोरैर् अन्वशाद्
वध्यताम् इति) 1. 101. 4-11; (4) some
Dasyus were in search of men who,
afraid of the Dasyus, had entered a forest;
the Dasyus asked the ascetic Kauśika
which way the men had disappeared;
Kauśika told them that they had taken
resort to the forest; the cruel Dasyus
found them out and killed them 8. 49. 43-
45; (5) Aśvagrīva (= Hayagrīva), whose
limbs were cut off while fighting with
Dasyus, enjoyed life in heaven 12. 25. 25;
(6) In order to illustrate that a Dasyu,
who observed proper limits, did not perish
after death (यथा दस्युः समर्यादः
प्रेत्यभावे न नश्यति) is told the story
of Kāpavya; he was born of a Niṣādī by a
Kṣatriya; he obtained perfection on account
of his being a (good) Dasyu (since he
lived righteously carrying out the duties
of a Kṣatriya) (दस्युत्वात् सिद्धिम् आप्तवान्);
when the Brāhmaṇas, who had retired to
a forest, did not accept food brought to
them by Kāpavya because he was a Dasyu,
he left some of it in their homes and went
away early in the morning; many Dasyus
who behaved cruelly disregarding the rules
elected Kāpavya as their leader; they
agreed to live as instructed by him and
requested him to act as their father
and mother; he taught them the way they
should live and ended by saying that
Dasyus, if they observed the rules of
धर्म, would obtain perfection in spite
of their being Dasyus (ये पुनर् धर्म-
शास्त्रेण वर्तेरन्न् इह दस्यवः।अपि ते
दस्यवो भूत्वा क्षिप्रं सिद्धिम् अवा-
प्नुयुः॥); the Dasyus carried out the
instructions of Kāpavya and abstained
from sinful deeds; Kāpavya, who by his act
turned the Dasyus away from committing
sins, obtained great perfection (मह
तीं सिद्धिम् आप्तवान्।साधूनाम् आचरन्
क्षेमं दस्यून् पापान् निवर्तयन्॥) 12.
133. 1-24; (7) A certain Brāhmaṇa,
Gautama by name, happened to take
shelter in the house of a wealthy Dasyu
who was truthful and generous; Gautama
got from the Dasyu new garments and
wife; he lived there happily and helped the
Dasyu to maintain his family; like the
Dasyus, Gautama began to kill geese
(वक्राङ्गान्) with arrows (Nī. who reads
चक्राङ्गान् explains it as हंसान्, Bom. Ed.
12. 168. 36): the Brāhmaṇa Gautama, due
to contact with Dasyus and leading their
life, became similar to them (दस्युभिः
समताम् इयात्); many months passed while
Gautama lived happily in the settlement of
the Dasyus (दस्युग्रामे) killing many
birds (पक्षिणः); once another Brāhmaṇa
happened to arrive in that settlement of the
Dasyus (दस्युग्रामम्); in that settlement
which was full of Dasyus (ग्रामे दस्यु-
जनाकीर्णे) he searched everywhere for a
Brāhmaṇa; he entered the house where
Gautama lived; he recognized that Gautama
belonged to Madhyadeśa; he asked Gau-
tama how he came to live like a Dasyu
(मध्यदेशपरिज्ञातो दस्युभावं गतः
कथम्) 12. 162. 29-44.
J. Mytho-
logical events: Gods appointed Kṛṣṇa to
kill Dasyus (here Asura Naraka and
his Asura followers are meant by the
word Dasyu) (न्ययोजयन् दस्युवधाय
कृष्णम्) 5. 47. 74, 76.
K. Future
event: Kalki will always be engaged in
killing Dasyus; they would perish crying
pitiable words like ‘oh father, oh son’
(कल्किश् चरिष्यति महीं सदा दस्यु-
वधे रतः॥हा तात हा सुतेत्य् एवं
तास् ता वाचः सुदारुणाः।विक्रोशमानान्
सुभृशं दस्यून् नेष्यति संशयम्॥) 3.
189. 5-6.

दाक्षिणात्य
Dākṣiṇātya m. (pl.): Designation of
the people or warriors of the south; certain
kings of the south designated as दाक्षिणात्य।
A. Description: Brave (शूर) 5. 30.
24; excellent warriors (प्रवीर) 8. 17. 2;
cruel and rough in battles (क्रूर, सं-
ग्रामकर्कश) 8. 15. 10; fighting with
swords and shields (असिचर्मिन्) 12. 102. 5;
also expert in fighting with all kinds of
weapons and missiles (सर्वशस्त्रास्त्र-
कुशल) 6. 16. 17; also fought from chariots
and riding elephants (दाक्षिणात्या … रथाः
5. 196. 6; गजयोधिन् 8. 17. 2).
B.
Status: According to the Rākṣasa Kal-
māṣapāda, the Dākṣiṇātyas were degraded
persons (वृषला दाक्षिणात्याः) 8. 30. 73.
C. Epic events: (1) A certain king of
the south brought for Yudhiṣṭhira an
armour at the time of the Rājasūya
(दाक्षिणात्यः संनहनम्) 2. 49. 7; (2)
Kings of the south sided with Duryodhana
to fight with Pāṇḍavas (दाक्षिणात्याः …
राजानः) 5. 30. 23-24; (3) Ulūka men-
tioned Dākṣiṇātyas among those who sided
with Duryodhana 5. 158. 20; (4) Saṃjaya
told Dhṛtarāṣṭra that killing Dākṣiṇātya
warriors would be Bhīmasena's responsi-
bility (दाक्षिणात्याश् च भीमसेनस्य भा-
गतः) 5. 56. 14; (5.) Chariot-fighters from
the south along with others started to-
wards Kurukṣetra (दाक्षिणात्याः … ये
रथाः) 5. 196. 6; (6) Duryodhana ex-
pected the Dākṣiṇātya warriors to protect
Bhīṣma in the war 6. 16. 17; (7) On
the eighth day of war, Bhīṣma, with
Dākṣiṇātya warriors, stood at the head of
his Mahāvyūha (अग्रतः सर्वसैन्यानाम्
 … दाक्षिणात्यैश् च) 6. 83. 5-6; (8) On
the eleventh day, Dākṣiṇātyas and others
took position at the extreme end (प्र-
पक्ष) of the left wing (सव्यं पार्श्वम्)
of the Śakaṭavyūha of the Kauravas (7. 6.
4, 7, 15); (9) On the fourteenth day, the
large army of Dākṣiṇātyas stood immedia-
tely behind the army of Āvantyas close to
Droṇa; according to Sātyaki, the southern
warriors were no match for Arjuna (उदीच्या
दाक्षिणात्याश् च … एते ऽर्जुनस्य क्रुद्ध-
स्य कलां नार्हन्ति षोडशीम्) 7. 86. 28-29;
Sātyaki asked his charioteer to drive his
chariot towards Dākṣiṇātya warriors who
were led by Karṇa (दाक्षिणात्यं महा-
बलम्) 7. 88. 30, (दाक्षिणात्याश् च बहवः
सूतपुत्रपुरोगमाः) 7. 88. 34; (10) On
the sixteenth day, Kṛpa, along with the
Dākṣiṇātya warriors stood at the right foot
of Makaravyūha of the Kauravas (पादे तु
दक्षिणे राजन्) 8. 7. 14, 18; on that day,
Pāṇḍya had killed many Dākṣiṇātyas and
others with his arrows after depriving them
of their weapons and armours (विशस्त्र-
कवचान् बाणैः कृत्वा) 8. 15. 10; (11) On
the sixteenth day, Dākṣiṇātyas mentioned
among those who, at the instance of Duryo-
dhana, attacked Dhṛṣṭadyumna 8. 17. 1-2;
(12) On the seventeenth day, Arjuna was
proud that he had cut off Dākṣiṇātyas
during the war (दाक्षिणात्या विशस्ताः) 8. 49.
96; (13) At the end of the seventeen days
of war, Saṃjaya mentioned Dākṣiṇātyas
among those who lost their lives while
fighting 8. 4. 47; at the end of the eighteen
days of war, all Dākṣiṇātyas were killed
(हता … दाक्षिणात्याश् च सर्वशः) 9. 1. 27;
(14) Among the past exploits of Kṛṣṇa,
Dhṛtarāṣṭra mentioned Kṛṣṇa's victory over
Dākṣiṇātyas (दाक्षिणात्यांश् च … जितवान्
पुण्डरीकाक्षः) 7. 10. 16, 18; Vasudeva too
remembered Kṛṣṇa's defeating Dākṣiṇātyas
16. 7. 11.
D. Past event: King Vyuṣi-
tāśva defeated, captured and carried off
kings of the south (स विजित्य गृहीत्वा च
नृपतीन् … दाक्षिणात्यान् अकालयत्) 1. 112. 11
(Nī. on Bom. Ed. 1. 121. 12: अकालयत्
वशीकृतवान्).
E. Kings characterized
generally as ‘southerner(s)’ or king of
Dākṣiṇātyas: (1) दाक्षिणात्यः 2. 49. 7;
(2) दाक्षिणात्यान् महीपान् 3. 119. 18;
दाक्षिणात्याश् च … राजानः 3. 226. 3; (ये
राजानः) 5. 30. 23-24; णृपाः 7. 68. 32; (3)
Rukmī was the son of the king of Dākṣi-
ṇātyas (viz. Bhīṣmaka) (दाक्षिणात्यपतेः
पुत्रो … ) 5. 155. 2. [See Dakṣiṇāpatha].

दारुण
Dāruṇa m. (pl.): Name of a people
(?) characterized as म्लेच्छ।
Listed by Saṃjaya among the northern
म्लेच्छ people of the Bhāratavarṣa
(उत्तराश् चापरे म्लेच्छा जना … ।यवनाश्
च सकाम्बोजा दारुणा म्लेच्छजातयः) 6.
10. 63-65; (Dāruṇa, name of a people,
or an adjective ‘rough’ describing the
म्लेच्छ tribes ?).

दार्व
Dārva m. (pl.): Name of a people.
A. Location: In the north (or north-
west (दिशं धनपतेर् …  2. 23. 1; प्रय-
याव् उत्तरां … दिशम्) 2. 24. 1; (for
location also see Epic events No. 3 below).
B. Description: Fierce and doing cruel
acts (उग्र, क्रूरकर्मन्) 8. 51. 18.
C.
Epic events: (1) Arjuna in his expedi-
tion to the north before the Rājasūya
defeated the Dārva Kṣatriyas along with
Trigartas and Kokanadas 2. 24. 17;
(2) The royal Kṣatriyas among Dārvas
brought riches in hundreds as tribute for
Yudhiṣṭhira's Rājasūya 2. 48. 12 (राजन्याः
2. 48. 13; क्षत्रियाः 2. 48. 16); (3)
Starting from Badarī, Pāṇḍavas crossed
the country of Dārvas on the difficult
terrain of Himavant before they reached
Subhāhu's realm (चीनांस् … सदार्वान्
 … अतीत्य दुर्गं हिमवत्प्रदेशं पुरं
सुबाहोर् ददृशुर् नृवीराः) 3. 174. 12;
(4) On the fourteenth day of war, innu-
merable Dārvas were killed by Arjuna 7.
68. 42-43; (5) On the seventeenth day,
they were among those who had gathered
round the Kuru warriors for the sake of
Duryodhana; according to Kṛṣṇa they
could not be conquered by any one except
Arjuna (दार्वाभिसारा … एते सुयोधन-
स्यार्थे शंरब्धाः कुरुभिः सह।न
शक्या युधि निर्जेतुं त्वदन्येन परं-
तप॥) 8. 51. 18, 20.

दाश
Dāśa m. (pl.): Name of a people.
According to Aṣṭāvakra, there are ten
Dāśas (दशेरका दश दाशा दशार्णाः) 3.
134. 16.

दाशार्ण
Dāśārṇa, Dāśārṇaka: See Daśārṇa.

दाशार्ह
Dāśārha: See Daśārha.

दाशेरक
Dāśeraka: See Daśeraka.

दासमीय
Dāsamīya (Daśamīya) m. (pl.):
Name of a settlement of degraded Brāh-
maṇas (?).
A. Location: North-west; They are
mentioned along with Āraṭṭas and Vrātyas
8. 30. 36.
B. Character: According to
a Brāhmaṇa who visited the Kauravas,
the Dāsamīya people were irreligious and
hence one should not visit their country
(आरट्टा नाम ते देशा नष्टधर्मान् न तान्
व्रजेत्।व्रात्यानां दासमीयानाम्) 8. 30.
36; Karṇa told Śalya that the Dāśamīyas
performed inauspicious deeds even in the
Kṛta age (दाशमीयानाम् कृते ऽप्य् अशुभ-
कर्मणाम्) 8. 30. 66 (Nī. on Bom. Ed. 8.
45. 20: कृते कृतयुगे ऽपि).
C. Epic
events: (1) They brought tribute of three
billions of gold for the Rājasūya, but were
not allowed to enter the gate; when they
brought additional tribute in the form of
shining golden कमण्डलुस् they were allow-
ed to enter (दासमीयाश् च सर्वशः। …
त्रिखर्वं बलिम् आदाय द्वारि तिष्ठन्ति वारि-
ताह्॥कमण्डलून् उपादाय जातरूपमयाञ्
शुभान्।एवं बलिं प्रदायाथ प्रवेशं
लेभिरे ततः॥) 2. 47. 5-6 (Nī., Bom.
Ed. 2. 51. 5 reads दासनीयाः and explains
दास्ययोग्याः शूद्रादयः ब्राह्मणा एव
वा तादृशाः); (2) Their large armies,
consisting of horse-fighters, charioteers,
and elephant-riders which went to the
battlefield, were killed by Arjuna (गोवा-
सदासमीयानां … उदीर्णाश् च महासेना
ब्रह्मक्षत्रस्य … ॥त्वां समासाद्य
निधनं गताः साश्वरथद्विपाः) 8. 51.
16-17.

दीप्ताक्ष
Dīptākṣa: Name of a people.
Mentioned by Bhīma among the sixteen
people whose kings extirpated their kinsmen
and friends together with their relatives;
their king's name was Purūravas (दीप्ताक्षा-
णां पुरूरवाः) 5. 72. 15.

दीर्घवेणु
Dīrghaveṇu m. (pl.): Name of a
people.
A. Location: They lived between the
mountains Meru and Mandara, along the
river Śailodā; they enjoyed the pleasing
shade of bamboos and reeds (मेरु-
मन्दरयोर् मध्ये शैलोदाम् अभितो नदीम्।
ये ते कीचकवेणूनां छायां रम्याम् उपा-
सते॥) 2. 48. 2-3.
B. Epic event: Their
kings brought as tribute for the Rājasūya
heaps of gold of the variety called पिपीलिक,
given as boon by ants (?), to be measured
by द्रोणस् (for citation see Ekāśanajyoha).

दुगूल
Dugūla m. (pl.): Name of a Janapada.
Listed by Saṃjaya among the nor-
thern Janapadas (also called Deśas 6. 10.
68) of the Bhāratavarṣa (जनपदान् निबो-
ध) 6. 10. 37, 5; (दुगूलाः प्रतिमत्स्याश्
च) 6. 10. 50.

दुन्दुभिस्वन
Dundubhisvana m. (sg.): Name of one
of the Deśas of the Krauñcadvīpa.
It is the last of the Deśas enumerated
of the Krauñcadvīpa; it is situated beyond
Munideśa (मुनिदेशात् परश् चैव प्रोच्यते
दुन्दुभिस्वनः) 6. 13. 22; it is full of
Siddhas and Cāraṇas and the people there
in general are white in complexion; it is
also frequented by gods and Gandharvas
(सिद्धचारणसंकीर्णो गौरप्रायो जना-
धिप।एते देशा महाराज देवगन्धर्व-
सेविताः) 6. 13. 22-23.

दुर्वारण
Durvāraṇa m. (pl.): Name of a
section of the Kāmbojas (?).
A. Characteristics: They were chariot-
fighters; their chariots bore golden banners
(ये त्व् एते रथिनो राजन् दृश्यन्ते काञ्चन-
ध्वजाः); they were brave (शूर), profi-
cient in sciences (कृतविद्य), expert in
archery (धनुर्वेदे च निष्ठिताः); keep-
ing close to each other, they wished to work
for the welfare of their comrades in wars
(संहतास् च भृशं ह्य् एते अन्योन्यस्य
हितैषिणः).
B. Epic events: An अक्षौ-
हिणी of them had gathered for Duryo-
dhana; protected by the Kuru hero, they
were waiting for Sātyaki's attack; watch-
ful, they came close to Sātyaki; Sātyaki
assured Yudhiṣṭhira that he would destroy
them as does fire the grass 7. 87. 42-45;
(दुर्वारण name of a people or an adje-
ctive ‘difficult to resist’ of Kāmbojas ?).

दुर्विभाग
Durvibhāga m. (pl.): Name of a
people.
Their Kṣatriyas brought riches by
hundreds for the Rājasūya of Yudhiṣṭhira
(औदुम्बरा दुर्विभागाः … आहार्षुः क्ष-
त्रिया वित्तं शतशो ऽजातशत्रवे) 2. 48.
12, 16.

द्रमिड
Dramiḍa (Dramiḷa), Draviḍa m. (pl.):
Name of a Janapada and its people.
A. Location: Listed by Saṃjaya
among the southern Janapadas (also called
Deśas 6. 10. 68) of Bhāratavarṣa (अथापरे
जनपदा दक्षिणा भरतर्षभ) 6. 10. 56,
5; (द्रविडाः केरलाः प्राच्या … ) 6. 10. 57;
Yudhiṣṭhira went to the south to reach
the Draviḍa country (प्रययौ दक्षिणा-
मुखः) 3. 117. 18; 3. 118. 4; Arjuna
fought with the Draviḍas when he reached
the southern ocean (प्रययौ … दक्षिणं
सलिलार्णवम्) 14. 84. 10.
B. Origin: (1)
Created, along with the Puṇḍras and
others, by Nandinī, the cow of Vasiṣṭha,
from her foam (द्रमिडान् … फेनतः सा
ससर्ज ह) 1. 165. 36; (2) They are
listed among those Kṣatriyas who were
degraded on account of not respecting
Brāhmaṇas (द्रमिऌआश् च कलिङ्गाश् च …
तास् ताः क्षत्रियजातयः।वृषलत्वं परि-
गता ब्राह्मणानाम् अदर्शनात्) 13. 33. 20-
21; (द्रमिडाः) 13. 35. 17; they became
degraded due to their neglect of the duties
of a Kṣatriya (त एते द्रमिडाः … वृषल-
त्वं परिगता व्युत्थानात् क्षत्रधर्मतः)
14. 29. 16.
C. Description: of terrific
valour (उग्रविक्रम) 8. 4. 46.
D. Epic
events: (1) Sahadeva, in his expedition
to the south (2. 28. 1, 8, 37) subjugated
the Draviḍas by just sending messengers
to them and made them pay tribute for
the Rājasūya (द्रविडांश् चैव … दूतैर्
एव वशे चक्रे करं चैनान् अदापयत्) 2.
28. 48; (2) Draviḍas mentioned among
those whose kings attended the Rāja-
sūya of Yudhiṣṭhira 2. 31. 12; Kṛṣṇa
saw them who, afraid of the luster of the
arms, attended the Rājasūya and acted as
servers (आगतान् अहम् अद्राक्षं यज्ञे ते
परिवेषकान्) 3. 48. 18, 22; (3) In his
pilgrimage Yudhiṣṭhira, going south along
the river Godāvarī, reached the sea in the
Draviḍa country before going to the
Agastyatīrtha and the Nārītīrthas (द्रवि-
डेषु … समुद्रम् आसाद्य) 3. 118. 4; (4)
Kṛṣṇa told Karṇa that the Draviḍas would
be among those who would lead his proce-
ssion if he joined the Pāṇḍavas (पुरोगमाश्
च ते सन्तु द्रविडाः सह कुन्तलैः) 5.
138. 25; (5) Ulūka mentioned Draviḍas
among those who had joined the army
of Duryodhana (राजचमूं समेताम् …
द्रविडान्ध्रकाञ्च्यैः) 5. 158. 19-20; (6)
On the sixteenth day of the war, Dhṛṣṭa-
dyumna, along with the Draviḍas (on the
side of the Pāṇḍavas), attacked the
Kaurava army (द्रविडैः) 8. 8. 14; (7)
On the seventeenth day, the Draviḍa foot-
soldiers (on the side of Pāṇḍavas), in-
cited by Sātyaki, attacked Karṇa; Karṇa
cut off with his arrows their arms and
head-gears and felled them down (द्रविड°
 … अभ्यर्दयञ् … कर्णं आहवे ते विबाहु-
शिरस्त्राणाः … प्रहताः कर्णसायकैः
पेतुः पृथिव्यां) 8. 33. 4-5; (8) Saṃjaya
listed Draviḍas among those who were
killed in the first seventeen days of war
(द्रविडाश् चोग्रविक्रमाः … निहताः) 8. 4.
46, 48; (9) Arjuna had to fight with the
Draviḍas (द्रविडैर्) when he accompanied
the Aśvamedha horse 14. 84. 11.
E. A
Dramiḍa king occurs in a comparison: The
glorious Aśoka tree, according to Dama-
yantī, with its chaplets (of blossoms),
shone like the glorious king of Dramiḍas
(अहो बतायम् अगमः श्रीमान् … आपीडैर्
बहुभिर् भाति श्रीमान् द्रमिडराड् इव) 3.
61. 98 (Nī. on Bom. Ed. 3. 64. 103: अगमः
वृक्षः आपीडैः पुष्पफलादिरूपैर् अलं-
कारैः).

द्वैधेय
Dvaidheya m. (pl.): Name of a Jana-
pada.
Listed by Saṃjaya among the northern
Janapadas (also called Deśas 6. 10. 68)
of the Bhāratavarṣa (अत ऊर्ध्वं जन-
पदान् निबोध) 6. 10. 37, 5; (कुट्टापरान्ता
द्वैधेयाः) 6. 10. 47.

द्व्यक्ष
Dvyakṣa m. (pl.): Name of a people.
They brought ample gold and silver
as tribute for the Rājasūya but were
stopped at the gate (द्व्यक्षांस् … समा-
गतान् … द्वारि वारितान्।बल्यर्थं ददतस्
तस्मै हिरण्यं रजतं बहु 2. 47.
15-16.

धृतिमत्|धृतिमन्त्
Dhṛtimant nt. (sg.): Name of a
Varṣa.
Fifth Varṣa in the list of the seven
Varṣas of Kuśadvīpa (धृतिमत् पञ्चमं
वर्षं … सप्तैते वर्षपुञ्जकाः) 6. 13.
13; for the description of the people of
Dhṛtimant (6. 13. 14-15) see Audbhida.

ध्वजिन्युत्सवसंकेत
Dhvajinyutsavasaṃketa m. (pl.):
Name of a Janapada.
One of the southern Janapadas (also
called Deśas 6. 10. 68) of Bhāratavarṣa
listed by Saṃjaya (अथापरे जनपदा
दक्षिणा … ) 6. 10. 56; (ध्वजिन्युत्सवसं-
केताः) 6. 10. 59; (Related to the Utsava-
saṃketas ?)

नग्नजित्
Nagnajit m. (pl.): Name of a people.
Described as very difficult to be con-
quered (सुदुर्जय) 8. 57. 31; Śalya
reminded Karṇa that he had once defeated
with great firmness Nagnajit people in
battle (नग्नजितस् त्वया)। … यया धृत्या
जिताः संख्ये सुदुर्जयाः) 8. 57. 31.

नन्दिवेग
Nandivega m. (pl.): Name of a people.
Bhīma mentioned Śama as the king of
the Nandivegas; he was one of the eighteen
famous kings who were born at the end
of the युग and who extirpated their
kinsmen, friends and relatives (अष्टादशेमे
राजानः प्रख्याता … । … शंअश् च नन्दि-
वेगानाम् … युगान्ते कृष्ण संभूताः) 5.
72. 11, 17.

नलकालक
Nalakālaka m. (pl.): Name of a Jana-
pada.
Listed by Saṃjaya among the southern
Janapadas (also called Deśas 6. 10. 68) of
Bhāratavarṣa (अथापरे जनपदा दक्षिणा … )
6. 10. 56, 5; (सोद्भिदा नलकालकाः) 6.
10. 58.

नवराष्ट्र
Navarāṣṭra nt. (sg.): Name of a
country (राष्ट्र) also called Janapada.
A. Location: Around the Kurus
(वासाय राष्ट्राणि कीर्तयिष्यामि … ॥ …
जनपदा … परितः कुरून्) 4. 1. 8-9.
B.
Description: pleasing (रमणीय) 4. 1. 8;
(रम्य) 4. 1. 9; having ample food
(बह्वन्न) 4. 1. 9; well-protected (गुप्त)
4. 1. 8.
C. Epic event: (1) Sahadeva
in his expedition to the south before the
Rājasūya (सहदेवस् तु दक्षिणां 2. 23.
9; प्रययौ दक्षिणां दिशम् 2. 28. 1, 8,
37) conquered Navarāṣṭra before marching
on the Kuntibhoja 2. 28. 6; (2) Listed
by Arjuna among those countries in one
of which the Pāṇḍavas could live during
their period of अज्ञातवास (दशार्णा नव-
राष्ट्रं च) 4. 1. 9.

नाकुल
Nākula m. (pl.): Name of a people (?).
On the second day of war, Nākulas
and others, led by Nakula and Sahadeva,
stood on the left side of the Krauñcāruṇa-
vyūha (6. 46. 39; Krauñca 6. 47. 1) of the
Pāṇḍavas (सह नाकुलैः … वामं पार्-
श्वं समाश्रिताः) 6. 46. 51; (name of a
people, or characterization of the warriors
led by Nakula ?)

नागद्वीप
Nāgadvīpa nt. (sg.): Name of a
द्वीप।
The shape of the Sudarśanadvīpa
(= Jambudvīpa) when reflected in the
moon looked like a hare; Nāgadvīpa for-
med one of the two ‘ears’ of the hare, the
other ear being Kaśyapadvīpa (यथा च
पुरुषः पश्येद् आदर्शे मुखम् आत्मनः।
एवं सुदर्शनद्वीपो दृश्यते चन्द्र-
मण्डले॥) 6. 6. 15; (कर्णौ तु नागद्वी-
पं च कश्यपद्वीपम् एव च॥) 6. 7. 52.

नारायण
Nārāyaṇa m. (pl.): Name of a class
of Gopas or Gopālas; their army referred
to as Nārāyaṇabala.
A. Description: All Nārāyṇas acted as
warriors (सर्वे संग्रामयोधिनः) 5. 7.
16; as warriors, equal to Kṛṣṇa in firmness
(मत्संहननतुल्य) 5. 7. 16; difficult to
be assailed in war (ते वा युधि दुराधर्षा
 … ) 5. 7. 17; fierce in war (युद्धदुर्मद)
9. 2. 36; in wars, they fought with weapons
of different kinds (विविधायुधपाणि) 7.
18. 7.
B. Epic events: (1) A large
number of Gopas called Nārayaṇas, an
अर्बुद strong, were taken by Duryodhana
to fight from his side (गोपानाम् अर्बुदं
महत्।नारायाणा इति ख्याताः) 5. 7. 16;
(सहस्राणां सहस्रं तु) 5. 7. 20-21;
(2) On the twelfth day of war, the fleeing
Nārāyaṇa Gopālas who formed a part of
the army of the Saṃśaptakas, incited by
Suśarman, returned to the battlefield deter-
mined to fight till death (संशप्तकगणाः
पुनः।नारायणाश् च गोपालाः कृत्वा
मृत्युं निवर्तनम्) 7. 17. 31; the angry
Nārāyaṇas surrounded Arjuna and covered
him with arrows; they made both Kṛṣṇa
and Arjuna invisible for a while; Arjuna
employed त्वाष्ट्र अस्त्र against them;
bewildered by the अस्त्र, they killed
each other; the अस्त्र reduced to ashes the
arrows released by Nārāyaṇas and killed
them 7. 18. 7-8, 11-15; later in the day,
Arjuna fought with the remainder of the
Saṃśaptakas and Nārāyaṇas stationed
to the right side of the army (दक्षिणेन
तु सेनायाः कुरुते कदनं बली।सं-
शप्तकावशेषस्य नारायणबलस्य च) 7.
30. 29; (3) On the fourteenth day, the
Nārāyaṇa Gopālas tried to check the
march of Arjuna in the direction of Jaya-
dratha; they were determined to risk their
lives while fighting with Arjuna (नारायणाश्
च गोपालाः … त्यक्त्वात्मानो ऽर्जुनं प्रति)
7. 66. 38-39; (4) On the sixteenth day,
the army of the Nārayaṇa Gopālas stood
at the left foot of the Makaravyūha (8. 7.
14) of the Kauravas: they were led by
Kṛtavarman (कृतवर्मा व्यवस्थितः।
नारायणबलैर् युक्तो गोपालैर् … ) 8. 7.
17; they (नारायणबलं च यत्) and the
Saṃśaptakas attacked Arjuna 8. 19. 2; (5)
On the seventeenth day, Arjuna killed the
army of the Nārāyaṇas (नारायणबलं
च यत्) and the Kosalas and the Saṃ-
śaptakas 8. 37. 2; (6) Mentioned by
Dhṛtarāṣṭra among those who were killed
in the war (नारायणा हता यत्र गोपाला … )
9. 2. 36.

निषध
Niṣadha m. (pl.): Name of a Jana-
pada and its people; the people also called
Naiṣadba (3. 58. 18).
A. Location: Listed by Saṃjaya
among the northern Janapadas (also called
Deśas 6. 10. 68) of the Bhāratavarṣa (अत
ऊर्ध्वं जनपदान् निबोध) 6. 10. 37, 5;
(निषादा निषधाः) 6. 10. 50.
B. Des-
cription: Skilled in fighting while riding
elephants (गजयुद्धेषु कुशलाः) 8. 17. 3;
(गजयोधिन्) 8. 17. 2.
C. Epic events:
On the sixteenth day of war, the Niṣadha
warriors, incited by Duryodhana, attacked
Dhṛṣṭadyumna 8. 17. 3; they showered
arrows, तोमरस् and नाराच type of arrows
on Dhṛṣṭadyumna 8. 17. 4 (the war
described in 8. 17. 5ff.).
D. Past events:
(1) Indra once took resort to a hermitage
on a mountain in the Niṣadha country
and lived there in disguise in order to
subdue his enemies (इन्द्रेण निषधान्
प्राप्य गिरिप्रस्थाश्रमे तदा।छन्नेनोष्य
कृतं कर्म) 3. 299. 11; (2) The swan
returned to the Niṣadha country and repor-
ted to Nala his meeting with Damayanti
(पुनर् आगम्य निषधान् नले सर्वं
न्यवेदयत्) 3. 50. 31; Kali dwelt for a long
time in the Niṣadha country looking for
an opportunity to enter Nala's body (स
नित्यम् अन्तरप्रेक्षी निषधेष्व् अवसच्
चिरम्) 3. 56. 2; Kali told Puṣkara to play
a game of dice with Nala, defeat him,
and obtain the kingdom of the Niṣadha
country (निषधान् प्रतिपद्यस्व) 3. 56.
5; the people of Niṣadha paid no regard
to Nala after his defeat since they
were threatened by Puṣkara (न सत्कारम्
अकुर्वन् मयि नैषधाः) 3. 58. 18; Nala
went to the Niṣadha country to challenge
Puṣkara for a game of dice (जगाम
निषधान् प्रति) 3. 77. 1.
E. Nala
(and his father Vīrasena) variously called
the king of the Niṣadhas, the guardian
of the lineage of Niṣadha, or one belong-
ing to the Niṣadha country: (1) गोप्ता
निषधवंशस्य: Nala 3. 61. 74; (2)
निषधाधिप: Nala 3. 54. 19; 3. 59. 5, 18;
3. 61. 26; 3. 65. 3; 3. 75. 1; 3. 76. 11; 3.
77. 29; (3) निषधाधिपति: Nala 3. 58.
12; 3. 61. 32, 73; 3. 70. 29; निषधानां
अधिपतिः: Nala 3. 61. 51, 88, 100;
(4) निषधानां जनाधिप: 3. 61. 12;
निषधानां जनाधिपः: Nala 3. 61.
82; (5) निषधेश्वर: Nala 3. 63. 19;
(6) निषधेषु नृपोत्तमः: Vīrasena 3.
61. 45; (7) निषधेषु महीपतिः: Nala 3.
50. 3, 26; (8) निषधेषु महीपालः:
वीरसेन 3. 49. 39; (9) नैषध: (i)
Nala 1. 1. 175; 3. 50. 15, 20; 3. 51. 28, 29;
3. 52. 3, 8. 9; 3. 54. 17, 21, 24, 25, 28,
29, 30, 31; 3. 56. 1, 13, 14; 3. 57. 15; 3.
58. 7, 23; 3. 60. 2, 8, 15, 21, 23, 24; 3. 61.
54, 87, 119; 3. 63. 10; 3. 64. 1, 19; 3.
65. 5, 22, 23; 3. 66. 2; 3. 68. 2; 3. 70. 34,
35; 3. 71. 11, 14, 31, 33, 34; 3. 72. 14; 3.
73. 26; 3. 75. 4; 3. 76. 10, 11, 17; 3. 77. 1,
11, 12, 25; 3. 85. 20; 13. 75. 25 (भूरि-
द्युम्नो नैषधः सोमकश् च। Does
नैषध refer to Nala, or is it an adj. of
Bhūridyumna ?) (ii) A certain warrior
(king ?), not named, on the side of the
Kauravas (नैषधश् च महाबलः) 7.
19. 13.

निषाद
Niṣāda m. (pl.): Name of a people of
low caste; their territory called निषाद-
विषय 7. 168. 35; 14. 84. 7; निषादराष्ट्र 3.
130. 4; निषादभूमि 2. 28. 5; their settle-
ment निषादालय 1. 24. 2; 12. 315. 14
(निषादानाम् आलयः).
A. Origin: (1) Sages killed Ati-
bala's son Vena with Kuśa blades and
produced from his right thigh a dwarfish
person (ह्रस्वाङ्गः); they asked him to sit
down; from him Niṣādas were born (निषीद
इत्य् एवम् ऊचुस् तम् ऋषयो ब्रह्मवादिनः।
तस्मान् निषादाः संभूताः) 12. 59. 102-
103; (this is also an etymological explana-
tion); (2) Niṣādas were born due to
intermixture of the original four castes
(निषादाः … ।एते चतुर्भ्यो वर्णेभ्यो
जायन्ते वै परस्परम्) 12. 285. 8-9.
B.
Location: (1) Listed by Saṃjaya among
the northern Janapadas (also called Deśas
6. 10. 68) of Bhāratavarṣa (अत ऊर्ध्वं
जनपदान् निबोध) 6. 10. 37, 5; शका
निषादा … ) 6. 10. 50; in the west: the Vina-
śana tīrtha on the river Sarasvatī called
the gate of the Niṣādarāṣṭra 3. 130. 4; the
territory of Niṣādas was located outside
the Samantapañcaka 7. 168. 35; 7. 121. 24,
34; (2) Another territory in the south-
west: Sahadeva in his expedition to the
south of Indraprastha (प्रययौ दक्षिणां
दिशम् 2. 28. 1; 2. 23. 9) conquered
the land of the Niṣādas (निषादभूमिम् …
व्यजयत्) 2. 28. 5; south of Śūrpāraka
2. 28. 43-44; Arjuna went from the
Daśārṇa country to the country of Niṣādas
14. 84. 5-7; from the country of Niṣādas,
he went to the southern ocean (प्रययौ
भूयः दक्षिणं सलिलार्णवम्) 14. 84. 10;
(3) In a past event, a settlement of
the Niṣādas is said to be in a solitary
place in the bay of the ocean (समुद्र-
कुक्षाव् एकान्ते निषादालयम् उत्तमम्) 1.
24. 2.
C. Low Status: A son be-
gotten on a Kṣatriya woman by a Śūdra
becomes Niṣāda 13. 48. 12; a Niṣāda unit-
ing with a Vaidehī begets Āhiṇḍika 13. 48.
27; a Niṣāda uniting with a woman of lower
caste begets a Mudgara and Dāśa who
lives by plying boats (दाशं नावोपजीवि-
नम्) 13. 48. 21; a Niṣāda also begets a
Madranābha who rides in vehicles drawn
by asses (निषादान् मद्रनाभं च खर-
यानप्रयायिनम्) 13. 48. 23; (2) A
Niṣādī from a Caṇḍāla gives birth to a son
who lives on the outskirts on the crema-
tion grounds; he is an outcaste among out-
castes (निषादी चापि चण्डालात् पुत्रम् अन्ता-
वसायिनम्।श्मशानगोचरं सूते बाह्यैर्
अपि बहिष्कृतम्॥) 13. 48. 28.
D. Profe-
ssion: They lived by catching fish (मत्स्य-
जीविनः; जालहस्ताः; मत्स्योद्धरणनिश्चि-
ताः; निश्चिता जालकर्मणि) 13. 50. 11, 12;
(निषादो मत्स्यघ्नः) 13. 48. 12; hence
also called कैवर्ताः 13. 50. 14.
E. Des-
cription: (i) Their settlement in the
ocean is said to be excellent (उत्तम) 1.
24. 2; (ii) People and warriors: residing
on mountains and in forests (शैलवना-
श्रय) 12. 59. 103; strong and brave,
they never returned from water-reservoirs
(empty-handed out of fear) (व्यायता
बलिनः शूराः सलिलेष्व् अनिवर्तिनः) 13. 50.
12; cruel (क्रूर) 12. 59. 103; skilled in
fighting with elephants (गजयोधिनः,
गजयुद्धेषु कुशलाः) 8. 17. 2-3; their
elephants often mentioned during war-
descriptions cf. 6. 50. 7; 7. 45. 21-22; 8.
12. 59; 8. 15. 8; 8. 17. 5, 22; 8. 33. 1, 4;
8. 43. 70; 8. 49. 78-79.
F. Their abode
used for comparison: The mountain
Himālaya without the sound of Vedic
recitation appeared like an abode of the
Niṣādas (न भ्राजते यथापूर्वं निषादा-
नाम् इवालयः। … वेदध्वनिनिराकृतः) 12
315. 14.
G. Epic events: (1) Sahadeva,
in his expedition to the south before the
Rājasūya, conquered the territory of the
Niṣādas and brought them under control
(निषादभूमिम् … व्यजयत्) 2. 28. 5;
(वशे चक्रे … निषादान्) 2. 28. 44; (2)
Karṇa had once defeated them and made
them pay tribute (चक्रे बलिभृतः पुरा)
8. 5. 19-20 (possibly a reference to Karṇa's
conquest of the earth before the Vaiṣṇava
sacrifice performed by Duryodhana 3. 241,
32 and Cr. Edn. Vol. 3, App. I. 24. 28-72);
(3) On the second day of the war, Yudhi-
ṣṭhira with Niṣādas (on the side of the
Pāṇḍavas) and other warriors, formed the
‘back’ of the Krauñcāruṇavyūha 6. 46. 39.
47 (Krauñca 6. 47. 1); (4) On the
same day, Ketumant, a Niṣāda prince
(नैषादि) with his Niṣāda warriors (on
the side of the Kauravas), riding elephants,
surrounded Bhīma (अयुतेन गजानां च
निषादैः सह केतुमान्); Cedis and other
warriors led by Bhīma, attacked Niṣādas;
in the fierce battle, Niṣādas and Kaliṅgas
outnumbered Cedis and their associates
(विमर्दः सुमहान् आसीद् अल्पानां बहुभिः
सह) 6. 50. 5, 7, 8, 14; (5) On the tenth
day, Niṣādas and other warriors, incited
by Duryodhana, attacked Arjuna 6. 112.
108; (6) On the thirteenth day, Niṣādas
and Kaliṅgas, riding elephants (गजानीकेन
दंशिताः; कुञ्जरानीकम्) obstructed the
advance of Abhimanyu; he scattered away
their army of elephants 7. 45. 21-22; (7)
On the fifteenth day, Dhṛṣṭadyumna
regretted that he did not throw away
the head of Droṇa in the territory of the
Niṣādas, as (Arjuna did) the head of
Jayadratha (यन् न तस्य शिरो मया।
निषादविषये क्षिप्तं जयद्रथशिरो यथा)
7. 168. 35; (8) On the sixteenth day,
Kaliṅga, Vaṅga and Niṣāda warriors,
riding elephants (अथ द्विपैर् देवपति-
द्विपाभैर्) rushed against Arjuna; Arjuna
killed both the elephants and the warriors
8. 12. 59-60; (9) On the same day, the
Pāṇḍya king killed many Niṣāda warriors,
who fought with शक्ति, प्रास and quivers
(i. e. arrows), along with their elephants
(द्विरदान्) and horses 8. 15. 5, 8-9; (10)
On the same day, incited by Duryodhana,
Niṣādas, riding elephants (हस्तिभिस्), attack-
ed Dhṛṣṭadyumna with arrows, तोमरस् and
नाराच arrows; Dhṛṣṭadyumna showered
नाराच arrows on them to crush their
elephants 8. 17. 1, 3-5; (11) On the same
day, they attacked Nakula with arrows and
तोमरस्; when warriors came to help
Nakula, a fierce battle took place between
chariot-riders and elephant-riders (युद्धं
रथिनां हस्तिभिः सह) 8. 17. 20-22;
(12) On the seventeenth day, Karṇa
killed many warriors in the army of Yudhi-
ṣṭhira consisting of Niṣādas (on the side
of the Pāṇḍavas) and others; when they
began to run away, Sātyaki incited them
to fight; on return, they were killed by
Karṇa who cut off their arms and removed
their head-gears (ते विबाहुशिरस्त्राणाः …
पेतुः पृथिव्यां … ) 8. 33. 1, 4-5; (13)
On the same day, Arjuna referred to
Bhīma's killing Niṣādas (on the side of
the Kauravas) and their elephants (नाग-
वरान् … सदामदान् नीलबलाहकोपमान्) 8.
49. 78-79; (14) When Arjuna moved
with the Aśvamedha horse, he had to fight
a fierce battle with the Niṣādas led by
Ekalavya's son 14. 84. 7-8.
H. Mythologi-
cal event: Vinatā allowed her son Garuḍa
to eat Niṣādas (but not the Brāhmaṇas)
while on his way to fetch अमृत 1. 24. 2;
when Garuḍa found the Niṣādas he colle-
cted them together; then, opening his beak
wide, he stood in the way of the Niṣādas;
they entered Garuḍa's mouth by hundreds
since they were deluded by the dust raised
by the wind; the hungry Garuḍa closed
his beak and killed many Niṣādas 1. 24.
10-14.
I. Past events: (1) Sarasvatī
disappeared at the gate of the Niṣādarāṣṭra
so that the Niṣādas might not see her 3.
130. 4; (2) Some Niṣādas once came to
the place where Cyavana was practising
austerities near the confluence of Gaṅgā and
Yamunā; the Niṣādas who wanted to catch
fishes threw their net in water; when they
drew their net they dragged Cyavana along
with fishes; they fell at the feet of Cyavana
and asked him what they should do;
Cyavana told the Niṣadas that he did not
want to forsake the fishes and hence would
get killed or sold along with them; afraid,
the Niṣādas reported the matter to king
Nahuṣa; Nahuṣa asked his priest to pay
one thousand (coins) to the Niṣādas as the
price of fishes and Cyavana; on Cyavana's
denial to accept this price, Nahuṣa went
on bidding higher and higher price to be
paid to Niṣādas; ultimately Cyavana was
purchased by giving a cow to Niṣādas;
they offered it to Cyavana; Cyavana sent
the Niṣādas and the fishes to heaven 13.
50. 3-26; 13. 51. 1-41.
I. Some persons
called the king of Niṣādas or one belong-
ing to the Niṣādas: (1) निषादराज: (i)
Ekalavya 5. 47. 71; (ii) Hiraṇyadhanus
1. 123. 10; (2) निषादराजन्: Ekalavya
14. 84. 7; (3) निषादाधिपति: (i) Hiraṇya-
dhanus 1. 123. 24, 28; 2. 27. 10 (?) (ii)
a certain Mahāsura 1. 61. 48; (4) नैषादि:
(i) Ekalavya: 1. 123. 11, 17, 18, 29, 38;
7. 156. 2, 17, 18; 16. 7. 10; (ii) Ekalavya's
son 14. 84. 10; (iii) Ketumant 6. 50. 5;
(iv) A Kuru warrior (not named; Eka-
lavya ?) 8. 43. 70; (v) Kāpavya 12. 133. 3;
(5) निषादज: Ekalavya 1. 123. 32; (6)
निषाद: Ekalavya 7. 155. 29; (7) Niṣādī
(f.), not named 12. 133. 3.

नीप
Nīpa m. (pl.): Name of a people.
Past events: (1) Aṅgirases had once
defeated them (नीपान् अङ्गिरसो ऽजयन्)
13. 34. 16; (2) Janamejaya, the king of
the Nīpas, was mentioned by Bhīma
among those eighteen kings who extirpated
their kinsmen, friends and relatives (ये
समुच्चिच्छिदुर् ज्ञातीन् सुहृदश् च सबान्ध-
वान् … नीपानां जनमेजयः) 5. 72. 11, 13;
(3) Their former kings were royal sages
(राजर्षयः) 2. 8. 25, 7; they were pious,
famous and learned and a hundred of
them waited on Yama in his Sabhā (शतं
नीपाः … एते राजर्षयः पुण्याः कीर्तिमन्तो
बहुश्रुताः।तस्यां सभायां राजर्षे
वैवस्वतम् उपासते॥) 2. 8. 21, 25.

नील
Nīla nt.: Name of a Varṣa.
One of the seven Varṣas of the Jambu-
dvīpa; beyond Nīla lay the Śvetavarṣa
(नीलात् परतरं श्वेतम्) 6. 7. 35; in
these Varṣas, people in each succeeding
one excelled those in the preceding one in
duration of life, health, as well as in
धर्म, काम, and अर्थ; in these Varṣas,
people lived in harmony with one another
6. 7. 37-38 (for citation see Airāvata).

नीलायुध
Nīlāyudha m. (pl.): Name of a
people (?)
A. Location: They lived in the south
(दक्षिणापथवासिभिः) 5. 19. 23.
B.
Description: Possessed of great heroic
qualities (महावीर्य) 5. 19. 23.
C. Epic
events: (1) King Nīla of Māhiṣmatī,
along with the Nīlāyudha warriors, one
अक्षौहिणी strong, joined the army of
Duryodhana (नीलो नीलायुधैः सह) 5.
19. 23; (2) On the third day of war,
king Nīla, along with his Nīlāyudha
warriors, (those on the side of the Pāṇḍa-
vās ?) stood behind Virāṭa and Drupada
at the southern tip (दक्षिणं शृङ्गम्) of
the Ardhacandravyūha of the Pāṇḍavas
6. 52. 10-12. (But Nīla is said to have
joined the Kaurava army, cf. Epic event
No. 1).

नैमिष
Naimiṣa, Naimiṣeya m. (pl.): The
people and the sages living in the Naimiṣa
forest.
A. The people: They are mentioned
among those people who knew the eternal
धर्म (मत्स्याः सनैमिषाः … धर्मं
जानन्ति शाश्वतम्) 8. 30. 60-61; (कुरवो
नैमिषाश् च … जानन्ति धर्मम्) 8. 30. 75.
B. The sages: (1) The Naimiṣeya sages
once started on a pilgrimage and first went
to Kurukṣetra (नैमिषेयास् तपोधनाः।
तीर्थयात्रां पुरस्कृत्य कुरुक्षेत्रं गताः
पुरा॥) 3. 81. 92; (2) The Naimiṣeya
sages of the Kṛtayuga once performed
a सत्र lasting for twelve years (पूर्वं
कृतयुगे राजन् नैमिषेयास् तपस्विनः।
 … सत्रे द्वादशवार्षिके) 9. 36. 39, 35.
[For Naimiṣa forest, see Vol. I. pp. 377-
379].

नैरृत
Nairṛta m. (pl.): Name of a Jana-
pada and its people.
A. Location: Listed by Saṃjaya
among the northern Janapadas (also called
Deśas 6. 10. 68) of the Bhāratavarṣa (अत
ऊर्ध्वं जनपदान् निबोध) 6. 10. 37, 5;
(तथैवानर्तनैरृताः) 6. 10. 50.
B.
Epic event: In the arrangement of the
army of the Kauravas before the start of
the war, Bhṛhadbala, along with Nairṛtas
who had taken up arms (नैरृतैर् आत्तशस्-
त्रैः), guarded the army in the south
(बलं त्वदीयं दक्षिणतो ऽभिपाति) 6.
20. 14.

पञ्चकर्पट
Pañcakarpaṭa m. (pl.): Name of a
people.
Nakula subjugated them in his expedi-
tion to the west (प्रतीचीं नकुलो राजन्
2. 23. 10; वासुदेवजिताम् आशाम् 2. 29. 1)
before the Rājasūya (वशे चक्रे … माल-
वान् पञ्चकर्पटान्) 2. 29. 6.

पञ्चनद
Pañcanada m. (pl.), nt. (sg.): Name
of a country and its people.
A. Location: West of Hāstinapura 2.
23. 10; 2. 29. 1; between the western ocean
and the Gāndhāra 14. 84. 17; on way
from Hāstinapura to Dvārakā 16. 8. 43
(see below Epic events No. 1, 5, 6, and
S. K. Belvalkar's Critical Notes to Mausala
Parvan Vol. 19, pp. 48-49).
B. Descrip-
tion: Brave (शूर) 6. 20. 10; croocked
(जिह्म) 8. 30. 62.
C. Characteristic: A
Certain Brāhmaṇa told the Kurusabhā (8.
30. 8) that the people of Pañcanada did
not follow the ancient धर्म (धर्मं
पुराणम् उपजीवन्ति सन्तो मद्रान् ऋते
पञ्चनदांश् च … ) 8. 30. 62; having seen
the धर्म practised by the people of
Pañcanada, Prajāpati exclaimed ‘fie’!; it
was thus censured by Prajāpati (धर्मं
पाञ्चनदं दृष्ट्वा धिग् इत्य् आह प्रजापतिः।
 … इति पाञ्चनदं धर्मम् अवमेने पिता-
महः) 8. 30. 65-66; the पाञ्चनद धर्म
is characterized as ingratitude, looting
wealth belonging to others, drinking wine,
violating the wife of a teacher; for them
there was no अधर्म (कृतघ्नता पर-
वित्तापहारः सुरापानं गुरुदारावमर्-
शः।येषां धर्मस् तान् प्रति नास्त्य् अधर्-
मः) 8. 30. 74; their country was very
large, full of riches and corn (एष देशः
सुविस्तीर्णः प्रभूतधनधान्यवान्) 5.
19. 31; prosperous, very prosperous
(स्फीत) 14. 84. 17; (अतिसमृद्धिमन्त्) 16.
8. 43.
D. Epic events: (1) The Pañca-
nada country was subjugated by Nakula
in his expedition to the west of Indra-
prastha (प्रतीचीम् नकुलो राजन् दिशं
व्यजयत् 2. 23. 10; वासुदेवजिताम् आशां …
व्यजयत् 2. 29. 1) before the Rājasūya 2.
29. 10; (2) The large army of the Kaura-
vas spread out as far as Pañcanada and
other countries near Hāstinapura 5. 19. 29;
(3) Before the war, when the Kaurava
army got ready, Bhīṣma stood at the head
of it along with Pañcanada and other
warriors 6. 20. 10; (4) On the third day
of the war, Pañcanadas were posted at
the ‘neck’ of the Gāruḍavyūha (6. 52. 2)
of the Kauravas 6. 52. 5; (5) The Aśva-
medha horse reached Pañcanada from the
western ocean and from Pañcanada it went
to Gāndhāra country (पश्चिमं देशं
समुद्रस्य तदा हयः। … व्यचरत् …
ततः पञ्चनदं ययौ॥तस्माद् अपि स
कौरव्य गान्धारविषयं हयः।विचचार)
14. 84. 17-18; (6) While Arjuna was
on his way from Dvārakā to Hāstinapura,
he arrived at Pañcanada and stayed there;
he was attacked by the Ābhīras (Dasyus
16. 8. 44) who lived in Pañcanada and
kidnapped the Vṛṣṇi women in his charge
16. 8. 43-61; (आभीरैर्॥।हृताः पञ्चनदा-
लयैः) 16. 9. 16 [for Pañcanada also see
Vol. I. 379].

पञ्चाल
Pañcāla: see Pāñcāla.

पटच्चर
Paṭaccara m. (pl.): Name of a Jana-
pada and its people; also called Rāṣṭra.
A. Location: Mentioned among the
Rāṣṭras or Janapadas situated around
Kurus (राष्ट्राणि … जनपदा … परितः
कुरून्। … शूरसेनाः पटच्चराः) 4. 1. 8,
9; mentioned among those people who,
afraid of Jarāsandha, had fled to the
south from the north (पतच्चराः। …
तथोत्तरां दिशं चापि परित्यज्य भयार्-
दिताः … दक्षिणां दिशम् आश्रिताः॥) 2.
13. 25, 27; Sahadeva subjugated Paṭa-
ccaras south of Indraprastha (प्रययु
दक्षिणां दिशम् 2. 28. 1; also 2. 23. 9;
see below Epic events No. 1).
B. Des-
cription: Pleasing (रमणीय) 4. 1. 8;
(रम्य) 4. 1. 9; having ample food
(बह्वन्न) 4. 1. 9; protected (गुप्त) 4. 1.
8.
C. Epic events; (1) Sahadeva, in
his expedition to the south before the
Rājasūya, defeated Paṭaccaras (व्यजयत्
स पटच्चरान्) 2. 28. 4; (2) On the
second day of the war, Yudhiṣṭhira along
with Paṭaccara and other warriors formed
the ‘back’ (पृष्ठम्) of the Krauñcāruṇa
(6. 46. 39; Krauñca 6. 47. 1) of the Pāṇḍa-
vas 6. 46. 47.
D. They figure in the
characterization of a king: A certain king
(not named) in the Pāṇdava army, is
referred to as ‘killer of the Paṭaccaras’;
he was driven by parrot-coloured horses
(तं पटच्चरहन्तारं शुकवर्णावहन्
ःअयाः) 7. 22. 53; (तं पटच्चरहन्तारम्)
7. 24. 32.

पत्तिपञ्जक
Pattipañjaka m. (pl.): Name of a
Janapada.
Listed by Saṃjaya among the southern
Janapadas (also called Deśas 6. 10. 68) of
Bhāratavarṣa (अथापरे जनपदा दक्षि-
ना … ) 6. 10. 56; (सतियः पत्तिपञ्जकाः)
6. 10. 62.

पनीतक
Panītaka m. (pl.): Name of a Jana-
pada.
Listed by Saṃjaya among the nor-
thern Janapadas (also called Deśas 6. 10.
68) of Bhāratavarṣa (जनपदान् निबोध)
6. 10. 37; गोपराष्ट्राः पनीतकाः) 6. 10. 42.

परतङ्गण
Parataṅgaṇa m. (pl.): Name of a
Janapada and its people.
A. Location: Listed by Saṃjaya
among the southern Janapadas (also called
Deśas 6. 10. 68) of Bhāratavarṣa (आथापरे
जनपदा दक्षिणा … ) 6. 10. 56; तङ्गणाः
परतङ्गणाः) 6. 10. 63; but they are also
said to have lived on a mountain between
Meru and Mandara, near the river Śailodā
and enjoyed the pleasing shade of bamboo
trees (मेरुमन्दरयोर् मध्ये शैलो-
दाम् अभितो नदीम्।ये ते कीचकवेणूनां
छायां रम्याम् उपासते॥) 2. 48. 2.
B. Epic events: (1) Their kings brought
as tribute for the Rājasūya gold called
‘पिपीलिक’, given as boon by ants, in heaps
to be measured by द्रोणस् (ते वै पिपीलिकं
नाम वरदत्तं पिपीलिकैः।जातरूपं
द्रोणमेयम् अहार्षुः पुञ्जशो नृपाः) 2.
48. 4; (2) On the sixth day of war, they
and other warriors were stationed on the
right side of the Krauñcāruṇavyūha (6.
46. 39; Krauñca 6. 47. 1) of the Pāṇḍavas
(दक्षिणं पक्षम् आश्रिताः) 6. 46. 49-50.

परमकाम्बोज
Paramakāmboja m. (pl.): Name of a
people.
Arjuna in his expedition to the north
(दिशं धनपतेर् इष्टाम्) 2. 23. 9; 2.
24. 1 and the north-west (प्रागुत्तरां
दिशम् 2. 24. 23) defeated Paramakāmbojas
(परमकाम्बोजान् व्यजयत्) 2. 24. 24.
[See Kāmboja].

परवल्लक
Paravallaka m. (pl.): Name of a
Janapada.
Listed by Saṃjaya among the northern
Janapadas (also called Deśas 6. 10. 68) of
Bhāratavarṣa (जनपदान् निबोध) 6. 10.
37, 5; (लाङ्गलाः परवल्लकाः) 6. 10. 55.

परसंचरक
Parasaṃcaraka m. (pl.): Name of a
Janapada.
Listed by Saṃjaya among the southern
Janapadas (also called Deśas 6. 10. 68) of
Bhāratavarṣa (अथापरे जनपदा दक्षि-
णा … ) 6. 10. 56, 5; (प्रोष्ठाः परसंचर-
कास् तथा) 6. 10. 60.

पर्वतान्तरवासिन्
Parvatāntaravāsin m. (pl.): General
characterization of people living in the
valleys.
They came for the Rājasūya of Yudhi-
ṣṭhira with large tributes of various kinds
but were stopped at the gate (पर्वतान्-
तरवासिनः … द्वारि वारितान्।बल्यर्थं
ददतस् तस्य नानारूपान् अनेकशः) 2. 47.
19-20; (बलिं च कृत्स्नम् आदाय द्वारि
तिष्ठन्ति वारिताः) 2. 47. 25; their tributes
consisting of asses, woolen and other
kinds of cloth, soft deer-skins, long swords
and other weapons, sharp axes produced
in the west, and various juices and per-
fumes described in 2. 47. 21-28.

पलदाश
Paladāśa m. (pl.): Name of a people.
On the second day of the war, they
and other warriors stood on the left side
of the Krauñcāruṇavyūha (6. 46. 39;
Krauñca 6. 47. 1) of the Pāṇḍavas (पल-
दाशाश् च भारत … वामं पार्श्वं समा-
श्रिताः) 6. 46. 51.

पल्लव
Pallava: See Pahlava.

पशु
Paśu m. (pl.): Name of a people.
Listed by Saṃjaya among the northern
mleccha people of the Bhāratavarṣa (उत्तराश्
चापरे म्लेच्छा जना … ) 6. 10. 63; (काश्मी-
राः पशुभिः सह) 6. 10. 66.

पशुप
Paśupa m. (pl.): Characterization of
a people.
A. Location: They lived between the
mountains Meru and Mandara, along the
river Śailodā and enjoyed the delightful
shade of the bamboos and reeds 2. 48.
2-3.
B. Epic events: Their kings brought
as tribute for the Rājasūya gold called
पिपीलिक, given as boon by the ants, in lumps
to be measured by द्रोणस् 2. 48. 4 (for
citations see Parataṅgaṇa).

पशुभूमि
Paśubhūmi f. (sg.): Name of a land.
Bhīma in his expedition to the east
(भीमसेनस् तथा प्राचीम् 2. 23. 9; 2. 26.
1; पूर्वदेशम् 2. 26. 9) before the Rāja-
śūya conquered the whole of the Paśu-
bhūmi (विजिग्ये … पशुभूमिं च सर्वशः)
2. 27. 7-8.

पश्चिमानूपक
Paścimānūpaka m. (pl.): Name of a
people (living near watery places ?)
They lived in the west; mentioned by
Drupada among the peoples whose kings
were to be approached by Yudhiṣṭhira for
help in war (ये नृपाः। … पश्चिमानूपकाश्
च ये) 5. 4. 15.

पह्लव
Pahlava (Pallava) m. (pl.): Name
of a people.
A. Mentioned by Saṃjaya while listing
the northern Janapadas (also called Deśas
6. 10. 68) of Bhāratavarṣa (जनपदान् निबो-
ध) 6. 10. 37, 5 (पल्लवाश् चर्मखण्डि-
काः) 6. 10. 46, and also while listing the
northern म्लेच्छ people of Bhāratavarṣa
(उत्तराश् चापरे म्लेच्छा जना … तुखाराश्
च पल्लव … ) 6. 10. 63, 66; they lived by the
gulf of the western ocean (प्रतीचीम् 2. 23.
10; 2. 29. 19); (सागरकुक्षिस्थान्) 2. 29.
15; also lived in the caves of mountains
(पल्लवा गिरिगह्वराः) 6. 10. 66.
B. Origin:
Created by Nandinī, the cow of Vasiṣṭha,
from her tail (असृजत् पह्लवान् पुच्छात्)
1. 165. 35.
C. Characterization: Called
म्लेच्छ पेओप्ले 6. 10. 63; very cruel म्ले-
च्छस् (म्लेच्छान् परमदारुणान्) 2. 29. 15;
they lived in countries but led the life of
दस्युस् (सर्वे विषयवासिनः। … सर्वे ते
दस्युजीविनः) 12. 65. 15.
D. Epic events:
(1) Nakula in his expedition to the west
(प्रतीचीम् 2. 23. 10; 2. 29. 11; वासुदेव-
जिताम् आशाम् 2. 29. 1) before the Rājasūya
brought Pahlavas under control (पह्लवान्
 … अनयद् वशम्) 2. 29. 15; (2) The
Kṣatriyas among them brought wealth by
hundreds as tribute for the Rājasūya
(पह्लवैः सह … आहार्षुः क्षत्रिया वित्तं
शतशो ऽजातशत्रवे) 2. 48. 14, 16; (3)
Drupada suggested to Yudhiṣṭhira to send
quickly messengers to the kings of Pahlavas
and others for help in war (दूता गच्छन्तु
शीघ्रगाः) 5. 4. 8, 25; (शकानां पह्लवा-
नां च … ये नृपाः) 5. 4. 15 (but
they joined the side of the Kauravas; see
the next); (4) When the army of the
Kauravas got ready for war, Kṛpa,
along with Pahlavas and others guarded
the army on the northern side (पह्लवैश्
च … चमूम् उत्तरतो ऽभिपाति) 6. 20. 13.
E. Past events: Māndhātṛ asked Indra
about the धर्म of the Pahlavas and others
and how they should be controlled by kings
like him (पह्लवाश् … कथं धर्मं
चरेयुस् ते … मद्विधैश् च कथं स्था-
प्याः) 12. 65. 13, 15; Indra then instructed
Māndhātṛ in the धर्म of Pahlavas 12.
65. 17-22.

पांशु
Pāṃśu(Pāṃsu)rāṣṭra n. (sg.), m.
(pl.): Name of a Janapada and its people.
A. Location: Listed by Saṃjaya
among the northern Janapadas (also called
Deśas 6. 10. 68) of Bhāratavarṣa (जन-
पदान् निबोध) 6. 10. 37, 5; (अश्मकाः
पांसुराष्ट्राश् च) 6. 10. 42.
B. Epic
events: King Vasudāna of Pāṃśurāṣṭra
offered as tribute for the Rājasūya twenty-
six elephants and two thousand horses,
wearing gold garlands, and who were
speedy, strong and of proper age (पांशु-
राष्ट्राद् वसुदानो राजा षड्विंशतिं गजान्।
अश्वानां च सहस्रे द्वे राजन् काञ्चनमा-
लिनां।जवसत्त्वोपपन्नानां वयःस्था-
नां नराधिप) 2. 48. 26-27.
C. A king
of Pāṃśurāṣṭra (not named; Vasudāna ?)
called पांसुराष्ट्राधिप 5. 4. 17.

पाञ्चाल
Pāñcāla m. (pl.): Name of a Jana-
pada or a Rāṣṭra and its people; Pāñcālas
are sometimes identified with Sṛñjayas, but
also often mentioned separately from them.
A. Location: Listed by Saṃjaya
twice among the northern Janapadas (also
called Deśas 6. 10. 68) of Bhāratavarṣa
(अत ऊर्ध्वं जनपदान् निबोध) 6. 10. 37,
5; तत्रेमे कुरूपाञ्चालाः) 6. 10. 37;
(पाञ्चालाः कौशिजाश् चैव) 6. 10. 40; called
Janapada also in 4. 1. 9. and Rāṣṭra in
1. 128. 7; 4. 1. 8; listed by Arjuna among
the Janapadas lying around the Kuru
country (सन्ति रम्या जनपदा … परितः
कुरून्।पाञ्चालाश् चेदिमत्स्याश् च) 4. 1. 9;
to the east of Indraprastha (ययौ प्राचीं
दिशं प्रति) 2. 26. 1; 2. 23. 9; (also see
Epic events No. 11 below); the way of
Pāṇḍavas from Dvaitavana (3. 295. 2-3, 5)
to the Matsya country lay between Pāñcāla
to the north and Daśārṇa to the south
(उत्तरेण दशार्णांस् ते पाञ्चालान् दक्षि-
णेन तु) 4. 5. 3; the तीर्थ Utpalāvata was
situated in Pāñcāla country 3. 85. 11;
Pāñcāla was divided by Droṇa into nor-
thern and southern Pāñcāla, the dividing
line being the river Bhāgīrathī (राजासि
दक्षिने कूले भागीरथ्याहम् उत्तरे) 1.
128. 12; southern Pāñcāla country lay to the
south of Gaṅgā and up to Carmaṇvatī river
(दक्षिणांश् चैव पाञ्चालान् यावच् चर्मण्-
वती नदी) 1. 128. 15, 12.
B. Origin:
All Pāñcālas traced their origin to Duḥṣanta
and Parameṣṭhin (तथेमे सर्वपाञ्चाला
दुःषन्तपरमेष्ठिनोः।अन्वयाः) 1. 89. 29.
C. Description: (1) Country: pleasing
(रमणीय), protected (गुप्त) and rich
in harvest (बह्वन्न) 4. 1. 9; alms were
easily available in the Pāñcāla country
(सुभिक्षाश् चैव पाञ्चालाः) 1. 156. 7; (2)
People: high-sould (महात्मन्) 5. 168.
11; 7. 132. 38; 8. 31. 51; 8. 43. 53; a certain
Brāhmaṇa told the assembly of Kurus
that Pāñcālas (as well as Kurus) knew
the eternal धर्म; they followed the
ancient धर्म; Pāñcālas were as good as
brahminhood incarnate (कुरवः सह-
पाञ्चालाः … धर्मं जानन्ति शाश्वतम्;
धर्मं पुराणम् उपजीवन्ति; आ पाञ्चाल-
भ्यः कुरवो … जानन्ति धर्मं; ब्राह्मं
पाञ्चालाः) 8. 30. 60-62; 73, 75; Pāñcālas
could guess correctly everything when
only a part was told to them (अर्धोक्ताः
कुरुपाञ्चालाः (जानन्ति)) 8. 30. 79; (3)
Warriors: having arms as long as a परिघ
(परिघबाहु) 6. 114. 107; heroic (शूर)
6. 114. 107; 7. 97. 51; 7. 101. 68; 8. 8. 19;
8. 32. 38; 8. 56. 47; (वीर) 7. 55. 9; of
great energy (महौजस्) 2. 72. 29; 3. 48.
6; 7. 132. 41; energetic (तरस्विन्) 8. 51.
99; great archers (महेष्वास) 6. 84. 3;
8. 51. 95; 9. 6. 40; great chariot-fighters
(महारथ) 5. 168. 11; 7. 85. 28; 8.
51. 95; tamers of enemies, they were
always determined to defeat the enemies
(ते नित्यम् उदिता जेतुं युद्धे शत्रून्
अरिंदमाः) 8. 51. 98; tormentors of
adversaries (परंतप) 8. 60. 26; arrogant
in wars (युद्धदुर्मद) 5. 162. 22; 8.
43. 3; who have done valorous deeds
(पराक्रान्त) 5. 52. 2; excellent among
those who wield weapons (सर्वशस्त्र-
भृतां वराः) 8. 43. 22; tigers among men
(नरव्याघ्र) 8. 43. 61; 8. 44. 8; 9. 1. 30;
9. 7. 42; compared with Indra (शक्रोपम)
7. 133. 4; difficult to resist, not easy to
attack them (दुर्निवार्य, दुरासद) 7.
31. 38; they fought like agitated elephants
(संरब्धा इव कुञ्जराः) 5. 168. 11;
not afraid while fighting (न त्व् एव भीताः)
8. 51. 95; not running away, rarely showing
their backs (अपलायिन्) 8. 43. 59; (कथं-
चित् स्युः पराङ्मुखाः) 8. 51. 95; their
great warriors did not care for death (न
हि मृत्युं महेष्वासा गणयन्ति महा-
रथाः) 8. 51. 95; in war they closely
followed the आर्यधर्म (आर्यधर्मसं-
रब्ध) 7. 31. 38; cruel (क्रूर) 7. 30. 6;
they are also called inauspicious (अशिव)
and capable of doing cruel deeds (क्रूर-
कर्मन्) 7. 7. 32; mean and betrayers of
friends and teacher, they could stray away
from धर्म (पाञ्चालाश् चलिता धर्मात्
क्षुद्रा मित्रगुरुद्रुहः) 7. 169. 18.
D.
Epic events: Drupada became the king of
the Uttara Pāñcāla after his father's death
1. 121. 10; (2) Kauravas and Pāṇḍavas
attacked the Pāñcālas and crushed the
capital town of Drupada (ममृदुस् तस्य
नगरं द्रुपदस्य) 1. 128. 4; (3) After
his defeat, Drupada was allowed by Droṇa
