पारतक
Pārataka m. (pl.): Name of a people.
Mentioned by Saṃjaya among the
northern Mleccha people of Bhāratavarṣa
(उत्तराश् चापरे म्लेच्छा जना … ) 6. 10. 63,
5; these म्लेच्छ tribes are described as
cruel (दारुणा म्लेच्छजातयः। … हूणाः
पारतकैः सह) 6. 10. 64.

पारद
Pārada m. (pl.): Name of a people
characterized as म्लेच्छस्।
A. Location: They are mentioned
along with other north-western tribes like
Daradas, Dārvas, Bāhlīkas and others
(वायव्या दरदा दार्वाः … पारदाः बाह्लि-
कैः सह) 2. 48. 12; (शकाः … यव-
नाः पारदास् तथा) 7. 97. 13; 7. 68. 41;
however, they are said to have been
born in the bay (?) of the ocean and
around Sindhu river (समुद्रनिष्कुटे जाताः
परिसिन्धु च मानवाः।ते … पारदाश् च)
2. 47. 9-10 (Nī., however, on Bom. Ed.
2. 51. 11 takes निष्कुट to mean a house-
garden: समुद्रसमीपस्थनिष्कुटे गृहो-
द्याने … ).
B. Characteristic: They main-
tained themselves on grains which grew of
their own accord or on those cultivated
with river water (इन्द्रकृष्टैर् वर्तयन्ति
धान्यैर् नदीमुखैश् च ये) 2. 47. 9 (Nī.
on Bom. Ed. 2. 51. 11: इन्द्रकृष्टैः इन्द्रे-
णैवाकृष्टैः न तु कर्षणादिक्षेत्रिययत्ना-
पेक्षैः वनधान्यैः वृष्ट्यभावे तु नदी-
मुखैः नदीप्रभवैः).
C. Descrip-
tion: Very frightful and having terrible
eyes; they knew the tricks of Asuras
(विदन्त्य् असुरमायां ये सुघोरा घोर-
चक्षुषः) 7. 68. 41.
D. Epic events: (1)
They brought for the Rājasūya of Yudhi-
ṣṭhira tribute of different kinds like goats
and sheep (अजाविकम्), cows, donkeys,
camels, gold, and jewels, wine made from
fruits (फलजं मधु) and blankets
(कम्बलान्), but were stopped at the gate
(द्वारि तिष्ठन्ति वारिताः) 2. 47. 10-11; their
kings (राजन्याः, क्षत्रियाः) brought wealth
by hundreds for the Rājasūya 2. 48. 12,
16, (13); (2) On the eighth day of war
they accompanied Droṇa who marched
out immediately after Bhīṣma 6. 83. 7;
(3) On the fourteenth day, a large number
of them were killed by Arjuna 7. 68. 41,
(33, 37, 44); on the same day, they, along
with Śakas and others and led by Duryo-
dhana, attacked Sātyaki; there were three
thousand horse-riders of them (त्रीणि सादि-
सहस्राणि) 7. 97. 13; they were killed by
Sātyaki 7. 97. 20.

पारसीक
Pārasīka m. (pl.): Name of a Jana-
pada.
Listed by Saṃjaya among the northern
Janapadas (also called Deśas 6. 10. 68) of
Bhāratavarṣa (जनपदान् निबोध … ) 6. 10.
37, 5; (तिलकाः पारसीकाश् च) 6. 10. 51.

पार्वतीय
Pārvatīya m. (pl.): Name of a Jana-
pada and its people living in mountainous
regions; their kings are also referred to as
Pārvatīyas.
A. Location: Listed by Saṃjaya
among the northern Janapadas (also called
Deśas 6. 10. 68) of Bhāratavarṣa (जन-
पदान् निबोध) 6. 10. 37, 5; (ससैरन्ध्राः
पार्वतीयाश् च) 6. 10. 56.
B. Description:
Living on mountains (शैलवासिन्) 7. 97.
32; heroic (शूर) 3. 255. 8; 5. 30. 24; 7.
97. 15, 26, 29, 37-38; wrathful, fond of
wars, strong, firm-fisted (संरम्भिणो
युद्धशौण्डा बलिनो दृब्धपाणयः) 8.
51. 19; very strong (सुमहाबल) 2. 48.
6; difficult to be defeated (दुर्जय)
and difficult to look at (दुर्दर्श) 8.
31. 13; (great) chariot-fighters (रथ)
5. 196. 6; 7. 97. 15; (महारथ) 3.
255. 8; rough like mountains (विषमा
यथैव गिरयस् तथा) 8. 30. 79; they
fought with rocks and were expert in
fighting with rocks (पाषाणयोधिन्, अश्म-
युद्धेषु कुशलाः) 7. 97. 15, 29-30; 34-35,
37-38; not cruel (अनृशंस) and of good
character and conduct (शीलवृत्तोपपन्न)
5. 30. 24; they could not be defeated
by any one except Arjuna (न शक्या
युधि निर्जेतुं त्वदन्येन परंतप) 8.
51. 20.
C. Epic events: (1) Pārvatīyas
brought for the Rajasūya tribute in the
form of black chowries and other chow-
ries white like moon, ample sweet honey
gathered from Himalayan flowers; flowers
brought down by waters from Uttara
Kurus, and powerful herbs from northern
Kailāsa; they were stopped at the gate
and not allowed to enter (कृष्णाल् लला-
मांश् चमराञ् शुक्लांश् चान्याञ् शशिप्र-
भान्।हिमवत्पुष्पजं चैव स्वादु क्षौ-
द्रं तथा बहु॥उत्तरेभ्यः कुरुभ्यस्
चाप्य् अपोढं माल्यम् अम्बुभिः।उत्तराद्
अपि कैलासाद् ओषधीः सुमहाबलाः॥ …
द्वारि तिष्ठन्ति वारिताः॥) 2. 48. 5-7;
(2) Arjuna killed five hundred Pārvatīya
chariot fighters who accompanied Jaya-
dratha 3. 255. 8; (3) Yudhiṣṭhira asked
Saṃjaya to convey to all the Pārva-
tīya kings who had sided with Duryo-
dhana against Pāṇḍavas that he enquired
about their welfare (तेषां सर्वेषां
कुशलं तात पृच्छेः) 5. 30. 23-24; (4)
Pārvatīya chariot-fighters, along with
others, marched towards Kurukṣetra in the
second division of the army (द्वितीये
निर्ययुर् बले) 5. 196. 6, 8, 11; (5) On
the twelfth day of war, Pārvatīyas and
others formed the back (पृष्ठ) of the
Suparṇavyūha of the Kauravas 7. 19. 4,
11; (6) On the fourteenth day, five
hundred chariot-fighters of Pārvatīyas
attacked Sātyaki; they were all expert in
fighting with rocks; hence Duḥśāsana in-
cited them to attack Sātyaki who was not
expert in fighting with rocks: Sātyaki cut
off with नाराच arrows their arms and
killed, first, five hundred and then many
thousands of them 7. 97. 15, 29-38; (7)
On the seventeenth day, Pārvatīyas, led by
Śakuni, and Ulūka, guarded the extreme end
(प्रपक्ष) of the right wing (दक्षिणम्
पक्षम्) of the व्यूह of the Kauravas 8.
31. 11-13; Kṛṣṇa listed Pārvatīyas among
those who took the side of the Kurus for
the sake of Duryodhana and who could
not be defeated by any body except Arjuna
8. 51. 19-20; (8) Saṃjaya listed Pārvatī-
yas among those who were killed in the
war (पार्वतीयाश् च यवनाश् च निपातिताः)
9. 1. 26; (9) Vasudeva listed Pārvatīya
kings (पार्वतीयांस् तथा नृपान्) among
those who were formerly defeated by
Kṛṣṇa 16. 7. 11; earlier Dhṛtarāṣṭra also
had referred to the same event 7. 10. 16.
D. 1. Some persons referred to as पार्व-
तीय: (i) Janamejaya (a certain king who
was killed by Durmukha) 8. 4. 70; (ii)
Śakuni 2. 56. 10; 3. 35. 3; 5. 30. 27; 2.
Their excellent horses are also referred to
as Pārvatīya (पार्वतीयान् … हयवरान्) 7.
97. 26.

पालन
Pālana nt. (sg.): Name of a Varṣa.
It is the fourth in a cluster of seven
Varṣas of the Kuśadvīpa which is situa-
ted to the north of Jambhudvīpa (उत्तरेषु
च … द्वीपेषु) 6. 13. 1; (चतुर्थं पालनं
स्मृतम्। … सप्तैते वर्षपुञ्जकाः) 6. 12.
12-13; for the description of the people
which is common to all the Varṣas of the
Kuśadvīpa (6. 13. 14-15) see Audbhida.

पिशाच
Piśāca m. (pl.): Name of a Janapada
and its people.
A. Called Janapada (पिशाचा दरदाश्
चैव … एते जनपदा राजन्) 6. 46. 49-50.
B. Epic events: (1) On the second day
of war, Piśācas on the side of the
Pāṇḍavas, along with Daradas, Puṇḍras
and others, stood on the right side of the
Krauñcāruṇavyūha (6. 46. 39, Krauñca 6.
47. 1) of the Pāṇḍavas (दक्षिणं पक्षम्
आश्रिताः) 6. 46. 49-50. (2) On the eighth
day, led by Bhagadatta, Piśācas on the
side of Kauravas marched behind Droṇa
6. 83. 8; (3) On the fourteenth day, led
by Duryodhana, they attacked Sātyaki who
was trying to reach Arjuna 7. 97. 14; (4)
Listed among those who were defeated by
Kṛṣṇa 7. 10. 16.
C. Their relationship
with Bāhlīkas: According to a certain
Brāhmaṇa who was speaking in the Kuru
assembly Bāhlīkas were the progeny of
two Piśācakas called Bahi and Hlīka who
lived near Vipāśā and they were not created
by Prajāpati (बहिश् च नाम ह्लीकश् च विपा-
शायां पिशाचकौ।तयोर् अपत्यं बाह्लीका
नैषा सृष्टिः प्रजापतेः॥) 8. 30. 44.
D.
A female reciter of an अनुवंश श्लोक:
A certain Piśāca woman (पिशाची), wear-
ing mortar-like ear-ornaments, used to
recite अनुवंश श्लोकस् near the gate of
Kurukṣetra (अत्रानुवंशं पठतः शृणु
मे कुरुनन्दन।उलूखलैर् आभरणैः
पिशाची यद् अभाषत॥ … द्वारम् एतद् धि
कौन्तेय कुरुक्षेत्रस्य … ) 3. 129. 8, 11
(the औन्वंश श्लोकस् are 3. 129. 9-10)
(Nī. on Bom. Ed. 3. 129. 8: अनुवंशं
परंपरागतम् आख्यानश्लोकम्).

पुण्ड्र
Puṇḍra(ka) m. (pl.): Name of a
Janapada and its people; the people,
warriors and their certain kings also desi-
gnated as Pauṇḍra(ka); once used as an
adj. (2. 13. 19).
A. Location: Listed by Saṃjaya
twice among the northern Janapadas (also
called Deśas 6. 10. 68) of Bhāratavarṣa
(जनपदान् निबोध) 6. 10. 37, 5: (पुण्ड्रा
भार्गाः किराताश् च) 6. 10. 49; (ओष्ट्राः
पुण्ड्राः ससैरन्ध्राः) 6. 10. 56; located
along the eastern ocean: From Magadha,
Arjuna directed the Aśvamedha horse to
the south along the sea passing through
Vaṅgas, Puṇḍras and Keralas (पाण्डवः
 … दक्षिणां दिशम् आस्थाय चारयाम्
आस तं हयम् 14. 84. 1; ततः समु-
द्रतीरेण वङ्गान् पुण्ड्रान् सकेरलान्)
14. 83. 29; called Janapada also in 6. 46.
49-50 (पुण्ड्राः … एते जनपदा राजन्).
B. Origin: Nandinī, the cow of Vasiṣṭha,
created Puṇḍras from her foam (पुण्ड्रान्
 … फेनतः सा ससर्ज ह) 1. 165. 36.
C.
Social status: Paunḍras, listed among
those Kṣatriyas who became degraded as
वृषल because they disregarded Brāhmaṇas
(पौण्ड्राः … क्षत्रियजातयः।वृषलत्वम्
अनुप्राप्ता ब्राह्मणानाम् अदर्शनात्) 13. 35.
17-18; and also because they violated the
धर्म of Kṣatriyas (क्षत्रियाः केचित् …
तेषां … प्रजा वृषलतां प्राप्ता ब्राह्मणा-
नाम् अदर्शनात्॥त एते … पुण्ड्राश् च … ।
वृषलत्वं परिगता व्युत्थानात् क्षत्रधर्-
मतः।) 14. 29. 14-16; called म्लेच्छस्
(पुण्ड्रान् सकेरलान्।तत्र तत्र च भू-
रीणि म्लेच्छसैन्यान्य् अनेकशः विजिग्ये॥।
धनंजयः) 14. 83. 29-30.
D. Special
feature: Their warriors fought riding ele-
phants; they were skilled in fighting battles
while riding elephants (गजयोधिनः;
गजयुद्धेषु कुशलाः) 8. 17. 2-3.
E.
Epic events: (1) Pāṇḍu spread the
fame of Kurus in the Puṇḍra country
(पुण्ड्रेषु … कुरूणाम् अकरोद् यशः) 1.
105. 12; (2) King Vāsudeva was known
as ‘Pauṇḍraka Vāsudeva’ among the
Vaṅgas, Puṇḍras and Kirātas (वङ्ग-
पुण्ड्रकिरातेषु राजा … ।पौण्ड्रको वासु-
देवेति … लोकेषु विश्रुतः) 2. 13. 19; Bhīma,
in his expedition to the east (ययौ प्राचीं
दिशं प्रति 2. 26. 1; 2. 23. 9) before
the Rājasūya, defeated the king of the
Pauṇḍra people in battle (पौण्ड्राधिपं
 … वासुदेवम् … निर्जित्याजौ) 2. 27. 20-21;
(3) Puṇḍra Kṣatriyas brought wealth in
hundreds for the Rājasūya (आहार्षुः क्ष-
त्रिया वित्तं शतशो ऽजातशत्रवे) 2. 48.
15-16; they (Puṇḍrakas) also brought
fine cloth, silk and woolen materials,
and mantles; they were asked by the
gatekeepers to bring more; when they
brought additional tribute they were
allowed to enter through the gate (for
citation see Tāmralipta) 2. 48. 17-20; a
Pauṇḍra king (not named, Vāsudeva ?),
among others, served as server at Rāja-
sūya (यत्र सर्वान् महीपालान् … सपौ-
ण्ड्रोड्रान् … यज्ञे ते परिवेषकान्) 3. 48.
18, 22; (4) On the second day of war,
Puṇḍras were one of the Janapadas who
stood at the right wing (दक्षिणं पक्षम्)
of the Krauñcāruṇavyūha (6. 46. 39;
Krauñca 6. 47. 1) of Pāṇḍavas 6. 46. 49-
50; (5) On the third day, Puṇḍras
(पुण्ड्राविषस् तथा ?) stood at the left
wing (वामं पक्षम्) of the Gāruḍa-
vyūha (6. 52. 2) of Kauravas 6. 52. 9;
(6) Among the past exploits of Kṛṣṇa,
Dhṛtarāṣṭra mentioned his victory over
Puṇḍras in battle 7. 10. 15; (7) On the
the twelfth day, Pauṇḍras formed the back
of the Suparṇavyūha (पृष्ठे … पौण्ड्र-
मद्रकाः) (7. 19. 4) of Kauravas 7. 19.
11; (8) On the fourteenth day, Arjuna
killed Puṇḍras and others in hundreds and
thousands (न ते स्म शक्याः संख्यातुम्
व्राता शतसहस्रशः) 7. 68. 42-43; (9)
On the sixteenth day, Karṇa's former
victory over Puṇḍras mentioned by Dhṛta-
rāṣṭra 8. 5. 19 (a reference to Karṇa's
दिग्विजय before Duryodhana's Vaiṣṇava-
yāga 3. 241. 29, 32; 3. App. I. 24. 28-34);
the same day, incited by Duryodhana,
Puṇḍras, riding elephants, attacked Dhṛṣṭa-
dyumna showering him with arrows,
तोमरस् and नाराच arrows 8. 17. 2; (10)
Arjuna, accompanying the horse for the
Aśvamedha, reached Puṇḍras in the south
and conquered their म्लेच्छ armies (म्ले-
च्छसैन्यान्य् अनेकशः) 14. 83. 30.
F.
Certain kings called Puṇḍra, Puṇḍraka,
king of the Pauṇḍras or they have the
epithet पौण्ड्रक: (1) Puṇḍra 1. 1. 174;
Puṇḍraka 2. 4. 21; (2) A king (Vāsu-
deva ?): पौण्ड्राधिप 2. 27. 20; he was
known among Puṇḍras, Aṅgas and Kīrātas
as Pauṇḍraka Vāsudeva 2. 13. 19.

पुरुषादक
Puruṣādaka m. (pl.): Name of a
people.
They brought for the Rājasūya of
Yudhiṣṭhira large quantities of gold and
silver as tribute but were stopped at the
gate (पुरुषादकान्॥ … द्वारि वारितान्।
बल्यर्थं ददतस् तस्मै हिरण्यं रज-
तं बहु) 2. 47. 15-16.

पुलिन्द
Pulinda m. (pl.): Name of a Jana-
pada and its people.
A. Location: Listed by Saṃjaya
among the southern Janapadas of the
Bhāratavarṣa (अथापरे जनपदा दक्षिणा
भरतर्षभ) 6. 10. 56, 5; (पुलिन्दाः
कल्कलैः सह) 6. 10. 60; listed among
those who were natives of Dakṣiṇāpatha
(दक्षिणापथजन्मानः … उत्साः पुलिन्दाः)
12. 200. 39; their capital town Pulinda-
nagara was in the south (ततो दक्षिणम्
आगम्य पुलिन्दनगरं महत्) 2. 26. 10.
B. Description: Cruel (क्रूर), rough
while fighting (संग्रामकर्कश) 8. 15.
10; wrathful (संरम्भिन्), fond of fighting
(युद्धशौण्ड), strong (बलिन्), firm-
fisted (दृब्धपाणि) 8. 51. 19; they could
not be defeated by any one except Arjuna
(न शक्या युधि निर्जेतुम् त्वदन्येन परं-
तप) 8. 51. 20; sinful, they lived like dogs,
crows, बलस् (?), and vultures (एते पाप-
कृतो … श्वकाकबलगृध्राणाम् सधर्-
माणो) 12. 200. 41; in the Kaliyuga (3. 186.
27), their sinful kings, given to lying,
ruled the wrong way (मिथ्यानुशासिनः
पापा मृषावादपरायणाः) 3. 186. 29, 30.
C. Social status: Classed as म्लेच्छस् 3.
186. 29; they lived in countries but led
the life of दस्युस् (विषयवासिनः … सर्वे
ते दस्युजीविनः) 12. 65. 14-15; they did
not exist in the Kṛtayuga but were to
be found since the Tretāyuga; they are
listed among those who did not believe
in Bhūtapati being the अध्यक्ष (of the
world) (एष भूतपतिस् तात स्वध्य-
क्षश् च प्रकीर्तितः।निरध्यक्षांस् तु
कौन्तेय कीर्तयिष्यामि तान् अपि॥उत्साः
पुलिन्दाः) 12. 200. 38-39; नैते कृतयुगे
तात चरन्ति पृथिवीम् इमाम्।त्रेताप्रभृति
वर्तन्ते) 12. 200. 42; they were originally
Kṣatriyas, but became degraded to the
status of a वृषल due to disregarding Brā-
hmaṇas (पुलिन्दाश् … तास् ताः क्षत्रियजात-
यः॥वृषलत्वं परिगता ब्राह्मणानाम्
अदर्शनात्) 13. 33. 20-21; those who do
not offer sacrifices do not obtain heaven
and remain established in the lower worlds
like Pulindas and Śabaras (अर्वाक् च प्रति-
तिष्ठन्ति पुलिन्दशबरा इव।न ह्य् अयज्ञा
अमुं लोकं प्राप्नुवन्ति कथंचन।)
12. 147. 8.
D. Epic events: (1) Bhīma
in his expedition before the Rājasūya went
to east (2. 23. 4; 2. 26. 1, 7, 9) and then
to the South to reach the capital town of
Pulindas; he vanquished there Sukumāra
and Sumitra, the kings of Pulindas (ततो
दक्षिणम् आगम्य पुलिन्दनगरं महत्।
सुकुमारं वशे चक्रे सुमित्रं च नरा-
धिपम्॥) 2. 26. 10; (2) Pulindas formed
a part of Duryodhana's army 5. 158. 20;
8. 51. 20; (3) On the eighth day of war,
they followed Droṇa who was behind
Bhīṣma standing in the forefront of the
Mahāvyūha of Kauravas 6. 83. 7, 22; (4)
On the sixteenth day, Pāṇḍya king killed
Pulindas riding horses and fighting with
शक्ति, प्रास, and arrows (सशक्तिप्रास-
तूणीरान् अश्वारोहान्) depriving them of
their weapons and arrows with his arrows
8. 15. 9-10.
E. Past event: Māndhātṛ
asked Indra the nature of the धर्म to
be followed by people like Pulindas and
how they should be made to behave properly
by kings like him (कथं धर्मं चरे-
युस् ते … मद्विधैश् च कथं स्थाप्याः)
12. 65. 14-15; Indra then taught the
धर्म of Dasyus 12. 65. 17-23. [See
Pulindaka].

पुलिन्दक
Pulindaka m. (pl.): Name of a Jana-
pada.
Listed separately from Pulinda by
Saṃjaya among the northern Janapadas
(also called Deśas 6. 10. 68) of Bhārata-
varṣa (अत ऊर्ध्वं जनपदान् निबोध)
6. 10. 37, 5; (सिन्धुपुलिन्दकाः) 6. 10. 39.
[See Pulinda].

पुष्कर
Puṣkara m.: Name of a द्वीप।
A. Location: It is one of the seven
द्वीपस् which are to the north of Jambū-
dvīpa (उत्तरेषु तु … द्वीपेषु) 6. 13. 1;
(सप्त त्व् अहं प्रवक्ष्यामि) 6. 12. 4.
B.
Characteristics: It has a mountain called
Puṣkara which is full of jewels (पुष्करे
पुष्करो नाम पर्वतो मणिरत्नमान्) 6.
13. 24; God Prajāpati lives on this mountain
and is worshipped with agreeable words
by gods and all great sages 6. 13. 24-25; for
characteristics which are common to all
Dvīpas see Kuśadvīpa.

पौण्ड्र
Pauṇḍra(ka): See Puṇḍra(ka).

पौरक
Pauraka m. (pl.): Name of a people.
Their kings (राजन्याः 2. 48. 13; क्षत्रि-
याः 2. 48. 16) brought tribute in hundreds
for Yudhiṣṭhira's Rājasūya (पौरका … । …
आहार्षुः क्षत्रिया वित्तं शतशो ऽजात-
शत्रवे) 2. 48. 13, 16.

पौरव
Paurava (Pauravaka) m. (pl.): Name
of a people, and general characterization
of those born in the family cf Pūru; only
once referred to as Pauravaka (6. 46. 47).
A. Origin: The lineage of Pūru
known as Paurava (पूरोस् तु पौरवो
वंशः) 1. 80. 27; (पूरोः पौरवाः) 1. 90.
10; (त्वं मे वंशकरः सुतः।पौरवो
वंश इति ते ख्यातिं लोके गमिष्यति) 1.
70. 45.
B. Characteristics of their kings:
of famous conduct and wise (प्रथितवृत्त,
विज्ञानशालिन्); no one of them ever lacked
character, heroism or progeny (न ह्य् अस्मिञ्
शीलहीनो वा निर्वीर्यो वा … प्रजाविरहितो वापि
भूतपूर्वः कदाचन॥) 1. 89. 2-3; they
were heroic, and in lustre they equalled
Indra (वीराञ् शक्रप्रतिमतेजसः) 1. 89. 4;
their acts did not distress others (अक्लिष्टकर्-
मन्) 1. 109. 20; the poem narrating the
Paurava dynasty was in every respect holy,
brought good fortune, wealth, long life and
fame (वंशं पौरवाणां च सर्वशः॥
 … पुण्यं स्वस्त्ययनं महत्।धन्यं
यशस्यम् आयुष्यं) 1. 70. 2; their warriors
were great archers (महेष्वास) 7. 145.
46.
C. Epic events: (1) Śaṃtanu
anointed his son Bhīṣma as the crown
prince of Pauravas (पौरवेषु ततः पुत्रं
यौवराज्ये ऽभ्यषेचयत्) 1. 94. 38; Bhīṣma
gratified the Pauravas by his conduct
(पौरवाञ् … रञ्जयाम् आस वृत्तेन) 1.
94. 39; (2) On the second day of war,
Yudhiṣṭhira, with Pauravakas and others
formed the back (पृष्ठम्) of the Krauñ-
cāruṇavyūha (6. 46. 39, Krauñca 6. 47. 1)
of the Pāṇḍavas 6. 46. 47; (3) On the
third day, Dhṛṣṭaketu, along with Paura-
vas and others stood at the right tip
(दक्षिणं शृङ्गम् आस्थाय) of the Ardha-
candravyūha (6. 52. 10) of Pāṇḍavas 6.
52. 13; (4) On the fourteenth day, Sātyaki
said that Pauravas (on the side of the
Kauravas) and others were no match for
Arjuna (कलां नार्हन्ति षोडशीम्) 7. 86.
28-29; (5) Hearing the sound of the
chariot and of Gāṇḍīva (श्रूत्वा तु रथनिर्-
घोषं गाण्डीवस्य च निस्वनम्), Karṇa
guessed that Arjuna had killed Śibis
and Pauravas (on the side of the Kaura-
vas) 7. 145. 45-46.
D. Past events:
Śakuntalā chose as a boon from Kaṇva
that those born in the lineage of Pūru be
firm in the practice of धर्म and not lose
their kingdom (ततो धर्मिष्ठतां वव्रे
राज्याच् चास्खलनं तथा। … पौरवाणाम्)
1. 67. 33.
E. Various persons called as
descendants of Pūru, delighters of Pūru's
descendants, propagators or bearers of the
line of Pūru: (A) Descendant of Pūru:
(i) पौरव: (1) Duḥṣanta 1. 68. 59; 1.
69. 32, 34; (2) Śaṃtanu 1. 94. 38; (3)
Saṃvaraṇa 1. 89. 39; (ii) पौरवदायाद:
Son of Viḍūratha (not named) 12. 49. 67;
(iii) पौरवाणां … वंशे जातः: Pāṇḍu
1. 109. 20; (B) Those who carry further
the line of Pauravas: (i) पौरवाणां
वंशकरः: Duḥṣanta 1. 62. 3; (ii) पौर-
वं वंशम् उद्वहन्: Taṃsu, son of
Matināra 1. 89. 12; (iii) पूरोर् वंश-
करान् नृपान् many kings 1. 89. 1; (iv)
पूरोर् वंशधरान् (नृपान्) 1. 89. 4: (C)
Delighter of the Pauravas: पौरवनन्दन
(1) Bharata 1. 89. 19; (2) Vasu Upari-
cara 1. 57. 2; (iii) Śaṃtanu 1. 93. 16;
(iv) Saṃvaraṇa 1. 160. 14.

प्रकुत्सक
Prakutsaka m. (pl.): Name of a Jana-
pada.
Listed by Saṃjaya among the northern
Janapadas (also called Deśas 6. 10. 68) of
Bhāratavarṣa (जनपदान् निबोध) 6. 10.
37, 5; (मधुमन्तः प्रकुत्सकाः) 6.
10. 51.

प्रचेत
Praceta m. (pl.): Name of a people.
Bṛhadbala, the king of Pracetas, listed
by Bhīma among the sixteen kings who
extirpated their kinsmen, friends and rela-
tives (ये समुच्चिछिदुर् ज्ञातीन् सुहृदश् च
सबान्धवान् … प्रचेतानां बृहद्बलः) 5.
72. 11, 16.

प्रतिमत्स्य
Pratimatsya m. (pl.): Name of a
Janapada.
Listed by Saṃjaya among the northern
Janapadas (also called Deśas 6. 10. 68) of
Bhāratavarṣa (जनपदान् निबोध) 6. 10.
37, 5; (दुगूलाः प्रतिमत्स्याश् च) 6. 10. 50.

प्रतीच्य
Pratīcya m. (pl.): General chara-
cterization of the western people; once
mentioned as Janapada (6. 114. 77).
A. Description of their warriors:
Brave (शूर) 8. 4. 49 and skilled in using
all kinds of weapons and missiles (सर्व-
शस्त्रास्त्रकुशल) 6. 16. 17; while fighting
they put on ornaments, besides armour
and good garments (सवर्माम्बरभू-
षण) 8. 4. 49; they were all brought up in
noble families (कुले ये च विवर्धिताः) 8.
4. 49.
B. Epic events: (1) To en-
courage Duryodhana, Karṇa reminded him
that kings of the west, along with the rest,
were made to pay tributes to him ( …
प्रतीच्योदीच्यवासिनः।कृताः करप्रदाः
सर्वे राजानस् ते नराधिप) 3. 226. 3; (2)
Yudhiṣṭhira asked Saṃjaya to convey to
western and other kings who had joined
the side of Duryodhana that he wished
them well (प्राच्योदीच्या … तेषां सर्वेषां
कुशलम् तात पृच्छेः) 5. 30. 23-24; (3)
Duryodhana's army was guarded among
others by the kings of the west 5. 158. 19-
20; their chariot-fighters mentioned among
those who marched towards Kurukṣetra
in Duryodhana's second division (दाक्षि-
णात्याः प्रातीच्याश् च … एते महारथाः
सर्वे द्वितीये निर्ययुर् बले) 5. 196. 6, 8;
(4) Before the start of the war, Duryo-
dhana instructed Duḥśāsana that the main
concern of westerners and others should
be to protect Bhīṣma 6. 16. 17; (5) On
the ninth day, Pratīcyas, though they were
getting killed by sharp arrows, did not
abandon Bhīṣma when he was fighting
with Pāṇḍava heroes (प्रतीच्योदीच्यमा-
लवाः। … संग्रामे नाजहुर् भीष्मं
वध्यमानाः शितैः शरैः) 6. 102. 7;
(6) On the tenth day, Pratīcyas were
among the twelve Janapadas who, though
they were pierced by arrows and wounded,
did not leave Bhīṣma alone who fought
with Arjuna (द्वादशैते जनपदाः शरार्ता
व्रणपी डिताः।संग्रामे नाजहुर् भीष्मं
युध्यमानं किरीटिना॥) 6. 114. 76-77;
(7) On the eleventh day, Pratīcyas and
others, led by Duryodhana, were behind
Karṇa who marched in front of all archers
(प्रतीच्योदीच्यवासिनः। … तवात्मजं
पुरस्कृत्य सूतपुत्रस्य पृष्ठतः॥ययौ
वैकर्तनः कर्णः प्रमुखे सर्वधन्वि-
नाम् 7. 6. 6-8; तावकानां मुखं कर्णः
7. 6. 21) of the Śakaṭavyūha of the Kaura-
vas 7. 6. 15; (8) On the seventeenth
day, Arjuna, while boasting himself before
Yudhiṣṭhira said that it was he who had
killed Pratīcyas and others 8. 49. 96; (9)
mentioned by Saṃjaya among those who
were killed in battle by Arjuna in the first
seventeen days of war 8. 4. 47; (10) Saṃ-
jaya, while reporting to Dhṛtarāṣṭra, men-
tioned Pratīcyas among those all of whom
were killed (उदीच्या निहताः सर्वे प्रतीच्याश्
च नराधिप) 9. 1. 27.

प्रदर
Pradara m. (pl.): Name of a people.
They lived in the region between the
mountains Meru and Mandara along the
river Śailodā and enjoyed the pleasing
shade of the bamboos and reeds; their
kings (नृपाः) brought Pipīlaka variety
of gold, given as boon by ants, in heaps
to be measured by द्रोण as tribute for the
Rājasūya; they also brought much other
tribute but were stopped at the gate 2.
48. 2-7; (for details and citations see
Ekāśanājyoha).

प्रभद्रक
Prabhadraka m. (pl.): Name of a
section of Pāñcālas; they figure only in
the context of war where they were led
generally by Śikhaṇḍin or Dhṛṣṭadyumna.
A. Description: Very quick (in action)
(शीघ्रतर), expert (in fighting) (विशा-
रद), whose strength was like that of a
lion (सिंहसमानवीर्य) 5. 47. 30; heroic
while fighting battles (पृतनाशूर) 6. 19.
21; very difficult to be conquered (सुदुर्-
जय) 10. 8. 47; cruel (क्रूर) 7. 70. 45;
six thousand of Prabhadrakas (here speci-
fically said to be Pāñcālas (प्रभद्रकास्
तु पाञ्चालाः) with ready weapons rode
chariots that were drawn by excellent horses
of different colours and were adorned with
variegated banners having gold shafts; they
stood with stretched bows and shook their
enemies by discharging arrows; they were
always determined to die together (उदायु-
धाः।नानावर्णैर् हयश्रेष्ठैर् हेम-
चित्ररथध्वजाः॥शरव्रातैर् विधुन्वन्-
तः शत्रून् विततकार्मुकाः।समानमृत्यवो
भूत्वा धृष्टद्युम्नं समन्वयुः॥) 7.
22. 36-37.
B. Epic events: (1) Arjuna
told Saṃjaya that in war when Prabha-
drakas would strike down the sons of
Dhṛtarāṣṭra, Duryodhana would repent
(प्रभद्रका॥।यदा क्षेप्तारो धार्त-
राष्ट्रान्) 5. 47. 30; (2) Mentioned
among those who were on the side of
Yudhiṣṭhira (पाञ्चालास् च प्रभद्रकाः)
5. 56. 33; as part of the army of the Pāṇḍa-
vas, they marched towards Kurukṣetra
5. 149. 50; they with Nakula, Sahadeva
and others and led by Dhṛṣṭadyumna
(धृष्टद्युम्नमुखान्) were ordered by
Yudhiṣṭhira to set out first towards Kuru-
kṣetra 5. 197. 12; (3) On the first day of
war, in the Vajravyūha of Pāṇḍavas (6. 19.
7), Prabhadrakas, led by Dhṛṣṭadyumna,
were among those who guarded the rear
(पृष्ठगोपाः) of Bhīma 6. 19. 20-21; on
that day Bhīṣma killed Prabhadrakas and
others (पाञ्चालान् … प्रभद्रकान्) 6. 45. 54;
(4) On the third day, Dhṛṣṭadyumna and
Śikhaṇḍin, along with Pāñcālas and Pra-
bhadrakas stood in the middle of the
Ardhacandravyūha (6. 52. 10) of Pāṇḍa-
vas (पाञ्चालाश् च प्रभद्रकाः) 6. 52. 14;
(5) On the tenth day, Prabhadrakas trem-
bled (समकम्पन्त) when they heard
the rattle produced by Droṇa's chariot 6.
107. 48; (6) On the thirteenth day, all
Prabhadrakas were among those who were
to follow Abhimanyu after he penetrated
the Cakravyūha (पाञ्चालाः … सर्वे प्र-
भद्रकाः) 7. 34. 22; (7) On the four-
teenth day, an Āvantya (not named) check-
ed the march of Dhṛṣṭadyumna who was
helped by Prabhadrakas 7. 70. 45; in the
evening of that day, six thousand striking
Prabhadrakas and Pāñcālas, led by Śhikha-
ṇḍin, attacked Droṇa (प्रभद्रकाश् च
पाञ्चालाः षट्सहस्राः प्रहारिणः) 7. 129.
10; (8) During the night war, Śikhaṇḍin
with three thousand Prabhadrakas followed
Yudhiṣṭhira when he started to fight with
Karṇa (त्रिसाहस्रैः प्रभद्रकैः) 7.
158. 49; Yudhiṣṭhīra wanted Prabhadrakas
and others to attack Droṇa 7. 159. 5; (9)
On the sixteenth day, Dhṛṣṭadyumna,
Śikhaṇḍin and Prabhadrakas attacked the
army of Kauravas 8. 8. 14; on the same
day Pāṇḍava heroes, aided by Prabhadra-
kas, fought with the army of elephants
attacking them; the elephants crushed them
with feet and broke them with tusks; but
Prabhadrakas and their leaders continued
to shower arrows on elephants 8. 17. 7-10,
26; they were among those excellent warriors
(प्रवीराः) who oppressed Karṇa (सर्वे
कर्णम् अपीडयन्) 8. 21. 25; (10) On the
seventeenth day Karṇa killed seventyseven
excellent Prabhadraka warriors (प्रभद्र-
काणां प्रवरान् अहनत् सप्तसप्ततिम्); ex-
cellent (प्रवीराः) Prabhadrakas attacked
Karṇa 8. 32. 32, 42; they checked the
advance of Karṇa (Vasuṣeṇa) in the
direction of Yudhiṣṭhira 8. 33. 21; when
Karṇa, angered, rushed towards Yudhi-
ṣṭhira many Prabhadrakas and other
Pāṇḍava heroes attacked him from diffe-
rent sides (विचेरुः) 8. 40. 66; Prabhadra-
kas and other Pāṇḍava heroes attacked
the army of Kauravas 8. 44. 7; Prabhadra-
kas attacking Karṇa appeared like entering
the mouth of a big fish or falling in the
wide open mouth of Death (महाझष-
स्येव मुखं प्रपन्नाः; … मृत्योर् आस्यं
व्यात्तम् इवान्वपद्यन् प्रभद्रकाः) 8. 47.
10; (11) On the eighteenth day, Śalya,
after he became the general of the Kaurava
army, boasted that all Prabhadrakas,
Pāñcālas and the rest would see his valour
(पाञ्चालाश् चैव … सर्वे चापि प्रभद्र-
काः॥विक्रमं मम पश्यन्तु) 9. 6. 13-
14; he killed Prabhadrakas by his arrows
9. 10. 21; Śikhaṇḍin, aided by Prabhadra-
kas, engaged Kṛtavarman and Kṛpa
(Gautama) in battle 9. 14. 7; after the
death of Śalya, Dhṛṣṭadyumna, along with
Prabhadrakas, attacked the elephants encir-
cling them 9. 24. 35; Dhṛṣṭadyumna and
the Prabhadrakas killed the army of Duryo-
dhana 9. 26. 6; (12) During the night
of the eighteenth day, Prabhadrakas were
awakened by the loud sound; they and
Śikhaṇḍin afflicted Aśvatthāman by dis-
charging arrows (शिली मुखैः … द्रोण-
पुत्रं समार्दयन्); seeing them shower-
ing arrows (शरवर्षाणि वर्षतः), he
uttered a loud roar wishing to kill them
10. 8. 46-47; Prabhadrakas and Śikhaṇḍin
attacked him with all sorts of weapons
(नानाप्रहरणैर्); Aśvatthāman first kill-
ed them all with sword 10. 8. 59, 61, 63;
(13) On the nineteenth day, in the fore-
noon (पूर्वाह्णसमये 9. 1. 14), Saṃjaya
reported to Dhṛtarāṣṭra that all Prabha-
drakas were killed in war 9. 1. 29 [See
Pāñcāla].

प्रभाकर
Prabhākara nt. (sg.): Name of a
Varṣa in the Kuśadvīpa.
A. Location: To the north of Jambu-
dvīpa (उत्तरेषु तु … द्वीपेषु) 6. 13. 1; it is
the sixth Varṣa among of the seven Varṣas of
Kuśadvīpa (षष्ठम् वर्षं प्रभाकरम्
6. 13. 13.
B. Characteristic: Gods and
Gandharvas sport there and are happy,
men do not die; there are neither Dasyus
nor Mleccha people on these Varṣas; all
people are fair and very delicate 6. 13. 13-
15 (for citation see Audbhida).

प्रमुद
Pramuda m. (pl.): Name of a Jana-
pada.
Listed by Saṃjaya among the northern
Janapadas (also called Deśas 6. 10. 68) of
Bhāratavarṣa (अत ऊर्ध्वं जनपदान्
निबोध) 6. 10. 37, 5; (सुदोष्णाः प्रमुदास्
तथा) 6. 10. 49.

प्रयाग
Prayāga m. (pl.): Name of a people.
On the second day of war, Prayāga
warriors were among those who stood at
the neck of the Krauñcāruṇavyūha (6.
46. 39; Krauñca 6. 47. 1) of Pāṇḍavas
(प्रयागाश् च … ग्रीवायां) 6. 46. 46.

प्रवाह
Pravāha m. (pl.): Name of a Jana-
pada.
Listed by Saṃjaya among the northern
Janapadas (also called Deśas 6. 10. 68) of
Bhāratavarṣa (अत ऊर्ध्वं जनपदान् निबो-
ध) 6. 10. 37, 5; (वानरास्याः प्रवाहाश् च)
6. 10. 43.

प्राच्य
Prācya m. (pl.): General designation
of the eastern people.
A. Location: Listed by Saṃjaya
among the southern Janapadas of Bhārata-
varṣa (अथापरे जनपदा दक्षिणा भरत-
र्षभ) 6. 10. 56, 5; (द्रविडाः केरलाः
प्राच्या … ) 6. 10. 57; also mentioned while
listing the twelve Janapadas (द्वादशैते
जनपदाः) 6. 114. 77.
B. Description:
Expert in the use of all kinds of weapons
and missiles (सर्वशस्त्रास्त्रकुशल) 6. 16.
17; excellent fighters (प्रवीर) and expert
in fighting while riding elephants (गजयो-
धिन्) 8. 17. 2; (गजयुद्धेषु कुशलाः) 8.
17. 3; (मातङ्गयुद्धेषु कुशलाः) 12. 102.
4; Prācyas employed deceitful means
while fighting (शठयोधिन्) 12. 102. 4.
C. Social status: According to Karṇa,
Prācyas were Dāsas (प्राच्या दासा … ) 8.
30. 73.
D. Epic events: (1) Yudhi-
ṣṭhira asked Saṃjaya to inform the Prācya
and other kings who had joined Kauravas
that he enquired about their welfare (कुश-
लं तात पृच्छेः) 5. 30. 23-24; (2) Accord-
ing to Saṃjaya, in the war, Prācyas would
be killed by Bhīma (प्राच्याश् च … भीम-
सेनस्य भागतः) 5. 56. 14; (3) Duryo-
dhana's royal army (राजचमू) included
Prācyas 5. 158. 19-20; a part of them
were to form the second division while
marching out of Hāstinapura to Kuru-
kṣetra (द्वितीये निर्ययुर् बले) 5. 196.
7-8; (4) In war, Prācyas and others were
assigned the duty of protecting Bhīṣma 6. 16.
14, 17; (5) On the second day of war,
Bhīṣma, protected by Prācyas, Sauvīras and
others, suddenly rushed towards Arjuna
6. 48. 21; (6) On the third day, at the
instance of Bhīṣma, Prācyas, Sauvīras
and others rushed towards Arjuna; they
were killed by him, that was his great feat,
unequalled by others (महत् कृतम् कर्म
धनंजयेन कर्तुं यथा नार्हति कश्चिद्
अन्यः) 6. 55. 74, 130; (7) On the ninth day,
Sauvīras, Prācyas and others did not aban-
don Bhīṣma although they were struck by
sharp arrows (वध्यमानाः शितैः शरैः)
6. 102. 7; (8) On the tenth day, instigated
by Duryodhana (6. 112. 102-106), Prācyas
and others attacked Arjuna as moths
jump on fire (पतङ्गा इव पावकम्) 6.
112. 109-110; a little while before the fall
of Bhīṣma, when others ran away, Prācyas
were among the twelve Janapadas who,
though pierced by arrows and afflicted
due to wounds (शरार्ता व्रणपीदिताः), did
not leave Bhīṣma alone 6. 114. 76-77; (9)
On the eleventh day, they followed Karṇa
who marched out at the head of all
archers (प्रमुखे सर्वधन्विनाम्) 7. 6.
8; (10) On the twelfth day, Prācyas were
stationed at the ‘neck’ (ग्रीवायाम्) of
the Suparṇavyūha of Kauravas 7. 19. 4,
7-8; (11) On the fourteenth day, at
the instance of Duryodhana, Prācyas and
others, riding huge elephants (कुञ्जरैः
पर्वतोपमैः), attacked Arjuna; he cut
off their heads and arms adorned with
ornaments 7. 68. 32-33; (12) On the
sixteenth day, Saṃjaya mentioned Prācyas
among those who, during the first fifteen
days of war were killed by Arjuna 8. 4.
47; on that day, as ordered by Duryodhana,
excellent Prācya warriors, riding elephants,
attacked Pāñcālas and showered them
with arrows, तोमरस् and नाराचस् (शर-
तोमरनाराचैर् वृष्टिमन्त इवाम्बुदाः) 8.
17. 1-4; (13) On the seventeenth day,
Arjuna, while boasting in the presence of
Yudhiṣṭhira, said that it was he who had
destroyed Prācyas (प्राच्या निरस्ता … ) 8.
49. 96; (14) On the eighteenth day,
Kṛṣṇa, while praising Bhīma for his deeds,
mentioned that he had killed Prācyas in the
great war (महायुद्धे निहताः) 9. 32. 22;
(15) In the forenoon (पूर्वाह्णसमये
9. 1. 14) of the nineteenth day, Saṃjaya
reported to Dhṛtarāṣṭra that all Prācyas
were killed in war 9. 1. 27; (16) Vasudeva
told Arjuna that Kṛṣṇa had once defeated
Prācyas 16. 7. 11.

प्रावर
Prāvara(ka) m. (sg.): Name of a
Deśa.
One of the Deśas on the Krauñcadvīpa
(देशांस् तत्र प्रवक्ष्यामि); Prāvaraka
lay beyond the Deśa called Uṣṇa, and
beyond Prāvara was the Deśa called
Andhakāraka (उष्णात् परः प्रावरकः
प्रावराद् अन्धकारकः) 6. 13. 20-21; (Was
Prāvaraka also related to the mountain
Vāmana ? 6. 13. 20); all these Deśas were
visited by gods and Gandharvas (एते देशा
महाराज देवगन्धर्वसेविताः) 6. 13. 23.

प्रावृषेय
Prāvṛṣeya m. (pl.): Name of a Jana-
pada.
Listed by Saṃjaya among the northern
Janapadas (also called Deśas 6. 10. 68)
of Bhāratavarṣa (जनपदान् निबोध) 6.
10. 37, 5; मह्युत्तराः प्रावृषेया … ) 6. 10.
49.

प्राहूत
Prāhūta m. (pl): Name of a Jana-
pada.
Listed by Saṃjaya among the northern
Janapadas (also called Deśas 6. 10. 68) of
Bhāratavarṣa (जनपदान् निबोध) 6. 10.
37, 5; (सुदेष्णाः प्राहूतास् … ) 6. 10. 45.

प्रोष्ठ
Proṣṭha m. (pl.): Name of a Jana-
pada.
Listed by Saṃjaya among the southern
Janapadas of Bhāratavarṣa (अथापरे जन-
पदा दक्षिणा … ) 6. 10. 56, 5; (केकरकाः
प्रोष्ठाः) 6. 10. 60.

बर्बर
Barbara m. (pl.): Name of a Jana-
pada and its people.
A. Location: Listed by Saṃjaya
among the northern Janapadas (also called
Deśas 6. 10. 68) of Bhāratavarṣa (जन-
पदान् निबोध) 6. 10. 37, 5; (किराता बर्-
बराः) 6. 10. 55; natives of Uttarāpatha
(उत्तरापथजन्मानः … किराता बर्बरैः
सह) 12. 200. 40; Nakula conquered them
when he went to the west of Indra-
prastha (निर्याय खाण्डवप्रस्थात् प्रती-
चीम् अभितो दिशम्) 2. 29. 2; (वासुदेव-
जिताम् आशाम्) 2. 29. 1; 2. 23. 10; they lived
by the gulf of the (western) ocean (सागर-
कुक्षिस्थान्) 2. 29. 15; (सागरानूपगान्)
3. 48. 19.
B. Origin: Barbaras and
others were created by Nandinī, the cow
of Vasiṣṭha, from her foam (बर्बरांस्
तथा … फेनतः सा ससर्ज ह) 1. 165. 36.
C. Low social status: Barbaras counted
among those who were reduced to the status
of वृषल due to their non-respecting
Brāhmaṇas 13. 35. 17-18; they were classed
as Dasyus 12. 65. 15 or म्लेच्छस् 1. 165.
36; 12. 65. 14; they did not believe in
Bhūtapati being the अध्यक्ष of all beings;
they were sinful and roamed over the earth
living the way dogs, crows, बलस् (?) and
vultures lived; they did not exist in the
Kṛtayuga and were to be found since
the Tretāyuga 12. 200. 38, 40-42; they lived
in countries but led the life of Dasyus;
king Māndhātṛ asked Indra what was
the duty of people like Barbaras and how
they should be controlled; thereupon Indra
told him what the duties of Dasyus were
12. 65. 13, 15, 17-22 (for citations see
Kirāta).
D. Epic events: (1) Nakula
subjugated Barbaras and their kings (बर्-
बरांश् चैव तान् सर्वान् अनयद् वशम्। …
वशे कृत्वा च पार्थिवान्) and collected jewels
as tribute for the Rājasūya of Yudhiṣṭhira
2. 29. 15-16; the kings attended the Rāja-
sūya and acted as servers (यज्ञे … परि-
वेषकान्) 3. 48. 22; (2) On the fourteenth
day of war Barbaras, holding different kinds
of weapons (विविधायुधपाणयः) faced
Sātyaki 7. 95. 13; he killed them and many
others by thousands (काम्बोजानां सह-
स्रैस् तु … बर्बराणां तथैव च) 7.
95. 38.

बलिराष्ट्र
Balirāṣṭra nt. (sg.): Name of a Jana-
papa.
Listed by Saṃjaya among the northern
Janapadas (also called Deśas 6. 10. 68)
of Bhāratavarṣa (जनपदान् निबोध) 6.
10. 37, 5; (बलिराष्ट्रं च केवलम्) 6.
10. 43.

बलिह
Baliha m. (pl.): Name of a people.
Listed by Bhīma among the eighteen
peoples whose kings were known to have
extirpated their kinsmen, friends and rela-
tives; Arkaja was then the king of Balīhas
(अष्टादशेमे राजानः प्रख्याता … ।ये
समुच्चिच्छिदुर् ज्ञातीन् सुहृदश् च सबान्ध-
वान्॥ … अर्कजश् च बलीहानाम्) 5. 72. 11, 14.

बहिर्गिर्य
Bahirgirya m. (pl.): Name of a Jana-
pada.
Listed by Saṃjaya among the northern
Janapadas (also called Deśas 6. 10. 68) of
Bhāratavarṣa (जनपदान् निबोध) 6. 10.
37, 5; (बहिर्गिर्याङ्गमलदा … ) 6. 10. 48
[cf. Antargirya].

बहुवाद्य
Bahuvādya m. (pl.): Name of a Jana-
pada.
Listed by Saṃjaya among the northern
Janapadas (also called Deśas 6. 10. 68) of
Bhāratavarṣa (जनपदान् निबोध) 6. 10.
37, 5; (बहुवाद्याश् च) 6. 10. 53.

बाहुक
Bāhuka m. (pl.): Name of a people.
They brought for the Rājasūya tribute
in the form of large quantities of gold and
silver, but were stopped at the gate
(बाहुकान् … । … द्वारि वारीतान्।बल्यर्थं
ददतस् तस्मै हिरण्यं रजतं बहु॥)
2. 47. 15-Jo.

बोध
Bodha m. (pl.): Name of a Janapada
and its people.
A. Location: Listed by Saṃjaya
among the northern Janapadas (also called
Deśas 6. 10. 68) of Bhāratavarṣa (जन-
पदान् निबोध) 6. 10. 37, 5, (बोधा मोकास्
तथैव च) 6. 10. 38.
B. Epic event:
Bodhas mentioned among those peoples
who due to fear of Jarāsandha migrated to
the west (प्रतीचीं दिशम् आश्रिताः॥शूर-
सेना भद्रकारा बोधाः) 2. 13. 24-25.

भद्रकार
Bhadrakāra m. (pl.): Name of a
people.
Mentioned among those peoples who
due to fear of Jarāsandha migrated to the
west 2. 13. 24-25 (for citation see Bodha).

भरत
Bharata, Bhārata m. (pl.): General
characterization of the descendants of
Bharata, the son of Duḥṣanta, very often
used to refer to Kauravas, or to Kauravas
and Pāṇḍavas, or to Pāṇḍavas; also used
as an adj. (fem. -ई) mostly to refer to the
lineage or the army of the Kauravas, occa-
sionally used also to refer to their narrative
and town.
A. Origin: The family was named
Bhārata after Bharata; his descendants as
well as those who preceded him (?) were
known as Bhāratas; the fame of Bhāratas
was due to Bharata (भरताद् भाराती
कीर्तिर् येनेदं भारतं कुलम्।अपरे ये
च पूर्वे च भारता इति विश्रुताः) 1. 69. 49;
1. 89. 16; 13. 75. 26; (1. 1. 44).
B. Line-
age (वंश or कुल), its importance: Since
the lineage was established by Bharatas
it was known as Bhārata (येनेदं
(i. e. भरतेन) भारतं कुलम्) 1. 69.
49; भारतं वंशम् 1, 99. 47; Arjuna
born in the lineage of Bharata (जातस्य
भारते वंशे) 2. 16. 1; Duryodhana
born in the lineage of Bharata (जातो
ऽसि भारते वंशे) 5. 7. 27; (भार-
तं कुलं) 1. 69. 49; 1. 92. 12; it was
respected by all kings (भारते वंशे
सर्वपार्थिवपूजिते) 5. 7. 27.
C. The
narrative of Bhāratas, its importance:
Vaiśaṃpāyana having received it from his
teacher Vyāsa was eager to narrate the
narrative of Bhāratas to Janamejaya, who
was a worthy person to listen to it (श्रोतुं
पात्रं च राजंस् त्वं प्राप्येमां भार-
तीं कथाम्।गुरोर् वक्तुं परिस्पन्दो
मुदा प्रोत्साहतीव माम्॥) 1. 55. 3; it
was told in the सर्पसत्र of king Jana-
mejaya (कथेयम् … भारतानाम्) 1. 2.
74; one who listened to the narration of
the birth of Bhāratas has no fear from
diseases, least of all of the next world; it
was holy, brought wealth, fame, long life
and heaven; it is also large and leads to
bliss (भारतानां महज् जन्म शृण्वताम्
 … ।नास्ति व्याधिभयं तेषां परलोक-
भयं कुतः॥धन्यं यशस्यम् आयु-
ष्यं स्वर्ग्यं पुण्यं तथैवच) 1. 56.
24-25; (वंशं … ।तथैव भारतानां
च पुण्यं स्वस्त्ययनं महत्।धन्यं
यशस्यम् आयुष्यं कीर्तयिष्यामि ते ऽन-
घ॥) 1. 70. 2; Mahābhārata so called
because it describes the life of the Bhāratas;
that is the etymology of the word (भारता-
नां महज् जन्म महाभारतम् उच्यते।
निरुक्तम् अस्य यो वेद) 1. 56. 31.
D.
Description of Bhāratas: Magnanimous
(महात्मन्) 1. 2. 74; 7. 61. 34; famous
(भारता इति विश्रुताः) 1. 69. 49; (प्र-
ख्यात) 1. 92. 12; (भरतवंशस्य
विप्रतस्थे महद् यशः) 1. 89. 16; best
men (उत्तमपुरुष) 2. 64. 8.
E. Epic
events: (1) Bhīṣma after defeating the
kings who came for the स्वयंवर of the
Kāśi princesses left for Bhāratas (i. e. to
the place where Bhāratas lived) (प्रायाद्
भारतो भारतान् प्रति) 1. 96. 24; (2)
Satyavatī asked Ambikā to bear a son
(from Vyāsa) and rescue the Bhārata
dynasty 1. 99. 47-48; (3) Satyavatī asked
Bhīṣma to get consecrated as a king and
rule the Bhāratas 1. 97. 11; (4) Satyavatī
told Ambikā that due to the wrong policy of
her son, Bhāratas and their relatives would
perish 1. 119. 9 (that is what she had heard
from Vyāsa 1. 119. 5); (5) Kauravas
and Pāṇḍavas born in the lineage of
Bharata (भरतस्यान्वये जाता॥) 1. 122. 15;
(6) Bhīṣma told Duryodhana that if Pāṇḍa-
vas did not get a share in the kingdom,
neither could he nor any other Bhārata
have one (कुत एव तवापीदं भारतस्य
च कस्यचित्) 1. 195. 6; (7) When Kṛṣṇa
arrived, the town of Bharatas (i. e. Indra-
prastha भारतं पुरम्) was delighted
2. 30. 15; (8) When Draupadī was
dragged to the Sabhā, she felt that the
law of Bhāratas had perished (नष्टः
खलु भारतानाम् धर्मस् … ) 2. 60. 33;
(9) Vidura felt that the end of Bharatas
had arrived when Draupadī was brought
to their Sabhā (एतदन्ताः स्थ भरता … )
2. 72. 27; (10) When Bhīma vowed to
break the thigh of Duryodhana Vidura
felt that the unlawful course, ordained
before by the fate, was proving true for the
Bharatas (Kauravas) (दैवेरितो नूनम्
अयं पुरस्तात् परो ऽनयो भरतेषूदपादि)
2. 63. 16; (11) Arjuna reminded Bhīma,
that the Bhāratas, since they were best
men, did not answer back the harsh
words, spoken or unspoken, by low men
(न चैवोक्ता न चानुक्ता हीनतः परुषा
गिरः।भारताः प्रतिजल्पन्ति सदा तूत्तम-
पूरुषाः) 2. 64. 8 (Nī. on Bom. Ed. 2.
72. 8: प्रतिजल्पन्ति प्रत्युत्तरयन्ति);
(12) The bad omens which occurred when
Pāṇḍavas started for वनवास predicted
extinction of Bhāratas (भारतानाम् अभा-
वाय) 2. 71. 28; (13) When Duryodhana
and others sought refuge with Droṇa, he
addressed them as well as the rest of the
Bhāratas present in the Sabhā 2. 71. 33;
(14) Yudhiṣṭhira took leave of Bharatas
like Bhīṣma, Bāhlīka Somadatta, and others
(which included all those who sided with
Kauravas) to go to वनवास (आमन्त्र-
यामि भरतांस् तथा वृद्धं पितामहम्)
2. 69. 1; (15) Dhṛtarāṣṭra remembered
that all Bhārata women, together with
Gāndhārī, had cried fiercely when Draupadī
was taken to Sabhā (प्राक्रोशन् भैरवं
तत्र) 2. 72. 19; (16) If Duryodhana did
not give Pāṇḍavas their share, that would
bring calamity to Bharatas (भरतानाम्
अभूतये) 3. 30. 48; (17) Yudhiṣṭhira re-
minded Bhīma what Duryodhana had stipu-
lated for his single bait in the presence
of all Bharatas (एकग्लहार्थं भरता-
नां समक्षम्); he had said that if the
Pāṇḍavas were found out by the spies of
Bhāratas (Kauravas), they would have to
spend another twelve years in the forest
(अवभोत्स्यन्ते भारतानां चराः स्म) 3.
35. 7, 9; (18) Dhṛtarāṣṭra imagined that
the army of Bhāratas (Kauravas) (भारती
चमूः) was torn on all sides (विदीर्णेव)
hearing the sound of Arjuna's chariot 3.
46. 17; it would be distressed (वित्रस्ता)
for the same reason 5. 51. 16; (19)
Bhāratas (Pāṇḍavas) spent a month on
the mountain Himavant (मासो ऽथ …
व्यतीतस् … भारतानाम्) 3. 161. 16; (20)
Brāhmaṇas blessed Bharatas (Pāṇḍavas)
(भरतान्) at the end of their वनवास
before taking their leave 3. 299. 25; (21)
Bhīṣma addressed the Bhāratas (Kauravas)
before they sent spies to search Pāṇḍavas
4. 27. 2; (22) Uttara did not dare enter
the army of the Bhāratas (Kauravas)
(भारतीं सेनां) 4. 36. 10; (23) When
Droṇa and Arjuna clashed with each other
the large army of Bharatas trembled exce-
ssively (प्राकम्पत) 4. 53. 13; (24)
Dhṛtarāṣṭra wanted Saṃjaya to speak
whatever was in the interest of the Bhāra-
tas (भारतानां हितं च) when he would
address the assembly of Virāṭa 5. 22. 39;
(25) Yudhiṣṭhira enquired with Saṃjaya
whether the mothers of Bhāratas were free
from grief (भारतानां जनन्यो … अव्य-
लीकाः) 5. 23. 14 (Nī., however, on Bom.
Ed. 5. 23. 14; अव्यलीकाः निष्कपटाः); (26)
The king of Bāhlīkas always wished noth-
ing but peace among the Bhāratas (यस्य
कामो वर्तते नित्यम् एव नान्यः शमाद्
भारतानाम् इति स्म) 5. 30. 19; (27)
Saṃjaya predicted that the subjects would
perish due to the conflict among Bhāratas 5.
32. 27; (28) Dhṛtarāṣṭra feared that in the
battle, destruction would overcome Bharatas
(क्षयः किलायं भरतान् उपैति) 5. 51.
19; (29) According to Dhṛtarāṣṭra, the
fighting of the Bhārata army (i. e. the
Kaurava army) with Sātyaki was going to
be an upstream task (प्रतीपम् इव मे
भाति युयुधानेन भारती) 5. 57. 21;
(30) Dhṛtarāṣṭra expected that Kṛṣṇa
would address words to be honoured by
Bhāratas (Kauravas and others on their
side) (ईरयन्तं भारतीं भारतानां
अभ्यर्चनीयां … ) 5. 69. 2 (Nī., however,
on Bom. Ed. 5. 71. 2; भारतानां पाण्डवा-
नां भारतीं वाचं ईरयन्तं अस्मत्-
सभायां कथयन्तम्); (31) Kṛṣṇa was
expected to pacify the Bhāratas (on the side
of Kauravas) (भारताञ् शमयेः प्रभो)
5. 70. 90; (32) Due to Duryodhana's wrath,
the Bhāratas (on both sides) would be
burnt (भारता … धक्ष्यन्ते) 5. 72. 10;
(33) Kṛṣṇa assured Draupadī that before
long she would see the women of Bharatas
(Kauravas) weeping when they heard their
kinsmen and relatives killed (रुदतीर्
भरतस्त्रियः) 5. 80. 44-45; (34) Kṛṣṇa
was to embrace individually all Bharatas
(senior ones on the side of Kauravas) in the
assembly of Kauravas (सर्वांश् च भरतान्
पृथक् … स्वजेथा मधुसूदन) 5. 81. 47-
48; (35) On way to Hāstinapura, Kṛṣṇa
saw many towns and countries happy and
protected by Bhāratas (Kauravas) (भार-
तैर् अभिरक्षिताः) 5. 82. 17; (36) Kṛṣṇa
told Dhṛtarāṣṭra that if the Bharatas
(Kauravas and Pāṇḍavas) remained united,
they together would work for him (i. e. for
Dhṛtarāṣṭra) (सहभूतास् तु भरतास्
तवैव स्युर् जनेश्वर) 5. 93. 16; he also
advised Duryodhana to come to terms with
Yudhiṣṭhira and be instrumental in achie-
ving complete well-being and health for
Bhāratas (Kauravas and Pāṇḍavas) (चर
स्वस्त्ययनं कृत्स्नं भारतानाम् अनाम-
यम्) 5. 123. 25; Kṛṣṇa requested Bhāratas
in the Sabhā of Kauravas to listen to his
words, if that pleased them, which were
in their interest (भवताम् आनुकूल्येन
यदि रोचेत भारताः) 5. 126. 35; (37)
To Kuntī, there could be nothing more
grievous than Pāṇḍavas and their allies
fighting with Bhāratas (Kauravas and the
Bhāratas on their side) 5. 142. 12; (38)
Saṃjaya was going to describe to Dhṛta-
rāṣṭra the great war of the Bhāratas
(Kauravas and Pāṇḍavas) 6. 16. 10; (39)
On the fourth day, Bhīṣma led the army
of the Bhāratas (भारतानाम् अनीकिनीनां
प्रमुखे) 6. 56. 1; (40) Abhimanyu
tormented the large army of Bhāratas
(भारती सा महाचमूः) 6. 96. 18; (41)
On the tenth day, bad omens occurred for
the army of Bhāratas (Kauravas) 6. 108. 6;
according to Droṇa, the wrath of Yudhi-
ṣṭhira was burning Bhāratas (Kauravas) 6.
108. 32; after Bhīṣma's fall, he was praised
by the ancient forefathers of Bharatas
(पितरश् चैव प्रशशंसुर् … ।भरतानां
च ये पूर्वे) 6. 114. 111; with the fall of
Bhīṣma, the army of the Bhāratas (Kaura-
vas) (भारती … सेना) was like a boat in
a big ocean, shaken by wind in all dire-
ctions and shattered 7. 1. 27-28; hearing
Bhīṣma's fall Dhṛtarāṣṭra swooned,
surrounded and touched by Bharata women
(भरतस्त्रियः परिवव्रुर् महाराजम्
अस्पृशंश् चैव पाणिभिः) 7. 9. 3; (42) On
the eleventh day, the eminent Bharatas (on
both sides) took their arms and started
for the war (निर्ययुर् भरतश्रेष्ठाः
शश्त्राण्य् आदाय सर्वशः) 7. 1. 21; (43)
Arjuna wielded in war the same bow
against Kṣatriyas (Kauravas) which once
before proved beneficial for Bharatas
(Kauravas) fleeing in their fight (with
Gandharvas cf. 3. 230 ff.) (यत् तद् अनाम-
यज् जिष्णुर् भरतानाम् अपायिनाम्।धनुः
क्षेमकरं संख्ये … ।तद् एव … क्षत्र-
विनाशाय धनुर् आयच्छद् अर्जुनः॥)
7. 27. 15-16; (44) On the thirteenth
day, Abhimanyu attacked the army of
Bhāratas (Kauravas) (अभ्यपतत् सेनां
भारतीम्) 7. 40. 11; Abhimanyu, lying
on the ground, was like the sun that
had set after tormenting the army of
Bhāratas (तप्त्वा भारतवाहिनीम्) 7. 48.
16; (45) On the fourteenth day, Dhṛta-
rāṣṭra remembered that he had told Duryo-
dhana that Pāṇḍavas would do what was
in his interest if Bhīṣma and other elderly
magnanimous Bharatas spoke to them
on his behalf (भीष्मस्य च महात्मनः।
 … अन्येषां चैव वृद्धानां भरतानां
महात्मनाम्) 7. 61. 33-34; Arjuna saw
many omens when the Bharatas (Kauravas),
desirous of fighting, were slowly getting
ready for the battle (अभिहारयत्सु शन-
कैर् भरतेषु युयुत्सुषु) 7. 64. 3 (Nī.
on Bom. Ed. 7. 88. 3: अभिहारयत्सु
सन्नह्यमानेषु अभियुज्यमानेषु वा
प्रहरत्स्व् इति केचित्); Arjuna attacked
the army of Bhāratas (Kauravas) killing
their eminent warriors (अभ्यगाद् भार-
तीं सेनाम्) 7. 68. 26, (प्राविशद्) 56;
the army of the Bhāratas was getting torn
to pieces (दीर्यमाणां च भारतीम्) 7.
85. 70; Arjuna had entered the army of
Bhāratas (प्रविष्टस् तात भारतीम्) 7. 85.
80, 82; the army of Bhāratas was reduced
to a miserable condition (शोच्येयं भारती
सेना) 7. 98. 8; Sātyaki had entered the
army of Bhāratas (भारतीं सेनाम्) 7. 102.
16; (भारतीम् चमूम्) 7. 102. 34; the
army of Bhāratas was besieged from be-
hind and in front (सा पुरस्ताच् च पश्चाच्
च गृहीता भारती चमूः) 7. 105. 12;
Bhīma discharged arrows towards Bhārata
warriors (sons of Dhṛtarāṣṭra 7. 112. 28)
who cut them asunder 7. 112. 26; Sātyaki
was in the midst of the army of Bhāratas
(here, the army of the Trigartas cf. 7. 116.
2) (भारतीमध्यम्); this army is descri-
bed as full of the sound made by palms of
hands and equipped with swords, शक्तिस्
and maces (तलघोषसमाकुल, असिशक्ति-
गदापूर्ण) 7. 116. 5; Sātyaki had entered
the army of Bhāratas (भारतीं सेनाम्)
after Arjuna had fought with Bhārata
heroes of great prowess (योधितश् च महा-
वीर्यैः सर्वैर् भारत भारतत्ः) 7. 117.
43; Droṇa took it for granted that with
the fall of Bhīṣma the army of the Bhāratas
was as good as perished (तदैवाज्ञासिषम्
अहं नेयम् अस्तीति भारती) 7. 126. 8 (Nī. on
Bom. Ed. 7. 126. 8: इयं सेना नास्तित्य् अस्य
नष्टेत्य् अर्थः); (46) Night war: During
the night, the army of Bhāratas (भारती
सेना) adorned with jewels and gold and
with ornaments like अङ्गदस्, ear-orna-
ments, निष्कस् and weapons shone like the
sky full of नक्षत्रस् (द्यौर् त्वासीत् सन-
क्षत्रा) 7. 129. 24, 27; the army of Bhāratas
(भारती सेना) was getting killed by
Arjuna 7. 132. 42; 7. 136. 16; when the
Bhārata warriors (on the side of Kauravas)
were in a difficult situation no one could
offer them protection (मज्जतां भारतास्
नां न स्म द्वीपस् तत्र कश्चिद् बभूव)
7. 154. 41; Duryodhana proposed to divide
the army of Bhāratas (on his side) and
kill Arjuna (द्वैधीकृत्याद्य भारतीम्) 7.
160. 22; (47) On the sixteenth day,
Kṛṣṇa pointed out to Arjuna the terrible
destruction of the Bharatas (on both sides)
that had taken place (महारौद्रो वर्तते
भरतक्षयः) 8. 14. 27; Dhṛtarāṣṭra
remembered that Arjuna had once prote-
cted Bharatas (Kauravas) (reference to
the fight with Gandharvas 3. 230. ff.) (एको
ऽभ्यरक्षद् भरतान्) 8. 22. 4; (48) On
the seventeenth day, the army of Bhāratas
(Kauravas 8. 43. 54) running away when
attacked by Bhīma's arrows appeared
pitiable (भारती सेना … कृपणदर्शना)
8. 43. 55; Arjuna boasted that he laid low
the army of Bhāratas (on the side of Kaura-
vas) which shone like the army of gods
(भारतीचमु … देवचमूप्रकाशा) 8. 49.
97; when the important heroes and other
warriors as well as horses and elephants in
the army of the Bhāratas (army of Kaura-
vas) were killed in battle it looked like the
sky devoid of the sun, the moon and the
नक्षत्रस् (हीना सूर्येन्दुनक्षत्रैर् द्यौर्
इवाभाति भारती॥ … सेनेयम्) 8. 51. 48-49;
the army of Bhāratas (भारती), along with
that of the Saṃśaptakas, led by Duḥśā-
sana attacked Bhīma 8. 53. 9; the army of
Bhāratas, afraid, was scattered by Bhīma
in all directions (बलं … भारतानां …
भीतं दिशो ऽकीर्यत भीमनुन्नम्) 8. 54.
9; Bhīma showed to his charioteer the
army of Bhāratas running away because
it was covered by the arrows of Arjuna
(भारतीं दीर्यमाणां … सैन्यं ह्य् एतच्
छादयत्य् आशु बाणैः) 8. 54. 21; (49) On
the eighteenth day, Arjuna, after the death
of Śalya, killed Śuśarman, his sons and
followers, and then turned towards the
remaining army of Bhāratas (अभ्यगाद्
भारतीं सेनां हतशेषाम्) 9. 26. 46;
(50) It was proper for Yuyutsu to return
to Kauravas after the destruction of Bhara-
tas (on Kaurava's side) (भरतक्षये) 9.
