F. Past events: (1) When Saṃvaraṇa
was the ruler of the Bhāratas, the land was
oppressed by many calamities; a certain
king of the Pāñcālas (not named) attacked
the Bhāratas; Saṃvaraṇa fled with his
wife and others from his country; the
Bhāratas lived for a long time in an inacce-
ssible place near a mountain in a country
near the river Sindhu; Vasiṣṭha then visited
the Bharatas; all Bhāratas welcomed him
with a respectful guest offering and told him
their condition; Saṃvaraṇa chose Vasiṣṭha,
who had lived with them for eight years,
to act as their पुरोहित; he said ‘yes’ to
Bhāratas; Saṃvaraṇa again occupied the
town which was formerly held by Bharatas
(अभ्यघ्नन् भारतांश् चैव सपत्नानां
बलानि च। … अभ्ययात् तं च पाञ्चाल्यो। …
सिन्धोर् नदस्य महतो निकुञ्जे न्यवसत्
तदा।नदीविषयपर्यन्ते पर्वतस्य समी-
पतः।तत्रावसन् बहून् कालान् भारता
दुर्गम् आश्रिताः॥ … अथाभ्यगच्छद् भर-
तान् वसिष्ठो भगवान् ऋषिः॥ … अर्घ्यम्
अभ्याहरंस् तस्मै ते सर्वे भारतास् तदा।
तं समाम् अष्टमीम् उष्टं राजा वव्रे
स्वयं तदा।पुरोहितो भवान् नो ऽस्तु
राज्याय प्रयतामहे।ओम् इत्य् एवं वसि-
ष्ठो ऽपि भारतान् प्रत्यपद्यत॥ … भरता-
ध्युषितं पूर्वं सो ऽध्यतिष्ठत् पुरोत्त-
मम्।) 1. 89. 31-40.
G. भारत as
adj.: Besides its adjectival use in conne-
ction with वंश (m.) or कुल (nt.), and
सेना or चमू (f.) (for which see above
B and E), भारत is also occasionally used
in connection with समिति, श्री or कीर्ति (all
f.) and पुर (nt.): (1) Gathering
(समिति): The brilliant gathering of Bhāra-
tas (both Kauravas and Pāṇḍavas) around
Bhīṣma lying on the bed of arrows shone
like the sun in the sky (शुशुभे भारती
दीप्ता दिवी वादित्यमण्डलम्) 6. 116. 7; (2)
Glory (श्री) or fame (कीर्ति): (i) Bhīṣma
appealed to Duryodhana not to destroy the
glory of Bhāratas shining brightly among
all kings (इमां श्रियं प्रज्वलितां भार-
तीं सर्वराजसु) 5. 123. 5; (ii) The fame
of Bhāratas had its origin in Bharata
(भरताद् भारती कीर्तिर् … ) 1. 69. 49; (3)
Town (pura) i. e. Indraprastha: Described
as the best town (पुरोत्तमं … भारतं
पुरम्) 2. 30. 14-15.
