मधुमत्|मधुमन्त्
Madhumant m. (pl.): Name of a Jana-
pada.
Listed by Saṃjaya among the northern
Janapadas (also called Deśas 6. 10. 68) of
Bhāratavarṣa; listed along with Pārasīkas,
hence, perhaps, belonged to the north-west
(अत ऊर्ध्वं जनपदान् निबोध) 6. 10.
37, 5; (तिलकाः पारसीकाश् च मधुमन्तः)
6. 10. 51.

मध्यदेश
Madhyadeśa, Madhyama deśa m. (sg.):
The midland country and its people.
A. Epic events: (1) Vṛṣṇis (2. 13.
51, 59) and Mādhavas (2. 13. 52) who,
along with Kṛṣṇa, left Mathurā (2. 13. 44)
and went to Kuśasthalī in the west always
remembered the Madhyama deśa (वीराः
स्मरन्तो मध्यमं देशं … ) 2. 13. 59;
(2) Many kings of midland (बहवो राजानो
मध्यदेशजाः) attended the Rājasūya of
Yudhiṣṭhita 2. 31. 17; (3) The warriors
of Madhyadeśa along with others comprised
the unassailable royal army of Kauravas
(राजचमूं … दुराधर्षैर् … कुरुमध्य-
देशैर् … ) 5. 158. 19-20.
B. Past events:
(1) Once a large settlement of Brāhmaṇas
existed in a part of the Madhyadeśa
between the rivers Gaṅgā and Yamunā
and adjacent to the mountain Yāmuna
(मध्यदेशे … गङ्गायमुनयोर् मध्ये
यामुनस्य गिरेर् अधः) 13. 67. 3; Yama
told Brāhmaṇas of this settlement the
importance of gifting sesame seeds and
lamps 13. 67. 15-27; (2) A Brāhmaṇa
named Gautama (12. 162. 33) of the
Madhyadeśa (मध्यदेशीयः 12. 162. 29)
happened to visit a settlement of the
Dasyus (दस्युग्राम 12. 162. 37) and lived
there; when another Brāhmaṇa later visited
the same settlement he recognized Gautama
as one who belonged to the Madhyadeśa
and asked him how he came to live like a
Dasyu (मध्यदेशपरिज्ञातो दस्युभावं
गतः कथम्) 12. 162. 44; when asked by
Virūpākṣa, the chief of Rākṣasas, Gautama
told him that he belonged to Midland but
he lived in the house of a Śabara (मध्य-
देशप्रसूतो ऽहं वासो मे शबरालये) 12.
165. 5.

मध्यमिकाय
Madhyamikāya m. (pl.): Designation
of a people (living in the Madhyama
country ?).
They lived to the west of Khāṇḍava-
prastha (खाण्डवप्रस्थात् प्रतीचीम् अभितो
दिशम्) 2. 29. 2; Nakula brought them
under control, along with the Vāṭadhāna
Brāhmaṇas, during his expedition to the
west (2. 29. 2; 2. 23. 10) before the Rāja-
sūya (वशे चक्रे॥।तथा मध्यमिकायांश्
च वाटधानान् द्विजान् अथ) 2. 29. 6-7. [See
Madhyadeśa].

मनोनुग
Manonuga m. (sg.): Name of a Deśa
of Krauñcadvīpa.
It was related to the second mountain
Vāmana of the Krauñcadvīpa; the Deśa
after Manonuga was called Uṣṇa (वामन-
स्य मनोनुगः॥मनोनुगात् परश् चोष्णो
देशः) 6. 13. 20-21, 17; all Deśas of
Krauñcadvīpa were frequented by gods
and Gandharvas (एते देशा महाराज देव-
गन्धर्वसेविताः) 6. 13. 23.

मन्दक
Mandaka m. (pl.): Name of a Jana-
pada.
Listed by Saṃjaya among the northern
Janapadas (also called Deśas 6. 10. 68) of
Bhāratavarṣa (अत ऊर्ध्वं जनपदान्
निबोध) 6. 10. 37, 5; (गोविन्दा मन्दकाः)
6. 10. 42.

मन्दग
Mandaga m. (sg. pl.): Name of a
Janapada of the Śākadvīpa.
A. Location: Listed by Saṃjaya
among the four Janapadas of Śākadvīpa
(तत्र जनपदाश् चत्वारो … मन्दगास्
तथा) 6. 12. 33.
B. Description: Holy
(पुण्य), respected by the people (लोक-
संमत) 6. 12. 33.
C. Characteristic: The
Śūdras of this Janapada always observed
their धर्म (शूद्रास् तु मन्दगे नित्यं
पुरुषा धर्मशीलिनः) 6. 12. 35; for another
characteristic common to all Janapadas of
Śākadvīpa see Maga.

मन्दर
Mandara m. (pl.): Name of a people.
On the fourteenth day of war, Man-
dara warriors were among those three
thousand horse-riders who, led by Duryo-
dhana, attacked Sātyaki (त्रीणि सादिसह-
स्राणि दुर्योधनपुरोगमाः।अभ्यद्र-
वन्त शैनेयम्) 7. 97. 13-14. [For Man-
dara mountain see Vol. I, pp. 403-405].

मरध
Maradha m. (pl.): Name of a people.
Listed by Saṃjaya, along with Cīnas,
among the northern Mlecchas of Bhārata-
varṣa (उत्तराश् चापरे म्लेच्छा जना … तथ-
इव मरधाश् चीनास् … ) 6. 10. 63, 65; (they
were also probably reckoned as a Janapada
(6. 10. 37) or a Deśa (6. 10. 68)); these
म्लेच्छ tribes were known to be rough
(दारुणा म्लेच्छजातयः) 6. 10. 64.

मरु
Maru, Marubhūmi, Marubhauma m. f.
(sg., pl.): Name of a country and its
people.
A. Location: Listed by Saṃjaya
among the northern Janapadas (also called
Deśas 6. 10. 68) of Bhāratavarṣa (अत
ऊर्ध्वं जनपदान् निबोध) 6. 10. 37, 5;
मरुभौमाश् च मारिष) 6. 10. 46; to the
west of Khāṇḍavaprastha (प्रतीचीम् अभितो
दिशम्) 2. 29. 5; 2. 23. 10; Kāmyaka forest
was at the northern extremity of Maru-
bhūmi (काम्यकं काननोत्तमम्।मरु-
भूमेः शिरः ख्यातम्) 3. 244. 13; near
the sea, where once Sarasvatī flew (13. 139.
26; see Past event below).
B. Characte-
ristic: As mostly unfertile land, it is con-
trasted with those producing abundant
corn (मरुभूमिं … तथैव बहुधा-
न्यकम्) 2. 29. 5.
C. Epic events:
(1) Nakula brought completely under
control the whole of Marubhūmi in his
expedition to the west before the Rāja-
sūya (मरुभूमिं च कार्त्स्न्येन … वशे
चक्रे) 2. 29. 5-6; (2) Since there was
not enough room in Hāstinapura, the large
army of Kauravas spread beyond the land
of five rivers even up to the whole of
Marubhūmi (न हास्तिनपुरे राजन्न् अव-
काशो ऽभवत् तदा। … ततः पञ्चनदं
चैव … मरुभूमिश् च केवला। … एष
देशः … बभूव कौरवेयाणाम् बलेन
सुसमाकुलः॥) 5. 19. 28-29, 31; (3)
After the mutual killings of Yādavas,
Vasudeva remembered that once Kṛṣṇa
had killed the kings of Marubhūmi
((विदेहान्) अकरोत् … मरुभूमौ च
पार्थिवान्) 16. 7. 9-10.
D. Past event:
Utathya asked Sarasvatī to disappear in
the Maru country; he wanted the land,
when deserted by the river, to be unholy;
in that land which was thus thoroughly
pounded, Varuṇa handed over Utathya
his wife who was abducted by him
(अदृश्या गच्छ भीरु त्वम् सरस्वति
मरुं प्रति। … अपुण्य एष भवतु देशस्
त्यक्तस् त्वया शुभे॥तस्मिन् संचूर्णिते
देशे भद्राम् आदाय वारिपः।अददाच् छर-
णं गत्वा भार्याम् आङ्गिरसाय वै) 13.
139. 26-27.

मर्त्य
Martya m. (pl.): Name of a coun-
try (?).
The Aśokatīrtha, abounding in आश्र-
मस्, was located in the Martya country (?)
in the south (दक्षिणस्यां तु पुण्यानि
शृणु तीर्थानि भारत) 3. 86. 1; (अशोक-
तीर्थं मर्त्येषु) 3. 86. 10.

मलद
Malada m. (pl.): Name of a people.
On the eleventh day of war, their
warriors were among those who, led by
Duḥśāsana, protected the extreme end of
the left wing of Droṇa's army (दुःशासन-
मुखा यत्ताः सव्यं पार्श्वम् अपालयन्॥
तेषां प्रपक्षाः … शूद्राश् च मलदत्ः
सह) 7. 6. 4-6; (or were they among those
who, led by Duryodhana, followed Karṇa ?
तवात्मजं पुरस्कृत्य सूतपुत्रस्य पृष्ठ-
तः 7. 6. 7).

मलय
Malaya m. (pl.): Name of a people.
Described as very strong (महाबल)
2. 27. 8; they were vanquished by Bhīma-
sena in his expedition to the east (ययौ
प्राचीं दिशं प्रति 2. 27. 1, 7; 2. 23. 9)
before the Rājasūya (विजिग्ये … मत्स्यान्
मलयांश् च) 2. 27. 7-8. [For Malaya1, 2
names of mountains see Vol. I pp. 407-
408].

मल्ल
Malla m. (pl.): Name of a Janapada
and its people; distinguished as Uttara,
Uttama Mallas and Dakṣlṇa Mallas; called
जनपद and also राष्ट्र (4. 1. 8-9).
A. Location: Listed by Saṃjaya
among the northern Janapadas (also called
Deśas 6. 10. 68) of Bhāratavarṣa (अत
ऊर्ध्वं जनपदान् निबोध) 6. 10. 37, 5;
(मल्लाः सुदेष्णाः) 6. 10. 45; between
Gopālakaccha and the Himālayas 2. 27.
3-4; little to the east of Khāṇḍavaprastha
and then to the north; Bhīma first went
to the east (ययौ प्राचीं दिशं प्रति 2.
26. 1, 7, 9; 2. 23. 9) before he reached the
country of Mallas 2. 27. 3, 11 (see Epic
event below); listed by Arjuna among the
countries around Kurus (परितः कुरून् …
मल्लाः शाल्वा युगन्धराः) 4. 1. 9.
B.
Description: Pleasant (रम्य, रमणीय),
protected (गुप्त), producing abundant
corn (बह्वन्न) 4. 1. 8-9.
C. Epic
event: Bhīmasena in his expedition to
the east before the Rājasūya defeated
Uttaramallas, Uttamamallas along with the
king of the Mallas and then also defeated
the Dakṣiṇamallas (सोत्तमान् अपि चोत्तरान्।
मल्लानाम् अधिपं चैव पार्थिवम् व्यजस्
यत् प्रभुः॥) 2. 27. 3; (ततो दक्षिणस्
मल्लांश् च … तरसैवाजयद् भीमो … ) 2.
27. 11. (See the next).

मल्लक
Mallaka m. (pl.): Name of a Jana-
pada.
Listed by Saṃjaya among the southern
Janapadas (also called Deśas 6. 10. 68)
of Bhāratavarṣa (अथापरे जनपदा दक्षि-
णा … ) 6. 10. 56, 5; (मालका मल्लकाश्
चैव) 6. 10. 61. [See Malla].

मशक
Maśaka m. (pl.): Name of a Jana-
pada of the Śākadvīpa.
A. Location: Listed by Saṃjaya
among the four Janapadas of Śākadvīpa
(तत्र … जनपदाश् चत्वारो … मशकाश्
चैव) 6. 12. 33.
B. Description; Holy
(पुण्य), respected by people (लोकसं-
मत) 6. 12. 33.
C. Characteristic: In
Maśaka all Kṣatriyas were religious; they
fulfilled all wishes (of the people) (मश-
केषु तु राजन्या धार्मिकाः सर्वकामदाः)
6. 12. 34; for another characteristic which
is common to all four Janapadas of Śāka-
dvīpa, see Maga.

महाकाश
Mahākāśa m.: Name of a Varṣa of
the Śākadvīpa.
Listed by Saṃjaya among the Varṣas
of Sākadvīpa; it was related to mountain
Mahāmeru (वर्षाणि तेषु … महामेरुर्
महाकाशो … ) 6. 12. 23.

महाभोज
Mahābhoja: See Bhoja.

महिषक
Mahiṣaka: See Māhiṣaka.

महौजस्
Mahaujas m. (pl.): Name of a people.
Varapra, the king of Mahaujas people,
listed by Bhīmasena among the eighteen
kings who in the past extirpated their
kinsmen, friends and relatives (अष्टादशेमे
राजानः … ।ये समुच्चिच्छिदुर् ज्ञातीन्
सुहृदश् च सबान्धवान्॥) 5. 72. 11; (वर-
प्रश् च महौजसाम्) 5. 72. 15.

मह्युत्तर
Mahyuttara m. (pl.): Name of a
Janapada.
Listed by Saṃjaya among the northern
Janapadas (also called Deśas 6. 10. 68) of
Bhāratavarṣa (अत ऊर्ध्वं जनपदान्
निबोध) 6. 10. 37, 5; (मह्युत्तराः प्रा-
वृषेया … ) 6. 10. 49.

माकन्दि
Mākandi f.: Name of the southern
part of the Pāñcāla country.
A. Location: Region south of Gaṅga
up to the river Carmaṇvatī (माकन्दीम्
अथ गङ्गायास् तीरे … ।दक्षिणांश् चैव
पाञ्चालान् यावच् चर्मण्वती नदी) 1. 128.
15; (राजासि दक्षिणे कूले भागीरथ्याहम्
उत्तरे।) 1. 128. 12.
B. Its Capital:
Kāmpilya, the best of the towns (काम्-
पिल्यं च पुरोत्तमम्) 1. 128. 15.
C. Description: It had many Janapadas
(माकन्दीम्॥।जनपदायुताम्) 1. 128. 15.
D. Epic event: Defeated Drupada was
offered by Droṇa half of the kingdom
of the Pāñcāla country (1. 128. 10); Dru-
pada then went to Mākandī and settled
down at Kāmpilya 1. 128. 15.

मागध
Mā̆gadha m. (pl.): Name of a Jana-
pada and its people: also called Magadha-
rāṣṭra (1. 105. 10); its capital town Rāja-
gṛha (1. 105. 10; 1. 196. 17; 14. 83. 2).
A. Location: Listed twice by Saṃjaya
among the northern Janapadas (also called
Deśas 6. 10. 68) of Bhāratavarṣa (जन-
पदान् निबोध) 6. 10. 37, 5; (विदेहका
मागधाश् च) 6. 10. 44; (बहिर्गिर्याङ्ग-
मलदा मागधा मानवर्जकाः) 6. 10. 48;
in the east, beyond Suhmas and Prācya-
suhmas; beyond the rivers Gaṅgā and
Śoṇa and near the mountain Goratha (see
below Epic events No. 5 and 6).
B.
Description: The country of Magadha was
large, charming, rich in cattle, having
water all the year round, free from
disease, abounding in excellent dwelling
houses and bright (एष पार्थ महान्
स्वादुः पशुमान् नित्यम् अम्बुमान्।
निरामयः सुवेश्ंआढ्यो निवेशो मागधः
शुभः) 2. 19. 1 (Nī. on Bom. Ed. 2.
21. 1; निवेशो विन्यासः); the Magadha
land was covered with Kurava trees
(कुरवोरश्छदं … मागधं क्षेत्रम्)
2. 18. 29; it could not be avoided by
clouds due to the presence of the serpent
Maṇi (अपरिहार्या मेघानां मागधेयं
मणेः कृते) 2. 19. 10; the Magadha
warriors were brave (शूर) 7. 82. 35, ener-
getic (तरस्विन्) 8. 31. 11, and performers
of exploits (पराक्रान्त) 5. 52. 2; skilled
in fighting while riding elephants (गज-
योधिन्, गजयुद्धेषु कुशलाः) 8. 17. 2-3;
their women were long-eyed (आयतनेत्र)
and had sweet voice (सुस्वर) 11. 25. 8:
C. Characteristic of the people: Karṇa
told Śalya that Magadhas knew what the
eternal धर्म was (मगधास् तथा॥ …
धर्मं जानन्ति शाश्वतम्) 8. 30. 60-61;
Māgadha elders followed the prescribed
धर्मस् (मागधाश् च शिष्टान् धर्मान्
उपजीवन्ति वृद्धाः) 8. 30. 75; Magadhas
understood the intentions of others
(even if they were not expressed in
so many words) (इङ्गितज्ञाश् च मग-
धाः) 8. 30. 79.
D. Epic events: (1)
Bhīṣma defeated all Māgadha warriors
when he forcibly carried away two prin-
cesses for Vicitravīrya 13. 44. 37; (2)
Pāṇḍu in his conquest of the earth killed
Dārva, the protector of Magadharāṣṭra, at
Rājagṛha (गोप्ता मगधराष्ट्रस्य) 1. 105.
10; (3) At the birth of Jarāsandha, his
father Bṛhadratha ordered a festival for the
Magadha people in honour of the Rākṣasī
Jarā (आज्ञापयच् च … मागधेषु महोत्स-
वम्) 2. 17. 5; (4) Once the sage Caṇḍa-
kauśika happened to visit the Magadha
country (मगधान् उपचक्राम) 2. 17. 8;
(5) Kṛṣṇa, along with Bhīma and Arjuna,
left Khāṇḍavaprastha for the Magadha
country (प्रतस्थुर् मागधं प्रति);
proceeding towards the east, they reached
the Magadha land after crossing the rivers
Gaṅgā and Śoṇa; when they reached the
Goratha mountain they saw the capital
town of Magadha (उत्तीर्य गङ्गां शोणं
च सर्वे ते प्राङ्मुखास् त्रयः … जग्मुर्
मागधं क्षेत्रम्॥ … गोरथं गिरिम्
आसाद्य ददृशुर् मागधं पुरम्॥) 2. 18.
21, 29-30; they proceeded towards the
capital town of the Magadha country (माग-
धं पुरम्) and attacked the very beautiful
surroundings of the चैत्यक of Māgadhas
(मागधानां सुरुचिरं चैत्यकान्तम्
उपाद्रवन्) 2. 19. 12, 17 (Nī. on Bom. Ed. 2.
21. 15: चैत्यकं नगरसूचकम्); when
they had entered the town, the Magadha
people, seeing them, were wonderstruck
2. 19. 19, 27; Kṛṣṇa advised Jarāsandha
not to disregard others because he had
the support of the large and strong army
of Māgadhas (मागधैर् विपुलैः सैन्यैर्
बाहुल्यबलदर्पितैः) 2. 20. 18; hearing
the loud roar of Bhīma and Jarāsandha
the people of Magadha were much afraid,
their pregnant women lost their foetus
(स्त्रीणां गर्भाश् च सुस्रुवुः); they
wondered whether the Himālaya had
broken down or whether the earth was
being torn apart (किं नु स्विद् धिमवान्
भिन्नः किं नु स्विद् दीर्यते मही।इति स्म
मागधा जज्ञुर् … ) 2. 22. 8-9; when the
Magadha people saw Kṛṣṇa, Bhīma and
Arjuna riding the chariot of Jarāsandha,
they were astounded 2. 22. 19; (6) Bhīma
in his expedition before the Rājasūya went
towards the east (ययौ प्राचीं दिशं
प्रति 2. 27. 1; 2. 23. 9); he defeated Suhmas
and Prācyasuhmas and then marched on
Magadha; there he pacified the son of
Jarāsandha and collected tribute from him
(ततः सुह्मान् प्राच्यसुह्मान् … विजित्य …
मागधान् उपयाद् … ॥जारासन्धिं सान्त्व-
यित्वा करे च विनिवेश्य ह) 2. 27. 14, 16;
Later, Sahadeva (not Bhīma) is said to
have defeated Magadhas in battle (यः
काशीन् अङ्गमगधान् … युधाजयत्।तेन
 … सहदेवेन) 5. 49. 28; (7) On the
second day of war, Droṇa, along with
Māgadhas and others, followed Bhīṣma
in the Mahāvyūha of Kauravas 6. 47. 12,
10: (8) On the third day, Māgadhas,
equipped for battle, stood at the right
wing of the Garuḍavyūha of Kauravas
(मागधाश् च … दक्षिणं पक्षम् आसाद्य
स्थिता व्यूहस्य दंशिताः) 6. 52. 8, 3; (9)
On the fourth day, the Magadha army of
ten thousand energetic elephants led by
Jayatsena (not named) attacked Bhīma
(अनीकं दशसाहस्रं कुञ्जराणां तर-
स्विनां।मागधं पुरतः कृत्वा भीम-
सेनं समभ्ययात्॥) 6. 58. 31; (10)
On the eighth day, Bhagadatta, along
with Māgadha warriors and others follow-
ed Droṇa in the Mahāvyūha of Kauravas
6. 83. 8; (11) On the twelfth day,
Māgadhas and others were stationed at the
back (पृष्ठे) of the Suparṇavyūha of the
Kauravas 7. 19. 11, 4-5; (12) On the
fourteenth day, when Vyāghradatta was
killed by Sātyaki, Māgadhas rushed towards
Sātyaki and showered him with arrows and
तोमरस् by thousands and also with
भिण्डिपाल, प्रास and मुद्गर; but Sātyaki
easily defeated them all and they fled 7. 82.
33-36; (13) After the death of Droṇa,
Dhṛtarāṣṭra, lamenting, recalled Kṛṣṇa's
exploits which included his victory over
Māgadhas 7. 10. 15; (14) On the sixteenth
day, Māgadhas (on Pāṇḍavas' side) attack-
ed the Kaurava army (मागधाश् चापि
दुद्रुवुः) 8. 8. 19; (15) The same day,
Māgadhas and others on the side of Kaura-
vas, skilled in fighting while riding ele-
phants, were driven by the elephant-riders
towards Dhṛṣṭadyumna; they showered
him with arrows, तोमरस् and नाराचस्;
Dhṛṣṭadyumna pierced the elephants of
the enemies with arrows-each one with
ten, six or eight arrows; Dhṛṣṭadyumna
and Pāṇḍava heroes succeeded in routing
the attack of elephants (हस्तिभिस् तु
महामात्रा … पार्षतम् अभ्ययुः॥ … गज-
योधिनः। … मागधास् ताम्रलिप्तकाः॥
गजयुद्देषु कुशलाः … ) 8. 17. 1-6; (एवं
हत्वा तव गजान्॥) 8. 17. 28; (16) On
the seventeenth day, Kṛpa, along with the
energetic Māgadha warriors, stood on the
right side of the Bārhaspatyavyūha (8. 31.
26) of the Kauravas (कृपः शारद्वतो
राजन् मागधश् च (for मागधाश् च ?)
तरस्विनः।सात्वतः कृतवर्मा च दक्षि-
णं पक्षम् आश्रिताः॥ 8. 31. 11 (the cr.
edn. adopts the reading मागधः (sg.);
but it is almost certain that we have to
read मागधाः (pl.); the plural तरस्विनः
is hardly meant to include Kṛpa, Kṛtavar-
man and some Māgadha prince (sg.); he
cannot be Jayatsena since he was already
killed by Abhimanyu; adjective like
तरस्विनः are used with reference to
general warriors; there are variant read-
ings to support मागधाः; the editor has
no note on the stanza); the same day,
Bhīma killed many Māgadhas (siding
with Kauravas) 8. 49. 79; (17) On the
eighteenth day, to praise Bhīma before his
duel with Duryodhana, Kṛṣṇa reminded
him that he had formerly killed many
Māgadhas along with other warriors 9.
32. 32; (18) After the war Gāndhārī
pointed out to Kṛṣṇa Māgadhī women,
who in grief had discarded their gold
ornaments, surrounding the dead body
of Jayatsena and weeping; they rolled on
the ground; their wailing sound deluded
the mind of Gāndhārī ( … प्ररुदिता
मागध्यः पश्य योषितः॥प्रकीर्ण-
स्वर्णाभरणा रुदन्त्यः शोककर्शिताः। …
मागध्यः शेरते भुवि॥) 11. 25. 7, 9;
(आसां … मनःश्रुतिहरो नादो मनो
मोहयतीव मे) 11. 25. 8; (19) While
recounting Kṛṣṇa's past exploits, Vasu-
deva remembered that Kṛṣṇa had slain
Māgadha Kings (चक्रे (विदेहान्) कालिङ्ग-
मागधान्) 16. 7. 10.
E. Past events;
(1) The eight sons of Asurī Kālakā
were born as kings; the first of them,
the great Asura, was Jayatsena who was
the illustrious king of the Magadha country
(कालकायास् तु ये पुत्रास् तेषाम् अष्टौ
नराधिपाः।जज्ञिरे … ॥मगधेषु जयत्-
सेनः श्रीमान् आसीत् स पार्थिवः।अष्टानां
प्रवरस् तेषां कालेयानां महासुरः॥)
1. 61. 45-46; (2) Kākṣīva(t) and others
were born of Śūdrā Auśīnarī from the
magnanimous sage Gautama in Maga-
dha; Gautama took his residence in
Magadha; since the kings favoured him,
he took resort with the Magadha dynasty
(शूद्रायां गौतमो यत्र महात्मा सं-
शितव्रतः।औशीनर्याम् अजनयत् काक्षीवा-
दीन् सुतान् ऋषिः॥गौतमः क्षयणाद् अस्माद्
अथासौ तत्र वेश्मनि।भजते मागधं
वंशं स नृपाणाम् अनुग्रहात्॥) 2. 19.
5-6; (3) Ambuvīca was formerly the
king at Rājagṛha who ruled over the
Māgadha chieftains (श्रूयते हि पुरा कश्चिद्
अम्बुवीच इति श्रुतः।आसीद् राजगृहे राजा
मागधानां महीक्षिताम्॥) 1. 196. 17.
F. Some persons designated after the
Magadha country or its people as one be-
longing to Magadha, or the king of
Magadha, or the foremost among the
Magadhas, or the protector of Magadha
country:
A. One belonging to Magadha:
(a) मागध: (1) Jayatsena, son of Jarā-
sandha 5. 19. 8; 6. 104. 14, 56; 6. 110. 29
(cf. 31); 8. 4. 31; 9. 2. 17, 34; in the
following references Jayatsena is probably
meant although he is not directly named 2.
49. 7 (or Sahadeva ?); 6. 17. 27; 6. 18. 15;
6. 58. 312, 42-43; 6. 77. 3; 7. 47. 7; (2)
Jarāsandha 2. 13. 21, 45; 2. 14. 18; 2. 17.
19; 2. 20. 21-24; 2. 21. 3, 18; 8. 5. 22; 12.
5. 1; (3) Jalasandha 5. 164. 24; 7. 91. 28;
(4) Daṇḍadhāra 8. 13. 3; (5) Bṛhadratha
2. 17. 11; (6) Meghasandhi 14. 83. 14-16,
26; 14. 84. 1; (7) Sahadeva (son of Jarā-
sandha) 5. 56. 8; 5. 154. 10; 8. 4. 85; (8)
Unidentified 8. 31. 11 (but we have proba-
bly to read मागधाश् च; see above Epic
events No. 16); (b) मागधी (f.) (1)
Amṛtā 1. 90. 43; (2) Saṃpriyā 1. 90. 42;
B. King of Magadha (or of Māgadhas):
(a) मगधराज्: Bṛhadratha 1. 57. 29;
(b) मगधाधिप: Jarāsandha 15. 32. 12;
(c) मगधाधिपति: (1) Bṛhadratha 2. 16.
12; 2. 17. 7, 21; मागधानाम् अधिपति-
Jayatsena 8. 51. 23; 11. 25. 7; (d) मग-
धेश्वर: Meghasaṃdhi (grandson of
Jarāsandha 14. 83. 3) 14. 83. 10;
C.
Chief or foremost among Māgadhas: (a)
मागधेन्द्र: Jarāsandha 5. 50. 38; (b)
मागधानां प्रवरः: Daṇḍadhāra 8. 13.
5;
D. Protector of the Magadha country:
गोप्ता मागधराष्ट्रस्य: Dārva 1. 105. 10.

माचेल्लक
Mācellaka m. (pl.): Name of a
people.
Epic events: (1) During the war, their
warriors were on the side of Kauravas; in
the evening of the eleventh day of the war
(7. 16. 1-2), in the camp of Kauravas
Mācellakas were among those who, led by
Suśarman, took the oath to kill Arjuna
(सुशर्मा … माचेल्लकैर् … सहितो … सो
ऽशपद् भ्रातृभिः सह) 7. 16. 19-20; (2)
On the twelfth day, Arjuna killed Mācella-
kas and others; they, too, heavily showered
arrows of different kinds on Kṛṣṇa and
Arjuna so that the two became invisible;
considering them killed, Mācellakas and
others were pleased; they shook their upper
garments (वासांस्य् आदुधुवुस् तदा) and
sounded various instruments; they roared
loudly; Arjuna scattered away their arrows
with वायव्यास्त्र 7. 18. 16-20, 22; (3) On
the fourteenth day, Mācellakas were among
those ten thousand warriors who, driven
in chariots, followed Jaya, Kṛtavarman
and others to check the advance of Arjuna
towards Jayadratha (तेषां दशसहस्राणि
रथानाम् अनुयायिनाम्। … माचेल्लका ललि-
त्थाश् च … नरव्याघ्रम् अवारयन् …
न्यवारयन्त) 7. 66. 37-38, 41, 43.

माद्रेय
Mādreya m. (pl.): Name of a Jana-
pada.
Listed by Saṃjaya among the northern
Janapadas (also called Deśas 6. 10. 68) of
the Bhāratavarṣa (अत ऊर्ध्वं जनपदान्
निबोध) 6. 10. 37, 5; (तत्रेमे … शाल्व-
माद्रेयजाङ्गलाः) 6. 10. 37.

माधव
Mādhava: See Madhu.

मानवर्जक
Mānavarjaka m. (pl.): Name of a
Janapada.
Listed by Saṃjaya among the northern
Janapadas (also called Deśas 6. 10. 68)
of Bhāratavarṣa (जनपदान् निबोध) 6.
10. 37. 5; (मागधा मानवर्जकाः) 6.
10. 48.

मानस
Mānasa m. (pl.): Name of a Jana-
pada of the Śākadvīpa.
Listed by Saṃjaya among the four
Janapadas of Śākadvīpa (मानसा मन्दगास्
तथा) 6. 12. 33; described as holy (पुण्य)
and honoured by the people (लोकसंमत)
6. 12. 33; the Vaiśya people of the Mānasa
Janapada earned their livelihood by doing
their work; they obtained all their desires,
were brave and clear in their minds about
धर्म and अर्थ (the two पुरुषार्थस्)
(मानसेषु महाराज वैश्याः कर्मोप-
जीविनः।सर्वकामसमायुक्ताः शूराः धर्-
मार्थनिश्चिताः॥) 6. 12. 5.

मर्तिकावत
Martikāvata m. (sg.): Name of a
country.
A. Epic event: Kṛṣṇa reached Mār-
tikāvata from Dvārakā to attack Śālva; he
crossed many countries, mountains full of
woods, lakes and rivers to reach Mārtikā-
vata (समतीत्य बहून् देशान् गिरींश् च
बहुपादपान्।सरांसि सरितश् चैव मार्ति-
कावतम् आसदम्॥) 3. 21. 14.
B. Certain
kings designated after the name of the
country: मार्तिकावतक: (1) Citraratha 3.
116. 6; (2) Bhoja 7. 47. 8; (3) Śālva 3.
15. 16. [See Addenda Mārtikāvata, name
of a town].

मालक
Mālaka m. (pl.): Name of a Jana-
pada.
Listed by Saṃjaya among the southern
Janapadas (also called Deśas 6. 10. 68) of
Bhāratavarṣa (अथापरे जनपदा दक्षिणा
 … ) 6. 10. 56, 5; (मालका मल्लकाश् चैव)
6. 10. 61.

मालव
Mālava1 m. (pl.): Name of a Jana-
pada and its people; sometimes mentioned
along with Kṣullakas.
A. Designation: Distinguished as
eastern, western and northern Mālavas;
they were included among the twelve
Janapadas (प्राच्याः प्रतीच्योदीच्यमाल-
वाः॥द्वादशैते जनपदाः) 6. 18. 13-14;
6. 114. 76-77.
B. Location: To the west
of Khāṇḍavaprastha (see Epic event (1)
below).
C. Description: Their warriors
were brave and prepared to sacrifice
their lives (शूर, तनूत्यज्) 6. 18. 14; 7. 132.
23; strong (बलवन्त्) 6. 112. 107; great
chariot-fighters (महारथ) 6. 112. 107,
111.
D. Epic events: (1) Nakula in his
expedition to the west (निर्याय खाण्डव-
प्रस्थात् प्रतीचीम् अभितो दिशम् 2. 29. 2;
2. 23. 10) before the Rājasūya subjugated
Mālavas (वशे चक्रे … ।मालवान् पञ्चकर्-
पटान्॥) 2. 29. 6; their Kṣatriyas brought
wealth in hundreds as tribute for the
Rājasūya (सह क्षुद्रकमालवैः॥ …
आहार्षुः क्षत्रिया वित्तं शतशो) 2. 48.
14-16; (2) In the war, they were to
be faced by the five Kekaya brothers
who were on the side of Pāṇḍavas
(भ्रातरः पञ्च केकयाः। … तेषाम् एव
कृतो भागो मालवाः) 5. 56. 17-18; (3)
Mālava warriors were among the twelve
Janapadas who, riding chariots, were to
protect Bhīṣma in the war (महता
रथवंशेन ते ऽभ्यरक्षन् पितामहम्)
16. 18. 13-14; (4) On the second day of
war, in the Mahāvyūha of Kauravas,
Duryodhana, assisted by Mālava warriors
and others gave protection to the army of
Śakuni (तथा क्षुद्रकमालवैः।अभ्य-
रक्षत … सौबलेयस्य वाहिनीम्) 6. 47. 10,
16; (5) On the third day of war, Kṣudra-
kas and Mālavas, led by Droṇa and others,
rushed towards Arjuna as directed by
Bhīṣma; they were killed by Arjuna with
the use of the Māhendra अस्त्र (क्षुद्रक-
मालवाश् च।किरीटिनं त्वरमाणाभिसस्रुर्
निदेशगाः शान्तनवस्य) 6. 55. 74; (निपाति-
ताः क्षुद्रकमालवाश् च) 6. 55. 130, 110,
120; (6) On the eighth day of war,
Bhīṣma, supported by Mālavas and others,
led the Mahāvyūha of Kauravas; he was
followed by Droṇa accompanied by Kṣu-
drakas and Mālavas (अग्रतः सर्वसैन्या-
नां भीष्मः … ययौ।मालवैर् दाक्षि-
णात्यैश् च … ॥ततो ऽनन्तरम् एवासीद्
भारद्वाजः … । … तथा क्षुद्रकमाल-
वैः॥) 6. 83. 5-7; (7) On the ninth day,
Mālavas were among those who did not
abandon Bhīṣma although they were being
killed by sharp arrows (संग्रामे नाजहुर्
भीष्मं वध्यमानाः शितैः शरैः) 6.
102. 7; (8) On the tenth day, exhorted
by Duryodhana (6. 112. 102, 105) the great
Mālava chariot-fighters (महारथाः 6. 112.
107, 111) attacked Arjuna; he struck them
with heavenly weapons (दिव्यान्य् अस्त्राणि)
which burnt them; afflicted by arrows,
they did not attack Arjuna (ते शरार्ता …
नाभ्यवर्तन्त … वानरध्वजम्); Arjuna
killed them 6. 112. 109-116; on that day
also they did not abandon Bhīṣma although
they were struck with arrows and were
afficted due to wounds (शरार्ता व्रण-
पीडिताः।संग्रामे न जहुर् भीष्मम्
युध्यमानं किरीटिना॥) 6. 114. 76-77;
(9) At the end of the eleventh day in the
camp of Kauravas, Mālavas were among
those thirty thousand chariot-fighters who,
led by Suśarman, took oath to kill
Arjuna (रथानाम् अयुतैस् त्रिभिः) 7.
16. 19-20; (10) On the twelfth day,
Arjuna pierced Mālavas with arrows, but
they continued to shower arrows of diffe-
rent kinds on him (व्यसृजन् शरवर्षाणि
पार्थे नानाविधानि च) so that Kṛṣṇa and
Arjuna could not be seen by others;
Mālavas thought that the two were
killed and were delighted; they sounded
instruments, roared, and waived their
upper garments (वासांस्य् आदुधुवुस् तदा);
Arjuna removed (the screen produced by)
the shower of their arrows by employing
वायव्यास्त्र (वायव्यास्त्रेण तैर् अस्तां
शरवृष्टिम् अपाहरत्) 7. 18. 16-22; (11)
During the night war (14th-15th day),
Yudhiṣṭhira killed many heroic Mālavas
and others (मालवाञ् शूरान् … गणान्) 7.
132. 23; 7. 136. 3; (12) After the death
of Droṇa, on the sixteenth day, Dhṛtarāṣṭra
while recounting Kṛṣṇa's former exploits
mentioned his victory over Mālavas 7. 10.
17; (13) On the night of the seventeenth
day, after the death of Karṇa (हते
कर्णे … निशि 8. 1. 25) Saṃjaya mentioned
Mālavas among those who were killed in
the first seventeen days of war 8. 4. 46.
E. Some persons referred to after the name
of the country:
A. One who belonged to
Mālava: (i) मालव: (1) Indravarman 7.
164. 101; 7. 165. 115; (2) Sudarśana 7.
171. 56, 58; 7. 172. 9; (ii) मालवी (f.):
Wife of king Aśvapati of the the Madra
country 3. 277. 22; 3. 281. 58; 3. 283. 13.

मालव
Mālava2 m. (pl.): Common designa-
tion of Sāvitrī's hundred brothers.
They were born of Mālavī, wife of
king Aśvapati of the Madra country (3.
277. 5-6) as a result of the boon given
by Yama to Sāvitrī (पितुश् च ते पुत्रशतं
भविता तव मातरि।मालव्यां मालवा
नाम … भ्रातरस् ते भविष्यन्ति) 3. 281.
58; 3. 283. 13; they are described as god-
like (त्रिदशोपमाः) and were to continue
their line for ever (शाश्वताः पुत्रपौत्रि-
णः) 3. 281. 58; they were very strong
(भ्रातॄणां … शतम्। … सुमहाबलम्) 3.
283. 13.

मालवाणक
Mālavāṇaka m. (pl.): Name of a
Janapada.
Listed by Saṃjaya among the southern
Janapadas (also called Deśas 6. 10. 68) of
Bhāratavarṣa (अथापरे जनपदा दक्षिणा
॥।) 6. 10. 56, 5; (कोङ्कणा मालवाणकाः)
6. 10. 58.

मावेल्लक
Māvellaka m. (pl.): Name of a people.
Their warriors fought on the side of
Kauravas; in his report to Dhṛtarāṣṭra
after the first seventeen days of war,
Saṃjaya mentioned Māvellakas among
those who were killed by Arjuna (मावेल्ल-
कास् … ते हताः समरे राजन् पार्थेन … )
8. 4. 47, 50.

माहिष
Māhiṣa m. (pl.): Name of Janapada.
Listed by Saṃjaya among the northern
Janapadas (also called Deśas 6. 10. 68)
of Bhāratavarṣa (अत ऊर्ध्वं जनपदान्
निबोध) 6. 10. 37. 5; (माहिषकार्षिकाः) 6.
10. 45 [See the next].

माहिषक
Māhiṣaka, Mahiṣaka m. (pl.): Name
of a Janapada and its people.
A. Location: Listed by Saṃjaya
among the northern Janapadas (also called
Deśas 6. 10. 68) of Bhāratavarṣa (जन-
पदान् निबोध) 6. 10. 37, 5; (उन्नत्यका
माहिषका … ) 6. 10. 57; but they are also
said to have resided near the southern
ocean (प्रययौ भूयो दक्षिणं सलिलार्-
णवम्) 14. 84. 10-11 (see Epic event).
B. Description and characteristic: Fierce
(रौद्रैर् माहिषकैर् अपि) 14. 84. 11
(रौद्र name of a different people or
description of Māhiṣakas ?); a Brāh-
maṇa reported to the Kuru assembly that
Māhiṣakas practised bad धर्म and
hence they should be avoided ( … उक्तवान्
सभ्यो ब्राह्मणः कुरुसंसदि; … माहि-
षकान् … दुर्धर्मांश् च विवर्जयेत्) 8.
30. 41, 45; they were originally a Kṣatriya
community but became degraded to the
status of a वृषल due to their disregard
of Brāhmaṇas (माहिषकास् तास् ताः क्षत्रिय-
जातयः॥वृषलत्वं परिगता ब्राह्मणा-
नाम् अदर्शनात्) 13. 33. 20-21.
C. Epic
event: Arjuna in his expedition before the
Aśvamedha fought a fierce battle with the
Māhiṣakas and others 14. 84. 11. [See
Māhiṣa].

मुकुट
Mukuṭa m. (pl.): Name of a people.
Their king Vigāhana mentioned by
Bhīma among the eighteen famous kings
who extirpated their kinsmen, friends, and
relatives (अष्टादशेमे राजानः प्रख्याता
 … ।ये समुच्चिच्छिदुर् ज्ञातीन् सुहृदश् च
सबान्धवान्॥ … मुकुटानां विगाहनः॥)
5. 72. 11, 16.

मुक्त
Mukta m. (pl.): Name of a people.
On the third day of the war, Mukta
warriors were among those who were
posted at the left wing of the Garuḍavyūha
(6. 52. 2-3) of the Kauravas (मुक्ताः
पुण्ड्रविषस् तथा। … वामं पक्षम् उपा-
श्रिताः) 6. 52. 9.

मुण्ड
Muṇḍa m. (pl.): Name of a people (?).
Kṛṣṇa had seen Muṇḍas and many
others acting as servants in the Rājasūya
of Yudhiṣṭhira (जागुडान् रमठान् मुण्डान्
 … आगतान् अहम् अद्राक्षं यज्ञे ते परि-
वेषकान्) 3. 48. 21-22; on the fourteenth
day of war, Sātyaki told his charioteer
that he would kill the army of Muṇḍas
again and again (मुण्डान् एतान् हनिष्यामि
 … मुण्डानीके हते सूत … चासकृत्) 7. 95.
20-21 (मुण्ड, name of a people or does
the word here describe (shaven) Jāguḍas,
Ramaṭhas and others like Kāmbojas 7.
95. 20 or Mlecchas 7. 68. 44 ?).

मुनिदेश
Munideśa m. (sg.): Name of a Deśa
of the Krauñcadvīpa.
Munideśa lay beyond Andhakāraka-
deśa and beyond Munideśa lay Dundubhi-
svanadeśa (अन्धकारकदेशात् तु मुनि-
देशः परः स्मृतः।मुनिदेशात् परश्
चैव प्रोच्यते दुन्दुभिस्वनः); all the
Deśas of Krauñcadvīpa were frequented by
gods and Gandharvas (देवगन्धर्वसेवि-
ताः) 6. 13. 22-23.

मूषक
Mūṣaka m. (pl.): Name of a Jana-
pada.
Listed by Saṃjaya twice among the
southern Janapadas (also called Deśas 6.
10. 68) of Bhāratavarṣa (अथापरे जन-
पदा दक्षिणा … ) 6. 10. 56, 5; (विकल्पा
मूषकास् तथा) 6. 10. 57; (मूषकाः
स्तनबालाश् च) 6. 10. 62.

मेकल
Mekala m. (pl.): Name of a Janapada
and its people.
A. Location: Listed by Saṃjaya
among the northern Janapadas (also called
Deśas 6. 10. 68) of Bhāratavarṣa (अत
ऊर्ध्वं जनपदान् निबोध) 6. 10. 37, 5;
(मेकलाश् चोत्कलैः सह) 6. 10. 39; (perhaps
in the east, since they are mentioned along
with Utkalas).
B. Description: Their
warriors skilled in fighting while riding
elephants (गजयुद्धेषु कुशलाः; गजयो-
धिनः) 8. 17. 3, 2.
C. Social status;
Characterized as म्लेच्छस् 8. 17. 9; origi-
nally Kṣatriyas, they were degraded to the
status of वृषलस् since they disregarded
Brāhmaṇas (मेकलाः … वृषलत्वम् अनु-
प्राप्ता ब्राह्मणानाम् अदर्शनात्) 13. 35.
17-18.
D. Epic events: (1) On the
second day of war, Droṇa supported by
Mekalas and other warriors followed
Bhīṣma who led the Mahāvyūha of the
Kauravas (विदर्भैर् मेकलैश् चैव) 6.
47. 13, 10; (2) On the eighth day,
Bṛhadbala along with Mekalas and others
followed Bhagadatta (who followed Droṇa
and Bhīṣma) in the Mahāvyūha of the
Kauravas (मेकलैस् त्रैपुरैश् चैव) 6.
83. 9, 5; (3) On the sixteenth day, as
ordered by Duryodhana, angry Mekalas
and other warriors attacked Dhṛṣṭadyumna
with elephants in order to kill him (हस्ति-
भिस् तु महामात्रास् तव पुत्रेण चोदिताः।
 … क्रुद्धाः पार्षतम् अभ्ययुः॥ … मेकला
 … ); they showered him with तोमरस्
and नाराच arrows; Dhṛṣṭadyumna repulsed
their attack with नाराच arrows by hitting
each elephant with six, eight, or ten
arrows (एकैकम् दशभिः षड्भिर् अष्टा-
भिर् अपि भारत।द्विरदान् अभिविव्याध)
8. 17. 1-6; later they attacked Nakula with
elephants showering arrows and तोमरस्
on him; the battle that ensued between
chariot- and elephant-fighters described 8,
17. 20-28.

मौक
Mauka m. (pl.): Name of a Jana-
pada.
Listed by Saṃjaya among the northern
Janapadas (also called Deśas 6. 10. 68)
of Bhāratavarṣa (अत ऊर्ध्वं जनपदान्
निबोध) 6. 10. 37, 5; (बोधा मौकास्
तथैव च) 6. 10. 38.

मौलेय
Mauleya m. (pl.): Name of a people.
Their Kṣatriyas and those of Vasātis
and others brought wealth in hundreds as
tribute for Yudhiṣṭhira's Rājasūya (वसा-
तयः समौलेयाः … ॥आहार्षुः क्षत्रिया
वित्तं शतशो ऽजातशत्रवे) 2. 48. 14, 16.

मौष्टिक
Mauṣṭika m. (pl.): Name of a people.
As told by Karṇa to Śalya, according
to the Rākṣasa Kalmāṣapāda, Mauṣṭikas
were as good as the dirt of Mlecchas, and
Śaṇḍas were the dirt of Mauṣṭikas (म्ले-
च्छानां मौष्टिका मलम्।मौष्टिकानां
मलं शण्डाः) 8. 30. 70 [See P. L.
Vaidya's note on the stanza, Cr. Edn. Vol.
10, p. 687; “Mauṣṭikāḥ or Muṣṭikāḥ,
probably a sub-caste of the Mlecchas. It is
likely that the term came to be confound-
ed with Auṣṭrikāḥ (a reading of the
Central group of manuscripts), a people
who made their living by trade in
camels”].

म्लेच्छ
Mleccha m. (pl.): General characte-
rization of peoples who are distinguished
from those who are designated as Āryas.
A. The following peoples are speci-
fically designated as म्लेच्छस्: Aṅgas 7.
25. 17; 7. 68. 31; 8. 17. 2, 14-16, 17-18;
Āndharas 3. 186. 29-30; Ābhīras 3. 186. 29-
30; 16. 8. 45; Utkalas 8. 17. 20; Aurṇakas
3. 186. 29-30; Kāmbojas 3. 186. 29-30; 6.
10. 64; Kāliṅgas 8. 17. 20; Kośalas 8. 17. 3;
Tāmraliptakas 8. 17. 2, 20; Daśārṇas 8. 17.
3; Dasyus of Pañcanada 16. 8. 43-44, 47,
58, 60; Niṣadhas 8. 17. 3, 20; Puṇḍras 8. 17.
3, 13; Pulindas 3. 186. 29; Madras 8. 17. 3;
8. 27. 91; Māgadhas 8. 17. 2; Mekalas 8.
17. 3, 20; Yavanas 3. 186. 29; 6. 10. 64;
8. 59. 12: Vaṅgas 8. 17. 2, 11; Śakas 3. 186.
29-30; Śūdras 3. 186. 29-30; Sindhusauvīras
8. 27. 91.
B. Location: They, along with
Āryas, inhabit the Bhāratavarṣa and drink
the waters of Gaṅgā, Sindhu and Sarasvatī
(6. 10. 12); in the north they are listed by
Saṃjaya among the northern tribes of
Bhāratavarṣa (उत्तराश् चापरे म्लेच्छा जना
 … ॥ … म्लेच्छजातयः।) 6. 10. 63, 64, 5;
in the north (उदीच्यां दिशि यद् वृत्तं
म्लेच्छेषु) 12. 162. 28; on the foot-hills
of Himavant: Pāṇḍavas saw them on
their way to Gandhamādana (देशान्
म्लेच्छगणाकीर्णान् … ददृशुर् गिरिपादांश्
च) 3. 145. 12; they lived also in the in-
accessible places of the Himavant moun-
tain (हिमवद्दुर्गवासिनाम्) 7. 87. 37; some
lived on the Vindhya mountain as well
(विन्ध्यनिलया म्लेच्छाः) 12. 59. 103; in
forests in general (वनं … म्लेच्छतस्क-
रनिषेवितम्) 3. 61. 2; located also in east
and south (प्राच्याश् च दाक्षिणात्याश् च; ते
म्लेच्छैः प्रेषिता नागाः) 8. 17. 2, 9; near
the oceans: they lived by the gulf of the
western ocean (reference to Nakula's
expedition to the west 2. 29. 2) (सागर-
कुक्षिस्थान् म्लेच्छान्) 2. 29. 15; along the
eastern ocean (सागरानूपवासिभिः) -here
they are mentioned along with Bhagadatta
of the east 2. 31. 9-10; 2. 47. 12; along
the ocean in general (सागरानूपगांश्
चैव) 3. 48. 19; (सागरानूपवासिनः) 8.
51. 19; समुद्रवासिनः) 1. 202. 8; on the
islands of the eastern ocean (reference
to Bhīma's expedition to the east 2. 26. 1)
(म्लेच्छनृपतीन् सागरद्वीपवासिनः) 2.
27. 25, 23; on the islands of the southern
ocean (reference to Sahadeva's expedi-
tion to the south 2. 28. 1) (सागरद्वीप-
वासांश् च नृपतीन् म्लेच्छयोनिजान्) 2. 28.
44; along the seacoast in Vaṅga, Puṇḍra
and Kerala (see epic event No. 15); they
did not exist in the Varṣas of the द्वीपस्
of Uttara Kuru (न तेषु दस्यवः सन्ति
म्लेच्छजात्योऽपि वा … ) 6. 13. 15, 1.
C.
Different Origins: (1) In the bygone
days, the sages churned the right thigh
of king Vena whom they had killed;
from it arose a dwarfish person (ह्रस्वा-
ङ्गः); him, the sages said ‘sit down’
(निषीद); from him were born Niṣādas
and other Mlecchas in hundreds and
thousands living on Vindhya mountain
(तस्मान् निषादाः संभूताः … ये चान्ये
विन्ध्यनिलयाः म्लेच्छाः शतसहस्रशः)
12. 59. 101-103; (2) Mlecchas were
produced by Nandinī, Vasiṣṭha's cow, from
her foam; they and other peoples produced
by Nandinī formed a large army; they wore
different armours and held different wea-
pons (म्लेच्छान् फेनतः सा ससर्ज ह॥
तैर् विसृष्टैर् महत् सैन्यं नानाम्लेच्छ-
गणैस् तदा।नानावरणसंछन्नैर् नाना-
युधधरैस् तथा) 1. 165. 36-37 (perhaps,
here the term म्लेच्छगण is used to in-
clude Pallavas and others who were also
then produced by Nandinī); the origin
of Mlecchas from cows also referred to in
7. 68. 42 (गोयोनिप्रभवा म्लेच्छाः) and
in 7. 87. 36 (सन्ति गोयोनयश् चात्र); (3)
All Mleccha tribes sprang from Anu, the
son of Yayāti (अनोस् तु म्लेच्छजातयः) 1.
80. 26; (4) Originally all were Brāhmaṇas
(न विशेषो ऽस्ति वर्णानां सर्वं ब्राह्मम्
इदं जगत्) 12. 181. 10; later, Brāhmaṇas
who did not know (the धर्म and did not
observe the vows and regulations) became
different tribes such as Mlecchas (ब्रह्म
चैतत् पुरा सृष्टं ये न जानन्त्य् अतद्विदः।
तेषां बहुविधास् त्व् अन्यास् तत्र तत्र हि
जातयः। … बहुधा म्लेच्छजातयः) 12.
181. 18; (5) Sinful men who lived under
the influence of greed and temptation were
born as Mlecchas who did not deserve
to be associated with (असंवासाः प्रजा-
यन्ते म्लेच्छाश् चापि न संशयः।नराः
पापसमाचारा लोभमोहसमन्विताः॥) 13.
112. 108.
D. Description and characte-
ristics: (1) Of Mlecchas in general: im-
pure (अशुचि) 7. 68. 44; sinful (पाप) 1. 79.
13; (पापकर्तृ) 7. 87. 37; bad (असत्)
7. 87. 37; cruel, harsh in all acts, eat
anything (म्लेच्छाः क्रूराः सर्वभक्षा
दारुणाः सर्वकर्मसु) 3. 188. 52; 6. 10.
64; (परमदारुण) 2. 29. 15; lusting after
the wives of their teachers, they follow
the laws of animals and are therefore as
good as born animals (गुरुदारप्रसक्तेषु
तिर्यग्योनिगतेषु च।पशुधर्मिषु …
म्लेच्छेषु) 1. 79. 13; their heads were
shaven, or half shaven, or they wore
twisted hair; their faces were bearded
(मुण्डार्धमुण्डजटिलान् … जटिलाननान्)
7. 68. 44; they had queer appearances
(नानाविकृतदर्शन) 7. 68. 37; Mlecchas
were born in sinful countries and were igno-
rant of धर्मस् (पापदेशोद्भवा म्लेच्छा
धर्माणाम् अविचक्षणाः) 8. 27. 91; they
lost knowledge and higher knowledge and
hence behaved as they liked (प्रनष्टज्ञान-
विज्ञानाः स्वच्छन्दाचारचेष्टिताः) 12. 181.
18; Rākṣasa Kalmāṣapāda told a certain
king that Mlecchas were the dirt of human
beings and Mauṣṭikas were the dirt of
Mlecchas (मानुषाणां मलं म्लेच्छा
म्लेच्छानां मौष्टिका मलम्) 8. 30. 70;
all varṇas including Mlecchas observe fast
(सर्वेषाम् एव वर्णानां म्लेच्छानां च … ।
उपवासे मतिर् … ) 13. 109. 1; they did not
deserve to be associated with (असंवासाः)
13. 112. 108; Mlecchas understood only
their own conventions (म्लेच्छाः स्वसंज्ञा-
नियताः) 8. 30. 80 (Nī., however, on Bom.
Ed. 8. 45. 36: (स्वससंज्ञायां स्वीयैः
कृतो यो धर्मसङ्केतस् तत्रैव नियताः
वैदिकं धर्मं न मानयन्तीत्य् अर्थः);
When the Pāṇḍavas left for Vāraṇāvata
Vidura spoke to Yudhiṣṭhira in the speech
of Mlecchas (unintelligible to others)
(उक्तो म्लेच्छवाचासि पाण्डव) 1. 135. 6;
(2) Mleccha warriors: Wore different kinds
of dresses (नानावेषधर) 7. 68. 38; they
were brave (शूर) 8. 31. 22, strong (बलिन्),
furious (संरम्भिन्), fond of battles
(युद्धशौण्ड) and firm-fisted (दृब्ध-
पाणि) 8. 51. 19; 7. 87. 17; skilled in fighting
battles (युद्धविशारद) 7. 103. 22; they
did not turn their backs to the enemies
(अनिवर्तिन्) 7. 98. 23; fought heroically with
various kinds of weapons (नानायुधवीर्य-
वन्त्) 5. 22. 21; (नानाशस्त्रौघसंवृत)
7. 68. 38; (विविधायुधपाणि) 7. 95. 13;
they were skilled in fighting while riding
elephants (गजयोधिन्, गजयुद्धेषु
कुशलाः) 8. 17. 2-3; their fights from ele-
phant-backs often mentioned 7. 68. 37,
40, 46 (also horses); 7. 87. 16-18; 8. 31.
22; their elephant-force known as अञ्जनक;
the elephants never turned back once they
were goaded to attack the enemies; they
preferred death to defeat (यद् एतत् कुञ्ज-
रानीकं साहस्रम् अनुपश्यसि।कुलम्
अञ्जनकं नाम … ; नैते जातु निवर्तेरन्
प्रेषिता हस्तिसादिभिः।अन्यत्र हि वधाद्
एषां नास्ति राजन् पराजयः) 7. 87. 16-17;
(3) Mleccha Kings: Acted as their teachers
(म्लेच्छाचार्याश् च राजानः) 12. 4. 8 (cf. S.
B. Belvalkar's note on this stanza in Vol.
13, p. 638. 1: “Mleccha kings of the west
were also the आचार्यस् or the spiritual heads
of their domain”).
E. Epic events:
(1) Duḥṣanta ruled over the entire earth
including the countries of the Mlecchas
and Āṭavikas (आ म्लेच्छाटविकान् सर्वान्)
1. 62. 5; (2) Bhīma in his expedition
to the east before the Rājasūya (ययौ
प्राचीं दिशं प्रति 2. 26. 1, 7; 2. 23. 9)
defeated Mleccha hordes who lived on the
islands of the eastern ocean (ये च सागर-
वासिनः।सर्वान् म्लेच्छगनांश् चैव
विजिग्ये) 2. 27. 23; he made their kings
pay tribute in the form of jewels and many
other precious articles including gold,
silver etc. (स सर्वान् म्लेच्छनृपतीन् सागर-
द्वीपवासिनः।करम् आहारयाम् आस रत्नान्त्
विविधानि च) 2. 27. 25-26; Sahadeva in
his expedition to the south (प्रययौ
दक्षिणां दिशम् 2. 28. 1; 2. 23. 9) brought
under control Mleccha kings living in
islands and made them pay tribute for the
Rājasūya (सागरद्वीपवासांश् च नृपतीन्
म्लेच्छयोनिजान्; करदान् पार्थिवान् कृत्वा)
2. 28. 44, 54; Nakula in his expedition to
the west (निर्याय खाण्डवप्रस्थात् प्रती-
चीम् अभितो दिशम् 2. 29. 2; 2. 23. 10)
brought under control Mlecchas living
along the western ocean (ततः सागरकुक्षि-
स्थान् म्लेच्छान्) 2. 29. 15; 5. 49. 26; Mle-
cchas were among those who made a crowd
at the Rājasūya (सर्वे म्लेच्छाः … ।पर्-
यस्त इव लोको ऽयं युधिष्ठिरनिवेशने)
2. 48. 33; Kṛṣṇa saw Mlecchas among
those who worked as attendants at the
Rājasūya (अहम् अद्राक्षं यज्ञे ते परि-
वेषकान्) 3. 48. 19; (3) Pāṇḍavas on
their way to Viśālā Badarī saw countries
inhabited by hordes of Mlecchas (देशान्
म्लेच्छगणाकीर्णान्) 3. 145. 12; (4) Some
Mlecchas had joined the army of Pāṇḍavas
(पाण्डवार्थे निविष्टाः) 5. 22. 21; others
had joined the army of Duryodhana
(राजचमूं समेताम्। … म्लेच्छैः) 5.
158. 19-20; (5) Mlecchas and Āryas, who
had gathered for war and who had seen
or heard about the conduct of Pāṇḍavas
wept with choked throats (म्लेच्छाश्
चार्याश् च … ददृशुः शुश्रुवुस् तदा।तद्
वृत्तं पाण्डुपुत्राणां रुरुदुस् ते सगद्-
गदाः॥) 6. 41. 103; (6) On the fourteenth
day, countless Mlecchas, along with the
elephants who carried them, were killed by
Arjuna with the माया of his अस्त्रस् (अस्त्र-
मायया); वडस्, कङ्कस् and wolves were
glad to drink their blood 7. 68. 37, 42,
44, 46; 7. 69. 30; (7) On the same day,
Sātyaki noticed the large army of Añjanaka
elephants ridden by Mlecchas 7. 87. 16-18;
having secured that large army of elephants
of Mlecchas, Duryodhana had felt contempt
for Pāṇḍavas (एतद् दुर्योधनो लब्ध्वा
समग्रं नागमण्डलम् … अवमन्यत
पाण्डवान्॥) 7. 87. 37-39; Sātyaki pointed
out to his charioteer the Mlecchas who,
riding chariots, horses and elephants, and
equipped with different weapons, desired to
fight with him 7. 95. 13-14; (8) Duḥśā-
sana, rebuked by Droṇa, attacked Sātyaki
along with a large army of Mlecchas (सै-
न्येन महता युक्तो म्लेच्छानाम् अनिवर्ति-
नाम्) 7. 98. 23; (9) The same day, Bhīma
defeated and passed beyond many hordes
of Mlecchas in order to get near Arjuna
7. 103. 32; (10) On the fifteenth day,
Bhīma while scolding Droṇa mentioned
that he, like a Cāṇḍāla, had killed many
hordes of Mlecchas 7. 165. 30; (11) On
the sixteenth day, Mlecchas (8. 17. 9) riding
elephants fought a severe battle with
Dhṛṣṭadyumna and other Pāṇḍava promi-
nent warriors 8. 17. 1-28 (for details of
the battle see Mekala); (12) On the
seventeenth day, Mlecchas riding elephants
in rut, led by Aśvatthāman and others,
followed the chariot-army of Duryodhana
at the back of the Bārhaspatyavyūha (8.
31. 26) of Kauravas 8. 31. 19-20, 22; the
same day, Kṛṣṇa in order to encourage
Arjuna said that Mlecchas who had asso-
ciated themselves with Kurus in the interest
of Duryodhana could not be conquered
by any one else except him (म्लेच्छाश् च …
एते सुयोधनस्यार्थे संरब्धाः कुरुभिः
सह।न शक्या युधि निर्जेतुं त्वदन्येन
परंतप॥) 8. 51. 19-20; Mlecchas, riding
thirteen hundred elephants in rut, attacked,
as directed by Duryodhana, Arjuna from
one side (पार्श्वतः); they showered
Arjuna with कर्णिन्, नालीक, and नाराच
arrows as also with तोमरस्, प्रासस्, शक्तिस्,
कम्पनस् and भिण्डिपालस्; Arjuna cut off
the shower of their arrows and weapons
with भल्ल and अर्धचन्द्र arrows; he
killed their elephants with different kinds
of महाशरस्; the elephants began to run
in all directions 8. 59. 10-16; (13)
After the war was over, while Saṃjaya
was reporting events of the eighteenth
day to Dhṛtarāṣṭra, the latter remembered
that once the whole earth, including
the Mlecchas and Āṭavikas was sustained
due to the graciousness of Duryodhana
(इयं च पृथिवी सर्वा सम्लेछाटविका … ।
प्रसादाद् ध्रियते यस्य) 9. 31. 3; later,
Saṃjaya in his account listed Mlecchas
among those who were killed in the great
war (म्लेच्छाश् च … निपातिताः) 9. 1. 26;
Dhṛtarāṣṭra remembered that Duryodhana,
before the war, counted Mlecchas among
those who, in thousands, were ready
to fight and give up their lives for him;
it was with their support that he was
going to fight with Pāṇḍavas (म्लेच्छाश्
च बहुसाहश्राः … मदर्थम् उद्यताः
सर्वे प्राणांस् त्यक्त्वा रणे प्रभो॥) 9.
2. 18, 21-22; that they were killed by
thousands, was due to bad fate according
to Dhṛtarāṣṭra (हता … म्लेच्छाश् च
बहुसाहस्रा किम् अन्यद् भागधेयतः।)
9. 2. 36; (14) Mlecchācāryas were
among those who attended the स्वयं-
वर of the Kaliṅga princess at Rājapura
12. 4. 8; (15) Arjuna in his wanderings
with the Aśvamedha horse had to fight
with Mlecchas who were formerly, in the
war, offended by him (म्लेच्छाश् चान्ये
बहुविधा पूर्वं विनिकृता रणे) 14,
72. 24; when the horse wandered along
the seacoast through Vaṅga, Puṇḍra and
Kerala countries, Arjuna defeated many
Mleccha armies many times (ततः समुद्र-
तीरेण वङ्गान् पुण्ड्रान् सकेरलान्॥तत्र
तत्र च भूरीणी म्लेच्छसैन्यान्य् अने-
कशः।विजिग्ये) 14. 83. 30; at the end of the
Aśvamedha sacrifice, the sacrificial priests
distributed a large quantity of gold among
the Brāhmaṇas; after that, what wealth
(gold) remained that was taken away
over a long period by Kṣatriyas, Vaiśyas,
Śūdras and Mleccha tribes (अनन्तरं
ब्राह्मणेभ्यः क्षत्रिया जह्रिरे वसु।
तथा विट्शूद्रसंघाश् च तथान्ये म्ले-
च्छजातयः।कालेन महता जह्रुस् तत्
सुवर्णम् ततस् ततः॥) 14. 91. 25; (16)
On Arjuna's way from Dvārakā to Hāstina-
pura, Mlecchas abducted Vṛṣṇi and
Andhaka women 16. 8. 61.
F. Past
events: (1) Demons Sunda and Upasunda
conquered all Mleccha tribes living in the
ocean (समुद्रवासिनः सर्वान् म्लेच्छ-
जातीन् विजिग्यतुः) 1. 202. 8; (2) Damayantī,
forsaken by Nala, entered a forest inhabited
by Mlecchas and thieves (म्लेच्छतस्कर-
सेवितम्) 3. 61. 2; (3) Indra taught king
Māndhātṛ the duties of Dasyus which term
included Mlecchas 12. 65. 14, 17-22; (4)
Bhīṣma told Yudhiṣṭhira a story related
to Mlecchas who lived in the north (the
term Dasyu is used in the story for
Mlecchas) 12. 162. 28 ff.; (5) Yayāti
cursed his son Turvasu to the effect that
he would be born among the Mlecchas
(म्लेच्छेषु प्रभविष्यसि) 1. 79. 13.
G.
Future event: Mārkaṇḍeya foretold that
in the Kali age (कलौ युगे 3. 186. 27)
there would be many Mleccha kings on
this earth; they would be sinful, given to
lies and rule the world the wrong way
(बहवो म्लेच्छराजानः पृथिव्यां … ।
मिथ्यानुशासिनः पापा मृषावादपराय-
णाः) 3. 186. 29; when the end of the aeon
will have arrived (युगान्ते समनुप्राप्ते
3. 186. 33; युगान्ते पर्युपस्थिते 3. 188.
19, 43-44. 47, 54, 76, 81-83; युगान्ते 3.
186. 34; 3. 188. 35-37, 39, 49, 53, 73,
79; युगस्यान्ते 3. 188. 32; अल्पावशिष्टे तु
तदा युगान्ते 3. 186. 24; क्षीणे युगे 3. 186.
54; युगे क्षीणे 3. 188. 66; गते युगे 3. 188.
69; संप्राप्ते युगसंक्षये 3. 188. 55;
युगसंक्षये 3. 188. 62; युगक्षये 3. 186.
36, 43, 48; 3. 188. 6, 20-23, 25, 33, 41, 50-
51, 78, 85; पूर्वरूपं क्षयस्य तत् 3. 186.
28; तदा संक्षेप्स्यते युगम् 3. 188. 59,
67-68; पश्चिमे काले 3. 188. 52) the world
would be full of Mlecchas (म्लेच्छभूतं
जगत् सर्वं … ) 3. 188. 29, 45; (म्लेच्छी-
भूतं जगत् सर्वं … ) 3. 188. 37;
(मही म्लेच्छसमाकीर्णा भविष्यति) 3.
188. 70); the condition of the world
at the end of the aeon described in 3. 186.
24-57; 3. 188. 14-85; A Brāhmaṇa named
Kalki Viṣṇuyaśas would be born in the
Sambhala town; he would become a
sovereign king (राजा चक्रवर्ती), destroy
all the Mleccha hordes, and give a turn
to the Yuga (युगस्य परिवर्तकः। …
उत्सादयिष्यति तदा सर्वान् म्लेच्छगणान्
द्विजः॥) 3. 188. 89-93.
H. Certain kings
referred to with reference to just Mlecchas
or as their kings:
A. (i) म्लेच्छ;
A certain Aṅga prince (not named) 7. 25.
14, 17; (ii) A certain Aṅga prince (not
named) who was an आचार्यपुत्र 8. 17. 14,
17-18; (iii) A certain Vaṅga king (not
named) 8. 17. 9, 11;
B. (i) म्लेच्छानाम्
अधिप-: Bhagadatta 2. 47. 12; (ii) म्ले-
च्छगणाधिप-: Śālva 9. 19. 1.

यदु
Yadu, Yādava m. (pl.): Name of
a people, often identified with Vṛṣṇis so
that their accounts get mixed up; some-
times mentioned also along with Andhakas
and Bhojas.
A. Origin: Yādavas were born in
the line of Yadu, son of Yayāti (यदोस्
तु यादवा जाताः) 1. 80. 26; (यदुश् च …
यादवानां कुलकरो … ) 5. 147. 6-7; the
lineage of Yadus is traced back to Viva-
svant (पुत्रा विवस्वतः सर्वे … तेभ्यो
ऽयं कुरुवंशश् च यदूनां भरतस्य
च) 1. 1. 41, 44; Other accounts: (1)
Baladeva and Kṛṣṇa were born from the
two hair-one white and the other black-
plucked by Hari and which entered Rohiṇī
and Devakī of the lineage of Yadus;
(स चापि केशौ हरिर् उद्बबर्ह शुक्लम्
एकम् अपरं चापि कृष्णम्।तौ चापि
केशौ विशतां यदूनां कुले स्त्रियौ
रोहिणीं देवकीं च।तयोर् एको बलदेवो
बभूव कृष्णो द्वितीयः) 1. 189. 31;
(2) Nārāyaṇa was born on this earth
(as Kṛṣṇa) in the house of Yadus and
in the lineage of Andhakas and Vṛṣṇis
( … नारायणः … अजायत यदुक्षये।क्षिताव्-
अन्धकवृष्णीनां वंशे) 2. 33. 16-17
(Nī. on Bom. Ed. 2. 36. 16; यदुक्षये
यदुगृहे).
B. Glorification of the family
of Yadus and of their narrative: Kings born
in the lineage of Yadus were incarnations
of gods (इति देवासुराणां ते … अंशावतर-
णं राजन् … कीर्तितम्॥ … महात्मानो
यदूनां च ये जाता विपुले कुले) 1. 61.
99-100, also cf. 92; the narrative of the
family of Yādavas, as also of Pauravas
and Bhāratas, is holy, leads to well-being,
brings wealth, fame and long life (यादवा-
नाम् इमं वंशं … पुण्यं स्वस्त्यय-
नं महत्।धन्यं यशस्यम् आयुष्यं … )
1. 70. 2.
C. Description: Of unlimited
energy (अमितौजस्) 16. 9. 12; spirited, of
true valour, very strong; led by Kṛṣṇa, they
all were like Indra and got all enjoyments
(कृष्णप्रणीताः सर्व एवेन्द्रकल्पाः।
मनस्विनः सत्यपराक्रमाश् च।महा-
बला यादवा भोगवन्तः॥) 5. 28. 12 (Nī.
on Bom. Ed. 5. 28. 12; कृष्णप्रणीताः
कृष्णेनल्व नीतिपथं नीताः); their kings
were magnanimous (महात्मन्) 1. 61. 100.
D. Epic events: (1) Yādavas, Andhakas
and Bhojas had abandoned Kaṃsa in
the interest of the family; after he was
killed by Kṛṣṇa, all his kinsmen lived
happily for a hundred years (अन्धका
यादवा भोजाः समेताः कंसम् अत्यजन्। …
एवं ते ज्ञातयः सर्वे मोदमानाः शतं
समाः॥) 2. 55. 6-7; कंसम् एकं परि-
त्यज्य कुलार्थे सर्वयादवाः।संभूय
सुखम् एधन्ते … अन्धकवृष्णयः॥)
5. 126. 39; (2) Karṇa advised Duryo-
dhana to use force against Pāṇḍavas before
Kṛṣṇa came with the army of Yādavas to
help them (कर्षन् यादववाहिनीम्) 1. 194.
15; (3) The messenger sent by Yudhi-
ṣṭhira to Kṛṣṇa reached the country of
Yādavas and saw him in Dvārakā (प्राप्य
यादवान्) 2. 12. 29; (4) Kṛṣṇa spread
the fame and pride of Yādavas by killing
Śiśupāla (यशोमानौ वर्धयन् यादवा-
नाम्) 5. 22. 26; (5) Pradyumna assured
Yādavas that he would destroy the army
of Śālva with his arrows 3. 17. 31; 3. 18. 1;
(6) Sahadeva recalled that Arjuna had
defeated Yādavas who had gathered toge-
ther when he abducted Subhadrā; Arjuna
had then stayed with the Yadus 3. 79. 27;
(यदुसदनं) 8. 26. 63; (7) Bhīma
assured Yudhiṣṭhira that Kṛṣṇa with
Yādavas would help him to achieve his
purpose 3. 173. 16; (8) In the forest,
Draupadī and Satyabhāmā told each other
interesting stories of those who ruled Kurus
and Yadus (कथयाम् आसतुश् चित्राः कथाः
कुरुयदुक्षिताम्) 3. 222. 2 (Nī. on Bom.
Ed. 3. 233. 3 who reads कुरुयदूत्थिताः)
explains it as कुरुषु यदुषु च उत्-
पन्नाः); (9) Dhṛtarāṣṭra remembered
that the Māgadha king with the assis-
tance of Karṇa had checked all Kṣatriyas
except Kauravas and Yādavas (अरौत्सीत्
पार्थिवं क्षत्रम् ऋते कौरवयादयान्)
8. 5. 22; (10) Kuntī felt that nothing
would be more painful to her than
the fight between Pāṇḍavas, Cedis,
Pāñcālas and Yādavas with Bhāratas (i. e.
Kauravas) ( … यादवाश् च समागताः।
भारतैर् यदि योत्स्यन्ति किं नु दुःखम्
अतः परम्) 5. 142. 12; (11) From Upa-
plavya, Balarāma along with all Yādavas
set out for तीर्थयात्रा to Sarasvatī under
the constellation Maitra (मैत्रे नक्षत्र-
योगे स्म सहितः सर्वयादवैः) 9. 34.
12; (12) Kṛṣṇa told Gāndhārī that he
had already foreseen the destruction of
Yādavas brought about by mutual killings
(परस्परकृतं नाशम् अतः प्राप्स्यन्ति
यादवाः) 11. 25. 45; (13) Younger Yāda-
vas took hold of the sacrificial horse of
Yudhiṣṭhira and were taking him away
when Ugrasena stopped them (यादवानां
कुमारकाः) 14. 84. 14; (14) Bhīma and
the rest, as well as Kurus and Yādavas,
enjoyed listening the stories of Arjuna 14,
89. 11; (15) Yādavas and their wives
went to Prabhāsa taking with them ample
food and drink and lived there 16. 4.
9; there Sātyaki told Kṛtavarman that
Yādavas had not forgotten his killing those
who were asleep 16. 4. 9, 17; Kṛṣṇa
told Dāruka to go to Kurus and inform
Arjuna about the killings of Yadus; he
wanted Arjuna to come to Dvārakā hear-
ing the news of the death of Yādavas due
to the curse of Brāhmaṇas (पार्थाय शं-
सस्व वधं यदूनाम्) 16. 5. 2; (श्रुत्वा
मृतान् यादवान् ब्रह्मशापात्) 16. 5. 3; Kṛṣṇa
told Vasudeva that he was witness to
the destruction of Yadus and that he
would not be able to bear the sight of
the city (Dvārakā) of Yādavas when it
was devoid of Yadus (दृष्टं मयेदं
निधनं यदूनां … नाहं विना यदुभिर्
यादवानां पुरीम् इमां द्रष्टुम् इहाद्य
शक्तः) 16. 5. 8; he told Vasudeva that
Arjuna, when he knew the misfortune of
the Yadus, would definitely come to
Dvārakā (श्रुत्वा … यदूनाम् अनयं
महत्) 16. 7. 14; Arjuna told Vyāsa that
he remembered again and again the des-
truction of Yadus of unlimited energy and
of Kṛṣṇa (पुनः पुनर् न मृश्यामि विनाशम्
अमितौजसाम्।चिन्तयानो यदूनां च
कृष्णस्य च … ) 16. 9. 12 (the event of
Arjuna's seeing the great destruction of
Yadu heroes in a drinking bout is mention-
ed earlier in the summary of Mausala-
parvan in 1. 2. 224 (ददर्श यदुवीराणाम्
आपाने वैशसं महत्; Nī. on Bom. Ed. 1. 2.
355: आपाने सुरापानस्थाने); (16) When
Pāṇḍavas started on their Great Journey
(महाप्रस्थान) Yudhiṣṭhira made Vajra,
who survived the destruction of Yadus,
the king of Śakraprastha (Indraprastha)
(यदूनां परिशेषश् च वज्रो राजा कृतश् च
ह; … शक्रप्रस्थे तु यादवः) 17. 1. 8-9;
(17) When Aśvatthāman had once stayed
with Kṛṣṇa to get his discus (चक्र), he
was respected by all Yādavas 10. 12. 34.
E. Past event: When the sword was created
as a new weapon by Manu it was handed
down from generation to generation; at
one stage it was obtained from Uśīnara by
Bhojas and Yādavas, and Śibi obtained
it from Yadus (उशीनरो वै धर्मात्मा
तस्माद् भोजाः सयादवाः।यदुभ्यश्
च शिबिर् लेभे) 12. 160. 71, 78.
