यवन
Yavana m. (pl.): Name of a people.
A. Location: Listed by Saṃjaya among
the northern Mleccha tribes of Bhāratavarṣa
(उत्तराश् चापरे म्लेच्छा जना … ।यवनाश्
च सकाम्बोजा … म्लेच्छजातयः॥) 6. 10.
64, 5; lived in different parts: (1) the
north-west (5. 19. 21), (2) the east (2.
47. 12), (3) outside India in Greece (2.
28. 49).
B. Different origins: (1) Yavanas
were sons of Turvasu, the son of Yayāti
(तुर्वसोर् यवनाः सुताः) 1. 80. 26; (2)
Angered Nandinī, cow of Vasiṣṭha, created
Yavanas from her urine (मूत्रतश् चासृजच्
चापि यवनान् क्रोधमूर्छिता) 1. 165. 35;
(3) Originally Kṣatriyas, they became
degraded to the status of वृषल due to
their disregard of Brāhmaṇas (यवन-
काम्बोजास् तास् ताः क्षत्रियजातयः।वृषल-
त्वं परिगता ब्राह्मणानाम् अदर्शनात्॥)
13. 33. 19; 13. 35. 18.
C. Description and
characteristics: Rough (दारुण) 6. 10. 64;
fierce and doing cruel deeds (उग्र,
क्रूरकर्मन्) 8. 51. 18; very terrible and
having fearful eyes (सुघोर, घोरचक्षुस्)
7. 68. 41; especially brave (शूराश् चैव
विशेषतः) 8. 30. 80; expert in fighting
with fists (नियुद्धकुशल) 12. 102. 5 (Nī.
on Bom. Ed. 12. 101. 5: नियुद्धं बाहु-
युद्धम्; they knew everything correctly
(though not expressed in words) (सर्वज्ञ)
8. 30. 80; they knew the मायास् of Asuras
(विदन्त्य् असुरमायां ये) 7. 68. 41; they
are occasionally characterized as म्लेच्छस्
2. 47. 12; 3. 186. 29-30; 6. 10. 63-64; 7. 95.
12-13; although they lived in countries
they led the life of Dasyus (सर्वे विषय-
वासिनः। … सर्वे ते दस्युजीविनः) 12. 65. 15.
D. Epic events: (1) Mighty king Kampana
all alone always terrified Yavanas (सततं
कम्पयाम् आस यवनान् एक एव सः) 2. 4.
20; (2) Sahadeva, in his expedition to
the south (2. 28. 1; 2. 23. 9) subjugated
the town of Yavanas (possibly Alexan-
dria) by just sending messengers and
made them pay tribute (यवनानां पुरं
तथा।दूतैर् एव वशे चक्रे करं चैनान्
अदापयत्) 2. 28. 49 (cf. Edgerton's
note on the stanza, Cr. Edn. Vol. II,
p. 502); Yavanas, led by Bhagadatta,
attended the Rājasūya of Yudhiṣṭhira 2.
47. 12; kings of Yavanas acted as servants
at the Rājasūya sacrifice (यज्ञे ते परि-
वेषकान्) 3. 48. 18, 20, 22; (3) Sudakṣiṇa,
a Kāmboja, with an army of Yavanas and
Śakas, अक्षौहिणी strong, joined the side
of Duryodhana 5. 19. 21; at the instance
of Duryodhana, Yavanas and others
marched out of Hāstinapura towards
Kurukṣetra in the second division (द्वितीये
निर्ययुर् बले) 5. 196. 7-8; (4) Before
the start of the war Yavanas and others
led by Kṛpa stood guard in the north
for the Vyūha of the Kauravas (6. 20. 3)
(चमूम् उत्तरतो ऽभिपाति) 6. 20. 13; (5)
On the second day of the war, Yavanas
and others, led by Duḥśāsana, were to
protect Bhīṣma (भीष्मम् एवाभिरक्षन्तु)
6. 47. 7, 9; (6) On the sixth day, Yava-
nas were among those who were posted
at the right wing of the Krauñcavyūha (6.
71. 14) of the Kauravas (दक्षिणं पक्षम्
आश्रित्य स्थिता व्यूहस्य) 6. 71. 20; (7)
On the eighth day, Trigarta, accompanied
by thousands of Yavanas, followed Bṛhad-
bala in the Mahāvyūha (6. 83. 9) of
Kauravas 6. 83. 10; (8) On the eleventh
day, Yavanas and Śakas riding swift horses
guarded the extreme end (प्रपक्ष) of
the left wing of the Śakaṭavyūha (7. 6. 15)
of the Kauravas (सव्यं पार्श्वम् अपाल-
यन्) 7. 6. 4-5; that day, Dhṛtarāṣṭra, while
recounting Kṛṣṇa's past exploits, mention-
ed his victory over Yavanas and their
followers (यवनांश् च सहानुगान्) 7. 10.
18; (9) On the twelfth day, Yavanas
were posted at the neck (ग्रीवायाम्) of
the Suparṇavyūha (7. 19. 4) of the Kaura-
vas 7. 19. 7; (10) On the fourteenth day,
Arjuna killed hundreds of thousands of
Yavanas (शतसहस्रशः) 7. 68. 41, 43; on
that day, striking Yavanas holding bows
and arrows in their hands and wearing
armours, led by Duryodhana faced
Sātyaki to fight with him; but Sātyaki
was going to kill them all, foot-soldiers
and those driving in chariots or riding
elephants along with their horses and ele-
phants, and break their chariots, (यत्रैते
सतनुत्राणाः सुयोधनपुरोगमाः। …
शरबाणासनधरा यवनाश् च प्रहारिणः)
7. 95. 11-14; when Sātyaki reached the
Yavanas, many of them, quick in action
(लघुहस्ताश् च) showered arrows on
him; Sātyaki cut off their arrows and
missiles; he also cut off their arms and
heads; his arrows pierced through their
steel armours (शैक्यायसानि वर्माणि)
and went through their bodies; dead,
they fell down on the ground by hundreds
7. 95. 31-36; Sātyaki killed five, six,
seven or even eight (पञ्च षट् सप्त
चाष्टौ च) of them at a time with his
arrows 7. 95. 37; thus Sātyaki routed
(विद्राव्य) the large army of Yavanas and
proceeded towards Arjuna 7. 95. 45; 7. 96.
1; at the instance of Duryodhana and led
by him Yavanas returned to fight once
again with Sātyaki and attacked him (ते
पुनः संन्यवर्तन्त … ।परां युद्धे
मतिं कृत्वा पुत्रस्य तव शासनात्॥) 7.
97. 12-14; (10) On the seventeenth day
Yavanas, in chariots and on horse-backs
and their footsoldiers, stood at the extreme
end of left side of the Bārhaspatyavyūha
(8. 31. 26) of Kauravas and, as directed
by Karṇa, challenged Arjuna and Kṛṣṇa
(वामं पार्श्वम् अपालयन्। … तेषां प्रप-
क्षः … शकाश् च यवनैः सह॥निदेशात्
सूतपुत्रस्य सरथाः साश्वपत्तयः।आह्व-
यन्तो ऽर्जुनं तस्थुः केशवं च … ॥) 8.
31. 14-16; at the instance of Śakuni, three
thousand Yavanas, honoured by the brave,
holding शक्तिस्, ऋष्टिस्, and प्रासस् in their
hands attacked Bhīma; when beaten and
slashed by Bhīma with sword, they raised
a loud roar (ताडितानां च सर्वशः।
असिभिश् छिद्यमानानाम्) 8. 35. 37; Arjuna
attacked the extreme end (of the left side
of) the व्यूह (8. 40. 99-100, 110) and
fought with Kāmbojas, Yavanas and Śakas
who rode horses; they were all smeared
with blood (यवनैः … ।शोनिताक्तैस् तदा
रक्तं सर्वम् आसीद् … ) 8. 40. 108; Kṛṣṇa
told Arjuna that no one else but he
(Arjuna) could conquer Yavanas and others
who had joined hands with Kauravas for
the sake of Duryodhana (एते दुर्योधन-
स्यार्थे संरब्धाः कुरुभिः सह।न
शक्या युधि निर्जेतुं त्वदन्येन परं-
तप॥) 8. 51. 18, 20; Yavanas riding horses
attacked Arjuna to kill him; Arjuna cut
off their arms, holding excellent weapons,
and their heads with क्षुर arrows (यव-
नाश् च सादिनः। … क्षुरैर् न्यकृन्तंस्
त्वरिताः शिरांसि च) 8. 64. 16-17; (11)
On the eighteenth day, Kṛpa accompanied
by Śakas and Yavanas stood on the right
side (दक्षिणे पार्श्वे) of the Sarvato-
bhadravyūha (9. 7. 19) of Kauravas 9. 7.
24; (12) On the nineteenth day, in the
morning (पूर्वाह्णसमये 9. 1. 14), Saṃ-
jaya returned from the camp and while
reporting to Dhṛtarāṣṭra about the war
mentioned that all Yavanas were killed 9.
1. 26; hearing that, Dhṛtarāṣṭra remem-
bered that Yavanas were ready to fight
for him unmindful of their death (मदर्-
थम् उद्यताः सर्वे प्राणांस् त्यक्त्वा
रणे … ) 9. 2. 18. 21.
E. Past event:
King Māndhātṛ once asked Indra the
धर्म of people like Yavanas and how
they should be controlled by kings like
him (कथं धर्मं चरेयुस् ते … मद्-
विधैश् च कथं स्थाप्याः) 12. 65. 13, 15;
Indra thereupon told him the duties of all
Dasyus (the term included Yavanas) 12.
65. 17-22.
F. Future event: Yavanas
listed among the Mleccha kings who in
the Kali age would rule the earth the
wrong way, would be sinful, and given to
telling lies (कलौ युगे … बहवो म्लेच्छ-
राजानः प्रिथिव्यां … मिथ्यानुशासिनः
पापा मृषावादपरायणाः॥ … यवनाश् च
नराधिपाः) 3. 186. 27, 29-30.
G. Some
kings characterized simply as Yavana or as
king of Yavanas: (1) यवन: Kaśerumant
3. 13. 29; (2) यवनाधिप: Naraka and
Mura 2. 13. 13; (3) यवनाधिपति: Not
named 2. 4. 22. [See Mleccha]

यादव
Yādava: See Yadu.

यायावर
Yāyāvara m. (pl.): Name of a group
(गण) of ऋषिस्।
A. Qualities: Of strict vows (सं-
शितव्रत) 1. 13. 14; 1. 41. 16; they practised
severe austerities and were expert knowers
of धर्म for they were the direct seers
of धर्म, hence characterized as ऋषिस्
( … प्रत्यक्सधर्माणस् तथा यायावरा
गणाः।ऋषीणाम् उग्रतपसाम् धर्म-
नैपुणदर्शिनाम्॥) 12. 236 19 (Nī.
on Bom. Ed. 12. 244. 19: प्रत्यक्षः
धर्मो धर्मफलं सत्यसङ्कल्पत्वा-
दिकं येषां ते प्रत्यक्षधर्माणः).
B. Their history: (1) Yāyāvaras were the
forefathers of Jaratkāru; he once saw
them hanging with their heads down and
holding on to a bunch of grass; a mouse
residing in a hole was slowly eating up
that bunch of grass; Jaratkāru addressed
them; he pitied their plight for they were
without food, were lean, pitiable, affli-
cted and waiting for help; he showed his
readiness to help them by offering them
the fourth, the third, the half, of his
austerities, or even all of them; Yāyāvaras
told him that they were falling down in
the impure hell because of the non-
continuation of their line (संतान-
प्रक्षय); his austerities would not
help them; they told him they were sages
known as Yāyāvaras, they had fallen
down from the holy world due to the
discontinuation of their line (संतान-
प्रक्षय); their austerities had come to an
end; there was no one to continue their line;
the only one, named Jaratkāru, was as good
as nothing for this purpose; he was versed
in the Vedas but had not married and had
no progeny; hence they were hanging head
down in the ditch; if ever the person to
whom they were addressing met Jaratkāru
he should tell him their plight, ask him to
marry and beget progeny; the bunch of
grass to which they were clinging was
their only support; if they fell down along
with their ancestors, Jaratkāru too would
fall down into the hell; neither austerities,
nor sacrifices, nor any thing else was equal
to a child 1. 41. 3-30; 1. 13. 10-30; Jarat-
kāru then disclosed his identity to Yāyā-
varas and asked them to punish him; they
told him that fortunately he had come
there and asked him the reason of his not
marrying; Jaratkāru told them that by ob-
serving celibacy he wanted to take his body
to the next world (ऊर्ध्वरेताः शरीरं वै
प्रापयेयम् अमुत्र वै); however now that
he had seen their plight he had decided to
marry provided he found a maiden having
his name and also if he was not required to
support her (सनाम्नीं यद्य् अहं कन्याम्
उपलप्स्ये कदाचन … न भरेयं च
याम् अहम्); Jaratkāru did not get a
maiden since he was old; dejected he went
to the forest and addressed all beings,
moving and not moving, and even those
concealed, telling them that Yāyāvaras had
asked him to marry and so he requested
them to give him a maiden who bore his
name and whom he was not required to
support 1. 42. 1-15; when Jaratkāru's
conditions were fulfilled, he married; when
Āstīka was born, he saved Yāyāvaras and
took off great burden of his ancestors;
Jaratkāru went to heaven, along with his
ancestors (पितॄंश् च तारयाम् आस संतत्या
तपसा तथा। … अपहृत्य गुरुं भारम्
पितॄणां … ।जरत्कारुर् गतः स्वर्गं
सहितः स्वैः पितामहैः॥) 1. 13. 41-46;
(2) Yāyāvaras mentioned among those
who, after retiring to forest (during the
वानप्रस्थाश्रम 12. 236. 4-5), went to
heaven 12. 236. 18-19.
C. Certain persons
referred to in relation to Yāyāvaras;
(1) Born in the family of Yāyāvaras;
Āstīka (यायावरकुलोत्पन्न) 15. 43. 10;
Jaratkāru (यायावरकुले … भविष्यति) 1.
34. 12; (2) Prominent among Yāyāvaras:
Jaratkāru (यायावराणां … प्रवरः) 1.
13. 10.

युगन्धर
Yugandhara m. (pl.): Name of a
Janapada.
A. Location: Saṃjaya listed Yugan-
dhara among the northern Janapadas
(also called Deśas 6. 10. 68) of Bhārata-
varṣa (अत ऊर्ध्वं जनपदान् निबोध)
6. 10. 37, 5; (शाल्वा युगन्धराः) 4. 1. 9;
also called Rāṣṭra 4. 1. 8; it lay around
the Kuru country (परितः कुरून्) 4. 1. 9.
B. Description: Pleasing (रम्य) 4. 1. 9;
(रमणिय) 4. 1. 8; protected (गुप्त) 4. 1.
8; having ample food (बह्वन्न) 4. 1. 9.
C. Epic event: Arjuna suggested Yugan-
dhara to Yudhiṣṭhira among those countries
(Rāṣṭras or Janapadas) where Pāṇḍavas
could stay during their अज्ञातवास (किं तु
वासाय राष्ट्राणि कीर्तयिष्यामि कानिचित्।
 … सन्ति रम्या जनपदा … मल्लाः शाल्वा
युगन्धराः) 4. 1. 8-9.

यौधेय
Yaudheya m. (pl.): Name of a people.
A. Description: Heroic (शूर) 7. 132.
25.
B. Epic events: (1) Their Kṣatriya
kings (राजन्याः 2. 48. 13; क्षत्रियाः 2. 48.
16) brought wealth by hundreds (आहार्षुः
क्षत्रिया वित्तं शतशो … ) for the Rāja-
sūya of Yudhiṣṭhira 2. 48. 13, 16; (2)
On the eleventh day of war, Arjuna affli-
cted Yaudheya Kṣatriyas with arrows; but
even though they were being killed by
Arjuna they showered different kinds of
arrows on Arjuna so that Arjuna, his
chariot, and Kṛṣṇa became invisible as
they were concealed by arrows; feeling
that they had hit the target and Arjuna
and Kṛṣṇa were killed, Yaudheyas and
others roared, waived their upper garments
and blew भेरिस्, horns and conches;
Arjuna removed the screen of arrows by
employing वायव्यास्त्र 7. 18. 16-22; (3)
In the night war, Yudhiṣṭhira killed hordes
of Yaudheyas and others; at that time the
Yaudheya warriors shouted in confusion
“kill him, bring him, capture him,” or
“pierce him, cut him” (हताहरत गृह्णीत
विध्यत व्यवकृन्तत।इत्य् आसित् तुमुलः
शब्दो युधिष्ठिररथं प्रति॥) 7. 132.
25-26; Arjuna too killed many Yaudheyas
with arrows 7. 136. 5; (4) On the seven-
teenth day, at night, when Dhṛtarāṣṭra
asked Saṃjaya who in the army of Kaura-
vas were dead and who were alive (8. 4. 3),
Saṃjaya mentioned Yaudheyas among
those who were killed by Arjuna 8. 4. 46.

यौन
Yauna m. (pl.): Name of a people.
A. Location: They, along with Kām-
bojas, Gāndhāras and others belonged to
the Uttarāpatha (उत्तरापथजन्मानः)
12. 200. 40.
B. Description: Sinful
(पापकृत्); they roamed over the earth
living like dogs, crows, बलस् and vultures;
they did not exist in the Kṛta age but
were to be found since the Tretā age; they
did not believe in Bhūtapati being the
superintendent of the people (एष भूत-
पतिस् तात स्वध्यक्षश् च प्रकीर्तितः।
निरध्यक्षांस् तु कौन्तेय कीर्तयिष्यामि
तान् अपि॥; यौनकाम्बोजगान्धाराः … ॥)
12. 200. 38, 40; (for other citations see
Uttarāpatha); according to Bhīṣma all
this information was declared by Nārada
(देवदेवर्षिर् आचष्ट नारदः) 12. 200. 44.

रथाकार
Rathākāra nt (sg.): Name of a Varṣa
of the Kuśadvīpa in the north.
A. Location: To the north of the
Jambudvīpa (उत्तरेषु तु कौरव्य द्वीपेषु)
6. 13. 1; listed third in the collection of
the Varṣas of the Kuśadvīpa (तृतीयं
वै रथाकारं … सप्तैते वर्षपुञ्जकाः)
6. 13. 12-13.
B. Characteristic: For
the characteristic which is common to
all the Varṣas see Audbhida.

रथोरग
Rathoraga m. (pl.): Name of a
people (?)
Listed by Saṃjaya among the northern
Janapadas (also called Deśas 6. 10. 68) of
Bhāratavarṣa (अत ऊर्ध्वं जनपदान्
निबोध) 6. 10. 37, 5; (वातजामरथो-
रगाः) 6. 10. 53 (It is not clear how the
compound is to be understood). [See
Uraga, Vātajāma]

रमठ
Ramaṭha m. (pl.): Name of a people.
A. Location: To the west of the
Khāṇḍavaprastha (see Epic event No. 1
below).
B. Description: Fierce (उग्र)
and doing cruel deeds (क्रूरकर्मन्) 8. 51.
18; they lived in countries but behaved
like Dasyus (सर्वे विषयवासिनः। …
सर्वे ते दस्युजीविनः) 12. 65. 15.
C.
Epic events: (1) Nakula in his expedition
to the west before the Rājasūya (निर्याय
खाण्डवप्रस्थात् प्रतीचीम् अभितो दिशम्
2. 29. 2; 2. 23. 10) subjugated Ramaṭhas
(रमठान् … वशे चक्रे) 2. 29. 11: they
attended the Rājasūya and acted as ser-
vants in the sacrifice (यज्ञे ते परिवेष-
कान्) 3. 48. 21-22; (2) Mentioned by
Kṛṣṇa among those who had joined the
Kuru army for the sake of Duryodhana;
on one except Arjuna could defeat them
(रमठतङ्गणाः।एते सुयोधनस्यार्थे
संरब्धाः कुरुभिः सह।न शक्या युधि
निर्जेतुम् त्वदन्येन परंतप॥) 8. 51.
18, 20.
D. Past event: King Māndhātṛ
once asked Indra how people like Rama-
ṭhas could be made to follow धर्म and
how they could be controlled by kings
like him (कथं धर्मं चरेयुस् ते … ।
मद्विधैश् च कथं स्थाप्याः) 12. 65.
15; Indra thereupon narrated to Māndhātṛ
the duties of Dasyus 12. 65. 17-22.

रमणक
Ramaṇaka nt. (sg.): Name of a
Varṣa of the Jambudvīpa.
A. Location: It lay to the south of
the Śveta mountain and to the north of the
Nīla mountain 6. 9. 2.
B. Description of
the people: They were fair and born in the
noble family, very pleasing to look at and
given to pleasures (of love ?): their minds
were always cheerful and they lived for ten
thousand and fifteen hundred years (शुक्ला-
भिजनसंपन्नाः सर्वे सुप्रियदर्शनाः।
रतिप्रधानाश् च तथा जायन्ते तत्र मान-
वाः॥दश वर्षसहस्राणि शतानि दश
पञ्च च।जीवन्ति ते महाराज नित्यं
मुदितमानसाः॥) 6. 9. 3-4.

रमणीयक
Ramaṇīyaka nt. (sg.): Name of an
island.
A. Location: Situated in an isolated
place in the bay of an ocean (समुद्र-
कुक्षाव् एकान्ते) 1. 21. 4; (सागराम्बु-
परीक्षिप्तम्) 1. 23. 1.
B. Characteristic:
It was the place where Nāgas lived (नागा-
नाम् आलयं) 1. 21. 4.
C. Description:
very beautiful (सुरम्य) 1. 21. 4; made
resonant by a large number of birds (पक्षि-
संघनिनादित); a forest in Ramaṇīyaka
was delightful to mind, holy and loved by
Gandharvas and Apsarases; it was pleasing
because it was full of sounds made by
different kinds of birds (मनःसंहर्ष-
णं पुण्यं गन्धर्वाप्सरसां प्रियम्।
नानापक्षिरुतं रम्यं … ॥) 1. 23. 5;
for the detailed description of the forest-
its trees, mansions (भवनैर् आवृतं),
lakes, breezes, and flowers see 1. 23. 2-5 ab.
D. Past event: As asked by Kadrū, Vinatā
took her, and Garuḍa the serpents to the
island Ramaṇīyaka; on reaching the forest
on the island the serpents merrily spent
their time there (1. 21. 4-5; 1. 23. 6).

रम्यकागण
Ramyakāgaṇa m. (pl.): Name of a
Janapada.
Listed by Saṃjaya among the northern
Janapadas (also called Deśas 6. 10. 68)
of Bhāratavarṣa (अत ऊर्ध्वं जनपदान्
निबोध) 6. 10. 37, 5; (राजिका रम्यका-
गणाः) 6. 10. 51.

राजिक
Rājika m. (pl.): Name of a Janapada.
Listed by Saṃjaya among the northern
Janapadas (also called Deśas) of Bhārata-
varṣa; (राजिका रम्यकागणाः) (for cita-
tions and references see the preceding
entry Ramyakāgaṇa).

रोमन्
Roman m. (pl.): Name of a Janapada.
Listed by Saṃjaya among the northern
Janapadas (also called Deśas 6. 10. 68)
of Bhāratavarṣa (अत ऊर्ध्वं जनपदान्
निबोध) 6. 10. 37, 5; (रोमाणः कुश-
बिन्दवः) 6. 10. 54; (for other references
see Ramyakāgaṇa). [On the resemblance
of the name, probably accidental, with
Romans (inhabitants of Rome) see the
Editor's note on this stanza in the Critical
edition Vol. VII. p. 763. 2].

रोमश
Romaśa m. (pl.): Name of a people.
Mentioned by Duryodhana along with
Śakas, Tukhāras and others who brought
as tribute for the Rājasūya an अर्बुद
of horses of high breed and going long
distances and also a पद्म of gold to
be counted by crores; even then they
were stopped at the gate and were not
allowed to enter ( … रोमशाः … ।महाग-
मान् दूरगमान् गणितान् अर्बुदं हयान्॥
कोटिशश् चैव बहुशः सुवर्णं पद्म-
संमितम्।बलिम् आदाय विविधं द्वारि
तिष्ठन्ति वारिताः॥) 2. 47. 26-27 (Are these
Romans ? See Romā Cul. Ind. Vol. II.
p. 559 and Roman above).

रौद्र
Raudra m. (pl.): Name of a people (?)
A. Location: Near the southern ocean
(see the Epic event).
B. Epic event:
When Arjuna, accompanying the Aśva-
medha horse, reached the southern ocean he
had to fight with Raudras and Māhiṣakas
along with others (प्रययौ भूयो दक्षि-
णं सलिलार्णवम्॥तत्रापि … रौद्रैर्
माहिषकैर् अपि। … युद्धम् आसीत् किरीटि-
नः॥) 14. 84. 10-11 (Is Raudra a proper
name, or does it mean ‘fierce’ and qualify
Māhiṣakas ?).

लडक
Laḍaka m. (pl.): Name of a Jana-
pada and its people.
On the second day of war, Laḍakas,
along with Piśācas and other peoples, were
stationed at the right wing of the Krauñ-
cāruṇavyūha (6. 46. 39; Krauñca 6. 47. 1)
of the Pāṇḍavas (मडका लडकाश् चैव
 … एते जनपदा राजन् दक्षिणं पक्षम्
आश्रिताः॥) 6. 46. 49-50.

ललाटाक्ष
Lalāṭākṣa m. (pl.): Name of a
people.
They came from different parts and
gave tribute for the Rājasūya of Yudhiṣṭhira
large quantity of gold and silver, but were
stopped at the gate (ललाटाक्षान् नानादिग्-
भ्यः समागतान्। … द्वारि तिष्ठन्ति वारि-
तान्।बल्यर्थं ददतस् तस्मै हिरण्यं
रजतं बहु॥) 2. 47. 15-16.

ललित्थ
Lalittha m. (pl.): Name of a people.
A. Description: Honoured by heroes
(शूरसंमत) 7. 66. 39; of firm determi-
nation (दृढनिश्चय) 7. 16. 27.
B. Epic
events: (1) On the eleventh day of the
war, at night, Lalitthas were among those
who, led by Suśarman and his five bro-
thers, vowed to kill Arjuna the next day;
the mode of the oath in the presence of the
fire in which offerings were given (ज्वल-
नम् आदाय हुत्वा सर्वे पृथक् पृथक् 7. 16.
22; तस्मिन्न् अगनौ तदा चक्रुः प्रतिज्ञां
दृढनिश्चयाः 7. 16. 27) and invoking
severe penalty in case of failure to carry out
the vow is described in 7. 16. 22-36; (2)
On twelfth day, Arjuna afflicted Lahtthas
with arrows; though getting killed, they
continued to shower arrows of different
kinds on Arjuna; as a result, both Arjuna
and Kṛṣṇa could not be seen due to the
shower of arrows; Lalitthas felt that they
had hit the target and therefore they raised
loud roar looking at each other; consider-
ing that Arjuna and Kṛṣṇa were killed
they joyfully waived their upper garments
and sounded भेरिस्, मृदङ्गस् and conches
in thousands (ततस् ते लब्धलक्ष्यत्वाद्
अन्योन्यम् अभिचुक्रुशुः।हतौ कृष्णाव् इति
प्रीता वासांस्य् आदुधुवुस् तदा। … सिंह-
नादरवांश् चोग्रांश् चक्रिरे) 7. 18. 17-20;
(3) On the fourteenth day, Lalitthas led
by Jaya, Kṛtavarman and Droṇa tried to
check the advance of Arjuna towards Jaya-
dratha 7. 66. 38-43; in this context, Saṃjaya
referred to Karṇa's former victory over
Lalitthas in battle (कर्णेन विजिताः पूर्वं
संग्रामे) 7. 66. 39 (reference to Karṇa's
दिग्विजय before Duryodhana's Vaiṣṇava-
yajña 3. 241. 29, 32; 3. App. I. 24. 28-34);
(4) After the death of Karṇa, Saṃjaya
while reporting to Dhṛtarāṣṭra mentioned
Lalitthas among those who were killed by
Arjuna in the war 8. 4. 46, 50.

लाङ्गल
Lāṅgala m. (pl.): Name of a Jana-
pada.
Listed by Saṃjaya among the northern
Janapadas (also called Deśas 6. 10. 68)
of Bhāratavarṣa (अत ऊर्ध्वं जनपदान्
निबोध) 6. 10. 37, 5; (लाङ्गलाः परवल्ल-
काः) 6. 10. 55.

लोह
Loha m. (pl.): Name of a people.
Conquered by Arjuna in his expedition
to the north (दिशं धनपतेर् इष्टाम् 2. 23.
9; 2. 24. 1) before the Rājasūya of Yudhi-
ṣṭhira (लोहान् … व्यजयत् पाकशासनिः) 2.
24. 24.

लोहजङ्घ
Lohajaṅgha m. (pl.): Name of a
people.
Mentioned by Duryodhana among
those who at the time of Rājasūya, lying
low, acted as dependents in the household
of Yudhiṣṭhira (आवर्जिता इवाभान्ति निघ्नाश्
 … ।कारस्करा लोहजङ्घा … ) 2. 46. 21
[Nī. on Bom. Ed. 2. 50. 20: आवर्जिताः
दासवद् वशगाः].

वक्र
Vakra m. (pl.): Name of a Janapada.
Listed by Saṃjaya among the northern
Janapadas (also called Deśas 6. 10. 68) of
Bhāratavarṣa (अत ऊर्ध्वं जनपदान्
निबोध) 6. 10. 37, 5; (वक्रा वक्रभयाः)
6. 10. 43.

वक्रभय
Vakrabhaya m. (pl.): Name of a
Janapada.
Listed by Saṃjaya among the northern
Janapadas (also called Deśas 6. 10. 68) of
Bhāratavarṣa (वक्रा वक्रभयाः) 6. 10.
43 (For other references see Vakra).

वङ्ग
Vaṅga m. (pl.): Name of a Janapada
and its people; the country is also referred
to as Viṣaya (2. 41. 9); sometimes Vaṅga is
mentioned along with Aṅga and Kaliṅga.
A. Location: (1) Listed by Saṃjaya
among the northern Janapadas (also called
Deśas 6. 10. 68) of Bhāratavarṣa (अत ऊर्ध्-
वं जनपदान् निबोध) 6. 10. 37. 5; (अङ्गा
वङ्गाः कलिङ्गाश् च) 6. 10. 44; (2) In the
east 1. 207. 5 (see Epic events No. 2 below);
(3) Vaṅga people said to be born on the bays
of ocean and along the rivers (समुद्र-
निष्कुटे जाताः परिसिन्धु च मानवाः) 2. 47.
9 (Nī. however, on Bom. Ed. 2. 51. 11:
समुद्रसमीपस्थनिष्कुटे गृहोद्याने); the
Aśvamedha horse of Yudhiṣṭhira went from
Magadha, along the (eastern) sea coast,
to Vaṅga, Puṇḍra and Kerala countries.
B. Description and characteristics: Diffi-
cult to be conquered (दुर्जय) 8. 5. 18;
their warriors fought while riding elephants
(गजयोधिन् 6. 87. 14; 8. 17. 2; गज-
युद्धेषु कुशलाः 8. 17. 3; also see Epic
events No. 4, 9, and 10 below); they lived
on crops produced in forest without plough-
ing by rain water or produced by river
water (इन्द्रकृष्टैर् वर्तयन्ति धान्यैर्
नदीमुखैश् च ये) 2. 47. 9 (Nī. on Bom.
Ed. 2. 51. 11; इन्द्रकृष्टैः इन्द्रेणैवा-
कृष्टैः न तु कर्षणादिक्षेत्रियकयत्ना-
पेक्षैः वनधान्यैः वृष्ट्यभावे तु नदी-
मुखैः नदीप्रभवैः).
C. Epic events;
(1) Caturyu (?) Bhoja, king of Vaṅgas,
Puṇḍras and Kirātas was known to the
worlds as Pauṇḍraka Vāsudeva 2. 13. 19-20;
(2) Arjuna during the period of his exile,
visited all the तीर्थस् in Aṅga, Vaṅga and
Kaliṅga countries in the east (प्राचीम्
दिशम् अभिप्रेप्सुः) 1. 207. 5, 9; (3)
Vaṅgas brought tribute in the form of
various jewels, goats, sheep, cows, gold,
donkeys, camels, various kinds of blankets
and wine produced from fruits (फलजं
मधु) for the Rājasūya; but they were
stopped at the gate 2. 47. 10-11 (Nī. on
Bom. Ed. 2. 51. 13: फलजं मधूकादि-
जातीयम्); their Kṣatriyas brought wealth in
hundreds for Yudhiṣṭhira (आहार्षुः क्षत्रिया
वित्तं शतशो ऽजातशत्रवे) 2. 48. 15; they
brought fine cloth, silk, silk (or cotton ?)
garments, पत्रोर्ण and covers (दुकूलं
कौशिकं चैव पत्रोर्णं प्रावरान् अपि)
2. 48. 17 (Nī. on 2. 51. 3: और्णान् मेष-
रोमजान्); when asked to give more to
get entrance, each one gave one thousand
elephants 2. 48. 18, 20 (description of
elephants 19-20); the king of Vaṅgas was
among those who, subdued by the fear of
the lustre of Pāṇḍavas' weapons, acted as
servants in the sacrifice (यज्ञे ते परिवेष-
कान्) 3. 48. 18, 22; (4) On the eighth day
of war, when Duryodhana attacked Ghaṭo-
tkaca he was followed by the king of
Vaṅgas with ten thousand elephant-fighters
(गजयोधिनः); the war between the
Rākṣasas of Ghaṭotkaca and the elephant-
fighters from Vaṅgas described in 6.
87. 10, 13-14; (5) During Saṃjaya's
report after the death of Droṇa, Dhṛta-
rāṣṭra, at one stage, while recounting
Kṛṣṇa's past exploits, mentioned his victory
over Vaṅgas 7. 10. 15; (6) On the
twelfth day, Dhṛtarāṣṭra mentioned Vaṅgas
among those who had joined the army of
Kauravas 7. 23. 7; (7) In the night
war (between the 14th and the 15th day),
Yudhiṣṭhira killed many Vaṅgas 7. 136. 3;
(8) When Karṇa's death was reported to
Dhṛṭarāṣṭra, he remembered that Karṇa
had once defeated Vaṅgas in battle and
made them pay tribute (यो जित्वा समरे
वीरश् चक्रे बलिभृतः पुरा) 8. 5. 19-20
(reference to Karṇa's Digvijaya before
the Vaiṣṇavayajña of Duryodhana 3. 241.
29-32; 3. App. I. 24. 42); (9) On the
sixteenth day, Vaṅgas and others riding
elephants, who were like the elephants of
Indra, rushed at Arjuna to kill him; Arjuna
cut off the armours, the vitals and trunks
of the elephants and also their controllers
(अथ द्विपैर् देवपतिद्विपाभैर् … कलिङ्ग-
वङ्ग° … ।तेषां द्विपानां विचकर्त
पार्थो वर्माणि मर्माणि करान् नियन्तॄन्)
8. 12. 59-60; on the same day, incited by
Duryodhana, Vaṅgas and others, riding
elephants, attacked Dhṛṣṭadyumna to kill
him; they showered arrows, तोमरस्,
नाराच arrows on him 8. 17. 2-3; other
Pāṇḍava heroes joined the battle; the
battle described in 8. 17. 5 ff.; Sātyaki killed
the king of Vaṅgas and his elephant 8. 17.
11; (10) On the seventeenth day, Arjuna
told Yudhiṣṭhira that Bhīma alone who had
killed Kaliṅgas, Vaṅgas and Aṅgas as also
their elephants had the right to blame him
8. 49. 79; (11) The sacrificial horse of
the Aśvamedha went from Magadha, along
the seacoast, to Vaṅga, Puṇḍra and Kerala
countries; Arjuna conquered there many
Mlecchas 14. 83. 29-30.
D. Some per-
sons referred to as the chief or the king
of Vaṅgas: (1) Karṇa called वङ्गाङ्ग-
विषयाध्यक्ष 2. 41. 9; (2) A king, not
named, referred to as king of Vaṅgas:
(i) वङ्गराज 2. 27. 21; (ii) राज्ञा वङ्गेन
6. 88. 8; (iii) वङ्गानाम् अधिपः 6. 88. 6;
(iv) वङ्गानाम् ईश्वरः 6. 88. 10.

वत्स
Vatsa m. (pl.), Vatsabhūmi f. (sg.):
Name of a country and its people.
A. Location: In the east, somewhat
to the north (see Epic event No. 1 below).
B. Description (1) of its warriors: Deter-
mined to win victory they were prepared
to give away their lives (त्यक्तात्मानो जये
धृताः) 5. 52. 1; valorous (पराक्रान्त)
5. 52. 2; (2) of their capital town:
pleasing (रम्या) 13. 31. 12; the country
was visited by Siddhas and Cāraṇas
(सिद्धचारणसेविता) and was the resort of
holy and magnanimous ascetics (आश्रमं
पुण्यशीलानां तापसानां मनस्विनाम्) 5.
187. 23.
C. Epic events: (1) Bhīma in
his expedition before the Rājasūya first went
to the east (ययौ प्राचीं दिशं प्रति 2.
26. 1; 2. 23. 9), and then to the north, and
conquered with force the land of the Vatsas
(प्रययाव् उत्तरामुखः।वत्सभूमिं च
कौन्तेयो विजिग्ये बलवान् बलात्॥) 2. 27. 9;
(2) Dhṛtarāṣṭra reminded Saṃjaya that
he had mentioned the kings of Vatsabhūmi
among the allies of Pāṇḍavas (अभिसरास्
तेषाम् … त्वम् एव हि … आचक्षीथाः … वत्स-
भूमिपान्) 5. 52. 1-2; (3) After practis-
ing severe austerites on the river Yamunā,
Ambā went to Vatsabhūmi; she bathed
there day and night in the holy places;
after visiting many तीर्थस् she returned
to Vatsabhūmi where a half of her body
became the river called Ambā; the river
had water once a year, it was full of
crocodiles and was difficult to cross 5.
187. 18-24; 34-35; 38-40; (4) On the
second day of war, led by Nakula and
Sahadeva, Vatsas and Nākulas were among
those who stood at the left wing of the
Krauñcāruṇavyūha (6. 46. 39; Krauñca
6. 47. 1) of Pāṇḍavas (वत्साश् च सह
नाकुलैः।नकुलः सहदेवश् च वामं
पार्श्वं समाश्रिताः) 6. 46. 51; (5) On
the eleventh day, Dhṛtarāṣṭra while re-
counting Kṛṣṇa's past exploits mentioned
his victory over Vatsas 7. 10. 15; (6) On
the sixteenth day, Dhṛtarāṣṭra remembered
that Karṇa had formerly won victory over
Vatsas and forced them to pay tribute
(वत्सान् … यो जित्वा समरे वीरश् चक्रे
बलिभृतः पुरा) 8. 5. 20 (reference to
Karṇa's conquest of the earth before the
Vaiṣnavayajña of Duryodhana 3. 241. 29,
32; 3. App. I. 24. 45-46.
D. Past event:
Hehaya and Tālajaṅgha, born in the line
of Śaryāti, once ruled over Vatsas; Heha-
yas killed in battle Haryaśva, king of Kāśi,
and returned to the (capital) town of
Vatsas (हेहयास् … ।प्रतिजग्मुः पुरीं
रम्यां वत्सानाम् … ॥) 13. 31. 7, 12.
E.
Yayāti referred to as king of Vatsas and
Kāśīs (वत्सकाशीशः) 5. 113. 2; certain
kings, not named, referred to as वत्स-
भूमिप- 5. 52. 2.

वत्सभूमि
Vatsabhūmi: See Vatsa.

वध्र
Vadhra m. (pl.): Name of a Janapada.
Listed by Saṃjaya among the northern
Janapadas (also called Deśas 6. 10. 68) of
Bhāratavarṣa (अत ऊर्ध्वं जनपदान्
निबोध) 6. 10. 37, 5; (वध्राः करीषकाश्
चापि) 6. 10. 54.

वनवासिन्
Vanavāsin m. (pl.): Name of a Jana-
pada.
Listed by Saṃjaya among the sou-
thern Janapadas (also called Deśas 6. 10.
68) of Bhāratavarṣa (अथापरे जनपदा
दक्षिणा भरतर्षभ) 6. 10. 56, 5; भूषिका
वनवासिनः 6. 10. 57.

वर्मक
Varmaka m. (pl.): Name of a people.
Bhīma in his expedition to the east
(ययौ प्राचीं दिषं प्रति 2. 26. 1; 2. 23.
9) before the Rājasūya won over Varmakas
through peaceful means (वर्मकांश् चैव
सान्त्वेनैवाजयत् प्रभुः) 2. 27. 12.

वसाति
Vasāti, Vasātika, Vasātīya m. (pl.):
Name of a Janapada (6. 18. 12, 14; 6. 114.
76-77) and its people; some of them desig-
nated as Brahmavasātīya (7. 48. 8).
A. Description: Their warriors: Brave
(शूर) 5. 196. 3; 6. 18. 14; respected by
brave (शूरसंमत) 7. 66. 39; strong,
very strong (बलवन्त्) 6. 112. 107; (महा-
बल) 5. 196. 3; chariot-fighters (महा-
रथ) 6. 112. 107; ready to give up their
lives (तनुत्यज्) 6. 18. 14; versed in Vedas,
observing vows, doing duties, bearing scars
of battles, desirous of winning other worlds
(by death) in battles, having concentrated
minds, trusting each other (सर्वे वेदविदः
 … सर्वे सुचरितव्रताः।सर्वे कर्मकृतश्
चैव सर्वे चाहवलक्षणाः॥आहवेषु पराल्̃
लोकाञ् जिगीषन्तो … ।एकाग्रमनसः सर्वे
श्रद्दधाना परस्य च॥) 5. 196. 3-4.
B. Characteristic: Karṇa while deriding
Śalya mentioned Vasātis among those who
were generally considered despicable
(वसाति° … प्रायो विकुत्सिताः) 8. 30. 47.
C. Epic events: (1) Vasāti Kṣatriyas
had brought wealth in hundreds for the
Rājasūya of Yudhiṣṭhira (आहार्षुः क्षत्रिया
वित्तं शतशो … ); when they were asked
by the doorkeepers to give more tribute,
each one gave one thousand elephants; they
were then allowed to enter (कृतकाराः
सुबलयस् ततो द्वारम् अवाप्स्यथ) 2. 48.
14, 18; the elephants they gave described
in 2. 48. 19-20; (2) Listed by Yudhiṣṭhira
among those who were gathered together
by Duryodhana to fight with Pāṇḍavas;
Yudhiṣṭhira asked Saṃjaya to enquire
on his behalf about their well-being (तेषां
सर्वेषां कुशलं तात पृच्छेः) 5. 30.
23-24; (3) As told by Duryodhana their
armies, along with Śakuni, left Hāstinapura
in the second division for Kurukṣetra
(द्वितीये निर्ययुर् बले); before departure,
they bathed, became pure, wore garlands
and white garments, took up their arms,
had the word स्वस्ति pronounced on them
and offered oblations in fire 5. 196. 1-2,
7-8; (4) Vasātis mentioned among
twelve Janapadas who with their large
army of chariot-fighters (महता रथवं-
शेन) were supposed to guard Bhīṣma 6.
18. 12; (5) On the second day of war,
Vasātis, led by Śakuni in the Mahāvyūha
of Kauravas (6. 47. 10), were stationed to
protect Droṇa (वसातयः।शकुनिश् च …
भारद्वाजम् अपालयत्) 6. 47. 14; (6) On
the third day, as directed by Bhīṣma, a
large number of horse-riders, foot-soliders,
and chariot-fighters of Vasātis attacked
Arjuna (वाजिपादातरथौघजालैः) 6. 55.
74-75; (7) On the ninth day, though
they were being killed by sharp arrows
did not abandon Bhīṣma (संग्रामे
नाजहुर् भीष्मं वध्यमानाः शितैः
शरैः) 6. 102. 7; (8) On the tenth day,
as directed by Duryodhana, their great
chariot-fighters attacked Arjuna 6. 112.
102, 105, 107, 109; Vasātis mentioned
among twelve Janapadas who though
afflicted by arrows and pained due to
wounds did not abandon Bhīṣma engaged
in fighting with Arjuna at a time when
the Kuru army fled (वयं … प्रद्रवाम
महारणात्। … शरार्ता व्रणपीडिताः।
संग्रामे न जहुर् भीष्मं युध्य-
मानं किरीटिना॥) 6. 114. 75-77;
(9) On the twelfth day, Vasātis were
among those who were posted at the
‘back’ (पृष्ठ) of the Suparṇavyūha of
Kauravas (7. 19. 4, 11); (10) On the
thirteenth day, Abhimanyu killed ten
chariot-fighters of Brahmavasātīyas (पुनर्
ब्रह्मवसातीयाञ् जघान रथिनो दश) 7.
48. 8; (11) On the fourteenth day at
one stage Saṃjaya recalled that Vasātis
were once defeated by Karṇa in battle
(वसातयः … कर्णेन विजिताः पूर्वं सं-
ग्रामे) 7. 66. 37, 39 (a reference to Karṇa's
दिग्विजय before the Vaiṣṇavayajña of
Duryodhana 3. 241. 29, 32; 3 App. I. 24. 28.
72); on that day Vasātis and chariot-
fighters totalling ten thousand tried to
obstruct the way of Arjuna bent on killing
Jayadratha; a fierce battle was fought
(धनंजयम् अवारयन्; जयद्रथ-
वधप्रेप्सुं … न्यवारयन्त सहिताः) 7.
66. 36-43; the same day when Śrutāyudha
was killed by Arjuna Vasātis and other
warriors, six thousand strong (तेषां षष्टि-
शतान्), showered arrows on him; when
Arjuna shot arrows, afraid, they ran away;
but they returned and surrounded Arjuna
on all sides; Arjuna cut off their heads and
arms 7. 68. 2-5; after the death of Jaya-
dratha, Duryodhana while blaming Droṇa
mentioned Vasātis among those who, for
his sake, got killed while fighting with
Arjuna (हता मदर्थं संग्रामे युध्य-
माना किरीटिना) 7. 125. 31-32; (12) During
the night war (14th-15th day), Yudhiṣṭhira
killed Vasātikas and others (बाह्लीकान्
सवसातिकान्) 7. 132. 24; (13) On the
fifteenth day, Dhṛṣṭadyumna dispersed
(व्यधमत्) Vasātis and others who were
protecting Droṇa 7. 165. 24; (14) On the
seventeenth day, Kṛṣṇa, to encourage
Arjuna, reminded him that in the past
seventeen days of war (अथ सप्तदशाहानि
वर्तमानस्य भारत 8. 51. 2) he had
killed armies of Vasātis, along with their
horses and elephants, when they fought with
him 8. 51. 16; (15) On the night of the
seventeenth day (निशि 8. 1. 25), Saṃjaya
while reporting the death of Karṇa men-
tioned that two thousand fighting Vasātis
were killed in the war (वसातयो … द्वि-
साहस्राः प्रहारिणः) 8. 4. 36.
D. Some
persons referred to as those belonging to
Vasātis: A certain hero of Vasātis, not
named, designated as वसातीय 7. 43. 8; and
then as वसात्य 7. 43. 11.

वस्त्रप
Vastrapa m. (pl.): Name of a people.
Their Kṣatriyas brought wealth in
hundreds for the Rājasūya of Yudhiṣṭhira
(वस्त्रपाः पह्लवैः सह।आहार्षुः क्ष-
त्रिया वित्तं शतशो ऽजातशत्रवे) 2. 48.
14, 16.

वाटधान
Vāṭadhāna m. (pl.): Name of a
Janapada and its people.
A. Location: Listed by Saṃjaya
among the northern Janapadas (also called
Deśas 6. 10. 68) of Bhāratavarṣa (अत
ऊर्ध्वं जनपदान् निबोध) 6. 10. 37, 5;
(वाहीका वाटधानाश् च) 6. 10. 45; situated
to the west of Indraprastha (see epic event
No. 1. below); beyond Pañcanada and
Kurujāṅgala and adjacent to the Yāmuna
mountain (see epic event No. 2 below).
B. Description: The country was very ex-
tensive and having ample wealth and grains
(सुविस्तीर्णः प्रभूतधनधान्यवान्) 5.
19. 30-31; rich in cattle (गोमन्त्) 2. 45. 24
(Nī. on Bom. Ed. 2. 49. 24; वाटाः क्षेत्रादि-
वृत्तयः तासां धाना अभिनवोद्भेदो
येषां ते इति व्यधिकरणो बहुव्रीहिः।
सस्यादिसंपन्नक्षेत्रादिवृत्तिमन्त इत्य् अर्-
थः).
C. Epic events: (1) In his
expedition to the west of the Khāṇḍava-
prastha (निर्याय खाण्डवप्रस्थात् प्रती-
चीम् अभितो दीशम् 2. 29. 2; 2. 23. 10),
Nakula subjugated the Vāṭadhāna Brāh-
maṇas (वशे चक्रे … वाटधानान् द्विजान्
अथ); hundreds of Vāṭadhāna Brāhmaṇas
(ब्राह्मणा वाटधानाश् च … शतसंघ-
शः) brought as tribute for the Rājasūya
thirty billions (of wealth) (त्रैखर्वं
बलिम्), but were stopped at the gate;
when they, in addition, gave bright water-
pots of gold they were allowed to enter
(कमण्डलून् उपादाय जातरूपमयाञ्
शुभान् … प्रवेशं लेभिरे ततः) 2. 45.
24-25; (2) Since there was not enough
room in Hāstinapura to accommodate the
army of Kauravas, it spread beyond
Pañcanada and Kurujāṅgala to Vāṭadhāna
country and Yāmuna mountain 5. 19.
30-31; (3) On the third day of the
war, Aśvatthāman and Kṛpa along with
Vāṭadhānas and others formed the
‘head’ (शीर्षम्) of the Garuḍavyūha of
Kauravas 6. 52. 2, 4; (4) At night of the
fifteenth day (निशि 7. 1. 7), when Droṇa's
death was reported to Dhṛtarāṣṭra he men-
tioned Kṛṣṇa's victory over Vāṭadhānas
among his exploits 7. 10. 17; (5) On
the seventeenth day, Kṛṣṇa, to encourage
Arjuna, reminded him that during the past
sixteen days of war (अद्य सप्तदशाहान्त्
8. 51. 2) he had killed large armies of
Vāṭadhāna Brāhmaṇas and other Kṣatriyas
along with their horses and elephants and
broken their chariots (व्रात्यानां वाट-
धानानाम् … महासेना ब्रह्मक्षत्रस्य
भारत। … साश्वरथद्विपाः) 8. 51. 16-17.
D. Vāṭadhāna, name of one of the kings
who were born from the Gaṇa called
Krodhavaśa (गणः क्रोधवशो नाम …
ततः संजज्ञिरे वीराः क्षिताव् इह नराधि-
पाः) 1. 59. 31; 1. 61. 54; (वाटधानो ऽथ
गोमुखः) 1. 61. 58 (Has this king's name
any relationship with the Janapada named
Vāṭadhāna ?).

वातजाम
Vātajāma m. (pl.): Name of a
Janapada (?).
Mentioned by Saṃjaya among the
northern Janapadas (also called Deśas 6.
10. 68) of Bhāratavarṣa (अत ऊर्ध्वं जन-
पदान् निबोध) 6. 10. 37, 5; (वातजाम-
रथोरगाः) 6. 10. 53 (It is not clear how
the compound वातजामरथोरग is to be
understood) [See Uraga and Rathoraga].

वानरास्य
Vānarāsya m. (pl.): Name of a
Janapada.
Listed by Saṃjaya among the northern
Janapadas (also called Deśas 6. 10. 68)
of Bhāratavarṣa (अत ऊर्ध्वं जनपदान्
निबोध) 6. 10. 37, 5; (वानरास्याः प्रवा-
हाश् च) 6. 10. 43.

वानायु
Vānāyu m. (pl.): Name of a Jana-
pada.
Listed by Saṃjaya among the northern
Janapadas (also called Deśas) of Bhāṛata-
varṣa (वानायवो दशापार्श्वाः) 6. 10. 54;
(for other references see the above entry).

वार्ष्णेय
Vārṣṇeya: See Vṛṣṇi.

वासिष्ठ
Vāsiṣṭha m. (pl.): A group of as-
cetics, the descendants of Vasiṣṭha.
A. Description: Ascetics (तपस्विन्)
3. 27. 6; the best Brāhmaṇas in the whole
world (सर्वस्य जगतः श्रेष्ठा ब्राह्म-
णाः) 3. 27. 8; who observed their vows
scrupulously (धृतव्रत) 3. 27. 7.
B.
Epic events: (1) Mentioned by Baka
Dālbhya among the Brāhmaṇas who had
gathered round Yudhiṣṭhira in the Dvaita-
vana (3. 27. 1); there, Vāsiṣṭhas and
others, protected by Yudhiṣṭhira practised
their धर्म (चरन्ति धर्मं … त्वया
गुप्ता … । … वासिष्ठाः … ॥) 3. 27. 7; due
to the sound of their Vedic recitations,
which was pleasing to the heart (हृदयं-
गम), the lake and the Dvaitavana forest
had become holy like the Brahmaloka
(ब्रह्मलोकसमं पुण्यम् आसीद् द्वैत-
वनं सरः) 3. 27. 2-3; (2) Mentioned
among the ascetics introduced by Lomaśa
to Yudhiṣṭhira on the Mahendra mountain
(महेन्द्रम् आशाद्य निशाम् उवास) 3. 114.
26; (आचख्यौ तत्र तापसान्। … वासिष्ठान्
अथ काश्यपान्) 3. 115. 2; Yudhiṣṭhira,
along with his brothers, honoured them all
(तापसानां परं चक्रे सत्कारं भ्रातृ-
भिः सह) 3. 115. 1.

वासुदेव
Vāsudeva m. (pl.): Designation of
Vṛṣṇis in general.

कर्ण
Karṇa told Śalya that the glory of all
the Vāsudevas was established in Kṛṣṇa
(सर्वेषां वासुदेवानां कृष्णे लक्ष्मीः
प्रतिष्ठिता) 8. 27. 62 [See Vṛṣṇi].

वाहीक
Vāhīka m. (pl.): Name of a Jana-
pada.
Listed by Saṃjaya among the Northern
Janapadas (also called Deśas 6. 10. 68)
of Bhāratavarṣa (अत ऊर्ध्वं जनपदान्
निबोध) 6. 10. 37, 5; (वाहीका वाटधानाश्
च) 6. 10. 45.

विकर्ण
Vikarṇa m. (pl.): Name of a people.
On the second day of war, Duryo-
dhana, supported by Vikarṇas and others,
offered protection to the army of Śakuni
in the Mahāvyūha of Kauravas (अश्वा-
तकैर् विकर्णैश् च) 6. 47. 10, 15-16.

विकल्प
Vikalpa m. (pl.): Name of a Jana-
pada.
Listed by Saṃjaya among the southern
Janapadas (also called Deśas 6. 10. 68) of
the Bhāratavarṣa (अथापरे जनपदा …
दक्षिणा) 6. 10. 56, 5; (विकल्पा मूषकास्
तथा) 6. 10. 57.

विकुञ्ज
Vikuñja m. (pl.): Name of a people.
On the third day of war, Vikuñjas and
others, led by Bṛhadbala, were stationed
at the left wing of the Garuḍavyūha
(6. 52. 2-3) of the Kauravas (विकुञ्जाश्
च … ।बृहद्बलेन सहिता वामं पक्षम्
उपाश्रिताः (6. 52. 9).

विजय
Vijaya m. (pl.): Name of a Janapada.
Listed by Saṃjaya among the northern
Janapadas (also called Deśas 6. 10. 68) of
Bhāratavarṣa (अत ऊर्ध्वं जनपदान्
निबोध) 6. 10. 37, 5; (सुह्माश् च विजयास्
तथा) 6. 10. 44.

विदर्भ
Vidarbha m. (pl.): Name of a Jana-
pada and its people; a king of the country
referred to as Vaidarbha and a princess as
Vaidarbhī.
A. Location: Listed by Saṃjaya
among the northern Janapadas (also called
Deśas 6. 10. 68) of Bhāratavarṣa (अत
ऊर्ध्वं जनपदान् निबोध) 6. 10. 37, 5;
(विधर्भानूपवासिकाः) 6. 10. 42; called
राष्ट्र (sg.) 12. 264. 3.
B. Description:
Excelling others in the observance of
धर्म, best (राष्ट्रे धर्मोत्तरे श्रेष्ठे
विदर्भेषु) 12. 264. 3.
C. Epic events:
(1) On the second day of war, Vidarbha
warriors and others along with their armies
accompanied Droṇa who was behind
Bhīṣma in the Mahāvyūha of Kauravas
(विदर्भैर् मेकलैश् चैव … सहिताः
सर्वसैन्येन) 6. 47. 10, 12-13.
D. Past
events: (a) from the story of Nala: (1)
King Bhīma once ruled over the Vidarbha
country 3. 50. 5; 3. 61. 72; he protected
it well (सम्यग् गोप्ता विदर्भाणां … ) 3.
61. 44; (2) The swans promised Nala
that they would praise him in the presence
of Damayantī, flew towards Vidharbha
and reached its principal town (विदर्भ-
नगरीं गत्वा) 3. 50. 21-22; (3) The
guardians of the world, Indra and others,
started for the Vidarbha country to attend
the स्वयंवर of Damayantī 3. 51. 24;
(4) As directed by Damayantī, Vārṣṇeya,
the charioteer of Nala, put her two children
(son and a daughter) on a chariot and
took them to her father in Vidarbha
(ययौ मिथुनम् आरोप्य विदर्भांस् तेन
वाहिना) 3. 57. 20 (Nī. on Bom. Ed. 3. 60.
19: मिथुनं कुमारं कुमारीं च):
(5) Nala pointed out to Damayantī the
road that led to the Vidarbha country; she
asked him why he showed to her the road
to Vidarbha; she suggested to him that
both of them together, and not she alone,
might go to Vidarbha 3. 58. 22, 30, 33; (6)
When Sudeva saw Damayantī in the Cedi
country, he thought her to be like a lotus
plant lifted from a pond of the Vidarbha
country (विदर्भसरसस् तस्माद् दैव-
दोषाद् इवोद्धृताम्। … मृणालीम् इव) 3. 65.
12; (7) Damayantī told the mother of
Subāhu, the king of Cedis, that she wished
to go to Vidarbha; she was accordingly
sent to Vidarbha 3. 66. 19, 22; (8) King
Ṛtuparṇa told Bāhuka (Nala) that he
wished to go to Vidarbha in a day to
attend Damayantī's स्वयंवर (विदर्भान्
यातुम् इच्छामि … ।एकाह्ना); Bāhuka assured
him that he would be able to reach the
capital town of Vidarbha in a day although
the horses he (Bāhuka) had chosen were
lean (प्रतिजानामि ते सत्यं गमिष्यसि … ।
एकाह्ना … विदर्भनगरीं नृप॥) 3. 69. 2,
9, 15; on way, Ṛtuparṇa, although he relied
on Bāhuka to reach Vidarbha on time,
told him not to raise any obstacle; if
Bāhuka took him to Vidarbha before sunset
he would give Bāhuka anything he wanted
(विदर्भान् यदि यात्वाद्य सूर्यं दर्श-
यितासि मे।कामं च ते करीष्यामि); but
Bāhuka told Ṛtuparṇa that he would first
count the Vibhītaka fruit and then proceed
to Vidarbha; when Kali had left Nala's
body, king Ṛtuparṇa proceeded to Vidarbha
3. 70. 17-19, 38; Ṛtuparṇa reached Vidarbha
in the evening (विदर्भान् संप्राप्तं
सायाह्ने) 3. 71. 1; (b) other past event:
Once a certain Brāhmaṇa lived in the Vida-
rbha country (विदर्भेष्व् अभवद् द्विजः)
12. 264. 3.
E. Some persons referred
to with reference to the Vidarbha country
as the king of Vidarbha, one belonging
to Vidarbha, etc.:
A. King of Vidarbha;
(a) विदर्भपति: Bhīma 3. 51. 5; (b)
विदर्भराज्: Bhīma 3. 61. 119; (c)
विदर्भराज: (1) Bhīma 3. 66. 1; (विद-
र्भराजदुहिता) 3. 51. 19; 3. 58. 34; (विद-
र्भराजतनया) 3. 61. 31; (2) A king, not
named, father of Lopāmudrā 3. 94. 18; (3)
A king, neither named or identified 3. 120.
30; (d) विदर्भाधिप: Bhīma 3. 61. 8
(विदर्भाधिपनन्दिनी); (e) विदर्भाधि-
पति: Bhīma 3. 61. 41; 3. 67. 7; (f) Pro-
tector of Vidarbhas: Bhīma गोप्ता विदर्-
भाणाम् 3. 61. 44;
B. Daughter of
Vidarbha: Damayantī: विदर्भतनया 3.
61. 11;
C. One belonging to Vidarbha:
(a) वैदर्भ: A king, not named, father
of Lopāmudrā 3. 94. 20; 3. 95. 1; (b)
वैदर्भी (f.): (1) Damayantī 3. 52. 11,
21; 3. 53. 5, 12; 3. 54. 11, 13; 3. 56. 8;
3. 59. 5, 17; 3. 61. 55; 3. 62. 12; 3. 64. 9;
3. 65. 6, 23, 27; 3. 68. 17; 3. 69. 5; 3. 71.
31; 3. 72. 7, 21-22; 3. 74. 5; 3. 75. 22; 3.
76. 1; 3. 77. 20; (2) Maryādā, wife of
Arācīna 1. 90. 18; (3) Lopāmudrā 3. 94.
27; 5. 115. 12; (4) Suṣuvā, wife of Jayat-
sena 1. 90. 17; (5) Wife of Sagara, not
named 3. 104. 8, 7;
D. The principal
town Kuṇḍina of Vidarbha referred to as
विदर्भनगरी 3. 50. 22; 3. 69. 9.

विदेह
Videha1 m. (pl.): Name of a Jana-
pada and its people; once named (perhaps
for metre) Videhaka 6. 10. 44.
A. Location: Listed by Saṃjaya
among the northern Janapadas (also called
Deśas 6. 10. 68) of Bhāratavarṣa (अत
ऊर्ध्वं जनपदान् निबोध) 6. 10. 37, 5;
(विदेहका मागधाश् च) 6. 10. 44 (here
Videhakas are listed along with Māgadhas
as apposed to Videhas2 listed by Saṃjaya
along with Kirātas, Barbaras and others);
the Janapada lay in the east beyond Pāñ-
cālas and the river Gaṇḍakī 2. 26. 3-4 (see
Epic event No. 2 below); Vātikaṣaṇḍa (?)
lay to the north of Videhas (एष वातिक-
षण्डो वै … विदेहान् उत्तरं च यः) 3.
130. 13; Videhas lived in Mithilā (see
Epic event No. 1 below) 1. 105. 11.
B.
Description of its warriors and people:
Strong (बलवन्त्) 6. 112. 107; great
chariot-fighters (महारथ) 6. 112. 107,
111; very difficult to be conquered in
battle (संख्ये सुदुर्जयाः) 8. 57. 31; the
Videha country was inhabited by very
prosperous people (समृद्धजनसेवित)
12. 312. 22.
C. Epic events: (1) In
Pāṇḍu's conquest of the earth which he
undertook after his marriage, he went
to Mithilā and defeated Videhas in
battle (जिगीषमाणो वसुधां … पाण्डुना
मिथिलां गत्वा विदेहाः समरे जिताः)
1. 105. 7, 11; (2) Bhīmasena, in his
expedition to the east (ययौ प्राचीं
दिशं प्रति 2. 26. 1; 2. 23. 9) went beyond
Pāñcālas and the river Gaṇḍakī and defeat-
ed Videhas 2. 26. 3-4; (3) On the tenth
day of the war, Videha warriors (on the
side of Kauravas) as directed by Duryo-
dhana who assured them the protection
of Bhīṣma, attacked Arjuna; Arjuna burnt
them and their armies with his heavenly
missiles (दिव्यान्य् अस्त्राणि संचिन्त्य प्र-
संधाय); afflicted by arrows and with
their chariots and banners broken they
did not attack Arjuna (शरार्ता …
विप्रकीर्णरथध्वजाः। … नाभ्यवर्तन्त
 … वानरध्वजम्) 6. 112. 102, 105, 108,
110-112, 114; on the same day, in the
meeting between Bhīṣma and Karṇa after
the former's downfall, Bhīṣma reminded
Karṇa in order to encourage him that he
had formerly defeated Videhas (7. 4. 5);
on the seventeenth day, Śalya too, in order
to encourage Karṇa reminded him that
he had once with great courage defeated
Videhas (वैदेहा° … यया धृत्या जिताः सं-
ख्ये सुदुर्जयाः) 8. 57. 31; later Dhṛta-
rāṣṭra while lamenting over the death of
Karṇa remembered that Karṇa had defeated
Videhas and made them pay tribute (विदे-
हांश् च … ।यो जित्वा समरे वीरश् चक्रे
बलिभृतः पुरा॥) 8. 5. 19-20 (reference
in all three cases to Karṇa's दिग्विजय
before the Vaiṣṇavayajña of Duryodhana
3. 241. 29, 32; 3. App. 24-42 (मिथिलान्));
(4) On the seventeenth day, at night
(निशि 8. 1. 25), Saṃjaya in his first brief
account of the death of Karṇa, mentioned
that Karṇa killed many Videhas (on the
side of Pāṇḍavas) in the presence of all
Sṛñjayas and Pāñcālas (स सृञ्जयानां
सर्वेषां पाञ्चालानां च पश्यताम् …
विदेहानाम् अकरोत् कदनं महत्॥) 8. 2.
18.
D. Past events: (1) King Janaka
gave his son the kingdom of Videha
and himself lived the life of a mendicant
(विदेहराज्यं तथा प्रतिष्ठाप्य सुतस्य
वै) 12. 306. 94; (2) Sulabhā went to
the capital town of Videhas (विदेहानां
पुरीं … ) 12. 308. 11; (3) Śuka, as
instructed by Vyāsa, reached the country
of Videhas which was protected by Janaka
(विदेहान् आससाद ह।रक्षितान् धर्मराजेन
जनकेन) 12. 312. 6, 19; Śuka entered the
country of Videhas and reached the garden
in Mithilā (स विदेहान् अतिक्रम्य … मिथि-
लोपवनं रम्यं आससाद) 12. 312. 22.
E. Some kings referred to as:
A. the
king of Videhas: (a) विदेहराज: (1)
Janaka, father of Sītā 3. 132. 4; 3. 258. 9;
(2) Janaka, the philosopher 12. 18. 3; 12.
28. 57; 12. 171. 55; 12. 268. 3; 12. 286. 41;
12. 313. 10; 13. 45. 7; (3) Hayagrīva 5.
72. 15; (4) A king, not named 13. 46.
11 (विदेहराजदुहिता); (b) विदेहराजन्;
Janaka, the philosopher 12. 18. 2;
B. some
kings and princesses referred to as belong-
ing to Videha: (a) वैदेह: (1) Karāla-
janaka 12. 296. 37 (cf. 12. 291. 7-8); (2)
Janaka, the philosopher 12. 28. 3; 12. 285.
16; 12. 286. 17; 12. 307. 4, 6; (3) Nimi 12.
226. 26; (4) A king, not named 12. 106. 6;
12. 107. 8. 9, 26; (5) A king, not named,
contemporary of Pāṇḍavas 2. 4. 24 (cf. the
next वैदेहक); (b) वैदेहक: Janaka,
contemporary of Pāṇḍavas, who was con-
quered by Bhīma 2. 27. 12 (cf. वैदेह (5)
above); (c) वैदेही (f.): (1) Maryādā
1. 90. 22; (2) Sītā, daughter of Janaka
3. 261. 28; 3. 262. 17, 23; 3. 263. 7, 10-11,
13-14, 23, 28-29; 3. 264. 5, 14, 53, 71; 3.
265. 17-18, 30; 3. 266. 23, 35, 55, 66; 3.
273. 26; 3. 275. 102, 21, 56, 63; 3. 276. 10;
4. 20. 9; (3) A princess, not named,
married to Śatānīka 1. 90. 95.

विदेह
Videha2 m. (pl.): Name of a Janapada.
A. Location: Listed by Saṃjaya
among the northern Janapadas (also called
Deśas 6. 10. 68) of Bhāratavarṣa (अत
ऊर्ध्वं जनपदान् निबोध) 6. 10. 37, 5;
(किराता बर्बराः सिद्धा विदेहास् ताम्रलिङ्ग-
काः) 6. 10. 55 (these Videhas seem to be
different from Videhas1 since these are listed
along with Kirātas and others).
B.
Description: Karṇa mentioned to Śalya
of a certain Brāhmaṇa who in the Kuru
assembly, equated Videhas with Āraṭṭas
(Bāhlīkas) and described them as non-
sacrificers, those who had lost their धर्म
and hence whose country should not be
visited; this description seems to apply to
these Videhas2 and not to Videha1 above
(आरट्टा नाम ते देशा नष्टधर्मान् न तान्
व्रजेत्।व्रात्यानां दासमी यानां विदेहानाम्
अयज्वनाम्) 8. 30. 36.

विन्ध्यपुलक
Vindhyapulaka m. (pl.): Name of a
Janapada.
Listed by Saṃjaya among the southern
Janapadas (also called Deśas 6. 10. 68)
of the Bhāratavarṣa (अथापरे जनपदा
दक्षिणा … ) 6. 10. 56, 5; (तथैव विन्ध्य-
पुलकाः पुलिन्दाः … ) 6. 10. 60.

वीतहव्य
Vītahavya: See Vaitahavya.

वीरक
Vīraka m. (pl.): Name of a people.
According to a Brāhmaṇa reporting to
the Kuru assembly, a certain Rākṣasī
described Vīrakas as those who followed
bad धर्म and therefore should be com-
pletely avoided (कर्कोटकान् वीरकांश् च
दुर्धर्मांश् च विवर्जयेत्) 8. 30. 41,
45-46.

वृष्णि
Vṛṣṇi m. (pl.): Name of a people,
occasionally referred to as Vārṣṇeyas; often
mentioned along with Andhakas and some-
times also with Bhojas.
A. Location: They lived in the city
Dvārakā; the city is referred to as वृष्णिपुर
3. 21. 4; 3. 180. 25; वृष्ण्यन्धकपुर
3. 16. 19 (see below Epic events No. 17).
B. Origin: The origin of the Vṛṣṇi race
is sought in the extensive race of Prajāpati
known as the progeny of Śaśabindu (प्रजाम्
आचक्षते विप्राः पौराणीं शाशबिन्दवीम्।
स वृष्णिवंशप्रभवो महावंशः प्रजा-
पतेः॥) 12. 201. 13 (Comm. Arjunamiśra
on 12. 201. 11: शशबिन्दुः वृष्णीनां
पूर्वजः। सो ऽपि प्रजापतिः); see Editor's
note, Cr. edn. Vol. 16, p. 2166).
C.
Greatness: While narrating the descent of
the first generations (आदिवंशावतार),
Vaiśaṃpāyana told Janamejaya that the all-
pervading Puruṣa took birth (as Kṛṣṇa)
among the Vṛṣṇis and Andhakas for fur-
thering the cause of धर्म (पुरुषः स
विभुः … ।धर्मसंवर्धनार्थाय प्र-
जज्ञे ऽन्धकवृष्णिषु) 1. 57. 87; Nārāyaṇa
was born as Kṛṣṇa in the family of Vṛṣṇis
and Andhakas 2. 33. 17; 2. 34. 15.
D.
Description and characteristics: Of good
nature (सुमनस्) 5. 84. 4; very fortunate
(सुमहाभाग) 12. 82. 8; having all enjoy-
ments (भोगवन्त्) 5. 28. 12; prosperous
(स्फीत) 5. 84. 3; prosperous because they
were always active (नित्योत्थानेन सं-
पन्नाः) 12. 82. 8; magnanimous (महात्-
मन्) 1. 213. 53; 3. 119. 2; 16. 9. 26;
of great lustre (सुमहौजस्) 1. 211. 5;
spirited (मनस्विन्) 5. 28. 12; brave (शूर)
and proud like lion (सिंहदर्प) 16.
9. 9; heroic (वीर, वीर्यवन्त्) 2. 13. 59;
excellent heroes (उत्तमवीर्य) 1. 213. 55:
strong, very strong (बलिन्) 2. 17. 27;
(महाबल) 2. 13. 59; 5. 28 12; 16. 9. 9;
(बलवन्त्) 12. 82. 8; powerful (सामर्थ्य-
वन्त्) 2. 13. 53; great archers (महेष्वास)
2. 72. 29; 3. 48. 6; tigers among men
(पुरुषव्याघ्र) 1. 212. 14; immensely
powerful like tigers (व्याघ्रैर् इव बलो-
त्कटैः) 5. 154. 17; proficient in all
शास्त्रस् (सर्वशास्त्रविशारद) 3. 119. 2;
difficult to be attacked (दुर्धर्ष) 2. 4.
26; (दुरासद) 12. 82. 8; of ture valour
(सत्यपराक्रम) 5. 28. 12; bringing toge-
ther people (?) (लोकसंहनन) 2. 13. 59;
having long arms, like iron bars (बाहुशालिन्,
परिघबाहु) 16. 9. 10-11; their arms were
capable of resisting maces, iron bars and
शक्तिस् (गदापरिघशक्तीनां सहाः) 16.
9. 10; they were like Indra (इन्द्रकल्प)
5. 28. 12; like gods (देवरूपिन्) 2. 4. 26;
attached to Kṛṣṇa (त्वय्य् आसक्ताः) 12. 82.
29; Vṛṣṇis and Andhakas followed the
advice of Kṛṣṇa (यस्य प्रज्ञाम् उपासते)
5. 84. 4; following Kṛṣṇa's advice, Vārṣṇe-
yas and Bhojas restrained their enemies and
gave delight to friends (वार्ष्णेयभोजाः
 … उपासीना वासुदेवस्य बुद्धिं निगृह्य
शत्रून् सुहृदो नन्दयन्ति) 5. 28. 11; no one
in the past was or in the future would be
equal to Vṛṣṇis in strength; they did not
disregard kinsmen, were obedient to elders,
gods, Asuras, Gandharvas, Yakṣas, Rākṣa-
sas; men were unable to defeat Vṛṣṇi
warriors in battles: they did not rob Brāh-
maṇas, teachers, kinsmen of their wealth;
on the other hand, if any one of them was
in difficulty they protected him; they were
wealthy, but were not arrogant; truthful,
they were devoted to Brāhmaṇas; they did
not underrate the strong ones, they uplifted
the weak ones; they worshipped gods, were
controlled and generous, but not given to
boasting; due to these virtues Vṛṣṇi warriors
were not attacked; one might carry moun-
tain Meru, cross the ocean, but not succeed
if he dared attack Vṛṣṇi warriors (न
तुल्यं … भूतं भव्यं भविष्यच् च
बलेन; समर्थान् नावमन्यन्ते दीनान्
अभ्युद्धरन्ति च; तेन वृष्णिप्रवीराणां
चक्रं न प्रतिहन्यते; Nī. on Bom. Ed.
7. 144. 28: चक्रं प्रतापः 7. 119. 22-27
(this description of Vṛṣṇis immediately
follows that of the Sātvatas (7. 119. 20-21)
which is indicative of the identity between
the two); Bhūriśravas deriding Sātyaki
ridiculed Vṛṣṇis as व्रात्यस्, not distin-
guishing between good and evil acts, and
despicable by very nature (व्रात्याः सं-
श्लिष्तकर्माणः प्रकृत्यैव विगर्हिताः)
7. 118. 15.
E. Epic events: (1) The
Vṛṣṇis went to the forest to meet Pāṇḍavas
(वृष्णीनाम् आगमो यत्र)—a reference to
a later epic event (see No. 15 below) in the
summary of the contents of the Āraṇyaka-
parvan (given in the sub-parvan पर्वसं-
ग्रह) 1. 2. 106; (2) Yudhiṣṭhira heard
from Nārada the massive mutual destruc-
tion of the Vṛṣṇis—a reference to a later
event (see below No. 65) in the summary
of the contents of the Āśramavāsikaparvan
1. 2. 217 (actually this event does not
form part of the Āśramavāsikaparvan but
of the Mausalaparvan and Yudhiṣṭhira
did not get the news from Nārada but
from Dāruka (cf. 16. 1. 7; 16. 6. 11);
Arjuna seeing Dvārakā without Vṛṣṇis was
dejected 1. 2. 223; he performed the funeral
rites of Rāma, Kṛṣṇa and other Vṛṣṇi-chiefs
(वृष्णीनां च प्रधानतः); he felt sad on
account of the abduction of Vṛṣṇi women
(नाशं वृष्णिकलत्राणाम्) 1. 2. 227—all
three events are references given in the
summary of the Mausalaparvan to later epic
events (see below Epic events Nos. 70-75);
(3) Vṛṣṇis learnt the science of archery
(धनुर्वेद) from Kṛpa 1. 120. 21; Vṛṣṇis
and Andhakas approached Droṇa to learn
the अस्त्रस् (अस्त्रार्थे … वृष्णयश् चान्धकाश्
चैव) 1. 122. 46; (4) Vṛṣṇi chiefs attend-
ed the स्वयंवर of Draupadī 1. 177. 18;
as advised by Kṛṣṇa they watched the pro-
ceedings of the स्वयंवर 1. 178. 8;
(5) Bhoja, Vṛṣṇi, and Andhaka women
gathered to see Arjuna when he arrived at
Dvārakā; Bhojas, Vṛṣṇis and Andhakas
honoured and greeted Arjuna; he paid his
respects to the deserving among them;
Vṛṣṇis, along with Bhojas and Andhakas
celebrated a grand festival in honour of
the Raivataka mountain; in that festival,
Vṛṣṇis and others gave gifts to thousands
of Brāhmaṇas; thousands of illustrious
youths of Vṛṣṇis put on ornaments and
moved about riding vehicles decorated with
gold; their wives and followers accompani-
ed them 1. 211. 1-2, 5-6; (6) On hearing
the sound of the drum sounded by the
guardian of the Sabhā, agitated Vṛṣṇis and
Andhakas, leaving aside food and drink,
assembled by hundreds in the Sabhā and
took their seats on the सिंहासनस्; the
Sabhāpāla told them that Arjuna had ab-
ducted Subhadrā; on hearing it they leaped
up from their seats and asked their chari-
oteers to yoke the chariots and bring their
weapons, bows and armours; others brought
forth their gold-decked horses; when all
these arrangements were being done there
arose a confused sound of the Vṛṣṇi
heroes 1. 212. 12-19; Bhojas, Vṛṣṇis and
Andhakas got ready to follow Balarāma
when he announced his intention to fight
with Arjuna (अन्वपद्यन्त ते सर्वे भोज-
वृष्ण्यन्धकास् तदा) 1. 212. 31-32; Vṛṣṇis
made their intention to attack Arjuna
known several times; but when Kṛṣṇa told
them that Arjuna had done the right thing,
they were pacified 1. 213. 2-11; Kṛṣṇa with
Vṛṣṇis and others went to the Khāṇḍava-
prastha to attend the marriage of Subhadrā
with Arjuna; they took with them large
number of nuptial gifts (हरणं बहु);
they were received by Nakula and Saha-
deva; the illustrious Vṛṣṇis (वृष्णिचक्रं
समृद्धिमत्) entered Khāṇḍavaprastha;
Yudhiṣṭhira received the seniors among
Vṛṣṇis with honours according to the rules
and following the actual practice (?) (प्रति-
जग्राह सत्कारैर् यथाविधि यथोपगम्);
he honoured some Vṛṣṇi-chiefs as elders,
some as friends; he greeted some with
affection and was himself greeted by some
(गुरुवत् पूजयाम् आस कांश्चित् कांश्चिद्
वयस्यवत्।कांश्चिद् अभ्यवदत् प्रेम्णा
कैश् चिद् अप्य् अभिवादितः॥) 1. 213. 23-24,
29, 31, 34, 38-39; after receiving their
gifts, Yudhiṣṭhira honoured the great
warriors of Vṛṣṇis and Andhakas (वृष्ण्य्-
अन्धकमहारथान्); the best among the
Vṛṣṇis and Andhakas (वृष्ण्यन्धकोत्त-
माः) lived happily with Kurus and enjoyed
with them great drinking bouts (महा-
पानैर् … विजह्रुः कुरुवृष्णयः); then,
after many days, the Vṛṣṇi and Andhaka
warriors (उत्तमवीर्यास् ते), led by Bala-
rāma, returned to Dvārakā taking with
them bright jewels given to them by
Kurus 1. 213. 52-56; (7) Vṛṣṇi princes
(वृष्णीनां … कुमारा … ) were among those
who waited on Dharmarāja in his Sabhā 2.
4. 26; (8) They were taught the science
of archery by Arjuna (कुमारा … वृष्णि-
नन्दनाः) 2. 4. 29; (9) Vṛṣṇis fled
from Mathurā and settled down at Kuśa-
sthalī in the west; they fortified the new
settlement in such a way as to make it
difficult to be captured even by gods; even
women could fight and hold it against
the attack (स्त्रियो ऽपि यस्यां युध्येयुः
किं पुनर् वृष्णिपुंगवाः 2. 13. 51);
Vṛṣṇis lived there without fear from any
quarter (अकुतोभयाः); although powerful,
they had allied themselves with Pāṇḍavas
because of their relationship (सामर्थ्य-
वन्तः सम्बन्धाद् भवन्तं समुपा-
श्रिताः); Cārudeṣṇa and all other Vṛṣṇi
heroes though free from grief, lived at
Kuśasthalī still remembering the Madhya-
deśa (where they formerly lived) (स्मरन्तो
मध्यमं देशं वृष्णिमध्ये गत-
व्यथाः) 2. 13. 53, 59; (10) Jarāsandha
was neglected by Vṛṣṇis, though strong,
out of considerations of policy (बलिभिः
 … वृष्णिभिश् च … नीतिहेतोर् उपेक्षितः) 2.
17. 27; (11) Vṛṣṇis arrived at Khāṇḍava-
prastha for the Rājasūya of Yudhiṣṭhira
2. 31. 16; (12) Vṛṣṇis and Andhakas
did not pay tribute to Yudhiṣṭhira for
Rājasūya because of their friendly relations
with Pāṇḍavas (सख्येनान्धकवृष्णयः)
2. 48. 42; however, Vārṣṇeyas are said to
have brought for Yudhiṣṭhira many kinds
of tribute (वार्ष्णेयान् हारहूणांश् च
 … बल्यर्थं ददतस् तस्मै नानारूपान्
अनेकशः) but were stopped at the gate 2.
47. 19-20, 25; the tribute is described in 2.
47. 21-25 (since Vārṣṇeyas are here listed
along with Cīnas, Hūṇas, Śakas, Oḍras,
forest-dwellers, and Hārahūṇas, are these
Vārṣṇeyas different from Vṛṣṇis who formed
a section of the Yādavas and did not pay
tribute ?): (13) Śiśupāla instigated the
kings assembled for the Rājasūya to fight
with Vṛṣṇis and Pāṇḍavas 2. 36. 14; (14)
Vidura warned Kauravas that Vṛṣṇis would
never forgive the hardship suffered by Drau-
padī in the Sabhā (तस्याः … परिक्लेशं
न क्षंस्यन्ते … ।वृष्णयो वा महेष्वासाः)
2. 72. 29; (15) Hearing that Pāṇḍavas
had gone into exile, Vṛṣṇis, Bhojas, and
Andhakas went to meet them in the
Dvaitavana (3. 12. 68); they sat around
Yudhiṣṭhira, blamed Kauravas and won-
dered what they could do (to help them)
3. 13. 1, 3-4; (16) Draupadī complained
to Kṛṣṇa that Kauravas had desired to
reduce her to the status of a दासी although
Vṛṣṇis were alive (दासीभावेन भोक्तुं
माम् ईषुस् ते मधुसूदन।जीवत्सु … अथ
वृष्णिषु) 3. 13. 56; 5. 80. 25; (17) When
Śālva attacked Dvārakā in the absence of
Kṛṣṇa, young Vṛṣṇi heroes fought with him
(बालकैर् वृष्णिपुंगवैः); Śālva killed
many of the excellent Vṛṣṇi heroes (वृष्णि-
प्रवीरांस् तान् बालान् हत्वा) 3. 15. 6-7;
during Śālva's attack on Dvārakā drinking
liquor was prohibited; Vṛṣṇis and Andha-
kas had to remain alert apprehending
Śālva might attack them when they were
drunk (प्रमत्तेष्व् अभिघातं हि कुर्यात्
 … इति कृत्वाप्रमत्तास् ते सर्वे वृष्ण्य्-
अन्धकाः स्थिताः॥) 3. 16. 12-13; it was
then ruled that no one in the town of
Vṛṣṇis and Andhakas could leave or enter
the town without valid permit (न चामुद्रो
ऽभिनिर्याति न चामुद्रः प्रवेश्यते।वृष्ण्य-
न्धकपुरे) 3. 16. 19; when the youthful
Vṛṣṇi princes saw Śālva's army attacking
Dvārakā, they came out and fought with
the opponents (कुमारा वृष्णिनन्दनाः)
3. 17. 8; when Pradyumna swooned, the
army of Vṛṣṇis and Andhakas raised a
cry of grief; when Pradyumna regained
consciousness he blamed his charioteer for
removing his chariot away from the battle-
field for that was not the battle-धर्म
of Vṛṣṇ warriors (नैष वृष्णिप्रवीराणाम्
आहवे धर्म उच्यते) 3. 19. 1-2, 5; he
told the charioteer that one who left the
battlefield was not born in the family of
Vṛṣṇis (न स वृष्णिकुले जातो यो वै त्यजति
संगरम्), nor he who killed one fallen
on the ground or who had surrendered,
or a woman, an old man or a child, or
one who was without a chariot, who was
shattered, and whose weapons were broken;
he reminded the charioteer that he (the
charioteer) knew what the धर्म of
Vṛṣṇis was in battles, and since he knew
the entire code of conduct of Vṛṣṇis en-
gaged in fighting he should not have taken
Pradyumna away form battlefield; (धर्-
मज्ञश् चासि वृष्णीनाम् आहवेष्व् अपि … ।स
जानंश् चरितं कृत्स्नं वृष्णीणां पृतना-
मुखे।) 3. 19. 13-16; Pradyumna wonder-
ed what the women of Vṛṣṇi heroes would
say to him when he met them 3. 19. 21;
Pradyumna asked his charioteer how he
could face Andhakas and Vṛṣṇis who
always vied with him (मया स्पर्धन्ति
सततं) 3. 19. 28; the charioteer in reply
told Pradyumna that he was conversant
with the war (conduct) of Vṛṣṇis (and
he defended his action) (युद्धज्ञश् चास्मि
वृष्णीनाम्) 3. 20. 2; Śālva tormented by
Vṛṣṇis rode his Saubha to rise up in
the sky and left Dvārakā 3. 20. 27; when
Kṛṣṇa returned to Dvārakā he was sur-
prised to see the town of Vṛṣṇis with men
and women extremely uneasy (अस्वस्थ-
नरनारीकम् इदं वृष्णिपुरं भृशम्) 3.
21. 4; Kṛṣṇa then spoke to Āhuka, Vasu-
deva and Vṛṣṇi heroes asking them to
remain alert (अप्रमादः सदा कार्यो); he
announced his decision to attack Śālva
which delighted Vṛṣṇis; comforted, they
asked him to kill the enemies and blessed
him 3. 21. 7-11; (18) Dhṛtarāṣṭra feared
that Vṛṣṇi archers and spirited Pāñcālas,
led by Kṛṣṇa, would burn the army of
Kauravas 3. 48. 6; he told Saṃjaya that
it was not possible even for mountains
to withstand the velocity (of the attack)
of Vṛṣṇis when led by Rāma and Kṛṣṇa
(वृष्णीनाम् … ।न शक्यः सहितुं वेगः)
3. 48. 7; (19) When Vṛṣṇis went to
Prabhāsa to meet the Pāṇḍavas during
the period of their exile, they found
them smeared with dirt resting on bare
ground; seeing them, Vṛṣṇis were filled
with sorrow and cried loudly; Yudhiṣṭhira
approached Vṛṣṇis and honoured them as
they deserved; they too in return honoured
Pāṇḍavas and sat around them 3. 118. 15,
18-21; Janamejaya asked Vaiśaṃpāyana to
tell him the details of the talks between
Vṛṣṇis, sitting around, and Pāṇḍavas at
Prabhāsa 3. 119. 1-3; Sātyaki suggested to
Balarāma that he should permit the army
of Daśārhas to march against Duryodhana
so that he would perish when overtaken
by the army of Vṛṣṇis; he also said that
the army consisting of principal Kṣatriya
warriors of Vṛṣṇis, Bhojas and Andhakas
should kill the sons of Dhṛtarāṣṭra and
enhance its fame (क्षत्रियशूरसेना लोके
यशः स्फीतम् उपाकरोतु) 3. 120. 5, 19;
(20) Kṛṣṇa told Draupadī that her
sons while they were in the town of
Vṛṣṇis (Dvārakā) they were not jealous
of gods (तवात्मजा वृष्णिपुरं प्रविश्य
न दैवतेभ्यः स्पृहयन्ति कृष्णे) 3. 180.
25; Satyabhāmā assured Draupadī that
Andhakas and Vṛṣṇis had the same affec-
tion for her sons as for Pradyumna 3. 224.
14; (21) Draupadī warned Jayadratha
