वैराम
Vairāma m. (pl.): Name of a people.
A. Location: They were born in the
bay (?) of the (western) ocean, near the
river Sindhu (समुद्रनिष्कुटे जाताः परि-
सिन्धु च मानवाः) 2. 47. 9 (Nī., however,
on Bom. Ed. 2. 51. 11: समुद्रसमी-
पस्थनिष्कुटे गृहोद्याने).
B. Characte-
ristics: They lived on grains which grew
of their own accord or which they culti-
vated using river water (इन्द्रकृष्टैर् वर्त-
यन्ति धान्यैर् नदीमुखैश् च ये) 2. 47. 9
(For Nīlakaṇṭha's comment see Pārada
p. 783).
C. Epic event: They brought
tribute for Yudhiṣṭhira's Rājasūya many
kinds of articles and jewels of various types
(वीविधं बलिम् आदाय रत्नानि विविधानि
च), but they were stopped at the gate
(ते वैरामाः … । … द्वारि तिष्ठन्ति वारिताः)
2. 47. 10-11 (the details of the tribute are
given in 2. 47. 11 for which see Pārada).

शक
Śaka m. (pl.): Name of a Janapada
and its people.
A. Location: Listed by Saṃjaya
among the northern Janapadas (also called
Deśas 6. 10. 68) of Bhāratavarṣa (अत
ऊर्ध्वं जनपदान् निबोध) 6. 10 37, 5;
(वक्रभयाः शकाः) 6. 10. 43; listed by
him again along with Niṣādas and Niṣadhas
(शका निषादा निषधास् … ) 6. 10. 50.
B.
Origin: They were produced, along with
Śabaras, by Nandinī, Vasiṣṭha's cow, from
her dung (शकृतः शबराञ् शकान्) 1. 165.
35; elsewhere it is stated that they were
originally Kṣatriyas but were degraded to
the status of a वृषल due to their neglect of
Brāhmaṇas (क्षत्रियजातयः।वृषलत्वं
परिगता ब्राह्मणानाम् अदर्शनात्) 13. 33.
19.
C. Description and characteristics:
Very strong (अतिबल) 8. 5. 18, (बलिन्) 8.
51. 19; very frightful (सुघोर), having
frightful eyes (घोरचक्षुस्) 7. 68. 41;
rough, doers of cruel deeds (उग्र, क्रूर-
कर्मन्) 8. 51. 18; impure (अशुचि), having
shaven, half-shaven heads, or having mat-
ted hair on heads and with bearded faces
(मुण्डार्धमुण्डजटिलान् … जटिलाननान्)
7. 68. 44; they knew the मायास् of demons
(विदन्त्य् असुरमायां ये) 7. 68. 41; excit-
ed, fond of wars, firm-fisted (संरंभिन्,
युद्धशौण्ड, दृब्धपाणि) 8. 51. 19;
quick in action (लघुहस्त) 7. 95. 32;
difficult to be conquered (दुर्जय) 8. 5.
18; difficult to be assailed (दुराधर्ष),
fiery, shining like burning fire (अग्निकल्प)
(प्रदीप्तैर् इव पावकैः); their valour was
like that of Indra (शक्रतुल्यपराक्रम)
7. 87. 50; characterized as म्लेच्छस् 7. 68.
44; 7. 95. 13; they lived in the caves of
mountains (गिरिगह्वरवासिन्) 7. 68 45;
also said to be living on country-side but
leading the life of Dasyus (सर्वे विषय-
वासिनः … सर्वे ते दस्युजीविनः) 12. 65. 15;
D. Epic events: (1) Śakas were among
several peoples like Cīnas, Hūṇas and
others who, although they brought tribute
of different kinds for Rājasūya, were
stopped at the gate (अभिगतान् विविधान्
द्वारि वारितान्; बलिं च कृत्स्नम् आदाय द्वारि
तिष्ठन्ति वारिताः) 2. 47. 19-20, 25; the
details of their tribute given in 2. 47. 21-25;
Śakas are mentioned once again along with
Tukhāras and others who brought tribute
in the form of an अर्बुद horses who
could go long distances and were of noble
descent, as well as gold in very large quan-
tities to be counted by crores and totalling
a पद्म, but were stopped at the gate
(महागमान् दूरगमान् गणितान् अर्बुदं
हयान्॥कोटिशश् चैव बहुशः सुवर्णं
पद्मसंमितम्॥बलिम् आदाय विविधं
द्वारि तिष्ठन्ति वारिताः॥) 2. 47. 26-27; they
are mentioned a third time along with
Aṅgas, Vaṅgas and others whose kings
(क्षत्रियाः) brought large amount of wealth
as tribute (आहार्षुः क्षत्रिया वित्तं शत-
शः); when asked by the gate-keepers to
give more, each one of them gave a thou-
sand elephants from the Kāmyaka lake and
then were allowed to enter; the elephants
given by them are described in stanzas 2.
48. 15-20; Kṛṣṇa mentioned Śakas among
those whose kings, afraid of the lustre of
the weapons of Pāṇḍavas, acted as servers
at the Rājasūya sacrifice (शकान्। … मही-
पालान् शस्त्रतेजोभयार्दितान्। … यज्ञे
ते परिवेषकान्) 3. 48. 18, 20, 22; (2)
Drupada asked Yudhiṣṭhira to send his
messengers to the kings of Śakas and others
to seek their help in war 5. 4. 7, 9, 15; (3)
Kāmboja Sudakṣiṇa came to Duryodhana
with an army of अक्षौहिणी fighters consi-
sting of Yavanas and Śakas; it looked like
a swarm of locusts (तस्य सेनासमावायः
शलभानाम् इवाबभौ) 5. 19. 21-22;
Duryodhana's army consisted of different
peoples, Śakas being one of them; like the
army of gods it was difficult to be attacked
(दुराधर्षां देवचमूप्रकाशाम्) 5. 158.
19-20; Śaka kings with their armies led
by Śakuni marched towards Kurukṣetra
in the second division of the Kaurava army
(शकाः … द्वितीये निर्ययुर् बले) 5. 196. 7;
there, on the battle-field, before the start of
the war, Kṛpa along with Śakas, Kirātas
and others protected the Kaurava army in
the north (चमूम् उत्तरतो ऽभिपाति) 6.
20. 13; (4) On the third day of the war,
the Kāmboja king along with the Śakas
was posted at the ‘tail’ (पुच्छम् आसन्) of
the Garuḍavyūha (6. 52. 2) of Kauravas
6. 52. 7; (5) On the sixth day, Śakas,
Yavanas and others stood at the right wing
(दक्षिणम् पक्षम् आश्रित्य) of the Krauñca-
vyūha (6. 71. 14) of the Kauravas 6. 71. 20;
(6) On the eleventh day, Śakas, Yavanas
and others riding swift horses stood at
the extreme end of the left wing (सव्यं
पार्श्वं … तेषां प्रपक्षाः … ययुर् अश्वैर्
महावेगैः) of the Śakaṭavyūha (7. 6. 15)
of Kauravas 7. 6. 4-5; (7) On the eleventh
day, Dhṛtarāṣṭra, while recounting past
exploits of Kṛṣṇa remembered his victory
over hordes of enemies consisting of Āvan-
tyas and others who came from different
directions and joined the Śakas riding
horses (?) (आवन्त्यान् … नानादिग्भ्यश् च
संप्राप्तान् व्रातान् अश्वशकान् प्रति।जितवान्
पुण्डरीकाक्षो … ) 7. 10. 16-18 (See Editor's
note on the stanza Vol. IX. pp. 1144-1145:
श्ब्र्। (शतपथ ब्राह्मण) appears to
use this word to signify ‘excrement of a
horse’! Here it seems to mean a particular
(disgusting ?) tribe of Śakas who were
horse-riders (cf. {#aSvapuruza#} in 6. 1. 7); (8)
On the twelfth day, Śakas were among
those who occupied the ‘neck’ (ग्रीवायाम्)
of the Suparṇavyūha (7. 19. 4) of Kaura-
vas 7. 19. 7-8; (9) On the fourteenth
day, fierce Śakas, Yavanas and others
formed innumerable hordes in hundreds
and thousands (व्राताः शतसहस्रशः) to
attack Arjuna; he fought them with arrows
and cut them off with his skill in shooting
arrows (अशातयत् … अस्त्रमायया); afraid,
they all fled 7. 68. 41-45; (10) The same
day, Sātyaki expected to encounter them in
his onward march towards Arjuna (शकैश्
चापि समेष्यामि) 7. 87. 50; Sātyaki asked
his charioteer to drive his chariot to Śakas
and other Mlecchas who, riding chariots
and elephants and holding different kinds
of weapons in their hands, were eager to
fight with him (माम् एवाभिमुखाः सर्वे
तिष्ठन्ति समरार्थिनः); Sātyaki was con-
fident to defeat them 7. 95. 13-14; in the
encounter that followed, Śakas and others
showered arrows on Sātyaki; he cut off
their arrows and killed them by thousands
covering the earth with their blood and
flesh; those who escaped death fled swiftly
in fright; Sātyaki thus defeated the large
army of Śakas 7. 95. 32-33, 38-39, 45;
three thousand horse-riders of Śakas and
others, led by Duryodhana, returned to
the battlefield to attack Sātyaki; he killed
many of them 7. 97. 13-14, 20; (11) On
the seventeenth day, Kāmbojas, Śakas and
Yavanas, led by Saṃśaptakas guarded the
extremity of the left side (वामं पार्श्वम्
अपालयन् … तेषां प्रपक्षः) of the Bārha-
spatyavyūha (8. 31. 26) of Kauravas 8. 31.
14-15; in the course of that day, after the
death of the younger brother of Kāmboja
Sudakṣiṇa, there was fierce fighting (घोरम्
अद्भुतदर्शनम्) in which Śakas riding
horses took part; a large number of them
were killed 8. 40. 107-110; later that day,
Kṛṣṇa in order to encourage Arjuna told him
that Śakas had joined the Kaurava army for
the sake of Duryodhana and no one else but
he (Arjuna) could defeat them (न शक्या
युधि निर्जेतुं त्वदन्येन परंतप) 8.
51. 18, 20; Śakas, who held excellent
weapons in their hands and were ready to
shoot arrows, riding horses, chariots and
elephants, rushed at Arjuna to kill him
(आततायिनः।शकास् … ॥वरायुधान् पाणिग-
तान्); Arjuna cut off their hands and heads,
killed their horses and elephants and broke
their chariots 8. 64. 16-17; (12) On the
seventeenth day, at night (निशि 8. 1. 25), when
Saṃjaya reported to Dhṛtarāṣṭra the death
of Karṇa, he while remembering the past
heroism of Karṇa mentioned that he had
formerly defeated Śakas and many others
and made them pay tribute (चक्रे बलिभृ-
तः पुरा) 8. 5. 18, 20 (reference to Karṇa's
दिग्विजय at the time of Duryodhana's
वैष्णवयज्ञ 3. 241. 19, 32 (Vol. 4. App.
I. 24. 28-34); (13) On the eighteenth
day, Kṛpa with Śakas and Yavanas stood
on the right side (दक्षिणे पार्श्वे) of the
Sarvatobhadravyūha (9. 7. 19) of Kaura-
vas 9. 7. 24; (14) At the end of the war,
Saṃjaya mentioned Śakas among those
who were killed in the war 9. 1. 26; Dhṛta-
rāṣṭra remembered that Śakas and others
had joined his side not caring for death
while fighting (मदर्थम् उद्यताः सर्वे
प्राणांस् त्यक्त्वा रणे); Duryodhana boast-
ed his ability to fight with Pāṇḍavas due to
the support of Śakas 9. 2. 8, 21-22.
E. Past
event: Māndhātṛ once asked Indra how
people like Śakas were to be made to follow
Dharma and how kings like him should
control them (कथं धर्मं चरेयुस् ते
 … मद्विधैश् च कथं स्थाप्याः); Indra
thereupon told Māndhātṛ the duties of
Dasyus (the term Dasyu apparently covered
Śakas) 12. 65. 13, 15, 17-21.
F. Future
event: Śakas are mentioned among many
kings who at the end of the Yuga (यु-
गान्ते समनुप्राप्ते) 3. 186. 30; युगान्ते 3.
186. 33; युगक्षये 3. 186. 43, 48) would
rule the earth the wrong way, would be
sinful and would be given to tell lies (मि-
थ्यानुशासिनः पापा मृषावादपरायणाः)
3. 186. 29-30.

शण्ड
Śaṇḍa m. (pl.): Name of a people.
Rākṣasa Kalmāṣapāda told a certain
king that Śaṇḍas were the bodily dirt of
Mauṣṭikas and those whose sacrificial
priests were of the warrior caste were the
dirt of Śaṇḍas (मौष्टिकानां मलं
शण्डाः शण्डानां राजयाजकाः) 8. 30. 70.

शबर
Śabara m. (pl.): Name of a forest
tribe.
A. Location: (1) Listed by Saṃjaya
among the northern Janapadas (also called
Deśas 6. 10. 68) of the Bhāratavarṣa (अत
ऊर्ध्वं जनपदान् निबोध) 6. 10. 37, 5;
अटवी शबराश् चैव 6. 10. 46 (Are Aṭavī-
śabaras living in the north different from
the other Śabaras who lived in the south ?
see the next); (2) Śabaras who lived in
the south (दक्षिणापथजन्मानः) 12. 200.
39 (these are, however, not listed by Saṃ-
jaya among the southern Janapadas of the
Bhāratavarṣa 6. 10. 56-63ab).
B. Origin:
(1) Angered Nandinī, the cow of Vasiṣṭha,
created Śabaras from her dung (असृजत् …
शकृतः शबरान् … क्रोधमूर्च्छिता) 1.
165. 35; this event is said to have occurred
also on a different occasion; when Viśvā-
mitra's army destroyed the forest near Vasi-
ṣṭha's आश्रम, he angered, asked his cow
to produce Śabaras; accordingly she pro-
duced them (क्रुद्धो … वसिष्ठः … ।
सृजस्व शबरान् घोरान् इति स्वां गाम् उवाच
ह) 9. 39. 20; (2) Some Kṣatriyas are
also said to have been degraded to the
state of a वृषल due to their disregard of
Brāhmaṇas (शबरबर्बराः॥ … तास् ताः
क्षत्रियजातयः।वृषलत्वम् अनुप्राप्ता
ब्राह्मणानाम् अदर्शनात्॥) 13. 35. 17-18;
elsewhere it is stated that the Kṣatriyas
who killed Jamadagni became वृषल due
to their transgressing the धर्म of Kṣa-
triyas and their disregard of Brāhmaṇas
(तेषां (i. e. क्षत्रियाणाम्)  … प्रजा वृषल-
तां प्राप्ता ब्राह्मणानाम् अदर्शनात्॥त
एते … पुण्ड्राश् च शबरैः सह।वृषलत्वं
परिगता व्युत्थानात् क्षत्रधर्मतः॥)
14. 29. 15-16; (3) But at one place it is
mentioned that Śabaras and others existed
since the Tretāyuga (त्रेताप्रभृति वर्तन्ते
ते जना …  (i. e. Śabaras and others) 12.
200. 39, 42.
C. Description: Fierce,
fierce to look at (घोर, घोरदर्शन) 9.
39. 20-21.
D. Their low status: They are
characterized as दस्युस् 12. 65. 17, 21; also
cf.
F. Past events (2) below; those men
who did not perform sacrifices remained
for ever in the nether worlds and did not
go to heaven; such men are compared with
Pulindas and Śabaras (अर्वाक् च प्रति-
तिष्ठन्ति पुलीन्दशबरा इव।न ह्य् अयज्ञा
अमुं लोकं प्राप्नुवन्ति कथंचन) 12.
147. 8; they are included among those
people who, though they lived in countries,
led the life of दस्युस् (शबरबर्बराः। …
सर्वे विषयवासिनः।सर्वे ते दस्युजीवि-
नः॥) 12. 65. 13, 15; they did not believe in
Bhūtapati as the अध्यक्ष (of the world);
sinful, they roamed over the earth leading
the life of dogs, crows, बलस् (?) and
vultures (निरध्यक्षांस् तु कौन्तेय कीर्त-
यिष्यामि … ।उत्साः पुलिन्दाः शबरा … ॥एते
पापकृतस् तात चरन्ति पृथिवीम् इमाम्।
श्वकाकबलगृध्राणां सधर्माणो … ॥)
12. 200. 38-39, 41.
E. Epic events:
(1) On the second day of the war,
Śabaras on the side of Pāṇḍavas stood on
the left side of the Krauñcāruṇavyūha (6.
46. 39; Krauñca 6. 47. 1) of Pāṇḍavas
(वामं पार्श्वं समाश्रिताः) 6. 46. 51;
(2) On the fourteenth day, Sātyaki
killed thousands of Śabaras (on the side
of Kauravas); he covered the ground
with their flesh and blood, and also with
their shaven heads and head gears (सशिर-
स्त्राणैः शिरोभिर् लूनमूर्धजैः) 7. 95.
38-40.
F. Past event: (1) King Mān-
dhātṛ once asked Indra the nature of the
धर्म of people like Śabaras and how
kings like him should govern them (कथं
धर्मं चरेयुस् ते … मद्विधैश् च
कथं स्थाप्याः) 12. 65. 13-15; thereupon
Indra told him the duties of Dasyus (the
term apparently covers Śabaras) 12. 65.
17-21; (2) A certain Brāhmaṇa, Gau-
tama by name, took residence in the house
of a Dasyu which is later designated as
the excellent house (गृहवर) of a rich,
Śabara (शबरालय) 12. 162. 30, 34; 12.
165. 5; 12. 167. 16 (see Dasyu, Past events
I, no. 7, p. 750 above).

शरदण्ड
Śaradaṇḍa m. (pl. ?): Name of a
country.
The horses of this country were referred
to as शरदण्डज; these horses were yoked
to the chariot of Daṇḍaketu (शरदण्डानु-
दण्डजाः। … दण्डकेतुम् उदावहन्) 7. 22.
58 [See Editor's note on the stanza, Cr.
Edn. Vol. 9, pp. 1147-1148: “ … Śaradaṇḍa
and Anudaṇḍa would be names of different
countries. We know nothing of Anudaṇḍa,
but Śaradaṇḍa was the name of a country
belonging to Śālva in Madhyadeśa (Kāśikā
on Pāṇini IV. 1. 173: शरदण्डाश् च शाल्वा-
वयवसंज्ञिताः)”].

शर्मक
Śarmaka m. (pl.): Name of a people.

भीम
Bhīma during his expedition to the
east (ययौ प्राचीं दिशम् प्रति 2. 26. 1;
2. 23. 9) before the Rājasūya won over
Śarmakas through conciliation (शर्मकान्
 … सान्त्वेनैवाजयत् प्रभुः) 2. 27. 12.

शर्मिल
Śarmila m. (pl.): Name of a people.
On the second day of war, Duryodhana
along with Śarmilas and others gave pro-
tection to the army of Śakuni (शर्मिल-
कोसलैः॥ … अभ्यरक्षत … सौबलेयस्य
वाहिनीम्) 6. 47. 15-16.

शाकद्वीप
Śākadvīpa nt. (sg.): Name of one of
the seven Dvīpas.
A. Location and extent: According
to Draupadī, it was similar to Krauñca-
dvīpa and lay to the east of Mahāmeru;
the Dvīpa known as Bhadrāśva which lay
to the north of Mahāmeru was in extent
equal to Śākadvīpa (क्रौञ्चद्वीपेन स-
दृशः शाकद्वीपो … ।पूर्वेण तु महा-
मेरोः … उत्तरेण महामेरोः शाकद्वीपेन
संमितः।भद्राश्वः … ॥) 12. 14 23-24;
according to Saṃjaya, Śākadvīpa was
double the size of Jambūdvīpa and the
ocean which surrounded it was also double
its size (जम्बूद्वीपप्रमाणेन द्विगुणः
स … ।विष्कम्भेण महाराज सागरोऽपि
विभागशः।क्षीरोदो भरतश्रेष्ठ येन
संपरिवारितः) 6. 12. 9; Śākadvīpa was
larger than Jambūdvīpa both in length
and breadth (परिवार्य तु कौरव्य दैर्-
घ्यं ह्रस्वत्वम् एव च।जम्बूद्वीपेन)
6. 12. 25.
B. Some geographical details of
the Śākadvīpa: There are seven mountains
on Śākadvīpa (Meru, Malaya, Jaladhāra,
Raivataka, Śyāma, Durgaśaila and Kesarī);
the mountains are described in 6. 12. 13-
21 (for which see Vol. I, section 5); the
Varṣas related to these mountains are
detailed in 6. 12. 22-24.
C. Possible
explanation of the name: A famous
big tree named Śāka stood in its middle
(that was why probably the Dvīpa was so
called) ( … विख्यातस् तस्य मध्ये महा-
द्रुमः॥शाको नाम महाराज तस्य
द्वीपस्य मध्यगः।) 6. 12. 25-26.
D. Description of the countries and the
peoples of Śākadvīpa: Highly lustrous
(महौजस्) 6. 12. 37; the Janapadas on
this Dvipa were holy; famine was not
known; the people were endowed with for-
bearance and lustre; they did not die (तत्र
पुण्या जनपदा (also 6. 12. 33) न तत्र
म्रियते जनः।कुत एव हि दुर्भिक्षं
क्षमातेजोयुता हि ते॥) 6. 12. 10; God
Śaṅkara was worshipped there (पूज्यते
तत्र शंकरः); Siddhas, Cāraṇas and
various deities visited it (तत्र गच्छन्ति
सिद्धाश् च चारणा दैवतानि च) 6. 12 26-
27; all the four kinds of subjects were
highly religious (धार्मिकाश् च प्रजा …
चत्वारो ऽतीव … ) 6. 12. 27; the Varṇas
followed their respective duties; they
were long-lived, free from oldage and
death; they multiplied like the rivers in
the rainy season (प्रजास् तत्र विवर्धन्ते
वर्षास्व् इव समुद्रगाः) 6. 12. 28-29;
no thief was ever met with there (न च
स्तेनोऽत्र दृश्यते) 6. 12. 28; there was
no king, no punishment, nor the officers to
inflict punishment (न तत्र राजा राजेन्द्र
न दण्डो न च दण्डिकाः); by following
their respective धर्मस् the people pro-
tected it and also protected one another
(स्वधर्मेणैव धर्मं च ते रक्षन्ति
परस्परम्) 6. 12. 36; the four holy Jana-
padas on the Dvīpa, honoured in the worlds
(लोकसंमताः), are known as Maga,
Maśaka, Mānasa and Mandaga; they are
described 6, 12. 33-36; the holy rivers
on the Śākadvīpa are Gaṅgā, flowing in
various streams (बहुधागतिः), Sukumārī,
Kumārī, Sītā, Kāverakā, Mahānadī, Maṇi-
jalā, and Ikṣuvardhanikā; several hundreds
and thousands of holy rivers arose from
them, from the waters of which Indra gave
rain (यतो वर्षति वासवः); it is not
possible to name them all nor to describe
their extent; all these excellent rivers are
holy (न तासां नामधेयानि परिमाणं
तथैव च।शक्यते परिसंख्यातुं
पुण्यास् ता हि सरिद्वराः) 6. 12. 29-32.
E. Epic events: (1) Dhṛtarāṣṭra asked
Saṃjaya to describe to him the Śāka-
dvīpa; Saṃjaya agreed and described it
in brief (शाकद्वीपस्य संक्षेपो … ) 6.
12. 2, 11; on Dhṛtarāṣṭra's further request
to describe the Dvīpa in details (विस्तरम्)
Saṃjaya described it in some detail which
was worth hearing (एतावद् एव श्रोतव्यम्);
that was about all that Saṃjaya could tell
about the Dvīpa 6. 12. 12, 37; (2) In
order to revive the spirits of Yudhiṣṭhira
after the war, Draupadī reminded him that
formerly he had passed through the ocean
and brought under control various large
Dvīpas including the Śākadvīpa and the
islands in-between and the Janapadas
situated on them (शाकद्वीपो … । … दण्डेन
मृदितस् त्वया; द्वीपाश् च सान्तरद्वीपा
नानाजनपदालयाः।विगाह्य सागरं वीर
दण्डेन मृदितास् त्वया) 12. 14. 23, 25 (a
reference to Arjuna's expedition before the
Rājasūya 2. 23. 15-16; Nīlakaṇṭha on Bom.
Ed. 12. 14. 23: क्रौञ्चद्वीपादिवशीकरणम्
सिद्धद्वारा (?) राजसूये).

शाकलावत्
Śākalāvat m. (pl.): People living in
the town Śākala.
Karṇa while deriding Śalya told him
what a certain Brāhmaṇa had once told
Dhṛtarāṣṭra (8. 30. 7, 28); according to him
the people of the town Śākala, young and
old, well-adorned, and their fair and large
women, ate meat of many rams mixed with
onions and गण्डूष (?), as also meat
of pigs, fowls, cows, asses and camels;
they said that the lives of those who did
not eat meat of sheep was futile; they
danced and sang songs of this nature
when they drank liquor; good conduct
was not expected of such people (ऐडं
च ये न खादन्ति तेषां जन्म निरर्थ-
कम्॥इति गायन्ति ये मत्ताः शीधुना
शाकलावतः।सबालवृद्धाः कूर्दन्तस्
तेषु वृत्तं कथं भवेत्॥) 8. 30. 31-
33; also cf. Śākala city p. 573).

शानवत्य
Śānavatya m. (pl.): Name of a
people.
Their Kṣatriyas brought wealth in
hundreds as tribute for the Rājasūya of
Yudhiṣṭhira (शानवत्या गयास् तथा। …
आहार्षुः क्षत्रिया वित्तं शतशोऽजातशत्रवे)
2. 48. 15-16; they and others were stopped
at the gate by gate-keepers and were asked
to give more to get entrance (कृतकाराः
सुबलयस् ततो द्वारम् अवाप्स्यथ); when
each one of them then gave one thousand
elephants from the Kāmyaka forest they
were allowed to enter (अभितः काम्यकं
सरः।दत्त्वैकैको दशशतान् कुञ्जरान्)
2. 48. 18-20; the elephants described in 2.
48. 19-20.

शाल्व
Śālva, Śālveya, Śālveyaka m. (pl.):
Name of a Janapada and its people; people
once referred to as शाल्वाश्रयाः 6. 114. 77.
A. Location: Listed by Saṃjaya
among the northern Janapadas of Bhārata-
varṣa (अत ऊर्ध्वं जनपदान् निबोध)
6. 10. 37, 5; (शाल्वमाद्रेयजाङ्गलाः) 6. 10.
37; designated as Janapada also in 4. 1.
9; 6. 18. 13-14; 6. 114. 77, and as Rāṣṭra
in 4. 1. 8; the Janapada lay around Kurus
(परितः कुरून्) 4. 1. 9.
B. Description:
(1) Of the Janapada: pleasant (रम-
णीय), (रम्य) 4. 1. 8-9; rich in food
(बह्वन्न) 4. 1. 9; well-protected (गुप्त)
4. 1. 8; (2) Of the warriors: brave
(शूर) and prepared to die while fighting
(तनुत्यज्) 6. 18. 14.
C. Epic events:
(1) Śālvas were among those peoples who,
afraid of Jarāsandha, had left north to take
shelter in the south; their (of Śālveyas)
kings also, along with their brothers and
followers, fled to the south (शाल्वाः पट-
च्चराः। … शाल्वेयानां च राजानः सोदर्या-
नुचरैः सह … तथोत्तरां दिशं चापि
परित्यज्य भयार्दिताः … दक्षिणां दिशम्
आश्रिताः) 2. 13. 25-27; (2) Jayadratha,
wanting to marry, was proceeding to the
country of Śālveyas (शाल्वेयान् प्रयातः सो
ऽभवत् तदा) 3. 248. 6; (3) Śālva was one
of the countries recommended by Arjuna to
Yudhiṣṭhira for their stay during the year
of अज्ञातवास 4. 1. 8-10; (4) Śālveyakas,
along with Matsyas led by Kīcaka, had
often subdued Suśarman, the king of Tri-
gartas (अस्कृन् निकृतः पूर्वं मत्स्यैः
शाल्वेयकैः सह) 4. 29. 2; (5) Saṃjaya
reported to Dhṛtarāṣṭra that Śālveyas were
among those who did not respect him any
longer and had gone to the side of Pāṇḍa-
vas (शाल्वेयाः … सर्वे त्वाम् अवजानते) 5.
53. 17; (6) According to Saṃjaya's
report, the five Kekaya brothers (on the
side of Pāṇḍavas) were supposed to engage
the Śālvas and Kekayas (both, on the
side of Kauravas) in the forthcoming war
(राजपुत्रा भ्रातरः पञ्च केकयाः। …
योत्स्यन्ति संयुगे॥तेषाम् एव कृतो भागो
 … शाल्वकेकयाः।) 5. 56. 17-18; (7) Ulūka
informed Yudhiṣṭhira that Duryodhana's
army, which included Śālvas and others
and was protected by their kings, had be-
come unassailable and had become like the
army of the gods (दुराधर्षां देवचमू-
प्रकाशां) 5. 158. 19-20; (8) Bhīṣma had
assured Duryodhana that he alone would
kill the Pāṇḍava army along with Śālve-
yakas; that was his responsibility (अहं
हन्ता पाण्डवानाम् अनीकं शाल्वेयकांश्
चेति ममैष भारः) 5. 160. 10; (9) On
the battle-field before the start of the war,
Śālvas were among the twelve Janapadas,
whose twenty thousand chariot-fighters
(रथा विंशतिसाहस्राः), offered protection
to Bhīṣma (द्वादशैते जनपदाः … महता
रथवंशेन तेऽभ्यरक्षन् पितामहम्)
6. 18. 12-14; (10) On the first day of
the war, Śālvas led by Jayadratha and other
heroes, were stationed in the middle of the
army (शाल्वा मत्स्याः … सर्वसैन्यस्य
मध्ये) 6. 20. 12; (11) On the fifth
day, Sātyaki, Cekitāna and Abhimanyu
attacked Śālvas and Kekayas 6. 68. 8;
(12) On the tenth day, the chariot-fighters
(महारथाः) of Śālvas and others, insti-
gated by Duryodhana (6. 112. 102-106),
attacked Arjuna; Arjuna burnt them with
heavenly missiles (दिव्यान्य् अस्त्राणि सं-
चिन्त्य … ददाह); afflicted by Arjuna's
arrows and their chariots and banners
broken (विप्रकीर्णरथध्वजाः), they did
not attack Arjuna (नाभ्यवर्तन्त … वानर-
ध्वजम्); he scattered their army (द्राव-
यित्वा वरूथिनीम्) (6. 112. 110-117); later,
the same day, just before the fall of Bhīṣma,
Śālvas were among the twelve Janapadas
who, though they were afflicted by arrows
and pained due to wounds (शरार्ता व्रण-
पीडिताः) did not abandon Bhīṣma fighting
with Arjuna, even when the Kaurava
army fled due to fear (वयं … भीताः …
प्रद्रवाम महारणात्; … शाल्वाश्रयास् …
द्वादशैते जनपदाः शरार्ता व्रणपीडिताः।
संग्रामे न जहुर् भीष्मं युध्यमानं
किरीटिना) 6. 114. 75-77; (13) On the
fourteenth day, Matsyas along with the
armies of Śālveyas, led by Dhṛṣṭadyumna
and Virāṭa, speedily attacked Droṇa (मत्-
स्याः शाल्वेयसेनाश् च द्रोणम् आजग्मुर्
अञ्जसा) 7. 73. 50; in the evening of that
day (सायाह्ने 7. 129. 5), they again
attacked Droṇa 7. 129. 7; (14) On the
sixteenth day, Śālvas were among those
who attacked Arjuna showering him with
arrows; although they were getting killed,
they did not leave Arjuna as the moths
the fire (समरे नाजहुः पाण्डवं
तदा। … शलभा इव पावकम्) 8. 19. 2-3,
7; (15) On the seventeenth day, Karṇa
told Śalya what a certain Brāhmaṇa had
once told Dhṛtarāṣṭra; according to him,
Śālvas knew what the eternal धर्म was
(धर्मं जानन्ति शाश्वतम्); he told Śalya
that Śālvas knew what the speaker intend-
ed to convey only when all details were
told to them (अर्धोक्ताः कुरुपाञ्चालाः
शाल्वाः कृत्स्नानुशासिनः) 8. 30. 8, 60-61,
79.
F. Past event: (1) King Dyumat-
sena once ruled the Śālvas until he became
blind 3. 278. 7; after some years his
subjects approached him in the forest to
request him to rule over them once again
(ततः प्रकृतयः सर्वाः शाल्वेभ्यो ऽभ्या-
गता … ) 3. 283. 3, 5.
G. Several kings
referred to as king of Śālvas (or Śālveyas):
A. King of Śālvas: (a) शाल्वपति: (1)
King of Śālvas (whom Ambā had first
chosen as her husband) not named 5. 171.
6; 5. 172. 2, 4, 10, 14. 18; 5. 174. 3; 5. 175.
22; 5. 176. 34; (2) Śālva, the king of
Saubha (the city flying in the sky) 3. 17. 8;
(b) शाल्वराज: (1) Śālva, the king of
Saubha (1. 96. 48), 1. 96. 25, 27, 32; 3.
17. 9, 10; 3. 18. 18; 3. 20. 22; 3. 21. 6, 8;
3. 23. 2, 27; 5. 47. 73; (2) King of Śālvas
(whom Ambā had first chosen as her hus-
band) 5. 171. 9; 5. 173. 6; 5. 176. 7, 11,
35; (3) A certain king (named Ugra-
karman ? Maheṣvāsa ?) fighting from the
side of Kauravas (उग्रकर्मा महेष्वासो
नामतः कर्मतस् तथा) 8. 4. 40; (4)
Dyutimant, a king of the past, who gave
away his kingdom to Ṛcīka 12. 226. 33;
(c) शाल्वराजन्: Śālva, the king of Saubha
1. 96. 37, 38; (d) शाल्वक: certain kings
who had joined the Kaurava army, not
specified 5. 30. 23;
B. King of Śālveyas:
शाल्वेयानाम् अधिप-; Virāṭa 5. 22. 18.

शाल्वेय
Śālveya, Śālveyaka: See Śālva.

शिनि
Śini, Śaineya m. (pl.): Name of a
people (descendants of Śini), a section of
the Yādavas.
A. Characteristic: Śaineyas, as well as
Andhakas and others, by following the coun-
sel of Kṛṣṇa, had tamed their enemies and
delighted their friends (शैनेया हि चैत्रकाश्
चान्धकाश् च … उपासीना वासुदेवस्य बुद्-
धिं निगृह्य शत्रून् सुहृदो नन्दयन्ति॥)
5. 28. 11.
B. Epic event: Śaineyas,
along with Andhakas and others, as dict-
ated by Kāla, killed one another while
fighting among themselves with pestles; the
एरका blade of grass which they held in hand
turned into a pestle appearing like वज्र
(ततो ऽन्धकाश् च … शैनेया … ।जघ्नुर्
अन्योन्यम् आक्रन्दे मुसलैः कालचोदिताः॥;
यस् तेषाम् एरकां कश्चिद् जग्राह … ।वज्र-
भूतेव सा राजन्न् अदृश्यत … ॥तृणं च
मुसलीभूतम् अपि तत्र व्यदृश्यत।) 16.
4. 36-38.
C. Sātyaki is variously desig-
nated with reference to Śinis or Śaineyas:
A. King of Śinis: शिनीनाम् अधिप- 5. 47.
41;
B. The chief (ऋषभ, पुंगव,
वृषभ) of Śinis: (a) शिनीनाम् ऋष्भ-
7. 89. 30; 7 115. 3; 8. 60. 23; (b) शिनि-
पुंगव 5. 154. 10; 6. 54. 22; 6. 107. 3;
7. 60. 27; 7. 72. 32; 7. 85. 40, 42, 97; 7.
86. 2; 7. 87. 1; 7. 92. 43; 7. 93. 7; 7. 94.
3, 8; 7. 96. 13, 30, 35; 7. 97. 35; 7. 115.
14; 7. 116. 33; 7. 117. 2, 23; 7. 137. 30; 7.
147. 11; 7. 157. 36; 7. 164. 24, 28, 153; 7.
169. 46, 52; 8. 31. 34; 9. 16. 73; 9. 20. 9,
13, 18, 21, 23, 28; 9. 26. 3; (c) शिनिवृषभ
8. 21. 10-11;
C. Delighter of Śaineyas:
शैनेयनन्दन 7. 102. 16;
D. Excellent
of Śinis or the excellent chariot-fighter of
Śinis: (a) शिनिप्रवर 7. 99. 8; (b) शिनी-
नां प्रवर-रथ। 7. 89. 39; E. Excellent
warrior of Śinis: शिनिप्रवीर 3. 120. 27;
5. 2. 13; 6. 55. 77-78, 82; 6. 59. 24; 7. 94.
1, 14; 7. 115. 9; 8. 21. 9; 8. 60. 6, 26; 9. 19.
25; 14. 51. 56.

शिबि
Śibi, (Śaibya) m. (pl.): Name of a
Janapada (6. 18. 14; 6. 114. 77) and its
people.
A. Location: To the west of Khā-
ṇḍavaprastha (see Epic event No. 1. below).
B. Description: Brave (शूर), ready to
die in battle (तनुत्यज्,) 6. 18. 14; honoured
by brave (शूरसंमत) 7. 66. 39; noble
(आर्य) 7. 68. 3; excellent chariot-fighters
(रथोदार) 8. 4. 37 (Nī., however, in a
different context, on Bom. Ed. 5. 165. 19;
रथोदारः रथेष्व् एव उदारो न तु महा-
रथः).
C. Epic events: (1) Nakula in
his expedition before the Rājasūya went to
the west of Khāṇḍavaprastha or Indra-
prastha (खाण्डवप्रस्थात् प्रतीचीम् अभितो
दिशम् 2. 29. 2; 2. 23. 19) and subjugated
Śibis 2. 29. 6; their Kṣatriyas (राजन्याः,
क्षत्रियाः) brought tribute in hundreds
for Yudhiṣṭhira's Rājasūya (आहार्षुः
 … वित्तं … शतशो … ) 2. 48. 13, 16);
(2) At the time of Jayadratha's attempt
to abduct Draupadī, his army, consist-
ing of Śibis and others, was dejected
when it saw Pāṇḍavas facing them; in the
battle that followed, Arjuna killed Śibi
and other chiefs who came within the
range of his arrows (शिबिसिन्धुत्रिगर्तानां
विषादश् चाप्य् अजायत; शिबिन् … जघान …
बाणगोचरम् आगतान्) 3. 255. 3, 28; (3)
Led by Bhīṣma and Aśvatthāman, Śibis
left Hāstinapura for Kurukṣetra in the
second division of the army (द्वितीये निर्-
ययुर् बले) 5. 196. 8; (4) Before the
start of the war, Śibis were among the
twelve Janapadas in the army of Kauravas
who in a large number of chariots guarded
the rear of Bhīṣma (पृष्ठगोपास् तु भी-
ष्मस्य … द्वादशैते जनपदाः … महता
रथवंशेन तेऽभ्यरक्षन् पितामहम्॥)
6. 18. 10, 12, 14; (5) On the second day
of war, Śibis and others protected Droṇa
in the Mahāvyūha of Kauravas (6. 47. 10,
14); (6) On the ninth day, Śibis and
others, though they were hit by sharp
arrows, did not abandon Bhīṣma; on the
other hand, they attacked Pāṇḍavas (सं-
ग्रामे नाजहुर् भीष्मं वध्यमानाः शितैः
शरैः। … पाण्डवान् अभ्यवर्तन्त) 6. 102.
7-8; (7) On the tenth day, Śibis and
others, incited by Duryodhana (6. 112.
102-107), attacked Arjuna; he burnt them
with his divine weapons (दिव्यान्य् अस्त्राणि
संचिन्त्य) and covered the earth with
their bodies as they fell down from their
chariots or from their horses and elephants;
those who survived fled 6. 112. 109-117;
the same day, when the Kaurava army
was running away, Śibis and other eleven
Janapadas did not abandon Bhīṣma though
they were struck with arrows and were
pained due to wounds (द्वादशैते जनपदा
शरार्ता व्रणपीडिताः।संग्रामे न जहुर्
भीष्मम्) 6. 114. 76-77; (8) On the
eleventh day, Śibis were among those who
led by Kṛpa and others protected the ex-
tremity (प्रपक्ष) of the left side (सव्यं
पार्श्वम् अपालयन्) of the Śakaṭavyūha of
Kauravas 7. 6. 4-6, 15; (9) On the
fourteenth day, Śibis and others making a
total of ten thousand chariot-fighters help-
ed Jaya and Kṛtavarman who tried to
check Arjuna proceeding towards Jaya-
dratha; they were willing to give up their
lives while fighting with Arjuna (त्यक्ता-
त्मानो ऽर्जुनं प्रति); as a result, a fierce
battle was fought 7. 66. 34-42; the battle
is described in 7. 67. 1-5; when Sudakṣiṇa
and Śrutāyudha were killed, angered Śibis
and others showered arrows on Arjuna;
Arjuna killed sixty hundred of them
(षष्टिशतान् आर्यान्); afraid, they ran away;
however, they returned only to get killed
by Arjuna 7. 68. 2-6; after the death
of Jayadratha, dejected Duryodhana told
Droṇa that since Śibis and others were
killed he would like to retire from battle
and give up his life 7. 125. 31-32; Saṃjaya,
in this context, mentioned Karṇa's former
victory over Śibis and others (कर्णेन
विजिताः पूर्वं संग्रामे) 7. 66. 39 (a
reference by Saṃjaya to Karṇa's conquest
of different peoples before the Vaiṣṇava-
yajña of Duryodhana 3. 241. 32 and Vol.
IV (Āraṇyakaparvan Part 2) App. I. 24,
pp. 1078-79; (10) In the night war,
Yudhiṣṭhira killed many Śibis in spite of
Droṇa and Kauravas 7. 132. 22-23; 7.
136. 3; Karṇa, on hearing the sound of
Arjuna's bow, guessed that he must have
killed all Śibis (एष सर्वाञ् शिबीन् हत्वा)
7. 145. 46; (11) On the fifteenth day,
Dhṛṣṭadyumna scattered away (व्यध-
मत्) Śibis and others who fought to
protect Droṇa 7. 165. 24; (12) On the
sixteenth day, Trigartas along with Śibis
and many others attacked Arjuna and
showered numerous arrows on him; though
they were being destroyed by Arjuna, they
did not give up fighting with him 8. 19.
2, 5-7; (13) On the seventeenth day,
after the death of Karṇa, Saṃjaya return-
ed to Hāstinapura at night (निशि 8. 1. 25)
and while reporting to Dhṛtarāṣṭra named
Śibis among those who were killed in war
8. 4. 37.
C. Past event: King Uśīnara
of Śibis offered the hawk (Indra) the
prosperous kingdom of Śibis in lieu of the
dove (Agni) (राज्यं शिबीनाम् ऋद्धं … )
3. 131. 20.
D. Certain persons referred
to with words expressive of their relation-
ship with king Śibi or Śibi people:
A.
Son of Śibi: (i) शिबिपुत्र: Gopati 12.
49. 70; (ii) शिबिसूनु: Vṛṣādarbhi 13. 94.
8; (also see शैब्य C below);
B. Pro-
minent among Śibis: शिबीनां प्रवर-;
Koṭikāśya (also see शैब्य C below);
C. Related to Śibis: (i) शैब्य: (1) Koṭi-
kāśya (son of Suratha) 3. 250. 4-5; 3. 251.
1, 4; (2) Govāsana 1. 90. 83; 6. 17. 20;
7. 70. 38; 7. 71. 11; (3) Vṛṣādarbhi (son
of Śibi) 13. 94. 12 (8); (4) Auśīnara
(son of Uśīnara = Śibi) 3. 120. 2. (cf. 1.
88. 6, 18); 7. 9. 65 (62); 12. 29. 38; 12.
281, 8 (?); (5) Grandson of Śaibya Auśī-
nara (i. e. Śibi), not named 7. 9. 66; (6)
Not identified 1. 1. 167 (= Auśīnara ?); 1.
1. 170; 3. 13. 27; (7) The following very
probably refer to the same king (= Govā-
sana, see above) fighting from the side of
Pāṇḍavas 4. 67. 16; 5. 161. 6; 6. 23. 5; 6.
46. 54; 6. 47. 27; (8) The king on the
side of Kauravas 6. 95. 27; (ii) शैब्या
(f.): (1) Sunandā, wife of Pratīpa 1. 90.
46; (2) Wife of Kṛṣṇa, not named 16. 8.
71; (3) Wife of Dyumatsena, not named
3. 282. 2, 26; 3. 283. 10; (4) Wife of
Sagara, not named 3. 104. 8 (6), 17; 3.
106. 10; (iii) Kāśipati, son of Śaibyā (?),
not named, on the side of Kauravas:
(शैब्यात्मजः काशिपतिः) 7. 7. 25.

शिव
Śiva m. (pl.): Name of a certain
group of Brāhmaṇas.
They lived in the south; they are de-
scribed as सिद्ध; they were well-versed in
the Vedas; they studied the Vedas along
with their supplements and then went to
the abode of Yama (इयं … दक्षिणेत्य्
उच्यतेऽथ दिक्) 5. 107. 1; (अत्र सिद्धाः
शिवा नाम ब्राह्मणा वेदपारगाः।अधीत्य
सखिलान् वेदान् आलभन्ते यमक्षयम्॥)
5. 107. 18.

शूकर
Śūkara m. (pl.): Name of a certain
country (and its people).
Their king, Kṛtin, gave as tribute to
Yudhiṣṭhira for his Rājasūya many hun-
dreds of excellent elephants (कृती तु राजा
 … शूकराणां … ।अददद् गजरत्नानां
शतानि सुबहून्य् अपि॥) 2. 48. 24 (Nī. on
Bom. Ed. 2. 52. 25: शूकराः देशभेदास्
तेषाम्; however, see Edgerton's note on
this stanza; {#“SUkara”#} epithet of elephants;
 … cf. Kirfel, कोस्मोग्रफिए, p. 329, Cr.
Edn. Vol. II, p. 507).

शूद्र
Śūdra m. (pl.): Name of a Janapada
and its people.
A. Location: Listed by Saṃjaya, first,
among the northern Janapadas (also called
Deśas 6. 10. 68) of the Bhāratavarṣa (अत
ऊर्ध्वं जनपदान् निबोध) 6. 10. 37, 5.
(अपरन्ध्राश् च शूद्राश् च) 6. 10. 46;
listed by him a second time among the
northern Mleccha people (उत्तराश् चापरे
म्लेच्छा जना … शूद्राभीराथ दरदाः)
6. 10. 63, 66; some Śūdras lived also in
the west near the river Sarasvatī (शूद्रा-
भीरगणाश् चैव ये चाश्रित्य सरस्वतीम्)
2. 29. 9 (see the Epic event No. 1 below).
B. Their nature and way of living:
They were harsh and were counted among
Mleccha people (दारुणा म्लेच्छजातयः)
6. 10. 64; (also cf. A. Location above
and E. Future event below) they lived
on fish, since they lived near the river
Sarasvatī (वर्तयन्ति च मत्स्यैर् … ) 2.
29. 9.
C. Epic events: (1) Nakula
in his expedition to the west of Khā-
ṇḍavaprastha (निर्याय खाण्डवप्रस्थात्
प्रतीचीम् अभितो दिशम्) 2. 29. 2; 2. 23.
10) brought them under control (शूद्रा-
भीरगणाश् चैव … वशे चक्रे) 2. 29. 9-10;
(2) On the eleventh day of war, Śūdras
were among those who guarded at the
extreme end (प्रपक्षाः) of the left side
of the Śakaṭavyūha (7. 6. 15) of Kauravas
(सव्यं पार्श्वम् अपालयन्) 7. 6. 4, 6.
D. Past event: The river Sarasvatī for-
merly disappeared at the Vinaśana tīrtha
due to her hatred of Śūdras and Ābhīras
(विनशनं नाम … शूद्राभीरान् प्रति द्वे-
षाद् यत्र नष्टा सरस्वती) 9. 36. 1.
E.
Future event: Mārkaṇḍeya predicted that
in the Kali age there would be many
Mleccha kings among whom some would
be Śūdras: these kings would be sinful,
given to lies and ruling the wrong way
(बहवो म्लेच्छराजानः पृथिव्यां … ।
मिथ्यानुशासिनः पापा मृषावादपरायणाः॥
 … शूद्रास् तथाभीरा … ) 3. 186. 29-30.

शूर
Śūra m. (pl): Name of a people.
A. Location: Śūras lived probably in
the north-west and were different from the
Śūrasenas since they are mentioned along
with Daradas, Bāhlīkas and others and since
they are said to have brought tribute for the
Rājasūya (see Epic event No. 1 below)
and also because they are grouped with
Yavanas (see B below).
B. Special
characteristic: According to a certain
Brāhmaṇa reporting to Dhṛtarāṣṭra in the
assembly of Kurus (8. 30. 7, 58), Śūras,
like Yavanas, had the special characteristic
of being clever in knowing everything
(even though what was to be conveyed
was not expressed in so many words)
(सर्वज्ञा यवना राजञ् शूराश् चैव विशे-
षतः) 8. 30. 80.
C. Epic event: The
Kṣatriyas among the Śūras, along with
Vāyavyas and others, brought wealth in
hundreds as tribute for the Rājasūya of
Yudhiṣṭhira (आहार्षुः क्षत्रिया वित्तं शतशो
ऽजातशत्रवे) 2. 48. 12, 16; (Vṛṣṇis and
Andhakas, however, who like Śūrasenas,
are sections of Yādavas, are reported to
have not given tribute for the Rājasūya
2. 48. 42).

शूरसेन
Śūrasena m. (pl.): Name of a Jana-
pada and its people; called Janapada at
various places (4. 1. 9; 6. 18. 14; 6. 114.
77) and once Rāṣṭra (4. 1. 8).
A. Location: Listed by Saṃjaya
among the northern Janapadas (also called
Deśas 6. 10. 68) of Bhāratavarṣa (अत
ऊर्ध्वं जनपदान् निबोध) 6. 10. 37, 5;
(शूरसेनाः कलिङ्गाश् च) 6. 10. 38; the
country lay around the Kurus (परितः
कुरून्) 4. 1. 9; Pāṇḍavas while proceed-
ing from Dvaitavana (3. 295. 2-3) to the
country of Matsyas had to pass through
Yakṛlloma and Śūrasena; their way lay to
the north of Daśārṇa and south of Pāñcāla
(उत्तरेण दशार्णांस् ते पाञ्चालान् दक्षिणेन
तु॥अन्तरेण यकृल्लोमाञ् शूरसेनांश् च
पाण्डवाः। … मत्स्यस्य विषयं प्राविशन्
वनात्) 4. 5. 3-4; the city of Mathurā
lay in it 2. 13. 44.
B. Description:
(a) of the country: delightful (रम्य),
(रमणीय), rich in grain (बह्वन्न), and
protected (गुप्त) 4. 1 8-9; (b) of the
warriors: strong (बलवन्त्) and great
chariot-fighters (महारथ) 6. 112. 107,
111; valorous (विक्रान्त) 8. 4. 36; heroic,
ready to give away their life (in war) (शूर,
तनुत्यज्) 6. 18. 14; (शूर, वीर) 8. 32. 17.
C. Characteristic: A certain Brāhmaṇa
while reporting the characteristics of diffe-
rent peoples to the Kuru assembly said that
Śūrasenas were sacrifice incarnate (i. e. as
sanctifying as sacrifice) (शूरसेनाश् च
यज्ञः) 8. 30. 73.
D. Epic events:
(1) Śūrasenas, due to fear of Jarāsandha,
resorted to the west (जरासन्धभयाद् एव
प्रतीचीं दिशं आश्रिताः।शूरसेना … ) 2.
13. 24-25; (2) Having heard the news
of the death of Haṃsa and Ḍibhaka, Jarā-
sandha (left the country) of Śūrasenas to
return to his town in Magadha (जरासन्-
धः … स्वपुरं शूरसेनानां प्रययौ)
2. 13. 43; (See Edgerton's note on the
stanza in Vol. II, p. 496: “This latter
reading (°सेनेभ्यः) confirms my inter-
pretation of शूरसेनानां as ablative
genitive (Speyer, व्। स्। स्। § ७३) in the sense
of “from the Śūrasena country””); (3)
Sahadeva in his expedition to the south of
Indraprastha (प्रययौ दक्षिणां दिशम् 2.
28. 1; 2. 23. 9) first conquered the entire
land of Śūrasenas (स शूरसेनान् कार्त्स्-
न्येन पूर्वम् एवाजयत् प्रभुः) 2. 28. 2;
(4) Arjuna mentioned Śūrasena among the
countries in which Pāṇḍavas could stay
during their अज्ञातवास 4. 1. 9; (5) Saṃ-
jaya told Dhṛtarāṣṭra that Śūrasenas no
longer respected him and that they had
joined the side of Yudhiṣṭhira recognizing
his heroism (वीर्यज्ञास् तस्य धीमतः)
5. 53. 17; (6) Before the start of the
war, Śūrasenas (who went to Kauravas)
were among the twelve Janapadas who,
led by Duḥśāsana and other sons of
Dhṛtarāṣṭra, guarded the rear of Bhīṣma;
they were all chariot-fighters twenty thou-
sand strong (पृष्ठगोपास् तु भिष्मस्य
 … रथा विंशतिसाहस्राः; महता रथ-
वंशेन ते ऽभ्यरक्षन् पितामहम्) 6.
18. 10, 12, 14; (7) On the second day
of the war, in the Mahāvyūha (6. 47. 10)
of Kauravas Duryodhana asked Śūrasenas
and others to protect Bhīṣma with their
armies (भीष्मम् एवाभिरक्षन्तु सह
सैन्यपुरस्कृताः) 6. 47. 7, 9; Arjuna while
proceeding to attack Bhīṣma killed many
Śūrasenas in the Kaurava army 6. 48. 19;
(8) On the third day, all Śūrasenas were
posted at the ‘tail’ of the Garuḍavyūha
(6. 52. 2-3) of Kauravas (पुच्छम् आसन् …
शूरसेनाश् च सर्वशः) 6. 52. 7; (9) On
the ninth day, Śūrasenas were among those
who did not forsake Bhīṣma in the battle
although they were being killed by sharp
arrows (संग्रामे नाजहुर् भीष्मं वध्य-
मानाः शितैः शरैः) 6. 102. 7; (10) On
the tenth day, incited by Duryodhana to
attack Arjuna Śūrasenas marched on him;
Arjuna burnt (ददाह) them with his divine
weapons; when afflicted by arrows and
when their chariots and banners were sha-
ttered, their kings stopped attacking Arjuna
(शरार्ता … विप्रकी र्णरथध्वजाः।नाभ्य-
वर्तन्त राजानः सहिता वानरध्वजम्);
Arjuna scattered their army (6. 112. 102-
106, 109-112, 114-116); towards the end
of that day, when the Kaurava army, afraid
of Arjuna, fled from the battle, Śūrasenas
were among those twelve Janapadas who,
though afflicted by arrows and pained due
to wounds, did not abandon Bhīṣma fighting
with Arjuna (शूरसेनाः … द्वादशैते जन-
पदा शरार्ता व्रणपीडिताः।संग्रामे न
जहुर् भीष्मं युध्यमानं किरीटिना॥)
6. 114. 76-77; (11) On the eleventh day,
Śūrasenas and others led by Duryodhana
marched behind Karṇa in the Śakaṭavyūha
(7. 6. 15) of Kauravas (तवात्मजं पुरस्-
कृत्य सूतपुत्रस्य पृष्ठतः) 7. 6. 6-7;
(12) On the twelfth day, Śūrasenas and
others riding elephants, horses and chariots
along with their foot-soldiers in hundreds
and thousands stood at the ‘neck’ of the
Suparṇavyūha of Kauravas (ग्रीवायां शूर-
सेनाश् च … गजाश्वरथपत्त्यौघास् तस्थुः
शतसहस्रशः) 7. 19. 8; (13) On the
fourteenth day, ten thousand chariot-war-
riors of Śūrasenas and others, led by Jaya
and Kṛtavarman, tried to check the onward
march of Arjuna towards Jayadratha 7. 66.
37; later, when Sudakṣiṇa and Śrutāyudha
were killed, angered Śūrasenas and others,
showered arrows on Arjuna; he killed six
thousand of them; afraid, they fled, but
returned and surrounded Arjuna; Arjuna
cut off their arms and heads 7. 68. 2-5;
towards the end of the day, while lamenting
the death of Jayadratha, Duryodhana men-
tioned Śūrasenas among those who fought
for him but were killed by Arjuna (हता
मदर्थं संग्रामे युध्यमानाः किरी-
टिना) 7. 125. 31-32; (14) During the
night war between the fourteenth and the
fifteenth day, Yudhiṣṭhira and Bhīma killed
Śūrasenas 7. 132. 24; 7. 136. 4; (15) On
the seventeenth day, Kṛpa and others
fought with Śūrasenas (on Pāṇḍavas' side);
they fought a battle which led them to
heaven in case of death (तेषाम् अन्तकरं
 … स्वर्ग्यं यशस्करम्) 8. 32. 17-18;
(16) At night, on the seventeenth day
(निशि) while reporting the death of Karṇa
to Dhṛtarāṣṭra (8. 1. 25-26) Saṃjaya
mentioned Śūrasenas among those who
were killed in war 8. 4. 36.
E. King
Sunāman brother of Kaṃsa is referred to
as king of Śūrasenas: शूरसेनराज् 7. 10. 8.

शृङ्गिन्
Śṛṅgin nara m. (pl.): Characterization
of a people (not named).
‘Horned men’ mentioned along with
Śakas, Tukhāras, Kaṅkas and Romaśas,
who brought tribute for the Rājasūya of
Yudhiṣṭhira in the form of an अर्बुद horses
whose pedigree was noble and who went
long distances; they also brought gold in
crores totalling a पद्म; even then they
were stopped at the gate (शकास् तुखाराः
 … शृङ्गिणो नराः।महागमान् दूरगमान्
गणितान् अर्बुदं हयान्॥कोटिशश् चैव
बहुशः सुवर्णं पद्मसंमितम्।बलिम्
आदाय विविधं द्वारि तिष्ठन्ति वारिताः॥)
2. 47. 26-27.

शैनेय
Śaineya: See Śini.

शैब्य
Śaibya: See Śibi.

शैवल
Śaivala m. (pl.): Name of a Janapada.
Listed by Saṃjaya among the northern
Janapadas (also called Deśas 6. 10. 68) of
Bhāratavarṣa (अत ऊर्ध्वं जनपदान्
निबोध) 6. 10. 37, 5; (शैवला बाह्लिकास्
तथा) 6. 10. 52.

शौण्डिक
Śauṇḍika m. (pl.): Name of a people.
A. Epic event: Their chiefs (क्षत्रि-
याः) brought tribute in hundreds for the
Rājasūya of Yudhiṣṭhira; at the instance of
the king, they were stopped at the gate by
the gatekeepers and were asked to give more
tribute; when each one of them further
gave elephants (their description 2. 48. 19-
20), they were allowed to enter (आहार्षुः
क्षत्रिया वित्तं शतशोऽजातशत्रवे। … तत्र
स्म द्वारपालैस् ते प्रोच्यन्ते राजशासनात्।
कृतकाराः सुबलयस् ततो द्वारम् अवाप्-
स्यथ॥) 2. 48. 15-16, 18-20 (Nī., Bom.
Ed. 2. 52. 19: reads कृतकालाः and expla-
ins the word as कृतप्रस्तावाः and remarks
कृतद्वारा इति पाठे द्वारम् प्रतीहारेण
सख्यम्।).
B. Their low social status:
Originally Kṣatriyas, Śauṇḍikas were de-
graded to the status of a वृषल due to
their disregard of Brāhmaṇas (तास् ताः
क्षत्रियजातयः।वृषलत्वम् अनुप्राप्ता
ब्राह्मणानाम् अदर्शनात्॥) 13. 33. 15.
17-19.

श्रेणि
Śreṇi m. (pl.): Name of a people (?)
A. Description: Brought up in cow-
herds (गोकुले नित्यसंवृद्धाः) and
highly skilled in fighting (युद्धे परम-
कोविदाः) 8. 4. 38.
B. Epic event: At
night of the seventeenth day (निशि 8. 1.
25), Saṃjaya, while reporting the death
of Karṇa to Dhṛtarāṣṭra, mentioned
Śreṇis among those who were killed in
thousands by Arjuna during the war
(श्रेणयो बहुसाहस्राः संशप्तकगणाश्
च ये।ते सर्वे पार्थम् आसाद्य गता
वैवस्वतक्षयम्॥) 8. 4. 38 (perhaps,
the word श्रेणि does not refer to a people
but means only ‘lines, rows of troops’ and
refers to Gopālas who, though not directly
mentioned are suggested by the expression
(गोकुले नित्यसंवृद्धाः) and by their
association with Saṃśaptakas, cf. Gopāla;
see, however, the next entry).

श्रेणिमत्|श्रेणिमन्त्
Śreṇimant m. (pl.): Name of a
people (?)
Their glorious Kṣatriyas of noble
birth, with weapons in hand, brought
tribute in hundreds for the Rājasūya
of Yudhiṣṭhira (सुजातयः श्रेणिमन्तः
श्रेयांसः शस्त्रपाणयः।आहार्षुः क्षत्रिया
वित्तं शतशो ऽजातशत्रवे॥) 2. 48. 16
(for other details of the tribute see Śau-
ṇḍika above). (Is Śreṇimant name of a
people or an adjective of Kṣatriyas mean-
ing ‘Kṣatriyas in troops’ ? See Sreṇi
above).

श्वेत
Śveta1 nt. (sg.): Name of a Varṣa of
Jambudvīpa.
It lay to the north of the Nīla Varṣa
(and the Śveta mountain); and to the
south of the Hairaṇyaka Varṣa (and the
Śṛṅgin mountain) (नीलात् परतरं श्वेतं
श्वेताद् धैरण्यकं परम्) 6. 7. 35.

श्वेत
Śveta2 m. (sg.): Name of a Dvīpa.
A. Location: Nārada saw it situated
to the north-west of mountain Meru, to
the north of Kṣīrodadhi (the ocean of
milk); according to the wise men it was
at a distance of more than thirtytwo
thousand योजनस् from the base of Meru
(अधिमेरौ … निलिल्ये॥तत्रावतस्थे च
मुनिर् (viz. Nārada) मुहूर्तम्। … आलोक-
यन्न् उत्तरपश्चिमेन ददर्श … ॥क्षीरो-
दधेर् उत्तरतो हि द्वीपः श्वेतः स नाम्ना
 … ।मेरोः सहस्रैः स हि योजनानां
द्वात्रिंशतोर्द्ध्वं कविभिर् निरुक्तः॥)
12. 322. 7-8 (Nī. on Bom. Ed. 12. 330. 9:
मेरुमूलात् द्वात्रिंशत्सहस्रयोजनाद् ऊर्-
ध्वम्); क्षीरोदधेर् उत्तरतः श्वेतद्वीपो
 … ) 12. 323. 23; क्षीरोदस्योत्तरं कूलम्
(probably a reference to Śvetadvīpa; the
island is not directly named) 12. 327. 39.
B. Description; (a) of the island; famous
(प्रथित); large (विशाल) 12. 322. 8;
(महाद्वीप) 12. 323. 28; 12. 325. 1; 12.
326. 117; 12. 331. 20; of great brightness
(महाप्रभ) 12. 323. 23; abode of bright-
ness (तेजोनिवास) 12. 323. 34; (b) of the
people on the Śvetadvīpa: white (श्वेत)
12. 322. 9; 12. 323. 31, 47; 12. 325. 1; 12.
331. 41; (Nī. on Bom. Ed. 12. 335. 10:
श्वेताः शुद्धसत्त्वप्रधानाः); auspicious
(शुभ) 12. 325. 1; devoid of the five sense
organs (पञ्चेन्द्रियविवर्जित) 12. 331. 41;
(सर्वेन्द्रियविवर्जित) 12. 323. 47; beyond
sense organs (अतीन्द्रिय) 12. 322. 9, 13; 12.
323. 25; (अनिन्द्रियाहार) 12. 326. 18. (Nī.
Bom. Ed. 12. 335. 10: reads अनीन्द्रियाः and
comments: स्थूलदेहसङ्गहीनाः; however,
see the next which refers to their bodies or
parts of bodies); their bodies have bones as
strong as वज्र (वज्रास्थिकाय) 12. 322. 10;
of auspicious strength (शुभसारोपेत)
12. 322. 10. (Nī. on 12. 335. 10: शुभः
योगप्रभावजः सारो बलं तेन उपेताः);
their heads have the shape of an umbrella
(छत्राकृतिशीर्ष) 12. 322. 10. (Nī. on 12.
335. 11: निर्मांसग्रीवत्वात्); having sixty
teeth (षष्ट्या दन्तैर् युक्ताः) 12. 322. 11.
(Nī. on 12. 335. 11; षष्ट्या षष्टिसंख्यैर्
दन्तैर् इव जगच्चणकचर्वणक्षमैः
संवत्सरैर् युक्ताः); have eight shining
jaws (शुक्लैर् अष्टाभिर् दंष्ट्राभिर् ये) 12.
322. 11 (Nī. on 12. 335. 11: अष्टौ दिशः
सर्वेषाम् आश्रयभूतास् ताभिश् च युक्ता
देशकालौ येषां मुखमध्ये प्रविष्टाव्
इत्य् अर्थः।); with their tongues they lick
on all sides their faces which shine like
the sun (जिह्वाभिर् ये विष्वग् वक्त्रं लेलि-
ह्यन्ते सूर्यप्रख्यम्) 12. 322. 11. (Nī.
12. 335. 11 reads विश्ववक्त्रम् and ex-
plains सूर्येण प्रख्यायते स्फुटीक्रियते
दिनमासर्तुसंवत्सरात्मा महाकालस् तं
विश्ववक्त्रं विश्वं वक्त्रे यस्य तादृशम्
जिह्वाभिर् इव स्वाङ्गभूताभी रसनाशक्ति-
भिर् लेलिह्यन्ते पायसम् इव लिहन्ति); they
have feet marked with a hundred lotuses
(राजीवशतपाद) 12. 322. 10 (Nī. 12.
335. 11 reads राजावच्छदपादाः and ex-
plains: राजीवत्यः पङ्क्तियुक्ताः शिरारेखास्
तासां शतैर् युक्ताः पादाः येषाम्; they
have स्वस्तिक marks resembling lotuses
(सत्पुष्करचतुष्क ? or they wear garlands
of four lotuses ?) 12. 322. 10. (Nī. 12.
335. 11: reads सममुष्कचतुष्काः and
explains: समं पीनत्वरहितं मुष्कौ
वृषणौ चतुष्कं अंसयोः कट्योश् चान्त-
रालं च मुष्कचतुष्कं।बाहुचतुष्कं
वा किमुत्त्वावान् (?) मुष्कयोर् बद्ध आसते
इति लिङ्गान् मुष्को बाहुः।शुष्कं काष्ठ-
तुल्यं चतुष्कं येषाम् संशुष्कचतुष्का
इत्य् अपि पठन्ति।); they are marked with
all (auspicious) marks (सर्वलक्षण-
लक्षित 12. 323. 31); their voice is like
the one produced by a cluster of clouds
(मेघौघनिनाद) 12. 322. 10; they look
like the moon, have lustre like the moon
(चन्द्रप्रतीकाश) 12. 323. 31; (चन्द्र-
वर्चस्) 12. 323. 24; 12. 326. 18; (चन्द्र-
प्रभ) 12. 325. 1; each one of them had
the lustre equal to that of the sun at the
time of the end of the aeon (या भवेन् …
भाः सूर्यस्य युगक्षये।एकैकस्य प्रभा
तादृक् साभवन् मानवस्य ह॥) 12. 323.
33; the visitors to the island felt that its
inhabitants had the lustre of a thousand
suns rising simultaneously (अथ सूर्यसह-
स्रस्य प्रभां युगपद् उत्थिताम्।सहसा
दृष्टवन्तः स्म … ॥) 12. 323. 35; they all
had the same lustre, no one more (nor less)
(न तत्राभ्यदिकः कश्चित् सर्वे ते सम-
तेजसः) 12. 323. 34; the lustre of the self-
luminous Bhagavān excelled the lustre of
the Śvetadvīpa (i. e. of the people living on
the Śvetadvīpa) (श्वेतद्वीपात् परं हि यत्।
तेज इत्य् अभिविख्यातं स्वयंभासावभासि-
तम्) 12. 331. 44; they do not take food
(निराहार) 12. 322. 13; 12. 323. 25; (अनिन्-
द्रियाहार) 12. 326. 18; (अनशन) 12. 322.
9 (Nī., however, on 12. 335. 9: अनशनाः
शब्दादिविषयभोगशून्याः); they make no
movements (निष्पन्दहीन) 12. 322. 9 (Nī.
on 12. 335. 9: निश्चेष्टाश् च); (अनिष्पन्द)
12. 322. 13; 12. 323. 25; they are auspici-
ously fragrant (सुसुगन्धिन्) 12. 322. 9.
(Nī., however, on 12. 335. 9: सुगन्धिः
परमात्मा सुगन्धिं पुष्टिवर्धनम् इति
मन्त्रलिङ्गात्।शोभनः सुगन्धिः सोऽस्त्य्
एषां ध्यानगोचर इति सुसुगन्धिनः।);
(सुगन्धिन्) 12. 322. 13; 12. 323. 25; they
are free of every kind of sin (गतसर्व-
पाप) 12. 322. 9; they deprive sinful men
of their eyesight (चक्षुर्मुषः पापकृतां
नराणाम्) 12. 322. 9; to them honour or
disrespect make no difference (सममानोन्-
मान) 12. 322. 10. (Nī. on 12. 335. 10;
मानश् च उन्मानो ऽपमानश् च समौ
येषां ते); in assemblies they are respected
by all beings (सदोगतास् तत्र ये वै
सर्वभूतनमस्कृताः) 12. 331. 29; they
have the appearance of those who have a
divine origin (दिव्यान्वयरूप) 12. 322. 10;
of pure origin (शुद्धयोनि) 12. 323. 44;
auspicious (शुभ) 12. 325. 1; perfect
(सिद्ध) and blessed (महाभाग) 12.
326. 19; magnanimous (महात्मन्) 12.
323. 32; knowers of five times (पञ्च-
कालज्ञ) 12. 323. 42; free of the qualities
तमस् and रजस् (तमोरजोविनिर्मुक्त) 12.
326. 19.
C. Characteristics: They are
devoted to god Puruṣottama (ते भक्ताः
पुरुषोत्तमम्) 12. 323. 24; (भक्ताश् च
पुरुषोत्तमम्) 12. 331. 41; (नारायणपर)
12. 323. 24; (मद्भक्ताः) 12. 326. 18;
they lick the god with devotion (i. e. they
are absorbed in devotion (? लेलिह्यन्ते …
भक्त्या देवम्) 12. 322. 11-12 (Nī. on 12.
335. 11: जीह्वाभिर् इव स्वाङ्गभूताभी
रसनाशक्तिभिर् लेलिह्यन्ते पायसम् इव
लिहन्ति); they are absorbed in complete
devotion (एकान्तभावोपगत) 12. 323. 24;
they are devoted to one god (एकान्तिन्)
12. 323. 26, 42 (Nī. on 12. 348. 3: एकान्-
तिनो निष्कामभक्ताः); 12. 326. 19; (एक-
भावम् अनुव्रताः) 12. 323. 45; (एकाग्राश्
चिन्तयेयुर् माम्) 12. 326. 18; completely
engrossed in ब्रह्मन् (ब्रह्मभावम्
अनुष्ठिताः) 12. 323. 45; they always wor-
ship the (one) god and he sports with
them (ते ऽर्चयन्ति सदा देवं तैः सार्धं
रमते च सः) 12. 331. 42; they are en-
lightened (प्रतिबुद्ध) 12. 331. 41; their
mode of devotion (जप) and offering बलि
as well as the result of their devotion and
offering described in 12. 323. 32, 36-41;
Nārada thought that Nara and Nārāyaṇa
(their description in 12. 331. 23-27) were
like the men he saw in the Śvetadvīpa
12. 331. 30; they are so blessed that if
one saw the people on the Śvetadvīpa
it was as good as seeing the god himself
(दृष्टो भवति देवेश एभिर् दृष्टैर् … ) 12.
323. 47; the people of Śvetadvīpa had
the same characteristic as that of the
liberated men (ये विमुक्ता भवन्तीह
 … तेषां लक्षणम् एतद् धि यच् छ्वेत-
द्वीपवासिनाम्) 12. 322. 14 (Nī. on 12.
335. 14; श्वेतद्वीपवासिनां जीवन्मुक्तानां
च निरिन्द्रियत्वादिकं एव लक्षणम्); (at
the end of their life) they enter the
eternal god of thousand lustres (ते सह-
स्रार्चीषं देवं प्रविशन्ति सनातनम्)
12. 323. 25; (मां प्रवेक्ष्यन्त्य् असं-
शयम्) 12. 326. 19.
D. Epic events:
(1) Yudhiṣṭhira asked Bhīṣma how
the people of the Śvetadvīpa were born
and what was the kind of life they were
going to obtain after death (कथं ते
पुरुषा जाताः का तेषां गतिर् उत्तमा) 12.
322. 13; thereupon Bhīṣma replied to his
question in details starting with the story
of king Uparicara 12. 322. 16 ff.; Bhīṣma
also told Yudhiṣṭhira how Nārada went to
Śvetadvīpa 12. 324. 39; (2) Janamejaya
asked Vaiśaṃpāyana why Nārada return-
ed from the Śvetadvīpa to the Badarī
आश्रम to see Nara and Nārāyaṇa, how
long he stayed there, and what were the
questions he asked to those two Ṛṣis 12.
331. 15-18; thereupon Vaiśaṃpāyana re-
plied to his question in details 12. 331. 19 ff.
E. Past events: (1) Nārada standing on
a peak of mountain Meru saw the Śveta-
dvīpa in the north-west direction as a
wonderful spectacle 12. 322. 7-8; Nārada
reached the Śvetadvīpa and saw the people
there; he respected them by bowing
down and they honoured him mentally
(पूजयाम् आस शिरसा मनसा तैश् च पूजि-
तः) 12. 325. 1-2; Bhagavān appeared
before Nārada, but told him to leave the
island immediately so that no disturbance
was caused to the contemplations of the
people of the Śvetadvīpa (गच्छ नारद
माचिरम्॥ … एकाग्राश् चिन्तयेयुर् मां
नैषां विघ्नो भवेद् इति) 12. 326. 17-18;
12. 331. 13; he left Śvetadvīpa and went
to mount Meru and from there to Gandha-
mādana to reach Badarī 12. 331. 20-22;
(also see the two epic events above);
Nārada told Nara and Nārāyaṇa that he
saw in Śvetadvīpa the people residing there
12. 331. 29-30; Nārāyaṇa asked Nārada if
he saw in Śvetadvīpa the Bhagavān who was
their (i. e. of Nara and Nārāyaṇa) higher
प्रकृति (अपि … स भगवान् … श्वेतद्वीपे
त्वया दृष्ट आवयोः प्रकृतिः परा) 12. 331.
35; Nārada replied that he did and also
told them he saw the white people who
were devoid of all sense-organs; as directed
by Bhagavān he returned from Śvetadvīpa
12. 331. 36, 41, 51; 12. 332. 1; Nara and
Nārāyaṇa then told Nārada that they too
had seen him (Nārada) meeting the Bhaga-
vān himself in Śvetadvīpa and had heard
his conversation with him (आवाभ्याम् अपि
दृष्टस् त्वं श्वेतद्वीपे … ।समागतो भग-
वता संजल्पं कृतवान् यथा॥) 12. 332.
22; (2) A noncorporeal voice told Ekata,
Dvita and Trita, who were practising severe
austerities on mountain Meru to go to
Śvetadvīpa where the Bhagavān had mani-
fested himself (गच्छध्वं तत्र) (i. e.
Śvetadvīpa) मुनयस् तत्रात्मा मे प्र-
काशितः) 12. 323. 21-23, 26; they reached
the Śvetadvīpa by following the way told
to them by the noncorporeal voice; having
reached the island, however, their eyes
were blinded and they could not see any
man (प्राप्य श्वेतं महाद्वीपं … ततो
नो दृष्टिविषयस् तदा प्रतिहतो ऽभवत्) 12.
323. 27-28; when Ekata, Dvita and Trita
further practised austerities for a hundred
years they were able to see the people of
the Śveta island; they had folded their
hands and, facing north-east, they did the
जप of Brahman; that जप was mental
(नित्याञ्जलिकृतान् ब्रह्म जपतः प्रागुदङ्-
मुखान्।मानसो नाम स जपो जप्यते
तैर् महात्मभिः॥) 12. 323. 32; suddenly
they saw lustre equal to that of a thousand
suns; the people of the island together be-
gan to run quickly, folding their hands and,
delighted, they continued to say ‘नमस्’;
when they were thus showing their reve-
rence, we heard a loud sound (ततो ऽभि-
वदतां तेषाम् अश्रौष्म विपुलं ध्वनिम्)
12. 323. 37; Ekata, Dvita and Trita were
not able to see anything, but they could
hear the praise of Bhagavān; at that time
wind blew heavenly flowers and plants
suitable for offerings; with that, people
gave offering to Hari (बलिः किलोपह्रियते
तस्य देवस्य तैर् नरैः); indeed, the god
himself had arrived there when they were
uttering sounds; from among those thou-
sands of men no one welcomed them
mentally, nor by looking at them; no one
thought of them and hence they were
worried (एतस्मिन्न् अन्तरे वायुः … दिव्यान्य्
उवाह पुष्पाणि कर्मण्याश् चौषधिस् तथा॥
 … चिन्ताव्याकुलितात्मानो जाताः स्मो … ।
मानवानां सहस्रेषु तेषु … ।अस्मान् न
कश्चिन् मनसा चक्षुषा वाप्य् अपूजयत्॥ …
नास्मासु दधिरे भावम्) 12. 323. 38-45;
a non-corporeal being then told them that
they had already seen the white people of
the island and that seeing them was as
good as seeing the chief god; they should
therefore quit the island without delay
(उवाच खस्थं किम् अपि भूतं तत्रा-
शरीरकम्॥दृष्टा वः पुरुषाः श्वेताः …
दृष्टो भवति देवेश एभिर् दृष्टैर् द्विजोत्त-
माः॥) 12. 323. 46-47; Bhagavān told
Nārada that Ekata, Dvita and Trita had
come to the Śveta island desirous of his
दर्शन, but they could not see him (इमं
देशम् अनुप्राप्ता मम दर्शनलालसाः)
12. 326. 11; (3) Vaiśaṃpāyana informed
Janamejaya that Nārada had told the
Sātvata धर्म to Vyāsa, which was, also
called the धर्म of the Ekāntins, followed
by the white ascetics (धर्मः सात्वतो … ।
एवं हि … नारदो गुरवे मम।श्वेतानां
यतीनाम् आह एकान्तगतिम् अव्ययाम्॥) 12.
336. 76, 78-79 (These ‘white ascetics’ are
probably to be identified with the people
of the Śvetadvīpa. Nī., however, on 12.
348. 85; श्वेतानां गृहस्थादीनाम्।यतीनां
काषायधारिणाम्).

षण्ड
Ṣaṇḍa m. (pl.): Name of a Janapada.
Listed by Saṃjaya among the northern
Janapadas (also called Deśas 6. 10. 68) of
Bhāratavarṣa (अत ऊर्ध्वं जनपदान्
निबोध) 6. 10. 37, 5; (गोविन्दा मन्दकाः
षण्डा … ) 6. 10. 42 [see Śaṇḍa].

संशप्तक
Saṃśaptaka m. (pl.): A general
term to designate the group of five Trigarta
brothers and their followers who together
took the oath to kill Arjuna; their army in
general, which included besides Trigartas
also Mālavas and many other Janapadas,
is also referred to as Saṃśaptaka; some-
times Nārāyaṇas and Gopālas also figure
in the context of Saṃśaptakas.
A. Description: Heroic (वीर) 3. 240.
33; 7. 17. 30; 8. 12. 4; 8. 14. 18; brave
(शूर) 8. 14. 5; 8. 40. 94; 8. 42. 3; tigers
among men (नरव्याघ्र) 7. 17. 2; skilled
in the use of missiles (कृतास्त्र) 6. 20. 15;
fond of battles (युद्धशौन्ड) 8. 31. 14;
great chariot-fighters (माहारथ) 1. 1.
131; 7. 26. 10, 18; famous, widely known
(प्रख्यात) 3. 240. 22; (नामलब्धानाम्
विदितानां समन्ततः) 8. 40. 94.
B. Epic
events: (1) Saṃśaptakas took away
Arjuna from the main battle-field; after
Abhimanyu's death, Arjuna killed all the
surviving Saṃśaptakas—these two chief
points of the epic events mentioned while
listing the contents of the Droṇaparvan in
the Parvasaṃgrahaparvan 1. 2. 160, 163;
(2) Dānavas informed Duryodhana who
was taken to Rāsātala by a कृत्या that the
Saṃśaptakas were Daityas and Rākṣasas in
hundreds and thousands appointed to kill
Arjuna and they would kill him; then Dur-
yodhana felt assured that (Karṇa and) the
Saṃśaptakas were meant to kill Arjuna and
that they were capable of accomplishing
the task; the mind of the Saṃśaptakas was
under the spell of Rākṣasas and, overcome
by the qualities रजस् and तमस्, they were
eager to kill Arjuna (सांशप्तकाश् च ते
वीरा राक्षसाविष्टचेतसः।रजस्तमोभ्यां
आक्रान्ताः फल्गुनस्य वधैषिणः॥) 3.
240. 22, 30, 33; (3) Saṃjaya told Dhṛta-
rāṣṭra that in the ensuing war the five
Kekaya brothers would take on the two
chief Trigartas of the Saṃśaptakas (त्रिगर्-
तानां च द्वौ मुख्यौ यौ तौ शंश-
प्तकाव् इति) 5. 56. 18; (4) An अयुत of
Saṃśaptaka chariot-fighters were meant to
fight with Arjuna resulting either in the
death or victory of Arjuna; they followed
Arjuna wherever he went (संशप्तकानाम्
अयुतं रथानां मृत्युर् जयो वार्जुनस्येति
सृष्टाः।येनार्जुनस् तेन … प्रयाता वै ते)
6. 20. 15 (Nī. on Bom. Ed. 6. 20. 15; येन
यत्र तेन तत्र); (5) Śuśarman, king of
Trigartas, and his five brothers Satyaratha,
Satyadharman, Satyavarman, Satyeṣuḥ and
Satyakarman together with their army of
Trigartas, as well as Mālavas, Tuṇḍikeras,
Mācellakas, Lalitthas, Madrakas and many
other Janapadas took the oath (शपथ)
to kill Arjuna 7. 16. 11, 15-21; the mode of
oath, also called प्रतिज्ञा, in which offerings
were given in fire, described 7. 16. 22-37;
in the description of the war, in the con-
text of Saṃśaptakas, besides some of those
groups of people mentioned above, also
occur Nārāyaṇas, Gopālas (7. 17. 31; 7. 18.
7), and Yaudheyas (7. 18. 16); (6) On
the twelfth day of the war, Droṇa planned a
battle between Arjuna and the Saṃśaptaka
troops and when Arjuna left the main battle-
field to fight with them, he arranged his
army in the Suparṇavyūha against Pāṇḍavas
(विधाय योगं पार्थेन संशप्तक-
गणैः सह) 7. 19. 2-4; the Saṃśaptakas
arranged their chariots on even ground
in the व्यूह called Candrārdha; they were
delighted to see Arjuna approaching them
for a fight; they roared loudly; Arjuna was
surprised to find that they were delighted
when actually they should have been
grieved; or, he thought, perhaps, they were
delighted because they would go to excellent
worlds (after death) which were otherwise
difficult to be obtained by bad people 7.
17. 1-6; hearing the sound of Devadatta
conch blown by Arjuna, the army of
Saṃśaptakas became motionless; regaining
consciousness they started fighting with
Arjuna by showering कङ्कपत्रिन् arrows
against him 7. 17. 9-11; the battle des-
cribed in which Subāhu, Sudharman and
Sudhanvan also participated 7. 17. 12-22;
at the death of Sudhanvan, his followers,
afraid, ran towards the army of Duryo-
dhana 7. 17. 23; Suśarman, king of Tri-
gartas, rebuked those who fled; he remind-
ed them of their terrific oaths (शप्त्वा तु
शपथान् घोरान्); the troops of Saṃśap-
takas then blew their conches and returned
to fight till death (मृत्युं कृत्वा निवर्त-
नम्॥) 7. 17. 27-31; seeing that the troops
of Saṃśaptakas were returning Arjuna asked
Kṛṣṇa to drive his chariot towards them;
he was determined to kill them 7. 18. 1-3;
the Vāyavyāstra released by Arjuna to ward
off the arrows of the opponents also blew
away a large number of Saṃśaptakas along
with their chariots, horses, elephants and
weapons; Arjuna killed a large number of
Saṃśaptakas; their condition as well as the
condition of the battle-field described 7. 18.
22-37; Dhṛtarāṣṭra asked Saṃjaya how
Arjuna dealt with the army of Saṃśaptakas
(संशप्तकबलं प्रति) and how did
they encounter him 7. 25. 2; Arjuna left
Saṃśaptakas for a while to fight with
Bhagadatta who was routing the Pāṇḍava
army; fourteen thousand Saṃśaptakas
followed him and challenged him; Arjuna
hesitated for a while whether to fight with
Saṃśaptakas or go to help Yudhiṣṭhira;
ultimately he decided to kill Saṃśaptakas
(first) (अभवद् भुयसी बुद्धिः संश-
प्तकवधे स्थिरा); the great Saṃśaptaka
chariot-fighters (संशप्तकमहारथाः)
discharged numerous smooth arrows (शत-
सहस्राणि शराणां नतपर्वणां) on
Arjuna with the result that, covered with
the arrows, neither Arjuna, nor Kṛṣṇa, nor
his horses, nor chariot, could be seen; when
Kṛṣṇa was deluded (मोहम् अनुप्राप्तः …
जनार्दनः) Arjuna killed Saṃśaptakas
with Vajrāstra 7. 26. 10, 12-14, 18-20; the
condition of Saṃśaptakas described 7. 26.
21-27; having killed Saṃśaptakas Arjuna
asked Kṛṣṇa to drive his chariot towards
Bhagadatta 7. 26. 29; but Suśarman and
his Saṃśaptaka brothers followed Arjuna
challenging him for a fight (युद्धार्थी
पृष्थतो ऽन्वयात्॥ … सुशर्माह्वयते
ऽच्युत॥); Arjuna therefore was again in
doubt-whether to kill Saṃśaptakas first
or to go to the aid of his side 7. 27. 2-5;
he asked Kṛṣṇa to turn back and started
fighting with Suśarman; his battle with
Saṃśaptaka brothers described in which
Suśarman swooned 7. 27. 7-10; later,
Arjuna continued to kill the surviving Saṃ-
śaptakas and Nārāyaṇas on the southern
side of the army (दक्षिणेन तु सेनायाः
कुरुते कदनं बलि।संशप्तकावशेषस्य
नारायणबलस्य च॥) 7. 30. 29; after
killing the Saṃśaptakas, Arjuna returned to
attack Droṇa and the Kaurava army 7. 31.
41-44; (7) On the thirteenth day, when
Droṇa reiterated the necessity of removing
Arjuna from the main battle, Saṃśapta-
kas renewed their challenge to Arjuna and
took him away to the south of the battle-
field (आह्वयन्न् अर्जुनं संख्ये दक्षिणाम्
अभितो दिशम्) 7. 32. 15; towards the end
of the day, Arjuna proceeded towards his
camp after killing Saṃśaptakas 7. 50. 1-3;
Yudhiṣṭhira, grieved over the death of
Abhimanyu, told Arjuna that after he left
to fight with the Saṃśaptaka army, Droṇa
made a serious attempt to capture him 7.
51. 1; (8) On the fourteenth day, at
the instance of Duryodhana, the army
of Kauravas, along with Saṃśaptakas,
returned to fight with Sātyaki with great
determination (ते पुनः संन्यवर्तन्त
कृत्वा संशप्तकान् मिथः) 7. 97. 12; when
Duḥśāsana was wounded by Sātyaki,
Duryodhana asked Trigartas to fight with
Sātyaki; Saṃśaptakas again made a deter-
mined effort to attack Sātyaki; Sātyaki
killed their five hundred chief warriors,
showering arrows on them, at the head of
the army (अग्रानीके व्यपोथयत्) 7. 99.
3-7; their condition described 7. 99. 8-11;
ultimately they retreated in the direction of
Droṇa 7. 99. 12; (9) When Dhṛtarāṣṭra
was told that on the sixteenth day, angry
Arjuna attacked the Saṃśaptaka troops
(संशप्तकगणान् 8. 9. 8) he wished to
know the details of the fight between Saṃ-
śaptakas and Arjuna; Arjuna entered the
large ocean-like troops of Saṃśaptakas
(संशप्तकगणं … अर्णवसंनिभम्)
and agitated it (व्यक्षोभयत्); the fight
in which Arjuna cut off the hands and heads
of his opponents with sharp arrows and
killed elephants and horses along with their
riders as well as chariot-fighters was hair-
raising (लोमहर्षणम्) 8. 12. 1, 3-13; at
that point Aśvatthāman challenged Arjuna;
hence he asked Kṛṣṇa whether he should
continue killing Saṃśaptakas or accept the
challenge of Aśvatthāman: Kṛṣṇa drove
him to Aśvatthāman 8. 12. 21-22; after
fighting with Aśvatthāman, Arjuna return-
ed to Saṃśaptaka horse-riders, chariot-
fighters, elephant-riders and foot-soldiers
(ततः संशप्तकान् भूयः साश्वसूतरथ-
द्विपान्।ध्वजपत्तिगणान्) 8. 12. 36; battle
described in which Arjuna killed all kinds
of his opponents (संशप्तकमहार्णवम्।
व्यशोषयत दुःशोषम् … ) and returned
to fight with Aśvatthāman 8. 12. 37-43, 47;
after fighting for a while with him, Arjuna
came back to Saṃśaptakas; he cut off the
hands, heads, weapons etc. of the opponents
who did not turn back (अपराङ्मुखानाम्)
8. 12. 54-58; after Arjuna's one more
encounter with Aśvatthāman in which the
latter was removed from the battle by his
horses, Arjuna continued his battle with
Saṃśaptakas 8. 12. 70-71; when there was
loud noise to the north of the battle-field
(8. 13. 1), Kṛṣṇa advised Arjuna to go
there and first fight with Māgadha Daṇḍa-
dhāra; he could later kill the Saṃśaptakas
8. 13. 4; accordingly, Arjuna first killed
Daṇḍadhāra and his elephant and came
back to Saṃśaptakas 8. 13. 25; in the
battle that followed, Arjuna killed many
Saṃśaptakas, while Kṛṣṇa drove his chariot
in various roundabout ways (वक्रानुव-
क्रगमनात्) 8. 14. 1; the battle described
8. 14. 2-21; at that moment Kṛṣṇa advised
Arjuna not to while away his time with
Saṃśaptakas; he should kill them without
loss of time and hasten to kill Karṇa
(किं क्रीडसे ऽनघ।संशप्तकान् प्रम-
थ्यैतांस् ततः कर्णवधे त्वर); Arjuna
agreed and killed quickly the remaining
Saṃśaptakas (क्षिप्रं शिष्टान् संशप्त-
कांस् तदा।आक्षिप्य शस्त्रेण बलाद् …
अवधीत्) 8. 14. 22-23; Trigartas, along with
Śālvas, Saṃśaptakas, and Nārāyaṇas, led
by the king of Trigartas and his brothers,
attacked Arjuna 8. 19. 2-4; the battle, in
which Saṃśaptakas were killed by hundreds
and thousands (शतशो ऽथ सहस्रशः 8.
19. 19) and at one stage they surrounded
Arjuna and showered him with weapons,
described 8. 19. 5-34; in the end almost
the entire Saṃśaptaka army turned back
and did not stay to face Arjuna (प्रायशो
विमुखं सर्वं नावतिष्ठत संयुगे);
Arjuna thus won victory over many Saṃ-
śaptaka troops (संशप्तकगणान् बहून्)
8. 19. 34-35; (10) On the seventeenth
day, thirty-four thousand chariot-fighters of
Śaṃśaptakas determined to fight to the end
stood on the left side of the Bārhaspatya-
vyūha of Kauravas (चतुस्त्रिंशत्सहस्राणि
रथानाम् अनिवर्तिनाम्।संशप्तका …
वामं पार्श्वम् अपालयन् … बार्हस्पत्यः
 … महाव्यूहः) 8. 31. 14, 26; Śalya
drew attention of Karṇa to Saṃśaptakas
who had challenged Arjuna; in response,
they were being attacked and killed by
Arjuna; angered Saṃśaptakas covered him
on all sides making Arjuna invisible
(संशप्तकैः क्रुद्धैः … छन्नः पार्थो
न दृश्यते) 8. 31. 56-57; Dhṛtarāṣṭra
asked Saṃjaya to describe to him the
battle between Arjuna and Saṃśaptakas;
Saṃjaya told him that when the armies
were arrayed (अथ व्यूढेष्व् अनीकेषु),
Arjuna attacked Saṃśaptakas; wishing
to kill Arjuna and determined to win
victory not minding death (विजये कृत-
संकल्पा मृत्युं कृत्वा निवर्तनम्) they
rushed towards Arjuna; their army consi-
sted of many horses, elephants, chariot-
fighters and foot-soldiers; a fierce battle
then took place; Arjuna cut off their hands,
holding different weapons, as well as their
heads; thinking Arjuna's chariot was
drowned in the large army, Saṃśaptakas
delightfully raised a roar (तस्मिन् सैन्ये
महावर्ते … ।निमग्नं तं रथं मत्वा
नेदुः संशप्तका मुदा।) 8. 32. 1-13; at
the site where Arjuna was killing Saṃśapta-
kas a loud sound of Gāṇḍīva was heard;
very much angered Saṃśaptakas, coveting
victory (जयगृद्धाः प्रमन्यवः) sho-
wered arrows on Arjuna; Arjuna braved
their attack and reached Suśarman; when
Arjuna started showering arrows on Suśar-
man, Saṃśaptakas responded the same way;
hearing the roar of the monkey on Arjuna's
chariot, the army of Saṃśaptakas was much
terrified and became motionless; regain-
ing consciousness, the warriors showered
arrows on Arjuna and covered his chariot;
they held firmly the horses, the wheels and
the shaft of Arjuna's chariot and roared
loudly (ते हयान् रथचक्रे च रथेषाश्
चापि भारत।निगृह्य बलवत्); some
mounted on Arjuna's chariot and held him
and Kṛṣṇa; shaking his hands Kṛṣṇa felled
them down; Arjuna saw Saṃśaptaka great
chariot-fighters encircling him and holding
his chariot and Kṛṣṇa; he felled many of
them down who had mounted the chariot
and other foot-soldiers who were close to
him by shooting arrows which went short
distances (अपातयत्।आसन्नांश् च ततो
योधाञ् शरैर् आसन्नयोधिभिः); he made
the rest run away; Arjuna pointed out to
Kṛṣṇa that he had killed thousands of
Saṃśaptakas who had achieved the difficult
task of checking his chariot (कुर्वाणान्
दारुणं कर्म … रथबन्धं इमं।
घोरं); Arjuna and Kṛṣṇa blew Deva-
datta and Pāñcajanya conches respy.;
hearing that sound, the Saṃśaptaka army
shook and became very much afraid (सं-
चचाल … वित्रस्ता चाभवद् भृशम्);
Arjuna then bound their feet by releasing
नागास्त्र; he killed them in that condition;
when they were being killed, they gave up
fighting with Arjuna and threw down their
weapons; then Suśarman released them
from their bonds by using सौपर्णास्त्र;
once free, they showered arrows and
weapons on Arjuna (ससृजुर् बाणसं-
घांश् च शस्त्रसंघांश् च); Arjuna cut
off the missiles with arrows and killed many
elephants, horses and chariot-fighters by
using ऐन्द्रास्त्र; the troops of Saṃśaptakas
and Nārāyaṇas were then very much afraid;
no one was able to fight back Arjuna (न
हि कश्चित् पुमांस् तत्र यो ऽर्जुनं प्रत्य-
विध्यत); Arjuna then killed an अयुत of
the opposing warriors; fourteen thousand
(foot) warriors, an अयुत of chariot-
fighters, and three thousand elephant-
riders of Saṃśaptakas who survived (यानि
शिष्टानि) once again surrounded Arjuna
determined either to return with victory
or die (मर्तवयम् इति निश्चित्य जयं वापि
निवर्तनम्); a fierce fighting then was
fought between them and Arjuna (8. 37.
1-38); Arjuna destroyed many Saṃśapta-
kas; their Kṣatriyas, tormented by him,
were killed (ते क्षत्रिया दह्यमानास् …
जग्मुर् विनाशम्) 8. 40. 5-61 after killing
many Saṃśaptaka troops (निहत्य … सं-
शप्तकगणान् बहून्), Arjuna pointed out
to Kṛṣṇa the great Saṃśaptaka chariot-
fighters who along with their troops ran
away as they were unable to resist his
arrows (धावन्ति सगणाः संशप्तकमहा-
रथाः।अपारयन्तो मद्बाणान्) 8. 40. 78-
80; Duryodhana again incited Saṃśaptakas
to face Arjuna; then a thousand chariot-
fighters, three hundred elephant-riders,
fourteen thousand horse-riders and two
hundred thousand archers turned towards
Kṛṣṇa and Arjuna covering them with
arrows; but Arjuna killed ten thousand
Saṃśaptakas 8. 40. 92-99; thus Arjuna
completely destroyed (कृत्स्नेन व्यध-
मत्) the Saṃśaptakas 8. 40. 130; when
the armies of Kurus and Sṛñjayas met
again only a few Saṃśaptakas had sur-
vived (संशप्तकेषु … किंचिच्छिष्टेषु);
Arjuna, after defeating Aśvatthāman (8.
42. 51), asked Kṛṣṇa to take him to Saṃ-
śaptakas since fighting with them was his
main task (कार्यम् एतत् परं मम) 8.
42. 3, 56; Arjuna killed the remaining Saṃ-
śaptaka troops with sharp arrows with the
result that they became the guests of Indra
and became free from grief as they were
happy (शक्रस्यातिथिताम् गत्वा विशोका ह्य्
अभवन् मुदा) 8. 43. 76-77; when Arjuna
told Bhīma that he could not leave the
battlefield (to go to enquire about Yudhi-
ṣṭhira) without killing Saṃśaptakas who
faced him, Bhīma assured him that he
himself would fight with the Saṃśaptakas
8. 45. 63-64; Arjuna while explaining to
Yudhiṣṭhira why he had not yet killed
Karṇa told him that during his fight with
Saṃśaptakas, Aśvatthāman had unexpec-
tedly intervened (to distract him) 8. 47.
2; later, while boasting about his heroic
deeds Arjuna mentioned that he had killed
almost all Saṃśaptakas and only a few of
them had survived (संशप्तकानां किंचिद्
एवावशिष्टम्) 8. 49. 96; at one stage, Duḥśā-
sana along with the fully equipped army of
Saṃśaptakas (पृतना समृद्धा) attacked
Bhīma 8. 53. 9; when Arjuna was proceeding
towards Karṇa, Saṃśaptaka chariot-fighters
attacked him showering arrows; Arjuna
killed many of them along with their chari-
oteers, and cut off their bows and banners
with sharp arrows; they all fell down from
their chariots 8. 59. 3-5; (11) On the
seventeenth day, at night, when Saṃjaya
reported to Dhṛtarāṣṭra the death of Karṇa
(8. 1. 25), he (Dhṛtarāṣṭra), while recalling
some of the major events of war, mention-
ed the killing of the Saṃśaptaka army by
Arjuna 8. 1. 41; in reply to Dhṛtarāṣṭra's
question who of the Kurus were still alive
and who dead (के नु जीवन्ति के मृताः)
8. 4. 3, Saṃjaya mentioned Saṃśaptaka
troops (संशप्तकगणाश् च ये) among
those who were killed by Arjuna 8. 4.
38; (12) On the eighteenth day, Arjuna
speedily rushed towards Kṛtavarman and
Saṃśaptaka troops which were posted on
the left side of the Sarvatobhadravyūha of
Kauravas 9. 7. 30, 19, 24 (where Saṃ-
śaptakas are designated as Trigartas);
Arjuna, having killed Saṃśaptakas in battle
(हत्वा संशप्तकान् रणे) rushed towards,
the army of Kauravas 9. 9. 59; as the
day advanced (मध्यंदिनगते सूर्ये),
Aśvatthāman, helped by Saṃśaptakas
(संशप्तकवृतो रणे), fought with Arjuna;
the battle was terrific in which a large
number of warriors were killed (तत्र
युद्धं महच् चासीत् … यमराष्ट्रविवर्-
धनम्) 9. 13. 42-43; (विमर्दस् तु महान्
आसीत्) 9. 13. 45; (13) On the nineteenth
day, after the war was over, Saṃjaya,
having returned early in the morning from
the camp (ततः पूर्वाह्णसमये शिबिराद्
एत्य संजयः 9. 1. 14), while reporting
to Dhṛtarāṣṭra the war-events mentioned
Saṃśaptakas among those who were killed
in war 9. 1. 26; Dhṛtarāṣṭra lamenting the
loss of life in war mentioned that many
Saṃśaptakas were killed (संशप्तकाश् च
बहवः (निहताः)) 9. 2. 34; (14) Kṛṣṇa,
while giving an account of war to Vasu-
deva, mentioned that before the fall of
Abhimanyu, Saṃśaptakas had challenged
Arjuna for a battle and took him away
from the main scene (समाहूते तु सं-
ग्रामे पार्थे संशप्तकैस् तदा) 14. 60.
19.
C. Arjuna is described as the
killer of Saṃśaptakas संशप्तकनिषूदन
14. 73. 32, संशप्तकनिहन्तृ 14. 76. 9.
[See Trigarta]

संस्थान
Saṃsthāna m. (pl.): Name of a
people.
On the second day of war, Duryodhana
asked Saṃsthāna warriors and others to
protect Bhīṣma in the Mahāvyūha of
Kauravas (संस्थानाः शूरसेनाश् च …
भीष्मम् एवाभिरक्षन्तु … ॥ … अव्यूहन्त
महाव्यूहं … ) 6. 47. 7-10.

सन्न्यस्तपाद|संन्यस्तपाद
Saṃnyastapāda m. (pl.): Name of a
people.
Saṃnyastapādas were among those
who, afraid of Jarāsandha, fied from north
to south (तथोत्तरां दिशं चापि परि-
त्यज्य भयार्दिताः। … संन्यस्तपादाश् च
दक्षिणां दिशम् आश्रिताः॥) 2. 13. 27.

सकच
Sakaca m. (pl.): Name of a Janapada.
Listed by Saṃjaya among the northern
Janapadas (also called Deśas 6. 10. 68)
of Bhāratavarṣa (अत ऊर्ध्वं जनपदान्
निबोध) 6. 10. 37, 5; (दर्वीकाः सकचा
दर्वा … ) 6. 10. 53.

सकलद्वीप
Sakaladvīpa m., n. (sg.): Name of a
country ?
Arjuna in his expedition to the north
(दिशं धनपतेर् इष्टाम् 2. 23. 9) before
the Rājasūya conquered the Sakaladvīpa,
its king Prativindhya, and its people
(विजिग्ये सकलं द्वीपं प्रतिविन्ध्यं च
पार्थिवम्॥सकलद्वीपवासाम्श् च) 2. 23.
15-16.

सक्षद्द्रुह्
Sakṣaddruh m. (pl.): Name of a
Janapada.
Listed by Saṃjaya among the southern
Janapadas (also called Deśas 6. 10. 68) of
Bhāratavarṣa (अथापरे जनपदा दक्षिणा
 … ) 6. 10. 56, 5; (सक्षद्द्रुहः कुन्तलाश्
च) 6. 10. 64.

सतिय
Satiya m. (sg. ?): Name of a Jana-
pada.
Listed by Saṃjaya among the southern
Janapadas (also called Deśas 6. 10. 68) of
Bhāratavarṣa (अथापरे जनपदा दक्षीणा
 … ) 6. 10. 56, 5; (सतियः पत्तिपञ्जकाः)
6. 10. 62.

सप्तद्वीप
Saptadvīpa m., nt. (sg.): Name of
some country to the north of Khāṇḍava-
prastha ?
Arjuna in his expedition to the north
(दिशं धनपतेर् इष्टाम् 2. 23. 9) before
the Rājasūya conquered the kings of the
Saptadvīpa (सप्तद्वीपे च ये नृपाः) 2. 23.
16 (this can impossibly refer to the seven
Dvīpas of this earth cf. 6. 12. 4; 12. 49. 31).

समक्ष
Samakṣa m. (pl.): Name of a people.
Bhīma in his expedition to the east
(ययौ प्राचीं दिशं प्रति 2. 26. 1, 7, 2.
23. 9) before the Rājasūya defeated Sama-
kṣas in battle (प्राच्यसुह्मान् समक्षांश्
चैव … विजित्य युधि) 2. 27. 14.

समङ्ग
Samaṅga m. (pl.): Name of a Jana-
pada.
Listed by Saṃjaya among the southern
Janapadas (also called Deśas 6. 10. 68) of
Bhāratavarṣa (अथापरे जनपदा दक्षिणा
 … ) 6. 10. 56, 5; (समङ्गाः कोपनाश् चैव)
6. 10. 59.

समन्दर
Samandara m. (pl): Name of a
people (referred to only twice and in
both cases along with Piśācas).
(1) On the fourteenth day of war,
Samandaras along with many others, led by
Duryodhana, attacked Sātyaki (दुर्योधन-
पुरोगमाः … पैशाचाश् च समन्दराः।
अभ्यद्रवन्त शैनेयं) 7. 97. 13-14;
(2) On the fifteenth day of war, when
Saṃjaya at night (शिबिरात् संजयं प्राप्तं
निशि नागाह्वयं पुरम् 7. 1. 7) reported
to Dhṛtarāṣṭra the death of Droṇa, he
(Dhṛtarāṣṭra) while recounting the past
exploits of Kṛṣṇa mentioned his victory
over Samandaras (पिशाचांस् च समन्दरान्)
7. 10. 16; (or does समन्दर- mean Piśācas
along with Mandaras ? see Mandara).

सागरानूपग
Sāgarānūpaga, Sāgarānūpavāsin adj.:
Characterization of peoples living along
ocean and marshy land.
A. Description: Haughty, fond of
battles, strong and firm-fisted (संरम्-
भिणो युद्धशौण्डा बलिनो दृब्धपाणयः)
8. 51. 19.
B. Epic events: (1) Kṛṣṇa
mentioned the people who lived near the
ocean and the marshy land (as also those
who lived in cities) among those whom he
saw attending the Rājasūya sacrifice and
acting as servers (सागरानूपगांश् चैव
ये च पत्तनवासिनः … आगतान् अहम् अद्रा-
क्षम् यज्ञे ते परिवेषकान्) 3. 48. 19, 22;
(2) On the seventeenth day of war (अद्य
सप्तादशाहानि वर्तमानस्य भारत) 8.
51. 2; Kṛṣṇa in order to encourage Arjuna
mentioned the warriors who lived along
the ocean and marshy lands among those
who had joined the side of Kauravas and
whom Arjuna alone was capable of defeat-
ing (सागरानूपवासिनः … एते सुयोधन-
स्यार्थे संरब्धाः कुरुभिः सह।न
शक्या युधि निर्जेतुम् त्वदन्येन परं-
तप) 8. 51. 19-20.

सात्वत
Sātvata (Sātvat) m. (pl.): Name of
a people who formed a section of the
Yādavas; Sātvat occurs only in complex
forms except in 1. 210. 12).
A. Description of their warriors:
Sātvatas were invincible in battles; they hit
their targets accurately in battles; they
fought in various ways; they were con-
querors of gods, demons and Gandharvas,
but were not proud; they depended for
victory on their own valour and were
not dependent on others (न हि शक्या
रणे जेतुं सात्वता … ॥लब्धलक्ष्याश्
च संग्रामे बहवश् चित्रयोधिनः।
देवदानवगन्धर्वान् विजेतारो ह्य् अवि-
स्मिताः।स्ववीर्यविजये युक्ता नैते परस्
परिग्रहाः॥) 7. 119. 20-21 (Nī. on Bom.
Ed. 7. 144. 22; परपरिग्रहाः पराधिनाः);
Sātvatas are not specifically mentioned in
the army of Sātyaki but his army which
consisted of warriors from different coun-
tries (तस्य योधा … नानादेशसमागताः)
must have also some Sātvatas (as Sātvatas,
formed a section of the Yādavas, and
Sātyaki is often referred to as a Sātvata,
see below section C, A. (5)); these war-
riors are described as heroic (वीर,
महावीर्य) and fighting with different
kinds of weapons (नानाप्रहरण) 5. 19.
2; their weapons detailed in 5. 19. 3-4.
B. Epic events: (1) Kṛṣṇa while trying
to pacify Baladeva and Vṛṣṇis who were
angered at the abduction of Subhadrā by
Arjuna by telling them that Arjuna did not
think of Sātvatas as covetous of wealth
(अर्थलुब्धान् न वः पार्थो मन्यते सात्व-
तान् सदा) 1. 213. 3; (2) Aśvatthāman was
honoured by Kurus, Pāṇḍavas and Sātvatas
(उपास्यमानो बहुभिः कुरुपाण्डवसात्व-
तत्ः) 7. 61. 14; (3) Sātvatas, along with
Sṛñjayas and Pāñcālas, followed Bhīma and
Arjuna who led the attack on Droṇa from
the southern and northern side (बीभत्सुर्
दक्षिणं पार्श्वम् उत्तरं तु वृकोदरः)
7. 132. 41; (4) Nārāyaṇa had told
Nārada that he as Kṛṣṇa would bring about
the annihilation of all the chiefs of Sātvatas
which was tantamount to the destruction
of his kinsmen (सर्वसात्वतमुख्यानां
द्वारकायाश् च … ।करिष्ये प्रलयं
घोरम् आत्मज्ञातिविनाशनम्) 12. 326. 92.
C. Sevaral persons referred to as belong-
ing to Sātvatas; or as their chiefs, or their
best; great chariot-fighters and the like:
A. Belonging to the Sātvatas: (a) Sātvata:
(1) Kṛtavarman 1. 213. 27; 5. 141. 39; 6.
16. 34; 6. 47. 19; 6. 52. 3; 6. 77. 2; 7. 66.
36; 7. 67. 19; 8. 31. 11; 9. 5. 2; 9. 20. 3,
5; 9. 24. 36, 55; 9. 26. 16; 9. 29. 9; 9. 63.
28; 9. 64. 2; 10. 4. 3, 10; 10. 5. 36; 10. 9.
6; (2) Kṛṣṇa 1. 210. 12 (Sātvat); 1. 215.
1; 3. 46. 41; 5. 69. 3; 9. 2. 64; (3) Ceki-
tāna 6. 80. 23-24; (4) Balarāma 9. 53. 1;
(5) Sātyaki 6. 55. 82-83; 6. 86. 81; 6. 99.
13; 6. 112. 12; 7. 9. 34; 7. 24. 45; 7. 60.
32; 7. 72. 35; 7. 73. 13; 7. 82. 38; 7. 85.
9, 39, 90, 101; 7. 88. 6, 15, 42; 7. 89. 16,
31, 38; 7. 91. 16, 19, 23, 40, 47, 49, 54; 7.
92. 13, 32, 39; 7. 93. 2, 11, 32; 7. 96. 29;
7. 97. 6, 33; 7. 98. 11; 7. 99. 22; 7. 102.
11; 7. 105. 1, 6; 7. 108. 5; 7. 116. 27; 7.
117. 1, 9, 42, 54; 7. 120. 38, 58; 7. 122. 34,
66, 87; 7. 128. 24; 7. 131. 2, 4, 6, 21, 24;
7. 132. 5-6, 12; 7. 133. 31; 7. 137. 5, 20,
24-25, 33; 7. 141. 9-10; 7. 145. 42, 66; 7.
146. 2; 7. 148. 56; 7. 157. 41; 7. 164. 25, 36,
159; 7. 169. 20, 38; 7. 171. 49; 8. 9. 292; 9.
2. 64; 9. 6. 28; 9. 14. 33; 9. 19. 26; 9. 20.
24. (b) Sātvatī (f.): (1) Devakī सात्वती-
(पुत्र) 2. 35. 8 (Kṛṣṇa, son of Sātvatī);
(2) Not named (her name Śrutaśravā ac-
cording to Harivaṃaśa 1. 24. 10): सात्वती-
(सुत) 2. 42. 6 (Śiśupāla, son of Sātvatī);
(3) Subhadrā: सात्वती 1. 213. 61; 14. 68. 12;
15. 1. 21; 15. 16. 20; 15. 36. 13; सात्वती-
पुत्र (Abhimanyu, son of Sātvatī) 6. 69.
30; 7. 38. 20; 7. 51. 8;
B. Chief or best
among the Sātvatas (or Sātvats): Kṛṣṇa
(i) ऋषभः सर्वसात्वतां 5. 70. 1; 5. 92.
5, 30; 5. 128. 7; (see सात्वतर्षभ below);
(ii) °सात्वतपुंगव: Sātyaki 7. 117. 41;
(iii) पुरोगः सर्वसात्वताम्: Kṛṣṇa 5. 84.
2; (iv) सात्वतप्रवर: (1) Kṛṣṇa 2. 42.
60; 10. 16. 5; (2) Sātyaki (प्रवरः
सात्वतानाम्) 7. 115. 23; 7. 117. 52; (v)
सात्वतानां महारथः: (1) Kṛtavarman
8. 5. 94; (2) Sātyaki 5. 19. 1; 7. 97. 45;
(vi) सात्वतमुख्य: (1) Kṛṣṇa 2. 43.
22; (2) Pradyumna 3. 20. 5; (3) Sātyaki
7. 94. 8; (vii) सात्वतर्षभ: Sātyaki 7.
122. 32; (viii) सात्वतां वरः: (1) Kṛṣṇa
9. 61. 40; (2) Sātyaki 7. 73. 37; (ix)
सात्वतानां वरिष्ठः: Kṛtavarman 8. 4.
92; (x) वृषभः सर्वसात्वताम्: Kṛṣṇa
12. 200. 16; (xi) सात्वतश्रेष्ठ: (1)
Kṛṣṇa 6. 102. 60; 9. 62. 28; (2) Sātyaki
7. 117. 58; (xii) सात्वताग्र्य: Sātyaki 6.
22. 4;
C. (i) Who is ill-willed towards
Sātvatas: सात्वतानां नृशंसात्मा: Śiśu-
pāla 2. 42. 6; (ii) Worst among Sātvatas:
सात्वताधम: Sātyaki 7. 145. 52;
D.
Daughter of the Sātvatas: सात्वतात्मजा:
Subhadrā 1. 213. 15. [See Yadu, Vṛṣṇi]

सामुद्रनिष्कुट
Sāmudraniṣkuṭa m. (pl.): Name of a
Janapada.
Listed by Saṃjaya among the northern
Janapadas (also called Deśas 6. 10. 68)
of Bhāratavarṣa (अत ऊर्ध्वं जनपदान्
निबोध) 6. 10. 37, 5; (काक्षाः सामुद्र-
निष्कुटाः) 6. 10. 47; (these are probably
identical with Vairāmas and others who are
mentioned as समुद्रनिष्कुटे जाताः 2. 47.
9-10; cf. also सागरकुक्षिस्थान् म्लेच्छान्
2. 29. 15 and other references to Mlecchas
living along the ocean and islands p. 840
and Sāgarānūpaga above).

सारस्वत
Sārasvata m. (pl.): Name of a people.
According to the report of Saṃjaya
to Dhṛtarāṣṭra before the war, Nakula was
supposed to fight against Ulūka and the
Sārasvata hordes (उलूकं चापि कैतव्यं
ये च सारस्वता गणाः।नकुलःकल्पयाम्
आस भागं … ) 5. 56. 23.

साल्वेयक
Sālveyaka m. (pl.): Name of a people.
Suśarman, the king of Trigartas, com-
plained to Duryodhana that he was, in the
bygone days, often humiliated and forcibly
oppressed by Sālveyakas and Matsyas
led by Kīcaka (असकृन् निकृतः पूर्वं
मत्स्यैः साल्वेयकैः सह।सूतेन चैव
मत्स्यस्य कीचकेन पुनः पुनः।बाधितो
 … बलात्) 4. 29. 2-3.

सावित्रीपुत्रकाञ्चल
Sāvitrīputrakāñcala m. (pl.): Name
of a people.
On the seventeenth day of the war,
at night (निशि 8. 1. 25), when Saṃjaya
reported to Dhṛtarāṣṭra the death of Karṇa,
he asked Saṃjaya who were killed in war
and who have survived (के नु जीवन्ति के
मृताः) 8. 4. 3; Saṃjaya mentioned Sāvitrī-
putrakāñcalas among those that were killed
8. 4. 47.

सिंहल
Siṃhala m. (pl.): Name of a people.
A. Origin: Nandinī, the cow of
Vasiṣṭha, created Siṃhalas from her foam
in order to fight with the army of Viśvā-
mitra (सिंहलान् … फेनतः सा ससर्ज ह)
1. 165. 36.
B. Description: Dark, having
eyes with red corners, clad in garments
which were set with gems (संवृता मणि-
चीरैस् तु श्यामास् ताम्रान्तलोचनाः) 2. 48.
31.
C. Epic events: (1) Siṃhalas were
among the people who arrived to attend
the Rājasūya of Yudhiṣṭhira 2. 31. 12; they
brought with them as tribute for Yudhi-
ṣṭhira the quintessence of the ocean viz.,
Vaiḍūrya, pearls, conches and hundreds of
elephant-coverings, but they were stopped
at the gate (समुद्रसारं वैडूर्यं
मुक्ताः शङ्खांस् तथैव च।शतशश् च
कुथांस् तत्र सिंहला समुपाहरन्) 2. 48.
30-31 (Nī. on Bom. Ed. 2. 52. 35: सनुद्र-
सारं मुक्ताफलादि, on 2. 52. 36: कुथान्
करिकम्बलान्); Siṃhalas mentioned by
Kṛṣṇa among those whose kings, frightened
by the lustre of weapons, attended the
Rājasūya and were seen by him working as
servants (यत्र सर्वान् महीपालान् शस्त्र-
तेजोभयार्दितान्।आगतान् अहं अद्राक्षं
यज्ञे ते परिवेषकान्) 3. 48. 18-19, 22;
(2) On the twelfth day of the war,
Siṃhalas were posted by Droṇa at the neck
(ग्रीवायाम्) of the Suparṇavyūha (7. 19.
4-5) of Kauravas 7. 19. 7.

सिद्ध
Siddha m. (pl.): Name of a Janapada.
Mentioned by Saṃjaya among the
northern Janapadas (also called Deśas 6.
10. 68) of Bhāratavarṣa (अत ऊर्ध्वं
जनपदान् निबोध) 6. 10. 37, 5; (बर्बराः
सिद्धा … ) 6. 10. 55.

सिन्धु
Sindhu, Saindhava m. (pl.): Name
of a Janapada and its people; also called
Rāṣṭra 8. 4. 11, Viṣaya 14. 76. 2, and Deśa
6. 10. 68; 7. 53. 47; 8. 27. 91; very often
mentioned along with Sauvīras.
A. Location: Listed twice by Saṃjaya,
among the northern Janapadas of Bhārata-
varṣa (अत ऊर्धवं जनपदान् निबोध)
6. 10. 37, 5; once, along with Sauvīras
(काश्मीराः सिन्धुसौवीरा … ) 6. 10. 52,
and then, with Pulindakas (भोजाः सिन्धु-
पुलिन्दकाः) 6. 10. 39.
B. Description of
the country, its warriors, and characteristics
of the people and horses: (a) country:
sinful (पापदेश) 7. 53. 47; 8. 27. 91;
(b) Warriors: brave (शूर) 7. 85. 73;
fighting with curved प्रासस् (नखरप्रास-
योधिन्) 7. 85. 73; 12. 102. 3; arrogant in
battles (युधदुर्मद) 14. 77. 9; Arjuna
described Sindhu warriors as doing sinful
acts in battles (पापाचारा रणाजिरे) 7.
53. 48; (c) People: (1) They ate rice
cooked in milk (सर्वक्षीरान्नभोक्तारः)
7. 53. 48; Madrakas, Sindhus and Sauvīras,
according to Karṇa, were म्लेच्छस् born
in sinful countries and hence incapable
of discerning what was proper धर्म
(मद्रकाः सिन्धुसौवीरा धर्मं विद्युः
कथं त्व् इह।पापदेशोद्भवा म्लेच्छा
धर्माणां अविचक्षणाः) 8. 27. 91; (2)
A certain Brāhmaṇa told Dhṛtarāṣṭra
in the assembly of the Kurus (8. 30.
7-8, 41) that in the opinion of a certain
Rākṣasī (राक्षसी काचिद् अब्रवीत्) Vasātis,
Sindhus and Sauvīras were, in general,
contemptible (वसातिसिन्धुसौवीरा इति प्रायो
विकुत्सिताः) 8. 30. 46-47; (3) Sindhu
country was the principal one among the
ten राष्ट्रस् which were under the control of
Jayadratha (सिन्धुराष्ट्रमुखानीह दश
राष्ट्राणि यस्य वै।वशे तिष्ठन्ति वीरस्य)
8. 4. 11; (d) The Sindhu horses yoked to
the chariot of Jayadratha were obedient to
the charioteer; they drew the chariot well,
moving in different directions; were large
and speedy like wind ( … सारथेर् वश्याः
सैन्धवाः साधुवाहिनः।विकुर्वाणा
बृहन्तो ऽश्वाः श्वसनोपमरंहसः॥)
7. 42. 2; the horses of the Sindhu country
which were chosen by Bāhuka (Nala)
to go to the Vidarbha country were
endowed with energy and strength, were of
noble breed and good temper, free from
interior marks, of broad nostrils and large
jaws, blameless as they were free from ten
curls, and having the speed of wind; though
lean they were capable (of going long dis-
tances) and enduring on roads (तेजोबल-
समायुक्तान् कुलशीलसमन्वितान्।वर्जिताल्̃
लक्षणैर् हीनैः पृथुप्रोथान् महाहनून्।
शुद्धान् दशभिर् आवर्तैः सिन्धुजान् वात-
रंहसः॥; कृशान् अश्वान् समर्थान्
अध्वनि क्षमान्) 3. 69. 12, 11, 17 (Nī. on
Bom. Ed. 3. 71. 13-14 (सीलं सादिचित्तानु-
सारिता हीनैर् लक्षणैः शतपदीप्रभृति-
भिर् वर्जितान्।प्रोथं नासिका।हनुः
अधरं मुखफलकम्।शुद्धान् ह्रदा-
वर्तादिदुष्टावर्तहीनान् सिन्धुजान् सिन्धु-
देशजान्।).
C. Epic events: (1) The
kings of Saindhavas, subdued by Pāṇḍavas,
attended the Rājasūya of Yudhiṣṭhira and
acted as servers (यत्र सर्वान् महीपालान्
शस्त्रतेजोभयार्दितान्। … सैन्धवांस्
तथा। … यज्ञे ते परिवेषकान्॥) 3. 48.
18, 21-22; (2) Jayadratha suggested to
Draupadī to abandon Pāṇḍavas who had
lost their kingdom and marry him so that
she could, along with him, rule over the
entire Sindhu and Suvīra countries (अखिलान्
सिन्धुसौवीरान् अवाप्नुहि मया सह) 3. 251.
18; the warriors of the Śibi, Sindhu and
Trigarta countries were dejected to see
Pāṇḍavas fighting with them 3. 255. 3;
Arjuna killed the Saindhavas who happened
to come within the range of his arrows
(त्रिगर्तान् सैन्धवान् अपि।जघान … बाण-
गोचरम् आगतान्) 3. 255. 28; when Jaya-
dratha fled, Arjuna asked Bhīma not to kill
any longer Saindhava warriors (वारयाम्
आस निघ्नन्तं भीमं सैन्धवसैनिकान्)
3. 255. 36; the inmates of the आश्रम
were delighted to see Yudhiṣṭhira return
with abducted Draupadī after defeating
the Sindhu and Sauvīra armies (जित्वा तान्
सिन्धुसौवी रान्) 3. 255. 50; (3) Jaya-
dratha, of the Sindhu country, joined the
army of Duryodhana (जयद्रथमुखाश्
चान्ये सिन्धुसौवी रवासिनः) 5. 19. 19: (4)
Before the start of the war, the Kṣatriyas
of the Sindhu country and others, headed
by Bhīṣma, stood in the front position of
the army (भीष्मो ऽग्रतः सर्वसैन्यस्य
वृद्धः … क्षत्रिया ये च सिन्धौ) 6. 20.
9-10; (5) On the second day of war,
Sindhu warriors and Sauvīras (सिन्धु-
सौवीराः), led by Śakuni, protected Droṇa
who was behind Bhīṣma in the Mahāvyūha
of Kauravas 6. 47. 10, 14; (6) On the
third day, Sindhu warriors and Sauvīras
(सिन्धुसौवीराः) were posted at the
‘neck’ position (ग्रिवायाम्) of the Garuḍa-
vyūha of Kauravas 6. 52. 2-3, 5; (7) On
the eighth dav, Irāvān, son of Arjuna,
attacked the Kaurava army with horses
of different countries some of them being
those from the Sindhu country (वाजिनाम्।
 … सिन्धुजानां च सर्वशः); the horses
were swift like wind (हयैर् वातजवैर् … )
6. 86. 3, 5-6; (8) On the thirteenth day,
Arjuna assured Kṛṣṇa that he would kill
the next day the Saindhava warriors along
with their kings (मया सराजका बाणैर्
नुन्ना नंक्ष्यन्ति सैन्धवाः) 7. 53. 48;
(9) On the fourteenth day, Yudhiṣṭhira
pointed out to Sātyaki that Arjuna, pro-
ceeding towards Jayadratha, was encircled
by the Sindhu warriors and Sauvīras
(संवृतः सिन्धुसौवीरैः) 7. 85. 73;
Sātyaki told Yudhiṣṭhira that Saindhavas
were no match for Arjuna (सैन्धव-
पौरवाः। … एते ऽर्जुनस्य क्रुद्धस्य
कलां नार्हन्ति षोडशीम्) 7. 86. 28-29; on
that day the Kaurava army which included
Sindhu warriors and Sauvīras ran helter-
skelter since they were being killed by the
arrows of Bhīma and Karṇa fighting each
other (ततो व्युदस्तं तत् सैन्यं सिन्धु-
सौवीरकौरवम्); they ran away from
them in all directions; the earth was covered
with their bodies along with their armours,
arrows and banners; when Karṇa saw the
destruction of the Kurus Sauvīras and Sain-
dhavas he was ablaze with anger (दृष्ट्वा
च कुरुसौवी रसैन्धवानां बलक्षयम्)
7. 113. 11-14; 7. 114. 17-18; (10) During
the night war (fourteenth-fifteenth day) all
Saindhavas and others, afraid, (simply)
watched Karṇa who alone could withstand
the shower of weapons released at him
by Ghaṭotkaca; they respected his compo-
sure in battle (असंमोहं पूजयन्तोऽस्य
संख्ये) 7. 154. 45; (11) After the war,
the women of Sindhu, Sauvīra and other
countries kept a watch on the dead body
of Jayadratha (सिन्धुसौवी रगान्धार-
काम्बोजयवनस्त्रियः) 11. 22. 11; (12)
When Arjuna reached the Sindhu country
along with Aśvamedha horse, the warriors
and their kings fought a fierce battle with
him; they encircled Arjuna so that he look-
ed like a bird moving in a cage (कोष्ठकी-
कृत्य कौन्तेयम् … अयोधयन्।स … ददृशे
 … पञ्जरान्तरसंचारी शकुन्त इव … ॥)
14. 76. 10, 13; Arjuna swooned for a
while due to the shower of the arrows of
Sindhu fighters (सैन्धवाः) 14. 76. 21-23;
when he recovered, he started showering
arrows so that the Saindhava warriors and
their kings could not be seen; the Sain-
dhavas were afraid due to the sound (of
the bow); they ran, wept due to sorrow
and lay down on the ground; the army (of
Saindhavas) was thus torn by Arjuna
(ततस् ते सैन्धवा योधाः सर्व एव
सराजकाः।नादृश्यन्त शरैः कीर्णाः … ॥
तस्य शब्देन वित्रेसुर् भयार्ताश् च विदु-
द्रुवः।मुमुचुश् चाश्रुशोकार्ताः सुषुपुश्
चापि सैन्धवाः॥ … सैन्यं विदार्य) 14.
76. 28-29, 32; the Saindhava warriors were
once again ready to fight with Arjuna and
they showered arrows at him; Arjuna told
them that he would not kill them if they
surrendered; but Saindhava warriors conti-
nued to shoot arrows; the kings of the
Sindhu country remembering the death of
Jayadratha threw प्रासस् and शक्तिस् on
Arjuna; he cut off their missiles before
they reached him; the warriors, desirous
of victory, continued their attack (आपत-
तां तेषां योधानां जयगृद्धिनाम्)
14. 77. 18; Arjuna cut off their heads; they
ran away but returned and although they
were being killed they fought with Arjuna
according to their vigour and energy
(यथाप्राणं यथोत्साहं योधयाम् आसुर्
अर्जुनम्) most of them, whose horses
were tired, swooned (कृता विसंज्ञा भू-
यिष्ठाः क्लान्तवाहनसैनिकाः); knowing
their plight, Duḥśalā, daughter of Dhṛta-
rāṣṭra, took her grandson with her and
approached Arjuna wishing peace for the
surviving warriors (शान्त्यर्थं सर्व-
योधानाम्; शमार्थं सर्वयोधानाम्); she
requested him to cease fighting with Sain-
dhavas (शमं गच्छ धनंजय); thus
Arjuna defeated Saindhava warriors 14. 77.
2-43.
D. Past event: Vidurā exhorted
her son not to let himself be dispirited
and be under the control of the maidens of
Sindhu country (मा च सैन्धवकन्या-
नाम् अवसन्नो वशं गमः) 5. 132. 32;
she told him that she would honour him if
he was able to kill all Saindhava warriors
(अथ त्वां पूजयिष्यामि हत्वा वै सर्वसैन्-
धवान्) 5. 133. 19.
