सुनिक
Sunika m. (pl.): Name of a people.
Mentioned along with Yavanas,
Pāradas and Śakas who knew the माया of
Asuras employed by them while fighting;
they are described as very fierce and having
fierce eyes; they fought with Arjuna and
were killed by him by the माया of his
missiles (विदन्त्य् असुरमायां ये सुघोरा
घोरचक्षुषः।यवनाः पारदाश् चैव
शकाश् च सुनिकैः सह॥) 7. 68. 41;
(म्लेच्छान् अशातयत् सर्वान् समेतान् अस्त्र-
मायया) 7. 68. 44.

सुन्दरवेग
Sundaravega m. (pl.): Name of a
people.
Their king Bāhu listed by Bhīma
among the eighteen well-known kings who
extirpated their kinsmen and friends along
with their relatives (अष्टादशेमे राजानः
प्रख्याता … ।ये समुच्चिच्छिदुर् ज्ञातीन्
सुहृदश् च सबान्धवान्॥ … बाहुः सुन्दर-
वेगानाम्) 5. 72. 11, 15.

सुमल्लिक
Sumallika m. (pl.): Name of a Jana-
pada.
Listed by Saṃjaya among the northern
Janapadas (also called Deśas 6. 10. 68)
of Bhāratavarṣa (अत ऊर्ध्वं जनपदान्
निबोध) 6. 10. 37, 5; (सुदामानः सुमल्लि-
काः) 6. 10. 53.

सुराष्ट्र
Surāṣṭra (Saurāṣṭraka) m. (pl.):
Name of a Janapada and its people.
A. Location: Listed by Saṃjaya
among the northern Janapadas (also called
Deśas 6. 10. 68: Viṣaya 2. 28. 40) of the
Bhāratavarṣa (अत ऊर्ध्वं जनपदान्
निबोध) 6. 10. 37, 5; (सुराष्ट्राः केकयास्
तथा) 6. 10. 47; near the western ocean
(see the next).
B. Holiness: There were
in Surāṣṭra holy places (आयतनानि) like
Camasonmajjana, Prabhāsa in the nearby
ocean (प्रभासं चोदधौ तीर्थम्), and
Piṇḍāraka; holy cities like Dvāravatī (पुण्या
द्वारवती); rivers, lakes and holy mountains
(पुण्ये गिरौ) like Ujjayanta (सरितः
शैलान् सरांसि च … ।सुराष्ट्रेषु … पुण्यान्य्
आयतनानि च) 3. 86. 16-24 (for Camason-
majjana, Prabhāsa, Piṇḍāraka, Dvāravatī
and mountain Ujjayanta see Vol. I).
C.
Characteristic: According to the demon
Kalmāṣapāda people of Surāṣṭra were of
mixed caste (संकरा वै सुराष्ट्राः) 8. 30.
73.
D. Epic events: (1) Sahadeva in
his expedition to the south of Indraprastha
before the Rājasūya (प्रययौ दक्षिणां
दिशम् 2. 28. 1, 37; 2. 23. 9) brought under
control Āhṛti, the king of Surāṣṭras, with
great effort; while he lived there (सुराष्ट्र-
विषयस्थश् च) he sent for Rukmin, the
king of Bhojakaṭa 2. 28. 39-40; (2) Before
the start of the war, on the battle-
field, Bṛhadbala helped by great chariot-
fighters from Surāṣṭra and other countries,
ready with their weapons, protected the
army of Kauravas in the south (महा-
रथैर् … सौराष्ट्रकैर् … आत्तशस्त्रैः।
बृहद्बलः … बलं त्वदीयं दक्षिणतो
ऽभिपाति) 6. 20. 14; (3) From the countries
of the southern ocean, the Aśvamedha
horse went to Gokarṇa, Prabhāsa and
Dvāravati in Surāṣṭra (सुराष्ट्रान् अभितो
ययौ) 14. 84. 12-13.
E. Past events:
Kuśarddhika, the king of Surāṣṭra, named
by Bhīma among the eighteen infamous
kings, who extirpated their kinsmen, friends
and their relatives (अष्टादशेमे राजानः
प्रख्याता … ।ये समुच्चिच्छिदुर् ज्ञातीन्
सुहृदश् च सबान्धवान् … सुराष्ट्राणां
कुशर्द्धिकः) 5. 72. 11, 14.
F. Āhṛti,
the king of Surāṣṭra, is referred to as
सुराष्ट्राधिपति 2. 28. 39.

सुवीर
Suvīra, Sauvīra (Sauvīraka) m. (pl.):
Name of a Janapada and its people; they
are often mentioned along with Sindhus.
A. Location: Listed by Saṃjaya
among the northern Janapadas (also called
Deśas 6. 10. 68) of Bhāratavarṣa (अत
ऊर्ध्वं जनपदान् निबोध) 6. 10. 37, 5;
(काश्मीराः सिन्धुसौवीरा … ) 6. 10. 52;
once also referred to as राष्ट्र (3. 252. 1).
B. Description of their warriors: Excellent
young heroes (सौवीरवीराः प्रवरा युवानो
 … ) 3. 249. 12; brave (शूर) 6. 18. 13;
strong (बलिन्) 3. 249. 12; 7. 85. 73; 6. 20.
10 (?); excellent attackers (प्रवराणां
प्रहारिणाम्) 3. 255. 9; ready to lay their
bodies (तनुत्यज्) 6. 18. 14; fighting with
sharp lances (नखरप्रासयोधिन्) 7. 85.
73; 12. 102. 3.
C. Characteristics of the
people: Karṇa while deriding Śalya men-
tioned Sindhus and Sauvīras as those who
did not know धर्म since they were
Mlecchas born in sinful countries and those
who could not discern between धर्म and
अधर्म; they wholeheartedly treaded on
despicable paths (आ केशाग्रान् नखाग्राच्
च वक्तव्येषु कुवर्त्मसु॥ … सिन्धुसौवीरा
धर्मं विद्युः कथं त्व् इह।पापदेशोद्-
भवा म्लेच्छा धर्माणाम् अविचक्षणाः॥)
8. 27. 90-91 (Nī. on Bom. Ed. 8. 40. 42:
वक्तव्येषु गर्हणीयेषु); he also told him
that according to a Rākṣasī, Sindhus and
Sauvīras were in general despicable; this
was reported by a certain Brāhmaṇa in
the Kuru assembly (वसातिसिन्धुसौवीरा
इति प्रायो विकुत्सिताः) 8. 30. 41, 46-47.
D. Epic events: (1) Kṛṣṇa recalled that
Śiśupāla had abducted the unwilling wife
of Babhru on her arrival at Suvīra country
from Dvārakā (?) (सौवीरान् प्रतिपत्तौ च
बभ्रोर् एष यशस्विनः।भार्याम् अभ्य-
हरन् मोहाद् अकामां ताम् इतो गताम्॥)
2. 42. 10 (Nī. reads (Bom. Ed. 2. 45.
10) सौवीरान् प्रतियाताम् and explains
सौवीरान् देशविशेषान् इतो हस्तिनापुरात्
गतां प्रस्थिताम्; he further adds:
सौवीरात् प्रतिपत्तौ चेति पाठे प्रति-
पत्तौ विवाहकाले बभ्रोर् यादवस्य);
(2) When Jayadratha had started for the
country of Śālvas (3. 248. 6), heroic,
young warriors of Suvīra country accom-
panied him (सौवीरवीरा … युवानो … अनु-
यान्ति) 3. 249. 12; Koṭikāśya suggested to
Jayadratha to abduct Draupadī and return
to Suvīra country (सुवीरान् … व्रज) 3. 251.
6; Jayadratha invited Draupadī to be his
wife and obtain the mastery of the entire
Sindhu and Suvīra countries (अखिलान्
सिन्धुसौवीरान् अवाप्नुहि) 3. 251. 18; during
the battle with Jayadratha, Yudhiṣṭhira
himself killed in a moment a hundred of
excellent, attacking Suvīra warriors (राजा
स्वयं सुवीराणां प्रवराणां प्रहारिणां।
निमेषमात्रेण शतं जघान) 3. 255. 9;
Arjuna cut off with भल्ल arrows the bows
and heads of all the twelve Suvīra princes
(सौवीरका द्वादश राजापुत्राः 3. 249. 9)
accompanying Jayadratha (द्वादशानां तु
सर्वेषां सौवीराणां … ) 3. 255. 27; the
inmates of the आश्रम were happy to see
Yudhiṣṭhira return with Draupadī after
defeating the Sindhu and Suvīra warriors
(जित्वा तान् सिन्धुसौवी रान्) 3. 255. 50; (3)
The kings of Sindhu and Suvīra countries
(सिन्धुसौवीरवासिनः), led by Jayadratha,
joined the side of Duryodhana; their army
was an अक्षौहिणी strong (तेषाम् अक्षौहिणी
सेना) 5. 19. 14, 19-20; (4) In the arrange-
ment of the Kaurava army on the battle-
field, Sauvīras (सौवीराः) were among the
twelve Janapadas who formed the rear-
guard of Bhīṣma (पृष्ठगोपाः); they
offered protection to Bhīṣma with their
large number of chariot-fighters (महता
रथवंशेन) 6. 18. 10, 13-14; 6. 20. 14;
(5) On the second day of the war, Sindhu
and Suvīra warriors (सिन्धुसौवीराः) pro-
tected Droṇa who was behind Bhīṣma in
the Mahāvyūha of Kauravas (6. 47. 10-12,
14); protected by Suvīra warriors and
others, (प्राच्यसौवीरकेकयैः) Bhīṣma
attacked Arjuna 6. 48. 21; (6) On the
third day, warriors of the Sindhu and Suvīra
countries, along with others, were posted
at the ‘neck’ of the Garuḍavyūha of the
Kauravas (मद्रकाः सिन्धुसौवीरास् … ॥ …
ग्रीवायां संनिवेशिताः) 6. 52. 2-3, 5-6;
as directed by Bhīṣma, all Suvīra troops,
along with many others, quickly marched
towards Arjuna ( … सौवीरगणाश् च सर्वे
 … किरीटिनं त्वरमाणाभिसस्रुर् … ) 6. 55.
74; on that day Arjuna killed all Sauvīra
troops (सौवीरगणाश् च सर्वे) with his
Māhendra (or Aindra 6. 55. 110, 120)
missile 6. 55. 130; (7) On the fifth day,
the Sauvīra warriors (मद्रसौवीरगान्धा-
रैस्) and others, afraid due to the sound
of the Gāṇḍīva bow, took refuge with the
king of Kaliṅga country and then all
together attacked Arjuna (6. 67. 13, 16);
(8) On the sixth day, Bhagadatta, accom-
panied by the warriors of the Madra,
Sauvīra and Kekaya countries, stood at
the ‘chest’ position of the Krauñcavyūha
of Kauravas (मद्रसौवीरकेकयैः।उरस्य्
अभून् … ) 6. 71. 14, 18; (9) On the ninth
day, Sauvīra warriors (सौवीराः) were
among those who did not forsake Bhīṣma
although they were getting killed by sharp
arrows (6. 102. 7); (10) On the tenth day,
Sauvīra warriors (सौवीराः), emboldened
by Duryodhana (6. 112. 102, 105, 107)
attacked Arjuna; he burnt (ददाह) them
by the use of divine missiles; they then
stopped attacking Arjuna who forced
them to run away (द्रावयित्वा वरूथिनीम्)
6. 112. 108, 110-117; towards the end of
the day, when the Kuru army afflicted by
the arrows of Arjuna fled, Sauvīra warriors
(सौवीराः) were among those twelve Jana-
padas who, though afflicted by arrows and
feeling pain due to wounds (शरार्ता
व्रणपीडिताः) did not abandon Bhīṣma
while he fought with Arjuna 6. 114. 75-
77; (11) On the eleventh day, Karṇa led
the archers (प्रमुखे सर्वधण्विनाम्)
of the Śakaṭavyūha of Kauravas; Duryo-
dhana who followed him was at the head
of the Sauvīra warriors (सौवीराः), Kitavas
and others 7. 6. 7-8, 15; (12) On the
fourteenth day, the king of Avanti helped
by the Sauvīra warriors (आवन्त्यः सह
सौवीरैः) checked the advance of Dhṛṣṭa-
dyumna towards Jayadratha 7. 70. 45, 51;
Yudhiṣṭhira, at one stage, drew attention
of Sātyaki towards Arjuna who was sur-
rounded by brave warriors of the Sindhu
and Suvīra countries, although their
number was very much diminished, using
sharp lances while fighting (सिन्धुसौवीरैर्
नखरप्रासयोधिभिः।अत्यन्तापचितैः
शूरैः) 7. 85. 73; but Sātyaki assured
Yudhiṣṭhira that the warriors of Suvīra
countries were not at all a match for
Arjuna once he was angry (ये च सौवीरका
योधास् … ।एते ऽर्जुनस्य क्रुद्धस्य कलां
नार्हन्ति षोडशीम्) 7. 86. 28-29; the army
of Kauravas which included warriors from
Sindhu, Suvīra and Kuru countries was
scattered by the swift arrows of both Karṇa
and Bhīma fighting with each other (ततो
व्युदस्तं तत् सैन्यं सिन्धुसौवीरकौर-
वम्।प्रोत्सारितं … ); afflicted by arrows
and with their horses and men killed and
chariots broken (हताश्वनरवाहनाः) they
left Bhīma and Karṇa and ran in all direc-
tions; thinking that the gods were deluding
them for the benefit of Bhīma (नूनं
पार्थार्थम् एवास्मान् मोहयन्ति दिवौ-
कसः) they stopped shooting arrows and
became spectators (शरपातं समुत्सृज्य
स्थिता युद्धदिदृक्षवः) 7. 113. 7, 11-14;
Karṇa was enraged to see the destruction
all around of the army of Kuru, Sindhu
and Suvīra countries (कुरुसौवीरसैन्ध-
वानां बलक्षयम् … सर्वतः), the dead
bodies of elephants, and the earth covered
with the armours, banners and weapons 7.
114. 17-18; (13) On the fifteenth day,
when Dhṛtarāṣṭra heard the death of Droṇa
he remembered that Sātyaki had formerly
defeated the large army of a king (not
named) of the Suvīra country (सौवीर-
राजस्य प्रमथ्य महतीं चमूं) 7.
9. 29; (14) When the war was over,
Gāndhārī, on the battle-field, pointed out
to Kṛṣṇa women of the Sindhu and Suvīra
countries who sat around the dead body
of Jayadratha keeping watch over him
(तम् एताः पर्युपासन्ते रक्षमाणा महा-
भुजम्।सिन्धुसौवीर° °स्त्रियः।) 11.
22. 9. 11.
E. Past events: (1) Vidurā
exhorted Saṃjaya not to be under the
control of the Sindhu maidens but live,
as before, feeling proud of being in the
company of the Sauvīra maidens (उष्य
सौवीरकन्याभिः श्लाघस्वार्थैर् यथा
पुरा।मा च सैन्धवकन्यानाम् अवसन्नो
वशं गमः॥) 5. 132. 32; (2) Ajabindu,
the king of the Suvīra people, mentioned by
Bhīma among those eighteen kings who,
born at the end of the aeon, extirpated their
kinsmen, friends and relatives (अष्टादशेमे
राजानः … ये समुच्चिच्छिदुर् ज्ञातीन् सु-
हृदश् च सबान्धवान्॥ … अजबिन्दुः …
सुवीराणां … । … यूगान्ते … संभूताः … )
5. 72. 11, 14, 17.
F. Some persons,
especially Jayadratha, are referred to as
belonging to the Suvīra country or as pro-
tector or king of Suvīra country or people:
A. One related to Suvīra country: (i)
सौवीर: Jayadratha 3. 251. 6; 3. 255. 8;
(ii) सौवीरी (f.): Wife (not named) of
Manasyu 1. 89. 7; (iii) सौवीरक: (1)
Jayadratha 3. 251. 1; (2) Twelve princes
(not named) who accompanied Jayadratha
3. 249. 9;
B. Heroes from Suvīra country:
सौवीरकवीर: Balāhaka, Anīka, Vidāraṇa
(or Anīkavidāraṇa ?) and others, brothers
of Jayadratha 3. 249. 12; C. Protector or
king of Suvīra country: (i) सुवीरराष्ट्रप:
Jayadratha 3. 252. 1; (ii) पतिः सौवीर-
(सिन्धूनाम्): Jayadratha 3. 251. 7; (iii)
सौवीरभर्तृ: Jayadratha 11. 22. 9; (iv)
सौवीरराज: (1) Jayadratha 3. 249. 11; 3.
3. 252. 12-132; (2) A king, not named 7. 9.
29; (v) राजा सुवीराणाम्: (1) Jayadratha
3. 255. 9; (2) Śatruṃtapa 12. 138. 4; (vi)
सौवीर (सिन्धूनाम्) ईश्वरः: Jayadratha
7. 53. 11.

सुस्थर
Susthara m. (pl.): Name of a people.
Mentioned among many others who,
afraid of Jarāsandha, left the north and
resorted to the south (सुस्थराश् च सुकु-
ट्टाश् च … ॥; तथोत्तरां दिशं चापि परि-
त्यज्य भयार्दिताः। … दक्षिणां दिशम्
आश्रिताः॥) 2. 13. 25, 27.

सुह्म
Suhma m. (pl.): Name of a people.
A. Location: Listed by Saṃjaya
among the northern Janapadas (also called
Deśas 6. 10. 68) of Bhāratavarṣa (अत
ऊर्ध्वं जनोपदान् निबोध) 6. 10. 37,
5; (सुह्माश् च विजयास् तथा) 6. 10. 44;
the country of Suhmas lay to the north
of Hāstinapura (see
B. Epic events No. 2
below) and also to the east of Hāstinapura
beyond Magadha and Videha (see B. Epic
events No. 1. below); a part of it was near
the Aṅga country and the other near Vaṅga
and Tāmralipta; this latter part was, it
appears, designated eastern Suhma (Prācya-
suhma) (see B. Epic events No. 3 below).
B. Epic events: (1) After his marriage,
Pāṇḍu wishing to conquer the whole earth
(कृतोद्वाहः … जिगीषमाणो वसुधाम् 1. 105.
7) conquered the Magadha and the Videha
countries and then extended the fame of
Kurus as far as Kāśis, Suhmas and Puṇḍras
(तथा काशिषु सुह्मेषु पुण्ड्रेषु … । …
कुरूणाम् अकरोद् यशः॥) 1. 105. 12;
(2) Arjuna in his expedition to the north
(दिशं धनपतेर् इष्टाम् 2. 23. 9; प्रयाव्
उत्तराम् तस्माद् दिशम् धनदपालिताम् 2. 24.
1) before the Rājasūya harassed Suhmas
and Colas (सुह्मांश् च चोलांश् च … । …
प्रामथत् कुरुनन्दनः) 2. 24. 20; (3)
Bhīmasena in his expedition to the east
(ययौ प्राचीं दिशं प्रति 2. 26. 1; 2. 27.
9) defeated in battle Suhmas and Prācya-
suhmas; he defeated the king of Suhmas
(ततः सुह्मान् प्राच्यसुह्मान् … विजित्य
युधि कौन्तेयो … ॥सुह्मानाम् अधिपं
चैव) 2. 27. 14, 23 (Suhmas here distin-
guished as Suhmas and Prācyasuhmas);
(4) On the seventeenth day of war, at
night, when Karṇa's death was reported to
Dhṛtarāṣṭra (हते कर्णे महाराज निशि …
8. 1. 25; 8. 2. 20; 8. 5. 1) he remembered
Karṇa's past exploits one of which was
his having defeated the Suhmas and made
them pay tribute (सुह्मान् अङ्गांश् च …
यो जित्वा समरे वीरश् चक्रे बलिभृतः
पुरा) 8. 5. 19-20 (reference to Karṇa's
दिग्विजय before the Vaiṣṇavayajña of
Duryodhana 3. 241. 32; Cr. edn. Vol. 4.
App. 1. 24. 41-44; however, Suhma is not
directly mentioned here among the eastern
countries).

सृञ्जय
Sṛñjaya m. (pl.): Name of a people,
very likely a section of the Pāñcālas; some-
times they are almost identified with them,
but sometimes mentioned along with them
and/or with Somakas.
A. Description of their warriors:
Magnanimous (महात्मन्) 6. 85. 21; very
vigorous (महौजस्) 7. 132. 41; heroic
(वीर) 6. 68. 15; of great strength (महा-
बल) 6. 86. 76; 6. 103. 11; difficult to be
attacked (दुराधर्ष) 6. 103. 10; great
archers (महेष्वास) 6. 16. 42; 8. 40. 4;
great chariot-fighters (महारथ) 8. 40. 2;
tigers among men (पुरुषव्याघ्र) 7. 101.
51.
B. Epic events: (1) Bhīma told
Yudhiṣṭhira that it was not impossible to
get back the kingdom by waging war
with Kauravas since Pāṇḍavas could count
on the help of Sṛñjayas, Kaikeyas and
Kṛṣṇa (in such contexts they are identified
with Pāñcālas) 3. 34. 85; he also told him
that all his relatives as well as Sṛñjayas
wish well of him and keep quiet (only he
and Draupadī got excited) (सर्वे ते प्रियम्
इच्छन्ति बान्धवाः सह सृञ्जयैः।अहम्
एको ऽभिसंतप्तो माता च प्रतिविन्ध्यतः॥)
3. 36. 15; (2) Dhṛtarāṣṭra felt that it
was better to give back to Pāṇḍavas their
share of kingdom before war broke out
in which Yudhiṣṭhira would be backed by
Kṛṣṇa, Sātyaki and Sṛñjayas 5. 22. 9; 5.
56. 33; when he sent Saṃjaya to Upa-
plavya, he asked him (Saṃjaya) to enquire
about the health of all including Sṛñjayas
(तेषां भागं … पुरा युद्धात् साधु तस्य
प्रदानम्॥ … अनामयं मद्वचनेन पृ-
च्छेः) 5. 22. 8-9, 38; (3) Sañjaya wanted
Yudhiṣṭhira to work for peace so that
Kauravas, Pāṇḍavas, Sṛñjayas and the rest
of the assembled kings would live in happi-
ness (शमं कुर्या येन शर्माप्नुयुस् ते)
5. 24. 9; Yudhiṣṭhira asked Saṃjaya to
communicate the message of Dhṛtarāṣṭra
to the assembly in which Sṛñjayas were
also present 5. 25. 1; Saṃjaya appealed to
all of them to act in a way that would
lead to the well-being of Kurus and Sṛñja-
yas (कृताञ्जलिः शरणं वः प्रपद्ये
कथं स्वस्ति स्यात् कुरुसृञ्जयानाम्) 5.
25. 14; Yudhiṣṭhira failed to see how there
could be well-being for Kurus and Sṛñjayas
when Dhṛtarāṣṭra had usurped the pro-
sperity of Pāṇḍavas (कथं स्वस्ति स्यात्
कुरुसृञ्जयानाम्।आत्तैश्वर्यो धृतराष्ट्रः
परेभ्यः।) 5. 26. 18; Yudhiṣṭhira also
told Saṃjaya that Sṛñjayas followed the
advice of Kṛṣṇa and hence were cap-
able of controlling their enemies and de-
lighting their friends (सृञ्जयाश् … ।उपासीना
वासुदेवस्य बुद्धिं … ) 5. 28. 11; (4)
Saṃjaya told Duryodhana that Pāṇḍavas
and Sṛñjayas heard attentively all that
Arjuna wanted him to convey to the
Kurus; Arjuna said that Duryodhana
would repent when he saw Dhṛṣṭa-
dyumna fighting at the head of the army
of Sṛñjayas; he also told Saṃjaya that
their Brāhmaṇas who were experts in
astrology had predicted the destruction of
Kurus and Sṛñjayas in war 5. 47. 5, 37,
93; (5) Dhṛtarāṣṭra envied those who
could see and listen to the words of Kṛṣṇa
which were meant for the welfare of
Sṛñjayas (भारतीम् … शङ्करीं सृञ्जया-
नाम्) 5. 69. 2 (Nī. on Bom. Ed. 5. 71. 2:
शंकरीं कल्याणकरीम्); (6) Kṛṣṇa
assured Yudhiṣṭhira that when he met the
Kauravas he would try to keep the agitated
Kurus and Sṛñjayas away from the noose
of death (मोचयेयं मृत्युपाशात् संरब्-
धान् कुरुसृञ्जयान्) 5. 70. 81; (7) Before
Kṛṣṇa left to meet the Kauravas, Drau-
padī told him that the Pāṇḍavas, along
with Sṛñjayas would be able to face the
army of Kauravas (शक्ष्यन्ति हि महाबाहो
पाण्डवाः सृञ्जयैः सह।धार्तराष्ट्र-
बलं … प्रतिसमासितुम्) 5. 80. 11 (Nī.
on Bom. Ed. 5. 82. 11: प्रतिसमासितुं
प्रतिपक्षतया स्थातुम्); according to her,
severe punishment should be quickly in-
flicted on Kauravas by Pāṇḍavas, Sṛñjayas
and Kṛṣṇa; he should take care to see
that he, along with Pāṇḍavas and Sṛñjayas,
was not blamed for not killing one who
deserved to be killed 5. 80. 14, 18-19;
(8) Kṛṣṇa assured Vidura that he would
attempt to bring about reconciliation
between Kurus and Sṛñjayas who would
otherwise perish in war (संग्रामे विन-
शिष्यताम्) 5. 91. 8; (9) Duryodhana
wanted to know from Kṛṣṇa what wrong
did the Kauravas do to Pāṇḍavas and
Sṛñjayas or for what fault of Kauravas
did they want to kill Kauravas (किम् अस्मा-
भिः कृतं तेषां कस्मिन् वा पुनर् आगसि) 5.
125. 11; (10) When Ulūka was asked by
Yudhiṣṭhira to convey to the assembly the
view of Duryodhana, he spoke to them
who included, among others, all Sṛñjayas
5. 158. 4-5; (11) Bhīṣma assured Duryo-
dhana that in case of war Droṇa would
kill Sṛñjayas (गच्छेद् अन्तं सृञ्जयानाम्)
5. 164. 15; (12) Before the start of the
war, Duryodhana told Duḥśāsana to pro-
tect Bhīṣma so that he might kill Pāṇḍavas
and Sṛñjayas 6. 16. 14; seeing Bhīṣma at the
head of the Kaurava army, Pāṇḍavas and
Sṛñjayas, led by Dhṛṣṭadyumna, shivered
(समकम्पन्त पाण्डवाः।सृञ्जयाश् च
 … धृष्टद्युम्नपुरोगमाः॥) 6. 16. 42;
(13) On the third day of the war, due to
the quickness of Bhīṣma's action, Pāṇḍavas
and Sṛñjayas felt that there were many
hundreds and thousands of him (अनेक-
शतसाहस्रम् समपश्यन्त लाघवात्) 6.
55. 22 (also cf. st. 21); (14) On the
fourth day, at one stage, Kurus and Sṛñja-
yas watched the duel between Bhīṣma and
Arjuna 6. 56. 28; (15) On the fifth day,
towards midday (मध्यन्दिनगते सूर्ये 6.
68. 12), Sṛñjayas fought a very fierce battle
with Kurus in which arrows, शक्तिस्, तोमरस्
were used 6. 68. 15-16; the battle describ-
ed 18-19; the same day, later, Sṛñjayas,
when they lost their armours, and their
chariots were broken and bows were cut
off, and their hair dishevelled, they wrestled
with Kurus (बाहुभिः समयुध्यन्त) 6.
69. 39; when the sun was about to set
(सूर्ये ऽस्तम् उपगच्छति 6. 70. 34), and
when the stopping of the war was declared,
Pāṇḍavas, along with Sṛñjayas, went to
their camps 6. 70. 37; (16) On the sixth
day, when Bhīṣma and Droṇa started killing
the Pāṇḍava army, Sṛñjayas and Kekayas
fied (पलायनपराभवन्) 6. 71. 32; (17)
On the seventh day, when Bhīṣma attack-
ed Yudhiṣṭhira, Sṛñjayas riding chariots,
elephants and horses trembled for they
feared Yudhiṣṭhira would soon be killed
(सरथनागाश्वाः समकम्पन्त सृञ्जयाः)
6. 82. 2-3; later in the afternoon (अपरां
दिशम् आस्थाय स्थिते सवितरि 6. 82. 28)
Bhīṣma neglected the challenge of Śikha-
ṇḍin and attacked Sṛñjayas; they were
happy to face Bhīṣma (सृञ्जयास् तु ततो
हृष्टा … ) and raised loud roars and blew
their conches; a fierce battle followed in
which chariot-fighters and elephant-riders
mingled with one another 6. 82. 26-28;
(18) On the eighth day, Bhīṣma started
killing Sṛñjayas, Pāñcālas and others; they
attacked Bhīṣma not fearing death (Sṛñja-
yas not directly mentioned, only Pāñcālas
are mentioned); Bhīṣma cut off arms and
heads of those riding horses and elephants
and deprived the chariot-fighters of their
chariots; he also killed elephants 6. 84.
3-7; when Droṇa killed Somakas and
Sṛñjayas a loud cry went up from their
army; the Kṣatriyas rolled on the ground
like those afflicted by ailments; their cry
was like one of those who become lean
due to hunger (विवेष्टन्तः स्म दृश्यन्ते
व्याधिक्लिष्टा नरा इव॥ … अनिशं श्रूयते
शब्दः क्षुत्कृशानां नृणाम् इव॥) 6. 85.
20-23; after the death of Irāvant, there
was fierce fighting in which the Kaurava
army and Sṛñjayas, not caring for their
lives in battle, killed one another; with
their hair loose and without their armours,
when they were deprived of their chariots
and their bows were cut off they wrestl-
ed with one another (जुह्वतः समरे
प्राणान् निजघ्नुर् इतरेतरम्॥मुक्तकेशा
विकवचा विरथाश् छिन्नकार्मुकाः।बाहु-
भिः समयुध्यन्त समवेताः परस्प-
रम्॥) 6. 86. 76-77; when Bhagadatta
proceeded to attack Yudhiṣṭhira, he fought
a severe battle with Pāñcālas, Sṛñjayas and
Kekayas who were ready to fight with their
weapons (उद्यतायुधैः) 6. 91. 79-80;
Bhīṣma told Duryodhana that since he had
dug up enmity with Pāṇḍavas and Sṛñjayas
he should fight with them manfully; he him-
self also would kill Somakas and Pāñcālas
(which term includes Sṛñjayas) (युध्यस्व
तान् अद्य रणे … पुरुषो भव) 6. 94. 13-
15; (19) At the end of the ninth day,
it appeared that Bhīṣma had defeated
Pāṇḍavas and Sṛñjayas; so at the start of
the night (रात्रिमुखे) Pāṇḍavas, Vṛṣṇis
and Sṛñjayas held consultation (मन्त्राय
समुपाविशन्) 6. 103. 8, 10-11; (20) At
the start of the tenth day, Kaurava army
was being destroyed by the sharp arrows
of Pāṇḍavas and Sṛñjayas; hence, Bhīṣma,
not caring for life, attacked them 6. 104.
23, 26, 29; Dhṛtarāṣṭra asked Saṃjaya
how on the tenth day Bhīṣma, when attack-
ed by Śikhaṇḍin determined to kill him
(6. 104. 45-46), fought with Pāṇḍavas and
Sṛñjayas (दशमे ऽहनि) 6. 105. 3; when
Bhīṣma began to destroy the Pāṇḍava army,
the great chariot-fighters (महारथाः)
of Sṛñjayas attacked Bhīṣma to kill him
(वधायाभ्यद्रवन् भीष्मम्) 6. 105. 35;
as the war advanced Pāṇḍavas, backed
by Sṛñjayas (संहताः सह सृञ्जयैः),
attacked Bhīṣma 6. 110. 40; Dhṛtarāṣṭra
once again asked Saṃjaya how Bhīṣma
fought with Pāṇḍavas and Sṛñjayas on
the tenth day 6. 111. 1; as advised
by Bhīṣma, Arjuna led Sṛñjayas (and
Pāñcālas) to attack Bhīṣma and kill him;
Sṛñjayas were asked to attack Bhīṣma
without fear as they would be protected by
Bhīma and Arjuna 6. 111. 15-20; exhorted
by Dhṛṣṭadyumna, Somakas and Sṛñjayas
attacked Bhīṣma showering weapons on
him (शस्त्रवृष्ट्या); angered Bhīṣma fought
with them 6. 113. 16-18; the weapons used
by Sṛñjayas are detailed in 6. 114. 2-3;
Sṛñjayas and Pāṇḍavas raised a loud roar
when Bhīṣma fell down 6. 114. 101; at the
end of the tenth day when Dhṛtarāṣṭra was
informed about Bhīṣma's downfall he
wondered who could be the warriors who
surrounded Bhīṣma (के वीराः पर्यवारयन्)
while he was showering arrows on Pāñcālas
and Sṛñjayas; he also wished to know who
from among the Kauravas were on the
left side of the wheel of Bhīṣma and shot
arrows on Sṛñjayas (वामे चक्रे वर्तमानाः
के ऽघ्नन् संजय सृञ्जयान्) 6. 15. 25,
28, 32; (21) On hearing the death of
Bhīṣma (7. 2. 1), Karṇa admitted that the
army which included Pāṇḍavas, Sātyaki,
Kṛṣṇa and Sṛñjayas was invincible by kings;
7. 2. 31; (22) On the eleventh day,
Pāṇḍavas and Sṛñjayas met with arrows
Droṇa's attack on them; Droṇa broke and
scattered their army; agitated by the arrows
of Droṇa, they were again and again sca-
ttered by him (ते कम्प्यमाना द्रोणेन
बाणैः पाण्डवसृञ्जयाः।पुनः पुनर् अभ-
ज्यन्त) 7. 6. 33, 35, 41; Sṛñjayas, though
they tried, were not able to kill the army
of Droṇa as it was protected by him; since
Droṇa was acting very swiftly, Pāṇḍavas and
Sṛñjayas felt as if there were many Droṇas
(एकम् आशुकारिणम् आहवे।अनेकम् इव
संत्रासान् मेनिरे) 7. 12. 19, 23; Sṛñjayas
trembled seeing Droṇa, like fire, burning
the army of Pāṇḍavas (साक्षाद् अग्निम् इवो-
त्थितम्) 7. 13. 2; Sṛñjayas and others with
their weapons raised (उद्यतायुधाः) met
the attack of Aśvasena and others; a fierce
battle ensued 7. 15. 11-12; at the sunset
when the withdrawal of the Pāṇḍava army
was declared by Arjuna (स्वान्य् अनीकानि …
अवहारयत्), Sṛñjayas greeted him for his
deeds during the day 7. 15. 49-50; (23) On
the twelfth day, after killing Śatānīka, Droṇa
repeatedly defeated Sṛñjayas and others;
seeing Droṇa, like fire, burning the army of
Pāṇḍavas, Sṛñjayas trembled; due to the
heroism of Droṇa, a river carrying the
bodies of Kurus and Pāñcālas to the god
of death began to flow (नदीम् अन्तक-
गामिनीम्) 7. 20. 23-24, 34, 36; when Droṇa
killed a Pāñcāla prince, Sṛñjayas and others
attacked Droṇa shouting ‘kill Droṇa, kill
Droṇa’ (हत द्रोणं हत द्रोणम् इत्य्
आसीत् तुमुलं महत्।); but Droṇa agitated
them who were very angry 7. 20. 48-49;
when Sṛñjayas and others were agitated and
were pushed back (चलितान् … प्रणुन्नान्)
by the arrows of Droṇa, Kauravas raised a
loud roar 7. 21. 7-8; Duryodhana drew
attention of Karṇa towards Bhīma who was
deserted by Pāṇḍava warriors and Sṛñjayas
(हीनः पाण्डवसृञ्जयैः) 7. 21. 16; (24)
On the thirteenth day, Pāñcāla army which
included thousands of Sṛñjayas attacked
Droṇa; but Droṇa arrested their advance
with arrows; then Pāñcālas and Sṛñjayas did
not attack him 7. 34. 5-7, 10; when Abhi-
manyu defeated Duḥśāsana, Sṛñjayas and
others were delighted 7. 39. 11, 17-18;
when Subhadrā heard the death of Abhi-
manyu, she pitied Sṛñjayas and the rest
who did not seem to know when Abhi-
manyu was felled down (धिक् केकयांस् …
सृञ्जयान्।ये त्वा रणे गतं वीरं न
जानन्ति निपातितम्) 7. 55. 13; (25) On the
fourteenth day, Sātyaki shot arrows at
Droṇa who was as though swallowing
(ग्रसन्तम् इव) Sṛñjayas 7. 72. 34; the
demon Alambusa made a river flow on the
battle-field carrying the dead bodies of
Sṛñjayas and others (नदीं प्रवर्तयाम्
आस) 7. 83. 30; when the Pāṇḍava army,
which included Sṛñjayas, attacked Droṇa
there was a loud roar among the Sṛñjayas
(तत्रारावो महान् आसीत्); when Droṇa
started killing them, Sṛñjayas found no
protector 7. 85. 20, 26; Yudhiṣṭhira assured
Sātyaki that when he (Sātyaki) would leave
to assist Arjuna, Sṛñjayas and others would
be there to protect him (Yudhiṣṭhira) 7.
86. 45; Sṛñjayas and others, thrilled, rushed
at Droṇa to fight with him with all their
might (सर्वशक्त्या); but Droṇa killed
them 7. 101. 50-52; Droṇa asked Duryo-
dhana to go to help Jayadratha; he himself
would obstruct the onward march of
Sṛñjayas and others 7. 105. 21; (26) After
the death of Jayadratha, before the start
of the night war between the fourteenth
and fifteenth day, Droṇa pointed out to
Duryodhana the armies of Pāṇḍavas and
Sṛñjayas marching towards him (Droṇa)
7. 126. 31; he directed Duryodhana to hold
back his army if he could, for Kurus and
Sṛñjayas would continue to fight even dur-
ing the night; with these words, Droṇa mar-
ched against Pāṇḍavas and Sṛñjayas (त्वं
च दुर्योधन बलं यदि शक्नोषि धारय)
7. 126. 38-39; then, there was fierce fighting
in the evening (संध्यायाम्) all around
between Droṇa and Sṛñjayas 7. 129. 18;
when the fierce fighting progressed during
the night, Pāṇḍavas and Sṛñjayas together
attacked Droṇa (रात्रियुद्धे तथा घोरे
वर्तमाने सुदारुणे); Droṇa forced all
of them back killing some of them (तान्
सर्वान् विमुखांश् चक्रे कांश्चिन् निन्ये
यमक्षयम्) 7. 129. 34-35; Dhṛtarāṣṭra
asked Saṃjaya how did Kauravas feel
when Droṇa entered the (army of) Sṛñjayas
(का वो ऽभूद् वै मतिस् तदा) 7. 130. 1;
Sṛñjayas and Pāñcālas followed Bhīma and
Arjuna who showered arrows on Droṇa
trying to scatter the army of Drupada with
Vāyavyāstra 7. 132. 37, 41; 7. 136. 14;
Aśvatthāman challenged his opponents to
attack him and then killed Pāñcālas and
Sṛñjayas; they abandoned Aśvatthāman and
fled in all directions (व्यद्रवन्त दिशो दश
7. 135. 19) when their chariots and banners
were scattered (विप्रकीर्णरथध्वजाः) 7.
135. 51; Duryodhana asked Duḥśāsana and
his other brothers to offer protection to
Droṇa who would then kill Sṛñjayas and
their kings (सृञ्जयांश् च सराजकान्); when
all Sṛñjayas were killed, Aśvatthāman would
kill Dhṛṣṭadyumna 7. 139. 24-25; in the
fighting that followed Aśvatthāman cover-
ed Drupada and Droṇa covered Sṛñjayas
with smooth arrows (छादयाम् आसतुः
संख्ये शरैः संनतपर्वभिः) 7. 139.
31; when Aśvatthāman swooned while fight-
ing with Ghaṭotkaca, Pāñcālas and Sṛñjayas
raised a loud roar (सिंहनादं प्रच-
क्रिरे) 7. 141. 32; considering that Bhīma
had killed Duryodhana, Pāñcālas, Sṛñjayas
and others made all effort to attack Droṇa
to fight with him (सर्वोद्योगेनाभिजग्मुर्
 … ); a fierce battle then was fought 7.
141. 60; when Pāñcālas and Sṛñjayas were
being killed by Karṇa, they apprehended
his presence nearby even when a blade of
grass stirred (तृणप्रस्पन्दनाच् चापि सूत-
पुत्रं स्म मेनिरे) 7. 148. 15 (Nī. on
Bom. Ed. 7. 173. 19: अतिभयात् तृणचलन-
मात्रेणापि कर्णं प्राप्तं मेनिरे); they
mistook a running warrior on their own
side to be Karṇa (अपि स्वं समरे योधं
धावमानं विचेतसः।कर्णम् एवाभ्य-
मन्यन्त … ); hence, afraid, they ran
but Karṇa attacked them from behind
(पृष्ठतो विकिरञ् शरान्) 7. 148. 15-17;
when Pāñcālas and Sṛñjayas were excessi-
vely tormented by the Rākṣasas of Alā-
yudha they had no peace of mind (न
शान्तिं लेभिरे तत्र) 7. 152. 31; Dhṛta-
rāṣṭra wondered why Karṇa, instead of
killing Ghaṭotkaca, did not kill Arjuna
with the शक्ति given to him by Indra; for,
the death of Arjuna would have meant the
death of all Pāṇḍavas and Sṛñjayas long
ago 7. 157. 2; the same opinion was held
by Kṛṣṇa (and hence he deluded the mind
of Karṇa whenever he faced Arjuna) 7.
157. 35; Dhṛtarāṣṭra asked Saṃjaya how
did Sṛñjayas and Pāñcālas with their armies
arrayed and in striking position (व्यूढानी-
काः प्रहारिणः) fight with Kurus and how
did they attack Droṇa who, not caring for
his life, had plunged into their army after
the death of Ghaṭotkaca (जीवितं त्यक्त्वा
गाहमानं वरूथिनीम्) 7. 158. 13-15;
Droṇa killed three grand-sons of Drupada
and then defeated Cedis, Kekayas, Sṛñjayas
and Matsyas 7. 161. 31-32; (27) On
the fifteenth day, Pāñcālas and Sṛñjayas,
although they were being killed by Droṇa,
attacked him and confused him (मोहयन्तो
महारथम्) 7. 164. 60; after killing Vasu-
dāna (king of Pāṃśurāṣṭra), Droṇa killed
six thousand Sṛñjayas 7. 164. 85; exhorted
by Yudhiṣṭhira to assist Dhṛṣṭadyumna, the
great chariot-fighters of Sṛñjayas attacked
Droṇa in order to kill him; Droṇa with
great speed moved against them not mind-
ing his death (मर्तव्यम् इति निश्चितः);
bad omens occurred; Droṇa, encircled by
the armies of Drupada, moved burning
host of Kṣatriyas and killed a very large
number of them 7. 165. 8-16; when ulti-
mately Droṇa was killed by Dhṛṣṭadyumna,
Pāṇḍavas and Sṛñjayas attacked the dis-
heartened Kurus with the result that their
army was shattered (निरुत्साहान् कुरून्
 … अभ्यद्रवन् … ततः सैन्यं व्यदीर्-
यत) 7. 165. 58; when Aśvatthāman
used his नारायणास्त्र, Pāṇḍavas, Pāñcālas
and Sṛñjayas were dismayed to see the
mid-region filled with different weapons
(शस्त्राकृतिभिर् आकीर्णम् अतीव … दृष्ट्वा-
न्तरिक्षम् आविग्नाः पाण्डुपाञ्चालसृञ्जयाः)
7. 170. 20; at the end of the day, when
Saṃjaya reported to Dhṛtarāṣṭra the
death of Droṇa, he asked Saṃjaya what
was Droṇa doing on the battle-field
when Pāṇḍavas and Sṛñjayas managed
to kill him (किं कुर्वाणं रणे द्रोणम्
जघ्नुः पाण्डवसृञ्जयाः) 7. 8. 1; Saṃjaya
assured Dhṛtarāṣṭra that since he was an
eye-witness to the whole event (सर्वं
प्रत्यक्षदर्शिवान्) he would narrate to him
how Droṇa fell when overpowered (सादितः)
by Pāṇḍavas and Sṛñjayas 7. 11. 1; (28)
On the sixteenth day, Duryodhana was
confident that with Karṇa as their general
Pāṇḍavas, Pāñcālas and Sṛñjayas would
loose their consciousness (गतचेतसः) 8.
6. 31; Kṛṣṇa pointed out to Arjuna that
Karṇa, as intended by Aśvatthāman (अश्व-
त्थामनश् च संकल्पाद् … ) had killed
Sṛñjayas 8. 16. 5; Karṇa brought Sṛñjayas
and Pāñcālas within the range of his arrows
and crushed them (शरगोचरम् आनयत्।
ममर्द); Kurus, Pāṇḍavas and Sṛñjayas
fought with great effort not caring for
their life (व्यायच्छमानाः सुभृशम् …
प्रियान् असून् रणे त्यक्त्वा) 8. 16. 22, 24-
25; battle described 8. 16. 26-38; at mid-
day (मध्यं गते दिनकरे 8. 17. 100),
although Karṇa killed Sṛñjayas they attack-
ed him 8. 17. 117; (29) On the seven-
teenth day, early morning (प्रभातायां
रजन्यां तु 8. 22. 29) before the start of
the war, Duryodhana while requesting Śalya
to act as a charioteer of Karṇa told him
that with a good charioteer like him, Karṇa
would be able to destroy Pāṇḍavas, Pāñcā-
las and Sṛñjayas 8. 23. 15; at the start of
the war on that day, Pāñcālas, Cedis and
Sṛñjayas fought a fierce battle with the
Kaurava army 8. 32. 15; Dhṛtarāṣṭra
remembered that Karṇa had boasted earlier
that he alone would kill Sṛñjayas along
with Pāṇḍavas 8. 35. 2; Sṛñjayas cut off
(शातयाम् आसुः) the arrows shot at them
by Kṛpa 8. 38. 4; Karṇa stopped the on-
ward march of Sṛñjayas and others who
were led by Bhīma 8. 38. 16; Karṇa killed
Cedis, Karūṣas and Sṛñjayas in the presence
of Bhīma; when Bhīma left Karṇa to fight
with the Kuru army, Karṇa killed thou-
sands of great archers of Sṛñjayas (सृञ्-
जयांश् च महेश्वासान् निजघान सहस्र-
शः) 8. 40. 2-4; Sṛñjayas were ‘burnt’ by
the fire in the form of Karṇa (कर्णाग्निना
 … दग्धा … ) 8. 40. 61; Arjuna pointed out
to Kṛṣṇa that the large army of Sṛñjayas
was being scattered (दीर्यते) by Karṇa
8. 40. 81; when Bhīma returned to fight
(संनिवृत्तो रणं प्रति), Pāñcālas and
Sṛñjayas, led by Dhṛṣṭadyumna, followed
him 8. 41. 3; Kurus led by Karṇa and
Sṛñjayas led by Yudhiṣṭhira faced one
another without fear (अभीताः) 8. 42. 1;
Kṛṣṇa pointed out to Arjuna that Karṇa,
after defeating Pāṇḍavas, Pāñcālas and
Sṛñjayas was looking for Arjuna: when
the Kuru warriors saw Karṇa displaying
his valour by harassing Pāṇḍavas and
thousands of Sṛñjayas they raised a loud
roar (नदन्ति); Karṇa encouraged Kau-
rava warriors to attack Sṛñjayas so that
none of them escaped alive (यथा जिवन्
न वः कश्चिन् मुच्यते) 8. 43. 36; Kṛṣṇa
was glad to point out to Arjuna that Bhīma,
along with Sātyaki and Sṛñjayas, had once
again returned to the battle-field 8. 43. 52;
Yudhiṣṭhira wondered whether the en-
counter of Sṛñjayas and Kauravas in which
he was humiliated had become known to
the fighters (कच्चित् संग्रामे विदितो वा
तदायं समागमः सृञ्जयकौरवा-
णाम्।यत्रावस्थाम् ईदृशीं प्रापितो ऽहम्)
8. 46. 41; Kṛṣṇa told Arjuna that all
Pāñcālas and Sṛñjayas with their followers
were prepared to fight when they had
resorted to him (एते च सर्वे पाञ्चालाः
सृञ्जयाश् च सहान्वयाः।त्वां समासाद्य
 … व्यवस्थिताः) 8. 51. 5; while taking
stock of some of the events of the battle
which had lasted for seventeen days (अद्य
सप्तदशाहानि 8. 51. 2), Kṛṣṇa reminded
Arjuna that while Bhīṣma was fighting,
Sṛñjayas were unable to look at him;
Bhīṣma routed Pāṇḍavas and Sṛñjayas
and distinguished himself as the sole
war hero (एकवीरत्वम् आगतः) 8. 51. 35;
Kṛṣṇa pointed out to Arjuna that Bhīma,
covered on all sides by Sṛñjayas, was
being tormented while fighting with Karṇa:
if Karṇa was neglected he might kill
Pāṇḍavas, Sṛñjayas and Pāñcālas 8. 51.
105-106; at one stage in the battle, Utta-
maujas had engaged Sṛñjayas 8. 53. 6;
Arjuna asked Kṛṣṇa to drive his chariot
towards Karṇa, lest he destroyed all Sṛñ-
jaya great chariot-fighters in battle in their
presence (राधेयो ऽप्य् अन्यथा पार्थान्
सृञ्जयांश् च महारथान्।निःशेषान्
समरे कुर्यात् पश्यतोर् नौ जनार्दन॥)
8. 57. 8; later, Kuru warriors and Sṛñjayas
fought with one another using straight-
flying and very sharp arrows (शरैस्
तदाञ्जोगतिभिः सुतेजनैः) 8. 57. 67; once
again a very severe fighting broke out
between Kurus and Sṛñjayas in which they
used besides arrows weapons like swords,
शक्तिस्, lances, maces and परश्वधस् 8.
62. 40; when Karṇa was killed, Arjuna was
honoured by Sṛñjayas, Pāñcālas and others
8. 69. 37; on the seventeenth night (निशि 8.
1. 25) while reporting Karṇa's death to
Dhṛtarāṣṭra Saṃjaya told him that Karṇa,
before his death, had killed Kekayas and
Videhas in the presence of all Sṛñjayas
and Pāñcālas (स सृञ्जयानां सर्वेषां
पाञ्चालानां च पश्यताम्।केकयानां
विदेहानाम् अकरोत् कदनं महत्॥) 8. 2.
18; Dhṛtarāṣṭra asked Saṃjaya who among
the Kurus and Sṛñjayas were dead and who
were alive 8. 4. 3; (30) On the eighteenth
day, when Śalya became the general the
Madras encouraged him saying that he
was capable of defeating in battle even
gods and demons, let alone mortals like
Somakas and Sṛñjayas 9. 6. 9; a fierce battle
was fought by Sṛñjayas with Kurus which
terrorized Kurus (कुरूणां भयवर्ध-
नम्) 9. 8. 1; as a result of the battle
there began to flow a terrific river (नदी
रौद्रा) filled with the bodies of Kurus
and Sṛñjayas (कुरुसृञ्जयसंकुला) 9. 8.
32; seeing the heroic deeds (विक्रमम्) of
Śalya, Duryodhana considered Pāṇḍavas,
Pāñcālas and Sṛñjayas (as good as) dead
(निहतान् … मेने) 9. 12. 28; finally, when
Śalya was killed, Pāṇḍavas and Śṛñjayas
chased the shattered (प्रभग्नान्) army
of Kauravas 9. 18. 28; when Śālva, riding
an elephant, attacked the Pāṇḍava army,
Sṛñjayas and others thought his swiftly
moving single elephant, to be several
thousands (सहस्रशो वै विचरन्तम्
एकम्) 9. 19. 6; when the Pāṇḍava army
was broken, Kaurava heroes blew, in joy,
their conches; Dhṛṣṭadyumna, the general
of the armies of Pāṇḍavas and Sṛñjayas,
could not bear the sound of the roar indi-
cative of the joy of Kauravas (8. 19. 10);
seeing the (heroic) deeds of Śālva, Sṛñjayas
and others encircled his elephant 9. 19. 21;
during the war of eighteen days eleven
अक्षौहिणिस् of Duryodhana's army were
killed by Pāṇḍavas and Sṛñjayas 9. 28.
14; Duryodhana felt confident to defeat
Pāṇḍavas, Pāñcālas and Sṛñjayas with
mace as his weapon 9. 31. 30; Bhīma
told Yudhiṣṭhira, accompanied by Sṛñjayas
(सृञ्जयैः सह तिष्ठन्तम्), that he was
prepared to accept the challenge of Duryo-
dhana 9. 32. 28; Pāñcālas and Sṛñjayas
applauded Duryodhana's words asking
Bhīma to prove his words (दर्शयस्व
बलं युद्धे) 9. 32. 49-50; when Balarāma
came to witness the duel between Bhīma
and Duryodhana, he embraced Pāṇḍavas
and Sṛñjayas and enquired about their
well being (अपृच्छत् कुशलं सर्वान्) 9.
33. 11; Duryodhana asked Yudhiṣṭhira,
along with Sṛñjayas, to watch the duel
9. 54. 38-39; when Duryodhana was forced
to kneel down by Bhīma, Sṛñjayas raised
a loud roar; hearing their roar, Duryo-
dhana was enraged 9. 56. 54-55; when
Bhīma felled down Duryodhana he told
Kṛṣṇa, Pāṇḍavas and Sṛñjayas that he
had killed the sons of Dhṛtarāṣṭra on
the strength of Draupadī's तपस् (रणे
हतांस् तपसा याज्ञसेन्याः) 9. 58. 9-10;
Dhṛtarāṣṭra asked Saṃjaya what did the
Sṛñjayas do when Duryodhana was struck
down; Saṃjaya told him that they waived
their upper garments and raised a loud
roar; the earth was unable to bear them
who were filled with delight (आविध्यन्
उत्तरीयाणि सिंहनादांश् च नेदिरे।नैतान्
हर्षसमाविष्टान् इयम् सेहे वसुन्धरा॥)
9. 60. 3-4; some shook their bows, others
their bow-strings; still others blew their
large conches or struck the दुन्दुभिस्; some
made sportive gestures, others laughed
(चिक्रीडुस् तथैवान्ये जहसुश् च) 9. 60.
5-6; they praised Bhīma's act in so many
words and were happy that he had brought
the enmity to an end (वैरस्य च गतः
पारम्); they said that the horripilation
experienced by them at the time of Duryo-
dhana's fall had not yet subsided (दुर्यो-
धनवधे यानि रोमाणी हृषितानि नः।अद्यापि
न विहृष्यन्ति तानि … ) 9. 60. 7-16; Kṛṣṇa
told Sṛñjayas not to rebuke Duryodhana
anymore because he was already killed when
he refused to give Pāṇḍavas their share
although advised to do that, among others,
by them (°गाङ्गेवसृञ्जयैः। … प्रोच्य-
मानो ऽपि) 9. 60. 20; (31) During the
massacre which took place at night of the
eighteenth day, Aśvatthāman killed Pāṇḍava
warriors and Sṛñjayas who were without
weapons and armours and were agitated
(अपेतशस्त्रसंनाहान् संरब्धान् पाण्डु-
सृञ्जयान्) 10. 8. 74; Kṛpa and Kṛtavarman
told Aśvatthāman that they had killed
Pāñcālas and Sṛñjayas by thousands (as
they were trying to escape from the camp)
(विनिकृत्तान् सहस्रशः) 10. 8. 141; (32)
More than a hundred Sṛñjayas (सृञ्जयांश्
च शताधिकान्) were put on the funeral
pyre along with the dead bodies of other
fallen heroes and were cremated according
to the prescribed rites 11. 26. 30, 33, 38.
C. Some person referred to as Sṛñjayas
which indicated their relationship with
them: (1) Dhṛṣṭadyumna 3. 34. 12 (cf. 3.
23. 46); (2) Hotravāhana (father of
Ambā's mother) 5. 175. 7, 12, 28; 5. 176.
4, 17, 20, 26; (3) Vainya, one of the
ancient kings 1. 1. 166.

सैन्धव
Saindhava: See Sindhu.

सैरन्ध्र
Sairandhra m. (pl.): Name of a
Janapada.
Listed by Saṃjaya among the northern
Janapadas (also called Deśas 6. 10. 68) of
Bhāratavarṣa (अत ऊर्ध्वं जनपदान्
निबोध) 6. 10. 37, 5; (ओष्ट्राः पुण्ड्राः
ससैरन्ध्राः) 6. 10. 56.

सोमक
Somaka m. (pl.): Name of a people,
a section of Pāñcālas, hence often men-
tioned along with them as also with Sṛñja-
yas; the name, however, often stands for
both Pāñcālas and Somakas.
A. Description: Versed in the Vedas
(वेदाध्ययनसंपन्न) 6. 1. 4; heroic
(शूर) 7. 102. 67; 7. 135. 20; 7. 143. 28;
(वीर) 6. 1. 2; 6. 104. 25; of great strength
(महाबल) 6. 1. 3; great chariot-fighters
(महारथ) 6. 103. 4; 6. 112. 75; great
archers (महेष्वास) 6. 93 38; welcoming
wars (युद्धाभिनन्दिन्) 6. 1. 4; wishing to
get victory or die in war (आशंसन्तो जयं
युद्धे वधं वाभिमुखा रणे) 6. 1. 4.
B. Epic events: (1) Recounting the war
events to Saṃjaya, Dhṛtarāṣṭra said that
before Bhīṣma's fall he had reduced Soma-
kas to a small number (कृत्वा सोमकान्
अल्पशेषान्) 1. 1. 127; (2) At the start of
the स्वयंवर of Draupadi, the priest of
Somakas (in such contexts they are identi-
fied with Pāñcālas) gave offerings in fire,
asked Brāhmaṇas to pronounce benediction
(ब्राह्मणान् स्वस्ति वाच्य च) and then
stopped the sound of musical instruments
1. 176. 31-32; (3) Dhṛtarāṣṭra asked
Saṃjaya how strong Somakas were with
Dhṛṣṭadyumna as their general (धृष्ट-
द्युम्नेन सेनान्या सोमकाः किम्बला इव)
5. 49. 9; (4) Duryodhana and others
thought that if Kṛṣṇa was arrested Pāṇḍa-
vas and Somakas would give up all their
effort (निरुद्यमा भविष्यन्ति) 5. 128. 7;
(5) When Pāṇḍavas had settled down at
Hiraṇvatī, Duryodhana sent Ulūka as his
messenger to them and Somakas 5. 157.
3; (6) Bhīṣma had assured Duryodhana
that he would kill Pāṇḍavas and Somakas
5. 170. 2; (7) Dhṛtarāṣṭra asked Saṃjaya
how did Kurus and Pāṇḍava-Somakas
fight with one another at Kurukṣetra;
thereupon Saṃjaya described to him how
they fought when Somakas, determined to
win or die while engaged in fighting, attack-
ed Kauravas (आशंसन्तो जयं युद्धे
वधं वाभिमुखा रणे) 6. 1. 1-4; Kau-
ravas and Pāṇḍava-Somakas sat together
before the start of the war and mutually
agreed upon certain conventions and
rules to be followed in the war (ततस् ते
समयं चक्रुः कुरुपाण्डवसोमकाः।
धर्मांश् च स्थापयाम् आसुर् युद्धानाम्
 … ॥) 6. 1. 26, 33; the conventions and
rules detailed in 6. 1. 27-32; (8) Duryo-
dhana told Duḥśāsana that if Bhīṣma was
protected in war he would kill Pāṇḍavas,
Somakas and Sṛñjayas 6. 16. 14; (9) When
Arjuna got prepared for the war Somakas
and others blew their conches 6. 41. 2;
(10) On the second day of the war,
Dhṛṣṭadyumna and Somakas showered
arrows on Droṇa 6. 48. 30; (11) On the
third day, Kṛṣṇa noticed Bhīṣma routing
Somakas chased by the delighted Kauravas
(प्रभग्नान् दृश्य सोमकान्) 6. 55. 68;
(12) On the fifth day, when Bhīṣma
started killing Pāñcālas and Somakas, they
acted nobly and decided to attack Bhīṣma
(आर्यां युद्धे मतिं कृत्वा भीष्मम्
एवाभिदुद्रुवुः) 6. 68. 31; (13) On the
sixth day, Śikhaṇḍin surrounded by Soma-
kas and Irāvant stood at the ‘tail’ of
the Makaravyūha of Pāṇḍavas (पुच्छे
मकरस्य) 6. 71. 4, 11; Somakas were
terrified (वित्रेसुः) to hear the sound of
Droṇa's conch when he blew it after defeat-
ing Drupada 6. 73. 46; (14) On the eighth
day, when the Pāṇḍava army attacked
Bhīṣma he killed Pāñcālas, Somakas and
Sṛñjayas with his arrows; nevertheless,
abandoning the fear of death they attacked
Bhīṣma (त्यक्त्वा मृत्युकृतं भयम्)
6. 84. 2-4; battle that ensued, in which
Bhīṣma cut off their hands and heads and
felled down those riding chariots, horses
and elephants (विरथान् रथिनश् चक्रे;
हयेभ्यो हयसादिनाम्; निर्मनुष्यांश् च
मातङ्गाञ् … ), described in 6. 84. 5-7;
when Droṇa attacked Somakas and Sṛñjayas
in order to kill them (अभ्यद्रवत …
प्रेषयिष्यम् यमक्षयम्) a loud cry was
raised by Sṛñjayas (by implication also by
Somakas) (तत्राक्रन्दो महान् आसीत् सृञ्ज-
यानाम्) 6. 85. 20-21; that night, Karṇa
assured Duryodhana that he would kill all
Pārthas and Somakas if Bhīṣma laid down
his arms and left the battlefield 6. 93. 13;
Duryodhana then went to Bhīṣma and
reminded him that he had assured him
(Duryodhana) to kill Somakas; he asked
Bhīṣma to carry out his assurance by killing
Somakas 6. 93. 37-38; thereupon Bhīṣma
once again assured Duryodhana that next
day he would either kill Somakas and Pāñ-
cālas to delight him or they would kill
him (तैर् वाहं निहतः संख्ये गमिष्ये
यमसादनम्।तान् वा निहत्य संग्रामे
प्रीतिम् दास्यामि वै तव॥) 6. 94. 14-15;
(15) On the ninth day, in the morning,
Duryodhana asked the kings to get ready
with their armies since Bhīṣma was going
to kill that day Somakas (अद्य भीष्मो …
निहनिष्यति सोमकान्) 6. 95. 1; at mid-day,
Bhīṣma fought a fierce battle with Somakas
blowing them away by hundreds and thou-
sands with his sharp arrows (व्यधमन्
 … शतशो ऽथ सहस्रशः) 6. 99. 1-2;
in the evening when the sun had set
(भास्करे ऽस्तम् उपागते 6. 103. 1), Yudhi-
ṣṭhira seeing that great chariot-fighters
among Somakas had been defeated and
had lost enthusiasm (जितान् दृष्त्वा … निरुत्-
साहान् महारथान्) felt like ordering
cessation of hostilities for that day (अव-
हारम् अरोचयत्) 6. 103. 4; (16) Dhṛta-
rāṣṭra asked Saṃjaya how, on the tenth
day, did Bhīṣma face Pāṇḍavas while at
the same time killing Somakas 6. 104. 25;
Dhṛṣṭadyumna, aided by Somakas, attack-
ed Droṇa 6. 111. 30; Bhīṣma, when attack-
ed by Śikhaṇḍin, killed Somakas who
followed Arjuna (पार्थपदानुगान्) 6.
112. 64; none of the great chariot-fighters
of Somakas hoped to live after facing
Bhīṣma in battle (न … यः संप्राप्य रणे
भीष्मं जीविते स्म मनो दधे) 6. 112.
75; exhorted by Dhṛṣṭadyumna, Somakas
and Sṛñjayas rushed at Bhīṣma showering
weapons on him from all sides (अभ्यद्र-
वन्त … शस्त्रवृष्ट्या समन्ततः) 6. 113.
16-17; Somakas and Pāñcālas were delight-
ed when Bhīṣma fell down 6. 114. 107;
(17) On the fourteenth day, when Droṇa
started killing Somakas no one succeeded
in facing him, nor was any one able to
pierce him (with an arrow) (न चाप्य-
भिययुः केचिद् अपरे नैव विव्यधुः) 7.
85. 34; watching the fierce duel between
Satyasena and Sātyaki, Kauravas and
Somakas praised them 7. 94. 7; in the
afternoon of that day, Droṇa again fought
with Somakas (अपराह्णे … संग्रामः
समपद्यत। … पुनर् द्रोणस्य सोमकल्ः)
7. 101. 1; when the different alignments of
the Pāṇḍava army were being agitated by
Droṇa (व्यूहेष्व् आलोड्यमानेषु), Pāṇḍavas,
Pāñcālas and Somakas went deep into the
army of Kauravas (सुदूरम् अन्वयुः); the
battle fought was so fierce that it looked
like the end of the world (युगान्त इव
भारत) 7. 102. 1-2; when Bhīma
marched to offer assistance to Arjuna,
Pāñcālas and Somakas followed him 7.
102. 67; after the death of Jayadratha, in
the evening (अस्तं गच्छति भास्करे),
Droṇa fought a fierce battle with Somakas
(सोमकैः सार्धम् संग्रामो लोमहर्ष-
णः); at that time great chariot-fighters
of Somakas made every attempt to kill
Droṇa (ते तु सर्वे प्रयत्नेन भारद्वाजं
जिघांसवः। … अयुध्यन्त महारथाः॥)
7. 121. 45-46; Droṇa sent a message to
Aśvatthāman through Duryodhana not to
spare Somakas in order to save his own
life (न सोमकाः प्रमोक्तव्या जीवितं
परिरक्षता) 7. 126. 33; (18) In the
night war (which took place between the
fourteenth and the fifteenth day), Duryo-
dhana assured his fleeing army that he
would himself kill Pārthas together with
Pāñcālas and Somakas 7. 134. 54: Duryo-
dhana requested Aśvatthāman to kill
Pāñcālas and Somakas who, agitated, were
moving in his army like a conflagration;
he should kill them before they killed
Kauravas (एते हि सोमका … मम सैन्येषु
संरब्धा विचरन्ति दवाग्निवत्) 7. 134.
76-78; Aśvatthāman assured Duryodhana
that for his sake and to delight him he
would fight with Pāñcālas, Somakas and
Kekayas (एष गच्छामि संग्रामे त्वत्-
कृते … । … त्वत्प्रियार्थम्); scorched by
his arrows, Somakas and others would
run away in all directions; seeing his
valour, Yudhiṣṭhira and Somakas would
consider the world full of Aśvatthāman
(अश्वत्थाममयं लोकं मंस्यन्ते);
Yudhiṣṭhira would be dejected seeing the
slain Pāñcālas and Somakas; Aśvatthāman
would kill only those who engaged him in
battle (ये मां युद्धे ऽभियोत्स्यन्ति तान्
हनिष्यामि … ); once Somakas were within
his reach they would not return alive 7.
135. 10-14; in the battle that followed
Pāñcālas and Somakas fled 7. 135. 20;
Sṛñjayas, Pāñcālas, Matsyas and Somakas
followed Arjuna and Bhīma to attack Droṇa
from right and left respectively (बीभत्सुर्
दक्षिणं पार्श्वम् उत्तरं तु वृकोदरः)
7. 136. 13-14; Duryodhana advised his
brothers to offer protection to Droṇa so
that he would be able to kill Pārthas,
Somakas and Sṛñjayas along with their
kings (सोमकान् हन्यात् सृञ्जयांश् च सरा-
जकान्) 7. 139. 21, 24; in the midst of the
fierce night war (रौद्रे रात्रियुद्धे),
Yudhiṣṭhira exhorted Pāṇḍavas and Soma-
kas to attack Droṇa alone in order to kill
him; accordingly, they attacked Droṇa
uttering frightening cries (अभ्यद्रवत
गच्छध्वं द्रोणम् एव जिघांसया। …
द्रोणम् एवाभ्यवर्तन्त नदन्तो भैर-
वान् रवान्) 7. 140. 2-3; when Karṇa's son
Vṛṣasena cut off the armours of Drupada's
army, Somakas, frightened, fied (सोमका
विप्रदुद्रुवुः); while they were running
away they appeared bright due to the light
of the torches (ततस् तु द्रुपदानीकं
शरैश् छिन्नतनुच्छदम्।संप्राद्रवत्
 … ।द्रवमाणाश् च सोमकाः व्यराजन्त …
प्रदीपैर् अवभासिताः); after defeating
great Somaka charriot-fighters Vṛṣasena
turned towards Yudhiṣṭhira 7. 143. 21, 24-
25, 28; when Śikhaṇḍin, defeated by Kṛpa
turned back, Somakas and others covered
him on all sides; then the battle started
again 7. 144. 25, 27-28; seeing Droṇa kill-
ing the Pāṇḍava army (पाण्डवीं चमूम्),
Somakas quickly pierced him by showering
arrows (विव्यधुः सोमकास् तूर्णं …
शरवृष्टिभिः); but Droṇa deprived them
of their lives 7. 147. 13-14; Kṛṣṇa drew
Arjuna's attention to Bhīma who, cover-
ed by Somakas and the Pāṇḍava army,
attacked Droṇa and Karṇa (वृतः सोमक-
पाण्डवैः) 7. 147. 28; when only the three
parts of the (last quarter of the) night
remained and the sun was about to rise,
Droṇa divided his army into two parts and
attacked Somakas and Pāṇḍavas along with
Pāñcālas (त्रिभागमात्रशेषायाम् रात्र्यां;
अरुणो ऽभ्युदयां चक्रे) 7. 161. 1-3 (Nī.
on Bom. Ed. 7. 186. 1; त्रिभागमात्रशेषा-
यां मुहूर्तत्रयावशिष्टायाम्); (19) On
the fifteenth day, Droṇa released ब्राह्म
missile trying to kill all Somakas (विनिघ्नन्
सर्वसोमकान्) 7. 164. 80; just before the
fall of Droṇa, Kurus and Somakas got
mixed up with one another in a battle
shouting and felling each other with wea-
pons (ततः प्रवृत्ते संग्रामे विमिश्राः
कुरुसोमकाः। … शस्त्रैर् देहान् अपात-
यन्॥) 7. 165. 99; when the fleeing Pāñcāla
warriors did not return to fight they were
made to stand still where they were by
Kṛṣṇa and Arjuna (7. 171. 67-69; 7. 172.
1-2); only Arjuna, along with Somakas
and the constituents of their armies (?)
returned to fight with Aśvatthāman (एक
एव तु बीभत्सुः सोमकावयवैः सह)
7. 172. 3 (Nī. on Bom. Ed. 7. 201. 3;
सोमकावयवैः सोमकानाम् अवयवरूपैर्
माण्डलिकैः); (20) On the sixteenth day,
when Aṅgas attacked Nakula, Pāṇḍavas,
Pāñcālas and Somakas attacked them to
cover Nakula (नकुलं … परि पेतुः …
पाण्डुपाञ्चालसोमकाः); then chariot-
fighters fought with elephant-riders (रथि-
नां हस्तिभिः सह) 8. 17. 21-22; when
Somakas were being killed by the arrows
of Karṇa, afflicted by pain and wounded
by arrows, they hid themselves (अवालीयन्त
राजेन्द्र वेदनार्ताः शरार्दिताः); (the
Kaurava army too, being killed by Nakula,
dispersed in all directions); the two armies
then, standing beyond the range of arrows,
chose to act as spectators (ते सेने …
प्रेक्षकवत् स्थिते) 8. 17. 73-75; (21)
Even after the battle of the sixteenth day,
Dhṛtarāṣṭra was confident that Karṇa alone
was capable of killing Pāṇḍavas and Soma-
kas 8. 22. 16; (22) On the seventeenth
day, Arjuna felt that by killing Karṇa he
would give satisfaction to the great chariot-
fighters of Somakas for having fulfilled
their task to help their allies in war (कृतं
कार्यं च मन्यन्तां मित्रकार्येप्सवो
युधि) 8. 52. 25; Karṇa in the afternoon
(अपराह्णे) of that day killed all Somakas
in the presence of Bhīma 8. 56. 7, 53;
Arjuna expressed his fear to Kṛṣṇa that
if Kṛpa, Kṛtavarman and Aśvatthāman
were not killed they would cause the des-
truction of Somakas (अवध्यमानास् ते
ऽस्माभिर् घातयिष्यन्ति सोमकान्) 8. 57. 5;
Karṇa fought a great battle with Somakas
in which he crushed them while destroy-
ing their chariots and killing horses and
elephants (सुमहत् … चक्रे युद्धं सोम-
कान् संप्रमृद्नन्) 8. 60. 14; when Karṇa
came up to Arjuna to kill him, Somakas
urged (अभ्यक्रोशन्) Arjuna to hasten to
pierce Karṇa (with an arrow), cut off his
head without delay and shatter the hope
of Duryodhana to get kingdom (विध्य
कर्णम्।छिन्द्ध्य् अस्य मूर्धानम् अलं
चिरेण श्रद्धां च राज्याद् धृतराष्ट्र-
सूनोः) 8. 65. 10; when Karṇa cover-
ed (समाचिनोत्) Arjuna with a hundred
Kṣudraka arrows and pierced (बिभेद)
Kṛṣṇa with sixty arrows, Somakas fied;
Arjuna stopped them (तदन्तरं सोमकाः
प्राद्रवन्त। … पार्थः सोमकान् प्रत्य-
गृह्णात्) 8. 65. 32-34; seeing Karṇa lying
dead on the ground, Somakas, delighted,
made loud noise, sounded musical instru-
ments and shook their (upper) garments
and hands; others danced and embraced
each other saying: “Karṇa is pierced with
an arrow as fire is extinguished by a strong
wind at the end of a sacrifice or at day-
break in a bedroom; Karṇa's body with
arrows all over it and smeared with blood
shines like sun with his rays; the sun in
the form of Karṇa has been forced to set
by Kāla in the form of Arjuna; as the sun
while setting takes away his light, so has
the arrow taken away Karṇa's life” 8.
67. 28-32; after the death of Karṇa, in the
evening, at the foot of the Himavant
(हैमवते प्रस्थे 9. 5. 1) and near the
river Sarasvatī (9. 4. 49), Śalya when
requested by Duryodhana to lead the army
(9. 5. 26-27), he (Śalya) assured him that
he would defeat Pārthas and Somakas in
battle 9. 6. 3; after Śalya's election as the
general, the great chariot-fighters of Madra-
kas while praising Śalya said that he was
capable of defeating in battle even gods,
demons and men, let alone Somakas and
Sṛñjayas (किमु सोमकसृञ्जयान्) 9. 6. 9;
that night, in the camp of Pāṇḍavas, Kṛṣṇa
encouraged Yudhiṣṭhira to fight with Śalya;
after he left, Yudhiṣṭhira gave leave to
Pāñcālas and Somakas to leave his camp
(विसृज्य पाञ्चालान् अथ सोमकान्) 9. 6. 39;
(23) On the eighteenth day when Bhīma
attacked Kṛpa, the great chariot-fighters of
Somakas too attacked him and others in
order to kill their opponents (अभ्य-
द्रवन्त … जिघांसन्तः परान् युधि) 9.
7. 31; Somakas fell down by thousands
due to the arrows of Śalya; after a while,
Śalya again struck down Somakas and
Pāṇḍava army and caused distress to Yudhi-
ṣṭhira (सोमकाश् च सहस्रशः।पतिताः;
शल्यो ऽपि … निघ्नन् सोमकपाण्डवान्। …
युधिष्ठिरम् अपीडयत्) 9. 10. 21, 41;
when Yudhiṣṭhira announced his decision
to kill Śalya, the army of Pāṇḍavas, espe-
cially the Pāñcālas, Somakas and Matsyas,
expressed delight which helped the fulfil-
ment of Yudhiṣṭhira's vow (i. e. encouraged
him) (ततः प्रहर्षः सैन्यानां … पाञ्चा-
लानां सोमकानां मत्स्यानां च विशेषतः।
प्रतिज्ञां तां च सङ्ग्रामे धर्मराजस्य
पूरयन्) 9. 15. 26-27; seeing Śalya, killing
his opponents, angered Somakas and others,
surrounded him (परिवव्रुः) 9. 16. 6;
after the death of Śalya, when the Madra
army attacked the Pāṇḍava army, Somakas
and others covered Yudhiṣṭhira on all
sides to protect him (युधिष्ठिरं परी-
प्सन्तः समन्तात् पर्यवारयन्) 9. 17. 8;
Somakas and others thought that the ele-
phant of king Śālva (9. 19. 2-3), though
one, was moving in thousand forms around
them (तम् एव नागं ददृशुः समन्तात्।
सहस्रशो वै विचरन्तम् एकम्) 9. 19. 6;
Duryodhana alone halted (अवारयत्) with
his sharp missiles the attack of Somakas
and others 9. 20. 34; Aśvatthāman assured
Duryodhana who had taken shelter in the
Dvaipāyana lake that he would kill Soma-
kas and others on that very day (अद्य
निहनिष्यामि सोमकान्) 9. 29. 19; when
Duryodhana's whereabouts became known,
delighted Somakas shouted loudly (प्रा-
क्रोशन् सोमकास् तत्र) 9. 29. 48; Somakas
and others held Duryodhana in high regard
(सर्व एवाभ्यपूजयन्) when he cha-
llenged Bhīma to prove his boasts 9. 55.
40; after the duel began, Somakas and
Pāṇḍavas were afraid when they noticed
the velocity of the wind produced by
Duryodhana's mace (गदा मारुतवेगं हि
दृष्ट्वा) 9. 56. 31; when at one stage
Bhīma lost consciousness due to the stroke
of Duryodhana's mace on his chest, Soma-
kas and Pāṇḍavas, their hopes dashed to
the ground, became dejected (भृशोपहत-
संकल्पा नहृष्टमनसो ऽभवन्) 9. 56.
49; Somakas were thrilled to see Duryo-
dhana fall down (ददृशुः हृष्टरोमाणः)
9. 58. 2; the chief warriors among Somakas,
who were righteous, did not approve of
Bhīma's putting his foot on the head of
fallen Duryodhana (नाभ्यनन्दन् धर्मा-
त्मानः सोमकानां प्रबर्हाः) 9. 58.
13; (24) Dhṛtarāṣṭra asked Saṃjaya
whether Kṛpa and Kṛtavarman took part
in destroying the camp of Pāṇḍavas and in
killing them and Somakas while fighting,
and then go the way Duryodhana did
(i. e. die in battle) (कच्चित् प्रमथ्य
शिबिरं हत्वा सोमकपाण्डवान्।दुर्यो-
धनस्य पदवीं गतौ परमिकां रणे॥)
10. 8. 3; while moving in the camp, Aśva-
tthāman happened to see the sons of Drau-
padī and the surviving Somakas (अव-
शिष्टांश् च सोमकान्) 10. 8. 44; as far as
the destruction of Somakas, who were
asleep and not on their guard, was con-
cerned that night proved to be extremely
cruel (एवंविधा हि सा रात्रिः सोमकानां
जनक्षये।प्रसुप्तानां प्रमत्तानाम् आसीत्
सुभृशदारुणा॥) 10. 8. 142; Aśvatthāman
was delighted that Somakas and the Mat-
syas who had survived were all killed by
him; he felt that he and his associates
had done their duty; he wanted to give
that very delightful news to Duryodhana
if he was still alive (सोमका मत्स्यशेषाश्
च सर्वे विनिहता मया॥इदानीं कृत-
कृत्याः स्म … ।यदि जीवति नो राजा तस्मै
शंसामहे प्रियम्॥) 10. 8. 150-151.
C. Certain persons referred to as the leader
or the prominent among the Somakas:
A. सोमकानां धुरंधर-: Drupada
5. 5. 1;
B. सोमकानां प्रबर्ह-: (1)
Dhṛṣṭadyumna 1. 185. 1; 5. 22. 17; 5. 47.
39; (2) Some prominent Somakas, not
named 9. 58. 13.

सोमकुल
Somakula (nt., sg.): The lineage of
Soma.
The king of Gāndhāra country (not
named) born in this lineage, was killed
by Māndhātṛ (सोमकुलोत्पन्नो गान्धारा-
धिपतिर् महान्) 3. 126. 40 [See the next
two entries].

सोमवंश
Somavaṃśa m. (sg.): The lineage of
Soma.
Bhīma told Hanūmant that he, a
Kaurava, was born in the lineage of Soma
(कौरवः सोमवंशीयः कुन्त्या गर्भेण
धारितः) 3. 147. 3 [See Somakula and
the next entry].

सोमान्ववाय
Somānvavāya m. (sg.): The lineage
of Soma.
Yayāti, son of Nahuṣa, was born in
the lineage of Soma (अस्ति सोमान्ववाये मे
जातः कश्चिन् नृपः सखा।यायातिर् नाम
राजर्षिर् … ) 5. 112. 6-7 (This is what Su-
parṇa told Gālava). [See the preceding
two entries].

सौध
Saudha m. (pl.): Name of a Janapada.
Listed by Saṃjaya among the northern
Janapadas (also called Deśas 6. 10. 68) of
Bhāratavarṣa (अत ऊर्ध्वं जनपदान् नि-
बोध) 6. 10. 37, 5; (सौधा मद्रा … )
6. 10. 40.

सौबल्य
Saubalya m. (pl.): Name of a Jana-
pada.
Listed by Saṃjaya among the northern
Janapadas (also called Deśas 6. 10. 68) of
Bhāratavarṣa (मत्स्याः सुकुट्यः सौब-
ल्याः) 6. 10. 38; (for other citation see
above Saudha).

सौराष्ट्र
Saurāṣṭra: See Surāṣṭra.

सौवीर
Sauvīra: See Suvīra.

हंसकायन
Haṃsakāyana m. (pl.): Name of a
people.
Their excellent Kṣatriyas, with weapons
in hands, brought wealth by hundreds to
Yudhiṣṭhira for his Rājasūya (हंसका-
यनाः। … श्रेयांसः शस्त्रपाणयः आहार्-
षुः क्षत्रिया वित्तं शतशो ऽजातशत्रवे)
2. 48. 13, 16.

हंसपद
Haṃsapada m. (pl.): Name of a
people.
On the twelfth day of the war, Haṃsa-
padas and many others, led by Kṛtavarman
and Kṛpa, formed the ‘eyes’ (चक्षुषी) of
the Suparṇavyūha of the Kauravas 7. 19. 4,
6-7 (to be identified with Haṃsamārga ?
Cf. Editor's Critical note on the stanza: “If
they are the same people as Haṃsamārga
mentioned in 6. 10. 68, then the B S reading
Haṃsapatha would be preferable” Cr. edn.
Vol. 9, p. 1147;) [See the next entry].

हंसमार्ग
Haṃsamārga m. (pl.): Name of a
Janapada.
Listed by Saṃjaya among the southern
Janapadas (also called Deśas 6. 10. 68) of
Bhāratavarṣa (अथापरे जनपदा दक्षिणा
 … ) 6. 10. 56, 5; (ताम्रा हंसमार्गाश् च)
6. 10. 68; [See Haṃsapada above].

हरिवर्ष
Harivarṣa nt. (sg.): Name of a Varṣa.
A. Location: Beyond Himavant and
Śveta mountains and the Hāṭakadeśa and
Gandharvanagara which were near the
Mānasa lake 2. 24. 27; 2. 25. 1-5 (see
section
C. Epic events below); according to
another reference, beyond the Bhāratavarṣa
and only beyond the Haimavatavarṣa and
the Hemakūṭa mountain (इदं तु भारतं
वर्षं ततो हैमवतं परम्।हेमकूटात्
परं चैव हरिवर्षं प्रचक्षते॥) 6. 7.
6.
B. Qualities of men and of the land:
In the Varṣas beyond the Himavant moun-
tain in the north there are holy Janapadas
where beings of all kinds live (तत्र पुण्या
जनपदास् … ।वसन्ति तेषु सत्त्वानि नाना-
जातीनि सर्वशः॥) 6. 7. 5; according to
Saṃjaya the qualities of men living in
the four युगस् of the Bhāratavarṣa were
bettered by those who lived in the Haima-
vata Varṣa and more than that by those in
the Harivarṣa (गुणोत्तरं हैमवतं
हरिवर्षं ततः परम्) 6. 11. 14; the lands
around Harivarṣa were known as Uttara-
kurus and no battles ever took place on that
land (उत्तराः कुरवो ह्य् एते नात्र युद्धं
प्रवर्तते) 2. 25. 11; for other charac-
teristics of the land see Epic event (No. 1)
below.
C. Epic events: (1) Arjuna in his
expedition to the north (दिशं धनपतेर्
इष्टाम् 2. 23. 9; 2. 24. 1) before the Rājasūya
went from the Hāṭaka Deśa to Harivarṣa;
he wished to conquer also that Varṣa but
was told by the gatekeepers, having large
bodies and great strength, that the city could
not be conquered by him; he should return
since the city could not be entered by
men; if men did enter, they would certainly
die (इदं पुरं यः प्रविशेद् ध्रुवं स
न भवेन् नरः) 2. 25. 10; (Nī., Bom. Ed.
2. 28. 10: न भवेत् म्रियेतेत्य् अर्थः);
moreover, if Arjuna entered it he would
not be able to see anything (नेह द्रक्ष्यसि
किंचन।न हि मानुषदेहेन शक्यम्
अत्राभिवीक्षितुम्) 2. 25. 11-12; Arjuna agreed
to return from Harivarṣa if the country
could not be entered by men; they asked
him if they could do something for him;
Arjuna desired sovereignty for Yudhi-
ṣṭhira and some tribute for him (पार्थिवत्-
वं चिकीर्षामि धर्मराजस्य धीमतः।
 … यत्किंचित् करवन् नः प्रदीयताम्);
after receiving from the gatekeepers tribute
in the form of heavenly garments, heavenly
ornaments and heavenly stripped-off hairy
skins of antelopes Arjuna turned back
(ततो दिव्यानि वस्त्रानि दिव्यान्य् आभरणानि
च।मोकाजिनानि दिव्यानि तस्मै ते प्रददुः
करम्॥) 2. 25. 13-16 (Nī., Bom. Ed.
2. 28. 16 reads क्षौमाजिनानि in place of
मोकाजिनानि and explains क्षुमातसीविशेषः
 … तत्तन्तुनिर्मितानि क्षौमाणि अजिनानि च।);
(2) Dhṛtarāṣṭra asked Saṃjaya to describe
to him the Harivarṣa in details (how long
the people there lived, the fruits they
received for their actions, auspicious or
otherwise, their past, present and future
(प्रमाणम् आयुषः सूत फलं चापि शुभा-
शुभम्।अनागतम् अतिक्रान्तं वर्तमानं
च संजय) 6. 11. 1-2; Saṃjaya then
told to him the qualities of the people of
the Bhāratavarṣa in the four Yugas and
further told him that the qualities were
found in a higher degree in the Harivarṣa
6. 11. 3-14 (see above section
B.).

हाटक
Hāṭaka m. (sg., pl.): Name of a
country and its people.
A. Location: Called Deśa (हाटकं
नाम देशम्) 2. 25. 1, 3, 5; it lay be-
yond the Śveta mountain (श्वेतपर्वतं
 … समतिक्रम्य) 2. 25. 1; near the lake
Mānasa and the country protected by
Gandharvas (सरो मानसम् आसाद्य हाट-
कान् अभितः … गन्धर्वरक्षितं देशम्)
2. 25. 4-5.
B. Inhabitants: It was the
abode of Kiṃpuruṣas and was protected
by Guhyakas (देशं किंपुरुषावासम्
 … देशं गुह्यकरक्षितम्) 2. 25. 1, 3.
C. Epic event: Arjuna in his expedition
to the north (दिशं धनपतेर् इष्टाम् 2.
23. 9; 2. 24. 1) before the Rājasūya reach-
ed Hāṭakadeśa and won over the people
through conciliation (तांस् तु सान्त्वेन
निर्जित्य) 2. 25. 3-4.

हारहूण
Hārahūṇa m. (pl.): Name of a
people.
Epic events: Nakula in his expedition
to the west (प्रतीचीम् अभितो दिशम् 2. 29.
2, 11; 2. 23. 10) before the Rājasūya
brought Hārahūṇas under control (वशे
चक्रे) 2. 29. 11; Hārahūṇas brought for
Yudhiṣṭhira tribute of different kinds but
were stopped at the gate (द्वारि वारितान्;
द्वारि तिष्थन्ति वारिताः) 2. 47. 19-20, 25;
the tribute described in details in 2. 47.
21-25; it consisted of different kinds of
asses (रासभान्), cloth and silk of different
kinds, hides, weapons, drinks and perfumes
(रसान् गन्धांश् च) and jewels; (however,
Nī. on Bom. Ed. 2. 51. 29 interprets रसान्
as juicy fruits: रसान् रसवन्ति तर्बुजा-
दीनि); Hārahūṇas mentioned by Kṛṣṇa
among those whose kings attended the
Rājasūya and acted as servants (मही
पालान् … हारहूणाश् … यज्ञे ते परिवेषकान्)
3. 48. 18, 21-22 [very likely they formed a
section of Hūṇas; see Hūṇa].

हुण्ड
Huṇḍa m. (pl.): Name of a people.
On the second day of the war, Huṇḍas
were among those who, led by Yudhiṣṭhira,
stood at the back of the Krauñcāruṇavyūha
(6. 46. 39-40) of Pāṇḍavas (हुण्डैश् च
 … पृष्ठम् आसीद् युधिष्ठिरः) 6. 46. 47.

हूण
Hūṇa m. (pl.): Name of a people.
A. Location: North of Āryāvarta;
mentioned by Saṃjaya among the northern
Mlecchas of Bhāratavarṣa (अत ऊर्ध्वं
जनपदान् निबोध) 6. 10. 37, 5; (उत्तरा
चापरे म्लेच्छा जना … । … हूणाः पार-
तकैः सह) 6. 10. 63-64; also see
B. Past
event.
B. Past event: While going to
Mithilā from mountain Meru (मेरुशृङ्गे
12. 310. 11-12; मेरुपृष्ठे 12. 311. 12),
Śuka after arriving at Bhāratavarṣa crossed
many countries inhabited by Cīnas and
Hūṇas before arriving at Āryāvarta; from
there he went to Mithilā in Videha (स
देशान् विविधान् पश्यंश् चीनहूणनिषेवितान्।
आर्यावर्तम् इमं देशम् आजगाम महा-
मुनिः) 12. 312. 15, 12, 19 [See Hāra-
hūṇa].

हृदिक
Hṛdika m. (pl.): Name of a people.
Kṛtavarman designated as the great
chariot-fighter of Hṛdikas (हृदिकानां
महारथम्) 8. 18. 62 (Hṛdika, father of
Kṛtavarman, perhaps also designated after
the people's name).

हैमवत
Haimavata nt. (sg.): Name of a
Varṣa.
A. Location: It lay immediately to the
north of Bhāratavarṣa (इदं तु भारतं
वर्षं ततो हैमवतम् परम्) 6. 7. 6;
(also see
D. Past event).
B. Charac-
teristic: Haimavatavarṣa was superior to
Bhāratavarṣa in qualities and Harivarṣa was
superior to Haimavatavarṣa (गुणोत्तरं
हैमवतं हरिवर्षं ततः परम्) 6.
11. 14; (for the qualities of the people
see Bhāratavarṣa in the Addenda to this
volume).
C. Epic event: Dhṛtarāṣṭra
asked Saṃjaya to describe to him the
longevity of the people of Haimavata, the
auspicious or bad effects of their action and
their past, present and future (तथा हैम-
वतस्य च।प्रमाणम् आयुषः सूत फलं
चापि शुभाशुभम्॥अनागतम् अतिक्रान्तं
वर्तमानं च संजय।) 6. 11. 1-2.
D.
Past event: Śuka while going to Mithilā
from mountain Meru crossed the Haima-
vatavarṣa before reaching the Bhāratavarṣa
(वर्षं हैमवतं तथा।क्रमेणैव
व्यतिक्रम्य भारतं वर्षम् आसदत्॥)
12. 312. 14.

हैरण्यक
Hairaṇyaka nt. (sg.): Name of a
Varṣa.
It lay to the north of the Śveta Varṣa
and the Śṛṅgavat mountain (श्वेताद् धै-
रण्यकं परम्।वर्षम् अत्रावतं नाम
ततः शृङ्गवतः परम्॥) 6. 7. 35.

हैहय
Haihaya m. (pl.): Name of a people.
A. Description: Having strong arms
(बाहुशालिन्) 12. 49. 65; of unbounded
prowess (अमितौजस्) 5. 153. 4; famous
(प्रथितात्मन्) 3. 182. 5; eminent Kṣatriyas
(क्षत्रियर्षभ) 5. 153. 5; (क्षत्रिय-
पुंगव) 12. 49. 66.
B. Past events: (1)
A certain prince, not named, of Haihayas
thought that he had killed a sage mistaking
him to be a deer; he reported the incident
to Haihayas; dejected, Haihayas (दीन-
मानसाः 3. 182. 7) went in search of the
dead sage; they reached the hermitage of
Tārkṣya Ariṣṭanemi; they were duly receiv-
ed by him (तेषां पूजाम् अथाहरत् 3. 182.
9); Haihayas, however, considered that
they were unworthy of the honour since
they had killed a Brāhmaṇa; they told
Ariṣṭanemi that they had searched for him
but could not find him; then they were
told by Ariṣṭanemi that they had commi-
tted no sin since whom they thought they
had killed was his son who was alive, and
was present in his आश्रम; Haihayas asked
Tārkṣya how his dead son came back to
life; they were told that since Ariṣṭanemi
and his son always acted truthfully and
never cherished a lie, and since they follow-
ed religion they had no fear from death
(सत्यम् एवाभिजानीमो नानृते कुर्महे
मनः।स्वधर्मम् अनुतिष्ठामस् तस्मान्
मृत्युभयं न नः 3. 182. 17); when
Haihayas knew that they were sinless, they
were delighted (हृष्टाः) and they returned
to their country 3. 182. 21; (2) Rāma
Jāmadagnya killed thousands of Haihayas
(हैहयसहस्राणि) along with Kārtavīrya
Arjuna's sons and grandsons and made
the earth full of their blood-stained mud
(चकार भार्गव्ō राजन् महीं शोणित-
कर्दमाम्) 12. 49. 45-46; after many years,
the Earth when not properly protected by
Kṣatriyas entered Rasātala and requested
Kaśyapa to see that some eminent Kṣa-
triyas protected her again; she specifically
mentioned for this purpose the Kṣatriyas
born in the family of Haihayas who were
protected by her when Paraśurāma killed all
Kṣatriyas (सन्ति … नृषु क्षत्रियपुंगवाः।
हैहयानां कुले जातास् ते संरक्षन्तु मां
मुने) 12. 49. 66; a reference to the killing
of Haihayas and of Kārtavīrya is made in
the Parvasaṃgrahaparvan while listing the
events of the Āraṇyakaparvan 1. 2. 117
(actually the event referred to here is des-
cribed in the Śāntiparvan as noted above;
the event briefly mentioned in the Āra-
ṇyakaparvan is different; see the next); (3)
King Sagara of Ikṣvāku family extirpated
Haihayas and Tālajaṅghas (स हैहयान्-
समुत्साद्य … ) 3. 104. 7; (4) Kṣatriya
Haihayas were attacked by Brāhmaṇas,
Vaiśyas and Śūdras; they were again and
again defeated by the Haihayas; the Brāh-
maṇas asked them the secret of their victory;
Haihayas replied saying that on the battle-
field they listened only to one among them
who had superior judgement; the Brāh-
maṇas and the rest who attacked them were
divided, each following his own judgement;
the Brāhmaṇas then chose one of them
who was skilled in policies and defeated
the Kṣatriya (Haihayas) (वयम् एकस्य
शृणुमो महाबुद्धिमतो रणे।भवन्तस्
तु पृथक् सर्वे स्वबुद्धिवशवर्तिनः॥)
5. 153. 4-9; (5) Udāvarta, king of
Haihayas, mentioned among the eighteen
kings who, at the end of the युग (युगा-
न्ते), extirpated their kinsmen, friends and
relatives (ये समुच्चिच्छिदुर् ज्ञतीन् सुहृदश्
च सबान्धवान् … हैहयानाम् उदावर्तो …
युगान्ते … संभूताः) 5. 72. 11, 13, 17;
these kings are described as disgraceful to
their race and mean (कुलपांसनाः;
कुलेषु पुरुषाधमाः).
C. Certain kings
referred to as one belonging to the Hai-
haya people, one born in that line; or the
kings of Haihayas; or foremost among the
Haihayas: A. (i) One belonging to Hai-
hayas: हथय: (1) Arjuna Kārtavīrya
12. 49. 35; 13. 137. 4; (2) Sumitra 12. 125.
9; (ii) One born in the line of Haihayas:
हैहयानां कुले जातः: Sumitra 12. 125.
25; हैहयान्वय: Arjuna Kārtavīrya 12.
49. 30; (iii) Ancestor of Haihayas: है-
हयानां कुलकरः: a certain prince, not
named 3. 182. 3:
B. The king of Haihayas:
(i) हैहयाधिपति: Arjuna Kārtavīrya 1.
98. 1; (ii) हैहयेश: Arjuna Kārtavīrya:
(Rāma Jāmadagnya called हैहयेशप्र-
माथिन्) 5. 182. 12;
C. The best or the
prominent among the Haihayas: (i) है-
हयेन्द्र: Arjuna Kārtavīrya 12. 49. 40;
(ii) हैहयश्रेष्ठ: Arjuna Kārtavīrya
13. 141. 1; (iii) हैहयर्षभ: Arjuna
Kārtavīrya 13. 140. 3.

आवह
Āvaha m.: Name of the second of the
seven winds.
A. Divine origin: All the seven
winds are Aditi's sons ( … एते ऽदितेः पुत्रा
मारुताः) 12. 315. 53.
B. Description:
All the seven winds are very wonderful;
they blow incessantly everywhere sustain-
ing all (creatures) (परमाद्भुताः।अनार-
मन्तः संवान्ति सर्वगाः सर्वधारिणः)
12. 315. 53; Āvaha makes noise while
blowing (नदन्) 12. 315. 37.
C. Activity:
There are seven paths of the winds which
blow on the earth and in the atmosphere;
Āvaha blows along the second path (पृथि-
व्याम् अन्तरिक्षे च यत्र संवान्ति वायवः।
सप्तैते वायुमार्गा वै) 12. 315. 31; (आवहो
नाम संवाति द्वितीयः) 12. 315. 37; the
Āvaha wind takes moisture from the clouds
and excellent lustre from the lightnings while
blowing in the sky (अम्बरे स्नेहम् अभ्रे-
भ्यस् तडिद्भ्यश् चोत्तमा द्युतिः।आवहो
नाम संवाति द्वितीयः श्वसनो नदन्॥)
12. 315. 37.

उद्वह
Udvaha m.: Name of the third of the
seven winds.
A. Divine origin: All the seven winds
are Aditi's sons ( … एते ऽदितेः पुत्रा मारु-
ताः … ) 12. 315. 53.
B. Description: Most
raining (वर्षिष्ठ) 12. 315. 40; all the seven
winds are very wonderful, blow incessantly
in all places sustaining all (creatures) (पर-
माद्भुताः।अनारमन्तः संवान्ति सर्वगाः
सर्वधारिणः) 12. 315. 53; (सदागति)
12. 315. 40; when it is inside the bodies
it is called by great sages उदान (अन्तर्-
देहेषु चोदानं यं वदन्ति महर्षयः)
12. 315. 38.
C. Activity: It blows along
the third of the seven paths of winds which
blow on the earth and in the atmosphere
(पृथिव्याम् अन्तरिक्षे च यत्र संवान्ति
वायवः।सप्तैते वायुमार्गा वै … ) 12.
315. 31; (उद्वहो नाम तृतीयः स सदागतिः)
12. 315. 40; it causes moon and other
luminaries to rise; it takes water from four
oceans, holds it, and then gives it first to
the clouds in the sky and next gives the
watery clouds to Parjanya (उदयं ज्योति-
षां शश्वत् सोमादीनां करोति यः। … यश्
चतुर्भ्यः समुद्रेभ्यो वायुर् धारयते
जलम्।उद्धृत्याददते चापो जीमूतेभ्यो
ऽम्बरे ऽनिलः॥यो ऽद्भिः संयोज्य जीमूतान्
पर्जन्याय प्रयच्छति।) 12. 315. 38-40.

कुण्डधार
Kuṇḍadhāra m.: Name of a cloud.
A. Description: An attendant of gods
(देवानुचर) 12. 263. 6; lustrous (कुण्ड-
धारस्य तेजसा) 12. 263. 13; of great
lustre (महाद्युति) 12. 263. 17, 20; of great
fame (महायशस्) 12. 263. 27; magnanim-
ous (महात्मन्) 12. 263. 7.
B. Kuṇḍa-
dhāra figures in an ancient narrative
(इतिहासं पुरातनम्) told by Bhīṣma to
Yudhiṣṭhira in reply to his question:
What is most profitable among the three
Puruṣārthas viz. धर्म, अर्थ and काम
(2. 263. 1-2); in the narrative, Kuṇḍadhāra
obliges a Brāhmaṇa due to affection for
his devotee (कुण्डधारेण यत् प्रीत्या
भक्तायोपकृतं पुरा) 12. 263. 2-55;
the narrative runs as follows: A certain
poor Brāhmaṇa desired to obtain wealth
in order to perform a sacrifice; he therefore
worshipped many deities but did not get
wealth; he then wondered which could be
that one deity which would show him favour
quickly; he then saw standing near him
the cloud Kuṇḍadhāra (जलधरं कुण्ड-
धारं st. 6) who appeared before him
assuming an agreeable form (सौम्येन
वपुषा st. 6); the Brāhmaṇa felt assured
by Kuṇḍadhāra's form and felt that he
would definitely give him ample wealth;
the Brāhmaṇa became his devotee and
worshipped Kuṇḍadhāra with incenses,
perfumes, garlands and oblations (ततो
धूपैश् च गन्धैश् च माल्यैर् उच्चावचैर्
अपि।बलिभिश् चापि … , st. 9); the cloud,
satisfied, told the Brāhmaṇa that there were
expiations for the sins committed due to
killing a Brāhmaṇa, drinking wine, theft,
breaking a vow, but there was no expiation
for the sin of ungratefulness (कृतघ्ने
नास्ति निष्कृतिः st. 11); अधर्म was the
child of craving, anger of envy, greed of
insult (निकृत्याः), and that an ungrateful
person did not deserve progeny (कृतघ्नो
नार्हति प्रजाम् st. 12); then the Brāhmaṇa,
lying on the कुश grass, due to the lustre
(तेजस्) of Kuṇḍadhāra, saw in a dream
(निदर्शनम् अपश्यत st. 14), Maṇibhadra
distributing kingdoms and wealth as desir-
ed by gods (मणिभद्रं व्यादिशन्तम् … ।
तत्र देवाः प्रयच्छन्ति राज्यानि च
धनानि च st. 15-16); Kuṇḍadhāra fell
at the feet of Maṇibhadra; Maṇibhadra, at
the instance of gods, asked Kuṇḍadhāra
what he desired; Kuṇḍadhāra replied that if
the gods were satisfied with him they should
show that kind of favour to the Brāhmaṇa
which would lead him to happiness (अस्या-
नुग्रहम् इच्छामि कृतं किंचित् सुखो-
दयम् st. 19); again, at the instance of
the gods, Maṇibhadra told Kuṇḍadhāra
that he was willing to give the Brāhmaṇa
as much wealth as desired by him; Kuṇḍa-
dhāra then, reflecting that a man's (wealth)
was fickle, decided to fix the Brāhmaṇa's
mind on practising austerities (विचार्य
कुण्डधारस् तु मानुषं चलम् अध्रुवम्।
तपसे मतिम् आधत्त ब्राह्मणस्य यशस्-
विनः) 12. 263. 22; Kuṇḍadhāra therefore
told Maṇibhadra that he would not seek
wealth for the Brāhmaṇa, but that the
Brāhmaṇa be devoted to धर्म; he desir-
ed that the Brāhmaṇa should take delight
in धर्म and should live following the
धर्म (भवेद् एष तु धार्मिकः।धर्मे
ऽस्य रमतां बुद्धिर् धर्मं चैवोप-
जीवतु।) 12. 263. 25; when Maṇibhadra
persisted on giving the Brāhmaṇa kingdom
and various kinds of happiness since that
was what one aspired to get by follow-
ing धर्म, Kuṇḍadhāra did not change
his mind and wanted his Brāhmaṇa devotee
to live following the धर्म; the gods
were pleased with him; Maṇibhadra told
Kuṇḍadhāra that the gods were satisfied
with him and that the Brāhmaṇa's mind
would be fixed on धर्म and that he would
be a धर्मात्मा; Kuṇḍadhāra was delight-
ed for having obtained what was desired in
the form of a boon not easily obtained by
others; the Brāhmaṇa saw thin garments
around him but his mind was not deluded;
abandoning them, he went to the forest
and practised severe austerities; he felt that
if he so desired he could certainly give
some one even kingdom (12. 263. 30-39);
at that juncture Kuṇḍadhāra again appeared
before the Brāhmaṇa due to his friendship
with him and the severe austerities per-
formed by him; the Brāhmaṇa, surprised,
received him according to the rites; Kuṇḍa-
dhāra told the Brāhmaṇa that he had now
obtained the highest divine insight (दिव्यं
ते चक्षुर् उत्तमम् 12. 263. 42) and by
using it the Brāhmaṇa should see the ulti-
mate fate of the kings and the worlds
they would get; then the Brāhmaṇa by his
divine eye saw thousands of kings sunk in
the hell; Kuṇḍadhāra wondered that if the
Brāhmaṇa, after worshipping him was to
get unhappiness, what kind of favour had
he done to him ? He therefore asked the
Brāhmaṇa (to use his divine eye and) to
realize that it was futile to run after various
longings because the door to heaven was
closed for such men (कामान् इच्छेद् कथं
नरः।स्वर्गद्वारं हि संरुद्धं मानु-
षेषु विशेषतः॥ 12. 263. 45); the Brāhmaṇa
then saw that lust, anger, greed, fear,
arrogance, sleep, drowsiness, laziness hinder
men from going to heaven (ततो ऽपश्यत् स
कामं च क्रोधं लोभं भयं मदम्।
निद्रां तन्द्रीं तथालस्यम् आवृत्य पुरुषान्
स्थितान्॥ 12. 263. 46); Kuṇḍadhāra again
told the Brāhmaṇa that the vices, mentioned
before, stopped men from going to heaven;
gods were afraid of such men; (these vices),
as ordained by the gods, create obstacles
all around (तथैव देववचनाद् विघ्नं
कुर्वन्ति सर्वशः॥ 12. 263. 47); no one
who was not permitted by gods could be
virtuous; the Brāhmaṇa, due to his auste-
rities, could confer kingdoms and wealth
on others; the Brāhmaṇa fell at the feet
of the cloud (तोयधारिणे i. e. Kuṇḍa-
dhāra) and told him that he had done a
great favour to him; he requested Kuṇḍa-
dhāra to forgive him for having formerly
envied him (पुरा ते यद् असूयितम्) due
to his hankerings and greed; Kuṇḍadhāra
embraced the Brāhmaṇa and told him that
he had forgiven him and then disappeared;
the Brāhmaṇa then roamed through the
skies due to his austerities to which he was
led by Kuṇḍadhāra; due to his virtuousness
he also gained what he wanted and the
highest bliss (विहायसा च गमनं तथा
संकल्पितार्थता।धर्माच् छक्त्या तथा
योगाद् या चैव परमा गतिः॥) 12. 263.
53.

कौस्तुभ
Kaustubha m.: Name of a jewel.
A. Origin: It arose from the ocean
(मन्थध्वम् उदधिं देवा …  1. 15. 13;
1. 16. 12); (मथ्यातां कलशोदधिः 1. 15.
12); (समुद्रम् उपतस्थिरे 1. 16. 8); when
it was churned by the gods and the demons
to obtain nectar (देवा मथितुम् आरब्धाः
समुद्रं … ।अमृतार्थिनस् … सहिता दैत्य-
दानवाः 1. 16. 12; कौस्तुभश् च … उत्पन्नो
ऽमृतसंभवः) 1. 16. 35; 5. 100. 12.
B. Descrption: A jewel (मणि) 1. 16. 35;
5. 92. 13; 12. 45. 15; best among jewels
(मणिरत्न) 5. 100. 12; heavenly (दिव्य),
lustrous (श्रीमन्त्), and brilliant due to
rays (मरीचिविकच) 1. 16. 35.
C. Nārā-
yaṇa (Kṛṣṇa) wears it: It rests on the
chest of Nārāyaṇa (नारायणौरोगतः)
1. 16. 35; on the chest of Kṛṣṇa
(कृष्णम् … कौस्तुभेन उरःस्थेन मणि-
नाभिविराजितम्) 12. 45. 13, 15; 5. 92. 13;
D. Epic events: (1) When Kṛṣṇa started
for Hāstinapura to mediate between the
Pāṇḍavas and the Kauravas he wore the
Kaustubha jewel and appeared very bright
due to excellent lustre (कौस्तुभं मणिम्
आमुच्य श्रिया परमया ज्वलन्) 5. 92. 13;
(2) when Yudhiṣṭhira went to meet Kṛṣṇa
after his coronation, he saw him adorned
with Kaustubha jewel (कौस्तुभेन उरः-
स्थेन) 12. 45. 15.
E. Viṣṇu (Hari),
Nārāyaṇa (Kṛṣṇa Vāsudeva) referred to as
किरीटकौस्तुभधर 3. 194. 15; 6. 62. 22.

जिवनी
Jivanī: See Saṃjīvanī.

ज्येष्ठसामन्
Jyeṣṭhasāman nt.: Name of a Sāman.
A. Referred to in some past events:
(1) Upamanyu told Śakra that when he saw
Śiva Mahādeva, he was being praised by all
gods (13. 14. 146); Nārāyaṇa at that time
praised Mahādeva by singing the स्तोत्र
using Jyeṣṭhasāman (ज्येष्ठसाम्ना च
देवेशं जगौ नारायणस् तदा) 13. 14. 147
[Editor's note, with a question mark, on the
stanza, Vol. 17, p. 1060 Jyeṣṭhasāman =
Bārhatasāman ?]; (2) In the Kṛtayuga the
Sātvata Dharma was received by Brahman
from Nārāyaṇa himself and was taught to
the Barhiṣad sages; from them it went to a
Brāhmaṇa called Jyeṣṭha who was versed in
the Sāmaveda (सामवेदान्तगं द्विजम्);
in this context it is said that god Hari
observes the व्रत of Jyeṣṭhasāman (ज्येष्ठ-
सामव्रतो हरिः) (i. e. Hari always uses
Jyeṣṭhasāman while singing praises) 12. 336.
42.
B. Its holiness: One who can sing
a स्तोत्र using Jyeṣṭhasāman melody is
included among those Brāhmaṇas who are
considered to be पङ्क्तिपावन or पाङ्क्तेय
(i. e. highly respectable, one who purifies
those who sit in a line with him while tak-
ing meals (पाङ्क्तेयांस् तु वक्ष्यामि ज्ञेयास्
ते पङ्क्तिपावनाः। … छन्दोगो ज्येष्ठ-
सामगः) 13. 90. 19-20.

परशुवन
Paraśuvana nt.: Name of a hell.
The name literally means ‘forest of
axes’; it is described as ‘a great hell’
(परमनिरय, महानिरय) 12. 309. 30-
31; a doer of evil deeds, who is covetous,
to whom untruth is dear, who is always
engaged in deception, he, due to these
cheatings (Nī. on Bom. Ed. 12. 321. 31:
उपनिधिभिश् छलेन), goes to this hell
and experiences great unhappiness; he
plunges into the great river Vaitaraṇī
whose waters are hot and then gets his
limbs cut by the leaves of trees which are
sharp like a sword; ultimately he falls in-
to the Paraśuvana hell; he lives there
experiencing great affliction (यो लुब्धः
सुभृशं प्रियानृतश् च मनुष्यः सतत-
निकृतिवञ्चनारतिः स्यात्।उपनिधिभिर्
असुखकृत् स परमनिरयगो भृशम्
असुखम् अनुभवति दुष्कृतकर्मा॥उष्णां
वैतरणीं महानदीं अवगाढो ऽसिपत्र-
वनभिन्नगात्रः।परशुवनशयो निपतितो
वसति च महानिरये भृशार्तः॥) 12. 309.
30-31.

परावह
Parāvaha m.: Name of the last of
the seven winds.
A. Divine origin: All the seven winds
are Aditi's sons ( … एते ऽदितेह् पुत्रा मारुताः)
12. 315. 53.
B. Description: The highest
(पर) and difficult to transgress (दुरति-
क्रम) 12. 315. 52; very wonderful (पर-
माद्भुत) 12. 315. 53; blowing constantly
without break in all places and sustaining
all (creatures) (अनारमन्तः संवान्ति
सर्वगाः सर्वधारिणः) 12. 315. 53.
C.
Activity: It blows in the seventh of the
seven paths of winds which blow on the
earth and in the atmosphere (पृथिव्याम्
अन्तरिक्षे च यत्र संवान्ति वायवः) 12.
315. 31 (Nī. on Bom. Ed. 12. 328. 31:
संवान्ति संगच्छन्ति); it takes away the
lives of living beings at the time of their
death; both Mṛtyu (Death) and Vaiva-
svata (Yama) follow its path; it leads those
to immortality who, with their intellect
calm and steady in आत्मन्, understand (the
world) correctly and who take delight in
the practice of meditation; having met Parā-
vaha ten thousand sons of Dakṣa Prajāpati
reached quickly the end of directions; one
who is created (touched ?) by it, is de-
feated; he goes away never to return (?)
(सर्वप्राणभृतां प्राणान् यो ऽन्तकाले
निरस्यति।यस्य वर्त्मानुवर्तेते मृत्यु-
वैवस्वताव् उभौ॥सम्यग् अन्वीक्षतां
बुद्ध्या शान्तयाध्यात्मनित्यया।ध्याना-
भ्यासाभिरा माणाम् यो ऽमृतत्वाय कल्पते॥
यं समासाद्य वेगेन दिशाम् अन्तं प्र-
पेदिरे।दक्षस्य दश पुत्राणां सहस्राणि
प्रजापतेः॥येन सृष्टः (स्पृष्टः ?) परा-
भूतो यात्य् एव न निवर्तते।परावहो
नाम परो वायुः स दुरतिक्रमः॥ 12.
315 49-52 (Nī. on Bom. Ed. 12. 328. 49-
52; मृत्युवैवस्वताव् अपि यदनुरेधिनौ
तयोर् अपि प्रेरक इत्य् अर्थः।एतेन मृत्यु-
ग्रस्तानां ब्रह्मादीनां तदधीनत्वं
कैमुतिकन्यायसिद्धं॥४९॥भो अध्या-
त्मचिन्तकाः … शान्तया बाह्याभ्यन्तर-
विषयेभ्य उपरतया बुद्ध्या सम्यग्
अहं ब्रह्मास्मीति वाक्यानुसन्धानपूर्व-
कं अन्वीक्षतां श्रवणमननम् अनु-
ध्यानेन पश्यतां ध्यानाभ्यासो निरन्-
तरं ध्यानम् एव अभिरामं येषां
तेषां यो ऽमृतत्वाय मोक्षाय कल्पते॥५०॥
दिशो ऽन्तं प्रतिपेदिरे ब्रह्माण्डं निर्-
भिद्य गता इत्य् अर्थः॥५१॥).

परिवह
Parivaha m.: Name of the sixth of
the seven winds.
A. Divine origin: All the seven winds
are Aditi's son's ( … ऽदितेः पुत्रा मारुताः)
12. 315. 53.
B. Description: Very
wonderful (परमाद्भुत) 12. 315. 53;
very speedy (जवतां वरः) 12. 315. 48.
C. Activity: (a) Common to all seven
winds: They all blow incessantly in all
direction and sustain all (creatures)
(अनारमन्तः संवान्ति सर्वगाः सर्व-
धारिणः) 12. 315. 53 (Nī. on Bom. Ed.
12. 328. 31: संवान्ति संगच्छन्ति);
they blow along the seven paths of
winds which blow together on the earth
and in the atmosphere (पृथिव्याम् अन्त-
रिक्षे च यत्र संवान्ति वायवः।सप्तैते
वायुमार्गा वै) 12. 315. 31; (b) Special
to Parivaha: Due to its circular movement
the heavenly waters flow in the atmosphere
(and do not fall down); it supports the
holy waters of celestial Gaṅgā; being
checked by this wind from a distance the
sun, though he is the source of a thousand
rays and brightens up the earth, appears
like having a single ray; due to this wind
the moon, which is the heavenly store of
nectar, waxes (after waning) (यस्मिन्
पारिप्लवे दिव्या वहन्त्य् आपो विहायसा।
पुण्यं चाकाशगङ्गायास् तोयं विष्टभ्य
तिष्ठति॥दूरात् प्रतिहतो यस्मिन्न् एकरश्मिर्
दिवाकरः।योनिर् अंशुसहस्रस्य येन
भाति वसुन्धरा॥यस्माद् आप्यायते सोमो
निधिर् दिव्यो ऽमृतस्य च।षष्ठः परिवहो
नाम स वायुर् … ) 12. 315. 46-48 (Nī.
on Bom. Ed. 12. 328. 46: परितः उपर्य् एव
यस्य वेगात् पतन्ति न त्व् अधः पतन्तीति
परिप्लवः।स्वार्थे तद्धितः।यः तोयं
विष्टभ्य आकाशे एवावस्थाप्य).

पारिजात
Pārijāta m.: Name of one of the five
heavenly trees.
Past event: Vidura scolds Duryodhana,
who wanted to arrest Kṛṣṇa, by reminding
him that Kṛṣṇa had defeated even Indra
when he took away the Pārijāta tree from
him (पारिजातं च हरता जितः साक्षाच्
छचीपतिः) 5. 128. 48; Dhṛtarāṣṭra while
describing the best exploits of Kṛṣṇa men-
tions that he had frightened Amarāvatī and
removed the Pārijāta from the abode of
Indra ( … त्रासयित्वामरावतीम्।म्छेन्द्र-
भवनाद् वीरः पारिजातम् उपानयत्) 7. 10.
22. (Its use in pl. in 3. 220. 23 (पारिजात-
वनैः) and 9. 36. 60 (पारिजातैः) denotes
the coral trees in general and hence those
references do not belong here).

पुष्पक
Puṣpaka nt.: Name of a विमान (a
vehicle moving in the air).
A. Origin: It was fashioned by Viśva-
karman (विश्वकर्मणा।विहितम्) 3. 158.
35.
B. Description: Moving in the air
(खेचर) 3. 275. 52: drawn by swans
(हंसयुक्त) 9. 46. 27; moving at will
(कामग) 3. 275. 52; heavenly (दिव्य) 9.
46. 27; brilliant (श्रीमन्त्) 3. 158. 35;
(विराजन्त्) 3. 275. 52; pleasant (रुचिर) 3.
221. 5; (मनोरम) 9. 46. 27; equipped
with excellent beds and seats (शय्यासन-
वर) 3. 158. 35; having variegated borders
(चित्रपर्यन्त) 3. 158. 35.
C. Epic event:
After Bhīma's fight with the Yakṣas, when
the Pāṇḍavas came to meet Kubera, he was
seated in the Puṣpaka 3. 158. 35.
D. Rāmā-
yaṇa events: (1) When Rāvaṇa defeated
Kubera and drove him out of Laṅkā, he
deprived Kubera of his Puṣpaka Vimāna;
Vaiśravaṇa, however, cursed Rāvaṇa that
the Vimāna would never carry him; it would
carry only him who would kill Rāvaṇa in a
battle (न त्वाम् एतद् वहिष्यति।यस् तु त्वां
समरे हन्ता तम् एवैतद् वहिष्यति) 3. 259.
34-35; (2) Rāma, after making arrange-
ments for the internal security of Laṅkā
(विधाय रक्षां लङ्कायां) crossed the
ocean riding the Puṣpaka 3. 275. 51-52;
(3) Rāma reached Kiṣkindhā riding the
Puṣpaka; on way he described to Sītā the
forest from the Vimāna (वैदेह्या दर्शयन्
वनम्) 3. 275. 56; (4) When Rāma was
anointed the king of Ayodhyā, he wor-
shipped the Puṣpaka and returned it to
Vaiśravaṇa (पुष्पकं च विमानं तत् पूज-
यित्वा) 3. 275. 68.
E. Mythological events:
(1) When Skanda was anointed the leader
of the army of the gods (यदाभिषिक्तो
 … सेनापत्येन पावकिः), Śiva started to
meet him at Bhadravaṭa; at that time
Kubera, riding his Puṣpaka, was in front of
Śiva 3. 221. 1, 5; (2) Kubera practised
austerities near a तीर्थ, which came to be
known as Kauberatīrtha; as a result, Kubera
received various boons and, as a gift, the
Puṣpaka Vimāna as his vehicle (वाहनं
चास्य तद् दत्तं … विमानं पुष्पकं)
9. 46. 27.

प्रतिस्मृति
Pratismṛti (f.): Name of a science.
A. Description: Called a science
(विद्या), a perfection in bodily form (सिद्धिं
मूर्तिमतीं) 3. 37. 27; a secret knowledge
(उपनिषद्) 3. 38. 9; (ब्रह्मन्) 3. 37. 36;
3. 38. 10; excellent योगविद्या (योगविद्याम्
अनुत्तमाम्) 3. 37. 34.
B. Its power: When
Arjuna would learn it, he would be able
to propitiate Rudra, Mahendra, Varuṇa,
Kubera and Dharmarāja (Yama) to obtain
their weapons 3. 37. 27-28; when one
knows that science, the whole world dawns
on him (जगत् सर्वं प्रकाशते) 3. 38. 9.
C. Epic event: It was taught by Vyāsa to
Yudhiṣṭhira when he was ready to receive
it and was sanctified (प्रपन्नाय शुचये)
3. 37. 34-35, 27; Yudhiṣṭhira memorized it
by reciting it from time to time (मनसा …
धारयाम् आस … काले काले समभ्यसन्)
3. 37. 36; he later taught it to Arjuna who
was initiated by him (दीक्षित) to receive it
3. 38. 13-14; it was taught to him in a
secluded and private place (विविक्ते, रहसि)
3. 38. 2-3, 9, 14; when endowed with
Pratismṛti science, Arjuna was to practise
austerities and wait for the proper time
to receive the favour of the gods (तेन त्वं
ब्रह्मणा तात संयुक्तः … ।देवतानां
यथाकालं प्रसादं प्रतिपालय) 3. 38.
10.

प्रवह
Pravaha m.: Name of the first of the
seven winds.
A. Divine origin: All the seven winds
are Aditi's sons ( … अदितेः पुत्रा मारुताः)
12. 315. 53 (Nī. on Bom. Ed. 12. 328. 53:
अदितेः खण्डनशून्याया अदीनायाः परम-
चितेः पुत्रा इव पुत्रा रूपभेदाः).
B.
Description: (a) Common to all winds:
All the seven winds are very wonderful;
they blow incessantly in all directions sus-
taining all (creatures) (परमाद्भुताः।
अनारमन्तः संवान्ति सर्वगाः सर्व-
धारिणः॥) 12. 315. 53; (b) Peculiar to
Pravaha: Subtle (सूक्ष्म), cool (शीत),
fragrant (सुगन्धिन्), pleasant to touch
(सुखस्पर्श); most mysterious (पर-
माद्भुत) 12. 315. 53; the best among
the seven winds; it blows to auspicious
worlds (सप्तानां मरुतां श्रेष्ठो लोकान्
गच्छति यः शुभान्) 12. 290. 72.
C.
Activity: They all move along the seven
paths of winds which blow on the earth and
in the atmosphere (पृथिव्याम् अन्तरिक्षे च
यत्र संवान्ति वायवः।सप्तैते वायुमार्गा
वै … ) 12. 315. 31; this particular Pravaha
wind, which impels the clouds which arise
due to smoke and heat, blows on the first
of the seven paths of the winds (प्रेरयत्य्
अभ्रसंघातान् धूमजांश् चोष्मजांश् च
यः।प्रथमः प्रथमे मार्गे प्रवहो
नाम सो ऽनिलः) 12. 315. 36; the perfected
ascetics (मुनयः सिद्धा … ), after death,
are first borne by the rays of the sun (तान् …
सूर्यो वहति रश्मिभिः); there, the Pravaha
wind receives them and carries them further
to the highest point of नभस्; (ultimately
they reach Nārāyaṇa and do not return
to this world) (स तान् वहति … नभसः
परमां गतिम्) 12. 290. 69-72, (74-75);
those who are versed in the Sāṃkhya
philosophy know the (character of) the
Pravaha wind which is one of the seven
winds 12. 290. 27.

